            'tr' => '
McCartney Peak (USGS Mt Angeles, McCartney Pk, Maiden Pk, Wellesley Pk) -
After the long drive, stopping for my camping permit at the Wilderness
Center in Port Angeles, and eating lunch at the trailhead at Obstruction
Point (6100 ft), it was 1:30 pm before I started on the trail to Grand
Valley. The magnificent views along the first mile and half of trail made
this almost flat, easy section a real treat. When I reached the 6450 ft
saddle where the trail begins to descend into Grand Valley, I stayed on the
ridge, following a way trail S.  This way trail was easily followed as it
climbed up and down along the crest, with only a few scramble moves, until
it hit the narrow ridge S of Pt 6580. Here an unpleasant descent down a
loose gully was followed by a traverse under cliffs and a climb back up to
the ridge at the saddle just N of Moose Pt.
 
After a side trip to the broad summit of Moose, I continued along the easy
ridge to the 5920 ft saddle to the south. Here I made a long and unpleasant
descending traverse S on steep scree and heather to a nice campsite on a
knoll (5450 ft) above the Lillian River.  This camp was directly below the
saddle between Grandview Pk (6701) and Pt 6381. It had taken 4 hours and,
even though I was now some 650 ft below my starting point at the TH, 1450
ft of elevation gain to get here. The bugs had not been bad hiking, but
once stopped they came out in force.  To escape them, after dinner I took a
quick evening walk up Pt 6381, making the round trip in 1:10 hr, then
turning in for the night.
 
The next morning I was on my way by 8:00. A pleasant hike up meadows and
talus past a waterfall, then easy snowslopes to the saddle above and a
simple scramble along the S ridge put me on the summit of McCartney at
9:30.  After a half hour to enjoy the views and leave a register where
there was none,  I continued on my way following the ridge S and E to Pt
6728. I stayed here long enough to paint a watercolor sketch of Mt Olympus,
then quickly descended back to camp for lunch.
 
For the trip out I decided on a different route than the one I had taken
in. I climbed up to the saddle directly E of camp, then went north along
the ridge to Grandview. From here a good way trail led down to Grand Pass
where the Grand Valley Trail led down, down, down to Moose Lake, only to
then climb up, up, up back to Obstruction Point. Grand total for the trip
with all the ups and downs, 17 miles and 7700 ft gain. Fay Pullen, 7/31-
8/1, 2002.
 
 
Snowfield Peak (USGS Diablo Dam, Ross Dam) - What a beautiful mountain this
turned out to be, although it was a bit of a pain getting there. When Linda
and I stopped in Marblemount for our permit, we discovered only one other
party signed out for the area, a Marty LaFare and friend, so we figured we
would have a certain amount of solitude. We started up the Pyramid Lake
trail just before noon. We had postponed our trip by a day to let a storm
pass and the weather was now improving rapidly.  It was still rather cool,
which made for pleasant hiking up the steep trail and kept the bugs at bay,
at least for a while. 
 
At the lake we picked up the climber\'s trail on the right shore and
followed it very steeply to the ridge. This "trail" was much better than I
had expected and was easily followed to this point, where we had our first
partial views of impressive Pyramid Peak. The trail now wandered along the
ridge, past a marshy area and lily pond and up a rockslide and awkward
scramble section to a survey marker knoll.  Then down a bit into brush and
blowdowns on a traverse right of the crest where we lost the way. After
beating the brush for a short while we picked up the trail again on the
crest. Another scramble section, a traverse on the left side, then right to
a fork in opening terrain. We chose the right fork (the left fork is
probably better) which traversed steep heather then snow to the right of
the ridge.  A final climb on snow straight up put us on the ridge at a tarn
nestled among rock slabs. ( 5 1/2 hrs, 4600 ft to here).
 
 We half expected to see Marty camped here, but we were all alone. Although
snowfree level spots were hard to come by, this was truly a lovely
campsite. The views were fantastic. We could see down to Diablo Lake and
across to the heart of the North Cascades.  Directly above us loomed aptly
named Pyramid Peak. And above to the left we could see Colonial Peak, the
toe of the Colonial Glacier (where a gorgeous waterfall spewed forth) and
the beginning of our route to Snowfield. We also had a nice source of water
in a stream issuing from the snow a short ways downhill. What more could
one want? Well, a few less mosquitoes would have been nice. They were now
out attacking in force.
 
We began our climb the next morning at 7:30. I had originally hoped to
climb Pyramid, Pinnacle, Paul Bunyan\'s Stump and Colonial in addition to
Snowfield, but... well, you know how it frequently goes. By the end of the
day we were happy just to have made Snowfield. From our camp, we picked up
the climber\'s trail (at the tarn) that descended several hundred feet down
a ramp to talus, traversed below cliffs of Pyramid Peak, then climbed back
up talus then snow, (following old footprints - someone had been this way
not too long ago) past the waterfall, and onto the Colonial Glacier at a
very interesting ice lake.  Again we expected to see Marty camped here, but
no signs of life.  Where on earth could they be. It became a running joke
with us.  Where was the phantom Marty?
 
We passed the ice lake on the right and continued up the glacier to the
Colonial - Neve col.  The last bit was steep and icy enough that we stopped
to put on crampons. At the col, where there was a nice bivy site (no, Marty
wasn\'t here either), we had our first view of Snowfield.  And what a
beautiful view it was. The Neve Glacier is quite large and encompasses the
high ridge of Snowfield, the Horseman and the Needle in a blanket of
rolling white.  The upper glacier looked quite smooth and free of crevasses
(turned out to be misleading) but the lower glacier was very broken up and
the right arm descended to Ladder Creek in a jumbled icefall. We descended
from the col until we could traverse left below cliffs to the large
flat saddle between the two arms of the lower Neve Glacier.  Here we roped
up.
 
Once on the glacier, we dodged a few crevasses on the flat, went up a rib,
traversed under a large crevasse and climbed onto the broad plateau of the
upper glacier. Here we discovered that what had appeared completely smooth
from below was actually riddled with dozens of traverse crevasses, some of
which went almost entirely across the slope and required a bit of wandering
around to avoid. The first ones were wide and open and easy to see, but the
higher ones were small and thinly covered with the fresh snow of the recent
storm. They were also easy to step over.
 
By noon we had worked our way to the notch on the west ridge.  We left ice
axes and crampons, unroped and scrambled up the easy slope of the ridge to
where we could work left into a gully. At the top of the gully we roped up
again for the exit left around a corner and down a step to an easy
ramp which was followed to a notch with rappel slings. (There is an easier
exit from the gully lower down that avoids the step down.) We stayed roped
to belay across the notch. but it was really quite easy with good holds,
then scrambled simultaneously the last bit to the summit at 2:00 (6 1/2
hours and 3500 ft).
 
The summit register had been placed in 1986 and had several interesting
entries. Jim Nelson and J. Martin had bivied on the summit while Martin
took the picture for his book, North Cascades Crest.  Don Goodman signed in
as part of a long traverse, and I recognized many other names, but Marty
was not among them.  So they hadn\'t gotten this far yet. We spent about an
hour on the summit enjoying the views to Eldorado, Backbone Ridge, Mt Baker
etc.
 
On the way down, the crevasses that had been covered on the way up had
melted out noticeable on this warm, sunny day. We were back at the Colonial
- Neve Col when the mystery of where Marty was was finally solved.  Linda
spotted  two figures far in the distance on the summit of Pyramid Peak.  It
was now 4:30.  Perhaps there was still time to try another peak, but we
both felt wiped out and decided to go directly back to camp, which we
reached at 6:15 (10:45 hrs and 4050 ft). We spent the remaining daylight
resting, eating, painting and fighting the bugs.
 
Our last day we were up at 5:30, and were feeling good enough to try for
Pyramid Peak before leaving. Pyramid is probably the easiest of the bunch
in this area and besides we wanted the meet the phantom Marty. So we
started again at 7:30 retracing our route to the ice lake. From there we
trended up and to the right until we could double back above the lower
cliffs toward Pyramid. Once on the gentle Pyramid ridge, an easy scramble
put us on top at 10:00 (2 1/2 hrs and 2000 ft), and who should be there but
Marty and friend.  They had bivied on the summit.  These two guys were very
familiar with the North Cascades. They spent every summer on an extended
trip exploring and poking around.  They were in no hurry to do anything,
just to soak up the beauty of the place. They were about half way through
their current 10 day trip and hoped to climb Snowfield the next day - or
maybe the day after.  They had weathered the recent storm in their tent
down on the Colonial Glacier. Their tent was rather hidden, off to side on
a small ourcropping of rock and being brown, blended in.  That is why we
never saw it.  We spent a pleasant hour chatting and they pointed out all
manner of neat climbs to do visible from our current vantage point.  Then
we got off on a discussion of summit registers and how the Park Service has
been removing them.  They were very much against this, as of course am I. 
I had brought a few registers with me to place as needed, but they beat me
to this one and Linda and I were cheerfully the second party to sign their
newly placed register.
 
We were back in camp by noon and left 2 hours later for the trip out. We
were able to stay on the trail where we had lost it on the way up but
almost lost it again at a different place.  We passed a party of two
sweating their way up the trail and wished them luck sticking to the trail.
We hit the lake at 4:00 and stopped long enough for a quick dip. Very
refreshing. We reached the car at 5:30. This was a great trip and I will be
back to get the peaks I missed. 23 miles and 11,250 ft.  Fay Pullen, 8/7-9,
2002

