            'title' => 'Bailey Range Traverse, Northern Section (USGS Mt Carrie, Hurricane Hill, Mt Olympus, Mt Queets)- 8/20-24, 2002.    ',
            'tr' => '
Bailey Range Traverse, Northern Section (USGS Mt Carrie, Hurricane Hill,  Mt
Olympus, Mt Queets) - It had always been a dream of mine to  do  the  Bailey
Range Traverse but the difficult car shuttles and the  length  of  the  trip
always put me off.  Then I got the idea to go in via Appleton Pass  and  out
over Dodger Point and the Long Ridge Tr.  This would shorten the trip  to  5
days and  put  the  two  trailheads  within  10  miles  of  one  another,  a
reasonable distance to bike or hike.  Then Linda agreed to go  with  me  and
that simplified things even further. The peaks I hoped to  climb  along  the
way were Cat, Carrie, Stephen, Pulitzer, Ferry, Ludden and Scott.  We  ended
up getting 6 of the 7. Not too bad. We carried an ice axe, no  crampons  and
only a thin 20 ft rope in case we needed a short assist in  the  many  gully
crossings of the traverse. If the peaks themselves could  not  be  scrambled
we would not climb them.  I was not going to carry heavy  climbing  gear  on
this trip.
 
Day One - Linda and I met at the Elwa RS, picked up our permit, left  a  car
at Whiskey Bend, then drove to the Appleton  Pass  TH  and  started  up  the
trail at 11:15. We  started  in  iffy  weather, but  the  forecast  was  for
improving conditions and soon we were  getting  partial  clearing  and  some
views. The upper trail had been cleared of  all  the  avalanche  debris that
had come down the previous winter. Appleton Pass was reached at  3:30  where
we had our first rest. Here we stayed on the ridge following the  Cat  Creek
way trail. The flowers on this ridge were just gorgeous,  fields  of  lupine
and avalanche lilies.
 
We missed the proper descent off the ridge, wandering around a bit  to  pick
up the trail again as it led to Spread Eagle Pass. From here the  trail  was
easily followed as it traversed up and  down  across  3  basins.  The  trail
disappeared in talus after crossing  the  last  rib  above  Cat  Basin.   We
descended a bit to a small flat basin and a nice creek where we set up  camp
(elev 4500 ft) at 6:45 (13 miles, 5000 ft  and  7:30  hrs).  The  bugs  were
still tolerable here.
 
Day Two - From our camp we could see the trail below us  in  Cat  Basin,  so
just headed downhill toward it, starting at 8:15.  This was  to  be  a  long
day as we hoped to climb both Cat and  Carrie  and get  far  enough  on  the
traverse to find a decent place to camp. There had been a heavy  dew  during
the night soaking the foliage, so by the time we got to the  trail  we  were
somewhat wet. We followed the trail out of Cat  Basin  to  its  intersection
with the High Divide trail on the  ridge  above,  then  followed  this  good
trail to its sudden end on a hillside (2 hrs and 1400 ft).
 
A steep way trail led up to the start of the "Catwalk".  We left  our  packs
here, taking only essentials (My pack\'s top lid converts to a  fanny  pack. 
Linda used a very light day pack), and climbed to the  easy  summit  of  Cat
Pk.  There was no register on top. We had a great view of our  entire  route
so far from Appleton Pass. On the way back we met 2 women  who  were  camped
above Cat Basin.  They had previously done the Bailey traverse and  told  us
of a great campsite a few miles on.
 
Back at our packs (RT to Cat - 2 hrs and 1100 ft) we prepared for  the  real
start of the Bailey Range Traverse, which begins at the Catwalk. I had  read
about the Catwalk for years and had envisioned a lovely  knife  edged  ridge
of clean rock. It turned out to be a rather  unattractive  vegetated  narrow
dirt and rotten rock ridge. It was not very difficult either, but one  still
had to be careful, especially carrying full packs. It took us 35 minutes  to
cross and on the other side was the tiny pond of Boston  Charlie\'s  Camp.  A
steep climb, then the traversing began through lovely flowery meadows. At  a
spur ridge, we dropped the packs again  at  2:30  for  the dash  up  Carrie.
After a steep climb we picked up a  climber  trail  along  the  main  summit
ridge, traversed on scree and talus to the right  below  the  false  summit,
then headed around an upper  basin  on  snow  then  cruddy  scree  with  bad
footing to the top at 3:30.  A large new register had been placed  in  2000.
We quickly enjoyed the views, as  they  were  beginning  to  disappear  with
encroaching fog, then zipped back to our packs (RT to Carrie  -  2  hrs  and
1400 ft).
 
All we wanted now was to find a decent campsite, but the terrain  was  steep
sidehill for several miles and there were no level places, or running  water
for that matter. We crossed several annoying gullies and continued in an  up
and down traverse with more down than up. At 6:00 we came  upon  the  lovely
campsite (elev 5150 ft), mentioned by the  two  women, on  a  meadowy  bench
with a delightful cascading creek nearby where we were more  than  ready  to
stop (10 miles, 5400 ft and 10 hrs total). I set up my tiny tent  and  Linda
laid out her bivy sack to dry in the intermittent sun (they had been  packed
wet that morning from the heavy dew)  before  the  fog  rolled  in  for  the
night. On the hillside above we spotted a lone bear and  a  herd  of  goats,
which made us take more than the  usual  precautions  to  protect  food  and
gear. After turning in, a lone goat wandered  around  our  camp  all  night,
keeping me partially awake hoping the bear wouldn\'t do the same.
 
Day Three - We awoke to a magnificent view of  Mt  Olympus  across  the  Hoh
River and the entire goat herd, including two adorable kids, milling  around
looking for mischief. The bear was still on the hillside above us,  but  far
enough away to not pose a threat. This camp was such a lovely spot  that  we
were loath to leave. We had fun watching the goats, although we did have  to
guard our stuff, and I took the time to paint a sketch  of  Mt  Olympus,  my
only one of the trip. By the time we were ready to leave it was 9:30,  later
than I had planned. We would have to hustle.  Today  would  be  the  hardest
part of the traverse and I also wanted to climb Stephen Pk.
 
The traverse continued on steep hillside following a still good  way  trail,
but the terrain gradually became more difficult with several  tough  gullies
to cross.  One entailed a very steep descent with treacherous footing.  This
section was quite slow and took more time than  anticipated.  We  could  see
the ridge coming down from Stephen Pk that we had to cross to get  to  Cream
Lake.  It looked so close, but around every  corner  was  another  gully  to
cross. Finally, the way improved as we descended to 11 Bull Basin.  After  a
steep climb out of the basin  to  the aforementioned  wooded  ridge  and  we
thought the hard part was over. Ha!
 
From the ridge the trail deteriorated as it first sidehilled toward  Stephen
Pk, then dropped like a bomb over 1500  ft,  where  it  became  increasingly
rough and hard to follow. It led right to an awful blowdown area of  tangled
trees.  Here the biting flies became so bad  that  both  Linda  and  I  were
driven to put on long pants and sleeves. On the other side of the  blowdown,
nearing the valley bottom, the trail, now  very  faint,  led  to  the  right
downstream and in the opposite direction from Cream Lake. This  confused  me
greatly.   Linda  suggested   that   perhaps   it   was   avoiding   another
blowdown. Maybe.  But it hadn\'t avoided the first one and I felt others  may
have been led astray by an animal trail and the safest thing to do was  head
crosscountry directly  toward  the  lake  (via  GPS).  This  we  did.  After
crossing some avalanche debris, we entered the woods on the  other  side  of
the valley and headed uphill toward the lake. Soon  we  picked  up  a  trail
that led past a waterfall to Cream Lake at 1:15
 
Two Park Rangers were at  the  lake  (yes,  they  did  ask  if  we  had  our
permits). We discussed our route to the lake and how  we  had  gone  astray.
They said that was the way most people go, more or less.  There is  supposed
to be a high route that avoids the big descent  but  they  have  never  been
able to find it. We took a long lunch at the lake, and even a quick  dip  to
rinse off.  Very quick. The water was cold and the bugs relentless.  We  ate
sitting under netting.
 
From Cream Lake we followed the  creek  upstream  to  the  farthest  branch,
where we picked up a rough trail in a grassy gully.  We came out at a  small
tarn and found a nice campsite (elev 4750 ft)  on  the  knoll  above  it  (5
miles, 1700 ft and 5 3/4 hrs).  We quickly set up  camp,  then  started  for
Stephen Pk at 3:50. A steeply rising traverse up wet meadows (many signs  of
elk) led up to the main ridge where we crossed to a snow slope on the  other
(N) side and traversed W under  several  rocky  pinnacles  until  below  the
summit (my GPS helped determine where this was). Up snow, talus then a  last
class 3 scramble on rotten rock put us on top at 5:30.  The summit  register
dated from 1982 and didn\'t  have  that  many  entries.  We  relaxed  for  30
minutes in the sun and watched a graceful hawk ride the air  currents  below
us. Magnificent! Then we beat a hasty retreat back to camp arriving at  7:15
(RT to Stephen 1900 ft and 3:25 hrs) where the bugs were out in force.
 
Day Four - We spotted a herd of elk  on  the  hillside  near  our  route  to
Stephen peak before we left at 8:30. When we started this trip Linda  stated
that this being the Olympics she wanted to see bear, goats and  elk.   Well,
she was now three for three. Upper Cream  Basin  was  gorgeous  open  alpine
terrain and there were many choices of route as  we  wandered  past  meadows
and many tarns heading for the Ferry - Pulitzer  saddle.   We  followed  the
main creek into a large flat basin, then into increasingly rocky  and  snowy
terrain to a large tarn at the foot of the tiny Pulitzer  Glacier.   Here  a
trail led up past cliffs to the smaller tarn just below the saddle. We  left
packs here for the short trip up Pulitzer Pk, on easy  snow  then  shattered
rock to the false summit.  The true summit was a short distance  away  along
a narrow exposed ridge.  It looked pretty bad.   Linda  wisely  decided  the
false summit was good enough, but I decided to give it a go. It  turned  out
to be not very difficult but rather dangerous.  I do believe  I  have  never
climbed on such rotten steep rock.  Every hold was loose  and  the  rock  as
sharp as the edge of a knife.  I ended up with several cuts on my hands.   I
did make it to the top but  in  retrospect  it  probably  wasn\'t  worth  the
risk.  I wouldn\'t do it again.  There was no register on  top  (probably  no
one else was stupid enough to  climb  it)  so  I  left  one.  After  a  nice
glissade we were back to our packs at noon (RT to Pulitzer - 700  ft  and  1
1/2 hrs).
 
From the saddle we headed up a way trail to  the  Ferry  shoulder.  We  left
packs again for the quick, trivial  ascent  of  Ferry  (RT  160  ft  and  20
minutes). Then we started the descent  off  Ferry  heading  for  the  Scott-
Ludden saddle.  We could see a good trail along the ridge in  the  distance,
but first we had to descend a rocky step a couple of hundred feet.  Here  we
met a couple going the same direction.  The husband  had  taken  the  wife\'s
pack down the step, so she could descend  pack  less,  then  come  back  for
his.  Wish I had someone like that - or do I? He "kindly"  offered  to  show
us the way to the saddle, but we declined, and soon  left  them  behind.  He
also offered advice on climbing Ludden that turned out to be  erroneous  and
contrary to my own instincts. Because of this we  left  our  packs  and  the
trail too  soon  and  ended  up  backtracking.  I  should  have  trusted  my
instincts.  We followed the ridge to the rather nondescript summit  where  I
left another register. Back to the packs (RT to Ludden - 800 ft and  2  hrs)
we followed the trail, very steeply in  places,  down  to  the  Scott-Ludden
saddle (elev 4750 ft) at 5:00 and a nice grassy meadow with  a  tiny  stream
(8 miles, 3500 ft and 8 1/2 hrs total).
 
I had wanted to try for Mt Scott, but both Linda  and  I  just  ran  out  of
steam. She suggested we climb it in the morning, but we had a  long  way  to
go out tomorrow and some possible routefinding problems  to  get  to  Dodger
Pt.  I felt we had to climb it now or not at all.  So we  called  it  a  day
and stopped at 6 peaks total. Our campsite was very  pleasant.   The  little
stream even had a pool large enough to wash up in, but  the  bugs  were  the
worst of the whole trip. We covered up  completely,  did  chores  with  head
nets on and ate dinner under a large net
 
Day Five - From the saddle we could see the abandoned trail we  were  aiming
for carved into the hillside across the  valley  at  pretty  much  the  same
elevation as we were at, but getting to it was no easy task (this trail  had
never been completed and so just came to a deadend on  the  side  of  Ludden
Pk).  A way trail descended about 500 ft very steeply to get  below  cliffs,
then dropped into a rugged gully (a few climbing moves needed  here)  before
climbing extremely steep loose dirt up the other side to hit the  old  trail
at its very end. (570 ft and 1:15 hrs) This point was not  real  obvious  so
Linda thoughtfully built a couple of cairns to help the next party out.
 
The old trail was easily followed and a pleasure after the rough  routes  of
the past few days,  until  we  rounded  a  corner  and  unexpectedly  hit  a
snowpatch in a narrow gully.  The snow was completely undermined by a  creek
and not safe to cross, and too steep to go around the  top,  so  we  entered
the resulting cave  from  the  top  and  exited  from  the  bottom,  getting
somewhat drenched in the process, where  we  could  climb  back  up  to  the
trail.
 
We hit the Long Ridge Tr at 11:30 where it was a long 10 miles down  to  the
Elwa trail.  Whoever engineered this trail must have been paid by the  mile.
It switchbacked endlessly barely losing any elevation  at  all.   The  trail
could easily have been made half as long  with no problem at all.   We  were
entertained on the long way out by various parties struggling up the  trail.
One fellow had a sock over his boot holding  a  separating  sole  together. 
And he was on the start of a 10 day trip to the Bailey Range (going  in  the
way we had just come out) that included climbing  Mt  Olympus.  I  shuddered
when I thought of that boot on the steep terrain we had  just  experienced. 
What                   was                   he                    thinking?





                                          I would have postponed my  trip  a
day in order to have decent boots. Another fellow we noticed had a bag  full
of spare batteries that must have weighed several pounds.  Perhaps he had  a
computer hidden in his pack.
 
We hit the Elwa bridge at 4:15 where  we  were  treated  to  a  fast  moving
thunderstorm, but very little rain, and Whiskey Bend at  5:30  (16.5  miles,
1800 ft and 8:15 hrs). Then all we had to do was pick up the  other  car  at
the Appleton Pass TH, which took another hour. Grand total - 55.5 miles  and
19600 ft. - Fay Pullen - 8/20-24, 2002.
 
 

