Ugly Duckling (USGS Chikamin Pk) - This is the 5140 ft peak NE  of  Swan  Lk
and is probably only of interest to Home Court peak baggers.  Logging  roads
climb to within 400 ft of the summit and would have little  to  offer  as  a
summer objective. However, as a winter ski trip it could be a  good  workout
and provide a little summit as a bonus. With this in mind,  I  started  from
the Kachess Lake SnoPark at 11:00 on a snowy morning.  The access road  from
I-90 had not yet been plowed and the 8 inches of fresh snow made me  glad  I
had a Cherokee.  Fortunately, the ubiquitous snowmobiles of this  area  were
already out in force and I did  not  have  to  break  trail  to  start.   An
advantage of a late start. I did, however have to  breathe  their  fumes  as
they streamed past.

I followed the well packed main road past Kachess Lake, then up  along  side
Gale Creek some 6 miles to the turnoff to  Swan  Lake.  No  snowmobiles  had
been up this side road so now I did have to break trail and my  pace  slowed
to half that on the main road. I followed this spur for  about  3  miles  to
the last switchback below the summit.  Here I left  the  road  and  followed
just inside the forest line, where trail breaking was easier, to  the  ridge
NW of the summit.  I kept on skis as long as  possible,  but  about  100  ft
from the top I was forced to abandon them due to steepness and scrub  trees.
Without  the  benefit  of  skis  I  immediately   sank   thigh   deep   into
unconsolidated snow.  But that wasn\'t the worst of my problems.  I  now  had
a clear view of the summit and  it  appeared  to  be  a  30  ft  high  rocky
pinnacle.  I wasn\'t prepared for this. From the map I had  thought  I  could
probably climb to the summit the whole way on skis.  Who knew  that  one  of
those contour lines hid a small cliff?

I immediately gave up on a direct attack on the pinnacle. I had no  climbing
gear, not even an ice axe and there was no way I could force my way up  that
last rock face safely.  My only chance was an end run around to the SW  side
and hope there was a break in the cliffs. So  I  descended  a  bit  until  I
could traverse a short ways under the cliff band, then worked  my  way  back
up to the ridge.  Work is the key word here.  Seldom have I worked  so  hard
to gain so little elevation.  I literally had to  built  steps  up,  pulling
the top foot of snow down and packing  it  in  one  step  at  a  time  so  I
wouldn\'t sink in to my waist.  It was painfully slow and daylight  was  fast
running out, but I wasn\'t going to quit now. I made  it  to  the  ridge  and
thankfully a smooth snow slope led to the summit on the other side.  It  had
taken over an hour to climb the last 100 ft to the top (3200 ft and  6  hr).
What a challenge this little peak turned out to be!

It was now 5:00 and dark. I quickly added  some  clothing,  changed  my  now
soaking gloves, got out my headlamp and started down. With my built trail  I
was soon back at my skis for the fun run down to the  main  road.  I  rather
enjoy skiing by headlamp.  I sometimes find the visibility even better  than
the flat light of day, and LED lights are often  enough  on  the  reflective
snow, especially on an  easy  logging  road.   Anyway,  I  was  back  to  my
snowcovered car at 8:30, slowed considerably at the end by  skis  that  iced
up terribly, despite frequent scraping, and refused to  glide  well  on  the
last long level stretch of road. It had snowed all day long. 18 miles,  3500
ft and 9:30 hr.  Fay Pullen, 12/30/02.
