Low Mountain (USGS Snoqualmie Pass) - As snow was too  sparse  and  icy  for
decent skiing, my intent on this beautiful cold sunny day was just  a  quick
climb up Granite Mtn to enjoy the views  and  get  some  exercise.  But  the
weather was so nice and the conditions so good for travel that on  the  spur
of the moment I decided to go for Low Mtn.  I have been up Granite  so  many
times I wanted to try something more exciting. So  where  the  summit  trail
(well booted but icy to this point) makes a big arc back to the NW  at  4400
ft, I continued straight ahead in a rising  traverse.  The  snow  was  hard,
though beginning to melt in the sun, and made for reasonable  step  kicking,
but the initial slopes were steep and concentration was needed  to  avoid  a
slip that could send me all the way down to the westbound lanes of I-90.

I crossed the SE ridge of Granite at about 4700 ft, then  began  a  downward
traverse through very pleasant  terrain  to  lovely  Denny  Lake.  Here  the
northern exposure slopes retained some unexpected  powdery  snow.  From  the
lake I headed up to the S ridge of Low.  So far the snow had  been  firm  if
not  icy,  but  once  on  the  crest  itself  it  softened  to  inconsistent
postholing, so I was finally forced to  put  on  snowshoes.   An  easy  trek
along the ridge with minor ups and down, led past  two  false  summits,  the
second of which was rocky and required removal of  snowshoes,  to  the  open
top with good views of surrounding peaks (4.5 hrs and 4450 ft).

For the return trip, I followed the ridge back to  the  saddle  above  Denny
Lake, but did not descend to the lake itself or retrace  my  steps  farther.
Instead I continued up the N ridge of Granite toward the  lookout.   I  kept
my snowshoes on the whole time, as  much  for  their  crampons  as  for  the
inconsistent snow. For it was now getting late and anything that had  melted
in the sun was starting to freeze again. When the ridge began to  gentle,  I
traversed on the E side until I hit the main Granite Mtn trail in the  basin
E of the lookout at about 5200 ft. I popped over the SE ridge just  at  dusk
with the last light fading behind Mt Rainier.

I was now the last person on the mountain and had it all to myself.  I  kept
the snowshoes on for a while, but the slope soon became too  steep  and  icy
for comfort, and crampons made for more security.  I kept those on  for  the
slippery trail all the way to  the  Pratt  Lake  junction,  where  all  snow
ended.  A peaceful hike down the rest of the trail by headlamp ended a  most
enjoyable trip.

I realize that there is a more direct route up Low Mtn  from  the  Denny  Cr
Trail, but I think the way I went has much to recommend it, particularly  in
stable winter conditions.  It is very scenic, there is no brush  and  it  is
surprising how interesting the terrain is on the  NE  side  of  Granite.  11
miles, 9 hrs, 5350 ft RT. Fay Pullen, 1/10/03.
