            'tr' => '
Colonial Pk, Paul Bunyan\'s Stump, Pinnacle Pk (USGS Ross Dam) - Last year  I
climbed Snowfield and Pyramid but didn\'t have time to  include  these  three
peaks, so I was back this year to correct this situation. I  approached  the
same way as before, up the Pyramid Lake trail and  then the  climbers  trail
to Pyramid Ridge.  As the saying goes, it is easier the second  time  around
and  this time made no errors in route finding.  I found a gravelly spot  to
camp very near the ice lake at the base of the Colonial Glacier at  5900  ft
(5000ft gain and 5:40 hrs).

I set up camp and attempted to heat water for some tea and soup.  But as  it
was very windy, I placed  my  windscreen  too  closely  around  my  canister
stove, which caused it to overheat and essentially  turn  into  a  fireball.
Then I burned  a  couple  a  fingers  on  both  hands  trying  to  move  the
windscreen and turn off the stove. I immediately  plunged  both  hands  into
the icy water of a nearby creek.  This was not  a  great  start  and  I  was
worried how my damaged fingers would affect my climbing, especially  on  the
rock of Pinnacle.

Undeterred, I was off at 4:30 pm to climb Colonial.  The  route  was  pretty
straightforward up the gentle Colonial Glacier to  the  base  of  a  steeper
snow finger leading toward the ridge above. On the way  up  my  now  painful
fingers caused me to insert them at frequent intervals into the  soft  snow.
This seemed to help.  As soon as possible I  exited  the  snow  finger  left
onto loose but easy rock and traversed around to talus  then  more  snow  to
the notch W of the peak.  An unpleasant loose gully led to more  solid  rock
on the ridge and the summit at 7:00.   A  deteriorating  notebook  inside  a
nice cylinder had been placed on May 25, l986.  I noted the ascent of  Laura
Zimmerman and Jim  Brisbane  on  June  1  of  this  year.   I  added  a  new
waterproof notebook to the register, then headed back down, arriving  at  my
tent at 8:45.

I now determined that my accident had destroyed the canister  and  my  stove
was nonfunctional, so I could not heat water for dinner. I made do  with  an
energy bar and cold drinks and turned in early. I  did  the  same  the  next
morning for breakfast and made the startling discovery that you  can  get  a
faster start if you don\'t have to cook. An advantage  surely,  but  I  still
missed my morning tea.  Surprisingly, my fingers hardly hurt at all  in  the
morning and gave me very little trouble the rest of  the  day.   Maybe  cold
therapy really works.

I was at the saddle S of Paul Bunyan\'s Stump by 7:00 am.  This was a  lovely
spot, flat and heathery and would be a nice place to camp.  I worked my  way
up the broad S ridge on heather and interesting slabs to  the  base  of  the
first cliffs.  The upper cliffs looked very  intimidating,  but  a  traverse
left revealed a wide ledge leading to a  gully  on  the  W  side  which  led
easily to the summit ridge. A few careful moves  along  the  narrow  exposed
crest and I was on top, a very pleasant climb indeed (1600 ft  and  2  hrs).
There was no register so I left one.

Next on the agenda was Pinnacle Pk.  I got a good look  the  SW  route  from
Paul Bunyan and didn\'t like what I saw so decided to try the N ridge  route.
So after descending from Paul Bunyan, I climbed back up on easy snow to  the
Pinnacle-Pyramid saddle.  I saw a possible  route  on  broken  rock  to  the
right above a snow finger.  The hardest part was exiting the  undercut  snow
onto the rock itself.  From here an easy but very loose gully led to  the  N
ridge.  The ridge itself was quite solid and fun, if  exposed,  climbing  to
the N notch. Here an 80 ft class 4 face caused me to rope up.   I  passed  a
rappel sling at the top of the  face.   The  summit  was  only  a  few  feet
farther along the crest (1000ft and 2 hrs from Paul Bunyan).  There  was  no
summit register but I had forgotten to bring one along when I left  my  pack
at the start of the rock climbing. Darn!

I did a couple of rappels to get off the rock, then  zipped  down  the  snow
back  to  my  tent.   I  had  a  couple  of  hours  to  enjoy  my  beautiful
surroundings before heading out.  It took 3.5 hrs to get  back  to  my  car.

About 21 miles and 10,000 ft elev gain.  Fay Pullen, 7/17-18/ 2003.

