            'subdir' => '2003-09-22-ironcap',
            'title' => 'September 19-20 and September 22-24, 2003, Iron Cap, Wild Goat, Tourmaline, Camp Robber, by Fay Pullen 
 IRON CAP (USGS Mt Daniel, Big Snow Mtn)
 WILD GOAT, TOURMALINE, CAMP ROBBER (USGS Big Snow Mtn)',
            'tr' => '
September 19-20 and September 22-24, 2003, Iron Cap, Wild Goat,  Tourmaline,
Camp Robber, by Fay Pullen

IRON CAP (USGS  Mt Daniel, Big Snow Mtn) - I had originally  planned  to  do
this peak and 3 others from the West Fork Foss  River,  but  concluded  that
was too ambitious for a 3-day trip.  Instead I decided to make it  the  sole
objective of a 2-day trip from the  Dutch  Miller  Trail.   Besides,  I  had
always wanted to camp at the charming Chain Lakes below La Bohn Gap  and  it
was now or never before the Middle Fork Snoqualmie River Road is  closed  at
Dingford Creek (planned for fall 2003).  So I again found myself driving  up
this awful road (I had climbed Burntboot Pk a few weeks  earlier)  and  then
starting from the TH in a  light  rain.   The  forecast  was  for  improving
conditions during the day and good weather  for  tomorrow.  The  light  rain
stayed with me all the way to Williams Lake where it began to  rain  harder.
I was beginning to doubt the accuracy of the forecast. Rounding the  lake  I
picked up the way trail to  Chain  Lakes  at  the  mine  on  the  far  side.
Miraculously, the rain quit just as I was picking out a scenic  campsite  on
a knoll between two of the larger tarns (9 miles, 3300 ft, 5:45  hrs).   But
by this time I was so wet and exposed to a chilling wind  that  things  were
looking rather bleak.  I retreated to my warm sleeping  bag  and  hoped  for
better things tomorrow.

I awoke the next morning to a bright blue sky and  sunshine  and  things  no
longer looked so bleak.  What a glorious day! Recharged with energy,  I  was
on my way by 7:30.  I climbed the ridge directly W  of  my  camp,  descended
400 ft into the basin on the other side  and  contoured  at  about  5300  ft
across steep talus until I could climb up to the broad flat  area  S  of  Pt
6263.  I then rambled through gorgeous meadows and rock  gardens,  following
the odd cairn and bits of way trail tread, to Iron Cap Pass.   This  has  to
be one of the most scenic sections of the Alpine Lakes High Traverse  and  I
thoroughly enjoyed every minute of it.

The way trail went downhill from the pass, but since my destination was  the
peak and not the traverse, I stayed high on the ridge until I could  contour
into the bowl on the NE side of Iron Cap.   A  few  icy  snowpatch  remnants
were easily avoided as I climbed toward the notch just E of the  summit  and
gained the "obvious" (I hate to use this term, but in this case it truly  is
obvious and the only viable escape through the cliffs) ledge slanting up  to
the right. At the end of the ledge a bit of steep heather  and  a  few  bush
belays led to the easy summit slopes and I was on top  by  11:15  (1900  ft,
3:45 hr).

I signed the register and noted a recent entry by  Don  Goodman  stating  he
had made the ascent via a traverse from Hardscrabble Lakes.  Looking W  down
the ridge in that direction it appeared a long and difficult route. I  spent
a pleasant hour on the summit, then headed back arriving  at  camp  at  3:00
(3100 ft, 7:30 hr).  Again I greatly enjoyed the traverse across the  lovely
alpine terrain.  I really didn\'t want it to end.  I spent some time at  camp
exploring old mines before leaving at 5:00 for the 4 hour trip to  the  car.
24 miles, 7000 ft, - Fay Pullen, Kent, 9/19-20.


WILD GOAT, TOURMALINE, CAMP ROBBER (USGS Big Snow Mtn)   -  Two  days  later
found me back in the area trying for the  other  three  peaks  on  my  list.
This time I approached from the West Fork Foss  River  Trail  and  I  had  a
companion, Linda. We began at 11:00 and by 4:00 we were at the  end  of  the
maintained trail at Big Heart Lake (passing Trout, Copper and  Little  Heart
Lakes on the way). Here we met two fellows coming out from  Azure  Lake  who
had cut short  their  original  plan  to  complete  the  Alpine  Lakes  High
Traverse to the Necklace  Valley  complaining  they  ran  out  of  time  and
energy.  One of them described the continuing way trail to Chetwood Lake  as
terrible and downright dangerous in places.  We did not find this to be  the
case.  As way trails go this one was easily  followed  and,  though  it  did
wander up and down a bit and had a few scramble moves here and there it  was
not really that bad.

As the way trail traversed  the  ridge  between  Big  Heart  Lake  and  Lake
Angeline, the terrain became increasingly more alpine and lovely in  nature.
 We set up camp by a delightful tarn on the E ridge of  Tourmaline  Pk  just
before the trail descended to Chetwood Lake (9 miles, 5000 ft, 7 hrs).

We woke the next morning to clouds and fog and a heavy  dew.   Not  what  we
had hoped for. Nevertheless we started at 8:45 for Wild Goat.   We  followed
the trail down to Chetwood Lake, then the rather rugged N  shore  (not  much
of a trail here) to Chetwood Pass.   We  climbed  SW  up  steep  heather,  W
across a spur right to drop into a talus basin, then up to the  notch  W  of
the summit for the final scramble along the ridge to the 6305 ft  top  (1450
ft, 2:50 hrs).  We found a bottle register  here  recently  placed  by  Mike
Collins.

The fog was  beginning  to  lift  by  now  and  we  had  fleeting  views  of
Tourmaline and Iron Cap.  I was really glad now that I had  already  climbed
Iron Cap and didn\'t have to add it to the agenda.  It looked like  it  would
take the rest of the day to get there from here.  We studied Tourmaline  for
a more direct ascent from  our  present  position.   Several  routes  looked
possible but the whole southern side facing us was quite cliffy,  and  since
we carried no climbing gear, we decided the best we could safely  do  was  a
direct route from Chetwood Pass to the E ridge,  rather  than  return  along
the shoreline of Chetwood Lake to the way trail.  This  we  managed  to  do,
staying below the cliffy areas, and emerged on the ridge  a  couple  hundred
ft above our camp.  From there it was an easy scramble up big  talus  blocks
and slabs to the 6245 ft summit (3000 ft, 6:45 hrs).  On  the  way  we  were
treated to several impressive veins of tourmaline rock for  which  the  peak
is named.

The fog had by now completely lifted.  Camp Robber, connected to  Tourmaline
by a long ridge, looked at least a mile off but  didn\'t  appear  to  be  too
difficult. Linda had had enough and elected to go directly back to camp,  so
I set off alone for my last peak at 4:00.  I descended NW to a  rocky  basin
and began a very enjoyable traverse on bedrock slabs and  large  blocks.   I
just love this type of scrambling and was greatly enjoying myself,  although
time was beginning to be an issue. It would be dark  at  7:00.  I  kept  the
traverse as high as possible below the  cliffs  of  the  ridgeline  until  I
could begin ascending to the summit ridge.  Unfortunately, I  misjudged  and
hit a false summit first.  Darn! A short descent and class 3  scramble  were
required to make it to the true 6286 ft summit at 5:00 (3600 ft,  8:15  hr).
Here I found a Mountaineer register left by Don Goodman on  6/5/01  and  the
familiar names of Mitch Blanton, Don Beavon and Mike Collins.

I miscued  a  bit  on  the  way  back.   Not  wanting  to  gain  unnecessary
elevation. I tried to contour from the rocky basin directly to  Tourmaline\'s
E ridge, got too low and ran into cliffs.  I had to climb up  and  over.   I
made it to camp at 6:30 where Linda had hot water  ready  for  dinner  (3800
ft, 9:45 hr).  I was one tired but happy climber.

Our last day dawned sunny and clear  but  with  another  heavy  dew.   While
waiting for the tent to dry in the sun, we were  first  visited  by  a  lone
(lonely?) fellow who talked our ears off for almost an hour.   He  had  come
from Big Heart Lake and was on his way to Chetwood Lake,  or  wherever.   He
really didn\'t care, as he had no destination.  He was just wandering  around
for a week or so.  He had gotten this far so we assumed he knew what he  was
doing although he seemed a little out  of  it.   We  were  next  visited  by
another fellow coming from Chetwood.  He was on  his  third  day  from  Lake
Dorothy.  He had intended to do  this  version  of  the  Alpine  Lakes  High
Traverse but found the terrain too difficult and slow and so  quit  at  this
point.  It seems many people underestimate the difficulty of  the  Traverse.
At least this guy didn\'t seem disposed to long conversation and was  quickly
on his way. Our campsite was becoming positively crowded and  tent  was  now
dry so it was time to go (10:30).

On the way out we were entertained by a fisherman  at  Big  Heart  Lake  who
complained that he hadn\'t had so much as a nibble.  No  sooner  had  we  sat
down nearby for a rest than he reeled  in  a  good  sized  trout,  which  he
promptly dropped and lost after unhooking it.  In the effort  to  hang  onto
it he fell into the water himself, boots  and  all.   He  then  tried  again
(after removing his soggy boots) and  landed  another  smaller  fish  a  few
minutes later.  This one he lost also, "deliberately", or so  he  said.   So
were we good luck or bad luck for him?

At Copper Lake we stopped to take a dip.  Although the  day  was  warm,  the
water was not, but it was refreshing.   Just  above  Trout  Lake  we  met  a
family with small children struggling up the trail  headed  for  a  camp  at
Malachite Lake.  It was now about 4:00.  We knew  they  had  a  stiff  climb
ahead of them and were going to be hard pressed to get to a campsite  before
dark.  They really should have stopped at Trout Lake.  25 miles, 10,100  ft,
- Fay Pullen, Kent, 9/22-24.



