            'title' => 'October 5-6, 2003, Tower Mtn and Golden Horn',
            'tr' => '
October 5-6, 2003, Tower Mtn and Golden Horn, by Fay Pullen

TOWER MTN, GOLDEN HORN (USGS Washington Pass) - I  was  well  aware  of  the
wildfires burning in the NE sections of our mountains at this  time  and  of
the many road and trail closures because of them, but I did not  expect  the
closures to extend to the west  of  Washington  Pass,  or  if  they  did,  I
expected the closures to be prominently displayed at  the  TH.   So  when  I
pulled into the PCT North TH near Rainy Pass at  10:30  on  a  bright  sunny
morning and saw several other cars in  the  parking  lot  and  no  signs,  I
thought I was safe.

I was packed up and ready to hit the trail by  11:00,  full  of  energy  and
anticipation to climb a pair of attractive peaks in an attractive area.   So
I was absolutely stunned when some 200 feet up the  trail  I  encountered  a
small sign stating the PCT was closed at  Cutthroat  Pass.   My  peaks  were
some 5 miles past Cutthroat Pass.  Why wasn\'t this sign on the reader  board
or at the very least visible from the TH?  In a somewhat state of shock  and
mostly propelled by momentum and not knowing what else to do, I  decided  to
continue to Cutthroat Pass and reassess the situation there.   Perhaps  they
had just forgotten to take the sign down.

Upon reaching Cutthroat Pass (5 miles, 1900 ft, 2.5 hrs), sure enough  there
was a trail barrier and sign indicating the trail was  closed.  What  to  do
now? After searching (very briefly) my usually very law abiding soul, I  did
what any  self-respecting  climber  would  do.   I  ignored  the  signs  and
continued on my way.  Now don\'t get me wrong.  I have the  greatest  respect
for and fear of wildfires.  They are not to be treated  lightly.   The  same
respect does not extend to bureaucrats who insist on  thinking  for  me  and
saving me from myself.  As a climber I am certainly able  to  assess  danger
to myself and how much I am willing to risk.  Climbers do it all  the  time.
So here I am at beautiful Cutthroat Pass.  There is not a cloud in the  sky.
 There are no fires visible on the horizon, or even smoke for  that  matter.
My conclusion is that the fires are far away and the forest service is  just
covering their rear ends and limiting their liability in case  a  fire  gets
out of hand.  If I am wrong in my assessment, then that is my  fault  and  I
am willing to pay the consequences.

And so I continue on the lovely trail past Cutthroat Pass.  My enjoyment  of
the beautiful scenery (this has to be one the most scenic  sections  of  the
PCT and a very impressive view of Tower and Golden Horn is to  be  had  from
the trail above Granite Pass) is tempered by my fear that behind every  rock
and around every corner is a ranger just waiting to give me a  citation  for
unlawful trespass.  I  don\'t  make  a  very  good  outlaw.   I  am  consoled
somewhat by fresh boot tracks in the dusty trail.  Others have been  outlaws
too.

I made it without incident (i.e. without  meeting  anyone)  to  lower  Snowy
Lake where I found a gorgeous site in full view of Tower Mtn to set up  camp
(10 miles, 2700 ft, 4:45 hrs).  Within an hour I  was  ready  to  start  for
Golden Horn.  Passing equally lovely Upper Snowy Lake, I continued  on  easy
open scree and sand, following way trails at times, to the  southeast  ridge
of Golden Horn. Then along the ridge,  past  the  false  summit,  to  circle
around and climb the summit rocks from the west (1800 ft,  1:45  hr).   From
the summit I could see smoke from the nearest fire two drainages  over,  not
close enough to cause me any concern.  A colorful sunset accompanied  me  on
my trip back to camp.

I set out the next morning at 7:30 for Tower Mtn.  The route description  in
Beckey is very accurate, so accurate I can only assume  it  was  written  by
someone who had actually climbed the mountain.  From camp I  made  a  rising
traverse over easy terrain to the talus basin W of the peak, then up a  very
loose broad gully to a notch in the SW ridge.  Scrambling  along  the  ridge
and then on the right side brought me to  the  base  of  the  summit  cliffs
where another gully, marked on the left by a small capstone spire, led  left
through the cliffs to a small notch.  I  descended  slightly  on  the  other
side of the notch and traversed under a cliff band until  I  could  enter  a
steep  gully.   I  followed  this  gully,  which  was  pleasant  class   2-3
scrambling, until stopped by a rock step.  This I turned  by  traversing  to
the right into a groove until I could get back  to  the  main  gully.   More
bedrock scrambling and I was stopped once again by a white wall  just  below
the ridgeline. I exited to the right and  traversed  right  several  hundred
feet on a series of exposed ledges until I could work my way  up  to  the  S
ridge.  What an interesting route this was turning out to  be.   Challenging
but not too difficult if you stayed on route.  At a  few  places  I  had  to
cast around for the easiest way.  I could see  if  you  got  off  route  you
could be in class 4 or even class 5 terrain  very  quickly.    A  few  well-
placed cairns did help along the way.

A short exposed scramble N along the ridge led to the  summit  where  I  was
greeted by a huge cairn and a nice summit register placed in  1995  by  Mike
Torok (1700 ft & 2:20 hr).   I  recognized  a  few  entries  including  Mike
Collins and Mitch Blanton on 8/31/02. But I  had  to  chuckle  at  the  most
recent entry by a fellow who had summitted a  week  earlier.   He  commented
that the forest service should close the PCT more often. Made for much  more
pleasant and less crowded camping at  Snowy  Lakes.   A  fellow  outlaw  and
kindred spirit.

 Careful downclimbing got me back to camp in  2  hours  at  noon.   After  a
pleasant 2 hour rest lounging in the sun, I  began  the  trip  out  reaching
Cutthroat Pass in a little over 2 hours where I was again "legal".   2  more
hours and I was back at the car.  And to think I could have  missed  out  on
this splendid trip if I had paid attention to the signs. 26 miles, 7400  ft,
Fay Pullen, Kent, 11/5-6.

