            'title' => 'October 12-13, 2003, Gilbert Mtn., by Fay Pullen',
            'tr' => '
October 12-13, 2003, Gilbert Mtn., by Fay Pullen

GILBERT  MTN.  (USGS  Gilbert  Mtn.)  -  Following  the  directions  in   75
Scrambles, I started up the North Creek Trail from  the  end  of  the  Twisp
River Road at 1:00 in a light but steady rain.  I met a  horse  part  coming
out just as I was getting  started.   They  informed  me  that  they  turned
around about half way to North Lake where they  encountered  several  inches
of new snow.  I could tell they thought I was crazy for going  out  in  such
lousy conditions, especially when they learned I was intending to spend  the
night.  By the time I reached North Lake (5 miles, 2250 ft, 3  hrs),  I  was
beginning to think they were right.  It was still  raining,  there  was  now
about 8 inches of wet snow on the ground, I was  quite  wet  and  cold,  and
prospects  for  climbing  my  peak  appeared  dismal.   But  trusting  to  a
favorable forecast for the next day and the fact that it  was  too  late  to
get back to the car before dark anyway, I made camp on a rare bare patch  of
ground under drippy trees and crawled  into  my  sheltering  tent  and  warm
sleeping bag.

 Strong winds and sideways rain and later snow during the night did  nothing
to improve the situation, but I spend a toasty, comfortable  night  sleeping
a solid 12 hours.  Miraculously, I emerged from my tent in  the  morning  to
blue skies and no wind.  Despite much fresh snow on the peak above  me,  how
could I not give it a try?  Thus 8:00 found  me  trudging  around  the  west
side of the lake and up a talus slope until forced to the right  by  cliffs.
Dodging more cliffs, I worked my up and into a large  bowl  below  Gilbert\'s
west ridge.  Snow was now knee deep and since I had no  snowshoes,  progress
slowed.  An easy snow slope led to the  ridge  between  Pts  7483  and  7414
(1600 ft, 2:45 hrs).

Bypassing Pt 7414, I continued up and down along the  pleasant  west  ridge.
Progress was still quite slow due to deep drifted snow in places  and  snow-
covered rocks, but there was little real difficulty until a  dicey  class  3
section along the very spine of the ridge just before the final major  notch
at the base of the summit pyramid.  Now the real scrambling  began,  500  ft
of continuous  class  2-3  made  much  more  difficult  by  the  fresh  snow
covering.  For the most part I stuck to the  crest  of  the  ridge,  despite
advice to leave the crest near the summit in 75 Scrambles.  That advice  was
probably correct as about 100 ft from the top I  found  myself  cliff  bound
above a minor notch.  Somehow I managed to  force  a  tricky  traverse  down
unstable snow on slabby rock to get  around  this  final  obstacle.   A  few
minutes later I was signing the summit register (2550 ft, 5 hrs).

The trip back to camp was much easier as all I  had  to  do  was  follow  my
broken trail, and I reached  my  tent  in  2.5  hours.   A  short  rest  to
recuperate, then 2 more hours on the trail and I was back at  the  car  just
at dark.  14 miles, 5150 ft, - Fay Pullen, Kent, 10/12-13.


