            'title' => 'October 31, 2003, SHROUD MTN (USGS Mt Daniel, Scenic)',
            'tr' => '
October 31, 2003, Shroud Mtn, by Fay Pullen

SHROUD MTN (USGS Mt Daniel, Scenic)  -  Encouraged  by  the  recent  glowing
report from Mark Owen and a most appropriate name I decided to treat  myself
to this climb for Halloween.  It turned out to be a bit  more  of  a  trick,
not the easy straightforward trip I had in mind.

I began the trip from near the end of the  Tonga  Ridge  Road.   This  road,
although in good shape, is a bit of a pain to drive as it wanders for  miles
on the north side of Tonga Ridge until  finally  ending  in  the  Fisher  Cr
drainage on the east side. Here I took the  little  used  but  good  2  mile
trail to Sawyer Pass.  The temperature at the  start  was  21  degrees  with
several inches of new snow.  More snow at Sawyer Pass made it  difficult  to
find and stay on the way trail to Fisher Lake.  I knew this trail climbed  a
bit onto a flat ridge, then dropped about 300 feet to the lake.  I  guess  I
dropped too much as  I  soon  found  myself  at  Lower  Fisher  Lake.   Lost
already. Not a great start to my climb.

I followed the outlet creek up to Fisher Lake  to  get  back  on  track  and
found the trail to Lower Ptarmigan Lake.  Again I  had  trouble  staying  on
the trail in the snow.  I passed the lake on the  west  shore  over  tedious
and treacherous snow-covered talus then continued up the  inviting  draw  to
Upper Ptarmigan Lake.  Here I encountered foot deep snow.   I  was  slow  to
here and getting slower and I could feel the day slipping away.   I  briefly
considered a direct approach to my peak up through  the  cliffs  surrounding
