            'title' => 'November 6-7, 2003, Loowit Trail (Mt St Helens), by Fay Pullen',
            'tr' => '
     November 6-7, 2003, Loowit Trail (Mt St Helens), by Fay Pullen


  Loowit Trail, Mt St Helens (Greentrails Mt St Helens NW # 364S) - And now
  for something different for me - not a summit but a trail trip,  although
  a very rugged trail, especially this time of year.


  I have always been fascinated with Mt St Helens, from the  first  time  I
  climbed her beautiful symmetrical  dome  many  years  ago  to  subsequent
  ascents up to a greatly altered post-eruption crater rim. So the  thought
  of circumnavigating the mountain on the Loowit Trail was  very  appealing
  and something I wanted to do every since I learned that a trail had  been
  "constructed" across the blast zone completing the  circle.   Be  advised
  that this trail is only shown on later versions of the Greentrails map or
  on the 1998 Geo-Graphics National Monument map.


  I arrived at the Climber\'s Bivouac trailhead, on the south  side  of  the
  mountain, at 11:00 amid much traffic from elk hunters, and started up the
  Ptarmigan Trail at 11:30 with several inches of well-trodden snow on  the
  ground.  The day was  fairly  warm  and  sunny,  but  a  stiff  wind  was
  worrisome. I soon reached the Loowit Trail (2.1 miles, 960 ft, 1 hr)  and
  turned right.  All footprints stopped and I was now making fresh  tracks.
  I was surprised at the loveliness of this first section  that  showed  no
  signs of the violent 1980 eruption.  It  was  open  meadowy  terrain  and
  looked very friendly. Much of the snow had melted  on  the  south  facing
  sunny slopes and a gorgeous view of Mt  Adams  was  dead  ahead.   I  was
  feeling inspired and all misgivings about doing this trip so late in  the
  year vanished.  I felt I would have no trouble making my destination  for
  the day - the Plains of Abraham just below  Windy  Pass,  some  10  miles
  distant. Little did I know!


  Soon I left the friendly sunny slopes,  entered  woods  where  the  light
  fluffy snow was calf deep, and began a 1300 ft descent to June Lake.  The
  trail switch backed down to Swift Cr then climbed up to  cross  the  Worm
  Flow lava field.  Here there was essentially no trail, just large  wooden
  poles stuck in the rock to follow, slow and tedious.  I was beginning  to
  lose my optimism that I would make my camp before nightfall.


  I passed the June Lake Trail at 2:15 (5.2 miles, 1140 ft, 2:45 hrs), then
  gradually climbed  to  regain  all  the  lost  elevation,  first  through
  meadows, then switch backing up a rocky ridge and beginning a long up and
  down traverse across many ravines on the east side of the mountain.  Here
  the snow deepened, in places drifted a foot or more.  The crossings  also
  showed the effects of the heavy rains of mid-October, which  washed  away
  the tread in many places.  Some were quite challenging as I scrambled  up
  and down the loose eroded rock.  Slowed even more, I was  now  certain  I
  would not make my destination before dark (5:00 this time of year).


  Somewhere along this section  I  was  astonished  to  come  upon  a  long
  abandoned mountain bike!  I was surprised to  learn  that  many  sections
  (except the restricted area) of the  Loowit  Trail  were  open  to  these
  machines.  This seemed crazy to me as the trail is too rough for them and
  they would have to be carried over many obstacles.   I  guess  one  rider
  agreed with my assessment and just abandoned his bike.

     I reached the Ape Canyon Trail at 5:00 (9.9 miles, 2800 ft,  5:30  hrs)
  where I ran into fresh mountain bike tracks in the snow.  This had to  be
  one tough biker. The snow here was wind crusted  and  must  have  been  a
  chore to ride or push through. I followed these tracks onto the Plains of
  Abraham and I must admit they were very helpful in allowing me to stay on
  course by just the light of an almost full moon.  This  trek  across  the
  flat open plains by moonlight was sheer  magic.  I  reached  the  Abraham
  trail at 6:00 where the tracks and I parted company.


  I was now on my own finding the way.  There  were  fewer  cairns  than  I
  expected and I soon lost the trail, but I could see  Windy  Pass  in  the
  distance and so just headed for it.  The wind was now  getting  to  be  a
  real problem on this open unprotected plain, but it was at my back  so  I
  was able to keep going.  There was supposed to be  a  water  source  just
  below Windy Pass, and this was where I had intended to camp.  But  I  had
  crossed no water in any of the previous ravines and  I  found  none  here
  either.  I guess the summer had been too dry.  I  was  getting  a  little
  desperate now.  No water and the wind was a real concern.  I had to  find
  a sheltered spot to camp soon.


  Forced by the wind to continue, I soon found myself at Windy  Pass.   One
  book I read had suggested camping at Windy Pass.  Where they got the idea
  that this was a possibility is beyond me.  It is called Windy Pass for  a
  reason and I doubt that there are many days per year when the wind  isn\'t
  blowing.  This night it was blowing so hard that I literally had to crawl
  the last bit to avoid being knocked off my feet.  The wind had to  be  in
  excess of 60 mph.


  I was really desperate now.  I had to get out of the  wind.   There  were
  several signs at the pass but I couldn\'t hang around long enough to  read
  them.  I can only assume they were informing me that I was  now  entering
  the restricted zone and that leaving the  trail  and  camping  were  both
  forbidden.  Well I had no choice.  At least  I  only  broke  one  of  the
  rules.  I went down the other side in knee-deep drifted snow  far  enough
  to get out of the worse of the wind and set up my tent  on  a  flat  spot
  next to the trail.  I rationalized I wasn\'t doing any harm as I camped on
  snow.  I gratefully crawled into the shelter of my  tent  at  7:00  (12.5
  miles, 3800 ft, 7:30 hrs) and spent the next 2 hours laboriously  melting
  powder snow for water in a tiny pot.


  The wind soon increased in intensity even  in  my  "sheltered"  spot  and
  raged all night long keeping me awake worrying if  I  would  be  able  to
  continue my trip or even reverse it  and  retreat.   Things  deteriorated
  even more when it began to snow  towards  morning.   Since  I  was  awake
  anyway, I began preparing breakfast at 4:30 AM. At first light I  emerged
  from my tent anticipating the worst and a  hasty  retreat.   Much  to  my
  surprise conditions were not that bad.  Visibility was good (although the
  top of the mountain was in fog), the wind had  lessened  just  enough  to
  allow movement and the snow  flurries  were  minor.   So  6:30  found  me
  continuing on my way, the wind still at my back.


  I was now in the no man\'s land of the blast zone - stark,  desolate,  and
  monochromatic.  Surely nothing could live in this barren  landscape.  Yet
  on closer inspection, here and there  a  lone  seedling  could  be  found
  struggling  to  grow  in  the  lee  of  a  boulder.   And  the  snow  was
  crisscrossed with the tracks of Elk, although I never saw one.  Nature is
  remarkable resilient. Under the conditions I was barely  able  to  follow
  the trail. Every hollow and depression was filled with drifted snow.  But
  exposed areas and ridges were wind blasted free of snow. Whenever  I  was
  uncertain where the trail went I would stop  and  look  in  the  distance
  until I could locate a cairn or section of visible tread.  I  passed  the
  Windy Trail at 6:55 and the Loowit Falls Trail at 7:25 then descended 600
  feet down the poorly marked Sasquatch Steps to the Willow  Springs  Trail
  at 7:45.




  I now began a long mostly flat traverse of the  Pumice  Plains  across  a
  moonscape of utter desolation. There was less snow  down  here  but  that
  didn\'t help much in finding the trail, which was mostly  nonexistent  and
  only marked with small hard to follow cairns.  There was no tread.   Much
  of the way showed new signs of erosion from the recent rains.  I  had  to
  chuckle at the rule of not straying off  the  trail  in  this  restricted
  area.  It was impossible to stay on the  "trail".  As  I  worked  my  way
  around the north side of the mountain I could look directly up  into  the
  breach of the crater, and I felt I was getting more  of  a  sense  of  St
  Helens than I  ever  got  from  just  climbing  to  the  crater  rim.   I
  thoroughly enjoyed this section, which had its own haunting beauty.


  I crossed Studebaker Ridge at 9:30 (5.4 miles, 950 ft, 3 hrs from  camp).
  I was soon out of the worst of the blast zone  and  entered  an  area  of
  growing trees on the west side of the mountain.   More  deep  snow,  more
  ravines to cross, a section of eerie standing dead forest  and  then  the
  1000-foot descent to the South Fork Toutle River.  Here I was  struck  by
  the carpets of brilliant yellow-green moss, in colorful contrast  to  the
  muted colors of the blast zone.  I completely lost the trail in the river
  bottom, so crossed at a likely spot on boulders and headed uphill on  the
  other side until I hit a trail.  It wasn\'t until I had contoured on  this
  trail for over a mile, when I knew I should be climbing steeply,  that  I
  figured out I had gotten on the Toutle Trail instead of the Loowit Trail.
   Darn! I didn\'t even know that trail existed, as it  didn\'t  show  on  my
  Greentrails map.  Not to worry.  I  soon  intersected  the  Sheep  Canyon
  Trail and followed it uphill 1300 feet to  once  again  gain  the  Loowit
  (12.1 miles, 3000 ft, 7 hrs).


  I felt most of my problems were now over.  I was sheltered from the  wind
  on this side, the sun was out and good trail, I thought, should lead  the
  rest of the way.  But the mountain wasn\'t through with  me  yet.  I  soon
  came to a huge ravine.  The original trail had completely washed away and
  to get across I had to descend 300 feet on a detour trail.   Bad  enough.
  But when crossing the bed of the ravine  I  was  confronted  by  a  newly
  formed 10-foot vertical wall.  More evidence of the  recent  flooding.  I
  could have used an ice ax to chop steps up the crumbly rock surface,  but
  I didn\'t have one with me.  So I scratched and clawed my way up the  wall
  and wearily climbed back up the 300 feet to the original trail.


  Good trail through pleasant meadows did lead to the Butte Trail at  3:15.
  There were a few more minor ravines to cross, then the final obstacle  of
  the Swift Creek Lava Flow where wooden poles again marked the  route.   I
  hit the Ptarmigan Trail at 4:45 just as the light was fading and made  it
  to the car without needing a headlamp at 5:30 (19.5 miles,  4000  ft,  11
  hrs).  

Grand total 32 miles, 7800 ft, - Fay Pullen, Kent, 11/6-7.





