Burntboot Pk (USGS Big Snow  Mtn)  -  The  good  news  is  the  Middle  Fork
Snoqualmie River Road is in good shape to  the  Taylor  River  bridge  -  it
appears to have been recently graded.  The bad news is the  road  from  that
point on is as bad as ever and a real pain to drive.  It took me about  1.5
hours to drive this 13 mile section.  A 4X4 is a real asset here.

I followed the route description by Carl Dreisbach in The Middle Fork  Guide
rather than that by Beckey, or at  least  I  tried  to.   Leaving  from  the
parking lot at the end of the road  at  10:20,  I  immediately  crossed  the
Middle Fork River.  This was no problem  this  time  of  year  in  this  dry
summer and I was able to cross  by  rock  hopping.   On  the  other  side  I
climbed  up  a  small  talus  slope  until  it  ended,  then  floundered  in
horrendous brush for an hour trying to traverse left  to  a  shallow  gully.
At times I had no idea where I was going.  Eventually I  reached  the  gully
where the going was tolerable up the rocky bed.  Soon I  was  stopped  by  a
rock step some 50 ft high that I surmounted by  doing  pull-ups  on  hanging
brush to the right.  This first part was the hardest part of the whole  trip
and took close to 2 hours.

Once back in the gully bed above the step, the going, though still  somewhat
brushy, was easier.  The gully slanted left following along  under  a  cliff
to the right.  Near the top of the cliff I was  able  to  enter  forest  and
gradually work my way up gentler terrain to open  heather  slopes  and  then
talus under the north face of  the  peak.  Impressive  views  opened  up  of
Chimney Rock  and  Overcoat.   Following  at  the  base  of  the  cliffs,  I
traversed east to the major gully on the NE side and up its  loose  rock  to
just below the summit ridge.  Here a really nifty ledge led  left  across  a
smooth slab to  the  ridge  just  below  the  summit.   This  ledge,  though
exposed, was a delight to climb.  A short final scramble put me  on  top  at
3:20.

The summit was marked by a large cairn, to which I added a register.   After
a 35-minute rest, I took the short walk to the  west  peak,  then  found  an
easier way down into the gully than the exposed ledge.  Once back  into  the
woods, I wandered around a bit staying on course to the lower gully where  a
rappel was needed to descend the rock step.  I followed the  gully  down  as
far as possible but did no better in avoiding brush  than  on  the  way  up.
There was no help for it and I again spent an hour crashing the awful  stuff
until emerging on the bank of the river at dusk.  

3800  ft,  9:30  hrs,  Fay
Pullen, Kent, 9/4/03.
