     RED MTN, WEST PK (USGS Mt Phelps,  Grotto)  -  The  Money  Cr  Road  is
closed by a big washout  2.5  miles  from  the  bridge  over  Money  Cr.   I
started from here by bike but was only able to get  0.75  mile  farther  before
being  stopped  by  snow.   I  continued  on  skis,   enduring   the   usual
intermittent snow patches of spring melting  patterns,  for  a  mile  or  so
before hitting consistent snow.  I was using skis fitted with Pika  bindings
that allow for the use of climbing boots.   These  bindings  are  heavy  and
clumsy but are adequate for plodding up logging roads.

     The weather was unsettled with off and on  heavy  showers,  so  by  the
time I reached Lake Elizabeth, some 4 miles up the road, I was beginning  to
get wet.   I followed the road a little past the lake to the divide  between
Money Cr and the S Fork Tolt R where I  stashed  the  skis.   The  rain  was
beginning to change to wet snow.  From the divide I  descended  slightly  to
cross a marshy area, then headed straight uphill into  the  woods  following
alongside a gully to a saddle in the ridge  E  of  Crater  Lk.   This  route
seemed preferable to me than contouring around the  ridge  directly  to  the
lake.

     From the saddle it was a long contour between  4000  and  42000  ft  on
steep wooded slopes around the lake basin  until  I  could  begin  ascending
directly toward the West Pk.  Two days earlier I had  tried  this  route  in
similar miserable conditions,  but  due  to  uncertainty  where  I  was  and
wishful thinking (i.e.  lousy  routefinding)  went  up  too  soon  following
inviting terrain and found myself on Pt 5139, actually a  very  nice  little
summit but not where I wanted to be.  Due to time constraints I had to  call
it a day, although it looked as if the ridge could be traversed to the  West
Pk.  So this time I knew to hold to the contour longer, and after  about  an
