            'title' => 'Big Chiwaukum (USGS Chiwaukum Mtn)',
            'tr' => '
Big Chiwaukum (USGS Chiwaukum Mtn) - This was  my  second  attempt  on  this
peak this year.  My first attempt was May 30-June1. On  that  trip  I  tried
first from up the NW ridge but  weird  unconsolidated  snow  that  made  for
insecure stepkicking and icy rock made the upper traverse too hazardous  for
me.  I then descended about 1500 feet  and  traversed  to  try  from  the SW
side.  This time I got to the false summit, but again  snow  conditions  and
ice stopped me. I spent a tense hour  trying  to  traverse  into  the  gully
leading to the summit feeling at any moment the snow might peel away and  me
with it. I finally gave up because even if I made it to the  gully  I  would
never be able to climb the final iced up rock. This dual  sided  attempt  so
wore me out that I spent a second night in camp and my planned two day  trip
turned into a three day one.
 
I didn\'t get to my second try until September. At least I  thought  the  ice
and snow would surely be gone. Yeah, right! Rain and a snow  level  of  6500
ft were predicted for that night, but I felt  I  could  sneak  my  climb  in
before that happened.  As it turned out, I found myself  climbing  the  peak
during the worse possible weather window.
 
I followed the Whitepine Tr, then Wildhorse Tr to  the  large  meadow  below
the W side of the mountain and found a nice campsite  several  hundred  feet
above the trail at 5750 ft. (6.5 miles, 3400 ft and  4  hours  to  here).  I
quickly set up camp then started for the peak at 4:15  pm.  I  could  see  a
storm brewing off in the direction of the Enchantments and heading  my  way.
The weather was coming in sooner than predicted.  Boy, you never  can  trust
those weathermen!  But my peak was still clear so I  continued  on,  gaining
elevation at a good pace aided by my previous experience with the  route.  I
headed up alongside a gully into an  upper  rocky  basin,  trending  to  the
right, to avoid cliffs, as I climbed. Then up a grassy gully onto scree  and
talus slopes, followed by a traverse left just below the S  ridgeline.  This
is where the weather broke  and  it  began  to  thunder  and  hail.  It  was
actually quite beautiful and exciting, but it  was  really  not  good  being
this high in a thunder storm.  However, the thunder seemed  to  stay  mostly
over the Enchantments so I continued on. I traversed under the false  summit
recognizing the high point of my previous attempt.  What had taken  an  hour
then, I easily passed in a few minutes on sandy ledges. Now the  interesting
rockwork began. I entered the gully, climbed to the top  and  exited  at  an
exposed notch onto a ledge which I followed to a  series  of  ramps  to  the
pointed summit arriving at 6:15 (2770 ft and 2 hours).

The weather was now getting positively  awful,  the  hail  changing  to  wet
sticky snow with thickening fog.  I quickly signed the register and  beat  a
hasty retreat. Descending the now snowy rock was a trial and my hands  froze
trying to find holds. Once off the rock, I breathed a sigh  of  relief,  but
with visibility now down to a hundred feet or so I  had  to  stay  alert  to
find the route back down.  Fortunately I had taken the  trouble  to  mark  a
few waypoints with my GPS on the way up, so I didn\'t go  completely  astray.
(The trouble with waypoints is they tell you where you want to  go  but  not
exactly how to get there.) The scree and  talus  now  had  a  layer  of  wet
slippery snow, and  the  descent  was  definitely  of  the  slip  and  slide
variety. Darkness descended upon me before I got completely down. I made  it
to the upper basin O.K., but missed the easy gully to the lower one with  my
camp.  I  got  completely  confused  and   nothing   seemed   familiar   (no
intermediate waypoints here, just one for  camp).   I  ended  up  slithering
down wet mossy rock on a  steep  hillside,  then  blindly  followed  my  GPS
through awful wet brush and several bogs back to my tent at  8:45  (Yes,  it
took me longer to go down than up). If not for my GPS I would have  wandered
around all night looking for my camp.

I awoke the next morning to much improved  weather,  although  my  peak  was
still in the fog and everything was very wet.  Oh  well,  you  can\'t  always
time things just right. Before heading out,  I  decided  to  add  Frosty  Pk
(6489) to my Backcourt checklist. Frosty turned out to  an  easy  hike  from
Frosty Pass (7 miles, 2750 ft, 4:30 hrs RT from camp). I was  back  in  camp
by 1:45 and ready for the trip out by 3:15, reaching the  car  at  6:15.  23
miles and 10,100 ft total for the trip.  Fay Pullen, 9/6-7/02
 
 
 
 

