            'title' => 'Mt Buckner, Mt Booker ( USGS Cascade Pass, Goode Mtn)',
            'tr' => '
Mt Buckner, Mt Booker ( USGS Cascade Pass, Goode Mtn) - I was really  helped
on this one by Stefan Feller\'s  recent  trip  report.  First  it  helped  me
decide to approach  Horseshoe Basin via the lower basin  rather  than  going
over Sahale Arm.  I didn\'t like the  idea  of  descending  such  treacherous
terrain with a full pack alone. Second it caused me to add Mt Booker,  which
sounded interesting, to the itinerary.  I toyed with the idea of also  doing
Horseshoe Pk when I learned it was on the 100  Highest  List,  but  I  would
make that decision when I actually saw the peak.

I started up the Casade Pass trail at 10:00 and reached the pass  at  11:45.
I was minding my  own  business,  resting  and  having  a  snack,  when  the
Ubiquitous Park Ranger descended upon me  demanding  to  know  where  I  was
going.  "Horseshoe Basin", I replied.  "There is  no  camping  in  Horseshoe
Basin," he answered belligerently.  "What!" I said.  "I  have  a  permit  to
camp there." "Impossible," he said. "Let me see your  permit.   Oh  this  is
for the Mt Buckner XC zone." "Does that  not  include  Horseshoe  Basin?"  I
said. "How are you going in?" He said.   "From  lower  Horseshoe  Basin",  I
said. " Past the waterfalls?" he grilled.  "Yes" I replied beginning to  get
rather annoyed. "What is the problem  here?  I  have  my  permit.  I  am  an
experienced climber. Why am  I  getting  the  third  degree?"  (I  was  also
thinking I was climbing mountains before this guy was  born!)  "Most  people
are not able to find the way  from  Lower  to  Upper  Horseshoe  Basin."  He
continued. At this point we were getting an audience  of  other  hikers  and
things were beginning to get embarrassing.  Even the  ranger\'s  partner  was
looking a little red in the face.  Eventually it dawned on  Mr  Ranger  that
he was coming on a bit strong and that maybe I was  a  reasonably  competent
climber despite my diminutive appearance and  there  was  no  call  for  his
attitude. To his credit, as we sorted things out, the ranger  did  apologize
at length, but it did not make the bad feeling go away.  I do  realize  that
rangers have to deal with a lot  of  idiots,  but  this  guy  was  seriously
lacking in people skills and I feel like I was a victim of "profiling" -   a
little old gray-haired lady couldn\'t possibly make it to Horseshoe Basin.

Pondering this unpleasant encounter, I continued down the  other  side  from
Cascade Pass, some 3 very hot miles to a junction with the  Horseshoe  Basin
trail, then 1.5 miles up into the lower basin.  This  route  was  worth  the
extra effort just to see this gorgeous cliff rimmed cirque with  its  dozens
of gushing waterfalls. But getting past the rim to the upper basin would  be
no easy matter. I chose to go up left of  the  Black  Warrior  mine,  as  it
looked shorter and less brushy and because crossing Basin Cr  to  the  right
looked a challenge.  But I did make a mental note of  a  possible  route  to
the right.

A snow slope took me part way up past the mine.  Then slabs,  a  steep  dirt
gully, some thick cedar scrub and finally open easy terrain  brought  me  to
the slopes directly below the route from Sahale Arm.   Looking  up  at  that
route, I was doubly glad I hadn\'t come in that way.   It  looked  wicked.  A
long traverse over talus, crossing myriad creeks, and I  found  a  wonderful
campsite just past the Big Cable on a heathery bench  at  5900  ft  directly
below Mt Buckner (9.5 miles, 4100 ft, 6.5 hrs).  It was  now  4:30.   I  was
too tired and it was too late to try for Booker today, my original plan.  So
I relaxed in my gorgeous surroundings, ate and rehydrated all afternoon  and
turned in early.

The route up Buckner the next morning was  straightforward  and  obvious.  A
short ways up I ran into old tracks in the snow traversing higher  from  the
Sahale Arm route and I followed these the rest of  the  way  to  the  summit
(3200 ft, 3.5 hrs). What glorious views from the top.  It  was  almost  more
than one could absorb. On the way up I was checking out Horseshoe Pk  but  I
had trouble seeing anything that looked as if it had 400 ft  of  prominence.
Because I wasn\'t  quite  sure  which  pinnacle  was  Horseshoe  and  because
everything on Ripsaw Ridge looked wicked, but mostly  just  because  I  just
didn\'t feel in the mood for anything that committing,  I  decided  to  forgo
that peak and try for Booker instead.  Even though it was now  11:00  and  I
knew it would be a very long day, and I would get out after dark, I  thought
I could still do it. Amazing what a good night\'s sleep will do for  you.  So
after descending from Buckner, I started a downward traverse  toward  Booker
at 7200 ft.  Stefan\'s route description  helped  greatly  and  prevented  me
from making the mistake of following Becky.  I crossed the rib at  6600  ft,
followed the gully then snow to the Buckner-Booker saddle,  went  up  to  pt
7840, dropped down the other side, traversed beneath cliffs  until  directly
below the summit, then up a snow finger and class 3 rock. Stefan  was  right
- it is a long way.  I made it to Booker\'s summit at 2:45 and back  to  camp
at 5:15, running into two goats on the way. (5700 ft, 10.5 hrs both  peaks).


I now had to hustle to make it  to  easy  terrain  before  dark.  I  quickly
packed up and was ready to head down at  6:15.  I  didn\'t  relish  the  long
traverse across the upper basin back to my ascent route.   Becky  made  some
vague reference to crossing Basin Cr in  the  lower  basin,  going  E  until
finding the Big Cable and following it to  the  upper  basin.   I  foolishly
thought I could reverse this and follow the  cable  downhill.   You\'d  think
that by now I would know better than to rely on Becky\'s vague directions.

 I was able to follow the cable  downhill  several  hundred  feet  until  it
disappeared over the rocky rim right  next  to  a  roaring  waterfall.   Too
scary for me.  On to Plan B.  My memory of looking up to the E of the  Black
Warrior Mine assured me there was a feasible  route  here,  so  I  headed  E
along the rim, passing the remains of two log  structures  and  more  mining
debris.  Then I slithered down awful thick scrub cedar until  I  could  work
my way over to the easier terrain I had seen from  below.   I  actually  ran
into a few bits of scattered flagging and even what looked  like  occasional
tread of an old trail, but for the most part a well used route  was  not  to
be found. I don\'t think many people approach Upper Horseshoe Basin from  the
lower one.  Most must go over Sahale Arm. Anyway, I found a  reasonable  way
down.  All that remained was to find a way across Basin  Creek,  no  trivial
matter. The area below the mine was  a  massive  snow  avalanche  deposition
zone. The snow was probably 20-30 deep, with huge moats and scary  crevasses
and gushing water underneath.  I was lucky to  find  a  collapsed  ice  wall
that offered a mostly safe passage across the  snow  to  the  trail  on  the
other side.

It was now 7:45.  All that remained was to follow the trail out.  I  dragged
my tired body up the 1800 ft to Cascade Pass  before  needing  my  headlamp,
then down the other side staggering into the TH at midnight.  No  Ubiquitous
Ranger at this hour.  Even he must sleep. 28 miles and 11,700 ft  gain.  Fay
Pullen 7/22-23/2003.
