            'title' => 'Robinson Mtn (USGS Robinson Mtn)',
            'tr' => '
Robinson Mtn (USGS Robinson Mtn) - For our annual overnight  trip  together,
this year my son wanted to go to the  Pasayten  Wilderness,  an  area  where
neither of us had previously  been.  Given  that,  I  chose  Robinson  as  a
desirable objective. We started up the Robinson Pass trail  (elev  2600)  at
2:45, pretty good for my son considering the long drive. The  day  was  warm
and sunny and the trail dusty from much horse traffic. Just past Beauty  Cr,
we picked up the unmarked trail  that  climbed  alongside  the  creek.  This
rough trail was easy to follow, helped by signs of recent horse  traffic.  I
didn\'t know you could get horses up such steep trails. But they  had  really
chewed up  the steeper sections.

 As we rounded the hillside into the upper valley, we  heard  several  rifle
shots. So much for solitude. After crossing many rockslides,  then  a  small
creek, we broke out into open meadow  (2600  ft,  4  hrs).  Sitting  in  the
meadow,  glassing  the  opposite  hillside  were  two  hunters.   They  were
friendly enough but they were occupying the  campsite  (elev  5200)  we  had
hoped to use. This is when we learned that the high hunt started  on  Sunday
(this was Friday). They had been brought in  by  packers  (hence  the  horse
traffic) and were staying the entire 10 days of the hunt.  I  guess  serious
hunters stake out their territory early. The rifle shots heard  earlier  was
one of them shooting at a bear who caught them offguard.  (Bear  season  was
already open.) Happily they missed.  We  had  a  nice  chat  and  they  even
offered to share their campsite  with  us,  but  we  declined.  They  seemed
genuinely concerned that we wouldn\'t be able to find a place to camp  as  it
was now getting late (6:45). I pointed out that there was  a  good  site  at
the tarn  at the base of Robinson if we had time to get to it, or  at  least
in the woods below. They replied they had  tramped  all  over  the  hillside
above and there was no tarn up there or even any  level  spots.   We  parted
with them shaking their heads with disbelief at those crazy climbers and  us
wondering why hunters can\'t read maps, or if they even have them.

We headed up the  initially  steep  meadow,  climbing  alongside  the  small
creek.  I didn\'t want to get far from that creek as finding water  could  be
a problem this time of year. The map indicated a  flattening  of  the  slope
and a possible place to camp at 6000 ft and  sure  enough  in  fading  light
(7:30) we came upon a wonderful spot, complete with  an  old  fire  ring,  a
level, rockless tent site and a great view out over Beauty Cr  valley  (4.5
miles, 3400 ft and 4 3/4 hrs). The creek was still nearby for water. I  made
dinner that balmy night by the light of a gorgeous moon and stars.

We started for Robinson the next day at  8:30  reaching  the  lovely  little
tarn at 9:00.  Looking at the rocky shoreline we were happy  we  had  camped
where we did.  From the tarn we climbed  to a  small  moraine  ridge  above,
then up talus and loose scree into a gully on the left. The  upper  part  of
the gully was very loose and unpleasant and we had  to  be  careful  not  to
knock rocks down on each other. The top of the gully  (elev  7400  ft)  gave
access to the long SE ridge of  Robinson.  It  was  now  a  matter  of  just
following this ridge N and W , first  on  the  crest,  then  sidehilling  on
scree past several bumps.  Climber and goat trails would come and  go.  Just
before the last false summit, some real  scrambling  began,  first  a  short
section down and around a rib into a gully.  Then up the gully to the  notch
above and a short exposed but easy scramble on the narrow ridge to a  survey
marker. The last bit was a simple walk on  talus  to  the  summit  at  12:30
(2700 ft and 4 hrs).

The views were lovely, but I had difficulty recognizing anything.  This  was
all virgin territory for me.  Great  possibilities  for  future  trips.   We
spent a pleasant, warm and mostly windless hour on the  summit.   I  left  a
large register before leaving.  I was surprised there was none there.

We left the ridge earlier than on the way up to avoid the awful  gully,  but
I don\'t think we gained much, descending steep loose  scree  slopes  farther
upvalley. Nearing the tarn we were surprised to be  greeted  by  a  friendly
black lab and her owner, a lone woman from Winthrop. She was camped  at  the
tarn and planned on climbing Robinson tomorrow with a friend who was  coming
up for the day (he didn\'t like to camp).  She had been  up  Robinson  before
so knew what to expect.  Her dog was a good scrambler.  She too had met  the
hunters below who once again insisted there was no tarn up here.  We  had  a
good chuckle over that.

We got back to the tent at 4:00 and left at 5:30.  We ran into  the  hunters
again on the trip out. They had been worried about us but  we  assured  them
we had found a comfortable campsite.  Then they asked if we were  going  out
that night, commenting that it was already 6:00. Certainly, I replied.   All
we had to do was get to the  main  trail  and  walk  out  by  headlamp.   No
problem.  Climbers do it all the time. Again we  parted  with  them  shaking
their heads at those crazy climbers.

We hit the Robinson creek trail at dusk (7:30) and walked the  rest  of  the
way out by headlamp.  There was one  unanticipated  problem  though.   There
had been even further horse traffic since yesterday, and the trail  was  now
ankle deep in dust.  We had to walk several  hundred  feet  apart  to  avoid
kicking up dust for each  other  and  even  then,  the  dust  we  kicked  up
ourselves was at times so thick  visibility  was  clouded  by  headlamp  and
breathing difficult.  But we survived  and  reached  the  TH  at  9:00.  The
parking lot was absolutely jammed with horse trailers!  14  miles  and  6200
ft. Fay Pullen 9/13-14/02.

