            'title' => 'Sawtooth Ridge (USGS Oval Pk, Hoodoo Pk, Prince Cr, Martin Pk)',
            'tr' => '
   Sawtooth Ridge (USGS Oval Pk, Hoodoo Pk,  Prince  Cr,  Martin  Pk)  -  I
   really wanted to do this trip as outlined in 75 Scrambles, climbing  all
   eight summits mentioned, but that had one going  in  the  West  Fork  of
   Buttermilk Cr Tr and out the Crater Cr Tr.  These TH\'s are  miles  apart
   and not feasible as a car shuttle for me alone. But careful  examination
   of the maps showed the East Fork Buttermilk Cr  TH  separated  from  the
   West Fork TH by only a couple of miles and a 1200 ft  ridge  that  could
   probably be linked by a crosscountry hike. If I  went  out  this  way  I
   would still be able to climb all the peaks on the ridge.


   Day 1 - With this plan in mind I started up the West Fork Tr at 10:30 on
   a sunny but cool morning.  There were two large horse  trailers  in  the
   parking lot and evidence on the trail of recent horse  traffic.  I  just
   hoped this horse party wasn\'t camped at Star Lake,  my  destination  for
   the day. About eight miles in and  a  mile  before  Fish  Cr  Pass,  the
   terrain opened up with gorgeous golden alpine larches everywhere and the
   sheer N cliffs of Star Pk looming above to the left. From Fish Cr Pass I
   descended a short distance to lovely Star  Lake  and  found  a  pleasant
   campsite nestled amongst the rocks at the N end (9 miles, 3600 ft and 4.5
   hrs). Much to my happiness, I was all alone at the lake.


   After setting up camp, I set off to climb Star Pk at 3:40. I  worked  my
   way up through larch groves S of the lake, then meadow and talus to pick
   up a way trail leading to the SW ridge  above.  It  was  then  a  simple
   matter to follow the ridge, or to the right of it, on talus all the  way
   to the easy summit. I was back in camp by 6:00, much sooner than  I  had
   expected (RT 1550 ft and 2:20 hr). I ate  dinner  watching  a  beautiful
   sunset (caused by approaching weather and clouds) reflected in the lake.
   That night was quite windy but warm.


   Day 2 - I began this day at 7:00 by climbing back up  to  Fish  Cr  Pass
   where I was treated to stunning views of miles of golden alpine  larches
   glowing in the early morning sun. The threatened storm of  the  previous
   night had fizzled out. From the pass I followed the easy ridge NW to the
   summit of Courtney Pk (8392) (1235 ft and 1 hr).  The  route  from  here
   followed the long curving ridge all the way to Oval Pk.


   From Courtney, I descended talus NE down to the saddle at 7680  ft  then
   back up to the summit of Buttermilk Ridge (8267) (1840 ft  and  2:15  hr
   cumulative), enjoying the view down to Oval Lakes on the way. Down again
   to 7700 ft then following the ridge to Pt 7978.  Here  I  descended  the
   cliffy NW side with some steep downclimbing, then traversed directly  to
   the Oval Pk saddle  at  7580,  rather  than  lose  excess  elevation  by
   descending the NE side as described in  75  Scrambles.   Rather  tedious
   talus led up to Oval Pk at 12:00 (3300 ft and 4:50).


   From Oval\'s summit I started back by going straight down more  talus  SE
   to the basin below, heading for a large tarn at 6936 ft. I  was  getting
   mighty tired of talus hopping. Once in the  basin,  I  wandered  through
   meadows and larch groves until I came out at the tarn.  Here I picked up
   an abandoned trail on  the  S  shore.   This  trail  was  fairly  easily
   followed back to the main trail about 1 mile below Fish Cr  Pass.   Just
   before hitting the main trail I  startled  a  magnificent  big  buck.  I
   wished him luck in the coming hunting season. On the climb  back  up  to
   the pass I met the horse party belonging  to  the  trailers  at  the  TH
   heading out.  We had a nice chat.  They  had  camped  much  farther  in.
   There were about 8 horses total, half of which were  pack  animals.   As
   they passed loaded with everything but the kitchen sink (and maybe  even
   that - I did spot a large wood stove tied to one packhorse), I reflected
   on our very different styles of camping. But here I am probably  in  the
   minority. This is definitely horse country.


   I was back in camp by 3:00 (8 miles, 4550 ft and  8  hr  total).  I  had
   originally planned to move camp this day a little farther down the trail
   toward my next destination, Boiling Lake, but I soon  gave  up  on  that
   idea. It had taken longer to climb to Oval and back than I  had  planned
   (too much tedious and slow talus).  My  camp  was  so  pleasant,  I  was
   rather tired and the thought of moving camp just didn\'t  appeal.   So  I
   lounged around the rest of the afternoon, painting, washing  up  by  the
   lake and enjoying the larches on the opposite shore backlit by the  late
   afternoon sun.  Magic! This night was calm and cold.


   Day 3 - I had much to do this day if I was to complete all my summits in
   my allotted four days, so I broke camp and was ready to go by 7:20.  The
   trail was very faint in the meadow below the lake but I had  checked  it
   out the evening before so knew where to go. It essentially went straight
   downhill through the center of the meadow following Fish  Cr,  until  it
   entered some trees below and became easy to follow again.  I  picked  up
   the Summit Trail (#1259) in another meadow  farther  down  and  followed
   this trail through some lovely open terrain, then forest,  up  and  down
   over two passes to a junction with the 1  mile  spur  trail  to  Boiling
   Lake.  I  was  now  out  of  the  Chelan-Sawtooth  Wilderness  and  into
   motorcycle country and the trails showed it, being built for  wheels.  I
   hit Boiling Lake at 1:20 and set up camp for my third  night  on  the  E
   side near a small creek (11 miles, 2560 ft and 6 hr). I had seen no  one
   all day and again I had the lake all to myself.


   I left to climb my next 3 summits at 2:00 hopeful but doubting  I  would
   be back before dark. From the lake I followed a good horse trail S up  a
   draw to a 7440 ft saddle, dropped a bit  on  the  other  side  to  avoid
   cliffs, then climbed up again to the S  ridge  of  Cheops  (8270).  This
   ridge was then followed N on tedious talus, first to the  left  then  to
   the right of the crest. The summit ridge of Cheops is quite  ragged  and
   not sure which of the points  was  the  highest,  I  ended  up  climbing
   several pinnacles.  My conclusion was the S point was the highest  (1500
   ft and 1:30 hr).


   I retraced my route back to the Cheops-Martin saddle, then  continued  S
   along the ridge toward Martin.  Where the ridge steepened,  I  traversed
   on the right flank then worked my way up to the summit (2200 ft and 2:40
   hr). Martin turned out to be a decent scramble on fun rock. There was  a
   large cairn on top and a register placed in 1994 by  Mike  Torok.   This
   was the first register I had found on any of the summits. (I  placed  my
   own registers on some of the other summits until I ran out.)


   Next on the agenda was Cooney (8321), also called Switchback  by  Becky.
   It looked a long ways off, and as it was now getting late I was  worried
   that I didn\'t have enough daylight left to make that summit,  especially
   if I had much slowing talus to cross.  But of course I continued on.  As
   it turned out the traverse to Cooney was quite pleasant and easier  than
   anticipated, and I greatly  enjoyed  the  terrain  above  the  beautiful
   Cooney Lake basin. The summit of Cooney had a huge cairn, behind which I
   took refuge from a now biting wind, but no register (2700  ft  and  3:40
   hr).  Now all I had to do was get back to camp.


   Impatience lured me directly down the W side of Cooney in  search  of  a
   "shortcut" rather than pick up  the  Foggy  Dew  Tr  (#417)  to  the  S.
   Probably not the best idea as I ran into  cruddy  scree  and  unpleasant
   gullies.  But I did make it down and hit the Summit Trail in  the  broad
   saddle SE of Pt 7228 at 6:20 in fading light some 3 miles from camp.  It
   was then an easy matter to follow this freeway of a motorcycle  trail  N
   back to the Boiling Lake Tr and then my tent, the last bit  by  headlamp
   (6 miles, 3250 ft and 5:50 hrs).  I was so tired that I crawled into  my
   sleeping bag right away and made a simple dinner lying down.
   Day 4 - This was by far the coldest night.  Everything  froze  hard  and
   there was a heavy layer of frost on my tent, which didn\'t help an  early
   start for my last summit and the trip out. But I did manage to get going
   by 8:30. I found another horse  trail  (they  were  everywhere)  leading
   directly from the lake toward Hoodoo Pass. Below the pass  at  a  likely
   looking spot I dropped my overnight pack for the dash up Bigelow  Pk  on
   the SW slope, a simple climb (1680 ft and  1:50  hr  from  Boiling  Lk).
   Bigelow had another register left by Mike  Torok.  Before  descending  I
   wandered over to an interesting rocky point on the ridge to the S with a
   fun little scramble.


   I took a long lunch at Hoodoo Pass and scoped out Hoodoo  Pk  and  Raven
   Ridge for a future outing, before beginning the 6.5 mile descent  of  the
   mostly uninteresting East Fork Buttermilk Tr.  Shortly below the pass  I
   met a couple coming up, my first  people  since  the  horse  party.   We
   chatted. I told them I had to get back to the West  Fork  Buttermilk  TH
   where my car was.  They kindly offered to drive me around, but  as  they
   were still on their way up, the timing wasn\'t quite right.   However,  I
   told them that if I was still at their TH when they  came  out  I  would
   gladly take them up on their offer.  But of course I wasn\'t.


   I hit the TH at 2:45.  From here I walked up the road over a mile toward
   Buttermilk Butte until I hit the ridge, then plunged downhill  for  1200
   ft on the other side.  At first I was able to follow  a  well  used  cow
   trail and I thought my descent would be easy.  But soon  the  cow  trail
   ended at a muddy spring.  Then I was on my own as I wandered down  awful
   forest so littered with deadfall and booby traps progress  slowed  to  a
   crawl. No wonder forest fires are so bad around here.  This forest was a
   tinderbox waiting to explode with so much dry fuel  on  the  ground.  It
   also wasn\'t that obvious which way to go, what with various ravines  and
   subridges to cross.  But eventually, with the help of my GPS, I hit  the
   West Fork Tr very close to the TH and the car at 4:30 (12.5  miles,  2480
   ft and 8 hr from Boiling Lk).


   I did find the miles of talus hopping this time of year tedious but  the
   beautiful golden alpine larches more  than  made  up  for  that.   I  do
   believe this is the best area I have ever been to for fall larch  color.
   Grand total for the trip 48.5 miles and 18,000 ft gain. Fay Pullen, 10/6-
   9/02










