improved a bit, but not greatly, and I struggled on heading blindly
uphill in a generally SE direction. Somewhere in this mess I happened
upon a lone flag tied to a tree.  Were they as lost as I was?

Eventually I reached the crest of Terrace\'s N ridge, but
disappointingly, travel did not improve.  I was getting positively
discouraged that I would ever make my destination at this rate with so
few daylight hours. Still, I carried on, until to my absolute delight
I stumbled upon a way trail (at 4800 ft) a short ways higher right on
the crest. This was a puzzle to me where it came from or where it was
to go.  Someone had obviously done a lot of work clipping brush to
make the way passable.  Although very steep and rough it was
infinitely better than crashing the brush and my spirits immediately
improved.

Following this way trail, I began to make much better time, soon
emerging  into the open at a flat area of the ridge (5300 ft) covered
with sparse crusty snow. Here I got my first view of Terrace. At the
far end of the flat I passed a messy campsite, then veered right with
the ridge. The way trail continued up, then contoured the grassy
hillside. Eventually it seemed to lead downhill, so I gave up
following it and headed back to the crest of the ridge. Perhaps the
trail went to Lake Clarice.

I continued up and down along the ever more inviting ridge, going over
Pt 5789 where the terrain became rocky and alpine. At about 5800 ft I
reached the final rise of the mountain.  This began as a narrow rocky
ridge that I attacked head on, for the most part class 2 scrambling.
Then I traversed a bit left onto broader slopes.  There was not much
snow but what there was very hard and icy. If there had been more I
would have sorely needed crampons.  As it was I was able to avoid most
of it and continued steeply back up to the crest.  At the false summit
(there is always a false summit) a notch and an interesting slot gully
barred the way. A 10 foot class 3 step down, then the final summit
