            'tr' => '

Reynolds Peak (8512 ft) & Rennie Peak (7742 ft), May 13-14, 2004


Starting up the Reynolds Cr trail off the Twisp River road, I ran  into  the
first snow at 4400 ft after about 2 miles. As the snow  depth  increased  so
did my frustration level as I alternately stayed on top and  postholed  knee
deep or deeper, never knowing which would occur when. At 5100 ft I  found  a
snow free spot in the woods to camp (4 miles, 2000 ft, 2:15 hr).

30 minutes later I was on my way to climb Rennie Pk.  The  frustrating  snow
continued to slow my progress.  I was able to stay on the trail  until  5600
ft. Open snow slopes and a short steep wooded rib led to the basin  east  of
the peak. Here conditions improved as the snow became firmer and  I  quickly
climbed to the final talus slopes leading to the summit (2650  ft,  2:30  hr
from camp).

There was a cairn but no register so I left one.  It  was  now  7:30  and  I
could see weather approaching from the Twisp River valley.  I knew  I  would
have to hurry to make it back to camp before dark to  be  able  to  find  my
tent in the featureless forest. Snow snifters soon changed  to  steady  snow
that began sticking on the rocks and ground.  I  did  make  it  down  before
dark, dragging into my tent at 8:55 where the snow had turned  to  rain.   I
made dinner and went to sleep in my toasty dry sleeping bag to the sound  of
several hours of light rain.

The next morning dawned clear and sunny. I started at 7:00 for  Reynolds.  I
began by traversing south through awful snowy woods where every  other  step
I sank in hip deep. This mostly level traverse of less than Â½ mile  took  40
minutes.  Not a great  start.  After  crossing  Reynolds  Cr  on  a  log,  I
traversed a slide path and began climbing steeply up the left  side  past  a
waterfall until the slope lessened with a series of lovely snow basins  that
led to the trough between the main and north peak of Reynolds. As lovely  as
this alpine area was, I couldn\'t appreciate  it  fully  as  the  frustrating
snow conditions still persisted. My pace slowed to  a  crawl,  I  seemed  to
lose energy and visions of a summit by 11:00 vanished.

As I slowly made progress upwards I examined the cliffs to  my  left  for  a
route onto Reynolds NE ridge.  I saw a  couple  of  possibilities  but  most
ended in overhanging cornices and I wasn\'t even sure the NE ridge  could  be
followed to the summit.  So I stayed in the trough  heading  for  the  route
from the E described in Becky which I knew culminated in a class 3-4  gully.
I could see the beginning of this gully in the distance  but  couldn\'t  tell
yet if it led easily to the summit.

I reached the base of the gully (8000 ft) at 10:40 and had my answer, or  so
I thought. Continuous snow led straight up seemingly  all  the  way  to  the
ridge.  Only 500 ft to go.  Piece of cake. Two hours later I  was  still  at
it. First, the snow in the gully suddenly turned icy, so I put on  crampons.
Second, the gully was deceptively steep, steeper than it had appeared to  me
from below.  Even with an ice axe in one hand and a  ski  pole  axe  in  the
other I felt decidedly insecure. I\'m not sure what the angle was  but  since
I kept bumping my knees that usually means 50 degrees or so. And third,  the
upper part of the gully steepened even more and ended  in  a  cornice.   The
bottom line was I was not a happy climber and by  the  time  I  figured  all
this out, several hundred feet up, it was too late to retreat gracefully.  I
was  getting  decidedly  freaked  out.  Considering  my   options,   neither
continuing up nor going back down the gully appealed.  I did have a rope  in
my pack but it did little good, as there was no way to get to it.  The  only
option that had any promise at all was to traverse to the right onto  broken
rock.  This I did and, after teetering on a ledge  to  remove  my  crampons,
was able to work my way out of  the  gully  and  onto  a  very  steep  upper
snowslope. The snow here was soft and unconsolidated  and  didn\'t  make  for
very secure stepkicking.  It was also punctuated here and  there  with  rock
and the resulting holes that often form next to such features.  I  ended  up
laboriously manufacturing holds by excavating the snow  from  the  rock  and
packing it down securely. After a hundred feet  or  so  of  this  I  reached
secure ground a few feet from the  summit  and  collapsed  with  a  sigh  of
relief (3500, 5:45 hrs.).

There was a large cairn on top and a  register  placed  by  the  Boealps  in
1985.  However, the  booklet  was  full  so  I  added  another  one  to  the
container. I spent a short Â½ hour on the summit, worrying how to  get  down.
No way was I going down the way I had come up.  I  briefly  toyed  with  the
idea of rappelling down the NW ridge.  It didn\'t look  that  long,  was  all
rock and I would probably be able to find anchors, but in the end I  decided
not to chance it. The SE face was melted out and  appeared  to  be  an  easy
scramble. If I could then traverse N beneath the summit pyramid  to  the  NE
ridge, there was a good chance I could find a way off  that  ridge  back  to
the snow trough of my ascent. I just didn\'t  know  if  I  could  follow  the
ridge far enough to be able to do that.  It looked pretty rocky. But it  all
worked out.  I was able to follow the ridge, with minor scrambling here  and
there and by staying high to bypass several deep gullies, although I had  to
go all the way to the saddle below Pt 7038 before I could  exit  the  ridge.
Soon I was on my uphill tracks and  back  at  camp  at  3:45  exhausted  and
soaked from sinking in knee deep on every step. After a  mandatory  hour  to
rest and rehydrate, I was on my way out, reaching the car at 6:30  happy  to
have survived my little adventure.

Grand total 17 miles, 8455 ft.

Fay Pullen



