Horse Lake Mtn (4640 ft), Jack Ridge (7828 ft) & Axis Pk (7550 ft) - May 19-
20, 2004

I had business in East Wenatchee at 6:30 PM on May 19 - a public hearing  of
the Douglas County Regional Planning Commission (Douglas County is where  my
cabin is located).  Not wanting to "waste" a trip to the area, I decided  to
combine business with pleasure. But what to  do,  especially  with  such  an
awkwardly timed meeting?

My plan was to first climb Horse Lake Mtn.  This low  Back  Court  Peak  had
never seemed worth the effort of a drive all the way to  Wenatchee.  But  it
seemed perfect for a little trip to complete before my meeting. I  drove  up
Number Two Canyon Road to the gated road, and started on  my  mountain  bike
at 1:40 PM. The trip actually turned out to be a  little  gem.  The  terrain
was  surprisingly  interesting,  but  most  noteworthy  was  the  absolutely
gorgeous display of wildflowers  -  vast  fields  of  solid  gold  arrowleaf
balsamroot and purple lupine.  I  have  never  seen  better.  They  were  so
beautiful I  kept  getting  distracted  and  had  trouble  concentrating  on
keeping my bike on track, especially on the fast ride back down.  I  reached
the cute little summit at 3:00 amongst gathering  thunderclouds  then  raced
back to the car just beating the rain (1800 ft, 2:45 hr).

My meeting was over at 7:30, which gave me time to drive  to  the  Eightmile
Lake TH and start up the trail at 9:00 by headlamp.  The  rain  had  stopped
but all was wet and fresh. I set up camp at the first campsite  I  found  at
the lake at 11:00. (3.3 miles, 1400 ft, 2 hrs)  I had  eaten  dinner  before
leaving, but I did have a snack, although I fell asleep  while  waiting  for
my cup of herbal tea to brew.

I was on my way the next morning at 6:45 heading for Jack  Ridge.   I  don\'t
have much to add to Jim Brisbine\'s recent report of  the  same  peak,  as  I
essentially went the same way, and I was on top  at  11:10  (3165  ft,  4:25
hr). I spent a glorious hour on the summit basking in the sun and  sketching
Mt Stuart.  I also scoped out Axis Pk.  I had no information as  to  how  to
climb it, but from what I could see from Jack and by looking at  the  map  a
reasonable route appeared from the snow basin west of  the  peak.  The  hard
part would be finding the base of  this  route  once  in  the  Eightmile  Cr
valley and getting across the roaring creek.  Also,  I  wasn\'t  sure  I  had
enough energy left for another climb and  thunderclouds  were  forming  over
the Enchantments and heading my way.  I would see how I  felt  and  how  the
weather held once I was back in the valley.

Both the weather and my energy level held.  I found an easy log crossing  of
the creek  and  traversed  upward  without  too  much  difficulty  onto  the
pleasant snowslopes of the  drainage  west  of  the  peak.  Where  the  main
drainage kept straight ahead, I climbed steeply left into a  hanging  basin.
From here a continuous steepening snowslope led upward to  emerge  onto  the
west ridge just shy of Pt 7397. Melted out sandy shelves  and  boulders  led
past several annoying false summits on the ridge until  finally  culminating
in the highest point, which I reached at 4:10 (5785 ft 9:28 hrs).   I  added
a register to the small cairn that  overlooked  Eightmile  Lake.   The  lake
looked so close below me. Alas, I would have to retrace my roundabout  route
back to it.

Descending down the west drainage, near the bottom I began  traversing  east
toward the lake but ran into unexpected cliffy and rugged  terrain  and  had
to wander around a bit before hitting the  flat  of  the  valley.   Again  I
found an easy log crossing of the creek.   Downed  trees  are  plentiful  in
this valley. I was back in camp at  6:30.  The  sun  was  shining,  my  camp
pleasant and I had the whole lake to myself. I  would  have  loved  to  have
spent another night, but family obligations required my  presence  the  next
morning. So after a rest and snack, I gathered my weary bones  together  and
headed out at 7:50 PM arriving at the car at 9:15 with enough light  to  get
by without a headlamp. Total 18 miles & 7350 ft.

Two incidents occurred on the way home, both  on  highway  97  over  Blewett
Pass. First I almost hit a deer. I mean I came within 2 feet of hitting  it.
 Thank heavens for ABS. Then a short time later I had a blowout and  had  to
change the tire by the side of  the  road  in  the  dark.   I  had  to  take
everything out of the back of my  Cherokee  (remember,  besides  my  camping
gear I also had a mountain bike) to get at the tire and  boy  are  those  16
in. tires heavy.  I could barely lift it. At least it wasn\'t raining. I  was
very happy to finally make it home at 12:30 AM.

Fay Pullen






