            'tr' => '

Mountaineer Peak (6935), May 27-28, 2004


The weather forecast was not good,  not  even  for  the  east  side,  but  I
figured I would still have better luck over there.  I  hoped  to  climb  the
high point of Mountaineer Ridge above Lake Stuart.  If things were  too  bad
to allow that at least I would have a nice hike to the  lake,  where  I  had
never been. I went expecting and prepared for rain.

In no hurry, as it was an easy 4.5 miles to  the  lake  on  good  trail,  and
perhaps hoping for improvement in the weather,  I  didn\'t  leave  town  till
2:00 pm and started on the trail to Lake Stuart at 5:20. It  rained  lightly
the whole way in, but I stayed mostly dry by using an  umbrella.  The  trail
was very pleasant hiking and snowfree until very  near  the  lake,  which  I
reached at 8:00 (4.5 miles, 1600  ft,  2:40  hrs).  I  found  a  lovely  bare
campsite right on the lake with a good view of  the  twin  gullies,  to  the
left and to the right of  the  summit,  leading  to  the  top  of  my  peak.
According to John Roper, the right one was easier.  I  fell  asleep  to  the
sound of wind waves lapping on the shore of the lake. The rain had ended.

On my way the next morning at 7:30, I followed  a  rough  trail  around  the
lake, then entered snowy woods and crossed the lake\'s inlet creek.  The  day
began with promise  -  partly  cloudy  skies  and  even  a  few  minutes  of
sunlight.  But that was  short  lived  as  the  clouds  gathered  themselves
together and by the time  I  reached  the  large  open  slopes  beneath  the
gullies it was snowing steadily and beginning to  accumulate.   Off  and  on
snow showers, with moderate clearing in between continued for  the  rest  of
the climb.

Despite the 1-2 inches of fresh topping, the underlying snow  was  hard  and
before entering the right gully I donned  crampons.  The  gully  appeared  a
straight shot up, but, as gullies usually do, steepened near  the  top,  and
after about 900 ft I opted for an exit right. Another  couple  hundred  feet
of steep snow brought me to the summit rocks. I  stashed  crampons  and  ice
axe, and scrambled up snow-covered rocks casting around for the  summit.   A
fearsome looked pinnacle loomed left and appeared the highest point.   Lucky
for me it was not, and, circumventing it, I continued left along  the  rocky
ridge to the cairned high point (1800 ft, 3 hrs). A film can  register  held
the familiar names of John Roper and Jim Brisbine.

Visibility was good enough to peer over the edge down  to  Lake  Stuart  and
across to Axis, where I had recently been.   But  the  top  portion  of  the
frightful north face  of  Stuart  was  buried  in  the  clouds.  I  gingerly
downclimbed the slippery rocks to my stash then began  the  tedious  process
of backing down my steps until the steepness of the snow relented. Slow  but
safe. I was back to my tent at 12:45 where I enjoyed a  2.5  hr  rest  before
heading out  at  3:20.  I  even  stopped  to  do  some  sketching  during  a
particularly inviting sunny period.  It had stopped precipitating,  but  the
clouds still came and went.  Once past the Colchuck Lake  turnoff,  I  began
meeting parties coming in getting a head start on the Memorial Day  weekend.
Some of them  looked  to  have  serious  plans  in  mind.   With  the  still
unsettled weather, I wished them luck. Back to  the  car  at  5:45,  a  most
leisurely and pleasant trip, despite the weather.  12 miles, 3400 feet.

Fay Pullen



