            'tr' => '

Martin Peak (8511) and Bonanza Peak Attempt (9511)      June 2-4, 2004


Up to now I have avoided trying Bonanza Peak because of the hassles (not  to
mention expense) of catching the Lake Chelan ferry to Lucerne and  then  the
bus up to Holden. I hate being dependent on ferry and  bus  schedules.   But
after searching for any possible alternative, I  finally  decided  this  was
still the fastest and easiest way to approach the peak.

So Wednesday found Linda and me leaving town at 6:00am  to  catch  the  9:45
Lady II at Field\'s Point. Cost was $12 to park the car for  two  nights  and
$28 RT each to Lucerne.  A $3 surcharge had been  recently  added  to  cover
the high cost of fuel. The boat landed in Lucerne at 11:30 where  we  and  a
dozen paying guests piled onto the school bus for the 12 mile, 2000 ft  ride
up to Holden.  We arrived in Holden at 12:15 but were held  captive  in  the
bus for another  15  minutes  while  the  guests  went  through  an  initial
orientation to the rules and  regulations  of  the  village.  We  then  made
reservations for the bus trip  out  on  Saturday  ($10  RT  each)  and  were
finally on our way up the Hart Lake trail at 1:00.

A mile on old road and another Â½ mile on trail  brought  us  to  the  Holden
Lake junction and we slowly began the hot climb  up  to  the  lake  sweating
under packs heavy with climbing gear. The trail was well maintained with  an
easy grade and snow free until we entered the lake basin where we  lost  the
trail.  Emerging on the shore of the lake at 4:45 (5.5 miles, 2000  ft,  3:45
hrs) we were startled to see a bear feeding  in  the  meadow  a  short  ways
away. He seemed unconcerned  and  completely  ignored  us  as  we  did  him,
although it did increase our resolve to hang our food high.

We spent the  next  hour  searching  for  a  snowfree  campsite;  eventually
finding a lovely spot nestled at the boundary between boulders and trees  on
the north side of the lake. Our campsite had a stellar view of the route  up
Bonanza and what I saw made my heart sink.  The  whole  face  was  plastered
with fresh snow from the previous two weeks of storms.  I  had  a  very  bad
feeling about the whole thing. Then while eating dinner  we  saw  a  strange
shining light appear in the sky and slowly set over  the  NE  ridge  of  the
mountain. Neither Linda nor I had ever seen anything like it.  Was it a  UFO
or our guardian angel trying to tell us something?  In retrospect I am  sure
it was the later. A further warning came during the night in the form  of  a
large avalanche roaring somewhere down the face. But being  single  focused,
as climbers frequently are, we awoke the next morning still planning  to  at
least go up and check things out.

We began at 8:00 on Thursday climbing toward Holden Pass. A late  start  you
may say for such a major peak, but we felt no  hurry  with  such  long  days
this time of year.  Good thing we were late. Below  Holden  Pass  we  turned
left to climb steeply through a cliff  band  unto  the  upper  snow  slopes.
Passing another smaller band with slabs beginning to melt out we worked  our
way toward the glacier. The day was  warm  and  sunny,  the  snow  soft  and
slushy.  It was beginning to be an effort breaking trail. At 11:00 and  7500
ft we stopped to rest and rope up to cross the glacier. All of a  sudden  an
avalanche let loose from the upper slopes of  Bonanza  and  swept  down  the
snow finger and onto the glacier, right over the route we would  have  taken
up. If we had left an hour earlier we would have been  right  in  its  path.
Linda and I looked at each other. No words were even necessary.  We  may  be
slow learners but we  weren\'t  completely  stupid.  Then  to  emphasize  the
situation, two more good sized slides let loose in  the  next  few  minutes.
But we needed no more  convincing.  Before  heading  down,  I  measured  the
amount of new snow over the old crust.  It was over 2 feet deep.

My original plan had been to climb Bonanza today (Thursday) and  Martin  the
next day (Friday) and hike out on Saturday. Probably the smart thing  to  do
would be to stick to that schedule, descend  to  camp  and  rest  and  start
fresh for Martin  tomorrow.  But  we  both  hated  to  have  to  regain  the
elevation again to Holden Pass and we still had a lot of daylight left.   So
we decided to head directly to Martin. We had a good view of  the  route  on
the west ridge.  It didn\'t look easy  but  it  was  mostly  snowfree  so  we
wouldn\'t have any avalanche dangers.

From Holden Pass, We followed the west ridge on easy snow  to  the  6640  ft
saddle below Pt 7205. Traversing below cliffs,  we  then  followed  an  easy
ramp trending left and back onto the broad  crest  of  the  ridge.  Here  we
stashed our unneeded glacier gear and crampons, but took the  rope  and  ice
axes. Following the crest to the next small  saddle,  we  traversed  on  the
south side, then followed a gully to a notch (#1). Ledges on the north  side
appeared possible but ended in a snowslope capped by a rocky step.  Back  to
the notch, where we left our ice axes, to try the more possible rock on  the
south side. We worked our way gradually up over increasingly difficult  rock
to another  airy  exposed  notch  (#2).  We  were  now  stuck.   Other  than
retreating, the only possible  way  was  along  the  narrow  rock  crest,  a
cheval. Roping up, I scooted along the crest some 50 ft  or  so  to  another
notch (#3) and easier terrain, then brought Linda over. A  gully  led  to  a
4th notch and a deadend.

It was now about 4:00, unbelievably my  altimeter  indicated  we  still  had
1000 ft of elevation to go and the terrain was getting harder,  not  easier.
Were we destined to fail a second time today?  Our only hope was to  descend
and hope for easier going. Back to notch #3 and down the  gully  to  a  snow
slope which we were forced to cross.  Fortunately, I had kept a second  very
short ice axe with me and the  snow  was  so  soft  it  was  not  a  problem
crossing it. On the other side, sandy ledges and scree led easily up and  we
finally began to make faster upward progress. After about  500  ft  we  were
back on the crest at a 5th notch. Here was an  old  tattered  rappel  sling,
the first sign of other climbers we had come across.  Linda had  had  enough
and decided to wait for me here while I made a last effort for the summit.

I headed up the last 500 feet at 4:30, taking  the  rope  and  promising  to
turn around at 6:00 at the latest. I climbed solid rock to the  left  of  an
unpleasant looking gully, then  traversed  into  the  gully  higher  up  and
continued to work my way up a series of ledges and gullies, always near  the
crest. An exposed but easy section along the  very  top  of  the  ridge  was
followed by a vertical 15 ft chimney and ledge to the final scramble  and  I
was on the summit at 5:20. My altimeter read 150  feet  low.   We  had  been
closer than we thought and this last bit  was  easier  than  anticipated.  A
quick photo, a sign-in of the old metal register (to which  I  added  a  new
notebook), a bite to eat and I was on my way back down at 5:30 and to  Linda
at 6:15.

I had rappelled the last unpleasant gully above the  notch,  and  since  the
rope was already out, we made  another  rappel  down  the  gully  below  the
notch. We downclimbed to notch #3, then rather than reversing the  a  cheval
ridge, crossed to the north side and descended ledges  to  the  cliff  above
the snowfield we had seen from notch #2. A rappel, where we  had  difficulty
finding an anchor, dropped us to the snow and the easy ledges  back  to  our
ice axes at notch #2. From there we were able to downclimb  to  our  glacier
gear stash.  All this took time and  it  was  now  8:30  with  one  hour  of
daylight left.

From the stash we traversed SE until directly above Holden Lake  and  zoomed
down easy snowslopes and a gully to emerge at the bear meadow  and  actually
made it to camp before dark at 9:30 (6 miles, 5000 ft and  13:30  hrs  total
for the day). By the time we collected ourselves, had dinner and  fell  into
bed it was 11:00.

Up the next day, Friday, at 7:00, left at 10:00 and back to Holden at  12:40
in time to make arrangements to take the bus out, one  day  early,  at  1:45
and catch the 2:30 (which actually  came  at  3:00)  boat  back  to  Field\'s
Point. We even had time to buy a hearty lunch at  Holden  and  cool  off  on
this very warm afternoon in the pleasant waters of Lake Chelan  waiting  for
the boat.

Grand total: 17 miles and 7000 ft.

Fay Pullen






