            'tr' => '
 Grotto Mtn (USGS Baring) - I was able to coax my Cherokee all  the  way  to
 the end of FR 6028 (2200 ft), although the last  bit  was  very  rough  and
 overgrown to a narrow passage. It was an easy start up the open clearcut at
 the end of the road to the woods about 500 ft  above,  then  along  a  spur
 ridge to 3400 ft where an unpleasant steep traverse left with  intermittent
 snow led into a snow gully at 3800 ft.

 The soft snow made for rapid step kicking up the gully until  coming  to  a
 large basin at 4600 ft  Here I was met with a  major  obstacle.   A  hidden
 "crevasse" crossed the entire slope. I have never seen anything quite  like
 this before at such a low elevation on non  glacial  snow.  It  was  not  a
 bergshrund or moat where the melting snow  pulls  away  from  rock  slabs. 
 Looking down into various holes it was solid snow as far  as  I  could  see
 (maybe 15 feet). Could this perhaps have something to do with  the  massive
 slab avalanche described by Stefan Feller (P&P  Mar 2002). Maybe  this  was
 the crown wall of the avalanche that had then been partially filled in with
 subsequent snowfalls and  avalanche  debris.  At  any  rate,  I  had  great
 problems getting across this thing, and lost about an hour in doing so.
 Once above the crevasse I veered right up steepening slopes to hit the SW
 spur ridge at 5500 ft. Another steep traverse up led to the main NW ridge.
 A vertical 15 ft snow pitch, which I belayed, and a tiptoe along the
 remaining corniced ridge and I was on the summit, with a stunning view of
 Mt Baring. A tiny register was in the bare summit rocks.

 I basked in the sun and the views for a while before heading down to tackle
 crossing, very carefully, the crevasse once  again.  Scary  business.  Once
 across, the rest of the descent was a piece of cake. 

3600 ft and  8  hours.
 Fay Pullen, Kent, 4/25.

 North Gardner and Gardner Mtns (USGS Silver Star  Mtn,  Mazama,  Gilbert  &
 Midnight Mtn) - After taking 7 hours to hike 12 miles and 3100 ft  gain  up
 the Wolf Cr trail, the last half of which  was  snow  covered,  I  found  a
 pleasant spot in Gardner Meadows (5800 ft) on bare  ground  under  a  tree,
 with a small meltwater creek close by, to pitch my tent. Light snow showers
 fell during dinner.

 The next morning I was off by 7:30, heading mostly  north  up  easy  frozen
 snow toward the saddle between  Gardner  and  Pt  8487. It  was  positively
 frigid and an icy wind made me regret not bringing a face mask. There  were
 intermittent light snow showers and sun breaks. At an upper basin  at  7000
 ft I veered left up a likely looking slope to gain the south  ridge  of  Pt
 8487 to avoid the nasty looking cornices near  the  saddle.  A  short  rock
 scramble, then easy snow and scree brought me to the  summit  of  Pt  8487.
 Then down to the saddle with North Gardner.  A pinnacle  was  in  the  way,
 which I bypassed by unpleasant loose scree then icy snow on  the  left.   I
 put on crampons for this snow traverse.

 Once at the main saddle, it was  a  pleasant  scramble  on  snow  and  rock
 working my way up to the summit of North Gardner (8956)at 11:45. Buried  in
 the snow I found the register that had been placed by Don Goodman in  1986.
 Surprisingly, after the icy wind and snow showers on much of the ascent, it
 was warm and sunny on the summit, and I took a moment to enjoy the views.
 I retraced my steps back to Pt 8487  then  descended  to  the  saddle  with
 Gardner (8200 ft). The climbing guide  implied  that  the  ridge  could  be
 followed from the saddle to the summit of Gardner, but  it  is  very  rocky
 with numerous small pinnacles and under the present icy conditions  I  gave
 up on that idea after a brief attempt.  If I wanted  to  climb  Gardner,  I
 would have to descend 800 ft and traverse around to the south side.
 An easy scree slope led down  from  the  saddle,  then  a  long  descending
 traverse on snow left around the basin under cliffs until the  south  slope
 could be accessed.  This slope then proved to be an easy climb up onto  the
 broad summit area.  I reached the summit of Gardner (8898) with  its  large
 cairn at 4:00. My descent back to camp was pretty much  directly  down  the
 south slope, which only took a little more than an hour. Again  dinner  was
 accompanied by light snow which fell much of the night.
 I awoke to warmer temperatures than yesterday, but about 2 inches of  fresh
 snow. I had a leisurely breakfast and left about 10:00. About 4 miles down,
 in the forest, I followed the fresh tracks of a good sized bear in the  new
 snow for a mile or so.  That kept me more alert than usual for the rest  of
 the trip out. I reached the car at 3:30. 

30 miles and 9550 ft. Fay  Pullen,
 Kent, 5/5-7.

 Sheep Mtn (USGS Bedal) - The road to Monte Cristo still had extensive  snow
 patches as I walked the long mile to the Sauk River bridge. Here I left the
 road and wandered NE across confusing bottomland. I crossed two streams  in
 this area flowing in opposite directions from each other.  Very strange.
 Once across the flat, travel improved as I made my way up  reasonably  open
 timbered slopes. At about 3200 ft I began to traverse left under cliffs and
 then entered a major snow gully at 3400 ft.  At the point  I  entered  this
 gully on a sort of level bench there was evidence of  a  massive  avalanche
 occurring earlier this winter. The avalanche  had  come  tearing  down  the
 gully, hit the level bench and continued 100 feet  or  so  up  and  over  a
 wooded spur above taking out every tree in sight. Trees large and small lay
 in a contorted and tangled mess of impenetrable shattered wood. I made good
 time up the gully although cracks were beginning to appear in the snow  and
 I could hear the creek roaring in the depths below.  These required caution
 to cross. At about 5000 ft the gully began to narrow and steepen and headed
 in a wall above, so I exited right up an easy snow slope  over  a  rib  and
 into the next gully.  Here  I  ran  into  old  kicked  steps  and  glissade
 tracks.  Someone had been this way recently.

 Bypassing a small waterfall on dirty rock on the left, I then made good use
 of the old steps up the steepening gully on continuous snow all the way  to
 a gap in the S summit ridge at 5860 ft. A short rock step out of the gap, a
 meander along the mostly snowy ridge and a simple  scramble  up  the  final
 rock tower, about 1/4 mile from the gap, led to  the  pleasant  summit.   I
 lamented the fact that I had no views on this misty and foggy day,  but  at
 least it wasn\'t raining. 

7 miles, 4100 ft & 8 3/4 hours.  Fay Pullen, Kent,
 6/4.
  
  
  

