            'tr' => '
Turquoise Pk. and Malachite Pk. (USGS Big Snow Mtn.) - The West Fork Foss
River trail was largely snow free to just before Malachite Lake.  The lake
itself was still mostly frozen over and surrounded by snow but I did find a
lovely campsite on a snow free bench slightly above the logjamed outlet (4
miles, 2500 ft and 3:15 hrs to here).  After lounging around for two hours
on this warm sunny day, I started for Turquoise Pk. at 5:00 PM. Thinking I
had plenty of time to climb this peak, I soon found I had underestimated
its difficulties and ended up barely making it back to camp before dark.
Thank heavens for the long days this time of year.

A traverse north from the lake\'s outlet on steep brushy hillside soon
brought me to an open snow basin below Malachite Pk. Easy snow led to the
saddle between Turquoise and Malachite, then  slightly steeper snow to the
false summit. So far so good.  But then I got my first good look at
Turquoise. More challenging than I had anticipated. A short descent would
gain the saddle below the final impressive summit pyramid where a long
traverse beneath an impassible rock wall would then be required before the
upper snow slopes could be accessed. These upper snow slopes were very
steep with the runout over the rock wall, so even though the soft snow made
for good step kicking, I elected to exit as soon as possible to the NW
ridge and slither through tree branches and up heathery rock the last 100
ft to the summit (2200 ft and 2:30 hr).

On top I found a film can register left a few years ago by John Roper and
Mitch Blanton. To this I added a new small register of my own. The descent
off the summit pyramid was tense and slow backing down my steps. The rest
was straight forward, but it was 9:30 PM before I dragged back to camp with
barely enough light to find my way.

I started the next morning at 7:30 AM for Malachite retracing my route to
the snow basin. From here I headed up the right side of the slope leading
directly toward the peak, mostly easy snow except for some scrub trees in
the middle. Near the top I diagonalled left to a notch at 5800 ft on the
south ridge. From here I traversed left directly beneath the rock wall,
partially on snow and partially on scree, to another notch on the west
ridge. Now on the north side of the summit, I was confronted by very steep
snow that first required a small descent to bypass a rock spur then a
traverse left and up.  Again I disliked the runout of this snow slope so
exited left as soon as possible to gain the east ridge. Here I followed the
narrow crest of the ridge and an easy but very exposed ledge on the south
side and through a notch that put me above the disagreeable snow slope. A
few more steps and I was on the summit. (2250 ft and 3:00 hrs). Here I
found a register left by Steve Fox the previous September.

I spent a very pleasant hour in the sun on the summit taking in the view of
all the peaks in the heart of the Alpine Lakes Wilderness before beginning
the nerve-wracking descent, again very carefully backing down the snow.
Then came several fun glissades and I was back in camp at 1:30. I left at
3:00 for the uneventful but hot trip out reaching the car at 5:30.  These
two days broke records for high temperatures in June. 14 miles and 7400 ft.
Fay Pullen, 6/4-5/03.


