            'title' => 'Black Pyramid and Three Musketeer Ridge (GT The Enchantments) 6/11-13/03.',
            'tr' => '
Black Pyramid and Three Musketeer Ridge  (GT  The  Enchantments)  -  For  my
annual pre-permit trip to the Enchantments Linda and I headed  up  the  Snow
Lake trail to Nada Lake. Shortly after crossing Nada Cr  we  picked  up  the
climber trail on the left side of the talus slope.  Near  the  head  of  the
talus a ledge gave access to the slabs left of  thundering  Nada  Waterfall,
and a steep cairned scramble route led into Temple Canyon where we ran  into
the first snow. We found a delightful campsite on a  snowfree  slabby  bench
right next to the creek at 6300 ft with a panoramic view  of  Black  Pyramid
and lower Temple Ridge (6.5 miles, 5000 ft and 7:20 hrs).

After a leisurely breakfast the next morning, we started for  Black  Pyramid
at 9:30, which gave time for the morning sun to soften the snow  (we  didn\'t
bring crampons). The peak looked very formidable from camp but Becky  listed
the East Ridge as class 3 and 4. However, the description of this route  was
very sketchy so I knew the climb would be an adventure.

From Camp we crossed a flat soggy  snow  basin  then  climbed  up  a  narrow
couloir to the broad shelf below the North Face.  By now the snow  was  soft
enough for good step kicking. We followed the shelf east to  its  end  where
we worked our way up unpleasant wet slabs to gain the  East  Ridge  at  6950
ft. We looked straight down on Snow Lakes, which  appeared  very  high  with
water  flowing  over  the  dam.   Here  roped  climbing  began  as  we  were
confronted with a steep step that we passed by going around a corner on  the
right and up a series of ledges back  to  the  crest.  A  tiptoe  along  the
narrow exposed crest brought us to the base of the  final  uplift,  where  a
scramble gully led left to a notch.

Crawling through a hole under a large boulder put us on a wide  sandy  ledge
on the  south  side  of  the  ridge.  Broken  rock  appeared  to  promise  a
reasonable route up from here.  But  what  appeared  reasonable  from  below
turned out to be quite challenging. Expecting moderate  class  3-4  rock  we
had not brought rock shoes and were climbing in heavy boots.  The  rock  was
quite downsloping and slippery with black lichen (from which the  peak  gets
its  name),  the  holds  were  sparse   and   protection   cracks   minimal.
Nevertheless, I managed to work my way up about 60  feet  to  a  ledge  with
several trees, then left to an alcove below a  vertical  wall.  Things  were
really looking bleak now and I was getting near my limit. But the  wall  had
a nice crack running all the way up that would  take  protection  nicely.  I
also found evidence of others passing this way, such as rappel slings and  a
dropped #10 hex.  I was on some route, but class 4 it was not. So  I  fought
my way up the crack, pulling on pro as needed, to a squeeze chimney  at  the
top that did major damage to my epidermis. Here I found I was on the  summit
ridge and could look straight down  the  North  Face.   But  where  was  the
summit?  I climbed to the top of the high point next to my notch  and  could
see pinnacles to both the east and west.  Which  was  highest  I  haven\'t  a
clue, but getting to either would be hazardous to my health  so  I  declared
my pinnacle the summit.  Good enough for me. My altimeter read 7425 ft.

Linda had gamely followed me to the tree ledge in order to belay me  higher,
but she too had had enough and elected not to go  higher.   So  much  for  a
reasonable class 4 route. Several rappels and much downclimbing got  us  off
the rock, careful plungstepping down the couloir and we  were  back  in  our
most welcome camp at 6:30 (1125 ft and 8:30 hr RT)

During the night marine air came in as a weak disturbance  approached.  Even
so we had intermittent sun for breakfast. Then we were on our  way  at  9:00
for Three Musketeer Ridge on the other side  of  Temple  Canyon  from  Black
Pyramid. This time we traveled light with no climbing gear except the  rope.
We gained the south ridge just above Musky Lake, which was then followed  up
easy scramble terrain bypassing cliffs and boulders on  the  left.   We  hit
the ridge just left of the twin highpoints  (east  of  the  three  pinnacles
that give the ridge its name) where we had  a  spectacular  view  of  Edward
Mesa, Toketie Lake and Leavenworth. Easy scrambling  up  big  boulders  with
fascinating clefts and cracks accessed both summits.  I concluded  the  east
one was higher, where I left a register. We lingered admiring  the  view  in
the other direction toward Temple Ridge and the Lost  World  Plateau.   From
this vantage point Black Pyramid looked like an insignificant,  though  very
jagged, bump on lower Temple  Ridge,  greatly  overshadowed  by  the  higher
Comet-Professor group and Mt Temple itself. I could pick out the pinnacle  I
had climbed in the center but I was still unable  to  determined  where  the
summit was, though most likely it was to the west.

We could see weather approaching from the direction of  Cashmere  Mtn.  Time
to go.  We descended directly to charming Musky Lake on very pleasant  sandy
slopes, but were caught halfway down by a rain shower.  This  continued  all
the way back to camp when it abruptly ended and welcome sun appeared to  dry
us out. (1400 ft 3.5 hrs RT).

A quick rest for lunch and we were on our way out at  2:00.   Another  short
rain shower caught us descending some of  the  worst  slabs  alongside  Nada
Waterfall. We made two rappels to aid  the  descent  with  the  heavy  packs
before reaching the trail at 4:00 and the TH at 7:00, more  than  ready  for
the fitting reward of a gourmet dinner in Leavenworth. 16 miles and 7700  ft
gain.  Fay Pullen, 6/11-13/03.






