            'title' => 'Sherpani Peak (6720+ ft) and Nursery Peak (6962 ft) - June 11-12, 2004',
            'tr' => '

Sherpani Peak (6720+ ft) and Nursery Peak (6962 ft) - June 11-12, 2004


It was sprinkling, never enough to get really wet, and the sun  even  shined
now and then as I started up the Paddy Go Easy Pass trail at 12:40  pm.  The
trail was snowfree until rounding the corner into the basin about  500  feet
below the pass, where snow soon took over. The pass  itself  was  completely
snow covered, but I was lucky enough to find a  bare  level  campsite  in  a
patch of trees slightly downhill on the north side (3 miles, 2800  ft,  2:40
hr). However, I had to descend another 250 feet to find running water.

After setting up camp, I started for Sherpani Peak  at  4:20  in  increasing
fog. The hard part was getting past the cliffs of Paddy Go North. I  climbed
onto the northeast shoulder, then descended some 500 feet down a steep  snow
gully until I could traverse  below  the  main  ridge  and  cross  the  east
shoulder of Pt 6564. A contour brought  me  to  the  saddle  just  south  of
Sherpani.  The south ridge was quite rocky,  so  I  traversed  to  the  east
ridge where easy snow led to the summit  rocks.  Though  short  these  rocks
looked rather intimidating in the damp fog, but a  crack,  and  then  ledges
spiraled counterclockwise to the final 6 foot summit block.   A  long  reach
(for me) from a small foothold pulled me on top the block (1275 ft and  2:10
hr from camp).

The summit register was a large notebook in an impressive metal case  placed
in 1992 and filled with tributes to Gene  Prater.  I  recognized  the  usual
assortment of names  including  Steve  Fox,  Mike  Torok,  John  Roper,  Don
Beavon, Mitch Blanton and Fred Beavon (exactly I year ago). I carefully  let
myself down off the block, circled back on the ledges,  but  in  going  down
the crack, I used an arm jam for a hold and promptly got my elbow stuck.   I
mean it was really stuck. As I struggled  for  several  painful  minutes  to
unjam it, I had a mental  image  of  the  next  summiters  coming  across  a
skeleton dangling by its  elbow  from  the  crack.  Not  a  pretty  picture!
Making little progress by struggling, I forced myself to relax and was  then
able to get free. I made it back to camp at 7:50 (1760 ft, 3:30  hr  RT),  a
little the worse for wear with a sore elbow. A very cold wind was blowing.

I awoke the next morning at 6:15 to the expected fog, but by the time I  was
ready to start for Nursery Peak at 7:30 the sun was shinning and views  were
appearing. I began the disheartening  1200  ft  descent  to  the  French  Cr
valley floor on snow, then down a rock step, then forest. I  hit  the  creek
in an open marshy meadow and  squished  my  way  upstream  looking  for  the
valley trail but only finding it very near the  saddle  to  Meadow  Cr,  too
late to do me much  good.  From  the  saddle  I  went  uphill  through  easy
meadows, heather and scree to hit Nursery\'s west ridge at the low point.  It
was then an easy matter to follow the ridge on the south side to the  summit
at 10:15 (2100 ft and 2:45 hr).

It was now sunny and warm and windless and I spent a glorious  hour  on  top
taking in the views I  had  missed  yesterday.  The  Cradle  was  especially
noticeable just to the north. The film can register had been placed in  1985
(it  identified  the  peak  as  "The  Bib")  and   only   had   5   entries.
Interestingly, 4 of them were from 2000 on, one each year to 2003.  Names  I
recognized were Greg Koenig and Mitch Blanton (from Bootjack and  Highchair,
10/15/00), Mike Torok (6/23/01) and Grant Myers (9/14/02).

On the way back I found the valley trail and followed  it  downhill  to  the
crossing of French Cr. It was higher up on the north side  above  the  creek
than I expected - probably to avoid the wet marshes. It looked  little  used
and went through several lovely meadows  carpeted  with  fields  of  glacier
lilies, spring beauties and shooting stars. From the creek crossing I  tried
to follow the trail leading to Paddy Go Easy Pass, but I  soon  lost  it  in
snow. Eventually I ran into my downhill tracks and  followed  them  back  to
camp (3300 ft and 6 hrs RT).

The brief period of good weather was coming  to  an  end  and  the  sky  was
clouding up. Rain had been predicted for later in the day.  So after  a  two
hour rest I packed up and zipped down the  trail  in  1:15  hr  beating  any
rain. I\'m not so sure about the couple I met at the trailhead just  starting
up though. I suspect they saw plenty of rain.  But they looked well  dressed
and equipped.  Oddly, the fellow lamented the fact that I had camped at  the
pass, stating he thought it was his secret spot. My reaction (unspoken)  was
is anyplace that has a good trail secret? Perhaps  he  meant  this  time  of
year when all is covered by snow.

Grand total 16 miles and 8100 feet

Fay Pullen

