            'title' => 'Bonanza Peak (9511 feet) - June 28-30, 2004',
            'tr' => '

Bonanza Peak (9511 feet) - June 28-30, 2004


The second time\'s the charm. After failing on Bonanza a  month  ago  due  to
fresh snow and avalanches, I was hot to give it another try,  but  I  wanted
to make sure the peak was in condition before going to all that  effort.  So
the previous week I climbed Copper with the secondary objective  of  getting
a good view of Bonanza.  What I saw looked good. The face  was  mostly  snow
free.  All  I  had  to  do  was  convince  Linda  to  come  with  me  again.
Surprisingly, she was all for it. So for the third time in a month  I  found
myself taking the  boat  and  bus  to  Holden.  It  was  all  becoming  very
familiar.

We started up the trail  to  Holden  Lake  at  1:40,  arriving  at  the  now
snowfree but buggy lake 3 hours and 2000 feet later. It was warm  and  sunny
but at least not sweltering like last week. Continuing around  the  lake  we
picked up the climbers trail, which was marshy and brushy at first, lost  it
briefly in talus and picked it up again on the other side,  reaching  Holden
Pass at 6:40 (7 miles, 3200 ft and 5 hrs). There were snow  patches  at  the
pass but we found a lovely bare spot to pitch our tent. We  fell  asleep  to
the thunder of the spectacular waterfalls spilling  over  the  cliffs  below
the Mary Green Glacier just across the valley.

On our way the next morning by 7:00, we began along  the  ridge,  passing  a
first small cliff through a slot to the left, up heather and talus and  snow
to the infamous waterfall slabs, which looked  quite  frightening.  We  were
able to cross a first waterfall by hugging the cliff on a ledge. Then up  on
slabs between watercourses to a second crossing, onto snow,  where,  if  you
lost it or the snow gave way, you would take  a  long  and  unpleasant  ride
down a waterslide over the lower falls. Next was easy snow along  the  right
edge of the glacier. At 8:30 and about 7900 feet we roped up and  began  the
traverse across the glacier toward the snowfinger leading to the SE face  of
the peak. We stayed high near the cliffs of the NE ridge  where  there  were
few if any crevasses.

Near the avalanche cone at the base of the  snowfinger  (we  speculated  how
much of that debris had come down during our first  attempt)  we  picked  up
the tracks of a previous party. We had learned in Holden  that  two  parties
were on the mountain the previous Saturday (this was Tuesday).  The  earlier
party was driven off by lightening and didn\'t make  the  summit.  The  later
party came after the storm and was successful. Timing is everything.

Linda led up the snowfinger following the previous tracks.  For some  reason
they hugged the right edge near glacial ice even  though  there  was  easier
terrain to the left. Linda, who excels on snow, made it up fine  but  called
down suggesting I put on my crampons. Good idea as  parts  were  quite  icy.
Snow was softer above this  section  but  there  was  still  occasional  ice
underneath. We continued to the  very  right-hand  top  of  the  snowfinger,
directly below the hanging snowpatch, crossed a suspect  snowbridge  to  the
end of the snow and cast around for a way  across  the  moat  and  onto  the
rock. We had to descend a short ways to find a reasonable spot. It  was  now
10:30 and 8650 feet.

We stashed our glacier gear, taking only one short ice axe,  racked  up  and
scoped  out  the  route  above.  It  looked  rather  intimidating.   Several
snowpatches were in the main gully and I could see one higher  up  near  the
ridge crest, where melting snow made the rock wet. It would be best to  stay
out of the gullies.  We  began  by  scrambling  a  couple  of  hundred  feet
simultaneously up easy rock, first right of the gully, then crossing on  wet
ledges to left of the gully. Soon the angle increased to the point where  we
began belaying. The climbing was never very difficult, mostly in  that  gray
area between scrambling and climbing. Several leads I didn\'t bother  to  put
in any pro, but at an occasional step or move it  felt  good  to  have  some
something in and belaying gave Linda the confidence to move faster  (She  is
more comfortable on snow than rock.  I am just the opposite, so  we  make  a
good team.)

We worked our way up the rock on a rib  to  the  left  of  the  gully,  then
traversed left to a wet gully below the upper  snowpatch.  There  was  great
latitude for variation, but the main route was fairly obvious following  the
line of least resistance and the many rappel stations. Some of the rock  was
very pleasant. Other was loose and careful climbing was  required  to  avoid
sending rocks down. I would not want to have  a  party  climbing  above  me.
Hardhats are recommended, which we did wear. We belayed perhaps  5  pitches.
I rather lost count. The last pitch I was forced onto the  upper  snowpatch.
Good thing I had my little ice axe along. From the snowpatch a  chimney  led
to the summit ridge and a rappel station on the north side.  From  here  the
needle like sheer ridge looked  impassible,  but  magically  a  hidden  slot
behind a horn led back to the south side and an  easy  but  loose  and  airy
scramble the final hundred feet to the summit at  2:30  (3100  ft  and  7.5
hrs).

The summit register  was  an  official  brass  Mountaineer  cylinder  placed
inside a metal clasped box. It dated from  1993  and  was  over  half  full,
having started on the back of the  pages.   We  were  the  second  party  to
summit this year, after the one successful party of the  previous  Saturday.
We spent a glorious hour on top basking in the reflection of a  panorama  of
snowy peaks before beginning the unpleasant but necessary  task  of  getting
off this thing.

Six or so rappels, again I lost count, got us down to the  scramble  section
below the main gully and then our equipment stash. We both put  on  crampons
for the trip down the snow finger. Linda led off and was out of  sight  with
me still close to  the  rock  when  the  rope  stopped  moving  for  several
minutes. As I climbed up to within sight of her she  informed  me  that  she
had fallen through the suspect snowbridge. She  saved  herself  by  throwing
herself horizontally across the gap and was glad she  had  crampons  on  for
purchase against the icy wall of the hole. Needless to say I found  a  lower
way onto the snowfinger proper. We stayed more to the right on the way  down
the finger and avoided most of the icy section of the way up.  It  was  then
clear sailing down the glacier, until we hit the waterfall slabs. They  were
even more frightening than on the way up as more water  was  cascading  over
the rocks than in the morning and facing downhill didn\'t  help  the  psyche.
The step off the snow onto the gushing wet  rock  was  unnerving.   We  both
survived, although we both also got wet feet. We were back in camp  at  8:00
for a 13-hour roundtrip.

We made the trip back to Holden the next morning in 3.75  hours  arriving  at
12:00 just as a thundershower hit. What timing! We were so happy  today  was
not our summit day.  It rained moderately heavy for over an  hour.  We  were
in time for the first sitting of lunch at 12:00 (the second is at 1:15)  and
the hearty meal of soup and salad and homemade bread fortified  us  for  the
long trip home.

Grand Total: 18 miles and 6250 feet

Fay Pullen












