            'title' => 'Cathedral Peak (8601 feet), Amphitheater Mountain (8358 feet) and Remmel Mountain (8685 feet) - July 7-9, 2004',
            'tr' => '
Cathedral Peak (8601 feet), Amphitheater Mountain (8358 feet) and Remmel
Mountain (8685 feet) - July 7-9, 2004

With showery weather forecast for several days over  the  Cascade  Crest,  I
decided to try  my  luck  farther  east  in  the  Pasayten  Wilderness.   My
preconceived wishful notion of this area was  that  it  is  normally  sunny,
warm, dry and bugless. It ended up being none of these.  My first  clue  was
arriving at the Thirtymile TH at the  end  of  the  Chewuck  River  road  to
clouds, light sprinkles and cold temperatures. I had packed  very  light  in
keeping with the long distances I would have to travel, but made a few  last
minute additions in keeping with the unexpected conditions  before  starting
up the trail a little before noon.

Unknown to me beforehand, the Chewuck Valley was the site  of  the  Farewell
Fire of 2003 and the results were immediately evident. In fact I  was  lucky
to even get to the trailhead.  The last couple of  miles  of  the  road  had
numerous washouts that had only recently  been  cleared.  The  trail  itself
wandered for the first  9  miles  or  so  through  charred  forest  and  the
extensive flood damage that inevitably occurs once  ground  cover  is  lost.
The flood damage was not limited to creek beds. In places it  appeared  that
whole hillsides had slid covering the trail for hundreds of feet in  debris.
A lot of work had been done recently to make the trail passable  and,  if  I
had to guess by the evidence of limited traffic so far,  was  probably  only
opened on the July 4th weekend. Many other trails in  the  area  were  still
closed, including Andrews Cr, Fire Cr and Coleman Ridge.

The weather was unsettled all day (in  fact  the  whole  trip),  alternating
between sun and sprinkles. It never rained hard enough to require rain  gear
but the threat was always there. At least it was cool hiking and there  were
no bugs. At 9 miles and 4:00 I turned onto the Tungsten Cr  trail.  At  15.2
miles and 7:15 I hit the Boundary trail and turned left  toward  Apex  Pass.
Soon after, I met a hiker (one of 3) with an East  Coast  accent  who  asked
how far it was to the Tungsten Cr trail. He seemed very  afraid  they  would
miss the junction (many of the trails are poorly marked  in  this  area).  I
told him he was very close and since it was right by old mine  buildings  he
couldn\'t miss it. He went on  to  tell  me  how  they  were  snowed  on  the
previous night at Remmel Lake, incredulity evident in his voice.  It  didn\'t
surprise me given how cold it was.

At 8:00 I crossed Apex Pass, a lovely meadowy area that would  have  made  a
nice camp, but I really  wanted  to  get  as  close  to  Cathedral  Pass  as
possible before stopping. Here I got my first look at Cathedral Pk, the  top
of which was in the fog. At 8:50 PM I found a  perfect  site  just  off  the
trail in the headwaters of Cathedral Cr and set up my camp in  waning  light
(19.5 miles, 4300 ft and 9 hrs). During the night I heard  precipitation  on
my bivy tent that sounded suspiciously like snow but it didn\'t last long.  I
briefly worried about my prospects the next morning, but mostly I slept  the
sleep of the weary.

I was able to get through breakfast and packing  the  next  morning  without
precipitation, but as soon as I began at 7:00 AM hiking  the  last  mile  to
Cathedral Pass it started to snow. At the pass it was  snowing  and  blowing
and foggy.  Things were not looking good. I  blindly  headed  uphill  a  few
hundred feet, stashed my overnight gear in the rocks and  continued  with  a
very light day pack - very light because I was wearing all my clothing.   It
had stopped snowing but was still very cold. Most of the snow had melted  or
was blown by the wind into protected areas.

I couldn\'t see the notch I was  supposed  to  be  heading  for  but  figured
following just left of the S ridge would get me to the vicinity. Soon I  was
high enough to see the notch, where I  picked  up  a  climbers  trail.  This
followed right along the base of cliffs and up rock,  where  occasionally  I
had to remove my gloves for handholds, to a fascinating vertical sided  slot
filled with snow. A large cairn was here. I descended into the  icy  slot  a
few feet where I could see a long step up would lead  to  a  ledge  and  the
ridge above. I dinked around here for a long time figuring out  how  protect
this move.  I am acutely aware that even  a  short  slip  can  have  serious
consequences for me climbing alone. I didn\'t have my usual  full  compliment
of gear, bringing only a 40-foot rope, an assortment of 7  small  to  medium
chocks, 4 carabiners and some slings. With a cam I  could  have  had  bomber
pro in a second.

Eventually, I rigged some pro to my satisfaction and  gained  the  ledge.  I
scrambled up to the ridge,  followed  along  the  crest  a  short  ways  and
descended slightly into a notch (actually the other end of  the  snow  slot)
where the move out of the notch over a  deep  cleft  again  gave  me  pause.
Some rime on the rock didn\'t help matters.  Once I figured  out  this  final
move it was an easy scramble the remaining few feet to the  summit  (3  hrs,
1570 ft from my camp).

Something wonderful happened while I was stuck in the slot - the fog  lifted
and the sun came out. I was ecstatic. Not only did I make my  summit  but  I
actually had views. I could see back to Apex Mtn, my  camp  of  last  night,
the unusual long ridge of Amphitheater, down  to  Cathedral  Pass  and  Lake
and, farther away, impressive Remmel Mtn. What gorgeous country.

 There was no register in the summit cairn that I could find so I  left  one
of mine, then started down arriving  at  my  overnight  pack  at  11:30  and
Cathedral Lake at noon. Here I took an hour rest for lunch lounging  in  the
most welcome sun. As I was preparing to leave, a couple on horseback  passed
by coming from Remmel Lake.  The man  exclaimed  the  beauty  of  this  high
country but complained of the monotony of the  long  trail  up  the  Chewuch
River.  He should try it on foot.

From the lake I continued on trail around the west arm of  Amphitheater  and
into the SW basin.  I was preparing to stash my overnight pack at  7500  ft,
when another horse party passed by headed for the saddle  between  the  west
and middle peaks to look down on Cathedral Lake. A good horse trail  led  to
the saddle.  I followed this a short ways then headed right up easy  terrain
to the summit of the higher middle peak. I found no register but  could  not
leave one of mine as I had only brought one on this trip. I was back  to  my
pack at 2:40 (1 hr RT from pack, 800 ft).

I was now hoping to add Remmel Mtn to  the  itinerary,  today  if  possible.
But how to get there from here? Remmel is easily climbed  by  the  trail  on
the SE side, but I was  on  the  NE  side  with  impressive  ridges  barring
access. Of course I could always follow trail down Remmel Cr  then  back  up
around the mountain to Four Point Lake, but  this  entailed  an  extra  6.5
miles and 1400 ft gain. I thought I could see a XC route that would  get  me
over the E ridge.  With this plan in  mind  I  continued  on  trail  through
gorgeous open country  headed  for  the  cutoff  trail  to  Remmel  Cr  that
bypasses Remmel Lake. Somehow I missed it and ended  up  at  the  lake,  not
where I wanted to be. The whole area  is  crisscrossed  by  a  confusion  of
unmarked horse trails. This lost me some time, then even more time as I  was
forced into a detour way around the impassible bog at the head of the  lake.
I then went downstream leaving the trail at 6600 ft and 4:15.

I next wandered through confusing forest littered with downed logs,  plagued
by bugs newly activated by moisture and the warming day with no view  as  to
where I was going. I got very discouraged and thought maybe  I  should  have
stuck with the trail. Climbing Remmel today was fast becoming not  possible.
But I stuck with it and eventually found myself  in  the  basin  NE  of  the
summit at a rocky tarn, just where I wanted to be.

The sun was gone, again, and it began to hail just in time to  accompany  me
up slippery talus to the 7640 ft notch at the head of the  basin.  I  wasn\'t
sure what the descent on the other side  would  be  like.   It  looked  very
steep on the map. As it turned  out  it  was  very  easy,  easier  than  the
ascent, on grass and dirt and I quickly descended to the  7088  ft  tarn  on
the south side.  I found a delightful campsite near  the  outlet  stream  at
7:00. (12.5 miles, 4000 ft and 12 hrs  for  the  day)  Fortunately,  it  had
stopped precipitating, which made setting up camp more pleasant. It was  too
late to try Remmel today, so I had a leisurely dinner and turned in early.

During the night it rained moderately hard for a long time and  I  think  it
also thundered but I was too tired to worry about it and slept soundly.  The
rain stopped by morning, thank heavens. Bivy tents are a pain  in  inclement
weather. Just dressing  inside  one  requires  all  manner  of  contortions.
Forget about eating or cooking in one.

I started for Remmel at 6:00 AM. I briefly considered  going  east  from  my
tarn directly to the summit.  It looked like it would go but it also  looked
quite steep and rocky near the top. Considering my time constraints and  the
wetness of the weather I decided not  to  chance  it.  Instead  I  contoured
south then east on wet talus into the basin SE of the summit where I  picked
up the old lookout trail, which is in very good shape, that led all the  way
to the summit, now in dense fog (1.5 miles, 1.5 hr and 1625 ft).  On  top  I
found a touching register placed in 1998 by Mike Torok in  memory  of  Chris
Weber. I was the first one to sign in for 2004, right  below  the  last  one
for 2003 by Don Beavon on 9/30, his 97th highest 100.  As  we  all  know  he
completed the last 3 a short time later. Another interesting entry was by  a
woman admitting she messed up royally.   She  was  trying  for  the  Coleman
Ridge trail and ended up here. Admittedly the unmarked trails in  this  area
are confusing, but you\'d think she would have begun to get suspicious  after
climbing up  over  a  thousand  feet  too  high.  She  stated  her  dog  was
particularly unhappy!

No views for me on this summit, but I was just happy to  be  on  it.  I  was
back down to camp by 9:00.  After a snack and  short  nap  I  was  ready  to
start the long hike out at  10:40.  I  went  downhill  from  my  tarn,  past
another tarn, and hit the trail below at 11:00. I met  another  horse  party
at the Four Point Lake junction going to the lake. 2.5 miles of rocky  trail
brought me to the Chewuch River at 12:15 and  no  bridge.  Oh  there  was  a
spindly log upstream a ways but it was not appealing. Besides  a  ford  felt
good to my complaining feet. On the other  side  I  picked  up  the  Chewuch
River trail. 4 miles of up and down and frequently boggy trail and I  closed
my lollipop loop at the Tungsten Cr trail. 9  more  miles  of  now  familiar
trail and I was back at the TH at 6:10, not a bit too  soon  as  far  as  my
feet were concerned. (16 miles, 375 ft, 7.5 hrs from tarn camp). I  had  met
no one on the trail since the horse party at Four Point Lake.

Grand Total: (51 miles and 10,300 ft)

Fay Pullen





