            'title' => 'Tieton Pk, Curtis Gilbert (USGS Pinegrass Ridge, Jennie\'s Butte, Walupt Lk)  7/10-11/2003',
            'tr' => '
Tieton Pk, Curtis Gilbert (USGS Pinegrass Ridge, Jennie\'s Butte, Walupt  Lk)
- Linda and I started up the South Fork Tieton River trail  at  11:00.   The
trailhead at Conrad Meadows was filled with horse  trailers  and  the  trail
had been turned to deep dust by the many horse hooves.  People on  foot  are
definitely in the minority here.  After about 2 miles  we  turned  off  onto
the unmaintained Tieton Pk trail.  This trail was easily followed  at  first
as it wandered some  3  miles  farther  along  beautiful  Conrad  Cr  before
seemingly coming to a deadend at an exceedingly marshy meadow.  We  squished
our way across, at places in danger of sinking calf deep  in  muck.  On  the
other side we picked up the trail again.

The trail now became harder to  follow  even  though  there  were  signs  of
recent work and horse travel.  I doubt  this  work  was  sanctioned  by  the
forest service as it mostly consisted of new blazes  or  dabs  of  turquoise
paint on trees. Very odd. The trail, which had thus far only climbed 600  ft
total, now decided to make up for lost elevation and  began  to  climb  very
steeply.  Eventually we lost the trail completely as the  blazes  and  paint
both ran out and we entered an area of many crisscrossing  elk  trails.   We
even saw a few of the critters that made these trails. We continued  up  and
left into opening meadowy terrain following whatever game trails led in  the
generally right direction around the E ridge of Tieton Pk. We stopped  in  a
delightful meadow  at 6300 ft directly below the SE slope  of  our  peak  (8
miles, 2400 ft and 4:45 hr).

After setting up camp we started up Tieton at 4:45.   Scree  and  then  snow
led to a notch on the S ridge where we were greeted with a magnificent  view
of Mt Rainier and Old Snowy.  We continued N along the  rotten  ridge  until
forced to the W side to bypass a pinnacle. To gain the ridge again  entailed
some of the loosest rock it has been my displeasure  to  ever  climb.  Every
step felt like you would set the whole hillside  in  motion.  At  one  point
crossing a gully we did set off a scree avalanche that just kept  going  for
several minutes while we hung on for dear life.  Very spooky.   We  made  it
off the loose stuff to safety for the last little bit along  the  ridge  and
an easy chimney on the right  to the summit (1400 ft and  1:30  hr).   There
was no summit register so I left one.   I  really  doubt  that  many  people
climb this pile of junk. By the way, Becky  has you climbing this peak  from
the saddle above Cold Lake and following the long (and loose)  SW ridge  all
the way to the summit.  Crazy!

On the way down we thankfully found  a  slightly  better  lower  route  that
bypassed the worst of the moveable gully. The  standing  glissade  down  the
snow from the notch almost made up for the unpleasant ridge.  We  were  back
in camp by 7:30.  We ate dinner watching a large herd (40?) of goats on  the
hillside across Conrad Cr.

I had already climbed Curtis Gilbert  via  the  usual  route  up  the  Meade
Glacier, but Linda had never been up it, so I agreed to climb it again  with
her.  To this end we started the next morning at 8:00, first  traversing  to
Cold Lake, then up the Conrad glacier to the  notch  leading  to  the  Meade
Glacier.  The snow was soft, the step-kicking easy. From the notch  a  steep
traverse on snow led to the summit ridge where we  picked  up  the  climbers
trail to the summit.  I had remembered the rock on Curtis Gilbert  as  being
very loose, but compared to Tieton it was positively  solid  and  a  joy  to
climb.  This relieved Linda greatly, as after  Tieton  she  had  anticipated
the worst. We were on the summit  by  11:00.   There  was  a  nice  register
container but it was filled with scraps of paper.  I had neglected to  bring
a waterproof notebook so we added our own scrap. Whatever  happened  to  all
those nice registers that used to adorn summits.  Is someone  systematically
removing them?

We were back in camp by 1:00 where we attempted to relax and rest.  But  the
sun was so hot in this shadeless campsite that we gave it  up  and  left  at
2:30.  We decided to return via the South Fork Tieton trail and make  a  big
loop back to the car.  This entailed traversing S over gorgeous open  alpine
meadows with dozens of creeks and waterfalls.  For the  most  part  we  were
able to follow a way trail, but there was still much snow this high  and  it
came and went. We anticipated an easy time of it so were not  prepared  when
we were completely stopped by a raging fork of Conrad Cr after about a  mile
(the main creek we were able to cross on a snow bridge).  We  could  see  no
other solution except to wade across. We chose a braided section  where  the
creek divided in two channels with a rest  on  the  island  in  the  middle.
Even so, by the time we were across our feet were numb from the icy water.

There were no more major difficulties in connecting to the  main  trail  and
following it 7.5 long, dusty miles back to the car at 7:30.   27  miles  and
6200 ft gain. Fay Pullen, 7/10-11/2003


