Big Craggy (8470 feet), West Craggy  (8366  feet)  and  Sherman  Peak  (8204
feet)

June 15-17, 2004

I once again had business with Douglas County, this time  in  Waterville  at
the County Courthouse before the County Commissioners. I decided to  combine
this trip with a climb of the Craggy Peaks since I was over half way  there.
My meeting was at 10:30 am and I was done by 11:00. I drove on to  Winthrop,
up the West Chewach River road and Eightmile Cr road to  the  Copper  Glance
TH.

I started up the old mine road at 2:30 on a warm sunny afternoon. Once  past
the mine, the road turned to trail, rounded  a  corner  through  very  green
meadows alive with yellow glacier lilies and blue forget-me-nots and gave  a
stunning view of Sherman Peak.  This  peak  was  not  on  my  agenda  but  I
couldn\'t help being intrigued by it and immediately started plotting how  to
add it to my agenda. It was a beautiful peak from this aspect with its  rock
walls and snowy couloirs. After crossing Copper Glance Cr I  stayed  on  the
trail to Copper Glance Lake until coming to a little pond. I  thought  if  I
camped here I would be in position to climb all three peaks.  But  the  pond
was uninviting as a campsite and had no views, very important to me. I  then
considered camping at the lake half a mile on, but it seemed  too  far  from
the Craggys. So I headed upslope along the  creek  and  found  a  delightful
site on a knoll at 6700 feet just below the  scree  slopes  leading  to  Big
Craggy where I had a view of all 3 peaks (3.5 miles, 2900 ft, 3:15 hrs)

Two weeks ago I had been surprised by how much snow was on Bonanza.  Here  I
was surprised by how little snow there was.  I  had  hoped  there  would  be
enough to cover at least some of the scree, but there was essentially  none,
so as I started the next morning at the leisurely time of 8:30 I was  doomed
to work my way up the loose,  unpleasant  stuff.   Not  difficult  but  very
tedious. I headed straight up from camp, then right  toward  the  SE  ridge.
Near the top things got a little more interesting  as  the  slope  steepened
and became rockier.  I topped out on the summit at 10:30 (1770 ft,  2  hrs).
The summit register was a metal cylinder capped with a rubber  cork.  Inside
were wet pages wrapped in a plastic bag. The pages  were  filled  the  usual
suspects - Mike Torok (\'94), Mitch Blanton (\'96), Grant  Myers  (\'97),  Paul
Cho (\'02). Greg Koenig and Stefan  Feller  (\'02)  and  Mike  Collins  (\'02).
Since there was no room to sign any more and the cylinder wasn\'t big  enough
to add one of my waterproof notebooks, I replaced the register with  one  of
mine, including the loose pages after I dried them out a bit.

Continuing on to West Craggy, I descended most unpleasant scree  (it  wasn\'t
even "screeable" - too big and  lumpy)  to  the  low  point  of  the  saddle
between the two peaks, then worked my way left and up over more  interesting
scramble terrain, to a minor notch. Through the notch,  up  a  gully  and  a
very steep but short snowpatch, the only place an ice axe  was  required  on
either peak, to the main summit ridge. An easy walk led  to  the  summit  of
West Craggy at 1:15 (2740 ft, 4:45 hrs). Surprisingly,  West  Craggy  had  a
better register than the higher Big  Craggy,  an  official  Mountaineer  one
placed by Mike  Torok  on  9/3/94.   The  signers  were  the  same  cast  of
characters as on Big Craggy except that Don and Natala Goodman\'s names  were
added via a scrap of paper dated 8/9/92 (probably from a previous  film  can
register) and they noted they had  already  climbed  Big  Craggy  and  North
Craggy in 1983.

I descended from West Craggy to the minor notch,  then  went  down  a  loose
gully directly to the upper basin of Copper Glance Cr.  There  was  actually
some useful snow here that facilitated the descent and I passed  two  lovely
tarns not shown on the map.  The upper one was still frozen over, the  lower
one would make for nice camping. From the lower tarn I contoured back to  my
camp at 3:30 (2975 ft, 7 hrs).

It was early and I still had Sherman Peak  on  my  mind.   I  thought  about
moving camp to Copper Glance Lake for an early start up  the  peak  tomorrow
morning, but the prospect of packing up was unappealing and my camp  was  so
pleasant I just stayed put and spent a leisurely afternoon  resting,  eating
and reading a good book. What a life!

I was up the next morning and on my way at 7:15 reaching Copper Glance  Lake
at 8:00. Here I stashed my overnight gear and started  up  Sherman  Peak  at
8:20. I had very little information about how to  climb  this  peak,  but  I
could tell from the map and by what I could see it would not be  trivial.  I
had no climbing gear (particularly useful would be crampons) with me,  other
than an ice axe. So I was prepared to back off if things got too dicey.  But
it was such an appealing peak, and I was here, I had to give it a try.

The line of least resistance seemed to be the  snow  slope  above  the  lake
leading to a 7800 ft notch S of Pt 8109. But the slope narrowed to  a  steep
snow finger several hundred feet below the notch.  It would  all  depend  on
how soft the snow was.  Once at the notch,  the  other  side  of  the  ridge
appeared gentler, but I had to traverse  past  Pt  8138  and  another  rocky
tower before being able to access the N ridge of Sherman.  It  all  depended
on how easy this traverse was. Only one way to find out.

The snow slope started out easy enough and the  snow  was  soft  enough  for
good step kicking, but gradually it got steeper and as I  entered  the  snow
finger in the narrow gully the snow got harder. But  vigorous  step  kicking
still worked. At one point the snow  narrowed  to  3-4  feet  wide  and  was
undercut with a black hole. Conveniently, a ledge presented  itself  on  the
rock wall to the right and I was able to bypass this obstacle  and  continue
up rock and snow and by moat crawling  to  the  notch  above.  Crossing  the
notch I was pleased to find easily traversed talus  and  scree  slopes  that
allowed me past Pt 8138. The next tower  was  another  matter.  My  traverse
abruptly ended at the rock walls of the tower above and a chasm of a  ravine
below. A ledge presented a possible way but I couldn\'t tell if it  continued
all the way to Sherman\'s N ridge. I didn\'t want to chance it and get  stuck.
 So I opted for the sure plan of descending  along  the  ravine  600  ft  to
gentler terrain where I could cross and head back up again.

The rest of the climb was up easy talus and snow  to  the  summit,  which  I
reached at noon (2775 ft, 3:40  from  lake).  Another  official  Mountaineer
register greeted me on top, but this one only had 3  entries.  It  had  been
placed by a Mountaineer party on 6/18/00, but evidently  not  on  the  right
summit.  The next entry, by Steve and Liz Fellstrom, noted  they  found  the
register two points to the south toward Burgett Pk and carried it up to  the
true summit. I would say that the one  basic  requirement  of  those  kindly
willing to carry registers to mountaintops is that they place  them  on  the
proper summit!  The only other entry was the  ubiquitous  John  Roper.  From
the comments in the  register,  I  gather  that  all  these  people  climbed
Sherman from the south along the gentle ridge from Burgett Pk.  I  liked  my
way better.

Starting back at 12:30, I  was  back  to  the  notch  at  1:30,  and,  after
carefully backing down the snow finger, then a wonderful  sitting  glissade,
my overnight pack at 2:15 (3530 ft, 6:05). On  the  way  out  I  stopped  to
explore the mine, but was only able to go  in  a  few  hundred  feet  before
being stopped by a cave-in. It was possible to continue  past  this,  but  I
didn\'t feel it worth the risk.

Grand total: 14.5 miles and 9565 ft.






