Jack Mountain (9066 feet) - July 13-15, 2004


Jack Mtn has been on my wish list for several years, but I kept  putting  it
off, either not finding anyone who  wanted  to  go  with  me  or  being  too
intimidated to try it alone. I didn\'t know if I  was  capable  of  doing  it
solo or if it was even wise (then again is  any  climbing  really  "wise"?),
but somehow the time seemed right  to  give  it  a  go.   The  clincher  was
rereading Mike Torok\'s trip  report  from  August  of  last  year  where  he
described the Jerry Glacier as free of crevasses and so crossed it  unroped.
 I had always worried about crossing the glacier by myself. And so  I  found
myself  starting  from  the  Canyon  Creek  TH  at  10:30  AM   with   great
expectations and not a little trepidation.

I was immediately confronted by a sign stating that  the  Canyon  Cr  bridge
was out.  An alternate start was suggested from the East  Bank  TH,  some  3
miles west, not very appealing.  Since  the  crossing  is  near  the  TH,  I
elected to check it out before going for the alternative.   It  didn\'t  look
so bad.  Of course, creek crossings are always deeper than they  look.   The
water ended up being crotch deep and by the time  I  got  across  my  shorts
were soaked and my bare feet and legs numb from the cold water. But  it  was
a warm day and once I started hiking the wet  clothing  actually  felt  good
and quickly dried.

Shortly after crossing, I was passed by  three  fellows  going  to  McMillan
Park. Thinking some explanation was necessary for my wet shorts I told  them
I got wet fording Canyon Cr. They seemed surprised, stating  that  they  had
looked at the creek and decided not to  cross,  instead  starting  from  the
East Bank TH.  Then they saw my ice axe and appeared a bit worried. "Do  you
think you will need an ice axe?"  they  asked.  "Yes,  most  definitely",  I
replied, as I explained I was climbing Jack Mtn. "Do you think we will  need
one?" they inquired further. "No", I answered. They seemed relieved,  but  I
really don\'t think they had a clue as to where I was going  in  relationship
to where they were going.

Once my  clothing  dried,  I  was  further  kept  cool  toiling  up  the  60
switchbacks on the steep trail by a thundershower that  brought  light  rain
off and on for an hour before the sun came back out.  As  I  was  hiking  it
came to me that I had forgotten to  put  a  fuel  canister  in  my  pack.  I
couldn\'t believe I had done that!  There would be no  hot  meals  or  drinks
for me on this trip. I reached the junction  to  Crater  Lake  at  2:15  and
Crater Lake itself at 3:00. Crater  Lake  is  located  in  a  lovely  cliffy
cirque with several spectacular waterfalls cascading down hundreds of  feet.
Another 1.5 hour up the Crater Mtn trail and I left the trail at 7100 ft.

A short steep descent on snow preceded a mostly level traverse to  the  7200
ft saddle between W and E Crater Mtns, and my first view  of  Jack  Mtn.  It
looked absolutely wicked, a long committing ways away, and I  had  my  first
"Moments of Doubt". The Jerry Glacier, however, looked benign and  I  easily
descended it to the 6600 ft saddle above the 5900 ft Jerry Lakes. A  further
descent and I found a wonderful campsite by the S lake at 6:15 (8.5  miles,
5200 ft, 7:45 hrs).  These lakes are worth the trip in themselves.

The campsite had a fire ring that looked well used. Hmmm! An  idea  came  to
me. I looked on the back of my wilderness  permit.  The  only  reference  to
campfires was if you had one to use dead down wood.  I  had  always  thought
campfires were prohibited in alpine areas.  Evidently not  in  the  Pasayten
Wilderness. Maybe I could have a hot dinner  after  all.  Now  it  has  been
years, if not decades, since I started a fire using only a match. I  had  to
go back to my Girl Scout training as a kid in New Mexico.   I  was  able  to
get a fire started and boil 2 pots of water for a  hearty  dinner  and  tea,
but my conclusion was campfires are highly overrated and more  trouble  than
they are worth except in an emergency. They are smoky,  time  consuming  and
take constant attention to keep  them  burning.  The  only  wood  available,
though plentiful,  was  dead  downed  branches  from  alpine  larches  that,
although they seemed dry enough, burned with a heavy sooty acrid  smoke.  My
blackened pot will never be the same and it will take heavy washing  to  get
the smell out of my clothing.

No hot breakfast or tea for me the next morning.  I made do with  an  energy
bar and some fresh fruit and was on my way at 6:00 AM.  I picked up the  way
trail out of the lake basin and over the 6550 ft saddle in the ridge  above,
then descended to the 5800 ft basin of Crater Cr and  up  easy  heather  and
snow to Jack\'s SE ridge at 7100 ft. A climber\'s trail starting on scree  led
to a long crampon traverse on snow under cliffs until  I  could  turn  right
and follow the snow to near it\'s high point and exit right onto a  ramp.  It
was now 9:30 and 7600 ft. The ramp led to a  higher  snowpatch  toped  by  a
short cliff that gave me trouble.  I tried several false leads getting  more
and more discouraged and having my second "Moments of Doubt". I was  finally
able to bypass  the  cliff  by  descending  right  along  the  base  of  the
snowpatch to cross below a  waterfall  then  back  up  on  its  right  side,
crossing left again above the waterfall and the cliff. This for me  was  the
key. Another short wall was just above, but this one had good  holds  and  I
had no trouble surmounting it. At the top was a rappel sling, the  only  one
I found on the whole mountain.

I didn\'t know it at the time, but this  waterfall  and  stream  drained  the
gully that leads directly to the notch just west of the summit, the notch  I
was supposed to be heading for.   But  this  gully,  partially  filled  with
snow, looked decidedly unpleasant to me and I stayed out of  it.  Above  the
rappel sling, the terrain eased off and climbing became  easier.   Mostly  I
stayed on the rib between the waterfall gully and the next shallow gully  to
the left.  Occasionally, I climbed in the shallow gully  itself.  Somehow  I
ended up too high, mistakenly heading for one of the spires on the W  ridge.
and was forced to make a dicey exposed traverse right  to  the  west  notch,
the most nerve-wracking part of the climb for me. From  the  notch  I  found
the climb along the ridge to the summit to  be  pleasant  and  enjoyable  on
decent rock. I reached the top at 12:15 (3900 ft, 6:15) greatly  elated  and
with that glow  that  comes  from  achieving  a  challenging  goal  with  an
uncertain outcome.

The summit register was a substantial plastic one with  a  small  loose-leaf
notebook inside placed on 8/5/95. Maybe 4-5 pages  were  filled,  one  side.
For such a major peak it doesn\'t seem Jack is climbed all that  often.   Don
and Fred Beavon signed in on 8/16/96, having climbed the N ridge  from  Ross
Lake. Mike Torok and party\'s climb of 8/2/03 was recorded.  The  last  entry
was 8/22/03. I was the first to sign in for 2004, which surprised  me  as  I
saw recent tracks at Jerry Lakes.

After properly enjoying the surrounding panorama of snowy peaks,  especially
recognizing the Snowfield Massive behind Ruby, I began my descent  a  little
after 1:00. Back at the notch, I was loath to repeat my dicey traverse so  I
headed straight down the gully.  It was  not  to  my  liking  either.   This
gully, though of low angle, was most unpleasant  with  loose  slippery  rock
and ball bearing gravel all perched above steep snow. As soon as possible  I
traversed out of the gully back to my ascent route on the rib to the  right.
Once there the descent went smoothly to  the  rappel  sling.  Since  it  was
there, I used it with the skinny 60-foot rope I had along, but I could  have
downclimbed just as well. Care was taken on the snow traverse (I didn\'t  use
crampons this time) to the SE ridge, then quickly  down  to  the  Crater  Cr
basin. A tiring plod 700 feet up to the ridge overlooking Jerry Lakes,  down
the other side and I was back to my tent at  6:00  (6  miles,  4700  ft,  12
hrs).

Although I had the time, I was too tired to face making another fire,  so  I
munched on odds and ends of cold food that included nuts,  crackers,  cheese
sticks and turkey jerky.  And I drank cup after cup  of  delicious  mountain
water. It was a very warm day. When I turned in before 9:00 it was still  67
degrees despite a short thundershower that produced a little rain  and  some
thunder.

I woke the next morning after 6:00 when sun hit the  tent,  and  left  after
leisurely packing up at 8:30. I was back to the Crater Mtn  trail  at  10:30
(2 miles, 1400  ft.  2  hrs).   Throughout  this  trip  the  other  dominant
feature, besides Jack, had been the main W peak of  Crater  Mtn  (8128  ft).
It is really a very impressive rocky crag that just  called  to  me,  so  of
course I had to climb it. I knew an old trail at one time led to  a  lookout
on the summit, but I had read the trail had fallen into disrepair.  A  steep
scramble section once had cables and ladders to facilitate  the  ascent  but
they were now gone. So  not  knowing  what  to  expect,  after  stashing  my
overnight pack, I took a daypack with my little rope  and  slings,  just  in
case. They were not needed.

I found the trail up Crater Mtn a delight, highly recommended.  Built  trail
ended at the base  of  the  cliffy  section  but  fading  yellow  paint  and
strategically placed cairns pointed the way.  It  was  fascinating  how  the
route zigged and zagged back and forth on ledges seeking out  weaknesses  in
the terrain. Looking from a  distance  you  wouldn\'t  think  the  route  was
climbable unroped but the rock and holds were good,  the  best  climbing  of
the trip. At the top of the cliff, built trail reappeared leading the  final
easy Â¼ mile to the top where I had lunch consisting of  a  dwindling  supply
of food. Of course the view  of  Jack  was  stunning.   I  was  back  to  my
overnight pack at 12:30 (2 miles, 1:45 hr, 900 ft RT).

At the McMillan Park Junction I soaked my  tired  feet  in  a  creek  before
heading down.  I met several backpacking parties sweating up the  steep  hot
trail. For the Canyon Cr  ford  I  left  on  boots  and  socks.  Crossing  a
slippery rock strewn  creek  bottom  is  much  easier  with  boots  on  than
barefooted. Despite higher water flow this hot afternoon, I  had  an  easier
time of it than on the way in.  I squished my way the  last  little  bit  to
the TH in soggy boots arriving at 4:15 (10.5 miles, 2300  ft,  7:45  hr  for
the day). Very hungry, I stopped in Sedro Woolly on the way home for a  much
needed delicious pasta dinner.

Grand Total: 25 miles and 12,200 ft      Fay Pullen










