Bismarck Peak (7585 feet) Traverse - July 20, 2004


I decided to take a "rest" this week from several months of weekly  multiday
trips. So for fun Linda and I decided to climb Bismarck Peak, which  neither
of us had been up, and then see if we could traverse the ridge north to  the
Mt Aix trail.  We had both seen  this  ridge  from  Mt  Aix  and  it  looked
inviting and since the two TH\'s are  only  a  few  hundred  feet  apart  the
logistics were simple.

We started up the Pear Butte  trail  at  8:00.   It  was  cloudy,  cool  and
sprinkling lightly. The high ridges were in the fog. Neither of us  expected
this. We had come from a heat wave on the West side and were expecting  very
hot temperatures. It is rarely cooler in  Eastern  Washington  than  Western
during the summer. Enjoying the cool weather (and,  I  might  add,  a  light
pack), we made  pleasant  progress  up  the  trail,  turning  off  onto  the
Bismarck Pk trail at 10:45 (4.6 miles, 2800 ft).  My  maps,  both  USGS  and
Greentrails, showed this trail generally following the ridge  up  and  down,
but traversing right (south) of Pt 6816, all the way to summit.  Forget  all
that.

First, the trail we followed, traversed left (north) of  Pt  6816  and  then
just ended in a lovely meadow at 6300 ft. Thinking we may  have  gotten  off
onto one of the many well traveled elk trails in the area, we headed  uphill
to the saddle just SW of the summit hoping to pick up the trail again  here.
At the saddle we could find no real obvious built  trail.   So  second,  the
Bismarck Pk trail no longer goes all the way to the  summit,  at  least  not
that we could find. We wandered around a bit, somewhat right of  the  ridge,
from faint animal trail to faint animal trail hoping  to  run  across  built
trail until finally giving up and just heading  uphill  on  steep  dirt  and
talus to the summit at 1:30 (7.5 miles, 5000 ft).

There had been a register at one time on the summit,  but  it  was  now  non
functional. The main body of the plastic tube was intact, but  the  cap  had
been shattered and the contents were missing. I added a  small  register  of
mine placing it wholly inside the bigger tube. The fog had lifted so we  did
have views, but it was still  cloudy  and  a  cold  wind  was  blowing.   We
actually got cold.

After eating lunch we turned our attention to the ridge leading north to  Mt
Aix. The first order of business was  to  access  it.   The  north  side  of
Bismarck is quite cliffy.  So we descended the SW ridge to 7100 ft where  we
could then traverse back to the N ridge. The first part of the ridge  to  Pt
7151 was rocky, but a traverse  on  the  west  side  bypassed  most  of  the
difficulties with easy scrambling. Pt 7335 was also bypassed on the left  by
an unpleasant traverse  on  loose  scree.  Thankfully,  a  few  goat  trails
appeared to help out. The next bump was bypassed on the right  but  we  went
over the top of Pt 7495. A final short uphill section and we hit the Mt  Aix
trail at 5:00 (11 miles, 6100 ft).

All that remained to complete a most satisfactory day trip  was  to  descent
the 5 miles down the well used Mt Aix trail, then close the loop by  a  very
short walk along the road back to the Pear Butte TH and the car.

Total: 16 miles, 6100 feet and 11.5 hours - Fay Pullen





