            'tr' => '
The Triad (USGS Eldorado Pk) - What a splendid climb this turned out  to  be
- highly recommended.  I am sure this peak can and has  been  climbed  in  a
day from the TH, but I wanted to savor the beauty of this high  country  and
so opted for a more leisurely 2-day trip with a  camp  at  Sibely  Cr  Pass.
Since the pass is right on the  boundary  of  the  North  Cascades  National
Park, I wasn\'t sure if I needed a permit to camp there,  but  just  to  make
sure I stopped at the ranger station to inquire.  They felt one was  needed.


Beginning from the Hidden Lake Peak TH, it was only  3  miles,  2600  ft  of
gain and 2:30 hrs to the pass, so despite a late start I arrived  in  plenty
of time to set of camp and lounge around before turning in  early  at  8:00.
I wasn\'t sure how camping would be at the pass, but  in  fact  there  was  a
large flat area for a tent and a snowpatch nearby for water  and  of  course
glorious views toward Sahale and Cascade Pass and  the  three  peaks  of  my
objective. Perfect!

I began the next morning at 7:30, following a  delightful  way  trail  north
and east that wandered up and down along the ridge through  glorious  alpine
terrain. I thought I was in heaven. The way trail ended at a notch where  it
was necessary to drop a bit on the north side and traverse on  snow  to  the
6700 ft notch SW of Pt 6804, marked by a large  cairn.   This  traverse  was
easy enough although the first part was icy enough that crampons felt  good.


From the notch a class 3 gully led down the south side  to  talus  and  snow
below.  A traverse at about 6340 ft rounded a rocky  spur  and  brought  the
Triad back into view. From here I  worked  my  way  down  a  bit  more  then
traversed right to the snowfield directly below the peak  and up  to  the  S
ridge of the E peak.  Now the fun began as I followed  a  broad  ledge  past
the E peak to the gully below the notch with the Middle Pk  (the highest  of
the three peaks), then a slab to the notch  itself.   An  exposed  pitch  up
from the notch and around  the  corner  on  the  S  (class  4)  bypassing  a
pinnacle led to more ledges and heather slopes and the summit ridge.  I  was
on the narrow top at noon (4:30 hrs and 1450 ft  from  Sibely  Cr  Pass),  a
most pleasant climb.

My route, except for the climb of the  Triad  itself,  is  part  of  a  high
alpine traverse that goes  between  the  Hidden  Lake  Peak  trail  and  the
Cascade River road.  From my perch I now had a  splendid  view  of  Eldorado
and the rest of this traverse.  It made me want to continue  on.  But  alas,
this was not to be,  at  least  not  this  day.  So  I  descended  my  route
(required a couple of rappels) and retraced my steps back to my  camp  (8:00
hrs and 2500 ft total RT).  I spent another couple  hours  relaxing  in  the
sun before beginning the short trip out to the TH. 12  miles,  5100  ft,   -
Fay Pullen, Kent - 7/29-30/03.


