            'tr' => '
Mt Logan (USGS Mt Logan, GT Diablo Dam & Mt Logan) - I have had  my  eye  on
this peak for some time, but I had  trouble  facing  the  long  approach  up
Thunder Cr. In fact it turned out to not be as bad  as  anticipated  despite
neglecting to read the map in detail and noticing that  part  of  the  trail
descends almost 1000ft on the way in losing hard gained elevation.

Stopping at the Marblemont RS for the fourth time  in  as  many  weeks,  the
rangers there were getting to know me by name.   There  was,  however,  some
confusion as to which campsite we wanted. I wanted the Upper  Thunder  Basin
Camp, but it doesn\'t seem to be very  well  differentiated  from  the  Lower
Thunder Basin Camp, which is supposedly a horse camp, nor is  it\'s  location
well defined.  All I knew is that it was higher  than  the  lower  one.  The
rangers didn\'t seem to know either. This bit of confusion  would  return  to
haunt us. Also, there was a new face behind the counter and  who  should  it
turn out to be but the ranger who had given me  a  hard  time  the  previous
week at Cascade Pass.  He recognized me  and  reintroduced  himself  as  the
ranger who had hassled me. He was properly contrite and we  had  a  pleasant
conversation as I told him how my climb of Buckner and Booker had  gone.  He
wished me a good time on Logan. All was forgiven.

And so Linda and I started up the long Thunder Cr  trail  at  10:45  in  hot
sunny weather and through tinder dry forest. The trail was  in  great  shape
until we entered the large expanse of Thunder Basin  where  it  deteriorated
and turned brushy.  By the time we reached the  camp  called  Thunder  Basin
Camp some 16.6 miles up the trail, just after crossing the  creek  at  7:45,
we were tempted to stop there for the night as we were both beat.  The  camp
sign gave no designation as being a horse camp. But, much to  our  surprise,
as we had seen no one on the trail for hours, the camp was already  occupied
by two fellows.  There seemed to be only  one  available  spot,  the  others
having been destroyed by  now  melting  avalanche  snow.  And  although  the
fellows seemed to think this was THE Thunder Basin Camp and even offered  to
share their site with us, we decided to push wearily onward. I felt  certain
there was a higher camp.  But  the  longer  we  went  without  running  into
anything the more doubt I had that this higher  camp  existed.  Finally,  at
8:30 and at a much higher elevation  (5200  ft)  than  I  thought  the  camp
should be, we became desperate to find a place in the fading light  to  rest
our weary bodies. Fortunately we found a reasonable spot just off the  trail
in the bushes to pitch our tent, had a quick dinner  and  collapsed  in  bed
(18 miles, 5200 ft & 9:45 hours).

Continuing up the trail the next morning  at  7:45,  within  a  few  hundred
yards we ran into the elusive Upper Thunder Basin Camp,  although  the  camp
sign listed no name. A few expletives  filled  the  air.  It  was  a  lovely
campsite with two sites and a composting toilet. We continued on  the  trail
crossing the head of the basin then  began  a  series  of  switchbacks  that
ended at a rocky meadow. Here we picked up a well-used climbers  trail  that
was easily followed until it  dead-ended  at  a  deep  ravine.  Climbing  up
alongside the ravine we ran into another good way trail at  its  top,  which
we followed as it led upward to cross a rocky  rib.  From  here  we  made  a
traverse across mixed talus and heather meadows past the  south  peak  until
we could head straight up to the edge of the Fremont Glacier.

We roped up for the glacier, crossed below the rib coming  from  the  middle
peak, and climbed a narrow strip of snow left of this rib  and  right  of  a
large expanse of bare glacier ice to the gentle snow shelf  above.   A  snow
finger gave access to a climber\'s trail up  a  slanting  rocky  gully  to  a
notch in the south ridge. From here a  most  interesting  route  followed  a
series of exposed but easy ledges on the east side to the talus slope  below
the final rock tower. A final pitch on steep but good rock and  we  were  on
top (4100 ft and 6 hrs).

We only took time to sign the summit register and for a few  quick  pictures
as we could see weather rapidly moving our way.  We  made  it  back  to  the
notch before the rain started. Thunder and lightening  accompanied  us  down
the gully where we elected to rappel the final distance to the  snow  below.
The thunderstorm increased in intensity during the trip  down  the  glacier,
but before we were back to the main trail it had quickly passed and the  sun
was once more shining.  We had a good view down  the  Thunder  Creek  valley
and were surprised to see the smoke of  three  small  fires  on  the  wooded
flank of Primus Peak.  Presumably,  these  had  just  been  started  by  the
recent lightening.  I tried to make a call with  my  cell  phone  to  report
these fires but had no reception.

Before returning to camp, we continued the  short  distance  to  Park  Creek
Pass.  We then decided to move our camp to the official site  to  spend  our
second night (4700 ft and 11 hrs total for the peak and  pass).  That  night
we went to bed dreaming about getting trapped by  raging  forest  fires.  We
needn\'t have worried.  We were soon awakened by a violent thunderstorm  with
dozens of lightening strikes and heavy rain that just  hung  over  the  area
for a couple of hours. Finally it let up, but we were  further  awakened  by
two large icefalls off the Thunder Glacier, probably  caused  by  the  heavy
rain.  A very active night.

We awoke the next morning to clearing skies but very wet brush  that  soaked
us on the hike out.  However, we were happy to see that the fires  had  been
extinguished for the most part by the heavy rain  (18  miles,  1600  ft  and
9:30 hrs out).  48 miles, 11,500 ft total, - Fay Pullen,  Kent,  8/4-6/03.









