            'title' => ' Horseshoe Peak (8480+ feet) - August 11-12, 2004',
            'tr' => '

Horseshoe Peak (8480+ feet) - August 11-12, 2004


Last year I climbed Buckner and  Booker  from  a  camp  in  upper  Horseshoe
Basin.  At that time I was vaguely aware of Horseshoe Peak but  didn\'t  have
much information about it.  Descending  from  Buckner  I  looked  at  Ripsaw
Ridge but couldn\'t figure out which peak was  Horseshoe,  saw  nothing  that
had at least 400 feet of prominence and so passed it by. I later  found  out
that Horseshoe was one of the Bulger peaks even though it didn\'t  have  what
I thought was the required prominence. And so I now found  myself  returning
to Horseshoe Basin to climb this peak that  I  had  missed  the  first  time
around.

I again stopped at the Marblemount RS and got a permit to spend  two  nights
in the Buckner XC zone. I thought I could do the trip with  just  one  night
out but I wanted to allow myself plenty of time just to be sure.  I am  very
slow when doing roped solo climbing. I found out there was one  other  party
signed out for that zone. I wondered if I would run into them.

Starting at 11:30 I toiled slowly  up  the  well-trodden  trail  to  Cascade
Pass, burdened by a heavy pack, excessive heat and  biting  flies,  arriving
at the pass at 2:00. As before, I elected to approach from  lower  Horseshoe
Basin rather than over Sahale Arm, and so continued downhill  on  the  trail
toward Stehekin. A short ways below the pass I ran into  a  ranger  and  who
should he turn out to be but the one who checked me out two  weeks  ago  for
Goode.  He remembered me and asked how that climb went.  I told him  and  we
chatted for a while. Then, of course, he had to ask  if  I  had  the  proper
permits for this trip.  I think rangers are required  to  do  this.  But  he
asked politely and in a friendly  manner.   This  was  a  far  cry  from  my
experience last year when I  was  hassled  by  a  different  very  officious
ranger.  Shortly past the turnoff  to  Pelton  Basin  camp,  I  met  another
ranger and once again was asked about permits.  She too was friendly and  it
was no problem.

At the crossing of Doubtful Cr I stopped for lunch and to soak  my  feet  in
the inviting water. At 4:00 I reached the  Horseshoe  Basin  trail  junction
and started back uphill.  Near the head of the basin I  ran  into  a  couple
coming out. They were the other party signed out for this area.   They  were
trying to climb Buckner but gave up after not being able to find  the  route
from lower to upper Horseshoe Basin through the waterfall  filled  headwall.
They asked if I knew the way. I replied that I had been up it last year  but
it certainly was not obvious or easy. I told them I had gone up to the  left
of waterfalls and down to the right.  There was less brush to the  left  but
to the right was more direct. I planned to go up to the right this time.   I
tried to convince them to try again with me, that together  I  was  sure  we
could find a way up, but they were wiped out  and  psyched  out.   They  had
been going for 11 hours.  11 hours! They must have started at  6:00  in  the
morning. The fellow said they were following directions  and  GPS  waypoints
from Washington\'s Highest Mountains and were seriously  led  off  route  and
confused, battling brush for hours. I pointed out the route as best I  could
to them for a future attempt then wished them luck as  they  continued  out.
Too bad.  They seemed like a nice couple and  I  would  have  enjoyed  their
company.

At 5:00 I crossed Basin Cr by boulder hopping, getting one foot wet  in  the
process, and started up the headwall. After a short rocky  scramble  section
right above the creek, I followed a ramp toward  a  waterfall,  then  turned
right (a cairn here and odds and ends of old flagging) very  steeply  uphill
into dense scrub cedar to the left of a short cliff. Pulling  myself  bodily
up the ladder of brush, I soon emerged to more moderate terrain  and  picked
my way up avoiding more brush as much as possible. At one point I crossed  a
side creek. After about 800 ft of climbing  and  another  short  section  of
dense cedar I broke out into the open meadows of the upper  basin.  At  7:00
and 6000 ft I found a delightful level spot  on  a  slab  right  next  to  a
babbling brook to pitch my bivy tent  (10.5  miles,  3950  ft,  7.5  hrs).
Surprisingly there were no bugs and I spent a pleasant evening  enjoying  my
lovely surroundings.

I started at 7:00 the next morning,  wandering  up  heather  and  talus  and
scree toward Horseshoe and the very distinctive Lick of Flame spire  to  its
right. I was surprised at how little snow there was. At 9:00 I  reached  the
basin below these peaks and the first snow, much of which  was  melted  down
to water ice, so I stopped to put on crampons.  I probably could have  found
a way around the ice but I had lugged crampons up this far and  by  golly  I
was going to use them. I crossed the basin to the left  (west),  onto  steep
dirt to a notch on the south shoulder of  the  false  summit  of  Horseshoe,
down a few feet on the other side and around a corner  into  a  loose  sandy
gully leading to the notch between the main and false summits

At the notch I roped up and followed a ledge left across the east face to  a
final steep move to the summit ridge. The ledge  was  easy  enough  but  the
move to the ridge was a stretch for me and by this time  I  was  far  enough
out onto the east face that the drop straight down to the  gully  was  about
80 feet so I dinked around finding adequate protection. That done, I  pulled
myself over the edge right at a rappel sling wrapped around  a  large  chunk
of the narrow summit ridge.  To the right a few feet was  the  summit  cairn
and to the left a few feet was the  summit  register.  The  register  was  a
spiral notebook that was soggy and in part illegible. It was placed in  1995
and averaged one or at most two ascents a year. Some years had  no  ascents.
Once again I was the first to sign in this year right after  Don  Beavon  on
7/17/03.  I seem to be following in Don\'s footsteps on  many  peaks  lately,
though not deliberately.

The tiny summit was not  conducive  to  hanging  around,  so  after  briefly
taking in the views for 10 minutes (I was particularly interested in  Boston
Peak, still on my to do list.  It didn\'t look so bad from  this  aspect),  I
started down at 11:00. I had only brought a 120 ft rope  that  didn\'t  reach
all the way straight down to the gully, so after  rappelling  the  step  off
the ridge, I downclimbed the ledge back to the notch.  Another  rappel  from
the notch got me down the worst of the gully. I was back in camp at 1:00  (2
miles, 2350 ft, 6 hrs), early enough to continue out this day.

I started out at 2:30 and did a slightly better  job  of  routefinding  down
the headwall, avoiding all the brush except that particularly bad  patch  of
scrub cedar near the bottom. Slithering through that awful  stuff,  dangling
off brush belays I lost a water bottle out of the mesh  side  pocket  of  my
pack. It wasn\'t so much the loss of the bottle that bothered me  as  it  was
the loss of the grape cytomax  inside.  My  dry  thirsty  mouth  was  really
looking forward to that drink.

I reached the Horseshoe Basin trail at 4:00, the Stehekin trail at 4:45  and
started the hot grind back up to Cascade Pass. I  couldn\'t  resist  stopping
once again at Doubtful Cr to soak my feet. Just before Cascade  Pass  I  ran
into the female ranger I had met on the way in.  She seemed genuinely  happy
that I was successful and had made it out  O.K.  She  had  seen  the  couple
coming out the previous evening.  She offered to let  them  stay  at  Pelton
but they elected to go all the way to the TH, a very long day. She was  also
interested in how to get from lower to upper Horseshoe Basin stating that  I
was the only person she knew who had done it.  I replied that probably  most
parties climbing Buckner or Horseshoe approach from Sahale  Arm.  I  reached
Cascade Pass at 7:00, where I took a short rest, and the TH at  8:30  (10.5
miles, 1700 ft, 6 hrs)

Grand Total: 23 miles, 8000 ft

Fay Pullen












