            'tr' => '
Osceola Peak (8587 ft.), Mt. Carru (8595 ft.), Mt. Lago (8745 ft.),
Blackcap Mtn. (8397), Mt. Rolo (8096) - September 8-10, 2004

Day 1 - Osceola Peak: With showers predicted for the next  several  days,  I
headed for the hopefully drier Pasayten Wilderness.  I  had  never  been  to
Harts Pass and was very impressed with this high  mountain  road,  but  also
wondered why it was ever built and how much money it must cost  to  maintain
it.  Whatever the reason I  was  happy  to  use  it  to  get  closer  to  my
objectives and I enjoyed the beautiful views (except  for  the  recent  burn
just before the pass). From Harts Pass I drove toward Slate Peak and  parked
at the second switchback and the start of  the  Buckskin  trail  just  below
Slate Pass at 6900 ft.

Due to the long drive it was almost noon as  I  started  up  the  trail  the
short distance to the Pass.  It was sunny and  warm  to  begin,  but  clouds
were already beginning to form.  On  the  other  side  the  trail  descended
easily through lovely meadows to a junction with the  Middle  Fork  Pasayten
River trail, then more steeply down, down, down to a crossing of the  river.
More gentle downhill for miles along the river, past the Robinson  Pass  and
Ferguson Lake trails, to the junction with the trail to  Shellrock  Pass  at
5000 ft. Now back uphill to Freds Lake where it began to rain lightly.  More
uphill to Freds saddle crossing into the Eureka Cr  drainage  where  shortly
beyond I picked up the side trail to Doris Lake at 7000 ft and  camp.  (12.5
miles, 2700 ft, 5:40 hrs)

Most accommodatingly, the rain had stopped, making it much more pleasant  to
set up my tent. At 6:10 I started for Osceola  Pk.   There  were  two  other
parties camped at the lake but I only stopped to chat briefly  as  I  didn\'t
have much time to make my summit before dark. From the lake I made a  rising
rightward traverse toward the ridge until I  could  climb  directly  up  the
steep talus of the SW slope to the summit at 7:10 (1700 ft, 1  hr).  A  cold
wind was blowing but it still wasn\'t raining.  There was no  register  so  I
left one. I was back to the lake (2.5 miles, 2 hr RT) just as  it  got  dark
enough to need a headlamp. Passing  the  tent  of  a  couple,  this  time  I
stopped to chat. They were happy to see I was back safely from my  mad  dash
up Osceola. Immediately they asked me if I knew Grant Myers, with whom  they
were friends, and when I said yes, they were  not  surprised,  as  dedicated
peak baggers frequently know of each  other.  This  was  their  third  night
camped at the lake and they were headed out the next day. They professed  to
not be scramblers but could have fooled me  as  they  had  climbed  Osceola,
Lago and Rolo during their stay. I also passed the  second  party  and  they
too were glad I was back safe  and  sound.  How  nice  that  strangers  were
kindly keeping track of me.

By the time I got water from the lake and retreated into  my  tent  to  make
dinner it was raining again. But I  was  cozy  and  comfortable  in  my  new
Montbell tent. Expecting rain I had brought this tent to try  out.  This  is
the lightest double wall single person tent  that  I  have  found  that  has
enough room to sit up in comfortably and has no mesh in the inner walls.  It
cleverly uses only one pole and weighs under 3 pounds. I  was  very  pleased
with its performance, as I stayed dry and toasty during  a  night  of  heavy
rain and strong winds and had plenty of room to cook inside.

Day 2 - Mt Carru, Mt Lago, Blackcap  Mtn:  The  rain  had  diminished  to  a
drizzle when I started for these three peaks at 7:30 the next  morning.  But
the brush was saturated, so after an hour or so my  feet  were  soaking  wet
and I continued to slosh in soggy socks the rest of the  day.   Why  oh  why
didn\'t I wear my Gore-Tex boots? I began by descending  to  the  main  trail
and following it maybe Â½ mile to a switchback. The trail drops some  800  ft
from this point to Eureka Cr. I  hoped  to  avoid  this  elevation  loss  by
climbing directly up to the W ridge of Carru.  I\'m  not  sure  I  saved  any
time or energy doing this but it made for a  much  more  interesting  route.
From the switchback I climbed up heather and meadows  to  the  saddle  below
the boilerplate cliffs of Osceola\'s E face. Trying to avoid  gaining  excess
elevation over Pt 7929, I was able to traverse  downward  between  7600  and
7400 ft on the S slope until I was past a  second  bump  on  the  ridge  and
could access the SW ridge of Carru.  Once on this ridge I worked my  way  up
talus and broken rock into loose gullies leading  past  small  pinnacles  to
the W ridge. Drizzle had now changed to light snow and  fog.  Wet,  slippery
black lichen covered rock made the traverse along the narrow ridge  somewhat
treacherous the last bit to the summit (3 miles, 2370 ft, 3:15 hr). A  large
register placed 7/21/93 by Mike Torok graced the summit  cairn.  There  were
only a few ascents each year and I recognized  entries  by  Don  and  Natala
Goodman (9/7/93), Mitch Blanton (8/21/95), Paul  Klenke  (8/21/01)  and  Don
Beavon (7/9/03). Mine was only the second ascent this year  after  one  made
just two days earlier on 9/7/04.

From the summit I continued down the normal ascent route along the  E  ridge
then descended S alongside cliffs to 7100 ft to get past a  rocky  buttress.
Crossing well below the Carru-Lago saddle, I climbed up to  the  S  spur  of
Lago and picked up a faint way trail that came and went. Fresh  tracks  were
probably made by the Doris Lake couple. I made the summit of  Lago  at  1:25
(5 miles, 4000 ft, 5:55 hr) where another register placed by Mike  Torok  on
the same day as Carru awaited me.  Lago is climbed more  often  than  Carru,
probably because it is higher, and  there  were  several  entries  for  2004
alone, plus all those who had signed in on the previous  peak.  The  weather
was now improving, it had stopped precipitating and views were beginning  to
appear.  Before I left I could see the summits of Osceola, Carru,  Ptarmigan
and Blackcap, my next objective.

To get to Blackcap I had hoped to traverse as high  as  possible  SE  toward
Shellrock Pass. But surveying the terrain between me  and  the  pass  I  was
dismayed at how unfriendly it looked. Several  ugly  gullies  and  frightful
rocky ribs stood in the way. Yet descending back the way I had come  and  on
down to the trail was not appealing either. So I decided to stick  with  the
original plan and let the chips fall where they may.  It would  either  play
out or it wouldn\'t. I began by following the SE  ridge  on  the  very  crest
until past the first gully. I was then able to descend  a  rib  between  two
gullies S down to about 7200  ft  at  which  point  I  could  begin  a  long
descending traverse across several more gullies and talus slope after  talus
slope to finally end up in the meadows below the pass at 7000  ft.   Shortly
after I ran into the trail which I followed only  a  short  distance  before
leaving it at a switchback and beginning the  climb  to  the  notch  in  the
ridge just E of Blackcap. More talus, but this talus was actually fun for  a
while as it consisted of large flat stable white rocks that I  could  almost
dance across. Alas,  the  talus  turned  more  unpleasant  and  loose  as  I
approached the notch.

From the notch, I scrambled the narrow ridge or just left of it to a  higher
notch below the final summit rocks. A short class 3 scramble put me  on  top
of Blackcap at 5:00 (8 miles, 5360 ft, 9:30 hr). I  was  thankful  that  the
rocks on this final bit had dried out in  the  now  sunny  weather.  Another
Mike Torok register awaited me on the summit, but this one had  been  placed
on a different outing from Lago and Carru on 7/3/95. I didn\'t take the  time
to peruse it very closely but did note that the  peak  wasn\'t  climbed  that
often, there being only one entry for 2003 and mine the only one  for  2004.
The only other entry that caught my  eye  was  Mitch  Blanton\'s  of  8/21/95
where he had already climbed Osceola, Carru and Lago  and  was  then  on  to
Lake! And I thought I was doing well to get three peaks in a day.

I quickly left hoping I could get back to camp before dark.  I  didn\'t  make
it. I hit the trail at 6:20 thinking I had  it  made.   But  parts  of  this
trail are very faint, especially through  meadows  where  it  is  marked  by
cairns, and at times I was in danger of losing  it.  It  would  be  hard  to
follow in the dark. The trail dropped to 5800 ft, then climbed 1200 ft  back
to Doris Lake.  During the last part I had to use my  headlamp  reaching  my
tent at 8:30 (15 miles, 6600 ft, 13 hrs).

Day 3 - Mt Rolo: That night was cold and  clear  with  a  light  frost,  the
first for me of the season. I was packed and on  my  way  by  8:30.  At  the
saddle overlooking Freds Lake, I stashed my  overnight  pack  and  continued
with a very light daypack. From there I  contoured  around  Pt  7442  on  an
unpleasant traverse, to the broad saddle N of the peak  where  there  was  a
dried up tarn. I picked up a climber\'s trail that led up meadows  and  talus
to the N ridge at a notch. I slipped a few times before realizing there  was
a light coating of frost on the rocks still  in  the  shade  that  warranted
careful foot placement. A steep step with class 3 scrambling led to  a  flat
shoulder and more talus to a  second  notch.  From  here  the  summit  block
looked quite formidable, but a traverse on the W  side  gave  access  to  an
easy scree slope that put me back on the ridge and a third notch.  This  was
turning out to be a  much  more  interesting  climb  than  I  had  expected.
Another traverse on the W and a steep loose gully put me  on  top  at  10:00
(1200 ft, 1 hr). Although there were signs that this peak is often  climbed,
with a discernable climber\'s trail most of the way, there was  no  register,
so I left one.

I was back to my overnight pack by 11:20 (2.5 miles RT),  climbing  over  Pt
7442 this time to avoid the unpleasant traverse around  it.   I  relaxed  in
the sun eating lunch and enjoying the sunny views before starting  the  trip
out at 12:00. During the hike out, the weather gradually  deteriorated.   By
the time I reached the car at 5:45,  it  had  begun  to  rain  again.  (12.5
miles, 2500 ft, 6:00 hr total from Lake Doris).

Grand Total: 45 miles and 14,700 feet

Fay Pullen






