            'title' => 'Lake Mountain (8371) and Monument Peak (8592) - September 15-17, 2004 h, never did shed its mantle of fog. At',
            'tr' => '

Lake Mountain (8371) and Monument Peak (8592) - September 15-17, 2004


With another week  of  unsettled  weather  predicted  it  was  back  to  the
Pasayten Wilderness again where if the weather didn\'t  turn  out  to  be  an
improvement over the West side at least the peaks are generally easy  enough
to be done in any event, or so I thought.  It was also the  opening  day  of
the High Hunt on September 15.  For these reasons I chose  the  Monument  Cr
trail which I knew would not be accessible to  horse  packers  and  hunters.
Even so I ran into one horse party camped at Eureka Cr  about  4  miles  in.
The trail to this point, which I reached at 1:00 (450 ft, 1:40  hr),  is  in
very good shape and a pleasure to hike, even in the  light  rain  I  had  to
start. From here on the trail is unmaintained and impassible to horses.

After a quick lunch at the  sturdy  bridge  over  Eureka  Cr,  I  began  the
grueling climb of some 4000 ft up the ridge  between  that  creek  and  Lost
River. At least it wasn\'t hot, even though it had  quit  raining  and  there
were now even a few sun breaks.   The  trail  began  with  long  switchbacks
across talus, but soon  deteriorated  to  a  steep  track  straight  up  the
hillside. After about 2000 ft gain, the ridge leveled out  briefly  where  I
lost the trail in thick wet snowbrush. I thrashed  around  a  bit,  but  was
soon back on track for another 1000 ft of steep gain after which  the  ridge
laid back for a couple of miles of gentler  ascent.  On  this  section  many
small downed crisscrossed trees made for tedious progress. At  an  elevation
of 6400 ft, the  trail  began  a  long,  seemingly  endless,  traverse  left
beneath Pistols Peaks before making the final 600 ft climb  to  Pistol  Pass
at 7000 ft. The trail on this traverse is in very good shape. Too  bad  this
trail is now unmaintained. Much of the tread is still quite  good  and  with
minimal work and log cutting it could be made very usable again.

More good trail descended the other side of the pass  in  long  switchbacks.
Here I ran into remnants of fresh snow. I left  the  trail  at  one  of  the
switchbacks after the slope lessened and I could  begin  traversing  through
open forest to Lake of the Woods which is 600 ft below and .7 mile from  the
pass.  I later found out that a way trail leads to  the  lake  from  farther
down the trail.  This junction is lower than the lake, so one has  to  climb
back up to it, but it avoids some of the steep  sidehill  I  encountered.  I
arrived at the lovely lake at 7:00 (12 miles, 5500 ft, 7:40 hr) just  as  it
began to rain again and with just enough light to set  up  camp.  It  rained
steadily most of that night.

I awoke the next morning to cloudy skies but no rain and  enough  visibility
to see where I was going. I left camp at 8:00 heading for  the  E  ridge  of
Lake Mountain through open woods and talus. A mostly solid gully with  rocky
ledges provided a fun scramble to the ridge.  The higher I climbed the  more
snow I encountered, but  it  didn\'t  present  any  great  problems  on  this
section. At 9:45 I topped out on the summit of Lake  (1750  ft,  1:45).  The
register was placed 5/29/88 by the  BoeAlps.   I  had  trouble  opening  the
screw lid as it was  frozen  shut.   I  was  finally  able  to  open  it  by
breathing on the threads and melting the ice. The booklet  inside  was  damp
and rather fragile so I didn\'t examine it closely. I did note Don Beavon  on
8/9/03 and two climbs for 2004.

I was now a little uncertain how to proceed to Monument. I had Don\'s  report
of last year where he climbed the E ridge. But that is rated class  3-4  and
Don stated he had to take care on it so I knew I didn\'t want  try  it  under
the present wet conditions.  I also had the route described in  Washington\'s
Highest Mountains, but that involved descending a disheartening 2000  ft  to
access the S ridge at 6400 ft.  I had hoped to find a way onto the  S  ridge
higher up (Beckey mentions a vague gully at 7800 ft) and to locate  a  route
visually from Lake, but the upper part of Monument was shrouded in  fog  and
I couldn\'t see anything. Well, I would just begin  by  descending  Lake\'s  N
ridge and hope something would work out.

Just getting off of Lake was not that easy.  I began down the  N  ridge  but
was soon stopped by icy ledges at a rappel sling. Under dry conditions  they
looked like they could be downclimbed, but I wasn\'t going to risk  it  under
the current conditions. This was one time, trying to save weight, I did  not
bring a thin rope. I was beginning to regret this decision. I  would  regret
it even more later. Although these are just scrambles  I  should  have  know
better.  Even Don took a rope along, just in case.

So it was back uphill to find a safer way down, which  I  did  more  to  the
west, though I still ran into some iced up rock. Eventually I worked my  way
back to the N ridge below the difficulties and followed this  ridge  to  the
head of the basin below Monument.  By now visibility  was  improving  and  I
thought I could see a broad gully that would get me onto the  S  ridge,  but
as I traversed around the head of the basin at the  base  of  the  cliffs  I
couldn\'t locate anything that seemed reasonable.  All I  saw  was  an  awful
looking rocky headwall. Continuing the traverse, I did come to  a  break  in
the cliffs, though I don\'t think this was what I saw from afar.  Once  below
it, I saw it was a steep narrow gully, definitely class  4  at  least,  that
looked like it might go, but I wasn\'t sure.  Did I  really  want  to  commit
myself to this thing without a rope?  I considered my options.  There  might
be another gully farther downhill. Then again there might not.  Or  I  could
descend all the way to  toe  of  the  ridge  at  6400  ft  from  my  present
elevation of 7900 ft, a sure but unappealing option.  In the end  I  decided
to give the gully a try.

I climbed into the gully and up a few feet to check it out. It  only  looked
a hundred feet or so to the ridge crest.  But soon the gully  steepened  and
I was forced onto the right wall on broken rock.  The rock was wet  but  not
icy, so I continued up slowly and carefully, testing each  hold.  I  knew  I
was running it out and with each move it  would  become  harder  to  reverse
myself if I reached an impasse.  I still couldn\'t see if  the  very  top  of
the gully would go. I would have felt so much better if only  I  had  had  a
rope to facilitate retreat. I worked my way back into the  gully  above  the
vertical section and finally saw the final  bit  was  an  8  ft  open  book.
Tackling the smooth rock  with  all  the  fervor  of  a  possibly  condemned
person, I launched myself upward, grabbed a thank god hold at  the  top  and
hauled myself over the edge.  What greeted me was  the  sweet  sight  of  an
easy romp on snow-covered talus the last 500 feet to the summit.  I  was  on
the S ridge! Even in my relief and joy at success, I  chastised  myself  for
being so extended.  Yes, the route did go.  But it could just  as  well  not
have and where would that have left me? It was really a  dumb  thing  to  do
and I vowed to be more prudent in the future.

I was on the summit of Monument at 1:40 (3100 ft, 5:40).  This  had  another
BoeAlps register placed 9/19/94. Entries  were  by  Grant  Meyers  (7/2/95),
Paul Klenke (8/24/01), Don Beavon (8/9/03) and two others for 2004.  I  must
make special mention of Mitch Blanton\'s 8/22/95 climb.   This  was  part  of
his marathon where he approached from Slate Pass on 8/20,  climbed  Osceola,
Carru, Lago, Blackcap and Lake  on  8/21  (noticed  during  my  climbs  last
week), and Monument on 8/22 continuing out the same day via  S  Fork  Eureka
Cr. He stated he was getting old and wanted to do a marathon  while  he  was
still able! I should say!

The weather had continued to clear sufficiently that I had decent views  and
could see north to Rolo, Osceola, Carru, Lago, and Blackcap, all  the  peaks
I had climbed last week, and Lost, yet to do.  They  were  all  coated  with
fresh snow on their upper levels. Robinson, to the  south,  never  did  shed
its mantle of fog. At 2:00 I started down intending to follow  the  S  ridge
and what I thought would be easy terrain.  I had had enough  challenges  for
the day. But the S ridge didn\'t turn out to the piece of  cake  anticipated.
I guess I didn\'t follow it far enough. I exited it  as  soon  as  it  seemed
reasonable, at about 7000 ft, but got hung up in a series of  broken  cliffs
that led to one dead end after another. Up and down  I  went  casting  about
for a way down.  At one point  I  was  within  30  feet  of  the  talus  but
couldn\'t get down that last bit.  Again I regretted not having a  rope.   To
make matters worse the weather was deteriorating once again and it began  to
rain.

I finally made it down, crossed the lower basin at 6200 ft,  and  began  the
climb back up a series of ribs and gullies to the 7400 ft  notch  in  the  S
ridge of Lake directly above Lake of the Woods. The rain had now  turned  to
wet snow. I reached my tent at 6:40 (8 miles, 4600 ft, 10:40 hr) rather  wet
and bedraggled. Having learned my lesson from last week, on this trip I  was
wearing my Gore-Tex boots so at least I wasn\'t sloshing in soggy socks.  All
thoughts of having a pleasant dinner outside enjoying the view of  the  lake
vanished as I retreated to the shelter of my tent. It snowed  most  of  that
night.

It was still snowing in the morning when I packed up and left  at  8:40  and
several more inches had accumulated on the ground. By  the  time  I  reached
the main Lost-Eureka divide at 11:00 clearing was occurring  again.  Partial
views toward my peaks revealed a fresh coating of snow, now a little  whiter
and a little lower than before. At this rate these high peaks will  soon  be
inaccessible. I was witnessing the coming of winter and I am not  yet  ready
for it. I reached the bridge over Eureka Cr at 1:40, where I stopped  for  a
long rest, and the car at 3:40 (12 miles, 1400 ft, 7 hrs).

Grand total: 32 miles and 11, 500 ft.

Fay Pullen












