Luahna Peak (8400+ feet) and Chalangin Peak (8360+ feet) - September 23-25,
2004


These are the unofficial names of the two peaks on the ridge between Clark
and Tenpeak Mountains in the Glacier Peak Wilderness Area.

I got a late start and traffic  was  terrible  getting  out  of  town  on  a
Thursday morning heading up I-405. Then I was stopped twice  near  the  town
of Skykomish where they are doing work to stabilize cliffs above Highway  2.
I also made a stop at the Lake Wenatchee RS to pick up a  Golden  Age  Pass.
I had just passed my  62nd  birthday,  which  makes  me  eligible  for  this
lifetime pass to federal fee areas (including Forest  Service  and  National
Park). Age does have its privileges. So it was noon by the  time  I  started
up the White River trail. But it was less than 10 miles to where  I  planned
to camp in the basin below Luahna Pk and I felt I had plenty of time to  get
there.

The High Hunt was still in effect,  and  the  trail  showed  signs  of  much
recent horse travel, but all of it turned off  onto  the  trail  to  Boulder
Pass, 4.1 miles in. Beyond here, where I stopped to have  lunch,  there  was
very little sign of any traffic of any kind and I saw no one. From here  the
trail leaves the woods and enters a series of meadows where it is  overgrown
with brush.  On this warm and sunny day (finally  some  good  weather),  the
brush was no problem, but if  wet  would  be  unpleasant  (as  I  found  out
later). At 6.4 miles I crossed Thunder Cr. The crossing is  washed  out  and
the bridge on a tilt but still usable and presented no great problem.

About .7 mile farther (20 minutes), on  a  straight  level  section  of  the
trail at 2800 ft, I began  looking  for  the  old  sheep  drive  trail  into
Thunder Basin.  There was supposed to be a tree marked with an arrow at  the
spot but I never found anything.  I gave up and  just  headed  uphill  at  a
likely spot and hoped for the best.  Sure enough, after a short while I  ran
into the trail.  I was surprised at  how  good  this  trail  is  and  easily
followed it up to 3650 ft where I found another more obscure  trail  leading
right toward Thunder Cr. It first went down  slightly  into  woods,  skirted
the top of a meadow and entered alder brush. From the  meadow  I  could  see
across the valley to the waterfall creek draining the basin below Luahna.  I
was led to believe that the route to the basin goes up  the  right  side  of
this creek. But the alder at this point was awful and getting to  the  creek
would be trying. The trail continued upstream so I  decided  to  follow  it.
Where it entered woods again, it was very near Thunder Cr and a faint  trail
led directly to it at a reasonable crossing via an alder  branch  and  rocks
at 3800 ft. On the other side I found myself in a large meadow on  the  left
side of the waterfall creek with no easy way to get to the right side.

Deciding I was stuck, I headed uphill to the left  of  the  waterfall  creek
toward a break in the brush. To my surprise, this  route  worked  out  quite
well. The initial brush only lasted a few hundred feet  until  I  broke  out
into a large open slabby rock area. I worked my way up staying close to  the
creek (on the way down I found it was better farther to the  left)  until  I
could enter woods above.  Here  a  series  of  climber?-animal?  trails  led
upward until at about 5100 ft I could traverse rightward on a  fern  covered
hillside with many small downed trees into the large  gorgeous  open  grassy
basin. At 6:30 I found a delightful campsite in the upper part of the  basin
at 5200 ft between two creeks (9.5 miles, 3000 ft, 6:30 hr)
.
I find it difficult to get out of a toasty sleeping bag  when  it  is  still
dark out.  These days it doesn\'t get light much before 7:00, so it was  8:00
before I got going the next morning, not the early start I wanted if  I  was
to do this climb in two days. But it was a gorgeous sunny day.   I  couldn\'t
ask for anything better.

Both Beckey and Washington\'s Highest Mountains leave big gaps in  the  route
description to the actual summit of Luahna. I had  very  little  information
from this point on except that the route was supposed to  be  easy  and  all
above timberline and a gully led to the top. The first problem  was  to  get
out of the basin. It was ringed with cliffs and although the  cliffs  didn\'t
look that steep they were covered with dense brush.  Maybe the book  writers
climbed the peak when all the brush was covered with snow. Some  6  separate
waterfalls cascaded down  the  cliffs.   Counting  from  left  to  right,  I
thought I could see a possible  route  connecting  semi-open  areas  between
waterfalls 3 and 4. That is where I headed, working my way  from  open  area
to open area as best I could, but I actually ran  into  some  of  the  worse
brush of the trip in this section.

Fortunately it was short and I soon popped out into the  meadows  above  the
cirque. From here I wandered up pleasant  terrain  toward  the  snow-covered
talus slopes below the SW escarpment of Luahna. I began  running  into  snow
about 7000 ft. I thought I could see a  gully  leading  through  the  cliffs
near the top of the talus slope but as I got closer it looked  wet  and  not
all that inviting. However, slightly below, a broad ramp led  right  through
the cliffs and up onto a gentle  snow-covered  slope  at  7900  ft.  From  I
worked my way farther right on snowy ledges to the S ridge at 8200  ft  just
above a small pinnacle. I then followed the crest of the  exposed  ridge  to
the summit at 11:15 (3200 ft, 3:15 hr).

The register was placed by Mike Torok 9/5/93 (I do believe Mike  has  placed
90% of the registers in the Cascades!). Don Goodman\'s film can  register  of
8/28/93 was transcribed. Other entries: Grant Myers 8/29/94,  Mitch  Blanton
(on to Chalangin and Tenpeak) 9/20/98,  Jim  Brisbine  and  Laura  Zimmerman
9/23/00, Don Beavon (I remember reading his account where one member of  his
party slipped on snow and self-arrested at the last moment  before  "certain
death") 11/30/02, Paul Klenke 8/20/03. There were two parties for 2004.

I took in the absolutely  stunning  view  of  Glacier  Peak  all  white  and
pristine under a fresh coat of white, and Clark  and  all  the  other  peaks
near and far. But  mostly  I  had  eyes  for  Chalangin.  It  looked  rather
fearsome from this vantage, harder than I expected.  But I thought  I  could
pick out a possible  route.  After  30  minutes  on  top,  I  started  down,
retracing my steps.  At the base  of  the  ramp,  at  7700  ft,  I  began  a
traverse toward Chalangin. I climbed to the saddle  between  the  two  peaks
but soon decided I  couldn\'t  follow  the  ridge.  I  continued  on  a  high
traverse on the left (S) side, up and down across gullies and  ribs  passing
three pinnacles. The traverse went on longer than  expected.  Naturally  the
summit was at the far end of the ridge. And for  all  the  rocky  terrain  I
worked my way past, the summit itself ended up being a  nondescript  rounded
bump, somewhat of an anticlimax, which I reached  at  1:45  (4000  ft,  5:45
hr). There was a cairn but no register so I left one.  15  minutes  later  I
started down.  I dearly wanted to find a direct  route  straight  down  from
the summit to the talus, but I couldn\'t take that chance with  no  knowledge
and no view from afar to confirm it possible.  So I retraced  the  traverse.
I was back to the talus in an hour. I missed the route I had  taken  up  the
cirque and ended up going down between waterfalls 4 and 5.  It  worked  out,
despite dense brush near the bottom.

I was now way behind schedule to go all the way out today. I  figured  if  I
got to camp by 3:00, 4:00 at the absolute latest, I could still make  it  to
the White River trail by dark.  I got back to camp at 4:15  (5  miles,  4100
ft, 8:15 hr), so I decided to stay another night.  No one  was  waiting  for
me at home except my kitty.   He  would  survive.  So  I  spent  a  glorious
afternoon basking in the sun reading, sketching and just  relaxing.  A  nice
change from always being on the go.

I was on my way the next morning at 7:15.  It is a little easier to  get  up
early when you have gone to bed the night  before  at  7:00.   There  was  a
heavy dew this morning and I had to pack up a wet tent.  I  had  no  trouble
getting down to the crossing of Thunder Creek, even finding  an  easier  way
down the slabby rock. I still ran into dense brush near the  bottom  but  it
was short.  I crossed Thunder creek at exactly the same place.   I  followed
the old sheep drive all the way to the White River trail,  which  I  reached
at 9:00. It was very good all the way except for the last  hundred  feet  or
so where it was obscured by several large logs. The junction is marked by  a
leaning cut stump and a gray blaze on a large tree.

I hiked the remaining 7.1 miles without a rest arriving at the TH  at  11:50
(9.5 miles, 300 ft, 4:35 hr). The dew was  especially  heavy  in  the  river
valley and the wet brush between Thunder and Boulder Cr  saturated  my  feet
and legs. I once again squished in soggy socks all the way out.   Even  when
the weather is good I still manage to get wet!

Grand Total: 24 miles and 7400 feet

Fay Pullen





