Ptarmigan Peak (8614 feet) and Lost Peak (8464 feet) - September 28-30,
2004


With an extended stretch of good weather in the forecast, I could  have  set
my sights on any number  of  technically  challenging  summits,  but  I  had
unfinished business in the Pasayten. Ptarmigan Peak and Lost Peak  were  the
last two Top 100 I needed to climb in that area.  Both  are  easy  scrambles
but in remote territory and hard to get  to.   The  challenge  would  be  in
combining them in one, hopefully three day, trip.  I came up with a plan  to
do just that, but it involved a  carry  over  Ptarmigan,  cross  country  to
Butte Pass, a dash up Lost, and out over Shellrock Pass.   To  this  end,  I
went as light as possible - an 8 oz bivy sack, a 1 lb sleeping bag, an 8  oz
siltarp just in case the weather report was wrong, and just enough  clothing
to get by.  No book, no sketchpad.  I wouldn\'t have time to read or  sketch.
 Every waking moment I would be on the go.  The plan was to hike as  far  as
possible each day and just bed down  whenever  I  ran  out  of  daylight  or
energy. I didn\'t weigh my pack but it must have been around 20 pounds.

I wanted to do this trip in three days, that was part of the challenge,  but
I was prepared to take four if necessary.  When  I  started  adding  up  the
mileages and elevation gains, I began having serious doubts. (As  an  aside,
the  mileage  listed  for  Ptarmigan  in  75  Scrambles  is  in  error   and
inconsistent. Some 3-5 miles each way must be added to the  total  depending
upon whether you believe  the  text  or  the  summary.  It  is  20.1  miles,
according to GT maps, to the saddle between Tatoosh Buttes, not 14.9  or  17
as stated.)  Success would hinge on two main factors - how far I  could  get
the first day and how difficult the cross-country section between  Ptarmigan
and Butte Pass would be. I had to get to Tatoosh Buttes the first day  if  I
had any chance at all.

I was out the door at 5:30 am. I am not, nor  have  ever  been,  a  painless
early riser so this was very good for me. That put me on the Buckskin  trail
from Slate Pass at 10:45. The day was  warm  and  sunny  and  I  started  in
shorts. Since my last visit here 3 weeks ago, the larches had  turned  color
and  I  began  my  descent  to  the  Middle  Fork  Pasayten  trail   through
spectacular golden groves. I  love  autumn  (when  the  weather  is  good!).
There are no bugs, few people (I saw no one this whole trip. There  was  not
even another car at the TH.), pleasant temperatures and gorgeous scenery.

The descending trail made for rapid progress,  with  one  caveat.  The  High
Hunt had ended the previous weekend, and the heavy horse traffic  that  this
generated, plus the recent rains, had turned sections  of  the  trail  to  a
lumpy, muddy mess that sucked up mere boots. On and on  I  hiked  for  miles
down the Middle Fork, past the Robinson Pass trail (4 miles) and  the  trail
to Shellrock Pass (9.1 miles, where I had a quick  lunch)  until  I  thought
for sure I was going to end up in Canada. River trails always  seem  endless
to me. At last I came to the marked trail to Tatoosh Buttes  at  4:35  (14.1
miles, 680 ft, 5:50 hr). One mile farther I crossed Lease Cr and  filled  up
on water. I wasn\'t sure I would find water any  higher.  It  was  now  after
5:00 and I still had 5 miles and over 2500 feet of elevation gain to get  to
the Buttes.  I was running out of time.

The trail suddenly tilted straight up and climbed very  steeply  through  an
old burn for several miles.  I caught glimpses of Tatoosh  Buttes,  Tamarack
Ridge and Ptarmigan Peak. They all still seemed very far away.  Just  before
7:00, at 6400 ft on the crest of a spur ridge, I  put  on  warmer  clothing,
took off my sunglasses, got out my headlamp and prepared to continue  hiking
as long as possible. In fading light, I hiked on into  more  and  more  open
country.  And then a most wonderful thing occurred. The full  moon  appeared
and turned the meadows to magic. I didn\'t even need a headlamp.  I  followed
the trail all the way to Tatoosh Buttes, even climbing  the  higher  of  the
two (7245 ft), and continued cross-country to  the  next  saddle  along  the
ridge where I found a wonderful grassy flat spot to lay my sleeping  bag  at
8:35 (21 miles, 3800 ft, 9:50 hr). I ate dinner by moonlight  on  this  most
magical and unforgettable of nights. I  was  pleased  to  have  gotten  even
farther than I had hoped.

I awoke the next morning to enchanting  surroundings.  Ptarmigan  may  be  a
walkup (a horse trail can be followed most of  the  way)  but  it  is  worth
every effort to get  to.   Extensive  friendly  meadows,  miles  of  rolling
ridges, and golden larch groves as far as the eye  could  see,  all  with  a
back drop of the rugged north cliffs of Osceola,  Carru  and  Lago  made  me
think I was in heaven.  Some  day,  when  climbing  peaks  no  longer  seems
important, I will return to this area just to wander and enjoy.

I began by meandering below Tamarack Ridge  toward  the  broad  saddle  with
Ptarmigan.  On the way I came across a trickle of water,  the  first  I  had
found since Lease Cr, and was able to augment  my  dwindling  supply.  In  a
reprieve from winter weather, most of the  recent  snows  had  melted,  with
only an odd patch left here and there. Climbing over Point 7748 and  up  the
easy ridge, I reached the summit of Ptarmigan at 9:50 (1650 ft,  2  hr).   I
left a register, as there was none.  I could see over to Butte  Pass  ridge.
It looked very inviting but a long ways away. I continued on the easy  ridge
descending to the saddle with Dot Mountain (8220 ft) and climbing that  peak
before descending steep loose scree to lovely Dot Lake for  lunch  and  much
needed water at noon.

From the lake I contoured at about 6900  ft  through  surprisingly  friendly
terrain to hit the ridge above Ptarmigan Cr just  SW  of  Pt  6946.  So  far
things were going very well. A steep narrow gully led off the ridge  to  the
creek basin below where I hoped to pick up the trail to Butte Pass.  But  in
the basin I ran into a tangle of  brush  and  downed  trees  and  floundered
around for an hour and a half trying to find the trail.  I  could  feel  the
time slipping away and had almost resigned myself to needing  an  extra  day
when, at 2:30 I stumbled across the trail.  I  was  back  in  business.  The
trail, though unmaintained and with numerous logs  across  it,  was  a  vast
improvement over what I had been going through and I easily followed it  for
another half hour to where it begins a traverse west to Butte Pass.  Here  I
left the trail and contoured around Pt 7275 to the saddle to the east  where
I found a pleasant bivy spot (10 miles, 3400 ft,  7:30  hr).  There  was  no
water but I had filled up at Ptarmigan Cr earlier.

Leaving behind all bivy gear, I started for Lost Pk with  a  lightened  pack
at 3:30 figuring I would be cutting it close to  get  back  before  dark.  I
followed the ridge toward Pass Butte,  then  contoured  below  it  around  a
corner and across talus past a saddle to the NW ridge of Lost Pk, which  was
then followed to the summit at 5:30 (1600 ft, 2 hr from bivy site).  I  left
a register in the cairn right next to the survey marker.  A  cold  wind  was
now blowing at about 30 mph and higher gusts threatened to blow me  off  the
ridge crest on the way down. This time I climbed over Pass Butte (8140  ft),
which I think was faster than contouring around it. I  arrived  back  at  my
camp at 7:15 in fading light (15 miles, 5400 ft, 11:20 hr for the day).

I spent a chilly windy night and kept thinking it was light  enough  to  get
up only to realize the brightness was the moon. I finally  awakened  in  the
morning after dreaming I had slept  till  1:00  pm.   It  was  7:00  am,  28
degrees and my sleeping bag was covered with ice crystals. I began  the  day
wearing all the clothing I  had  brought.   I  returned  to  the  trail  and
followed it to Butte Pass, descended down the other side  to  intersect  the
trail to Shellrock Pass and ascended  to  the  pass  through  more  gorgeous
meadows at 10:00. Gradually during the ascent I began  shedding  clothes  as
both I and the day warmed up. From the pass I could see most of the peaks  I
had climbed in the past few weeks, Rolo,  Osceola,  Carru,  Lago,  Blackcap,
Lake, Monument, Ptarmigan and Lost. They all felt like old friends now,  and
yet I felt a moment of regret at having climbed them all with none  left  to
do.  Then I cheered up thinking of all the lower peaks I could  still  climb
that would give me an excuse to come back to this lovely area (Do  I  really
need an "excuse" to come back?).

On the other side of the pass I was  soon  on  familiar  territory  from  my
previous trip. It was now just a matter of putting in the required  time  to
hike the long distance out. I reached Freds  Pass  at  12:45,  the  Paysaten
River trail at 2:00, Robinson Pass trail at 4:10 and  the  TH  at  6:20  (20
miles, 4800 ft, 10:30 hr).

Grand Total: 56 miles and 14,000 feet

Fay Pullen



