Greenwood Mountain (8415 feet) - October 9-10, 2004


Locked into a weekend (I  am  usual  out  during  the  week)  with  an  iffy
forecast by family commitments, I arrived at the Phelps Creek  TH  at  11:30
to light sprinkles and fresh snow on  the  higher  mountains.  The  previous
several days had been heavy rain. Five cars were parked in the  lot.  I  met
four of the five parties who belonged to said vehicles coming out as I  made
my way up the trail. Two were  coming  out  early,  chased  away  from  more
ambitious plans by the bad weather. One fellow had already spent two  nights
in Spider Meadow with pouring rain. He had had enough.  Another  couple  was
retreating from Leroy Basin where the original intention had been  to  climb
Maude and Seven Fingered Jack. Camped higher, they had been  snowed  on  the
previous night. Being fellow climbers, I stopped to  chat  with  them.  When
asked what I was climbing I told them  Greenwood.  They  were  not  familiar
with it, so I identified  it  as  the  peak  behind  Dumbbell.  They  seemed
intrigued and said they would have to check it out on a  map.  Then,  seeing
that I was alone, the woman asked very seriously in a stern  tone  of  voice
if I had told anyone where I was  going.  She  came  on  so  strong  that  I
replied, "What are you, my Mother?"  She answered, "Yes."  I really took  no
offense at this. I just thought it was funny a complete  stranger  would  be
so concerned and take it upon herself to chastise me. As a matter  of  fact,
my family knew exactly where I was and what I was doing this time, but I  do
admit that for some simpler outings I don\'t always  bother  telling  someone
personally (although I always leave a note at  home).  So  she  did  have  a
point. A person alone should always let someone know where they  are  going.
This led to a discussion of the fellow  who  had  recently  been  lost  near
Colchuck Lake and could not be found because no one knew where he  was.  And
then to the couple querying themselves if they  had  informed  anyone  where
they were going. Just because there were two of them didn\'t mean  they  were
immune to mishap. We parted friends and  I  continued  up  the  trail  still
chuckling to myself.

I set up camp on a flat grassy  site  just  inside  Phelps  Basin  at  3:30,
elevation 5400 feet (7 miles, 1900 ft, 3:15 hr).  I  crawled  into  my  tent
just in time as the light sprinkles turned to heavier showers, ate an  early
dinner and went to sleep at 7:00.  It rained most of the night, which  meant
it snowed at higher elevations.

I started next morning at 7:30.  It had quit raining  and  begun  to  clear.
The route to Greenwood has been described several times  recently  in  other
trip reports so I won\'t repeat it.  I began to run  into  fresh  snow  about
6000 feet and by the time I got to the talus basin below Dumbbell there  was
several inches of the wet treacherous white stuff  covering  the  rocks.  My
biggest fear, of course, was if I would be able to traverse the  goat  ledge
with fresh snow on it. At the notch I made a slight error in route  finding.
I was under the (mistaken) impression that I had to  descend  the  gully  on
the other side a short ways to access the ledge. In  retrospect,  I  believe
that the ledge everyone talks about  starts  from  the  same  level  as  the
notch, and in fact I found this ledge on the way back.  My  error  may  have
been a fortunate one though, as this ledge looked  challenging  and  exposed
in the snow. In any event I descended the gully about 30 feet or  so,  which
was wet and slippery and required a rope (which I  left  in  place  for  the
return) to get down, to a  wider,  probably  easier  ledge  below  that  led
across the face to the snowfield. Only the first part of this ledge gave  me
pause, as it was exposed and snowy. The  snowfield  itself  had  fresh  snow
over ice.  I had crampons along just for this section, but didn\'t use  them.
 For the most part the fresh snow gave good footing, although I did  slip  a
few times on the harder stuff underneath. Once on the SW ridge it  was  easy
going to the summit at 11:30 (3300 ft, 4 hr).

I had a devil of a time finding the  register  in  the  fresh  snow  on  the
summit.  I was beginning to think  I  wasn\'t  on  the  right  bump,  when  I
finally excavated it from a hole slightly  off  to  the  side  of  the  high
point. I signed in after Paul Cho of 9/6/04. Per his suggestion, I  added  a
new Ziploc bag.  I am amazed that the register has weathered so  many  years
so well.  The weather continued to clear and I was beginning to  get  views.
I could see to the N peak. I am aware there is some  question  as  to  which
peak is higher.  To settle this I had carried a  small  sighting  clinometer
up with me. This is a quality surveying  instrument  that  will  tell  if  a
distant point is higher or lower than the one sighted  from.  It  will  only
tell if it is higher or lower.  It will not tell by how  much.  I  was  very
careful to sight at the level of the summit  to  the  N  peak.  I  did  this
several times.  By my reckoning, the summit I  was  on,  the  one  with  the
register, is definitely higher, by about 1 degree. Case closed as far  as  I
am concerned.  I was very glad as I didn\'t want  to  have  to  climb  the  N
peak.

There was even more clearing and more views during the return trip.  It  was
turning out to be a lovely day. Reluctant to end the day, from the  notch  I
continued S along the ridge thinking I could follow it all  the  way  to  Pt
8039, but I was stopped by cliffs above a saddle at a  high  point  of  7960
ft. I arrived back in camp at 3:00 with enough time for  tea  and  a  sketch
before leaving an hour  later.  The  trip  out  through  Spider  Meadow  was
delightful with the fall colors and I had it all to myself.  I  reached  the
TH at 6:15, the only car left.

Total: 20 miles and 5750 feet

Fay Pullen






