            'tr' => '

South Spectacle Butte (8392 feet)


First Attempt and the Mouse Wars - October  21-22,  2004  -  This  trip  was
doomed from the start. First the weather forecast  was  not  good.   Second,
family commitments prevented me from getting an early start on Thursday  and
required me to be back early on Friday.   But  I  needed  the  exercise  and
decided to give it a try anyway.

I started up the Entiat River trail at 1:45 on a mountain bike  under  sunny
skies and pleasant temperatures.  Normally I don\'t like to mountain bike  up
hiking trails.  I am not a very strong biker and usually end up pushing  the
bike more than riding it, so I don\'t consider it worth  the  effort.  But  I
was getting such a late start I would try anything to gain  a  little  time.
By the time I reached the Glacier Peak Wilderness  boundary  at  3:10,  4.5
miles in, I was ready to stash the bike and continue on foot. At 8  miles  I
turned onto the Ice Creek trail. I made  camp  at  a  well-established  bare
site in the woods just before the trail crossed  Ice  Creek  for  the  first
time at 6:15, elevation 4800 ft (11 miles, 2000 ft, 4.5 hr).

I was awakened at 1:00 am by a mouse scurrying over my tent. It  was  zipped
up tight so I assumed the mouse was outside the  tent.  I  shook  the  walls
hoping to scare it away. This went on for half an  hour  until  I  felt  the
mouse run over  my  head.  That  meant  it  was  inside  the  tent  and  the
implications of that were too terrible to contemplate.  On came  the  light.
Searching my tent yielded no mouse, but I did find the feared hole that  had
been chewed through the foot of the tent wall. This was war!  Off  went  the
light. Play possum. Back came the mouse. On with the light and I saw a  tail
disappear into my pack. Several minutes more of off and on light and  I  saw
the mouse in the open and was able to catch him with  my  hand.  Success!  I
felt like a mighty hunter until I looked at the terrified  little  creature.
Good heavens, what do I do now?   If  I  just  toss  him  outside,  he  will
probably come back in again. Maybe I could wring his neck, but he  was  soft
and squishy I doubted it. Maybe I could chop off his head, but  that  seemed
overly gruesome and  messy  with  my  small  pocketknife.  Meanwhile,  as  I
contemplated all these various solutions, I continued to hold  tightly  onto
the little guy so he wouldn\'t get away.  I  guess  I  was  squeezing  pretty
hard, because he wasn\'t looking too good. Maybe I suffocated him or he  just
died of fright. In any event, I  threw  him  out  the  tent  door.   In  the
morning he was still there, very dead. I felt bad, but not too  bad.   After
all he had chewed a hole in my good tent.

I was awakened at 3:30 by another mouse running over my  head.   Not  again!
Was I ever going to get any sleep? However, this mouse had  the  good  sense
to be scared off by my thrashing and crashing. He didn\'t want  to  meet  the
same fate at mouse #1. This is one reason I don\'t like to camp at well  used
sites. The critters are too habituated to finding  food  in  tents  and  are
very bold in their pursuit of it. I usually camp in remote, off  the  beaten
path places and rarely have such problems.

I finally fell asleep fully expecting more  mouse  encounters,  but  when  I
awoke it was already 7:00.  Not the early start I had wanted. But it  really
didn\'t matter. It had snowed all night long and was  still  snowing  lightly
and was windy, so making my summit was pretty much out of the  question.   I
even considered just packing up and heading straight out, but I needed  more
of a workout.  2000 feet of elevation was hardly enough  to  get  the  blood
circulating. So I headed up the trail at 8:00. Once I  got  moving,  it  was
really very pleasant. The meadows  were  lovely  all  covered  with  several
inches of fresh snow.  I  was  able  to  follow  the  trail  past  two  more
crossings of Ice Creek (I made note of a good  campsite  between  these  two
crossing) before leaving it at 5400 ft to head up the gully leading  to  the
saddle between N and S Spectacle Buttes. I soon exited the gully right  onto
a wooded rib that I followed in ever increasing  snow  depth  to  the  basin
below S Spectacle\'s W face where I began  wallowing  in  knee-deep  snow.  I
exhausted myself continuing up  the  treacherous  hole  filled  snow-covered
talus. Reason prevailed when I reached the SW ridge at 7000 ft  in  blizzard
conditions and turned around. It was 10:30. At least I had my workout.

Total - 27 miles and 4800 feet

Second Attempt and Success  -  October  27-28,  2004  -  I  hate  unfinished
business. My family commitments were over on Tuesday. So on Wednesday,  with
a forecast of two days of good weather, I was back  at  the  Entiat  TH  for
another try. This time I was able to get an  earlier  start.  I  reached  my
intended  campsite,  about  a  mile  farther  than  last  week\'s,  at  4:15,
elevation 5250 ft (12 miles, 2500 ft, 5 hr). In the intervening week it  had
snowed more, but I found a bare spot under a tree to  pitch  my  tent.   The
promised good weather had materialized and it was a beautiful sunny day.  At
5:00 I started up the trail to Ice Lakes  and  reached  the  lower  lake  at
6:15. I had a great view of my route up S Spectacle and along the SW  ridge.
 It looked rather frightful with  snow  covering  the  rock.   I  could  see
several pinnacles along the ridge that could give  some  problems.   I  also
had Jim Brisbine\'s recent report where he reported difficulty  getting  past
one of them.  It was probably rather optimistic  of  me  to  think  I  could
climb this peak under these conditions. But I was going to give it one  last
try before giving up for this year.

I was back to my tent at 7:30 (2 miles, 1600 ft,  2.5  hr).  This  was  the
night of the full moon and the lunar  eclipse.   I  had  a  front  row  seat
viewing it from my tent door as  I  ate  dinner.  It  was  rather  a  spooky
reddish subdued light. I turned in at 8:30 and almost immediately was  again
annoyed by a mouse running over my tent.  I  had  patched  the  hole  chewed
last week.  I had visions of having to patch another one. But after  several
violent shakings of the tent wall the mouse left me alone. I  slept  soundly
through the night.  But the next morning I found a hole chewed  in  my  food
bag that had been hung from a tree branch.  What is it with these Ice  Creek
mice? They must be super mice with radar for  noses  that  can  detect  food
anywhere. I had a mental image of a mouse hanging by his tail while  chewing
a hole in the bottom of the bag.

I started at 7:00 by headlamp on this cold crisp  morning.  By  the  time  I
turned off the trail the headlamp was  no  longer  needed.   I  followed  my
route of last week to the basin, where I again wallowed in  knee-deep  snow,
and onto the SW ridge. The snow was even deeper now and  progress  was  slow
up steep slopes and around a first rocky point. Here I crossed to the  sunny
side of the ridge and the snow depth diminished, even being melted  down  to
bare rock in places.  At  9:30  I  reached  the  base  of  the  first  major
pinnacle at 7500 ft. I believe this was the  pinnacle  that  caused  Jim  so
much trouble getting around.  He took the assault high, almost to  the  top.
I knew I didn\'t want to go the way he did.   It  sounded  bad  enough  under
good conditions. I decided to stay low. I could see a ramp that led  to  the
right at the base of the pinnacle toward  the  major  gully  on  that  side.
Perhaps I could get into the gully from there. To my surprise the  ramp  led
around the corner to a wide ledge that traversed the  length  of  the  south
side of the pinnacle all the way to the top of the  gully.   The  exit  from
the ledge to gully was a tad tricky but nothing that made  me  too  nervous.
Several hundred feet  of  step  kicking  up  variable  snow,  from  hard  to
breakable crust to knee-deep powder,  led  to  a  second  smaller  pinnacle.
After crossing a notch, another south side ledge traverse that looked  worse
than it turned  out  to  be,  gave  way  to  easier  terrain  before  I  was
confronted with the final few hundred feet of the summit pyramid. This  took
an hour or so to surmount as I carefully worked my way up snowy  ledges  and
broken rock. I topped out at 11:30 (3150 ft, 4:30 hr). I signed in on  Jim\'s
newly placed register. I had gorgeous views of Maude, Seven  Fingered  Jack,
Fernow, both Ice Lakes and the whole of the Entiat area.

 I was elated that I had been able to climb my  peak.   But  congratulations
were not yet in order. The climb was only half over.  I still  had  get  off
the thing. Getting down the summit pyramid was tricky  and  slow  going.   I
had trouble reversing a couple of moves and had a few  nervous  moments.   I
did have a rope and slings with me, but I never used them. I was glad I  had
my tracks in the snow to follow down.  The route was  not  at  all  obvious.
At 1:20 I was at the base of the ridge. Once on continuous snow things  went
faster and I was back to camp at 2:00. I left at 2:45 and reached the  TH  a
little before 7:00, in the dark.  Now  I  could  congratulate  myself  on  a
successful climb and the end of a  successful  season  climbing  25  of  the
Highest Hundred.

Total - 30 miles and 7700 feet

Fay Pullen


