            'title' => 'Fortune Mountain (5903 feet) - November 4-5, 2004',
            'tr' => '

      Fortune Mountain (5903 feet) - November 4-5, 2004



      This time of year you have to be flexible.  My original  plan  was  to
      climb Mac Peak and Swallowtail from Deception Lakes  using  the  Tonga
      Ridge road as a shortcut to the trail. But I started running into deep
      snow at about 3200 ft, well before the highpoint of the road and  knew
      I would never be able to get to the TH.  On to Plan  B.  This  was  to
      climb Fortune Mountain from the Meadow Cr  trail  and  Fortune  Ponds,
      where access started from the lower (2000 ft) Rapid River road.


      The first mile of the trail was snow-free to 3000 ft.  Then  I  turned
      the corner from the sunny south-facing slope into the Meadow Cr valley
      and immediately ran into snow. I was able to follow the trail, despite
      increasing snow depth, all the way to a camp at 4800 ft  in  the  flat
      meadow below Fortune Mountain just before the trail descends  slightly
      to the lower pond (6.5 miles, 3100 ft, 4:30 hr). Snow depth  here  was
      about 2 feet. The last mile or so I began breaking  through  the  rain
      crust under several inches of fluffy powder. Snowshoes would have been
      nice, but I had elected not to carry them in and in  fact  they  would
      have been marginally useful.  I only broke through the  crust  on  the
      trail where it had been undercut by running water. Once off trail  the
      crust held my weight and boots alone worked fine.


      I took over an  hour  choosing  and  then  preparing  a  site  for  my
      freestanding tent. I chose a place out in  the  open,  despite  deeper
      snow and more required  shoveling,  rather  than  be  dripped  on  and
      bombarded all night long under trees whose  fresh  load  of  snow  was
      melting in the sun and would turn to ice as  soon  as  it  set.  After
      being treated to a spectacular sunset, I crawled into my tent for  the
      long cold night. During the night I was let  down,  literally,  by  my
      Thermarest as it gradually lost air to become a useless flat  pancake.
      How could this be?  It had been fine when I had  used  it  last  week.
      Then I remembered I had laid it out to dry at home on  the  spare  bed
      where my cat likes to hang out.  Bad kitty!  Cat claws are  sharp  but
      tiny.  I could not find the pinprick leak. (I found it later  at  home
      by immersing it in a tub full of water.)  Thank heavens I had  brought
      a second foam pad or the cold night would have been even colder.


      It was 24 degrees when I woke at  7:00  the  next  morning  and  as  I
      crawled out of my warm sleeping bag, I had to remind myself that I was
      having fun, really I was. Once I got moving I actually  did  start  to
      enjoy myself. The fresh snow was lovely, all sparkly  with  new  frost
      crystals, the step kicking up the steep slope was straight forward and
      invigorating, and the view of Glacier Peak from the summit gorgeous. I
      descended directly to upper Fortune Pond and then to  the  lower  one.
      Both were frozen over, although Peach Lake, which I also saw from  the
      summit, was not. I was back to my tent, now in the sun,  by  10:30  (2
      miles, 1300 ft, 2:30 hr). I spent a very  pleasant  hour  and  a  half
      sitting in the warm sun drinking tea,  reading  and  sketching  before
      heading out at noon. Three hours later I was at the car, with over two
      hours of daylight to spare.


      Total: 15 miles and 4600 ft.  Fay Pullen






