Atrium (5359 feet) and St. Agnes Ridge (5547 feet) - November 10-11, 2004


Even with good weather, backpacking this time of year involves dealing  with
short days, cold temperatures, unpleasant conditions, and many hours in  the
tent to pass the long night, so I was somewhat surprised when  Linda  agreed
to accompany me on this trip. I was very happy to have the company,  not  to
mention help breaking trail.

We were able to stay on the trail all the way to Big Heart Lake. (Stefan,  I
must agree with you that it is at least 8 miles to  here,  not  the  6.8  GT
says.) The  first  snow  was  encountered  shortly  before  the  turnoff  to
Malachite Lake. From Little Heart to Big Heart the snow increased  in  depth
to about 2 feet and was inconsistent, alternating between crust  and  slush,
making trailbreaking slow and exhausting  (Again,  we  had  elected  not  to
bring snowshoes). We arrived at Big  Heart  Lake  a  little  after  4:00  (8
miles, 3540 ft, 6 hrs) with plenty of time to set up camp in  daylight.   We
pitched the tent on snow but had a snow free spot under a tree  to  organize
our kitchen. We ate dinner by headlamp, prolonging it as  long  as  possible
before being driven into the tent by the cold. It  was  a  beautiful,  clear
starlit night.

Twelve hours later, we emerged from our warm  sleeping  bags,  having  slept
soundly most of that time. I guess we were tired. My leaking  Thermarest  of
last week had been successfully repaired and I was well insulated  from  the
ground. Most of the snow had frozen solid overnight, to the point  just  shy
of needing crampons (which we hadn\'t brought anyway). Yet there  were  those
odd places, mostly under the protection of trees, that hadn\'t  frozen  where
we would sink in unexpectedly to our knees and this prevented any  sense  of
security and steady rhythm. Despite  this  we  made  rapid  progress  toward
Atrium, our first destination, still able  to  follow  the  trail  until  it
traversed left at 5000 ft toward the NE ridge and then  continuing  straight
up the N ridge to the top (850 ft, :50 hr).

We basked in the sun and the view of all the snowy  peaks  (most  impressive
was the cold, forbidding north face of Chimney Rock) and alpine lakes  (none
of which were yet frozen) for thirty minutes, before continuing  on  to  St.
Agnes Ridge. We had a pretty  good  view  of  where  we  wanted  to  go.  We
descended NE from the summit of Atrium down hard snow to  the  outlet  creek
of Angeline Lake. Here we found an unexpected mini gorge with  no  easy  way
down the vertical wall. We wandered around  a  bit  searching  for  a  route
until finding a wooded ledge upstream that gave  access  to  the  creek.   A
treacherous crossing on hole filled snow covered large boulders  put  us  on
the NW ridge of St Agnes. Once there it was mostly a trouble free  climb  on
solid snow until reaching a cliff at about 5300 ft. From  the  map  a  route
appeared feasible to the left of the cliff, but  that  would  have  involved
traversing an extensive partially snow-covered talus  basin  that  was  very
unappealing. From our distant view, another route  looked  possible  to  the
right through trees even though the map showed it to be  very  steep.  Steep
it was, but we managed to work our way through short cliffs,  climbing  root
ladders and pulling ourselves up brush and branches to emerge on the  gentle
ridge above. At noon we came upon the summit cairn (1950 ft, 3:45 hr).

Buried in the cairn was the historic glass jar register transcribed  by  Don
and Natala Goodman during their 2002 climb. The  only  other  entry  was  by
Stefan Feller in July of this year.  On  late  season  or  winter  climbs  I
don\'t expect to find registers as they are usually buried under snow,  so  I
was very happy to have found this one.  It was so pleasant  on  the  summit,
we spent almost an hour eating  lunch  and  enjoying  more  sun  and  views,
despite knowing the day was fast diminishing.  We already knew we  would  be
going out in the dark.

We followed our footsteps down. We had found most of the holes  on  way  up,
but a few new ones appeared in the warming day, especially in  those  places
heated by the sun, and care was needed to avoid injury to  lower  limbs.  It
was essential that we cross the Angeline  Lake  outlet  creek  in  the  same
place  and  find  the  ledge  leading  out  of  the  gorge.  Once  that  was
accomplished we worked our way to the NE ridge of Atrium where we  hoped  to
pick up the trail again. But once on the ridge we couldn\'t find  the  trail.
A hairy traverse on the north slope to check things out made me  believe  we
were too low. Sure enough a short climb up from the traverse  we  found  the
trail. It was clear sailing back to camp at 3:00 (4  miles,  2500  ft,  6:40
hr).

We quickly packed up and were ready to go at 3:40.  We  made  it  to  Copper
Lake before needing headlamps at 5:30. The trail seemed to  go  on  forever,
as it always does when you are ready for things to end, before reaching  the
TH at 7:40 (8 miles, 560 ft, 4 hrs). The parking  lot  puddles  had  already
refrozen and the car windows  were  covered  with  ice.  We  celebrated  our
success with a satisfying Mexican dinner in Sultan.

Total: 20 miles and 6600 ft

Fay Pullen

