            'tr' => '

Nimbus Mountain (6711 feet) and Thor Peak (6804 feet) - November 16-17,
2004


I wasn\'t sure what either the weather or I was going  to  do  on  these  two
days. We both ended up exceeding expectations.  I  headed  for  the  Stevens
Pass area hoping to bag another Back Court peak. I first  tried  once  again
(I had tried two weeks ago) to drive up the Tonga Ridge road to get  to  the
short cut to Deception Lakes and Mac Pk. I didn\'t really think I would  make
it but at least this time I got farther.  The road was mostly clear  to  the
high point turnoff to Mt Sawyer, but once on the other  side  of  the  ridge
turned snowy and after sliding out of the icy track several times I  decided
not to risk it any further. It was on to the Surprise Cr TH and  a  try  for
Nimbus.

This trail has had a lot of work done since I was  last  on  it.  Dozens  of
wooden steps and bridges have been added in the  first  mile  to  the  creek
crossing. Very nice on a warm day, but these same wooden improvements  would
cause me grief on the way out. Once past the crossing I began  running  into
snow, but a well-broken track went all the way to Surprise Lake.  I found  a
nice level spot to camp along the creek at the junction to  Trap  Pass  just
before Surprise Lake (4 miles, 2300 ft, 2:40 hr).

It was still early in the afternoon, so I killed a little time by  wandering
over to Surprise Lake.  It was partially frozen. Back at  camp,  just  as  I
started to do a sketch of the lovely snowy creek,  it  started  to  snow.  I
finished it sitting inside my tent peering out the door. It was  still  only
4:00. I made an early dinner and read a while.  Now  it  was  6:00.  Camping
this time of year would be so much more pleasant if only you didn\'t have  to
spend the night. I listened  to  my  newly  acquired  MP3  player.   What  a
marvelous invention. Quality music in a tiny package.  I was  even  able  to
pick up an FM station from Canada. Light rock they called it. Not really  my
cup of tea.  I am more of a classical fan, but I wasn\'t in a position to  be
picky (I had only had time to record 1 hour of my music onto the player).  I
fell asleep listening to it. It snowed all night  long  and  periodically  I
would wake up to shake snow off the tent.

I awoke the next morning to clear blue skies.  What a surprise!   After  the
usual unpleasantries getting the body going, I started up the trail to  Trap
Pass at 7:30 on snowshoes. It had snowed about 4 inches overnight on top  of
a several foot base at the deepest. I easily followed the trail to the  pass
then traversed right of the ridge to where it steepened. At the  top  of  an
open slope on the west side I ran into a short cliffy wooded  section  which
required removal of the snowshoes. Above this  I  began  a  delightful  open
traverse that wandered up and down across broad benches and  around  gullies
on the east side of the pinnacled ridge. I passed beneath Slippery Slab  and
several other equally impressive rock towers.  The way was very  scenic  and
the views expansive in the glorious sunshine. What a day!

I hit the SE ridge of Nimbus at 6600 ft, with a view down to frozen  Thunder
Mtn Lake, and soon after exchanged snowshoes for boots and ice  ax  for  the
final hundred foot climb to the summit (2500 ft, 3:30 hr). I found  a  cairn
(no register so I left one) on a flat boulder between  two  slightly  higher
points. I\'m not sure which was highest. One I was able to climb.  The  other
was a sheer boulder.  The best I  could  do  without  a  rope  or  someone\'s
shoulder to stand on was to touch the top. It would have to do

I now turned my attention to Thor.  I had thought to perhaps include  it  in
the itinerary if I had the time. But it had taken longer to  get  to  Nimbus
than I had hoped and I wasted more time trying to get up the sheer  boulder.
Thor looked very inviting and easy, if I could get to the saddle between  it
and Nimbus.  That would be the key.  From the map the  descent  from  Nimbus
looked to be very cliffy. Conditions and weather were both good.  I  had  to
at least try, although that meant I would be going  out  in  the  dark  once
again. The first obstacle was to get around  the  rocky  point  just  SE  of
Nimbus. A tricky, exposed but short traverse on hard  snow  just  below  the
cliffs on the north side led to easier terrain and back to the crest of  the
ridge. Cliffs were below on both sides but by sticking to the  nose  of  the
ridge I was able  to  work  my  way  down,  several  times  slithering  down
vertical shrubby steps, to the saddle some 400 feet below. From  the  saddle
pleasant slopes led easily to the summit of Thor (3300 ft, 5:40 hr).

I found a cairn and glass jar register on the  rocky  summit.  The  register
dated from 1987 and contained the usual roster of familiar peak baggers:  C.
Hickenbottem, 8/19/91;Grant  Meyers,  9/10/95;  Mitch  Blanton  8/1/98;  Don
Beavon & Mike Torok, 3/6/01; John Roper, 8/8/02; and Steve Fox & John  Tolan
6/16/04. It was so glorious on top, the weather so friendly, warm and  sunny
and no wind, and the views so gorgeous I was reluctant to leave.  I  finally
forced myself to go at 1:30.

I was down to the saddle in 10 minutes. The  climb  up  from  there  went  a
little slower as I had to bodily pull myself up the steps on  branches.  The
tricky traverse was faster and easier with steps already  kicked.   I  found
an easier way off the ridge the final bit  to  Trap  Pass  and  avoided  the
cliffy section in the woods. I was back to camp at 4:00 (6 miles,  3800  ft,
8:30 hrs) and packed up and ready to leave  at  4:25.  The  sunny  warm  day
faded to a distant memory with the fading light as the night  turned  frigid
and the trail turned into  an  icy  treacherous  descent.  Several  times  I
slipped only to catch myself with my poles. I crawled the  log  crossing  of
Surprise Creek rather than surely slip  off  and  tiptoed  down  the  wooden
steps and bridges that glistened with ice and  frost.  The  trail  was  much
more dangerous than anything I had done  on  my  peaks.   I  reached  a  car
coated in ice at 6:45.

Total: 14 miles and 6100 feet

Fay Pullen






