Little Bulger Peak (5111 feet) - November 30, 2004


With snow levels low and the passes treacherous driving  I  stayed  west  of
the crest and headed up the Middle Fork Snoqualmie  River  Road.  The  first
part of the road was as potholed as ever but once past the Taylor River  the
road seemed better than I remembered it and I arrived at the Dingford Cr  TH
sooner than expected. A light dusting of snow covered the road.

I followed the trail to Myrtle Lake (5.5 miles,  2500  ft,  3:15  hr)  where
there was about 1 foot of fresh snow. It was foggy with snow showers.   More
of a problem was the occasional bombardment of masses of  snow  falling  off
tree boughs in  the  warming  temperatures.   A  few  were  direct  hits.  I
continued following the trail toward Little Myrtle Lake but  soon  lost  the
way and just headed uphill after crossing the creek between the  two  lakes.
I trended to the right to avoid cliffs and boulder fields then back  to  the
left to hit the ridge north of the summit. The snow was over knee  deep  and
here I could feel old snow under the new. At times I  floundered  in  deeper
holes. I tried snowshoes for a while, but I sank in as deep with them on  as
with them off.  No help at all. The last bit to the top was  slow  going.  I
topped out at 3:10 (3550 ft, 5:25  hr).  Not  much  of  a  view  but  I  was
impressed by the cliffs on the west side of the ridge which I could see.

I was back to the lake in an hour.  40 minutes later it was  headlamp  time,
after which I proceeded to stumble slowly down the slippery rocky trail.  It
snowed lightly most of the way out.

13 miles, 3800 ft, 9:45 hrs

Fay Pullen
