 Second Try - December 2, 2004.',
            'tr' => '

Bentrim Hill (6078 feet)


You can almost drive to the top of this peak in the  summer,  especially  if
you have a 4-wheel drive vehicle, but what is the point  in  that?  My  plan
was to make a real trip of it and bicycle as far as possible from the  south
up Naneum Canyon. I took the Kittitas exit off I-90 and the Naneum  Cr  Road
to a school bus turn-around and a locked gate at the entrance to the  canyon
at 2500 ft.


First Attempt - November 24, 2004. This was  the  day  before  Thanksgiving.
The night before and that day was heavy rain in the west, but  it  was  only
light sprinkles when I started out on my  bike.  However,  enough  rain  had
already fallen to turn much of the road to a muddy  mess.  One  section  was
such sticky gumbo that my wheels and brakes  and  chain  became  so  clogged
with goo that they would barely turn. I really should have  given  up  then,
but I was stubborn (stupid?) and continued to push and half  carry  my  bike
to firmer terra. Then  after  taking  3.75  hours  to  bike  11.6  miles,  I
mistakenly stashed my bike too soon at  the  wrong  junction  (the  area  is
riddled with unmarked roads), came to the end of my chosen  road,  tried  to
continue cross-country and proceeded to get myself  thoroughly  confused  in
dense woods. I ended up on the shoulder of  Pt  5537  (an  interesting  open
scab rock ridge)  still  a  mile  from  Bentrim  with  darkness  falling.  I
considered continuing on using my headlamp and GPS, as  once  on  Bentrim  I
could pick up the proper road and easily follow it back to my bike. But  the
batteries in both my headlamp and GPS were failing (I forgot to change  them
from my last trip and had no spares). If I had any  hope  of  navigating  my
way back to my bike that night I had to  turn  around  immediately.  (I  was
making Thanksgiving dinner for my kids the next day.  It  would  nice  if  I
made it home in time to prepare it).


Fortunately, I had marked the position of my bike with the  GPS,  so  all  I
had to do was follow it back. Unfortunately, my GPS soon went totally  dead.
I was now in the dense woods and confusing rolling terrain of Naneum  Basin.
Oh the hazards of depending on battery operated gadgets. What to do?  I  did
have a low tech, but always functional, compass in my  pack,  but  that  was
only a last resort.  Besides, I only had a vague notion of where  I  was  (I
determined later I was near Pt 5537). If you don\'t know where you  are,  you
don\'t know what course to  follow,  except  in  a  most  general  manner  to
perhaps hit the main road somewhere. My headlamp was a Black  Diamond  Zenix
with two strengths of LEDs and uses the same AAA batteries as my GPS.  Thank
heavens for LEDs.  They use  very  little  battery  power.  I  switched  the
slightly better batteries of the headlamp to the GPS  and  vice  versa.  The
GPS batteries still had enough power left to operate the lowest  setting  of
LED. And so I managed to find my way back to my bike after wandering  around
in the dark for two hours, switching my GPS on every 15 minutes or so for  a
course correction all  the  while  hoping  it  wouldn\'t  die  again.  In  an
interesting footnote, while wandering around in the woods I  came  across  3
separate complete elk skeletons. The Colockum  Wildlife  Area  does  have  a
large elk population, but I was surprised to find evidence of them  in  such
dense  woods.  These  woods  were  really  dense  with   many   downed   and
crisscrossed trees that made travel difficult.   At  times  I  could  barely
find a way through much  less  a  large  animal.   Perhaps  they  pick  such
protected places to go to die. I fleetingly wondered if I might  be  joining
them.
For the trip out on bike, I  switched  the  better  batteries  back  to  the
headlamp and used  the  higher  LED  setting.  It  was  barely  adequate  to
negotiate the road and I had to keep my speed down on the steeper  descents.
 I did get  some  help  from  an  almost  full  moon  in  the  now  clearing
conditions. When I hit the  gumbo  section  of  road  again,  things  turned
positively ugly. The wheels immediately clogged so badly they wouldn\'t  turn
at all. I had to carry the bike and once past clean out the wheels  as  best
I could. There was no way to stay clean and I soon gave up  and  became  one
with the mud as it got everywhere, on my  gloves,  on  the  handlebars,  the
shifters, the seat, my  water  bottle,  my  pants,  my  boots,  my  hat,  my
glasses, my pack - you get the picture. I couldn\'t even see the brakes,  not
that it mattered. There was so much friction even after I got the wheels  to
turn again that I never needed to use them.  In fact I often  had  to  pedal
even on the downhills to keep moving. I got back to the  car  at  10:00  and
home after midnight. I did make a successful Thanksgiving  dinner  the  next
day, but it took me several hours to clean up my bike.

Lessons learned: Always carry extra batteries and do not ride a bike in  the
Colockum after a rainstorm

Total: 28 miles, 4200 ft, 11:15 hrs.

Second Try - December 2, 2004. For my second attempt  I  waited  a  week  of
mostly dry cold weather for the road to dry out. I couldn\'t wait  too  long,
though, as any heavy snowstorm would prevent access. I got an earlier  start
at 9:45. It was below freezing. I could tell immediately the road was  drier
and frozen and would give little trouble in that regard,  but  I  could  see
fresh snow on the higher hills.  No telling how deep  it  was  where  I  was
going. The road began with a stiff climb, then  leveled  out  and  descended
slightly to a lovely section near  the  bottom  of  the  canyon  and  frozen
Naneum Cr, only to climb steadily once again. At  4.4  miles  I  came  to  a
second gate and entered the Colockum Wildlife Area. I began to  run  into  a
light dusting of powder snow. I passed the gumbo section without  incidence.
Bicycling is so much more fun when the wheels turn! At 8.3 miles  I  crossed
Naneum Creek and at 9.8 miles crossed again. Now  the  road  began  climbing
more steeply.  I passed my bike highpoint of last week and continued to  the
proper junction at 12.7 miles.  This  spur  was  even  steeper  and  I  soon
stashed my bike where it crossed a ravine at 4600 ft (13.1 miles,  2300  ft,
3:15 hrs). The snow here was about 2 inches deep, no real problem.

Continuing on foot, I hiked up the ravine cutting a switchback in  the  road
and cutting a second one farther up, then easily following the road  to  the
top (15.4 miles, 3900 ft, 4:55 hrs).  The last bit was  a  very  steep  jeep
trail. Bentrim Hill is just that, a hill. Not very exciting.  More  exciting
was Pt 5537, the rocky ridge I been so close  to  last  week.  It  was  very
close and very inviting.  So, despite it getting late, on  the  way  down  I
took a little detour up it just to feel like I had climbed a real summit.  I
started my bike descent  a  little  after  4:00,  and  with  wheels  turning
freely, reached the car at 6:00.

Total: 31 miles, 4300 ft, 8:15 hrs - 26.2 miles and 2500 ft on bike

Fay Pullen









