            'tr' => '

Blue Mountain (3080+ ft - 1040 ft Prominence - Wallace Lk Quad) - January
25, 2005


The easy way to do this low mountain is to drive up the  Sultan  Basin  Road
to just before Olney Pass, turn left onto the Blue Mountain  Road,  drive  a
rough 2 miles to the gate and walk a little over a mile  to  the  top.   But
easy wasn\'t the point of this trip.  I wanted a good workout with the  added
bonus of a summit and a loop. To this end, I drove up the Sultan Basin  Road
5.5 miles to a gated logging road at 740 ft and began on bicycle at 11:45.

The gate was open and as I got  myself  ready  to  go  four  logging  trucks
passed by, not a good sign. Obviously, active logging was  occurring  on  my
chosen access road, one disadvantage of cycling up logging roads during  the
week.  The well-used road began gently, and, spurred on by  the  thought  of
meeting more trucks, especially on  narrow  sections,  I  pedaled  furiously
upward making good progress. I was  passed  by  four  more  trucks,  but  it
really was not the problem I had feared, as I could hear them coming a  mile
away and had plenty of time to get well off the road. I  gave  them  each  a
friendly wave.

At 2.75 miles I passed the active logging site where  all  the  trucks  were
headed and at 3.2 miles reached the first of  several  switchbacks  climbing
Blue Mountain\'s W ridge. The road still showed signs of much recent  traffic
and did not seem to correspond to my map and I proceeded to get myself  very
confused with new roads to newly logged areas. Led  astray  by  following  a
well-used road I ended up at a dead-end on a current logging  platform.  The
diesel motor was still running on the crane but no one seemed to be  around.
Perhaps they were having lunch. Realizing my  error,  I  turned  around  and
found the correct road, which was a very obscure junction.  No wonder I  had
missed it.

My road showed no signs of use and in fact looked abandoned. It  was  steep,
rough, rocky and eroded and I pushed my bike up most of this section. I  was
now in lovely woods, a nice change from all the previous clear-cuts and  new
slash. But from the looks of all the  surveyors\'  tape  I  encountered,  the
loggers had designs on this road as well and the trees  were  not  long  for
this world.

After about an hour of pushing, the road leveled out at 2800 ft and 7  miles
on the crest of the ridge and I could start riding  again.  A  few  ups  and
downs for 1.5 miles, a final steep section and I was at the  tower  near  the
top at 2:40 (8.9 miles, 2700 ft). A 5-minute walk led  to  the  wooded  high
point after which I found a great viewpoint below the  tower.  I  ate  lunch
looking across the  Pilchuck  River  valley  toward  Mt  Pilchuck  and  Bald
Mountain.

There were a few more ups and downs continuing E along the  ridge  from  the
summit until I hit the gate. Then the road plunged downward losing  1000  ft
in two miles.  This road was better than the road I  had  ascended,  but  it
was still darn steep and rough and there were areas where it  was  necessary
to keep speed down to avoid a mishap. I was most happy to reach  the  Sultan
Basin Road at 3:50 and give my hands a rest from braking. The  rest  of  the
cruise down to the car was a fun fast descent first  on  smooth  dirt,  then
pavement. I knocked off the 8 miles in 40 minutes. Fun, fun, fun!  Made  all
that pushing worth it. Total: 20 miles, 3950 ft, 4:50 hrs.














