            'title' => 'Ten-Four Mountain (4384 ft - 2744 Prominence - Gold Bar Quad) - January 27, 2005',
            'tr' => '

Ten-Four Mountain (4384 ft - 2744 Prominence - Gold Bar Quad) - January 27,
2005


It looked so easy on the map.  A series of logging roads led to within  half
a mile and 300 feet of the top of this mountain. To be  sure,  it  would  be
over 4000 feet of elevation gain and 20  miles  so  I  expected  a  workout.
What I didn\'t expect was how bad some of the roads would be, the  wet  brush
and impenetrable second growth to the  top,  and  the  snow.  With  all  the
melting of the past weeks I really didn\'t  think  a  puny  4384-foot  summit
would have snow.  How quickly we become spoiled and forget.

I began at 10:55 up a gated logging road off Ben Howard Road out of  Sultan,
elevation 130 ft. Things began well despite the fact that it  was  drizzling
and that the gate was open which usually means active logging. Sure  enough,
I was soon passed by a couple a logging trucks.  I guess that  is  why  they
are called logging roads. But the road itself was smooth, if  a  bit  muddy,
and quite gentle for the  first  5  miles  gaining  only  750  ft  wandering
through woods past ponds and creeks and funny  little  blobby  hills,  which
made for very pleasant pedaling. Then the climbing began. After huffing  and
puffing and pushing for 2 more miles and 1000 feet I passed the  turnoff  to
the active logging and continued straight ahead. The road had been  recently
graded for another half mile through a new  clear-cut,  which  rendered  the
surface loose, muddy and unstable. I made a note to use caution on  the  way
down. Soon all signs of recent traffic ended  as  the  road  entered  woods,
climbed steeply and gradually deteriorated while I mostly walked and  pushed
for another mile to tiny Airplane Lake. I carried my bike across the  washed
out crossing of the outlet creek to the road continuing on the  other  side.
It had quit raining and I had a pleasant quick lunch at the  lake  at  1:45,
3100 ft and 8.3 miles.

From  the  lake  things  turned  ugly  as  the  "road"  degenerated  into  a
completely washed out rocky stream bed and I had to push and carry the  bike
up and over and around boulders for most of the next .8 mile and  500  feet.
Near the end were lovely views of the Skykomish River valley.  I topped  out
on the ridge at 2:25, 3600 ft and 9.1 miles, took a quick side trip W  to  a
tower and more views, and then headed E  along  the  S  side  of  the  ridge
toward Ten-Four.

The road remained rough but rideable until all at once I began to  run  into
patches of snow. This took me by surprise.  There had been no signs of  snow
up to this point.  Snow in January! Who would have  thought?  I  pushed  the
bike through a few patches until stopped by a longer section.  Here  I  left
the bike at 3:10, 3900 ft and 10.7 miles, and  walked  the  remaining  short
distance to the end of the road, maybe Â¼ mile and 150  ft,  where  I  headed
uphill toward the summit ridge. Once again things turned ugly as  I  entered
second (or maybe third or  fourth)  growth  at  its  worst.  Wet  brush  and
impenetrable thick scrubby evergreens and downed logs all with  intermittent
slushy snow conspired to make progress difficult. To make matters  worse,  I
was in cleated  bike  shoes,  completely  inadequate  for  the  terrain  and
conditions. I did have on good rain gear so the rest of me stayed  dry,  but
my feet were soon soaked. Had I realized what I was  in  for  I  would  have
used toe clip pedals so I could wear better boots.  Clip-in  pedals  are  so
much more efficient for pedaling, but they were a bad choice for this trip.

It had looked so easy on the map - maybe Â½ mile cross-country from  the  end
of the road. It took me 40 minutes to struggle that short  distance  to  the
top at 4:00. The summit was in older forest and showed no  signs  of  anyone
having been there. I doubt this summit is high on many people\'s  list.   The
trip down was no more pleasant but  it  was  faster.  Once  on  the  road  I
stopped to wring out my dripping socks and place plastic bags over  them  in
an effort to reduce evaporative cooling on the ride  down.   I  had  no  dry
socks along. I reached my bike at 4:35 and the junction  off  the  ridge  at
4:55. I had to walk the bike down the awful road  to  Airplane  Lake,  which
was fine with me as it allowed my frozen feet to warm up a bit. I  rode  the
rest of the way down from the lake. I hit the  unstable  section  of  graded
road noted on the way  up  in  fading  light.   I  was  aware  of  it,  took
precautions and still lost it and took a tumble. At  least  I  wasn\'t  going
very fast and didn\'t get hurt. Anticipating a long trip  and  possible  late
return I had carried my heavy 15-watt Nite Rider bike light with me. At  the
junction with the  logging  activity  at  5:30,  I  put  the  light  on  and
negotiated the rest of the way back to the car by its  generous  lumination.
The last 5 mile gentle section was even rather fun in the dark.   I  reached
the car at 6:35.  The logging gate was now closed.

Total: 21.2 miles on bike, 1.5 mile on foot, 4500 ft gain, 7:40 hrs.


