            'title' => 'Cascade Lookout (3702 ft) & Phelps Ridge (Devils Slide Quad) - February 1, 2005',
            'tr' => '

Cascade Lookout (3702 ft) & Phelps Ridge (Devils Slide Quad) - February 1,
2005


This is not really much of a summit as it only has prominence  of  a  little
over 200 ft (although it might almost qualify if you include the  height  of
the lookout), but it is a great viewpoint and I had a  good  workout  and  a
bit of an adventure getting there. You just never know what  you  are  going
to encounter when you venture onto old logging roads.

I began by cycling up gated road 29000 (2002  GT  Mt  Si  map  is  best  for
showing roads), about 9.5 miles up the  North  Fork  Snoqualmie  River  Road
(just after crossing Deep Cr), elevation 1250 ft. After a level 1.3 miles  I
came to a 4-way junction,  crossed  main  road  29400  to  29600  and  began
climbing steadily up a series of switchbacks. At the fourth  switchback  and
a junction with 29610, elevation 2000 ft, the road was blocked by  a  downed
tree and looked very unused, not a good sign. Hoping  29610  would  continue
upward, even though the map showed it to be a dead-end, I turned  onto  this
spur and  proceeded  to  waste  45  minutes,  1.8  miles  and  400  ft  gain
confirming that it indeed led nowhere but a clear-cut.

Back at the switchback, I considered my options. I  could  retreat  and  try
and find another way up, but that would mean descending all the way  to  the
4-way junction and would essentially mean starting the trip all over  again.
 Or I could try and force my way up a road that had not been used in a  long
time, probably for a reason. Neither option  seemed  very  good,  but  I  am
programmed to go up whenever possible, not down, so up I went.

Things began badly as I encountered half a dozen fallen trees  to  lift  the
bike over or around, then improved as I left the forest and entered  an  old
clear-cut where there were  no  trees  left  to  fall  down.  The  road  was
overgrown with weeds but easily followed until I rounded  the  corner  of  a
sub ridge, entered the valley of Deep Cr and saw the  reason  the  road  was
unused - a massive rockslide had obliterated several  hundred  feet  of  the
road. Now a sane person would have ended  the  trip  here,  but  I  probably
don\'t qualify as such a being. So I spent the next hour  wrestling  my  bike
over and around refrigerator sized rocks and then  up  a  steep  loose  dirt
slope to the roadbed on the other side of the slide.  I took two trips,  one
with my gear to lighten the load and one with the  bike.  I  also  cut  some
small alder trees with the folding saw I carry for such emergencies so  they
wouldn\'t snag handlebars and pedals.  The slide was old  enough  for  alders
to start growing again.

Getting my bike across the slide took the limit of  my  meager  strength.  I
think I looked upon it as a challenge, the crux of the day so to speak,  and
I just wanted to see if I could do it and I was  most  happy  to  reach  the
road on the other side and start pedaling again. The road was in good  shape
now.  Soon I crossed Deep Cr and at the head of the valley, at 3000  ft  and
7 miles, intersected road 29520, my planned return route. A short ways on  I
reached the junction to the lookout, road 29660, and pushed and pedaled  the
last 1.5 miles to the top. I encountered a few snow patches along  the  ridge
but nothing that was a problem.

The lookout itself is a nifty old  wooden  structure  over  a  hundred  feet
high. The stairs winding up are in good  shape  with  sturdy  handrails  and
lead to the bare but still mostly intact room on  top.  It  is  high  enough
above the surrounding trees to give a fantastic view all  around,  from  the
Tolt Watershed to the North Fork Snoqualmie and all the surrounding peaks  -
Phelps, McLain, Bare, Red, Index, Frozen, Twin,  Dog  and  into  the  Alpine
Lakes. A great place to hang around for a while. A  very  sparse  snow  pack
was in evidence.

I had hoped to get to Mt Phelps (or Little Phelps depending  on  which  name
you like) but I had lost so much time with my misadventures it was now  2:30
and I was running out of daylight. But I had some time left  and  decided  I
could go on till 4:00. So I continued E on the  road  along  the  ridge  top
about 2 miles until it descended very steeply to rejoin 29600 at  a  saddle.
I followed 29600 up and down another 1.5  miles  E,  with  the  road  getting
rougher and rougher, until completely stopped by  another  slide  just  past
the last saddle on the ridge before the final switchbacks to the ponds W  of
Phelps, elevation 3800 ft, 13.5 miles. This could be an interesting  way  to
climb Phelps.  Someday I may come back and try it.  But it was just as  well
I was stopped here.  It was 3:55 and time to turn around.

The trip down was fast and delightful. I stayed on  29600  to  the  junction
with 29520. An annoying little climb led to a U-turn  around  a  spur  ridge
and a recently logged area then to steady descent.  The road was  steep  but
mostly smoothed by much traffic and  I  flew  downhill.   I  ran  into  more
current logging operations lower down but I was late enough in the day  that
everyone had gone home. I intersected 29500, then 29400 and  finally  29000,
closing my loop. The last bit to the car was in growing darkness and I  just
made it without needing a light at 5:40.

Total: 23.5 miles, 4100 ft gain and 7:30 hr

Fay Pullen
