McDonald Mtn (3570 ft - P2170 - Eagle Gorge Quad) - February 2, 2005


I vaguely remember climbing this mountain years ago, but I am not certain  I
went to the highest point so I felt I had to go back and make sure. This  is
my first P2000 peak that I have climbed deliberately knowing it  is  on  the
list. I have been aware of this list for a while but have resisted  pursuing
it up to now.  But many of the peaks on the list can be climbed on bike  and
it gives me something to work toward  in  this  year  of  no  snow.  I  like
definite destinations for my trips.

I really shouldn\'t have done this trip the day after I wore  myself  out  on
Cascade Lookout, but the day was so gorgeous I  couldn\'t  help  myself  from
going out again. Besides, McDonald is in my backyard and only a short  drive
away, but I did get a late start. I drove to the gate off SE  Courtney  (off
Kanasket-Kangley Road).  The sign on the gate said  no  unauthorized  entry,
no ATV\'s or motorcycles but made no mention of  feet  or  bicycle.  Probably
they were allowed, but the last time I parked by such a sign I had the  back
window of my car smashed in. Maybe there was a connection or  maybe  it  was
unrelated random vandalism but it made me nervous.   So  I  continued  N  on
Kanasket-Kangley and found another entry point  at  an  unsigned  gate  just
past the intersection with Kent-Kangley, elevation 960 ft.

This jeep road turned out to be a more attractive way up through  woods  and
avoided the clear-cuts on the main logging road. It appeared  well  used  by
ATV\'s and motorcycles. I intersected the main road after an hour  of  mostly
pushing at 2260 ft and 2.2 miles. Shortly  after  was  another  sturdy  gate
that was serious in keeping out  motorized  vehicles.  I  had  trouble  just
getting my bike past it. Once past the gate I ran into 3 hikers coming  down
and stopped to chat.  They had come up from the Courtney gate and  were  not
deterred by the sign.

I passed the turnoff to the radio tower in another mile at 2840 ft. Now  the
road descended and passed another  gate  that  was  also  difficult  to  get
around. The road continued descending to 2585 ft then began a gradual  climb
on a long traverse where I could zip along at a good  clip.  I  reached  the
turnoff to the summit at 2900 ft and 6.6 miles. The  spur  to  the  top  was
rough and had deep water bars so I had  to  push  again.   On  the  ridge  I
turned left. The water bars ended but the road eventually  became  so  rough
with large loose rocks that I knew I wouldn\'t be able to  ride  down,  so  I
left the bike at 3300 ft and 7.3 miles and walked the last bit  to  the  top
arriving at 3:55. The summit was uninspiring, but I was able to get  a  semi
view by working my way through young alder to the edge of the ridge.

The nice thing about biking is the best comes last. At times  you  don\'t  go
any faster uphill than walking, but  on  the  level  and  downhill  you  can
really move. I did have to walk down to the main road  and  then  there  was
that distressing 300 ft climb back to the tower turnoff, but the rest was  a
fun trip down and I reached the car at 5:30.

Total: 14.6 miles on bike, 0.75 mile on foot, 3300 ft gain and 4:15  hr.    Fay
Pullen





