Drunken Charlie Mountain (2840+ ft - 460P - Sultan Quad) - February 5, 2005


I wanted to do this trip on the weekend when  I  wouldn\'t  have  to  contend
with logging trucks on the  North  Fork  Snoqualmie  Mainline  road.  I  had
planned for Sunday but the forecast was bad with lowering snow levels so  at
the last minute I decided to go Saturday hoping to beat the snow.  Ha!  This
got me another late start, really too late for such a long trip  but  I  had
my trusty bike light along and figured I could come out in the dark.

I began from 5.4 miles up the North Fork road at the first gate on the  left
past Spur 10 gate, elevation 1040 ft. There was already 2 inches of snow  on
the ground here from the storm on Friday.  So much  for  beating  the  snow.
But I didn\'t have to break trail as  the  mainline  logging  road  was  well
tracked from traffic on Friday. However, from what I could see on the  hills
higher up I knew I would be running into even more snow.  I wasn\'t sure  how
far I could get, but I decided to give it a try anyway.

I began on mile after mile of almost  level  road,  great  for  making  good
time. Gradually the snow depth got less as some had melted in the sun  or  I
just got out of the microclimate that had produced it in  the  first  place.
By the time I crossed the South Fork Tolt River at 8.8 miles  the  road  was
completely bare. I crossed the North Fork  Tolt  at  12.8  miles,  elevation
1175 ft, and finally began to climb. By the time I reached 2100 feet  I  was
back in consistent snow, but again vehicle tracks  helped  me  out  until  I
took a left turn heading toward Yellow Cr and the tracks went straight.  Now
I was on my own in 2-3 inches  of  snow.  It  is  amazing  to  me  how  much
friction there is breaking trail in snow with a bicycle. I had to work  just
to pedal on the level. Forget about pedaling uphill.

At 16.8 miles, elevation 2370 ft, I crossed Yellow Cr  and  turned  left.  A
short ways on a spur led up and right and I was forced to  push.  It  wasn\'t
really that steep but the ever deepening snow made pedaling too  much  of  a
chore. I reached the high point of the road at 19 miles and took 10  minutes
to wander around in the rolling woods just off to the left looking  for  the
summit.  It was not obvious exactly where it was but I must have crossed  it
at some point.

I turned around at 4:50 and proceeded to slip and slide down.  Bicycles  are
not terribly stable in snow. Up here I couldn\'t get my feet  clipped  in  as
both the pedals and cleats were choked with snow, but I really  didn\'t  want
them locked in anyway. Wheels, chain and cogs were also  filled  with  snow.
At least snow, as opposed to mud, melts off cleanly. I made it to  the  main
tracked road at 5:40 where I stopped to put on  my  light.  A  fast  descent
followed to the North Fork Tolt, then the endless miles  of  level  pedaling
that seemed to go on forever before reaching the car at 7:55.

It goes without saying that this would make for a much nicer bike ride  with
summer conditions for those into long distances and fast  cruising.  Without
snow the roads could be pedaled all the way  to  the  top  and  coming  down
would also be faster reducing the total time significantly. And FYI  I  wore
booties over my cycling shoes to keep the snow out.

Total: 38 miles, 2800 ft gain and 7:50 hrs.  Fay Pullen






