Rock Peak (3320+ ft - 2000P - Mt Tebo Quad) - February 25, 2005


I began running into old snow and ice on the Skokomish  River  Road  at  the
pitifully low elevation of 700  ft  and  began  to  think  maybe  I  was  in
trouble.  Who would have thought snow was this low after a  week  of  lovely
weather? Then I remembered that Mason County -  Hood  Canal  had  a  healthy
dose of lowland snow during the last storm and with night  temperatures  low
I guess it just didn\'t have a chance to melt.  Seeing  the  sunny  hillsides
above me were mostly snow free though, I  figured  I  could  probably  still
make my summit.

Shortly after crossing Rock Cr, I turned off the main road onto 2351,  drove
another mile, parked at the intersection with 2352 (elev 1115)  and  started
up this road by bike (for those not wishing to work so hard,  this  road  is
not gated and can be driven). It began  at  an  easy  grade  then  steepened
until I hit the main ridge at 2100 ft. The road wandered up and  down  along
the ridge gradually gaining elevation for several miles and I began  running
into snow in the shaded areas.  By the time I crossed to the  N  side  below
Rock Peak there was  a  consistent  8-12  inches  of  snow.   Fortunately  a
vehicle had been this far and left useful tracks.

I stashed my bike below the N peak and searched  for  a  way  up  the  steep
rocky hillside.  It was only 200 feet to the top, but it was a  little  more
than I had expected, a class 2 scramble made more challenging with snow  and
bike shoes.  Once on top, after taking in the  view  of  surrounding  peaks,
most notably Mt Washington, I followed the ridge to the S peak,  15  minutes
away, sinking in calf deep snow much of the way. I returned to  the  saddle,
then descended on snow directly to the road. The knee I had injured  a  week
ago skiing was already hurting again. Good thing going down by bike is  easy
on knees and I had a great run back to the car despite wet feet.  Total:  12
miles, 3020 ft and 4:10 hours.

Dennie Ahl Hill (2004 ft - 924P - Lightening Pk Quad)

Rock Peak didn\'t fill the day and since I was  right  there  I  extended  it
with a ride up to this old lookout site. Fortunately I had  a  pair  of  dry
socks in the car to replace my wet ones. I drove  back  down  the  Skokomish
River Road, turned onto 2340 and parked after about half a  mile,  elev  600
ft. The first part of this road is dead level and smooth enough for  a  road
bike although it was surprisingly wet due to melting snow  on  the  side.  I
passed the turnoff to West Lake and then crossed High Steel Bridge over  the
S Fork Skokomish River, an impressive deep rocky gorge. A short ways  on,  I
turned left onto spur 200 and followed this pleasantly graded forested  road
as it wound completely around the hill. On the N side I again ran into  snow
patches. Unfortunately, by the time I reached the top  an  evening  fog  had
developed and I got no view. The trip down was very pleasant even  though  I
reached the car after dark. I met no cars on either of these  trips.  Total:
18.4 miles, 1540 ft and 3.5 hours.

Fay Pullen


