Mt. Elbert (4327 ft - 2607P - The Rockies Quad) - March 4, 2005


Continuing my quest for 2000P peaks by bike, I chose this one  near  Mineral
despite the higher elevation meaning I would most certainly be running  into
a fair amount of snow. I drove up FR 74 (off Highway 7) about  2  miles  and
parked at the first switchback, elevation 1650 ft.  The road  climbed  at  a
steady but rideable grade and I did very little pushing except  through  the
snow patches that began to appear on shady NE aspects after about  3000  ft.
Vehicles had made tracks in the snow but parts were still too  deep  or  icy
to pedal through. After crossing East Cr  twice  and  pushing  up  a  longer
snowy section, I emerged onto a saddle on the ridge to welcome  sunshine  on
southerly slopes at 3500 ft and 5.3 miles.

A pickup truck was parked here and I could hear two male voices  calling  to
each other from somewhere off the road. Not knowing what manner of  mischief
(if any) they were up to, I pedaled furiously  away.  The  road  was  fairly
level for the next mile and a half and completely free of  snow  so  I  soon
left the commotion behind me. Views  opened  up  and  I  passed  beneath  an
interesting rock ridge. At 6.8 miles I came to another saddle  where  FR  74
crossed to the N and descended some 600 ft. There appeared to be  a  lot  of
snow on the road with no vehicle tracks and also not  wanting  to  lose  all
that elevation I re-examined the map for an alternate  route.  I  discovered
an abandoned road (283) that stayed mostly on the ridge  or  S  of  it  that
joined FR 70 and reconnected with my planned route after some 2.5  miles.  I
did save about 300 ft of elevation (this road also descended,  just  not  as
much), however I still ran into a fair amount of snow. And the old road  was
rough and overgrown. I probably should have  stashed  the  bike  sooner  and
walked, but I kept being lured on by snow free sections that were rideable.

At 9.5 miles I reconnected with my planned route at the junction  of  FR  70
(which branches off FR 74) and 7312. At 10.25 miles and elevation 3700 ft  I
gained the NE ridge of Elbert and stashed the bike  where  7312  crossed  to
the N.  The snow here was too deep for the bike. I continued on  foot  until
I could see a way up the road cut. The first hundred feet or  so  was  quite
steep.  Thank heavens for bush belays. Then the angle eased off  and  all  I
had to contend with was slushy, knee-deep unconsolidated snow over  annoying
brush - a real pain. The 600 ft to  the  top  took  a  good  45  minutes  of
unpleasant postholing. This peak has been clear-cut to the  summit,  but  at
least that afforded good views. There were a  number  of  interesting  rocky
bumps around that might warrant future exploration.

It took longer to reverse the old  road  than  I  had  anticipated.  Despite
having my bike tracks to follow, it seemed to take as much work to push  the
bike through the snow going out as coming in,  particularly  on  the  uphill
section. I was pretty much done in by the time I reached  FR  74.  But  from
that point on it was just a matter of  letting  gravity  take  me  downhill.
What a pleasure!

Total: 20.5 miles on bike, 1 mile on foot, 3800 ft and 7:45 hrs.

Fay Pullen



