            'tr' => '

Whacme Mtn (3087 ft - 2727P - Lake Whatcom Quad) - March 6, 2005


This mountain may have a local name.  I saw it referred to as Haner  Mtn  on
a map of the Mt Baker area and I ran across a sign on the DNR  logging  road
mentioning the Haner Ranch forest plantings. Whatever its name, this is  the
mountain E of Lookout Mtn on the other side of Lake Whatcom.

My access was up a gated DNR logging road on the S side that left Highway  9
a couple of miles S of Acme, elevation 380 ft. It began  in  clearcuts,  but
immediate and almost constant views of the Twin Sisters and  Mt  Baker  made
up for the initial ugliness as I mostly pushed up the very  steep  road.  At
1.4 miles I went left at a junction and at 2.3 miles came to a  power  line.
At 4.5 miles and 2700 ft the road  leveled  off  for  fast  cruising  as  it
traversed, then gradually dropped 200 ft to  a  4-way  intersection  at  5.9
miles. Here I took the rightmost branch under the power line again,  crossed
a creek, passed under a bright red gate and began the final steep  climb  to
the top at 7.25 miles.

On logged over summits it is sometimes difficult to  determine  the  highest
point, which often may be nothing more than a stump or pile  of  slash,  but
this time I settled on real earth as worthy of that designation.  I  ate  my
lunch  in  a  very  light  (almost  non-existent)  drizzle  watching  clouds
gradually lower over Mt Baker and the Twin Sisters and begin to  obscure  my
view. I found myself hoping that the clouds would turn  into  a  real  storm
and actually dump some much needed precipitation. No such luck.  All  I  got
were clouds.

I met a motorcyclist coming up as I left the summit.  We chatted a bit.   He
had come up from Lake Whatcom on the N side and volunteered  that  his  mode
of transportation was less work than mine, but that on occasion he too  rode
a mountain bike. He passed me again  about  half  way  down  and  asked  for
confirmation that the road we were on led to Highway 9  and  that  he  could
get his motorcycle around the gate. I told him there was no problem  and  he
was off to make his grand loop, and I to make my final fast  plunge  to  the
car.

Total: 14.5 miles, 3200 ft and 4:30 hrs.

Fay Pullen
