Huffaker Mtn (3640 ft - 2320P - Cowlitz Falls Quad) - March 10, 2005


I chose the wrong approach road for this mountain relying on the  map  being
accurate.  It was not. Things started well. I parked at the intersection  of
FR 25 and 2505,  some  5  miles  S  of  Randle,  elevation  1149.  2505  was
moderately graded, smooth treaded, little used with grass growing  down  the
center, and wandered through attractive  woods,  everything  a  forest  road
should  be  for  pleasant  bike  pedaling.  But  shortly  after  the  fourth
switchback it suddenly ended at a junction at 5.1 miles and 2950  ft.  4X4\'s
had gone left, but the map indicated my route was  right  even  though  this
showed no use.  I followed it a short ways but was soon  stopped  by  fallen
trees and brush.  The road was  completely  abandoned.  I  then  tried  left
following the jeep tracks. These soon ended at a  turnaround.   I  continued
on the overgrown spur following it to its end a short ways  on,  5.25  miles
and 3050 ft.

I now had little other choice but to stash the bike and  head  off  on  foot
the remaining half mile and 600 feet to the top. I had not  planned  on  any
footwork as the map showed the road going all the way to the summit.  I  was
dressed in shorts and SS shirt on this very warm day and was not pleased  to
have to pick my way  uphill  through  brush  trying  to  avoid  getting  too
scratched. But by going slow and wandering around a bit I was able to  avoid
the worst of it. Then to add insult to injury,  at  about  3400  ft  I  came
across a good road. Darn!  Where  did  this  road  come  from?  Whatever,  I
followed it the rest of the way to the top where I had a nice view of Mt  St
Helens still belching some steam.

I decided to follow the road down a ways to see  where  it  came  from,  and
thinking maybe I could find a link back to Rd  2505  and  avoid  the  brushy
crosscountry section. I followed it over a mile to 2800 ft  before  figuring
out that I descending to the W (I was to the E)  and  would  never  hook  up
with my road. I never saw any sign of where 2505 would  have  joined  in.  I
later determined that this road must  be  the  undesignated  4WD  road  that
climbs the S and W slopes from Woods Cr Road. So I had to retrace my  steps.
Once back to my bike and down the spur it was a very pleasant cruise to  the
car. I did like this road.

Total: 10.5 mile by bike, 1  mile  on  foot,  2630  ft  and  3:45  hrs  (not
counting my detour)

Bluff Mtn (2600 ft - 1020P - Greenhorn Buttes Quad) With  several  hours  of
daylight left I decided to add this bonus. I began  from  the  gate  several
miles up Road 2506 where it intersects 037, elevation  1735.  This  gate  is
closed from Dec to April to protect wildlife habitat.  It  must  be  working
because as I cycled up this pleasant  road  I  saw  over  a  dozen  deer.  I
followed 2506 then 056 to the end at  2.6  miles  and  2550  ft,  walked  10
minutes to the wooded summit and zipped back to the car. Total:  5.2  miles,
875 ft, 1:40 hrs.

I then tried to get up Kraus Ridge (2400+ ft, 480P) starting from  the  same
point, up spur 037 (also  gated)  but  again  the  map  wasn\'t  accurate.  I
pedaled up to the  ridge  at  2000  ft  and  descended  to  1800  ft  before
realizing I had missed the road that was supposed to stay on the  ridge.   I
never saw any sign of it. As it was getting dark and I would have over  half
a mile to go crosscoutry along the ridge I quit for the day, satisfied  with
two summits.

Fay Pullen






