            'title' => 'Lyman Hill (4280+ ft - 3400P - Sedro-Wooley North Quad) - March 27, 2005',
            'tr' => '

Lyman Hill (4280+ ft - 3400P - Sedro-Wooley North Quad) - March 27, 2005


I certainly picked the hard way up this mountain.  Whatever  you  do,  don\'t
go the way I did, at least not with a bike.

I started from the gate on Pipeline  Road  1.2  miles  from  Highway  20  in
Lyman, elevation 400 ft, in a light rain.  The  forecast  for  the  day  was
more rain so I expected and was prepared to get wet.  The  map  showed  this
road to climb the S slopes of Lyman Hill and then join a  road  coming  from
the mainline logging road to Lyman Pass to the E.  This  it  did,  sort  of.
However, after about a mile it rapidly deteriorated to  a  quad  track  that
was narrow, rough, rutted, muddy and overgrown.  Then  after  a  switchback,
bad became worse as the old roadbed was completely decommissioned with  deep
ditches where culverts had been removed at every creek  crossing.  Even  the
quads gave up. I continued to wrestle my bike across the many trenches,  all
the time seriously debating whether I should  just  admit  defeat  and  turn
around. I decided to at least go as far as the junction with the  road  from
the E.  If things didn\'t improve, then I would turn around.

At 4 miles and 1600 ft I hit the junction, which turned out to  be  a  well-
maintained and well-used logging road. I  kicked  myself  for  not  choosing
this road in the first place. With a late start and having used up almost  2
hours just to get this far, time was getting away  from  me,  but  with  the
prospect of a good road to pedal up from now on, I felt I could  still  make
the top and get most of the way down before dark. I had to  stay  alert  and
constantly refer to  the  map  to  choose  the  correct  fork  at  the  many
junctions in the road. At 9 miles and 3600 ft I stashed the bike, after  the
gradually increasing snow depth became too deep for  pedaling,  and  slogged
the last 1.5 miles to the top, which was  adorned  by  a  cluster  of  radio
towers of various sizes and shapes. The rain had turned to snow.

Back at the bike, I put on all my clothes and changed to dry gloves for  the
ride down.  The weather was getting worse and it was raining harder  now.  I
wisely passed on my  uphill  route  from  Pipeline  Road,  sticking  to  the
logging road all the way down. I crossed Jones Cr, passed a  gate  and  came
to the mainline road just at dark, 17 miles and  580  ft.  I  then  unwisely
tried to find a shortcut to Highway 20. The mainline  road  meanders  E  for
3.5 miles before hitting 20 some  3  miles  from  Pipeline  Road.   The  map
showed several lesser roads going W that would have saved some mileage.  The
only problem was I couldn\'t find the right one. I wandered  around  dead-end
roads in the dark for over an hour only to end up having to go back  to  the
mainline road after all.  You would think I would  have  learned  my  lesson
earlier - STICK TO THE MAIN ROAD!

Fortunately, I was able to do most of the mileage back to Pipeline  Road  on
Hamilton Cemetery Road which parallels 20 and 20 has  a  wide  shoulder  for
the .8 miles where I was forced onto it. The  last  bit  was  the  1.2  mile
climb up Pipeline Road to the most welcome sight of my  car.  The  word  wet
doesn\'t do justice to my condition upon arrival.

Total: 4400 ft,  28  miles  and  7.5  hours  (not  counting  my  crazy  lost
wanderings).

Fay Pullen






