Captain Point (5724 ft - 764P - Captain Point Quad) - March 30, 2005


I was able to drive to the Martin Cr TH for the Iron Goat  Trail,  elevation
2400 ft, before being stopped by some 4-6 inch of new  wet  slushy  slippery
snow. Fresh vehicle tracks continued but I soon caught  up  to  them  on  my
skis in the form of 3 pickup trucks stuck and  in  the  process  of  turning
around and unloading snowmobiles in the middle of the road. It is beyond  me
why they didn\'t stop at the TH before they got  stuck  and  where  they  had
plenty of room to park and maneuver. It is not like they  saved  any  energy
by not having to walk farther- they had snowmobiles for goodness sakes.

Whatever, I made use of the snowmobile  tracks  and  didn\'t  have  to  break
trail for a mile or so until their tracks headed uphill to the  right  on  a
side road toward Windy Ridge and I continued  straight  ahead  on  the  main
road. A short ways on, I turned left  at  a  junction,  crossed  Martin  Cr,
turned right, passed a gate and began a long slow climb. After 2.5  hours  of
hard work breaking trail in ever deepening snow, I left the road at the  5th
switchback, elevation 4500 ft, heading for the saddle S  of  Captain  Point.
Progress that had  been  slow  became  even  slower  as  snow  deepened  and
steepened. Another exhausting hour and half got me to the open  basin  below
the saddle. On the final climb to the ridge, progress  that  had  been  slow
became almost non-existent.  The last few feet were too steep and  deep  for
skis.  I had to take them off, then excavate a trench uphill compacting  the
snow as I went to form steps firm enough that I wouldn\'t  sink  in  over  my
waist.  This is the most snow I have run into all "winter".

It took an hour to force my way to the saddle  and  another  30  minutes  to
work my way the short distance along the ridge to the summit. Sunbreaks  and
partial views revealed a newly created winter wonderland,  a  sight  I  have
not had enough of this year.  The ski down was fast but clumsy in  the  deep
snow.  I emerged onto the road 30 minutes later looking like a snowman.   My
solitude was immediately disrupted by 2  snowmobiles  coming  uphill.  Where
were they when they would have done me some good in  breaking  trail  on  my
way up?  Now all they did was destroy my track and form deep ruts that  made
skiing down the road a challenge. But once back to  the  main  road,  enough
snowmobiles had been by that the track was smooth  and  facilitated  a  fast
pleasant run the rest of the way to car, even on the flat sections.  At  the
bottom I passed more trucks parked smack in the middle  of  the  road,  this
time loading snowmobiles. I had no idea this  road  was  such  a  mecca  for
these machines. I thought I would have the place to myself.

Total: 12 miles, 3400 ft, 6 hrs up and 1:30 hrs down.

Fay Pullen
