Anderson Mtn (3364 ft - 3034P - Lake Whatcom Quad) - April 3, 2005


I began this ride from the DNR gate on Alger Mtn Road, elevation 350 ft,  on
the SW side of Anderson Mtn. The gate was open and in fact looked as  if  it
hadn\'t been closed in a very long time. As I was  unloading  my  bike  in  a
steady rain, a convoy of trucks pulling trailers filled  with  quads  passed
by headed uphill. Once they passed, though,  I  had  the  pleasant  road  to
myself and I was able to pedal up the  moderate  grade  all  the  way  to  a
gravel pit at 3.7 miles and 1800 ft.

Once past the pit, the road steepened and  began  to  switchback.   A  short
ways on I met the herd of quads coming downhill. I have no idea  where  they
had been or where they  came  from  as  I  never  saw  their  trucks  parked
anywhere. At the second switchback, elevation 2400 ft,  the  rain  began  to
turn to snow and snow started appearing on the road. The 4-wheelers\'  tracks
allowed me to continue with my bike for  a  while,  but  shortly  after  the
third switchback, at 5.8 miles and 2800 ft, the snow became  too  deep  even
for them and their tracks stopped. Here I stashed the bike and continued  on
foot.

I slowly plodded along the now almost level road with  wet  snowfall  adding
to the already 8-12 inches of snow on the ground.  At one point I looked  up
to see a cat-like creature stroll across the road and into the woods a  mere
100 feet from me.  Size and the lack of a tail indicated it to be a  bobcat.
 It was either unaware of or unconcerned  by  my  presence.  After  about  a
mile, I rounded the nose of the S ridge of Anderson and  started  N  up  the
spur road along the ridge. I stuck to  the  main  track  for  another  mile,
taking a left then two rights at junctions until coming to a  switchback  at
a saddle.  From here it was a short but snowy wet trek  into  the  woods  to
the high point.

I didn\'t relish the thought of the 2-mile plod back to my  bike,  1  mile  S
along the ridge then another mile N again along the main  road.  Looking  at
the map, it seemed like it would be so simple to head directly  W  from  the
summit and cut across both roads, a distance of no more than .3 of  a  mile.
Of course, things are never  as  simple  as  they  look,  and  I  knew  they
wouldn\'t be. For one thing, I didn\'t have my GPS  with  me  (It,  or  rather
it\'s software, was under repair).  Nor did I have a compass (Shame on  me!).
I know how confusing things can get once you are surrounded by the  sameness
of dense forest and terrain. Without  a  direction  indicator  would  I  get
myself in trouble? For another  thing,  the  terrain  was  unappealing,  all
snowy and brushy.  I would get all wet.  But then I was  already  wet.   How
much wetter than wet  can  one  get?  In  the  end  I  couldn\'t  resist  the
shortcut. And, yes, I did get very confused and I did get wetter  than  wet,
even slithering down a creek bed and wading through a marsh,  but  not  only
did I hit the road but I came out right at my  bike  and  it  only  took  30
minutes. I was most pleased.

I went slowly through the snow, but once on dirt again  I  zipped  down  the
road on my trusty bike at speeds at times  in  excess  of  20mph  hoping  to
reach my warm car before my entire body turned into a frozen Popsicle. As  a
footnote, when I unloaded my bike at home, the back tire was flat.  I am  so
glad the tire lasted until I got to the car.

Total: 11.6 miles by bike, 2.3 miles on  foot,  3000  ft  and  5  hrs.   Fay
Pullen




