Boistfort Pk (3120+ ft - 2680P - Boistfort Pk Quad) - April 8, 2005


The nice thing about pursuing silly lists is that it gets you to places  you
would never go otherwise. This peak took me to the SW part of the state,  an
area I have seldom visited. Beginning in Pe Ell on Highway 6, I turned  left
onto Pe Ell-McDonald road (signed to Vader),  right  onto  Halsea  Cr  Road,
left onto a main logging road and right again, parking by the open  gate  on
the road leading up the N ridge of Boistfort  Pk,  elevation  800  ft.  Rain
that  had  been  forecast  for  the  day,  especially  in  the  S,  did  not
materialize and I started in semi-sunshine.  Biking is  certainly  more  fun
when it isn\'t raining!

The road began steeply, climbing 1000 ft in 2 miles, then leveled off a  bit
upon reaching the ridge,  where  pedaling  and  views  of  tree  farms  were
enjoyable.  I went left at a main junction at 2.7 miles and  straight  ahead
at a 4-way junction at 3.2 miles, elevation  2200  ft.  A  mostly  level  to
slightly down section on the E side of the ridge went past  recent  logging,
then through nice woods, to a Weyerhaeuser  "red dot" gate at  a  switchback
at 5 miles (a red dot means no public vehicle entry). A steep  .5  mile  led
back to the crest for the final up and down, but mostly up, 1.5 miles  along
the ridge to the top. The last mile was very steep indeed, gaining  800  ft,
and got progressively rougher.  At  the  last  junction,  when  the  tallest
summit tower was in view, I erred in taking a  right  spur  directly  toward
it. This soon dead-ended.  I had to backtrack and take the left spur,  which
circled around to the S before reaching the cluster of 6 COM towers on  top,
7 miles.

I started down 30 minutes later.  I just love my new  bike.  I  am  still  a
very cautious downhill rider, often walking down suspicious terrain  that  I
feel could be hazardous to my health.  But with this  bike  I  can  go  down
things I never would have tried with my old bike.   Rear  suspension  really
does help, as do disk brakes.  Anyway, I was able to  ride  down  the  steep
stuff, although slowly, then cruise the rest (except for the short  annoying
uphill sections) and zip  back  to  the  car  in  under  an  hour.  This  is
definitely logging country but, although I  could  hear  truck  traffic  and
active logging going on in the distance, I met no one on my  route  and  had
the whole peak to myself. I drove  back  to  I-5  through  lovely  Boistfort
Prairie.

Total: 14 miles, 2900 ft and 4 hrs.

Fay Pullen


