Mt Walker (2804 ft - 2044P - Mt Walker Quad) - April 14, 2005


This is one of those mountains that I have driven past countless  times  but
never stopped to hike up or even drive up (there is a trail up  it  as  well
as a road).  That was before I knew it was a 2000P peak  and  before  I  was
into biking up as many of those as I could.

The Mt Walker road begins off Highway 101 S of Quilcene, elevation  750  ft.
I soon passed the TH for the trail up the mountain where several  cars  were
parked and I almost got tangled up with a hiker\'s overly friendly dogs.  The
entire 4.5 miles of road was a steady  consistent  unrelenting  500  ft  per
mile climb. With no level sections for a rest, I just kept pedaling away  in
granny gear and 90 minutes later emerged onto the N  viewpoint  to  a  short
but furious hailstorm. I  caught  glimpses  of  snow-covered  Olympic  Peaks
through the clouds, then pedaled to the S viewpoint for  a  better  view  of
Quilcene Bay, after which I flew down the road in 18  minutes  flat.  Total:
9.8 miles, 2100 ft and 2:20 hrs.

What to do now? I was not ready to end the day, but neither  was  I  up  for
another big effort, so I went looking for bonus peaks in  the  area  that  I
could drive most of the way up. My first attempt was Buck Mtn  (3760+  ft  -
1000P - Mt Walker Quad). I  drove  up  Rocky  Brook  road  (FR2620),  almost
directly across 101 from the Mt Walker road, but  was  stopped  by  snow  at
2600 ft on the spur leading to the summit. Slogging  up  the  road  did  not
appeal.  On to Plan B and lower summits. I  continued  on  the  Rocky  Brook
road to the Jackson Cr road following it and a spur to  an  end  (some  snow
encountered on the way but my Cherokee made it through) on the  E  ridge  of
Mt Turner (3400+ ft - 520P -Brinnon Quad), elevation 3000 ft.  I  hiked  the
remaining 1/3 mile up and back down the  ridge  in  wet  snowy  rhododendron
thickets to the densely wooded summit in 47  minutes.  Believe  me,  Olympic
rhododendrons can rival the worst Cascade brush. I then drove back down  the
Jackson Cr road to the end of the rough spur on the E  side  of  Green  Hill
(2380 ft - 420P - Brinnon Quad) where a 5 minute walk put me on the  top  of
that hill.  I did not  feel  the  same  sense  of  accomplishment  on  these
summits that I feel after a hard  workout,  but  I  must  admit  I  had  fun
exploring miles of logging roads by car. I  also  had  nice  views  of  Hood
Canal country and saw  two  deer.  Not  too  bad.  It  certainly  is  easier
exploring by car than by bike. On the return  I  continued  down  the  Rocky
Brook road making a loop that came out on  the  Dosewallips  road  and  then
Highway 101 near Brinnon.

Fay Pullen






