            'tr' => '

Goat Mtn (5407 ft - 2087P - Spirit Lk East Quad)  - April 18, 2005


I joined forces with Paul Klenke for this trip. We drove FR26 out of  Randle
to Ryan Lake and then 2612 about 2 miles, passing the Goat Mtn  TH,  parking
at spur 635, elevation 2840 ft. This spur is shown on the USGS  map  and  is
directly S of Goat\'s E summit. There was a light dusting of new snow on  the
trees, but there did not appear to be that much snow  higher  up  from  what
could be seen. We, perhaps unwisely, chose not to carry snowshoes.

We followed the overgrown brushy spur, getting quite wet in the process,  to
the 4th switchback, elevation 3800 ft, exiting right across a creek  into  a
forested band. Travel in the trees was fairly open and pleasant and we  made
good progress up the steep slope until we  hit  deep  unconsolidated  slushy
snow beginning somewhere around 4800  ft.  Thank  heavens  for  Paul\'s  long
strong legs. He broke all the trail in this section  sinking  in  well  over
his knees.  I had a hard enough time  just  following  in  holes  that  were
deeper than my short legs.

We hit the Goat Mtn trail 400 ft below the E summit and began the more  than
a mile traverse to the W and  accepted  higher  summit.  Frustratingly  deep
snow continued until we rounded a slight  corner  to  a  different  exposure
where more melting had occurred. Better conditions continued as we  followed
the ridge W to the high point. One small rocky pinnacle required a  traverse
on snowy rock ledges that added a bit of interest.

The W summit is measured as 5407 ft.  The E summit has a  5400  ft  contour.
They are obviously very close in elevation.  I  had  brought  my  clinometer
along to help determine which was really higher. All  day  the  weather  had
alternated between snow showers  and  clouds  and  sunshine  and  blue  sky.
Naturally, once we were on top, we were encased in clouds and fog and  never
really had a clear sight to the E summit. Oh  well,  there  was  always  the
chance we could do it in the opposite direction. So off to the E  summit  we
went. One hour later we were on that top and we did have a  clear  view.  We
both sighted to the W summit. Paul did a better job of it  than  I  did  and
concluded it to be 2 degrees lower as measured by the clinometer.   I  leave
it to the mathematicians to decide if that translates to mean the  W  summit
is actually lower than the E summit (I\'m told the  curvature  of  the  earth
has to be figured in).  Since I climbed  both  it  is  no  longer  of  great
importance to me.

For the return, we dropped directly S off the E summit. For  a  few  hundred
feet we were able to do a semi sitting glissade before the snow became  such
a quagmire we just sank in and went  no  where.  Deep  postholing  was  soon
replaced by slipping and sliding down remnants of  melting  snow  and  slick
mud. We stuck to the forest band all the way down, bypassing  the  overgrown
road, and hit the road Â½ mile from the car.  A much better way to go.

3:15 hr to W summit, 1 hr W summit to E summit, 1 hr down, 3300 ft total.

Fay Pullen
