 Chelan Butte (3835 ft - 2275P - Chelan Quad) - April 22, 2005',
            'tr' => '

Badger Mtn (4254 ft - 2674P - Orondo Quad) - April 21, 2005


From East Wenatchee I drove the paved  Badger  Mtn  Road  N  several  miles,
climbing up onto the farmland plateau  of  this  broad  bulky  mountain  and
parked just S of the  intersection  with  Clark  Road,  elevation  3400  ft.
Despite starting so high I was still able to get in my desired  2000  ft  of
elevation gain due to the rolling up and down nature of the terrain.

I began biking by crossing to the N of Badger Mtn Road onto a farm road  and
proceeding to seek out a back way to the summit on dirt roads.  I  found  my
map to be less than  accurate  several  times.  I  will  not  give  detailed
directions, as I doubt anyone could follow them or would want  to  for  that
matter.  Suffice it to say I wandered around a series of farm roads,  closed
roads and rough tracks, boldly passing a no trespassing sign in a farm  yard
(no one was around to ask  permission),  crossing  through  two  gates  and,
after forced cross-country across sagebrush prairie when a road just  ended,
went under two decrepit barbed wire fences before hitting a  powerline  road
and finally making my way to the dual survey markers  on  top.  Despite  the
uncertainty of my route I greatly enjoyed this ride  through  farmland  with
the ever present backdrop of the snow covered Enchantments always in view.

Not wanting to press my luck and  (rightly)  anger  some  irate  farmer  for
trespassing, I did not reverse my route,  but  sought  out  a  way  back  to
Badger Mtn Road as quickly as possible. I normally don\'t like  biking  paved
roads, but this road had little traffic and  it  was  rather  refreshing  to
actually use my big chainwheel for a change and fly downhill at  30  mph.  I
did have to be wary of some gusty crosswinds, however, or I might  have  let
it rip even faster. Total: 20.5 miles, 2170 ft and 3:50 hrs


Chelan Butte (3835 ft - 2275P - Chelan Quad) - April 22, 2005


This is one steep road, too steep really for biking up, at least for  me.  I
drove as far as I dared (and still make my  2000  ft  gain)  up  the  Chelan
Butte Road out of Chelan, parking just before the pavement ended,  elevation
1800 ft. I was mighty tempted to keep driving, but standards are  standards.
I was able to pedal a few short sections but mostly I pushed all the way  to
the top, 2000 ft in 3.5 miles and 1.5 hours.

Views from the top (and much of the way up) were outstanding - Chelan,  Lake
Chelan, snowy mountains all around, the Columbia River and right across  the
river a birdseye view of my cabin and property.   I  can\'t  believe  I  have
been going back and forth to my cabin for 25 years and never took  the  time
to come up to this viewpoint. I found a nice  rock  outcrop  away  from  the
many towers for a pleasant rest and snack. On the way down I  took  a  short
detour to Pt 3716, a better destination than the tower studded  high  point.
This is where the hang gliders and para gliders launch. Then it  was  reward
time for all my pushing as I bombed back to the car in  15  minutes.  Total:
7.2 miles, 2100 ft and 2:15 hrs

Fay Pullen




