Opportunity Mtn (7502 ft - 462P - Chiwaukum Mtns Quad) and Painters Thumb
(6744 ft - 504P -Big Jim Mtn Quad) - April 26-28, 2005

Oh the best laid plans often go awry and in this  case  turned  an  expected
two-day trip into three. My plan was to hike in on day one, set up camp  and
climb Painters Thumb. On day two I would climb  Opportunity  and  then  hike
out.  I didn\'t allow for  the  difficulty  of  getting  across  the  S  Fork
Chiwaukum Cr.

My approach was up the Chiwaukum Cr Trail  off  Highway  2  (1900  ft).  The
first mile is along a gated road accessing private  land  and  homes  before
turning to actual trail always in  sight  or  sound  of  the  raging  creek.
Alternating fields of glacier lilies and trilliums decorated  the  way.  The
day was very warm and sunny. At 6 miles the trail crossed the N  Fork  on  a
good log and I proceeded up the S Fork  Trail,  past  a  junction  with  the
Painter Cr Trail, to a lovely campsite, complete with a  flat  stone  table,
in upper Timothy Meadow (4000 ft) right next to the creek (8.5  miles,  2300
ft, 4:30 hrs). There were patches of snow but most of the meadow was bare.

My original plan (A) was to continue up the trail .5 mile  to  the  junction
with the Index Cr Trail, cross the creek there and climb the W ridge to  the
top of Painters Thumb. But right across the creek from my camp  was  a  very
appealing direct route up a broad gully on the NW  slopes  (Plan  B).  There
was some brush lower down but above were open slopes soon  turning  to  snow
that went all the way to the summit ridge. The only problem  was  I  had  to
get across the S Fork Chiwaukum Cr, no trivial task. I searched  around  for
a log.  No luck. However, right at my camp the creek looked fordable. I  was
halfway across in bare feet, about knee deep, with the  deeper  and  swifter
water yet to come, when I knew I couldn\'t make it.   Already  my  feet  were
numb in the freezing water and I turned around before they wouldn\'t work  at
all.

Back to Plan A. I hiked to the Index Cr  Junction  hoping  the  trail  would
lead me to a log across the creek.  Much to my dismay,  there  was  no  log,
only a ford much worse than the one I had just tried.  I hiked all  the  way
back to camp along the bank of the creek looking for a way across and  found
nothing but a raging torrent. On to Plan C, except that I didn\'t  know  what
Plan C was yet.  I would have to ponder the matter,  or  perhaps  just  give
up.

I was annoyed that I had several hours of daylight left and nowhere  to  go.
I hadn\'t even brought a book, as I didn\'t think I would have time  to  read.
I spent an hour making a feeble attempt  to  build  a  bridge.   Impossible,
given my limited strength and the swift current.  I  did  paint  a  picture,
then turned in early, before dark. I marked  the  high  water  line  of  the
creek before going to bed.

The next morning I noticed the water line had  gone  down  several  vertical
inches. Hmmm! But my first priority was climbing Opportunity, so I  set  off
up the trail at 6:40 to that end. After about 1 mile, I left  the  trail  at
4500 ft and headed NW upslope, well to the right of the major gully  between
Opportunity and Pt 7157.  This whole slope is quite brushy.  I made  use  of
game trails and a shallow dry rocky gully, but mostly I battled brush  until
gradually getting above it at about 5600 ft. Pleasant open slopes  continued
up until I could traverse talus and scree high under the cliffs of  Pt  7157
to the saddle with Opportunity. From here  a  steep  scramble  up  rock  and
small snow patches led to the final easy walk to the high point at  the  far
end of the bare ridge (3500 ft, 4 hrs). I had carried snowshoes and ice  axe
all the way up but used neither as there was very little snow on the  south-
facing route I went up. This really surprised me given the conditions I  had
run into on Frigid and  Goat  just  a  week  ago.  Looking  across  to  more
northern exposures encompassing Snowgrass and Big Chiwaukum there  certainly
was more snow but it still looked rather pitiful for this time of year.

I left a register in the summit cairn before starting  down.  I  sought  out
snow slopes for the descent following the ridge toward Pt  6844  as  far  as
possible before traversing much lower below Pt 7157 back to my ascent  route
and arriving in camp 2.5 hours later.

This day was cloudy and cooler than yesterday. When I  looked  at  my  water
marker the level was still down.  Thus I came up with Plan  C  for  Painters
Thumb. I would try again to ford the creek at camp, but this  time  I  would
wear my boots and I would tie my scramble rope to a tree.  Then  If  I  lost
my footing at least I would be swept to the proper side. And  since  it  was
now 2:30 I would most likely spend another night. I was  able  to  wade  the
creek without too much difficulty.  The water  level  was  lower  and  boots
make all the difference in protecting feet, but that did mean my  feet  were
wet for the rest of the day.  Even though I removed socks and  insoles,  the
lining of the boots was so wet it soon soaked everything else.

The initial brush was annoying but not terrible and only lasted 500  ft  and
40 minutes. Then it was clear sailing up open slopes and snow.  Most of  the
snow was good step kicking, but deep and slushy and made my  wet  feet  even
wetter and very cold. The only hard part was near the ridge  in  the  forest
where the slope was very steep and thin snow covering frozen dirt  made  for
a very slick surface.  I had left snowshoes in camp but brought  my  ice  ax
and this was the only place I used it. Once on the snowy  ridge,  it  was  a
short walk to the small rocky summit (2750 ft, 2:40  hrs).  I  left  another
register.

It took 1.5 hrs to get  down.   I  was  little  worried  about  finding  the
crossing as once in the brush I couldn\'t see where I was going, but  I  came
out right at it and had no trouble getting back  across,  despite  the  fact
that the water level had begun to rise again. It was 7:00 and I  was  tired,
wet and cold. All I wanted to do was crawl into my warm  sleeping  bag.   It
is nice to have the option to spend another night  when  desired.  Food  was
sparse. For dinner I ate my lunch sandwich that I had never  gotten  to  and
had cup after cup of warm drink.  For breakfast I made  do  with  an  energy
bar and cup of tea. I was on my way at 7:00 the next morning and to the  car
by 10:30. Much better than dragging out the night before in the dark.

Total: 26 miles and 9000 ft

Fay Pullen




