Silo Mtn (4150 ft - 2430P - Haystack Mtn Quad) - May 15, 2005


It seems like the majority of my bike rides up  2000P  peaks  are  in  lousy
weather.  Maybe the fact that I save these trips as something to  do  during
bad conditions has something to do with it. At  any  rate,  I  began  biking
from the gate (elevation 150 ft)  just  off  South  Skagit  Hwy  near  Sedro
Woolley in a steady rain. The road was a very steady steep 500 ft/mile,  but
I was able to pedal up most of it as long as I never  stopped.   I  find  it
very difficult to get going again if I stop on a steep grade.

After several switchbacks, at about 3.5 miles, the main road went right  and
I went left. The steady rain was now a downpour  and  water  poured  off  my
helmet,  dripped  off  my  nose  and  my  feet  began  getting  wet  despite
waterproof booties. Fortunately, the temperature  was  mild  so  I  was  not
cold.  At 5.5 miles I took another left and the road turned into a  pleasant
grassy mossy little used spur. After another switchback  I  pedaled  through
the saddle between Haystack and Silo. The road  went  farther  than  my  map
indicated, for which I was very grateful as I was not looking forward  to  a
wet bushwhack, traversing to directly below the summit on the  W  side  (7.9
miles). A 15 minute scramble up 250 ft of talus and steep dirt  led  to  the
wooded top.  I didn\'t even get any wetter than I already was  as  there  was
little brush and it had miraculously stopped raining.

Back at the saddle I decided to add Haystack to the itinerary.  On  the  way
up I was thinking of passing it by, as at that point it was  so  wet  all  I
wanted to do was climb Silo and get out.  But with the  rain  stopped,  both
my spirits and ambition improved.  Haystack, at 4045 ft only has 285  ft  of
prominence but it does have an official name. So I pedaled  to  the  end  of
the short grassy track to  the  SE  side  and  scrambled  up  steep  forest,
skirting an interesting cliffy area on the way, to the top.

The weather continued to improve on the 45 minute blast down to the car  and
I actually got a few views of the Skagit River Valley.

Total 16 miles, 4400 ft and 5:30 hrs.

Fay Pullen


