Chiwaukum Mtns (7423 ft - 423P - Chiwaukum Mtns Quad) - May 17, 2005


I was sure lucky with my choice of route on this peak. All of it  is  cross-
country  and  I  was  afraid  I  would  run  into  thousands  of   feet   of
bushwhacking.  As it turned out it  was  all  clear  sailing,  though  quite
steep, with very little brush.  Good thing too, or I would have had  trouble
completing the climb in the time I had available.

I began at the White Pine TH E  of  Stevens  Pass,  elevation  2800  ft,  by
hiking the trail 5 minutes before heading uphill at a likely spot into  open
woods. At 3450 ft I hit the crest of a spur  ridge  where  travel  got  even
better as I followed this ridge through alternating open  areas  and  woods.
There was even a bit of a faint trail much of the way.  At 6000 ft  my  spur
ridge merged with the NW ridge of Pt 7132 as I began encountering  snow  and
I got my first view of both Pt 7132 and my objective. After a  short  narrow
rocky section, the ridge leveled out a bit with more snow. I crossed to  the
S side and traversed directly to the  saddle  between  Chiwaukum  and  7132.
This traverse was not bad, but recent storms  had  coated  the  scrub  trees
with melting rime, which got my boots and legs quite wet.

From the saddle it was an easy pleasant scramble up remnant  snow  and  rock
to the summit (4700 ft and 3:50 hrs). I expected to  find  a  register,  but
did not so I added one of mine. Visibility was  reasonable,  with  views  to
Jim Hill, Arrowhead, Big Chiwaukum, Chiwaukum Lake and  Larch  Lake,  but  I
could see weather approaching from the W.  Soon it would be  upon  me  so  I
did not tarry long.

On the way back, rather than traverse below Pt 7132 through the  wet  trees,
I went over the top and followed the ridge down until I ran into  my  uphill
tracks in the snow. By now the weather had caught up to me and it  began  to
snow. It didn\'t last long, maybe 30  minutes,  but  it  did  get  everything
white and wet (me included).

 It is always harder to follow a minor spur ridge down than  up,  as  it  is
frequently very easy to get off track, but GPS waypoints kept  me  on  route
until the very end. I didn\'t exit the spur soon enough and ended up in  very
steep  congested  woods  slithering  down  hanging  logs  trying  to   avoid
vegetated cliffs until I was able to traverse back to  the  friendly  forest
of my up route. It was only a minor detour.  Still, I was most happy when  I
stumbled out of the woods onto the trail in almost the exact  same  place  I
had left it.

Total: Maybe 6 miles, 4950 ft, 6:40 hrs.
