            'tr' => '

Big Snagtooth (8330+ ft - Silver Star Mtn Quad) - May 25-27, 2005


I doubt that many climbers take  three  days  to  climb  Big  Snagtooth.  Of
course I started late on the first day and came out early on the  third  day
so that doesn\'t really count as three full  days.   Still,  it  took  longer
than I expected. Oh, I expected the summit block to give me  problems.  When
a shoulder stand is suggested to begin  the  final  moves,  just  how  am  I
supposed to achieve that going solo? But I have many  tricks  up  my  sleeve
and I was pretty sure I could find a way if I just had enough time.  What  I
didn\'t expect was the extremely icy conditions I encountered in  the  summit
gully.

Plans for the Memorial Day weekend with others didn\'t work out,  so  at  the
last minute, not wanting to let good weather go  unused,  I  changed  to  my
backup. This got me a very late start and it was  12:30  pm  before  I  left
town. Another delay of 20 minutes at the rockslide near Newhalem  (Are  they
ever going to get this fixed?  It must be going on 3  years  now.),  and  it
was 4:30 by the time I left the car on the shoulder of Hwy 20 near MP166,  4
miles E of Washington Pass (elev 4300 ft).

I dropped 250 ft down road cut debris and talus  into  the  woods  to  cross
Early Winters Cr. I looked for but found no  sign  of  any  climbers  trail.
One must be there as this is the start of the  main  route  up  Silver  Star
Mtn. I crossed the creek on  a  log  and  began  a  rising  traverse  across
numerous ravines into the Willow Cr drainage.  The day  was  warm,  my  pack
heavy with 10 extra pounds of climbing gear, and there was  moderate  brush,
all of which conspired to make progress slower than  desired.  Eventually  I
headed left steeply  uphill,  soon  intersecting  and  following  the  creek
draining Snagtooth Basin. Above 6000 ft I began  running  into  wet,  slushy
snow. At 8:15 and 6700 ft, I found a nice bivy spot on a flat knoll  to  the
left of the creek, with just enough time to set up camp and eat before  dark
(2.5 miles, 2650 ft, 3:45 hr).

I was on my way the next morning by 5:45. In 20 minutes I was  in  Snagtooth
Basin. Snow in the basin was unconsolidated,  but  as  I  turned  right  and
headed to the ridge to the S the snow turned crusty then  icy  as  I  neared
its upper melt-freeze edge.  I opted for loose scree the rest of the way  to
the  7500  ft  ridge  saddle.  Following  to  the  right  of  the  ridge  on
alternating hard snow and scree brought me to the 8200 ft  Willow  Tooth-Big
Snagtooth saddle. It was only 7:45, the summit rocks looked sunny and  snow-
free, and things were looking great.  Then it all  fell  apart.  First,  the
guidebook directions were confusing (aren\'t they often?).  One  implied  you
could climb directly from the saddle, but should avoid  the  central  gully.
Another mentioned a hidden gully with a giant chockstone (is this  the  same
as the central gully?) but said it was to the SW (it is actually on  the  SW
slope but to get to it you must go to the NE). Second, I wasn\'t  sure  which
rock block was the summit. There were three visible. I knew  you  could  see
the summit from the saddle, but that isn\'t too helpful  if  you  don\'t  know
which one it is.

I spent an hour or so checking out possibilities. A route directly from  the
saddle looked possible but more than the class 3-4 I was expecting.  I  then
contoured to the right on the SW face below a massive block but was  stopped
by a deep gully. Perhaps this was the "hidden gully". For  my  third  try  I
descended until I could contour into this  gully.   When  I  saw  the  giant
chockstone near the top I  knew  this  was  the  scramble  route.  The  only
problem was it was filled with snow.  Still, it didn\'t look that bad or  too
steep.  How wrong I was! In that  dark  shady  gully  where  the  sun  never
shines the snow was very hard. Kicking steps didn\'t make a dent.   I  hadn\'t
brought crampons so that left chopping steps.

For the next hour I chopped steps and was making progress,  however  slowly,
until I came to the end of the snow where the gully made  a  slight  jog  to
the right at a rock  step  and  things  went  from  bad  to  worse.  Here  I
encountered water ice from melting snow running down the rock and  freezing.
To continue up I had to make a dicey move to the right across the  ice  onto
a slab that also had a thin coating  of  ice.  The  first  priority  was  to
anchor myself in. Fortunately, I had put on my harness at the saddle, but  I
had not racked up.  I find a dangling rack gets in the way when  scrambling.
I was in a precarious position perched on cut steps and a rock sticking  out
of the snow, yet somehow I managed to take off my pack, get out my rack  and
slings and rope and attach myself to a horn off to the side  (thank  heavens
that was there). Then I tried to protect the step across.  No  luck.   There
were cracks all right, but they were all coated with ice.  Cams  won\'t  hold
on ice.  I\'m not sure how long I dinked around trying  to  figure  something
out. I was so focused I lost all track of time. I almost gave up,  but  with
nothing to lose I began chopping at the ice with my axe.  That didn\'t do  my
poor aluminum axe much good (for once I really wish I had  brought  along  a
heavier steel axeâ¦ and cramponsâ¦ and maybe some ice screws as well).  To  my
surprise I was able to chip the ice off the rock and  find  some  reasonable
footholds underneath. With that done I could make the step  onto  the  slab.
When  a  nice  ice-free  crack  on  the  other  side  provided  much  wanted
protection, I breathed a sigh of relief.  For me this was the  crux  of  the
climb. My troubles weren\'t over, as water ice continued in the  bed  of  the
gully (under the giant chockstone) the rest of the way to the  top,  but  so
did good cracks to provide protection.

At 11:30 I reached the top of the gully and the base of  the  summit  block,
blessedly in the sun. I anchored the top end of the  rope,  rapped  down  to
clean, re-climbed, then focused my attention on the summit block. The  first
10 feet or so were vertical, then it layed back.  It  looked  climbable  but
could not be protected. It was not that high in  total,  maybe  20-30  feet.
The other side was also accessible via a narrow ledge.  So  I  was  able  to
throw my rope over the top (took a dozen or so tries) and anchor it  on  the
other side.  That way I had the protection of a top rope to make  the  moves
onto the block. I left a register in the summit cairn,  rappelled  down  and
dismantled my top rope.

I scrambled a short ways down the ridge to a rap station and did  one  short
rappel directly to the Willow Tooth saddle. Perhaps I should  have  come  up
this way.  It had to be easier than the way I had gone. It  was  now  almost
3:00 and knew I would be spending another night. I seem to be doing more  of
that lately and I kind of like it.  I guess I am slowing down or maybe I  am
just not in as much of a hurry as I used to be. Anyway, I took the  time  to
go up Willow Tooth, an easy ascent from the  saddle,  then  ambled  down  to
camp, enjoying the gorgeous views of Kangaroo Ridge,  Silver  Star  and  the
Wine Spires on the way, arriving at 4:30 (2300ft, 10:45 hr). I made  it  out
to the car by 10:00 am the next day.

Total: A pitiful 7 miles and 5200 ft in 3 days.    Fay Pullen






