            'title' => 'Flora Mtn (8320 - Pinnacle Mtn Quad) - June 2-4, 2005',
            'tr' => '

Flora Mtn (8320 - Pinnacle Mtn Quad) - June 2-4, 2005


Flora is really an easy peak, but getting to it is not.  Of several  choices
for an approach, I picked the one  from  Ten  Mile  Pass  above  Holden,  as
described in Peggy Goldman\'s book Washington\'s Highest Mountains.  I  really
should know better than to trust this book as it  has  led  me  astray  many
times. I even had reservations before starting out. Checking out  the  route
on the map, where it goes over the ridge at the 7800 ft pass between  Devore
Cr and Riddle Cr (just N of Riddle Pk) it seemed to me the contour lines  on
the other  side  where  you  are  supposed  to  descend  looked  darn  close
together, maybe even cliffy! But  I  convinced  myself  that  contour  lines
don\'t tell everything and there must be a scramble  route  down  that  isn\'t
obvious from the map.  After all the book said it was so.  I  really  should
have known better.

After the usual hassles and delays of taking the boat  up  Lake  Chelan  and
the bus to Holden, it was 1:30 by the time I started on the  10  Mile  Falls
trail from the village, elev 3200 ft. But I didn\'t have far to  go.  A  wide
groomed trail led 1 mile to the falls, then started uphill in earnest as  it
steepened and narrowed, climbing above the gorge  before  dropping  back  to
creek level. The trail stayed reasonable, though it  became  rougher  and  a
bit brushy, to a nice campsite along the creek at 4600 ft, where  it  ended.
I continued a short ways upstream on a very faint trail to where  the  creek
draining Ten Mile Pass joined Ten Mile Cr on the other side. A cairn  marked
this spot.  I waded Ten Mile Cr rather than  risk  getting  wet  boots  this
early in the trip by falling off a slippery log. I followed to the  left  of
the side creek and soon ran into a way trail marked by yellow  flagging.  At
5200 ft I hit the Devore Cr trail and followed this good trail the  rest  of
the way to Ten Mile Pass and a lovely camp, elev 6500 ft (5 miles,  3450  ft
and 4 hrs.) There was patchy snow at the pass and the sun was shining.

I awoke the next morning to fog.  Beginning at 6:50, I dropped  to  6200  ft
on soft slushy snow (so much for needing the crampons I lugged  along)  down
the N side of Ten Mile Pass.  I  then  contoured  NE  until  I  could  begin
climbing to the 7800 ft pass N of Riddle Pk. Two snow fingers through  cliff
bands necessitated the use of ice axe, but the snow remained soft.  At  9:00
I arrived at the pass, peered over the other side and  had  my  worst  fears
realized. It was all cliffs cut by ugly loose steep  rock  gullies  plunging
over 1000 ft to the Riddle Cr valley below.   No  scramble  route  here.  It
freaked me out just looking down. No way was I going  to  descend  that.   I
can\'t believe that anyone in their right mind would or has.  Something  must
have been left out of Goldman\'s route description.

Realizing that I could be at the end of my trip if I  didn\'t  come  up  with
something, I began looking for another way  off  the  ridge.   I  could  see
easier terrain on a rib farther N but I couldn\'t get to it  from  the  pass,
so I climbed N along the ridge toward Pt 7990 passing several minor  notches
until at one I met with reasonable scramble terrain on the other side.  Thus
began a complicated 2  hour  descending  traverse  N  over  mostly  class  2
ledges, crossing several broad gullies and one  major  rib,  until  I  could
drop down steeper class 3 terrain to snow fields and the 7000  pass  between
Pt 7990 and Pt 7716. The wide gully leading up to this pass from  Fourth  of
July Basin on Devore Cr is one  of  the  alternative  routes  for  accessing
Flora, a route I would now recommend in retrospect. Looking back at the  way
I had descended, it didn\'t look possible without a rope.  You  can\'t  always
tell just by looking.

From the 7000 pass I continued along the ridge until I could contour  around
the basin SE of Pt 7716 to the 7400 ft pass leading to  Castle  Cr.  This  1
hour contour was more trouble than it was  worth  and  it  would  have  been
easier to just descend to the basin floor at 6800 ft. Another  descent  down
very steep dirt to snow slopes below followed into the Castle  Cr  basin.  I
could pick out a possible broad ledge cutting across cliffs below the  ridge
between Flora and Pt 7734 that would save descending  all  the  way  to  the
basin floor at 6600 ft. This worked well as I  traversed  very  slushy  snow
slopes to the ledge and followed it, at a few points doubtful that it  would
continue, all the way to the snow basin SW of Flora. The  last  bit  was  an
easy but tedious ascent up scree and talus to the summit at 2:20  (6  miles,
3700 ft, 7:30 hrs). Goldman had allowed 8 hours from Ten Mile Pass to  Flora
and I had thought that surely it wouldn\'t take  me  that  long.  Well  guess
what! It was darn close to that. Everything on this convoluted route up  and
down over three passes was more difficult and took longer than I thought  it
would.

The register had been placed on 9/18/03  by  friends  and  family  of  Chris
Weber as a touching memorial to him and the last of the 100 Highest  climbed
for him. The only other entry was Don  Duncan  on  9/27/03.  I  enjoyed  the
views that were now just beginning to appear from a lifting fog, but  I  was
worried about the time.  It could take almost as long to get back as it  had
to come, what with all the ups and downs. That would put it after  dark.  So
I didn\'t stay long.

I retraced my steps to  the  7400  ft  Castle  Cr  pass.  But  from  here  I
descended directly to the basin floor to the S  at  6800  ft  and  contoured
easy terrain to the 7000 ft Devore Cr pass. I most  definitely  did  not  to
want to reverse my scramble route up the E rock face of Pt 7990 to the  7800
ft Riddle pass.  In fact I wasn\'t even sure I  would  be  able  to  stay  on
route to reverse it. Instead I headed directly down from the  7000  pass  on
easy snow toward Fourth of July Basin and Devore Cr.  At  about  6000  ft  I
began an unpleasant brushy traverse S below the cliffs on the W side  of  Pt
7990 to eventually run into the Devore Cr trail, which I was able to  follow
almost all the way to Ten Mile Pass before losing  it  in  snow.  I  dragged
into camp at 8:10 somewhat more than tired, but happy I had made  it  before
dark (12 miles, 5400 ft, 13:20 hrs).

It was very cold that night and by morning my  sopping  wet  boots,  despite
being in the tent vestibule, had frozen hard.  I  had  a  devil  of  a  time
getting them on. Too bad this hadn\'t happened the previous night.  It  would
have been much easier going on hard snow and my boots wouldn\'t  have  gotten
so wet. Despite the cold, I was on my way at 6:55 and I got down  to  Holden
at 9:30 in plenty of time to catch the Lady Express home.

Total: 22 miles and 9000 ft.

Fay Pullen
