            'title' => 'Pilot Peak (7088 ft - 1528P - Downey Mtn Quad) - June 15, 2005',
            'tr' => '

Pilot Peak (7088 ft - 1528P - Downey Mtn Quad) - June 15, 2005


Mike Collins and I joined forces for a day climb.  He  suggested  this  peak
and what a wonderful suggestion it was.  It makes for a long  and  strenuous
day but is well worth the effort. Easy travel on  an  interesting  abandoned
trail,  beautiful  forest,  open  green  ridge  rambling,  views  in   every
directions with Dome Pk front and center - what is not to like? Thanks  Mike
for getting me to an area that wasn\'t even on my radar screen.

We began up the Downey Cr Trail at the end of the washed out Suiattle  River
Road at 8:20, elevation 1400 ft. About 2 miles up the trail,  shortly  after
crossing the creek draining the W side of Downey Mtn,  an  old  trail  takes
off uphill to the right.   The  beginning  is  quite  obscure  and  hard  to
locate, but higher up the trail begins to switchback  and  is  really  quite
good. We actually missed the start  of  the  trail  but  found  it  by  just
heading uphill until we ran into  it.  Once  on  the  trail,  it  is  easily
followed (some windfall of course) through lovely moss carpeted forest  some
3 miles and 2600 ft gain to the tiny lake N of Downey, elevation 4800 ft  (3
hrs).

The trail crosses the outlet of the lake and continues up in woods  to  open
slopes gradually becoming rougher and fainter. A wet mildly  brushy  section
in the transition zone got us both soaked before it changed to  heather  and
low  vegetation.  However,  the  initially  cloudy  and  misty  morning  was
clearing nicely and the appearing sun soon dried us  out.  We  followed  the
fading trail as far as possible as it  headed  NE,  perhaps  to  Lake  5808,
before heading uphill to hit the ridge at 6600 ft, just N of Pt 6640.

We could now see our objective at the end  of  a  gorgeous  startling  green
sinuous undulating ridge. It was now just a matter of following  it  some  2
miles, mostly on the crest, all the way to the top.  Of course there were  a
few minor annoyances, there always are. For one, we had to loss  600  ft  of
elevation to a 6000 ft saddle. There was also  a  short  cliffy  section  to
downclimb (We avoided this by a traverse below it on  the  way  back).  And,
closer to the summit, a steep traverse below rocks  on  slippery  vegetation
and dirt was hard on ankles.  But for the most  part  it  was  a  delightful
high alpine ridge ramble with the backdrop of the many peaks  of  the  North
Cascades and Glacier Peak Wilderness. It really doesn\'t get any better  than
this.

We reached the small rocky summit at 2:50 (8 miles,  6600  ft,  6.5  hrs).  A
glass jar summit register revealed the small number of  ascents.   Ours  was
the 12th after mostly recognizable names such as  Mike  Torok,  Don  Beavon,
Mitch Blanton, John Roper and Stefan Fellar. We  stayed  on  the  summit  35
minutes identifying peaks all around from Snowking, Baker, Eldorado,  Goode,
Dome, Bonanza to Glacier, and many in-between.

On the way back we went the short distance to the top  of  Pt  6640  (640P),
which had another small register with  mostly  the  same  names.  We  stayed
another 30 minutes or so on the ridge soaking in the  sights  loath  to  end
this glorious day. But all good things must eventually come to  an  end  and
down we went. We reached the car at 9:15 in fading light.

Total: 16 miles, 7500 ft, and 13 hrs.   Fay Pullen


