            'tr' => '

Mt Formidable (8325 ft - Cascade Pass Quad) - June 19-21, 2005


I was all psyched to climb Mt Formidable, so when the  first  3-day  stretch
of good weather in some time appeared I was ready  to  go.   When  my  usual
climbing partner Linda was not available (I  may  have  lost  her  for  this
whole season as she has taken a  summer  job.   Too  bad,  we  made  a  good
team.), I decided to go alone. I had some  trepidation  climbing  this  peak
solo. Formidable is a big mountain and fairly remote and  I  would  have  to
cross the Middle Cascade Glacier, but I would be  cautious  and  going  this
early in the season the glacier hopefully wouldn\'t have many  crevasses  and
I  have  been  having  good  success  lately.   It   never   pays   to   get
overconfident. Every once in a while I need a reality check and  a  reminder
that perhaps I have been having way too much fun. Climbing mountains can  be
dangerous and if you go out  often  enough  something  is  bound  to  happen
eventually.

I headed up the Cascade Pass Trail  (elev  3600  ft)  in  warm  sunny  clear
weather.  For once I  had  a  chance  to  wear  shorts.   From  the  pass  I
continued on the climbers trail up Mix-up Arm to Cache Col.  This  route  is
now about half melted out.  Steep snow slopes still need to be  crossed  but
the snow was soft and no problem other than  the  work  of  breaking  trail.
The greatest difficulty was crossing the rib about  halfway  where  a  large
cornice made it difficult to climb down onto the Cache Glacier. I could  see
old tracks crossing the glacier that were partially  filled  in  with  fresh
snow, probably from the heavy precipitation  the  area  had  had  the  night
before. From Cache Col (elev 6900 ft) I descended 800 feet to a  spectacular
camp at Kool-Aid Lake, elev 6100 ft (6.5 miles, 3400 ft, 5:20 hrs).

I arrived in plenty of time to lounge around,  sketch,  and  scope  out  the
route.  I identified the Red Ledge that crosses the  rock  cliff  on  the  W
ridge of Arts Knoll. It was partially snow covered and I hoped  it  wouldn\'t
be as bad as it looked. I was quietly eating  dinner  and  reading  my  book
when I glanced up and was shocked  to  see  a  coyote  nonchalantly  walking
through my camp.  I was on one side of my tent, he on the other not  5  feet
away. He continued sauntering up the path never once looking my way,  almost
like I didn\'t exist. I blinked.  He was still there  and  I  watched  as  he
disappeared from sight. Had I just dreamed that? It was like an  apparition.
In retrospect, I now wonder if he was an  omen.   In  Native  American  lore
coyote is the trickster. Were the mountains about to play a trick on me?

I started at 6:00 the next morning, another beautiful warm sunny  day.   The
snow had not frozen and was still  soft.  I  followed  way  trail  and  snow
slopes to the snow finger leading to the Red  Ledge,  greatly  enjoying  the
lovely alpine terrain  and  the  high  peaks  all  around.  The  N  face  of
Formidable was front and center,  but  behind  me  Johannesburg,  and  sharp
pointed Mix-up were equally impressive. I gained the ledge with  no  problem
(elev 6400 ft). The snow on the ledge itself was melted back enough  that  I
could thread my way between it and the cliff  edge  on  dirt.  Part  of  the
ledge was completely snow free. About 2/3 of the way a small  gully  had  to
be crossed on exposed snow.   Remember this gully. (There is  a  picture  of
this gully on page 86 of Washington\'s Highest Mountains.) It  gave  me  some
concern, but I carefully kicked steps across and continued  to  the  end  of
the ledge.

Once across the ledge, the route traversed downward  across  more  beautiful
alpine terrain to pass beneath another rock rib (elev 6200 ft) on the  ridge
between Arts Knoll and Spider Mtn. Finally I was able to  begin  the  ascent
up the Middle Cascade Glacier to the Spider-Formidable Col.  I  stayed  high
on the glacier where no crevasses showed.  Even so I  was  nervous  in  this
section.  This is a  real  glacier  with  an  impressive  icefall  and  many
crevasses on its lower reaches. Snow conditions varied  from  calf  deep  to
breakable crust to crust to crampons being  useful  near  the  very  top.  I
reached the left-hand of the twin cols, elev 7350, at 8:50  (1600  ft,  2:50
hrs).

From the col, I descended on the S side some 200 ft on snow, which was  soft
and getting softer in the warm sun, and began  a  long  tiring  traverse  SW
breaking trail through calf deep or deeper slush.  I  could  still  see  old
boot tracks, which were covered by small avalanches that had  recently  come
off the rock cliffs above in many areas. These tracks were  actually  headed
for Yang Yang Lakes and presumably the Ptarmigan Traverse (on which route  I
had been up to now), and soon  they  and  I  parted  company  as  they  went
downhill to the left and I uphill to the right to the 7000 ft notch on a  SW
trending spur ridge.

Another 200 foot descent down steep snow  on  the  NW  side  of  the  notch,
another traverse across slushy snow then up to cross another  rocky  rib  on
ledges at 7400 ft and I finally reached the so-called "snow patch" (hard  to
tell as it was all snow) below Formidable\'s S face. I climbed this slope  to
the left hand edge where a steep unpleasant looking gully  led  up.  It  was
all snow to 7900 ft. The exit onto rock was unstable snow and wet  and  gave
some trouble, but I knew I was on the right route as  I  passed  two  rappel
slings attached to old pitons. The final rock scramble, with  a  snow  patch
here and there thrown in, was more difficult  than  I  expected,  but  maybe
that was because  I  was  feeling  vulnerable,  overextended  and  a  little
freaked out.  Nevertheless, at 12:50 I emerged onto  the  summit  (3300  ft,
6:50 hrs).

There was a nice metal register on top but it was filled  with  only  scraps
of paper. I was able to piece out a few  recognizable  names.  The  earliest
entry I found was Don Goodman on 8/11/90 (he climbed it again  on  7/31/04).
Paul  Michelson  was  on  8/7/94.  and  Mike  Torok  7/95   (the   day   was
indecipherable). The last entry was 8/21/04. I added  a  waterproof  booklet
to give some order to future entries.

I enjoyed the views of countless peaks in all directions for  half  an  hour
before heading down. I downclimbed very slowly and carefully,  testing  each
hand and foothold. There was a lot of loose rock and  the  terrain  did  not
seem friendly to me. In the gully I began a  series  of  4-5  short  rappels
(Underestimating the difficulties of this  section  I  had  only  brought  a
short 60 ft rope. I wished I had brought a longer one) to get  me  past  the
worst of the wet rock and unstable snow until I could plunge step  down  the
rest of the gully. By now the snow was really slushy, I was sinking in  knee
deep and setting off small surface sluffs.   I  reversed  my  route  to  the
Spider-Formidable Col without incidence but the way seemed  all  uphill  and
the added trail breaking was exhausting. From the col it was downhill  until
at the base of the glacier then more uphill. I rested at  a  creek  to  fill
up.  I had run out of water.  I  had  found  none  once  I  started  up  the
glacier.  It was all under snow.

And then I came to the Red Ledge.  I  hesitate  to  describe  what  happened
next.  For one thing, I am embarrassed - no one likes to admit they blew  it
and who wants to be known as the climber who fell off  the  Red  Ledge.  For
another I don\'t want to feed those finger-wagging critics of  solo  climbers
who love to say I told you so and that solo climbing is crazy and not  safe.
Be that as it may, what happened, happened and there is no sense hiding  it.
 Of course, having companions along does not prevent accidents per  se.   It
only mitigates the consequences of the accident after it happens,  which  is
of course very important. (As an aside,  my  worse  accident  ever,  when  I
broke my leg by sliding 400 feet  down  an  icy  snowslope  and  catching  a
crampon, occurred with a companion along.  In fact  the  companion  was  the
cause of the fall. And I was the one with the cell phone.  I called 911  and
directed my own rescue from my end, so my companion, who was not  hurt,  was
of little use. This really proves nothing but it does  show  that  having  a
companion along is not always helpful and in fact can be detrimental.)

Back to the Red Ledge. I was crossing  the  gully  mentioned  earlier.   The
snow was very slushy and rotten by now.  The  traverse  was  slightly  down.
Kicking steps on a downward traverse is  always  awkward.  For  sure  I  was
tired and perhaps my concentration lapsed. In any  event  I  kicked  a  step
down, went to put weight on it, it broke out, my ice axe pulled through  the
slush and down I went. This was not a place you would want  to  fall.  Below
me the steep narrow mostly snow filled gully plunged  over  100  ft  through
the cliff to open snow slopes below.  I  distinctly  recall  thinking  as  I
fell, "So this is it! Damn!" I fully expected to fall  the  full  length  of
the gully, bouncing off the rock walls on the way down only to be  spit  out
onto the snow at the bottom. Instead, I rocketed  down  some  snow,  over  a
bare rock step, down some more snow and  to  my  astonishment  ended  wedged
upright in a moat some 30-40 feet down, my feet dangling  over  a  hole,  my
left shoulder taking the impact of the landing as  it  crashed  against  the
rock wall with a thud.

I was stunned.  Stunned that I had  fallen,  stunned  that  I  had  stopped,
stunned that I was conscious, stunned that I was  alive  and,  well,  I  was
just plain stunned. I took a few moments to collect myself  and  assess  the
damage. My left shoulder and arm hurt, but they seemed to  work  O.K.  There
were no broken bones or gushing blood.  Everything else seemed  to  be  O.K.
as well. In fact I was remarkably unhurt considering the  fall  I  had  just
taken. The next order of business was to get myself out of  my  predicament.
There was a ledge off to the left just  down  from  where  I  landed,  so  I
extricated myself from the moat and over to that  ledge.  Looking  over  the
situation, it seemed preferable to continue down the gully rather  than  try
to climb back up to the Red Ledge.  Again I wished I had a longer rope,  but
I was thankful I had any rope at all. I set up a rappel using a sling  on  a
bollard on the snow edge of the moat. This got me  to  where  I  could  kick
steps down facing in and reach the snow slope below (Both my ice axe and  my
pole axe were still in my hands when I landed. I hadn\'t lost either).

Shaken, but not quite aware of what  had  just  happened  (the  full  impact
would come later), I thought about the  irony  of  making  it  up  and  down
Formidable only to fall off the Red Ledge. Yes, Mr. Coyote certainly  played
a trick on me. I thankfully made it back to camp at 7:30 (8 miles, 4500  ft,
13:30 hrs). I immediately  iced  (snowed)  my  shoulder  and  later  applied
BioFreeze (I usually carry some for my aching back), which seemed  to  help.
I had a good dinner then went to bed and slept the sleep of the reprieved.

I felt pretty good the next morning, better than I expected.  But  I  wasn\'t
about to let my guard down. I still had to cross the  snowslopes  on  Mix-up
Arm back to Cascade Pass, many of which  have  runouts  over  cliffs.  I  am
getting to where I don\'t particularly like snow, especially traverses.  With
rock, what you see it what you get.  Snow is always  different.  It  can  be
rock hard or light as a feather, bottomless slush  or  nicely  consolidated,
and it has the audacity to change throughout the course of a day. And  often
it just won\'t stay put. It has a nasty tendency to move  downhill.   It  can
be tricky slippery shifty stuff.  Of the 5 falls of my climbing  career  all
have been on snow.

I made it to Cascade Pass without further incidence and  on  to  the  TH  by
1:00 (6.5 miles, 950 ft, 4:30 hr). I stopped by the Marblemount RS to  check
out and chatted with the rangers. I even met  Kelly  Bush,  who  coordinates
rescues for the Park. I was surprised that she knew who I was.  I  guess  my
name has popped up often enough over the years that  she  recognized  it.  I
was reassured when they told me they take the climbing  sign-in  sheet  very
seriously and comforted by their expertise. But I did tell  her  I  hoped  I
never needed her help.

Did this incident scare me? You better believe it  did.   Will  it  stop  me
from climbing solo? Not likely.  I love climbing too much and going solo  is
often the  only  way  I  can  get  out.  But  it  will  probably  change  my
perspective, make me even more careful (never, never let your  guard  down),
and cause me to seek out companions with a  little  more  zeal,  although  I
have always been open to going  out  with  others  if  their  schedules  and
objectives meshed with mine. I may take it easy for while, then again I  may
not. I am now licking my wounds, reflecting on  what  could  have  been  and
thanking the mountain gods for allowing me to climb another day.

Total: 21 miles and 8850 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen













