            'title' => 'Mesahchie Pk (8795 ft) and Katsuk Pk (8680+ ft) - Mt Logan and Mt Arriva Quads',
            'tr' => '

Mesahchie Pk (8795 ft) and Katsuk Pk (8680+ ft) - Mt Logan and Mt Arriva
Quads

June 30 - July 2, 2005

I had never been to Easy Pass or the Fisher Cr valley before,  and  what  an
enchanting area this is. Well worth a trip  in  itself.  Starting  from  the
Easy Pass TH (elev 3700 ft) off the North Cascades Highway, I hiked the  3.5
miles to the 6500 ft pass (2800 ft, 2:30 hrs) in ever increasing  loveliness
of meadows and views. From the pass  rugged  mountains  were  in  sight  all
around, Fisher Pk, Mt Arriva, Mt Goode  and  dead  center  the  bulk  of  Mt
Logan. Off to the right I could see Mesahchie and the route from the  valley
floor I would take to my high camp in the 6600 ft snow basin S of the  peak.
It didn\'t look too bad. But first I had to descend a heartbreaking  1500  ft
and 3 miles to Fisher Cr. This descent was  more  than  compensated  by  the
gorgeous flower meadows and the fields of lupine,  penstemon  and  valerian.
Absolutely stunning.

After wandering about a mile through the meadows, I left the trail  at  5000
ft and headed uphill along the edge of a timber  spur.  Although  the  going
was not that difficult, there was some brush to start and, in retrospect,  I
believe it would have been better to head uphill sooner in meadows and  then
traverse leftward to the W in open terrain above the brush. I worked my  way
up steep hillside, avoiding cliffy  areas,  heading  slightly  to  the  left
until I could follow alongside the outlet creek to the basin.  Here I  found
a delightful campsite nestled in the  rocks  with  a  fabulous  view  of  Mt
Arriva (7.5 miles, 4500 ft, 5:40 hrs).

I was awakened during the night to the sound of rain  that  seemed  to  last
about an hour, but the next day dawned mostly blue skies and sunny.  I  left
camp at 6:30 and made my way up easy terrain to the ridge above Pt  7430.  I
avoided what little snow  there  was,  which  was  rock  hard,  as  much  as
possible.  The ridge was guarded by a long vertical cornice for most of  its
length, but I was able to gain access at the far N end by  crawling  between
snow and rock.  Once on the ridge, I followed it easily until  it  began  to
steepen below Katsuk\'s E peak. I scrambled up another  couple  hundred  feet
until confronted by a headwall. Here I worked  my  way  left  a  short  ways
until I could began a rightward traverse  at  8200  ft  on  a  narrow  ledge
around a corner to the dreaded downsloping boilerplate slabs.

Mindful of my mishap of last week, I was moving  carefully  and  cautiously,
and up to this point I had been doing okay, although it will take  me  while
to move again with my previous level of  confidence.  But  I  did  not  like
these slabs. Normally, if I have good hand and  foot  holds,  exposure  does
not bother me that much. However, if the  holds  become  tenuous,  I  become
very nervous, even if over just a 10-foot drop. These  slabs  were  above  a
steep snowslope that funneled into a gully that  plunged  down  hundreds  of
feet. And of course on slabs you rely mostly on  foot  friction,  there  are
few handholds. I kept visualizing my feet slipping out from under me and  me
careening  downhill,  not  a  good  vision  to  have  psychologically.   The
frightening thing about having taken  a  fall  is  that  now  you  know  how
quickly and without warning it can  happen  and  that  once  you  lose  your
balance and start to slide you are gone unless luck intervenes.  No,  I  did
not like these slabs, but I did  make  it  across,  slowly  and  cautiously,
picking my line with great care.

I crossed a rib and another set of slabs, not as bad as the first ones,  and
came to the 8200 ft Katsuk-Mesahchie Col. I contoured left (N) a very  short
ways, scrambled up a slot, across a minor rib and entered the  long  winding
summit gully. The gully was  completely  snow  free  except  for  one  small
patch, easily avoided. I  thoroughly  enjoyed  climbing  up  this  gully.  I
exited to the left near the top, then tiptoed along  the  exposed  ridge  to
the summit (2300 ft,  3:30  hrs).  The  official  Mountaineer  register  was
placed by Mike Torok on 7/29/94. Other entries: Don Beavon -  9/23/00,  Paul
Klenke - 8/12/01, Paul Cho and Mark Owen (1 hr from Katsuk!  Impressive!  It
would take me 2:30 hrs) - 9/21/03, Mike Collins and Jim Brisbine -  8/21/04.
I thought I had seen relatively recent footprints  here  and  there  in  the
dirt along the route, and sure enough there was an entry  for  6/20/05,  the
only one for this year.

I spent a pleasant 30 minutes on the sunny summit, then started for  Katsuk.
I downclimbed the gully,  traversed  the  first  slabs,  but  couldn\'t  face
another trip across the main slabs. I  spotted  a  more  appealing  (to  me)
feasible route below the snow slope below the slabs then up  a  broken  face
back to the traverse ledge. This was steeper but the holds were good  and  I
was more comfortable on it. Once back to the start  of  the  traverse  below
Katsuk\'s E peak, I continued traversing W  around  an  airy  corner  and  on
ledges to cross a series  of  gullies  and  ribs  to  a  broad  gully  below
Katsuk\'s E ridge. I climbed up this gully to the ridge and along the  ridge,
where some snow, nicely softened by now, necessitated the  use  of  the  ice
axe for the first time, around and over several pinnacles until  I  came  to
the one farthest W. I thought  this  must  be  the  summit,  but  it  looked
awfully difficult and I couldn\'t see any  rappel  slings  that  I  was  sure
would be needed to get back down. I turned around and  looked  back  to  the
next pinnacle to the E that I had just come down. Maybe  it  was  higher.  I
frequently have  trouble  determining  the  highest  point  on  a  ridge.  I
scrambled back up it and sure enough under an easily missed  cairn  I  found
an aluminum canister engraved with "Roper â68" (3150 ft,  6:30  hr).  I  was
most happy I didn\'t have to climb the western pinnacle.

Inside the canister was the original notebook left by Chris and  John  Roper
on their first ascent of 8/22/68. It was in very good shape  considering  it
was almost 40 years old.  There  were  fewer  entries  than  for  Mesahchie,
despite it being older. I guess Katsuk is climbed  less  often.  There  were
the same names as mentioned for Mesahchie  plus:  Don  Goodman  -  10/10/89,
Grant Meyers - 7/11/91, and Paul Michelson and  Martin  Shetter  -  9/15/91.
The last entry was 8/8/04.

I looked longingly at Kimtah, the next peak  W.  It  didn\'t  look  that  far
away, as the crow flies.  But the ridge between it  and  me  looked  awfully
ragged with numerous intervening gullies. It isn\'t called Ragged  Ridge  for
nothing. It was still early (1:30), but not that  early.  I  wasn\'t  exactly
breaking speed records and I wasn\'t sure I could make  it  up  and  back  to
camp before dark. Also, dark clouds were beginning to gather over Logan  and
Goode.  It could be raining soon. So I decided not to push my  luck  and  to
be satisfied with two peaks. If tomorrow was a good day, I could  still  try
for Kimtah on a lower level traverse from camp.  Otherwise I  could  combine
it on another trip with Cosho, the peak farthest W on the ridge.

I reversed my route along Katsuk\'s E ridge and down the main  gully,  but  I
lost my way across the ribs and side gullies, taking a higher line. I  ended
up at the right spot below Katsuk\'s E peak and started down the S  ridge.  I
thought I was going to make it through this climb  without  using  my  rope,
but once again I lost the line and ended up cliff bound. Rather  than  climb
up and find the proper line, I made 2 rappels to  get  on  track  again.  At
least that justified bringing the rope along.  I ambled the rest of the  way
down in no hurry, soaking in my beautiful surroundings. I think  I  consider
any time I am now allowed in the presence of the mountain gods to be a  gift
and I want to properly appreciate it. I returned to camp at 4:30  (3  miles,
3300 ft, 10 hrs) with plenty of  time  to  relax  and  leisurely  enjoy  the
afternoon.

The expected rain made its appearance sometime  during  the  night.  When  I
awoke at 5:00 the next morning, it was foggy  and  still  raining  steadily.
There would be no climbing Kimtah this day. I rolled over and went  back  to
sleep till 7:00, hoping the rain  would  diminish.  This  it  did  gradually
until by the time I left at 9:00  it  had  mostly  stopped.  The  brush  and
flowers would, however, stay wet the rest of the day, so, in  an  effort  to
keep my feet dry, I pulled the old plastic bag trick.  I  put  produce  bags
from the grocery store on my feet between the  boot  and  sock.  These  bags
weight nothing, take no room and I always carry a couple sets  in  my  ditty
bag. This in conjunction with gaiters and rain pants kept me mostly dry  for
the trip out.

It took 1:30 hours to slip and slide  down  wet  slopes  to  the  trail  and
another 2 hours to climb back up to Easy Pass.  During this time  I  saw  no
one. The sun gradually made a return appearance and the fog began  to  lift.
The high peaks to the S remained obscured but Golden Horn to the N lived  up
to its name as it was briefly highlighted by sunshine. Once at  the  pass  I
began running into the "crowds" coming  in  for  the  holiday  weekend.  The
parking lot was full by the time I reached the TH at 2:30 (7.5  miles,  1600
ft, 5:30 hrs).

I was pleased that on this first solo trip after my  fall  I  have  more  or
less  successfully  faced  my  personal  demons.   And  while  I  have   not
completely put them to rest, I have kept them at bay, at least for a while.

Total: 18 miles and 9500 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen





