Bulls Tooth (6840+ ft) and  Lemool  Mtn  (6284  ft),  Stevens  Pass  Quad  -
Doughgob Mtn (6172 ft), Chiwaukum Mtns Quad - July 7-8, 2005

Thursday was forecast to be sunny with rain returning on  Friday.   I  would
have one good weather day.  Indecision as to where to  go  and  what  to  do
made for a late start.  I finally decided on these three  Back  Court  peaks
as I hoped things would be better E of the crest or that I could climb  them
even in the rain. My plan was a loop trip from Whitepine Cr to Wildhorse  Cr
to Frosty Pass to Chain Lakes to Icicle Cr and back to  Whitepine,  climbing
the peaks on the way. It looked good on paper, but ended  up  not  being  so
great in execution due to the condition of the upper Whitepine trail. I  had
no idea this trail was in such bad shape.

I began from the Whitepine TH (elev 2800 ft), off Highway  2  E  of  Stevens
Pass. At 2.5 miles I turned onto the Wildhorse trail  and  followed  it  6.6
miles to 5800 ft Frosty Pass. From here a rough trail (shown on GT  but  not
on USGS map) goes another 3 miles to Doelle Lakes. I was  making  good  time
with a light pack, enjoying the warm sunny day and the lovely meadows  below
Big Chiwaukum, Snowgrass and Frosty Mtn. I was also  idly  wondering  why  I
hadn\'t run into any bugs yet this season, when I entered  the  large  marshy
basin S of Doughgob and the hordes descended upon me en masse. I was  forced
to cover up head to toe to escape their voracious appetites.   So  much  for
no bugs this season.

In the basin I dropped my pack for the 1 hr, 700 ft RT up Doughgob.  (As  an
aside, is this the proper spelling or it is  a  misprint?   The  Back  Court
lists it as Doughgob, but the creek for which  it  is  presumably  named  is
Doughgod.)  It was now 8:00 and I was running out of daylight.  I  continued
past lovely Doelle lakes, over the 6200 ft pass on  Bulls  Tooth  ridge  and
down to 5700 Chain Lakes on the other side where I found  a  campsite  on  a
knoll between two of the lakes at 9:20 (14.5 miles, 6050 ft, 9 hrs) where  I
had just enough time to set up my tent before dark.

I fully expected it to rain during  the  night,  but  by  morning  it  still
hadn\'t started and visibility was reasonable.  What luck.  It  would  be  so
much more pleasant climbing Bulls Tooth without  rain.  I  made  the  RT  to
Bulls Tooth in 2 hrs (1200 ft). The hardest  part  was  getting  around  the
lake on large talus. The highest point, to the  E  of  the  6807  ft  summit
marked on maps, had a Mountaineer register placed by Johnny Jeans  in  2001.
There were only 4 or 5 other entries since then.  I was surprised it  wasn\'t
climbed more often.  Perhaps most people go to the 6807 ft summit.

By the time I was packed and  ready  to  leave  my  camp  it  was  drizzling
lightly. At the last lake where the trail starts downhill,  I  left  it  for
the saddle to the N and, carrying my full pack, easily climbed the  ridge  W
to the summit of Lemool. The actual high point was  buried  in  thick  scrub
trees but a cairn was a few feet away in the open.  Here I left  a  register
(I also left one on Doughgob.)  Right by the cairn I found  a  pair  of  red
gloves, which I packed out.

From Lemool, I headed directly S downhill to intersect the trail once  again
and followed it down 2.5 miles to the Icicle Cr Trail (elev 3800  ft).  This
trail I then followed uphill 2.5 miles to the Whitepine Trail  junction  and
over the saddle (elev 4600) into the  Whitepine  drainage.  It  was  raining
steadily by now, and would continue to do so for the rest of the day, but  I
figured it was all downhill from now on and all on trail so I had  it  made.
Ha! My first inkling that all was not well was when I almost lost the  trail
in the marshy meadows of the saddle. From there  things  just  deteriorated.
This is an absolutely horrid trail. Oh the tread is still there, but  it  is
so brushed over you often can\'t see  it  as  your  feet  feel  for  the  way
through the waist high foliage of meadows or the even worse  over  the  head
high brush of the alder thickets. This went on for an  endless  4  miles  or
so. It rivaled the worst  climber  trails  I  have  been  on,  such  as  the
Bachelor Cr Trail. I was not expecting this. And  it  was  WET!  Under  such
conditions, there is no way to stay dry no matter what you wear (although  a
drysuit might work).  I gave up and embraced the  wetness  as  part  of  the
experience. Whatever you do, do not take this "trail" in the rain.

After an interminable amount of oneness with the  wetness,  I  came  to  the
crossing of Whitepine Cr. Earlier in the season  this  can  be  a  difficult
crossing but now it was low. A  few  spindly  logs  had  been  placed  as  a
makeshift bridge. I used them but I could just as  well  have  waded  across
clothes and all.  I couldn\'t have gotten any wetter. Just on the other  side
was the Wildhorse Trail junction and the closing of my loop.  The  last  2.5
miles to the TH seemed like a super highway compared to what I just been  on
(14.5 miles, 2150 ft, 8 hrs - plus 1 mile, 1200 ft, 2 hrs for Bulls Tooth).

Total: 30 miles, 9400 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen




