            'tr' => '
Mt Spickard (8979 ft), Mt Custer (8630 ft)  and  Mt  Rahm  (8430  ft)  -  Mt
Redoubt and Mt Spickard Quads - July 14-18, 2005

My original plan was to go with a group to climb Redoubt and the Mox  Peaks,
and then stay an extra 2 or 3 days to climb Spickard, Custer and Rahm.  When
the group cancelled due to forecast  rain  on  Saturday,  I  decided  to  go
anyway and at least get the 3 peaks I could do on my own.  I  was  a  little
nervous about going into such a rugged remote area alone, but I vowed to  be
extra careful and not do anything stupid.

Thursday - I left town at 2:30  pm  and  stopped  in  Sedro  Woolley  for  a
permit. Although permits are not strictly  necessary,  I  mainly  wanted  to
sign the climber\'s register. The more people who know where I am  going  and
what my plans are when I am solo, the better. Once in Canada,  I  drove  the
Chilliwack Lake Road to the last official  campground  (Riverside)  where  I
spent the night in my Cherokee. The grizzled campground host,  who  accepted
my $10 US in lieu of Canadian, couldn\'t understand why I was camping  alone.
"No fun in that," he replied. When I mentioned the  peaks  I  was  going  to
climb, he had never heard of them.

Friday - I managed to find my way the short remaining distance to the  Depot
Cr TH, despite having several differing directions as to how to  get  there.
From the  end  of  the  paved  road  at  the  entrance  to  Chilliwack  Lake
Provincial Park, it was 6.4 miles on  a  very  potholed  dirt  road  to  the
unmarked Depot Cr road on the left. This road is very  rough  and  overgrown
and can now only be driven 1.7 miles to a large washout. A normal car  might
make it with care .9 miles to a parking  area,  but  from  then  on  a  high
clearance 4-wheel drive is required. One car was parked at .9  miles  and  2
trucks at the end.  I would have company.

I shouldered my heavy pack and  started  walking  the  road  at  8:30  under
overcast skies. The forecast was for showers tonight  and  tomorrow  morning
with clearing by afternoon. I hoped to complete my itinerary in 4  days  but
I carried food for 5 in case I lost a day to bad  weather.  After  about  10
minutes walking, the "road" turned steeply uphill to a T, then took a  right
to become level, muddy and even more overgrown. Here I  met  a  Park  Ranger
and  helper  coming  out.   They  were  part  of  a  5-person  team   making
measurements on the Silver Lake Glacier. I would meet  the  other  3  later.
When I told the ranger I was planning on climbing Spickard solo, I got  that
disapproving look and she proceeded  to  inform  me  that  the  Silver  Lake
Glacier had crevasses. When I told here I wasn\'t  climbing  up  the  glacier
but up the S side, she looked puzzled, as if  she  wasn\'t  aware  there  was
another route up the mountain.

In about an hour I reached the International Monument and  the  registration
book for entering the North Cascades National Park. In the book it  said  it
was okay if you didn\'t have a permit for the Park but they  wanted  everyone
to register to gage usage. One other party of 4  was  currently  registered.
Only about 5 climbing parties had registered for 2005 so far. Several  other
parties had gone only as far as the falls. From the  monument,  the  "trail"
wound its way up and down through lovely  mossy  old  growth  forest,  often
close to Depot Cr.   Many  logs  were  across  the  trail  and  several  bad
windfalls. Progress was slow. After a couple of miles, the  trail  began  to
climb and it began to drizzle. Darn, the system was coming in sooner than  I
expected. I stopped to put on rain gear,  mostly  because  of  the  now  wet
brush.  Then I met the other 3 rangers coming out. Once  again  I  got  that
disapproving look when I told the guy in charge I was going in solo, but  to
his credit he didn\'t give me  a  lecture  and  only  told  me  to  be  safe.
However, he did ask if I had a permit and seemed genuinely surprised when  I
told him I had gotten one in Sedro Woolley. He also told me the party  of  4
planned to climb Spickard on Saturday, weather permitting.

After 3:45 hrs I came to the foot of the famed Depot  Cr  Falls.  Impressive
doesn\'t begin to describe these  beautiful  falls.  Not  free  falling,  but
rather cascading down a thousand feet of slabs and ledges, these  falls  are
truly spectacular. After a spray covered wet  step,  helped  by  a  handline
left in place, the way continued  up  the  very  edge  of  the  falls,  past
another lesser muddy step with a second handline and  up  alternating  talus
and boot track in the woods. Sparse cairns  and  flags  helped  keep  me  on
route on this very steep section. Farther up the way edged the falls  again.
You could almost reach out and touch them. At the top Depot Cr was  squeezed
into a slot and shot out from the rim in free falling splendor.

At 5 hrs I topped out into level upper Depot Cr valley at a  nice  campsite.
The way followed the extreme left hand edge of the valley until  reaching  a
vast open washout of boulders from the creek. I picked my way slowly up  the
valley. The showers were coming and going and  things  were  getting  pretty
wet.  I was beginning to think I might have to stop at Ouzel Lake to set  up
camp if the weather continued to deteriorate, although I  really  wanted  to
locate at the highest point on the benches  below  Spickard  where  I  could
access all my peaks, some 1200 feet above the lake. After  another  hour  or
so, the rain let up and visibility was good although the high  summits  were
in fog. I was above Ouzel Lake and I could see that it would be  out  of  my
way to drop down to it, so I just kept going up toward Silver Lake  Pass.  I
could see the party of 4 camped at the lake. At  4:00  I  found  a  pleasant
campsite at 6800 ft on a heather bench just below the talus  fields  on  the
SW slope of Spickard (6.5 miles, 4400 ft, 7:30 hr). This would  be  my  home
for at least the next 3 nights. I set up camp and found water (about 200  ft
below me) before the rain started in earnest.

Saturday - It rained steadily all night long and was raining  still  in  the
morning. I killed time eating, sleeping and reading.   Good  thing  my  book
was a page-turner or I would have really been bored. Somewhere around  11:00
am I could tell the rain was letting up and I prepared to  give  Spickard  a
go, starting out at noon. I was a little premature in my assessment  of  the
weather\'s improvement  as  it  was  very  foggy  and  a  few  showers  still
lingered, but I was getting desperate.  I am  not  good  at  hanging  around
camp doing nothing.

From camp, I headed up talus toward the  pocket  glacier  on  Spickard\'s  SW
slope. Momentary clearing gave me my bearings. I hugged the right hand  edge
of the snowfield to avoid bare ice that  was  beginning  to  appear  in  the
center. Even so, the snow was a little icy and I donned crampons.  I  easily
climbed the snow and a short cruddy class 3 rock  section  to  the  8000  ft
notch in the SW ridge, descended the other side onto snow and  traversed  to
a gully that crossed to the open SE slopes. Easy snow led  up,  but  in  the
fog I gained the S ridge too soon, at  about  8600  ft,  and  had  to  cross
several gullies and follow the rocky  ridge  up  and  down  over  two  false
summits before making the top (2300 ft, 3:30  hrs).   By  now  it  had  quit
raining and the sun was even beginning to make an appearance.   I  had  nice
views of Silver Lake, Silver Lake Glacier, Custer and Rahm to the N but  the
S was still completely enveloped in fog. A Mountaineer register was  on  the
summit, placed by Bill Maxwell in  1983,  but  inexplicably  a  Park  Ranger
entry in 1993 noted that he had cut out  all  the  used  pages  up  to  that
point, some dozen pages. Why  on  earth  would  a  ranger  do  something  so
stupid? What was the purpose?   Not  only  did  that  destroy  the  historic
record, it deprived climbers of the joy of reading the entries and  lessened
the space to add new entries (normally the front of  the  pages  are  filled
first then the back of the pages), as the remaining pages were almost  full.
I know that many in the Park Service for some reason,  which  I  have  never
understood, do not like summit  registers  and  often  remove  them  but  to
mutilate one is completely beyond my comprehension.

I had enough visibility on the way down to find a  gully  that  went  almost
directly off the  summit  to  the  snow  slopes  below  from  where  I  then
traversed back to my uphill route.  I was back in camp  by  6:00  (2  miles,
2500 ft, 6 hrs RT) but also back in the fog. My hoped for  evening  sunshine
did not materialize.

Sunday - This day I awoke to clear blue skies and sunshine  and  a  stunning
view of Mt Redoubt shining  in  the  morning  light  across  Depot  Cr.  The
weather forecast was right. I started  at  7:30  for  Custer  and  Rahm  and
reached the 7400 ft Silver Lake Pass, which is more like a  vast  undulating
talus field than a definite pass, in 45 minutes. Deciding  to  climb  Custer
first, I dropped slightly, traversed some slabs and a snowfield to gain  the
gentle SE slopes. The step off the snow onto rock at the  far  side  of  the
snowfield was a tricky wet class 4 move that gave me some  difficulty.  Once
across it was easy to gain Custer\'s S ridge just N of  Pt  8385.  The  ridge
looked frightful but for the most part was easier than it looked.  I  stayed
on the very crest.  It was quite exposed but not difficult until I  came  to
the  last  pinnacle  before  the  low  point  in  the  ridge.  Here  a  most
unpleasant, exposed loose class 3 downclimb on the E side slowed me up as  I
carefully picked my way down. A little more on the crest and I came  to  the
last easy but very loose scree slopes leading to the summit at  11:15  (2100
ft, 3:45 hrs). I could find no register  so  I  left  the  only  one  I  had
brought.

I reversed the S ridge (the unpleasant downclimb was  much  easier  climbing
up) to the point I had gained it, then descended the rib SE  until  I  could
drop onto the plateau leading to Rahm. A long traverse of an hour  at  about
7600 ft across mostly talus but some snow ended at a cliff band and  a  deep
gully draining the snowfield above. Before the  deep  gully  was  a  shallow
snowfree gully that looked like it would go to the top of the cliffs.  There
was a short 5-foot step about half way up this 200 ft gully that gave  me  a
little trouble. I surmounted it by climbing without my pack and  pulling  it
up after on a rope. Once past that it was clear sailing to  the  snow  basin
above.  A large cairn marked the top of this gully. I followed snow as  high
as possible then more loose talus and scree to  the  top  of  Rahm  at  3:40
(3400 ft, 8:10 hrs). Here I found an intact register placed by  Chris  Weber
and Mike Torok in 1995. An entry  for  4/29/04  by  Lowell  and  Carl  Skoog
caught my eye.  They skied from Depot Cr.  Can you imagine carrying skis  up
that trail? Those are two tough brothers. Other entries  I  recognized  were
Grant Meyers and  Don  Beavon  in  2000,  Paul  Klenke  in  2003,  and  Paul
Michelson in 2004.

I lounged in the sun for a while, taking in the views on this  perfect  day.
In the gully I rappelled the step, although it took me a  while  to  find  a
solid anchor. I took a low route back to Silver Lake  Pass,  dropping  to  a
lowpoint of 7100 ft and  traversing  over  endless  loose  awful  talus  and
scree. I dragged into camp at 7:15 (7 miles, 3900 ft, 11:45  hrs).  My  tent
was in full sun and it was sweltering. No shade was in sight. Now  I  wished
I were camped at the lake so I could jump in and cool off.   I  didn\'t  even
have a stream nearby to wash up in. How quickly  conditions  change  in  the
mountains.  I stripped in my tent and waited for the sun to go down and  for
it to cool off.


Monday - I slept in, then took my time getting  ready  to  leave.  I  looked
longingly over at Mt Redoubt.  What a beautiful mountain! It  was  so  close
and conditions were perfect and yet it was completely out of  reach  for  me
alone. I left reluctantly, but with the knowledge that  I  would  return  to
this lovely area.


I went out slowly and carefully. It would never do to blow  it  on  the  way
out on the treacherous  talus  and  trail  after  successfully  climbing  my
peaks. The party of 4 was no longer at the lake.  I  was  completely  alone.
The falls and all the creeks were noticeably higher on this hot  sunny  day.
Once down in the forest, I stopped by the raging creek to wash up  and  cool
off. At the monument and Park register the party of 4 made a note that  they
were rained out of Mt Spickard, but presumably made it up  Redoubt  and  the
Mox peaks, their stated goals. I reached the car at  4:30  (7  hrs),  taking
almost as much time going out as coming in. But I was tired, took  more  and
longer rests and that counts my stop to take a dip in the creek.

Total: 22 miles and 11, 500 ft in 4 days.

Fay Pullen








