            'subdir' => '2005-07-22-chaval',
            'title' => 'Mt Chaval (7127 ft) and Pk 6400 - Prairie Mtn, Huckleberry Mtn & Snowking Mtn Quads - July 22-24, 2005',
            'tr' => '

Mt Chaval (7127 ft) and Pk 6400 - Prairie Mtn, Huckleberry Mtn & Snowking
Mtn Quads - July 22-24, 2005


I met Dale, Mike T, John and Deb at the Darrington  RS  at  9:10  on  Friday
morning with it raining steadily all the way from  Seattle.  This  rain  was
not forecast and was unexpected. Since our approach was  crosscountry  on  a
way trail and through brush, none of us  were  anxious  to  head  out  right
away. The updated forecast at the RS indicated clearing by afternoon  so  we
decided to wait for a few hours to see  what  would  happen.  After  killing
time till 12:30 in the local  restaurant,  entertained  by  John\'s  humorous
tales of the inner workings of Mountain Rescue, the rain  did  indeed  stop,
and we decided to go, knowing full well we would encounter wet brush on  the
way in.

We drove Grade Cr Road 2640, off the Suiattle River Road, 4.8 miles  to  the
junction with spur 2643. Here Dale left  his  car  and  we  all  piled  into
Mike\'s truck and my Cherokee for a further 1.2 miles to 2700 ft.  This  spur
has deep waterbars that require a high clearance 4X4; in fact I barely  made
it across one of them.  We started walking up the remaining .7 mile  of  the
road at 2:30. At the 3100 ft switchback we left the road  and  picked  up  a
rough way trail which we soon lost as it descended to  cross  a  gully  with
many huge downed trees. We proceeded to wander around in awful  terrain  for
the next hour traversing to a second gully before finding the trail again  a
hundred feet or so below us. It is essential to stay on  the  way  trail  to
avoid unpleasant brush. Stay low and look for flags after the  first  gully.
The way trail, although rough with numerous ups and downs, has had a lot  of
work done by someone cutting out  many  of  the  logs.  It  traverses  steep
hillside, crosses a small talus field and two creeks then  climbs  to  cross
Jug Cr in a marshy meadow.  From here on the trail is very faint but  it  is
no longer essential to stay on it as it follows the creek to Bluff Lake.  We
found a campsite for our 3 tents on the N side of the 4200 ft lake  at  7:20
(3 miles, 2000 ft, 5 hrs). This is lower than we had originally  planned  on
getting but we were happy to get that far  considering  our  delayed  start.
Mike built a campfire that served the dual purpose  of  drying  us  out  and
keeping the bugs away.

The next morning at 7:50 we headed N from the E end of Bluff Lake then E  to
follow a creek toward Cliff Lake. The day began  with  fog  and  clouds  but
gradually cleared to extensive views.  An open hillside above the  lake  led
N then E again to the lovely basin SW of Pk 6400. Here we  made  a  tactical
error and ended up too high and unable to cross the S ridge of Pk  6400.  We
had to descend to 5600 ft to find an easy place  to  cross  into  the  rocky
basin SE of Pk 6400. A steep heather gully on the  other  side  led  to  the
5960 pass SE of Pt 6356. From here we dropped down a ledge onto a  permanent
snowfield (oddly not shown on the map), where a short section  of  bare  ice
on the snowfield caused me to  put  on  crampons.  They  were  not  strictly
necessary and the others got across without them but my recent fall made  me
nervous. From the end of the snow, pleasant scrambling up slabs  put  us  at
the base of Chaval\'s W face. A short class 3 step  and  steep  heather  gave
access to the very obvious large ramp slanting  left  to  right  across  the
face. This ramp is easier then it appears. At the top of the ramp it  was  a
short distance on the S ridge to the summit at 2:30 (3750 ft, 6:40 hrs).

The register was placed in 2001 by Johnny Jeans. Chaval doesn\'t seem  to  be
climbed all that often, with only 2 or 3 ascents a  year.  I  recognized  no
other names entered. Dale, Deb and John soon headed down while  Mike  and  I
stayed longer enjoying  the  views.  Mike  proceeded  to  identify  all  the
surrounding peaks and reminisce about a few of his many trips in  the  area.
It is fun being out with someone so knowledgeable. By the time  we  left  at
3:15, the others were down the ramp.

We were all back to the 5960 ft pass by 4:20. There Mike and  I  decided  to
take off and try for the "bonus" Peak 6400. It is a very impressive  looking
rock spire from Chaval. We reached the base of the rock at  the  deep  notch
to the E in an hour but the rock looked  too  difficult  and  would  require
some pro to lead. All we had was a 120 ft rope and some slings.  We  circled
around the base of the rock to the W looking for a  scramble  route  up  and
were just about to give up when a steep  gully  directly  below  the  summit
offered a possibility. I led up, encouraged by Mike, to a ledge at  midface.
Then Mike took over up a chimney and rib the rest of the  way  to  the  top.
The whole thing turned out to be more difficult than we had expected,  about
my limit of comfort for unroped climbing (high class 4  or  maybe  very  low
class 5) but did provide added interest to the day. We reached  the  top  at
6:00 where I left one of my small registers.

To get down we rappelled directly to the E notch. We  found  an  old  rappel
sling on a shallow horn, which Mike replaced with a  new  one.  We  couldn\'t
see if the rope reached all the way down. I went first and  soon  discovered
our 120 ft rope was about 10 feet short of the notch. I secured myself on  a
ledge while Mike lengthened the system with another sling so the  rope  just
barely allowed me to reach the notch. We were both off  the  rock  by  7:00,
after which we zipped back to camp at 8:00 (6 miles, 4700  ft,  12:10  hrs).
We had a quick dinner as the voracious bugs soon drove us to our tents.

We made it out the next morning in 3.5 hours.  We found where  we  had  lost
the way in the first two gullies. It was  so  much  easier  staying  on  the
trail, although the first gully is still a bit of a pain.

Total: 12 miles and 7150 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen


