            'title' => 'Boston Pk (8894 ft - Cascade Pass Quad) - July 27-28, 2005',
            'tr' => '

Boston Pk (8894 ft - Cascade Pass Quad) - July 27-28, 2005


What a surprise this peak turned out to be! The first surprise  was  that  I
was actually able to solo it.  The second surprise was that it was really  a
very pleasant climb. Boston Pk has a reputation  for  horrible  loose  rock.
Few climbers have anything nice to say about it or express a  desire  for  a
repeat ascent. The TR by Jim Brisbine of his and Mike C\'s ascent in July  of
2004 did little to dispel that impression.  Theirs  was  a  desperate  climb
done in terrible conditions  of  fresh  snow,  wet  unprotectable  rock  and
limited visibility.  Mine was in perfect conditions  where  I  was  able  to
find  a  reasonable  route  of  fairly  solid  rock.  That  makes  all   the
difference.

However, I didn\'t know what the outcome  would  be  when  I  started  making
plans. Boston has been on my wish list for years,  way  before  I  began  my
quest for the 100  Highest.  Its  reputation  and  fearsome  appearance  has
always prevented me from giving it a try. Now the time seemed right.  Still,
I worried that maybe I was crazy for even considering soloing it. There  was
only one way to find out.  I  was  mentally  prepared  to  give  it  a  good
attempt, but I was also prepared to back off at the slightest real  problem.
I took a 50m rope, a light alpine rack, 2 ice axes (for an anticipated  hard
moat crossing) and crampons. (All I needed was the rope and one ice axe.)  I
would also allow 3 days, so I had one full day for the climb.  I  do  better
on technical terrain if I have plenty of time and don\'t feel rushed.

When getting my permit to camp at Sahale Glacier Camp,  I  learned  a  youth
(13-year old boys) group of 12 would also be camped there.  Just my luck.  I
have camped often enough near youth groups to know what to expect.  Teenaged
boys do not know how to be quiet and melt into the background. Sure  enough,
I caught up to the raucous group at Cascade Pass.  Not wanting to  be  stuck
behind them, I continued on, without  stopping  to  rest  at  the  pass,  up
lovely Sahale Arm to Sahale Glacier Camp (6 miles, 4000  ft,  4:20  hrs).  I
had time to set up camp, eat dinner, have a pleasant  chat  with  two  other
small parties camped nearby and enjoy a little tranquility before the  youth
group dragged in a good 2 hours later at 8:00.  Naturally they chose a  spot
barely 200 feet from me. I resigned myself to putting up  with  their  noise
and commotion as I turned in at 8:30. But when I was awakened at about  9:00
by the loud voices of 4 boys not more than 10 feet  from  me  unconcerningly
chatting away, it was more than I could bear. I stuck  my  head  out  of  my
bivy tent and pointed out that I was trying to get some sleep and they  were
invading my personal space. They did apologize.  I really  think  they  were
totally unaware of the inappropriateness of their actions.

I was on my way at 6:00 the next morning before anyone  else  was  stirring.
(That also allowed me private uninterrupted use of the  open-air  composting
toilet). The Sahale Glacier was beginning to show some bare ice but  it  was
easily avoided to the left.  I quickly climbed up the snow to  the  S  ridge
of Sahale and scrambled up to the notch just to the  right  of  the  summit,
crossed the notch and got my first look at Boston. It  looked  as  frightful
as ever but I wasn\'t going to let that  affect  me.  The  ridge  leading  to
Boston was mostly bare. There was only  a  short  section  of  snow  at  the
beginning.  I descended to the Sahale-Boston Col then made my way along  the
ridge. I expected this ridge to be loose, exposed and unpleasant.  In  fact,
I found it rather enjoyable. Custer\'s S ridge, which I  had  recently  done,
is much worse.

I worked my way along the ridge, over the false summit  and  along  a  ledge
(marked by a cairn) to cross onto the upper toe of  the  Boston  Glacier.  A
large bergshrund crossed the entire toe just below me preventing  access  to
the main glacier. No matter. I only needed to cross the very upper  part  to
the SE corner of the summit block. I easily gained access  to  the  rock  (I
left ice axes and crampons here) and scrambled up a few feet to a  prominent
ledge.  This was the loosest section of the  whole  climb.  I  followed  the
ledge NE until it narrowed. Most directions have you continue up  and  right
working your way onto the N ridge some distance  from  the  summit,  but  at
this point I spotted an appealing chimney  up  and  to  the  left.   I  like
chimneys.  I feel secure in chimneys. It was class 4, but the rock was  good
so I scrambled up it. At the top a ramp and broken  rock  continued  up  and
before I knew it I was on the ridge about 100 feet N of the summit. I  could
barely believe my good luck at  choice  of  route.  I  scrambled  the  short
remaining distance to the top (1500 ft, 3:10 hrs).

I spent a glorious half hour on top taking in all the  glorious  surrounding
peaks. The register was a large classy bound book in a  heavy  Mazama  metal
case dating back to 1966. There was plenty of space left, as there  were  on
average only several entries per year. In fact mine was the first for  2005.
Other entries were John and Chris Roper\'s 1968 climb  in  memory  of  Robert
Schneller who died climbing the peak the year before; Paul  Michelson   â87;
Don Goodman \'93; Mike Torok \'96; Paul Klenke \'00; Don Beavon  \'02  and  Mike
Collins and Jim Brisbine \'04.  The most humorous entry was from a poor  lost
soul in â89 who stated he thought he was climbing the W ridge of  Forbidden.
He was really lost, but then he was from California.

I made the 3 standard rappels from the summit back to the  glacier  toe.   I
had a 50m rope with me but from the amount of excess rope at each rappel,  a
shorter rope would have worked.  The rappel anchors  were  probably  put  in
when 120 ft ropes were standard. I took my time retracing the route back  to
Sahale along the ridge. I was back in camp at 12:00 (1800  ft,  6  hrs),  in
plenty of time to go out  this  same  day.  The  trip  out  (3:10  hrs)  was
uneventful, except for the steady stream of tourists  asking  what  my  rope
was for.  It is not  that  I  mind  explaining  to  people,  but  after  the
twentieth time it got a bit tiresome.

Total: 15 miles and 5800 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen


