            'title' => 'Dorado Needle (8440+ ft - Cascade Pass, Eldorado Peak, Forbidden Peak Quads) - July 31-August 2, 2005',
            'tr' => '

Dorado Needle (8440+ ft - Cascade Pass, Eldorado Peak, Forbidden Peak
Quads) - July 31-August 2, 2005


After a couple of months of frustrating  weather  related  cancellations  of
trying to get together, I finally  joined  Paul  Michelson  and  his  friend
David for a successful ascent of this peak. It was worth the wait.   What  a
beautiful mountain and area!

Paul and I left early on Sunday, starting  from  the  Eldorado  parking  lot
(elev 2100 ft) at 9:30. David couldn\'t get  away  till  noon  and  would  be
joining us later at high camp. From the parking area a logjam a few  hundred
feet down the road allows  an  easy  crossing  of  the  Cascade  River.  The
climber\'s trail begins on the other side gaining  elevation  steeply  almost
immediately and never letting up. It is definitely a grunt.  After  2000  ft
gain in the woods, the way breaks out into the  open  at  a  boulder  field.
Sparse cairns mark the way, but care is required in  negotiating  the  rocks
and to stay on the best route. Heat and annoying biting flies added  to  the
fun in this section. In another 1000 ft we were at the top of  most  of  the
talus and took a break for lunch at a small waterfall.

Above the waterfall, views of all the Cascade Pass area  peaks  improved  as
we worked our way up into lovely  Eldorado  basin.  Near  the  head  of  the
basin, the route crosses the ridge on the left at about 6100 ft and drops  a
hundred feet into the  Roush  Cr  drainage  at  the  foot  of  the  receding
Eldorado Glacier. More talus and slabs led to the toe of the glacier,  which
we ascended on the extreme right hand side on a well-worn path to  the  high
camp on Eldorado\'s rocky W ridge, elevation 7500 ft (5 miles, 5800 ft,  8:30
hrs). There were several other parties camped here as well, but we  found  a
reasonable site for Paul\'s three-man tent. A strong wind threatened to  turn
the tent into a sail as we struggled to get it  up.  We  had  time  to  find
water, eat dinner and relax while waiting for David to arrive. This  he  did
at 9:30 just as it got really dark and we were beginning to worry.

Sunday was a gorgeous day.  Monday was forecast to rain. We were hoping  the
forecast was wrong.  Unfortunately it was not. We awoke on  Monday  to  zero
visibility and wind and soon after that rain that kept us in  the  tent  all
day. We were not happy campers as we lost an entire day, but at least I  got
caught up on my sleep.

Tuesday dawned cold and clear and we were off at 6:30. We roped  up  on  the
Inspiration Glacier and cramponed on perfect snow one mile to  the  8000  ft
pass NE of Tepeh Towers Pt 8386. A few crevasses were beginning to  open  up
but the way was generally easy and straightforward. From  the  pass  we  had
our first look at Dorado Needle and  it  looked  good.   A  track  even  led
toward it.  Someone else had been up it recently. We  dropped  600  ft  onto
the McAllister Glacier, then climbed back up to the base  of  the  tower  on
the NW ridge (1000 ft, 2 hrs.).

Steep snow led most of the way to the notch on ridge.  A  moat  crossed  the
snow about half way up but was still crossable on a narrow bridge. Paul  put
in a masterful lead on this section, placing two pickets,  while  I  belayed
him with a boot axe belay, and going almost the full length of our main  60m
rope. He commented he could have used a  third  picket  and  a  second  tool
under the very hard snow conditions. I followed up and  was  glad  I  didn\'t
have to lead it. Some front pointing was  necessary  to  the  moat,  then  a
traverse left along the edge of the moat to the bridge and on up where  Paul
had chopped helpful steps. We brought David up on  our  second  thinner  50m
rope.

We stashed crampons and ice axes at  the  notch,  left  the  thin  rope  and
reroped with all three of us on the 60m rope. I took over the lead  for  the
rock. I found the ridge most enjoyable.  There was a little loose  stuff  on
the first pitch but for the most part the rock  was  sound  with  plenty  of
holds and could be mostly protected with  slings  alone.  It  was,  however,
very exposed, especially the two short au  cheval  sections.  Because  there
were three of us on the rope and  to  enhance  communication,  I  broke  the
climb into 3 short pitches, so the rockwork took time. I reached the  summit
at 11:30 (5 hrs).  David came up second, followed by  Paul.  I  looked  hard
but could not find a register. I was so sure a register  would  be  on  this
summit, I didn\'t bring one of my own. Darn!

We down climbed the route back to the notch, with Paul coming last.  We  had
left a few pieces of pro on the chevals to help with the down climb. At  the
notch, we tied the two ropes together for a long  rappel  that  reached  all
the way to the bottom of the steep snow. We were all happy  for  the  second
rope that allowed for this. The snow of the glacier had softened up  by  now
and no longer required crampons. We quickly retraced our route back to  camp
arriving at 3:30 (4 miles, 1700 ft, 9 hrs RT).

Paul and I packed up and left  30  minutes  later.   David  wanted  to  stay
another night and climb Eldorado so we left him the tent. It was  almost  as
much of a grunt going down the knee-busting trail.  At least  it  wasn\'t  as
hot and the bugs weren\'t very bad. Again care  must  be  taken  to  stay  on
route in the boulder field.  It is essential to find the trail  again  where
it enters the woods. We reached the cars at 7:45  (6  miles,  250  ft,  3:45
hrs.)

I still have Klawatti, Austera and Primus to do on the Eldorado Icecap.  Due
to schedules, a day of bad weather and logistics I was not able to  get  any
of these on this trip, but I was elated to climb Dorado Needle and  am  more
than satisfied. And I look forward to returning to this lovely area.

Total: 14 miles and 7750 ft.

Fay Pullen






