            'title' => 'Azurite Peak (8400+ ft - Azurite Pk Quad) - August 7-9, 2005',
            'tr' => '

Azurite Peak (8400+ ft - Azurite Pk Quad) - August 7-9, 2005


I don\'t think I could have chosen a more difficult approach  to  climb  this
peak.  Since I wanted to combine it with Ballard, I decided  to  go  in  via
the Canyon Cr, Chancellor Cr and Mill Cr trails to a camp  at  Azurite  Mine
as suggested in the book Summit Routes.  I really  believe  the  authors  of
that book never actually took this route, or maybe they like to sandbag,  as
the problems we ran into were not indicated and their times  were  way  off.
It is ironic that I went this way so I could also bag Ballard, but then  was
so wiped out just getting Azurite that I had to pass on that  peak.  If  all
you are after is Azurite it  is  definitely  better  to  approach  from  the
Methow and Azurite Pass.

To make matters worse I was joined by a new climbing companion,  Annette.  I
lured her to come along with promises of an  easy  all  trail  approach  and
class 3 climbing max. After all the  problems  we  encountered,  I  wouldn\'t
have been surprise if she never wanted to go out with me again. In  the  end
though, I think she enjoyed the trip and did  not  seem  opposed  to  future
trips together.  She is one tough woman.

Things started well enough at the  Canyon  Cr  TH  off  the  North  Cascades
Highway, elev 1900. Oh yes, there was that tiny little sign  on  the  reader
board, so tiny I doubt that anyone but me actually  read  it,  stating  that
the Chancellor trail was closed and impassible to foot and  stock  from  the
Boulder Cr trail all the way to the Slate Pass road. As it was too  late  to
do anything else, we pushed ahead, but I  really  didn\'t  believe  the  sign
anyway.  How could the trail be impassible to foot travel?  There is  always
a way to go. In any event the first 5 miles of  trail  were  a  delight  and
made us think this would be a piece of  cake.  The  trail  was  gentle  with
excellent tread, shady on this  very  warm  day  and  crossed  several  cool
creeks. It did go up and down a bit, but overall we made good  time  to  the
Boulder Cr trail junction.

And then it all gradually fell apart. The trail descended some 400  feet  to
Mill Cr. Near the bottom a section of the trail had slid away,  but  it  was
passable with a few cautious steps.  Not so bad, I thought.  A  nice  bridge
crossed the creek, elev 2600 ft (5.5 miles, 1650 ft, 3 hrs).  On  the  other
side we briefly lost the trail, located it going downstream and then  switch
backing uphill to a junction with the unmarked Mill  Cr  trail.  Now  things
really got interesting. This trail shows no signs of maintenance  for  years
or even recent travel by anyone for that matter.  It  is  not  that  bad  in
wooded areas, but open areas were brushy and just got worse and worse  until
near the end we were head high in, as Annette put  it,  "old  growth"  brush
and ferns and stumbling along feeling our way with our feet. She  does  have
a sense a humor. Good thing because she needed one. We also lost  the  trail
at a rockslide and wandered around for a while before finding it  again.  To
add to our misery, the S facing slopes were sweltering  in  the  midday  sun
and heat and bone dry. We had both run out of water and  were  parched  when
we were saved by the one and only creek about 2.5 miles from the junction.

It took us 3.5 hours to slowly battle our way the 3.3 miles to the  junction
with the Cady Pass "trail", elev 4000 ft. When we reached  the  junction  we
were shocked to discover this "trail" is really a "road"  and  had  recently
been traveled by a tracked vehicle. Ordinarily I would  be  quite  upset  to
come across a road so far into the backcountry, but I  was  so  glad  to  be
free of the awful brush that I welcomed it with open  arms.  The  road  must
have something to do with the mine (I  do  hope  they  are  not  considering
reopening it) and must come  from  the  end  of  the  Slate  Pass  Road.  We
gratefully followed the road the last 1.2 miles to the mine and  a  spacious
flat campsite next to an old mine building, elev 4400 ft (10.5  miles,  3800
ft, 8 hrs.)  The area around the mine was a no man\'s land of bleak red  dirt
tailings. We were visited at dinner by a very healthy looking deer that  had
somehow taken on the color of the tailings.   She  blended  right  into  the
background. We hung our food but that didn\'t stop her from trying  to  reach
it all night long. She didn\'t succeed.

We headed out the next morning optimistic that this  day  would  go  better.
After all the book said 4 hrs from  the  mine  to  the  summit  of  Azurite.
Forget that! Of course I really knew better than to believe  the  book  now.
Our troubles began again as soon as the road crossed Mill Cr  to  head  back
downstream to the mineshaft on the slopes of  Majestic  Mtn.  There  was  no
sign of a trail heading upstream. We wandered  around  a  bit  and  found  a
segment uphill but soon lost it again. Eventually we figured out  it  was  a
waste of time to try and  follow  an  almost  nonexistent  trail,  and  just
traversed upstream a few hundred feet above the creek through  awful  brush,
rockslides and tangled woods until I figured we were close  enough  to  head
straight uphill. It was slow  exhausting  travel,  made  even  worse  by  us
stumbling across a yellow jacket nest and Annette  getting  stung.  But  she
took it all in stride.

After what seemed an eternity, we came to a major gully and followed  it  up
slippery sand covered slab to open slopes below the  cliffs  of  Azurite.  I
had no idea where we were in relation to the usual route from  Azurite  Pass
and along the S ridge, only that  we  were  somewhere  on  the  W  face.  We
continued working our way  up  until  forced  to  traverse  left  below  the
cliffs. I could see a reddish colored gully that offered  a  possible  route
to the summit but the lower section looked ugly and steep.  Easy  ramps  and
wide ledges led left toward the gully higher up. Just before  the  gully  we
came to a narrow exposed class 4 ledge leading  around  a  corner.  At  this
point Annette had reached her scrambling comfort level. It would  take  time
to set up a belay on the ledge traverse and we were running out of time.  So
Annette graciously agreed to wait while I continued on.

I went as fast as I could reasonably safely go and it  took  me  1  hour  RT
from this point (about 8000 ft elev). The ledge continued around the  corner
about 10 feet and allowed a drop into the red gully. This was a  very  loose
unpleasant gully and I knocked rocks down left and right as I climbed up  it
to the top of the ridge.  Much to my dismay I was  still  a  ways  from  the
summit and had to climb over a rib and drop  into  a  second  summit  gully.
This gully was steeper and had a couple of steps  approaching  class  4  and
was also very loose. At the top of this gully, I turned right to the  summit
ridge and followed it the short ways left to the summit (4400  ft,  7  hrs).
Mindful of Annette waiting, I quickly signed the register, noting only  that
it had been placed in 1998, took a picture and headed back down.

I took only a short rest when I was back to Annette, as  I  was  fearful  we
would run out of time if we didn\'t find a faster  way  down.  Thankfully  we
did. We descended the major slabby gully for  a  ways  then  got  onto  much
friendlier terrain on the S side that went all the way down to the  Mill  Cr
valley floor. We then followed along the creek through a  series  of  lovely
meadows, and then in the gravelly creek bottom itself all the way down.   It
was surprisingly open and pleasant most of the  way  and  infinitely  better
than our ascent route. We reached camp at  6:45,  much  sooner  than  I  had
expected (8 miles, 4400 ft, 11 hrs).

I was too tired and my feet too trashed the next morning  to  even  consider
climbing Ballard.  Too bad, it looked to be an easy  climb  from  the  mine.
However, I was happy to just to have made it up Azurite. Neither of  us  was
looking forward to going out the awful Mill Cr trail.  But as is  often  the
case, it wasn\'t as bad as we anticipated.  This time we knew what to  expect
and we were able to stay on the trail without losing  it.  Expectations  can
be everything.  We weren\'t expecting a bad  trail  coming  in  and  we  were
going out. We made it to the Chancellor trail in 2:20 hrs. We  took  a  long
lunch at the Mill Cr crossing, then went out  at  our  separate  paces  with
Annette beating me by a long shot (10.5 miles, 1050 ft, 5:30 hrs).  We  both
washed up in Granite Cr to cool off  and  feel  presentable  for  the  drive
home.

Total: 29 miles and 9250 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen





