            'title' => 'Cosho Pk (8332 ft) and Kimtah Pk (8600+ ft) - Mt Logan and Mt Arriva Quads - August 15-17, 2005.',
            'tr' => '
Cosho Pk (8332 ft) and Kimtah Pk (8600+ ft) - Mt Logan and Mt Arriva Quads
- August 15-17, 2005.

It was back to Ragged Ridge to pick up  these  last  two  peaks,  as  I  had
already climbed Mesahchie and Katsuk early in July. I had the  usual  delays
getting to the Easy Pass TH.   They  really  need  to  overhaul  the  permit
process at the Marblemount RS.  It can take upwards of  30  minutes  to  get
one. This time both rangers on duty were busy, one taking care  of  a  large
youth group explaining rules and regulations and checking out multiple  bear
canisters, the other helping a couple who didn\'t know where they  wanted  to
go or for how long. I knew exactly where I  was  going  and  it  would  have
taken me only a few minutes but I had to wait in line.  It  was  finally  my
turn and then the phone rang and of course the ranger gave  that  precedence
over me. And they wonder why some climbers don\'t  bother  with  permits  and
take their chances. And then there was the traffic.  Monday morning  traffic
getting out of town, traffic stopped and backed  up  at  the  Newhalem  rock
slide and slow traffic on Hywy 20  where  many  refuse  to  obey  the  signs
"delay of 5 vehicles illegal, must use turnouts." Slow, slow, slow!

So it was sweltering in the heat of the day by the time  I  finally  started
up the trail to Easy Pass. Then it was down the other side into  the  Fisher
Cr valley and farther down the valley  to  Cosho  Camp,  elev  3750  ft  (10
miles, 2800 ft, 5:15 hrs). This  is  a  very  pleasant  camp  in  the  woods
located right on the banks of Fisher Cr. There are 3 sites far enough  apart
for privacy, each with its own access to the creek. I  took  the  last  site
available.

I began the next day (Tuesday) at 6:45. I knew this would  be  a  long  day.
Summit Routes even suggests a high bivy to allow enough time to  climb  both
peaks, but carrying bivy gear along didn\'t appeal to me. I would  just  have
to fit it all into one day even if that meant coming down in the dark.  Good
thing I didn\'t bivy, as I found no  water  anywhere  on  the  entire  route.
There was some snow on the N side of the main summit ridge, but  that  would
have been a very high bivy indeed. Fortunately, I suspected there  would  be
no water and carried enough with me to last the  day,  although  I  ran  out
near the very end.

Both Becky and Summit Routes tell you to cross Fisher Cr on  the  trail  and
continue downstream Â¼ mile until opposite the Central Gully draining  the  S
slopes of Cosho. This is in error as are  both  the  USGS  and  GT  maps  in
showing where the trail crosses Fisher Cr. It  actually  crosses  the  creek
almost directly opposite the gully so there is no reason to  cross  (perhaps
the trail has been rerouted in recent years). Just before  the  crossing,  I
left the trail and headed uphill in reasonably open forest staying  just  to
the right of the gully until forced by cliffs at about  5000  ft  elev  left
into the Central Gully proper. By now I was above all the  gully  brush  and
the route up was clear.  The bed of  the  gully  was  mostly  water  scoured
(bone dry now) lovely white rock that made for fun scrambling. A  few  class
3-4 short steps added interest.

The gully wound its way through cliffs for a thousand  feet  before  opening
up to wider less constricted terrain and more  unpleasant  loose  scree  and
rocks.  Views of Cosho to the left and the spire of Thieves Pk to the  right
appeared. I worked my way up increasingly  unpleasant  loose  stuff  to  the
8000 ft notch between Cosho and Thieves. The final bit was a short  class  4
step, then class 3 the rest of the way to the summit (4600 ft, 5  hrs).  The
summit register was the original aluminum canister placed by John  Roper  on
his first ascent on June 6, 1970. There were only scraps  of  paper  inside,
but they were in good condition with enough room  for  added  entries  so  I
decided to leave well enough alone and not replace it with a register of  my
own. The screw-on lid was a bit corroded and hard to get off, though,  so  I
lubricated it with my lip balm.  That seemed to help, at least in the  short
term. I again made note of the amazing Skoog brothers who  traversed  Ragged
Ridge on skis on June 1, 1991.

I looked over to Kimtah Pk. It looked an awfully long  ways  away  with  the
imposing obstacle of Thieves Pk between it and me. I  left  Cosho  at  noon,
descending awful loose stuff to about 7200 ft, the first point I  could  get
beneath the cliffs of Thieves Pk.  Here I climbed a steep gully and  heather
face (class 3 and 4) to cross  Thieves\'  S  ridge  at  7600  ft.  An  upward
traverse on ramps and ledges, never very  difficult,  led  to  the  7800  ft
notch to the right of Thieves.   Another  traverse  below  the  ridge  crest
crossed  a  spur  to  the  slopes  SW  of  Kimtah\'s  W  summit.  Of  several
possibilities from here, I chose a high traverse at 8000 ft on  a  prominent
ledge system that worked its way in and out  of  numerous  gullies.  I  came
across one conspicuous cairn so I was on someone\'s route. This was  actually
a fun traverse and I enjoyed it. Once past the cliffs of the  W  summit  and
on the S slopes of Kimtah proper, easy scree led  to  the  ridge  and  final
summit rocks (6350 ft, 9 hrs).

A Mike Torok register placed 7/30/94 graced the summit. There seemed  to  be
more entries than for Cosho, in spite of it being placed later.  I  find  it
hard to believe this peak (which is probably the hardest on Ragged Ridge  to
get to) is climbed more often.  Maybe the scraps  of  paper  were  deceiving
and I just didn\'t see them all. I recognized Don Goodman and Paul  Michelson
7/13/97, Grant Myers and Mitch Blanton 7/20/97, Dale Flynn and  Matt  Burton
8/20/99, and Mike Collins and Don Beavon 8/10/02.

It was now 4:00 and I had a long ways to  go  to  get  down.   It  was  very
tempting to descend directly from Kimtah  to  Fisher  Cr  down  any  one  of
several possible gullies. But I couldn\'t see all the way down  any  of  them
and looking at the map the contours were very close  together  suggesting  I
could run into ugly terrain. No, it was best to go back the way I had  come,
a way I knew would go. I did cross Thieves\' S ridge at a lower  point  (7000
ft) to avoid the steep terrain  I  had  ascended,  but  other  than  that  I
reversed my route back to and down the Central Gully then  into  the  woods.
Things went faster than I expected  and  I  staggered  into  camp  at  8:20,
happily before dark (8 miles, 6500 ft, 13.5 hrs).

When I left town, the forecast for Wednesday was  10%  chance  of  rain  but
with "widespread drizzle."  What on earth did that mean?  It seemed  like  a
contradiction to me. Maybe drizzle doesn\'t qualify as  rain.  The  "drizzle"
forecast made me nervous, so I had brought a full sized tent rather  than  a
bivy tent. Sure enough, during the night it rained  and  continued  to  rain
all the way out the next day (10 miles, 2900 ft, 5.5 hrs - yes  it  took  me
longer to go out than coming in, but it was all up to Easy Pass  and  I  was
tired and wet).

Total: 28 miles and 12, 200 ft in 3 days         Fay Pullen




