            'tr' => '
Primus Peak (8508 ft) and Tricouni Peak (8102 ft) - Ross Dam  and  Forbidden
Peak Quads - August 24-26, 2005

Day 1: I thought maybe I could still get up Primus Peak  this  season  if  I
went in from Thunder Creek, although I knew getting up the Borealis  Glacier
this late in a very low snow year could be a problem.  I  went  on-line  and
found out the upper bridge across Thunder  Creek  to  McAllister  Camp  (6.5
miles in) has been replaced after being out for  two  years.   Without  that
bridge I would not have been able to access the route, so it  all  seemed  a
go. It didn\'t occur to me that the lower bridge (1 mile in) would  still  be
out (Why would they replace the upper bridge, and one that only  went  to  a
camp, before the one on the main trail?). I was informed of this  unexpected
fact when I picked up my permit at the Marblemount RS. But the  ranger  made
it sound like no big problem. Just cross  Thunder  Arm  on  the  Highway  20
bridge (elev 1200 ft) and follow the flagged route on the E side of the  Arm
and creek to intersect Thunder Cr trail about 1.5 miles in. It  only  adds  Â½
mile. Yeh, right! Let me tell you this is one rough  detour  that  is  worse
than many climber trails I have been on. It took me 1:15  hr  of  exhausting
travel to intersect the main trail, adding at least 45  minutes  of  time  I
would sorely need later. I recommend not  going  up  the  Thunder  Cr  trail
until the bridge is replaced (hopefully soon),  or  you  will  be  worn  out
before you even start.

Once on the excellent main trail I made much better time. I  passed  Thunder
Cr Camp, where I heard some sort of motorized work going on.  That  is  when
it occurred to me that the Park Service may  have  wanted  to  get  all  the
camps ready for use before opening the main trail so hikers would have  some
place to stay.  Now that made sense to me.  Near  McAllister  Horse  Camp  I
stopped at a creek to fill up on water.  I knew the ridge  route  to  Primus
would have none. Shortly after, I came to the  turnoff  to  McAllister  Camp
and the new bridge over the creek (7 miles,  1300  ft,  4:20  hrs).  On  the
other side 3 new campsites had been carved out of the forest.  Here  I  left
the trail (elev 1900 ft) and headed uphill to the  south  trending  ridge  I
would climb for 4100 ft to the base of the Borealis Glacier.

As I had hoped, once on the crest of  the  ridge  I  picked  up  a  climbers
trail. This trail is rough and steep and works  its  way  up  several  cliff
bands, but I expected this, and it is reasonably easy  to  follow  for  2000
ft, although care must be taken to stay on route. Then comes  a  section  of
dense trees and moderate brush, especially when the ridge levels off  at  Pt
4835, where it is hard to follow. When the ridge steepens again at  5000  ft
and soon opens to heather, the trail gradually improves the rest of the  way
and is once again easily followed.  Good thing, as I was beginning to  worry
about making my camp before dark.

As I pulled over the last rise and had my first view of Tricouni and  Primus
and the Borealis Glacier my heart fell. I would not be climbing  the  normal
route up the glacier to Lucky Pass. The glacier has  receded  so  much,  the
route was either evil looking slabs or evil looking broken up  glacier  ice.
(Every 30 minutes or so, all night and all day, ice would break off the  ice
cliffs of the upper Borealis Glacier and crash down the rock  slabs.  I  was
seeing the glacier disappear before my very eyes.) I would  have  to  go  to
Plan B to climb my peak, except that I didn\'t  know  what  Plan  B  was.   I
would think about that in the morning. Now I had to find  a  place  to  camp
and water quickly. I descended slightly to the toe of the Borealis  Glacier,
or rather to the good-sized ice lake that has  now  formed  at  the  toe.  I
found a flat gravel bar near the shore (elev 6000 ft) for my bivy  tent  (10
miles, 5400 ft, 9 hrs), but there was no running  water  anywhere.  The  ice
lake appeared to have no outlet.  Water would have to  come  from  the  lake
itself, a rather unappealing prospect. The water was cloudy and most  likely
has been locked up in glacier ice for centuries, if not  longer.  It  tasted
that way too, but beggars can\'t be  choosey.  Large  ice  islands  that  had
calved off the glacier edge floated in the pea green soup. Despite the  warm
temperature, a dip was not appealing either in the 32-degree water.



Day 2: I slept in till 7:00, worn out by the previous day and really  having
no plan. I sat staring at Primus while eating breakfast and I came  up  with
3 possible ones. Plan A: I could climb to near the N  ridge  of  Primus  and
then traverse high on the upper Borealis Glacier back  to  Lucky  Pass.  But
the traverse looked almost as bad in places as the direct  route  and  would
be above cliffs with no runout. Plan B: There was a  rock  route  up  the  N
ridge of Primus. But it was low class 5, a thousand  feet  long  and  I  had
only a 60 ft rope and a few slings. Plan C: I could cross the N ridge  to  a
small glacier on the NW slope where a couloir gave  access  to  the  easy  W
ridge. This sounded the most promising, depending on the  condition  of  the
NW glacier. Since all plans involved going to the N ridge that  is  where  I
headed.

The first problem was getting around the ice lake on slabs, not  that  easy.
Then I made my way up heather slopes to  a  spur  ridge,  circumventing  the
lower glacier, until I could work my way up rock to the base  of  the  upper
glacier below Pt 7740. Here I found  welcome  pure  lovely  tasting  running
water, and filled up. I donned crampons and  began  a  traverse  toward  the
7500 ft saddle on the N ridge of Primus.  The steepness  was  only  moderate
but the snow rock hard and icy. My ice axe penetrated  less  than  an  inch.
Self arrest would not be an option.  This convinced me of the folly of  Plan
A. I had enough trouble just making it to the saddle  (1750  ft,  2:45  hr).
The N ridge looked frightful but the NW glacier didn\'t look too bad. It  was
icy but gentle with a good runout. I crossed easily low down until  I  could
see the couloir leading to the W ridge.  Darn,  it  was  still  filled  with
wickedly steep hard hanging snow. No thank you!

Running out of options and not feeling very optimistic,  I  headed  back  to
the N ridge to take a closer look. The NW glacier climbed  high  up  the  NW
slopes and was easier travel than the ridge.  Perhaps I could climb  to  its
highest point and gain the N ridge higher up. I was able to  climb  to  8000
ft before running out of snow, which put me smack in the middle  of  the  NW
face  directly  below  the  summit.  The  face  looked  fairly  broken   up,
especially toward the right and the W ridge,  and  looked  climbable  to  me
(Plan D). It was, barely. Oh it wasn\'t that hard or  even  that  steep,  but
once past some initial  slabs,  the  route  become  very  unpleasant,  nerve
wracking loose dirt and gravel  where  nothing  stayed  put.  I  essentially
crawled my way up the face from solid point to solid  point,  never  feeling
very secure. It took 1.5 hrs to scramble up the 500 ft and emerge  on  the  W
ridge very near the top.  I walked the  few  remaining  feet  to  the  broad
summit (2900 ft, 5:30 hrs.) and left a register in  a  quickly  built  small
cairn. I admired  the  gorgeous  views  all  around,  especially  across  to
Austera and Klawatti (yet to do) and Eldorado and Dorado Needle.

It was now 2:30. I really wanted to climb Tricouni. The  route  is  straight
forward and technically easy, mostly on talus and  stable  rock,  but  would
mean descending 1300 ft to 7200-foot Lucky Pass,  then  up  900  ft  to  the
summit, and then reversing it all back to Primus again.  It was  almost  too
much to consider this late in the day. But I knew if I didn\'t  climb  it  on
this trip, I would probably never climb it. I would  not  be  repeating  the
trip up the ridge to high camp any time soon. So down I went.  Once  I  made
the decision to go I entered a state of mind where I got renewed energy  and
took great enjoyment in moving fast (I left rope and other  gear  on  Primus
to lighten my pack). I almost felt like I was dancing up and down the  rock.
I was on Tricouni in 1:25 hrs (I left another register) and back  to  Primus
1:40 hr more (5000 ft, 9:15 hrs).

Now all I had to do was  get  down  the  awful  NW  face.   Because  of  the
unstable dirt/gravel I did a lot of short rappels on my 60 ft rope, just  so
I wouldn\'t lose my balance and start sliding down the junk. I lost count  of
the number, but it was probably a dozen or  so.  I  didn\'t  have  that  many
slings, but fortunately there were a surprising  number  of  solid  horns  I
could wrap the rope around directly. I did downclimb some  also,  mostly  on
the seat of my pants.  I breathed a sigh of relief when I reached the  snow,
which took another 1.5 hrs. Then it was quickly down to the N saddle,  across
the upper Borealis Glacier and most of the upper rock scramble. I  did  take
time to fill up again on good water for camp. Darkness caught me  on  tricky
slabs above the lower glacier. I couldn\'t see far enough to  find  the  best
route down, so wandered back and forth on ledges finally descending all  the
way to the ice lake just to get my bearings, knowing full well I would  have
to climb up again to get past  some  cliffs  that  went  straight  into  the
water. I dragged into camp at 10:30 (6 miles, 5200  ft,  14  hrs),  all  but
done in. But I did take the time to eat  a  good  dinner  and  rehydrate.  I
would need the energy for the next day.

Day 3: I left at 9:30, dreading the descent of the ridge. It was  almost  as
bad as I anticipated. This is one hard ridge to stay on going down.  And  if
you get seriously off route, heaven help  you.   I  had  fortunately  marked
several waypoints with my GPS on the way up, and this saved me. I  lost  the
trail in the 5000-4000 ft section several times, but my GPS got me  back  on
track.  The lower trail was easier to follow, just darn steep and a pain  to
go down. I made the McAllister bridge at 2:00 and  the  detour  at  5:15.  I
took 15 minutes to check out the old bridge crossing,  hoping  there  was  a
way across so I wouldn\'t have to use the detour. There was  a  large  logjam
but it didn\'t completely cross the creek and the water was too deep and  the
current too swift to ford. So it was the awful detour after all.  Just  what
I needed at the end of 3 hard days. I reached the  car  at  6:40  with  very
sore feet. (10 miles, 900 ft, 9 hrs).

Total: 26 miles and 11,500 ft in 3 days.

Fay Pullen




