            'tr' => '

Mac Peak (6859 ft) and Swallowtail Peak (6317 ft) - Scenic and Stevens Pass
Quads

September 8-9, 2005

My original plan to climb these Back Court peaks was to hike in  to  a  camp
at Deception Lakes and climb Jungeselle Pk (6527 ft,  S  of  Mac  and  Talus
Lake on The Cradle quad) on the first day, then climb  Mac  and  Swallowtail
and hike out on the second day. However,  Thursday  was  the  only  forecast
good weather day and Friday was supposed to rain, so I  decided  to  reverse
the order and get in the two "harder" (i.e.  take  more  time)  ones  first.
Maybe I could still get up Jungeselle in the rain.

At the last minute Mike Collins joined me. Good thing, as he kept  me  going
at a faster pace than I would have gone alone  and  since  I  didn\'t  get  a
early start (got in late the night before), I doubt I would have  made  both
peaks without him along (of course it was also nice to  have  his  company).
We drove the Tonga Ridge road to the Deception Cr Cutoff  Trail  (elev  3700
ft) and dropped 500 ft to follow the Deception Cr, Deception Lk and  Pacific
Crest Trails to a camp on the N shore of the middle  lake,  elev  5050  (4.5
miles, 1950 ft, 2:20 hrs).

After setting up camp, we took off for Swallowtail at 2:00. From  the  lower
lakes, we worked our way upstream through lovely  meadows  filled  with  the
aroma of ripe blueberries (naturally we had  to  partake),  past  the  upper
lake to the saddle in the ridge N of Mac and dropped into  the  Square  Lake
drainage. Here on the north slopes of Mac we were surprised  to  still  find
an old dirty patch of snow. We contoured the basin and climbed to  the  5960
ft saddle on the NE ridge of Mac. After a  minor  bit  of  confusion  as  to
which peak was actually Swallowtail, we headed NE along the  ridge  dropping
to a 5760 saddle before climbing to the base of  the  impressive  cliffs  on
the NW face of the false summit. We worked around the rocky ridge on  ledges
to the S until we could access the final easy slopes leading to  the  gentle
summit (2200 ft, 2:40 hrs). A tiny cairn marked the top  but  we  could  not
find any register (I left one).

Now setting our sights on Mac, we retraced our steps to the 5960  ft  saddle
then continued SW along the ridge to steep heather slopes and the  E  ridge.
A cliffy section along this ridge required a slight detour to the  S  before
gaining the summit (3600 ft, 4:20 hrs) where we found a  film  can  register
left by Don and Natala Goodman in 1999. It was not in the best of shape,  so
I left a new register and placed the tattered contents of  the  old  one  in
it.

It was now 6:45.  We  could  see  weather  brewing  to  the  W.  Daniel  was
disappearing in the gathering dark clouds. Streaks of  sunbeams  accentuated
the prominent terracing that presumably  gave  Terrace  Mtn  its  name.  The
resulting lighting effects were beautiful but also made us hurry to make  it
back to camp before both storm and darkness hit. We made  a  direct  descent
NW to the lakes, at first down friendly heather,  then  a  not  so  friendly
cliffband and an endless talus field that consisted of huge white  boulders.
We came out right at the PCT bridge over the lake outlet creek  and  reached
camp at 8:20 only needing headlamps at the very end (6 miles, 3750 ft,  6:10
hrs).



Surprisingly, the weather held off until well after midnight,  but  then  it
came in with a vengeance - drenching rain and strong gusty winds.  The  next
morning a short lull in the rain and a tiny blue-sky sucker hole allowed  us
to optimistically think we could still climb Jungeselle. So we  set  off  at
7:30 hiking S on the PCT some 2 miles  (the  trail  loses  600  ft  in  this
distance) until just past the creek draining  Talus  Lake.  Here  we  headed
uphill to Jungeselle\'s S ridge through open timber and light brush.  By  now
it was raining again. Somewhere around 5400 ft the  rain  began  turning  to
snow. By the time we reached the summit ridge, several  inches  of  the  wet
slippery white stuff covered everything. The last bit  to  the  top  was  an
unexpected narrow rocky ridge.  We were able  to  go  several  hundred  feet
along the crest of the ridge, but were stopped  by  a  final  pinnacle  that
required a steep traverse and descent to the final notch. The  summit  block
also looked difficult  and  dicey  under  the  present  conditions,  it  was
snowing so hard we could barely see and both of us were  cold  and  wet.  It
was really quite grim. So we turned around 100 vertical feet and 350  linear
feet from the summit. What ever happened to summer?

The snow followed us all the slip-slidey way down  to  the  trail.  We  were
back to camp at 12:45 (7 miles, 3000 ft, 5:15 hrs), where  both  tents  were
covered with over an inch of snow. We took an hour to  put  on  dry  clothes
and warm up before leaving at 2:00 and arriving at  the  car  at  4:00  (4.5
miles, 600 ft, 2 hrs).

Total: 22 miles and 9300 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen




