            'tr' => '
Granite Mtn S Pk (7080 ft), French Ridge W Pk (6748 ft) & E  Pk  (6767  ft),
and Jungeselle Pk (6527 ft) - The Cradle Quad - September 13-15, 2005

The Robin Lakes area is so beautiful it is well  worth  a  trip  in  itself.
Gorgeous white  granite  slabs  alternating  with  rolling  meadows  provide
friendly rambling terrain. Numerous sparkling lakes  and  tarns  fill  every
basin and around  every  corner  are  new  delights  and  hidden  nooks  and
corners. Add four new peaks, no bugs and few people this time  of  year  and
it is heaven on earth. It doesn\'t get any better than this!

I began from the Deception Pass Trail (elev 3400 ft), at the end of the  Cle
Elum River Road, and hiked the 4.5 miles to  the  Robin  Lakes  junction.  I
passed two older women struggling up the steep,  rough  1.5  mile  trail  to
Tuck Lake, 1000 ft below Robin Lakes. They asked me if I had  ever  been  up
this trail before.  "Yes", I replied. "Does the trail  to  Robin  Lakes  get
any worse?" they then asked. "Most certainly", I answered.  "It  requires  a
bit of scrambling and following cairns across slabs." They  looked  dismayed
as they explained they had started backpacking late in  life  and  this  was
the hardest thing they had ever done. I  encouraged  them  and  wished  them
luck, but I knew that if they were having trouble on this section they  most
likely would not make it to the higher lakes. Too bad.

From Tuck Lake, I continued up  the  worsening  way  trail  as  it  wandered
through cliff bands and then leveled somewhat the last bit to crossing  huge
slabs, marked by cairns, to then drop to the lower of the two  Robin  Lakes.
At 3:00 I found a secluded spot for my tent in the bed of a  tiny  dried  up
tarn (where I could do no damage) above the upper lake (7  miles,  3350  ft,
4:30 hrs). I took off an hour later for S  Granite  Mtn.  The  route  was  a
sheer pleasure of expanding views down to the lakes  and  scrambling  across
slabs, heading toward then contouring beneath  Granite  Mtn  to  the  saddle
with the S Pk. Here were nestled twin tarns sparkling in the  sunshine.  The
final easy ascent was up the NW ridge (1250 ft, 1:30 hr). A tiny  cairn,  in
which I left a register, marked the summit. On the way back I saw a herd  of
half a dozen mountain goats, always such a treat. (3 miles, 1650 ft,  3  hrs
RT)

Most of the first day (Tuesday) was sunny and warm, but by the  time  I  got
back to camp it was beginning to cloud up, Mt  Daniel  was  disappearing  in
the fog and a cold wind was blowing.  I was afraid the weather was  changing
for the worse, but when I awoke Wednesday morning, it was still fine  except
for a few clouds.  It did get cloudier with fog forming on  the  summits  as
the day progressed but it never rained. I left  at  8:30,  climbing  to  the
Trico-Granite divide above Granite Mtn Potholes  and  working  my  way  down
over gorgeous massive white slabs to the heather and blueberry  basin  below
the SW slopes of W French Ridge.  Progress was slow as I grazed on the  ripe
fruit along the way. I climbed to the S ridge and followed this the rest  of
the way to the top (670 ft, 1:20 hr). The actual summit was a 10 ft  boulder
that I surmounted with an assist from my rope thrown over the top.   I  left
another register and improved the cairn tottering on the sloping top  but  I
am not optimistic either will stay there long.

The E face of this peak is quite sheer and impressive,  but  by  going  down
the S ridge a short ways I found a reasonable route  directly  down  to  the
saddle with Pt 6555. I then had to skirt cliffs below this  point  to  reach
the saddle between it and E French Ridge from where easy slopes led  to  the
summit (1745 ft, 3:30 hrs). I was surprised to find a tiny register on  top,
but I recognized it as one of Dick Kegel\'s even before I opened it.  He  had
placed it on 9/21/03 and his was the  only  entry.   These  obscure  unnamed
peaks aren\'t climbed very often.

By 2:00 I had worked my way back to the  blueberry  basin  SW  of  W  French
Ridge. I now had a decision to  make.  It  was  still  early.   I  could  go
directly back to camp and lounge around for several hours  (actually  rather
appealing) ORâ¦.  I could see Jungeselle off in the distance.  This  was  the
peak I had barely missed last week with Mike Collins due to miserable  snowy
conditions.  It looked an awfully long ways away (probably  about  3  rugged
miles) and would require dropping 1000 ft  to  Lake  Phoebe.  On  the  other
hand, the route looked feasible and it was the last of the  100  Back  Court
Peaks for me to do. So off I went, knowing that I might  not  make  it  down
before dark.

I dropped the distressing 1000 ft to Lake Phoebe, skirted  the  W  shore  on
slowing  talus,  traversed  above  Lower  Phoebe  Lake  through  woods  then
foolishly chose a high line climbing to 6000 ft on tedious talus above  both
Jungfrau Lake and the small unnamed lake above it. I  then  contoured  below
the cliffs of Jungeselle\'s E face until I could climb up to  the  open  left
slanting heather ramp  I  had  spotted  from  a  distance.   This  ramp  led
directly to the notch between the summit and the pinnacle that  had  stopped
Mike and me. The dark slabs that had appeared so  ominous  to  Mike  and  me
were easily turned to the left and I emerged on the summit of my  last  Back
Court Peak at 5:00 (3825  ft,  8:30).  Again  only  a  small  cairn  and  no
register.  I left my third of the day. No view of Mac. It and  most  of  the
surrounding area was in the fog.

Tired of talus hopping, I took a lower line directly down  the  drainage  on
mostly heather to the unnamed lake, Jungfrau Lake  and  Lower  Phoebe  Lake.
Much faster and easier. I found a way trail leading up to Lake Phoebe  where
there was no avoiding the talus on its shore once again. I wanted  to  climb
directly to Granite Mtn Potholes but from below I didn\'t  pick  the  correct
gully through the many cliffs and ended up in one farther E. This gully  got
frightfully steep near the top, so I exited on  ledges  to  the  left  where
darkness caught me on the same massive white slabs I had  descended  earlier
in the day. I wandered around a bit in the dark in the confusing  flat  area
of the Trico-Granite saddle until I stumbled across  the  way  trail  around
Upper Robin Lake and found my way to camp at 8:30 (10  miles,  5250  ft,  12
hrs).

It sprinkled during the night, but nothing serious.   The  next  day  dawned
foggy but cleared to just cloudy and cool. I left at 9:30  and  reached  the
car at 1:45, stopping for lunch on the way (7 miles, 500 ft, 4:15  hrs),  an
easy end to a lovely trip.

Total: 27 miles and 10,750 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen


