            'tr' => '

Bandit Peak (7625 ft) - Schaefer Lake Quad - September 17-18, 2005


Bandit can be done as a long day climb, but Jim Brisbine and I were  happier
turning it into a more leisurely two-day trip.  That  allowed  for  a  later
start in the morning. Thus we were able to begin from the Schaefer  Lake  TH
(elev 2500 ft), on the Chiwawa River Road, a little after noon.  The  logjam
was in place for an easy crossing of the Chiwawa River and  the  good  trail
and good conversation put us at Schaefer Lake (elev 5100 ft) in what  seemed
no time at all (5 miles, 2750 ft, 2:30 hrs). From the lake we happened  upon
an unexpected way trail that led easily to the long 6100 ft  saddle  between
Pts 6931 and 6641 (6 miles, 3850 ft, 3:45 hrs). Here we  dropped  our  packs
for a quick scramble up Pt 6764 (Jim had climbed this peaks  previously  but
he graciously accompanied me up it) and a great view of  our  objective  and
down to D Lake (1 mile, 1.5 hrs and 650 ft RT counting  Â½  hour  on  top).  A
tiny register was on top placed by a fellow who had just climbed  it  a  few
weeks earlier.

Our original intention was to camp at D Lake. The  saddle  itself  was  very
appealing with friendly flat grassy terrain and a great view,  but  appeared
at first glance to be without water. As we began the descent to D Lake  what
should run across but a welcome trickling creek! That cinched it and we  set
up a delightful camp in this delightful spot.

The next morning was chilly with frost on  the  tent  but  with  clear  blue
skies. We descended some 200 feet down the  gully  on  the  N  side  of  our
saddle to the upper end of D Lake basin, climbed up  talus  and  heather  to
cross an E trending spur ridge at 6400 ft  and  began  a  long  traverse  on
talus on E slopes below cliffs until we could easily  climb  to  Bandit\'s  N
ridge at about 7300 ft. We were now somewhat surprised to find  the  terrain
more intimidating than expected. There were  cliffs  on  both  side  of  the
ridge and the only feasible route was following the  crest.  We  worked  our
way S along the ridge and discovered it was not as  difficult  as  it  first
appeared, but it was always near the upper limit of comfortable  scrambling.
At one point we had to descend on the E face to  get  past  a  sharp  notch.
From the notch more steep scrambling put us on the summit of the NE Pk.

 Now came the challenge of getting off this summit.  Beckey  mentions  an  E
and W Pk, with the W Pk being higher, but I would describe Bandit as  having
three summits, NE and SE Pts on the main N-S ridge, and  the  actual  summit
being slightly off this main ridge to the W.  The notch between the  NE  and
SE Pks was frightfully steep and not accessible directly from the summit  we
were on. We could, however, see a ramp/ledge system leading W to  the  small
bowl surrounded by all three summits, from where it appeared to be  an  easy
scramble to the true summit. Fortunately Jim had brought his 75 ft  scramble
rope and we made good use of this for a short rappel down a  step  onto  the
ramp. Steep down climbing with two more short steps  and  we  were  able  to
scramble on to the summit (2150 ft, 4:15 hrs).

An interesting large round  cookie  tin  held  the  summit  register,  which
consisted of scraps of deteriorating paper. I placed the  scraps  in  a  new
register of mine that I then put back in the cookie tin. The earliest  entry
I could make out (just barely) was in 1990 by one  of  the  Praters.  Others
were Don Goodman in 1993, Don Beavon and Mitch Blanton  in  1998,  and  Greg
Koenig also in 1998. There were a total of  7  entries.  This  peak  is  not
climbed all that often. The most interesting comment was  by  a  fellow  who
climbed it in 2000 stating, "A tough Peak.  My route was so complex I  doubt
I can describe it to anyone.  There must be  an  easier  way."   Perhaps  he
followed the route in an old Beckey that suggests  following  the  ridge  on
the WEST! side all the way from Schaefer Lake. That is  the  way  Greg  went
but from the map it looks to me as if it would be an awful route.

We made note of the  fact  that  Mitch  and  Don  had  climbed  up  via  the
prominent E gully between the SE and NE Pks, and decided  that  would  be  a
more direct route down to the talus fields.  It  was  but  it  was  also  an
awful, steep, loose route with not too much  to  recommend  it.  There  were
several steps in the 1000 ft gully.  We took comfort  in  knowing  we  could
rappel if necessary (we did  pass  one  rappel  sling  left  by  a  previous
party), but we always found a scramble way down. We arrived back in camp  at
3:45 (4 miles, 2700 ft, 7:45 hrs), quickly packed up, leaving at  4:30,  and
reached the car at 7:00 (6 miles, 150 ft, 2.5 hr). A lovely trip with a  good
companion and unexpected challenging but pleasant scrambling.

Total: 17 miles and 7350 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen


