            'tr' => '

Crook Mtn (6930 ft) - Schaefer Lake Quad - September 21, 2005


With only a short day available I decided to see if I  could  approach  this
peak from the maze of logging roads on the  SE  side.  I  turned  left  onto
Meadow Cr Rd 6300 from the Chiwawa River  Rd  just  before  it  crosses  the
river, right on 6307, and left on 6306. The gate shown  at  the  next  major
intersection on the GT map is not in evidence and I  was  able  to  continue
driving another 2 miles to where the road comes very near the old Raging  Cr
Trail (elev 3400 ft). This last bit of the  road  is  quite  overgrown  with
alder scratching both sides of  the  car  but  other  than  that  is  easily
drivable.

I picked up the trail a very short ways to the left  in  woods.  This  trail
appears to be abandoned but is still  in  reasonable  shape  and  is  fairly
easily followed. It climbs steadily to 4800 ft, then drops for  no  apparent
reason to 4400 ft, crosses a creek, passes a hunter  camp,  and  wanders  up
and down a bit before a final steep climb to end on the NE spur of  Pt  5999
at elev 5400 ft. (4 miles, 2800 ft, 2.5 hrs).

From trail end I followed the spur SW to Pt 5999, and then  the  main  ridge
NW all the way to the summit of Crook Mtn.  This ridge is quite  rocky  with
many bumps and obstacles that required  minor  detours,  mostly  on  the  SW
slope  but  occasionally  on  the  NE  slope,  but  is  for  the  most  part
interesting and fun scrambling.  It took the  better  part  of  2  hours  to
traverse the ridge and climb the final open heather slopes to the top  (4800
ft, 4:50 hrs). I found a tiny film can register with many familiar names  in
the summit cairn. Most had come from Schaefer  Lake  while  climbing  others
peaks in the area: Mitch Blanton and Don Beavon on 9/14/98, Don  Goodman  on
8/8/99 (his fifth time up, on a grand traverse this time),  Janet  Putz  and
Mike Torok on 9/2/01 and Greg Koenig on  9/11/01.  The  last  entry  was  in
2004.

It was now 5:15 and I was running out of time (the days are getting  shorter
way too fast), so to speed things up I dropped into the basins SE  of  Crook
to return to the trail. I made  splendid  time  through  lovely  meadows  at
first but eventually I had to crash horrid  brush  traversing  below  cliffs
back to the spur. However, I  still  made  it  to  the  trail  in  1:20  hr.
Darkness caught me 40 minutes from the car. I worried  about  following  the
faint trail by headlamp but it was  surprisingly  easy  to  stay  on  and  I
reached the car at 8:30.

 Total: 12 miles, 5700 ft and 8:30 hrs.

Fay Pullen


