            'title' => 'Mt Index (5991 ft) - Index Quad - September 24-25, 2005',
            'tr' => '

Mt Index (5991 ft) - Index Quad - September 24-25, 2005


I had climbed Mt Index many years ago from Lake Serene and I  was  not  very
keen on a repeat ascent. However, my son, Walter, really wanted to climb  it
so I reluctantly agreed to accompany him, but  by  which  route?   None  are
really appealing. The route via Lake Serene is technical late  in  the  year
and the traverse from Persis long with many ups and  downs.  That  left  the
"direct" route from the N Fork Tolt Road. Direct, that is after  getting  to
the final logging road. With a gate preventing vehicle access,  6  miles  of
boring roads must be traveled first. Bicycles seemed the order  of  the  day
for this. So the two of us tried this route last  year  in  August  the  day
after a heavy rain. We encountered wet alder on  the  very  overgrown  final
logging road and then horrid brush, also still wet,  once  leaving  the  old
road. We ran out of time, energy and desire and turned around some  1500  ft
below the summit. I vowed never to return - well,  at  least  not  when  the
brush is wet.

This time we planned on 2 days, with a bivy at the  end  of  the  old  road.
With a perfect weather forecast the brush should be  dry.  We  started  from
the gate on the Proctor Cr Road, elev 1600  ft,  on  bicycles  at  2:00  pm.
After 2 slightly downhill miles, we turned left onto the N  Fork  Tolt  Road
steeply at first then gently uphill 3 more miles before turning left onto  a
spur where the main road descends to cross the river. Another  mile  brought
us to a junction, elev 2000 ft, where we stashed the  bikes  (6  miles,  600
ft, 1:30 hrs) and started hiking left uphill. At a junction  with  a  quarry
spur we turned left again. Last year starting at  this  point  we  ran  into
terrible thick (and wet) overgrown alder. At places you  could  barely  bull
your way through. This time the road was completely cleared. What  a  shock!
Why on earth would they have cleared the road? This lasted  past  the  first
switchback to the first small creek crossing,  maybe  a  mile,  and  had  we
known, bicycles could have been ridden this  far.   Beyond  the  creek,  the
road was ditched a dozen or so times as if to  decommission  it.   But  why?
The road was nicely returning to nature on its own  with  alders  and  brush
already having a nice start. Probably some nonsensical rule or regulation.

Beyond the ditching the road returned to the condition we knew so well  from
last year, thick overgrown  alder.   I  had  brought  clippers  and  clipped
minimally just enough to get through as we slowly  worked  our  way  up  the
road. We followed the old road some 2 more miles past  3  more  switchbacks,
with it getting rougher and rockier all the time, to its high point at  4000
ft (9 miles, 2600 ft, 4 hrs). Here we cleared two tiny bivy spots among  the
boulders. The road continued a short rough  distance  slightly  downhill  to
end at a deep ravine where we found a  tiny  trickle  of  water.  It  was  a
surprisingly pleasant camp and we  fell  asleep  watching  the  sunset  over
Puget Sound.

We started the next morning at 8:00 leaving the road almost  directly  above
our camp. We worked our way up and right through horrid steep brush  growing
over horrid old logging slash, avoiding a cliff and crossing above a  ravine
to traverse to the ridge coming S from Pt 5212 crossing at 4700  ft.  It  is
only 700 ft of elevation gain to here but this section is  really  the  crux
of the whole climb and a real trial but at least it was  dry.  The  rest  of
the route is easy and a pleasure in comparison. We dropped slightly off  the
ridge into a lovely meadow bench where we had a clear view of the route  and
the summit. We followed the bench N, grazing  on  blueberries  as  we  went,
above a ravine toward Anderson Pass until  we  could  traverse  right  below
cliffs to reach the 5500 ft notch in the W ridge of  Index.  We  crossed  to
the N and traversed steep dirt below cliffs until we  could  turn  right  up
the final easy talus and heather slopes to the summit (2150 ft, 3:45 hrs).

What a glorious place! Views in every  direction.  The  rugged  Persis-Index
ridge was very impressive from this side. Lake Serene was partially  visible
3500 feet straight  down  impossibly  steep  cliffs.  Up  close  were  Gunn,
Merchant, Baring, and off  in  the  distance  Baker,  Glacier,  Mt  Rainier,
Stuart, and on and on seemingly forever.  I  also  closely  examined  Middle
Index and wondered if I would ever be able to climb it to  finish  the  Home
Court list (it will probably be the last one left after  whittling  away  at
the others). It actually didn\'t look that bad  itself  but  getting  to  the
notch below it looked frightful. We took over an hour soaking it all  up  in
the warm sunshine.

A trip report from 1997 stated a register was on the summit,  but  we  could
not find one.  That was a disappointment, as I  really  wanted  to  see  how
often this peak is climbed. I know someone had climbed  it  recently  as  we
ran into fresh footprints, from the day before if I had to guess,  from  the
notch on. I did leave a new register of my own but I doubt I  will  ever  be
back to check it for entries.

We left the summit at 1:15 and meandered back to the meadow bench.  We  were
reluctant to leave this glorious area, seldom visited by others.  Once  over
the ridge, we plunged once again down the horrid brush.  It  was  every  bit
as bad going down as it was on the way up.  It is very easy to get  hung  up
on hidden cliffs and steep gullies. Somehow we managed to hit  the  road  at
exactly the same spot we had left it (3 miles, 2250 ft, 7:50 hr total).

We quickly packed up camp and reached our bikes in 1:45 hr and the car in  a
little over an hour more, just as it was getting dark at 7:30 (9 miles,  250
ft, 3:00 hrs total from camp). We were both elated to have  pulled  off  the
ascent of this well known but elusive peak and it was a very special Mother-
Son trip to remember for a long time to come.

Total: 21 miles and 5100 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen


