            'tr' => '

Dip Top Peak (7291 ft) and Lynch Peak (7280+ ft) - Mt Daniel Quad

October 4-5, 2005

I had originally planned to climb these two peaks from Marmot  Lake  to  the
north, but that seemed like an awfully  long  route  and  would  take  three
days. If I approached from the east, I figured I could  shorten  it  to  two
days. And with only one day forecast to  be  really  good  weather,  I  also
hoped I could climb both peaks on the first day after  setting  up  camp.  I
was a bit optimistic in that assessment.

For the second time in less than a month (see Back  Court  Finale)  I  found
myself hiking up the Deception Pass Trail at the end of the Cle  Elum  River
Road. At Deception Pass, elev 4500 ft (5 miles, 1250 ft, 2:10 hr), I went  S
on the Pacific Crest Trail about 1.5 miles, losing 600  ft  in  the  process.
Shortly before crossing the creek draining the 4900  ft  flat  basin  SE  of
Lynch, I left the trail at elev 3900 ft and headed  steeply  uphill  through
the forest. After a few hundred feet I stumbled onto an old climbers  trail.
This trail doesn\'t look as if it has been used recently, but once above  the
dense forest, it is fairly distinct and greatly facilitates  route  finding.
It essentially follows the rib to the N  of  the  deep  creek  ravine  until
above the basin, then works its way  through  cliffs  to  traverse  to  open
talus slopes below Lynch Pk. I began running into snow at about 5000 ft  and
by the time I found a campsite at Lynch Draw by Pea  Soup  Lake,  elev  6300
ft, the snow was 6-12" deep where it wasn\'t melted off (8  miles,  3900  ft,
5:30 hrs).

The rugged terrain and snow-covered talus had taken more  time  than  I  had
hoped.  By the time I set up camp and started for  my  peaks  it  was  5:00.
Yet both peaks looked so close and easy on the map, I thought I could  still
squeeze them in before dark. They were only 1000 ft above me. All I  had  to
do was get to Dip Top Gap between the peaks. Dip Top looked easy via  the  E
ridge. The W ridge of Lynch did look steeper but Beckey said it was an  easy
class 2 scramble and if that didn\'t work the S slope appeared feasible.

The first problem was getting to Dip Top Gap.  I  couldn\'t  get  around  Pea
Soup Lake on a low traverse due to cliffs that went into the water and  when
I tried a high traverse I ended up 200 ft above the gap with  cliffs  below.
It sure didn\'t look that steep on the map. The only possible  way  down  was
an exposed ramp-ledge system that diagonalled down  across  the  cliff  back
toward the lake. It was a very interesting route, made more  interesting  by
snow and wet rock, but it took time I  didn\'t  have  to  spare  and  led  to
treacherous snow-covered talus way below the gap that took  even  more  time
to climb back up.

The second problem was that Dip Top is not an  easy  walkup  from  the  gap.
Cliffs and slabs forced a circuitous route on  the  SE  side  to  the  final
narrow exposed summit ridge.  By the time I summited it  was  6:40  and  the
light was fading fast (1400 ft, 1:40 hr). I quickly added a register to  the
summit cairn and headed down to escape the increasing cold wind.

The third problem was that the W ridge of Lynch was not  class  2  from  the
gap.  It didn\'t even look class 3. In fact it didn\'t look climbable  without
a rope under the current conditions. But that was really  a  moot  point  as
there was no way I could still climb Lynch this  day.   I  had  run  out  of
time.  I would have my problems just getting back to camp in the  dark.  The
snow was good for one thing though - I could follow my  footprints  much  of
the way, which was most helpful in staying on track. I was not able to  find
any shortcut through the cliffs lower down by the light of my  headlamp,  so
I was forced to climb back up the  ramp-ledge  system.  I\'m  not  even  sure
there was a better way. The cliffs on that side  are  extensive.  I  dragged
into camp at 8:20 (2 miles, 1850 ft, 3:20 hr). So much for a simple  ascent.
 I just hoped the weather would hold so I could climb Lynch in the morning.

A strong wind roared all night threatening to blow my tent and me  into  the
next county and light snow fell but the next morning dawned with  reasonable
conditions. It was cloudy and still snowing lightly off and on but the  wind
died down a bit. I set out for Lynch at 8:15. Using my  tracks  of  the  day
before until below the S slopes I then climbed rapidly  up  easy  slopes  to
the summit (.5 mile, 1000 ft, :50 hr). I left another register and was  back
to camp by 9:45. This ascent was as easy as I had hoped.

I left at 10:30 taking my time going down so as  not  to  lose  the  way.  I
still lost it in the forest some 500 ft above the PCT and  got  too  far  to
the N. Here I was suckered in to continuing to the next drainage N  where  I
could see an inviting meadow. The meadow was nice,  while  it  lasted,  then
funneled into a waterfall creek ravine that  I  avoided  by  crashing  awful
steep brush to the side until I  was  spit  out  onto  the  PCT.  I  do  not
recommend this route. A half mile before the PCT reached  Deception  Pass  I
took a XC shortcut to hit  the  Deception  Pass  Trail  at  the  Robin  Lake
turnoff. This saved me about a mile of circuitous trail  hiking.  I  reached
the car at 4:00 (8 miles, 750 ft, 5:30) after a short stop for lunch. I  had
a few sprinkles on the way out but nothing serious.

Total: 19 miles and 7500 ft in 2 days.

Fay Pullen


