            'tr' => '
Mt David (7420 ft - 2420P) and Mt Jonathan (7195 ft - 275P) - Mt David and
Poe Mtn Quads - October 14, 2005

I wanted a good workout but only had the day available as I drove back  from
a family get together in Chelan. The Mt David trail seemed to fit the  bill.
I started from the end of the White River Road past Lake  Wenatchee  on  the
Indian Cr Trail, elev 2300 ft. Directly after crossing the bridge  over  the
White River, I turned left downstream a long mile,  annoyingly  losing  some
200 ft, until I came to the Mt David Trail.  This  good  trail  now  climbed
steadily to first gain the ridge at 5300 ft and then wander along the  ridge
or on one side or the  other  through  lovely  alpine  terrain  to  the  old
lookout site on the summit (8 miles, 5600 ft, 4:10 hrs).

I had hoped to add Mt Jonathan to the agenda but wasn\'t sure  how  difficult
the traverse was from David or if  I  had  enough  time  to  find  the  way.
Although there was some fog, I had glimpses of views and even the  sun  when
the fog thinned momentarily and the weather seemed to be holding. I had  run
into a few inches of snow on the trail on the NE exposure above 7000 ft  and
there was more on the NW side, but the southern slopes were completely  snow
free. So I decided to give it a try.

I retreated a short ways down the trail until I could traverse  W  and  then
descend to about 6800 ft on easy SW slopes. I  decided  to  stay  below  the
ridge (it looked worse than it was), planning to drop further  to  easy  alp
slopes and bypass a buttress completely but  found  myself  trapped  at  mid
level on cliffs and slabs  with  no  way  down.  Fortunately,  a  continuous
interesting but exposed ledge led all the way across the problem area on  an
upward traverse until I could gain the ridge  again.  I  then  followed  the
crest of the ridge with pleasant scrambling all the way to the point  marked
7195 ft on the map.  Unfortunately,  this  is  not  the  high  point  and  I
glimpsed a higher summit .1 mile farther W peaking out of the fog. For  this
last bit, I descended slightly to avoid the  jumbled  ridge  and  approached
the final top from the S.  Sure enough here I  found  a  cairn  to  which  I
added one of my registers (500 ft, 1:10 hrs from David).

I stayed high on the way back to Mt David, avoiding  the  ledge  across  the
cliff.  This was an easier way to go. I hit the  trail  at  5:30  (1.5  mile,
1000 ft, 2:15 hrs RT from David). Darkness caught me  about  1.5  hours  from
the TH and I came out the rest of the way by headlamp reaching  the  car  at
8:30.

Total: 17.5 miles, 7000 ft and 9:45 hrs.

Fay Pullen
