            'tr' => '

Ares Pk (Venus-Spade) - 6596 ft - Mt Daniel Quad - October 26-28, 2005


With a good weather forecast for Wednesday and  Thursday  (but  rain  and  a
4500 ft snow level for Thursday night and Friday) and  much  of  the  recent
snow melted off, I felt I had a good shot at this Home Court  Peak  near  Mt
Daniel. I would need a full day to hike the 13.5 miles to Spade  Lake  where
I intended to camp.

Beginning at the spacious multiple trailhead near Salmon La Sac  (elev  2500
ft), I hiked the Waptus River Trail  with  its  numerous  annoying  ups  and
downs a long 9.5 miles to the Spade Lake Trail Junction. The  net  elevation
gain up to this point was a scant 500 ft (gross gain was 3 times that),  but
the Spade Lake Trail quickly made up for this gaining 1500  ft  straight  up
the hillside before beginning a long traverse punctuated  by  several  steep
descents followed by even more steep ascents and gaining  another  1500  ft.
Views of snowy Summit Chief and Bears Breast appeared in  openings  on  this
mostly sunny day. By the time I reached the basin of  Spade  Lake  dusk  was
falling. I spent another 45 minutes wandering around  in  the  dark  looking
for a decent campsite at the S end of the lake. This area  is  riddled  with
deep slots between steep slabs and what isn\'t rocky is filled with ponds  or
marshy ground. Campsites were few and far between. I finally  found  a  rare
level spot on bare ground a hundred feet or so above  the  lake,  elev  5350
ft, and set up my tent by headlamp (13.5 miles, 4500 ft, 8 hrs).

In these last days of Daylight Savings Time, dawn comes late. It was  barely
light at 7:30 am, so I didn\'t get going until 8:30 the next morning.  But  I
was in no hurry.  After all I had all day to get up and down my peak and  it
wasn\'t that far away.  I even entertained thoughts of  beating  the  weather
and going out the same day if I got back to camp early enough. Little did  I
know I would need most of the day just for the climb! But  than  I  seem  to
have a talent for making a peak more difficult and taking more time than  is
usual.

I began by taking the way trail around the E side of the  lake  and  heading
for the waterfall stream flowing from Venus Lake at the N end. There  was  a
heavy frost during the night and  I  crunched  along  on  frozen  ground.  I
climbed the gorgeous white slabs to the  right  of  the  waterfall,  a  most
enjoyable scramble but carefully avoiding icy sections,  emerging  into  the
rather barren basin of Venus Lake, 450 ft above Spade Lk. My intended  route
up the E slopes of Ares looked much more intimidating than I  had  expected,
with downsloping slabs and  rock  cliffs.  The  face  was  quite  broken  up
though, and under warm summer conditions would be a pleasant  scramble,  but
covered with patches of snow and ice, I was challenged to  pick  my  way  up
safely. I ended up on the N ridge separated from the summit by a  small  but
impassible notch. I had to pass it by descending on the  slippery  snowy  NW
side. Then I dropped one of my poles and had  to  descend  even  farther  to
retrieve it, but hey I was lucky it didn\'t keep  falling  hundreds  of  feet
into the headwaters of Shovel Lake never to be seen again.

I topped out on Ares flat summit at 11:00  (1600  ft,  2:30  hrs),  where  I
located one of the cutest summit registers I have come across,  a  tiny  Oil
of Olay bottle complete with the tiniest of pencils (1  inch  long).  Inside
was a John Roper business card folded 4 times to  fit.  He  had  climbed  on
7/13/97 in a party of five. There were only 2 other  entries,  Mike  Collins
and Don Beavon on 7/3/03 and John Morrow, wilderness ranger, on 7/10/05.  As
there was very little room for more names, I added a  register  of  mine  to
the summit cairn.

I am sure the views would have been gorgeous if  I  could  have  seen  them.
Unfortunately the high peaks were all in the  fog,  where  they  stayed  all
day.  I never even caught a glimpse of Mt Daniel. The weather  was  actually
not as good as I had hoped this day, and in  fact  looked  as  if  it  could
start precipitating at any moment. And I was getting a little worried as  to
how to get off my peak.  I had no rope (Why do I always talk myself  out  of
the added weight of bringing a rope - you would think I would know  better!)
and didn\'t want to descend the slippery slabs I had come up, and so  decided
to go down the S side, thinking that would be less icy. Not a  good  choice.
In this case the evil that I knew (the E side) was better than  the  evil  I
did not know (the S side).

The descent started well, with easy ramps and scree leading past cliffs.  At
one point I had to backtrack to avoid a wet slab but I quickly found  a  way
past it. Then I was funneled into an  ugly  wet  gully.  I  bypassed  it  by
lowering myself on brush "rappels" to a ledge that  skirted  the  top  of  a
final cliff. I could see I only had 20 feet or so to  go  to  easy  terrain,
but I couldn\'t find a safe way down. A broken area looked doable but it  was
not only wet but also coated in ice. I resigned myself to climbing back  up.
 My poles were really in the way, so I tossed them over the cliff,  planning
to retrieve them once down. I muscled my way  back  up  the  brush  "rappel"
until I could cross the ugly gully to the W, where  I  found  another  cliff
that was covered with brush (that I could  hang  onto)  all  the  way  down.
Sometimes brush is useful.

I traversed back to below my problem cliff looking  for  my  poles,  and  of
course I couldn\'t find them. I must have spent a  good  45  minutes  looking
for them and being very confused and puzzled before I realized I  was  below
a lower cliff band. From above it had appeared a continuous  slope  all  the
way down. It fact there was a shelf between  two  cliff  bands.  Fortunately
the lower cliffs were easily climbed and when I climbed  up  to  the  shelf,
there were my poles.

Not yet done with bad decisions, I returned to camp by going  around  the  W
side of Spade Lake.  No trail along this side should have been  a  clue.   I
ran into brush and one cliff that went right into the  water  that  required
an unpleasant detour. But the S end of the lake was delightful  with  lovely
striated slabs,  picturesque  slots,  numerous  ponds  and  tarns  and  tiny
meadows that made up for my trials. I am embarrassed to say when I got  back
to camp, but it was much too late to think about heading out (4 miles,  2400
ft, 6:40 hrs).

I spent what was left of the day  enjoying  my  beautiful  surroundings  and
fixing in my mind the route out of the basin so I could find  my  way  after
the snowfall, which I was sure was on its way.  Sure  enough,  it  began  to
snow about 8:00  pm  and  snowed  all  night.  By  morning  4-5  inches  had
accumulated transforming all to a fresh winter white. The snow  stayed  with
me to 4000 ft where it was melting  rapidly  and  dripping  off  the  trees.
Scattered showers followed me the rest of the way out (13.5 miles, 1300  ft,
7:20 hrs).

Total: 30 miles and 8400 ft in 3 days.       Fay Pullen


