            'title' => 'Galleon Mtn (5283 ft) and Sorcery Mtn (5273 ft) - Snoqualmie Lk Quad - November 2-3, 2005',
            'tr' => '
Galleon Mtn (5283 ft) and Sorcery Mtn (5273 ft) - Snoqualmie Lk Quad -
November 2-3, 2005

With shorter days and lowering snow level, I am lowering  my  ambitions  and
staying closer to home.  But the  summits  don\'t  seem  to  be  getting  any
easier to attain. I had to work very  hard  to  get  these  two  Home  Court
peaks. Well, Sorcery wasn\'t that bad but Galleon was a real effort.

The weather was better than I expected when I started  up  the  Dingford  Cr
Trail off the Middle Fork Snoqualmie River Road, elev  1400  ft.  It  wasn\'t
raining and the sun even made a brief appearance.  After  about  2  miles  I
found the way trail to Horseshoe Lake between the braids of  Goat  Cr,  elev
2600 ft. I would have stayed dry the whole way, but  after  500  ft  gain  I
began running into melting snow on trees and brush. This was as  bad  as  or
worse than rain. I reached Horseshoe Lk at 12:00 where I had hoped  to  camp
at the outlet but it was all big boulders and brush. I finally found a  tent
site at the base of the W ridge of Sorcery that took me  another  half  hour
to get to due to the difficulty of getting around the lake  (3  miles,  2600
ft, 3:00 hrs).

I quickly set up camp and headed for Sorcery at 1:15. I climbed steadily  up
the steep wooded W ridge working around  interesting  rock  formations.  The
snow deepened at I got higher, becoming knee deep in open areas.  I  carried
snowshoes, but they were of little use in the varying terrain  and  changing
snow depth. So I just postholed through the  deeper  areas.  The  worse  was
after reaching the false summit. It took almost 30 minutes to  make  my  way
from there to the summit on snowcovered boulders (.75 miles, 1400  ft,  1:50
hr).

I spent another 30 minutes looking for a cairn under the  snow  but  had  no
success.  I could not find one on the summit slab. I had fleeting  views  of
Big Snow Mtn to the E, but for the most  part  clouds  obscured  everything.
It was reassuring, however, to see the snowpack was  building  nicely  after
the parched summer. I was back to my tent in hour, quite damp from  slogging
through  and  under  wet  snow.  I  changed  to  dry  clothes  and  spent  a
comfortable night.

It began to snow lightly as I prepared to leave for  Galleon  Mtn  the  next
morning at 7:30. Galleon was not that far away as the crow flys - less  than
a mile - but first I had to get around the lake. Mountain  Lakes  can  be  a
real impediment to travel and this  one  was  no  exception.  Up  and  down,
bypassing cliffs, crashing brush, crossing gullies and creeks, it seemed  to
take forever and made me seriously consider if I really wanted to  continue.
At least the cold night hardened the snow so it was no  longer  so  wet  and
slushy.

From the NW end of the lake,  I  headed  for  the  tiny  pond  basin  SE  of
Galleon. Here 2 feet of unconsolidated snow covering a talus slope  made  it
worth lugging snowshoes along; they kept me from  sinking  into  treacherous
holes between the rocks. I stashed the snowshoes where the  slope  steepened
just below the notch in Galleon\'s NE ridge. It was now snowing heavily  with
a strong wind as I made my way to the notch. I only had 300 ft  more  to  go
but it took me over an hour to battle my way this last bit to the  top.  The
ridge was rocky, the snow deep and the wind gusts blew  snow  into  my  face
and covered my glasses so I couldn\'t see.  I  am  almost  blind  without  my
glasses (20/400) but this is one time I could see better with them off  than
on. I mostly stayed on the N side of the ridge where the wind was less,  but
the snow deeper, and literally excavated a trench thigh deep.  Twice  I  was
forced onto the S side where I could barely keep my eyes open  in  the  face
of the pelting snow and I was afraid my eyelashes would freeze together.  At
a rock step I had to remove snow to find solid footholds and  several  times
I wallowed through snow-laden trees using the  branches  as  handholds.  One
might wonder why I continued in the face of such difficulties. (1)  I  found
it a challenge to see if I could force my way upward in such conditions  and
was even enjoying myself in a perverse sort of way (2) I was  not  cold  and
did not feel overextended and (3) I am stubborn and don\'t like to give up.

In any event, I did make it to the summit at 11:45 (1850 ft,  4:15  hrs).  I
immediately turned around and started down. For the most part I was able  to
follow my trench down, but in the windy areas it was already obliterated.  I
also got off track once because without  my  glasses  I  can\'t  clearly  see
farther than my feet. I did two rappels off trees  (yes,  this  time  I  did
bring a rope) at steep sections rather than risk a snowy  slide.  Below  the
notch I had  trouble  locating  my  snowshoes,  as  my  uphill  tracks  were
completely gone, but did eventually find them and gratefully  used  them  to
the lip of the pond basin. I followed the pond outlet creek all the  way  to
the lake. From here it looked much shorter to continue  counterclockwise  to
camp than to return clockwise the way I  had  come.   The  problem  was  you
couldn\'t go that way due to impassible cliffs,  so  after  wasting  an  hour
finding that out I ended up going back clockwise anyway.

I dragged into camp at the incredible hour of 3:45 (2 miles, 2350  ft,  8:15
hrs.). I couldn\'t believe it had taken so  long.  My  tent  was  practically
buried in snow, I had to pack up  the  whole  sodden  mess,  I  had  no  dry
clothes left (although I still wasn\'t cold as long as  I  kept  moving)  and
there was a little over 1 hour of daylight left. I  jammed  everything  into
my pack, which felt as if it had gained at least 10 pounds in water  weight.
 I could barely lift the thing. I must admit I wasn\'t having a whole lot  of
fun at that point.

I managed to get down to the Dingford Cr Trail,  where  there  was  still  a
dusting of snow, before dark and staggered  out  the  rest  of  the  way  by
headlamp. A trip like this really makes you appreciate a warm shower  and  a
dry heated house.  In fact just my car looked pretty good to me  waiting  at
the end of the trail (3 miles, 50 ft, 2:15 hrs)

Total: 9.5 miles and 6400 ft in 2 days.

Fay Pullen






