            'title' => 'North Mtn (3840+ ft - 2200P - Darrington Quad) - November 21, 2005 
 Haystack Mtn (2715 ft - 500P - Goldbar Quad) - November 17, 2005 
 Peak 2740+ (500P - Goldbar Quad) - November 19, 2005',
            'tr' => '

North Mtn (3840+ ft - 2200P - Darrington Quad) - November 21, 2005


I would really rather be skiing this time of year, backcountry  skiing  that
is, but only if the conditions are good. Since they  aren\'t  at  the  moment
what\'s a body to do? I have been known to snowshoe at  times,  but  only  if
desperate and only if I can\'t get to where I  want  to  go  any  other  way.
Instead I turn to mountain biking and search for summits I can cycle  up.  I
like the change of pace, the fact I don\'t have to wear a pack and of  course
the fast downhill run.

I am running out of low elevation 2000 Prominence peaks, but with  the  high
freezing level and warm sunny weather of the past week  I  thought  I  might
still be able to make it much of the way up this peak  before  running  into
snow. Most of the drive to Darrington was in the fog, but once in  town  all
was clear blue sunny sky. In keeping with my personal  standard  of  gaining
at least 2000 ft by bike in order for a 2000P peak to count (no  driving  to
the top), I parked just after turning off Hywy 530 (elev 500 ft), and  began
cycling up Road 28. It began as a narrow paved road, crossed  a  power  line
and entered woods before climbing a short steep hill. At  2.65  miles,  elev
1045, the pavement ended as I went right at a junction. Another steep  climb
and then the road gentled to climb the rest of  the  way  at  a  steady  but
bikeable rate. The warm sun and  the  views  of  the  snowy  north  face  of
Whitehorse and the multiple summits of Higgins made for  pleasant  pedaling.
Somewhere around 3000 feet I began running into mud and snow,  but  previous
vehicle traffic provided tracks to follow. At the 6th switchback, elev  3350
ft, all tracks stopped and any further progress by bike  was  impossible  in
the deep slushy snow and I stashed my bike (11.7 miles, 2850 ft, 3:40 hr).

Proceeding on foot, I began on an old spur road  off  the  switchback,  then
decided to head directly for the summit following my GPS, as the  road  took
me out of my way. The summit was little more than half a  mile  and  600  ft
gain away, but I was floundering through knee-deep slush and at the  rate  I
was going it could take the better part of a hour to get there.  I  followed
the S ridge to the summit area and encountered one of the  most  fascinating
geological features I have come across  on  a  low  forested  mountain.  The
entire area was riddled with many deep 10 to 15 foot clefts in the  bedrock.
Fascinating, but also a real impediment to travel as I made my  way  up  and
down and in and out of the holes casting around for  the  high  point.   The
slushy snow and numerous downed trees didn\'t help either. I finally  settled
on a summit (3315 ft, 4:40 hr) from which point I could look across  to  the
tower that graces the end of the main road.

By the time I made my circuitous floundering way back to my  bike,  darkness
was falling. I changed to dry socks (bike  shoes  are  not  very  waterproof
even with booties on) and bundled up for the  ride  down.  After  taking  it
easy on the first snowy and muddy section, I let her rip and zipped back  to
my car by the generous light of my  Nite  Rider  in  1:20  hr.  Total:  23.5
miles, 3315 ft and 7 hrs.

Following are two lesser summits I did earlier. One a bike ride  and  one  a
brush bash.


Haystack Mtn (2715 ft - 500P - Goldbar Quad) - November 17, 2005


For this bike ride I started from the intersection of Road 62 and  the  road
going up Haystack (Rd 6221), elev 1600 ft, turned right at the  junction  at
saddle in a recent clearcut and followed the deteriorating lumpy  and  bumpy
but gentle road as it made its way  completely  around  the  mountain  to  a
deadend on the W side, elev 2550. A  ten  minute  climb  on  foot  up  rocky
terrain led to the surprisingly pleasant open summit slab. A nice place  for
lunch in the sun with a good view of Mt Persis. Total: 7.2  miles,  1500  ft
and 3 hrs.

With time left in the day after I got back to the car, I  decided  to  check
out Pk 2740, a short ways farther on Road 62.  Rather than load  and  unload
the bike again, I cycled the 1.5 miles to the gate. After another 1.5  miles
I turned right and wandered around  logging  roads  looking  for  a  way  to
approach this peak from the S. I had fun biking, but I had no  luck  getting
close enough to the peak to easily climb it in bike togs.  I  was,  however,
very impressed with the appearance of this peak. For such a minor  low  peak
it is very steep on all sides and from the S is a rocky  forested  fin.   It
deserves to have a proper name. Additional stats: 11.3 miles, 765  ft,  2:20
hrs.


Peak 2740+ (500P - Goldbar Quad) - November 19, 2005


Miffed that I didn\'t make it up this peak, I was back two  days  later  with
my son Walter. It was his 34th birthday and he wanted a short easy  but  new
climb. I suggested this. He didn\'t know what he was getting  into.   Neither
did I for that matter. We parked at the gate on Road 62, elev 1600  ft.  The
peak is directly W of the gate less than Â½ mile away.  It  looked  so  close
and so easy. Surely we\'d be up and down in a couple of hours. Well, it  took
almost 1.5 hours just to force our way through gosh  awful  brush,  stickery
vines and rotten logging slash with treacherous footing to the saddle  N  of
the peak. Then it took another hour to follow  the  steep  narrow  wooded  N
ridge to the top.  This ridge was mostly just steep dirt  and  moss  with  a
few vegetated cliffy steps but obstacles were everywhere and progress  slow.
I kept expecting Walter to complain, but he seemed to be  enjoying  himself.
Takes after his mother I guess.

There were no signs of previous travel. Surely no one else was crazy  enough
to climb this thing. Well, guess what we found on top? A film can  register.
The contents were mostly illegible, but I could  tell  there  was  only  one
entry made by Ian McKay and Dougal (I think) somebody. I  think  it  was  in
2001 and I think he claimed a first ascent, but I am not sure. He called  it
"Knob 2740".  Walter and I christened it "Birthday Knob" to commemorate  the
occasion if not the appearance of the peak. I do not recommend climbing  the
way we did, but it is still an impressive looking "knob", at  least  from  a
distance. Maybe it would be a better climb up  the  rocky  S  ridge.  Total:
Maybe 1.5 mile, 1290 ft and 5.5 hrs.

Fay Pullen


