Jeff Pk (6217 ft - 537P - Noble Knob Quad) - December 1, 2005


Corral Pass is one of my favorite places to ski tour. Last  year  there  was
never enough snow in the area, so it  has  been  two  years  since  I  skied
there. I usually play around the basin below Castle Mtn or wander the  ridge
toward Mutton Mtn. With my new interest  in  checking  out  all  peaks  with
greater than 400 ft of prominence on Jeff  Howbert\'s  Master  Quad  List,  I
discovered this peak I hadn\'t climbed yet. (John,  does  this  peak  have  a
name?) A new peak that could be climbed on skis!  What could be better?

Despite recent lowland snow, Highway 410  was  clear  all  the  way  to  the
Corral Pass Road. Getting up this road, though,  through  8  inches  of  new
snow to the parking area at the gate (elev 3000 ft) required low range  four
wheel drive and was close to limit of what my Jeep  could  make  it  through
without chains. A snowmobile had been up the road the day before.   Perfect.
 I would have little trail to break.  Nor would I have to put  up  with  the
noise or smell of the infernal machines.

On the lower road there was no base under the new snow and I could feel  the
gravel underneath at times, especially where the snowmobile had  churned  it
up.  I would have to watch it on the downhill run to spare my  ski  bottoms.
Somewhere  around  5000  ft  the  snow  deepened  quickly  and  wind  drifts
increased trailbreaking. Even so I made it to Corral  Pass,  elev  5650,  in
good time (6 miles, 2700 ft, 2:55  hrs).  It  was  19  degrees  and  snowing
lightly, as it continued to do all day.

At the pass I left the snowmobile tracks  and  immediately  bogged  down  in
deep snow. Progress was slow and I began to wonder if I  would  run  out  of
daylight. I was able to follow the trail to Pt 5935,  then  went  along  the
ridge over Pt 6135 down to the saddle and up to Pk  6217.  The  terrain  was
lovely and ski friendly, just slow breaking trail. It took 2.5 hours  to  ski
the additional 2 miles and 1000 ft of elevation gain from Corral Pass.

The nice thing about skiing is the fast easy downhill run. It wouldn\'t  take
nearly as long to get out.  But first I had to climb the 200 ft back  up  to
Pt 6135.  I had taken my skins off at  the  summit  for  the  glide  through
gentle open woods to the saddle and elected not to take the time and  effort
to put them on again. My waxless base did not climb well in  the  cold  snow
and my downhill tracks were too steep to follow. But once up Pt 6135 it  was
all downhill.  Even so I did the last  bit  of  the  road  by  headlight,  a
surreal experience with dazzling dancing snowflakes distracting me.

I made  it  home  before  the  next  round  of  lowland  snow  made  driving
hazardous.

Total: 16 miles, 3900 ft and 8 hours.

Fay Pullen

