            'title' => 'Lost Ranger Pk (6176 ft - 456P - Noble Knob Quad) - December 7, 2005',
            'tr' => '

Lost Ranger Pk (6176 ft - 456P - Noble Knob Quad) - December 7, 2005


I had so much fun skiing in the Corral Pass area last week that  I  returned
to ski up this peak, another new one for  me  that  I  had  previously  been
unaware of. I again started at the gate on the Corral Pass Road  (elev  3000
ft), but this time for variety I chose to ski up the  Deep  Cr  Trail.  This
saved me from repeating 6 miles of road skiing  and  got  me  closer  to  my
objective, but I doubt it saved much time or, particularly, energy.

A connector trail goes downhill from the gate for Â½ mile to cross  Deep  Cr,
joins the main trail on the other side and then climbs  4  miles,  sometimes
steeply, to the Noble Knob Trail below the S ridge of Lost Ranger Pk.  There
was barely enough snow cover in the dense woods to allow  skiing  at  first.
My skins protected ski bottoms from numerous protruding rocks.  Skiing  down
this trail would not be an option.

At the Noble Knob Trail junction (elev 5860 ft) the sign was still  visible,
but I was not able to follow this trail here in the now 2-3  foot  snowpack.
No matter, the terrain was open and I just headed uphill  toward  the  crest
of the ridge. The snow had consolidated considerably  since  last  week  and
trailbreaking was not a problem. I was surprised  to  come  across  a  rocky
section of ridge and traversed just below this interesting  cliffy  area  on
the W slope until I could easily gain the saddle just to SE of  the  summit.
From here it was a short gentle climb to the wooded top  (5.5  miles,  3500
ft, 4 hrs).

With time left in the day, I returned to the saddle SE  of  the  summit  and
decided to ski into the basin to the E. What a delightful run! The snow  was
perfect and untracked, the
turns effortless and had I not known I would have to climb back up  again  I
would have been tempted to continue on down toward Lost Lake. As  it  was  I
stopped at about 5600 ft and  then  contoured  and  climbed  through  lovely
benches to the Mutton-Lost Ranger saddle.  Since I had  taken  the  time  to
put skins on again, from here I just continued to the summit of  Mutton  Mtn
(6156 ft) where the views  were  much  better  than  from  Lost  Ranger.  Mt
Rainier was particularly spectacular silhouetted by the low  winter  sun.  I
could also see Jeff Mtn  where  I  was  last  week,  but  it  did  not  look
particularly impressive from this angle, as it was lost  behind  intervening
ridges.

I had another good run off Mutton to the Noble Knob  Trail  below,  which  I
followed to Corral Pass. The road was now packed solid from  the  snowmobile
traffic of the previous  weekend,  but  there  was  still  enough  untracked
shoulder to make for a pleasant schuss back to the car to close my loop.

Total: 14 miles, 4150 ft and 7:40 hrs.

Fay Pullen


