            'title' => 'Rampart Ridge SE Pk (5606 ft - 446P - Chikamin Pk Quad) - December 15, 2005',
            'tr' => '

Rampart Ridge SE Pk (5606 ft - 446P - Chikamin Pk Quad) - December 15, 2005


My original plan was to explore the logging roads up Mine and Hall Crs W  of
McClellan Butte on skis. However, I made it less than  a  mile  up  Rd  9020
(off I-90, Exit 38) when I lost traction with my Jeep  and  began  to  slide
backwards down the icy road (It didn\'t seem that slippery until I lost  it).
Believe me it was a helpless feeling  putting  my  foot  on  the  brake  and
having zero result.  S-C-A-R-Y!  I  had  my  hands  full  steering  the  car
backwards and keeping it on the road as I gained momentum, and I was sure  I
was going to end up going over the  side.  Miraculously,  somehow  my  slide
stopped. At that point, sobered and having learned my  lesson,  I  installed
chains, turned around and retreated.

Hoping to still salvage the day, I turned to my backup plan (to  climb  this
peak next to Mt Margaret) and  drove  on  to  Snoqualmie  Pass  and  the  Mt
Margaret Rd (elev 2500 ft). It was 15 degrees.  The road was  well  traveled
by snowmobiles, which broke  up  the  ice  layer  and  made  for  reasonable
skiing. At the 4th switchback, I headed N on the spur  that  goes  up  Rocky
Run. At the switchback at 3800 ft I continued straight along Rocky  Run  and
soon stashed my skis and switched to  snowshoes  (4  miles,  1650  ft,  2:30
hrs). Snow conditions and steep terrain were no longer conducive to skiing.

I crossed the outlet creek of Twin Lakes, turned right uphill and worked  my
way more to the right past cliffs.  Snow varied from crust to ice to  powder
depending upon exposure to the sun. At about 5000 ft I hit a steep icy  open
slope and reverted to boots and ice axe. Above this,  easy  slopes  led  the
final 400 feet  to  the  gentle  summit  (3400  ft,  4:40  hr).  Views  were
expansive of mountaintops, but valley fog was beginning to  form  again.  It
was 16 degrees on top with a chilly breeze and my water  bottle  was  frozen
slush.

Despite a late start made even later by my earlier misadventure, I  made  it
back to the car without needing a headlamp, but only because  the  ski  down
the wide smooth road was more  pleasant  than  expected  and  the  last  bit
paralleling I-90 was illuminated by the headlights of the traffic.

Total: 10 miles, 3500 ft and 7 hrs.

Fay Pullen




