            'title' => 'Peak 4973 (453P - Sun Top Quad) - December 20, 2005',
            'tr' => '

Peak 4973 (453P - Sun Top Quad) - December 20, 2005


I was in a quandary as to where to go  this  day.  Ice  storm  warnings  for
freezing  rain  ruled  out  all  the  passes  and  western  approaches.  Icy
conditions ruled out driving all back roads (I learned my lesson  last  week
after a long backward slide). That didn\'t leave a whole lot  of  choices.  I
ended up driving along 410 to Forest Road 72 and climbing this peak where  I
could start right from the highway (elev 2100 ft). The road  was  now  gated
for winter elk protection but not before traffic had turned  anywhere  tires
had gone into icy tracks.  In fact just turning around and  parking  I  slid
and slipped. But any untracked snow was soft and slushy. I  stubbornly  held
onto the unreasonable notion that I could still turn this into  a  ski  trip
despite much evidence to the contrary. I even had snowshoes in  the  car.  I
guess snowshoeing up roads is foreign to  my  nature.  In  retrospect,  just
walking would have been the best idea.

Skins worked very well on the icy track and I glided happily along in  light
mist. At the first switchback at 2800 ft I went straight  on  a  spur  road,
which was ditched and abandoned in less than a mile. After turning a  corner
into the Minnehaha Cr drainage onto a S exposure,  what  little  snow  there
was quickly vanished. By the time I came to a switchback (elev  3500)  at  a
major side creek, I was carrying  my  skis.  Here  the  "road"  deteriorated
completely and following it was no longer helpful. So I just  headed  uphill
on unpleasant loose scree, slippery steep muddy  dirt  and  ancient  logging
slash. Being shod in square-toed ski boots didn\'t help.  More  serious  rain
added to the fun. Oh the joys of winter climbing in  the  Pacific  Northwest
where temperatures,  freezing  levels  and  quantity  and  quality  of  snow
fluctuate all over the map. Nevertheless, the trek up was quite  interesting
as I worked my way past pinnacles and through cliff bands. At the top  of  a
gully (elev 4400 ft) I reached a spur ridge, crossed to the  N  side  and  a
gentler slope and wallowed in knee-deep slush the rest of  the  way  to  the
summit (4 miles, 2900 ft, 4:30 hrs). Many downed logs made skis unusable.

Not wanting to descend the way I had come up on the treacherous terrain  and
determined to still get in some skiing (why  else  carry  my  skis  up?),  I
dropped off the summit to the N (actually I had  to  go  S  first  to  avoid
cliffs, then N) to pick up a series of abandoned roads that  climbed  to  FR
72 high on Dalles Ridge. Once on FR 72 the skiing  was  reasonably  pleasant
(relative to what had gone before - all things are relative),  as  I  glided
along in the slow slush of old snowmobile tracks. But it was a very  long  7
Â½ miles back to the car. Once I hit old tire tracks (about  halfway),  slush
turned to ice and speed increased, but it was surprisingly not  bad  skiing.
Except for those few places melted out to  gravel  where  I  was  forced  to
remove skis, I was able to ski most of the way down.

Total: 13 miles, 3400 ft, 8:30 hrs.

Fay Pullen




