            'title' => 'Sawmill Ridge (5207 ft - 1047P - Lester Quad) - December 29, 2005',
            'tr' => '

Sawmill Ridge (5207 ft - 1047P - Lester Quad) - December 29, 2005


Coming off a week\'s illness I wanted something close,  short  and  not  very
difficult.  I have skied in the Greenwater area  for  years  and  yet  never
made it up to the high point of Sawmill Ridge, so this peak  seemed  to  fit
the bill. The trip actually turned out to be longer than  anticipated  as  I
had hoped to be able to drive farther than I was able (or  willing)  up  the
approach road, but it really didn\'t matter as I  also  felt  better  than  I
thought I would.

New snow overnight coated Road 70 with  several  inches  of  slippery  stuff
right from Highway 410 and made me nervous about going farther  up  Whistler
Cr on Road 7030 than about .3 mile (elev 2400 ft). I was surprised the  snow
level was so low here as this area is frequently in a micro banana belt.  It
did, however, take until the switchback at 3100 ft for the depth  to  become
reasonably consistent. By the time I reached  the  4200  ft  saddle  between
Whistler and Twin Camp Crs, I was breaking trail in a foot of almost  powder
snow (4 miles, 1800 ft, 1:50 hrs).

I turned left off the main  road  at  the  saddle  and  right  at  the  next
junction to follow the spur road that meanders up and  down  another  couple
of miles along Sawmill Ridge until I was at the 4700 ft  saddle  SW  of  the
high point. Here I left the road and climbed on the lee slope (to escape  an
increasing wind) to the left of the corniced ridge. This little peak  turned
into a pleasant surprise with a much more alpine summit than expected  (3200
ft, 4:15 hrs).

I managed a few turns down to the road, then climbed up Pt  5022  to  the  W
just so I could get in some more. A  pleasant  run  down  in  my  track  was
brought to a screeching halt after about Â½ mile on  the  main  road  when  I
came upon fresh tire tracks made by 4X4\'s at play. Darn!  I  guess  I  can\'t
really condemn them, after all it is a road and meant for vehicles  and  not
skis (even I would have driven farther if I had had more  guts).  Only  deep
snow or a gate keeps them out. I still had a good run on the shoulder  until
the melting snow lower down got so thin  (very  near  my  car)  that  I  was
forced to walk.

Total: 13 miles, 3650 ft and 6:45 hrs

Fay Pullen
