            'tr' => '

Enumclaw Mtn (2780+ ft - 420P - Cumberland Quad) - January 8, 2006


I have decided that biking up logging roads to a low and close-in summit  is
a good way to spend a Sunday afternoon  this  time  of  year.  There  is  no
logging traffic and I can begin at a  very  civilized  hour.  So  when  this
Sunday dawned with a break in the rain it was off to  give  Enumclaw  Mtn  a
try.  I get a great deal of pleasure out of  figuring  out  how  to  get  up
these minor 400+ ft prominence peaks listed on Jeff  Howbert\'s  Master  Quad
list with no prior information.  Just study the map, pick a route  and  hope
it will work out.  In the case of logging roads it is  a  matter  of  hoping
the roads shown on the maps are still bikeable  and  not  abandoned.   There
are often little surprises, but that is part of the fun.

There were no surprises on this trip, other than the  pleasant  one  that  I
could  drive  from  Cumberland  E  on  SE  Kuzak  Rd  all  the  way  to  the
Weyerhaeuser Mainline Rd.  I really thought it would be gated  before  this.
Saved me a few miles of biking. This is the same mainline  road  I  biked  N
from Highway 410 last Sunday to go up Boise Ridge. This time, starting  from
the closed gate (no intimidating signs, elev 1200 ft),  I  biked  S  on  the
Mainline, but only a few feet as I immediately turned  left  uphill  onto  a
road that climbed up the E side of the S Fork Coal Cr valley. At  2.6  miles
(elev 2275 ft) I turned right onto a side road. At first I thought  I  might
be in trouble as this road looked very little  used  and  I  was  afraid  it
might become impassible, but I needn\'t have worried, although I did have  to
dodge alder branches crowding the edges at times. I climbed to 2450 ft  then
descended to 2000 feet to cross the creek to the W side of the valley  in  a
series of ups and downs before climbing once again to hit a  major  road  at
6.5 miles and 2300 ft.  This road goes S to connect with the one I  took  up
Boise Ridge. At 7.25 mile I turned left onto the  final  Â¼  mile  spur  that
went to within 50 ft of the top. A rough trail circled around  the  backside
away from the road cut and a plastic rose marked the summit (2500  ft,  2:40
hrs).

I had a nice view of the Enumclaw plateau to the  W  with  all  its  strange
little bumps. It looked like the playground  of  a  family  of  busy  moles.
There are enough blobs  there  to  keep  a  body  busy  for  many  a  Sunday
afternoon, although some of them do not qualify for 400 ft of prominence.  I
was just below the snowline to E where several higher summits would have  to
wait until the snow melted. The trip "down" had more up than  I  would  have
liked but I made it back to the car just as the next  round  of  rain  began
again.

Total: 19 miles, 3350 ft and 4:20 hrs.

Fay Pullen


