            'tr' => '
Table Mtn (6200+ ft - 120P) and Diamond Head (5915 ft - 275P) -  Swauk  Pass
Quad - January 9, 2006

Despite extensive skiing in the Blewett Pass area I had never been up  Table
Mtn,  put  off  I  suppose  by  the  perception  of  it  being  overrun   by
snowmobiles. And it usually is, especially on  weekends  and  holidays.  Too
bad as it makes for a marvelous ski trip. Even more so on this day,  because
even though I expected to meet many of the smelly beasts, I  only  ran  into
two of them and that at the end of the day.  So I essentially had the  whole
place to myself. Add to that sunny weather with good  views  and  nice  snow
and I had the makings of a stellar tour.

The parking lot was empty when I started at 9:30.  Road  9716  was  recently
groomed and somewhat icy, but I found good traction in a  fresh  dusting  of
snow on the side. The road was very gentle and took forever to get  anywhere
but I happily glided in silence and solitude  the  easy  5.5  miles  to  the
junction with Table Mtn Road 35. This road was not recently groomed and  had
more fresh snow but trailbreaking was still not a problem. I  did,  however,
run into a dozen or so trees that  had  presumably  come  down  in  Sunday\'s
storm where winds in excess of 100mph were clocked in Wenatchee and  Mission
Ridge. They were easily bypassed. I doubt the snowmobilers will allow  these
trees to impede their access for long.

I left the road at its  high  point  and  skied  along  the  edge  of  Table
Mountain. I counted three closed contours of 6200  ft  along  its  almost  2
mile length on the map. Which one was the high  point?  I  didn\'t  know  and
really didn\'t care, as the plan was to ski the entire ridge anyway.  This  I
did and it was delightful skiing, as long I stayed in the trees  100  ft  or
so away from the edge where the wind was  howling  and  snow  flutings  made
travel difficult. My side trips to the high points were quick.   Good  thing
the wind was coming from the west or  I  might  have  been  blown  over  the
cliff.

Once at the south end of the ridge I returned  to  the  road  for  the  trip
back. I ran into the  two  snowmobilers  mentioned  earlier  very  near  the
junction with Road 9712 at the start of the downed trees.  I  informed  them
there were about a dozen more to contend with and they were  not  happy.  At
the junction myself, I decided to continue to the top of  Diamond  Head.   I
had never been there and it was so close. Near the top  it  was  very  windy
and I was forced onto the east slope to escape and find softer snow.

I had a good run down from the summit east to a saddle and down  a  drainage
where I soon picked up the Haney Meadow Trail. It  was  freshly  tracked  by
snowshoes. Skiing in snowshoe tracks is not my  favorite  thing,  but  there
was enough soft snow on the side for good skiing. The last bit was  done  by
headlamp. I hit the road about a mile from the Sno-Park.

Total: 16 miles, 3000 ft and 8 hrs.

Fay Pullen






