            'tr' => '

Big Muffin (4600+ ft - 920P) & Little Muffin (4280+ ft - 480P) - Lost Lake
Quad

January 12, 2006

I usually avoid the Crystal Springs SnoPark lot E of Snoqualmie Pass, as  it
is Snowmobile City. However, there is a lot of good skiing in  the  area  if
you can put up with the noise and smell of the  infernal  machines.   It  is
best to go during the week although even then you cannot get away from  them
completely. The one advantage is that during periods of heavy new  snowfall,
such as now, you will have little if any trailbreaking.

I started from the far end of the huge (and unplowed - I needed  my  4-wheel
drive just to navigate the foot of slush) lot where space is set  aside  for
skiers and dog sleds (elev 2400 ft).   Here  a  snowmobile  forbidden  trail
wanders through the woods a mile or  so  to  connect  with  the  Iron  Horse
Trail. Another mile of flat gliding along the set tracks and  I  turned  off
onto  the  Meadow  Cr  Road  5483.  Three  more  miles  along  this  groomed
snowmobile road and I turned left onto road 5484  to  cross  Meadow  Cr  and
start uphill (5 miles, 600 ft, 2 hrs). There had only been  a  dozen  or  so
snowmobiles in the lot when I started, but I think every one of  them  found
me and followed me like annoying buzzing mosquitoes I couldn\'t shake. I  had
to keep reminding myself I was in their territory so what did I  expect  and
at least I wasn\'t breaking trail.  For the distances I  was  going  on  this
trip there is no way I could make it on my own if  I  had  to  break  trail.
Still, a few moments of solitude would have been nice.

I soon took a right onto a spur road climbing toward Big Muffin.  This  road
was no longer groomed but a snowmobile had been up  it  so  I  still  didn\'t
have to break trail.  However, it was a mixed blessing  as  I  struggled  up
the resulting deep trench and the "moguls"  that  are  kicked  up  when  the
machines are powered through heavy snow. I  finally  left  all  traces  them
behind when I turned off the road to climb up the E ridge through  a  clear-
cut to the summit (2400 ft, 4:10 hrs). I had a pleasant run down the  clear-
cut and back to the saddle between Big  and  Little  Muffin.   Another  road
that snowmobiles had chewed up climbed with 2 switchbacks to  circle  around
to the S side of Little Muffin. A short trek through open woods led  to  the
flat summit where I wandered around a bit until  I  felt  I  must  certainly
have hit the highest point (3050 ft, 5:40).

It was now snowing heavily and windy, a blizzard really and I  could  barely
see a thing, which might actually have helped on the run down the chewed  up
road.  Why snowmobiles can\'t just  go  straight  up  a  road  I  will  never
understand, but they can\'t.  They must go up and  down,  in  and  out,  high
mark onto the uphill shoulder, cut across,  dig  deep  holes  and  generally
render a road unfit to ski. If I had been able to see all this  on  the  run
down I  would  have  been  very  intimidated.   Since  I  couldn\'t  and  was
essentially skiing blind I just kept it loose, bent the knees and  went  for
it.  Fortunately, the snow was soft and forgiving and I made it down to  the
groomed road in one piece. The rest of the 5+ miles of very  flat  road  and
trail took as long to go out as to come in. I arrived to a car buried  in  6
inches of new wet heavy snow, an effort to get out of the lot and a  tedious
drive over Snoqualmie Pass.
Total: 19 miles, 3200 ft and 8 hrs.  Fay Pullen






