            'title' => 'Peak 4080+ (600P - Stampede Pass Quad) - January 17, 2006',
            'tr' => '

Peak 4080+ (600P - Stampede Pass Quad) - January 17, 2006




Still not completely recuperated from my  climb  of  Anthracite  and  Beaver
with Stefan, Paul and company on Sunday, I was looking for  a  wimpy  little
peak with  a  short  drive  that  I  could  do  on  skis  without  too  much
trailbreaking. This peak fit the bill as the most difficult thing  about  it
was locating it on the map. With only an elevation of 4080+ ft to go  by,  I
had to search all over the Stampede Pass Quad to find it. I  first  found  a
4080 ft summit close to Stampede Pass itself but  then  realized  it  didn\'t
have the proper prominence.  I finally found this curious low  bump  nestled
amongst much higher summits between Gale  and  Box  Canyon  Creeks  where  I
least expected it.

I began from the Kachess Lake SnoPark (elev 2400) fully  expecting  to  take
advantage of the groomed snowmobile roads to get me close to  my  objective.
Alas, I was the first to arrive at the lot for the day and just overnight  a
foot of heavy wet snow had fallen. As I  was  contemplating  my  misfortune,
two snowmobiles whizzed by me out of nowhere and proceeded up the road.   No
trail breaking for me after all, at least to start.

The road to start is very flat as it  wanders  along  the  edge  of  Kachess
Lake, but I glided happily  along  in  the  snowmobile  track  enjoying  the
freedom of motion skiing provides  (as  opposed  to  the  plodding  of  snow
shoeing, which I only tolerate as a means of  transportation).  I  even  had
magnanimous thoughts for the snowmobiles, which allowed for this  (they  can
be useful at times). After 2 miles the road began to climb along Gale Cr.  I
thought about approaching my peak more directly from the E, but  missed  the
spur road (it was untracked.) so ended up going another 3.5  miles  on  the
main road to a spur (elev 3480) going up  the  W  side.  Unfortunately  this
spur was also untracked. It also  maddeningly  went  down  a  bit  and  then
contoured for over a mile circling around  to  the  S  side  before  finally
climbing to the saddle between Pk 4080 and a 4040 ft knoll.  Breaking  trail
through deep heavy snow on these 2 miles took almost  2  hours.  The  summit
was a cute knob that even sported a small cornice (7.5 miles, 2100 ft,  4.5
hrs).

I made a few good turns off the summit despite the heavy snow and  continued
to the 4040 ft knoll.  From there I could look straight down onto  the  main
road. I couldn\'t resist a direct descent down the N  side  and  although  it
was quite steep with deep snow it wasn\'t bad skiing. The main road was  fast
going down as by now many snowmobiles  had  been  by.  Even  the  flat  went
quickly. This may be a wimpy peak, but wimpy peaks can  be  a  lot  of  fun,
especially on skis.

Total 14 miles, 2600 ft and 7 hrs

Fay Pullen


