            'title' => 'Snowshed Head (3796 ft - 356P - Stampede Pass Quad) and Lake Laura - January 19, 2006',
            'tr' => '
Snowshed Head (3796 ft - 356P - Stampede Pass Quad) and Lake Laura -
January 19, 2006

Snowshed Head doesn\'t have 400 ft of prominence and certainly doesn\'t  merit
a trip in and of itself.  Still, it is a named peak and was the last for  me
to do on the Stampede Pass Quad. So I had to climb it.   In  order  to  make
the trip worth my while I decided to combine it with a trip to  Lake  Laura.
I had never been to this lake.   I  also  wanted  to  see  if  it  would  be
possible to climb Dungeon Pk (5640+) via the E ridge from the lake.   I  had
already climbed Dungeon several years ago via the S ridge which looked  from
the map as if it would go entirely on skis.   It  did  not.   An  impressive
rock wall necessitated a 300 foot descent followed by a  climb  up  a  steep
gully to the NW.  Skis were left behind.

Starting from the Mt Margaret SnoPark (elev 2600 ft),  I  bypassed  Snowshed
leaving it till the end and skied to the switchback on  the  road  up  Rocky
Run, a repeat of my route up the SE Pk of Rampart Ridge of a few weeks  ago.
Donning skins, I continued upstream to the right of Rocky Run in the  trees.
 The left side of the creek was all cliffs and did not  appear  to  offer  a
reasonable route. The outlet creek from Twin Lakes was  more  of  a  problem
than the map would indicate.  It was a steep  rocky  ravine  that  was  best
crossed very low. A small cliff band with a waterfall  was  the  only  other
obstacle, but I found a way through that could be climbed on  skis.   Above,
an open slope led to a small spur ridge and a short descent to  lovely  Lake
Laura, elev 4400 ft. (2600 ft, 3:20 hrs)

The lake itself was mostly surrounded by cliffs but a  slope  on  the  other
side offered the possibility of a continued way up. With limited  visibility
I couldn\'t tell for sure. An attempt on Dungeon  from  here  would  have  to
wait for another day with better weather, better snow and  more  time.   But
at least I now knew I could get to the lake on skis.

My next destination was Twin Lakes, elev 4600 ft, nestled in a bowl N of  Mt
Margaret. I had been to these lakes on summer trail but  never  on  skis.  I
climbed out of Lake Laura and traversed upward  on  easy  terrain,  much  of
which crossed avalanche debris that had come down off the  steep  slopes  of
SE Rampart.  It took a bit less than an hour to get there. To  get  back  to
my start, from the lakes I was forced to climb to  over  5000  ft  to  avoid
very steep sidehill. Once past Mt Margaret, I took off skins, and  began  my
greatly anticipated downhill first through  trees  than  massive  clearcuts.
Fun, fun, fun.  Eventually I ended up on the main  groomed  snowmobile  road
and headed for Snowshed.

From Resort Cr Pond I was surprised to find a cat track went almost all  the
way up  Snowshed  Head.   Evidently  the  DOT  uses  this  summit  to  blast
hazardous snow above I-90 (It is directly  above  the  snowshed,  hence  the
name). I passed all manner of intimidating signs warning of the  possibility
of being blown to smithereens if one  proceeded.  While  on  the  summit,  a
groomer had come by on the snowmobile road, leveling out  all  the  annoying
rollers and ruts that snowmobiles make and allowing for  a  let-her-rip  run
down the road. But alas, I soon  caught  the  groomer  and  passed  it  (the
operator was somewhat shocked to see me). He passed me again on the flat.

Total: 13 miles, 4100 ft and 7:50 hrs        Fay Pullen

