Meadow Mtn (5440+ ft - 1840P - Lost Lake Quad) - January 24, 2006


Just because there is zero percent chance of rain  (as  there  was  on  this
day), that doesn\'t mean the weather, or particularly  the  snow  conditions,
will be good. I lost on both accounts this  time  out.   I  arrived  at  the
Crystal Springs SnoPark (elev 2400 ft) to thick fog  and  icy  crusty  snow,
but I was early enough to beat the snowmobiles. I repeated  my  route  of  a
few weeks before up Big and Little Muffin for the first 5  miles  -  up  the
ski trail, Iron Horse Trail and Meadow  Cr  Road.  My  waxless  skis  worked
marginally on the flat, but once on the road, despite it being  only  gently
uphill, I was forced to put on kicker skins to get any traction  at  all  on
the ice. Rather than continue another mile to the road  directly  to  Meadow
Pass, for variety I turned onto Road 5484 for a  short  ways  and  tried  to
take a shortcut to Stirrup Lake. But I couldn\'t find the trail and ended  up
wandering through close trees until I ran into a road that took  me  to  the
lake. From here I climbed through trees to Meadow  Pass,  elev  3640  ft  (7
miles, 1850 ft, 4 hrs). I don\'t think I saved  any  time  but  it  was  more
interesting than just slogging along the road.

From the pass I followed a road well tracked by snowmobiles  that  took  its
time climbing up the S side of Meadow Mtn through clearcuts. At 4000 ft  the
snowmobile tracks ended. The fog was  beginning  to  lift  with  tantalizing
glimpses of the sun and a few views, but I could see my summit was still  in
the fog with little hope for improvement.  There was also a very nasty  wind
from the SE with gusts strong enough to knock me off balance.  At  the  last
switchback, I abandoned my plan to climb the SW ridge and instead  traversed
straight into the trees onto the W  slope  to  escape  the  wind.  The  only
problem was this put me on a very steep sidehill. Still, it wasn\'t  too  bad
on skis as here the snow was mostly  soft  slush  with  a  slight  breakable
crust. I continued traversing N until I reached an open bowl  below  cliffs,
then traversed back S to the first place I could climb to the summit  ridge.
The last 200 feet were quite steep. I stashed my skis just below the  ridge,
emerged onto the crest to the full force  of  the  wind  and  punched  steps
through awful ice crust the remaining .2 mile to the summit (10 miles,  3900
ft, 6:30 hrs).  It seemed to take forever in the raging wind and  of  course
the summit was the farthest bump as it always is.

The ski back to the switchback was not as bad as I had anticipated, but  the
ski down the untracked road was treacherous. I could  stay  on  top  of  the
breakable crust as long as weight was evenly distributed between both  skis,
but put more weight on one ski and it would break through and down  I  would
go. I finally settled on a slow  thigh-busting  snowplow.   Things  improved
once I hit the snowmobile tracks, if only slightly.  I didn\'t break  through
a crust but the track was icy, fast and rutted. I stayed  on  the  road  all
the way to the groomed Meadow Cr Road. By now it was dark. The last 6  miles
were enjoyable as I rocketed down the smooth road on  any  slight  downhill.
Even the flat zipped by as here the snow had  softened  just  enough  during
the day for a good kick and glide.

Total: 20 miles, 4100 ft and 10 hrs.

Fay Pullen


