Huckleberry Ridge (5000+ ft - 600P - Clear West Quad) - January 31, 2006


What a difference a few days makes! I found  myself  back  at  the  Sun  Top
SnoPark where Saturday I had a splendid trip to  the  lookout  with  Jim  in
gorgeous powder. All that beautiful fluff was now replaced by rained on  and
frozen crust. It was enough to make grown men (and women) cry. But  such  is
the life of a backcountry skier in the Washington Cascades, where the  cycle
of snow is constantly shifting back and forth between the  sublime  and  the
awful and you are never quite sure what you are going to end up with.

Actually I was happy that there was still enough snow, bad  as  it  was,  to
ski right from the car (elev 2300 ft). My  destination  this  trip  was  the
high point of Huckleberry Ridge, directly across  Huckleberry  Cr  from  Sun
Top. After 15 minutes on the main Rd  73,  I  turned  right  onto  Rd  7320,
crossed the creek and in another 15 minutes turned  left  uphill.  The  road
was very chewed up with old snowshoe and boot and ski tracks, but  soon  all
tracks ended  and  the  way  blessedly  smoothed  out  a  bit.  At  the  4th
switchback the road essentially ended with  both  spurs  shown  on  the  map
blocked. However, I was able to continue up the right spur despite it  being
somewhat overgrown and lumpy with downed trees and debris. This took  me  to
a side ridge where all road ended, elev 3880. Here I  had  a  last  view  of
both Sun Top and my objective as weather was fast approaching.

Fortunately, I was able to follow a narrow open thread through  dense  trees
along the crest of the side ridge until I hit a good road on the main  ridge
(elev 4200 ft). This road was delightful after what I had been  on.   I  was
now high enough for 2-3 inches of fresh snow since the last rain  and  there
was no sign of any traffic of any sort (I thought  maybe  snowmobiles  might
come up this way from the W Fork White River). I followed the  road  up  and
down along the ridge until it dead-ended in a clearcut  below  Haller  Pass.
From here I wandered to the top of the clearcut and through the trees  until
I could descend to the road and saddle just N of Huckleberry Ridge. A  final
clearcut, where skins were required once again (I had also used then on  the
side ridge), led easily to the high point (3450 ft, 5:15 hrs).  It  was  now
snowing hard and very windy.

There was enough snow over the crust on the clearcuts to  ski  down  safely,
just not enough for carefree turns, but the upper road  was  very  pleasant.
Then much side-slipping and crashing in breakable crust down the side  ridge
and overgrown spur road until I reached the lower road where by  now  enough
new snow had fallen to make it a reasonable ski down.  But  by  the  time  I
reached the car, the snow was already turning to rain as snow  levels  began
rising once again in a seemingly never ending cycle.

As an aside, I almost ran into a downed  tree  across  Highway  410  on  the
drive home. Fortunately I saw it in time in the dark and wasn\'t  going  that
fast.  Still it was scary!  I was  barely  able  to  squeak  by  it  on  the
outside shoulder.  It wasn\'t a huge  tree  but  it  would  have  done  major
damage had I hit it head on.

Total: 11 miles, 3800 ft and 8 hrs.   Fay Pullen


