Greenway Mtn (4440+ ft - 440P - Chester Morse Lk Quad) - February 5, 2006


I have been waiting all winter for just the  right  conditions  to  do  this
trip. I needed enough snow to make the long road approach skiable,  but  not
so much that trailbreaking would be a problem or that the access  road  from
I-90 off Exit 38 would not be drivable. (The last time I tried this  trip  I
ended up sliding backwards down the road in my jeep.  I  gave  up  and  went
elsewhere.) This Super Bowl Sunday everything seemed  to  fall  into  place.
Even the weather was nice.

I was able to drive Rd 9020 this time with no problem. I ran into the  first
snow at the intersection with Rd 9021 and was stopped very shortly after  at
the power line, where I  parked,  elev  2000  ft.  At  the  next  very  soon
intersection I went straight ahead  on  a  gated  road  (gate  open  but  no
vehicle tracks).  Past the gate the road had 8-12 inches of base  snow  with
a dusting of fresh on top and made for good skiing right from the  start.  I
followed the "main" road as it took its time  and  meandered  up  and  down,
first into the Mine Cr Valley, crossed that  creek,  then  rounded  a  ridge
into the Hall Cr Valley and eventually switchbacked up to the ridge  marking
the boundary of the Cedar River Watershed. Parts  of  the  lower  road  were
rather overgrown and presented some obstacles,  but  other  than  that,  the
whole route made for very pleasant skiing. By the time I reached  the  ridge
there was 3-4 inches of delectable powder over a deep smooth base.   Perfect
conditions.

The ridge road came very near the summit of Greenway, and it  was  a  simple
matter to ski to the very top (7 miles, 3050 ft, 4:30 hrs). The day  was  so
lovely and  the  skiing  so  pleasant  that  I  couldn\'t  resist  adding  Mt
Washington (4400+ ft - 280P)  and  Change  Pk  (4320+  ft  -  320P)  to  the
itinerary.  I had been up both from the Mt Washington trail  in  summer  but
had never skied the ridge roads to them (the  final  ascents  were  on  foot
though). This made for a very long trip indeed but a  very  satisfying  one.
Who would have thought such a nice ski trip would be possible in this area!

Total: 20.5 miles, 4500 ft and 10 hrs.

Fay Pullen
