            'tr' => '
Grass Mtn, N Pk (3880+ ft - 880P) and Hudson Mtn (3640+ ft - 560P) - Eagle
Gorge Quad - February 9, 2006

I wanted something easy and close that would not require an early start  for
this day. I succeeded in the last two requirements but easy it  was  not.  I
always seem to overreach in what I think is reasonable for  a  certain  time
frame.  Or maybe it is just that I  am  perpetually  overly  optimistic.   I
would like to think it is the latter. In any event,  these  two  peaks  have
been on my radar screen for a while now. I knew that  there  would  be  snow
the last 1000 feet or so.  I considered waiting until  the  snow  completely
melted so I could bike the whole way, but by  the  time  that  happens  this
snowy year I will be on to bigger and badder mountains. So I decided to  try
a "bike and ski".  I have wanted to combine biking and skiing for some  time
but the difficulty of carrying skis on a bike always got in the  way.  Sure,
they could be carried on a pack, but skis  on  a  pack  can  interfere  with
biking (I know, I  have  tried  it).  What  I  really  need  is  folding  or
telescoping skis. Since those are not yet available,  I  came  up  with  the
idea of using kids cross-country skis.  These are  very  short,  very  light
and the simple binding can be used with any footwear, including bike  shoes.


And so I started at the gate at the end of  Kuzak  Rd  in  Cumberland,  elev
1200 ft, a little before noon on my bike with skis  and  poles  attached  to
the panniers. Past the S gate I turned left and went steadily  uphill.   The
day was windy, not unusual for this area, but nothing out  of  the  ordinary
had been predicted.  "Breezy", is what the forecast  called  it.  Well,  the
wind got steadily worse the  higher  I  climbed  until  it  began  to  be  a
hindrance in forward progress (Of course I was going into the  wind).   Then
I rounded the corner of a rib at about 2300 ft and entered  the  full  force
of what had to be a wind tunnel effect where the  wind  was  channeled  into
such speed that I literally could not  push  the  bike  uphill  against  it.
Gusts had to be 50-60 mph. I could only make  progress  between  the  gusts.
At this point I considered turning around, but you know me.   I  don\'t  give
up easily. Proceeding on the hope that I would get out of the  worst  of  it
after I got out of the "tunnel" I slowly continued up.

I did eventually get to a more protected area after passing through an  open
blue DNR gate and taking a left at the next road junction onto  the  N  side
of the spur ridge. Soon I began  running  into  snow  and  soon  after  that
stashed the bike at 2850 ft (4 miles, 1650 ft, 1:45 hrs). I continued on  my
little skis.  Conditions were perfect for these  little  guys,  soft  crust.
They climbed well yet didn\'t sink in very far. I think I was  able  to  make
faster progress on them than on my bike.  In 30 minutes I was  at  the  3040
ft saddle between the two peaks. I went N to  climb  Hudson  first.  A  road
traverses the E side and climbs all the way to the summit from the N, but  I
decided to chance a route up the shorter S ridge. Not a good choice. A  spur
road went up a ways then deadended in awful  scrub  trees.  Not  wanting  to
repeat that, when I finally made my way to the summit  (6  miles,  2500  ft,
3:15 hrs), I decided to come back down the road. It  took  a  while  to  get
used to the short squirrelly feel of my tiny  skis,  but  once  I  did  they
worked very well for the downhill run. You can\'t do any real skiing on  them
but for straight running up and down roads they worked fine.

Back at the saddle I went S following the road that  went  all  the  way  to
very near the summit of N Grass Mtn by traversing the W and then S  side.  I
was able to keep skis on to the very top (10 miles, 3600  ft,  5  hrs).  You
will notice that I haven\'t mentioned the wind again.   That  is  because  it
was no great problem even on the summits. Sure it was still very  windy  but
nothing really unusual for mountain ridges. I skied down the  2.5  miles  to
the saddle in 20 minutes and the  last  mile  to  the  bike  in  another  15
minutes (this section was flatter and slower). It was now dark but at  least
I had had the forethought to bring my good bike light.

I should have been down the 4 miles of good road on my bike  in  30  minutes
or less.  I should have been but I wasn\'t.  I had hoped the  wind  had  died
down by now where it had been so bad on the way up.  After  all,  it  wasn\'t
terrible on the summit.  How naÃ¯ve could I be?  When  I  entered  the  "wind
tunnel" not only was it not better it was worse. There was no  way  I  could
ride down that section and keep control of my bike.  One  gust  and  I\'d  be
down, or worse blown off the edge of the road. Even  walking  my  bike  down
was hazardous to my health. At the worse place  a  gust  hit  and  literally
picked both me and my bike up and hurled us into  the  shoulder  ditch.  And
while we were both down it continued to blow us  across  the  road.  I  have
never in my life been in such a strong wind.  It had to be in excess  of  70
mph. Several more times the wind blew us over  until  I  gratefully  rounded
the rib to relative shelter. I was so shaken, though, I  continued  to  walk
the bike for far longer than was probably necessary. It took  over  an  hour
to go the final 4 miles to the car.

Interestingly, the DNR gate was closed by the time I came down.  That  means
someone drove up and down the road.  I wonder how they fared  in  the  wind,
as it was strong enough to affect a vehicle.  In fact I  saw  a  wreck  just
over the edge in the area. Perhaps it was blown there.

The next day high wind warnings  went  up  for  the  foothills  and  reports
verified a 70mph gust in Cumberland.  A day late as far as I am concerned.

Total: 17.7 miles, 3800 ft and 7 hours.

Fay Pullen
