Bald Mtn, W Pk (4240+ ft - 440P) and Pk 3440+ (480P) - Mallardy Ridge Quad
- February 14, 2006

I am eternally optimistic and constantly imagining  optimal  conditions  for
ski trips. They rarely materialize.  This  trip  was  no  exception.  Things
really looked promising when I left in the morning. There was  lowland  snow
with 2 inches at Granite Falls and cold temperatures. Surely there would  be
enough to ski on where I was going. Not so! Strangely, the farther  I  drove
up the Mountain Loop Highway, the less the new  snowfall.   By  the  time  I
reached the Schweitzer Cr Rd 4020, it had dwindled to a mere dusting.  Darn!
I should have gone to Snoqualmie Pass with its reported 8 inches  of  fresh.
But when I was making my decision as to where to go in the morning,  Hwy  18
was closed at Maple Valley due to a fatal accident. That is my  usual  route
to I-90. And so I headed N on I-405. I fared no better  here  where  traffic
was awful and added a full hour to the normal drive time.  But  it  was  too
late to change destinations.

I was able to drive 2.5 miles up Rd 4020 until being stopped  by  old  snow,
elev 2000 ft. The skiing was acceptable, with just enough  new  over  frozen
crust to give traction. Soon I took a right  onto  Rd  4021.  After  some  2
miles, I took a left to the Ashland Lakes TH. I was able to continue  skiing
until the old road turned to true trail. Then it became  obvious  that  skis
would be of no use.  The rest of the trip would be on foot.  The  trail  was
essentially a frozen creek  bed  with  slippery  planks  and  log  crossings
covered with icy snow.  Crampons would have been the order of the day had  I
thought to bring them along.  Since I didn\'t, I had to  make  due  with  ice
axe and ski pole axe and put up with a lot of slipping and sliding.

Above Ashland Lake I had trouble following the Bald Mtn Trail  and  wandered
around a bit going up and down in confusing topography.  Eventually  I  made
my way to Bald\'s NW ridge and followed it to the wooded summit  (5.3  miles,
3200 ft, 5 hrs). The terrain in this area would have been very  skiable  had
only the conditions cooperated. Too bad I didn\'t hit it right. I had  a  few
good views through the  trees  from  the  top.   Of  especial  interest  was
Fletcher Pk where I had just been two days previous.

Back at the Ashland Lake Junction, I made  a  mad  dash  up  Pk  3440,  just
beating darkness (.8 miles, 500 ft, :50 hr RT). The rest of the way out  was
by headlamp. A nice trip really, just not what I had imagined or hoped for.

Total: 11.4 miles, 4000 ft and 9:30 hrs

Fay Pullen



