Pk 4898 (658P) and Pk 4506 (466P) - Blowout Mtn Quad - February 16, 2006


The area S of I-90 and E of Stampede Pass had never much  interested  me  in
the past, and with good reason.  It is  essentially  one  gigantic  clearcut
with  roads  everywhere,  overrun  with  snowmobiles  in  the  winter   (and
motorbikes in the summer).  But  with  my  current  pursuit  of  all  things
greater than 400 ft of prominence  and  new  summits  to  seek  out,  I  see
everything in a different light. The snows of  winter  can  lend  beauty  to
even the ugliest clearcut and if you hit it right, when  snowmobile  traffic
is low, skiing can be remarkably good.

I hit it just right on this trip. There  was  only  one  other  rig  in  the
Crystal Springs Sno-Park  (elev  2400  ft)  when  I  arrived  and  the  cold
temperatures (it was 12  degrees  to  start)  had  preserved  the  last  new
snowfall of several days ago. I was able to ski on the shoulder of Rd 41  in
1-2 inches of lovely sparkling powder and the miles of  road  skiing  ticked
by pleasantly enough. Soon I was passed by two snowmobiles  (from  the  rig)
and shortly after by one more going to Stampede Pass.  But that was  it  and
I didn\'t even hear any more for the rest of the day. A real rarity for  this
area.

I followed Rd 41 to the saddle N of Pk 4506 from where I headed  S  up  open
slopes to the summit (7 miles, 2250 ft, 3:50 hrs). Views were fantastic  all
around. Close by to the NW I was impressed by Meadow Mtn, which  stands  out
in a land of rounded summits. I was also interested in the  area  to  the  S
and E, a vast unexplored area for me with new summits  just  begging  to  be
skied (such as Cabin Mtn, Cole Butte and Snowshoe Butte).

The ski off the summit back to the saddle was fantastic with 3 inches or  so
of delectable dry powder over a frozen base. This was only  so  because  the
open clearcuts collect maximum snow and because the terrain is  gentle.   On
steeper terrain, edges wouldn\'t hold  on  the  underlying  crust,  but  here
turning was effortless and a  sheer  delight,  as  long  as  I  avoided  old
snowmobile tracks.

Clearly this was turning into a stellar ski  day,  one  that  needed  to  be
prolonged as long as possible.  With that in mind,  I  first  ambled  up  Pt
4873 before making my way to Pk 4898 (10  miles,  3550  ft,  6  hrs.),  then
skied more entrancing terrain to the radio  towers  at  4520  ft.  From  the
towers I skied N along the ridge until hitting  one  of  the  few  remaining
stands of trees around. Since skiing in the trees was not good, I  exited  W
down another clearcut until I picked up a spur road that led back to Rd  41.
From the Stampede Pass junction on the road had been newly  groomed,  and  I
whizzed smoothly down the last bit by headlight. I am constantly  amazed  at
how often and how well these snowmobile roads are groomed.

Total: 17 miles, 3850 ft, 9 hrs.

Fay Pullen
