Wiley Ridge (4200+ ft - 840P - Mallardy Ridge Quad) - February 19, 2006


This peak has been nagging at me ever since I  had  to  miss  Paul  Klenke\'s
trip due to illness back in December. I had planned  on  staying  home  this
weekend, but I couldn\'t resist taking advantage of the beautiful sunny,  but
cold, weather. This seemed the time to lay "Wiley Coyote" to  rest.  (Coyote
Pt is what Paul calls the true summit.)

Armed with Paul\'s TR, I began on the gated road, elev  1300  ft,  just  past
the Red Bridge on the N side of the Mountain Loop Hwy. After  1.2  miles  on
the road, just past the bridge over Gordon Cr  I  found  the  old  overgrown
road, just where Paul said it was.  I followed this road easily  another  .7
mile to the deep ravine,  also  mentioned  by  Paul.  Seeing  no  particular
reason to cross the thing, I headed uphill to the right of it  crossing  the
switchbacking road 3 times. I briefly tried following the road, but  it  was
now so overgrown that it offered no advantage to travel. I continued  uphill
on a slight rib through reasonably pleasant open woods, although there  were
many  large  downed  trees  to  avoid.  The  ground  was  frozen   but   not
particularly slippery.

I began running into crusty snow about  2800  ft,  and,  after  an  annoying
section of thick scrubby trees, put on crampons and got out the ice  axe  at
3400 ft. The final 600 feet to the SE ridge was quite  steep  on  very  hard
snow and I  found  myself  frontpointing  at  times.  A  cliff  at  the  top
necessitated a short traverse to the right to hit  the  ridge  at  4000  ft.
From there it was an easy climb along the crest or slightly to the right  to
the first, false summit (3000 ft, 4:15 hrs).

I thought I had it made, but Wiley Coyote had a few tricks  up  his  sleeve,
as he frequently does. I knew there was  one  short  exposed  section  where
Paul recommended a long sling for protection. Instead  I  brought  a  40  ft
rope.  I wish I had brought a longer one (for rappels).  I  continued  along
the crest of the ridge until I came to a short snowcovered rock  step.   Was
this the problem spot?  Whether or not, it came  me  trouble.  I  roped  up,
fiddled around wasting time, finally got  up  the  thing  and  discovered  I
still had a ways to go to the summit. So I had to go back and  retrieve  the
rope and waste more time. I tiptoed farther along  the  narrow  snowy  crest
until coming to a final short steep mostly  snowcovered  cliffy  section.  I
was able to get up this by frontpointing after which I found myself  on  the
bare summit with a glorious view of  Three  Fingers,  Liberty  and  Fletcher
(3200 ft, 5:30 hrs).

I never did quite figure out where the exposed spot Paul  referred  to  was,
but my conditions were  very  different  from  his.  Anyway,  I  had  enough
problems of my own. I was nervous descending  from  the  summit  and  did  3
short 20 ft rappels.  I also rappelled the first rock step.  I  backed  down
much of the steep snow below the ridge. Then  I  got  off  my  uphill  line,
descending slightly farther W. This was not all bad.  The  woods  seemed  to
have fewer obstacles on this line and I missed  most  of  the  dense  scrub.
But this put me on the wrong side of the ravine on the lower road and I  had
some trouble crossing. Despite my delays, slow pace and  non-early  start  I
still made it down before dark (barely).          Total: 5.5 miles, 3500  ft
and 9 hrs.     Fay Pullen


