Cabin Mtn (4980 ft - 1060P - Blowout Mtn Quad) - February 21, 2006


One of the side effects of pursuing lists is that it  takes  you  to  places
you otherwise wouldn\'t think to go. If not for climbing 400P peaks  I  would
never even have considered coming here, and it turned out  to  be  a  little
gem of a ski trip. Yes, it is in the heart  of  snowmobile  country,  but  I
only ran into two of the machines on the main road (on  the  other  side  of
Cabin Cr coming from Crystal Springs), and found no evidence of them at  all
on the mountain itself. And with less than ideal snow conditions,  being  an
all road trip (except for the very last bit) was an asset.

From Exit 71 on I-90 at Easton I followed Cabin Creek Road about 3 miles  to
its plowed end at the so-called "Easton Reload" Sno-Park, elev 2250  ft.   I
didn\'t even know this Sno-Park existed. It is obviously not as well used  as
the huge Crystal Springs Sno-Park off Exit 62 as I had  the  entire  lot  to
myself all day. Of course this was a weekday.

From the Sno-Park, I skied along groomed Rd 41 a long mile  to  a  junction.
The main groomed road went straight, while  Rd  41,  now  closed  due  to  a
bridge out, went right. However, innovative  snowmobilers  had  installed  a
bridge of their own across Cabin Cr giving them through  access  to  Crystal
Springs and environs. This section of the abandoned road  was  not  groomed.
After another 2.5 miles, I turned right onto the spur  road  up  Cabin  Mtn,
elev 2900 ft. I climbed 2000 ft on this road up  ever  increasing  appealing
terrain until just S of the summit. The  last  200  ft  was  a  steep  climb
through icy woods to the top (2900 ft, 4:15 hr)

It had been snowing lightly all day, but only put down an inch or so of  new
snow over a hard crust. This was enough for a pleasant ski  down  the  road,
but not enough for good skiing off road. However, with  better  snow,  there
are all kinds  of  possibilities  for  exciting  downhills.  A  return  trip
someday is certainly warranted. As I descended, the  snow  turned  decidedly
wet and wetter until it became just plain  old  rain.   What  was  going  on
here? The snow level was supposed to be  1000  ft.  No  way!   It  was  even
raining when I returned over  Snoqualmie  Pass.  The  recent  artic  air  is
certainly a thing of the past.

Total: 15 miles, 3100 ft and 7 hrs.

Fay Pullen
