Cole Butte BM (5504 ft - 1504P - Easton Quad) - February 28, 2006


This turned out to be another hidden gem in snowmobile country, even  better
than my trip last week up Cabin Mtn.  I began from the same Sno-Park at  the
end of the plowed Cabin Cr Rd, elev 2240 ft. Again, I had the lot to  myself
and neither saw nor heard any snowmobiles all day,  although  a  couple  had
recently been part way up the road. The light  precipitation  to  start  was
closer to rain than snow and there was maybe an inch of wet new  stuff  over
a rained upon snowpack, which made for good waxless ski traction.

This time at the main junction at 1.5 miles, I turned left and followed  the
road up along the W side of Cole  Cr.  As  I  climbed  the  temperature  got
colder, the snow better and weather worse. By the time I  reached  the  head
of the valley, it was snowing hard, the wind was howling and all  traces  of
old snowmobile tracks had vanished under some  6  inches  of  fresh  blowing
snow. I continued around the head of the valley to the E side following  the
road through clearcuts until the uphill slope gentled enough  that  I  could
enter the woods and begin to climb to the ridge just S of Cole  Butte.   The
initial woods were very pleasant but soon steepened, and a final  open  area
below the ridge was wind blasted down to bare crust.  I  struggled  up  this
last section. Once on the easy ridge it was again very nice  as  long  as  I
traveled beneath the cornice line on the lee slope.  I  topped  out  on  the
summit to high winds and foggy views (3350 ft, 5 hrs).

The ski down to the road was tricky with  unfriendly  steep  snow  requiring
much sideslipping, traversing and kickturning, but  I  did  manage  to  stay
upright - mostly. The weather was now beginning to clear with  better  views
(all photos were taken on the way down) and  I  could  see  the  surrounding
terrain. With the high point of Cole Ridge (which did  not  offer  the  best
skiing in the area) out of the way, I could see all kinds  of  possibilities
for quality skiing on future tours.

Total: 13 miles, 3550 ft and 8 hrs.

Fay Pullen


