            'tr' => '

Cole Butte (5502 ft - P422 - Blowout Mtn Quad) - March 2, 2006


I was going to go to Swauk  Pass  and  ski  up  Tronsen  Meadow,  but  while
driving past Easton conditions looked really good  -  blue  skies,  sunshine
and fresh snow. I also had the added incentive of a new  peak  to  climb  in
the area. So why drive another 45 minutes?  Two days ago I skied up  what  I
thought was the only prominence point on Cole Ridge.  After sending  out  my
TR, JR replied with his report from August of last year and I  discovered  I
had somehow missed a second peak on the ridge, probably because it was on  a
different quad. Cole Butte is a  long  horseshoe  ridge  with  "Cole  Butte"
(5502 ft - P422 - Blowout Mtn Quad) on the W side and  "Cole  Butte  BM"  or
"Old King Cole" (5504 ft - P1504 -  Easton  Quad)  on  the  E  side.  I  had
climbed the latter two days ago.  The funny thing  is,  I  remember  reading
John\'s TR last summer, but it didn\'t  register.  I  was  busy  at  the  time
pursuing bigger and higher peaks.

It really didn\'t matter that I wasn\'t aware of the  second  peak,  as  there
was no way I could have climbed both on the same day. It  just  gave  me  an
excuse to return sooner than I had planned to a delightful area.  This  time
I followed the road some 5 miles to the head of  Cole  Cr  valley  and  then
climbed up ski friendly terrain through a wide open clearcut to  the  saddle
below Pt 5361. I then bypassed Pt 5361 on the left and went over Pt 5449  to
follow the ridge to Cole Butte.  This ridge  was  all  in  woods  but  still
pleasant skiing. The summit was a small open area, with  limited  views,  in
the sun and thus made for a comfortable stop (3600 ft, 4:30 hrs).

Slopes exposed to the sun had already developed a breakable  crust.   Slopes
in the shade still held 3-4 inches of very nice powder. You can guess  which
I sought out to provide a very nice ski down the clearcut.  There  are  many
more clearcuts that I could see on my way down  that  will  warrant  further
explorations.  I am not yet done with this area.

Total: 14 miles, 4100 ft and 7:30 hrs.

Fay Pullen


