Peak 5528 (P1248 ft - Mt Wow Quad) - March 7, 2006


For a change of pace I headed S to ski up this peak  above  Lake  Christine.
Just before the Nisqually Entrance to Mt Rainier I turned left  onto  Rd  59
and drove some 2.5 miles until stopped by  snow  at  elevation  2960  ft.  I
skied the road another 1.5 miles before turning right onto Rd  5920  leading
to the summer TH for Lake Christine. I had hoped  to  find  a  skiable  line
directly up the drainage to the lake but  nothing  really  looked  appealing
and I ended up going all the way to the end of the  2-mile  road.  This  was
not a wise plan as I was unable to find and follow  the  trail  and  had  to
drop to avoid very steep sidehill, cross the outlet creek  and  struggle  up
unfriendly terrain to the lake. However, once at the lake it was easy  going
to the W ridge and I was able to ski along this to the very top (3000 ft,  5
hrs).

The weather throughout the day was off and on snow showers, quite  heavy  at
times, mixed with periods of partial clearing where the sun  almost  put  in
an appearance but views did not. I am sure there is a splendid  view  of  Mt
Rainier, or at the very least Mt Wow directly across  Goat  Cr,  but  I  saw
none of it. The amount of new snow varied from a couple  of  inches  at  the
start to nearly a foot on top and for the most part it  was  the  usual  wet
heavy Cascade Concrete.  I had to get above Lake Christine for  it  to  even
begin to resemble anything like powder.   The  temperature  never  got  much
below freezing; even on the summit it hovered around 32 degrees.

I was not going to descend my ascent route to Lake  Christine,  and  instead
sought out a direct route down to the road, but I must  say  I  didn\'t  fare
much better.  The terrain is steeper than it  looks  on  the  map  with  all
manner of thick trees, gullies  and  obstacles.  There  are  some  appealing
clearcuts below Mt Beljica, but they don\'t really get  close  enough.  There
seems to be no good way to get to Lake Christine, at least not on skis.

I spent much of this trip, while slowly plodding through heavy new snow  and
laboring through obstacles, reflecting on  the  pleasant  experience  of  my
recent climb of Twin Peaks, lamenting the lack of  companions  on  this  one
and wishing I had a Dave Creeden along to break trail for me  and  a  Stefan
to find me a good route. And how about a Paul who can write  an  interesting
report for any trip?

Total: 9 miles, 3000 ft and 7.5 hrs.

Fay Pullen
