Cross Under Butte (3945 ft - 465P - Blowout Mtn Quad) - March 10, 2006


I woke up to an inch of snow on my front lawn. This after  a  huge  dump  of
snow in the mountains the day before (I stayed  home  that  day  because  of
high avalanche danger and terrible driving  conditions  over  and  near  the
passes.)  I thought maybe conditions would finally be just right for  skiing
up the Mt Teneriffe Rd.  This road makes a  very  nice  ski  trip  but  only
comes into condition once every few years when snow  levels  are  very  low.
Things looked promising as I drove over Tiger Summit where there was  enough
snow to ski (and a jack-knifed semi) but as I descended to  North  Bend  all
snow suddenly disappeared. The  Mt  Teneriffe  road  itself  was  completely
bare. There was plenty of snow higher up but it looked as if  I  would  have
to walk the gated road about a thousand feet to get to it, not how I  wanted
to squander this fresh snow day.

On to Plan B. The drive over Snoqualmie was completely clear with  the  road
just bare and wet - what a difference a day makes - but I felt certain  that
if I went somewhere I had to break my own trail it would be  exhausting  and
I wouldn\'t get very far. It is either feast or famine - not enough  snow  or
too much. So it was back to my newfound Easton Sno-Park where  I  could  get
an assist from snowmobile tracks. Again, no one was  in  the  lot  but  sure
enough  the  road  was  freshly  tracked.  (Just  when  do   these   phantom
snowmobiles go out - in the middle of the night?)

I easily skied 4.5 miles up Rd 41 in the tracks, past the major junction  of
Rd 4110 up Log Cr, to an untracked spur road climbing the NE side  of  Cross
Under Butte. I slowly broke trail  through  delicious  powder,  deciding  to
first climb Pt 3920 (just for fun and to extend the  day)  and  sticking  to
the road the whole way so I wouldn\'t have to skin up. I then had a  pleasant
ski straight down the clearcut to the saddle before climbing along a forest-
clearcut interface, sticking to the woods as  much  as  possible  where  the
snow was not as deep, up the NW ridge to the top of Cross Under Butte  (2350
ft, 4:45 hr).  I had another fun run down to my tracks on the spur road  and
then a long glide out. All in all a good day of skiing  after  a  heavy  new
fall of snow.

Total: 13.5 miles, 2650 ft and 7:15 hrs.

Fay Pullen

