Psilocybin Hill (5130 ft - 530P - Lost Lake Quad) - March 16, 2006


This peak has been on my to-do  list  ever  since  climbing  Meadow  Mtn  in
January.  The surrounding terrain is very appealing for skiing, but it is  a
L-O-N-G ways in and the summit itself is in the Cedar River Watershed, so  I
kept putting it off waiting for longer days and the  proper  motivation.  It
might have been smarter to put it way off until the roads melted out  and  I
could drive closer, but I am not well known for  doing  things  the  easiest
way. Beside I thought a stealth visit into  forbidden  territory  under  the
cover of extensive snow and bad weather  would  stand  a  better  chance  of
being undetected. (Why extensive logging is allowed  in  the  watershed  and
not such low impact activities as hiking, biking and  skiing  is  beyond  me
but that is a whole debate in itself and I doubt such reasoning  would  have
much sway with a judge if I were caught.)

Beginning from the Crystal Springs Sno-Park (elev 2400  ft),  I  skied  mile
after mile after mile on ski trail, the Iron Horse Trail, Meadow Cr Rd  5483
and Meadow Pass Rd reaching the 3600 ft pass at 7.75 miles  in  3  hrs.  Some
people might find such a long, relatively flat (1350 ft  gain)  road  to  be
positively boring.  Not me. The  old  reasonably  smooth  snowmobile  tracks
covered with a dusting of fresh snow made for very  pleasant  and  efficient
striding. I just love the feel of a gliding ski underfoot  and  the  freedom
of movement it provides.  I can (and did) do it all day long, as long  as  I
can do it at my pace.

From Meadow Pass I turned right traversing around the S ridge of Meadow  Mtn
and following a drainage to the saddle between Meadow Mtn and Pt 4953.  Here
I picked up a road coming from the watershed and entered. In my defense,  no
signs were visible, probably buried under feet of snow. This whole  area  is
one clearcut after another. So it was a pleasant surprise to find  a  lovely
glade of open woods on the broad top of Pt 4953.  The  trees  preserved  the
powder snow and made this section A+ skiing.  I  made  my  way  through  the
glade to the SE ridge of Psilocybin. I hugged the edge of the  forest  along
the ridge (the  SE  slope  was  all  clearcut)  seeking  better  snow  until
reaching the main NE ridge. Here the snow was  so  windblown  and  fluted  I
left skis to kick steps up the last 200 ft to the top (11.75 miles, 3200  ft,
5:45 hrs).

I had some nice skiing downhill in the powder in the woods.  And  the  roads
were all in perfect condition for  carefree  downhill  sliding  or  gliding,
soft and untrenched. I met no snowmobiles all day. A very satisfying day  on
the snow.

 I only have one more peak on the Lost Lake Quad, but it is very far  inside
the watershed, too far for a winter trip, I think, so I am not  sure  how  I
can get to that one undetected. I also had an intriguing  view  of  a  tooth
like peak to the SW I later identified as Goat Mtn (Findley Lk  Quad).  This
is in the Green River Watershed  (Tacoma),  which  doesn\'t  seem  to  be  as
officious as the Cedar River Watershed (Seattle) so there is hope I can  get
up that one.

Total: 23.5 miles, 3700 ft and 9:30 hrs.

Fay Pullen


