            'title' => 'Snowshoe Butte (5135 ft - 1495P) and Bearpaw Butte (4800+ ft - 280P) - Blowout Mtn Quad - March 31, 2006',
            'tr' => '
Snowshoe Butte (5135 ft - 1495P) and Bearpaw Butte (4800+ ft - 280P) -
Blowout Mtn Quad - March 31, 2006

I knew this would be another long road ski trip, but I didn\'t  know  exactly
how long. That was probably just as well or I might have  been  discouraged.
Sometimes ignorance is best. I tried for an early start but I was  sabotaged
by a terrible traffic jam at the  I-90  Hwy  18  interchange  caused  by  an
overturned flatbed semi (no doubt he took the exit ramp too fast). Not  only
did I lose precious time but I also arrived at the Crystal Springs  Sno-Park
frazzled and too late to beat the snowmobiles.  Thankfully  there  were  not
that many and for the most part they were not going where I was going.

It felt good to have snow underfoot again after a week of hiking in  parched
New Mexico. The snow was in excellent soft spring  condition  and  made  for
pleasant skiing mile after mile. The weather was warm  enough  to  start  in
shirtsleeves, with light rain/snow/hail showers at times. I began on Rd  41.
At the junction to Stampede Pass I took a  higher  spur  road,  through  two
sets of power lines, that eventually deadended below the wooded  ridgecrest.
I climbed to the ridge and followed it S until I ran into another road  that
traversed clearcuts around the W side of Pk 4898 before it ended as well.  I
followed the ridge through another wooded section until  reaching  the  last
saddle and open slopes below Snowshoe Butte  for  the  final  climb  to  the
summit (8.5 miles, 3200 ft, 4:50 hrs).

I descended the S ridge down good ski terrain to  intersect  the  connecting
ridge to Bearpaw Butte, following this  up  and  down  to  that  summit  (10
miles, 3700 ft, 5:45 hrs). I was now a very long distance from my start  and
the question was how to get  back  without  gaining  or  losing  unnecessary
elevation. I certainly didn\'t want to return  over  Snowshoe  but  the  deep
drainage of Cabin Cr was in the way of a direct route. I could  descend  the
NE ridge of Bearpaw directly to Rd  41,  however  at  that  point  the  road
dropped to 3200 ft to cross Cabin Cr and I would have to climb  back  up  to
4000 ft to get around Cross Over Butte. Not appealing. I could  see  a  road
that seemed to contour the E side of Snowshoe above Cabin  Cr,  if  I  could
get to it.

I returned along the ridge toward Snowshoe until I was able to descend  open
cleacut slopes to the N side of Cabin Cr and pick up the road  I  had  seen.
This I followed several miles until I could regain Rd 41 at the saddle N  of
Cross Over Butte. Now all  I  had  to  do  was  follow  this  well  traveled
snowmobile road back to Crystal Springs. It was  getting  late  enough  that
the road surface was beginning to ice over but this was actually helpful  as
the otherwise the gentle road would have been very slow.  I  ended  up  only
needing my headlamp for about the last half hour.

A last thought: does it count to climb Snowshoe Butte on skis? Somehow  that
doesn\'t seem quite right. I suppose I could rename it "Ski Butte"  but  that
lacks pizzazz.

Total: 21.5 miles, 4400 ft and 9:20 hrs.

Fay Pullen




