Pk 4485 (645P - Silverton Quad) - April 4, 2006


I was able to drive 2.4  miles  up  Rd  4030  (Mallardy  Ridge  Rd  off  the
Mountain Loop Hwy) until stopped by snow at the first switchback, elev  2000
ft. Of course this didn\'t mean that I could ski from this point on.   I  had
to half walk half ski for another 0.75 miles until I  hit  consistent  snow,  a
normal situation for spring conditions. I then skied the rest of  the  road,
taking a left on a better looking spur at a final junction, to  its  end  at
3400 ft below the NW ridge (4 miles, 2 hrs).  No open clearcuts  here,  just
regrown second growth.  Still, I was able to stay on skis for the  climb  to
the ridge until it narrowed and the trees thickened even more.  Then  I  was
forced to switch to snowshoes. I followed the ridge up  and  down  until  it
steepened at 3900 ft, where I then elected to traverse semi-open  slopes  on
the N side of Pt 4472 until I could regain the ridge past this point  via  a
steep gully. The snow  was  very  slushy  and  deep  and  trailbreaking  was
exhausting. I topped out at 3:30 (2850 ft, 4:45 hr). Most of the  ridge  and
summit was wooded but a hundred feet or so farther along the  crest  was  an
open area with  good  views  of  Big  Four.  I  originally  had  visions  of
including the two 4480+ prominence points farther along the  ridge  on  this
trip but I ran out of energy. With better snow and/or  help  breaking  trail
they probably would have been possible. Instead I turned  around  early  and
for once skied down a road in daylight.

Total: 10.5 miles, 3150 ft, 8 hrs.

Fay Pullen

