Sleepover Butte (4880+ ft - 480P - Blowout Mtn Quad) - April 6, 2006


This will probably be my last time this year skiing from this Sno-Park  near
Easton. The snow is getting mighty thin  and  already  the  4X4  yahoos  are
starting to make tracks up the road. Still skiing was  reasonable  on  solid
snow until I came to a section of road melting  out  below  the  S  side  of
Cabin Mtn. Here I skied dirty  ribbons  of  snow  and  tiptoed  across  bare
ground so I wouldn\'t have to take off my skis. They were my "rock  skis"  so
I wasn\'t too concerned about ruining their bottoms.

I followed Rd 41 4.5 miles to the junction with Rd 4110  up  Log  Cr.  After
another mile I turned right on  spur  123  and  skied  a  long  4  miles  on
increasingly slushy snow to its end  on  the  ridge  at  4500  ft.  Here  an
unexpected narrow thickly wooded crest led  down  to  the  open  saddle  and
clearcut slopes below Sleepover. The snow was  sticky  enough  I  needed  no
skins for the final 400 ft climb to the summit (10 miles, 3000 ft, 5 hrs).

Seeking a different way back, I took a direct line down the narrow  nose  of
a SE spur ridge, which offered fun but challenging skiing,  until  I  hit  a
road and found my way back to Rd 4110 along Log  Cr.  Partially  wanting  to
avoid the melted out section of Rd 41, but more wanting to explore  inviting
clearcuts I had seen on the N slope of Cole Butte, I turned right uphill  on
a logging spur just before the intersection with Rd 41. Bad Idea! I  thought
I had plenty of time left  for  this  exploration  and  both  the  USGS  and
Greentrails maps showed this spur going all the way through to the  road  up
Cole Cr.  They were both wrong. I have learned not to completely trust  USGS
maps when it comes to old roads but if you can\'t trust a  currently  revised
Greentrails map who can you trust?

After climbing some 1200 ft  I  came  to  a  junction  where  my  supposedly
through spur went down hill, but the main obviously better spur  (which  the
maps showed deadending) went uphill. This was a clue.  I  followed  my  spur
downhill with increasing trepidation as  it  increasingly  deteriorated.  It
had to descend 1000 ft to get below a cliffy ridge and I was able to  follow
a road of sorts to this point but then it just ended and I was in a  bit  of
trouble. I was too far down (and far too tired) to  return  the  way  I  had
come.  I couldn\'t continue straight down to Rd 41 (only 400 ft below me)  as
I was on the wrong side of Cabin Cr and would never be able to cross  it.  I
was stranded on a gosh awful steep wooded, brushy hillside with  gosh  awful
patchy snow and darkness was not far away. I didn\'t have much choice but  to
continue contouring, hoping I would run into the road from the  other  side,
hoping there was a road from the other side. I will spare  you  the  details
of wrestling myself and my skis through this stuff. But eventually  I  spied
a log landing.  Where there is a log landing there is  a  logging  road.  It
was higher than the road indicated on the map but when I climbed  up  to  it
sure enough there was a road and it led all the way to the Cole  Cr  Rd  and
my way out.  Of course the last bit was in the dark,  again.  But  that  was
okay.  After all I do have a reputation to uphold.

Total: 22 miles, 4500 ft and 10:30 hrs.

Fay Pullen
