Prairie Mtn (5678 ft - 1358P - Prairie Mtn Quad) - April 11, 2006


I had this crazy notion that Prairie Mtn could be climbed on skis.  I  guess
I was unreasonably influenced by all the logging roads that  are  marked  on
the maps on the W side. What I neglected to fully notice was that the  roads
are very old and not really connected and that  there  is  plenty  of  steep
unknown terrain to negotiate. But being the perennial optimist that I  am  I
sallied forth on this day with great expectations of  wonderful  skiing.  My
first inkling of trouble was when I came to a premature end of  the  Prairie
Mtn Rd at 2600 ft without encountering a bit of snow. The road  was  blocked
at this point and obviously decommissioned  and  abandoned  with  the  usual
ditches every hundred or feet or so. My vision of skiing up the road to  its
end came crashing to a halt. At this point the smart thing to do would  have
been to give up my dream of skiing and just accept that to  get  the  summit
snowshoes would be the obvious choice. Did I do this? Of course not!

I trudged up the road carrying my skis  (and  also  snowshoes  -  I  am  not
completely stupid). Eventually I ran into continuous snow  that  would  have
been skiable except that each ditch across the road was  bare  with  running
water.  After taking skis on and off half a dozen times I realized this  was
ridiculous and switched to snowshoes so I could walk across the  ditches.  I
then came to the end of the road at 3100 ft at a  spur  ridge.  Here  things
looked even bleaker. No nice clearcuts in sight just awful dense woods  with
patchy rotten snow. I had a  long  debating  conversation  with  myself  and
waffled as to what to do. I really should have cut my losses and  gone  home
to pet my kitties or at the very least recognized skis as a  very  bad  idea
and left them here.  Did I do either? Of course not!

I continued on up the ridge struggling with skis  getting  caught  on  every
branch and twig in sight and falling numerous times through terrible  rotten
snow into holes hip deep. This with  snowshoes  on.  Progress  was  slow  to
nonexistent and punctuated with loud cursing and much gnashing of  teeth.  I
think I continued on sheer faith that things would get  better,  remembering
the many times a trip has looked hopeless only to have it turn out,  if  not
exactly wonderful, at least successful  summit-wise.  Well  things  did  get
better.  After taking a full hour to gain a mere 500 feet  I  came  upon  an
upper road. This road too was abandoned but although it was a bit  overgrown
it was not ditched and I could ski it to its end higher on the  ridge  (elev
4000 ft). I now had a view of my objective and possible route.   All  memory
of my previous difficulties vanished as things began looking up.

From the end of the road I contoured on surprisingly  pleasant  terrain,  on
skis, around the head of Gravel Cr to a 1000 ft snow gully  leading  to  the
open slope below the cliffs of the long  Prairie  Mtn  ridge.  As  the  open
slope steepened I began to litter it with my discarded  gear.  First  to  go
were my skis, then my snowshoes and finally my ski pole when I  switched  to
an ice ax and kicked steps up hardening snow near the  very  end.  I  topped
out on the ridge at a 5500 ft notch just to the S of Pt 5586.  I  was  lucky
this was a place I could descend the other side about 100 ft to an easy  but
exhausting knee deep slushy traverse below the rocky and pinnacled ridge.  I
kept to the traverse until forced up to tiptoe on the crest  to  bypass  the
headwall of All Cr.  Once past this I dropped down again  to  contour  below
the final summit rocks and ascend up the E ridge.

A flagpole and melted out plaque in memory of Rick Green "from  the  Prairie
Boys" marked the summit (3700 ft, 6 hrs). I reveled in my surroundings,  all
the more sweet because of previous difficulties  and  uncertainty.  I  could
see Glacier and Baker and much of the  North  Cascades.  Closer  were  Three
Fingers and Whitehorse across the Sauk River.  But most impressive  was  the
N face of White Chuck just to the S. However the  views  were  beginning  to
fade.  I could see ominous weather moving my way  and  it  was  starting  to
precipitate.  It was time to go.

 The trip back to the notch was a wallow through ever  deeper  and  slushier
snow.  I faced in for the steep first bit down  from  the  notch,  then  ran
down to my skis retrieving discarded gear on  the  way.  The  ski  down  the
gully was mostly marginal in tip trapping deep slush  and  of  the  survival
style although I did get in a few turns. The traverse back to the  road  was
again pleasant and fast.  Traverses are  so  much  more  fun  on  skis  than
snowshoes. Skiing down the upper road I was struck by  the  fantastic  image
of dark storm clouds forming over Three Fingers  and  Whitehorse.  Beautiful
and foreboding both. I even heard some thunder.  The rest  of  the  way  out
was in light rain.  I took a different way down to the lower  road  avoiding
the dense trees by following an open creek drainage on foot where I  instead
fell through rotten snow into the water many times.  By now my feet were  so
wet it didn\'t matter. I also cut the  switchback  on  the  lower  road  thus
lessening the number of annoying ditches I had to cross. I  arrived  at  the
car (before dark I may add) a very happy climber.  Maybe the  skiing  wasn\'t
exactly superb but considering the way  the  day  started  I  was  certainly
satisfied with it.

Total: 8 miles, 4000 ft and 9:30 hrs.

Fay Pullen

Directions: From Darrington and Hyw 530 turn right just before the  RS  onto
Sauk Prairie Rd, then after several miles right  onto  Prairie  Mtn  Rd,  Rd
2140. This road is marked, but not well and looks like a driveway to  start.
 I missed it on my first pass. The road goes about 6 miles before ending  at
2600 ft at a big ditch
