            'tr' => '

Scarface (6180 ft - 708P - Sunrise Quad) - April 13, 2006


My original plan was to drive up the West Fork White River Rd 74 as  far  as
possible to ski up some obscure peaks on the Clear West Quad, but  the  road
was still gated at the river crossing with no snow in sight. So  it  was  on
to my backup plan. Instead I drove up Rd 75, very near  the  gate,  about  1
mile until stopped by snow at 2700 ft.  The  usual  patchy  transition  zone
lasted to 3100 ft where continuous snow took over. I continued up Rd  75  to
Rd 7530 and finally the spur road that ended at Lonesome  Lake  (6.5  miles,
2100 ft, 3 hrs).

This whole area is very ski friendly with numerous logging roads,  clearcuts
and patches of open woods that provide  excellent  skiing  under  the  right
snow conditions. Today conditions were not  ideal  with  all  the  slush  of
recent days having frozen to hard crust. But it did make for easy uphill  as
I made my across Lonesome Lake and through pleasant terrain  to  a  clearcut
and the ridge above.  On the ridge I came across a road  not  shown  on  the
map, which I followed S around Pt 5880 to its end  at  another  clearcut  on
the boundary of Mt Rainier National  Park.  A  traverse  led  to  the  final
delightful N ridge of Scarface, easily skiable all the  way  to  the  summit
(8.5 miles, 3500 ft, 5 hrs). Here I was treated to a view of the  impressive
cliffs of the E ridge that overlook Lake Eleanor, though  I  could  not  see
the lake itself. It also looked as if the S ridge could be easily skied  for
a distance, perhaps all the way to Grand Park.

It was now snowing and enough fresh had fallen, a  good  inch,  that  skiing
down the ridge was very nice indeed. On the way back I continued  to  follow
the ridge road N to more clearcuts and a gentle descent to  the  main  road.
At about 4000 ft the snow turned to rain and the rest of the way out was  on
wet, slow snow. I was very pleased my unexpected "backup" plan  turned  into
a gem. There are many opportunities for continued exploration in  this  area
and it certainly warrants return visits.

Total: 17 miles, 3600 ft and 8 hrs.

Fay Pullen
