Grand Park Pk (5840+ ft - 440P - Sunrise Quad) - April, 18 2006


After two  wonderful  ski  trips  in  a  row,  Scarface  last  Thursday  and
Elizabeth Ridge with Jim  and  Eileen  on  Sunday,  I  was  hoping  to  take
advantage of this last winter blast and powder snow and make  it  three.  Of
course you can never really recapture the magic of a  prior  trip,  but  you
can create a new and different magic.  Although I missed the wonderful  snow
by a day (or maybe just half a day or even hours), I did  get  my  magic  in
the form of good weather and views to die for. And  the  skiing  wasn\'t  all
bad. It just wasn\'t wonderful.

I was so taken by the skiing and terrain on  my  trip  up  Scarface  that  I
wanted to return to this area to explore  more  and  get  the  views  I  had
missed the first time. Then I noticed that there was a new peak above  Grand
Park that I had not climbed. So now I had a destination.

I began again up Rd 75 off the West Fork White River Rd 74. This time I  was
able to drive 1.7 miles, to 3200 ft, (.7 miles farther than  last  time)  up
the road although  it  required  putting  on  chains  to  negotiate  a  deep
snowpatch to accomplish that.  I am not sure I gained much time but it  sure
was nice not to have to walk the  mostly  bare  road  after  the  snowpatch,
especially on the way down when I was  really  tired.  I  tried  to  find  a
shortcut up Mule Cr on a spur road shown on  the  map,  but  this  road  was
ditched and overgrown.  I did cut a couple of the switchbacks  on  the  main
road but for the most part I followed my previous route to the  ridge  above
Lonesome Lk. Snow varied from frozen crust  to  powder  to  slush  depending
upon exposure.

I was forced to go over the summit of Scarface again, then descend  700  ft,
as cliffs prevented any contouring around it.  But I really didn\'t mind,  as
I wanted to ski the S ridge anyway, which had  looked  so  appealing  to  me
before. And it was very nice. Even the final descent off the ridge to the  W
in the trees was pleasant. Snow by  now  was  quite  slushy  in  the  rising
temperatures but still skiable.  I  then  contoured  through  more  pleasant
terrain to a tarn and up the E ridge to the summit of Grand  Park  Pk  (4000
ft, 6:15 hrs). Most of the  terrain  to  here  and  the  summit  itself  was
wooded, but just to the S was a spectacular viewpoint of Grand Park  and  Mt
Rainier. As I looked down on Grand Park, surely one of  my  favorite  places
in the whole of Rainier, I felt privileged to be one of the  few  people  to
ever have seen it at this time of year.

I enjoyed my magic as long as I could as  it  soon  turned  to  frustration.
Already (4:00) much of the snow was developing a pesky breakable  crust.  It
didn\'t even have to be in the shade (the sun was low  enough  it  no  longer
melted it). By the time I climbed back up  to  Scarface,  things  were  even
worse. There were still pockets of protected powder but I  was  never  quite
sure where they were.  And so the ski out was a challenge.  Even  the  upper
road had turned into breakable crust, even in  my  uphill  tracks,  and  was
very slow going. The lower road was still soft and wet, but by  the  time  I
got there it was dark. When I reached the car I  was  most  happy  for  that
extra .7 mile I didn\'t have to walk.

Total: 18 miles, 4900 ft and 11 hrs.      Fay Pullen

