            'title' => 'Natapoc Mtn (4204 ft - 2124P - Winton Quad) & Natapoc Ridge (3291 ft - 171P - Plain Quad) - April 27, 2006 
 Tumwater Mtn (4480+ ft - 2320P - Leavenworth Quad) - April 28, 2006',
            'tr' => '
Natapoc Mtn (4204 ft - 2124P - Winton Quad) & Natapoc Ridge (3291 ft - 171P
- Plain Quad) - April 27, 2006

This should have been a very nice bike ride, but  not  this  early  and  not
this year.  There was still too much snow. However, this was the time I  had
free to do this trip and so I went  for  it  anyway,  hoping  I  could  push
through the odd snowpatch  to  bike  high  enough  to  get  within  striking
distance. No such luck. I began on bike at 2120 ft on the N end of  Rd  6601
near Plain. I originally chose this road rather then the more direct S  end,
because it was a gentler climb and  because  it  went  past  Natapoc  Ridge,
which I also wanted to climb. At 2600 ft I hit a snowpatch that had  stopped
all vehicle traffic but I was able to push through it.  At  2900  ft,  where
the road turns to the N side, I hit continuous snow and all hope  was  lost.
I was too far away to  force  the  summit  on  foot.  I  turned  around  and
followed a lower spur road until also stopped by snow, but here I was  close
enough to climb Natapoc Ridge on foot. At least I had something to show  for
my effort. RT: 8 miles, 1365 ft and 3 hrs.

Not yet giving up on the day, I now tried the S end of Rd 6601  with  a  new
plan in mind. Forget the bike and drive as close as possible to  the  summit
and climb directly on foot. I ran into impassible snow at  2500  ft,  turned
around and parked at a spur road at 2300 ft. From here  I  climbed  a  steep
wooded spur ridge, ran into an old road that contoured right around  a  hill
to a powerline, and  followed  the  powerline  road  until  past  a  ravine.
Pleasant open woods with patchy snow led the rest of the way to  the  mostly
bare N ridge at 4000 ft. The summit was marked with a cairn. There  were  no
views on the wooded summit. RT: 2.5 miles, 1900 ft and 2.5 hrs.

Tumwater Mtn (4480+ ft - 2320P - Leavenworth Quad) - April 28, 2006

For this peak I was forced to use the bike  to  start,  even  though  I  was
certain I wouldn\'t get too far, as the road, just  outside  Leavenworth,  is
gated at the beginning at 1400 ft. This is a steep road, most of  which  was
too steep for me to ride up. So I pushed. At  around  2400  ft  I  ran  into
several trees across the road that required huffing and puffing to  get  the
bike over, under and around. Just past the junction with  the  4WD  road  at
3000 ft I ran into snow. So I left my bike here and headed up the  E  ridge.
This would have been very pleasant travel except for the fact  that  it  had
been recently burned and the fallen dead  trees  and  debris  made  for  all
manner of obstacles.  Rather  like  hiking  through  slash  with  the  added
delight that everything you touch turns to black soot. The last 500 feet  or
so was solid snow and much easier going. Not knowing which bump on the  main
ridge was higher I climbed both, concluding the N one the true summit.

It may have been an effort to push the bike up the road, but the  ride  down
was sweet and made it all worthwhile. RT: 6.6 mile, 3200 ft and 4 hrs.

Fay Pullen


