            'title' => 'Dark Peak - 8504 ft - 264P - Agnes Mtn Quad - May 28-31, 2006',
            'tr' => '

Dark Peak - 8504 ft - 264P - Agnes Mtn Quad - May 28-31, 2006


A long planned trip to Dome/Sinister was thwarted this Memorial Day  weekend
by bad weather, as I am  sure  were  many  other  climber\'s  trips.  Of  the
original party members, only Annette and I were free and flexible enough  to
postpone departure by a day and change the destination  to  when  and  where
the weather would be better. Dark Peak seemed a natural choice for  us.   It
was on both our must do lists (Annette had tried it 3 years earlier and  was
itching to even the score. It was her first 100 Highest  peak)  and  it  was
not so committing that we wouldn\'t feel comfortable with  just  the  two  of
us.

Day 1: So it was a last minute scramble  to  figure  out  the  logistics  of
approaching the peak. This early in the season there are only  two  shuttles
a day from Stehekin to High Bridge, at 8am and 3pm, neither  geared  to  the
hiker or climber. This weird and inconvenient schedule meant  we  needed  at
least 4 days for the climb. We caught  the  9:45  sailing  of  the  Lady  II
(there was no advantage to taking the  earlier  Lady  Express)  to  Stehekin
where we then had to wait  around  until  3:00  for  the  shuttle.  At  High
Bridge, elev 1600 ft, we met Martin and  Wendy  coming  out  after  climbing
McGregor Mtn. What a small world the world  of  climbing  is  sometimes.  We
finally started hiking the Agnes Cr Trail (PCT) at 4:15 an easy but  up  and
down 5.5 miles to pleasant Fivemile Camp, elev 2200 ft (1200 ft,  2:20  hr).
This is in the Glacier Pk Wilderness and requires no permit to camp.  Up  to
now we had had no rain but there were threatening clouds lurking  about  and
they did produce some showers during the night while we  were  snug  in  our
tent.

Day 2: The next morning was mostly sunny and we were on our way at 8:30.  We
stashed some food and unneeded items before taking off, as we  had  to  camp
here again on night 3 in order to make it to High Bridge in  time  to  catch
the 9am shuttle. We soon began running into patchy snow on  the  trail  that
clearly showed the recent very large paw prints of a very large  bear  (yes,
our stashed food was hung high in  a  tree).  This  had  us  looking  around
nervously and making extra noise but we never encountered  Mr.  Bear.  After
about a mile, the trail came very close to an impressive gorge along  the  S
Fork Agnes Cr. From this point on the trail was completely snow-covered  and
we wandered around a bit but eventually came right out at  the  bridge  over
Swamp Cr, elev 2800 (3.1 miles, 660 ft, 2 hrs).

From the  bridge  we  headed  up  the  open,  forested,  and,  surprisingly,
snowfree ridge to the right of Swamp Cr.  Soon we ran into a segment of  the
old unmaintained trail and followed this into the  creek  valley  until  all
was again lost under snow.  The  heavy  snow  cover  was  most  helpful  and
covered most of the brush which I was expecting  as  described  by  numerous
tales of horror from previous parties. We pulled into the  basin  below  the
gorgeous roaring waterfall, elev 4350 ft, at 2:00 (6.7 miles, 2250 ft,  5:20
hrs from Fivemile). We had plenty of time to lounge  around,  eat,  nap  and
eat again, but once the sun left the basin it quickly became chilly  and  we
were happy to turn in early at 7:00.  Tomorrow would be a big day.   We  had
to climb the peak, break camp and get back to  Fivemile  or  chance  missing
the shuttle and taking another whole day (or hiking the additional 12  miles
to Stehekin).

Day 3: Summit Day dawned cold and clear with crampons required  right  away.
We started at 5:30 to the left of the waterfall following the  base  of  the
cliff up a steep broad gully almost to its end where a break led back  right
into the trees to the upper basin, elev 5000 ft.  A  complete  view  of  the
route was now before us and it looked  very  good  indeed.  We  crossed  the
basin to the base of the main gully below the Dark Glacier  where  we  roped
up. We worked our way up the right side of the gully  trying  to  avoid  the
jumble of recent avalanche debris filling most of it and  unto  a  rib  that
offered a direct way up a short steep step to a flatter area  above  beneath
a small rock wall.  Up to now the snow had been  either  perfect  cramponing
hard frozen snow or breakable crust, with both offering good  footing.  Then
unexpectedly in the middle of the step I ran into about  10  feet  of  water
ice hidden under several inches of unconsolidated new snow. This  pitch  got
my adrenaline flowing as I chopped both hand and footholds until  I  reached
easier snow again.

Above the ice pitch, a long easy traverse led across several  new  avalanche
tracks (we were thankful several days of sunny weather  had  stabilized  the
snow) to the base of the upper icefall  which  looked  as  if  it  could  be
bypassed either on the left or the right.  We elected for the left,  hugging
the bottom of a rock cliff as it was in the  shade  and  we  felt  the  snow
would be firmer.  Already the snow was beginning to soften in  the  sun  and
in places we were starting to break through the  crust.  We  then  traversed
the bowl above the icefall to the 8200 ft saddle on the  W  ridge.  A  short
steep tiptop along the edge of a moat abyss and we were on  the  broad  open
slopes leading to the final rocky S ridge and the summit (4300 ft, 6 hrs).

I was very puzzled by the wicked  ridge  leading  S  to  an  obviously  much
higher peak until it dawned on me that it was Bonanza.  What  an  impressive
peak that is from this vantage point. I knew we had to  be  on  the  summit,
still I was very happy when we found the register confirming this to be  the
case (Remember Dark does not have much prominence and  although  it  appears
very peak-like and worthy from the N,  once  on  the  summit  it  is  rather
dwarfed by Bonanza and not much more than a bump on the ridge.) But I  doubt
I was happier than Annette who I believe was ecstatic to  finally  make  the
summit.

I think I recognized every single name in the register, not that there  were
that many. I do believe only those pursuing  the  Bulger  100  Highest  List
climb Dark Pk. The register was placed on 9/3/95 by  Chris  Weber  and  Dave
Creeden followed by  Peggy  Goldman  and  Jim  Quade  6/27/98;  the  Bailles
6/18/99; Mike Torok and Dale Flynn 6/18/00;  Don  Beavon  7/27/01  (he  also
climbed Agnes, The  Needle  and  Heather  Ridge  on  the  same  trip);  Paul
Michelson, Martin Shetter and  Stu  Frinke  6/1/03;  Paul  Klenke  and  Mark
Iffrig (climbing from Fivemile in  one  day)  5/26/05;  and  last  the  ever
persistent Roy McMurtrey 7/18/05 after 5 tries in the same year.

The views from the top were stunning, with too many mountains  to  identify.
I picked out the most obvious and left it at that.  We could not tarry  long
on top as we still had miles to go before we slept.  Once  below  the  upper
icefall we removed crampons for the rest of  the  way  down  as  they  began
balling up badly. We avoided the ice pitch by taking a longer route  to  the
W down through waist high avalanche deposits and then back E to  our  uphill
tracks. We were in camp by 3:30, had a hot drink, ate, packed  up  and  were
ready to go again in an hour. We had a little trouble  finding  the  segment
of trail leading out of the Swamp Cr valley and  more  trouble  finding  the
main trail by the gorge and we were very tired and  running  out  of  steam,
but we did make it to Fivemile before dark, barely,  at  9:00  (11.7  miles,
4400 ft, 15:30 hrs total for the day). We had a hot meal before  turning  in
at 10:30.

Day 4: We rolled out of bed at 5:10 and left at 5:40  without  breakfast  to
assure plenty of time to make the shuttle.  We needn\'t have  worried  as  we
arrived at High Bridge a little after 8:00. The shuttle showed at 8:45  with
only two people aboard and the driver.  These were the first people  we  had
seen since leaving 3 days earlier. With nothing left now but time until  the
2:00 boat, we enjoyed the company of the couple  (from  Tennessee)  and  the
personable driver, an older gentleman in his 4th year driving the  bus,  who
gave a running commentary  of  the  history  of  the  Stehekin  Valley.   We
stopped at Rainbow Falls, the old one room schoolhouse and  the  bakery.  We
filled our tummies at the  restaurant  after  a  wonderful  hot,  and  free,
shower (clean clothes were stashed at the  ranger  station).  We  still  had
time to kill.  We missed the sailing of  the  earlier  Lady  Express,  which
would start daily runs on June 1, by one day. No,  the  schedule  makers  do
not make it easy to climb peaks in this area this time of year in  a  timely
manner.

Total: 28.4 miles and 8400 ft in 4 days.

Fay Pullen




