            'tr' => '
Klawatti Pk (8485 ft) & Austera Pk (8334 ft) - Forbidden Pk Quad - June 20-
22, 2006

After an absence of over a year, I was thrilled to  once  again  climb  with
Linda. We make a very compatible team.  She  too  was  excited  to  get  out
again, although I think this trip was perhaps a bit  more  than  would  have
been ideal for her first outing in a long time. But she knows  me  well  and
really didn\'t expect anything less.

Day 1: In any event we started up the  climber\'s  trail  to  Eldorado  (elev
2200 ft) at 10:00   (after  stopping  for  the  appropriate  permit  at  the
Marblemount RS). Right off the bat the multiple log crossing of the  Cascade
River got the adrenaline flowing as we wrestled with balancing  packs  heavy
with climbing gear.  The trail  on  the  other  side  then  wasted  no  time
climbing steeply up through woods 1500 ft to a  series  of  tedious  boulder
fields.  We began running into patches of snow at the top of  the  last  one
and by the time we broke out into the open basin above, snow was  continuous
and deep. The high peaks and ridges were all in fog despite  a  forecast  of
zero percent chance of rain. We followed tracks to  the  ridge  crossing  at
6200 ft and down the other side on melting  out  slabs  (tricky  with  heavy
packs) onto the snow below the Eldorado Glacier.  Here we met a party  of  3
coming down from Eldorado after climbing it in a day and then  we  were  all
alone. A long seemingly endless plod up moderate slopes with  packs  getting
heavier and us getting more tired brought us to the usual  camping  spot  on
the E ridge of Eldorado at 5:30, elev 7600 ft (5 miles, 5600 ft,  7:30  hr).
We found a nice mostly bare tent site but no running water. A  cold  blowing
fog kept everything frozen solid. We would have to melt snow for water.

Day 2: It froze even more overnight and we began at 7:20 with  crampons  on.
We were right at fog level, with it drifting in and out. Below was  a  solid
layer of marine air.  We had had a good look at Klawatti  the  previous  day
before reaching camp and it had looked frightfully  steep  to  me  with  the
moat beginning to appear part way up the snowfinger. But I knew better  than
to  freak  out  at  a  distance  view  where   perspective   is   frequently
foreshortened. Today we had enough of a view  to  plot  our  long  (2  mile)
traverse across the Inspiration Glacier  to  Klawatti  Col.  It  was  really
quite straight forward with only a few crevasses in appearance, but I  think
we were both feeling a little nervous as a lone 2-person rope team  on  such
a large glacier.  But  the  cramponing  was  excellent  and  we  arrived  at
Klawatti Col in an hour.

After a rest and stashing extra gear and water at the col, we  traversed  to
the base of the snowfinger. It didn\'t look as bad as it had from a  distance
and the moat appeared to be crossable on the right side. I  led  off  across
the moat after placing our one and only picket, using two ice axes.  It  was
quite steep but the snow was excellent and I was  able  to  kick  reassuring
deep steps. At the full length of our 50m rope I reached a rock  band  above
and was able to get in  a  piece  of  protection.  Climbing  simultaneously,
Linda reached the rock band before I was able to get to  the  next  one  and
place another piece of protection. Another picket would have been nice.  But
the snow was good and neither of us  felt  uncomfortable,  so  we  continued
climbing simultaneously. Still, I felt better when I finally  got  something
in after another half rope length. A further  short  traverse  left  and  we
were on the bare rock of the S ridge where  an  easy  scramble  led  to  the
summit at 10:50 (1050 ft, 3:30 hr). There was no register  so  I  left  one.
From the top we did have a fairly good view of Austera and it looked  to  be
easy going to the summit rocks, just smooth crevasse less snow slopes.

We put crampons back on to go down and used the same protection as  the  way
up for running belays, but basically we just downclimbed facing in.  At  the
rock band above the moat, I set up a belay and brought Linda down, then  she
belayed me over the moat (our rope was too short to set up  a  rappel).  The
moat was  already  softening  in  the  intermittent  sun  and  our  previous
crossing was no longer trustworthy. I probed and stamped finding  what  firm
footing there was before taking a big step/jump across, and then  I  belayed
Linda across from the picket. I doubt this moat will be  crossable  on  snow
anymore this year.

Back at the col, it was now  completely  fogged  in.  We  removed  crampons,
picked up our stashed geared and crossed the col to the  McAllister  Glacier
to traverse below the W face of Klawatti to the small notch on the  N  ridge
leading to the Klawatti Glacier.  At the  notch  we  were  confronted  by  a
steep wind sculpted snow cliff on one side and a short 10 ft rock  cliff  on
the other.  The  rock  cliff  was  still  downclimbable,  but  we  used  the
assistance of a small 25 ft rope I had brought along just for this  purpose.
Once across the notch we were in sunshine again for the  rest  of  the  easy
way to the base of Austera. Crossing the ridge leading to the false  summit,
we got our first look at the true summit and the chockstone  chimney.   Once
again from a distance it looked frightful,  but  after  dropping  down  ugly
loose rock (which really was frightful)  to  the  base  of  the  chimney  it
didn\'t look too bad. There was a bit of snow and ice in the chimney,  but  I
was able to sling the chockstone itself for  protection  and  bodily  pulled
myself over the top. It was basically one  move.  Above  the  chockstone,  a
crawl along a moat and easy solid rock led to the summit at 4:00  (1800  ft,
8:40 hr). Again there was no register but I had already used the only one  I
brought.

We downclimbed to  the  chockstone  and  then  rappelled  over  it.  We  had
reasonable visibility the rest of the way back, arriving at Klawatti col  at
6:20 and camp at 7:50 (9 miles, 2250 ft, 12:30 hrs). But  camp  was  in  the
shade and cold and still no running water  was  available.  We  melted  more
snow and ate and drank as long as we could until forced into the comfort  of
our warm sleeping bags.

Day 3: We awoke late (7:00) the next morning to sunshine on our tent  and  a
bluebird day, or so we thought. We were able to lounge in the sun for a  few
hours but a thick layer of marine air below  gradually  rose  until  by  the
time we left at 10:00 we were in the fog again. It stayed foggy  and  cloudy
all the way down to the car (5 miles, 200 ft, 4:30 hrs.)

Total: 19 miles and 8050 ft in 3 days.

Fay Pullen


