            'tr' => '
Tupshin Pk (8320+ ft - Stehekin Quad) & Devore Pk (8360+ ft - Mt Lyall
Quad) - June 25-28, 2006

Day 1: Bird Cr Camp. One of the major  disadvantages  of  climbing  solo  is
that you have to carry everything yourself. This was made  very  evident  to
me as I struggled up the Devore Cr Trail weighed down with  some  12  pounds
of technical gear. Fortunately, the weather was sunny and hot,  so  I  could
pare down the weight of personal gear to the bare minimum  clothing,  my  1-
pound sleeping bag and a bivy tent. Still my  pack  weight  was  pushing  40
pounds, heavy for me. Also unfortunately, the weather  was  sunny  and  hot.
Very hot.  By the time I  took  the  9:20  Field\'s  Point  Lady  Express  to
Stehekin and the 11:15 slow shuttle (Surprisingly, the driver remembered  me
from Dark Pk a month earlier, but then I  guess  there  are  not  that  many
little old gray-haired lady climbers about.) to Harlequin Bridge, elev  1200
ft, I found myself starting in the heat of the day. Then I  wandered  around
on unmarked roads searching for the start of the Stehekin R Trail,  which  I
finally found by heading for the airfield and skirting  around  it  until  I
came to the main trail on the other side. Four flat miles  later  I  finally
started up Devore Cr. I had tried to take a float plane directly  to  Weaver
Pt, but the flooding of the Stehekin R in May of  this  year  had  destroyed
the dock there so I was out of luck. It was now 2:30.

I vastly under estimated  the  time  it  would  take  to  get  to  Bird  Cr,
supposedly only 4 miles. With my heavy  pack  and  the  enervating  heat,  I
plodded slowly upward. At least the first section of trail was pretty as  it
switchbacked through open grassy glades and  alongside  a  deep  gorge.  But
higher up where it entered the valley it was so overgrown I had to  feel  my
way with my feet, which slowed me down even more. I began  to  despair  that
my idea of soloing these two peaks was  not  such  a  good  one.  I  finally
pulled into the most welcome sight of Bird Cr Camp, elev 4200  ft,  at  6:30
(8 miles, 3200 ft, 6 hrs).

Day 2: Tupshin Pk. I was following the excellent directions by  Paul  Klenke
on summitpost.org for both peaks. Good thing I had those as the ones in  the
Becky, Goldman and Stephenson books were all misleading, vague or  downright
wrong.  Beginning from camp at 6:30,  I  headed  up  and  rightward  through
pleasant mostly brushfree woods until I came to a  major  stream  gully.   I
then essentially followed the rib to the left of this creek  on  easy  semi-
open terrain to 6800 ft until I could drop  slightly  into  the  snow  basin
below Tupshin. I followed the snow to high below the E face where  the  rock
climbing began at 7600 ft (3500 ft, 4:30 hrs) on a rightward leading ramp.

I tried to follow Paul\'s direction, but somehow got off  track.  No  matter,
the climbing was easy and well within my comfort level. I scrambled  up  the
ramp and probably followed it too far. I saw no rappel anchors so just  kept
scrambling. From the end of the ramp I worked my way back  left  toward  the
center of the face where I reached my level of confidence and  roped  up.  I
think this was somewhere in the middle of Paul\'s pitch 3 as above it I  came
to the pitch 4 anchor (it was reassuring that I was now  on  route)  at  the
base of his chimney/right facing corner. I didn\'t  like  the  looks  of  the
corner and went up the broken face maybe 10-20 to the right where I  thought
I could get in better protection. I went up the wall and  then  left  almost
the full length of my 50 m rope to the last (pitch 5) rappel anchor. I  left
my rope here and scrambled the rest of the way to the summit at  1:15  (4150
ft, 6:45 hr) Being able to scramble so much saved me  immeasurable  time.  I
had originally thought I would have to rope solo 5 pitches,  which  meant  I
would have 10 pitches to climb  (each  pitch  climbed  twice).  I  ended  up
belaying only 2 pitches, and I only had to climb  the  first  one  twice.  I
found the rock on Tupshin excellent with plenty of  good  holds  and  places
for pro. I enjoyed the climbing greatly.

The original register was on top but it was mostly illegible.  A few  pieces
of new paper had been added on which were the names Mitch  Blanton  6/05/99,
Paul Klenke and Mark  Iffrig  6/29/05,  Roy  McMurtrey  8/15/05,  and  Scott
Stephenson and Bongi 6/6/06.

I downclimbed to the last rappel anchor (#5), then downclimbed on belay  (my
rope was still attached at the bottom and out the full length so I  couldn\'t
use it for a rappel to begin) until I had enough free rope  I  could  rappel
to anchor #4. Somehow I once again  missed  anchor  #3  so  set  up  my  own
rappel. I found anchor #2 on a horn to the right, which got me to  the  ramp
where I now found anchor #1 on a bush. I rappelled down the ramp and set  up
another rappel to reach the snow and my ice ax.  The  rappels  had  taken  2
hours. I was back in camp with no further problems by 6:00 (4200  ft,  11:30
hr).

Day 3: Devore Pk.  If Tupshin had gone  better  than  expected,  Devore  was
worse, although it started out well enough. Again  I  began  at  6:30,  this
time going straight uphill just to the  right  of  Bird  Cr.  I  essentially
stayed in the woods most of the way just above the brush line in  the  creek
bottom and travel was really quite good. I never came to the  rock  wall  at
4900 ft mentioned by Paul however I did cross a short patch of brush with  a
side creek below a wall, which he did not mention.   Perhaps  he  was  above
this. The only other real brush was  just  above  the  lower  basin,  but  I
followed Paul\'s directions by going high  and  it  too  was  very  short.  I
emerged into the gorgeous open  5800  ft  upper  basin  with  its  beautiful
waterfalls at 9:00 (1600 ft, 2:30 hr).

I found a convenient log to cross the much smaller yet still  roaring  creek
and started up the obvious snow gully on the other side to exit  the  basin.
The snow was in the shade and although not hard enough to make me  wish  for
crampons it was hard enough for me to take care. At the head  of  the  gully
at 6400 ft I crossed a bowl and climbed to its head at 7000  ft.  The  upper
part was somewhat hazardous with rotten snow between rock outcrops  undercut
by running water.  Above I was in the lake basin and thought the rest  would
be clear sailing, but as I looked at  the  saddle  of  the  E  ridge  I  was
dismayed to see most its length guarded by impassible cornices. I  saw  only
two possible ways up, one to the left up two disconnected  outcroppings  and
one to the right threading between the cornice and a  short  rock  wall.   I
headed to the right one first as it was more direct, but  as  I  approached,
the snow looked frightfully steep and I couldn\'t really tell if there was  a
passage around the corner through the rock. So I headed left. This  was  not
pleasant either as I scrambled up wet slippery loose rock and  rotten  snow.
I made it to the ridge but I decidedly did not want to go down that way.

Once on the ridge I easily followed along its crest, then on the  left  side
on loose scree to below the rock towers Paul calls  "the  Bottles".  I  must
admit they did look like bottles. I passed the bottles on the right on  snow
and crossed a notch to the S side. A  rising  traverse  scrambling  class  3
rock trying to avoid remnant rotten snow patches led to  another  notch  and
the  SW  side  of  Devore.  I  could  now  see  the  false  summit  and  the
"unavoidable 20 foot class 4 step". Darn! It looked higher than 20  ft.   It
also looked harder than class 4. Getting closer  didn\'t  make  it  look  any
easier. It was frankly more than I expected and felt harder than anything  I
had done on Tupshin, but maybe that was just because I wasn\'t  prepared  for
it or was getting tired. But at least I  found  several  cracks  to  provide
protection, which justified me bringing a small rack (I pared it  down  from
what I took on Tupshin). I tied off my rope at the rappel anchor  above  and
continued ropeless as I didn\'t want to have to climb that thing twice.  That
was a mistake. As I rounded the corner of the exposed but easy ledge  around
the false summit I saw the supposedly class 3 summit gully.  It sure  looked
harder to me. At that point I should have gone back  for  the  rope,  but  I
didn\'t. The gully wasn\'t as hard as it looked but  it  did  have  two  short
what I would consider class 4 steps in it and I  knew  they  would  give  me
trouble going down.

I reached the summit at 2:15 (4200 ft, 7:45 hrs). The original register  was
also on this peak but it was legible.  It was placed 7/28/1940 by the  first
ascent party. I also noted Paul Michelson and Martin Shetter  9/2/95,  Peggy
Goldman, Mike Torok and Dale Flynn 6/15/96  and  the  same  people  who  had
signed in on Tupshin.

As expected, descending the summit  gully  gave  me  trouble  and  I  dinked
around looking for an easier way (there wasn\'t one)  and  using  the  slings
and pro I had with me to set up a short belay.   But  there  were  no  solid
anchors and in the end I just downclimbed carefully after wasting a  lot  of
time. I then rappelled the 4th class step. I  reversed  everything  back  to
the E ridge saddle where I decided to rappel  down  the  rock  wall  of  the
right option of the way up. I found a solid horn for an  anchor  and  I  was
happy to have lugged my 50m rope along as it got me down the  wall  and  the
steepest part of the snow to more gentle slopes  below.  Fast  plungstepping
and glissading worked until the rim of the bowl where more care  was  needed
to get down. The final snow gully was in the shade once  again  (or  perhaps
still) so care was needed here also. I was very happy to reach the  relative
safety of the upper basin at 4:45. Two hours later I was back in camp  (4200
ft, 12:15 hrs).

Day 4: Successful Retreat.  I got up relatively early so I  could  leave  by
7:00 to catch the 12:30 shuttle. The trail did seem shorter on the way  down
but still longer than 4 miles and it took me 2:40 hr  of  steady  hiking  to
reach the  river  trail.  Interestingly,  parts  of  the  river  trail  were
slightly under water now as the river continued to rise  and  flood  in  the
very warm weather, but it was no great problem. I reached  Harlequin  Bridge
at 11:30 (8 miles, 300 ft, 4 hrs) with plenty of time  to  wash  up  in  the
river before the shuttle came. It was the same friendly  driver  and  I  was
the only one on the bus. We stopped at the bakery  where  I  ordered  a  ham
sandwich which I devoured in  record  time.  I  caught  the  2:00  Lady  II,
sleeping most of the  way  back  and  dreaming  of  wonderful  (and  not  so
wonderful) rock climbing.  I stopped for  delicious  actually  tree  ripened
fruit at a stand in Entiat and had another meal at the  Big  Y  CafÃ©  before
making the final drive home.

Total: 24 miles and 11900 ft in 4 days.

Fay Pullen

















