            'tr' => '

Hozomeen Mtn, S Pk (8003 ft - 1483P - Skagit Pk Quad) - July1-3, 2006


I really had no idea what I was getting into  when  I  first  accepted  Mike
Torok\'s invitation to climb both Hozomeen Pks. I had vaguely  heard  of  the
higher N Hozomeen and I knew it was not trivial but I had done  no  research
and had very little detail. Of the S Pk I knew next to nothing.  Then  as  I
began to look at the map and route descriptions  and  actual  (intimidating)
pictures of the mountain, it slowly dawned  on  me  that  this  would  be  a
challenging ascent, particularly of the harder S Pk.

Day 1: Rounding out the party were  Jim  Brisbine,  Dave  Creeden  and  Beth
Blattenberger. We drove  in  two  separate  cars,  through  Canada,  to  the
Hozomeen Lake TH (back in the USA) elev 1700 ft  and  began  at  11:15.  The
trail was in good shape, except for one very large blowdown, and we  covered
the 3.6 miles to the 2800 ft lake in 1:40 hrs despite the  oppressive  heat.
We had a good view of the mountain from the lake  and  could  pick  out  the
gully we were aiming for that led to the col  between  the  SW  and  S  Pks,
planning on climbing the S Pk first. It took a good 1:30 hrs to  get  around
the lake on the E side through moderate brush and reach a dry boulder  gully
to the N. Not recognizing  this  as  the  gully  we  wanted  to  follow  (we
expected water to be in it)  we  continued  traversing  N  and  up.  Finally
realizing our mistake we headed back S again,  still  on  an  upward  trend,
through more difficult brush. By the time we came back to the gully  it  was
too cliffy to enter so we continued up  very  steep  hillside  along  its  N
edge. By now the heat was taking its toll, we were all dragging and we  were
running out of water.

Somewhere around 7:00 and 4800 ft things became critical.  We were  all  out
of water, we hadn\'t been able to get into the gully  and  the  hillside  was
too steep to set up a camp. Our first priority was water, so we dropped  our
packs while the guys searched for a way to  get  into  the  gully,  carrying
everyone\'s water bottles. Beth and I stayed behind so they  could  find  the
packs again and while waiting I looked around for any feasible bivy spot.  A
short ways uphill I found a cluster of boulders in the woods that offered  a
few minimal semi-flat spots.  It wasn\'t great but it was better  than  where
we had dropped the packs. Meanwhile the guys had found a way down  into  the
main gully where a dry gully entered from the left,  and  40  minutes  later
returned with enough of the life saving liquid to get us through the  night.
We set up camp, elev 4950 ft (3300ft, 8:30 hr), such as it was, had  a  cold
dinner not even bothering to heat water, and turned in at 9:30.  It  was  so
warm we slept much of the night on top of our  sleeping  bags  (but  in  the
bivy sacks for protection from the bugs).

Day 2: We started the next morning at 5:45, with daypacks, by following  the
guy\'s previous route into  the  gully,  where  we  refilled  all  the  water
bottles. It was now possible to follow the gully up.  We  emerged  from  the
bouldery gully at 7:30, elev 5800 ft, into an open basin and worked our  way
up rubblely slabs toward the SW Col. We were all surprised with  how  little
snow there was. Near the top the terrain steepened. A  broad  ledge  led  to
the wide col, but for some reason we were tricked to head for a more  direct
notch to the left of a 7300 ft knob on the ridge line. This was not  a  good
idea but by the time we realized it we were too far above the ledge to  want
to descend. So we ended up  climbing  class  3-4  rotten  rock  up  the  rib
leading to the top of the knob. Somewhere in here Jim was  almost  clobbered
by a huge rock.

Once on top of the knob, at 10:00, we finally had our first view  of  the  S
Pk. What we saw was not encouraging. It looked horrific to  me  and  no  one
could see an obvious or even reasonable  route.   In  a  moment  of  supreme
hopeful optimism Mike drolly stated, "Well,  it  must  lay  back!"   We  all
burst out laughing. From the knob we descended the  short  distance  to  the
notch and then down into  a  gully  several  hundred  feet  until  we  could
traverse to up and over the next rib. Here we ran into the first snow.  More
rock and snow traverses on the other side put us below the  S  face  of  the
peak and incredibly loose rotten awful cruddy class 3-4 ledges, gullies  and
ramps. It was very unpleasant stuff and rockfall  was  a  constant  problem.
After a couple hundred feet of  this,  generally  working  our  way  to  the
right, the terrain steepened to class 4+ low class 5 unprotectable rock  and
we began to question the wisdom of proceeding on this line. I  for  one  had
reached my level of comfort and I think several others  were  also  at  that
point or fast approaching it.

This was the low point of the climb. We were in very dangerous  terrain  and
saw no obvious way out of it.  Prospects were bleak indeed. I would have  to
say Dave saved the day.  Unwilling to give up,  he  traversed  back  to  the
left and found a hidden gully/ledge system that, although  still  loose  and
unpleasant, was much better than the way we had  been  going.  Part  of  the
problem was that we had no good route description to help out.  Beckey\'s  is
very confusing.  The key is that you have to go  to  the  notch  in  the  SW
Ridge. Once we made it to  the  notch  we  essentially  followed  the  ridge
crest, which does indeed "lay back", at least enough  so  it  is  climbable.
Jim lead one pitch up a groove that did have a  few  cracks  for  protection
and fixed a line for us to follow on prussik. We used another fixed line  on
one other short exposed section, but for the  most  part  we  scrambled  the
mostly class 4 rock unroped. There simply  was  not  enough  time  to  belay
everything and the lack of good protection  and  the  loose  rock  where  it
would be more of a liability than a help precluded the use of a rope.

And then we came to the 12 ft 5.6 step. 12 ft can seem awfully high when  it
is steep and difficult and unprotectable (we could  find  no  place  to  put
pro). We all stood at the base waffling and hoping someone else  would  take
the lead. Again Dave saved the day, and after a false start, swarmed  up  it
in one magnificent push. The rest of  us  followed  on  belay.  I  found  it
difficult but did manage to climb it without help from the rope  other  than
psychological. And that was it. The rest was an easy scramble to  the  broad
summit. Though, least you get too overconfident at this point, I was  almost
done in by rockfall in the final gully  when  several  rocks  cascaded  down
upon me. Most harmlessly hit my helmet but one small one did get me  in  the
shoulder, fortunately with no great harm. It was partially my own fault  for
following too closely below the person above me  in  my  zeal  to  make  the
summit.

We summited at 3:00 (3900 ft, 9:15 hr) where we found  a  register  in  very
good shape inside a glass jar. There were only two  entries;  one  for  1990
and one for 1993. Holy Smokes! No one else had  climbed  this  peak  for  13
years! I had no idea it was climbed  so  infrequently.  We  were  even  more
elated at our success. But our climb wasn\'t over yet.  We still had  to  get
down, no trivial thing.

We rappelled the step and the groove,  downclimbing  all  the  rest  to  the
notch. Then we set up two double rope rappels down the  cruddy  ledges  that
got us all the way to the snow and the traverse and climb  back  up  to  the
knob notch and the knob. From the knob we descended all the way to  the  col
where we picked up the easy ledge (we really should have come up this  way).
Then it was just a seemingly endless descent down the slabs  and  the  gully
on loose rock where you had to stay ever vigilant to avoid disaster. At  our
entry into the gully, we washed up, soaked our aching feet, cooled  off  and
replenished our water.  We got all hot and sweaty again on the final 200  ft
up to our bivy, which at this point was looking pretty good to  us  (my  how
standards can go down when you are desperate). We all dragged into camp  one
at a time somewhere around 9:45 (4400 ft, 16 hr) just before dark.   We  did
take the time to heat water for a hot meal, finally going  to  bed  sometime
after 11:00.

Day 3: There was some discussion,  but  not  a  whole  lot.  It  was  almost
understood we were all too fried and beat to give the N Pk  a  try.  All  we
wanted was to get down to Ross Lake for a refreshing dip. From our  bivy  we
headed straight W downhill, somehow missing much of the  brush  of  the  way
up, until we crossed Hozomeen Cr. We then contoured as well as  possible  to
hit the trail maybe a mile  or  so  from  the  TH.  We  did  run  into  some
unpleasantness in the creek bottom, but it was much better than  going  back
around the lake. We were somewhat guided  to  the  trail  by  the  sound  of
chainsaws as the Park Service was cutting  out  the  huge  blowdown  on  the
trail as we went by. We hit the TH at11:50 (100 ft 3:45 hr).

We did cool off in  Ross  Lake,  then  had  a  late  lunch/early  supper  in
Bellingham before officially calling a close to  the  trip.   I  was  really
reluctant for it all to end. This is one trip I will  remember  for  a  long
time.

Total: Maybe 12 miles and 7800 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen

