            'tr' => '
Mt Ballard (8340 ft - 780P), Cady Pt (6542 ft - 582P) and Pk 7385 (585P) -
Azurite Pk Quad - July 8-10, 2006

I had missed bagging Ballard when Annette and I climbed  Azurite  in  August
of 2005.  We were wiped out by the horrid, and non-existent above the  mine,
Mill Cr Trail and ran out of time and energy to do another peak.  So  I  was
eager  to  return  for  another   try.    The   peak   had   looked   fairly
straightforward  going  upslope  from  the  Azurite  Mine.    I   considered
approaching from the E over Cady Pass  this  time  and  sparing  myself  the
agonies of the Mill Cr Trail again, but the much longer drive put me off.

Day 1:  So once again I headed out from the Canyon Cr TH off  Hwy  20,  elev
1900 ft, at 10:50. The Chancellor Trail (as the trail that  goes  up  Canyon
Cr is called) is  still  officially  closed  after  the  junction  with  the
Boulder Cr Trail, 5  miles  in,  presumably  because  of  minor  sliding  of
portions of the trail as it descends steep hillside to  cross  Mill  Cr.  It
was no worse than last year and is certainly passable on foot with care  and
I arrived at the Mill Cr Trail junction, elev 2800 ft,  at  2:20  (6  miles,
1900 ft, 3.5 hr).

Now, because I wanted to go to inviting looking Cady Pass and  add  Cady  Pt
and Pk 7385 to the itinerary, I headed uphill toward the W ridge of the  Pt.
My pack was blessedly light compared to my previous  several  hard  climbing
trips.  The only climbing gear I carried was a very  short,  light  ice  axe
and a thin 60-foot scramble rope. The axe was never needed  but  I  did  use
the rope once and it gave me a psychological boost the rest of the time.  So
I climbed fairly easily through the mostly  brush  free  open  woods.   Then
what should I run into but an old trail. This was obviously  a  built  trail
that switchbacked back and forth across the ridge. Since I also ran into  an
old telephone wire I\'m guessing this trail led to the lookout that was  once
on Cady Pt. It was in reasonably good shape to begin, although the  resident
animal population did not take kindly  to  switchbacks  and  had  their  own
route straight up cutting across them, and it facilitated travel for a  1000
ft or so. Then I lost it in  a  snowbrushy  old  burn.  Some  unpleasantness
ensued before I broke out into open meadowy alpine terrain. The rest of  the
route was a ridge rambler\'s delight marred only by the ugly scar of the  old
mine road crossing Cady Pass. I topped out on Cady  Pt  at  6:15  (5500  ft,
7:25 hr).

From the Pt I wandered through idyllic meadows on the broad  ridge  to  Cady
Pass. It was so gorgeous I had to keep pinching myself to make  sure  I  was
not dreaming. I had originally planned to climb Pk 7385 and then  head  down
to a camp at the mine. But it was getting late, Pk 7385 looked a  long  ways
off and it was so beautiful I didn\'t want to hurry or leave.  There  were  a
few snow patches around to supply water so I decided to camp on  the  ridge.
How could I not? Flat roomy places to bivy, water nearby and  views  to  die
for.  After S Hozomeen last week what a concept! I found my  ideal  spot  at
7:20 and set up camp, elev 6000 ft (9.5 miles, 5500 ft, 8.5 hr)  enjoying  a
leisurely dinner in my picturesque surroundings.

Day 2: I started at 6:40 for Pk 7385, which presented  an  appealing  aspect
from my camp.  There was a few hundred feet of easy scrambling getting up  a
buttress but for the most part this was another rambler\'s  delight  directly
along the ridgecrest.  I reached the top at 8:10 (1.5 miles, 1500 ft,  1:30)
where the summit cairn was adorned by a broken shovel. Who but miners  would
carry a shovel up here?  I had a naÃ¯ve thought that perhaps I  could  follow
the ridge all the way to Ballard and thus save myself the descent into  Mill
Cr and allow another night in my idyllic spot, but one look and  I  knew  it
would not be possible. Darn! But then I really knew that would be  the  case
just by looking at the map. There was no help for it. So  I  broke  camp  at
10:00 and followed  the  mine  road  down.  I  was  soon  so  bored  by  the
interminable switchbacks and low gradient that I cut the  switchbacks  until
increasing brush forced me to stay on the track. Last year a dozer had  been
along the road smoothing things out and trampling down the brush.   No  such
luck this year and already lower down the brush was  closing  in  again  and
washouts cutting across as Nature reclaimed what was rightfully hers. I  saw
no signs that anyone had been this way, on machine or  foot,  since  Annette
and I. Except for bears.  There was bear scat  everywhere.  In  fact  coming
off of Pk 7385 I had come across fresh  bear  tracks  in  the  snow  -  very
fresh, as they hadn\'t been there on the way up.

I pulled into the campsite right next to the old mine  building,  elev  4600
ft, at 12:00 (4.5 miles, 500 ft, 2 hrs from camp 1). I was setting  up  camp
when I heard a great crash and rattling of corrugated metal from inside  the
shack. Something or someone big must surely  be  making  such  a  racket.  A
bear? A miner\'s ghost? Going to investigate it  turned  out  to  be  nothing
more than an innocuous marmot making noise all  out  of  proportion  to  its
size. I was just glad it wasn\'t a bear.

I left at 12:30 to climb Ballard, climbing up the left  side  of  the  large
open creek gully just up the road from camp. A short initial  class  3  wall
led past the first waterfalls, then it was  just  a  matter  of  working  up
endless class 2 loose rock  ledges  and  gullies  and  scree,  easy  if  not
pleasant. About half way up, I suddenly  noticed  that  my  blue  skies  had
clouded up and it looked as if it could  rain,  but  all  it  ever  did  was
sprinkle lightly. The clouds and few drops actually  felt  good  and  cooled
things off a bit.  At 6800 ft I crossed the creek  on  a  snow  remnant  and
worked right to the shoulder of  a  rib.   A  thousand  more  feet  of  very
unpleasant moveable scree and small talus led  to  the  base  of  the  rocky
summit ridge. A short class 3 section, with  maybe  a  few  class  4  moves,
brought me to the ridge itself and a look at the final summit  rocks.  Whoa!
This was a little more than the walkup I had expected.  It  reminded  me  of
Azurite, with ugly gullies and a series of pinnacles and me not  sure  which
was the highest, only on a smaller scale.

I worked along the base of the pinnacles, then up  a  gully  and  definitely
class 4 wall to the ridge line again, crossed the top  of  the  gully  at  a
notch, and climbed the next pinnacle to the  N.  Darn,  there  was  still  a
higher one farther N. Back down, traverse to another notch, up a  short  but
exposed class 4 step above the notch and I was on  top  at  4:40  (2  miles,
3800 ft, 4:10 from camp 2). I was surprised not to find a  register  in  the
summit cairn, but I had brought one to leave just in case.

I spent 20 minutes on top, then began down.   I  carefully  downclimbed  the
first class 4 step to the notch, but used my short rope on the  lower  class
4 wall. Then it was just reversing all the tedious loose  scree,  talus  and
gullies, slipping and sliding as I went.  To feet still not fully  recovered
from the battering they took on S  Hozomeen,  it  was  painful  business.  I
hobbled into camp at 8:00 (7:30 hrs)  with  badly  bruised  heels  and  feet
wondering how or if I would ever be able to make  the  10.5  miles  out  the
next day. (11.5 miles, 5800 ft, 13:20 hr for the day).

Day 3: I gratefully slept in till after 7:00 and started down the mine  road
at 8:30. At 9:00 I came to the "junction"  with  the  Mill  Cr  Trail.  This
junction is marked with a faded orange flag  but  there  is  no  sign  of  a
trail.  For the first 100 feet or so you just  have  to  crash  through  the
brush.  Good thing I had been on this trail before or  I  would  have  never
been able to find it. For 2 miles it goes in and out of brush, some  so  bad
as to seem impenetrable.  The only way to stay  on  track  is  to  part  the
brush down to the ground until you can see the tread and then  follow  this.
However, sections in the trees are still quite good. The  last  mile  or  so
breaks out onto open hot hillside but things do not  improve  as  ferns  and
thimbleberries and alder are traded for snowbrush as the dominant  irritant.
Much of the tread is also filling in on the loose sandy  hillside  and  soon
will be  completely  gone.  I  thankfully  reached  the  junction  with  the
Chancellor Trail at 11:30, after 2.5 hours of misery.

I ate lunch at the crossing of Mill Cr, soaked my  aching  feet  and  washed
up. The rest of the way  out  was  almost  pleasant  by  comparison,  or  as
pleasant as a trail can be when you are tired, your feet hurt  and  all  you
want is to get out. Despite many ups and downs, this is really a  very  nice
trail.  Most of it is in cool forest and a refreshing breeze was blowing.  I
was in no hurry and stopped once more to soak my feet. I reached the  TH  at
3:30 (10.5 miles, 1050 ft, 7 hr).

Total: 31.5 miles and 12,350 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen

