            'tr' => '
Majestic Mtn (7520+ ft - 680P), Pk 7510 ("Majestic End" - 430P) & McKay
Ridge (7000+ ft - 760P) - Azurite Pk Quad - July 14-16, 2006

I like ridges, especially high alpine ridges, and even when they go  up  and
down unnecessarily, as ridges are wont to do, I still like ridges.   I  like
the feeling of treading that space  between  heaven  and  earth  and  having
constant views in every direction. So when I saw  the  long  Majestic  Ridge
across Mill Cr from Cady Ridge last week it just called to me. At that  time
if I could have I would have accessed it from  Azurite  Mine  and  gone  out
that way. But I could see no reasonable way up out of Mill Cr. It  was  just
as well.  I was too beat, the  ridge  was  longer  than  it  looked  and  it
deserved a trip of its own. Then I discovered two other  peaks  of  interest
nearby, Pk 7510 at the N end of the ridge that would  make  a  fitting  turn
around point for my traverse, and McKay Ridge on the other side  of  Boulder
Cr. Now I had a full itinerary and a definite plan.

Day 1: I began from the East Cr TH, elev 2600 ft, off Hwy 20 at  12:30.  The
trail dropped to cross Granite Cr on a large bridge  then  climbed  steadily
for a thousand feet up semi open hillside where spindly small  firs  offered
little shade. Fortunately, this day was not terribly hot so I didn\'t  suffer
too much. The tread is  in  good  shape  although  there  are  a  number  of
annoying blowdowns that have not yet been cut.  After  another  gentle  mile
through cool forest the first water is reached at a crossing of East  Cr  on
a log. On the other side, the trail changes character becoming brushier  and
several side streams are crossed  before  reaching  the  marked  Boulder  Cr
Trail junction (4 miles, 2300 ft, 3 hrs). This trail is  not  shown  on  the
USGS map but is on the GT Mt Logan.

I easily followed the trail, crossing the line of an interesting old  6-inch
metal pipe (did they pump water up from East Cr?), to the  Gold  Hill  Mine,
elev 5000 ft. There are several buildings, a lot  of  disturbed  ground  and
much equipment strewn around, some of it looking fairly new,  that  confused
the situation as to  where  the  continuation  of  the  trail  went.  Seeing
nothing obvious, I headed up left of the main shack  figuring  I  would  run
into the trail.  I did run into what I thought was the trail  a  short  ways
up, but it soon petered out in a meadow. So I just headed up the meadow  and
when that became too brushy aimed for  the  forest  to  the  left.   I  kept
expecting to run into the trail again but I never did.  This  probably  cost
me close to an hour in time. At  about  5800  ft  I  began  traversing  left
toward Boulder Cr Pass, crossing three gullies on the way. The last one  had
water and not at all sure that there would be any at the pass  I  filled  up
my gallon container. At  5:45 I reached the pass, elev  6400  ft  (6  miles,
3900 ft, 5:15 hr). The trail distinctly ran through  the  pass.  How  did  I
miss it?

What a lovely spot! Two old fire rings each with a  nice  flat  spot  for  a
tent gave me a choice for my campsite. Neither looked  very  used.  However,
as I had feared there was no water - all snowpatches were gone. There was  a
gorgeous view of Ragged Ridge across Hwy 20 and up East Cr where a  striking
peak caught my attention at the head of the valley near Meebee  Pass.   What
was this peak? It was not named on my map  but  I  later  found  out  it  is
called the Methow Pinnacles. I had a leisurely dinner and turned in  at  the
absurd hour of 7:30.

Day 2: Despite my early retirement, I slept soundly until 6:00, 10.5  hours!
 My schedule must be getting to me. The morning was cooler than  I  expected
(40 degrees inside my bivy tent) with a heavy dew. Being high on a  ridge  I
had expected the sun to hit early,  but  it  was  blocked  by  Pt  7450  and
besides it was cloudy with fog swirling around the higher peaks. It took  me
a full hour of moving to warm up completely.  (I  had  gone  very  light  on
clothes expecting conditions to be as warm as  my  last  three  trips.  Just
goes to show, never count on anything in the mountains.)

I started up the ridge E of camp at 7:30 arriving on Pt 7450 an hour  later.
I stayed on the crest of the ridge as I would for all of the day.  I  looked
for a shortcut to the saddle with Majestic Mtn but it was too cliffy. So  it
was down 350 ft and back up to the summit of Majestic (1450 ft, 2 hr).  Here
I found a film can register, not  in  the  summit  cairn  but  several  feet
downhill from it. I was lucky to have spotted it.  Inside on a  soggy  piece
of paper were two entries. It was  originally  placed  by  Don  Goodman  and
company on October 24, 1987, "the year of the drought" (they must  have  had
to haul water a long ways that time of year in a drought no  less).  One  of
the party referred to this summit as "Truly Majestic",  which  gave  me  the
idea of calling my 7510 peak at the N end of the ridge "Majestic  End".  The
other entry was August 18, 1991. This peak hadn\'t been climbed in  15  years
if you believe the register. Sure it is not a major  objective,  but  it  is
not difficult and very scenic.  Maybe  some  others  just  didn\'t  find  the
register. Oh there was one other entry but I didn\'t think  it  counted.   On
July 16, 1990 two helicopter personal set a radio relay  for  the  Jack  Mtn
Complex Fire. I left a register of my own, transcribing all the entries.

For the next 3 hours I threaded my way N along the ridge toward Pk 7510.  At
times it looked as if I surely had come to an impasses,  but  a  way  always
appeared, always on the very crest and never  more  than  class  3.  It  was
ridge scrambling at its best and I enjoyed every minute of  it.  Views  were
not as good as I had hoped to begin, with persistent  clouds  and  fog,  but
gradually things cleared and I felt on top of the world. I went up and  over
two more major points and numerous smaller ones. Between  Majestic  and  the
next point I spotted several lovely tarns (not shown on the map) in a  basin
below. There were a few snow patches here and there that I was able  to  use
to augment my meager water supply. It was much farther to Pk  7510  than  it
looked on the map with many ups and downs. Finally  I  made  the  summit  at
12:30 (2800 ft, 5 hrs).

I spent a good hour on top just enjoying myself and the  spectacular  views.
Then I retraced my steps to the first point S and dropped into the basin  to
the W. It would take too long to reverse the entire ridge and besides I  had
to find another source of water for camp.  I  traversed  at  about  6600  ft
over a shoulder and dropped further to 6000 ft into the next drainage  where
I found a running creek and filled up my  gallon  container.  The  next  and
last drainage had no water at the elevation I crossed it, although  I  could
hear and see water a couple hundred feet lower. I traversed to  the  Boulder
Cr Trail, which I could see in the distance and followed it back up  to  the
pass and camp (6 miles, 3800 ft, 8:45 hrs).

Fifteen minutes later I was off again at 4:30 to  climb  McKay  Ridge.  This
was another ridge scrambling delight going W from camp. Again  I  stayed  on
the crest of the ridge the whole way, except for the  last  200  ft  to  the
summit on the SE face which was cruddy scree. There were the usual  ups  and
downs, but much less than on Majestic Ridge, with little surprises  and  fun
scrambling sections here and there. I reached the summit at 6:30  (1300  ft,
2 hrs). I was very surprised to find an official large Mountaineer  register
on top but when I read the one and only entry I understood.  It  was  placed
by none other than Ian MacKay on 7/26/03. How appropriate.  I  was  back  in
camp at 8:20 (4 miles, 2000 ft, 3:50 hrs) more than ready to  quit  for  the
day.

Day 3: Another cold morning, but it helped that I slept  in  till  7:30  and
the sun hit camp an hour later.  I  lounged  around  reading  and  sketching
Ragged Ridge while a resident deer made an appearance paying me no mind  and
a curious marmot watched from a rock lookout  while  I  painted.  I  finally
left at 10:45 following the trail down. Darn! It was a good  trail  all  the
way. It had begun to the right of the main mine building about 100 ft  up  a
bulldozed track, completely unmarked. I had been to the left  and  below  it
all the way up. I ambled the rest of  the  way  out,  stopping  for  a  long
lunch, and reached the TH at 2:15 (6 miles, 200 ft, 3:30 hrs)

Total: 22 miles and 9900 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen






