            'tr' => '
SE Twin Spire, "Hard Mox" - (8504 ft - 904P), NE Twin Spire, "Easy Mox" -
(8407 ft - 527P) & Mt Redoubt (8969 ft - 1649P) - July 21-25, 2006

Never have I had so many things go wrong on a trip,  with  close  calls  and
uncertain outcomes, and still have a  successful  conclusion.  In  spite  of
that, I would have to rank this trip as one of my best ever and very  likely
the high point of my "climbing career". The hard climbing,  the  spectacular
scenery and most of all the working together as a team to make it  happen  -
it just doesn\'t get any better.

Day 1: The cast of characters in this drama were Paul Michelson, Stu  Frink,
Tim Jackson, Annette Day, Craig Day, David Diehl, Jon Zak,  and  of  course,
myself. After spending the night at a motel in Chilliwack, the eight  of  us
started from the end of the Depot Cr road at 8:00, elev  2500  ft  with  the
day already heating up.  The  first  near  miss  occurred  just  before  the
waterfall when Tim almost took his eye out on  a  sharp  protruding  branch.
With blood streaming out of his eye we were all relieved to  determine  that
it actually came from a gash near the eyebrow. His glasses  may  have  saved
him worse damage even though they were knocked off  his  head  and  it  took
quite a while to find them again.

The waterfall was running at high capacity, higher than any of us  had  ever
seen it before, and it was  like  climbing  in  a  full  blast  downpour  on
terribly slick wet rock. By the time we got through  this  section  we  were
all drenched. At the top of the waterfall we had planned on  splitting  into
two groups, with Craig, Jon  and  David  heading  to  Ouzel  Lake  to  climb
Custer, Rahm and Spickard while the rest of us  hoped  to  take  the  direct
route to the Redoubt Glacier. But we couldn\'t get across  roaring  Depot  Cr
and so everyone ended up going to  the  lake.  Even  then  we  couldn\'t  get
across the outlet and had to go uplake to find a place to wade across.  Here
we left the other three and the five  of  us  made  our  way  up  the  rocky
buttress W of the lake on ledges and onto the Redoubt Glacier.  By  now  the
heat was beginning to take its toll and some members were ready to  stop  at
the first available flat spot, but we pushed on  to  a  delightful  spot  at
7200 ft near rock outcroppings with  slab  benches  for  seats  and  running
water. We shoveled tent platforms in the snow for our three  tents  and  set
up a pleasant camp at 7:00 (8 miles, 4900 ft, 11 hrs)

Day 2 - Hard Mox: Paul, Tim, Stu and I started for Hard Mox  at  6:20.  From
the 7200 Redoubt-Depot Cr ridge we dropped several  hundred  feet  on  snow,
talus and scree and began a long traverse until we could climb  back  up  to
the Col of the Wild between the two Moxes at 7840 ft (1200  ft,  1:45  hrs).
The last bit to the col was gosh awful loose, loose scree. From  the  col  a
ramp led right past a tiny snowpatch, around a  corner  and  into  a  gully.
From the top of the gully a short class 4 wall, with a rappel anchor  above,
was climbed to a series of loose ledges up and right to  a  sharp  notch  in
the Ridge of Gendarmes. Somewhere in here I was almost taken out by a  large
rock. Here we had our first real look at Hard Mox. Oh my gosh!  What  had  I
gotten myself into! It really looked unclimbable.

From the notch we descended a couple hundred  of  feet  on  exposed  ledges,
where a few cairns helped to point the way, to a snowfinger. Both  the  snow
itself and the rock on the side were  most  unappealing,  so  we  set  up  a
single rope rappel to get down another hundred feet almost to  the  base  of
the snow. Going off this rappel I clumsily dropped my ATC rappel  device  (I
still don\'t know how the keeper came off the carabiner.). While not a  total
disaster, not having my ATC would have severely hampered  both  my  belaying
and rappelling. But sharp-eyed Tim spotted it a short ways farther down  the
gully and all was saved. From the base of the snow  we  traversed  left  and
into the  second  of  two  converging  gullies  where  we  came  across  the
chockstone chimney. After going  under  the  chockstone,  we  encountered  a
short wall were we began roped climbing as two independent ropes,  Paul  and
I and Tim and Stu. I led up the wall and into bed of the gully but was  soon
stopped by another steep chimney with a cave in the back. Perhaps some  long
legged guys can stem this thing but not I, so I found a way  around  on  the
right wall and back into the gully above. Rockfall  is  a  real  problem  in
this gully and we all had to be extremely careful.

At noon (2000 ft, 5:40 hrs) we reached the high notch below  the  Spire\'s  W
wall, where the "serious"  climbing  supposedly  begins  (as  if  it  wasn\'t
serious up to now). Paul took the lead following a ledge right and  up  then
back left around a corner to a belay anchor. I took the next  lead  more  or
less following  the  ridge  crest.  I  didn\'t  find  the  climbing  so  much
difficult as just plain stressful. The  rock  was  quite  loose  and  I  had
trouble finding  solid  holds  and  particularly  solid  places  to  put  in
protection. Following, Paul had a foothold completely break  on  him,  which
got his adrenaline flowing. Paul took us the last easier bit to  the  summit
at 1:50 (2200 ft, 7:30 hrs). We were both elated to have made  this  elusive
peak.

The summit register was a  fascinating  complete  climbing  history  of  the
peak, including pasted in photocopies of the first ascent by Fred and  Helmy
Beckey in 1941. Ours was the 22nd ascent right after Paul  Klenke  and  Mark
Iffrig in 2004. The register read like a Who\'s Who of  Bulger  climbers  and
averaged an ascent every  other  year  or  so  recently,  with  larger  gaps
earlier.

Tim and Stu joined us a short time later and then we began the rappels  down
using our two 60m ropes. The  first  rappel  went  smoothly.  Then  disaster
struck. On the second rappel down to the high notch, when pulling the  ropes
the upper rope got stuck just shortly  after  the  knot  reached  us.  Three
strong guys couldn\'t get it down. It was now 4:00, time was an issue and  we
really didn\'t have enough to climb up  to  free  it,  so  we  cut  the  rope
leaving us with a somewhat useless 30 ft remnant. Naturally it was  my  rope
and it was brand new. I really didn\'t care that much about the rope per  se.
 But I did recognize that having only one rope would  severely  handicap  us
on the rest of the rappels on this peak and also for climbing Easy  Mox  the
next day. But if anyone climbs Hard Mox  soon  there  is  a  nice  50m  rope
dangling in the wind.

And so we were forced into a series of single rope rappels to get  down  the
gully. By the time we got back to the Col  of  the  Wild  it  was  9:00.  We
dragged into camp at 10:40 by headlamp where Annette,  bless  her,  pampered
us by having hot water ready for dinner (3100 ft, 16:15 hrs).

Day 3 - Easy Mox: What a misnomer! Easy Mox is not  easy.   I  have  decided
these two peaks should be called Hard Mox and Harder Mox. Worn out from  our
previous day, Tim bowed out and Annette joined us. We got a  late  start  at
8:30 and descended a couple hundred feet to get below rock ribs onto  the  E
lobe of the Redoubt Glacier. This lobe is heavily crevassed and  requires  a
rope to cross (we didn\'t bother roping up on the way up to  camp  on  the  W
edge of the glacier). Then we got a look at the route  up  to  the  N  ridge
notch. The snow, which was supposed to give easy access to a ramp  that  cut
right and then left leading to broken rock to the ridge, had  receded  to  a
nasty moat and jumble of unstable broken blocks  of  ice.  There  was  brief
talk of working our way through the jumble to the ramp but as if on cue  one
of the blocks came crashing down almost as we spoke putting the nix on  that
idea.

With no other option, I took the lead across the  left  edge  of  the  moat,
where it was easy to cross, and onto the rock and essentially went  straight
up to the left trending ramp, maybe an 80 ft pitch. I  would  say  this  was
the hardest climbing of the whole trip and certainly the crux for Easy  Mox.
The rock was solid, but slabby and hard to protect and I was  definitely  at
my limit.  I remember distinctly thinking while making  one  of  the  harder
moves on a somewhat runout  partial  traverse,  "Don\'t  fall!  Please  don\'t
fall! It would really suck to fall right now and would probably put  an  end
to the trip not to mention what it would do to my body." Paul  was  thinking
the same thing and planning to reel in the rope as fast as possible  if  the
worst did happen. Somehow I made it to the  ramp  and  breathed  a  sigh  of
relief. It is amazing what adrenaline can make us capable of doing.

There was another easy pitch, in comparison, to  the  broad  7600  ft  ridge
(250 ft, 4:30 hrs).
We scrambled a ways along the  easy  ridge  until  coming  to  a  step  that
required an exposed traverse around a corner. It was now  2:00  and  it  was
becoming obvious that 4 people on one rope was awkward and slow and  at  our
present pace we would not make the summit. So we took Annette off  the  rope
at a safe spot and continued as a rope of  three.   She  was  naturally  not
happy but did understand and in the spirit of  making  the  best  of  a  bad
situation decided to start a new list "The 100 Highest Lunch Spots."

With three on the rope things went faster as we simulclimbed. There was  one
more traverse left around a step, but most of  the  way  was  right  on  the
crest which was getting narrower and more exposed  the  higher  we  went.  I
rather enjoyed this ridge.  The  rock  was  fairly  solid  and  it  was  fun
scrambling. About 200 ft from the summit we reached a  series  of  pinnacles
that required a 40 ft descent left down a steep gully  to  a  rubble  ledge,
which was followed to directly below the summit. A 100 ft class 5 pitch  put
us at a tiny high notch with a final easy scramble remaining to the  summit,
which was reached at 4:30 (1100 ft, 8 hrs). We barely took time to  look  at
the soggy and illegible register before heading down.

We rappelled down to the rubble ledge  and  downclimbed  the  rest  back  to
Annette and on to the notch where we left the  ridge.   We  had  passed  two
rappel anchors on the way up. From the second anchor a  double  rope  rappel
would have made it to the glacier, but of course we didn\'t  have  two  ropes
and I found myself stranded  on  the  slabby  ramp  with  no  obvious  third
anchor. After searching for more time than we could afford  to  lose  I  was
getting desperate. There was some discussion about tying the  rope  off  and
rappelling on a single strand  (which  meant  we  would  have  to  leave  it
behind) but we really couldn\'t afford to lose another rope. We needed it  to
cross the glacier and for Redoubt the next day.  There  were  better  things
to leave behind than the rope. After much searching I found a shallow  crack
that would just allow a thin spectra sling to hang on it and  a  bomber  cam
crack nearby. By equalizing these two points I felt it was  safe  enough  to
rappel from. This got us to the glacier below at 8:30 and back  to  camp  at
10:15 (1600 ft, 13:45 hrs) for another late dinner. Let\'s see now -  so  far
I had lost my 60m rope, a cam, a spectra sling  and  Paul  almost  lost  his
rope. This trip was being decidedly hard on gear.

Day 4 - Mt Redoubt: The other three members of our party had  come  up  from
the lake the previous night to join us at our glacier  camp.  They  had  all
climbed Spickard, backed off the nasty Custer ridge  and  David  had  soloed
Rahm. Jon had climbed Redoubt before and stayed  in  camp  so  seven  of  us
headed for that peak at 7:30. We climbed the glacier to the 7800 ft notch  S
of the imposing Flying Buttress. A short class 4 pitch led to a  descent  on
loose talus down the other side and a traverse to a snow gully on  Redoubt\'s
S slope. We ended up going up the gully too far (beware the  fallible  human
memory of someone  who  has  previously  climbed  a  mountain)  and  had  to
backtrack to the snowslope on the left and a broad scree  shoulder.  A  ramp
above went right below the summit cliffs.  There  were  several  choices  of
gullies to take from the ramp and we chose one near its end,  evidently  not
the correct one. This put us below a final steep cliff just below the top.

Tim led up this cliff, a solid class 5 pitch which was much harder than  any
of us had anticipated. We must be  off  route.  The  plan  for  everyone  to
follow this on our one rope using a prusik was not  going  to  work.  On  to
Plan B. Tim belayed me and Paul up to his stance, which was an  easy  50  ft
scramble across a narrow notch to the summit (2200 ft, 5 hrs). We then  tied
off the rope at a rappel anchor near the summit and I rappelled on a  single
strand down from the notch where what should I discover but the  Cannonhole.
We had gone over the top of it! I then went down and to climber\'s left  over
a shoulder. It was an awkward  rappel  and  I  had  to  place  a  couple  of
direction slings to keep the rope on the right line but it was  much  easier
than the way Tim had gone. The rest of the party was now able to  follow  on
prusik. Everyone but Tim rappelled down the single  line.  Tim  then  did  a
normal rappel down his face lead so we could retrieve the rope.

There were no further problems, other than taking great care  with  rockfall
downclimbing the gully and we were all back to camp by 5:45 (2500 ft,  10:15
hrs). There has been talk earlier about some people going out  this  day  (I
had always planned to spend a fifth  day)  but  now  no  one  wanted  to  go
anywhere. Each of these peaks had taken more time and  been  more  difficult
than anyone had expected. There were multiple cell phone  calls  to  arrange
another day with work and family.  And for once we had  a  leisurely  dinner
in daylight and got to bed at a reasonable hour.

Day 5: We got up with the sun at 6:00 and were packed and ready to leave  at
7:30. Both the feeder creeks to the lake and the waterfall  were  noticeably
lower in volume. We reached the cars at 2:00 (8 miles, 300  ft,  .6:30  hrs)
everyone looking forward to a dip in Chilliwack Lake.  But this is  not  the
end of the story.  We never got the dip in the lake.  David\'s  van  died  on
the way down (fortunately he was past the Depot Cr  road).  He  had  a  dead
battery. Perhaps it was the alternator. At any rate the  vehicle  would  not
run. He limped into Chilliwack by me giving him  a  jump  and  charging  his
battery from my Cherokee a few minutes a time. Each charge would  allow  him
to drive 3-4 miles before the engine died again.   I  must  have  given  him
close to 10 jumps before making it into town and a car  repair  place.  They
said they probably couldn\'t get to it until the next day. (It did  turn  out
to be the alternator and both David and his van made it home the next  day.)
I drove 5 people home. The others made arrangements to be  picked  up  by  a
family member. A rather ignominious end  to  an  interesting,  eventful  and
challenging trip, but it will not change my opinion  that  this  could  very
well be my best climb ever.

Total: Maybe 30 miles and 12,400 ft in 5 days

Fay Pullen








