Illabot Peaks (5944 ft - 2864P) & Peak 4680+ (480P) - Illabot Peaks Quad


Fizzle Hill (1760+ ft - 600P) & Wall Mtn (2250 ft - 650P) - Rockport Quad

July 31-August 1, 2006

I know that most people climb Illabot Peaks  from  the  north  in  one  day.
Looking at the map and reading Stefan\'s recent report  going  that  way  did
not  appeal  to  me.  Ever  since  skiing  up  Suiattle  Mtn  this   winter,
approaching from the end of the West Boundary Road  and  climbing  from  the
south appeared more scenic and since I wanted  to  do  it  as  an  overnight
several tarns on the way would provide a nice place to camp.

Day 1: Since the approach to  my  proposed  camp  would  be  very  short,  I
planned to also climb as many little bumps along the road on the way  in  as
possible. My first objective was Fizzle Hill, on which I almost  fizzled.  I
wandered back and forth along the main road looking for a  spur  that  would
get me as close as possible.  I finally settled on a  very  short  one  less
than half a mile from the top. (I ran into a road part  way  up  that  would
have halved the misery but darned if  I  could  figure  out  where  it  came
from.) I will not go into detail as I doubt anyone will ever  follow  in  my
footsteps up this horrendous pile  of  stickery  head  high  brushy  logging
slash and if anyone should be crazy (stupid) enough to try they  can  figure
it out for themselves. Suffice it to say it took me 2:50 hrs to go  the  750
ft and 1 mile RT and I ended up wet, dirty, all scratched up and in  a  foul
mood.

Wall Mtn was next and a slight improvement.  At  least  the  summit  was  in
forest and had several cute rocky promontories with  a  vista  down  to  the
Sauk River (1.5 miles, 800 ft, 1:45 hrs). Neither  of  these  two  bumps  is
really worth the effort unless you are a terminal peak bagger (What? Who  me
you say?)

I continued driving to the end of the West Boundary Road past  Suiattle  Mtn
to the saddle E of Peak 4680. The  road  actually  continues  a  short  ways
farther than shown on the map up the spur ridge to the E  and  I  gratefully
drove as far as possible.  It was now so late (5:30) and I was so  worn  out
from my brush bashes that I worried about getting to  a  camp  in  a  timely
manner. I needn\'t have worried. The route along the spur ridge went  swiftly
through the open forest despite a large number of  fallen  trees  along  the
way.  I had half expected to find a reasonable fisherman\'s  trail  to  Tupso
Lake, but all I found  was  a  faint  path  sporadically  marked  with  blue
flagging. At the main ridge I dropped over the other side  to  a  collection
of three lovely tarns, elev 4650 ft, and set up a pleasant camp at  6:50  (1
mile, 725 ft, 1:20 hr). The  mosquitoes  were  ferocious,  but  anticipating
this I had brought along a large netting and placed it over the entrance  to
my tent for a bug free place to make and eat dinner. There was  no  sign  of
anyone ever having camped here.

Day 2: I slept in and didn\'t get going until 8:00.  It was  nice  to  be  so
relaxed and not in a hurry. I began by wandering N through meadows.  Soon  I
ran into a very good boot trail.  I  followed  it  a  short  ways  until  it
headed to the left of the ridge ahead.  I wanted to go to the  right  so  we
parted ways.  This must be a continuation of the fisherman\'s trail  to  Lake
Louise going on to Lake Tupso. I took the  traverse  around  the  ridge  too
low, ran into cliffs and had to drop to bypass  them  until  I  could  climb
back up again. Turning the ridge I came upon two  more  tarns  at  5120  ft.
From here I dropped once more until I could gain the 5080 ft saddle  to  the
left of an impressive rocky ridge where I  had  my  first  view  of  Illabot
Peaks.

After another drop into the basin on the other side, I began working my  way
to the W ridge of my peak. I was mistakenly under the  impression  that  you
then just follow this ridge to the  top.   No  can  do.  It  is  rocky  with
several bumps and gaps and it is best to traverse below on the S side  until
reaching a rock wall just below the summit.  From here I was uncertain  what
to do. There were cliffs everywhere  and  no  sign  of  the  class  3  gully
mentioned in Beckey.  I hadn\'t brought Stefan\'s report with me and  couldn\'t
remember exactly what he had said.  I should have  paid  more  attention.  I
hadn\'t expected such difficulties. I ended up crossing to  the  N  side  and
forcing a way up a very steep treed slope to the right of  a  slab  where  I
could use limbs to pull myself up. I topped out at 11:00  (1.5  miles,  1850
ft, 3:00 hrs).

The summit is supposed to be a good viewpoint but  I  could  see  little  as
clouds and fog obscured all the higher peaks and  many  of  the  lower  ones
too.  Too much marine air still around from  Sunday\'s  system.   Even  so  I
spent an hour on top and even wandered over to the E summit.  After  leaving
a register, I started down a different way, staying on the ridge as long  as
possible.  I managed to downclimb almost all the  way  until  I  came  to  a
steep chimney, which I rappelled with my 80 ft  rope.  The  rest  was  easy.
From the upper tarns I climbed to the ridge crest, where I could  look  down
on Lake Louise, for a higher route back to camp to miss the  cliffs  of  the
way up. I reached camp at 2:00 (2400 ft, 6 hrs RT) and relaxed for  over  an
hour before heading out, reaching the car at 4:15 (1 mile, 270 ft, 1 hr).

I still had time to climb Peak 4680.  This  turned  out  to  be  a  pleasant
though steep climb through mostly brushfree  woods.  The  hardest  part  was
finding a way up the road cut. I left a small matchbox register  on  top  in
honor of this being the only secondary bump on this trip worth climbing  (.5
miles, 520 ft, 1 hr RT).

Total for all peaks: 8 miles and 5465 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen




