Sinister Peak (8440+ ft - 840P - Dome Pk Quad) - August 5-7, 2006


Via the South Side and SW Ridge


This was my second attempt on this peak  this  year,  the  first  one  being
thwarted by bad weather. That meant that once again  I  had  to  endure  the
enervating approach up Downey and Bachelor  Creeks.  I  was  definitely  not
looking forward to it but there was no other alternative other than to  grit
my teeth and bear it. Much as I dislike this approach it is the fastest  way
in to Sinister.

Day 1: And so 8:00 on  Saturday  morning  found  our  party  of  four,  Paul
Michelson, Tim Jackson, Paul Klenke and I, starting up the Downey Cr  Trail,
elev 1400 ft. Three hours later we were at Bachelor Cr, elev  2400  ft,  and
stopped for lunch  (6.5 miles, 1350 ft) before heading up  the  Bachelor  Cr
Trail with its  notorious  windfalls  and  brush.  The  blackflies  on  this
section were atrocious, so thick that during rest  stops  my  light  colored
pants took on a dark polka-dotted pattern. Then Tim  was  stung  by  a  wasp
when a nest was disturbed by our passage. Also the brush  was  fully  leafed
out now and much thicker than when I was last here in early June.  No,  this
"trail" is not a whole lot of fun.

On the avalanche slope at the head of the  valley,  Klenke  was  ahead  (his
usual position) by a couple hundred feet when he called  down  that  he  had
just seen a cougar. Darn! I would have liked to have seen that. What a  rare
and special occurrence!  In all my years of wandering I have  never  seen  a
cougar in the wild. Above the avalanche we picked up  good  tread  again  in
open country, crossed Cub Lake Pass, dropped to Cub  Lake  and  climbed  the
last thousand feet to a delightful camp on Itswoot Ridge, elev 6300  ft  (14
miles, 5800 ft, 9:30 hrs). We had the whole place to ourselves  and  it  was
early  enough  to  wash  up  in  the  nearby  creek,  relax  and  enjoy  the
spectacular views all around before eating a leisurely  dinner  and  turning
in at 8:30.

Day 2: Tim, who is not fanatically pursuing  the  100  Highest,  decided  to
spend the day taking it easy. So Michelson, Klenke and I took  off  at  6:00
and left him to enjoy the ambience and beauty of the area.  We  dropped  off
the ridge several hundred  feet  before  beginning  a  long,  very  l-o-n-g,
traverse beneath the south slopes of Dome Peak  just  to  get  to  Sinister.
Sinister was not even in sight for a long time. We  traversed  at  generally
between 6000 and 6200 ft on talus and scree  and  heather  to  the  polished
slabs below the icefall on the Dome Glacier. These slabs  were  rather  fun,
but the rest was just tedious, slow going over loose unstable rocks. At  one
point Michelson  stepped  onto  a  loose  boulder  that  rolled  under  foot
pitching him forward downhill bruising his knee and  breaking  the  tip  off
his trekking pole. After a few minutes to collect himself, he determined  he
was able to continue, but it was a close call.

Once past the slabs, we climbed up past two small snow patches to a 7000  ft
saddle in Dome\'s SW Ridge (1100 ft, 2:15 hrs). The snow was  ice  hard,  but
we could bypass it on rock.  Any extended snow travel at  this  point  would
require crampons so we tried to avoid that until it had a chance  to  soften
up. More tedious traversing continued on the other side  of  the  SW  Ridge,
only broken by the crossing of a roaring glacial creek in a  deep  slot.  We
barely made it across, and I did get one wet foot.  We  knew  this  crossing
would give us trouble on the way back when the volume would be much higher.

At 9:15 (1400 ft, 3:15 hrs) we reached "the  Impasse"  on  the  S  Ridge  of
Dome, elev 7000 ft, where we had our first view of Sinister. It took  us  an
hour to find "the Ramp" and figure out a way down the cliffs  on  the  other
side. We even briefly considered rappelling. Actually there are a couple  of
ways down, but they are hard to discern from above.  We  began  on  a  steep
heather trough. Then Klenke went skier\'s right on a narrow ledge to a  broad
slabby ramp (is this "the Ramp"?) ending up lower,  while  Michelson  and  I
went skier\'s left on a ledge (or is this "the  Ramp"?)  that  curled  around
leading to a snowslope below which  we  then  took  down  to  meet  up  with
Klenke. We could now finally begin the climb up to Sinister.

A  broad  gully  led  up  through  cliffs  to  the  gentle  snowfield  below
Sinister\'s W Face. All we had to do now was find "the Gully" leading to  the
W Ridge, but of course the proper, supposedly class 3, gully was not at  all
obvious and the route descriptions we had were vague and not  that  helpful.
We bypassed one gully  that  looked  much  too  steep  to  be  class  3  (in
retrospect this was probably the correct one)  and  continued  traversing  S
below cliffs almost to the SW Ridge where a deep gully  at  the  head  of  a
short but steep snowslope slanted to the left.  I  donned  my  crampons  and
went up to take a look. A nasty moat greeted me at the  top  with  a  10  ft
vertical wall on the other side. Warning my  companions  not  to  come  this
way, I now had to extricate myself from  my  predicament.   This  I  did  by
straddling the snow lip until I found a spot I could  frontpoint  down  into
the moat.

My companions soon joined me by crawling the moat  on  the  right  side.  We
could now see that the left trending gully appeared to end  in  a  headwall.
However, after a short rock step, an easy ramp led right to a notch  in  the
SW Ridge.  Klenke led up the maybe 5.0 step, brought the two of us up,  then
I followed the ramp to the SW Ridge. It was now  obvious  we  were  way  off
route and had completely missed the W Ridge, but it appeared that  we  could
continue on our ridge to the top and we had little choice at this point  but
to give it a go. It actually turned out to be a nice route, mostly  class  3
and 4, with a few harder moves here and there, on reasonable  rock  that  we
simul-climbed on our two 30m ropes. I lead for a couple hundred  feet  until
running out of pro (we didn\'t bring that much as  we  didn\'t  expect  to  do
this much rock climbing) then leapfrogged with Klenke taking us the rest  of
the way. The last bit was easy scree and we  summitted  at  2:45  (3500  ft,
8:45 hrs).

We congratulated each other. This was #92 for Klenke, #98 for Michelson  and
#99 for me. Amongst the three of us  we  had  climbed  289  Hundred  Highest
Peaks. The register still contained the original first ascent entry  of  May
29,1939  by  Lloyd  Anderson,  Jim  Crooks  and  Clint  Kelley  on  an   old
Mountaineer roll. It was dry but tattered and torn and  in  bad  shape.   We
left the tatters for historic reasons but added a  new  waterproof  booklet.
As an aside, I had climbed several  peaks  with  Clint  Kelley  back  in  my
Mountaineer days in the â70s before he was killed by a fall on Mt Shuksan.

We left the summit at 3:30 and headed down the W Ridge. I was  surprised  at
how easy this ridge was.  We were able to bypass any snow  on  the  left  on
scree and talus and it was mostly a simple walk to the rappel  anchor  at  a
point where the ridge narrows just before the  Dome-Sinister  Col.  However,
this rappel was anything but simple.  I would have to rate it as one of  the
worst starts to a rappel I have ever done. It was very awkward, as  you  had
to walk out to climber\'s left of the anchor, which then  put  you  above  an
overhang with the anchor off to the right.  Once you  step  off  into  space
you then pendulum right in a freefall and hang on for dear life.  No, I  did
not like that rappel. Also our two 30m ropes did not quite make it  all  the
way down and left us 20 feet short above another  nasty  moat.  Klenke  went
first and somehow levitated himself down the last  bit  and  over  the  moat
onto the snow. Being mere mortals, Michelson and  I  set  up  another  short
rappel, after which I threw the other end of  the  rope  to  Klenke  and  he
pulled me over the moat.

We quickly glissaded the snow as far as possible, downclimbed  to  the  base
of âthe Impasse" and took Klenke\'s route up slippery slabs and deadly  steep
heather.  I liked Michelson\'s and my downroute better. The rest of  the  way
back is a bit of a blur of endless traversing, although two events  made  it
through the blur. First, the crossing of the roaring creek  was  as  bad  as
expected.  We could not cross in the same place  as  earlier.   It  was  not
just a question of getting wet feet; it was a question of being  swept  away
over waterfalls to a possible death. So we went  uphill  to  where  we  were
lucky to find a crossing below a snowbridge on boulders.  I  ended  up  with
two wet feet and Klenke had to haul me up a sheer rock  step,  but  it  sure
beat the alternative. Then second, while crossing the slabs below  the  Dome
Icefall a chunk of ice the size of an automobile broke  off.  The  sound  of
ice falling is a sound that strikes terror in the hearts  of  all  climbers.
Fortunately the ice stopped well above us but  the  adrenaline  rush  kicked
all our tired bodies into a higher gear  that  lasted  until  clear  of  the
glacier.

We didn\'t quite make it back to camp without needing headlamps,  pulling  in
at 9:45 (maybe 8 miles, 5100 ft, 15:45 hrs). We  now  had  company.  Another
party, already in bed, coming off the Ptarmigan Traverse was camped  nearby,
planning on climbing Dome the next day. Tim had made their acquaintance.  He
also had hot water ready  for  our  dinner,  which  we  devoured  ravenously
before turning in an hour later.

Day 3: Not much to be said for the trip out except  that  it  was  long  and
once again not a lot of fun. Once at Downey Cr I  decided  not  to  try  and
keep up with my long-legged companions, went at my  own  pace  and  probably
reached the car a good 30 minutes after everyone else. (14 miles,  1000  ft,
8 hrs)

Total: 36 miles and 11,900 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen


