            'tr' => '

Big Gee (5080+ ft - 3120P - Gee Point Quad) - August 13, 2006


I sure underestimated this peak. Looking at the map, it  appeared  to  be  a
simple 2-mile ridge ramble from the end of the road. Stefan\'s TR from  June,
where he took 1.5 hours to reach  the  summit,  did  little  to  dispel  this
notion. Of course I knew it would take me longer than Stefan, but  I  didn\'t
think it would take nearly twice as long.  I wasn\'t prepared for the  amount
of annoying brush or the rugged rocky nature of the ridge with all  its  ups
and downs. And Stefan did this as a prelude to climbing Mt Lincoln.  For  me
it was the focus of the day, although I did hope to also climb a  few  other
bumps in the vicinity afterward. No luck with that.

I avoided the Seattle rush hour traffic on this Sunday, but not  the  hordes
of motorcycle riders that seem to turn out by the hundreds  (thousands?)  on
sunny weekends to travel the  North  Cascade  Highway.  They  stretched  for
miles appearing to believe that  the  roadway  is  for  their  personal  and
exclusive use and seem to delight in riding in such a tight  slow  formation
that passing is difficult to impossible. I found this as frustrating as  any
rush hour traffic and was  happy  when  I  could  turn  off  Highway  20  in
Concrete onto the Concrete-Sauk Valley Road. I then followed  Finney  Cr  Rd
17 and Rd 1705 to a saddle at 4064 ft by an open gate  where  I  parked.  Rd
1705 is in good shape, just a  little  overgrown,  but  does  have  numerous
slowing waterbars. It takes a long time to drive these roads.

Getting to the ridge was brushy and the brush  was  wet,  surprisingly.  Not
that it mattered, as the wetness felt good on this  hot  day.  Once  on  the
ridge, even though it was wooded, there was still a fair amount of brush  in
the form of small thick trees and travel was slower than expected.   I  went
over a 4600 ft bump and dropped a bit  before  climbing  the  next  4725  ft
bump, which Dalles Kloke calls Exclamation Point  (he  also  calls  Big  Gee
Whiz Peak). There was a nice view of Big  Gee  and  surrounding  peaks  from
this rocky point. Now things got interesting. There was a steep  descent  to
the next saddle, sections of narrow ridge and then a pinnacle that  required
a bypass.  I went left on slippery vegetated slabs that I did not  like.  On
the way back I went right which is much better. A final bit on  more  narrow
rocky ridge led to the high point at the NW end and another nice view  point
(1660 ft, 2:50 hrs). It took almost as long to get back (4 miles,  2330  ft,
5:20 hrs).

I had hoped to climb several more peaks in the "Gee Whiz" group  but  all  I
managed to do was drive to the tower on Leonards Ridge 3920+ ft.  I  thought
I might still be able to squeak out Finney Peak but the access  road  (1735)
was ditched lower than I expected and I just didn\'t have the  time  to  make
the summit.  I decided to return another day with a bike to follow  the  old
road, which appeared to go very near the  top.  The  peak  itself  is  quite
rocky and looked very interesting. I returned home  via  Road  18  to  Swede
Heaven Road and Highway 530 near  Darrington.  This  is  another  very  good
forest road but it takes forever to drive.

Fay Pullen


