Forbidden Peak (8815 ft - 1055P - Forbidden Pk Quad) - August 17-19, 2006


There is a reason I left Forbidden Peak till  last  on  the  Bulger  Hundred
Highest  list.  I  have  known  about  this  beautiful  peak  forever,  been
intimidated by it forever and forever thought it beyond  my  reach.  I  know
these feelings are purely  psychological,  and  many  would  consider  other
peaks  I  have  already  done  to  be  harder,  but  climbing  is  often   a
psychological sport where feelings  and  perceptions  play  a  big  role  in
success. And so this is how I found myself at #99 with only Forbidden  left.
I could put it off no longer. In many ways the climb lived  up  to  both  my
expectations of a beautiful climb and my fears that it  was  too  difficult,
but it was the perfect peak for me to finish on.

Day 1: I was so paranoid about getting a permit for  Boston  Basin,  that  I
met Beth at the unnecessarily early hour of 6:00 am  near  the  intersection
of I-5 and I-405 so we could be at the Marblemount RS  not  too  long  after
they opened. I needn\'t have worried.  Only one other permit (of  6  allowed)
had been issued. With permit in hand, we took our time on  the  rough  trail
to Boston Basin arriving at the high 6200 ft camp slightly  before  2:00  pm
with plenty of leisure time to enjoy our surroundings (3.5 miles,  3000  ft,
4:10 hrs).   Neither of us had been to Boston Basin before and we were  both
blown away  with  how  gorgeous  it  was.  The  views  were  incredible,  of
Johannesburg across the valley, of Boston and Sahale,  and  of  Torment  and
Forbidden. We were also surprised with how nice the camp area was, with  all
the amenities - nearby running  water,  flat  gravel  tent  or  bivy  sites,
composting toilet (with a view to die for) and even a large boulder to  hang
food away from the marauding marmots.

We relaxed in the sun and scoped out the  route  with  binoculars.  We  both
really wanted to do the W Ridge but the normal snow couloir approach to  the
W Ridge notch looked awful. We were aware of a bypass on rock  to  the  left
up a gully, but were not sure where it was. Our second choice was to do  the
E Face ledges. We were debating what we should do, when two  Canadian  women
(the other permit holder) came down about 3:00  after  having  just  climbed
the W Ridge. They had started at 6:30 that morning and had gained the  ridge
via a gully they vaguely pointed out to  us  and  described  as  class  3-4.
Encouraged that they had done the climb so quickly, we  immediately  decided
to go their way and went to bed that night full of optimism.  As  it  turned
out this was somewhat false optimism.  It is not that they sandbagged us  so
much as we were just not in their league, not  even  close.  I  should  have
guessed.  They were tall, young,  athletic,  muscular  and  tanned  and  had
obviously climbed together often.

Day 2-3: We started at 6:45 the  next  morning.  Shortly  above  camp  in  a
higher flat basin we came across two fellows  bivied  and  not  yet  out  of
their sleeping bags. They had snuck past us  the  previous  evening.  So  we
would have company after all, we thought.  But  no.  On  talking  with  them
they were taking two days to do the  difficult  Torment-Forbidden  Traverse.
From the basin we climbed a short step and lovely gentle white  slabs  (some
cairns here) to a right trending gully  that  passed  beneath  an  extensive
cliff with several waterfalls. At the top of the cliff  more  slabs  led  to
the toe of the small unnamed glacier nestled below Forbidden\'s  S  Face.  We
donned crampons to cross a short section of broken  chaotic  ice  blocks  to
easier snow beyond, working our way to the base  of  the  snow  couloir  and
onto a rock promontory to the left  (1500  ft,  1:55  hrs).   Here  we  left
crampons and ice axes.

We could now see we had a choice of two gullies on the left  to  bypass  the
couloir. The Canadian women had said you could see rappel slings  about  100
ft up the gully they had taken,  but  this  was  not  really  that  helpful.
There are rappel slings all over the place here, in  the  couloir,  in  both
gullies and on the ribs in-between. The left most gully  looked  easiest  to
us but as we started up the  initial  slabs  we  somehow  ended  up  in  the
steeper looking blackish gully on the right.  I  am  still  not  sure  which
gully is best.  We later rappelled down the left  one  and  it  sure  didn\'t
look all that easy. But the right one we went  up  wasn\'t  easy  either.  It
definitely was not class 4. I started the lead and immediately knew  it  was
going to be harder than expected. I passed a rappel sling  and  did  several
class 5 moves until coming to a short steep chimney/cave with  an  abandoned
nut. Here I was stymied.  To  get  out  of  the  cave  required  a  slightly
overhanging off balance strenuous pull up to the left.  The  footholds  were
not good and I did not have the reach or strength in my arms to pull  myself
up and over. After almost coming off a couple times when my foot slipped,  I
brought Beth up. She is probably the better rock climber, is taller  with  a
longer reach and had rock shoes along.  I was climbing in  boots.  Even  so,
on her first try she almost came off. She then tried an  alternate  strategy
by first taking off her pack and then stemming the  chimney  more  directly.
This worked and 10 feet higher she set up a belay, brought up her  pack  and
then me on a tight rope. Whew! That was a close one  and  definitely  turned
out to be the crux of the whole climb.

Although Beth is better than me,  she  has  had  little  experience  placing
protection, so above the crux I took over the  lead  again  and  we  climbed
simultaneously. The gully was now easier,  class  3,  but  with  downsloping
slippery grass, dirt  and  slabs  and  scary  exposure,  I  placed  lots  of
protection. All this took time and by the time we reached the W Ridge  notch
it was 11:45 (2000 ft, 5 hrs).  From the notch the beautiful  W  Ridge  rose
in a perfect line to the heavens.  I could barely believe  we  had  actually
made it this far.

We began on the ridge simulclimbing. I  passed  on  the  direct  start  that
includes a big jump over a chockstone chimney, instead  electing  to  thread
between snow and rock on the N side below  the  chimney  and  regaining  the
ridge beyond. We continued directly on the crest for  several  hundred  feet
of lovely climbing.  It just doesn\'t get any better than this. The rock  was
gorgeous and solid and horns and cracks abounded for protection. At a  large
intimidating steep tower, we began belayed climbing as I bypassed it on  the
N side via exposed ledges of  moderate  difficulty  and  then  regained  the
ridge well past the tower. The remainder of the climb stayed  on  the  ridge
going over the top of the W false summit, down a short  steep  step  into  a
notch and up the final easy bit to the summit (2500 ft, 8:50 hrs).

Despite the growing lateness of the hour, we stayed long enough  on  top  to
enjoy the views, to take pictures and to  properly  congratulate  ourselves.
We could find no register, but I really didn\'t expect one, and as  often  as
the peak is climbed I saw no point in leaving one of  my  little  ones.   It
would fill up in a month. We left at 4:15, now almost certain we  would  get
down after dark. Little did we know how long after dark. (Well,  technically
we made it back to camp in daylight, but it was daylight of the next day.)

We downclimbed to the false summit then began a series of rappels along  the
ridge off established rappel anchors. I lost count of the number of  rappels
but it was somewhere around 5 or 6.  I found  many  of  the  rappels  to  be
rather awkward in keeping on the crest of the ridge. Rappels work best  down
the fall line, not along a ridge or traverse. And I was  constantly  worried
that our rope would get hung up, especially after my  recent  experience  of
losing one on Hard Mox. We only had one rope and could not  afford  to  lose
it. But we had no trouble. Beth and I worked well together getting the  rope
down, she pulling and me threading through the next anchor and  coiling.  We
regained the notch at 7:15 and downclimbed to  the  first  of  a  series  of
rappel anchors on the rib to the west of both of the bypass ascent  gullies.


These rappels (again I lost count but I think there were 5) were  easier  as
they were straight down the fall line and were exactly 50m  apart  and  went
quickly enough that we almost made it off the  rock  before  dark.   Almost.
But unexpectantly our 50m rope did not reach to the last anchor  and  I  was
left high and dry on exposed slabs very much not to my likeing about  20  ft
short in waning light. By the time we figured out a safe  way  down  it  was
pitch dark and we had to do the last (and steepest, it was down  a  vertical
cliff) rappel by headlamp. We reached the rock promontory and our  stash  of
gear at 9:45.

Our problems weren\'t over yet even though we were down the technical  stuff.
To avoid the ice on the glacier toe, we followed the snow, now  soft  enough
for boots, down as far as we could.  We did avoid the ice, but this  put  us
far W above the waterfall cliff from where we  had  bypassed  it.  We  tried
going directly down from where we were and almost made it.  Almost.  But  we
couldn\'t see well enough to find a route and ended up traversing the top  of
the cliff all the way back to our ascent gully. Once down  this,  we  picked
up the line of cairns on the slabs, now knew where we were and  almost  made
it back to camp. Almost. But we  lost  the  way  in  the  featureless  lower
terrain and completely missed it. We knew camp was at  6200  ft,  and  after
going down to 6100 ft tried climbing back to 6200  ft  and  traversing  back
and forth.  Little did we know that our altimeter was reading  high  and  we
were traversing 100 ft too low. You may well ask why I  didn\'t  just  follow
my GPS to camp as I have done on countless other trips. Well I  did  have  a
GPS with me (my low tech lightweight mapless one) but  I  had  neglected  to
mark a waypoint for camp, a major oversight and just plain dumb.  Without  a
waypoint the GPS was  useless.  And  so  we  wandered  in  the  dark  for  a
considerable length of time getting more and more confused until  it  became
obvious we didn\'t have a clue where we were or which way to go.

It was now 2am and in about 3 hrs would be light again,  so  we  decided  to
wait it out, picked a comfy level spot by a  creek,  and  plopped  ourselves
down for a little rest. I put on all my clothes, took off my boots,  put  my
feet in my pack, laid down on my short foam pad and  using  my  harness  and
rack for a lumpy pillow went to sleep.  Almost. I really didn\'t  sleep  that
much as I soon got chilled, despite the mild night.  Beth  fared  better  as
she had the foresight to have a space blanket along  and  I  think  she  did
actually sleep. I usually  take  a  3  oz  space  emergency  bag  along  but
inexplicably neglected to bring one  this  time.   Dumb,  dumb,  dumb.  That
would have really helped in keeping the light but chilling wind off.   So  I
was awake as it began getting light and I soon recognized where we were.  We
were literally only 200 yards or so from camp. What we  had  done  was  come
down W of camp, traversed 50-100 feet below it and come up to the  E  of  it
making a semicircle around it. Well we had almost found camp.  Almost!

We dragged ourselves to camp, crawled into our bags  and  had  some  quality
sleep until awakened at 8:30 by a blazing hot sun. Then I had  "dinner"  and
rehydrated and we rested more until finally packing up and leaving a  little
after noon.  On the way out, we encountered the hordes  of  climbers  coming
in for the weekend. One party of two exceptionally fit looking fellows  with
very light packs was headed for the N Ridge of Forbidden, but  most  of  the
others were after the W Ridge. We  passed  on  what  useful  information  we
could. With tired bodies moving at half speed, we reached  the  TH  at  3:00
(3.5 miles, 2:50 hrs).

Total: 10 miles and 6200 ft in 3 days

Despite our difficulties and problems, I couldn\'t ask  for  a  more  fitting
end to my  quest  to  climb  the  Bulger  Hundred  Highest  -  a  beautiful,
challenging peak, an epic adventure and my first ever  unplanned  bivy,  all
shared with a congenial compatible partner. And even though it did  take  us
a long time we got up and down safely and that is what counts. I would  also
like to thank all those generous climbers would encouraged and supported  me
throughout this quest, and who accompanied me on my other climbs.  You  know
who you are.  I couldn\'t have done it without you.

Fay Pullen.
