            'tr' => '
Graybeard Pk (7965 ft - 1005P), Kitling Pk (8003 ft - 523P),  Cub  Pk  (7985
ft - 305P) & New Morning Pk (7230 ft - 110P) - Mt Arriva Quad -  August  24-
25, 2006

I  love  Easy  Pass.  It  has  a  pleasant  short  trail  that  leads  to  a
spectacularly scenic area. With the added incentive of several worthy  peaks
to climb on either side of the pass, it seemed perfect for a laid back  two-
day trip. The only caveat was it was too late in the season for water to  be
available at the pass itself so I had to haul it  from  the  last  available
source about 1500 ft below. This added a noticeable  7  pounds  to  my  pack
weight but was total worth it to be able to camp at  the  pass.  I  found  a
wonderful campsite several hundred yards away from  the  trail  and  on  the
National Forest side of the ridge so as to be legal without  a  Park  permit
(3.5 miles, 2:45 hrs, 2850 ft).

Graybeard Pk: I quickly set up camp and started for Graybeard at  2:50.  You
cannot see Graybeard from Easy Pass and must first get around a 7360  ft  NW
cliffy point. This I did by climbing the ridge SE to about 6800 ft and  then
traversing and dropping into a western basin. This basin contained  a  small
tarn and creek and would make a nice place to camp (this is in the  National
Park though and requires a permit). From the lower end of a basin I  spotted
a ramp that appeared to go around a cliff to give simple  access  to  the  W
Ridge, but instead led to 200 ft of sporting  class  4  climbing  with  good
holds. Once above this the ridge leveled off at  a  7200  ft  saddle  before
rising again where I worked my way up class 2-3 terrain along the  crest.  I
soon came to the "25 ft notch that requires climbing" mentioned  in  Beckey.
Not knowing exactly what this meant I had come prepared with an 80  ft  rope
and very light rack but the notch ended up being only a 10 ft class  4  step
with good holds that did not require any of the above. I topped out  on  the
summit at 5:05 (1650 ft, 2:15). I could find no register  and  left  one  of
mine.

When I had left in the morning the forecast was for  10  percent  chance  of
rain during the day and  zero  percent  at  night.  Despite  this,  I  could
clearly see weather headed  my  way  as  fog  began  enveloping  the  higher
summits and a few raindrops began falling. Where  the  heck  did  this  come
from? I had planned on climbing Little Tack (7400 ft - 160P) just to the  S,
and to this end quickly descended southern scree slopes to a  broad  saddle.
I then climbed up to a cute point just N of the spire (which  I  have  taken
the liberty of naming Tiny Tack) but Little  Tack  looked  to  be  a  fairly
serious undertaking, at least one or maybe two roped pitches  and  with  the
deteriorating weather it didn\'t seem advisable  to  continue.  So  I  headed
back to the 7200 ft saddle in the W Ridge and an  easier  descent  into  the
basin than the way I had come up and hastened back to camp arriving at  7:15
(3 miles, 2050 ft, 4:25 hrs RT). It was now raining lightly  and  everything
was all wet. With me in my confining bivy tent, changing clothes and  making
a  hot  dinner  was  a  challenge  requiring  all  manner  of  uncomfortable
contortions.  It rained lightly but steadily for a good two hours.  I  guess
zero percent chance of rain doesn\'t mean it can\'t rain!

Kitling Pk: I started for Kitling the next morning under clearing  skies  at
7:15 climbing directly N from Easy Pass to the crest  of  the  ridge  above.
This is the start of the aptly  named  Ragged  Ridge  and  it  certainly  is
ragged. I climbed to a 7280 highpoint, then  had  to  descend  and  traverse
unpleasant scree and hard dirt around the cliffs of Pt 7690 (210P)  until  I
could ascend to the top of this point from  the  SW.  I  then  followed  the
ridge to the saddle with Kitling, ascending that peak via  class  3  gullies
on the SW slope. I reached the summit at 10:00 (1950 ft, 2:45 hrs). I  found
a film can register placed June 15, 1996  by  Dallas  Kloke.  There  were  5
other entries including Stefan Feller and Greg Koenig on  9/16/05  and  Mike
Torok on 10/10/05. I transcribed the entries into one  of  my  registers  as
best I could (they were a little hard to read)  and  included  the  original
piece of paper.

Cub Pk: I now headed for this peak descending my ascent route until I  could
traverse W below cliffs to a 7440 ft saddle (Mesahchie Col). From  here  the
ridge looked harder than it turned out to be.  I still carried my  rope  and
rack but I didn\'t need them (in fact I didn\'t use them the whole  trip,  but
it was comforting to know I could if necessary).   Cub  may  not  have  much
prominence but it is a named peak and turned out  to  be  a  very  enjoyable
mostly class 3, with a few class 4 moves, climb  by  staying  right  on  the
crest. It also has a most  spectacular  head-on  view  of  the  W  ridge  of
Mesahchie. I topped out at 11:50 (2500 ft, 4:35 hrs) and found the  original
first ascent register placed on August 24, 1968 by  John  and  Chris  Roper.
The two scraps of paper were in surprisingly good shape considering the  old
metal film can was corroded through in several spots. It was  still  legible
because John had signed in with a  permanent  black  marker.   He  stated  "
named Cub Pk because it\'s the smaller companion to Panther Pk 8795  directly
to the west". Panther Pk was John\'s original name for Mesahchie Pk.  I  love
the sense of history these old registers provide. There were 7 more  entries
including Grant Meyers 7/10/91, Mitch Blanton 5/23/92  and  Don  and  Natala
Goodman 9/25/93, the last being in 2002. I  only  had  a  matchbox  register
left with me, which was too small to include the original paper.  So  I  put
that in the intact plastic film can I had removed  from  Kitling  to  better
protect it and placed both it and the new matchbox in the summit cairn.

From Mesahchie Col I dropped  directly  SE  down  scree  to  begin  a  lower
traverse than on the way in at 7200 ft back to the  ridge  above  Easy  Pass
from where I hoped to climb New Morning Pk.  Beckey describes  the  W  Ridge
of this peak as "a hike".  He has got to be kidding! He obviously has  never
climbed this peak or even looked at it. This is the  impressive  rocky  peak
that looms to the N directly above the last 1000 ft of the Easy Pass  Trail.
Not only is the W ridge not a hike, I am not sure  it  can  be  climbed,  at
least not very easily.  I scrambled along the ridge  as  far  as  reasonably
possible until stopped by notches and sheer pinnacles. I was quickly  losing
my desire to continue until I spotted a route by descending a  hundred  feet
or so and traversing on awful scree ledges to get past the  pinnacles  until
an even worse awful loose gully allowed a way up to the ridge and summit  at
2:35. I did make the top but as a  climb  it  has  little  to  recommend  it
except a lovely name.  At least it was mercifully short. No  register  other
than a rusted can with some sort of banner crammed inside.

I was back to camp by 3:30 (4 miles, 3100 ft, 8:15  hrs),  left  45  minutes
later and at the car at 5:30.

Total: 14 miles and 8000 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen


