            'month' => '09',
            'subdir' => '2006-09-08-duckabush',
            'title' => 'Mt Duckabush, East Pk (6233 ft - 1233P), Middle Pk (ca. 6225?) &West Pk (ca. 6250?); White Mtn (6360+ ft - 480P) & Overlook Pk (5680+ ft - 600P) - Mt Steel Quad - September 8-11, 2006',
            'tr' => '
Mt Duckabush, East Pk (6233 ft - 1233P), Middle Pk (ca. 6225?) &West Pk
(ca. 6250?); White Mtn (6360+ ft - 480P) & Overlook Pk (5680+ ft - 600P) -
Mt Steel Quad - September 8-11, 2006

It has been over two years since I have been to the Olympics (been too  busy
chasing after Big Boys, none of  which  reside  there)  and  I  have  sorely
missed them.  I love the Olympics. So  when  a  trip  to  climb  Fisher  and
Arriva was cancelled due to impending bad  weather  and  other  problems,  I
figured it was time to rectify the situation. I had always wanted  to  visit
the high mountain lakes of  LaCrosse,  Hart  and  Marmot,  whose  beauty  is
legendary, but they are so far in that I just never got around to it. I  had
four days available to me, Friday  to  Monday  with  rain  predicted  Friday
night and Saturday. A little rain would not be a big problem for the  mostly
trail approach and for viewing the lakes.  And if  the  weather  turned  out
better than expected, there were several worthwhile peaks  in  the  vicinity
to climb.

Day 1: I began the long approach up  the  East  Fork  Quinault  River  Trail
(elev 600 ft) at 10:15. I  had  a  minor  setback  when  I  discovered  that
permits are no longer issued at the TH  (they  were  the  last  time  I  was
there) but must be obtained at a ranger station. I was considering  being  a
scofflaw rather than drive all the way  back  to  Quinault,  when  a  Ranger
drove up and I talked him,  after  some  resistance,  into  issuing  me  one
personally. I politely suggested that a prominent  sign  be  posted  at  the
start of the road to the effect that permits must be obtained at the  ranger
station. He said there was a sign.  Perhaps, but it was not  obvious  enough
for me to notice it.

I carried my climbing boots and  hiked  the  13.3  miles  to  the  Enchanted
Valley in light trail shoes to save my feet, changing to  boots  only  after
the trail became rougher and started climbing  steeply  above  the  river  a
couple miles farther on. At 16.9 miles (elev 3200 ft) I turned off onto  the
O\'Neil Pass Trail. It was now 6:45 and  I  knew  I  couldn\'t  get  too  much
farther before dark.  I had hoped to camp at the edge of  White  Cr  Meadow,
elev 3750, about another mile, but both  established  campsites  there  were
occupied, so I continued off trail another 200 ft into the  basin  of  White
Cr and found an adequate flat spot between boulders at 7:45 (18 miles,  4600
ft, 9:30 hrs) with just enough light left to set  up  camp.  Dinner  was  by
headlamp.

Day 2 - White Mtn: The entire day Friday had remained  sunny  and  warm  but
sometime  during  the  night  weather  moved  in  and  it  rained  steadily,
occasionally even hard, until daylight. Then it quit. Must have been a  fast
moving cold  front.  But  everything  was  wet  and  lingering  fog  limited
visibility.  Still, I thought I could climb White Mtn from where I was.   It
was a straight shot some 2400 ft above me.  All  I  had  to  do  was  follow
White Cr. This  route  is  not  even  mentioned  in  the  Olympic  Mountains
Climbing Guide, but it has to be the easiest way up.

Despite the fog, the route up meadows was pleasant and easy  going  until  I
reached the upper cliffy area and even  then  it  was  not  bad  by  Olympic
standards. My GPS guided me in the general direction of the top through  the
cliffs to a notch and a final class 3-4 scramble (1 mile, 2400 ft,  2  hrs).
The guide calls it class 2, but then it  always  underestimates  difficulty,
although I probably didn\'t find the easiest way. The fog  was  beginning  to
lift and views were slowly appearing. There are three points that appear  on
the map with the same number of contours.  I was  on  the  north  summit.  I
could see the two southern points well enough  to  sight  on  them  with  my
clinometer and both read enough lower that I was  convinced  my  summit  was
the high point. There was also a cairn (no register  but  I  left  one)  and
that is where the name is located on the map. Good enough for me.

I was back in camp by 12:30 and packed by 1:30. Meanwhile I  had  formulated
a plan to continue crosscountry  to  Lake  LaCrosse  rather  than  take  the
trail. Robert Wood in his Trail Guide to the Olympic  Mountains  mentions  a
route over Fishers Notch that could  be  done  by  experienced  backpackers.
Unfortunately, I had descended into fog again and couldn\'t  see  the  route.
Still, there had to be one, although it looked awfully  steep  on  the  map,
and I thought if I just headed in the general direction I  would  figure  it
out. It actually turned out to be a nice way to go,  although  a  bit  of  a
grunt with a full pack on the loose rock. I pulled over the  5400  ft  notch
at 3:15 and entered heaven on the other side.

I descended lovely meadows, picked up the trail at  Lake  LaCrosse,  took  a
side trip to Hart Lake, went past  Marmot  Lake  and  a  junction  with  the
Duckabush River Trail and wandered up and down to a delightful  campsite  by
a small mossy babbling brook just below O\'Neil  Pass.  This  whole  area  is
every bit as beautiful as its reputation would have you  believe.  Even  the
billowing fog did not detract but  only  added  a  bit  of  mystery  to  the
landscape. I also had it all to myself, seeing no one else anywhere.  I  set
up camp at 6:15 with enough time to  relax  and  watch  Mt  Anderson  slowly
emerge from the clouds in the distance (5 miles,  2400  ft,  4:45  hrs  from
White Cr camp).

Day 3 - Mt Duckabush and Overlook Pk: Morning dawned cold and  clear  and  I
started for Mt Duckabush at 7:50. I traversed from camp and  found  a  steep
ramp to descend into the snow basin N of  the  mountain.  Mt  Duckabush  has
three summits, East, Middle and West. The East Pk is surveyed  at  6233  ft,
is where the name is printed on the map and is what I would  presume  to  be
the high point. According to map contours the Middle Pk is 6160+ ft and  the
West Pk 6200+ ft.  Yet for some strange reason  the  Climber\'s  Guide  lists
the West Pk as 6250 ft and considers it to be  the  summit.  Perhaps  giving
this peak a higher  elevation  is  wishful  thinking  as  it  is  much  more
imposing and difficult to attain. I have found the  Climber\'s  Guide  to  be
inconsistent and puzzling with many anomalies  when  it  comes  to  relating
names to high points.  This however left me in a quandary as to  which  peak
to climb. The logical solution, of course, was to climb  both.  However  the
East Pk was listed as class 3 and the West Pk as class 4. Since I have  also
found the guide listings to be consistently underrated (always  increase  it
by one class) I was not sure I had the skills, time or gear (I only  had  an
80 ft rope and 2 slings) to climb their class 4.

All these considerations aside, I wasn\'t  sure  I  could  even  get  up  the
easier East Pk.  The standard route up  the  snowfinger  and  gully  to  the
notch between East and Middle Peaks looked awful and my heart  sank  when  I
discovered the snow was frozen to ice hard. To save weight on the long  trek
in I had brought aluminum half-crampons with 6 points that only covered  the
front half of my boots. Would I be able to climb the steepening finger  with
these? To my surprise  they  worked  better  than  expected  as  long  as  I
concentrated on keeping my weight on the front  of  my  boots,  but  it  was
still a nervewracking tiptoeing cotton-mouthed business.  The  point  of  my
aluminum axe did not penetrate the snow enough to do any good  but  I  found
that by swinging full force the pick went  in  about  an  inch  and  gave  a
surprisingly solid handhold. In this manner I was able to get to the end  of
the snow and enter the gully, where things did not improve that much.   Even
by Olympic standards (renowned for loose crud) this gully was awful. I  kept
my crampons on (much to their detriment) mainly because I couldn\'t  keep  my
balance long enough to remove them but also  because  they  actually  helped
give me purchase on the steep dirt.  Even so  I  was  barely  able  to  make
upward progress and  often  slipped  backwards  in  the  shifting  junk.  As
gullies go, this has to rank as one of my worst ever.  (Note  that  if  this
gully were filled with reasonably soft snow all the  way  to  the  notch  it
would be an easy romp.)

I thankfully topped out at the 6000 ft notch at 10:10 and  the  East  Pk  20
minutes later (1500 ft, 2:40 hrs). There was a cairn but no register. I  did
leave one of mine. I spent a half hour on top enjoying all the views  I  had
missed the previous day. But what to do now? I was not keen  on  going  back
down the gully and snowfinger, which was in the shade and would  not  soften
significantly all day. There was supposed to be a class 3 route all on  rock
directly down the NW arÃªte from the West Peak. The Middle  (you  had  to  go
over the Middle Pk to get to the West  Pk)  and  West  Peaks  looked  rather
challenging but doable if the rock wasn\'t too bad. Maybe I could do  a  loop
and avoid the gully entirely.  And so I chose the evil I  didn\'t  know  over
the evil I did know. Not always a wise thing to do.

I actually found the climb over the Middle Pk to  the  West  Pk  reasonable,
and dare I say it, enjoyable. It really was mostly class 4 with maybe a  few
very low class 5 moves.  The holds were good although some were loose.   But
the traverse, which stayed for the most part right on the ridge  crest,  was
very exposed.  So I took my time, tested each hold and arrived at  the  West
Summit at 12:05 (1800 ft, 4:15 hrs). I had sighted from East to West Pk  and
now I sighted  West  to  East  Pk  with  my  clinometer.   According  to  my
measurements the East 6233 ft Pk is definitely higher. No matter. I found  a
register on the West Pk so "those  in  the  know"  must  consider  this  the
summit. The register was placed 8/4/86 and there were only 4 other  entries.


About now I was feeling pretty good and  looking  forward  to  a  relatively
easy class 3 descent down the arÃªte.  Almost  immediately  that  expectation
was shattered as I came to a steep wall just  below  the  summit.  Class  3?
Where oh where is there a class 3 route down this wall?  Or even a  class  4
one. Search as I did I could find none. The thought of reversing  everything
back to the notch and gully was almost  unthinkable  at  this  point.  So  I
found a very circuitous way to do an end run on the S  slopes  to  get  past
the wall and crossed over the W ridge back to the NW  arÃªte.  Much  of  this
was on awful loose ledges and the farther I descended the more I felt I  was
sealing my fate and fast reaching the point of no return. Once on the  arÃªte
I looked up at the wall and still could see no way up  it.  I  was  able  to
downclimb the arÃªte for a couple hundred feet  until  I  hit  another  step.
Class 3? You have got to be kidding! I should have known better. I got  down
this section with 3 rappels using my woefully short 80 ft  rope.   Two  were
off trees and one off a rock horn.  While pulling the rope off the  horn,  a
rock came down and smashed my right index finger. Better my finger  than  my
head. Eventually the terrain on the left moderated enough that  I  left  the
arÃªte for sandy ledges and slabs and worked my way down to a snow slope  (in
the sun and soft enough for boots) above an ice lake. This whole descent  of
little more than 600 ft took over 2 hours.

From the ice lake I wandered gentle terrain  back  to  O\'Neil  Pass.  I  had
thought to climb O\'Neil Pk but I was running out of time and  energy  and  I
decided not to press my luck any farther. I felt fortunate to  have  escaped
Duckabush intact. I did however  have  time  to  zip  up  easy  Overlook  Pk
directly above the pass. Despite being slowed by luscious blueberries I  was
on that summit in 30  minutes.  This  peak  is  aptly  named,  as  it  is  a
wonderful viewpoint. I found an illegible register in a  jar  half  full  of
water on top. I was back in camp by 5:00 (3 miles, 2800 ft, 9  hrs  for  the
day).

Day 4: I was awakened to the wonderful wilderness sound of an  elk  bugling.
I poked my nose out my tent and sure enough a bull  was  jealously  guarding
his harem in the basin directly below. It was getting that time of  year.  I
began the long trip out at 8:30 staying on trail the whole way.  The  entire
O\'Neil Pass trail is a delight as it traverses up and  down  through  scenic
meadows. I began running into people coming in. I had seen  no  one  at  all
the whole time I was in the Lakes Basin. Just after crossing  White  Cr  and
turning a corner in the trail I startled a bear not 10 feet away. It  was  a
tossup who  was  more  frightened,  he  or  I.  I  heard  more  elk  bugling
throughout the day but saw no more. I reached the junction  with  the  trail
to Anderson Pass at 12:15 and the Enchanted Valley at 2:00.  I  stopped  for
lunch by the river, soaked my aching feet and changed from  boots  to  light
shoes for the rest of the trip out. I wasn\'t sure I could  make  it  out  in
one day, but it wasn\'t as bad as I had thought and my body and feet held  up
reasonably well. I reached the TH at 8:00 just at dark  without  needing  to
use my headlamp (24 miles, 1900 ft, 11:30 hrs).

Grand Total: 52 miles and 14,100 ft in 4 days

Fay Pullen








