            'tr' => '
Mt Olsen (5289 ft - 849P), Mt Olsen West Pk (5105 ft- 425P) & Pk 5050
(450P) - Mt Olsen Quad - September 22-24, 2006

I have had my eye on Mt Olsen for a number of years. It is not  a  difficult
peak, just a long ways in, as many Olympic peaks are. I  originally  thought
to access it from the N Fork Skokomish and long steep Six Ridge  Trail,  but
the closure of Staircase due to fire damage to the road made me look for  an
alternative. So that is how I ended up going in over Wynoochee Pass. I  have
long been intrigued by  this  trail,  but  it  had  a  reputation  of  being
difficult to find  and  difficult  to  follow  and  was  reported  to  being
essentially abandoned. Thus, before trying to use this trail  for  access  I
decided to scout it out on a 2-day trip beforehand.  Good thing I did, as  I
got royally lost trying to find  the  trailhead  in  the  maze  of  unmarked
logging roads beyond Wynoochee Lake.  But I also discovered that  the  trail
is far from abandoned and is in fact completely logged and  brushed  out.  I
got as far  as  McGravey  Lakes  on  my  reconnaissance,  became  completely
enchanted with the area, couldn\'t wait to return and even climbed  the  high
point of Six Ridge (5122 ft - 762P).

Day 1: Even with previous knowledge of how to get to the TH, it  still  took
forever to drive the nearly 50 miles of logging roads N from  Montesano  and
it was almost 11:00  before  Linda  and  I  left  the  car,  elev  2500  ft.
Surprisingly there was one other car  parked.  The  road  is  blocked  by  a
washout  .3 mile before the true TH.  Walking the road,  we  soon  ran  into
the owner of the parked vehicle coming out.  He  was  a  volunteer  for  the
Park and had a permanent camp at the crossing of  the  Wynoochee  R  some  2
miles in. (I had noticed this tent on my prior trip and wondered about  it.)
 He told us that volunteers had been working on the trail  for  the  past  6
years and had finally completed the work. What good timing for  us!  He  was
coming back in a few days to dismantle his camp  before  the  seasonal  road
closure Oct 1.

At the switchback in the road,  the  true  trail  (unmarked)  went  straight
ahead and immediately entered lovely mossy woods, in sharp contrast  to  the
miles of clearcuts before. In another .3  miles,  the  boundary  of  Olympic
National  Park  was  reached  where  permits  were  available.   The   trail
continued, in good shape but rough in spots and obviously not heavily  used,
2.4 miles to the small meadow at Wynoochee Pass,  elev  3600  ft  (1250  ft,
1:40 hr). From here the trail drops 900 ft in 1.4 miles to a  junction  with
the Graves Cr Trail, only to climb back up again.  Over the years, to  avoid
this ridiculous unnecessary elevation loss, hikers have booted in  a  cutoff
trail that more or less contours from one trail branch to the other.  It  is
rough and brushy but well marked with flags and easily followed.  It  begins
about .3 mile down from the pass.

Once back on the main trail, we passed the junction with  the  Sundown  Pass
and S Fork Skokomish Trail at a meadow where we  startled  a  bear  cub  (no
mama in sight), then continued on to Sundown Lake  where  an  elk  herd  was
foraging the slopes above. From here the trail climbed to  Six  Ridge  Pass,
elev 4700 ft, only to drop steeply to McGravey Lakes, elev 4000 ft where  we
saw another bear. Another 2 miles of up and down took  us  to  Belview,  the
site of a shelter now gone, and a final uphill mile met the junction of  the
trail to Lake Success on the crest of the Ridge, elev 4400 (10  miles,  4300
ft, 7:20 hrs). Even though this section of trail went exasperatingly up  and
down, it traversed delightful terrain full of  meadows,  creeks,  tarns  and
views.

We really wanted to make Lake Success for camp, but it was getting late,  it
was still 3 miles away and we were worried we wouldn\'t make it before  dark.
Fortunately, the Lake Success Trail, actually part of the old  abandoned  Mt
Olsen Trail that used to go all the way to the Enchanted Valley  Trail,  was
in much better shape than expected. It began by more or less  following  the
crest of Six Ridge to a saddle (elev 4900 ft) between two towers (Shaw  5065
ft & Heather 5025 ft), dropped 600 ft into the basin beyond, climbed  up  to
a spur ridge, crossed, dropped on the other side, climbed again to the  spur
ridge before making a final drop to the beautiful meadows of  Success  Basin
where we saw another bear. Yikes, this one was  too  close  for  comfort  to
where we would be camping. We found a wonderful spot for our tent above  the
lake at 7:30, elev 4200 ft (13 miles, 5300 ft,  8:30  hours.  Note  that  we
ended up only 1700 ft above the elevation of the car but had  to  gain  5300
ft on the up and down route to get there.

Day 2: Mt Olsen is not far from Lake Success, so we were in no great  hurry,
starting at 9:40. We began on the old Mt Olsen Trail, but this trail is  now
very sketchy and we soon lost it in the initial steep brushy  hillside.   We
picked it up again at the edge of a high meadow, where we saw bear # 4,  but
soon lost it again. The trail actually stays in the woods to  the  right  of
the meadow climbing nearly to the saddle NE of Pt 4935 before  crossing  the
meadow high and traversing to the saddle E of Mt Olsen.  We  could  see  the
trail switchbacking down into the basin on the other side  but  I  doubt  it
can be followed very far anymore before disappearing  completely  in  brush.
From the saddle, Mt Olsen is an easy climb up steep heather and  blueberries
and we reached the summit at 11:30 (1150 ft, 1:50 hr).

Views were spectacular and we spent a good half hour  enjoying  them  before
attempting the traverse to the West Peak. I wasn\'t sure this peak  would  go
very easily.  Looking at the map, the connecting ridge  looked  narrow  with
steep contours on either side, often a sign of  rocky  pinnacles  and  other
obstacles. Even getting down to the saddle between  the  two  peaks  was  no
picnic and harder than it looked mostly because views to  the  W  Peak  were
obstructed and it was not obvious how to get on the ridge. Then once at  the
saddle, some four notches had to be crossed. The first two  were  easy;  the
third had a 50 wall that was surmounted directly  by  pulling  on  branches.
But the last notch was a shocker.  Just when I  thought  I  had  the  summit
made I came to a deep seemingly impassible 100 ft  notch.   I  couldn\'t  see
any way down directly so backtracked to descend  an  awful  side  gully  and
traversed questionable dirt and rock ledges  until  I  could  get  into  the
notch from below. A final easy scramble led to the summit at 1:20 (1900  ft,
3:40 hrs).

On the way back I was able to ascend out of the notch directly  as  I  could
see where to go. Branch belays helped. It was also easier to  climb  up  the
ridge to Mt Olsen. I was back on that summit at 2:40 and we were  both  back
to camp at 4:20 after seeing bear #5 (3.5 miles, 2900 ft, 6:40) I  rested  a
bit then took off for  Peak  5050.  Linda  elected  to  stay  in  camp.  The
approach to this peak was delightful through meadows to an upper  tarn  just
below the ridgeline.  Here I saw a lone bull elk with  a  very  large  rack.
My, what a handsome fellow he was. The rest of the way to the summit was  up
easy heather and blueberries, a short pleasant climb. I ambled back to  camp
through more meadows and saw yet another bear (1.5 miles, 850  ft,  1:30  hr
RT). While I was gone Linda discovered a full set of elk antlers.

Day 3: With all the ups and downs and rest stops it actually took us  longer
to hike out than in. We took a side trip up Heather  Pt  for  the  fantastic
view of where we had been.  We had a long rest at Belview and  stopped  even
longer at McGravey Lakes where I soaked my feet and Linda took a very  quick
dip in the cold water. We saw  our  last  bear  (#7)  in  the  meadows  near
Sundown Pass junction.  This is the same place we saw the  cub  on  the  way
in, but this bear was BIG.  Maybe it was mama bear. Despite  all  the  bears
we saw, none gave us a bit of trouble and ran away as soon as they  saw  us.
We continued our leisurely pace and reached the car at 6:45 (13 miles,  3750
ft, 10 hrs).

Total: 31 miles and 12,800 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen


