            'tr' => '
Discovery Pk (4837 ft - 637P) & West Discovery Pk (4665 ft - 425P) - Mt
Hoquiam Quad - September 27, 2006

I ran across these peaks while researching the Wynoochee  Pass  approach  to
Mt Olsen and what a pleasant surprise they turned out to be  -  little  gems
hidden in a maze of logging roads and clearcuts. Both are on the ridge  that
forms the boundary of the Olympic National Park in  this  area  but  neither
has been logged to the summit. Yes the approach is on an  old  logging  road
(about 1 mile long), but a nice little fisherman\'s  trail  (about  .5  mile)
leads from the end of the road to Discovery Lake and  lovely  meadows.  From
the lake it is a fun little scramble to the rocky summits of both peaks.

A bonus is the rock spires of Grosbeak (4400+  ft)  peaking  out  above  the
forest on the S ridge of the W Peak in a most  unexpected  location.   These
unique looking spires are visible from where the car is parked but there  is
no indication of them on the map. I spent a couple hours  climbing  the  two
highest ones. The N spire is easily climbed via the class 3  but  exposed  N
ridge. The S spire can probably be climbed from the notch  with  the  N  one
but looked to be class 5 and I had  no  gear  with  me  so  didn\'t  try  it.
Instead I found a class 4 route from the notch with a lesser spire on the  S
and up the S ridge. There are many other  climbing  possibilities  on  these
fun spires if you come prepared.

I had good views into the heart of the Olympics and to  the  near  peaks  of
Capitol, Church, Three Peaks and Hoquiam, all  of  which  looked  rocky  and
inviting. They are all now on my to do list but I will have  to  wait  until
next year as the seasonal road closure begins October  1  and  will  prevent
access unless you are willing to have  a  long  bike  ride  with  a  lot  of
elevation gain. This area has opened up many  new  possibilities  for  short
but quality climbs for me. The  only  caveat  is  the  long  drive  and  the
possibility of getting lost on the miles of unmarked logging  roads  in  the
Wynoochee lake area.

Total: 6.5 miles, 2700 ft and 7 hrs.

Fay Pullen
