            'title' => 'Mt LaCrosse (6417 ft - 977P) and Mt Elk Lick (6517 ft - 1997P) - Mt Steel Quad - September 29 - October 1, 2006',
            'tr' => '
Mt LaCrosse (6417 ft - 977P) and Mt Elk Lick (6517 ft - 1997P) - Mt Steel
Quad - September 29 - October 1, 2006

After seeing Mt LaCrosse from White Mtn a few  weeks  ago,  I  was  keen  to
climb this peak. It looked so inviting. And, of course, while  in  the  area
it made sense to go after Mt Elk Lick also  as  both  can  be  climbed  from
LaCrosse Pass. Before the washout and closure of the Dosewallips River  Road
some 4 miles before the TH, the shortest approach would  have  been  up  the
West Fork Dosewallips River Trail. It still  may  be  the  shortest,  but  I
decided to go in via the Duckabush River Trail  instead,  despite  its  many
ups and downs, as I had never been up that trail.

Day 1: I left the TH (elev 440 ft) at  10:20  under  sunny  skies  and  warm
temperatures. The trail was in excellent shape (I hiked the  entire  day  in
light trail shoes carrying my boots), first climbing on an old road  to  The
Brothers Wilderness Boundary at  1  mile,  elev  900  ft,  at  Little  Hump,
dropping about 300 ft to the river and then  climbing  in  many  switchbacks
steeply to Big Hump, elev 1700 ft (4 miles, 1770 ft, 2:20 hrs). Big Hump  is
an annoyance to hikers, but it was also  a  barrier  to  early  loggers  and
spared the upper Duckabush old growth forest from their  saws.  It  is  also
somewhat of a geologic curiosity as I found out when I decided to  climb  to
the high point of Big Hump (1817 ft - 57P - Mt Jupiter Quad).  It looked  so
easy on the map and I thought it would be a  fun  little  10  minutes  round
trip to a scenic viewpoint. Well, Big Hump is actually a cluster of  several
little steep rocky mossy "humps" each surrounded by a 50-75 ft  deep  "moat"
that make finding the highest hump and travel between  humps  difficult.  It
was interesting and I did get my viewpoint on top  the  highest  hump  (with
the help of my GPS) but the RT took 35 minutes and was rather  more  than  I
bargained for.

From Big Hump the trail dropped again some 600 ft to the scenic  river  full
of pools and rapids and narrow canyons.  The  trail  wandered  up  and  down
through lovely mossy old growth forest and campsites were numerous.  At  6.5
miles was the boundary of Olympic National Park and at 10.6 miles the  large
established (and smelly) stock camp of Tenmile, elev 1500 ft (2700 ft,  6:15
hr).

I would have liked to camp at LaCrosse Pass, but knew that I could  not  get
that far (20.1 miles) this time  of  year.  The  days  are  too  short  now.
Instead, I hoped to get to the junction with the LaCrosse Pass  Trail  (15.9
miles). But even that was beginning to look like a stretch unless  I  wanted
to set up camp in the dark.  So when I came  upon  an  inviting  established
site just opposite where Crazy Cr joins the Duckabush  at  5:50  (elev  1900
ft), I decided to go no farther (13.5 miles, 3400 ft, 7:30 hrs). I was  able
to wash up in the river, set  up  camp  and  eat  dinner  all  before  dark.
Actually this camp worked out for the best.   From  near  here  there  is  a
route directly upslope to Elk Lick. If I could come down that  way  I  would
save myself miles and hours by not returning to LaCrosse Pass.

Day 2: Knowing this would be a very long day, I  got  going  as  soon  as  I
could drag myself from the comfort of a warm sleeping bag and  was  underway
at 6:45. I used my  headlamp  for  the  first  20  minutes.  I  reached  the
LaCrosse Pass Trail, elev 2680 ft, at 8:00. I left this  trail  at  5200  ft
and climbed meadows directly to the ridge above, following the  crest  W  to
the base of the false summit. Here I  attacked  the  false  summit  head  on
getting into slightly tricky class 3-4 terrain.  It would have  been  easier
to contour around.  From the saddle with the main summit, I traversed  below
cliffs to a diagonal cleft that gave  access  to  steep  heather  and  scree
slopes on the S slope. I topped out at 11:30 (4800  ft,  4:45  hrs).  In  an
interesting note, the survey marker on the  summit  was  engraved  with  the
elevation 6410 ft. Since all the guides  list  the  elevation  as  6417  ft,
either the books are wrong, the marker is wrong or the marker is not on  the
high point. I have no idea  which  but  I  placed  my  register  on  a  bump
slightly E of the marker. It appeared slightly higher to  me  but  mostly  I
put it there because I could build a better cairn there to house it.

Views were spectacular (I spent 45 minutes on top), even though  marine  air
was forming and fingers of fog were beginning  to  work  their  way  up  the
river valleys below me. Rain was predicted for the night and  following  day
and it appeared to be on its way.  I just hoped it would hold off  a  while.
I returned to the saddle but from  that  point  traversed  below  the  false
summit and entire ridge all the way back to the trail. I followed the  trail
a very short distance before leaving it again at 1:25,  elev  5300  ft,  and
beginning a long traverse E toward Elk Lick.

The traverse began easily enough, through colorful  meadows  following  game
trails staying at about 5400 ft until coming to a spur ridge S of  Pt  6206.
Here I was forced to climb another couple hundred feet before finding a  way
to drop into the basin beyond. I continued dropping to 5100 ft  until  below
cliffs, then climbed again toward a  distinctive  looking  gendarme  that  I
thought was on the  summit  ridge.   No  such  luck.   As  I  got  closer  I
discovered I had another rocky rib to cross, another basin to drop into  and
the summit was still a long  ways  off.  Goldman  in  her  75  Scrambles  in
Washington states that "the trip to Elk Lick takes  about  7  hours  and  is
much longer than it appears". She got that right, although presumably the  7
hours is RT from LaCrosse Pass, not one way.

Once in the final basin below the summit, I could see no simple way  to  the
top. As I climbed upward, though, two gullies appeared feasible.  The  right
one was more direct but the upper part was obscured by a  chockstone/boulder
and I couldn\'t tell if it went all the way up. The left one  looked  easier,
at least to start.  I chose the left one and discovered it wasn\'t that  easy
soon encountering class 3-4 terrain and very steep  loose  dirt  and  scree.
Near the top I also  ran  into  dense  annoying  scrub  trees  that  impeded
progress. I reached the broad flat summit  at  4:20  (7000  ft,  9:35  hrs).
There was a register but the top was off and the bottom missing so  you  can
guess the condition of any contents. I remedied the situation  by  replacing
it with one of mine.

The fog obscured some of the views but the weather  was  still  holding.  It
was getting late with no time to spare and I quickly  left  for  my  planned
route straight down to camp. I decided to descend the  right  gully,  rather
than the left one I had ascended, as it appeared to be a direct  shot  down.
It was until I reached a rock step just above the  chockstone/boulder.  Here
I fiddled around trying to find a way to downclimb, tossed my poles down  to
get them out of my way, ended up rappelling another way then had  to  search
around to find my poles again all this wasting precious time. By the time  I
got off the rock it was 5:30 with little daylight left.
I began by making good time down meadows and scree following  to  the  right
of the cliffs of the S ridge of Elk Lick. Once below the cliffs I  tried  to
traverse left toward the supposed line of the uphill  route  from  Crazy  Cr
but it soon became obvious this was not feasible  as  there  were  too  many
brushy ravines to cross.  Note that the Crazy Cr route climbs  the  SE  side
of Elk Lick and may not even connect (at least not easily) with the SW  side
route I had just done. So I resigned myself to dropping down the  fall  line
into uncharted territory. I tried to stay on timbered ribs,  but  twice  the
ribs ended and funneled me into ugly ravines clogged  with  brush.  Crossing
the particularly nasty second ravine, I placed my pole  on  what  I  thought
was solid ground to get down to the creek at the bottom, watched it go  into
space up to the handle and me follow it head over  heel.  As  I  lay  upside
down completely devoured by the brush hole two thoughts  came  to  me:  one,
that I bet no other human being had ever been in this  exact  place  before;
and two, that should I meet my demise here I would never ever be found.

Once across that ravine, I was able to stay on a  timbered  rib  with  light
brush the rest of the way and I stumbled across  the  trail  at  7:25  (elev
2400 ft) not having needed my headlamp. I had, however,  missed  camp  by  a
mile, literally. I hobbled the last mile back along the  trail  to  camp  by
headlamp in 30 minutes (15 miles, 7150 ft, 13:10 hrs).

Day 3: I slept in till 7:30 and  left  at  9:15.  The  expected  rain  never
materialized and I awoke to sunshine and blue skies. Was  I  really  in  the
"rainy" Olympics? The trip out was  uneventful  and  leisurely.  Long  river
bottom trails are not really my favorite thing, but I embraced this one  and
took time to enjoy the beautiful forest and river. I met  one  other  camper
at TenMile, then a few Sunday day hikers once past the uphill grind  to  Big
Hump. Not having learned my lesson on Big Hump, I climbed to the high  point
of Little Hump (997 ft - 77P - Mt Jupiter Quad). It  was  a  repeat  of  Big
Hump with similar geology but, appropriately, the "humps" were on a  smaller
scale.  The RT from the trail took 35 minutes.  I  pulled  into  the  TH  at
4:30 (13.5 miles, 1750 ft, 7:15 hrs).

Total: 42 miles and 12,300 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen

