            'tr' => '
Mt Lena, East Pk (5800+ ft - 640P - The Brothers Quad) & The Bandersnatch
(5480+ ft - Mt Skokomish Quad) - October 4-6, 2006

My plan was to do the Scout Lake Way Trail between Upper Lena Lake  and  the
Putvin Trail and to connect the two trailheads, about 4.5 miles apart,  with
a bike ride. That was the plan.  But as things  often  go,  my  plan  didn\'t
work out the way I had hoped. I had a great time anyway  and  completed  two
enjoyable rock climbs along the way.

Day 1: After stashing my bike at the Putvin TH (elev  1600  ft),  I  started
from the Lena Lake TH (elev 700 ft). Things began badly right  away  when  I
discovered I hadn\'t replaced my trekking poles  in  my  car  at  home  after
removing them to load my bike. This for me is a major faux pas,  as  I  have
trouble staying upright without poles. I made  due  by  finding  a  suitable
wooden stick in the woods, but it was not the same. Then I was 5 minutes  up
the trail when I remembered  I  had  forgotten  to  set  my  car  alarm.   I
returned to the car and not only was the alarm not set but I  had  not  even
locked the doors.  Good grief! Where was my mind?  At least the rest of  the
hike to Upper Lena Lake (elev 4600 ft) went without  incidence  (7.5  miles,
4050 ft, 5 hrs).

I set up camp in designated site #6 right next to a handy bear  wire.  There
are some dozen designated sites around  the  lake  plus  one  for  a  group.
There is also a ranger stationed here in the summer so it  must  be  a  busy
place then, but on this day I had the entire  lake  all  to  myself.  I  had
hiked up in shorts but it was getting cooler and I was  in  the  process  of
zipping the  legs  back  on  my  convertible  pants  when  the  slider  came
completely off the zipper of the right leg.  Convertible  pants  that  won\'t
convert are next to useless. After much cursing and  gnashing  of  teeth,  I
managed to get the slider back on track and  the  leg  zipped  on,  but  the
zipper was damaged and I had no faith it would hold together.  I  reinforced
it with some strategically placed safety pins. This would be the  last  trip
for these pants.

I now headed for the East Peak of Lena.  It was not far from  camp,  but  it
had taken longer to get to the lake than  anticipated  and  I  had  lost  at
least 30 additional valuable minutes on the zipper episode. Also, I  had  no
prior information on the climbing route.  The most direct route would be  up
the W ridge. However, the close map contours indicated  I  could  very  well
run into difficulties. Any other route would take more time to  figure  out,
and what with the ever-shortening days,  I  may  not  have  enough  daylight
left. Ever optimistic though, I climbed  diagonally  up  from  camp  through
steep meadow to the saddle W of the peak. Climbing through brush out of  the
saddle, I heard that awful buzzing sound of impending doom  as  a  disturbed
yellow jacket nest swarmed out of  the  ground  around  me.  One  nailed  me
between shirt cuff and glove on my  right  wrist,  but  it  could  have  and
should have been much worse. They must have been somewhat lethargic  nearing
the end of their lifespan with the lateness of the year.

With wrist burning, I emerged from  the  brush  onto  the  open  rocky  very
narrow exposed ridge. Goodness gracious!  I was not sure it would  go  as  a
scramble.  But it turned out to not be as bad as it looked and  was  a  very
enjoyable class 3 scramble mostly along the very crest. I  reached  the  top
at 6:15 (.5 mile, 1250 ft, 1:15 hr). An old rusted can and unopenable  glass
jar graced the summit cairn. I added a register of mine. I made it  down  to
camp by 7:30 aided by the light of a  full  moon.  I  ran  into  the  yellow
jackets again, but I was prepared for them and went by  so  fast  (downhill)
that they missed me. I went to sleep that night with the distant  lights  of
Pugetopolis and the full moon framed in my open tent door. Magic!

Day 2: From Upper Lena Lake, I followed the Scout  Lake  Way  Trail  through
lovely meadowy terrain full of tarns and views.  This way trail is  in  good
shape and easily followed to Scout Lake  Pass  (5200  ft).  Here  the  trail
deteriorates and gets harder to follow as it descends on the other  side.  I
got confused several times and had to pause  to  find  the  correct  way.  I
passed Deerheart Lake, then dropped very  steeply  (difficult  with  a  full
pack) to a junction at 4500 ft.  Here I dropped my pack and  took  the  spur
down to Scout lake at 4200 ft. To be honest, I don\'t think it is  worth  the
effort to visit this lake.   It  is  an  awful  trail  down  to  it,  it  is
surrounded by thick forest and has no shoreline to  speak  of.   Camping  is
not allowed but I don\'t know why anyone would  want  to  camp  there  anyway
when there are so many more inviting lakes and tarns and meadows  everywhere
else near by. (Note that  the  7.5  USGS  Mt  Washington  Quad  uses  80  ft
contours, whereas all the surrounding  quads  use  the  more  normal  40  ft
contours. Very odd and very confusing. Makes the  terrain  on  much  of  the
Scout Lake Way Trail appear less steep than it really is.)

I continued from the junction uphill through more lovely meadows  and  tarns
to Stone Ponds Pass elev 5000  ft.  At  this  point  the  trail  essentially
disappeared. I worked my way down to the larger of the ponds, elev 4700  ft,
where I set up my second camp (6 miles, 1650 ft, 4:30  hrs.)   My  plan  now
was to climb The Bandersnatch, a 150 ft spire  mentioned  in  the  guide  as
being N of Stone Ponds and E of Mt Stone\'s N Ridge.  The  only  problem  was
that I didn\'t have a clue as to where this spire was. It is  not  marked  on
any map and I certainly couldn\'t see it from the Pond. It  would  have  been
nice if the guide had indicated how  far  N  from  the  Pond  it  was.  With
nothing more than a direction and a vague elevation of ca.5300 ft to go  on,
I set out N hoping that I would eventually locate it.

I climbed back up to Stone Ponds Pass, then veered left (W)  away  from  the
way trail keeping to the left of the inlet creek to Scout Lake.   Topping  a
small rise I suddenly saw the impressive objective.  There was no  mistaking
the spire. But gee whiz it was a long ways away,  probably  a  mile  as  the
crow flies and across difficult terrain. Once again I  was  worried  that  I
wouldn\'t have enough daylight. It took 1:30 hr to  work  my  way  traversing
bushy cliff terraces to the base of the tower.  It was now 4:45.  The  first
class 4 pitch was a chimney I scrambled up to  the  notch  between  the  two
summits. Here I roped up for the second  80  ft  5.6  class  pitch.  It  was
committing climbing but the  holds  were  good  and  I  was  able  to  place
adequate protection. I reached the summit at 6:00. No register, just  slings
so old as to be completely weathered and useless.  I would guess this  thing
hasn\'t been climbed in several years. (As a note I would estimate the  spire
to be 175 ft high and its elevation to be 5480+ ft)

In order to save weight I had brought only an 80 ft climbing rope and an  80
ft 5mm accessory cord so I could tie the two together for an 80  ft  rappel.
Remind me not to do that again. The rappel worked okay, but  retrieving  the
rope did not. The knot kept getting  stuck.   After  reclimbing  the  entire
pitch to free the knot and fiddling with it as it got stuck a  second  time,
then having the rope get stuck once again  rappelling  the  chimney,  I  was
ready  to  abandon  the  whole  business.  But  I  eventually  succeeded  in
retrieving both ropes - at the cost of an hour. I reached the  base  of  the
rock at 7:00.

Knowing I would never be able to find my way across the  cliff  traverse  in
the dark, I decided to descend straight down  into  the  drainage  of  Scout
Lake\'s inlet creek below the cliffs, then climb back up  on  easier  terrain
past the cliffs.  Although I ran into some nightmare brush  initially  doing
this and it took longer, I eventually ran into meadows and a safer way  back
to camp.  I do not consciously try  to  be  out  after  dark,  but  when  it
becomes necessary and unavoidable, I end up embracing and even enjoying  the
experience. There is something magical about wandering around the  mountains
during the night. It is a whole different world. I was again  aided  by  the
light of a glorious full moon and reached camp at 9:15 (3 miles, 1700 ft,  6
hrs)

Day 3: It rained all night and I awoke to fog and drizzle. I  had  hoped  to
continue my loop but the previous day I had a good look at  the  route  that
would go over the high 5900 ft col called St Peter\'s Gate. It  was  a  rough
1200 ft climb from Stone Ponds on talus and snow. In order  to  save  weight
(I did have all that rock gear), I gambled that I would not need an ice  axe
and did not bring one. I gambled and lost. The final bit to the  col  looked
steep and icy. Not something I wanted to try  without  an  ice  ax  or  even
poles. However, I am not sure I would have tried it even if  I  had  an  axe
under the wet foggy conditions. I had been up the Purvin Trail years ago  to
climb Mt Stone and knew it was  a  steep  difficult  trail  with  scrambling
sections.  It and the descent from  St  Peter\'s  Gate  would  be  even  more
difficult and downright treacherous when wet. So at the moment  of  decision
I trusted my gut feeling, turned my back on St Peter and went out  the  same
way I came in even though it would  be  twice  as  long.  All  was  not  bad
though.  I got to hike back through all those lovely meadows  and  now  have
an excuse to return someday and complete my route.  (12.5  miles,  1450  ft,
7:30 hrs).

Total: 30 miles and 10,100 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen

