            'title' => 'Indian Head Pk (7400+ ft - 2000P - Glacier Pk East Quad), White Mtn (7043 ft - 523P - Glacier Pk West Quad), Wenatchee Ridge, N End (6052 ft - 412P - Poe Mtn Quad) & Cady Ridge (5816 ft - 496P - Bench Mark Mtn Quad) - October 27-29, 2006 (Fri-Sun)',
            'tr' => '
Indian Head Pk (7400+ ft - 2000P - Glacier Pk East Quad),  White  Mtn  (7043
ft - 523P - Glacier Pk West Quad), Wenatchee Ridge, N End (6052 ft - 412P  -
Poe Mtn Quad) & Cady Ridge (5816 ft - 496P - Bench Mark Mtn Quad) -  October
27-29, 2006 (Fri-Sun)

The forecast for this three day period was for clearing from the S  on  Fri,
a sunny day Sat and rain and lowering snow levels coming  in  on  Sun.  Good
enough, I thought, to sneak in a few peaks in the area  before  the  weather
deteriorated and snow accumulated enough to completely prevent access.

Day 1: The weather may have been clearing from the S, but I  was  driving  N
and by the time I got to the Little  Wenatchee  River  TH  (elev  3000  ft),
light rain was still falling. It wasn\'t  really  enough  to  be  much  of  a
problem except for the brush along the trail, which was wet enough  to  soon
soak my feet. I began running into snow below  Meander  Meadow  (about  4500
ft) and in fact lost the trail in the meadow itself so  just  headed  uphill
to intersect it once again on Wenatchee Ridge (5700 ft). Snow was  now  6-12
inches deep, but the wide Pacific Crest Trail was easily  followed  down  to
Indian Pass where I found a pleasant campsite  on  bare  ground  under  some
trees, elev 5000 ft (9 miles, 3000 ft, 5:30 hrs.).

Day 2: It rained all night long, and fairly  hard.  That  supposed  clearing
from the S sure was taking its time. I could almost hear the  meteorologists
spouting their usual  excuse  when  they  blow  the  forecast  -  the  front
stalled. Not only was it not getting better it was  getting  worse.  It  was
discouraging enough that I was seriously considering packing up and  heading
out a day early empty handed. Then toward morning the rain  stopped  and  by
the time I was ready to go at 7:40 I had partial views up  to  Indian  Head.
That was enough to revitalize me and off I went.

I followed the trail a short half mile to the  wooded  SW  ridge  of  Indian
Head and climbed this to wide open slopes where I began a long  traverse  to
the rocky S spur. No real difficulties, unless you count  the  howling  wind
that threatened to blow me off the mountain or the icy rock  that  made  for
slippery going. I topped out at 10:20 (2600 ft, 2:40 hrs).  I found  a  nice
Mountaineer Register placed in 1999 with no pencil, so I  added  one.  There
were a fair number of entries, but I didn\'t take  much  time  to  look  then
over. I couldn\'t hang around too long in the wind  with  my  wet  boots  and
cold feet. Had to  keep  moving.  I  did  however  notice  Stefan  and  Paul
Klenke\'s ascent of last year and several other comments to the  effect  that
the NE Peak appeared to be just as high as the one I was on.  In fact I  was
not sure which peak was the summit looking at the map as they  both  measure
7400 ft by contour lines. So naturally I had to pop over and  climb  the  NE
one also. I still don\'t know which is higher. My altimeter read the same  on
each and I didn\'t bring my clinometer. It looks to be a tossup  to  me,  but
the register is on the SW Peak.

Both the weather and views continued to  improve.  It  was  turning  into  a
gorgeous fall day. Amazing how a little sun  can  make  everything  seem  so
much more friendly. Even the wind diminished. I had  to  make  the  most  of
this opportunity. There was still time to head N  on  the  Crest  trail  and
pick up White Mtn.  This has to be one of the more scenic  sections  of  the
PCT. I had stunning views of Glacier Pk, Luana, Clark,  Tenpeak  and  Kokolo
Pks the whole way to White Pass.  I  then  climbed  a  well-used  way  trail
directly up the S Ridge to the summit of White (5100 ft, 8 hrs).  There  was
no register I could find and I felt any small one I could leave  would  soon
fill up.

I had hoped that if the front on Fri had stalled, maybe  the  one  scheduled
to come in Sun would be late also, but I soon was dissuaded of that  notion.
Already the higher peaks were getting lost in the fog. I  was  beginning  to
worry about getting caught in bad weather my last day, and  yet  I  wouldn\'t
have missed this beautiful day for anything.  I  would  just  have  to  take
what came. I arrived back in camp just at dark (12.5 miles, 5200  ft,  10:30
hrs).

Day 3: Sure enough, sometime during the night it began to rain and the  wind
picked up again. Then the sound of rain  turned  suspiciously  to  something
else - snow. Not that I really mind snow.  In fact I prefer it to rain.   If
it is a dry snow you don\'t get as wet.  And it  is  pretty.  All  white  and
clean and fresh. But if it snowed too much, I might have  trouble  following
the trail out, especially since my plan was to make a  loop  with  the  Cady
Ridge Trail.

I left at 8:45, packing up a frozen ice encrusted tent. It  snowed  all  day
and the snow level continuously went  down.  The  going  was  reasonable  to
Wenatchee Ridge, where I dropped my pack to climb the high point  at  the  N
end.  Somehow I had missed this bump when doing the Poet Peaks.  A  1  hour,
585 ft side trip. Then it began snowing harder and from Wenatchee  Ridge  to
the Cady Ridge Trail breaking trail in over a foot of snow began to slow  me
down. I was still able to follow the trail easily enough, but  with  another
6 inches or so it would be lost under a sea of white. As I plodded along,  I
longed for skis.  The less used Cady Ridge Trail was more of a problem,  but
I managed to lose it only a few times briefly. I  dropped  my  pack  at  the
high point of the trail for the 30-minute, 200 ft side trip up  Cady  Ridge.
It continued to snow all the way down to the car (11.5  miles,  2700  ft.  8
hrs.).

I thought my troubles were over. Not so.  The  DOT  was  caught  with  their
pants down by this early snowstorm and Snoqualmie Pass was  closed  to  both
directions for some  5  hours  while  they  scrambled  getting  tow  trucks,
snowplows and deicing trucks in place to clear the  roadway.  I  sat  for  2
hours in a sea of cars and trucks going nowhere, then crawled over the  pass
for another hour and had a normal 3 hour drive turn into a 6 hour one.

Total: 33 miles and 10,900 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen


