I found this trail to be a real gem, well worth the long  drive.  It  is  in
excellent shape, well maintained, with a number of points of interest  along
the way, has varied ecosystems from near rain forest to open alpine  meadows
and rock outcropping and great views (though I was not able to see  them  on
this misty foggy day). And if I had been content to just stick to the  trail
it would have been a very pleasant experience. But of course I  was  not.  I
just had to add a second peak and turn a simple trip into my usual bash.  At
least that made for a longer hike time than drive time.

I decided to hike the loop trail counterclockwise so I could  get  my  bonus
peak out of the way first.  That way if I ran out of daylight I  would  have
trail to follow the rest of the way out. The first  couple  miles  of  trail
parallels Highway 101 but it is well out of view and  the  trail  is  lovely
with a rain forest look despite parts of it  having  been  recently  logged.
The tread is smooth and begs to be ridden on bike. In fact  the  entire  13-
mile trail is open to mountain bike and could be done  by  a  strong  rider,
but the elevation gain is over 3000 ft and much pushing would  be  involved.


After crossing Hutch Cr in about an hour, the  trail  began  to  climb.   In
another half hour I came to a cluster of giant mossy boulders,  the  largest
of which is named Fout\'s Rock House and is well worth the short  side  trip.
In 2:40 hr I came to the ridge, elev 2800 ft and  set  off  right  along  it
toward Pk 3700. Now this peak is only a little over a mile  away  from  this
point and yet it took me 2 hours to get there. I  am  constantly  amazed  at
how far a mile can be and how long it can take to travel that distance  when
going crosscountry. You would think  I  would  have  learned  that  by  now.
Somehow I thought going along a ridge  would  be  easier  or  that  by  some
miracle there would be a trail or a hint of a trail. All  I  got  was  awful
scrubby trees and brush made even worse by a dusting of wet snow.  At  times
I was literally reduced to crawling under branches to  make  progress.  When
possible I stayed on the N side of the ridge where there was less  brush  in
the dark forest, but for the most part I was forced to stay  on  the  crest.
The actual summit was a rocky mossy knoll that would have had  a  good  view
if I could have seen anything in the fog. At least it wasn\'t raining.

Now there was no way I was going to go back  the  same  way  I  came.   That
would take another 2 hours of misery.   So  I  hatched  an  escape  plan  by
dropping down about 600 ft on the N side to a road that showed  on  my  map.
I then followed this road about 1.5 mile to below  the  saddle  where  I  had
originally left the trail and climbed back  up  500  ft  through  reasonable
open woods to regain the trail. This took  1  hour  and  saved  considerable
time not to mention effort. I then continued on trail to Mt Muller  arriving
just at dark and completed the rest of the loop by headlight.

Total: 16.5 miles, 5345 ft and 9:30 hrs.

Fay Pullen
