Poch Pk (5080+ ft - 640P), Poch West Pk (5000+ ft - 560P) & August Pk
(4680+ ft - 120P)  - Golden Lakes Quad - November 14, 2006

This day did not start out well.  I had planned on skiing  up  some  logging
roads on the Clear West Quad, but I found Rd  74  up  the  West  Fork  White
River gated less than a mile from Highway 410. Whether  this  was  a  winter
closure or due to flood damage I am not sure but I  suspect  the  latter.  I
would have continued to Chinook Pass had it been open (it was not) or  could
have continued to Crystal had I been so inclined  (I  was  not).  Instead  I
backtracked to the Mowich Lake Road. I had no idea if this road was open  or
how far I could drive up it. The good news was there was active  logging  in
the area that assured the road was open and I was able to follow very  large
logging truck tire tracks through the snow.  The  bad  news  was  there  was
active logging in the area and I had to dodge half a dozen very large  fully
loaded logging trucks. In any event I was able to make it to  the  Evans  Cr
ORV Park TH, elev 3300 ft, on the edge of Mt Rainer National Park where  6-8
inches  of  untracked  snow  made  skiing  the  extensive  system  of  roads
inviting.

I lost a good hour travel time to my change of  destination.  That  combined
with more time lost on last minute searches in  the  morning  for  ski  gear
long dormant and hidden over the summer meant a not too early start. By  the
time I stepped into my ski bindings it was already 10:30. There are 6  peaks
in this area that I had my sights on, 4 in Rainier  National  Park  (August,
Virginia, Berry and Martin) and two just outside (Poch  and  W  Poch).  With
the late start I knew I wouldn\'t be able to do them all even if  they  could
all be done on skis. So I decided to concentrate on Poch and  W  Poch,  both
of which appeared to have roads to very near the top and could  most  likely
easily be climbed on skis. Even so, it was farther and took  longer  than  I
anticipated just for those two.  At  least  I  had  the  sense  to  put  new
batteries in my headlamp.

It felt good to be skiing again as I glided easily  along  the  gentle  road
through lovely powder snow and I was in heaven. At least  until  heaven  was
shattered when I was passed by a Forest Service truck. They said  they  were
checking out the condition of the ORV trails  in  the  area.  In  the  snow?
Personally I think they were  just  out  playing  in  their  big  truck.  No
matter. I soon met them coming out, having been stopped by  deep  snow,  and
once again I was in heaven. I followed the main road for 5 miles,  with  the
snow getting deeper and trail breaking more work,  to  the  4432  ft  saddle
between W Poch and Poch. From here I went up the NE ridge of  W  Poch  on  a
motorcycle trail that went all the way to the  wooded  top  (1750  ft,  3:40
hrs). Made for very nice skiing indeed. Back at the saddle I then went up  a
road on the W ridge of Poch to its high point, then up semi open  slopes  to
that top (2500 ft, 5:20 hrs). I skied down the E ridge  through  open  woods
to pick up a road that led to the saddle with August Peak. It was  now  4:30
but I was so close to August Peak  I  couldn\'t  pass  it  up.  This  was  in
Rainier Park in dense woods with sketchy snow, so I left my skis  and  hiked
up to that summit, 40 minutes RT. The ski out was by headlamp and  was  very
pleasant until the last mile where more  vehicle  traffic  had  churned  the
road to a chaotic mess. That is always the chance you take  when  skiing  up
an ungated road. Still it did  not  alter  the  fact  that  the  skiing  was
wonderful up to that point and worth putting up  with  a  little  annoyance.
12.5 miles, 2800 ft & 8:20 hrs. Fay Pullen



