            'tr' => '
Berry Pk (5120+ ft - 120P), Martin Pk (4880+ ft - 320P), Virginia Pk  (4880+
ft - 120P) & Paul Pk (4800 ft - 360P) - Golden Lakes  Quad  -  November  17,
2006

Of course you knew I would be back to pick up the peaks I missed on my  last
outing.  My, but what a difference three days makes. All that heavenly  snow
I skied on was gone. Not that it really mattered, as I  wasn\'t  planning  on
skiing this time anyway.  I was able to easily  drive  to  the  Mowich  Lake
Entrance of Mt Rainier National Park with essentially no snow on  the  road.
I was hoping to take the old Boundary Trail to near  Martin  Pk  but  wasn\'t
sure what shape it was in or if I could even find it. As  it  turned  out  I
had no trouble locating it about  1/10  mile  from  the  entrance,  where  I
parked on the side of the road, elev 3600 ft.

The old trail was in great shape, with only a few minor blowdowns and  would
make for a pleasant hike in  lovely  woods  away  from  the  crowds  in  the
summer. It took two switchbacks before beginning a traverse on  the  E  side
of Martin Pk. The last one dipped out of the park to the W to briefly  enter
a clearcut. Here above me I was astonished  to  see  a  rock  tooth  looming
above in a most unexpected location. I had never  seen  nor  heard  of  this
thing before.  It was impressive enough to deserve a name. Naturally  I  had
to climb over to it to check it out and climb it  if  possible.  I  was  not
able to climb it (it looked to be exposed unprotectable class  5)  but  that
was probably appropriate. On the uphill side I found a  plaque  attached  to
the rock as a  memorial  to  Jack  Pasero,  Jr  of  Wilkeson  "Friend,  Dad,
Companion, 9/4/17 - 12/23/99."  What  a  nice  memorial!   I  wouldn\'t  mind
having something like that for me after I am gone.

Back on the trail, I followed it to the E  side  of  Martin  Pk,  then  went
straight uphill to the summit. I quickly entered  the  snowline.   From  the
look of things Wednesday\'s storm had brought only  rain  and  freezing  rain
(no new snow). The annoying result  was  that  awful  stuff  where  you  are
slipping on ice one moment and wishing for crampons and breaking through  to
knees, or worse, the next and wishing for  snowshoes.  The  last  1/10  mile
probably took half an hour as I alternately slipped and wallowed.  The  snow
was so bad on this peak because it had been clearcut to the  ridgeline  with
resulting deeper drifts and many downed trees (1300 ft, 1:50 hrs)

From Martin I followed the ridge N to  the  saddle  with  Virginia  where  I
picked up the trail again. I then left the trail for good  on  Virginia\'s  W
ridge, which I followed to the top (1550 ft,  2:45  hrs).  From  Virginia  I
went to the saddle to the N,  then  traversed  to  the  ridge  W  of  Berry.
Travel was reasonable through open  woods  despite  inconsistent  snow.  The
final ridge to Berry had a few minor open rocky bumps that  added  a  little
interest but no views to speak of (2300 ft, 4:20 hrs). I backtracked to  the
W saddle then plunged straight downhill to intersect the  Mowich  Lake  Road
(elev 3800 ft) about 6/10 mile from the Paul Peak  TH.  Here  the  road  was
completely snowcovered. There were snowshoe tracks but no ski tracks.

It was now 3:15. I figured I had just enough time to  make  Paul  Pk  before
