 Pk 5480+ (680P) - Mt Wow Quad - November 24, 2006',
            'tr' => '
Glacier View (5450 ft - 250P) & Pk 5507 (947P) - Mt Wow Quad - November  22,
2006

I have wanted to ski up these peaks for some time now, but in  order  to  do
that conditions had to be just right. There had to be enough  snow  to  ski,
but not so much that I couldn\'t drive  reasonably  close.  The  time  seemed
right and indeed I was able to drive to the Christine  Lake  road  junction,
some 4 miles up Road 59 and elevation 3760 ft. The  last  half  mile  though
was dicey through fresh snow in an old deep track. New tires on my  Cherokee
helped. I was first up the road and thought I had it all to myself,  but  no
sooner had I turned around and parked than a  4X4  came  up  after  me.  The
driver told me I shouldn\'t try to go farther  as  several  rigs  were  stuck
farther up the road. I told him I had no  intention  of  going  any  farther
(Did he really think I would? I was already turned around  and  parked!).  A
few minutes after that a couple from Florida pulled up in  their  SUV.  They
just wanted to see some snow and since Mt Rainier was closed  this  was  the
best they could do. They took off walking the road  toward  Lake  Christine.
Then I was confronted by a monster truck backing down the road  from  above.
They were one of the rigs that had been stuck all night. Goodness  gracious,
it was like Grand Central Station.

Skiing the now churned up road and meeting more stuck or  unstuck  rigs  was
not appealing, so as soon as possible I left the main road at  an  old  road
and headed directly up to Copper Cr Ridge,  elevation  4600  ft.  The  lower
section was quite brushy, but things soon thinned out  and  I  was  able  to
thread my way through open terrain. Once on the ridge, where I had a  fairly
good view of my first destination, I descended straight down  steep  terrain
200 feet to the road on the other side. There were no fresh  vehicle  tracks
here so the rigs were not stuck on this road and I skied  the  road  to  the
Glacier View TH (2 miles, 1280 ft, 2:20 hrs).

The Glacier View Trail was a joy; trail skiing at its best. I had gotten  an
early (for me) start and was making good time so I  was  having  visions  of
adding Puyallup Point and Pk 5480+ to the  itinerary  -  until  I  lost  the
trail as it went around the W side of Pk 5507.  I soon found myself on  very
steep sidehill with difficult travel. I managed to work  my  way  to  the  W
ridge at elev 5300 where I stashed my skis for the final steep climb to  the
summit.  The last bit was tricky icy snow and rock made  worse  by  the  now
deteriorating weather and a brutal wind that blasted me with  pellets  while
threatening to  blow  me  off  the  mountain.  I  didn\'t  tarry  under  such
condition, quickly returning to my skis.

I had to descend several hundred feet down the ridge until I  could  find  a
place to drop to the N. I stumbled onto the trail lower  down  and  followed
it to the saddle S of Glacier View and on to the  summit  itself  (5  miles,
2900 ft 5:40 hrs). The wind was no less brutal  here  but  the  terrain  was
less precipitous so I did not feel unduly threatened.  It was now  2:45  and
a bit late to try for any other peaks so I headed out.  I  found  the  trail
around Pk 5507 and it made for much better skiing.   It  essential  contours
at the 5000 ft level, much lower than shown on the map.

I had the "brilliant" idea of staying on the trail  past  the  Glacier  View
TH, going toward Mt Beljica and then taking the spur  trail  right  directly
to Copper Cr Ridge as shown on the map. This turned out to be a disaster  as
I could not find the trail and ended up in a mess  of  downed  trees.   Ever
try to walk a snowcovered log 10 feet above the ground on  skis.  T-r-i-c-k-
y! Eventually I made it to the ridge very near Pt 4892 but I lost a  lot  of
time. I thought I was now "out of the woods" but things got  even  worse.  I
was able to follow my uphill tracks down for a while but soon lost  them  in
terrible brush the last 200 feet or so to the road. I  ended  up  taking  my
skis off and on several times to slither through.  When  I  finally  reached
the car it was 7:30 (10 miles, 3500 ft, 9 hrs.)


Pk 5480+ (680P) - Mt Wow Quad - November 24, 2006


Despite my difficulties, I really did have a good time on my  previous  trip
so two days later I was back for more hoping this time  to  make  the  other
two peaks - Pk 5480+ and Puyallup Point. I soon realized this would  not  be
likely. There was way too much new snow. I began running into snow just  out
of Eatonville and it just kept getting worse. I was still able  to  make  it
to my previous parking place but only because the monster  trucks  had  kept
the track open. There was probably 1- 1.5 feet of new and let  me  tell  you
it was scary driving up a 3 foot deep trench with no possibility of  getting
out of  it  or  turning  around  until  reaching  the  Christine  Lake  road
junction.

I was even earlier than before and first on the scene.  I learned my  lesson
last  time  and  stayed  on  the  road  resisting  the  temptation  for  any
shortcuts.  Monster trucks have very wide tires, they had been  up  recently
and only an inch or two of fresh snow on the track actually made the  skiing
very good. I reached Copper Cr Pass in 1:10 hrs (3 miles, 925 ft). Here  all
vehicle traffic stopped.  The moment of truth was upon me.  How would it  be
breaking my own trail from now on? It wasn\'t terrible  but  it  wasn\'t  good
either. I sank in about calf deep, deep enough to  make  progress  slow  but
not deep enough to stop me in my tracks. So I plodded on.  It  was  becoming
more and more  likely  that  I  would  not  make  my  peaks.  I  lowered  my
expectations to maybe making one.  If not  even  that,  well  the  snow  was
lovely and I would just enjoy the skiing.

I reached the Glacier View TH in another 1:15 hrs (4.5 miles, 1215  ft)  and
started up the trail. I had hoped that my tracks from  two  days  ago  would
help.  No such luck. They were completely gone and I couldn\'t even find  the
trail around Pt 5419. I lost more time just finding a  route.  I  picked  up
the trail again around Pk 5507.  Skiing is so much easier on a  clear  path.
I reached the Glacier View Saddle at 2:10 (7  miles,  2075  ft,  5:30  hrs).
Clearly if I went on to Pk 5480+ I would be coming out in the dark - way  in
the dark. But I had a nice track to follow out and it was not  snowing  hard
enough to obliterate it. I had worked so hard to  get  to  this  point,  the
peak was so close (well, it really  wasn\'t  THAT  close)  and  the  snow  so
lovely, even if there was too much of it, and so I decided to go on.

I dropped 400 feet to the pond  at  the  base  of  my  peak\'s  S  ridge  and
followed this ridge all the way to the summit, arriving at 4:10 (8.5  miles,
2850 ft, 7:30 hrs).  It really made for a very nice ski ascent.  I  made  it
down to the pond before needing my headlight. The climb back up  to  Glacier
View\'s saddle was an effort, but then it was just a matter of  following  my
ski tracks out.  This was pure joy until the  last  climb  on  the  road  to
Copper Cr Pass. I was running out of steam by that point and  it  seemed  to
take forever. The run down the road was  pretty  good,  despite  the  narrow
track (It seemed narrower on the way down), probably  because  the  road  is
not very steep. But the tracks looked awfully fresh  for  it  having  snowed
most of the day.  Half way down I found out why when I ran  into  a  caravan
of monster trucks.  Three were headed downhill, one uphill and the last  two
were nose to nose in a classic impasse. How they got out of that jam I  have
no idea but I think the three downhill vehicles  solved  the  problem.  They
were experienced enthusiasts. The uphill truck was stuck and driven  by  two
young inexperienced males.  I had a nice conversation with the  one  of  the
experienced crew (a woman) and from what she said  I  gathered  they  didn\'t
think much of them. One of young men made the comment, somewhat  critically,
that I was getting out late.  I almost burst out laughing. It was  okay  for
them to be out after dark but not for me. I chuckled as I  glided  past  the
whole mess. I reached my car at 8:40 (17 miles, 3800 ft, 12 hrs).

Fay Pullen
