            'tr' => '
I have long been intrigued by the "Tops" around Mineral. The only  one  that
has an official name is Roundtop but the others have all been given  similar
appropriate ones in keeping with that theme.

Spiraltop (2703 ft - 1143P), Towertop (2608 ft - 1088 ft) &  Laketop  (2120+
ft - 640P) - Mineral Quad - December 1, 2006

Taking advantage of low snowlevels, I was able to ski up these  low  summits
near Mineral. The gate on the  Spiraltop  road  was  open  but  all  vehicle
traffic stopped at a downed tree not  far  up.  The  road  was  consistently
covered with snow the whole way and indeed spirals to the top.  Made  for  a
very pleasant ski trip. (5.3 miles, 1280 ft. 2:15 hrs RT)

The road up Towertop and Laketop was gated and the first  half  mile  or  so
deficient of snow. I took a wrong turn a mile up the road and ended up on  a
road that deadended in a clearcut about 400  ft  below  the  summit.  Rather
than backtrack I forced a route to the upper road.  Not pretty  on  skis.  I
probably lost a good  hour.  Snowshoes  would  have  worked  better  in  the
snowcovered slash. There is indeed a tower on Towertop but it is not on  the
top. It was a nice run down to the Laketop road on  consistent  snow  except
for the short descent to near Mineral Lake.  There is  indeed  a  lake  near
Laketop. The road does not go to the tiptop and a short hike  was  required.
By now the snow was freezing which made for a very fast  run  down.  I  came
out the last bit by the light of the almost full  moon.  (10.4  miles,  2415
ft, 5:45 hrs RT)

Doubletop (2180 ft -860P), Stumptop (2080+ ft - 480P) & Roundtop (2670 ft  -
910P) - Mineral Quad - December 6, 2006

 I returned 5 days later to very different conditions.   Much  of  the  snow
had melted but I expected this and came with a bike instead of skis.

I started with Doubletop, parking at the intersection of its road  with  the
Pleasant Valley road although there was no gate. There was only  minor  snow
on the N side and vehicle tracks allowed me to bike the  whole  way  to  the
top. Doubletop does indeed have a double top but I only went to the  highest
one. (3.75 miles, 930 ft, 1:30 RT)

Next up was Stumptop.  Despite a  rather  unattractive  sounding  name,  the
gated, little used, gentle  road  makes  for  a  very  pleasant  bike  ride.
Unfortunately, on this day I ran into too much snow on the N  side  to  bike
the whole way.  Expecting this (from what I found on  Doubletop)  and  since
there were no tire tracks to help out I took along my tiny  kid\'s  skis  and
"skied" the rest of the way to the top. There is indeed a stump on  Stumptop
and I climbed to the top of the stump. (3.3 miles, 690 ft, 2 hrs RT)

I saved the hardest for last. I knew Roundtop  might  give  me  trouble.   I
could see clearcuts fairly high on the S side that were free of snow  but  I
saw no road cuts. And from the map contours, and cliffs  I  could  see,  the
upper part was very steep. I couldn\'t find any TR to help  either,  although
I know both Stefan and Klenke have done this (and the  other)  peaks  fairly
recently.  I really need a better filing system. Somehow I  muddled  through
despite several false starts. I began at the gated road, passed a  promising
road to the right (not shown on my map) at the second switchback  and  biked
a pleasant additional mile to the N side where I soon  got  bogged  down  in
snow.  I took a short spur that deadended but gave a view of snowy  cleacuts
above.  There must be a road that accessed  the  clearcuts  but  even  if  I
found it it would do no good, as there was too much snow  to  bike  or  even
ski with my tiny skis.  So it was back to the friendly sunny S side and  the
junction I had originally passed by. I went up this road a short  ways  then
took a hard left on a spur that ended below a clearcut, elev 1800  ft.  (The
main road probably circled around to the clearcuts I  had  seen  on  the  NE
side) From here I forced a route the  remaining  900  ft  to  the  top.   An
animal trail helped greatly to get me to  the  top  of  the  clearcut,  then
steep wooded slopes wound through cliffs to the summit  ridge  where  I  was
greeted with a stunning view of a frosted white  Mt  Rainier.  A  2/10  mile
walk  along  the  ridge  led  to  the  summit.  This  was  turning  into  an
interesting little peak. Roundtop is indeed round on top  but  it  is  quite
steep on all sides. (6.6 miles, 1400 ft, 3 hrs RT including side trips)

Although I got back to the car before dark (but only barely),  it  was  dark
by the time I drove through Mineral, Elbe and Eatonville, so I was  able  to
enjoy the Christmas lights and decorations these small towns  have  put  up.
Then to cap it off, just outside of Eatonville at the first gas station,  on
Highway 161, a "Christmas Truck" was parked with lights  and  music  blazing
and blaring.  I have never seen anything like this truck.  I  think  it  was
sponsored by Ohop Light or some such.  Made me smile all the way home.

Fay Pullen
