            'title' => 'Pelletgun Hill (1840+ ft - 520P) & Destitution Hill (1520+ ft - 400P) - Mt Si Quad; Pk 2480+ ft (920P), Pk 2000+ ft (560P) & Pk 1760+ ft (400P) - Devils Slide Quad - December 3, 2006',
            'tr' => '
Pelletgun Hill (1840+ ft - 520P) & Destitution Hill (1520+ ft - 400P)  -  Mt
Si Quad; Pk 2480+ ft (920P), Pk 2000+ ft (560P)  &  Pk  1760+  ft  (400P)  -
Devils Slide Quad - December 3, 2006

The challenge with biking up little peaks like these is finding a road  that
gets you as close as possible to the summit.  Since  I  do  not  use  aerial
photos (too much time and effort to download on my  old  slow  computer),  I
must rely on maps, many of which are not  up  to  date,  trip  reports  from
other peakbaggers if I can find them (I know Stefan has done some or all  of
these peaks), on-site visual inspection and  just  plain  luck.  This  often
results in surprises, some good and some bad. But it all adds to the  spirit
of exploration and I do like to explore. This trip everything went well  and
I managed to fit all five hoped for peaks in one day, although the last  one
was done in the dark.

I went for the  farthest  and  highest  one  first,  Pk  2480+,  biking  the
mainline logging road some 3 miles to the spur junction. This  is  the  only
one I ran into significant snow on, which began  about  1800  ft,  but  tire
tracks allowed me to bike to just below the  summit.  I  next  went  for  Pk
1760+. This one had the most crosscountry work, 400 ft  up  a  steep  wooded
hillside with just enough downed trees and debris to  be  annoying  but  not
obnoxious. Then on to Pk 2000+ where a new road extension (I could  see  the
roadcut from below) switchbacked to the ridge. Only a short hike was  needed
to reach the wooded top.

The day was now waning, but I thought I still could get up Destitution  Hill
before dark if I was lucky enough to find a road to the top. I  was  and  it
did, although the road I found was not on my map at all. When I got back  to
the car and loaded the bike it was dark, but I was right next to  Pelletgun.
How could I not go for it? I drove the short distance to the gated  road  up
this hill.  Rather than take  the  trouble  to  unload  the  bike  again,  I
decided to just hike the whole way. The road went all the way to  the  ridge
and a cat track littered with slash led along the ridge to the  top.  Except
for the slash section, I was able to hike without a headlamp  by  the  light
of a full moon. It was actually quite lovely.  Surely more lovely  than  the
clearcut would have been in the daylight.

Total for 4 peaks by bike: 19 miles, 3550 ft & 7 hrs.
Additional for Pelletgun: 3.2 miles, 750 ft & 1:20 hrs.

Fay Pullen


