            'title' => 'Siberia Mtn (2280+ ft - 1440P), Pk 2080+ (440P), Dalhberg Mtn (1880+ ft - 280P) & Miniature Mtn (1440+ ft - 440P) - Riley Lk Quad - December 8, 2006',
            'tr' => '
Siberia Mtn (2280+ ft - 1440P), Pk 2080+ (440P), Dalhberg Mtn  (1880+  ft  -
280P) & Miniature Mtn (1440+ ft - 440P) - Riley Lk Quad - December 8, 2006

I thought I might be in for real trouble when I found  residual  snow  along
the Mountain Loop Highway where I  parked  at  the  gated  logging  road.  I
expected some snow higher up but not here at only 600 ft  elevation.  As  it
turned out, the snow was only in  protected  areas,  the  logging  road  was
clear and I was able to easily bike the 3+ miles up the E ridge to near  the
top of Miniature Mtn (I believe this peak was recently named  by  Roper).  A
short trek on foot through debris-laden woods took me the rest of the way.

I was now pondering how to proceed to Siberia Mtn.  None of my  maps  showed
roads connecting directly from Miniature Mtn without major backtracking  and
loss of elevation. I had no view from the summit  itself  but  came  upon  a
decent one while biking down the W ridge. I  could  see  a  road  cut  in  a
clearcut on the S slope of Siberia that did not correspond to  any  road  on
my map. Perhaps this road connected to the one I was  on.  I  optimistically
proceeded on this assumption and, by following  the  most  traveled  looking
road at the many junctions encountered,  soon  found  myself  just  where  I
wanted to be. I climbed to a high point of 1850 ft,  turned  a  corner  into
more snowy terrain and began a gradual descent. I was  looking  for  a  spur
that my map showed to climb fairly high on the NW slope.  I found  the  spur
but I also found too much snow to take it any distance.

I decided to continue to Dalhberg and try Siberia on  the  way  back  via  a
spur I had passed on the S slope. I could  see  a  log  landing  directly  S
across a deep ravine on the N slope of Dalhberg. It  looked  so  close,  but
getting to it was a round about business. Now even the main road was  snowy.
Fortunately, vehicle tracks made it possible for me to continue until I  got
through the snowy section. I found my way to the log landing  from  where  I
proceeded on foot to the summit of Dalhberg. It was only 2/10 mile away  but
took almost 20 minutes to cover  the  snowy  stickery  slash.  Then  to  add
insult to injury I crossed another spur road very  near  the  top.  I  could
have avoided the whole nuisance altogether if I had found this one.

I next went for Pk 2080. I could see a  tower  on  the  top  of  this  peak.
Where there is a tower there is a road. All I had to do was find it. This  I
did with only a few minor detours. First I had to  descend  another  hundred
feet or so to a very good road coming up from the S. Then  I  just  followed
this main road, which was a real dream to bike, and then  the  tracked  road
when I got into snow again and I ended up at the tower.   Unfortunately  the
tower was not on the tiptop, so I had  another  unpleasant,  but  mercifully
short, flounder through snowy debris to the summit.

An hour later I was back at the spur road I had passed going up the  S  side
of Siberia. I was able to bike this about half a mile  before  running  into
the deepest snow of the trip. Tire tracks helped for a  quarter  mile  until
the last switchback where  even  they  gave  up.   Then  it  was  postholing
through calf deep slush for another quarter mile to the  end  of  the  road.
Again the summit was a little higher. When I returned  to  my  bike  it  was
5:30 and dark. By now my feet were soaked but I had dry  socks  to  put  on.
Fortunately it was positively balmy for this time of year and I did not  get
cold.
I had not planned on this trip taking so long (I  should  have  known.  They
always take longer than I think) so did not have my good  bike  light  along
(it is very heavy and I only take it when I am sure  I  will  need  it).  Of
course I did have a headlamp - I ALWAYS have a  headlamp.  But  it  did  not
give adequate light to allow for normal speed downhill and I had to keep  it
way down. Then, taking the lower road back around Miniature Mtn (I  had  not
come up this way) I ran into dozens of downed trees. A real  windstorm  must
have come through here. Most were easily passed around, over or  under,  but
a few needed assistance from my folding saw before I could get by. All  this
probably made the trip out an hour longer than it should  have  been  and  I
reached the car at 7:00.

Total: 21.6 miles by bike, maybe 1.6 miles on foot, 4360 ft, 10 hrs.

Fay Pullen
