            'title' => 'Worthy Hill (2375 ft - 935P - Verlot Quad); and Olfactory Hill (1800+ ft - 560P), Flat Tire Hill (1460+ ft - 720P) & Pk 1480+ ft (700P) - Granite Falls Quad - December 12, 2006',
            'tr' => '
Worthy Hill (2375 ft - 935P - Verlot Quad); and Olfactory Hill (1800+ ft -
560P), Flat Tire Hill (1460+ ft - 720P) & Pk 1480+ ft (700P) - Granite
Falls Quad - December 12, 2006

I really thought I was going to  get  drenched  on  this  trip  and  I  went
prepared for rain and to bail out early if things got too bad.  But the  day
turned out quite nice, much better than expected and I only got a half  hour
or so of moderate rain toward the end of the day.  I  was  hoping  to  drive
farther up Scotty Road than I was able to. A gate stopped me  about  a  mile
up the road.  It was open but logging trucks were coming  and  going  and  I
felt there was a good possibility it would be closed by the time I  got  out
even though there was no sign saying it might be. There was  a  sign  saying
no unauthorized vehicles allowed and many making it  clear  no  parking  was
allowed by the gate. Now I am very paranoid  about  where  I  park  my  car.
Since it was going to be there  all  day,  I  thought  it  prudent  to  look
elsewhere and I found an unobtrusive spot out of the way about .8 mile  back
(elev 580 ft). No big deal on a bike.

I thought I was in trouble when at about another .8 mile  past  the  gate  I
came upon the active operations of the  O\'Brien  Sand  and  Gravel  Company.
This was right smack in the middle of the road at the junction to  the  spur
up Flat Tire Hill. But just then a logging truck came by  so  the  road  was
obviously passable and open.  Sure enough, a bypass went around  the  gravel
pit and reconnected with the road farther  up.  I  came  upon  another  gate
after another mile. This one did say it could be  closed  at  any  time  but
also said the area was open to hiking, biking and horseback riding.  I  felt
better knowing I was not in there illegally.

I left the logging truck traffic where I took the uphill  road  at  Chitwood
Lake.  They had cleared the road this far.  Now there were many  more  trees
down, however all but two (maybe these  came  down  in  the  previous  day\'s
storm) had been cut through just enough to allow passage of a pickup  truck.
My folding saw came in handy on those two.  Other  than  that  the  road  to
Worthy was a joy to bike, although it did get  steep  toward  the  top.  The
summit was just off the clearcut in the woods  above  the  tower  (8  miles,
1800 ft, 2:50 hrs).

Next up was Olfactory.  From Worthy I could see a road went all the  way  to
the top, even though my map did not show one. I made a fast run down to  the
junction of the road up Olfactory.  This road was fairly steep, didn\'t  look
well used and I mostly pushed up. It went very close  to  the  summit,  with
only a few steps into the usual brush required (14 miles, 2900 ft, 5 hrs).

From Olfactory I could see a road switchbacking to the top of Pk  1480+  but
I couldn\'t see where the road came from.  There were  two  possibilities.  I
tried the first one I came to first. It was not the right one  and  I  ended
up wasting about 45 minutes before I figured that  out.  The  next  road  in
line was the one up Flat Tire Hill. Again a bypass  had  been  built  around
the gravel operation to access this road, although it  practically  entailed
going head to head  with  their  big  machines.  I  felt  mighty  small  and
vulnerable but no one there gave me any trouble. This was another road  that
was a pleasure to bike at least until I got to the summit  area.  There  are
three points here with the same map elevation.  I  hate  summits  like  that
because I never know which is the highest and usually end up  going  to  all
of them just to be certain. I first went to the  two  southern  points.  The
eastern one was tolerable being the usual annoying brush  and  stickers  but
the western one was unbelievable. It was such a jumble of overgrown  rotting
downed trees and brush it was almost impossible to move  through  it.  There
was no solid ground underfoot, just logs  and  chest  deep  holes.  To  make
matters worse this is when my 30 minutes  of  rain  decided  to  fall.  Even
though I was within 350 linear feet according to my GPS, I probably spent  a
good 20 minutes wandering around looking for the high point. I am  not  even
sure I found it.  How can you tell when you are  in  head  high  garbage?  I
just trusted my GPS. A ditched but hikeable old road went  .2  mile  to  the
northern point. It read 10 ft higher  on  my  altimeter  than  the  southern
points which both read the same. I called it the summit (22 miles, 4100  ft,
8:15 hrs).

It was now 5:00 and dark but I still had one peak I wanted to  do.  When  it
started to rain I seriously  considering  forgetting  the  whole  thing  and
beating a hasty retreat.  Then the rain quit and my resolve returned. I  was
smart enough this time to bring my  good  bike  light  along  so  I  had  no
trouble zipping down to the main road. Amazing  what  a  difference  a  good
light makes when biking. Then it was a second try up the  next  road  to  Pk
1480+.  This one did the trick. It led all the way to a  new  cleacut  right
on the summit. (27 miles, 5035 ft, 9:50 hrs). I doubt this  summit  is  very
attractive in the daylight but  I  had  a  lovely  view  of  the  lights  of
Everett.

Both gates were closed when I came out.

Total: 30 miles, 5035 ft, 10:20 hrs.

Fay Pullen

