            'title' => 'Pk 4097 (537P) & Layercake Pk (3909 ft - 429P) - The Rockies Quad - December 14, 2006
Snugtop (2880+ ft - 720P) & TV Tower Hill (3600+ ft - 1080P) - Anderson Lk Quad - December 19, 2006
Mt Goodie (4040+ ft - 640P - Mineral Quad), Quiemuth Pk (2922 ft - 762P - Eatonville Quad); and Stahl Mtn (3716 - 756P) & Ladd Mtn (3920+ ft - 520P) - The Rockies Quad - December 21, 2006',
            'tr' => '
Mineral MoreTops

Pk 4097 (537P) & Layercake Pk (3909 ft - 429P) - The Rockies Quad -
December 14, 2006

The less said about this trip the better.  This was the day before the  "Big
Wind Storm" and silly me thought I would beat the weather. I did not.  There
was torrential rain all day long and the wind began kicking up  much  sooner
than expected. I drove to the snowline at 2500 ft on Rd 74  and  skied  from
there. If you discounted the wind and rain the  skiing  was  actually  quite
good. Roads went very near the tops of both peaks, although  the  road  from
Pk 4097 to Layercake was much more overgrown than I expected.  Both  summits
were open and would make for fine viewpoints in better weather. I had  hoped
to perhaps also do Goodie or Ladd on this trip but the  conditions  were  so
bad I gave it up early and retreated like a drowned rat.  I  felt  lucky  to
get out before trees started falling.

16 miles, 3960 ft and 8:30 hrs.

Snugtop (2880+ ft - 720P) & TV Tower Hill (3600+ ft - 1080P) -  Anderson  Lk
Quad - December 19, 2006

This was 5 days after the "Big Wind Storm" and the power was  still  out  at
my home. I wasn\'t sure what I would run into on back roads, but I figured  I
might as well be out and about.  I would be warmer exercising  outside  than
vegetating inside a cold house. I started from the gated logging  road  near
Roundtop, elev 1400 ft, on bike. No sooner did  I  turn  a  corner  not  100
yards from the car than I was greeted by two very large cedar  trees  across
the road. Darn! This did not bode well for the rest of  the  trip.  Still  I
had nothing better to do and only a cold house to return  to  so  I  may  as
well give it a try. I struggled and huffed  and  lifted  my  bike  over  the
obstruction and much to my surprise was able to bike to the  grassy  end  of
the spur road below Snugtop mentioned in Paul  Klenke\'s  recent  TR.  I  was
helped by the previous passage of ATV\'s who had  cut  or  forced  their  way
through several more  downed  trees.  They  were  probably  locals  who  had
obviously gained access another way. Even ATV\'s couldn\'t get over the  large
cedars. From the end of the road it was a  pleasant  1:30  hour  RT  through
mostly open woods to the wooded top. I found Paul\'s cairn  on  top  a  stump
but his film can register was nowhere to be seen.

I continued up the main road another 3 miles to a junction where  the  ATV\'s
went left and I went right where I  was  almost  immediately  stopped  by  a
large windfall that I couldn\'t get my bike through so I continued  on  foot.
Too bad as the rest of the road was mostly clear and  I  could  have  easily
biked another 2 miles to where I left the road at 2700 ft. From here I  went
up now snowy woods and debris to the top where I did not find a TV Tower.

15.4 miles, 3465 ft and 8 hrs.


Mt Goodie (4040+ ft - 640P - Mineral Quad), Quiemuth Pk (2922 ft  -  762P  -
Eatonville Quad); and Stahl Mtn (3716 - 756P) & Ladd Mtn (3920+ ft  -  520P)
- The Rockies Quad - December 21, 2006

I was determined to snag Mt Goodie (after several previous  failed  attempts
due to lack of time or bad weather) and finish off the Mineral  Quad.  Again
I wasn\'t sure of the condition of back roads after "The Wind Storm" and  how
far I could drive. This time I tried the approach from the N side up a  spur
off Rd 74. I was able to drive to the snow line at 2700 ft  only  having  to
cut out one small tree. From here I skied the road all the way to  the  top,
very easy skiing. 4.5 mile, 1370 ft and 2 hrs.

Goodie went so well I decided to see what else I could accomplish this  day.
 I continued on Rd 74 to the spur heading up the E side of  Ladd  but  found
it washed out a short ways up. Back to Highway 7  and  the  Pleasant  Valley
Rd.  Past all the farms this road becomes the N end of Rd 74, which used  to
be a loop but now does not go all the way  through.  It  wanders  for  miles
circling Quiemuth Pk and I didn\'t have much hope of it being  drivable  very
far.  But it was. Someone had been through and cut out trees just enough  to
get by.  It was slow going  with  many  obstacles  but  eventually  I  found
myself at the junction of the spur up Quiemuth. I was soon stopped  on  this
spur by a large windfall, elev 2000 ft, but I was now close enough  to  hike
the spur to its end S of the summit. A  short  350  ft  climb  through  open
woods led to the summit cairn and register  where  I  found  out  it  was  a
county high point. Duh!   Another  CoHP  bites  the  dust  without  me  even
knowing it. I wonder how many CoHPs I will have  done  by  the  time  I  get
around to going after this list. The entire  trip  was  snowfree.  3  miles,
1045 ft, 2 hrs.

I continued on the main road to the saddle  between  Stahl  and  Ladd,  elev
2960 ft. Here I was surprised to find a lovely trail, although  now  with  a
number of recent blowdowns, leading all the way to the summit.  Made  for  a
fast trip. Again completely snowfree. 1.5 miles, 800 ft, :50 hrs.

It was now after 4:00 but I was so close I  wasn\'t  leaving  without  adding
Ladd. I was only able to drive on a short distance before being  stopped  by
snow, elev 3020 ft. I walked the road until  I  spotted  a  reasonably  open
line up the snowcovered clearcut to the W ridge. Here  I  followed  edge  of
the ridge to the snowcovered summit. I came down by headlamp as it began  to
snow. It was really very pretty. 1.5 miles, 875 ft, 1:22 hrs.

Fay Pullen




