Eatonville Eight

Peak 3200+ (1080P), Dobbs Mtn (2767 ft - 447P) & Alder BM (2186 ft  -  506P)
- Elbe Quad; and Reliance Hill  (1860+  ft  -  520P  -  Eatonville  Quad)  -
December 17, 2006

I did these peaks two days after the big windstorm and  was  totally  amazed
how quickly people living in rural areas get  their  roads  open.  Owning  a
chainsaw must be a requirement for these  residents.  That  is  not  to  say
anyone had power. At almost every home I heard a generator running.  In  any
event I thought I might have trouble getting anywhere, but  I  was  able  to
drive Scott Turner Road off the Eatonville Cutoff all the way past the  last
residence and into the Elbe State Forest. I parked along the road  as  close
as I could get S of the summit  of  Dobbs,  elev  1900  ft,  and  then  went
straight uphill  through  surprisingly  open  and  pleasant  forest  to  the
summit.  A large cairn and a reasonable view graced the top. 1 mile, 875  ft
and 1:10 hrs.

I continued along the road another several miles to  the  seasonal  gate  on
the road going up Pk 3200+, elev 2744 ft. Here there was  about  1-2  inches
of fluffy powder snow. I carried skis along but soon abandoned that idea  as
the snow was not deep enough or substantial enough to cover the road  gravel
and I ended up just hiking. The road itself was too flat  and  long  for  my
taste and I cut up through a clearcut as soon as possible  to  intersect  it
higher up. From the end of the road, in a new clearcut, a  final  unpleasant
section through twisted trees led to the high point.  It was  not  clear  to
me if the mess was caused by the windstorm or by logging. Probably  both.  5
miles, 635 ft and 2:30 hrs.

Back to the Eatonville Cutoff, I turned onto Mashel Road and drove as  close
as I could below the E side of Alder BM  parking  just  before  numerous  No
Trespassing signs adorned high fences on both sides of the road,  elev  1620
ft. An initial stickery brushy section of old clearcut was soon followed  by
more reasonable woods.  I found the BM on top. .5 mile, 565 ft and :50 hrs.

I just had time to try for Reliance Hill before total darkness. I  ended  up
doing a carbon copy of Klenke\'s trip, although  I  didn\'t  know  it  at  the
time, as I didn\'t remember his TR even though I had read it.  (I  reread  it
afterward.)  I drove Little Dale Rd off Highway 7 to  a  wide  parking  area
below a clearcut (elev 1700 ft) climbed up the clearcut to a fence,  crossed
the fence and snuck up to the mossy boulder summit above a picnic table  and
observation deck. Stealth was aided by dusk and the covering  sound  of  the
generator running at the nearby home. Although I did not  encounter  any  no
trespassing signs it was clearly private property and I felt the  thrill  of
a tresbagger.  Paul you would have been proud of me. .2  mile,  160  ft,  15
minutes.

Ohop BM (2335 ft - 535P) & Pk 2400+ (400P) -  Lake  Kapowsin  Quad;  and  Pk
2040+ (640P) & Hugo Pk (1740+ - 120P) - Eatonville Quad - December 23, 2006

The first two peaks turned out to be a splendid bike ride  on  a  series  of
well-graded logging roads with  few  difficulties  other  than  finding  the
proper way at the many junctions. I began at the gate  on  the  Weyerhaeuser
Mainline just outside Eatonville, elev 1000 ft. I was stopped  by  a  single
fallen tree .9 mile from the summit of Ohop BM and had to walk  from  there.
Some snow the last bit. The road was clear all the way  to  the  top  of  Pk
2400+. Again some snow near the top but not enough to hinder my  bike.  20.8
miles, 3120 ft, 5:17 hrs.

I still had time left to zip over to Pack Forest and bike  up  Hugo  and  Pk
2040+. The gate on the normally open road was closed, elev 940 ft. This  was
probably due to storm damage.   Even  though  the  many  downed  trees  were
already cut out on the main roads, there was much  debris  lying  about  and
the secondary roads still needed work. In fact the final spur to Hugo was  a
disaster and I could barely make it through on foot. 6.5 miles, 1260 ft  and
1:55 hr.

Fay Pullen
