 Total - 13.5 miles, 2650 ft and 6:30 hrs.',
            'tr' => '

Peak 4235 (595P) - Easton Quad - January 11, 2007


This was a Plan B trip. I awoke to 5 inches of snow  at  my  house  Thursday
morning. With that much snow on the ground so low I had  visions  of  skiing
up Mt Teneriffe again, this time right from the gate (last  time  I  had  to
walk 2.5 miles to skiable snow), or  even  Rattlesnake  Mtn  if  roads  were
really bad. Well, I did have trouble getting out  of  my  neighborhood,  but
the amount of snow diminished rapidly and by the time I  got  to  Tiger  Mtn
Summit and then North Bend there was only a dusting of snow,  hardly  enough
to ski on. I could hardly believe it. This area must  truly  be  in  a  snow
shadow.  This is the 3rd  time  this  winter  I  have  experienced  such  an
anomaly. So I had no choice but to continue on to Plan B. You should  always
have a Plan B.

I-90 was completely clear and I could drive the speed limit all the  way  to
Easton. Even with my late start (10:30 at the lot - I  waited  for  daylight
to start the drive so I could see the ice),  the  Sno-Park  was  empty  with
about 3 inches of untracked fluffy powder over a crust. Cold and sunny -  10
degrees.  Made for wonderful road skiing the 5 miles  to  below  Peak  4235.
Then up a clearcut to the top. Down a different clearcut.  Not quite  enough
powder for great turns but not bad. Great views. With time left,  I  decided
to go up Point 4114. More good skiing and views of  Goat  Pk.   Also  got  a
good view of Monohan Mtn across Tucker  Cr  where  I  could  see  roads  and
clearcuts that looked like they would make for another good ski  tour.  Back
to the car before dark. Only met 2 snowmobiles at the end of  the  day  near
the Sno-Park.

Total - 13.5 miles, 2650 ft and 6:30 hrs.

Fay Pullen
