            'title' => 'Monohan Mtn, aka "Fever" by JR (3775 ft - 1535P) & "Tucker Pk" (3366 ft - 646P) - Easton Quad - January 16, 2007 
 "Little Pk" (3440+ ft - 560P) - Easton Quad - January 18, 2007',
            'tr' => '
Monohan Mtn, aka "Fever" by JR (3775 ft - 1535P) & "Tucker Pk" (3366 ft -
646P) - Easton Quad - January 16, 2007

More lowland snow when I woke up caused another  late  start  but  not  much
trouble driving to Easton. Conditions at the Easton  Sno-Park  were  similar
to when I was there last Thursday - another  inch  or  so  powder  over  the
previous 3 inches on top of a hard rain crust and cold at 16  degrees,  with
light snow showers. There was evidence of much snowmobile traffic  over  the
holiday weekend but again the lot was empty when I arrived on this Tuesday.

I again skied up the road toward Goat Pk and Pk 4235, but this time  took  a
left onto an old road at 3 Â¼ miles. I was able to follow this  road  another
mile until I lost it (or it ended) in the valley bottom. I  crossed  several
small creeks to the base of the SW slope of Tucker where  I  left  my  skis.
The hillside was much too steep and crusty for skis.  In fact it was  almost
too crusty for boots.  I was wishing I had  brought  an  ice  axe  and  even
crampons. Once on the ridge crest it  was  more  pleasant  going.  From  the
summit I had a nice view of Pk 4235, but Goat Pk was lost in the  clouds  (5
miles, 1500 ft, 3:30 hrs).

Heading back on the main road I went right on a well-used  (by  snowmobiles)
road that is 2 Â¼ miles from the Sno-Park. At the third  switchback  most  of
the snowmobile tracks went downhill  toward  Easton.  I  (and  a  few  stray
snowmobile tracks) went uphill two more switchbacks to  gain  the  ridge  at
about 3100 ft and 1.75 miles. The road then wandered the crest for another  0.75
mile until it ended in a clearcut below  Pt  3525.  Here  a  steep  traverse
required removal of skis to regain the ridge. A  final  pleasant  ski  along
the ridge led to the summit (10.5 miles, 3200 ft, 6:50 hrs).

It was now 4:45 and getting dark. I could play it safe and just  reverse  my
up route, most of which was road and easily skied by headlamp. But  I  could
see the main road directly below me with a clearcut going much  of  the  way
down from the saddle between the summit and Pt 3525 and  I  couldn\'t  resist
taking that route.  Luckily the clearcut, though not great skiing,  was  not
overly steep and had just enough fresh snow over the crust that I could  ski
it.  I did take skis off for a crusty section in the lower woods and to  get
across the swampy creek in the valley bottom. I regained the  main  road  on
the other side about 1.5 miles from the Sno-Park. Total:  13.5  miles,  3300
ft and 8:30 hrs.


"Little Pk" (3440+ ft - 560P) - Easton Quad - January 18, 2007


I returned to the area two days later, this time accompanied  by  my  friend
Christine, for a very pleasant short tour. From Exit 78 off  I-90  we  drove
to the end of a plowed road, elev  2460.  It  was  21  degrees  and  snowing
lightly with 1 inch new. From  here  the  road  dropped  slightly  to  cross
Little Cr, then paralleled the powerline a flat mile  to  a  switchback.   A
designated and well-used snowmobile route  went  straight  while  we  turned
left uphill. The road continued  another  couple  miles  to  very  near  the
summit with only a short distance required XC through the woods to the  top.
By now the light snow was turning to freezing rain. This did  not  adversely
affect the  skiing  but  did  make  the  drive  back  over  Snoqualmie  Pass
troublesome. 8 miles, 1400 ft and 4 hrs.  Fay Pullen



