            'title' => 'Hicks Butte (5518 ft - 638P) & South Cle Elum Ridge, West Pk (5040+ ft - 440P) - Ronald Quad - January 23, 2007 
 South Cle Elum Ridge, East Pk (4320+ ft - 480P), Cle Elum Pt (4040+ ft - 40P) & Peoh Pt (4000+ ft - 0P) - Cle Elum Quad - January 25, 2007',
            'tr' => '
Hicks Butte (5518 ft - 638P) & South Cle Elum Ridge, West Pk (5040+ ft -
440P) - Ronald Quad - January 23, 2007

This trip was almost entirely  on  groomed  snowmobile  roads.  And  with  a
rapidly  rising  freezing  level  I  certainly  didn\'t  expect  any  quality
downhill terrain or conditions. I was pleasantly  surprised.  I  began  from
the Woods and Steele Sno-Park S of  Cle  Elum.  The  groomed  road  remained
fairly icy the entire gentle 5 miles of climbing on the shady N  side  to  S
Cle Elum Ridge, but I was able to climb without skins.  Once  on  the  ridge
and in the sun the snow began to soften up until by the time I was  climbing
cross country to my two summits, the lovely powder of a day or two  ago  had
turned to a melting soggy sticky  mess  that  stuck  to  my  skis  in  heavy
clumps. Despite  the  painful  ascent,  the  descent  off  both  peaks  down
clearcuts was amazingly good skiing.  A total of  some  1400  ft  of  linked
turns. Not bad, not bad at all. But then I discovered  I  had  neglected  to
put my regular glasses in my pack (they were left sitting on the front  seat
of my car). That made the final hour out by  headlamp  down  the  road  very
slow and a bit of a hazard.  Ever try  skiing  at  night  by  headlamp  with
sunglasses  on?  Rather  diminishes  what  you  can  see.   Remember  I   am
practically blind without my prescription glasses so my choices were to  ski
without my glasses and not see anything despite having  more  light  or  ski
with my sunglasses on and see but have  very  little  light.   I  chose  the
latter.

Total: 18 miles, 4500 ft and 8:20 hrs.

South Cle Elum Ridge, East Pk (4320+ ft - 480P), Cle Elum  Pt  (4040+  ft  -
40P) & Peoh Pt (4000+ ft - 0P) - Cle Elum Quad - January 25, 2007

I began this trip from the end of plowing on the South Cle Elum  Ridge  Road
3350. Although a designated and groomed snowmobile route, there was no  Sno-
Park here and almost no parking, with barely a spot to put my  one  car.  It
was foggy and 24 degrees and conditions were so icy  I  needed  skins  right
away even on the gentle road. Since I had skins on, I  figured  I  might  as
well try a short cut up a lesser road.  Bad idea.  I took a wrong  turn  and
ended up on a deadend at a building.  I forced a route XC on awful crust  to
the correct road but soon gave that up also and  just  went  uphill  to  the
main road where I should have stayed to begin with. At least it was  groomed
and smooth. At least until the turnoff to Peoh Pt where a steep section  was
so rutted as to be virtually unskiable. I walked. Temperatures stayed  below
freezing with only open areas in full sun softening up. I had maybe a  dozen
quality turns off Cle Elum Pt.  That was it for any decent  downhill.  There
seem to be two equal summits to the east end of South  Cle  Elum  Ridge  and
not knowing which was higher I climbed them both.  My altimeter implied  the
west one was higher by some 30 feet.  Skiing off that peak XC  was  strictly
survival style. But the final run down the road, in daylight this time,  was
sheer bliss. It sure helps when you can see.  4  miles  and  1500  ft  in  a
blazing half hour.  Fun, fun, fun. Groomed snowmobile roads  do  have  their
upside.

Total: 16 miles, 3000 ft and 7:20 hrs. Fay Pullen


