            'title' => 'Frog Mtn (4880+ ft - 400P - Blanca Lk Quad) & Silica Mtn (5400+ ft - 880P - Evergreen Mtn Quad) - February 11, 2007',
            'tr' => '
Frog Mtn (4880+ ft - 400P - Blanca Lk Quad) & Silica Mtn (5400+ ft - 880P  -
Evergreen Mtn Quad) - February 11, 2007

I climbed these peaks with Stefan and company - well sort of. Despite  heavy
rain on the drive to Jack Pass, it conveniently stopped raining just  as  we
started and we even had some clearing. I  really  wanted  to  ski  Frog,  so
carried skis to the top while snowshoeing so I could be with  the  group.  I
had a nice time chatting with Natala and enjoying a gorgeous  view  of  Bear
Mtn on the way up. We regrouped on top (2300 ft &  2  hrs).  Stefan,  Chris,
Kathy and Stan continued along the ridge  toward  Silica.  Greg,  Sarah  and
Natala headed down to the cars.

My original intention was to just ski down Frog and  then  perhaps  ski  San
Juan Hill. (I have already climbed San Juan but have never skied it.   I  do
think it would make a fine ski trip.)  But the start of the ridge to  Silica
was so inviting, I decided at the last minute to ski along it  for  a  ways.
Well, the ridge just kept going and I just  kept  going  with  it.   I  kept
expecting it to get nasty, at which point I was just going to bail and  turn
around. But it never did. It really was a lovely ridge  and  I  do  so  love
ridges. It did get a little narrow and steep  in  a  few  spots  and  I  did
remove my skis a couple of times but it was nothing  serious.   Then  I  met
Kathy and Stan coming back. They had turned around at a steep traverse  past
a small pinnacle. This worried me, but when I got to  the  traverse  it  was
not too bad. Stefan and Chris had very good steps  for  me  to  follow.  The
last bit to Silica was easily done on skis and I reached the summit at  2:00
(4100 ft & 5:40 hrs).

The snowshoe tracks of Stefan and Chris continued  to  Pk  5327.  The  ridge
still looked inviting, but I had had enough and had to  think  about  how  I
was going to get down.  I really didn\'t want to return among the ridge.   It
would take much too long. I was on my own now, with no tracks to  follow.  I
knew Stefan\'s plan was to descend from Pk 5327 somehow  to  the  road  along
Evergreen Cr and follow this back to Jack Pass. So  I  opted  for  a  direct
descent off Silica to this same road. I wasn\'t sure how this  would  go  but
it ended up being pretty good.  I had  a  few  hundred  feet  of  reasonable
downhill before being funneled into a steep narrow  gully.  Here  postholing
worked better than skiing through the kneedeep slush. Lower I worked my  way
out of the gully into open forest and more solid snow. I  hit  the  road  at
2900 ft in a little over an hour.

I half expected to come  across  Stefan  and  Chris\'s  tracks  on  the  road
despite their extra peak. They were probably Â½-1 hour ahead of me  and  much
faster. But there were no tracks. I was thankful I had  skis  for  the  long
trek back along the very flat and even partially  uphill  road.  There  were
two washed out stream crossings to contend  with  before  hitting  the  main
road to Evergreen Lookout. The second one probably took a  good  15  minutes
to get across the vertical 5-foot wall on the other side.  The snow  was  so
slushy I had difficulty kicking  any  steps  that  held  up  it.  They  kept
breaking out. I reached the cars at 5:15. I  hung  around  until  Chris  and
Stefan showed up about 30 minutes later.  I was sorry my ski  tracks  hadn\'t
helped them more plodding along that road on snowshoes.

Although snowshoes and skis don\'t ordinarily mix on the  same  trip,  things
worked out well for me this time.  I had the best  of  both  worlds.  I  had
company on the way up Frog, could go at my own pace along the ridge and  not
worry about holding anyone up, tracks to follow all the way  to  Silica  and
the comfort of knowing others were in the area.

Total: 9 miles, 4500 ft and 8:55 hrs    Fay Pullen


