            'tr' => '

El Capitan (5327 ft - 247P - Evergreen Mtn Quad) - February 14, 2007


I always thought San Juan Hill would make a good ski trip  and  so  it  did,
though it would have been even nicer with better snow that would  allow  for
skiing the clearcuts. Since I had already  climbed  San  Juan,  I  added  El
Capitan as the destination for  greater  incentive.  I  also  wanted  to  do
Quarter Dome but it didn\'t happen due to  bad  weather  and  lack  of  time.
Because of snow conditions, I stuck to the road the whole way  to  its  high
point. This was no problem as roads, even long ones, can  be  fun  on  skis.
The lower part was crusty with marginal traction but things improved by  the
first switchback as I climbed to a  dusting  of  fresh  snow  and  I  glided
happily along. I began in fog, but much to my surprise, given  the  horrible
forecast for the day, the weather improved all morning to the point where  I
had reasonable views and could even  see  the  route  I  had  taken  3  days
previously from Frog along the ridge to Silica.

At the road end (4.5 miles, 1800 ft & 2:20 hrs) I put on skins to enter  the
woods.  Here the snow was crusty to downright icy and not really  very  good
for skis. Things got better once I gained the  ridge  with  some  reasonable
skiing up and down along the ridge. Then more unpleasantness  as  I  had  to
make a very steep and once again icy traverse around the cliffs of Pt  4841.
I did run into a line of  old  snowshoe  tracks  (presumably  from  Stefan\'s
recent trip?) that helped. Once back on the  ridge  things  improved  again.
The terrain opened up, there was now 6-8 inches of dry new snow  and  skiing
was a joy as I easily  followed  the  ridge  to  El  Capitan.  However,  the
forecast was now coming true and it was beginning to snow and visibility  to
diminish.  I made the summit before the weather deteriorated  completely  (8
miles, 3600 ft & 5:30 hrs).

I had some delightful skiing off El Capitan. Even  the  traverse  around  Pt
4841 wasn\'t as bad as the new snow began accumulating.  By the  time  I  got
back to the road it was snowing heavily and had  already  put  down  several
inches. In fact there was so much of the sticky new stuff I got  zero  glide
until I stopped to wax my skis. That worked like a charm and  I  zipped  the
rest of the way down the road. Although there was 2 inches or  so  of  slush
on my car, by the time I reached it what was coming down was more like  rain
than snow and very wet.

Total: 16 miles, 4200 ft & 9:30 hrs.

Fay Pullen
