Cle Elum Ridge (3760+ ft - 480P - Teanaway Butte Quad) - February 20, 2007


With recent heavy new snow  over  a  slick  crust  at  the  passes,  I  knew
avalanche danger would be an issue. I thought things might be better to  the
East with less snow. My  original  plan  was  to  ski  Swauk  Ridge  out  of
Liberty.  After crawling  over  Snoqualmie  Pass  with  chains  required,  a
closure for Avy  control  and  almost  blizzard  conditions,  I  arrived  at
Liberty to  sunshine,  no  new  snow  and  not  even  enough  old  snow  for
reasonable  skiing.  I  was  shocked.  I  am  continually  amazed   at   the
inconsistencies of snowfall.  Back to Cle Elum for Plan B, Cle  Elum  Ridge,
where I wandered around for an hour trying to find a viable road to  get  me
close enough to ski it. No luck. Then I tried to access it from Roslyn.   In
all cases I couldn\'t find a way past private roads  and  drives.  I  finally
found a road between Roslyn and Ronald that worked.  With all the delays  it
was after 12:00 before I actually put on the skis.  I started from  a  gated
logging road off plowed roads  of  a  new  development.  Perhaps  eventually
homes will work their way all the way up to the  ridgecrest,  but  for  now,
once under way, the route and ridge are  still  delightful.  I  reached  the
high point in 2 hours then skied along the gentle ridge until I ran  out  of
time. There was  about  1  foot  of  new  snow  along  the  ridge,  but  old
snowmobile tracks made trailbreaking easy most of the  way  until  they  all
headed down to Number 3 Mine near Ronald. Weather alternated  between  heavy
snow squalls and clearing sunbreaks. Despite my late start, this was a  most
enjoyable easy tour, highly recommended with very pleasant skiable terrain.

Total: 11 miles, 1900 ft and 5:30 hrs.

Tarzan Butte (4385 ft - 825P - Teanaway Butte Quad) - February 22, 2007

What a difference two days make. I drove the  speed  limit  (and  over)  the
whole way, with no delays, to the 29 Pines Sno-Park on  the  Teanaway  River
Road. This is mainly a snowmobile lot that accesses the  Teanaway,  but  the
Jungle Cr Road is designated for skiers only  (with  a  voluntary  motorized
closure). There were no snowmobile tracks on that road or on the  spur  road
I took toward Tarzan Butte.  All snowmobiles stayed on the  road  along  Rye
Cr toward Teanaway Butte. Trailbreaking was a bit of work, but  nevertheless
enjoyable. Weather started foggy then cleared to sunbreaks. There  are  many
roads in the area not shown on the map and I took a wrong turn at one  point
but eventually ended up where I wanted to be. I used  skins  for  the  final
climb up the E ridge to the summit. An open area a short ways  down  the  NW
side provided a few views. The new  snow  was  beginning  to  melt  for  the
downhill run but still provided some  quality  turns.  All  in  all  another
pleasant short tour.

Total: 7 miles, 2100 ft and 5 hrs.

Fay Pullen


