Swauk Ridge (4205 ft - 405P - Liberty Quad) - February 27, 2007


I tried this trip last week but there wasn\'t enough new snow  then  to  make
it go, so I tried again this week.  This time  it  worked  although  it  was
harder to get to the ridge than I had anticipated, for a number of  reasons.
I began from Liberty, where a couple of inches of fresh snow over  the  many
snowmobile tracks made skiing up the Lion  Gulch  Road  fast  and  pleasant.
After about a mile I began looking for a way to cut  XC  up  to  the  ridge,
choosing a semi-open area along a side creek. This soon  narrowed  to  creek
bottom where I then took to going straight up a S  facing  slope  where  the
snow cover was decidedly marginal. It was about this time that I  discovered
why my skiing to this point had seemed vaguely unsymmetrical when I  finally
noticed that my skis were mismatched.  I  had  inadvertently  paired  a  fat
160cm Rebound ski on my right foot with a skinnier 170cm Snobound ski on  my
left foot! How in heavens name could  I  have  done  that  without  noticing
right away? I must be losing it. It would have been hilarious  (actually  it
WAS hilarious) if it weren\'t that it  could  potentially  be  a  trip-ending
mistake as this meant I couldn\'t  use  the  skins  I  had  brought  for  the
shorter Rebound skis. Well, I suppose I could have put a skin  on  one  ski,
but I am not sure how well that would have worked. Such are the  hazards  of
having too much gear (who me you say?).  This wouldn\'t have  happened  if  I
had had only one pair of skis to choose from.

I struggled my lopsided way up the thin  snow  cover,  without  the  use  of
skins, eventually making it to the upper road shown on the map.   This  road
didn\'t help that much as it never accessed the ridge itself but I  did  stay
on it until past Pt 3890 where I again went XC to the main  ridge.  Once  on
the ridge the snow was deeper and the skiing very nice.  There  were  a  few
rocky pinnacles to work around but nothing major.  From  the  high  point  I
continued a ways N along the ridge until I found a reasonable slope  to  ski
down. Here is where my mismatched skis really made their differences  clear.
I could turn left  much  more  easily  than  right  and  I  never  made  the
adjustment from one to other properly so the downhill run was not  a  pretty
sight. Once I hit the main road I gave up  on  the  day,  despite  it  still
being early, vowing never to make such a mistake again.

Total: 8 miles, 1800 ft and 5 hrs.

Nelson Hill (4375 ft), Snowshoe Ridge (4125 ft) & Flag  Mtn  (3834  ft)  via
Table Mtn (6200 ft) Loop - Liberty & Swauk Pass Quads - March 1, 2007

This turned into one of my best ski trips of the season, despite one  of  my
worst drives over Snoqualmie Pass. I  had  several  inches  of  snow  in  my
driveway in the morning, Highway 18 over Tiger  Mtn  was  completely  closed
and I had to drive to I-90 a roundabout way via Issaquah,  I-90  itself  had
significant snow all the way from Issaquah to Easton, chains  were  required
over the pass where it was snowing heavily with limited visibility  and  the
plows couldn\'t keep up resulting in rutted tracks and 30 mph speeds. It  was
as bad as I have ever seen it without the pass being closed and  added  1:15
hour to the drive time. Fortunately, traffic was light, many  probably  kept
home by the freak lowland snow. I probably should  have  stayed  home  also,
but I knew if I could just get to where I wanted  to  go,  skiing  would  be
great. It was too.

I began once again from Liberty, this time going up the Cougar  Gulch  Road.
And once again, in contrast to the  miserable  conditions  over  Snoqualmie,
the sun was shining and there was just enough new snow on the road  to  make
skiing nice. This time I made sure my skis were matched, but  I  did  forget
my camera in the car so could take no pictures. Every trip I seem to  either
forget something, lose something, get off  route  or  do  something  equally
stupid to make things more difficult. I have come to accept this as  a  flaw
in my character and  even  enjoy  the  challenge  of  figuring  out  how  to
persevere in spite of my errors. However, I do regret forgetting  my  camera
on this beautiful day.

About a mile up Cougar Gulch  I  turned  right  onto  Williams  Creek  Road.
Although no longer groomed, a snowmobile had  been  up  this  road  recently
enough that it made trailbreaking no problem.  I  followed  the  old  track,
putting on skins when it steepened, to Nelson Hill (1700 ft, 2 hrs)  and  on
as it continued up the ridge. I had hoped the track would lead  me  all  the
way to Table Mtn, but this was not the case.  It  began  contouring  N  away
from where I wanted to go, so at about 5000 ft I left the track to head  SE.
Here trailbreaking became more work through the now over  a  foot  of  fresh
snow. I worked my way past a rocky  point  up  steep  slopes  and  contoured
below the fascinating cliffs of Table Mtn near Pt  5885  to  eventually  hit
the main Table Mtn Road at about 6000 ft (3500 ft, 4:20 hrs).

I followed this road about 2 miles, over a high  point  of  6200  ft,  to  a
saddle where I could drop  off  the  ridge.  After  a  short  windblown  icy
section the ski down to pick up Snowshoe Ridge was to die for - the kind  of
deep forgiving powder where you could do no wrong. All too soon it ended  as
I followed a narrow track down Snowshoe Ridge, but  the  snow  was  so  good
even this skiing was easy and fun and fast. Soon the track hit a  road  with
fresh snowmobile tracks, which I followed to Snowshoe Ridge proper.  Next  I
wanted to ski to Flag Mtn. I thought this would all be on  easy  road.   Not
so. Most of the way was on an old track that  was  blocked  to  snowmobiles.
So I had more trailbreaking, some of it up and my  skis  were  not  climbing
well, (I didn\'t take the time to put skins back on)  or  maybe  I  was  just
getting tired. Then the summit of Flag (4100  ft,  7  hrs)  was  a  surprise
rocky little scramble. All this took longer than expected. I  thought  about
skiing directly off Flag to a road below but in the end decided it  was  too
steep, the snow cover  too  thin  and  the  terrain  too  uncertain  and  so
reversed my track to the main road. The fast run down the groomed road  made
up for lost time and I still made the car before dark, though just barely.

The drive home over Snoqualmie Pass in the evening bore  no  resemblance  at
all to my morning one. The road was bare and  dry  the  whole  way  with  no
evidence at all of the storm that had hit a short time earlier. How  quickly
conditions can change!

Total: 16 miles, 4200 ft and 8 hrs.

Fay Pullen





