            'tr' => '

Jolly Mtn (6443 ft - 963P - Davis Pk Quad) - March 6, 2007


Yes, I know.  I was just up much of Jolly Mtn  on  Saturday,  March  3  with
Jim, Eileen and Beth. But we didn\'t make the top  (not  that  is  seemed  to
matter much at the time) and I so like this trip that  when  Tuesday  dawned
an A+ sunny warm day, I found myself inexplicably headed back  to  the  same
place. I just wanted a sure thing with known conditions  and  high  mountain
views to take full advantage of the exemplary weather. And did  I  ever.  In
addition, since neither my companions, route nor snow  conditions  were  the
same as Saturday, it really ended up being an entirely different trip.

I had thought to make use of the track we had set up the road  on  Saturday,
but the road to begin was so crusty I needed skins right away.  Skinning  up
a gentle road is something I usually avoid,  so  I  left  it  at  the  first
switchback and went straight uphill all the way to Sasse  Ridge  (2.8  mile,
2800 ft, 2:20 hrs). I passed below our previous high  point  in  another  45
minutes and began the longer-than-it-looks up and down traverse to the  5960
ft saddle N of Jolly. Despite a supposedly 8000 ft freezing level,  anything
in the shade or not fully exposed to the  sun  remained  crusty,  especially
the last 500 foot climb up the N ridge to the summit (5.5  miles,  4300  ft,
4:30 hrs).

Views were to die for, which was of course why I  was  there  in  the  first
place, and I went crazy snapping pictures. I  felt  on  top  of  the  world.
While I took a short break for lunch, a hawk soared overhead  to  check  out
this anomalous creature. He circled half a dozen times as if to say, "  See!
I can fly higher than you can!" True enough, but  I  felt  pretty  satisfied
with my own height!

The ski down the N ridge was still crusty, but anything in  the  direct  sun
had turned to deep heavy slush. I managed to cut two of the  switchbacks  on
the main road before my knees began to complain and  my  telemark  technique
to suffer accordingly. I finished the day content to  follow  the  road  the
rest of the way down and was most thankful  for  the  previous  track  so  I
didn\'t have to break trail downhill, reaching the car well before dark.

My improved time over Saturday was not due to  my  moving  any  faster,  but
rather to the shorter distance cutting straight uphill (I shaved off a  good
3 miles going this way), better snow for climbing and to  taking  only  very
short breaks. Comparing the two  trips,  I  much  prefer  the  laughter  and
company of good friends, but this one came in a close second.

Total: 13.6 miles, 4500 ft and 7:45 hrs.

Fay Pullen
