 Red Mtn, West Pk (5480+ ft - 400P - Polallie Ridge Quad) - March 13, 2007',
            'tr' => '

Red Mtn (5880+ ft - 2560P - Polallie Ridge Quad) - March 9, 2007


I have Jim Brisbine to thank for suggesting skiing up the north side of  Red
Mtn.  I would never have thought to try that as it  had  always  seemed  too
steep to me for skiing and really  more  suited  to  snowshoes.   But  while
skiing up Jolly Mtn recently, with a great view of Red  across  the  valley,
Jim pointed out a series of clearcuts and a  traversing  road  half  way  up
that clearly offered possibilities and confessed his hope to some  day  give
it a go. I must apologize to Jim for stealing  his  idea  and  running  away
with it, but I am an impatient by nature and once an idea enters my  head  I
am compelled to act upon it as quickly as possible.

Now the first question was how to get to the  road  we  saw  without  skiing
miles with snowmobiles. It appeared that it  should  be  accessible  from  a
clearcut very near the Cooper River Rd bridge over the Cle Elum  River,  but
as I skied  up  this  groomed  snowmobile  route  I  saw  no  side  road  or
reasonable XC route in this area. My map did show a road going  uphill  some
3 miles farther on, a route I had hoped to avoid, but now I was  stuck  with
it. Somehow I didn\'t go quite far enough, missed the road I wanted and  took
another, not shown on my map, that started up a  clearcut.  It  soon  became
obvious I wasn\'t on the right road, but rather than retreat, I went with  my
mistake skinning straight up the steep slopes. Soon I could see the  road  I
had wanted across a deep ravine but I couldn\'t get to it at that  point.  So
I just continued up until I eventually intersected  the  traversing  road  I
had originally wanted.

The second question was what to do now that I was on the road.  It  appeared
to traverse into the drainage between Red Mtn and the West Pk of  Red  where
I didn\'t think it would be that helpful as a route to the  summit.  However,
a spur continued uphill to another clearcut below Red\'s NE  ridge  and  this
looked promising. Not only was it promising, it  was  positively  delightful
as a ski route.  After a short wooded section at the top of the clearcut,  I
gained access to the ridge itself and then a  series  of  open  slopes,  all
very skiable. I would never have  guessed  this  looking  at  the  map.  The
summit itself was a corniced ridge (5.2 miles, 3700 ft,  4:45  hrs).  I  had
thought to continue to the West Pk but the  ridge  looked  difficult  and  I
doubted I had enough time.  The West Pk  would  have  to  wait  for  another
trip.

Climbing up the first clearcut I went through a very slushy snow  transition
zone before gradually getting to firmer snow  higher  up.  Near  the  summit
there was 4-5 inches of fresh snow over a crusty base, with  the  new  stuff
turning wet fast.  Not perfect conditions for downhill, but not bad  either,
and I managed a reasonable run off the summit. It was tempting  to  continue
down very inviting terrain into the NE basin, but  this  appeared  from  the
map to end in a steep narrow ravine. I was afraid to try it  without  having
come up that way. Instead, I went straight down as far as I dared  and  then
traversed back to the NE ridge and my up route.

Once back on the traversing road at 4000 ft, I  continued  following  it  SW
hoping to find a better way down to the valley. After  about  1.5  miles  of
flat trailbreaking, I came to the edge of the clearcut  I  had  seen  almost
directly above the Cle  Elum  River  Bridge.  But  I  found  no  road  going
downhill. Rather, at this point the road went  uphill  and  I  found  myself
stranded at a dead-end 1300 ft above the valley. To make  matters  worse,  I
couldn\'t ski down the clearcut without climbing up past a  deep  ravine.   I
was forced to ski down steep forest. Actually it wasn\'t as bad as I  thought
it would be.  The snow was very soft and the trees far apart. Still  it  was
a rather challenging trip down. I hit the groomed road  about  a  mile  from
the car.

The irony of this trip is that the road that Jim and I had  spotted  halfway
up Red was really of no practical use. Still it did  lure  me  to  the  peak
where I discovered some fabulous ski terrain. It will warrant  future  trips
and exploration. Total: 11 miles, 3700 ft and 7:30 hrs.


Red Mtn, West Pk (5480+ ft - 400P - Polallie Ridge Quad) - March 13, 2007


It only took until the following Tuesday for me to get back to the West  Pk.
I did say I am an impatient person. This  time  I  found  the  correct  road
uphill .4 miles farther on from where I went uphill  last  time  (3.4  miles
total from the car). This  made  climbing  much  easier,  although  I  still
needed skins as the snow was very crusty despite a  mostly  sunny  start  to
the day. I followed the road another 4 miles  to  the  vast  clearcut  basin
between Red Mtn and the West Peak.

After my last few trips out  where  the  snow  had  become  very  slushy,  I
expected it to quickly soften. Instead  the  snow  level  appeared  to  have
taken a nose dive on me and temperatures remained  below  freezing  all  day
above 3000 ft. Eventually it dawned  on  me  that  the  snow  would  not  be
softening at all this day and I would have to content with  nasty  crust  on
the downhill. It was not going to be a stellar ski day. I  even  had  doubts
as to whether I would make my summit, by any means. Where I  left  the  road
to gain the ridge to the West Pk, the  snow  was  downright  icy.  Then  the
summit itself was steeper and more challenging than I had  expected.  I  was
able to keep skis on to reach the summit  ridge  on  the  north  but  I  was
unable to follow it directly to the top. I was forced onto a steep  traverse
across the east face to gain the ridge from the south.  And  me  without  an
ice axe. I didn\'t think I would need one.  Looking at the map I  thought  it
would be an easy ski ascent. If the  slope  had  been  really  icy,  I  most
likely would have turned around at this point. Fortunately,  the  slope  was
in the sun and had softened enough  that  I  could  kick  reasonable  steps.
Still, it was unnerving to cross with just ski poles. I reached  the  summit
at 2:45 (3500 ft, 5 hrs).

I did more walking than skiing getting back to the road.  What  a  shame  as
the terrain would make great  skiing  with  even  reasonable  snow.  I  even
expected the road ski to be a disaster and I really wasn\'t  looking  forward
to 7 miles of plodding. But much to my surprise the road  was  a  great  ski
down, partially because it was not steep, partially because it  was  groomed
and smooth and partially because it did softened up a little in the sun.  So
it wasn\'t a total bust as a ski trip. Total: 16.4 miles, 3600 ft and 8 hrs.

Fay Pullen





