            'title' => 'Flapjack Point (5191 ft - 471P - Evergreen Mtn Quad) - March 20, 2007',
            'tr' => '

Flapjack Point (5191 ft - 471P - Evergreen Mtn Quad) - March 20, 2007


Snow advisories for the mountains caused the cancellation of more  ambitious
climbing plans, so I went skiing  instead  and  I  wasn\'t  really  all  that
unhappy.  Did  I  ever  mention  before  that  I  love  backcountry  skiing,
especially up a new peak, especially in new snow? Although I  must  say  the
new snow was almost too much of a good thing.  It  snowed  heavily  all  day
long racking up a good  18  inches  total  that  completely  obliterated  my
uphill tracks  on  the  approach  road  so  not  only  did  I  have  serious
trailbreaking on the way in, I had to do it all over again on the  way  out.
Was this really the first day of spring?  Maybe  it  was  the  last  day  of
winter.

I drove as far as I could on road 6514  (Eagle  Cr  Road)  off  the  Beckler
River Road until stopped by a fallen  tree  at  1900  ft.  I  couldn\'t  have
gotten much farther anyway, as a patch of old  snow  was  just  beyond.  The
snow level had just started its plunge downward, the rain quickly turned  to
heavy snowfall and just as quickly beginning  sticking  to  the  bare  road.
Good thing, as the first mile had many bare sections  that  were  made  just
barely skiable.  As I climbed the new snow became deeper  and  deeper  until
by the time I crossed Eagle Cr at 3.5 miles, elev 3240  ft,  I  was  plowing
through 6 inches and more. The main road continued depressingly flat, so  as
soon as possible I put on skins and went  straight  uphill  through  an  old
clearcut even though the  second  growth  trees  were  discouragingly  close
together. When I hit an upper spur (elev 3600 ft), I headed left  into  open
woods that offered better travel, not to mention less fresh  snow  to  break
trail through. It was fairly steep to start, but as I climbed  the  gradient
gentled and the going was very pleasant.

I broke out of the trees at a saddle (elev 4600 ft) and  was  treated  to  a
brief (like 30 seconds) moment of clearing with almost sun and  almost  blue
sky, the only of the day. In the open now, and higher,  the  deep  new  snow
really slowed me down and I took about an hour to go the last  600  ft.  The
summit ridge and summit itself made for a  very  nice  ski  ascent,  but  of
course I had no views.  I am sure they would be very nice when visible.

The snow was a tad too deep for  elegant  skiing  off  the  summit  but  the
skiing down through the forest was delightful. Then I hit the road.   I  had
hoped to pick up two more peaks in the area  but  those  hopes  were  dashed
when I came to the realization that it had snowed so much while  I  was  out
my uphill tracks were gone and of no use. Not only would I not be doing  any
more uphill I would have to work just to go down. There are few things  more
disheartening than having to break trail downhill on skis.  After  all,  the
whole point of skiing is the free downhill run. But I am not complaining.  I
still had a great trip and I am happy any time I have skis on my feet.

Total: 11 miles, 3900 ft and 8:40 hrs.

Fay Pullen


