            'tr' => '
Spinnaker Pk (5645 ft - 845P - Captain Point Quad) and Sky Mtn  (5482  ft  -
1122P - Labyrinth Mtn Quad) - March 22, 2007

I had thought to return to Eagle Cr and pick up the two peaks  I  missed  on
Tuesday, but somehow a predicted snow level of 3000 ft changed overnight  to
4500 ft. Since both peaks were right  around  4500  ft  high  and  I  didn\'t
relish spending the entire day in the rain, I just  kept  going  to  Stevens
Pass where it was 33 degrees and snowing. I hoped I would  get  high  enough
to get into some of the beautiful new snow I had run into two  days  earlier
but it was not to be. The snow level may have been 4500 ft but  the  melting
level was much higher and all that gorgeous  snow  was  already  turning  to
foot deep slush and just got wetter and wetter and heavier  and  heavier  as
the day went on.

I started in skins right away up the steep cat track that ended at a  tower,
then traversed on an old ski trail to Skyline Ridge and followed the  ridge,
more or less, to the summit of Sky Mtn. I have been up Sky before but I  was
so close I couldn\'t resist a  repeat  visit.  In  virgin  territory  now,  I
descended in reasonable conditions 1000 ft, past Tye Lake, to  the  4360  ft
saddle between Tye and Spinnaker. The snow was now so sticky I was  able  to
climb from there without reapplying skins all the  way  to  Spinnaker  (4.75
mile, 3200 ft, 5 hrs). The ridge was easy skiing and since I had the time  I
continued on to the Martin BM, Â½ mile farther.

The terrain off the ridge back to the saddle was good for  skiing,  but  the
snow was now so wet and heavy, that it took all the leg muscle I had  to  be
able to turn in it. And it was a very good lesson in keeping  weight  evenly
distributed over both skis. If I got too much weight over the front ski,  it
would dive deeply into the snow becoming completely buried and down I  would
go. Such is the life of  a  backcountry  skier  in  the  Pacific  Northwest.
Conditions are rarely ideal, with the snow level jumping up and down like  a
yoyo, and one must learn to ski the crude (or at least survive it)  or  stay
home 90% of the time.

At the saddle, the prospect of breaking trail 1000 ft up  to  Skyline  Ridge
was more than I could bear. Even going downhill had about done me in. I  saw
I was very close to the PCT and I naively thought I could just pick  up  the
trail and follow it, seemingly mostly downhill or  level,  back  to  Stevens
Pass. This turned out to be more difficult than I had imagined.  I  couldn\'t
find any trace of the trail and there were no signs of  anyone  having  been
in the area since the last storm. I wandered up and down through  woods  and
meadows and across steep slopes breaking trail through exhausting slush.  To
make matters worse, whatever precipitation coming down  now  was  closer  to
rain than snow and I was beginning to get very wet.  I  finally  ran  across
the trail about 1.5 miles from the pass, but  it  took  another  Â½  mile  of
trailbreaking before I found any helpful fresh tracks. Total it had taken  2
Â½ hours to get out the 3 miles from the saddle.

Total: 10.1 miles, 4350 ft and 10 hrs.

Fay Pullen




