            'title' => 'Peak 5495 (415P - Blowout Mtn Quad) - April 5, 2007',
            'tr' => '

Peak 5495 (415P - Blowout Mtn Quad) - April 5, 2007


This was my second attempt on this peak. During the first one, on March  16,
I was thwarted by discovering that the snowmobile bridge over Cabin  Cr  was
gone (it was there last year), evidently washed away  by  the  fall  floods,
which made my planned approach via the roads  along  Cabin  and  Log  Creeks
impossible. In a futile attempt to find an alternate  way,  I  followed  the
groomed route up Cole Cr (not knowing where it went) in the hopes  it  would
lead where I wanted to go.  It would  have,  eventually,  by  climbing  high
around the N end of Cole Butte then descending 1200 ft  to  Log  Cr.  But  I
didn\'t have the time or energy to pursue it and instead salvaged the day  by
staying high and making a loop over Pt 5230 and in the  process  discovering
some new clearcuts with marvelous skiing.

I returned three weeks later with more time and  energy  for  a  route  over
Cole Butte ridge which would involve an  additional  2400  ft  of  elevation
gain over the original plan. The Sno-Park  (elev  2200  ft)  was  no  longer
officially open (all signs and  the  porta-potty  removed),  but  there  was
still snow at the start although  it  was  getting  thin  with  a  few  bare
patches. All went well until I turned off the groomed road and discovered  a
huge cat had  gone  up  my  road  leaving  horrid  deep  rutted  tracks  and
completely destroying it for skiing. In places the  twin  tracks  were  2.5-3
feet deep. Had I known I was going to have to contend with such a  disaster,
I might very well have  considered  going  elsewhere.   But  they  were  not
noticeable on the groomed road so it was too late by the  time  I  ran  into
them to do anything else.

Thankfully, the cat tracks turned off my route onto a side  road  after  2.2
miles and 1200 ft. I have no idea why this  cat  was  traveling  up  a  snow
covered road. It is not like it was  plowing  the  road.  Maybe  the  Forest
Service was doing an early check of a timber sale. If so, why couldn\'t  they
have gone by snowmobile?  It certainly would have been  easier  and  cheaper
not to mention made  it  better  for  me  to  ski.  By  the  way,  even  the
snowmobiles seemed to have had trouble getting up the cat tracks.

I continued on the now trackless road in bliss until leaving it to climb  up
the large clearcut to the 5200 ft saddle on Cole Butte ridge. I now  had  to
drop 1200 ft to the 4000 ft saddle between Log Creek and Big  Creek.  I  had
hoped to ski  straight  down,  but  steep  terrain,  thick  trees  and  snow
conditions made it easier to stick to the road. From the low saddle  another
road led easily to the final open wooded slopes and the summit  of  Pk  5495
(11 miles, 4700 ft, 6 hrs).

I had a pleasant lunch in the sun before beginning the long trek  back.  The
ski off the summit and down the road was fast and  fun  until  I  was  faced
with the 1200 ft climb back up to Cole Butte ridge. I put on skins and  went
straight uphill rather than follow the long road hoping it would  save  time
and energy. I don\'t think it did.  By the time I topped  out  I  was  pretty
much done in and it was all I could do to ski decently down the clearcut  on
the other side. And then I came to the dreaded cat track. It was as  bad  as
I had imagined. I could ski neither the deep track nor the narrow middle in-
between.  That left me with the downhill edge of  the  road,  which  worked,
sort of, most of the time. But it was a real challenge.  This  is  about  as
bad as it gets for road skiing. However, the snow was soft, so  I  guess  it
would have been worse if it had  been  icy.   In  that  case  I  would  most
certainly have been walking down.

Total: 21 miles, 6150 ft and 11 hrs.

Fay Pullen
