Quarterdome (5276 ft - 596P - Evergreen Mtn Quad) - April 10, 2007


I knew it was going to be a long hard day when I arrived  at  Jack  Pass  to
over 5 inches of fresh wet snow with more  coming  down.  Trailbreaking  was
definitely going to  take  its  toll.  By  the  time  I  got  to  the  first
switchback on the main road up San Juan Hill I began looking  for  a  faster
way uphill. To this end, I went straight on a spur road looking to  skin  up
a clearcut to the ridge above. But I  hadn\'t  counted  on  this  spur  being
decommissioned and the culverts being removed (or  washed  out).  The  first
two creek crossings were fairly easily bypassed but the third and  main  one
was a deep chasm that took me a good half hour to find a  way  across.  Once
past this, easy clearcuts and open forest led to the main ridge of San  Juan
Hill.

After a short pleasant ski along the ridge to a 4400 ft  saddle,  I  dropped
off the ridge down steep slopes to 3900 ft and the  open  meadows  of  upper
San Juan Cr and then tried to work my way toward the  4640  ft  El  Capitan-
Quarterdome saddle. I actually traversed  too  far,  completely  missed  the
saddle and found myself  on  the  quite  steep  SE  slopes  of  Quarterdome.
Although there were brief periods of clearing and even  sun  at  times,  for
the most part it was foggy and snowing with little visibility  most  of  the
day. I topped out on the summit, with no views, at 3:10 (3500 ft, 6:10 hr).

Seeking to avoid my uphill error, I  skied  down  the  S  ridge  to  the  El
Capitan-Quarterdome saddle (much better ski terrain) and then took  as  high
a traverse as possible under the cliffs of Pt 4841 around San Juan Cr  basin
and back to San Juan ridge saving  a  little  elevation  gain.  I  had  some
lovely skiing down through open forest and clearcuts until the  snow  became
so deep and wet and heavy that turning was a chore. I chose  a  route  so  I
didn\'t have to repeat the tough creek crossing of the way up,  but  I  still
had to contend with difficult skiing through close trees below the  clearcut
before hitting the spur road. My tracks on the main road were mostly  snowed
in but I thankfully still got a little glide for the last bit  back  to  the
car.

Total: 12 miles, 4100 ft and 10:20 hrs.

Fay Pullen
