            'tr' => '
D Mtn (5409 ft - 729P) and Valhalla Mtn (5200+ ft - 160P)  -  Captain  Point
Quad - April 13, 2007

I was able to drive about .3 mile beyond the Iron Goat TH (elev 2600 ft)  on
Martin Cr Rd 6710. Continuous skiable snow started right  from  the  car.  I
followed the road  to  the  upper  valley,  across  Martin  Cr  and  up  two
switchbacks to the 4640 ft saddle with Captain Point (5.7  miles,  2200  ft,
3:30 hrs), where there were several inches of fresh  snow  and  more  coming
down. From the saddle I skied up the gentle and pleasant S  ridge,  half  in
clearcut and half in open woods, to the summit of D  Mtn  (6.7  miles,  3000
ft, 4:30 hrs). Much to my surprise I found the register stuffed  in  a  tree
hole by Stefan on 2/10/07. He had ascended from the north over Valhalla.

I descended 400 ft and easily followed the  ridge  NE  to  Valhalla  Mtn  (8
miles, 3200 ft, 5:30 hrs). I found no register here although I  know  Stefan
also climbed this peak on the same day as D. The snow level  was  noticeably
rising, the precipitation was turning to rain  and  the  snow  was  becoming
slushy. Despite that, this made for a very enjoyable,  relatively  easy,  if
somewhat long, ski tour.

Total: 15.8 miles, 3300 ft and 8:45 hrs.

Thatsit Pk (5498 ft - 458P - Captain Point Quad) - April 17, 2007

While climbing D Mtn I made plans to return and give Thatsit  Pk  a  try  by
possibly going high on Captain Point and contouring above  Kelley  Cr  to  a
saddle on the N ridge. Then  I  noticed  another  possible  route  from  the
Beckler River Rd and Johnson Cr Rd 6520 that appeared  to  go  through  much
more appealing and ski friendly terrain on the N side of  Mt  Fernow,  if  I
could just get to it. My map showed an old spur road  going  up  Johnson  Cr
that might work. I was able to drive within .3 mile of this  spur  but  upon
reaching it I discovered that it was very old indeed and very overgrown  and
with the low snowcover at this elevation was not really  skiable.  Still,  I
perservered, half skiing, half walking, pestered by annoying  brush  covered
with fresh wet snow, until I gradually hit more consistent  snow  and  could
head straight uphill to a higher road

This upper road was blessedly skiable and I blissfully followed  it  a  flat
1.5 miles to its end in a clearcut. From here an easy  contour  led  to  the
lovely Mt Fernow Potholes and inviting open terrain below the cliffs  of  Mt
Fernow which made all  my  earlier  struggles  with  brush  well  worth  the
effort. I gleefully skied up easy (except for one short steep  step)  slopes
to the 5000 ft saddle on the S ridge of Thatsit.   More  good  skiing  along
the ridge and I was on the summit at 2:00  (3200  ft,  5:10  hrs).  My  only
regret was that the variable mostly snowy and foggy weather  did  not  allow
for any good views of the rocky N face of Mt Fernow.

The ski back was all pleasant until I had to descend off the upper  road  to
the brushy spur road below. I thought maybe I could just stay on  the  upper
road. Eventually it would connect with the main Johnsen Cr Rd,  but  looking
at my map it wandered level forever and would take me miles out of  my  way.
So I bit the bullet and dropped off the upper road at a point where I  could
just go down the fall-line. I was initially able to ski a few  hundred  feet
before giving it up as  a  lost  cause,  taking  off  my  skis  and  booting
downhill through the brush. It was actually better and less brushy  than  my
uphill route and I came out very close to the junction with the main road.

Total: 10.5 miles, 3450 ft and 9 hrs.

Fay Pullen
