            'tr' => '
Nason Ridge 1 (5576 ft - 616P) and Nason Ridge 2 (5550 ft - 470P) -
Labyrinth Mtn Quad - April 19, 2007

A strange mix of winter and spring weather of late keeps extending  the  ski
season for me. Continuing low snow levels for this time of  year  and  fresh
snow conspire to lure me out on skis for "one last trip" before  turning  to
climbing. Add longer daylight and mostly better than  expected  weather  and
my thoughts turn to routes I wouldn\'t dare try during  winter.  This  day  I
ran into a couple inches fresh snow going over Stevens Pass with a bit  less
at my start at Smith Brook Road.

I stayed on the road most of the way to 4600 ft  Nason  Saddle  (3.4  miles,
1500 ft, 2 hrs), only cutting the final switchback even  though  this  meant
putting on skins because of the hard crust under  the  fresh  dusting.  From
the saddle I went slightly  right  up  through  surprisingly  pleasant  open
woods to the summit of Nason1 (2500 ft, 3  hrs).  No  difficulties  to  this
point. But I also wanted to continue on to Nason2 and I knew this  could  be
a problem or even impossible. Looking at the map there were several  suspect
areas where close contours might mean  cliffs.  But  you  never  know  until
seeing it firsthand.  I have found perfectly reasonable  routes  where  maps
indicated cliffs. Conversely, I have had great difficulty where  nothing  at
all showed on a map. Maybe I would get lucky.

I did not get lucky. From the  summit  of  Nason1  I  could  see  the  ridge
leading east was all rocky  and  pinnacled  and  not  at  all  feasible.  In
particular Pt 5406 would be difficult to get around. I almost gave it up  as
a bad idea right there on the summit. But it was much too early in  the  day
to go home. And so I started down off the summit. I backtracked  west  to  a
point where I could ski NE off the ridge and did  okay  until  coming  to  a
steep step I couldn\'t handle on skis. Off they  came  as  I  booted  down  a
narrow gully to a lower basin.  Then thinking I was below the cliffs  of  Pt
5406, I traversed too high hoping to save elevation  and  got  cliffed  out.
Retreat and backtrack. Down another steep gully  on  foot  until  I  finally
reached a reasonable traverse line at 4600 ft. All this had taken 1.5  hours.
Any more difficulties and I would be running out of time.

Fortunately, there were no more problems. I  climbed  up  to  cross  a  spur
ridge at 5120 ft and then did a mostly level traverse to the 5160 ft  saddle
on the S ridge of Nason2. The skiing was surprising good  as  was  the  snow
which was several inches of mostly lovely powder preserved by being on  a  N
slope. The final bit to the summit of Nason2 (3500  ft,  5:45  hrs)  was  on
open slopes softening in the full sun with the  gorgeous  backdrop  of  Rock
Mtn filling the view.

I avoided all cliffs on the way back by staying low  and  going  farther  to
the right (N) but it was still very steep and I still had to climb  1000  ft
almost to the summit of Nason1 again. And I had to  put  on  skins  for  the
third time.  Good thing I had recently reglued them or the wet soggy  things
wouldn\'t have stuck to my skis. I had a reasonable ski  down  to  the  road.
Softening snow helped.  But it made for a sobering realization  skiing  down
the road. I am aware that the upper Smith Brook Rd is known as an  avalanche
area. I found this to be true first hand. Snow  on  the  very  steep  slopes
above the  road  softened  to  liquid  slush  in  the  direct  sunlight  had
avalanched over my uphill tracks. And it was  still  unstable.  I  left  the
road and retreated down through the trees but I still set off  small  sluffs
of my own in the extremely wet foot deep mush. I didn\'t much care for  that.
Once on the lower road  the  snow  was  beginning  to  freeze  again  and  I
rocketed the last few miles to the car.

Total: 13 miles, 4600 ft and 9:15 hrs.

Fay Pullen

