            'tr' => '
Aegeus Pk (6012 ft - 412P) and Labyrinth Mtn3 (5754 ft - 554P) - Labyrinth
Mtn Quad - April 26, 2007

I have a whole list of peaks yet to do along Highway 2, and  I  had  several
in mind this day, but the rain kept me driving until I found myself back  at
Smith Brook Road east of Stevens Pass where I  was  just  last  week  skiing
Nason Ridge 1&2. I was hoping for better conditions here  and  at  first  it
appeared I would have them. There was even a brief sun  break  or  two.  But
that didn\'t last long and the weather gradually deteriorated throughout  the
day.

It was fairly mild and with the cloud cover the snow was  soft  even  at  my
relatively early 8 am start. It would only get softer. To avoid a repeat  of
my scare of last week with the avalanche, I  completely  avoided  the  upper
road and went straight uphill at the first switchback through  steep  forest
directly to Nason Pass (2.4 miles, 1400 ft, 1:40 hrs). This saved some  time
and distance if not effort. Now  began  a  heartbreaking  1000-foot  descent
into the Rainy Cr valley. I gained some solace by  the  excellent  downhill,
the best of the day, through the clearcut to the road below.  But  this  was
followed by 2.4 miles of maddeningly flat road to the Minotaur Lake TH  (5.4
miles, 1650 ft, 3 hrs).

I left the road just past the TH on  the  other  side  of  the  lake  outlet
creek. The steep open woods and initial hard snow were very unappealing  for
skis so I carried them to about 4400 ft where the gradient lessened and  the
snow improved. The rest of the way  to  the  summit  of  Labyrinth3  was  no
problem on skis (6.3 miles, 3700 ft, 5 hrs). It was now snowing and  blowing
and views left something to be desired. I never got any good ones of  either
Labyrinth Mtn, Rock Mtn or Nason Ridge.

I skied back to the saddle with Aegeus and  easily  up  the  ridge  to  that
summit (7.9 miles, 4550 ft, 6:40 hrs). At this point I probably should  have
skied down my up route, but I really wanted to continue on to Minotaur  Lake
and so I did. The skiing was good to the lake and down  the  first  part  of
the trail. Then I got into a mess of close scrub  trees  and  steep  terrain
above the outlet creek gully with  very  slushy  snow  that  made  for  slow
going. It had also begun to rain. As soon  as  I  got  to  open  forest  and
harder snow I took off the skis and walked the rest of the way to the road.

The flat road looked pretty good to me now and with my earlier track set  in
the slush made for pretty pleasant gliding. A final climb  up  the  clearcut
to Nason Pass (12.9  miles,  5550  ft,  10:20  hrs)  and  then  it  was  all
downhill, though in a steady rain, the rest of the way out.

Total: 15.6 miles, 5600 ft and 11:25 hrs

Fay Pullen
