            'tr' => '
Cascade Mtn (5591 ft - 1031P) and Mile High Mtn (5280+ ft - 1120P) -
Snoqualmie Lk Quad - April 29-30

I have been hard pressed to find two days in a row lately without  at  least
some rain in the forecast, and I really didn\'t want to try  these  peaks  in
bad weather. I also felt I couldn\'t do them in one day and needed a camp  at
Dream Lake. So when Sunday afternoon and all day Monday  were  predicted  to
be sunny I figured I  had  my  two  days.  Turns  out  the  forecast  wasn\'t
entirely correct, but it was good enough.

Sunday started out cloudy with a little drizzle as I started up  the  Taylor
River Trail on my bike. Bikes are allowed as far as the Snoqualmie Lake  TH,
but the old road is rapidly deteriorating and I found the  bike  more  of  a
hindrance than a help, as least with an overnight pack. Although  there  are
sections that are very rideable, much of the way is also  rough  and  rocky,
there are numerous washouts and creek crossings  and  several  downed  trees
that have not yet been cleared this year. So when I came to a  rockslide  at
3.25 miles, I had enough, stashed the bike and continued on foot. From  that
point on things only got worse with more washouts, more downed trees  and  a
particularly large blowndown that even the burliest guy would  have  trouble
getting his bike over.

Just before the bridge over Big Cr, elev 1720 ft,  (4.5  miles,  700  ft,  2
hrs), I left the trail and headed uphill to Dream Lake. Dream Lake may be  a
"dream" as a lake but the route  to  it  is  no  "dream"  but  more  like  a
nightmare. It started out well enough in  reasonable  forest  but  that  all
ended at a large basin filled with horrid brush  at  2500  ft.  I  tried  to
avoid it by traversing uphill into what I thought was forest  but  it  ended
up being thick scrub cedar that was even worse than the brush. When  I  came
to an impassible ravine, I had to descend to the basin anyway  having  taken
an hour for a net gain of 1/10 mile.  I  crashed  brush  in  the  basin  for
another hour, found a way across the rushing creek,  much  smaller  at  this
point, and climbed a rib until the way improved when I  hit  solid  snowpack
above about 3100 ft.  I found a level campsite right by the outlet creek  of
Dream Lake at 4:00, elev 3450 ft (6 miles, 2800 ft, 6 hrs.).  It  had  taken
me 4 hrs to go a distance of about 1.5 miles from the trail.

I quickly set up camp and left for Mile High Mtn at 5:00.  I  knew  I  would
have to get lucky  to  make  the  summit  in  the  time  left  before  dark,
especially since I had no clear idea of where  to  go  as  I  could  see  no
obvious route on the map. The mountain has defenses  on  all  sides.  I  saw
several possible routes but they all had close contours at some  point  that
could indicate impassible cliffs. I would just have to go and see. My  first
choice was a gully system on the west side that led directly to the  summit,
but contours indicated a possible cliff band at 4600  ft.  I  climbed  above
Pothole Lake, and just kept traversing open slopes past my  supposed  gully,
seeing only cliffs above, until I ended up on the  SW  ridge,  which  turned
out to be impassible. I turned around at 7:20 and 5050 ft and  was  back  in
camp by 8:30 (1700 ft, 3:30 hrs). The snow had become  very  slushy  in  the
afternoon sun. The next morning it was frozen hard.

Dream Lake is surrounded by cliffs and the hardest  part  of  the  route  up
Cascade Mtn was finding a way up these cliffs to a large basin SW  of  Smith
Lake. I had a good view from Mile High and chose a snow  gully  that  seemed
like it would work. But first I had to get to it by going around  the  lake.
At the base of the gully was a large deposition of avalanche snow  that  had
spilled into the lake. I made the mistaken assumption that  this  was  solid
and used it to cross the edge of the lake to avoid  a  steep  slope.  I  was
shocked when a misstep between piles of snow  tuned  out  to  be  less  than
stable and my right foot went into water up to my knee.  I  will  state  the
obvious and say that Gore-Tex boots are not  waterproof  if  you  step  into
water over their top and for the rest of the trip my  right  foot  was  cold
and wet. But I will also say I was lucky that the rest of me  didn\'t  follow
my foot into the lake. My climb was almost over before it began.

I donned crampons and climbed the gully for several  hundred  feet  until  I
could exit right onto a rib. I continued up this to about 4200  ft  until  I
could cross another smaller gully then traverse a bit and  descend  slightly
into the large basin. I climbed up alongside avalanche debris to Smith  Lake
and from there to a gorgeous saddle W of  Cascade  Mtn.  Perfect  cramponing
snow led to the N ridge and the final very steep  exposed  corniced  bit  to
the summit (2360 ft, 3 hrs). The summit itself  was  a  steep  cornice  with
nowhere to relax. I was not keen on descending the  same  way.  A  few  feet
down the W face was broken rock with a few small trees so I made  two  short
rappels with my 60 ft "panic rope" to  get  down  the  worse  of  the  steep
stuff.

Once past the W saddle, wherever the sun hit the snow it was  softening  and
I soon removed my crampons and followed my tracks back  to  the  gully  down
which I had a nice glissade. I had some  trouble  getting  around  the  lake
again as no way was I going to chance another wet foot or worse.  I  was  in
camp at 12:45 and on my way again for a second attempt on Mile High at  1:15
determined to get to the top. At least I knew  which  way  NOT  to  go  this
time. I followed my tracks to a gully I had noticed  on  the  first  attempt
that seemed to go most of the way to the N ridge. I hadn\'t followed  it  the
first time as the map indicated it curved  to  the  right  and  became  very
steep the last 200 feet and I was afraid it ended in cliffs I couldn\'t  see.
Well it did go all the way, on snow, to the ridge but  it  did  also  become
very steep near the top. A gentle section  where  I  could  breath  easy,  a
short steep climb onto the NW ridge followed by a  final  tricky  bit  along
the narrow crest and I was on top at 3:30 (1925 ft, 2:15 hrs.).

I got back to camp at 5:00 and left at 5:45. I had to hustle  if  I  was  to
hit the trail before dark. I had come up the W side of Big  Cr.   I  decided
to go down the E side. I don\'t know which side is better as  they  are  both
horrid.  I think  the  brush  is  a  little  easier  on  the  E  side  (even
discounting my futile side trip into the scrub cedar on the W side)  but  it
is longer to get to the trees. Then once there  a  large  blowdown  area  of
huge trees is all but impassible and must be bypassed  by  going  almost  to
the creek where there is more brush. Yes there is  a  fisherman\'s  trail  of
sorts (isn\'t there a fisherman\'s trail to every fishable lake?) once in  the
trees on the E side but it wanders all  over,  has  many  downed  trees  and
obstacles and I didn\'t find it much better than the open  forest  on  the  W
side. Carl Dreisbach in his Middle Fork Guide describes the route  to  Dream
Lake as 2 hours up from the trail. But then he gets through the brush  basin
by following the stream bed (in July!). Can\'t be done this time of year.

I reached the trail at 7:45 and my bike at 8:30. From midafternoon on I  had
watched the weather gradually get worse and now  it  was  raining.  It  took
until 10:00 for me to reach the car. Yes, I  have  definitely  decided  that
riding a bike with an overnight pack is not my cup of tea,  especially  when
I am exhausted, especially at night, especially when it is raining.

An interesting incidence happened about 2 miles  from  the  TH  when  I  was
startled by a scream that seemed to come out of the darkness  from  nowhere,
"He\'s friendly".  I was so unnerved I screamed back. Then I  saw  the  light
of a fellow in the trail struggling to keep  control  of  a  huge  dog  that
weighed more than I did and looked eager to devour me in one  mouthful.  The
fellow was dressed in shorts and coming UP the trail. I  didn\'t  see  if  he
had an overnight pack as my attention was on the big beast  out  to  get  me
and I have no idea where he was going or what he was doing out  so  late  in
the rain.  And people think I\'m crazy.

Total: 20 miles and 9400 ft in 2  days  (includes  unsuccessful  attempt  on
Mile High)

Fay Pullen






