Sheep Rock (3500 ft - 580P) - Monitor Quad - May 4, 2007


This turned out to be another gem discovered  only  because  I  am  pursuing
Jeff\'s Master List of Peaks. As I have mentioned before, this list takes  me
to peaks I never would climb otherwise. I started from the Devils  Gulch  TH
(elev 1750 ft) on Mission Cr  out  of  Cashmere.  From  there  I  just  went
uphill, dodging small cliffs and slabs at first, to the SW ridge. I found  a
way trail that contoured around Pt 2702 and then  regained  the  ridge.  The
south side of Sheep Rock is all impressive sandstone  slabs  but  the  north
side is easily hiked.

Total: 2.7 miles, 2200 ft and 2:30 hrs.

Old Butte (1946 ft), Squaw Saddle (1982 ft) and  Castle  Rock  (1756  ft)  -
Wenatchee Quad - May 5, 2007

These are interesting crags that are very visible in the  western  foothills
just above Wenatchee. All three  are  fun  easy  scrambles  on  solid  rock,
though a bit exposed. For Old Butte and Squaw Saddle I found  public  access
just off Skyline Drive at the Jacobson Preserve TH, elev 1050 ft. From  here
a very nice trail wanders uphill. Jeff lists Old Butte as 1946 ft  but  this
turned out to be just a grassy knob. It seemed more logical to me  that  the
true "Old Butte" is the rocky crag slightly lower to the east. This is  also
where the name is placed on the map. Naturally, I climbed both  just  to  be
sure.  Squaw Saddle also has two crags. I climbed the higher one. The  lower
fin-like one looked to me to require a rope and protection. On the way  back
I climbed Pt 2228. From here I could see many inviting trails leading  west.
You could spend a full day wandering around these ridges.

Castle Rock is on private property and the hardest part of  that  climb  was
finding access that wasn\'t posted as no trespassing  or  didn\'t  go  through
someone\'s backyard. I think I spend more time looking for access than I  did
climbing it. I finally found a way by driving Castle Rock Road  to  its  end
in new housing construction (elev 1000 ft). Since these  houses  were  still
being built and were unoccupied and this was a Saturday (and there  were  no
signs), I had no qualms about parking  and  entering  there.  A  short  ways
uphill I ran into a trail that went all the way  up.  The  locals  obviously
hike Castle Rock all the time. The last bit avoided cliffs by going  to  the
right up steep loose scree. On top I climbed a short pinnacle  that  may  or
may not have been higher than the flat summit.

Totals: Old Butte and Squaw Saddle- 4.2 miles, 1050 ft and 2:30 hr
            Castle Rock - 1.2 miles, 770 ft and :45 hr
