Castle Pk (8306 ft - 3226P), Full Moon  Rising  Pk(7855  ft  -  775P),  Buck
Heaven Mtn (6887 ft - 487P), Outback Mtn (6972 ft  -  852P),  Freezeout  Mtn
(7744 ft - 504P) & Three Aunts Pk (7760+ ft - 880P) - Skagit Pk & Castle  Pk
Quads - May 9-13, 2007

When Paul and Stefan invited me to join them on this trip I  jumped  at  the
chance to climb Castle. However, their plan  was  an  ambitious  4-day  high
traverse carryover bagging many other peaks along the way.  Since  I  wasn\'t
sure I had the strength or stamina to pull that off (I don\'t  do  that  well
with a full pack), I proposed  being  completely  independent  in  gear  and
starting a day early. That way I could go at my own pace to the  first  high
camp and bail out  at  any  time  if  things  got  too  much  for  me.  They
graciously accommodated me.

Day 1:  I made the long 5+ hour drive into Canada and drove to  the  end  of
the Silver-Skagit Road, which was gated at the US Border. I  biked  the  1.5-
mile road to the Hozomeen Lk trail in  20  minutes,  stashed  the  bike  and
started up the trail on foot at 2:00. Normally this is a  very  good  trail,
but it had not yet been logged out  for  the  season  and  there  were  many
blowdowns to negotiate. I wasn\'t sure how far I would get, but when  I  came
to Nightmare camp at 6:20 (after an annoying  800  ft  descent  from  Willow
Lake), it was too inviting to pass up. I am not sure why this spot is  named
"Nightmare" as it is a delightful place  to  camp,  complete  with  benches,
firepit, flat tent sites, water  and  a  toilet,  although  the  latter  was
rendered marginally usable by a blowdown on top of it.

Day 1 Total: 9.8 miles, 1400 ft, and 4:40 hrs

Day 2: After a wonderful night\'s sleep I  was  on  my  way  at  6:30.  Thank
heavens the bridge over Lightening Cr is still  intact;  else  it  would  be
impossible to cross this roaring torrent. On the other side  of  the  bridge
the start of the Freezeout Cr trail is  completely  obliterated  by  several
hundred feet of washout and avalanche debris but once  across  this  section
the trail is easily located. I was under the impression that this  abandoned
trail was in horrible shape, brushy and hard to follow. Not  so.  The  tread
is in great shape, is easily followed and there is no brush. That is not  to
say, however, that it is a piece of cake. It has not  been  logged  out  for
many years, and there are countless blowdowns. I  would  say  there  is  one
every few hundred feet or so the whole way.  Very  exhausting  to  negotiate
with a full pack. There are also four large  creeks  to  cross  that  are  a
problem this time of year. The first was  small  enough  that  it  could  be
crossed on rocks. The other three required finding logs.

I ran into sections of snow after the first  creek  crossing  that  made  it
difficult to stay on the trail at times. By the third creek crossing it  was
solid snow and progress slowed  to  a  crawl  as  I  negotiated  frustrating
inconsistent snow that varied from ice to knee deep postholing. I  also  had
trouble finding a suitable log across Freezeout Cr, the last  crossing.  All
in all it took me much longer to get to our agreed upon campsite at 5400  ft
in Freezeout Cr basin than I had hoped. I was glad I had  allowed  an  extra
day. At the first opening out of the forest I  found  a  wonderful  spot  to
camp with running water and a clear view of Castle at 3:30.

Stefan and Paul had car camped at the gate and planned to start at  6:00  am
to get all the way to camp. On the way they hoped to climb Outback and  Buck
Heaven. I didn\'t expect them until late, maybe even after dark.  So  imagine
my surprise when they showed up at 4:30.  Either they were supermen  or  the
plan had changed.  Well, the plan had changed. They had passed on the  peaks
and were so wiped out by the trip in that a carryover was now out. We  would
be doing the climb with light packs from camp. Truth be  told,  that  suited
me just fine. I was even  relieved.  We  all  spent  the  rest  of  the  day
lounging in the sun and recuperating. It was a lovely spot to do just  that.
We went to bed before 8:00.

Day 2 Total: 9 miles, 3800 ft and 9 hours

Day 3: I am absolutely amazed at how fast Stefan can be ready to go  in  the
morning. Paul is no slouch in that  department  either,  but  Stefan  really
takes the prize.  I swear from the time he poked his nose out  of  his  tent
to the time he was heading uphill was 10 minutes. Good thing  I  got  up  45
minutes before him or I would never catch up. I started  at  5:45,  maybe  5
minutes behind. It froze hard during the clear night, which  made  for  good
cramponing. Castle Pk was first up as we climbed to the head of  the  valley
and up a steep couloir leading to the SW shoulder at 7900 ft,  then  up  the
shoulder to the summit at 8:15 (2950 ft, 2:30 hr). We found  a  pill  bottle
register placed the year before by Mike Collins and Don Beavon.

Next was Full Moon  Rising  Pk.  I  elected  to  downclimb  the  couloir  by
frontpointing facing in. Stefan and Paul came down the SW ridge to the  side
of the couloir.  After  descending  to  about  6000  ft,  we  began  a  long
exhausting traverse around the head  of  Freezeout  Cr  basin.  By  now  the
slopes were in the sun and the snow was beginning to soften,  in  places  to
kneedeep, or worse, postholing.  The guys had more problem with this than  I
did. I was often able to stay on the surface while  they  broke  through.  I
tried to do my share of trailbreaking but it didn\'t help  much.  They  would
just break through my steps. After what seemed an interminable traverse,  we
crossed the ridge into Boundary Cr, descended a bit, traversed  around  this
basin and climbed the SW slope to  the  summit  ridge.  Naturally  the  high
point was at the far end, which we reached at 1:25 (5000 ft, 7:40 hr).  Here
we found John Roper\'s film can register of 1983.

On to Buck Heaven Mtn. After a  fast  glissade  off  Full  Moon  Rising,  we
regained the ridge leading to Buck Heaven and had a pleasant walk along  the
ridge to that summit at 3:10 (5600 ft, 9:30). By now Stefan  was  in  summit
mode and a good 15 minutes ahead of Paul and me. He  had  blown  right  over
the summit and was already on his way to the last one of  the  day,  Outback
Mtn (although he did stop long enough for his customary "kiss the  summit").
 At this point I was beginning to feel a "wee" bit  tired.  I  sat  on  Buck
Heaven (truly a heavenly spot), looking across to Outback a  good  mile  and
800 ft gain away, wondering if I had it in me to continue. I  guess  I  did,
though barely, as I made that summit at 4:30 (6500 ft, 10:45 hrs).  On  this
summit I gloried in the perfect weather  and  fantastic  views  all  around.
Especially  striking  was  Hozomeen.   All  day  the  distinctive  and  very
impressive S Peak was in view and a constant reminder of  one  of  the  most
memorable climbs of my life. It was so satisfying to look at that  peak  and
say "been there, done that!"

We still had to get back to camp. The snow conditions were  now  mush.  Paul
and Stefan had lugged snowshoes  along  all  day  in  anticipation  of  such
conditions. In fact Stefan had used snowshoes from Buck Heaven on. Paul  now
used his. I had elected to take my  chances  and  had  left  mine  in  camp.
Although I sank in a bit, it wasn\'t too bad  and  it  worked  out  okay.  We
descended back to the saddle with Buck Heaven, where we had left our  packs,
and then traversed the basin SW of Buck Heaven until we could  climb  up  to
the S ridge. Once across, a series of glissades and traverses  got  us  back
to camp at 6:30. I for one was absolutely beat. Paul  and  Stefan  had  four
more peaks on their agenda for the next day, but I knew I would not be  able
to put in another day like today back-to-back.

Day 3 Total: 10 miles, 7150ft and 12:45 hours

Day 4:  I thought  about  my  options  overnight  and  decided  I  would  do
Freezeout Mtn with the guys and then reassess.  I got  up  an  hour  earlier
than Stefan at 4:45 so I would be ready to go at  6:00  and  he  still  left
before I did.  It is just impossible to get ahead of this  guy!  We  carried
full packs down to the creek draining the 6639 lake S of Freezeout,  stashed
gear and continued up the left side of the creek with daypacks  starting  at
8:00. The first part was in easy forest to an open slide alder  basin  where
another creek draining the lake below Joker joined in. A  short  section  of
brush and small trees led above a waterfall and into the snow  filled  gully
itself. The snow was hard enough to require crampons. Open slopes  then  led
to the SE ridge. The final bit along  the  ridge  was  easy  but  loose  and
unpleasant scree and talus. We summitted at 11:30 (3840 ft, 5:30 hrs).

Various body parts were now beginning to object to the abuse to  which  they
had been subjected the last 4 days, but I felt I still had  enough  left  in
me to make Three Aunts, especially since it was so  close  and  looked  easy
and would actually provide a better way down  than  from  Freezeout.  So  we
followed the ridge SE arriving on the first summit  at  12:30.  Three  Aunts
shows two summits each with an elevation of 7760+ ft. No one could tell  for
sure which was higher so we went on to the second  summit.  It  then  became
clear the first (W) summit was higher. We were back to this summit  at  1:10
(4600 ft, 7:10 hr). Previously mentioned body  parts  were  now  complaining
loudly and it was clear to me this was my last summit of  the  trip.  So  we
said our goodbyes and Stefan and Paul headed  for  Three  Uncles  and  Joker
while I headed down.

After a nice glissade followed by deep postholing I  reached  the  overnight
packs at 3:30 and continued out. My goal was  just  to  get  all  the  creek
crossings out of the way and camp on bare ground. Most of my  gear  was  wet
by now and I really didn\'t want to camp on snow again. But for  some  reason
I just kept going, despite my right hip and left  foot  (bunion)  giving  me
much grief, and made it all the way to Nightmare camp at 8:40  where  I  ate
dinner in the dark but spent a warm pleasant nightâ¦ until  sometime  in  the
wee small hours I heard the telltale pitter-patter of raindrops on  my  bivy
tent. This was totally unexpected. Rain had not been predicted at  all.  But
this was the North Cascades where anything can happen. I had spread  my  wet
gear out all over the log benches to semidry and had  to  scurry  around  in
the dark to get it all under cover. I listened  to  rain  the  rest  of  the
night.

Day 4 Total: 14 miles, 5050 ft and 14:50 hours.

Day 5: When I awoke at 6:00 it was still raining and everything was  wet.  I
hurriedly packed up, forgoing a proper breakfast, and took off at  6:40.  My
pack  felt  heavier  than  on  the  way  in.  But  now  I  knew  why  I  had
instinctively pushed so hard to make Nighmare the  day  before.   I  was  so
glad not to have to negotiate the creek crossings and  all  those  blowdowns
in the rain. The trip out was slow and painful but relatively short  and  at
least all body parts were still functioning, more  or  less.  I  reached  my
bike at 10:40 and the car at 11:00.

Day 5 Total: 9.8 miles, 880 ft and 4:20 hours.

I want to thank Stefan and Paul for allowing me to join  their  trip.  I  am
very satisfied with what I was able to do.  From my point of view  the  trip
was a success once I set foot on the summit of Castle. All other peaks  were
a bonus.  I have no regrets about turning around when  I  did.   Oh  sure  I
would have liked to have made those last two peaks, but  I  really  think  I
pushed myself as far as was prudent.

Stefan and Paul did climb (of course they did!) Three Uncles and  Joker  and
got down to their overnight gear around 6:00 where they spent the  night  on
the snow. They reached the car at 2:30 the next day.

Grand Total: 52.6 mile and 18,280 ft in 5 days

Fay Pullen










