Wild Dare Pk (5311 ft - 671P - Snoqualmie Pass Quad) - May 22, 2007


I cannot really recommend this peak, at least not by the route  I  took.  It
is probably only of interest to deranged peak  baggers  and  Home  Courters.
Most of the way is very unpleasant brush and  windfall  broken  up  by  many
mossy cliff bands and is slow going indeed. Of course it didn\'t help that  I
was in fog all day, had no views and, although it wasn\'t raining, it may  as
well have been since the brush was dripping wet from the  previous  day  and
night\'s deluge.

The good news is the Middle Fork Road has been recently  graded  and  is  in
good shape now, much better than when I was up it a couple of weeks  ago  to
climb Cascade and Mile High. You can  actually  drive  it  at  a  reasonable
speed. I parked at the Dingford Cr TH, took the trail  down  to  the  bridge
across the Middle Fork Snoqualmie River  and  almost  immediately  left  the
trail to head up the NE ridge. The  first  600  ft  were  in  pleasant  open
forest and I was encouraged that all would go well.  That didn\'t last  long.
At about 2000 ft elev I hit a mossy cliff band. However,  a  way  trail  led
around to the left and threaded its way up.  I was  still  encouraged.  Then
it all  fell  apart.  The  trail  disappeared,  brush  and  myriad  windfall
appeared, there were more cliff bands to negotiate and progress slowed.

Somewhere around 4000 ft consistent snow helped  considerably  and  progress
improved. Improvement was soon lost again trying to get around  Pt  5082.  A
seemingly too steep traverse (tried too high) tricked me to go up  and  over
5082 where I was soon cliffed  out  on  the  ridge  and  forced  to  descend
treacherous mixed terrain.  The  final  snowy  slopes  to  the  summit  were
blessedly easy in comparison but very slushy  with  a  covering  of  several
inches of new. I finally reached the wooded top at 2:45 (4400  ft,  6  hrs).
On the way down I took the traverse around 5082 low, at about 4550 ft.  This
worked much better. The rest of  the  way  I  had  trouble  staying  on  the
indistinct ridge and managed to find even worse brush and windfall  than  on
the way up.

Total: 4.5 miles, 4650 ft and 10:45 hrs.

Fay Pullen
