I already had a plan to climb Garfield East Pk and Treen  on  a  2-day  trip
approaching from Green Ridge Lake trail, when  I  had  a  conversation  with
Mitch at Don Beavon\'s K2 party. I mentioned that I was very  intimidated  by
Garfield Mtn and didn\'t know if I would ever get up the  thing.  He  replied
that it was fairly easy from the north if done early enough that the  summit
gully was completely snow filled. I asked  how  he  got  across  the  Taylor
River as the only north route I was aware of started from the  Taylor  River
trail and had to cross the river. He answered  that  it  could  be  accessed
from the Green Ridge Lake trail and a crossover gully  near  Lower  Garfield
Mtn Lk. Great! He did caution, however, that it  was  probably  already  too
late in the season for the gully to go. Still,  I  was  going  to  the  area
anyway. I would add another possible day  and  just  see  how  it  went.  It
turned out Mitch was right, of course, but I had to try.

Day 1: After my experience climbing Wild Dare and crashing  brush  just  two
days earlier on the other side of the  Middle  Fork  Snoqualmie  River,  the
Green Ridge Lake way trail was a sheer delight. It starts  just  before  the
Middle Fork road crosses Green Ridge Lake Cr at  1320  ft  elev  and  climbs
relentlessly, but with little brush or windfall,  and  is  easily  followed.
At 3500 ft the main trail leaves the ridge to traverse to  the  lake,  where
most people (i.e. fishermen) presumably go. The way along the ridge  becomes
less distinct, but since it follows the crest it is no problem  to  stay  on
it. Somewhere around 4500 ft I all of a sudden hit snow and it was snow  the
rest of the way. I found it easier to continue left on the ridge going  over
two bumps, despite added elevation gain, rather than trying  to  contour  to
my campsite just above the tarn at 4662 ft elev (2Â¼ m, 3750  ft,  3:50  hr).
The tarn was melted out just enough to provide liquid water.

I set up camp and left for Garfield Mtn East Pk at 2:00. I had a  good  view
from camp. It looked so close. Yeah, right.  This  is  one  of  Mark  Owen\'s
favorite climbs. But the normal route starts from East Pass after  a  direct
approach up a gully from the Middle Fork road. First I had to  get  to  East
Pass. I didn\'t anticipate it being so much trouble. I stayed  on  the  ridge
and found the only way past Pt 4962 was to go over the top. By  the  time  I
got to East Pass it was already 3:30. Then there was another 4920+  ft  bump
in the way I had to go over. I finally started up the main E ridge at  4:10.


An initial rock wall forced a bypass left up steep dirt  and  snow  until  I
could gain the ridge again. It  was  then  a  series  of  tiptoes  along  or
slightly below the undulating crest, sometimes on rock, sometimes  on  snow.
I do believe it would have been easier if it had been all snow or all  rock.
As it was the combination made for tricky going,  especially  at  transition
points from one to the other. At one point I was  forced  to  crawl  a  deep
moat and slither through a dripping snow tunnel to get  onto  bypass  ledges
on the right side. At another point I was tricked onto some  appealing  rock
straight up the crest only to have it  cliff  out.  I  had  to  retreat  and
bypass to the left. The final bit to the top was snow  free,  dry  rock  and
this section I really enjoyed. I reached the  summit  at  6:00,  much  later
than I had hoped for (1700 ft, 4 hrs).

Views of the whole Garfield massive  were  very  impressive.   I  could  see
Garfield Mtn, Courte Echelle, North  Peak,  Outrigger  Spire  plus  numerous
other unnamed pinnacles. This is one rugged area. There were no shortage  of
summit registers - three to be exact.  Unfortunately none were of  any  use.
Two, one in a PVC tube and the other in a small poly  bottle,  were  useless
sodden messes. The third, a film can, was dry but only contained  one  piece
of empty paper. Did the leavers forget to sign their own register?  And  now
there are four registers as I left one of my own.

By the time I returned to the saddle at the base of the main  ridge  it  was
7:45. The thought of retracing my steps over Pt  4920+,  East  Pass  and  Pt
4962 was not appealing. It would probably take close to 2 hours  and  I  was
running out of daylight. It looked to me as  if  I  could  descend  directly
from the saddle into the basin above Upper Garfield Mtn Lk,  traverse  below
all the cliffs and then climb up to camp, all on snow.  This I  did  and  it
worked well, although I did have to descend to 4200  ft  and  the  snow  was
very slushy.  I should have approached this  way  as  well.  It  would  have
saved me at least an hour. I got back to camp at 8:40,  tired  and  wet  but
very satisfied. (3 m, 2400 ft, 6:40 hrs)

Day1 Total: 5 Â¼ miles, 6150 ft and 10:30 hrs

Day 2: Treen Pk - Treen was a piece of cake.   No  problems  whatsoever  and
the climb went faster than expected, despite having to descend all  the  way
to Upper Garfield Mtn Lk at 4000 ft. How often does a climb go  faster  than
expected? Not that often. From Upper Garfield  Mtn  Lk  I  made  my  way  to
Charlie Brown Lk where a narrow avalanche gully provided a direct  route  to
a 5000 ft snow basin on the S slope. From here an open slope led  to  the  S
ridge and hence the summit at 9:00 (1775 ft, 2:20 hrs). Although  relatively
warm, the clear night had  frozen  the  surface  in  the  open  and  I  used
crampons on the upper slopes, although  I  probably  could  have  gotten  by
without them.

It was now on to give Garfield Mtn a try. To this end I descended  to  Lower
Garfield Mtn Lk at 3600 ft. I had no trouble  finding  the  crossover  gully
that would lead to the north route, but I didn\'t like the looks  of  it.  It
was an ugly narrow ribbon of snow snaking up a deep dark cleft, broken  near
the top. I wasted time waffling before deciding it probably  wasn\'t  as  bad
as it looked (it wasn\'t), but I did have some nasty wet  pull-ups  on  brush
belays getting past a small waterfall near the top. Once up, it was an  easy
snow traverse below the cliffs of Outrigger Spire until  I  could  climb  to
North Pass. I descended a couple hundred feet into the basin  on  the  other
side where I finally got my first view of the  Garfield  summit  gully.   My
heart sank.  I could see it broken about half way up.  Mitch  was  right.  I
was too late. Still I wasn\'t positive I couldn\'t  get  across.  I  had  come
this far. I had to make sure.  So I climbed up to the break.  I  could  find
no way across and believe me I looked. The break went  all  the  way  across
the gully, only filled a bit in the center  with  rotten  snow.   Underneath
was a deep moat that looked bottomless. To the right was vertical cliff.  To
the left were wet downsloping slabs capped by  precarious  snow.  Everything
was primed for collapse.  It was a scary spot and I  got  out  of  there  as
soon as possible. It was 2:50.

Of course I was disappointed but it was just not to  be,  and  I  really  do
value my life more than any summit. I was  probably  150  ft  from  the  col
between Garfield and Leaning Spire.  I am told  that  from  the  col  it  is
mostly an easy scramble to the top. So close  and  yet  so  far.  As  if  to
underscore my retreat, while climbing back to North Pass  I  saw  and  heard
several snow chunks let loose off the cliffs. I dragged the rest of the  way
back to camp where the 1100-foot climb through  slush  from  Lower  Garfield
Lake seemed to take forever. Although I made camp at 6:00, I was  too  tired
to go out that day. I spent the rest of the afternoon  lounging  and  drying
out in the sun.

Day 2 Total: 7 miles, 5300 ft and 11: 20 hrs

Day 3: All day yesterday I watched the sky gradually cloud up.  It  was  not
the perfect blue-sky day predicted, but it wasn\'t  bad  either.  Fortunately
the sun came out in the afternoon strong enough to dry things out  and  warm
me up. I figured  it  was  a  sign  of  approaching  weather  so  it  didn\'t
surprised me when there were a few sprinkles during the night.  But  it  was
nothing serious and the morning dawned cloudy but  dry.   I  was  just  very
happy I didn\'t have to descend the steep trail in the rain.  I  reached  the
car at 11:00. On the drive out along the Middle Fork road  I  had  to  dodge
all the  vehicles  (cars,  motorcycles  and  bicycles)  coming  in  for  the
Memorial Day weekend.

Day 3 Total: 2 Â¼ miles, 350 ft and 2:50 hrs.

I did make my original goal of climbing Garfield East Pk  and  Treen  and  I
was happy with that. I found the East Peak to be a  challenging  interesting
climb.  As for Garfield, there is always next year  (the  end  of  April  or
beginning of May should be about the right  timing  for  the  north  route),
unless, of course, I can twist some poor sap\'s  arm  to  accompany  me  this
year up the south side. That is one route I don\'t want to solo.

Grand Total: 14.5 miles and 11, 800 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen








