Sherman Pk (10160+ ft - 400P) and Colfax Pk (9440+ ft - 400P) - Mt Baker
Quad;

Park Butte (5440+ ft - 560P), Meadow Pt (5483 ft  -  243P),  Cathedral  Crag
(5200+ ft - 200P) and Survey Pt (5184 ft - 184P) - Baker Pass Quad - June 1-
3, 2007

Day 1: I do believe I have figured out how to keep up with the  Superguys  -
start a day early and come out a day late. Sure works for me.  That  was  my
plan when Paul Klenke invited me along on his  one-day  7500+  ft  climb  of
Sherman and Colfax. Then Mike Collins decided to join me on my  head  start.
So I would have company after all. Mike and I started from where Road 13  is
blocked by snow (elev 3200 ft) Â½ mile before Schriebers Meadow at  12:30  on
Friday. It was warm and sunny but a stiff wind kept us cool  as  we  trudged
up the boot and snowmobile tracks to a scenic campsite near the  last  trees
at 5500 ft on Railroad Grade (3.5 miles,  2300  ft,  3:30  hrs).  We  hauled
water from 500 ft below so we wouldn\'t have to melt snow.

Day 2: Superguys Paul and Dave Creeden  started  Saturday  morning  at  5:30
from the cars taking a direct line up the Scott Paul  trail  to  Crag  View.
Art Freeman and Silas Wild followed a half hour later  carrying  skis.  Mike
and I left from our camp at 6:10 traversing across the lower Easton  Glacier
to intersect the Squak Glacier above Crag View at about  6800  ft.  We  felt
comfortable climbing unroped as crevasses were few and snowmobiles had  been
over the terrain. We were about 500 ft above Paul and Dave  who  were  maybe
1000 ft above Art and Silas. We all kept in touch with 2-way  radios.   Mike
and I continued climbing up the Squak  to  just  below  the  rime  festooned
summit ridge of Sherman where we met up with Paul and Dave.  The four of  us
summitted together at 10:50 (4650 ft, 4:40 hrs).

Art  and  Silas  were  still  climbing  up  when  we  left  the  summit  and
unfortunately I never even got to  see  them.   I  had  never  climbed  with
either one before and was looking forward  to  that  changing  but  it  just
didn\'t happen. Dave (who had already climbed Colfax) returned the  same  way
planning to run into those two. He left the rope (which he had carried up  -
thanks Dave) for Paul, Mike and me to use. We needed  it  for  the  traverse
across the upper Easton and Deming Glaciers  to  Coleman  Saddle,  as  there
were many crevasses  on  this  traverse.  From  the  saddle  it  was  fairly
straightforward up the east ridge of  Colfax,  although  getting  around  Pt
9355 gave a moment of pause (it was passed on  the  left).  We  reached  the
summit at 1:40 (5300 ft, 7:30 hrs).

Views were gorgeous on this perfect weather day (except for  the  wind  that
howled through Coleman Saddle. Surprisingly, though, it  wasn\'t  that  windy
on the summit.) Lincoln was particularly  impressive.   In  fact  it  looked
downright frightening.  It may be next on the list  for  me  if  I  can  get
myself psyched up for it. We spent about 30 minutes on top before  taking  a
direct route from the saddle down the Deming Glacier to Railroad  Grade.  We
had only a few wimpy glissades in the soft wet slush of  afternoon  and  hit
camp at 4:20 (9 miles, 5500 ft, 9:10 hrs). Mike  packed  up  and  left  with
Paul.  Although I had the time  and  energy  to  go  out,  my  camp  was  so
pleasant I elected to stay another night and further savor  the  experience.
I had a view of Twin Sisters to one side and all of Baker  to  other  and  I
let another good climb digest as I lounged  in  the  sun  the  rest  of  the
afternoon. Besides, I had plans for a few more minor summits the  next  day.
The only fly in the ointment was the incessant sound of snowmobiles  buzzing
around. I don\'t know of a more annoying sound in the world. It is  up  there
on a par with a mosquito in your ear. Eventually they all went  to  wherever
it is those nasty machines go at  night  and  left  what  really  should  be
wilderness in peace and quiet.

Day 3: The next day I climbed four minor summits in the area. Although  only
Park Butte has prominence, the other three  named  features  are  all  quite
notable, interesting and fun  little  climbs.  I  first  traversed  over  to
Meadow Point from camp, which was farther than it looked (3 miles, 900 ft  &
2:20 hrs RT). It had a cute rocky bump for a top and a great view  into  the
chasm of the lower Deming Glacier. I then packed up and left camp  at  9:00.
I dropped my big pack at Baker Pass for the 200 ft climb up Cathedral  Crag.
At first I didn\'t think I was going to be able to get the final  rocky  crag
without a rope, but then I found a treed ledge on the  right  that  was  the
key.

I dropped my pack again at the saddle between Cathedral Crag and Park  Butte
at 10:30. I took some time finding a place to  hide  it.  I  had  thought  I
would get away from the snowmobiles in this area, that they would all be  on
the main slopes of Mt Baker. It was just my luck that  a  group  decided  to
use Park Butte and Survey Point  as  their  playground  right  while  I  was
there. You just cannot get away  from  them  here.  They  go  everywhere.  I
climbed directly to the lookout on Park Butte. From there I headed  over  to
Survey Point, dropping some 700 feet to  Pocket  Lake  before  regaining  it
again to the summit. Survey Point probably has the best overall view of  the
whole south side of Mt Baker.  There was even a glass jar register  on  top,
but I was unable to screw off the rusted cap. I  was  back  to  my  pack  at
1:20. I was beginning to feel the effects of the very warm  day.  The  final
trudge out in the sweltering sun and soft snow I felt as if  I  were  in  an
oven. By the time I reached  the  car,  where  it  was  82  degrees,  I  was
definitely cooked to overdone (8 miles, 2000 ft, 6:30 from camp).

Art and Silas did summit Sherman making that #100 for Silas on  the  400  ft
Clean Prominence Highest List. Congratulations Silas! They then had  a  nice
ski down.

Grand Total: 23.5 miles and 10,700 ft in three days

Fay Pullen
