Lincoln Pk Attempt (9080 ft)- June 17-18, 2007


Although this was an unsuccessful climb, it still warrants at least a  short
report with a few pictures. Let me begin by  stating  that  all  reports  of
Lincoln being a difficult and steep  alpine  climb  are  true.  It  is  most
certainly the hardest snow climb I have ever  attempted  and  challenged  my
limits.

Prospects were not great from the get-go as Paul K, Tom  S,  Mike  C  and  I
started from 3500 ft on Rd 38 on Sunday in a steady rain.  Three  hours  and
2600 ft of misery through dense brush on the  approach  didn\'t  do  much  to
improve our spirits. We found a pleasant enough bare ground campsite on  the
ridge at 5900 ft, but by then we were all soaking wet and only had  thoughts
of hunkering down in our tents. Rain continued to nightfall  and  visibility
was limited.

Monday dawned with no rain, lifting fog and improving weather. But we  could
see the upper mountain covered with fresh white. We roped up at  about  6500
ft. The bergschrund (7500 ft) was passed on the left side and from  here  on
the route was steep and stayed steep with very  few  spots  to  rest.  Also,
here the precipitation of the previous  day  had  fallen  as  freezing  rain
leaving a slick hard ice coating on the surface of the snow. This  made  for
slow progress as the leaders worked to kick steps through the ice layer  and
put in pickets for protection.   We  had  8  pickets,  which  seemed  barely
adequate at the time.  Each climber had two ice axes or  tools.  We  climbed
as two teams on 60 M ropes.

Tom took the lead up past the bergshrund for 500 ft and Paul took  over  for
the traverse to and climb up the middle (crux) gully. On both  the  traverse
and in the gully we were constantly exposed to  small  ice  pebbles  falling
from the cliffs above as the day warmed up. The gully  itself  had  a  well-
used runnel in the center down which small sluffs were  constantly  running.
Occasionally, a larger slide would whoosh past as we climbed on the side.  A
couple a times rocks came zipping down. Miraculously, no one  got  hit  with
anything significant.

The top of the middle gully (8500 ft)  ended  in  a  peculiar  very  exposed
knife-edged snow arÃªte. Another difficult traverse was required to  continue
to the next gully and summit ridge.  It was  now  1:00  and  with  our  slow
progress it was clear we did not have time to reach the top.  We  began  the
slow nerve racking process of going down. It took 7 rappels, 5 from  pickets
and 2 from rock horns, and 6.5 hrs to get off the steep stuff. Paul came  up
with the idea of going straight down from the middle gully  to  a  gully  to
skiers right of bergshrund slope. This saved some  time  by  not  having  to
reverse the traverse, but still was no piece of cake.  Most  of  the  rappel
points were award stances on steep terrain. The last rappel down the  narrow
gully ended in a vertical ice wall. Definitely one of the  more  interesting
rappels of my climbing career.

We all breathed a sight of relief when we were once  again  on  gentle  safe
terrain.  It was now 7:30. We were back to camp at 8:45 and  packed  up  and
ready to go by 9:15. We had just as miserable a trip down the brushy  ridge,
which had not dried due to valley fog. We almost  missed  the  road  in  the
dark, finally staggering to the car at midnight. As the  designated  driver,
I managed to stay alert enough to drive us home. I reached my home  just  as
the eastern sky was beginning to lighten for a new  day.  (4:15  am).  I  do
believe that is the latest I have ever returned from a climb. It was  a  24-
hour day from rising in the morning to  when  my  head  hit  a  pillow  once
again.

Soâ¦ no summit.  But surely a memorable alpine climb, with a great  group  of
guys, that stretched my limits. It is now unfinished business  that  I  will
hopefully finish some day. I seem to be having a lot of unfinished  business
this year

Fay Pullen
