            'tr' => '
Bacon Pk (7061 ft - 2501P), Mt Watson (6280+ ft - 1360P) & Mt Watson  SE  Pk
(5960+ ft - 440P) - Bacon Pk Quad - June 26-27, 2007

This was a spur of the moment trip after coming home late on Sunday  from  a
trip to Albuquerque to visit family. I was itching to get out after  a  week
off and wanted to take advantage of good weather  before  it  turned  again.
This meant I only had a day to get organized  and  pack  before  leaving  on
Tuesday, which resulted in a few errors, such as forgetting my  dinner.  But
it was totally worth the rush and effort.

Day 1: I was able to drive all the way to  the  Watson  Lakes  TH  (off  the
Baker Lake Road), but just barely and only because some big  rigs  had  made
tracks through a couple of snow patches. I started from the  TH,  elev  4300
ft, at 11:30 and ran into solid snow after about  a  mile  where  the  trail
enters meadows. From  a  little  below  the  saddle  above  Watson  Lakes  I
contoured and climbed to Upper Anderson Lake where I took a gully  to  cross
the NW ridge of Mt Watson  to  the  extensive  snowfield  on  the  N  slope,
climbing to 5600 ft below the saddle with the W Pk. Here I  dropped  my  big
pack at 2:50. From the saddle  a  combination  of  rather  unpleasant  steep
snow, dirt and heather led to the rocky summit at 3:40. I found no  register
so left one. I had a good view of Bacon.  My but it looked a long  ways  off
with many cliffs and obstacles on route.

I was back to my pack at 4:20. I now had to drop to 4800 ft  to  get  around
the extensive cliffs of Watson\'s NE ridge, then climb up past a frozen  tarn
to 5400 ft at the saddle just W of  Pt  5580.  Here  I  found  a  delightful
heather bench for a bivy at 5:40 (5 miles,  3200  ft,  6:10  hrs,  including
climb of Mt Watson). I was pleased not to have to camp on  snow.  There  was
even running water off a nearby cliff and a fantastic view  of  Mt  Shuksan.
What more could I ask for?

After setting up camp I left for the SE Pk of Watson at 6:25, climbing  snow
alongside an impressive pile of huge snow chunks  that  had  avalanched  off
slabs. Once on the SE ridge an enjoyable scramble  led  to  that  summit  at
7:00 and more views of Bacon. It didn\'t look any closer  or  easier  to  get
to. I was in camp again at 7:40 (1/2 mile, 500 ft, 1:15 hr RT)  with  plenty
of time for a leisurely dinner, especially since I had no dinner to eat.   I
couldn\'t believe I had forgotten it. I made do  with  soup  and  snacks  and
tea.

Day 2: Bacon Pk - The next morning I did have a breakfast  to  eat  and  was
ready to go at 6:20. It had been a warm night with some cloud cover  and  it
did not freeze. I descended easy soft snow to two lakes  at  4450  ft,  then
contoured E below cliffs descending another  couple  hundred  feet  until  I
could ascend again to the basin S of Bacon that  contained  a  frozen  tarn.
This was the hardest and most unpleasant part of the whole trip. I  followed
a nasty gully with snow at the bottom and wet rock approaching  class  4  in
places near the top to get through the cliffs,  traversing  right  onto  the
basin at about 5000 ft.

From the basin I followed a broad snow gully through cliffs above the  tarn.
A large avalanche had come down this gully very recently,  within  the  last
couple of days. Above, another steeper gully to the  right  put  me  on  the
main S ridge of Bacon. I elected to stay on the crest of the  ridge,  mainly
because it looked difficult to drop off an almost vertical cornice onto  the
easier E slopes. The first part of the ridge was fun rock scrambling.  Later
in the year, probably the whole ridge would be fun rock, but now part of  it
was still a knife-edge snow ridge that gave  me  pause.  I  was  reduced  to
straddling a portion of the most exposed  part  but  it  was  still  fun.  I
dropped to the E slopes as soon  as  possible  to  contour  around  a  false
summit then climbed a final knife-edge snow ridge to the small rocky top  at
10:50 (3 miles, 3000 ft, 4:30 hrs). I found  the  register  placed  by  Mike
Torok on 7/25/02. The notepad inside was soggy but still legible.   I  tried
to dry it out a bit. The last entry was by Paul  Klenke,  Dave  Creeden  and
Martin Shetter on 8/19/06. They climbed in 6.5  hours  from  the  TH!  Also
signing in were Don and Natala Goodman on 7/3/06. Don had last been  on  the
peak in 1984. Both the Goodmans and Mike (with Matt Burton and others)  were
on longer traverses and came in a different way than I did.

I had great views of a sea of peaks, most  of  which  I  couldn\'t  identify.
Bacon is really a lovely peak with extensive beautiful snowfields on  the  E
slopes. They were so inviting that in order to extend my stay, I climbed  Pt
6561 before leaving. (This point has an elevation 6580+ on  the  USGS  Bacon
Pk quad but is listed as 6561 on the  GT  Marblemount  map  and  in  Beckey.
Perhaps a later survey?). This put me on a lower traverse on E slopes  below
the S ridge on my return. I did have to climb the steep cornice back to  the
ridge but it was easier up than it would have been down.

From the S basin I tried a different way  down  than  my  nasty  gully  that
initially was easier but eventually I was funneled into another  gully  that
had some tricky moves and even  required  a  short  rappel  to  get  past  a
waterfall. If there is a better way past those lower cliffs  I  didn\'t  find
it. After the 1000 ft climb back up to camp at 4:20 (8 miles,  5500  ft,  10
hrs), I was hot, tired  and  dehydrated  and  needed  a  short  rest  before
packing up and heading out at 5:30.  I  tried  a  lower  traverse  below  Mt
Watson to Anderson Lake, but because of terrain features and steep slopes  I
still had to climb quite a bit and ended up crossing Watson\'s  NW  ridge  at
the same point. I reached the car at 8:30 (4.5 miles, 1100 ft,  3  hrs  from
camp).

Grand Total: 18 miles and 10,300 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen


