            'tr' => '

Hozomeen Mtn (8066 ft - 3966P - Hozomeen Mtn Quad) - June 30-July 2, 2007


Forget all those horror stories about Hozomeen.  It doesn\'t have  to  be.  I
found this peak to be downright enjoyable. It all comes down  to  route  and
conditions. Our route was pleasant and our conditions  almost  perfect.  And
we took our time, at least Beth and I did. Determined not  turn  this  climb
into the usual one day marathon book ended by a 5-hour  drive,  Beth  and  I
planned from the start a 3-day trip and a mostly  trail  approach  from  the
north through Canada. Mike  T  and  Matt,  constrained  by  work  schedules,
condensed their trip to two days.

Day 1: We drove to the Skyline II TH (elev 1650 ft)  off  the  Silver-Skagit
Road a few miles before the US border in BC in  two  separate  vehicles  and
started up the trail at 10:45. Ordinarily this  trail  would  be  very  easy
hiking. The tread is in good shape and the grade gentle.   But  it  had  not
yet been logged out this year and there were  a  surprising  number  of  new
blowdowns to contend with. Also  the  grade  was  so  gentle  with  so  many
switchbacks, that the trail took  forever  to  get  anywhere  and  gain  any
elevation. Still, it was for the most part pleasant hiking, the  woods  were
lovely and it certainly beat crashing brush on the  usual  route.  The  last
couple miles broke out into open meadows with both views of Hozomeen  and  a
profusion of wildflowers. At 4:15 we reached the marked  trail  junction  on
Hozomeen Ridge and found a wonderful campsite about  0.75  mile  farther  south
along the ridge (8.5 miles, 4700 ft, 6:30 hrs). A snowpatch nearby  provided
running water and we had a stunning view of our peak. There  was  more  snow
on it than I expected and it looked darn steep (I do not like  steep  snow),
but that actually turned out to work in our favor.

Day 2: We started at 5:50 by following the good way trail  south  along  the
ridge. Although there was considerable up and  down,  the  way  was  through
very pleasant meadows and woods. After about 2 miles  we  came  to  a  rocky
peak that we had to get around (I will refer to this peak  as  "Monument  74
Peak"). We tried to contour around it but ran into slabby cliffs.  Beth  and
Matt continued on the contour and  forced  a  way  around  but  declared  it
wasn\'t worth the effort.  Mike and I decided it was easier to  go  over  the
top despite an extra 500 ft of gain. We all met up  at  the  saddle  on  the
other side and then crossed the US border at Monument 74.

From the saddle we contoured beneath  cliffs  onto  the  snowfield  directly
below the north face of Hozomeen donning crampons and  ice  axe.  The  route
went up the lower snowfield traversing right at its top below a  cliff  band
on a snow finger to a middle snowfield. Matt led this section. Without  this
snowfinger it would be much more difficult to  gain  the  middle  snowfield.
Yes, we definitely hit conditions just  right.  From  the  middle  snowfield
another cliffband guarded an upper snowfield and we had a  choice  of  going
left to the NE ridge or right to the NW ridge. From below, the NE ridge  had
looked more friendly but once at  the  middle  snowfield  it  was  obviously
better to the right and the NW ridge. Another steep snow  traverse,  led  by
Mike, gained access to that ridge at a very exposed spot. The next  30  feet
were the most intimidating  of  the  whole  climb,  mostly  because  of  the
exposure which fell a few thousand feet down the  W  face  and  because  the
holds seemed less than secure to me. But once past that, the rock laid  back
and it was an easy scramble the rest of the way to the summit  (3200  ft,  5
hrs).

The register was placed 5/31/92  by  Don  Goodman.  Jim  Brisbine  and  Mike
Collins signed in on 6/23/05 and Paul Klenke and Dave  Creeden  on  7/22/06.
Both those climbs had more difficult conditions than we  did.  The  view  of
South Hozomeen was incredible. We could see much of the route  we  had  done
last year (Both Beth and Mike were on that climb  also).  I  still  find  it
hard to believe I climbed that monster.  Although  the  day  was  sunny  and
warm, there was a very cold wind blowing on top and I was  chilling  rapidly
so I started down before the others to escape  it.  I  also  wanted  a  head
start so I could take my time downclimbing the rock. The  last  30  feet  to
the snow was as nerve-wracking  as  I  expected,  and  the  two  steep  snow
traverses took care but for the most part the whole climb turned out  to  be
easier than I had anticipated and, dare I say it, even fun.

On the way back we all went over the top of Monument 74 Peak and  even  went
to the summit. This peak is in Canada and the maps and  contours  in  metric
units hard to read,  but  we  all  agreed  it  had  at  least  500  feet  of
prominence.  My first Canadian summit! We were  back  in  camp  at  3:00  (8
miles, 4400 ft, 9 hrs). Mike and Matt left an hour later, while Beth  and  I
relaxed, gloating over our  success  and  at  not  having  to  leave.  After
dinner, I decided to take a hike N along the ridge. I had in the back of  my
mind going all the way to Nepopekum Mtn, but it ended up being farther  than
it looked on the Canadian map. I just  couldn\'t  read  those  maps  properly
particularly because I couldn\'t figure out the scale. But it was a  gorgeous
snowfree ramble along the ridge through  flower  meadows.  I  turned  around
after a couple of miles and 750 ft gain.  I figured I was still an  hour  or
so from the peak at 7:45 and just didn\'t have enough time to get there.

Day 3: There was a heavy dew in the morning, getting everything wet. We  had
a leisurely breakfast trying to dry out our tents before  leaving  at  7:55.
At the first big blowdown we headed down through the woods thinking we  were
cutting only one switchback. Somehow we missed a whole series  of  them  and
ended up descending over a thousand feet before  hitting  the  trail  again.
But it all worked to our advantage as the going was easy and we  missed  the
worst of the blowdowns. I am sure we saved a lot  of  time  and  effort.  We
reached the car at 11:20 (8.5 miles, 350 ft, 3:25 hrs).

Grand Total: 29 miles and 10, 200 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen
