            'tr' => '
Mt Blum (7680 ft - 3280P - Mt Blum Quad) and Hagan Mtn (7080+ ft  -  600P  -
Damnation Pk Quad) - July 4-6, 2007

At the last minute I decided to  join  Jim  Brisbine  on  his  trip  when  I
learned he planned a 4-day  Blum-Hagan-Bacon-Watson  one-way  traverse.  But
since I had just done Bacon and Watson the previous week (we chuckled  about
great minds thinking alike), I would only do Blum and Hagan, taking  3  days
and coming out the same way we went in.  I wasn\'t sure I could be  ready  to
go again in one day after doing Hozomeen, but I couldn\'t resist having  good
company for two peaks I was planning on doing anyway and I found you can  do
most anything if you really want to. Besides, Beth also only had one day  to
get ready after Hozomeen.  If she could do it surely I could too.

Day 1: I stopped in  Sedro  Woolley  for  a  North  Cascades  National  Park
backcountry camping permit, then drove to the Baker River TH (elev  800  ft)
at the end of the Baker Lake Road where I met Jim, Eileen, Beth  and  Steve.
It took them longer than anticipated to run the car shuttle to the  Anderson
Lake TH (their exit point), so it was almost 2:00 by the time we started  up
the trail. We hiked Â½ mile upstream, crossed the Baker River  on  the  large
bridge, went downstream to just before the bridge over Blum Cr  and  plunged
into the forest casting around for the way trail to Blum  Lakes.  Eventually
we stumbled upon it. This way trail is difficult to follow in places,  rough
and very steep. We kept losing it and having to wander  around  to  find  it
again. Then somewhere around 3000 ft was a several hundred-foot  section  of
horrid recent blowdowns that was a nightmare to get through. Heat and  heavy
packs added to the slow progress. Be aware that this route  is  totally  dry
until the lakes and all water must be carried from the  bottom.  To  make  a
long unpleasant story short, it took 7 Â¼ -8.5 hrs to reach the lakes.  Steve
and I arrived first and were able to find a  level  spot  to  camp  on  snow
before it got dark. Another party of four was already camped  at  the  first
lake and occupied the only bare ground. We chatted briefly with  them.  They
were doing the same traverse and had done no better than we  had  coming  up
the ridge time wise, but had gotten a much earlier start. The  rest  of  our
party straggled in after dark guided by shouts  and  headlamps.  All  anyone
wanted was a quick dinner and to crash in sleeping bags. Not  an  auspicious
start. We wondered what other surprises were in store for us on  this  trip!
(3 miles, 4500 ft, 7:15 hrs)

Day 2: After the previous tough and late  day,  everyone  slept  in.  I  was
planning on returning to the lakes for  a  second  night,  so  took  only  a
daypack. The others had to break camp and carry full packs.  From  our  camp
we first had to cross Blum Cr, which was running high. I  found  a  rock  to
cross on.  The others jumped a narrow spot between snow  banks  after  first
throwing packs across. From the second higher lake, we climbed a snow  gully
to Upper Blum Lk and another gully to slightly below a saddle on  the  ridge
where full packs were left. The ridge itself was  rocky  and  pinnacled  and
not climbable, so we took a series of rocky ledges through  the  cliff  band
on the left to the easy snow slopes above and the summit (2850 ft,  4  hrs).
Here we met up with the other party, who had left about an hour  before  us.
Views were gorgeous and we spent a pleasant hour on top.

We dropped down to where the full packs had been left,  climbed  up  to  the
ridge saddle and followed the ridge toward Hagan. The big  obstacle  in  the
way was Pt 6800. To get  around  this  rocky  point,  we  dropped  a  couple
hundred feet into the basin above Berdeen Lk. We were helped  by  the  party
ahead of us and their tracks.  Even so I found this descent a bit tricky  in
places, even with just a daypack and the others did it with full  packs!  We
then climbed to the notch S of Pt 6800  and  easy  slopes  to  the  base  of
Hagan\'s main S Pk. The party of 4 was setting  up  camp  at  the  col  here.
Darn, no more tracks to follow. Worried about the growing lateness  and  the
need to get back to my camp at the lakes, I had pulled ahead of the rest  of
my group. After donning crampons, I started up the short steep  snow  finger
to the notch left of the summit rocks. After a tiptoe along the top  of  the
moat and a wiggle between snow and rock, I crossed the notch to the  S  side
where a series of fun class 3+ ledges led to the top at 6:45 (4050 ft,  8:30
hrs). I found two soggy barely legible film can registers. Beth reached  the
summit as I was leaving, just in time to take my picture. I passed  everyone
else on the way down and said my goodbyes.

From the base of the snow finger, it only took an  hour  on  a  surprisingly
easy and direct route back to camp. I did, however, have to  wade  icy  Blum
Cr to get across, as the water was considerably higher than in the  morning.
I reached my tent at 8:30 and had  enough  daylight  left  for  a  leisurely
dinner (7 miles, 4100 ft, 10:15 hrs).

Day 3: I slept in again, waiting for the sun to hit my tent at 8:00. It  had
been a cold clear night with heavy dew. I left at 10:00 and was not  looking
forward to the trip down the ridge. It was as bad as expected. I did  manage
to find the "trail" but I kept losing it and having to search around for  it
again. It was particularly bad at the blowdowns. I would  say  that  without
my GPS waypoints and "breadcrumb" trail that I had marked on the way  up,  I
never would have been able to find my way down. Whenever I  lost  the  trail
my GPS would tell me which way to look for it  again.  And  as  bad  as  the
trail was it was infinitely better than nothing, as  I  consistently  proved
when I got off route. So I took my time making sure I never got too far  off
the track, went slowly on the rough terrain and took many rests. I ended  up
taking almost as long to go down as it had  to  go  up,  but  I  did  do  it
safely, which was the most important thing. I reached the car  at  5:00  and
had a refreshing wash in the Baker River before leaving. (3 miles,  350  ft,
7 hrs).

Grand Total: 13 miles and 8950 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen

Footnote: It turns out the continuing traverse for the  rest  of  the  party
took an unexpected turn when Jim made a misstep, broke his ankle and had  to
be helicoptered off the saddle between Hagan and Bacon.  But  I  will  leave
it to Jim to tell that tale.

