            'tr' => '
Spire Mtn (6213 ft - 1853P) - Conglomerate Pt (5375 ft - 135P) &  Spire  Mtn
BM (6065 ft - 385P) - Baring Quad - July12-13, 2007

Armed with the knowledge provided by Jim Brisbine\'s July 15,  2002  TR  that
this is a long one-day climb with at least one roped  pitch,  I  decided  to
take two days. Even so I got back after dark on my second  day,  although  I
had a few surprises causing unexpected delays.  Still,  how  Jim,  and  most
other people, do it in one day is beyond me.

Day 1: The last time I had been up the Trout Cr Rd  was  February  27,  2001
when I skied to Iron Mtn. The road was in terrible  shape  then  but  I  had
managed to get up it 1.2 miles in my Jeep. It is in  much  worse  shape  now
and I didn\'t even try driving it,  instead  starting  from  the  North  Fork
Skykomish River Rd at 10:00, elev 860 ft. After .9 mile I took a  left  onto
a spur road that is  now  so  washed  out,  rocky  and  rutted  that  it  is
virtually impassible to any wheeled vehicle. With a full pack,  I  struggled
up what was more like a stream bed than a road on this very  hot  and  muggy
day. It didn\'t seem to me much better than the previous  day  that  had  set
records for high temperatures all over Western Washington.  By  the  time  I
reached the end of the spur at 4200 ft (4 miles, 3400 ft, 4:15  hrs)  I  and
everything I was wearing was dripping wet and I couldn\'t seem to drink  fast
enough to replace the sweat that  was  streaming  from  every  pore.  I  was
beginning to think this whole trip was a bad idea. I could have stayed  home
in a relatively cool home reading a good book and sipping an iced drink.  At
least there were no bugs, not yet anyway.

From the end of the road I  went  straight  up  through  a  semi-brushy  old
clearcut to the 4700 ft saddle SE of Iron Mtn. Here a  remarkably  good  way
trail, though somewhat brushy in spots,  followed  up  and  down  along  the
crest of the ridge all  the  way  to  Conglomerate  Pt.  There  was  a  nice
register on top but it had been  placed  in  2006  and  only  had  two  solo
entries.  One person had also climbed Iron and was on his way to  Spire.   I
wonder if he knew what was in store for him?

From Conglomerate Pt I continued following the way  trail  along  the  ridge
toward Spire as it dropped to a first saddle at 5200 ft.  On a  level  bench
below this saddle I found a pleasant spot to camp with  running  water  from
snowpatches (6 miles, 4800 ft, 7:15 hrs). It was only 5:30 so I  had  plenty
of time to rest and rehydrate. Things were looking up.

Day 2: Just as I was ready to go at 6:45 it began to sprinkle  out  of  what
appeared to be a mostly blue sky. Where on earth did this  come  from?  Well
thunderstorms had been predicted as a possibility for  overnight,  but  they
were supposed to be dry thunderstorms and clear out early. For the  rest  of
the morning one fast moving thundershower after another passed through  very
quickly, but  they  never  amounted  to  much,  never  required  putting  on
raingear and were always followed by warm sunshine.

From camp I regained the ridge, climbed to  a  second  5520  ft  saddle  and
traversed to the right around the cliffs of Spire Mtn 6065 ft  BM.  Once  on
the E side, snow slopes provided easy travel  to  just  below  the  5640  ft
saddle with Spire Mtn proper. The snow  was  hard  enough,  though,  that  I
donned crampons for better footing. Next a descent to 5000 ft  was  required
to skirt below cliffs before an upward traverse, again  all  on  easy  snow,
could resume toward the main peak. It was all such pleasant  terrain  and  I
was having such a good time that I was surprised when I looked behind me  to
notice a fast approaching black  wall  of  weather.   This  looked  serious,
unlike the previous brief  benign  squalls.  Sure  enough,  just  as  I  was
approaching the notch NW of the summit the storm hit. And it was  a  doozey.
Within minutes the temperature plummeted, the wind kicked up, the rain  fell
in big wet drops and fog  engulfed  everything  limiting  visibility  to  50
feet. And then came the thunder and lightening. I couldn\'t have  been  in  a
worse place. First order of business was to put on warmer clothes  and  rain
gear. Already I was freezing.  Wasn\'t I sweltering in sunshine just  minutes
ago? I am not sure I have ever witnessed a faster change of  weather  in  my
life.

So what to do? Things were looking bleak indeed and at that moment I  feared
my climb was over. But I am ever the optimist.  All  the  other  storms  had
passed by quickly.  Maybe this one would also. But I knew that  even  if  it
did, I still might not be able to make the climb, as the rock would  now  be
all wet. In the end I decided to hunker down in a protected spot  and  wait,
hoping against hope. And sure enough after an hour or so, the  storm  passed
and just as quickly the sun came out and all was right with the world  again
- except that now everything was wet. Well no way to tell  how  things  were
except to go take a look.

I climbed the last bit to the notch and plunged into the  scrub  trees  that
initially guarded the summit ridge. This section was easy  if  wet,  but  at
this point I was in summit mode and barely noticed. Above at  a  flat  place
on the ridge, I put on my harness and left my pack, taking  only  my  ropes,
pro and a fanny pack that included my cell phone (just  in  case).  A  short
ways on I came to the narrow, steep exposed section of the  ridge  mentioned
by Jim. Here I roped up.  In order to save weight I had  brought  an  80  ft
climbing rope and an 80 ft 5 mm rope, which together would allow for  an  80
ft rappel. I had thought 80 feet would get me past the step. It  didn\'t.   I
ended up doing two pitches. The first pitch was short  and  got  me  to  the
base of the crux move. The second pitch went the full length  of  my  80  ft
rope and got to easy scramble terrain again. I had a devil of a time  making
the crux move. I went up a crack slightly left of the  crest  and  a  multi-
slung rappel horn, and it took me a long time to figure out  the  moves  and
to get up the nerve to go for it.  Also, I had  inadvertently  neglected  to
bring my solo belay device, so had to make do with  the  low-tech  technique
of multiple overhand knots.  This works but  lengthens  any  fall  over  the
solo device if a slip occurs, and I was very aware of this.  All  this  took
time but at least by now the rock had dried and that was not an issue.

Above the step, I abandoned my rope and  scrambled  the  rest  of  the  way,
going over a small false summit, reaching the top at 12:30 (2.5 miles,  2300
ft, 5:45 hrs). I was very disappointed not to find any summit  register  and
practically dismantled the cairn looking for one.  There  had  been  one  in
2002 when Jim had climbed the peak. I wanted  to  read  about  Stefan\'s  and
Mike T\'s ascents and Mike C\'s and Don B\'s solo ascents for myself. Also  now
I didn\'t know if the fellow who signed in on Conglomerate Pt  actually  made
it to here. I only had an emergency matchbox register  with  me  but  I  did
leave that.

I didn\'t dally on top, knowing I had lost a lot of time, had a long  way  to
go to get out today and worried another storm could  hit  at  any  time  (it
never did). I got down with downclimbing and two 80 ft rappels. Despite  the
late hour, I took the time on the way back to climb to the top of Spire  Mtn
BM. Although lacking 400 ft clean prominence (but only by 15 ft), it  is  an
impressive mountain in its own right, very cliffy on  the  SW  slope  and  a
nice viewpoint. A short class  3  gully  with  curious  imbedded  old  wired
wooden stakes led to the summit at 4:00. I also found a large roll  of  wire
on top (from the surveyors?)  It was  worth  the  side  trip  just  for  the
spectacular shot of Spire Mtn above a sea of fog. You can  clearly  see  why
it is called Spire Mountain, with  the  Central  toothlike  Spire  the  most
impressive.

I reached camp at 5:00 (5 miles, 3600 ft, 10:15 hrs RT), had  a  short  rest
and left at 6:00, more or driven out by droves  of  (newly  hatched?)  bugs.
They plaqued me the rest of the day, my first really bad  bug  encounter  of
the season. I reached the road at 7:45 and the car at 10:00  (6  miles,  700
ft, 4 hrs from camp), needing my headlamp only for last  half  hour  or  so.
Despite taking 2 days, I really didn\'t get down much earlier than  Jim,  who
had done his one day climb from 7 am to 11 pm.

Grand Total: 17 miles and 9100 ft in two days

Fay Pullen






