            'title' => 'Big Devil Pk (7055 ft - 1655P), Little Devil Pk (6984ft - 1024P), The Trapezoid (6943 ft - 823 ft) & Baksit Pk (6960+ ft) - Big Devil Quad - July 25-27, 2007',
            'tr' => '
Big Devil Pk (7055 ft - 1655P),  Little  Devil  Pk  (6984ft  -  1024P),  The
Trapezoid (6943 ft - 823 ft) & Baksit Pk (6960+ ft) - Big Devil Quad -  July
25-27, 2007

Day 1: After getting the proper permit for camping  in  the  North  Cascades
National Park at Marblemount, I started up the Lookout  Mtn  trail  off  the
Cascade River Road (elev 1250 ft) at  noon.  What  a  nice  trail  this  is,
climbing steadily in lovely mossy forest. A  cool  breeze  made  the  upward
trudge as pleasant as possible and I was even  enjoying  myself,  despite  a
pack heavy with climbing gear, until I was stung on the leg by a  bee.  That
brought me back to earth while the pain  slowly  subsided.  Then  the  black
flies began to make an appearance as the day  heated  up  and  my  enjoyment
lessened in direct proportion to their increase.

The trail was  in  great  shape  except  for  one  blowdown  shortly  before
crossing a creek near the Monogram Lake Trail junction. As I was  making  my
way around the top of it, I heard a pitiful voice calling from above  asking
if I were on the trail. "Not at the moment", I replied, "but it is  not  far
away." Then out of the brush appeared a somewhat  worse-for-the-wear  fellow
exclaiming that he had lost the trail and spent the last 3  hours  wandering
around. He had tried  going  straight  uphill  to  intersect  the  trail  to
Monogram Lake, had gotten into very steep terrain, given up  and  come  back
down. Now I admit I have experienced blowdowns where it is possible or  even
easy to lose the trail, but this was not one of them. On a  scale  of  1  to
10, this one was maybe a 2. You could see the trail on the  other  side  for
goodness sake! How on earth could he lose it? And why on earth,  instead  of
searching harder for it, would he head uphill where the trail  was  1400  ft
above him by the route he was taking? Yes, you meet some strange  people  in
the wilderness.

Safely back on the trail and, I suppose, not wanting to lose the comfort  of
another human being immediately, I couldn\'t shake this fellow. He  stuck  to
me like glue as we both took the trail to Monogram  Lake,  talking  non-stop
the whole time. I learned more than I ever wanted to know about him  -  like
how he had just broken up with  his  girlfriend  (maybe  he  talked  her  to
death?). He did have a sense of humor, however, noting how he had started  3
hours earlier than I (at 9am) and we were now both in the same place. But  I
was grateful I wasn\'t going to the Lake (his destination) and could take  my
leave at 5000 ft where the trail crossed the creek again in  an  open  basin
(4 miles, 3600 ft, 4 hrs).

I climbed up steep meadows to cross a spur ridge at 6100 ft  just  S  of  Pt
6438. Note that this point is shown as 6708 ft on the Big  Devil  Quad  with
400 feet of very close contours.  I  had  puzzled  over  this  anomaly  when
studying the map. If these contours  were  correct  this  would  be  a  very
noticeable spire and most likely have a name and climbing  history.  It  had
neither. Also Beckey and the GT Marblemount map lists the elevation as  6438
ft. This is the correct elevation and there is  no  spire.   I  mention  all
this just to show how wrong a map can be. Why the  USGS  Quad  lists  it  as
having been surveyed at 6708 ft I have no idea.  Maybe  the  surveyors  were
drunk or the map-making equipment ran amok making  contour  lines.  I  found
other anomalies on this quad but they were less obvious.

From the ridge I began  a  delightful  traverse  on  heather  benches  above
Monogram Lake. Along the way I crossed countless creeks and found dozens  of
suitable places to camp all with fantastic views of  the  Snowking  Mountain
and Cascade Pass areas.  I was tempted to stop here to  camp  but  I  really
wanted to be closer to Little Devil so I kept going. As I rounded the  ridge
coming off of Pt 6844 I feared I made an error as I  left  the  sunny  green
meadows and entered a world of bleak and shadowed snow and rock. However,  I
ended up finding a wonderful campsite on smooth, level  bedrock  slabs  near
an ice lake just below the permanent snowfield S of Little Devil, elev  6000
ft (6 miles, 5200 ft, 7 hrs).

Day 2: I was up and going by 7:15. I climbed gentle snow to the saddle W  of
Little Devil and followed the ridge easily to  the  summit  (1000  ft,  1:10
hr). I found no register although  I  know  that  Janet  had  been  up  here
earlier this year (in one day). From the top  I  had  a  great  view  of  my
destination and all surrounding peaks.

Next up was Baksit (Middle Devil). It was only  about  Â½  mile  away  but  I
could not follow the ridge from Little Devil.   I  could  see  a  relatively
easy route that entailed dropping a few hundred feet  to  get  past  cliffs.
This I did with little difficulty and I was on the summit at 10:00 (1550,  3
hrs). I had an even better view of my peaks  and  my  route  to  them  along
jagged Teebone Ridge. My oh my but they looked a long  ways  off.  I  wasn\'t
sure I could even get to Big Devil much less The Trapezoid. I had  hoped  to
also climb Fallen Angel, which looked very impressive and appealing. I  even
had rock climbing gear with me, but I was now sure I wouldn\'t have time  for
it.  It would have to wait for another trip.

I had to backtrack a short ways along the S ridge of Baksit before  I  could
drop E onto moderate snow and traverse to the 6700  ft  saddle  with  Fallen
Angel. From this saddle I dropped again down steep snow, using crampons,  to
about 6000 ft and began a long traverse on the S slopes  of  Teebone  Ridge.
The going was easy enough - even enjoyable - but very  slow,  up  and  down,
across snow, scree, talus and heather. The main obstacle  was  crossing  the
low point in the ridge just NW of Pt 6154. This turned  out  to  be  a  very
deep rocky notch at 5900 ft. I ended up too high and cliffbound, and had  to
backtrack a bit to work my way steeply down.  Once  across  the  notch,  the
terrain opened up again but the last part still was  farther  away  than  it
looked and took longer than expected. I mostly followed  the  crest  of  the
ridge on easy rock, avoiding steep heather gullies, but  several  times  got
stopped by short walls I  had  to  work  my  way  across.  I  surprised  two
mountain goats in this area.  I  finally  pulled  onto  the  broad  heathery
summit of Big Devil at 2:25 (3000 ft, 7 hrs).

I found a film can register with only two entries - Don Goodman  on  8/28/99
and Stefan, Mike C and Dave Creeden on 3/13/05. Both those parties had  come
up from the Skagit River to the N. Views were  to  die  for,  but  I  mostly
couldn\'t take my eyes off The Trapezoid (Last Devil).  I really wanted  this
peak but it was getting late, it was over a mile away, would add 2000 ft  of
elevation gain and the last few hundred  feet  was  Beckey  class  3,  which
could mean class 4. I waffled for  30  minutes  while  I  rested,  before  I
decided to go for it even though I knew this meant I would get back to  camp
after dark. Fortunately the approach along the ridge was easy and fast  snow
and heather and I reached the notch on the W ridge in slightly more than  an
hour. I left my pack, taking only my rope and scrambled up class 3+ rock  to
the summit (4000 ft, 9:10 hrs). I left the  last  of  the  registers  I  had
brought with me. I did not use the rope but I saw if you got off  route  you
could easily be in class 4 or worse territory.

I was elated to make the entire traverse of Teebone Ridge, but  now  reality
was setting in. What had I gotten myself into? It was now 4:30 and I  had  a
long, long way to go, much of it uphill. Best not to think too  much.   Just
do it. First I had to climb almost up to the  summit  of  Big  Devil  again.
There was no short cut. Then the steep descent down to  the  notch  where  I
did better job finding a way across. Then the long  traverse  below  Teebone
Ridge and the steep snow climb (crampons again) to the Fallen  Angel  saddle
and Baksit Ridge.  By now I was losing light but an almost full moon  helped
immensely especially on the reflective snow.  It  was  actually  a  gorgeous
evening and if I weren\'t so tired I would have enjoyed  it  greatly.  I  set
down my black gloves taking off my crampons  to  cross  a  short  rock  band
descending off Baksit, and forgot them in the dark.  Darn!  I  really  liked
those gloves. Another climb up snow to  Little  Devil  Saddle  and  a  final
stagger down to camp where I ended  up  needing  my  headlamp  the  last  15
minutes as I entered a fogbank and lost the moonlight. I reached my tent  at
10:40 (12 miles, 6200 ft, 15:30 hrs) too tired to do  more  than  make  soup
and tea before falling asleep.

Day 3: I slept in and left camp at 9:45. All thoughts of  going  up  Lookout
Mtn on the way out were forgotten, but I did drop directly down to  Monogram
Lake and took the trail out from there. That really saved no time  and  even
added extra elevation gain (the trail drops 500 ft to the lake), but  it  is
a lovely lake and I was able to take a quick dip (quick being the  operative
word as the water was icy cold).  I reached the car at 3:45  (6  miles,  750
ft, 6 hrs) just as 3 fellows were starting up the trail.  I  wondered  where
they planned to camp starting so late and if they  knew  it  would  take  at
least 5 hours to get to the  lake.  I  left  them  to  their  fate  as  they
solicited no information and so I offered none.

Grand Total: 24 miles and 12,100 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen

