            'title' => 'Luna Peak (8311 ft - 3071P - Mt Challenger Quad) - July 31-August 4, 2007',
            'tr' => '

Luna Peak (8311 ft - 3071P - Mt Challenger Quad) - July 31-August 4, 2007


I had never been to the Pickets before, never even been  close,  never  even
had a really good look from afar, so this trip was completely new  territory
for me. I had heard numerous horror stories  about  how  all  approaches  to
this area are horrendous and always  take  longer  than  anticipated,  so  I
allowed a generous 5 days for the climb. Some people do  it  in  3  days.  I
don\'t see how they do it. I was delighted when  my  good  friend  Linda  was
available to join me. We hadn\'t done a long trip together for a while and  I
always enjoy climbing with her. We had perfect weather the  whole  time  and
it ended up being a wonderful adventure.

Day 1: We arrived at the Ross Lake TH  (elev  2100  ft)  above  the  dam  at
10:20, hiked 1 mile down to the water taxi dock (elev 1600  ft)  and  called
on the resort phone there to confirm our arrival for our  prearranged  12:00
pick-up to be ferried across the lake to the Big Beaver  TH.   The  cost  is
now $35 each way for up to 6 people but saves 6 miles  of  hiking.  We  were
picked up a bit early and began hiking the Big Beaver trail at  11:40.  This
trail is in very good shape climbing very slowly with a few  ups  and  downs
and is mostly in cool mossy forest with some very impressive  giant  cedars.
I hiked in light trail shoes carrying boots. This saved  my  feet  wear  and
tear but added to an already heavy  pack.  We  had  a  few  encounters  with
annoying bugs, both mosquitoes and black flies. We arrived at pleasant  Luna
Camp, elev 2500 ft, at 5:00 (10 miles, 1300 ft, 5:20  hrs)  with  plenty  of
time to wash up and relax before turning in early. We had the  camp  all  to
ourselves, met only two people on the trail on the way in and  in  fact  saw
no one for the next 3 days.

Day 2: We stashed some food at Luna Camp for the return  (why  carry  it  up
just to carry it back down?) before starting the next morning  at  8:00.  We
hiked about Â½ mile up trail to  just  past  a  small  creek  before  heading
straight downhill to cross Big Beaver Cr on a huge logjam.  Many  thanks  go
to Don Goodman for reporting the location of this  logjam.  Without  knowing
where it was we could have wandered around for hours searching for a way  to
cross. The crossing was easy but getting to it was not. The creek bottom  is
an awful jungle of swamp and brush.

Once across we headed diagonally uphill  through  moderate  brush  until  we
could hear Access Cr, then followed the left (S) side of  that  creek  until
coming to a large brush patch that forced us  to  cross  to  the  right  (N)
side. We crossed again at about 3700 ft, really too soon,  and  got  into  a
mess of brush.  The correct crossing  is  higher,  about  3900  ft,  and  is
easier to find on the way out (which we did). The rest of the way, once  out
of the brush, is on large talus.  Be aware that the route up  Access  Cr  is
very slow travel and takes much longer than one  might  think.  It  look  us
7:30 hrs, although we did take our time, took several long rests and made  a
few route-finding errors. We found a marvelous campsite in  the  open  basin
at 4300 ft (4 miles, 2100 ft, 7:30 hrs) and opted to stay there even  though
we had the time to go farther. We had a great view of the rocky  E  face  of
Luna Pk above and of Mt Prophet across the valley. Bugs were tolerable.

Day 3:  We were on our way at 7:00 with light daypacks, climbing up an  easy
gully on the left (S) side of the  basin.  At  the  top  of  this  gully  we
climbed another gully to the right to a 6200 ft notch. The upper part  still
had snow in it that was quite steep near the top where we did use  crampons.
At the notch (1900 ft, 2 hrs)  we  had  our  first  fantastic  view  of  the
southern Pickets. They certainly  are  aptly  named,  looking  just  like  a
picket fence with rugged spire after spire.

From the notch we  went  uphill  on  steep  heather  until  we  could  begin
traversing west across the basin on the south side of Luna, but we  got  too
high and had some difficulty crossing a notch and gully at  about  6600  ft.
Fortunately we did find a way across without having to backtrack, but it  is
best to drop at the start below  a  cliff  band  to  about  6200  ft  before
beginning the traverse. Once past this cliffy area the rest of the  gorgeous
traverse, always in sight of the southern Pickets, is  fairly  easy  heather
and snow to the 7200 ft notch on Luna\'s SW ridge (3100 ft, 4:45  hrs).  Here
we had our first view of the northern Pickets,  including  Mt  Fury  and  Mt
Challenger. Spectacular!

After stashing crampons and ice  axes,  we  climbed  up  easy,  if  somewhat
unpleasant, talus, scree and loose rock on the SW ridge and S  face  to  the
false  summit  at  1:20  (4100  ft,  6  hrs).   The  view  from   here   was
indescribable on this perfect weather day. To the right were  the  whole  of
the northern Pickets and to the left the whole of southern Pickets.  It  was
almost more than the mind could take in at one time  and  we  reveled  in  a
sight few are privileged to see.

But we were not yet on the true summit. This loomed a  very  short  distance
to the N along a narrow exposed very intimidating looking  ridge.  We  roped
up on our short 100 ft rope and I set out along  the  ridge.  At  first  all
went well and seemed it wouldn\'t be as bad as it had looked.  Then  about  a
rope length out I tried to pass a coffee table sized block  perched  on  the
crest and the whole thing tottered. It and the rock it was resting  on  were
both loose and threatened to tumble over the  rotten  edge  taking  me  with
them. I absolutely freaked thinking the whole  ridge  would  be  like  that,
backed off and looked for an alternate route. I know there is one on  the  W
side, but it is accessed from lower down and we really couldn\'t  get  to  it
now from where we were. However, on the E side were a series of wide  ledges
that looked as if they would go. So we dropped about 50-100 ft  down  the  E
side and worked our way along these ledges back up to the ridge.  This  took
5-6 belayed and protected pitches with our short  rope  and  a  considerable
amount of time but we did make it to the true summit (4200 ft, 8:30 hr)  and
it was actually rather fun climbing.

From the summit, the ridge back to the false summit looked so close that  we
returned that way. It was actually much easier than it  had  looked  before,
with part of it being on a nice ledge just below the crest. When I  came  to
the freaky teetering  rock  again,  I  was  able  to  trundle  some  of  the
underlying loose rocks and stabilize things a bit,  at  least  enough  so  I
could get by it. That  was  actually  the  worst  part  of  the  ridge,  and
although it did make one question the stability of the rest of the ridge,  I
found the rest of the climbing rather enjoyable.  It  certainly  was  faster
than the lower ledge route and we were back to the false summit in an  hour,
at 5:00. Now we would have to hustle to get back to camp before dark.

We did make it before dark, but just barely.  We  corrected  a  few  of  our
route-finding errors of the way up, which speeded things up,  but  then  ran
into rock-hard snow (and terrible bugs) descending from the  6200  ft  notch
and had to front-point down, which slowed things down again. We pulled  into
camp at 9:00 (6 miles, 4400 ft, 14 hrs) with just enough light to  navigate.
Although tired, we washed up and had a good  dinner  enjoying  the  now  bug
free, mild and moonlit night.

Day 4: We slept in and awoke to clouds and high mountain fog. The summit  of
Luna was no longer visible from camp. We were so happy to have had  a  clear
day for our summit. To have missed all those spectacular  views  would  have
verged on unbearable. Since our goal for the day was to  just  get  back  to
Luna Camp, we were in no particular hurry  and  started  down  at  9:45.  We
found the proper upper crossing of Access  Cr  (it  was  marked  by  several
cairns) and avoided some of the worst brush we had wallowed through  on  the
way up. We stayed on the N side of the creek  until  about  3200  ft  before
crossing to the S side, stumbling upon a convenient log at  just  the  right
spot. Some brush was unavoidable. We then traversed high  above  Big  Beaver
Creek before coming out  right  at  the  logjam  (I  had  marked  the  exact
location on my GPS). Another 30  minutes  of  jungle  bashing  was  required
before we hit the trail. 15 minutes after that  we  were  in  Luna  Camp  (4
miles, 150 ft, 5:30 hrs) where our food cache was still safely  hanging.  It
was only a little after 3:00 but our  permit  was  for  Luna  Camp.   Had  I
thought more about it, I probably should have made the  last  night  for  39
mile Camp so we had less to go the next day. But  we  were  not  unhappy  to
stop early and we enjoyed a leisurely afternoon.  Once  again  we  had  Luna
Camp all to ourselves (there are only two campsites there).

Day 5: We were up and going by 7:30. We  had  10  miles  to  go  before  our
scheduled pickup at 1:20 and we didn\'t want to miss the  boat.  Shortly  out
of camp we met a ranger. She was friendly enough but  still  looked  at  our
permit. She said another party was supposed to have been camped at Luna  the
previous night. It was probably the party we were to  share  the  boat  ride
with. We hoped they were okay.

Somewhere past 39 Mile Camp we ran into a scruffy  looking  guy  dressed  in
camouflage and toting a high-powered scoped rifle. I  was  totally  startled
by such an encounter and at first couldn\'t figure  out  what  he  was  doing
there. Was he a psycho bent on doing harm? Turns out it  was  the  start  of
bear hunting season and since we were then in the Ross Lake Recreation  Area
and not the National Park anymore, it  was  all  legal,  but  it  was  still
disconcerting if not downright disturbing. A little farther on we came  upon
a fresh cigarette butt in the middle of the trail that had  burned  down  to
the filter, and obviously had not been put out before being  flicked  aside.
Then we smelled smoke. Smoke? Where was that from? The  smell  got  stronger
and stronger until rounding a corner of the trail, maybe  a  mile  from  the
hunter, we came upon an open flame burning some 8 inches high in  a  rotting
stump by the side of the trail. Now  Linda  has  had  firefighting  training
with the DNR and knew what to do and we spent the next  20  minutes  putting
the fire out. It had burned quite a ways into the  stump  and  could  easily
have spread farther, especially if a wind  had  kicked  up.  We  figure  the
cigarette smoker had sat on the stump smoking  and  just  tossed  the  still
smoldering butt aside. We saw no one else  other  than  the  hunter  in  the
vicinity.  You connect the dots.

Despite our delay putting out the fire, we still made the  dock  (10  miles,
600 ft, 5 hrs) in plenty of time to catch the  boat,  which  came  right  on
schedule at 1:20. We even had time  for  a  refreshing  dip  in  Ross  Lake.
Shortly after we arrived, a very nice couple from Salt Lake City showed  up.
They were the ones that were supposed to be at Luna Camp the  night  before.
They had only made it to Beaver Pass. They had  been  on  a  6-day  trip  up
Little Beaver to Whatcom Pass, Perfect Pass,  Challenger  Arm  and  out  Big
Beaver. It all took longer than they had expected.  Sharing  the  boat  ride
made the cost much more reasonable. We  all  could  have  done  without  the
final mile and 500 ft climb up to the parking lot and car at the  other  end
of the boat ride.

Grand total: 36 miles and 9050 ft in 5 days

Fay Pullen
