            'title' => 'Cascade Mtn, N Pk (5553 ft - 873P - Grotto Quad) - August 15, 2007',
            'tr' => '

Cascade Mtn, N Pk (5553 ft - 873P - Grotto Quad) - August 15, 2007


I tried this peak earlier in the year but was thwarted by not being able  to
cross the rushing West Fork Miller River. I had  no  such  problem  on  this
day. I parked at the gate across the old West Fork Miller  road  (elev  1300
ft). This road has deteriorated to the point  where  it  has  many  bouldery
stretches that would make it virtually impossible to  bike  and  even  makes
for difficult hiking at times. At about  2.5  miles  where  the  road  comes
close to the river and  near  where  the  outlet  creek  from  Francis  Lake
intersects, I found an easy crossing  on  rocks.  After  a  short  but  very
brushy section on the other side, I entered trees and followed  the  rib  on
the left (E) of the outlet creek. If you can find  it  and  stay  on  it,  a
faint fisherman\'s trail leads all the way to Francis  Lake.  I  lost  it  in
dense huckleberry bushes about 500 ft below the lake, ended up too high  and
too far E but still managed to find a way to the NE ridge of my peak.

From the ridge, a pleasant traverse on talus  and  heather  on  the  W  side
below a pinnacle led to a notch just N of the summit. The final  ascent  was
easy scrambling on the E side (4400 ft, 5:15 hrs). I found  no  register  so
left one of mine.  On the way down, I descended directly to the  lake  (some
cliffs to avoid) and went  around  it  on  the  W  side.  I  picked  up  the
fisherman\'s trail at the outlet.  Note that the outlet creek  is  not  where
it is indicated on the USGS map but is farther E out  of  the  lake  arm.  I
again lost the trail on the way down,  ended  up  cliff  bound  and  had  to
ascend a bit to get back on track. The trail takes a turn to the E to  avoid
these cliffs. Others have made this same mistake as I  came  across  fishing
gear (pole, paddles, sleeping pad, plates, etc) that was  abandoned  at  the
top of the cliffs.  I found no body attached so I  assume  whoever  left  it
eventually made it out okay. I  followed  the  trail  lower  down  until  it
disappeared in river bottom brush. Floundering blindly through this  section
I hit the river in a different place than on the way up  with  no  rocks  to
cross and rather than crash more brush looking for a better  spot  I  simply
waded (waist deep but calm) across - boots, pants and all.  It  felt  rather
refreshing on this warm day and I didn\'t even mind  squishing  out  dripping
wet.

Total: 9 miles, 4700 ft and 10 hrs.

Fay Pullen
