            'tr' => '
Anderson Butte (5720+ ft - 880P) & Bacon5 (5040+ ft - 640P) - Bacon Pk  Quad
- August 26, 2007

After over a week of inactivity, I  was  desperate  to  get  out  despite  a
forecast of 50% chance rain. I decided to return to the unfinished  business
of Anderson Butte which I felt could be done in iffy weather. I  hadn\'t  had
time for it when I was in the area earlier  climbing  Bacon  and  Watson.  I
also planned to climb the nearby Bacon5 and maybe some others.

As soon as I left the Watson Lake TH at 10:30, it began to rain  and  rained
steadily until just before I got back to the car.  It  was  44  degrees  and
quite chilly. I took the trail to the Anderson Butte LO site leaving  it  at
the ridge saddle to climb to the main W ridge of the true summit. I  crossed
to the S and traversed on steep slick  wet  heather  below  rocky  pinnacles
until I could make my way to the high point. It was truly  lousy  weather  -
heavy rain, windy, zero visibility and, although the rest of  me  was  still
reasonably dry at this point, my hands were freezing  in  soaked  gloves.  I
left a register in the cairn and quickly retreated (1900 ft, 2 hrs).

For Bacon5, I crashed dripping brush and soggy marsh from  the  lower  trail
toward the saddle to the S, getting very wet in the process. Almost  to  the
saddle I came upon an old road, which I followed to its end  in  awful  head
high brush. I made my way as quickly as possible to forest which  was  steep
but offered reasonable travel. Bacon5 has 3 bumps on the ridge each  with  a
5040 ft contour. Going on the theory that the summit is ALWAYS the  farthest
bump, I headed to the N summit first. It had the best high  point  and  read
higher on my altimeter and that is where I left a register, but I picked  up
the other two bumps on the way out just to make sure. I found no  cairns  or
any other evidence of anyone having been  there.  I  descended  to  the  old
road, which led back to the TH. Even though it was still early and the  rain
had now finally stopped, the thought of crashing  any  more  wet  brush  was
decidedly not appealing and I called it  a  day,  passing  on  several  more
possible summits on the drive home.

Total: 6 miles, 3400 ft and 6 hrs.

Fay Pullen
