            'title' => 'Elephant Butte (7380 ft - 1060P), Stetattle Ridge N Pk (6728 ft - 1768P), Stetattle Ridge S Pk (6495 ft - 415P) & Sourdough Mtn (6120 ft - 200P) - Mt Prophet Quad; and Pumpkin1 (6607 ft - 1647P - Pumpkin Mtn Quad) - August 28- 30, 2007',
            'tr' => '
Elephant Butte (7380 ft - 1060P), Stetattle Ridge N Pk (6728  ft  -  1768P),
Stetattle Ridge S Pk (6495 ft - 415P) & Sourdough Mtn (6120 ft - 200P) -  Mt
Prophet Quad; and Pumpkin1 (6607 ft - 1647P - Pumpkin Mtn Quad) - August 28-
30, 2007

On my climb of Luna last  month,  Elephant  Butte  dominated  views  up  Big
Beaver Cr and I became intrigued by that mountain. After a little  research,
I learned it could be approached from  "scenic"  (as  described  by  Beckey)
Stetattle Ridge and done solo. It seemed  the  perfect  trip  to  regain  my
mental balance after a tough couple weeks dealing with a family crisis.

Day 1: After obtaining a permit for the Sourdough Cross Country Zone in  the
North Cascades National Park, I easily found the Sourdough Mtn TH, elev  900
ft, in the tiny town of Diablo at 11:30. This is an excellent trail,  mostly
in cool forest, well maintained  and  with  a  grade  that  gains  elevation
rapidly. Before I knew it I was at the crossing of Sourdough Cr where I  was
to leave the trail at elev 4900  ft  (4.2  miles,  4000  ft,  3:15  hrs).  I
followed the spur to the camp area (two leveled campsites)  and  encountered
a little minor brush before it opened to meadows  and  talus  and  I  easily
gained the ridge to the left of the creek at  a  5480  ft  saddle.  A  short
class 2 rocky section soon gave  way  to  broad  heather,  flower  and  rock
gardens. "Scenic" doesn\'t begin to describe the beauty of this  ridge.  Just
past tarn 5916 I found a perfect spot  to  camp  with  a  gorgeous  view  of
Snowfield out my front door (5 miles, 4900 ft, 4:30 hrs). Out my  back  door
I could see the Southern Pickets and McMillian Spires across  Stetattle  Cr.
Although it was still early, I was afraid if I went farther  I  wouldn\'t  be
able to find any water. In fact there was no running water  even  here,  but
the tarn provided a surprisingly clean supply. After a little rest, I  hiked
the short distance to the high point of Sourdough Mtn (1 mile, 400  ft,  :50
hr RT), then leisurely ate dinner before turning in early.

Day 2: I awoke to a stunning sunrise over McMillian  Spires  and  a  setting
full moon. As I started along the long ridge toward Elephant Butte at  7:30,
I was absolutely floored by the scenery.  Stetattle Ridge has to be  one  of
the most beautiful ridges in all of Washington  and  you  know  how  I  love
ridges. So I was enjoying myself immensely as I ambled  along  the  friendly
terrain with gorgeous views in every direction. Much of the way had a  faint
trail, not that one was needed. You could wander most anywhere.  There  were
many ups and downs with rocky knobs and grassy  swales  and  hidden  notches
and little  tarns  here  and  there  to  cross,  but  travel  was  easy  and
absolutely delightful.

I reached the 6495 ft S Peak of the ridge at 8:50 and the 6728 ft N Peak  at
10:30 (4 miles, 1800 ft, 3 hrs). Neither had a register. To  experience  the
best of the ridge stop here. I had a great view of McMillian  Spires,  Fury,
Luna and Elephant Butte. The latter looked oh so  close  and  not  all  that
difficult, but it was very deceptive. In fact it was another  4  miles  away
and not all that easy to get to. There were  several  more  bumps  to  climb
over before making a major almost 2000 ft descent to the  saddle  E  of  the
Butte. The first part was straight forward but by trying to avoid  Pt  6154,
I started down too soon and ended up in a  mess  of  brushy  cliffs  and  an
awful traverse and didn\'t reach the 4900 ft saddle until 12:40.

There was more brush and hidden cliffs getting  out  of  the  saddle.  After
several hundred  feet  of  unpleasantness,  the  terrain  opened  up  again.
Reasonable travel prevailed until I reached  the  snowfield  below  a  cliff
band at 6400 ft. I was forced left to where I found a short  class  4  break
in the cliff that allowed me to gain the SE ridge. I followed this  ridge  a
short ways but could see it was likely I would soon be  stopped  by  notches
and cliffs. Beckey describes this ridge as class 3-4, but it  looked  harder
than that to me and I had no gear other than my 60 ft "panic" rope  and  two
slings. I was afraid to continue and instead  found  an  easy  way  off  the
ridge and a traverse W until  almost  directly  below  the  summit  where  I
climbed an awful loose gully back to the ridge again. I  thought  I  had  it
made. But at the last moment, about 50 feet from the summit I encountered  a
30 ft class 5 wall at a final notch. Darn, darn and triple darn!

Now there is an easy route up Elephant Butte from the W but  it  is  a  very
long traverse from the E past S cliffs to get to it  and  I  was  trying  to
avoid that.  In the end, though, that is probably what I should  have  done.
It would have saved time in the long run. But now I  was  stuck  just  below
the summit on the E ridge with time running out and no other option than  to
retreat or climb the  cliff  unprotected.  After  looking  at  all  possible
routes and weighing the risks, I climbed (without  my  pack)  a  deep  crack
with good holds and made it up the initial vertical 10 feet.  The  rest  was
easier and I triumphantly set foot on the summit at 4:30 (8 miles, 4700  ft,
9 hrs). There was a large cairn on top with a tiny  film  can  register.  It
recorded John Roper\'s Oct 14, 1978 climb where he  stated,  "it  is  farther
than it looks". You got that right John! The only other  entries  were  from
1960, 1962, 1966, 1974 and 1991. Surely others have climbed this  peak  more
recently. Maybe "he who removes all registers  from  North  Cascades  Peaks"
removed a more recent one and missed the film can. In any event  I  added  a
new register.

It was getting late and I knew I would be getting  back  after  dark  -  way
after dark - but just how "way after dark" it turned  out  to  be  surprised
even me. First I had to rappel the cliff (thank heavens for my panic  rope).
Then I tried a different way down than my loose awful  gully.  This  started
well on easy heather and scree until I came to a hidden cliff band  and  was
funneled into a steep gully-chimney where I did another couple  of  rappels.
I then did a much lower traverse below all the S side cliffs to get back  to
my up route, but had to do another rappel on the  brushy  cliffs  above  the
saddle. I reached the saddle at 8:20 just as it was  getting  dark.  I  went
straight up from the saddle almost to the summit of  Pt  6154,  zigging  and
zagging around cliffs but avoiding the horrid brush of the  way  down.  Then
everything became a bit of a blur as I slowly followed  the  ridge  back  in
the dark. It seemed to me I was always going up. A full moon helped keep  me
on track for the distant route but progress was a snail\'s pace.  Toward  the
end my LED headlamp seemed to be getting dim. Now when was it  that  I  last
changed batteries? Oh yes, for Big Devil. I really  should  have  added  new
ones for this trip. I finally dragged into a most welcome  looking  camp  at
2:30 am (16 miles, 8300 ft, 19 hrs). I was too tired to do more than have  a
tiny snack and drink a quart of liquid.

Day 3: I awoke at 7:30 to sun on my tent, much earlier  than  I  would  have
liked, but I couldn\'t get back to sleep. So I  ate  breakfast  and  finished
reading the book I had brought. Now it was 9:30. Much  too  early  to  leave
this lovely spot. What  to  do?   I  think  there  is  definitely  something
seriously wrong with me. Why  couldn\'t  I  just  lounge  around?  Instead  I
decided to climb Peak 6607 (Pumpkin Mtn Quad 1). But really the peak  didn\'t
look that hard. I descended 1000 ft to just above  Sourdough  Lake,  getting
into some brief bad brush near the low point. Once on the main SW  ridge  it
was easy going to the summit (2 miles, 1800 ft, 2:15  hrs).  A  small  cairn
was on top and I had a nice view of Stetattle  Ridge.  On  the  way  back  I
avoided the brush at the bottom by staying on the crest of the  ridge.  This
was better even though it had a short rock step. I was back in camp at  2:30
(4 miles, 3000 ft, 5 hrs). I left at 3:30, hit the trail  at  4:15  and  the
car at 6:30. Needless to say, I was totally wiped out  and  I  could  barely
walk anymore but I felt marvelous and completely rejuvenated.

Grand Total: 30 miles and 16,600 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen








