            'title' => 'Methow Pinnacles (7562 ft - 1002P - Mt Arriva Quad); and Azurite1 (7592 ft - 872P) & Azurite4 (7157 ft - 717P) - Azurite Pk Quad - September 12-14, 2007',
            'tr' => '
Methow Pinnacles (7562 ft - 1002P - Mt Arriva Quad); and Azurite1  (7592  ft
- 872P) & Azurite4 (7157 ft - 717P) - Azurite Pk  Quad  -  September  12-14,
2007

While climbing Majestic Mtn  last  year,  I  was  intrigued  by  a  striking
pyramid shaped peak framed at the head of the East Cr valley  to  the  right
of Mebee Pass. I later identified it as the Methow Pinnacles.  I  had  never
even heard of it before but knew I had to eventually go back and  climb  it.
Then I noticed there were two unnamed peaks of prominence on either side  of
the pass. My challenge would be to see if I could connect these three  peaks
in one horseshoe traverse high on connecting  ridges  without  running  into
undue difficulties with cliffs.

Day 1: The East Cr Trail has a spacious marked TH (elev  2600  ft)  off  the
North Cascades Hwy and is shown as a solid green line going all the  way  to
Mebee Pass on the 2003 Mt Logan GT map,  so  it  should  be  a  good  trail,
right? Wrong! This fact slowly  dawned  on  me  as  I  toiled  up  the  many
switchbacks at the beginning. This section goes through an  open  forest  of
weak spindly jack trees. I remembered from last  year  that  many  of  these
small trees had fallen across  the  trail  and  were  a  real  pain  to  get
through, but I had hopes that they had been logged out by now. Not only  had
the old ones not been logged out, but many new ones had also been  added  by
recent storms. Now admittedly they were all a foot or less in  diameter  and
not a great impediment as blowdowns go, but they all  required  at  least  a
high step to get over, and after counting well over a hundred of them  in  a
distance of about half a mile, they  began  to  take  their  toll  and  slow
progress.

Things improved when I entered older more mature forest after about  a  mile
and started the traverse along East Cr. The blowdowns were  now  larger  but
thankfully  much  less  frequent.  Then  once  past  the  Boulder  Cr  Trail
junction, elev 4700 ft (4 miles, 2300 ft, 2:45  hr),  the  trail  completely
deteriorated. I don\'t think this section has been maintained  in  years,  if
not decades. I stayed with it as it dropped about 300  ft,  then  completely
lost it in heavy brush and multiple blowdowns. It took me  another  hour  of
brush crashing to stumble upon it  again.  It  actually  crosses  the  creek
twice and not exactly where  the  map  indicates.  After  the  second  creek
crossing, there was less brush but more large blowdowns to contend  with.  I
found little evidence of travel by other people and no signs  of  previously
used campsites. Any normal backpacker would have given up well  before  now.
I had to make my own spot to camp in the woods at 5:45 just  past  the  (now
dry) creek that drains the basin W of Azurite1, elev 4960 ft (6 miles,  2900
ft, 5:00 hrs).

Day 2: The days are getting noticeable shorter. It was dark when I  went  to
bed at 8:00 and still dark when I got up at  6:00,  but  I  slept  long  and
well. I left camp a little after 7:00, crossed the  creek  and  headed  west
upslope toward Azurite4. Travel was fairly easy, in fact it was easier  than
the "trail" had been, and in an hour I reached lovely Lake 5925.  More  easy
travel up heather and scree that snaked through minor cliffs and  along  the
ridge put me on the summit of Azurite4 (Pk 7157)  at  9:45  where  I  had  a
gorgeous view of Majestic Mtn, McKay Ridge, Ragged  Ridge  and  anything  to
the north and west. The sun was still too low in  the  sky  to  clearly  see
peaks to the east and south. There was a cairn on top but no register.

I now began my proposed horseshoe traverse, following the  ridge  south  and
east toward Methow Pinnacles. This ridge is an absolute delight,  easily  up
there with "my best ridges ever".  It may not be quite as good  as  my  last
ridge trip (Stetattle Ridge), but it was  darn  close.  I  wandered  up  and
down, went over Pt 7073, dropped to a level section with a grove  of  alpine
larches just beginning to show gold (give them another couple of  weeks  and
they will be at their prime),  passed  a  short  narrow  rocky  section  and
dropped again to the broad low point saddle (elev 6400 ft) before  beginning
the final climb to the Pinnacles. Here red fall color made a sharp  contrast
to the gray dead trees of a recent burn. After some unpleasant  loose  scree
I reached the high point of the Methow Pinnacles (the North Peak) at  12:50.
There was neither a cairn nor a  register.  I  added  both  to  the  highest
boulder. I looked S toward the appealing rocky Middle Peak concluding I  did
not have the time to add it to my itinerary. It would  take  some  technical
climbing to get up.

My problem now was how to get down to Mebee Pass and continue  to  Azurite1.
All of the E face of the Pinnacles is a 1000 ft rock wall and most of the  N
face is quite cliffy as well. If I couldn\'t find a direct  descent  I  would
have to make a long detour. Beckey mentions a party that had climbed  the  E
face and then descended a "ravine" to Mebee Pass  from  the  N  end  of  the
ridge. What he meant by a "ravine", I had no clue. I would just have  to  go
take a look and see if it was something I could easily descend. I  traversed
N on more unpleasant loose scree, on the west slope, to the very end of  the
ridge at about 7200 ft, where I did indeed find a way  down.  The  beginning
was a steep loose gully but lower down  it  broadened  nicely  (Is  a  broad
gully a ravine?) and easily brought me to  Mebee  Pass,  elev  6480  ft,  at
2:40.

I crossed the trail at the Pass, staying on the crest of the ridge. I  could
see it looked doable as far as Pt 7482. Beyond that I couldn\'t really  tell,
but the map indicated possible problems. The ridge to Azurite1  was  not  as
delightful as the one from Azurite4, but it was still pleasant enough and  I
had an added unexpected bonus of stumbling upon an abandoned lookout with  a
great view on the first promontory above the pass.  Where on earth did  this
come from? I have never heard of this lookout, had no idea it was  here  and
I ran across no trail going to it. Then I came to the notch  below  Pt  7482
and my heart sank.  The  ridge  connecting  to  Azurite1  was  a  series  of
gendarmes and impassible. To make matters worse, it wasn\'t going to be  easy
to get off the ridge from where I was now to  descend  to  the  basin  below
Azurite1 and the peak itself didn\'t look trivial either.  It  certainly  was
not a walkup.

I did manage to find a way off the ridge down a gosh awful  extremely  steep
loose gully.  It is times like these that I am glad I  am  alone  because  I
doubt many people would follow me down such a gully and if they were  stupid
enough to actually do so we might very likely  end  up  killing  each  other
with falling rock. Alone I didn\'t have to worry about talking  someone  into
doing something dangerous or kicking rocks down on anyone else.  And  I  did
send quite a few downhill. Once below the gendarmes, I traversed to a  gully
(It wasn\'t as bad as it had looked from a distance)  that  threaded  between
cliffs to the summit  of  Azirite1  at  4:45.  There  was  a  cairn  but  no
register, which surprised me a little as I am  pretty  sure  Stefan  climbed
this peak from Azurite Pass.  The sun was in the right position  now  for  a
magnificent close-up view of Azurite.

I now had to get back to camp, hopefully before dark. I reversed  the  final
gully, then headed straight downhill  keeping  to  the  left  of  the  basin
drainage creek. I ran into a little brush, but for the most part it  was  an
easy descent and I came right out at camp at 6:30 (8 miles, 5500  ft,  11:20
hrs) with enough daylight left to wash  up  in  the  creek  and  eat  dinner
before turning in again at 8:00.

Day 3: I did a better job of staying on the trail on the  way  out  and  saw
where I lost it on the way in. Even so, it was still slow tedious going  and
I didn\'t improve much on my in time. I left at 8:00 and hit the TH at  12:15
(6 miles, 600 ft, 4:15 hrs). I saw no one on the trail or anywhere else  for
that matter the whole 3 days I was out.

Grand Total: 20 miles and 9000 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen

P.S. Azurite1 and Azurite4 finishes up the Azurite Pk Quad for me.


