            'tr' => '
Switchblade Pk (7805 ft - 1085P), Hock Mtn  (7750  ft  -  750P),  Twisp  Mtn
(7161 ft - 881P), Lincoln Butte (7065 ft - 785P), Jacknife Pk  (7700+  ft  -
220P) and Stiletto Pk (7660 ft - 380P) - McAlester Mtn Quad - September  19-
21, 2007

I seem to forget something on every trip. Usually it is a  minor  thing  and
of little consequence, but this time I forgot a  doozey.  I  forgot  all  my
food, a first for me. Well, not entirely all of it.  I  did  have  my  fresh
fruit, hardboiled egg and cheese (These  things  I  put  in  the  morning  I
leave. The rest I usually put in the night before.) But  everything  else  I
forgot. Shows my state of mind lately. Fortunately, I  remembered  I  forgot
(it that an oxymoron?) while still in Marblemount, getting my permit,  where
there is a small Food Mart. Pickings were pretty slim here for someone  with
my dietary restrictions, but I did manage to add enough food to  survive.  I
was so happy they had Cliff Bars. Not that I am that fond of  them,  but  at
least they are fairly healthy. Actually, I don\'t really eat that much  while
exercising strenuously. What I really missed was my powdered  Cytomax  sport
drink, which gets me through the day, and all my supplements.  I  discovered
I can exist without them, but they really do make a difference.

Day 1: Delayed by my side trip to the  Food  Mart  and  by  stopping  for  a
hamburger to at least start with a full tummy, it was 1:35  by  the  time  I
started from the Bridge Cr TH, elev 4600 ft, on the North  Cascades  Hwy.  I
followed the Stiletto Spur Trail 3.3 miles downhill and then the Twisp  Pass
Trail 3.3 miles uphill to a camp on Dagger Lake  (6.6  miles,  1900  ft  and
3:15 hrs). I set up camp and was just starting for  Lincoln  Butte,  when  a
lone woman showed up obviously intending to spend the  night  at  the  lake.
Since there is only one party permit (but that can include up to 12  people)
issued for Dagger Lake, and I  had  it,  I  knew  she  didn\'t  have  one.  I
explained to her that she was in the North Cascades  National  Park,  should
have a permit and, if she ran into a ranger, would most certainly  be  asked
to produce one. She was from California visiting a friend and  had  no  idea
about the rules and regulations of this area. Since  she  was  a  very  nice
young woman (her name was Sara) and I feel a  special  kindred  spirit  with
all solo females, I welcomed her company. I might have felt differently  had
she been a rowdy group of teenagers.

It was now about 5:45 and I was pushing it to get up Lincoln Butte and  back
before dark. I reached Twisp Pass at 6:11 and, going  as  fast  as  I  could
possibly go, the summit at 7:00. It was farther and harder than I  expected,
with a class 3 rocky section that required a little care and, as  always,  a
false summit, with the true summit on along a  narrow  ridge  that  required
more care. I ran into a little fresh snow from the last storm along the  way
but it caused no problem. I came down the last bit to camp by headlamp  (3.5
miles, 1800 ft, 2:40 hrs RT), ate my meager cold dinner, but with warm  tea,
and turned in at 9:30. It was a cold night and I was glad I had switched  to
my warmer sleeping bag for this trip.

Day 2: I was up at 6:00. Sara had hung her food with mine at the  bear  wire
by my site and came to get it as I was starting for Hock Mtn  at  7:30.  She
complained of having spent a cold night. From  camp  I  crossed  the  outlet
creek of Dagger Lake and angled SW to the large  talus  basin  below  the  N
face of Hock, and onto the NW ridge, which I followed  to  the  summit.   It
was easy enough going, easier than Lincoln Butte, but a  freezing  wind  was
blowing and I was mighty cold. I had on  all  my  clothes,  except  my  down
jacket and I even considered wearing that.  My  hands  were  especially  bad
off. I needed warmer gloves. Whatever happened to summer?  The forecast  had
been good for today when I left town, but I could  see  weather  approaching
the whole time I was climbing the ridge. By the time I  reached  the  summit
(2400 ft, 2:20 hrs) views were limited and it  began  to  snow  lightly.  My
plan to follow the ridge to Twisp was unwise under  such  conditions  if  it
was even doable.

I retreated to the N talus basin and  traversed  below  the  ridge  until  I
could climb easy heather slopes to the summit  of  Twisp  Mtn  (3700  ft,  5
hrs). I was now in complete fog and could see  nothing.  Again,  I  felt  it
unwise to follow the ridge to Twisp Pass, and  was  forced  by  terrain  and
conditions to descend the NW ridge back to Dagger  Lake.  Precipitation  was
light, but now more rain than snow, all the brush was wet and my  feet  were
soaked. I stopped by my tent to change socks and ran into Sara  again.   She
had hiked to Twisp Pass and was getting ready to have a warm  drink.  I  was
actually surprised she was still around and hadn\'t hightailed  it  out.  But
although  this  was  her  first  solo  overnight,  she  was  actually  quite
experienced and had led trips before.  She just wasn\'t  used  to  the  North
Cascades.

After changing socks, I started for  Switchblade  Pk,  picking  up  the  old
trail from Twisp Pass toward Stiletto and then finding a way trail  to  Lake
6795. This is a lovely high mountain lake, quite large and  deep.  I  had  a
little trouble finding a way up Switchblade from the lake, as  I  could  see
nothing. Trusting the map, I headed for the SW face where the contours  seem
the  most  friendly.  It  wasn\'t  difficult   climbing,   just   challenging
routefinding in the fog and mist as I wove my way up  from  gully  to  gully
onto the S ridge and the summit (6300 ft, 9:30 hrs). I especially had to  be
careful coming down to retrace my route exactly  and  not  get  hung  up  on
cliffs.  I headed straight back to camp having had enough for  this  day  (8
miles, 6300 ft, 11:30 hrs). The last  two  peaks  would  have  to  wait  for
tomorrow, or another trip if the weather  did  not  improve.  My  feet  were
soaked again and I was down to my last pair of dry  socks.  Sara  was  still
around and we commiserated over the fickleness of  North  Cascades  weather.
We hoped with the cloud cover tonight would at least be warmer.

Day 3: It was not warmer.  It was colder. My  boots  even  froze  inside  my
tent. But that meant there was clearing and it promised to  be  a  beautiful
day. I was happy that Sara would have at least one nice day.  She  did  plan
on going out today. I packed up all my gear and  headed  once  again  toward
Twisp Pass at 8:00, planning on picking up my last  two  peaks  while  going
out the Stiletto Pk trail - if I could find it. The GT map shows this  trail
ending well below Stiletto Pk, but an old trail went all the  way  to  Twisp
Pass at one time. This trail is quite good for about a mile from  the  pass,
then is lost in a large meadow below Lake 6795. No matter. I knew  where  it
was  supposed  to  go,  so  just  headed  in  the  right  direction  through
absolutely gorgeous meadows.  I had no idea this area was  so  beautiful.  I
highly recommend a visit, peaks or no peaks.

I dropped my big pack (1600 ft,  2  hrs)  in  a  strategic  spot  below  and
between Stiletto Pk and Jacknife Pk, continuing with a light daypack. I  was
now in blessed sunshine with all the views I  had  missed  the  day  before.
Both peaks were very pleasant class 3+ scrambles on fun (and now dry)  rock.
Stiletto had an old heavy brass Mountaineer register  on  top,  but  it  was
only filled with scraps of paper. I recognized  the  names  of  Don  Goodman
(8/20/00) and Fred Beavon (8/31/04). Jacknife had a glass  jar  register  in
which I recognized Don Beavon (7/3/98) and Martin Shetter (7/5/03).  A  John
Burroughs climbed the peak on 7/11/81 claiming a first ascent and naming  it
"Dirk Pk". The name certainly didn\'t stick.

I was back at my pack at 12:15 (2700, 4:15 hrs.)  and  continued  traversing
around Stiletto Pk though more lovely meadows making my way to a final  6240
ft saddle below the old 7223 ft LO site. I had hoped to pick  up  the  trail
here but I had trouble finding it. I had to descend straight down  from  the
saddle before finally running into the trail at  5500  ft.   This  ended  up
being a very good trail. Someday I must follow it all the way uphill to  its
end. I certainly wouldn\'t mind revisiting all those gorgeous meadows. I  hit
the main trail at 2:15 and followed it annoyingly uphill  the  rest  of  the
way back to the car (9.4 miles, 3400 ft, 7 hrs). When I  got  home  my  food
bag was just where I had left it on the kitchen counter. Well, I guess I  am
already packed for my next trip.

Grand Total: 27.5 miles and 13,200 ft in 3 days.

Fay Pullen




