            'tr' => '

American Ridge


American Ridge is a scenic ridge about  15  miles  long  that  lies  between
American River and Bumping River E of Mt Rainier.  Along  the  up  and  down
crest are 7 peaks of prominence. The only one  that  is  named  is  Goat  Pk
(6473 ft) and that was the only one I had previously climbed.  The  other  6
are referred to in Jeff\'s Master List as American  Ridge  1  to  6,  running
from W to E. 5 of these 6 are easily accessed from the  trail  that  follows
most of the ridge. But the highest point, American Ridge 3 (6960+ ft), is  a
craggy summit that the trail avoids by traversing far beneath it. It is  the
only one that offers more than a hike.  However the others are  worth  doing
just for the pleasure of following the ridge. The entire ridge is  too  long
to do in one day, so I broke it up into two daytrips.

American Ridge 4 (6240+ ft - 400P), American Ridge 5 (6320+ ft -  480P)  and
American Ridge 6 (6197 ft - 477P) - Goose Prairie Quad - September 27, 2007

For this section of the ridge I created a loop trip by going up the Goat  Cr
Trail, hiking the crest that included these three summits, coming  down  the
Goose Prairie Trail and connecting the two trailheads with a 3.6  mile  bike
ride along the Bumping Lake Road. The day was warm and  pleasant  with  good
views and I in fact hiked the whole day in shorts. I reached American  Ridge
6 in 2:45 hrs, American Ridge 5 in 4 hrs, American  Ridge  4  in  4:45,  and
(after a small shortcut to bypass a meandering trail) my bike at the far  TH
on the paved road at 7:25 hrs. A 20-minute pedal put me back at my car.

Total: 16 miles, 4400 ft and 7:45 hrs.

Old Scab Mtn (6608 ft - 968P) & Pk 6435 (515P) - Old Scab Mtn Quad;  and  Pk
4440+ (400P) & Haystack Rock (3932 ft - 452P) -  Cliffdell  Quad  -  Oct  3,
2007

Before I could get back to the rest of American Ridge  the  weather  made  a
turn for the worse with snow levels dropping and a very unsettled  forecast.
I really didn\'t want to be on the ridge under such conditions, so I  decided
to instead go for Old Scab Mtn on the  other  side  of  the  Bumping  River.
Getting to the high TH at 5900 ft would entail  wandering  miles  of  forest
roads, which seemed like a good plan for a  bad  weather  day.   There  were
several other summits of prominence nearby, all approached by more miles  of
roads.

I knew I would be getting into significant snow, so it would have been  nice
to have been in my Jeep.  However, it had been creamed by  a  falling  maple
branch in my driveway a few days before that put  two  large  dents  in  the
roof and took out a rear side window and was in  the  shop  being  repaired.
That left me with my Subaru, which I did manage to coax all the way  to  the
TH, although I did a bit of slipping and sliding in 4-5 inches  of  snow  at
the top and almost got myself stuck turning around on the narrow  road.  Old
Scab Mtn itself turned out to be an interesting if short climb up the  steep
SE ridge, made somewhat treacherous by the  fresh  snow  coating  the  final
summit rocks. Total: 3.5 miles, 1725 ft and 3.45 hrs.
To fill out the day, I also climbed 3 other peaks. Pk  6435,  Pk  4440+  and
Haystack Rock were each no more than 30 minutes RT  on  foot.   The  hardest
part of the latter two was finding the correct roads to  get  close  enough.
Haystack Rock was the most interesting with its rocky little crags.

American Ridge 2 (6265 ft - 465P - Cougar Lk  Quad)  and  American  Ridge  3
(6960+ ft - 1880P - Bumping Lk Quad) - October 5, 2007

I waited for another good weather day before returning  to  American  Ridge.
This time I approached from the Mesatchee Cr Trail and  reached  the  summit
of American Ridge 2 in 2:45 hrs. I descended back to the trail and  followed
it another couple miles to the Big Basin S of American Ridge 3.  This  is  a
gorgeous open basin that was now covered with significant snow, 8 inches  or
more where drifted, and I  was  slowed  down  by  trailbreaking.  There  was
enough of the white stuff that I lost the trail and was  wishing  I  had  my
skis. I traversed out of the basin onto the S slope of  the  peak,  crossing
multiple gullies and  slabby  rocky  ribs  until  I  could  make  the  final
scramble to top. It was farther and harder to get to than I had thought  and
took 5:30 hrs total. From the summit, I could see that the N  slope  was  an
easier route back, although it entailed traversing steep snow that was  knee
deep in places. Once past Pt 6946, I crossed the ridge and took  a  shortcut
straight downhill to intersect the trail  saving  myself  several  miles  of
backtracking.

Total: 13.5 miles, 5200 ft and 8 hrs.

Fay Pullen

Oh yes, I still have American Ridge 1 left to do.





