            'tr' => '
Nelson Ridge (7292 ft - 852P - Bumping Lk Quad) and Timberwolf  Mtn  3,  aka
"Buffalo Hump" (6960+ ft - 720P -Timberwolf Mtn Quad) - October 8, 2007

Other than Mt Aix and Bismarck Pk, I really haven\'t done much  exploring  in
that portion of the  William  O.  Douglas  Wilderness  E  of  Bumping  Lake.
Judging by the quality of these two peaks and others I  got  a  view  of,  I
should really do more.

I had a little trouble finding the TH for the  Richmond  Mine  (Thunder  Cr)
Trail. It is at the  end  of  an  obscure  unmarked  road  that  turns  left
immediately after the paved road crosses the Bumping  River.  Several  rough
tracks wander around the area but the TH (elev 3400  ft)  is  marked  and  a
Forest Pass required. As I was getting ready to go, a hunter  on  foot  came
out the trail and two more showed up in  a  pickup  truck,  all  dressed  in
camouflage. Turns out it is muzzle loading season. Who outside  the  hunting
community can keep track of all the  various  seasons  -  early  hunt,  high
hunt, late hunt, archery, muzzle loading, modern firearm,  bear,  deer,  elk
etc., etc.? The best bet is once late summer and fall arrives,  just  assume
there is some hunt going on.

 I had a nice conversation with the fellow on foot. When I talk to  hunters,
they seem like pleasant and reasonable people,  for  the  most  part,  doing
what they enjoy. It is just that our interests are so  very  different,  and
somehow they make me uncomfortable and  feeling  vulnerable  carrying  their
powerful weapons when I am completely unarmed. Ironically (since he  was  in
camouflage), the hunter asked if I was  wearing  anything  brightly  colored
and warned me to be careful. Warned ME  to  be  careful?  How  about  HE  be
careful and look well before taking a shot! In the end, though, once on  the
trail it really didn\'t matter. Hunters are by nature mostly lazy and do  not
stray too far from  their  vehicles  as  they  know  if  they  actually  bag
anything they then have to pack  it  out.  Unless  of  course  they  are  on
horseback - but that is another story. I soon left the  hunters  far  behind
and saw no one the rest of the day.

It was a good trail and in 2 hours I reached  the  6200  ft  saddle  in  the
ridge above Richmond Lake. I continued SW along  the  ridge  until  I  could
traverse S across a snowy basin to the main ridge N of Nelson Ridge.  Travel
was slowed as I broke trail across snow covered talus  often  finding  holes
and sinking in to my knees or deeper. Nelson Ridge,  both  on  the  map  and
from this viewpoint, appeared quite craggy and I worried it  would  give  me
some difficulty but that  was  not  the  case.  All  pinnacles  were  easily
bypassed on the  W  slope.  The  climb  was  little  more  than  a  hike  in
difficulty, but it was varied and interesting. I  soon  reached  the  summit
(4200 ft, 4 hrs) and spent a pleasant half hour on top eating  my  lunch  in
the sun.

I had a good view of  Timberwolf  3.  This  peak  is  listed  in  Beckey  as
"Buffalo Hump" and he describes it as "hardly more than  a  scramble",  what
ever that means. Well, what I saw didn\'t look that easy. The  summit  was  a
cliffy fin-like crag that sure looked like it could be a problem. But  maybe
there was an easier way up than what I could see  from  my  viewpoint.  Only
one way to find out. I  retraced  my  steps  to  Richmond  saddle  and  then
followed the ridge NE past an impressive spire to the  base  of  the  summit
rocks. Sure enough, it all looked like impassible cliff. I hadn\'t  bargained
on this and had no climbing gear with me other than my  60  ft  panic  rope.
Didn\'t even bring any slings. My only  hope,  I  thought,  was  to  traverse
around the cliffs on the W (the E was a sheer cliff) to the N side  and  see
if things looked better there. In doing that, I discovered a small break  in
the wall on the SW corner. Leaving my pack, and taking only my  rope  and  a
register, I climbed the break to discover a  series  of  narrow,  but  quite
passable, ledges circling back around to the E above  the  wall  and  easier
ground. In total it was about 100 ft of exposed class 4 rock,  really  quite
a lot of fun. I passed an old tattered  rappel  sling  at  the  end  of  the
tricky stuff before the final short scramble  to  the  top  (5200  ft,  6:20
hrs). I found an old rusted threaded pipe  on  top,  but  it  was  empty.  I
placed my register inside it.

I downclimbed back to my pack, went W straight downhill and intersected  the
trail at 5600 ft. I startled a lone mountain goat  shortly  below  the  crag
and he took off running. Then once on the trail, I was  startled  to  see  a
large owl glide directly for me.  At  the  last  minute,  perhaps  correctly
deciding I was a tad large for dinner,  he  swerved  up  and  perched  on  a
branch not two feet from my head. I reached the car at  dusk.  The  hunters\'
truck was still there but they were nowhere to be seen.

Total: 12 miles, 5200 ft and 8: 15 hrs.

Fay Pullen


