            'title' => 'Tahtlum Pk (6567 ft - 1127P - Cougar Lk Quad) and Norse Pk Quad 3 (6085 ft - 445P - Norse Pk Quad) - October 21, 2007',
            'tr' => 'Tahtlum Pk (6567 ft - 1127P - Cougar Lk Quad) and Norse Pk Quad 3 (6085 ft - 445P - Norse Pk Quad) - October 21, 2007

The DOT usually closes Chinook Pass at the first big snowstorm, but October is a bit early even for them, so when 1.5-2 feet of snow fell  on Saturday (October 20) I had my first chance in many a year to ski there.   I had saved these two peaks for possible ski ascents and now seemed my opportunity to try for them. The first peak made for a reasonable ski ascent. The second was more questionable.

A not too early start on a Sunday worked to my advantage by allowing someone else to already break trail to the Naches-Tahtlum Ridge. From then on I was on my own, but it wasn\'t too bad and the skiing was really quite good to the summit of Tahtlum Pk (3 miles, 1400 ft, 2:30 hrs). Now the hard part started. I knew from the map that getting to Norse3 would be difficult on skis. It was not possible to follow the ridge, but I did see a reasonable way down, at least to start, from a 6400 ft saddle slightly N of the summit. I even got in a few good turns. Then it turned steep, with hidden cliff bands and inadequately snow cover on brush and logs and I was forced to remove skis several times to get past obstacles and to descend to 5300 ft. This was followed by a steep climb to the 5600 ft saddle S of Norse3, again on foot. I got in a little more skiing on the gentle ridge before it became too narrow and rocky. I reached the summit at 3:40 (5 miles, 2400 ft, 5:30 hrs) much later than I had hoped.

I now knew I would be coming out in the dark. I tried to correct some of my route finding errors of the way in by dropping even lower, to 5000 ft, but I don\'t think I gained much. I was able to keep skis on for the entire 1400 ft climb back to the 6400 ft saddle, but the trailbreaking was so exhausting in the deep snow that I didn\'t reach it till 7:00. In addition, I was using my winter ski pack for the first time this year and had neglected to check the headlamp that always resides there. When I went to turn it on, I discovered the batteries were dead. At this point I began to get a little worried. Then I remembered that I always carry a backup light in this pack. It was not as powerful as my main headlamp (with good batteries, that is) but it was good enough to get me out as all I had to do was follow my ski tracks. Actually, from the 6400 ft saddle on, the skiing was enjoyable. I really don\'t mind skiing by headlamp and find I can often see better by it than in the flat light of a foggy day. Nevertheless, I was most happy when I reached the car at 9:00.

Total: 10 miles, 4300 ft and 10:50 hrs

Fay Pullen
