            'tr' => '
Raven Roost (6160+ ft - 680P) and Raven Roost Quad 1  (6081  ft  -  401P)  -
Raven Roost Quad - November 21, 2007

There was snow right away as I turned off Hwy 410  onto  the  Little  Naches
River Road. When I read the sign saying "Raven Roost 14  miles"  as  I  next
turned onto road 1902 it seemed hopeless that I could get  close  enough  to
climb it. But miraculously I was able,  with  difficulty  and  only  because
there was a good track made by others (and I was in my Jeep),  to  drive  to
5000 ft and within 3 miles. That made for a very easy ski  up  the  road  to
the tower studded summit. Just as I reached  the  top  I  was  joined  by  3
snowmobiles. I soon left them, and they could not  follow,  as  I  descended
off the summit into the Norse Peak  Wilderness  to  the  saddle  with  Raven
Roost 1. The snow was absolutely gorgeous dry powder,  the  kind  where  you
can do no wrong, the only caveat being there wasn\'t quite enough of  it.  In
the vegetated meadows it was fine but I had to watch in it rocky  areas.   I
did put a few more scratches on my ski bases. From the saddle  I  worked  my
way up the delightful ridge to the summit of Raven  Roost  1.  Although  the
temperature was in the low 20s, the sun was warm  and  I  spent  a  pleasant
half hour on top. I could not get over the beauty of the  snow  on  the  ski
out.  This must be the norm for Eastern Washington. Quite a contrast to  our
usual Western Washington slush. Wish I could ski in this area more often.

Total: 8.5 miles, 2000 ft and 4:30 hrs.



Raven Roost Quad 2 (4907 ft - 587P) - Raven Roost Quad - November 28, 2007

I had planned to ski east of Cayuse Pass on this day, but when I woke up  in
the morning both Chinook and Cayuse had been closed overnight. Darn!  On  to
Plan B. While checking out peaks on the Raven  Roost  Quad,  I  had  noticed
that Raven Roost 2 could be approached from  the  Pyramid  Cr  SnoPark  near
Greenwater on the west. It would be a long trip and would involve a  descent
into the Naches drainage but it could be done.

The bad news was the Pyramid Cr SnoPark was already in  place  and  I  could
drive no higher (2700 ft). The good news was the road  to  the  SnoPark  was
plowed. I swear they plow this road better than Hwy 410. For variety,  after
skiing about a mile, I turned off onto a spur  road  that  led  to  the  Old
Naches Wagon Trail. Probably not a good idea as  this  historic  route  over
Naches Pass is quite narrow, wanders up and down  along  the  ridge  and  is
very steep in spots. At one point it was so steep I took  off  my  skis  and
walked up but that was because I didn\'t want to put on skins.  Eventually  I
connected with the main road again and hit the high point of 4900 ft at  the
Pyramid Peak Saddle (5.7 miles, 2700 ft, 3 hrs). A descent of 2.7 miles  and
600 ft followed until I was below the summit of Raven Roost 2. Here  I  left
skis, as there was not enough snow to cover brush and logs,  and  booted  to
the top (8.7 miles, 3400 ft, 4:30 hrs). It started  to  snow  as  I  slogged
back to the saddle, but once there it was a pleasant ski  down  to  the  car
sticking to the main road the whole way this time. I was passed  by  several
groups of snowmobiles. I could tell they were not  used  to  encountering  a
skier in this area. When I reached the SnoPark the plow  was  hard  at  work
once again.



Total: 18.2 miles, 4100 ft and 7:45 hrs.





