            'title' => 'Skate Mtn, East Pk (4800+ ft - 760P - Tatoosh Lakes Quad) - December 6, 2007 
 Skate Mtn, West Pk (5240+ ft - 1480P - Wahpenayo Pk Quad) - December 17, 2007',
            'tr' => '
Skate Mtn Peaks

I have to remind myself each winter to scale  back  my  ambitions.   I  keep
thinking I can knock off several peaks  per  trip.  Then  reality  sets  in.
Either I can\'t drive as far as I had planned,  trailbreaking  is  more  work
than anticipated, the weather is worse than hoped  for,  the  peak  is  more
difficult than I thought or I just plain run out of time.  For  these  peaks
it was all of the above. It took me 3 separate trips to  get  all  of  them.
There are at least 3 more peaks in the vicinity  that  would  probably  take
another 3 separate trips, were I ever to go back for them.

Skate Mtn, East Pk (4800+ ft - 760P - Tatoosh  Lakes  Quad)  -  December  6,
2007

My original plan this day was to climb the 3 peaks of Dixon Mtn. Stefan  had
done just that the previous weekend so I had good  beta  on  conditions  and
route. Problem was the big storm hit in the interim and the  gate  on  Skate
Cr Road was closed due to a washout. So I instead set my  sights  on  nearby
Skate Mtn, which road had no gate, naively thinking I could do  both  peaks.
I was lucky to get one.

I drove Road 47 and Road 4720 to the snowline at 2600 ft. I  could  probably
have gotten farther had I been in my Jeep. Instead I was in my  Subaru,  not
planning on having to drive snowy back roads. So  I  had  some  intermittent
bare road patches the first half mile until I reached consistent  snow.  The
base snow had been rained on a lot but there was a couple  inches  fresh  on
top that made for good road skiing.   Shortly  before  the  main  Skate  Mtn
ridge, elev 4000 ft, I picked up an old ditched road that made  its  way  on
the N side of the ridge to  end  in  a  clearcut.  From  there  I  traversed
crosscountry to the final saddle W of what I thought was the summit.

At the saddle the snow was too thin to cover the downed trees and debris  in
the initial woods and so I mistakenly left my skis  behind  and  booted  the
rest of the way to the first summit. This was okay in  the  woods  but  near
the top it opened up and there I postholed  in  kneedeep  slush.  Then  upon
reaching the first summit I could see another point to the  SE  that  looked
higher to me (it had the same map contour of 4800 ft) along the fairly  open
crest. I knew it would take a long time to posthole  there  even  though  it
was only about .3 mile away. But by now I had given up also  getting  the  W
peak. Even If I had had the time, the ridge to it  looked  long  and  cliffy
and probably was not a good way to go. The W Pk would best be  climbed  from
the W on another trip.  So I trudged on to the second  summit  which  turned
out to be a small rocky knob that did read higher on my  altimeter.  But  it
was slow going through awful deep slush. By the time I got back to  my  skis
it was almost 4:00 (RT had taken 2 hrs). I made it to the main  road  before
dark, and then had an enjoyable run by headlight to  the  car.   Total:  9.5
miles, 2850 ft and 6:30 hrs.

Skate Mtn, West Pk (5240+ ft - 1480P - Wahpenayo Pk  Quad)  -  December  17,
2007

I had to wait a week and a half for skiing conditions to  improve  with  new
snow and when it did there was almost too much of it.  I drove  Road  47  to
where a sign stated it was closed to all motor vehicles except  snowmobiles,
elev 2400 ft, at which point there was a consistent snowpack of  6-8  inches
(this time I was in my Jeep). The snow depth increased rapidly to the  point
of a foot or more of fresh by the time I skied the 4  miles  to  Road  4745,
elev 3200 ft. To my dismay there was no evidence  of  any  snowmobiles  ever
having been up the road so I had to break trail all  by  myself.  Where  are
those pesky machines when you need them? When they would be of use they  are
nowhere to be seen and when you want  them  to  go  away  they  are  buzzing
around everywhere.

My speed continued to decrease as the  snow  depth  increased  and  it  took
another 2 hours to travel the additional 2 miles to the main W  ridge,  elev
4200 ft. I could feel the time slipping away. Again I  had  hoped  to  climb
more peaks in the area and again I was lucky to  get  one.  To  add  to  the
problems, when I got my first good look at the W Pk  it  was  much  cliffier
than I had expected and I wasn\'t even sure I could find a  reasonable  route
up the final rocks in the allotted time.

I put on skins, left the road and headed straight up the last thousand  feet
toward the summit through old clearcut. There  was  some  brush  to  contend
with, but for the most part the going was open with enough  snow  cover  for
skis. But the trailbreaking was exhausting and took another 2.5 hours.  When
I reached the base of the cliffs, I traversed right beneath them  to  the  S
ridge, elev about 5100 ft, where I luckily found a way  through  the  rocks.
Here I left my skis and kicked steps up a steep  gully.  Fortunately  I  had
brought an ice  axe  along,  as  the  first  part  was  a  bit  tricky  with
unconsolidated powder snow. Even though it was knee to thigh  deep,  I  sank
all the way in to the slippery frozen turf and rock  underneath.  I  emerged
onto the summit at 6:00. Needless to say it was now dark.

I had a great  ski,  with  some  very  nice  turns,  back  to  the  road  by
headlight. I was down in 30 minutes what had taken 2.5 hours to get up.  The
road itself wasn\'t as fast. With only one person breaking trail,  my   track
wasn\'t that great and much of the road was gentle to  downright  flat  (even
slightly uphill in a few spots) so I got very little free glide and  had  to
stride most of the way out. By the time I reached the car at 9:00,  I  swore
I would never ski this road again. How quickly I forget. Total: 13.5  miles,
3100 ft and 10:15 hrs.

Wahpenayo3 (4560+ ft - 400P - Wahpenayo Pk Quad) - December 21, 2007

I was back 4 days later, miffed that I was previously so close to this  peak
and yet  unable to get it. I again drove to the sign on Road 47,  this  time
barely making it that far in my Jeep. Again no snowmobiles had been  on  the
road so with the new dump of fresh snow, I had to break trail up  this  road
all over again and it was just as much work and  just  as  slow  as  before.
Again I hoped to get other peaks. Again I was lucky to get just one. Will  I
ever learn?

I skinned up and left Road 4745 near the upper switchback (5 Â¼  miles,  1650
ft, 4 hrs) heading straight for Wahpenayo3.  I  thought  I  would  be  there
easily in an hour, but it was harder than I thought  to  actually  find  the
peak in the featureless forest terrain and I did a bit of wandering  around,
all while breaking heavy trail. I finally stumbled onto the summit almost  2
hours later just at sunset (6.5 miles, 2400 ft, 5:50 hrs).  I  actually  had
fun skiing out my track to the road and there was a gorgeous  full  moon  to
add to the delight, but the road itself  was  as  annoyingly  flat  as  last
time.  Let\'s see if this time I can stick to  my  resolution  never  to  ski
this road again, despite several more peaks in the area.  Total:  13  miles,
2450 ft and 9 hrs.

Fay Pullen



