            'tr' => '
Taneum Point (3920+ ft) and Osborn Point (3880+ ft) - Frost Mtn Quad -
January 9, 2008

Worn out by exhausting trailbreaking and frustrated by  not  being  able  to
get anywhere in knee deep snow from the frequent  storms  of  the  past  few
weeks, I gave up on  the  backcountry  and  headed  for  groomed  snowmobile
country. I wasn\'t expecting much other than being  able  to  get  in  a  few
miles without breaking trail, but I ended up having a surprisingly  pleasant
tour.

I started from the Taneum Sno-Park (elev 2400 ft), 6 miles up Taneum  Cr  on
Road 33 from I-90 near Thorp. At first I thought I wasn\'t  going  to  escape
breaking trail even here as I was the first one to navigate the  6-8  inches
of fresh snow on the road in my Subaru on this Wednesday morning.  But  upon
reaching the Sno-Park, I discovered the snowmobile road  had  been  recently
groomed and only had a dusting of fresh snow.  As I have discovered  before,
much  to  my  amazement  and  puzzlement,  the  "trails"  are  groomed   for
snowmobiles more often than the roads are plowed for vehicles.

 In any event, once I made it to the Sno-Park, the skiing was perfect and  I
enjoyed actually being able to glide  along,  even  on  the  beginning  flat
road. About 1.5 miles in, I turned right up  a  road  marked  Cedar  Cr  and
began a steady climb for  another  1.5  miles  to  a  junction,  with  fresh
snowmobile tracks, that connects with  the  Elk  Heights  Sno-Park.  I  took
another left at 4 miles on the loop road to Osborn and Taneum  Points.  This
section was very nice as it meandered along the edge of the ridge with  good
views at both points.  Then, for some variety, after  Taneum  Pt  I  took  a
little crosscountry shortcut over a bump in the ridge to reconnect with  the
N section of the loop road. The terrain was  very  friendly  and  the  trail
breaking  wasn\'t  too  bad  leading  me  to  conclude  there  may  be   more
possibilities for off road travel in this area,  even  with  heavy  snowfall
elsewhere.

I did run into about a dozen or so snowmobiles in the  course  of  the  day.
Not enough to really be annoying, except for the  one  that  almost  ran  me
over. He came racing around a blind corner and  because  of  the  terrain  I
couldn\'t hear him coming until the last minute.  I jumped out of the way  in
time but he came within a couple feet of hitting  me.  What  an  ignominious
end to my outdoor career that would have been -  flattened  by  my  favorite
machine. One could argue that  it  was  my  own  fault  for  entering  their
territory and taking my chances. But then again,  I  could  just  as  easily
have been another snowmobile. If that had been the case I doubt a  collision
could have been avoided.

My entire route was groomed (except, of course the short crosscountry  bit).
And once back to the junction from the Elk  Heights  Sno-Park  is  was  even
freshly groomed since I had  been  on  it  in  the  morning.  Not  a  single
snowmobile track marred  its  surface.  Did  they  groom  it  just  for  me?
Whatever, I had a delicious smooth fast run down to Road  33,  probably  the
best road run I have had this season. I  then  had  a  flat  1.5  miles  the
remaining distance to the car but even that was "track" skiing at its  best.


The road out was still not plowed.

Total: 15.5 miles, 2050 ft and 6:20 hours

Fay Pullen







