Lone Tree Mtn (4640+ ft - 920P - Tower Rock Quad) - January 17, 2008

I really wanted to ski up Greenhorn Buttes on this day  but  I  was  stopped
very near the start of Road 77 by a small downed tree and  for  some  reason
the saw I usually carry in my car was missing.  So I went to Plan B.   Again
I was stopped by a downed tree at 2100 ft on Road 55 leading  to  Lone  Tree
Mtn, but by this elevation the snow was deep  enough  to  ski  so  I  didn\'t
mind.  There were a couple of inches of fresh powder over a crust that  made
for excellent road skiing and I made fast work  of  the  3.5  miles  to  the
junction with the Lone Tree Mtn Road.  I then took a spur left  thinking  it
would be more direct and faster than the circuitous main road. Yeah,  right!
Not only did the spur dead-end far from my objective but I proceeded to  get
completely twisted around (even using my GPS) and managed to take an  almost
more circuitous route. The visibility was such that I couldn\'t see  where  I
was going and ended up on a narrow steep ridge I  couldn\'t  easily  get  off
of.  A GPS will tell you what direction you should go but it won\'t tell  you
if it is possible to go in  that  direction.   I  couldn\'t  go  the  way  it
pointed because of the terrain. And so I wandered around for an  extra  hour
or so, eventually climbing a very steep icy slope on foot  to  get  back  on
route.

Once on the proper route I was able to follow the NE  ridge  easily  to  the
summit. But my troubles weren\'t over. I still had to get  down  and  I  sure
wasn\'t going down the way I came up. I probably should have  gone  down  the
road, but it was so long and so far out of the  way  that  I  just  couldn\'t
bring myself to do it.  And so  I  skied  straight  down  from  the  summit.
Despite tricky crust, steep sections and some mild brush, it wasn\'t a  total
disaster. I did get to see Lone Tree Lake. And once I hit the spur road  and
the main road it was a great ski down.

This was supposed to be a relatively short easy "Plan  B"  alternative,  but
it had turned out to be longer and  harder  than  I  had  anticipated  (this
frequently seems to  be  the  case).   And  to  make  matters  worse  I  had
forgotten my water bottle (don\'t ask!) and  so  had  no  liquid  refreshment
along.  I had remembered I had forgotten it (is that an oxymoron?)  about  a
mile into the trip but I wasn\'t going back for it. How long could this  trip
take - 3 or 4 hours? I could last that long.  But how about  6  hours?  That
was pushing it. By the time I reached the car I was  mighty  thirsty  and  I
downed the contents of the bottle in one big  delicious  gulp.  Total:  11.4
miles, 2800 ft and 6 hrs.

Greenhorn Buttes (4825 ft - 385P - Greenhorn  Buttes  Quad)  -  January  22,
2008

The next week I was back with saw  in  hand.  By  cutting  through  3  small
downed trees I was able to drive Road 77 to 1840 ft to where  a  very  large
downed tree stopped me.  I hadn\'t gotten as far as I would  have  liked  but
it would have to do. I was able to ski right  from  the  car,  although  the
snow cover was very thin to start. It was again a few inches of powder  over
a crust - perfect for road skiing with  very  little  trailbreaking.   Which
was a good thing as the road was quite gentle, took forever to get  anywhere
and this turned out to be a very long trip indeed.

