dark I would be fine. As I have mentioned many times  I  really  don\'t  mind
skiing down a road by headlamp. In fact I rather like it.

There had been no melting since my last trip and I was able use my  previous
tracks and I skied the 6 miles to the Iron Cr Butte turnoff in 2:50 hrs,  15
minutes faster than before. I skied the spur to the base of a clear-cut  and
skinned up it to the open south  summit  then  followed  the  ridge  to  the
wooded north summit. The north summit was definitely higher. I had a  lovely
ski down the clear-cut before needing my headlamp for the rest  of  the  way
out. The night sky was clear  but  the  moon  had  not  yet  risen.  What  a
difference 2 days makes. Having been over the track 2  more  times  made  it
noticeably faster down the gentle road than before. Total: 14.5 miles,  2500
ft, 6:40 hrs.

Big Bottom Butte (2664 ft - 1544P - Vanson Pk Quad) and Glenoma BM (2411  ft
- 611P - Cowlitz Falls Quad) - February 7, 2008

The same big dump of snow down to low elevations that has made  it  hard  to
get to higher peaks, made it possible to ski up these two lower ones. I  was
able to ski right from the car up a gated spur road  after  parking  on  the
shoulder of Anderson Road, elev 1000 ft.  It was  above  freezing  with  the
snow wet, slushy and sticky enough I didn\'t need skins all day despite  some
areas being quite steep.  In an hour I reached the 1800 ft saddle  and  went
right to the towers on Big Bottom Butte  (2.7  miles,  1700  ft,  2hrs).  No
views as it was now snowing and blowing  and  I  couldn\'t  see  a  thing.  I
quickly retreated to the more protected saddle to clean  my  glasses.  While
wiping the left lens it came out in my hand.  The  frame  screw  had  worked
loose, fallen out and now, of course, was hopelessly lost. Darn. Due to  the
low light conditions I was wearing my regular glasses. I now switched to  my
sunglasses. I would deal with how to get my regular glasses  functional  for
the drive home in the dark later.

From the saddle I went in the opposite direction of Big Bottom, following  a
road that didn\'t show on my map and that I hoped would  get  me  to  Glenoma
BM. What it did was climb around an initial bump to a large  flat  clear-cut
where I was able to follow a series of roads to  where  I  could  enter  the
trees and take the broad west ridge to the summit (5.7  miles,  2500  ft,  4
hrs.). I had a pretty good run, for the most part, back to car where it  was
raining.  I still had to put the lens back in my glasses. My  first  thought
was to use a screw  from  my  sunglasses  but  it  needed  a  tiny  Phillips
screwdriver, which of course I didn\'t have (my regular glasses used  a  tiny
normal screwdriver which could be faked by a knife  blade  in  a  pinch).  I
ended up taping the lens in place. It wasn\'t pretty  but  it  got  me  home,
where I have proper tools and spare screws. Total: 9 miles, 2550  ft  and  6
hrs.

