From the saddle I went in the opposite direction of Big Bottom, following  a
road that didn\'t show on my map and that I hoped would  get  me  to  Glenoma
BM. What it did was climb around an initial bump to a large  flat  clear-cut
where I was able to pick up a series of roads to  where  I  could  take  the
broad west ridge through the trees to the summit  (5.7  miles,  2500  ft,  4
hrs.).  I had a pretty good run, for the most part, in  my  tracks  back  to
car where it was raining.  I still had to put the lens back in  my  glasses.
My first thought was to use a screw from my sunglasses but it needed a  tiny
Phillips screwdriver, which of course I  didn\'t  have  (my  regular  glasses
used a slotted screwdriver which could at least be faked by  a  knife  blade
in a pinch). I ended up taping the lens in place. It wasn\'t  pretty  but  it
got me home, where I had proper tools and  spare  screws.  Total:  9  miles,
2550 ft and 6 hrs.

Burley Mtn (5304 ft - 1184P) and Tower Rock (3335 ft -  95P)  -  Tower  Rock
Quad - February 14, 2008

I had to wait  for  the  snow  to  consolidate  from  recent  storms  before
attempting this peak and consolidate it did to  the  point  of  frozen  rain
crust. At least that meant I wouldn\'t have  any  trailbreaking,  although  I
did have to use skins right away. I started at the junction of Roads 76  and
7605, elev 1273. I could possibly have driven a mile farther  up  Road  7605
to 1900 ft (another vehicle had) but didn\'t think it worth the risk  on  the
steep icy road, especially considering I had passed  a  logging  truck  that
had slid on a slick patch and crashed into the snow  bank  on  Hwy  7  above
Morton on the drive over.

I have long wanted to stand  on  the  top  of  Tower  Rock,  which  is  very
impressive looking from the north but gentle on the  south,  and  thought  I
could work that into this trip. At about 4 miles where  a  switchback  comes
closest to the Rock, I  left  the  road  and  headed  into  the  woods.  The
contours indicated a fairly steep hillside, but other than the  crossing  of
2  ravines  that  required  brief  step  kicking,  the  terrain  was  easily
traversed on skis. I left my skis below the south side and kicked  steps  up
the final hundred feet to the open summit (5 miles, 2400 ft, 3 hrs). On  the
west end of the ridge were several memorial crosses. Care was  needed  along
this slightly corniced ridge, as one misstep would mean a plunge of  over  a
thousand feet down the sheer north face.

From the Rock I  continued  cross-country  south  up  the  wooded  ridge  to
intersect the road again higher up at 4000 ft. From this point on there  was
enough fresh snow over the crust (2-3 inches) for very nice skiing, that  is
until I left the road to strike out directly for  Burley\'s  summit.  The  NW
ridge was wind scoured down to a very hard  icy  crust  that  my  ski  edges
barely held on. I reached the protection of the historic Burley Mtn  Lookout
at 4:30 (8 miles, 4700 ft, 6 hrs) and was blown away (no pun intended as  it
wasn\'t that windy) by the superb 360 degree view.  This has  to  be  one  of
the best viewpoints in all of the South Cascades. NW was Mt Rainier,  SW  Mt
St Helens and SE Mt Adams, all bigger than life.  Several  plaques  sticking
out of the snow identified many of the peaks in-between.

I found friendlier slopes than the NW ridge to return to road and  even  got
in a few turns before a fun fast run down the road itself until  I  ran  out
of the fresh snow. I had actually been quite worried  about  descending  the
crusty road, but other than a short transition zone  that  never  got  above
freezing and required continuous snowplowing, I was happy  to  discover  the
lower road had thawed and softened to the point where  it  too  made  for  a
pleasant run down - the last bit, of course, by headlamp.  Total: 16  miles,
4700 ft and 9 hrs.

Fay Pullen





