lovely woods to soon intersect a rough new  looking  muddy  road  coming  up
from the north.  From here the peak appears quite steep with  mossy  cliffs.
I stuck with the road which, unlikely as it appeared from  below,  continued
switchbacking  up  the  west  side  then  circled  past  the  cliffs  as  it
deteriorated to an overgrown cat track and climbed the south side almost  to
the very top. What luck. Without this track the brush would have  been  very
unpleasant. As I was descending the road, I  heard  a  motor  coming  uphill
toward me. Oh no. Caught again.  But I had  encountered  no  no  trespassing
signs although I was clearly on private property. Soon  a  young  man  on  a
quad appeared followed by  his  father  on  foot.  They  were  the  property
owners, had seen me from below and wanted to know what I  was  up  to.  They
were actually very friendly and we  had  a  pleasant  conversation.  When  I
explained that I was just out  hiking  and  peakbagging,  they  even  seemed
pleased that I appreciated the beauty of their surroundings and  invited  me
to start from their home next time. I doubt  I  will  ever  be  back  but  I
appreciated the offer. 1.5 miles, 760 ft  and  1:18  hrs  including  the  15
minute conversation.

I drove Falls Road several miles to a  junction  with  a  sign  for  Cowlitz
Falls Dam and parked. Up to now the weather had been good, but as I  started
up Cowlitz 2, it began to  rain  lightly.  I  crossed  an  open  field  with
strange abandoned structures to a power line road and followed  it  a  short
distance until I found a reasonable spot to  head  uphill  through  moderate
brush. I crossed a snowy road 2 times but it seemed more expedient  to  just
continue uphill until I hit the nondistinct  summit  area.  By  the  time  I
returned it was raining harder and the brush was all wet. 1.1 miles, 630  ft
and 1:24 hrs RT.

