Vanson Pk 1 (2320+ ft - 560P) & Vanson Pk 2 (1560+ ft - 640P)  -  Vanson  Pk
Quad; and Rainy BM (2040+ ft - 760P - Kiona Pk Quad) - February 19, 2008

Sometimes these little blobs can be deceiving. They look so easy on the  map
but by the time I got done with these three  I  had  accumulated  some  14.5
miles, 4350 ft and 9:15 hrs (not counting transitions), a full  day\'s  work.
Since there had been a fair amount of lowland melting of snow, I  brought  a
bike along on this trip plus skis, just in case.

First up was Vanson 1.  I started from the gated logging road on a bike  and
got to a road junction at 1880 ft before  hitting  continuous  snow.  I  had
carried skis up on the bike and skied the rest  of  the  way  to  top.  Even
though it was quite warm,  it was still early enough that snow open  to  the
night sky that had frozen overnight due to radiation  cooling  had  not  yet
thawed. Protected areas were already getting  soft.  No  Views.  5.5  miles,
1610 ft and 2:30 hrs.

For Vanson 2  I had planned on biking a gated logging road I had noticed  on
my last visit that went to the base of the peak on the north side. But  when
I got to the road the gate was open and obviously in heavy  use.   A  loaded
logging truck was nearby and a fast moving dump truck almost took me out  as
it careened onto the main road without even stopping to see  if  anyone  was
coming. No way was I going to bike that road.  Instead I parked at a  gravel
pit along the main road directly opposite the summit  and  walked  across  a
vast wasteland clear-cut. Part way across I ran smack into a  curious  high-
fenced plot with some sort of protected planting. Even though it was in  the
way and I had to walk around it, it wasn\'t all bad as the  fence  line  made
for better walking than the clear-cut.

I could hear and see active logging to my left at the  base  of  Vanson  2\'s
east peak and logging trucks were moving to and fro along  the  road  I  had
originally intended to bike. I was afraid someone might spot me  and  object
to my being near their operation, but once I crossed  the  road,  I  entered
new growth forest of 15-20 ft high  trees  and  I  was  no  longer  visible.
Travel here was not too bad with many  pathways  between  the  young  trees.
Once on the ridge, I followed it to the  high  point.   Nice  views  if  you
ignored the wastelands. I ran into a road just before the summit  coming  up
from the south. If one could figure out where this road came from  it  would
be possible to bike all the way to the top. However, I could  also  hear  an
active logging operation on that side. Poor Vanson 2. Soon it would  be  one
continuous clear-cut.

From the summit, I peered to the east peak and I feared it might be  higher.
 According to the map it was not.  Still I felt I had to go over  to  it  to
make sure. It was father and more dangerous than it looked,  but  the  first
part was also quite fun as I followed a rough path along  the  narrow  rocky
crest that still had some trees. The problem was the closer  I  got  to  the
east peak the closer  I  got  to  the  upper  part  of  the  active  logging
operation. When I began running into freshly cut trees right on  the  ridge,
I began to get worried. When I practically stumbled  over  a  huge  chainsaw
and a gas can, I knew I should get out of there. All  I  needed  was  to  be
crushed by a newly felled tree because no one knew I was there. But  nothing
came crashing down and I saw no one. I believe I hit the  time  (3:00)  just
as the loggers were quitting for the day. Had I been a little earlier, I  am
sure I would have run into someone or something worse.  I  did  get  to  the
high point of the east peak but it was not higher than the west peak  so  it
was all for naught. I think it looked higher  because  it  still  had  large
trees on it.  2.2 miles, 1050 ft and 2:25 hrs.

Even though it was now after 4:00 I thought I had time  for  Rainy  BM.  The
weather was holding and it was  close  to  the  full  moon.  I  did  take  a
headlamp though. I started on bike from the gated  logging  road  off  Kiona
Road, elev 840 ft, but only got to 1440 ft before being stopped  by  a  long
snow patch. I hadn\'t expected snow so soon. This  time  I  didn\'t  bring  my
skis,  not  that  they  would  have  helped  that  much  as  the  snow   was
intermittent for the next mile and when the snow did get deeper  there  were
too many obstacles. Snowshoes would have been nice but I  didn\'t  have  them
along.  I continued on foot.   At  a  broad  saddle  at  1760  ft  the  road
descended slightly, then climbed a bit to end in  an  old  clear-cut.   Here
things deteriorated to horrendous postholing in knee deep and  deeper  slush
through logging slash. It took over an hour to go the  last  .3  mile.  Then
just below the summit I ran into a good road. I have no idea where  it  came
from. Maybe I missed a turn somewhere  or  it  came  in  from  the  east.  I
reached the summit at 6:40. This was probably the best viewpoint but  all  I
saw were the lights of civilization along Hwy 12.  The  full  moon  kept  me
company for the 2 hour trip out.  7 miles, 1680 ft and 4:20 hrs.

Fay Pullen





