            'tr' => '
Grass Mtn (4382 ft - 902P) and Grass Mtn #2 (3980 ft - 380P) - Cyclone Cr
Quad - January 31, 2008

Record mountain snowfall, lowland snow with  resulting  traffic  woes,  pass
closures, avalanche warnings - what\'s a backcountry skier to do?  Ski  areas
close to home that are normally not skiable, that\'s  what,  like  this  tour
barely 10 miles east of Enumclaw that turned out to  be  a  real  gem  (well
mostly). Grass Mtn itself does  often  have  enough  snow  to  ski  but  you
normally can\'t get to it as the access roads on  private  timber  lands  are
gated at Hwy 410. To ski right from the highway requires unusually  low  and
heavy snow.

I began with a reconnaissance trip on January 29. I  had  a  choice  of  two
access roads, one from gate 1494 and one  from  gate  1460.  Gate  1494  was
open, the road plowed  and  an  active  logging  operation  in  progress  so
scratch that one. On to gate 1460. That road was also plowed  but  the  gate
was closed and there was enough fresh snow to  make  the  road  skiable.  In
fact the skiing was great. I followed the plowed road for 2 miles to a  spur
road left that climbed steeply toward Grass Mtn ridge. This road had  a  few
downed trees but they were no problem. The snow was fantastic  light  powder
and no great impediment to breaking trail, but it snowed all  day  long  and
the wind was ferocious. At times I was almost blown away. I called it a  day
at a highpoint of 4200 ft on a small bump and had a fantastic run back  down
the  road.  In  many  places  my  uphill  tracks  were  already   completely
obliterated by the fresh snow and wind. I did determine there was  a  cutoff
road, that did not show on my map, from my highpoint to the main  Grass  Mtn
ridge. 10.5 miles, 3000 ft and 6:45 hrs for this day.

Now that I had a route figured out, I returned two days later determined  to
get all the way to both Grass Mtns. I knew it would be a very long day so  I
got an early start. There was more snow at  the  gate  than  last  time  but
unfortunately it was very wet and heavy. This posed no problem until I  left
the plowed road where I soon determined trailbreaking  could  be  an  issue.
Fortunately as I climbed higher the snow got better and more windpacked  and
trailbreaking easier. There  was  little  sign  of  my  previous  tracks.  I
reached the cutoff road to the ridge at 12:00.

 It was again windy, though not quite as bad as  before,  and  again  snowed
heavily most of the day. I wasn\'t sure what it would be like on  the  ridge,
but it turned out to be absolutely delightful.  The  road  wandered  up  and
down along the ridge  through  a  corridor  of  mature  trees  that  offered
protection from the wind and was much more scenic than  expected.  The  snow
was wonderful also, fun to make fresh tracks through, and I greatly  enjoyed
this section of the trip. I reached the  tower  on  Grass  Mtn  at  1:45  (7
miles, 3300 ft, 5 hrs).

If I had ended the trip here  it  would  have  been  a  most  pleasant  trip
indeed. But it was still early, an untrod summit called and I  have  trouble
knowing when to quit, so on I went. I dropped directly off the  summit  down
the initially steep ridge on a supposed road but you could hardly  tell  one
was there. This section was open, windy, lightly corniced  and  fluted,  and
what with the heavy snowfall, wind and low visibility made  for  challenging
skiing. I could barely see where I was going. I made it down to the  gentler
ridge below and tried to stay on it, but in this section the ridge road  was
not all that obvious and at some point I got off onto a spur that  ended  up
going downhill to the left and then went the wrong direction. By the time  I
discovered my error I didn\'t want to reverse. I had to drop to a  low  point
of 3600 ft at some point anyway, so I just kept dropping XC until  I  hit  a
lower road which then traversed to the 3600 ft saddle. After a  short  climb
I came upon a good road coming in from the right that led the  rest  of  the
way to the fantastically rimed tower on Grass Mtn #2 (10.2  miles,  4000  ft
and 7:30 hrs).

It was now 4:30 and I had an awfully long ways to go to get  out.  I  had  a
good run off Grass #2 and nice track skiing along  the  ridge  and  traverse
side road until I came to the end of my tracks  at  which  point  I  had  to
break fresh trail until I hit Road 5200. Here I made  the  fateful  decision
to continue downhill rather than climb 500 ft back to the ridge  and  my  in
tracks. Bad mistake. But I was getting tired, the lure of  gravity  was  too
great and my map showed a series of roads that would get me back  to  my  up
route on a lower traverse.

I did have a good run down Road 5200 until I hit  the  junction  and  turned
onto Road 6200. Here is where it all fell apart. This  road  is  maddeningly
flat and took forever to get anywhere. Add to  that  trailbreaking  in  ever
increasingly wet heavy snow and I swear it felt like I was going uphill  the
entire 4.2 miles despite the fact that the road lost close to 1000  feet  in
elevation. At one  point  I  became  so  frustrated  that  I  cut  the  last
switchback, despite having to wallow through snowy brush on  foot,  just  to
break the monotony and use different muscles. I lost all sense of  time  yet
still felt the hours slip away. Then I discovered the last road  that  would
connect with my  up  route  no  longer  goes  through  but  is  blocked  and
impassible. Probably the bridge over Cyclone Cr is  out  and  has  been  for
while as the road remnant past the block was terribly overgrown.  I  had  no
choice but to reverse and follow Road 6200 out to Hwy 410. I  soon  came  to
the active logging operation and freshly plowed portion  of  the  road  that
made the last Â½ mile unskiable. I thought I was also going to have  to  walk
410 the 1.2 miles back to my car but there was enough snow on  the  shoulder
to ski. I wonder what the few cars that  drove  by  thought  of  that  crazy
person skiing along the highway at that late hour and I kept hoping a  State
Trooper would come along and offer me ride. No such luck. I reached  my  car
at 10:30. At least I had a short drive home.

20.5 miles, 4400 ft and 13:30 hrs.

Fay Pullen

