            'subdir' => '2008-03-04-rampart',
            'title' => 'Rampart Ridge (4100 ft), Cougar Rock (3760+ ft) and Mildred Point (5935 ft) - Mt Rainier West Quad - March 4, 2008',
            'tr' => '
Rampart Ridge (4100 ft), Cougar Rock (3760+ ft) and Mildred Point (5935 ft)
- Mt Rainier West Quad - March 4, 2008

I have long wanted to ski the length of Rampart Ridge all  the  way  to  Van
Trump Park.  Conditions had to be just right to give it a go - enough  fresh
snow down low to make skiing possible but not  so  much  as  to  make  trail
breaking up high a chore.  With fresh snow  and  forecast  sunshine,  I  had
thought to ski at Paradise on this day, but when I arrived at  Longmire  the
road was closed and not scheduled to open until 11 am.  Since  it  was  only
9:30 and I really didn\'t want to waste an hour and a half waiting around,  I
decided this was my opportunity for Rampart Ridge. The snow conditions  were
reasonably good with 2-3 inches new at Longmire and nearly a foot  up  high,
but the promised clearing never materialized.  It  snowed  lightly  all  day
(and night) long.

I quickly located the start of  the  trail  to  Rampart  Ridge  and  had  no
trouble sticking to it all the way to the crest. From then on it was  pretty
much lost in the snow, but  the  going  was  for  the  most  part  easy  and
pleasant along the ridge. I reached the high  point  of  4100  ft  at  11:45
where I removed my skins for the next downhill section. I  had  a  nice  run
down to a low point of 3800 ft and then began a long contour to the  top  of
Cougar Rock. In retrospect, I really shouldn\'t have taken  this  side  trip.
It looked so close on the map, but in reality  was  much  farther  and  took
much more time than anticipated as I was forced around the head of  a  steep
ravine. Along the way I looked for the Wonderland Trail, which was to be  my
exit route. I had to cross it at some point but I  never  recognized  it.  I
reached Cougar Rock at 1:30.

From Cougar Rock, I reapplied skins and ascended directly back to the  ridge
following it north along once again easy terrain,  but  trail  breaking  was
becoming more of a problem. It wasn\'t that the snow was so deep as  that  it
had a strange compactness to it that occasionally caused  my  skis  to  dive
under it and become trapped which then took effort to extricate.  Powder  it
was not.  And although pleasant this ridge is  long.  It  seemed  to  go  on
forever. I reached Point 4952 at 3:45 and left my skins on for the 200  foot
descent to the saddle below. Past this saddle was a  steep  400  ft  section
before I finally broke out into the open meadows of  Van  Trump  Park.  Even
though visibility was limited, it was a  lovely  place.  I  reached  Mildred
Point at 6:00, a wee bit later than I had planned. Good  thing  I  had  just
recharged my headlamp. I was certainly going to need it - once again.

I had a good run off Mildred Point and down Van Trump Park and it  was  even
surprisingly good down the steep section of ridge during which I  still  had
light to see. And then I was confronted with the  climb  back  up  to  Point
4952. I stubbornly decided not to put skins on  again  thinking  that  would
save time and effort. It did not and I  needlessly  struggled  a  good  half
hour up the 200 feet exhausting myself in the process. Once on top,  though,
the ski down the ridge in my uphill  tracks  was  delightful,  even  in  the
dark. That is until my tracks diverged  toward  Cougar  Rock  and  I  headed
straight for my exit route down  the  Wonderland  Trail.  It  was  somewhere
around here that the good skiing ended.  A  combination  of  worsening  snow
conditions, fatigue, no tracks to follow anymore and less  friendly  terrain
all contributed.

At some point I did cross my contour tracks to Cougar Rock again.  At  least
I thought they were my tracks. Strange thing was  they  weren\'t  ski  tracks
anymore, they were snowshoe tracks.  My  first  thought  was  "great".  Some
snowshoers had come up the Wonderland Trail and would show me the way  down.
 Then I realized they had  come  up  the  Rampart  Ridge  Trail,  were  just
following my tracks and had returned the same way they had  come.  I  had  a
bit a chuckle wondering how long they followed my tracks  before  coming  to
the conclusion that this was one crazy skier!

Once I crossed the snowshoe tracks I continued downhill trying to  find  the
Wonderland Trail. I missed completely and ended up on  very  steep  terrain.
At one point I had to remove skis and boot down.  Somewhere around  3200  ft
I ran into the trail and followed it to the Paradise  Road.  Somehow  I  had
thought it would connect  directly  to  the  Rampart  Ridge  Trail,  but  it
doesn\'t. It crosses the road and continues on the other  side  to  Longmire.
At this point I had had enough and just walked the  now  gated  road  to  my
car, which I reached at 10:00. Longmire was pretty much deserted and  I  was
the last car in the parking lot.

Total: 14 miles, 4100 ft and 12 hrs.

Fay Pullen

