            'title' => 'Morton Blobs',
            'tr' => 'For those interested in such things, yesterday I did these four blobs near Morton. No pictures as the weather was generally bad, though not as bad as I had expected; just intermittent snow/rain showers. Here are brief descriptions. More details on the route map.
Cottlers Rock (2760+ ft - 1440P - Morton Quad)  I really lucked out on this one. The road was plowed all the way to the ridge and first summit where there was a good 2-3 feet of snow. I passed 2 gates but both were open. They may possibly always be open. I am not sure. Part at least is in the Cowlitz Wildlife Area and I think open to the public. I even passed an official Peterman Hill Trailhead with a genuine trail. I must check it out some day but it was much too far from my objective to be useful for that.  Cottlers has multiple summits. After driving over the first, I parked and hiked over the other 4 through mushy snow and debris. My vote for the highest is the southern most but it is hard to tell. They are probably all within 20 ft of each other.
Moss BM (1600+ ft - 640P - Mossyrock Quad)  This was a fairly easy bike ride with no snow except some of the roads shown on my map no longer exist or barely exist. I am sure there is another route on good roads all the way starting from another point somewhere but it would be longer. I made the mistake of taking a dead-end spur to the summit ridge too soon and having to walk debris strewn woods to the top where I then found a road.  If I had stayed on the main road a little while longer I could have biked all the way to the top. 5.7 miles, 1000 ft and 2 hrs.
Mossyrock Quad 1 (2440+ ft - 680P) and Bellicum Pk (2280+ ft - 480P) - Mossyrock Quad.  These two gave me more trouble and took longer than anticipated, but only because I ran into more snow than thought and had neither snowshoes nor skis along on my bike (dumb, dumb!).  For Mossyrock 1 I was able to avoid some snow by sticking to the woods. The south side of the summit had fresh logging cuttings and debris strewn all over and was completely impenetrable. Fortunately the summit itself was clear although I had to do an end-run around to get to it. It was all snow all the way to Bellicum with no way to avoid it. I tried a spur road that looked shorter on the map but I don\'t think it was and probably should have stuck to the main road. I ended up eventually back on it anyway. It continued around the south side of Bellicum to switchback to the summit ridge but took too long to do so I went straight up through dense woods.  This peak is fairly steep near the top and has some rocky areas.  10 miles, 2600 ft and 5:15 hrs.
Fling Mtn (2880+ ft - 1720P - Morton Quad)  For completion I have included my route up this blob although I did it in January. I just never got around to writing it up. I was able to ski right from the car. Somehow I got off on a good looking spur road that then deadened below the radio tower. Rather than retreat, I forced a way to the tower road and continued on my way. I had to leave skis just below the summit and boot through thick woods to the top. It was a nice ski back down the road. 7 miles, 1300 ft and 3 hrs.
Fay',
