            'tr' => '
Coal Cr Bluff (4720+ ft - 400P) and Ohanapecosh Hot Springs Quad 3 (4320+
ft - 440P) - Ohanapecosh Hot Springs Quad - March 18, 2008

I really thought this day was going to be  a  disaster.  It  rained  heavily
most of the drive to Packwood. Then I had  to  change  plans  when  I  could
drive no farther than the Skate Cr Sno-Park at a miserably low elevation  of
1600 ft. That was too far away from the peaks along Road 47 I had  hoped  to
ski up. So it was on to Plan B. I got no higher  on  Road  46  before  being
stopped by snow at an elevation of 1520 ft, but at least here  my  objective
two peaks were closer and within  striking  range.  It  was  still  raining,
heavily, as I prepared to start and things were looking very dismal  indeed.
The snow level was supposed to be around 3500 feet and I so did not want  to
ski up 2000 feet in the pouring rain. I very nearly gave  up  on  the  whole
day, but after the long drive and with the cost of gas these days I  had  to
get something for my money. Miraculously, as soon as I stepped  outside  the
car and into my skis the rain let up. That is not to say it  was  completely
dry the rest of the day, but it never really rained hard again  and  was  so
much better than it could have been. I didn\'t even get very wet.

We have now entered that annoying time of year where there is too much  snow
low down on the approach roads for a vehicle to get through but  not  enough
consistently for good skiing.  So for the first 2 miles the snow was  patchy
with several long bare spots that required removal of skis.  Once  past  the
switchback at 2000  ft  elevation,  though,  the  snow  remained  consistent
though very slushy. At 5 miles and 2800 ft elevation (2:40 hrs) I  left  the
road, put on skins and headed up through pleasant open forest on  the  broad
ridge to the wooded summit of Ohanapecosh 3 (2800  ft,  4:20  hrs).   I  had
entered the fresh snow zone but the snow remained very  wet  and  heavy.  At
this point I decided to try to follow  the  ridge  line  to  Coal  Cr  Bluff
rather than descend back to the road, even though I knew the  route  finding
would be challenging, as that would save me 1000 feet of elevation loss  and
regain.

I had a reasonable descent to a low  point  of  3800  ft  elevation   before
entering rather confusing up and down terrain. Somehow I got  on  the  wrong
side of a deep ravine and had  to  climb  up  alongside  it  a  ways  before
finding a  way  across.  Then  began  a  very  steep  200  ft  section  that
culminated in having to kick steps past a rock wall.  Once  above  this  the
ridge gentled and made for very nice skiing all the way  to  the  summit  of
Coal Cr Bluff (4100 ft, 7:50 hrs).  There would have been  good  views  from
this peak but it was snowing lightly and I could see  nothing.  It  was  now
7:30 and would be dark soon. I seem to be making a habit lately of  reaching
my summits right at sunset, partly because of continually later  than  hoped
for starts and partly because I am always trying to fit  the  most  possible
into a day.

I didn\'t know what I would run into on a direct descent  back  to  the  road
but it turned out to be quite reasonable. The beginning even had  some  open
glades with snow good enough for a few turns -  at  least  until  it  turned
dark  enough  to  require  a  headlamp.  Lower  the  terrain  did   steepen,
particularly near Purcell Cr, at which point I  kicked  steps  down.  I  had
been worried about finding a way across this creek but luckily hit it  right
at a snow covered log bridge and had no problem. The rest of  the  ski  down
the road was less than fast considering the soggy snow, a very  gentle  road
and several ski removals for walking bare patches. Okay, so the  skiing  was
not all that great but the trip itself was. I just love it when  I  can  put
together an unknown route, especially a loop, and make it work.

Total: 15 miles, 4150 ft and 11:20 hrs.

Fay Pullen

