            'title' => 'Divide Ridge (4878 ft - 638P), Huckleberry Mtn (4903 ft - 743P) and Nagrom Quad 1 (3080+ ft - 400P) - Nagrom Quad - March 22, 2008',
            'tr' => 'Divide Ridge (4878 ft - 638P), Huckleberry Mtn (4903 ft - 743P) and Nagrom Quad 1 (3080+ ft - 400P) - Nagrom Quad - March 22, 2008
Even though these peaks are in my back yard, I just never got around to climbing them. Part of the reason is that the access Road 7010 (elev 1870 ft) is gated at Road 70 (the Greenwater River Road) from December to May and closed to motorized vehicles to protect wildlife. This means snowmobiles are not allowed, which should make it very appealing for skiing. The problem is this area doesn\'t get that much lowland snow in a normal year and it is a very long way to the good stuff higher on the ridges. But this is anything but a normal year and for this trip snow started right at the gate. There were a few short bare patches to work through near the beginning but they were expected and not a real problem. Other than that the snow conditions were almost ideal for good road travel - consolidated enough so I didn\'t sink in but soft enough so my waxless skis worked well.
After 2.5 miles I took a right onto Road 7012. Although my main goal was to climb Divide Ridge and Huckleberry Mtn, Nagrom 1 was more or less on the way and so I took a 3 mile, 400 ft and 1:30 hr RT detour to ski up that forested peak before returning to Road 7012.  At 9.5 miles and 5 hrs I reached the 4200 ft saddle between Huckleberry Mtn and Divide Ridge and gazed into the forbidden Green River Watershed. Inviting clearcuts were all around that would provide many possibilities for very nice skiing indeed if that was all one had in mind. But I had summits to climb, first of which was Divide Ridge. I followed a spur road to its end under an interesting pinnacle, and then went up a fairly steep slope to the summit ridge. Here I was met with a surprise. What had appeared from a distance as an easy wooded ridge, turned out to be narrow and rocky with very steep slopes on either side. I had to leave skis, get out the ice axe and kick steps on the north slope. It took the better part of an hour to slowly work my way along and below the crest to the 4878 ft survey point at the east end marked on the map. This turned out to be a small open knoll in the trees but I am convinced it is not the highest point. Several of the rocky pinnacles before it appeared higher and I climbed the two most likely contenders just to make sure.
Back at the saddle I picked up another spur road that curved around Point 4758 to dead end on the south side. From here I climbed XC up to the ridge and followed it some 1.5 miles through pleasant forest to the open summit of Huckleberry Mtn (13 miles, 4800 ft and 8:40 hrs. I had an absolutely wonderful ski off this peak through open trees where several inches of powder snow were still preserved. I soon picked up Road 7010 below. This road went for miles and miles in long switchbacks but ended up also being a delightful run down. It was getting late enough in the day that sun softened snow was beginning to set up, however it was so solid and so smooth and the grade so gentle that the skiing was just fast enough to be fun but not so fast as to be treacherous. It took less than an hour to zip down the 5 miles to close my loop as I continued to hit conditions just right all day long. I even almost made it to car before dark, but things slowed the last 2.5 miles as the snow softened and became slower and the road flattened with those annoying bare spots to deal with. Still, I only needed my headlamp for 30 minutes, a big improvement over many recent trips.
Total: 21 miles, 4900 ft and 11 hrs.      Fay Pullen

