            'tr' => '
Osborne Mtn (5051 ft - 371P) and Sawtooth Ridge (5323 ft - 523P) -  Sawtooth
Ridge Quad, April 3, 2008

As I have mentioned many times before, I am always forgetting things. It  is
getting so bad that when I start each trip I now ask myself,  "What  have  I
forgotten this time?" It doesn\'t seem to do any good,  though,  as  I  still
forget something. On this occasion I left my map in the  car.  You  think  I
would have noticed right away as I always have my map in a  case  around  my
neck and I refer to it often. But I didn\'t, and by the time I  did,  it  was
too late to go back for it. Under normal circumstances, this  wouldn\'t  have
been a total disaster as I also have my GPS along  with  maps  of  the  area
loaded onto a data card. But I had just returned from a trip to  Albuquerque
and had forgotten to change out the New Mexico card for the Washington  one.
 So two errors conspired together to leave me  with  no  reference  maps  at
all. The only thing I had to guide  me  was  my  memory  which  this  entire
discourse has just shown is not that reliable.

I have been checking on this trip for the last month or so each time  hoping
I could drive farther up the road and each time  being  stopped  at  exactly
the same place - the end of the plowed road near Teeley Cr. The  way  things
are going this spring I figured it would take till summer for  the  road  to
melt out enough to do me any good. So  this  time  I  decided  to  bite  the
bullet and just do it even though that meant starting  lower  than  I  would
have liked. Several snowmobiles were ahead of me,  which  might  be  helpful
with the recent new snow. After .7 mile on Road 52 I turned right onto  Road
84 and after another 1.5 miles onto Road 8410. The good  news  was  that  no
snowmobiles had been on this road and I would have peace and quiet. The  bad
news was that no snowmobiles had been on this  road  and  I  would  have  to
break trail after all.

After cutting a couple a switchbacks, I followed the road  into  the  Teeley
Cr basin where there were several inviting clearcuts and views  of  imposing
Sawtooth Ridge and Mt Rainier. I soon lost the road  and  couldn\'t  remember
enough of where it went to find it again so just went up  a  large  clearcut
toward the saddle in the ridge south of  Osborne  Mtn.  The  clearcut  ended
before the ridge and in the trees I misjudged where the saddle  was,  got  a
bit confused and ended up on the east ridge higher  than  I  wanted  to  be.
Once I crossed the south ridge I entered another clearcut and could see  the
road below me. Rather than descend to it I continued to follow the  corniced
east ridge to the wooded summit (6.5 miles, 3200 ft, 5:20 hrs).

I skied directly off the summit to  the  road  below  following  it  to  the
saddle and beyond until it began to veer away  from  my  intended  route  to
Sawtooth Ridge. There was good skiing in this section. I knew I had  to  get
to the south side of Sawtooth Ridge as the north side is very  cliffy.  This
entailed traversing steep slopes below the cliffs to  Bertha  May  Lake  and
then climbing the rib between that  lake  and  Granite  Lake  to  the  ridge
crest. This went well although slowly as I wandered around  finding  my  way
and breaking trail. Up here there was a good foot of new  snow  that  varied
from wet and slushy in sunny  areas  to  almost  powder  in  more  protected
places. Once on the ridge it  took  another  hour  to  traverse  below  some
wicked looking pinnacles. I was glad I didn\'t have  to  climb  any  of  them
when the summit turned out to be a gentle open point  and  I  easily  kicked
steps the last little bit to the top (10 miles, 4800 ft, 9 hrs).  It  helped
to have the summit waypoint marked on my GPS.

The trip out started well then steadily deteriorated.  The  snow  was  still
reasonable on the open traverse to where I crossed the  ridge  but  I  could
feel it was already beginning to ice over as the sun lowered in the sky.  It
remained soft in the trees down to the lake and I even got in a  few  turns.
From this point on things went from bad to  worse.  Rather  than  follow  my
tracks uphill all the way back to the road near the saddle, I  opted  for  a
more "direct" route downhill. I figured I couldn\'t miss the road and I  also
had the "breadcrumb" track on my GPS to head for, but it was just a line  on
a blank screen with no map features and every time I headed directly  toward
it, it seemed I had to go uphill. Without a map  I  got  very  confused  and
ended up wandering around quite a bit as it was now dark.  At  one  point  I
came to a large open area that at the time I thought was a  clearcut  but  I
later realized was Pothole Lake. I also had two ravines to get  across  that
I didn\'t know were there. By the time I reached  the  road  my  worst  fears
were realized when the soft snow had turned to that which  I  dread  most  -
breakable crust. I endured this hideous condition until I got lower to  more
protected and softer snow. But actually the best skiing  of  the  night  was
once I hit Road 84 and the snowmobile tracks. All things are relative.

When I reached my car the map was on the front seat right where I  had  left
it. I doubt I will be forgetting my map again anytime soon but I  will  most
likely be forgetting something else.

Total: 16 miles, 5000 ft and 14 hrs.

Fay Pullen



