            'tr' => '
Quartz Mtn, West Peak (4487 ft - 487P - Lake  Philippa  Quad)  -  April  26,
2008

When I climbed Quartz Mtn, many years ago, I could drive Road 120  .6  miles
to its end at the creek crossing. This time I had trouble even  finding  its
start, which has been totally obliterated. Once I did locate it,  though,  I
could easily hike the old road about half a mile to  its  intersection  with
the recent extension of the CCC Trail. I followed this good  trail  a  short
distance over two massive (expensive?) bridges and a ford of the main  creek
until I could enter open mossy forest  and  head  uphill.  Travel  here  was
pleasant for a while but it didn\'t take long to start running into snow  and
by the time I came to the first gully at 2000 ft  it  was  continuous,  deep
and very slushy.

I have very little recollection of my previous route up Quartz  even  though
I climbed that peak twice, once solo and once  with  my  son.  I  am  pretty
sure, though not positive, that I stayed low at this  point  and  worked  my
way into the main creek drainage. This time I found myself higher above  the
creek, lured ever upward and away from it by the appealing open  highway  of
this first gully. I followed it several hundred feet  until  I  got  nervous
that I might  be  trapped  and  unable  to  get  out  by  cliffs  that  were
developing along the sides, so I soon exited steeply onto  the  rib  to  the
left. Here the going was even better until I began  an  upward  traverse  at
3000 ft to get back to the main drainage. This traverse was quite  steep  in
spots, crossed 4 annoying gullies that required working  up  and  down  past
small cliffs and in general was a lot of effort and very slow going.  I  was
most relieved when I reached the more friendly terrain of  the  basin  below
Quartz Pass.

Now I had to contend with ever softening, wet slushy snow. I  had  made  the
deliberate decision not to bring snowshoes, partly because I didn\'t want  to
carry the weight and party because I really didn\'t think they  would  be  of
that much help. Despite now postholing calf deep, and  occasionally  deeper,
I didn\'t regret my decision. Most of  the  way  was  really  too  steep  for
snowshoes especially the traverses where  I  actually  find  them  to  be  a
hazard. For me breaking trail in snowshoes is as much or  more  effort  than
postholing. The only  time  they  are  really  useful  to  me  is  when  the
postholing is so deep I just can\'t make any progress at all or if I am  with
a group where someone else has already broken trail. But  remember  I  am  a
prejudiced skier.

And so I slowly postholed my way upward. Before Quartz Pass  I  veered  left
up a steep gully to the south ridge and corniced summit  of  the  West  Peak
(2.5 miles, 3700 ft, 5:30 hrs). The top was surrounded  by  trees  -  it  is
after all not  that  high  -  and  unobstructed  views  were  limited.  Most
impressive was nearby Bessemer and I managed  to  find  a  reasonably  clear
shot from the ridge. I was  most  disappointed  not  to  have  any  view  of
Garfield. It was completely hidden behind the main peak of Quartz.

I did an improved job of route finding on the way out staying lower  on  the
traverse and finding better ways across all the gullies to cut  my  up  time
in half. The ascent of this peak finishes off the  Lake  Philippa  Quad  for
me.

Total: 5 miles, 3700 ft and 8:20 hrs

Fay Pullen

