            'title' => 'Garfield Mtn (5519 ft - 839P - Snoqualmie Lake Quad) - May 18, 2008',
            'tr' => '
Garfield Mtn (5519 ft - 839P - Snoqualmie Lake Quad) - May 18, 2008

I had long thought to give Garfield Mtn a try via the north  side  from  the
Taylor River since I considered the notorious south side  route  beyond  me.
However, the only route on the north described in  Beckey  involves  fording
the Taylor River during high spring melt, decidedly  not  appealing  if  not
downright deadly. Then I discovered you could  get  to  the  north  side  by
traversing from Lower Garfield Mtn Lake. And this is what I did on  May  25,
2007 during a 3-day solo trip up Green Ridge to  climb  the  East  Peak  and
Treen. Unfortunately I was thwarted by an impassible moat about  halfway  up
the summit gully. Then Don Goodman informed me that the north side could  be
accessed from the Taylor River  TH  without  fording  the  Taylor  River  by
travelling XC on the south side  of  the  river  to  the  creek  draining  N
directly from the summit.  So this was to be my next plan of attack.

The main problem with the north route is that it has  only  a  small  window
during which it can be climbed. It must be done late enough  that  the  snow
is stable but early enough that the summit gully is completely snow  filled.
 Once the snow melts the gully is very difficult. This usually means  before
the middle of May. Don had good conditions on May 13, 2006. Last year I  was
already too late by May 25.  This  year  I  began  trying  to  get  a  party
together in April and joined forces with Jim Brisbine and Mike  Torok.   But
our unusual spring weather of unseasonably cold temperatures  with  constant
new snow followed by brief unseasonably high temperatures produced  a  cycle
of dangerous avalanche conditions that kept putting off the  trip.  I  could
feel the window slowly closing. Finally things  came  together  on  May  18,
though only after a last minute reconsideration after  initially  cancelling
once again due to high avalanche conditions. It  was  getting  late  to  try
this route but surely the window would stay open longer  this  year  due  to
the higher than normal snowpack. Little did we  know  that  the  window  had
already closed. It was only because Mike pried it open again with  guts  and
a shovel that we made the summit.

Following Don\'s route description, we started from the Taylor  River  TH  at
6:30 paralleling the river on the south side.  The  previous  two  days  had
been unseasonably hot and the Taylor River was a raging  torrent.  There  is
no  way  anyone  could  get  across  that  river  without  a  bridge.   This
observation and the fact that Don\'s first "dry" stream now had a  good  flow
in it warned that we might encounter some unusual conditions  on  this  day.
Sure enough, the objective second  stream  was  roaring  and  could  not  be
crossed without a log. There was a possibility very near the  junction  with
the Taylor River, but we scouted upstream looking for something  better.  We
soon  encountered  a  gorge  with  several  waterfalls  and  retreated  back
downstream to the first log. We all scooted across  and  followed  the  east
side of the creek through  pleasant  woods.  We  came  to  Don\'s  two  talus
fields, the predicted brush  and  the  diagonal  descent  down  the  top  of
treacherous dripping wet slabs into the north gully proper  at  2200  ft  (3
hrs). Here was continuous snow and extensive avalanche debris littered  with
tree parts. We could see the summit of Garfield but the summit  gully  would
not be visible until right beneath it.

The next section  of  the  route  was  delightful.  The  snow  was  in  good
condition, not at all slushy as we had feared it might  be.  Good  thing  we
hadn\'t lugged snowshoes along. They were not needed at all.  We  worked  our
way up to the 4400 ft basin directly below Garfield (5 hrs). When we  turned
a corner and the summit gully came into  view,  my  heart  sank.  It  looked
almost identical to last year with  two  major  breaks  already  across  the
gully. We were too late. Where had all this year\'s snow gone? At that  point
I all but gave up. Sure we were this far and would go  take  a  look  but  I
knew  what  we  were  going  to  find.  I  didn\'t,  however,  consider   the
determination of one of my companions.

Donning harness and crampons, we climbed to the first break,  the  same  one
that had stopped  me  last  year,  and  roped  up.  A  deep  moat  stretched
completely across the gully. There were two thin snow bridges,  one  in  the
center and one to the left perched precariously over slabs.  Jim  was  first
to inspect. He backed off both declaring neither one to his  liking.  I  was
no help either not really wanting to go any farther. I think both Jim and  I
were ready to turn around at this point and try again  another  year.  Mike,
though, did not give up so easily. He first looked  at  the  center  bridge,
didn\'t like it, looked at the left bridge, liked it even less and went  back
to the center bridge. Though narrow, it really did go down  a  ways  and  he
declared it solid enough to cross, and cross it he did while Jim and I  held
our breath fully expecting the whole fragile thing to collapse.  Guts.  That
is all I can say. Mike has guts. Even with a top rope I was totally  freaked
crossing this bridge. It was very thin, only a foot wide at  its  narrowest,
maybe 3 feet long and spanned a deep wet evil looking moat.

We still had the second break to  contend  with.  This  one  looked  totally
impassible to me with no possible way across. It wasn\'t  really  a  moat  in
the true sense as the snow went right up the rock but the rock was  vertical
with a vertical snow wall on the left  accessed  by  a  sloping  rock  slab.
Again Jim and I were ready to turn around. Again Mike  didn\'t  give  up.  He
merely pulled out his shovel and  went  to  work.  Jim  and  I  stood  there
incredulously with our mouths  open  as  Mike  spent  the  next  30  minutes
excavating a route up the vertical snow wall. This guy  is  unreal.  Such  a
technique would never in a million years have occurred to me. He did such  a
good job that I had no trouble getting up that wall.

We now thought we had it made and Jim led the rest of the way to  the  Notch
(8  hrs).   But  when  we  got  to  the  notch  it   looked   anything   but
straightforward. Where was this continuous snow Don described? What we  were
faced with was  a  series  of  wet  dripping  slabs  and  intermittent  snow
patches. It took another 1:30 to work our way, Jim leading again,  the  last
350 ft to the summit (4600 ft, 9:30 hrs).  Given what had  gone  before,  it
took a while to soak in that I was really on the summit. And yet I  couldn\'t
get too elated - yet. We still had to get down and across that snow bridge.

The summit register was soaking wet, which really  annoyed  Mike.  While  he
partially dried it out, Jim and I made 3 rappels back to the notch. Mike  is
so comfortable downclimbing that is what he did,  removing  our  anchors  on
the way down. We belayed from the notch down, Mike  coming  last.  The  only
place Mike really wanted a belay was across the snowbridge. Miraculously  we
all made it across and everyone breathed a sigh of  relief.  We  made  short
work of descending the snow to where we had to  climb  out  the  main  gully
past the wet slabs. Things slowed in the  brush  and  talus  and  forest  as
fatigue began to take its toll. We crossed the log over  the  big  creek  at
last light and did the final bit along the  river  by  headlamp,  thankfully
reaching the car at 10:20. Now we could really celebrate our  success  -  up
and down the mountain. I gave both Jim  and  Mike  a  big  grateful  hug.  I
couldn\'t have climbed Garfield without them.

Total: 6 miles, 5200 ft and 15:45 hrs             Fay Pullen





