            'tr' => '
North Craggy (8205 ft - 445P) and Eightmile Pk (7840+ ft  -  480P)  -  Billy
Goat Mtn Quad - June 8, 2008

Stefan, Don B, Tom S, Martin S and I started from  a  previous  night\'s  car
camp at the Billy Goat Horse TH at 7:20. Actually Stefan drove a further  .5
mile to the switchback at 4560 ft where  a  large  avalanche  pile  of  snow
blocked the road. I had checked this out the day  before  and  after  barely
being able to turn around, I elected to walk  this  section.  I  watched  in
disbelief as Stefan drove past my turnaround point, one wheel  on  the  snow
the other on the  very  edge  of  the  shoulder  to  a  wider  spot  at  the
switchback proper. I never would have had the guts to try that on my own.

From the switchback we headed up along Eightmile  Cr.  We  soon  came  to  a
curious hump in the drainage not  shown  on  the  map  and  had  to  descent
slightly on the other side.  Since water cannot flow uphill, the  creek  had
to go under this hump somehow. We continued up  the  creek  until  we  could
begin an upward traverse through talus and moderate brush toward  the  creek
draining No Dice Lake. Somewhere in here Tom went left up an  inviting  snow
couloir toward the N Ridge  while  the  rest  of  us  stayed  right  on  the
traverse. Tom reported he got quite high on the ridge in class  3-4  terrain
before being stopped by a potential rappel off a  pinnacle.  Had  he  had  a
rope, he might have continued all the way to the summit, but having none  he
descended somewhat and traversed to meet up with us above No Dice Lake.

Once we hit the drainage at about 6000 ft the terrain opened up  with  solid
snow and easy travel the rest of the way to No Dice Lake (2500 ft,  3  hrs).
This alpine basin is lovely, surrounded as it is with the three Craggys  and
Eightmile Pk. We were, however, stunned to see how little snow there was  on
the west slope of North Craggy. We  were  expecting  a  snow  climb  and  it
turned out to be mostly scree and class  2-3  rock  up  a  series  of  loose
gullies. We had to be very careful with rockfall. None of us had thought  to
bring a hardhat. About halfway up Tom intersected  our  route  and  we  were
together once again. We hit the easy S Ridge just  shy  of  the  summit  and
pulled onto the top at 12:00 (4000 ft, 4:30 hrs). What snow  there  was  was
mostly of the fresh variety from recent storms. The N  face  of  Big  Craggy
looked especially wintry with its new coat of white.

There was a film can register but I  decided  this  Top  200  peak  deserved
something better and added a large one of my own.  We spent  a  pleasant  20
minutes or so on top.  Views were quite expansive with Tom ticking  off  the
names of all the surrounding Pasayten peaks. The wind was  minimal  and  the
sun even came out briefly.  But clouds were thick to the west where I  doubt
the weather was very good. This area was certainly a good  choice  for  this
weekend.

We quickly descended, making use of a few ribbons of snow, to No  Dice  Lake
and worked our way up the other side to the S Ridge of  Eightmile  Pk.  From
this point, and from the map, the S Ridge looked  as  if  it  could  present
some problems but in fact it turned out  to  be  quite  delightful  and  fun
scrambling, mostly on the very crest, with nothing harder than class 3.   We
reached the summit at 3:00 (5500 ft, 7:30 hrs).  There was  no  register  so
again I left one of mine. More expansive  views,  including  down  into  the
remote Lost River Gorge, and more enjoyable summit time before starting  our
descent by continuing north along the ridge.

The first part of the North Ridge to  the  surveyed  7756  point  was  quite
mellow, after which it divided and took a decidedly steep  downward  plunge.
Fortunately, Stefan noticed a snowfilled gully to the left that  provided  a
fast and easy way down via a long  glissade.  Unfortunately,  what  followed
after that was unpleasant  brush  and  talus  and  forested  cliffs  through
rather confusing topography  as  Stefan,  Martin  and  I  made  our  way  to
Eightmile Pass and the trail. It took  longer  to  navigate  than  expected.
Somewhere in this brush we parted company with Don and Tom. They  never  did
find the trail, but still found a reasonable route and beat us back  to  the
car. We hit the good trail at 5:20, which was snow and obstacle free  and  a
pleasure to walk after what had gone before. We reached  the  switchback  at
6:20, where believe it or not another car  was  parked  alongside  Stefan\'s.
That made turning around for him a bit more difficult. Thanking  all  for  a
great day, I took my leave of the guys and walked the last half mile  to  my
car and a planned second car camp. They all  waved  as  they  drove  past  a
short time later.

Total: 9 miles, 5800 ft and 11 hrs.

Fay Pullen





