            'title' => 'Billy Goat Mtn (7633 ft - 1033P), Billy Goat Mtn Quad 3 (7697 ft - 537P) and Burch Mtn (7782 ft - 542P) - Billy Goat Mtn Quad - June 9, 2008',
            'tr' => '
Billy Goat Mtn (7633 ft - 1033P), Billy Goat Mtn Quad 3  (7697  ft  -  537P)
and Burch Mtn (7782 ft - 542P) - Billy Goat Mtn Quad - June 9, 2008

Continued from North Craggy TR.

I had a second pleasant car camp at the Billy Goat  Horse  TH  with  a  good
night\'s sleep having the place all to myself. The lone  car  that  had  been
parked there the previous day was undisturbed and  no  other  cars  made  an
appearance. The forecast for this day was not encouraging - 60 %  chance  of
precipitation. But nothing came in during the night and I  awoke  to  partly
sunny skies. My plan was to climb Billy Goat Mtn, Billy  Goat  3  and  Burch
Mtn, although I wasn\'t quite sure how I was going to link them together.

This time I did drive to the switchback since I now knew it could  be  done,
although I turned around right away before parking next  to  the  other  car
which was still there. I started up the trail at  6:30,  reaching  Eightmile
Pass an hour later, then just headed up the S slopes toward Billy  Goat.  No
real problems other than the fact that I  felt  really  tired  and  slow.  I
guess the guys had pretty much worn me out the day before. The  terrain  was
open and snow free, except for the hidden high basin below the peak at  7100
ft, the final ridge a walkup and I reached the  top  at  9:30  (3200  ft,  3
hrs).  Despite having a huge summit cairn, I could find  no  register  so  I
left one of mine. It was warm and sunny and I spent 25 minutes relaxing  and
taking in views of the Craggys and where I had been just the day before.

Too soon, it was time to determine how I would get to Billy  Goat  Pass  and
my next two peaks. Going down the same S slopes I had ascended was not  very
appealing. Numerous pinnacles  and  cliffs  to  the  SE  would  mean  either
descending almost all the way  back  to  Eightmile  Pass  or  trying  for  a
tedious and doubtful higher traverse to the Billy Goat  Pass  trail.  Either
would involve substantial elevation loss. On the  other  hand,  if  I  could
find a way down the N slopes it would be ever so much shorter  and  I  could
essentially traverse to the  Pass  with  minimal  unneeded  elevation  loss.
Problem was the N slope looked frightfully steep on the map  and  even  more
frightful at first glance in person from the ridge. But the  more  I  looked
the more I thought I could pick out a route down. The first part was  a  bit
tricky on a loose rocky rib between steep snow gullies. I did have my 60  ft
panic rope along and two short rappels off trees got me into the  left  snow
gully at a point  where  the  steepness  lessened  and  it  appeared  to  be
continuous all the way to the valley below. Thankfully  the  snow  was  soft
and I could kick steps and glissade to 6400 ft after which an easy  traverse
led to 6600 ft Billy Goat Pass (3500 ft, 5 hrs).

At the Pass I was unable to find the Burch Mtn Trail in  the  snow  so  just
headed uphill. I did stumble onto a trail; although it was much higher  than
where the GT Map indicated it should be (this trail  is  not  shown  on  the
USGS Billy Goat Mtn Quad). At this point  I  could  see  the  predicted  bad
weather making its way toward me.  I followed  the  snow  covered  trail  to
just below Billy 3, climbed easy terrain to that summit  (4600  ft,  6  hrs)
and  left  another  register.   It  was  now  snowing  and  visibility   was
diminishing so I didn\'t tarry but hurried off to Burch reaching that  summit
at 2:00 (5400 ft, 7:30 hrs). There was no register but since  a  trail  lead
to this top I didn\'t bother to leave one.

I quickly returned to Billy Goat Pass  where  I  had  a  bit  of  difficulty
finding the trail in the snow. At one point I thought  I  saw  tracks  going
down a gully, but when I got closer they were too fat and  round  for  human
tracks. Besides they had big claws.  Definitely  bear  tracks.   Fortunately
they were not fresh so  hopefully  Mr.  Bear  was  now  far  away  from  me.
Eventually I did find the trail, although it remained snow covered to  about
5800 ft. Easy travel on real trail led to  reaching  my  car  at  5:00.  The
other car was still there.

Driving home it was sunny once again from Winthrop to Wenatchee.  I  stopped
for dinner at the Big Y CafÃ© at the Junction of Hwys 2 and 97. I hit  really
bad weather coming over Snoqualmie Pass with winds  that  buffeted  my  poor
Subaru all over the road and heavy rain  and  snow.  Yes  it  was  seriously
snowing at Snoqualmie Pass. Is this really June?

Total: 10 miles, 5600 ft and 10:30 hrs.

Fay Pullen



