            'title' => 'Damfino Pk (6145 ft - 825P) & Mt Larrabee Quad 3 (5854 ft - 454P) - Mt Larrabee Quad; Bearpaw Mtn Quad 1 (5930 ft - 570P) & Excelsior Pk (5712 ft) - Bearpaw Mtn Quad; - June 14-15, 2008 ',
            'tr' => '
Damfino Pk (6145 ft - 825P) & Mt Larrabee Quad 3  (5854  ft  -  454P)  -  Mt
Larrabee Quad; Bearpaw Mtn Quad 1 (5930 ft - 570P) & Excelsior Pk (5712  ft)
- Bearpaw Mtn Quad; - June 14-15, 2008

Ever since snowshoeing to Welcome Pass on Matt\'s trip in  February,  I  have
been dying to return to this lovely area. The view of Damfino  Pk  from  the
pass  especially  piqued  my  interest  and  I  made  this  summit  my  main
objective. I wasn\'t sure it  was  within  my  capabilities,  though,  as  it
certainly looked like a challenging  rock  climb  from  a  distance.  Beckey
describes it as only class 2-3 but I have been fooled by Beckey before so  I
wasn\'t sure what to expect. In any event there were also a couple  of  other
easier climbs along scenic Excelsior Ridge to serve  as  consolation  prizes
should I not succeed

Day 1: I started up the Welcome Pass Trail at 12:00.  There  was  one  other
car at the TH. About halfway up I met  the  couple  belonging  to  this  car
coming down. I was in shorts; they were bundled up head to  toe.  The  woman
looked at me rather incredulously and commented, "There is a lot of snow  up
there!"  "Well duh," I thought to myself, but  I  politely  answered  "I  am
expecting snow," and left it at that. Shortly after leaving them,  somewhere
around 4200 ft, I hit consistent snow. At 2:40 I  reached  5200  ft  Welcome
Pass (2.5 miles, 2800 ft, 2:40 hrs). The views were as good  as  remembered.
Well, almost. The higher mountains, including Baker,  Shuksan  and  Tomyhoi,
were still hidden under marine clouds only gradually making  their  presence
known.

The snow in the forest was rock hard, but  here  on  the  open  sun  exposed
ridge was soft and slushy. My plan was  to  wander  along  Excelsior  Ridge,
climbing Larrabee3 on the way, and find a camp near  its  intersection  with
the ridge to Damfino Pk.  Crossing the S ridge of Larrabee  3  I  dumped  my
pack and strolled up the mostly bare ridge to that summit (360  ft,  :45  hr
RT). I had a great view of Damfino Pk from the  top.  It  didn\'t  look  that
easy nor did just getting to it for that matter.

I stayed mostly on the ridge crest because  that  seemed  easier  than  side
hilling, but then had to descend a bit to the saddle with the  ridge  coming
from Pt 6087 where I wanted to make camp. Here I found a small bare  heather
patch flat enough for my tent (5 miles, 4050 ft, 5:30 total). Though it  was
a bit cramped and uncomfortable it  beat  sleeping  on  slushy  snow.  After
setting up camp I headed further west along  the  Excelsior  crest  climbing
over Bearpaw 1 to Excelsior Pk just  above  Excelsior  Pass.  Although  very
easy going the distance was farther than it looked and took more  time  than
expected (5 miles, 1700 ft, 3 hrs RT). By the time I  returned  to  camp  it
was 9:20.

Total for the day: 10 miles, 5750 ft and 9:20 hrs

Day 2: Marine air moved in again during the night and when I awoke  at  5:00
it was foggy with no visibility. So I turned over and went  back  to  sleep.
At 7:00 things were looking better with patches of blue beginning to  appear
and by the time I was underway at 8:30 I had good visibility  and  sunshine.
I had brought crampons along thinking that if the night were clear  I  might
need them, but with the cloud cover it hadn\'t even come  close  to  freezing
overnight and the snow remained soft. I easily made my way north  along  the
ridge, then on the west side to the saddle south of Pt 6087. Now  I  had  to
get past the east rocky rib of Pt  6087.   There  were  several  choices  of
moderately steep snow gullies. I chose the least intimidating  looking  even
though this meant climbing higher than necessary. Once across  I  dropped  a
couple hundred feet to traverse below the West  Ridge  of  Damfino  until  I
could climb to the saddle just west of the summit block. On this traverse  I
set off many surface slides of the top several inches of  recent  new  snow.
None were serious enough to worry me but the constant sound of snow  sliding
on snow is not a sound I like to hear.

The actual climb of the summit rock was much  easier  than  I  expected.  It
really was only class 2-3, with maybe one or two class 4 moves for  a  short
person such as myself. I had a rope along but never used it, up or  down.  I
basically just worked my way up the West Ridge,  staying  left  at  a  small
tower half way up - 400 feet of enjoyable scrambling. You  just  never  know
how difficult or easy a climb will  be  until  you  rub  noses  with  it.  I
reached the summit at 10:40 (1.5 miles, 1300 ft 2:10 hrs). I  found  a  film
can register on top but  the  contents  were  dripping  wet  and  completely
illegible. I have said this many times before and  I will say it  again.  If
you are going to go to the trouble  of  placing  a  register  on  a  summit,
please, please, please use waterproof paper! All registers can leak,  either
from faulty design or improper closing.  Once  wet,  if  the  paper  is  not
waterproof it quickly becomes a soggy mess. A register that cannot  be  read
is useless. It goes without saying that I left a  register  with  waterproof
paper.

On the summit the higher peaks were not yet visible, not even  Tomyhoi  just
across Damfino Cr. But the views continued to improve on the  trip  back  to
camp (3 miles, 1850 ft,  4  hrs  RT)  until  even  Baker  and  Shuksan  were
completely out. I had time for a nap in the sun at camp before taking  leave
of this gorgeous area at 2:30. I took a lower route  back  to  Welcome  Pass
reaching it at 4:00. There were no footprints in the snow indicating  anyone
else had been up to the pass. The descent in the forest was still rock  hard
snow and rather treacherous until I hit bare trail. Then easy going  to  the
car at 5:40.

Total for the day: 8 miles, 2200 ft and 7:10 hrs

Grand Total: 18 miles and 7950 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen.

P.S.  As a minor detail,  Beckey  and  the  GT  Mt  Shuksan  map  gives  the
elevation of Damfino Pk as  6157  ft  but  the  USGS  Mt  Larrabee  map  and
Howbert\'s Master List gives it as 6145 ft.



