            'tr' => '
South Point (5980 ft - 1940P) and  Packwood  Quad  1  (5718  ft  -  478P)  -
Packwood Quad - June 20, 2008

Had I know what I was getting myself into on  this  traverse  trip  I  would
have brought more real climbing gear. As it was, all I had with me  was  100
ft of 6mm rope, not really enough to do the job with confidence.  I  suppose
I should have guessed from looking at the  map  that  South  Point  is  very
cliffy and could be a problem,  but  I  was  deceived  by  reading  a  brief
mention of an old trail that continues south along the ridge to  and  beyond
Packwood 1. How difficult could it be if there is a trail?

The trip started well enough up the 3.5 miles trail to the old lookout  site
on South Point. This little used trail begins from an obscure,  but  marked,
TH about 5 miles up Road 20 just west of Packwood. The trail was  in  better
shape than expected and easily followed until I began running into  snow  at
about 4200 ft. I was able to stay with the trail  off  and  on  for  another
1000 ft before losing it completely and just heading  uphill  along  the  NE
Ridge on snow for the final 800 ft to the summit  (3200  ft,  3:40  hrs).  I
spent a pleasant 45 minutes on top in the sun eating  lunch  and  taking  in
the views before trying to  figure  out  how  to  continue  my  traverse  to
Packwood 1.

The trail ascent route up the NE Ridge is easy going but all  other  aspects
of South Point are quite cliffy and most especially the south face which  is
where I wanted to descend. So where the heck did this supposed  continuation
of a trail go? I hadn\'t a clue and I still  don\'t.  I  wandered  around  the
summit area looking for clues and found  none.  Maybe  I  could  have  found
something had there been less snow. The only  thing  I  found  was  a  trail
leading to an outhouse (which surely belongs  on  a  list  of  the  10  most
scenic in the state). A sort of trail continued  down  from  there  but  got
worse and worse until it could no longer really be called a trail.

At this point I seriously considered calling it a day, forgoing  Packwood  1
and just returning the way I had come. I knew I could get myself  into  real
trouble descending unknown technical terrain with only a thin 100  ft  rope.
But the terrain continued down in interesting  scrambleable  rock  and  just
sort of lured me on. I took it  slow,  careful  not  to  make  any  moves  I
couldn\'t reverse. Then I came to some short class 4 moves and made a  couple
easy rappels from trees. I still felt I could climb back  up  if  necessary.
This brought me to the top a narrow  gully  where  I  saw  a  mountain  goat
below. Was this an omen? More importantly was this a  good  omen  or  a  bad
omen? The gully itself looked easy but  I  couldn\'t  see  what  was  at  the
bottom of it without climbing down farther. Sure enough the gully  ended  in
a cliff. This was the point of no return. Once I  rappelled  this  I  didn\'t
think I could get back up. But below the terrain looked much  easier.  So  I
down I went.

Beware of making judgments as to the ease of a descent by  looking  down  on
it. It is frequently harder than it looks. That was the  case  here.  I  was
still a long ways from being down to easy terrain  and  had  to  wander  all
over the face from ledge to ledge to find a scramble  route  down.  I  think
Mr. Billy Goat was laughing at me the whole time although  I  did  find  the
climbing fun and exciting. Even so I breathed a sigh of relief  when  I  hit
continuous snow and could traverse to the ridge connecting  to  Packwood  1.
It had taken me over an hour and a half to find my way down 450 ft of  rock.
The rest of the way to Packwood 1 was easy (4100  ft,  7:20  hrs).   I  even
came across sections of old trail along the partially melted out ridge.

I now had to figure out how to get down to my car. I sure wasn\'t going  back
over South Point. Looking at the  map,  the  most  direct  of  the  feasible
routes appeared to be to descend the slope just north of  the  false  summit
to get into the main drainage west between South Point and Packwood 1.  This
worked reasonably well. After an initial very steep forested cliffy  section
just off the ridgeline, the slope eased. Open forest lasted  to  about  4000
ft where I was funneled into the creek bottom. Brush was  not  bad  but  the
creek had  multiple  waterfalls,  obstacles  and  large  fallen  trees  that
required many detours climbing up and down on the south sidehill.  When  the
creek leveled out I crossed to the north side and followed  pleasant  forest
to hit the road about Â¼ mile from my car.

Total: 7 miles, 4300 ft and 10 hrs.

Fay Pullen



