            'title' => 'Lincoln Peak (9080+ ft - 720P - Mt Baker Quad) - June 27-29, 2008',
            'tr' => '
Lincoln Peak (9080+ ft - 720P - Mt Baker Quad) - June 27-29, 2008

I had more or less resigned myself to the fact that I would  never  make  it
up this peak. It is much too difficult for me to try on  my  own.  I  needed
the help of climbers stronger and better than I. I did  get  a  shot  at  it
last year when Paul K, Tom S and Mike C invited me to  join  their  attempt.
But conditions were less than ideal and we turned around at the top  of  the
first gully. I figured that was my  one  chance.  I  probably  wouldn\'t  get
another and after that climb I wasn\'t even sure I wanted another  chance.  I
was seriously spooked by that scary monster.  So be it. Life  would  go  on.
Then I got a call out of the blue from Paul to join him and Tom  once  again
on this year\'s attempt. It took me all of two seconds to decide  to  accept.
I got the call on Wednesday evening for  a  Friday-Sunday  climb.  Not  much
time to prepare. But I  had  been  planning  my  own  3-day  trip  Thursday-
Saturday (I almost went Wednesday-Friday in which case I wouldn\'t have  been
home to take the call. Some things are just meant to  be.)  So  I  had  most
things ready to go. I only had  to  add  the  technical  gear.  And  it  was
probably a good thing I had short notice as that allowed for  less  time  to
stress out. As it was, I didn\'t get much sleep that night.

Day 1: Rounding out the party was Sean, a friend of Tom\'s whom I  had  never
met before. We drove up the Middle Fork Nooksack River Road 38 to Road  023.
With the guys cutting out the most  offending  protruding  branches,  I  was
able to coax my Jeep to the end of drivable road at 3700 ft but the last  .5
miles is very overgrown and it is probably best to  park  at  the  preceding
switchback. We started hiking the now abandoned  road  at  11:30,  taking  a
straight line from its end to a  small  lake  at  5100  ft  and  a  pleasant
campsite on the ridge above at 6000 ft (2 miles, 2300 ft, 3 hrs).  This  has
to be one of the easiest approaches to a major peak in all of the  Cascades.
We had a good view of the route  and  could  see  several  possible  problem
areas. The first bergshrund looked challenging and a second  bergshrund  had
opened up at the base of the first gully. We all turned in around 7 pm  with
a planned wakeup call at  2:30  am.  I  tossed  and  turned  at  first  with
disturbing visions  of  ugly  gullies,  horrid  steep  slopes  and  crushing
falling debris dancing in my head. I think  I  finally  dozed  off  sometime
after it got dark around 10:00. It was a warm night and nothing froze.

Day 2: We were climbing by 3:00 am, dropping off the ridge  into  the  basin
below the SW Face. In the basin we stopped to rope up and put  on  crampons,
mine brand new steel ones. The snow was still soft but we figured  we  would
need them at some point.  We climbed 1500 ft up ever steeping  snow  to  the
base of the first bergshrund at which point it was beginning to  get  light.
From here on we protected with running belays. Because of the soft snow  all
pickets were placed as deadmen. The shrund  went  all  the  way  across  the
slope, the only possibility a thin snowbridge on the  right  wall.  Tom  led
across this and up left to where it was necessary to traverse  to  the  base
of the first gully. Here Sean took over  the  lead.  The  second  bergshrund
prevented direct access to the gully forcing Sean onto  dicey  rock  on  the
left to bypass it. My experience climbing rock in  crampons  is  limited.  I
have decided I really don\'t like it but I was glad my crampons  were  steel.
A flat spot on top of the rock provided  a  rare  opportunity  to  rest  and
regroup.

Tom took over the lead again to the top of the first  gully.  Near  the  top
was a short section of water ice where crampons  were  essential  but  above
that was very rotten unstable snow. I was last up the gully and between  the
60 m length of the rope and the curvature of the gully  I  couldn\'t  see  or
hear anything of what was happening above me except that I was in  the  line
of fire of snow debris being kicked down by the lead climbers.  Fortunately,
nothing serious came down but I couldn\'t get out of  there  fast  enough  to
suit me.  When I emerged at the top of the gully, I saw Paul was  leading  a
second traverse to the base of the second gully near  a  leaning  tower.  We
were now above the high point of our  trip  last  year.   The  traverse  led
across to another short rock section then entered the gully by  the  leaning
tower. Paul did his best to hug the right wall and stay out  of  harm\'s  way
in the shade but soon there was no way to avoid the sun and  ever  softening
snow of the upper part. My altimeter was reading 250 feet low so  I  thought
we still had a ways to go when I heard Paul unexpectedly give out a  gleeful
victory yell. The gully led straight to the top and he was  on  the  summit.
After setting up a belay, Paul brought me  up  about  30  minutes  later  at
12:40 (3000 ft, 9:40 hrs), with Tom and Sean joining shortly thereafter.

The summit turned out to be an extremely aerie  perch  of  jumbled  boulders
whose stability was questionable. One false move and you would end  up  over
a thousand feet below on the Thunder Glacier to  the  north  or  the  Deming
Glacier to the east. But  there  was  room  for  all  four  of  us  and  the
panoramic view was out of this world. We had been informed  that  there  was
no register on top so I had brought one of mine in which  Paul  had  entered
the names of all known previous parties. We now joyfully added ours.

We spent over a glorious hour  on  top  before  reality  sank  in  with  the
realization that now we had to get down this monster. What  followed  was  a
blur of 11 rappels. They all kind of ran together so I can\'t vouch  for  the
accuracy of my memory. Rap 1 was off a summit horn into  the  gully.  Rap  2
was another horn. Rap 3 was from a deadman in the middle of gully to a  horn
near the leaning tower. Number 4 was a very awkward  horizontal  semi-rappel
across the traverse to the top  of  the  first  gully.  This  one  seriously
freaked me out. It was in full sun, the snow gave no sense of  security  and
in fact I almost lost it when one of my steps broke  out.  In  addition  Tom
fell into a hidden  hole  many  of  which  were  beginning  to  appear  with
alarming frequency and Sean just missed getting  creamed  by  a  significant
sluff that came from high above. We  all  watched  with  fascination  as  it
bounced and careened down the fall line to disappear into the funnel at  the
bottom.

Raps 5 and 6 were from deadmen down the first gully. This  was  now  in  the
shade but it is a narrow gully and we were all exposed to falling debris  as
we waited for our turns to rappel. Many small sluffs and rocks  were  kicked
off by each of us as we descended but they all stayed in the deep runnel  in
the center and no one was hit. About this time I began having  trouble  with
the weight of the now saturated ropes. I generally like to  rappel  and  get
pleasure in descending down fluidly, but the long ropes were  so  heavy  now
that I had to manually feed them through my belay device which  made  for  a
jerky and awkward movement. I am just too light.

Rap 7 was from a horn on the rock at the base of the first  gully.  Here  we
deviated from our up route and went straight  downhill  to  avoid  the  long
first traverse and the first bergshrund. We had  gone  this  way  last  year
with the final rap being vertical to free over  an  ice  cliff.  Somehow  it
escaped us that on this warn sunny day with the mountain melting before  our
very eyes it would no longer be ice. 3 more deadmen raps brought us  to  the
edge of the cliff. Sure enough we could hear  water  roaring  below  us  but
none of us knew what was really down there. It turned out  much  worse  than
any of us expected. Sean volunteered to be first down as he had for much  of
the descent. Oh to be young and fearless.   Over  he  went.  20  minutes  of
uncertainty went by during which we heard nothing  above  the  roar  of  the
water. Did he drown? Did he fall in  a  hole?  Actually  the  poor  guy  was
untangling the rope while being drenched with water but we didn\'t know  that
at the time. When he finally did yell "off rappel", we all breathed  a  sigh
of relief. At least it was possible to get down. Tom went next. Then it  was
my turn.  I stepped over the edge.  The  first  thing  I  saw  was  an  ugly
bottomless black hole below me into  which  a  rather  large  waterfall  was
pouring. Then I saw the waterfall which could not be  avoided.  Then  I  saw
Tom yelling at me frantically but I couldn\'t hear above the  roar.  What  he
was yelling was to go fast. Problem was I couldn\'t. The rope  was  right  in
the waterfall and even heavier now than before. If I completely  let  go  of
the rope, I would just hang in space. I  had  to  painfully  feed  the  rope
through and inch down with water washing  over  me  from  chest  down.  Then
there was the challenge of not  ending  up  in  the  black  hole.  One  more
obstacle of a gaping moat below that and I was home free. I felt like I  had
been delivered from the jaws of a whale. That was one scary  evil  waterfall
gully.

It was now about 9:30 and almost dark. Sean was already out of sight  making
a beeline back to camp and dry clothes. It was a matter of survival.  I  was
also drenched and freezing cold, my feet blocks of ice, and Tom told  me  to
do the same. I felt bad about leaving the ropes to him and  Paul  but  again
it was a matter of survival. Tom with his extra weight had been almost  able
to free fall through the waterfall and didn\'t get soaked. I reached camp  at
10:40 warmed slightly by the movement (3100  ft,  19:40  hrs).   I  had  dry
socks and upper clothes but nothing except rain pants for  the  lower  half.
It would have to do. Fortunately, the night was warm, though windy.

Day 3: I slept like a rock until being awakened by a horrible  squawking  at
first light. I thought it was a crow until I looked out the  tent  door  and
saw a very vocal ptarmigan perched on a rock not 5 feet away. I  don\'t  know
what her problem was. I went back to sleep until awakened again  by  sun  on
the tent at 8:00. We had a leisurely breakfast, all of us  gazing  at  where
we had been the day before  and  each  of  us  thankful  that  we  had  been
delivered safely from evil and never had to return again.  Between  the  sun
and the warm wind most of my clothes dried by the time we left at 10:30.  We
were back to the car an hour and a half later.

I still can\'t believe I climbed Lincoln. Of course I couldn\'t  have  without
the help of three great guys. I will be eternally grateful to them  all  for
making such a special experience possible, especially Paul.  And  after  all
my stressing and worrying, I was  actually  surprised  that  I  enjoyed  the
climbing as much as I did. The only things that really freaked me  out  were
the horizontal rappel from the second to the first gully and  the  waterfall
rappel. But the climbing on Lincoln is not so much a physical  challenge  as
it is a mental one. It is just so relentless,  constantly  steep  with  very
few resting places and continually exposed to  falling  debris.  It  is  one
scary mountain.

Total: 6 miles and 5500 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen





