Liberty Cap (14,112 ft - 472P - Mt Rainier West Quad) - July 8-10, 2008

I didn\'t want to have to climb Mt Rainier again,  I  really  didn\'t.   Don\'t
get me wrong. I love Mt Rainier and  think  it  a  beautiful  mountain,  but
after 3 times up it (and two other  failed  attempts  fairly  high)  I  just
thought I was done with it and would ever after appreciate its  beauty  from
afar. It is a lot of work to climb Mt Rainier and on each previous  climb  I
got a mild but still unpleasant case of altitude  sickness  which  wasn\'t  a
whole lot of fun. Of course, strictly  speaking,  Liberty  Cap  is  not  the
actual summit of Mt Rainier, Columbia Crest is. But they are so close  there
is essentially no difference in the effort required. So I repeat,  I  really
didn\'t want to climb Mt Rainier again. Then, after  I  finished  the  Bulger
100 Highest list, John Roper put the idea in my head  to  do  the  REAL  100
Highest Peaks in Washington - that is only those that have a clean 400  feet
of prominence, no other criteria or  finagling.  Never  one  to  pass  up  a
challenge, I looked at the difference between the two lists  to  see  if  it
were possible for me to do.  Only two seemed a  problem.  Lincoln  I  didn\'t
think I was capable of doing and Liberty Cap I didn\'t  want  to  do.   So  I
left those for last. When I actually ended up climbing  Lincoln,  that  then
meant I simply HAD to climb Liberty Cap.

Day 1: I enlisted the aid of my friend Linda and we decided to approach  via
Glacier Basin, Camp Schurman and the Emmons Glacier. Linda has a cabin  near
Crystal Mtn, worked on the Ski Patrol there and knows  just  about  everyone
in that area, including the climbing ranger Sam at Camp Schurman. The  first
part of the trail to Glacier Basin was obliterated in the  2006  floods  and
is still very rough, but once past that it was easy going the  rest  of  the
way. The Inter Glacier was mostly crevasse free and smooth but we  made  the
mistake of staying unroped when  dropping  off  Steamboat  Prow  on  to  the
Emmons. Not a good idea as several potentially large and deep crevasses  had
to be crossed. We reached Camp Schurman at 4:00 (5350 ft,  7  hrs).  It  was
quite windy that night.

Day 2: We started next morning at 3:30, joined by Dan  who  is  the  Sunrise
Ranger. This was his first year in the park and he had not yet  climbed  the
mountain. He had hoped to climb with Sam, but Sam had already  been  up  the
day before and was going the next day with his girlfriend. So Dan  asked  if
he could join Linda and me. We pointed out we were going to Liberty Cap  and
not Columbia Crest but he felt he could safely solo from where   the  routes
diverge at the saddle between the two. So we readily agreed thinking   three
on a rope was safer than  two.  He  turned  out  to  be  a  very  compatible
ropemate.

The climb was every bit as much work as I had remembered but at  least  this
time I didn\'t get altitude sickness, a real plus. However, I  had  forgotten
how huge and  beautiful  the  Emmons  Glacier  is.  And  the  crevasses  are
massive. The route itself is rather intricate,  though  easily  followed  as
hordes of climbers have been on it, and wanders here and there as it  weaves
around countless crevasses and seracs. One particularly interesting  section
was dubbed the Maze by Dan. At around 13,500  ft  the  route  makes  a  long
traverse to the Liberty Cap saddle  to  avoid  the  bergshrund  that  always
forms on the upper Emmons. Here we left Dan to his own devises at  8:30  and
continued on to Liberty Cap, reaching that important summit  at  9:30  (4750
ft, 6 hrs). The upper part of the mountain was  very  windy.  Several  gusts
blew me off balance, so we didn\'t tarry long. For those who may soon  follow
I left a register in a hole in the snow but I have no idea how long it  will
remain there.

We were back to the saddle at 10:30 and picked up Dan again  who  timed  the
meeting just right as he could see our progress  from  far  off.   The  snow
began to soften on the way down making the last bit to Camp Schurman a  real
chore. An earlier start  probably  would  have  been  better.   Although  we
reached camp at 1:30 (10 hrs RT) and had the time, both  Linda  and  I  were
too tired to continue out.  After a rest, I took a short hike to the top  of
Steamboat Prow via the class 3 trail right behind the Ranger cabin. Then  it
was dinner and to bed at 7:00.  It was  even  windier  this  night.  Several
times I thought our tent was going to take flight.

Day 3: We awoke at 6:00, after 11 hours of sleep,  only  slightly  disturbed
by the new batch of climbers getting ready for their climbs.  It  was  still
very windy and several parties had  already  turned  around  because  of  it
before we left at 7:30. To avoid roping up for the glacier we went out  over
the trail up Steamboat Prow. We then followed the ridge to  its  low  point.
Linda found a sheltered spot to wait while I made a 30 minute sprint  up  Mt
Ruth. This involved one class 4  move  and  almost  getting  blown  off  the
ridge. We had a great glissade down the Inter Glacier before the final  trek
through welcome green, after the stark world of snow and ice above,  Glacier
Basin to the car (1000 ft, 5 hrs).

Total: 11,100 ft in 3 days.

Fay Pullen





