            'tr' => '
Chimney Rock (7727 ft - 2727P or 7680+ ft according to Beckey) - July 23-
25, 2008

Beth and I had been hoping to do this peak for some  time  but  neither  our
schedules nor the weather  ever  seemed  to  co-operate.   With  her  recent
retirement and resulting greater flexibility things finally came together.

Day 1:  We  started  from  the  Pete  Lake  TH  at  Cooper  Lake  and  hiked
approximately 7 miles to the  first  switchback  on  the  PCT  opposite  the
waterfalls draining the Chimney Glacier (1000 ft, 3:45 hr). We  had  trouble
locating any discernable climber\'s trail  and  ended  up  just  bushwhacking
down to Chimney Cr and then wasting a good hour finding  a  way  across.  We
really wanted to get into the woods to the  right  of  the  broad  avalanche
slope below the waterfalls but the only good log jam crossed below  and  led
to more brush. We eventually worked our way  into  the  woods  and  stumbled
across the climber\'s trail but this trail appears little used  and  is  hard
to follow. We wasted another hour after losing the trail in  a  cliffy  area
and getting too high. At this critical point the trail dropped a  bit  below
the cliffs and crossed a minor gully into woods where the trail became  more
obvious. It then climbed very steeply at the  base  of  the  cliffs  through
ferns and vegetated talus,  crossed  a  small  creek  and  turned  right  up
extremely steep forest until it could traverse left  above  a  deep  ravine.
Sparse flagging helped out now and then to stay on route. We soon came to  a
creek and small level bench at 4750 ft that made for an  ideal  campsite  (8
miles, 2700 ft, 7:45 hr).

Day 2: Starting at 6:30, we quickly gained the  barren  moraine  above  camp
and had our first look at the mountain. We had  several  choices  of  route.
The glacier itself looked in good shape but the snow finger leading to  both
the East Face routes looked broken up and it  was  questionable  whether  we
could easily get up it. The snow gully to  the  U-Gap  looked  passable.  We
both wanted as little roped climbing as  possible  and  since  the  traverse
from the U-Gap was supposed to be the easiest way to the base of the  summit
rock, we decided on that route.

We descended 100 feet off the moraine onto the  lower  glacier  heading  for
the rock cliff left of the icefall. A gully dissecting this cliff up and  to
the right is supposed to give the  easiest  access  to  the  upper  glacier.
Well, it isn\'t all that easy. Just getting into the gully involved  climbing
some of the worse loose rock covered steep hard dirt crude I have ever  been
on. It was truly horrid and took much longer  than  anticipated.  The  gully
itself wasn\'t much better. More loose rock and wet class 3-4 junk. Beth  and
I found separate ways up so we wouldn\'t kill each  other  with  rockfall.  I
stayed in the gully while she worked onto the left wall. We  met  higher  up
for a last easier bit to the upper glacier.

Once on the upper glacier easy terrain led into the wide gully below the  U-
Gap. But even here we ran into unexpected  difficulties.  What  appeared  as
smooth continuous snow from below actually contained a series  of  crevasses
many of which almost completely crossed the slope. The  snow  also  suddenly
turned icy. We had to don crampons and   zigzag  our  way  through  or  step
across the smaller ones. Fortunately the  snow  edges  were  solid  and  the
cracks themselves not that deep  or  scary.  Near  the  top  though  was  an
impasse that forced us off the snow onto rock  on  the  right  a  couple  of
hundred feet below the gap.

We were following the route description in Beckey that states you leave  the
snow gully just below the U-Gap on a large bench to  begin  the  traverse  N
below the S Peak. Only problem was there was no bench visible, only a  sheer
cliff, and we ended up going all the way to the U-Gap. We had  assumed  that
Beckey meant you leave the gully just before getting to the U-Gap.  What  he
really meant was you go all the way to the U-Gap, cross over  to  the  other
side and just below, on the OTHER side, you find the bench.  We  had  a  few
anxious moments of thinking we were way off  route  until  we  figured  this
out.

There was indeed a broad bench, but with a short tricky  slabby  section  to
access it, that went up and around to the east side of the South  Peak.  But
once again there was a little confusion of  where  to  go  from  there.  The
bench itself slanted down to end at a  precipice  and  went  nowhere.  There
were two other possibilities.  Beth explored  a  likely  looking  ramp  that
went up left while I checked out a  more  unlikely  looking  narrow  exposed
ledge that went straight ahead into what looked  like  space.  Beth\'s  route
led to 5th class climbing but mine miraculously went around the  corner  and
opened up into a wide continuous heather ledge that traversed  all  the  way
across the face  to connect with the East Face  route  300  feet  below  the
South Peak-Main Peak notch. I had always thought that this traverse  was  on
a series of disjointed loose rock wildly exposed ledges, but in  reality  it
turned out to be a very  enjoyable  single  continuous  heather  ledge  wide
enough, for the most part, that the feeling of exposure was  minimized.  One
of  the  most  pleasant  surprises  I  have  encountered  in   my   climbing
experience.

The ledge soon turned a corner to a spectacular view of  the  summit  tower.
It looked positively frightful and completely unclimbable. However  were  we
going to get up that thing? We could see the notorious "Key  Ledge"  though.
It must lead to the route out of sight  on  the  other  side.  We  descended
slightly off our heather ledge to a series of lovely solid white rock  steps
which connected to the East Face route and worked our way up  this  pleasant
class 3-4 section to just below the notch. Here we traversed  right  passing
beneath a tower to the so called "Blind Chimney," descended to the top of  a
loose gully, crossed and went up an easy ramp on the other side to  the  Key
Ledge.

We had scrambled the entire route to this point. It was now time to get  out
the rope. Pitch 1 started directly from the Key Ledge.  It  was  a  60  foot
vegetated steep chimney that turned out to be much  harder  than  it  looked
with awkward off balance moves and sparse holds. I  thrashed  and  contorted
my way  desperately  upward  using  all  of  my  limited  arm  strength  and
collapsed with a sigh of relief at the top totally done in.  After  a  short
easy heathery section right, I gratefully turned over the lead to  Beth  for
pitch 2 up a slabby face to a wide bench with multiple  rappel  anchors.  By
the end of that pitch I had  recovered  sufficiently  to  take  on  pitch  3
around the corner to the right,  a  deep  chimney  which  was  a  full  rope
length. The first part was easy then it increased in difficulty as I  exited
left out of the chimney proper onto the face. The pitch ended at  the  ridge
only a few feet from the summit (3370 ft, 10:30 hrs).

It was now almost 5:00, but despite the lateness of the hour, worries  about
getting down and thoughts of an impending bivy, we took  a  few  moments  to
enjoy the spectacular views and our long coveted aerie perch.  We  did  find
a register but it was irretrievable at the bottom of a 10 foot crack,  so  I
placed a new one of mine. I was disappointed we couldn\'t see when  the  last
ascent was.

Two rappels got us down the chimney, and two more back  to  the  key  ledge,
then it was all downclimbing, slowly and carefully retracing our  up  route.
We reached the U-Gap at 8:45, put on crampons and had just enough  light  to
thread our way down the crevasse maze. At the top of the gully to the  lower
glacier we finally had to get out headlamps.  On  the  steepest  section  we
came upon a rappel anchor that Beth had noticed on the way up.  This  was  a
most interesting anchor consisting of two tricams and  a  nut  in  the  same
crack all equalized with a long sling and attached to a full  climbing  rope
with a locking biner. One wonders what the story was  behind  this  and  how
desperate  the  party  was  to  have  abandoned  all  this  expensive  gear.
Unfortunately, the rope had been there long enough to show serious signs  of
wear and we could not trust it. The anchor looked okay, though, and  we  did
use it with our rope for one last slightly wet rappel into the  gully.  Then
it was down the awful loose crud to the snow  below.  This  seemed  to  take
forever. But once on the lower glacier we knew we  could  make  it  back  to
camp and would not have to bivy, although it took until 1:30 am and  we  did
need the GPS to help us find it. Yes, indeed, unlike on Forbidden this  time
I did remember to mark camp (3 miles, 3700 ft, 19 hrs).

Day 3: We slept in until 9:00 when the heat of the sun on  the  tent  forced
us to get up and left at 11:00 after a leisurely breakfast.  We  had  to  be
careful to stay on route descending the climber\'s trail. It is not all  that
well used or obvious in many spots. Once again my GPS helped in this  regard
as I had the upward track for guidance. We reached  the  creek  crossing  at
1:00 and Pete Lake at 2:45 where we had a long lunch and Beth took a dip  to
cool off.  A cool breeze here made the rest pleasant but  the  rest  of  the
way back to car we were plagued  by  hordes  of  maddening  mosquitoes.  The
welcome sight of the car came at 5:40, not a moment too soon for this  tired
body (8 miles, 600 ft, 6:40 hrs).

Total: 19 miles and 7000 ft in 3 days.

Additional Notes:

Gear: 50 m 8.2mm rope, full set of Alien cams, set of small  nuts,  a  dozen
or so carabineers and slings, hard hat, crampons  and  ice  axe.  Beth  took
rock shoes. I did not.

From the look of the climber\'s trail and the  old  tattered  rappel  slings,
this peak doesn\'t appear to be climbed all that often, which  surprised  me.
I thought it saw more traffic. But we found no new slings and no signs of  a
recent ascent other  than  a  few  possible  footprints  lower  down.  Maybe
everyone just uses the old slings.

Our times surely do not set any speed records. You might even say  they  are
downright slow, but we took our time to be careful and did make  it  up  and
down safely. And I don\'t think that is too bad for two 60+ older ladies.

Fay Pullen



