            'tr' => '
Agnes Mtn. (8115 ft - 1355P), Mt Asa  (7060  ft  -  220P)  and  Lyall  Ridge
(7760+ ft - 760P) - Agnes Mtn. Quad - August 7-12, 2008

Day 1 (Thursday) - Swamp Cr Camp: Stefan, Mike Torok,  Erin  Reading  and  I
left from my house at 5:30  to  catch  the  9:20  Lady  Express  at  Field\'s
Landing to Stehekin. They now have a fuel and excess  baggage  surcharge.  I
think you are allowed 75# total with each individual  item  less  than  55#,
but it was somewhat confusing and not well posted. In any event  they  tried
to rip off Stefan for some $12 more since his pack weighed 70#  but  somehow
he talked them out of it. It seems that with the high  cost  of  fuel  these
days all modes of transportation are looking  for  more  revenue.  This  did
not, however, apply to the bus shuttle to High  Bridge  which  is  still  $5
each way for the 11 mile trip, a real bargain. It was 12:30 by the  time  we
started up the Agnes Cr trail in stifling heat. I  do  not  normally  go  on
this long a trip and the unusually heavy weight of my pack  took  its  toll.
Fortunately the trail was  good  and  the  distance  not  that  far  to  our
comfortable camp at Swamp Cr (8.6 miles,  1700  ft,  4:30  hrs).  There  was
thunder and lightning with light rain during the night.

Day 2 (Friday) - Lyall Ridge: The original plan was  to  climb  Agnes  first
with bonus peaks added later as time  allowed,  but  unsettled  weather  and
thundershowers were predicted through Saturday, so  we  decided  to  reverse
things and climb Lyall Ridge  first.  This  turned  out  to  be  a  straight
forward trek up mostly pleasant terrain to the north  ridge  with  class  3+
scrambling the rest of the way to the summit (4900 ft, 4:45 hrs).  We  could
see a few spot fires (one on Needle Pk) started by last  night\'s  lightening
and a helicopter circling the area checking them out. The  day  had  started
mostly sunny but by the time we reached  the  top  at  1:20,  we  could  see
thunderclouds forming and when we left  an  hour  later  they  were  looking
downright ominous. We made it off the rock and about half  way  down  before
the storm hit. And I do mean hard. The first  wave  of  rain  came  down  in
buckets, so hard we sought shelter under a tree to wait  out  the  worst  of
it. We thought we had and started down again. Then a second wave hit and  it
rained even harder and added marble sized hail to the mix. Again  we  sought
shelter under a tree but it was hopeless. We were all soaked  and  cold  and
getting colder. It let up slightly only to have a third wave hit just as  we
dragged into camp looking and feeling like drowned  rats  (4.8  miles,  5300
ft, 8:45 hrs). Much of the ground was white with hail or flooded  with  deep
puddles. Swamp Creek was already running muddy brown.

Stefan, bless him, had thought to bring a large tarp which  he  had  erected
the night before over a fire pit. Now Mike, bless him also,  got  a  roaring
fire going. Once under the tarp in front of a warm fire things  didn\'t  look
quite so bleak and we spent the rest of the evening warming  up  and  drying
out.

Day 3 (Saturday) - Swamp Cr Camp: After our experience the  day  before  and
with the threat of more thundershowers, no one was  anxious  to  move  to  a
high camp. We did not want to be up high in such conditions. We even  passed
on a day climb of Needle Pk, putting all our hopes on improving weather  the
next day. But we were running out of time to climb Agnes. Actually  the  day
turned out to not be that bad, and we wondered if  we  had  made  the  right
decision to stay put. However, it was clear the weather was  still  unstable
and in fact it did rain again lightly in the  evening  and  the  high  peaks
stayed in fog. We kept a fire going all day enjoying  each  other\'s  company
and almost drying out our boots.

Day 4 (Sunday) - Mt Asa and High Camp:  This day dawned  cloudy  and  foggy.
With much trepidation and uncertainty, we decided to try for Agnes.  It  was
now or never.  Mostly  we  were  banking  on  the  long  range  forecast  of
improving weather that we had gotten before the start of  the  trip  but  we
had no idea if it was still valid. We left my tent and the tarp  up,  sorted
out any unneeded gear and hung extra food to lighten our  load  as  much  as
possible and started at 8:40. We followed the trail about a mile farther  to
near the confluence of Agnes and Spruce Creeks, crossed Agnes Cr on  a  log,
went upstream along Spruce Cr a short ways then headed uphill on a  timbered
rib. The going was actually quite good with very little brush. We  had  some
sun and some sprinkles on the way up and it was never certain which way  the
weather would go. About 1000 feet below the ridge we began traversing  right
to hit the 6800 ft saddle just SW of Asa, dumped our packs and followed  the
easy ridge to that summit (4300 ft, 5:30 hrs).

Mt Asa has little prominence but is a very historic summit. It was the  site
of a 1908 survey by Asa  Post  and  party  and  still  boasts  the  original
register. I have never before climbed any peak  with  a  register  over  100
years old. Adding even more interest was the second  ascent  by  Asa\'s  well
known son Austin Post  39  years  later.  After  reaching  this  summit  and
reading the historic register we all felt our trip was already a success.

The next hour was a race to beat the weather that we could  see  approaching
to our campsite. This we found in a delightful 7000 foot  meadow  saddle  SE
of Pt 7458 (4 miles, 4750 ft, 6:30 hr). We even had  running  water  from  a
snow patch a short ways downhill. I just managed to get my bivy tent up  and
all my gear stowed when it began to  rain.  But  it  wasn\'t  very  hard  and
didn\'t last long. We were able to have a  pleasant  dinner  outside  in  the
open.

Day 5 (Monday) - Agnes Mtn: It froze during the night and by morning  I  was
cold in my light sleeping bag, but that meant the  sky  was  clear  and  the
weather had finally turned for the better. We had a perfect summit  day.  We
were on our way by 6:00. Or rather I was on my way at 6:00. Stefan had  left
maybe 15 minutes earlier. He is the only person I know who can literally  be
ready 5 minutes after rolling out of his sleeping bag. This morning he  took
a little longer while he fired up the stove as a concession to those  of  us
who wanted something hot for breakfast. Anyone who  has  ever  climbed  with
Stefan also knows that normal people cannot keep  up  with  him.  Well  Erin
qualifies as not normal. This energetic woman is unreal. Not  only  can  she
keep up with Stefan, I think she could pass him. But then  she  is  only  25
years old. She left after me, blew past me and quickly  caught  up  to  him.
Between Stefan and Erin, poor Mike and I were  constantly  driven  close  to
exhaustion working at maximum capacity just to keep up. And I  must  mention
that Erin\'s choice of footwear is light low-cut tennies.  That  is  all  she
ever wears. She even straps on crampons when needed. No amount of  reasoning
can get her to acknowledge the advantage of  boots.  Of  course  you  cannot
argue with success. She does just  fine  and  certainly  can  climb  circles
around me. She did take rock shoes for the rock pitches though.

From camp we headed for Pt 7458 but got too high.  It  is  best  to  contour
this point via ledges on the left to the 7200 ft  (first)  notch  before  Pt
7760. We made another mistake  by  staying  on  the  ridge  here  and  doing
several roped pitches thinking we were climbing Pt 7760 only to discover  we
were on a sub point and had to do  a  short  rappel  to  get  off  it.  This
consumed a couple of hours and we weren\'t even past  Pt  7760  and  its  5.4
pitch yet. Fortunately Mike spied the slab bypass, which he  led,  mentioned
by Tom and Dan Sjolseth in their TR of last year that avoided that pitch.

On the ridge again easy terrain led to the final  notch  before  the  summit
tower of Agnes. We donned crampons to cross the snow patch and then  entered
a very loose gully up and to the  left.  After  several  hundred  feet,  the
gully came to a headwall just below the ridge and  we  scrambled  right.  We
passed a deep chimney with a chockstone and just beyond  that  was  the  5.6
crux pitch. Stefan led this difficult pitch then brought the rest of us  up.
At the top were rappel slings so we knew we were on route. Above  this  Mike
led another short slabby pitch to the last easy but loose  scramble  to  the
summit at 1:00 (1800 ft, 7 hrs). A large mountaineer register  indicated  we
were the 25th party to summit.

We did not tarry long as we had to get all the way  back  to  our  Swamp  Cr
camp before day\'s end. Two rappels  got  us  to  the  gully  which  we  then
downclimbed slowly  and  carefully  staying  close  together.  Rockfall  was
abundant. At the (final) notch Stefan came up with the idea to descend  1200
ft into the Yew Cr valley, traverse well below Pt 7760 and climb back up  to
the first notch and thus avoid the entire rocky ridge.  The  first  part  of
the descent gully was horrible loose rock and slick dirt and we all  thought
maybe this idea was  a  mistake.  Lower  we  were  able  to  get  onto  snow
(crampons needed) and with Mike making steps down things  got  easier.  Then
it was easy traversing on talus and softer snow to the  first  notch.  Notch
to notch took 2 hours which we all agreed  was  faster  than  reversing  the
ridge route. We were back to high  camp  by  5:15,  quickly  packed  up  and
dropped directly down on a left traverse until we intersected our up  route.
 We reached the log crossing in growing darkness and made our Swamp Cr  camp
at 9:30 (6 miles, 3100 ft, 11:15 hrs). We took time for a hot dinner  before
turning in, tired but happy climbers.

Day 6 (Tuesday) - Heading Home: We were up at  6:00  and  left  at  7:30  in
order to make the 12:15 shuttle at High Bridge.  We  all  went  at  our  own
pace. Erin made it first, followed by Stefan, then Mike. I  brought  up  the
rear but still got to High Bridge in plenty  of  time  to  wash  up  in  the
Stehekin River and put on the clean clothes I had stashed there (8.6  miles,
650 ft, 3:40 hrs). We had a little time to kill in Stehekin before the  2:15
boat so we checked out the visitor center and listened to a  short  talk  on
the disadvantages of constant fire  suppression  given  by  an  enthusiastic
young Park Ranger. I slept almost the  entire  boat  ride  back  to  Field\'s
Point. We reached my home, after a stop for dinner, at 9:30. Yes indeed,  it
takes a long time to travel to the Stehekin area.

Grand Total: 32 miles and 15,500 ft in 6 days.

Fay Pullen

