            'title' => 'Gabriel Pk (7920+ ft - 1920P), Elija Ridge (7739 ft - 2019P), Joseph Pk (7521 ft - 401P), Beebe Mtn (7416 ft - 1056P), Tarheel Pk (7160+ ft - 600P) and Mebee BM (6570 ft - 330P) - Crater Mtn Quad - August 22-24, 2008',
            'tr' => '
Gabriel Pk (7920+ ft - 1920P), Elija Ridge (7739  ft  -  2019P),  Joseph  Pk
(7521 ft - 401P), Beebe Mtn (7416 ft - 1056P), Tarheel Pk (7160+ ft -  600P)
and Mebee BM (6570 ft - 330P) - Crater Mtn Quad - August 22-24, 2008

I was somewhat worried about doing this  group  of  peaks  so  late  in  the
season, afraid I would run into horrible brush on the approach and  lack  of
water for camping on the  ridge.  I  also  wanted  longer  daylight.  I  had
actually planned on doing this trip back in June when  such  concerns  would
not be an issue, but the night before I was all set to go I got a call  from
Paul Klenke inviting me on Lincoln. Guess which peak took precedence!

Day 1(Friday): Mebee and Tarheel - I essentially  followed  the  route  that
Mike T and Matt B did in early June  of  last  year,  except  that  they  of
course had much more snow  which  would  have  made  much  of  the  approach
easier. I parked at the turnout just past County Line Cr (elev 2700 ft)  and
followed the ridge just to the left. It began well enough  in  an  old  burn
and open forest but soon deteriorated to moderate brush.  It  wasn\'t  really
horrible, just enough to be annoying, slow  me  down  and  prevent  me  from
wearing shorts. Somewhere around 5000 ft I broke out into open  meadows  and
the going became much more pleasant with views expanding at  every  step.  I
reached the summit of Mebee BM at  3:45  (3  miles,  3750  ft,  4  hrs)  and
reveled in my spectacular surroundings.

From Mebee I dropped down the left side past cliffs to 6200 ft and  followed
the lovely meadowed ridge over Pt 6740 to a  gorgeous  campsite,  elev  6680
ft, at 5:00 (4.25 miles, 4300 ft, 5:15 hr).  I had a view  of  Ragged  Ridge
out my front door and a view of Crater and Jack out my back door. What  more
could I ask for? Well, water somewhere nearby  would  have  been  nice.   My
fears of the ridge being dry materialized. I could see  small  snow  patches
on the ridge and in the  basin  below  Tarheel,  but  on  closer  inspection
neither produced running water. As a last resort there was a  5919  ft  lake
far below but I so didn\'t want to descend 800 ft. Melting snow was  my  only
other option. Such are the hazards of ridge camping late in the season.

After setting up camp, I wandered  the  short  distance  up  Tarheel.  After
climbing the main summit, I also went up the NE peak which turned out to  be
a fun little class 3-4 scramble. On the way back  to  camp  I  filled  up  a
large bag with snow to melt for dinner (1.25 miles, 800 ft. 2 hrs).

Day 2(Saturday): Joseph Pk, Elija Ridge and  Gabriel  -  I  began  the  next
morning at 7:15, not as early as I  would  have  liked,  but  the  days  are
already getting noticeably shorter and it doesn\'t  get  light  until  around
6:00 now. After being out recently  on  Agnes  with  super  guy  and  wonder
woman, it was a real pleasure to go at my own pace. It was also a  necessity
as I was still recovering from a virus I most likely picked up on  the  boat
ride back from Stehekin  and  I  was  feeling  a  bit  slow  and  lethargic.
However, the lovely terrain invigorated me and gave me  energy  as  I  began
the long traverse toward Elija Ridge. This entailed dropping to the 6320  ft
saddle between Elija and  Tarheel,  traversing  seemingly  endless  somewhat
unpleasant scree and talus to Joseph, dropping again to the 7120 ft  Joseph-
Elija saddle before the final climb to the high  point  of  Elija  Ridge  (3
miles, 1900 ft, 3 hrs).  I had been warned there  was  no  register  so  had
brought one of mine.

Although I had already  climbed  Joseph  on  the  way  to  Elija,  I  wasn\'t
positive where the actual summit was and since  it  appeared  easier  to  go
back over the top rather than traverse  some  very  unpleasant  sidehill,  I
reclimbed to that summit (2300 ft, 5 hrs). This is when I  came  across  the
register placed by Stefan on 5/19/02. (I am not sure how  I  missed  it  the
first time around.)  Stefan  had  named  this  peak  Joseph  at  that  time,
although I believe JR calls it Ezekiel. The register  was  soaking  wet  and
partially illegible. I spent the better part of 20  minutes  drying  it  out
and transcribing the entries onto WATERPROOF paper.  Included were:

    7/4/04 - Don and Natala Goodman  on  a  traverse  of  Elija  Ridge  from
Panther to Cabinet Creeks

    8/6/05 - Paul Klenke and Mike Collins

    6/2/07 - Mike Torok, Matt Burton, Eric Johnson, Billie  Butterfield  and
Erin Reading

    6/2/08??? -my best guess, hard to read - Dave Creeden

I was surprised there was a register on this minor peak and  none  on  Elija
Ridge. I realize Elija could  have  originally  fallen  victim  to  "He  Who
Removes All Registers From The North Cascades National Park",  but  come  on
guys, one of you could have replaced it since. I  always  feel  disappointed
when I am denied the chance to read  the  previous  climbing  history  of  a
major peak.

Gabriel was next on the agenda. I had a good view earlier of  the  basin  to
the NE and the three possible gullies leading to the SE ridge  mentioned  by
Mike in his TR. None contained any significant snow. I had  brought  ice  ax
and crampons along but seeing no snow had left them both in camp. To get  to
the basin I first had to descend some  1800  ft  to  the  5700  ft  Gabriel-
Cabinet Cr saddle. I was afraid I would run into brush in the  creek  bottom
but was pleasantly surprised to find it very easy travel through open  woods
and marshy meadows. Here I ran into my first running water of the  trip  and
stopped to soak my poor aching  feet  and  augment  my  water  supply.  Good
travel continued up alongside a gushing creek into the beautiful  NE  basin.
Then it all went to heck. With no snow all the gullies looked unpleasant  so
I took the most direct first one on the right. Bad choice.  The  upper  part
was gosh awful hard dirt and slabby rock that I barely managed  to  claw  my
way up. No way was I coming down that.

At the top of the gully I was confronted with  more  unpleasant  terrain,  a
series of ribs and gullies to cross over class  2-3+  terrain.  I  took  the
traverse quite high. At times it looked as if I would  be  cliffed  out  but
when needed a ledge always appeared that went.   After  taking  much  longer
(or was I just  getting  tired  and  footsore?)  than  anticipated  for  the
distance, I topped out on Gabriel\'s summit at 5:00 (7 miles, 4700  ft,  9:45
hrs). Again I left a register as there was none. I retraced my route,  which
was intricate in spots, to my up notch but continued traversing to the  next
notch to the SE along the ridge. After a short step off the ridge  this  led
to an easy gully (I believe this is the one Mike and Matt  took)  with  fast
scree plunge stepping. In no time at all I was down to the  5700  ft  saddle
and creek. I again soaked my even more aching feet  and  filled  up  with  Â½
gallon of water for dinner. It was then a slow tired grind  uphill  to  camp
where I arrived at 8:15 in dimming light (10 miles, 5700 ft, 13 hrs).

Day 3(Sunday): Beebe Mtn - The weather  forecast  was  for  rain  coming  in
sometime during the day. Exactly when was  uncertain.  My  plan  was  if  it
looked bad in the morning I would just head out,  otherwise  I  would  climb
Beebe. A strong wind came in during the night  signaling  a  change  in  the
weather but rain held off, so at 7:00 I headed for Beebe.  First  I  had  to
get past the annoying rocky bump of Pt 7026. This I did by  going  over  the
top. At times it looked like I would get cliffed out on the descent  to  the
Beebe saddle, but by going to the left there was a way down.  From  then  on
it was a most enjoyable ridge ramble to the  summit  of  Beebe  (2.5  miles,
1300 ft, 2 hrs).  On the way back I contoured around the  left  side  of  Pt
7026 on an interesting ledge into the basin N of Tarheel  and  regained  the
ridge up easy scree. This was easier than going over the top again.

I was back in camp at 11:00 (5 miles, 2000 ft, 4 hrs)  and  after  taking  a
short rest, packed up and left  at  12:30.  I  could  see  the  weather  was
deteriorating. In fact it was beginning to sprinkle lightly. I did not  want
to return over Mebee. Instead I went down a spur arm ridge off Pt 6740  that
led to County Line Creek. I was afraid this route might  be  brushy  but  it
wasn\'t too bad, certainly better than Meebe\'s ridge. When I came  to  County
Line Creek at 4000 ft, I crossed it and then traversed to my up route  below
all the brush. I reached the car at  3:30  just  as  it  began  to  rain  in
earnest (3 miles, 100 ft, 3 hrs).

Total: 23.5 miles and 12,900 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen











