            'tr' => '
Mt Arriva (8215 ft - 1215P) and Fisher Pk (8040+ ft  -  720P)  -  Mt  Arriva
Quad - August 29-31, 2008

I joined Jim, Eileen, Kevin, Beth and Don  for  this  trip  into  the  North
Cascades National Park. Given the steadily  deteriorating  weather  forecast
before we left, I put our chance of success  during  the  3-day  time  frame
allotted at close to zero. So convinced was I of this  that  I  allowed  for
another day to increase my chances or perhaps do other peaks  in  the  area.
What I didn\'t take into consideration  was  the  lucky  "honeymoon  effect".
Jim and Eileen had just been married the week before.

Day 1 (Friday) - We all met at the Easy Pass TH at  10:30,  hiked  the  easy
3.5 miles to the pass and descended 2 miles down the other side into  Fisher
Cr. We were all delighted that the weather  was  holding  and  we  even  had
passable views. At the stake pointing to Fisher Cr camp  we  came  across  a
volunteer Park Ranger.  Good  thing  I  had  stopped  to  get  a  permit  in
Marblemount. I had a feeling this popular trail  would  be  patrolled  on  a
holiday weekend.

From the stake we followed a way trail into  beautiful  Fisher  Creek  Basin
until it was obliterated by a  massive  avalanche  that  had  come  off  the
cliffs of Arches and swept up the opposite side of the valley.   We  crossed
the creek and continued up the open valley to the base  of  the  gully  that
leads to Silent Lakes. Jim calls this Silent Gully but it  is  a  bit  of  a
misnomer as it was anything but silent as the six of us made our way up  the
horrid almost fluid loose mixture of mud and dirt and rocks.  Just  when  we
thought the gully couldn\'t get any worse we found it capped by 200  foot  of
hard snow. With the day being reasonably warm we  were  just  able  to  kick
steps up it (none of us had crampons)  but  with  temperatures  forecast  to
soon plummet we all knew it would be a problem on  the  way  down.  To  make
matters even worse just as we topped the crest to Silent Lakes  the  weather
took a nosedive with driving wind and rain. We found a  partially  protected
heather bowl above the upper lake and set up camp (7.5 miles, 4800 ft,  7:15
hrs). My only thought was to crawl into my tent and sleeping bag out of  the
weather and  hole  up  for  the  rest  of  the  night.   But  soon  I  heard
conversation and laughter as everyone else gathered outside for dinner.  How
could I not join them? It took a lot to dampen  the  high  spirits  of  this
group, although I suspect much of it was fueled  by  gourmet  chocolate  and
brandy. Even so, as we heard rain much of the night no  one  had  much  hope
for a decent summit day on the morrow.

Day 2 (Saturday) - We were all stunned to awaken to a  reasonable  day.  The
fog came and went as did the views, but it  was  dry  and  stayed  that  way
until the very end of the day. It  was,  however,  downright  cold  and  had
frozen overnight.  So off we went to try for Arriva first. We were aided  by
Mike Torok\'s report from his and Matt\'s Labor Day trip of  last  year.  From
Upper Silent Lake we made our way to a first notch at 7200  ft  to  cross  a
rocky rib, then made a long up and down rising traverse to  a  second  notch
at 7400 ft leading to a large talus basin below a third  7760  ft  notch  in
Arriva\'s S ridge. A fun class 2-3 scramble along this ridge on ledges and  a
short gully led to the summit block where we had  several  choices.  I  went
all the way to another notch in the E ridge where a class 4  crack  appealed
to me but Beth found an easier all class 3 route by following a  ledge  back
to the S ridge. We were all on the summit by 12:30 (1800 ft, 3:15 hr).

For the way back, the gals followed a low route that went below the  rib  of
the second notch while the guys retraced the high route. We had  to  descend
a few hundred feet but the terrain was mostly heather slopes and easier  and
faster to traverse. We were back in camp by 4:00 where five of us  took  off
immediately for Fisher. Don decided to try his hand  at  fishing  the  lakes
but reported them barren.

Fisher turned out to be a delightful mostly class 3 scramble  along  the  NW
ridge with only one short class 4 section where some might like a rope,  and
we were on the summit by 5:20 (1250 ft, 1:20 hr). Unfortunately the  weather
was deteriorating again and we had no views. We made it back  to  camp  just
as it began to snow lightly. Despite the  snow,  we  had  another  laughter,
chocolate and brandy filled social dinner until the  increasing  cold  drove
even the highest of spirit into warm sleeping bags.

Day 3 (Sunday) - We did not wake to reasonable weather on this day.  It  was
cold and foggy and windy and had snowed maybe an inch. All  thoughts  of  my
staying another day and climbing other  peaks  quickly  evaporated.   A  hot
shower and warm bed sounded mighty appealing. But first we had to  get  down
the dreaded snow slope. If anything it was worse than anticipated  -  frozen
rock solid and impossible to kick any kind of a decent step  into.  Our  one
rope was only 120 ft long but we managed to get down the steepest part  with
one double rope rappel from a boulder anchor at the top and  a  single  rope
rappel from a chopped ledge and bollard anchor in the middle. This left  Jim
to downclimb belayed by Kevin from another bollard. There was  just  no  way
to get an ice axe all the way into the snow. After all of us made it  safely
down the snow the rest of the gully seemed a piece of cake.  We  ambled  the
rest of the way  to  the  TH  accompanied  by  intermittent  snow  and  rain
showers.  None of us minded. We were all grateful to have  squeaked  in  our
two peaks during the only possible weather window. (7.5 miles,  1700  ft,  7
hrs).

Total: 20 miles and 10,200 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen





