South Twin Sister (7000+ ft - 3520P) - Twin Sisters Mtn Quad - September
10, 2008

Okay, so I feel really stupid, although I like to think my error is  due  to
the fact that I am a perennial optimist. When I came to the bridge over  the
Middle Fork Nooksack River on the approach road to Twin Sisters I  found  no
warning signs and saw no gate. I suppose  I  should  have  known  better  as
there was a gate somewhere hereabouts when I climbed North Twin a few  years
ago and all recent descriptions start the climb by biking up the  road  from
the gate. I did have a bike with me and I did expect to use it.  But  things
could have changed as there were signs of new repair work  near  the  bridge
and I optimistically thought maybe they had removed the gate and opened  the
road to the public. So I just kept driving feeling very lucky. I  felt  even
luckier when I discovered the side road toward  the  Twins  was  also  newly
bulldozed and I could drive the spur road all the way to  its  end  at  3300
ft. However, I didn\'t feel so lucky on the return.

By saving some 5 miles (one way) and a couple of hours of  biking  by  being
able to drive so high, I felt much less time pressure so was  able  to  take
my time to thoroughly enjoy the  climb.  I  followed  the  remnants  of  the
abandoned road beyond where I parked about 0.75 mile, where I  then  picked  up
the rough climber\'s trail that leads to the  large  basin  between  the  two
Twin Sisters.  I stayed too high, ignoring a cairned trail into  brush,  and
lost time traversing cliffy and scrubby terrain to reach  the  upper  basin.
It is best to get into the basin lower. I corrected this mistake on the  way
out. From the basin I worked my way up the north side onto  the  west  ridge
to a notch just before Pt 6405. From there  I  followed  the  ridge  to  the
summit. If you stay on route and follow the easiest path the whole climb  is
class 2-3. Much of the way is cairned. Several  pinnacles  are  bypassed  on
ledges first on the south then on the north. The final climb to  the  summit
plateau is on the south side.  The  rock  is  that  wonderful  reddish-brown
periodotite that makes  for  delightful  scrambling  (and  makes  N  Twin  a
classic) and in several places I couldn\'t resist foregoing sandy ledges  for
better climbing.  Be aware though that it is farther along  the  west  ridge
to the summit than it looks and takes longer  than  one  might  think  (2.75
miles, 3900 ft, 5 hrs).

Although according to the map the high point of 7000+ ft  is  the  NW  bump,
the register is on the SE  bump  which  actually  also  read  higher  on  my
altimeter. The register was placed in 1997 and filled with the usual  scraps
of paper which although dry were still mostly illegible. The only entries  I
recognized, that I was able to read, were by Jim  Brisbine  on  8/10/03  and
Paul Klenke/Jeff Rodgers on 7/15/06. The most recent ascent was  5/25/08.  I
added my name and a few sheets of waterproof paper. I stayed 40  minutes  on
top before taking almost 4 hours to descend, not being terribly faster  than
on the way up.

I was feeling pretty pleased with myself at finally bagging this peak  until
driving out and being shocked to  see  a  closed  and  locked  gate  on  the
bridge. I swear I hadn\'t seen it in  the  morning.  It  was  on  the  bridge
itself and I guess in the open position had looked like part of  the  bridge
guard rail. But I am certain there were no warning signs. I am usually  very
careful about not driving through open gates for fear  of  this  very  thing
happening but this one took me completely by surprise. What to  do?  Well  I
had seen an open gate on the Blue Mtn Road off Mosquito  Lake  Road  on  the
drive in. The map indicated that road connected with  the  road  I  was  on.
Maybe I would get lucky and that gate would still be open. I was not  lucky.
By the time I got there, after driving some 10  winding  dusty  miles,  that
gate was closed and locked also. There was no help for it. I would  have  to
wait it out till morning (I sure am glad this wasn\'t a Friday). I decided  I
would stay at this gate as it was closer to my route home and I  thought  it
might be opened earlier than the other gate.  I  found  a  partially  hidden
spot off the road a short ways away  for  my  second  unplanned  peak  bivy,
although I am not sure if a car bivy counts.

I was a little cramped as I had a bike in the car and  I  did  not  want  to
remove it so I could make a fast getaway. I did have  a  change  of  clothes
and a blanket and enough to drink. My main problem was I was very hungry.  I
didn\'t have enough food with me.  Precisely at 3:50 am I was awakened  by  a
large dump truck driving by. These guys sure start work  early!  30  seconds
later I pulled out of my bivy hoping I didn\'t meet a logging or  dump  truck
caravan and that the gate was now open. I didn\'t and it was. I  was  out  of
there without being seen. Such an early start allowed me to get  home  by  6
am and miss all the morning rush hour. Even so I was surprised by  how  much
traffic there is at 5 am during a weekday. Being a night person I am  rarely
up at that hour.

Such was the ignominious end to a very nice climb.

Fay Pullen

