            'tr' => '
American Border Peak (7994 ft - 2794P) - September 13-14, 2008

Day 1 (Saturday) - Mike and I had been trying to get this peak for a  couple
of years but things never quite  worked  out.  It  all  came  together  when
Stefan invited us to join  him  and  Greg  on  this  beautiful  weekend.  We
couldn\'t have had nicer weather. Due to family commitments, Stefan  couldn\'t
leave town until fairly late, so  Mike  and  I  decided  to  go  up  earlier
together so we could take our time. Mike drove his truck up  the  rough  but
reasonably passable road to Twin Lakes and the High Pass TH  (5200  ft).  We
were both shocked at the  number  of  vehicles  parked  at  these  otherwise
beautiful lakes. There must have been close to 50 with  another  50  at  the
Yellow Aster Butte TH  farther  down.  Good  weather  sure  brings  out  the
hordes.

We started for High Pass at 12:45 taking a tad over an hour to get there  (2
miles, 1100 ft). From there we dropped down a couple of hundred feet on  the
Gargett Mine trail to where it crossed the creek, descended  a  few  hundred
more feet and then traversed across this first basin to cross a  wooded  rib
at about 5400 ft. We were following Paul Klenke\'s excellent TR and  pictures
from September 9, 2007 which saved us a lot of time and possible  confusion.
Much to our surprise we ran into a couple coming  out  while  crossing  this
first rib. They had not made the summit, being put off by a distant view  of
"hanging snow" in the snow gully but they had not  investigated  closer.  We
thought this a bit odd and not at all typical  of  hard  core  climbers  and
concluded one or  the  other  was  psyched  out  and  just  didn\'t  want  to
continue.

We crossed the second basin and rib high through a  6240  ft  notch.  Up  to
this point the approach was fairly pleasant but the climb to this notch  was
anything but. The last bit was very steep loose scree and dirt. The  descent
down the other side into the third basin and to  our  intended  campsite  at
5600 ft was no better. The rocks were bigger but still  just  as  loose.  At
the base of a dwindling snowpatch we found a semi-level  vegetated  spot  to
camp with an old stone wall. Although one would be hard-pressed  to  find  a
spot big enough for a full sized tent  it  was  reasonably  comfortable  for
bivys. Just downhill of  the  snowpatch  we  found  running  water  when  we
arrived at 5:00  (3.5  miles,  2000  ft,  4:15  hr).  It  is  noteworthy  to
emphasize though, just as Klenke observed, that when we  returned  the  next
day at 1:30 there was no running water. In anticipation of this Mike  filled
a large bag.

Even though they left well after us, Stefan and  Greg  showed  up  at  6:30.
They must have really been moving. We had all agreed to bring no  stove  and
have cold dinners. After all it was only  one  night  and  the  weather  was
warm. I do like  my  cup  of  tea  with  dinner  though,  so  I  decided  to
experiment with a tiny Esbit stove that used  solid  fuel  cubes.  With  one
fuel cube the whole thing only weighed 1.5 oz. Paired with  a  titanium  cup
it seemed like the perfect setup for a light bivy. Well, it  turned  out  to
be a total bust. What they don\'t tell you is that those fuel cubes stink  to
high heaven while burning. I ended up almost poisoning poor  Mike  and  Greg
with the fumes and ruining their appetites to boot (they  were  downwind  of
me). Then the cubes are terribly  inefficient.  It  took  about  15  minutes
using a whole cube to heat one cup of water and it  never  even  boiled.  It
did get hot enough to brew my tea but it was not worth the wait and smell.

Day 2 (Sunday) - We started at 6:30 taking a  high  route  at  the  base  of
slabs to climb to the 6840 ft saddle in the American  Border-Larrabee  ridge
(1250 ft, 1 hr). From the saddle we picked up a faint trail along the  crest
until coming to nasty looking grey slabs on the right  side.  A  nice  ledge
crossed below these slabs to a gully left of "de Gaulle\'s Nose". This  gully
had a steep step and lots of loose rock. From the top of the gully we  could
see the snow gully that had turned back the  couple.  Goodness  gracious  it
didn\'t look bad at all and other than more horribly  loose  rock  above  and
below the snow it wasn\'t. We easily crawled the right  hand  moat.  No  snow
gear needed at all. From the notch at the top a narrow  ledge,  exposed  but
easily scrambled, led to the base of the chimney.

Here we roped up. Stefan led directly up the  5.4  route  into  the  Chimney
with Greg following. Mike opted for the Klenke  class  4  bypass  which  was
fine by me. Easier is better as far as I am concerned. Mike set up  a  belay
to the side and we waited until Stefan and Greg were  all  the  way  up  the
chimney before I led through.  The  first  part  of  the  chimney  was  easy
scrambling until reaching two chockstones. The last one gave me trouble.  At
the top of the chimney was the keyhole which even I  had  a  little  trouble
squeezing through even after taking off my pack. It is not very big.

We scrambled another steep loose gully above the chimney to get to the  easy
summit ridge, bypassed a pinnacle on the  left  and  climbed  to  the  final
summit tower arriving on top at 10:00  (2300  ft,  3:30  hr).  There  was  a
register with the usual scraps of paper so I added a waterproof notebook.  I
really don\'t understand why so many registers have just scraps of  paper  in
them. If someone goes to the trouble of bringing up a register container  in
the first place why not include  a  (preferably  waterproof)  notebook?  Why
just scraps  of  paper,  which  are  often  just  the  back  side  of  route
descriptions as if no other paper was available? Oh well, I  guess  it  just
serves to give me a mission in life.

A handline was used down the first gully above the chimney. We  set  up  two
single rope rappels down the chimney to make the ropes easier  to  pull  and
each person rappelled all the way to the bottom to be out  of  the  line  of
rockfall. The rest of the route we downclimbed. We  were  back  in  camp  at
1:30. Stefan and Greg left 15 minutes later, Mike and  I  15  minutes  after
that. By the time we reached the High Pass trail 2.5  hours  later  we  had
both had enough of scree  and  talus  and  sidehilling  and  our  feet  were
complaining loudly. In comparison the last hour to the TH was heaven  to  be
on level trail. (3.5 miles, 1600 ft, 3:40 hrs from camp).

Total: 10 miles and 6000 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen







