            'title' => 'Cowap Pk (5658 ft - 858P), East Canyon Ridge (5408 ft - 408P) & Middle Canyon Ridge (5405 ft - 405P) - Bearpaw Mtn Quad; and West Canyon Ridge (5327 ft - 687P) - Glacier Quad - September 17-18, 2008',
            'tr' => '
Cowap Pk (5658 ft - 858P), East Canyon Ridge  (5408  ft  -  408P)  &  Middle
Canyon Ridge (5405 ft - 405P) - Bearpaw Mtn  Quad;  and  West  Canyon  Ridge
(5327 ft - 687P) - Glacier Quad - September 17-18, 2008

Canyon Ridge is a beautiful lonesome ridge  about  8  miles  long  a  couple
miles south of the Canadian Border and north of Bearpaw Mtn. Counting  Cowap
Pk at the east edge, there are 4 peaks of prominence  along  its  length.  A
trail follows most of the ridge but it is little used and hard to follow  in
spots especially in meadowy areas at the west end. My plan was to  car  camp
at the Damfino Lakes TH at the east end  to  also  allow  time  to  hike  to
Excelsior Pass and the superb High Divide Trail which is gorgeous this  time
of year.

Day 1: Cowap and East & Middle Canyon Ridge  -  I  began  from  the  Damfino
Lakes TH which is some 15 miles up Road 31  (Canyon  Cr  Road)  off  the  Mt
Baker Highway. I followed the Damfino Lakes Trail .7  miles  to  the  Canyon
Ridge Trail junction and this trail .4 miles farther  to  the  Boundary  Way
Trail. This trail can be followed to the NE ridge  for  a  walkup  route  on
Cowap but I chose a shorter faster route directly up   a  steep  gully  that
hit the ridge just SW of the summit and involved a short scramble. From  the
summit I had a splendid though somewhat hazy view of  American  Border  Peak
where I had just been a few days before (1450 ft, 1:30 hr).

From Cowap I followed  the  ridge  SW  and  then  W  (some  brush)  until  I
intersected the Canyon Ridge Trail which then led all the way to the  summit
of East Canyon Ridge (3 hrs). The trail was fairly good to this point.  From
there on it was unmaintained and deteriorated as it went up and  down  along
the ridge until I lost it completely in extensive wet  (and  buggy)  meadows
in the broad saddle between Middle Canyon  and  Liumchen  Mtn.  This  latter
peak is in B.C., very close at this point and  rather  attractive.  I  would
have liked to have climbed it also but it was  another  1000  ft  or  so  of
elevation and I just didn\'t have the time.  As  it  was,  I  reached  Middle
Canyon summit at the late hour of 5:00 and I even had to forego West  Canyon
Ridge which was about another 2.5 rugged miles distant. The whole ridge  had
taken longer to traverse than I had anticipated. I barely made  it  back  to
the TH before dark even taking a shortcut directly  down  to  the  road  (11
miles, 3400 ft, 7:45 hrs). The days are definitely getting shorter.

Day 2: Excelsior Pass  and  High  Divide  Trail  -  This  is  an  absolutely
gorgeous trail and highly recommended as a mellow trip.  But  just  in  case
some of you might think I have slipped a cog hiking a trail that had no  new
peaks for me along it (I had previously done them all from Welcome Pass),  I
did have an ulterior motive. When camping on the ridge to  do  Damfino  Peak
back in June I had lost my spoon and I wanted to see if  I  could  find  it.
You might think that was a lot of trouble to go to just for a spoon  but  it
was my favorite (expensive) titanium spoon. I also  discovered  it  was  not
available anymore and could not be replaced. All  I  could  find  were  much
larger ones or sporks, which I don\'t care for. Besides,  that  spoon  and  I
had shared many a mountain  meal  together  and  I  just  couldn\'t  bear  to
abandon it without at least trying to find it. I did find it and had a  most
enjoyable trail hike in the process of doing so  (12  miles,  2600  ft  5:20
hr).

West Canyon Ridge - I still wanted to pick up this peak.  The  Canyon  Ridge
trail can also be accessed from the west end off Road 3140  so  on  the  way
out I drove up this road which is in good shape to the  ridge  saddle  (4400
ft). The trail doesn\'t start here but starts from the end of  a  very  rough
road that switchbacks downhill to 4000 ft. I drove this road for  1.2  miles
as far I dared then started hiking. The trail climbs over a spur  saddle  at
4400 ft and descends to a meadow at 4200.  I  could  see  it  was  going  to
descend even farther to get around the cliffs on  the  north  side  of  West
Canyon Ridge before climbing back  to  the  ridge  on  the  east.  I  hadn\'t
counted on such a roundabout route. From the 4200  ft  meadow  I  spotted  a
steep vegetated slope that looked like it would go all the way to  the  west
ridge through the cliffs. This worked well but then I ran into cliffs  at  a
200 ft step along the ridge and, although I forced a way up, I did a lot  of
zigging and zagging and using bush belays to pull myself up.   Once  on  the
summit (1:45 hr) I didn\'t think I could safely go back down the  way  I  had
come up. So I continued east along the ridge, dropping  to  the  north  once
past cliffs to pick up the trail and follow it back to  the  car  (3  miles,
2000 ft and 3:20 hrs). My assessment  is  that  West  Canyon  Ridge  is  for
demented peakbaggers only. It is fairly brushy, has no real  views  and  the
trail (and road) to get near it is steep, rough and wanders all over out  of
the way. For enjoyment stick to the east portion of Canyon Ridge.

Fay Pullen

