            'title' => 'Fool Hen Peak (8168 ft - 1048P), Billy Goat Mtn Quad 1 (8055 ft - 455P), Billy Goat Mtn Quad 2 (7851 ft - 571P), Billy Goat Mtn Quad 4 (7553 ft - 433P) & Billy Goat Mtn Quad 5 (7277 ft - 637P) - Billy Goat Mtn Quad; and Ashnola Pass Quad 1 (8025 ft - 905P), Ashnola Pass Quad 2 (7949 ft - 989 ft), Ashnola Pass Quad 3 (7838 ft - 998P) & Diamond Pt (7916 ft - 396P) - Ashnola Pass Quad - September 26-29, 2008',
            'tr' => '
Fool Hen Peak (8168 ft - 1048P), Billy Goat Mtn Quad  1 (8055  ft  -  455P),
Billy Goat Mtn Quad 2 (7851 ft - 571P), Billy Goat Mtn Quad  4  (7553  ft  -
433P) & Billy Goat Mtn Quad 5 (7277 ft - 637P) - Billy Goat  Mtn  Quad;  and
Ashnola Pass Quad 1 (8025 ft - 905P), Ashnola Pass Quad 2  (7949  ft  -  989
ft), Ashnola Pass Quad 3 (7838 ft - 998P) & Diamond Pt (7916 ft  -  396P)  -
Ashnola Pass Quad - September 26-29, 2008

I spent 4 glorious days wandering open high country  from  a  base  camp  at
Fool Hen Lake. This area is truly a ridge rambler\'s delight and  appears  to
be little visited. I found no registers on any of the summits  but  expected
this and took enough of my own for all of them except Diamond  Pt.  Many  of
the minor trails are hard to follow or  non-existent,  but  the  terrain  is
mellow and crosscountry travel easy  most  everywhere,  although  there  are
many ups and downs. The only downside is much of the scenery  is  marred  by
the aftereffects of the extensive fires of recent years.

Day 1 (Friday): Billy Goat Mtn 1 and Billy Goat Mtn 2 - I started  from  the
Billy Goat TH at 12:15. My goal was to reach Fool Hen  Lake  but  I  knew  I
would be hard pressed to do that before dark. I reached Billy Goat  Pass  at
1:45 where I met two hunters coming out. The High Hunt had  just  ended  the
previous day. These were the only people I saw the entire trip. At the  pass
I picked up the marked Burch Mtn Trail which climbs high  on  the  flank  of
Billy Goat 3 before dropping to the saddle  with  Burch  Mtn.  Larches  were
lovely here, just beginning to turn golden. I had previously  climbed  Billy
Goat 3 and Burch so  could  bypass  them  both,  but  I  actually  ended  up
following the trail almost all the way to the summit of Burch once again  as
this was easier than trying to go around on the cliffy north side.  Once  on
the ridge it was easy travel over Billy Goat 2 and on to Billy Goat 1  (4900
ft, 6:30 hrs).

It was now 6:45 and rapidly getting dark. I traversed most of the  way  past
Pt 7987 before needing a headlamp. My main worry was finding a way  off  the
ridge. My hope was to find Trail 532 that The Billy Goat  Mtn  Green  Trails
map shows crossing the ridge at "Fool Hen Pass", but it was also  marked  as
" hard to follow" so I wasn\'t surprised when I found no sign of  it  when  I
reached the broad pass in the  dark.  I  briefly  considered  camping  right
there but there was no water and I had very little left to get  through  the
night. So I decided to try to just head to  Fool  Hen  Lake  by  my  GPS.  I
continued along the ridge over Pt 7836 and up toward Pt  8062  to  get  past
cliffs to where I could descend more easily and by  golly  I  stumbled  onto
the large cairn that marked the spot where the trail  exited  the  ridge  at
about 7900 ft. It was really quite good as it switchbacked down but  I  lost
it again in a basin at 7400 ft. I continued  blindly  on  following  my  GPS
wandering up and down on a steep traverse above cliffs  until  I  reached  a
gentle basin and could descend toward the  lake.  A  little  after  10:00  I
joyfully found running water (the first all day) and set up my tent  on  the
first flat spot I found. It turned out to be a primo spot. Not too  bad  for
a choice made in the dark (10 miles, 5700 ft, 10 hrs).

Day 2 (Saturday): Fool Hen Pk, Billy Goat Mtn 4, Diamond Pt, Ashnola Pass  1
(aka Diamond Ridge) and Ashnola Pass 2 -  Another advantage of my choice  of
campsite that I wasn\'t aware of the night before was that  it  captured  the
morning sun very early, a real bonus as it froze during the  night.  But  by
the time I began the day at 8:30 I was nicely warmed up.  Fool Hen Pk was  a
simple and leisurely 50 minutes above camp. Then it was  on  to  Billy  Goat
Mtn 4. I had first to descend to tarn  7119.  I  had  thought  that  in  the
daylight I would be able to find Trail 532  in  the  basin  above  Hen  Fool
Lake. I didn\'t. In fact I never saw any sign of the trail until I  descended
onto the open flat spur below Pt 7615. Here  the  trail  magically  appeared
and was fairly good all the way to "Diamond Pass".

Billy Goat Mtn 4 was a short pleasant hike  off  the  trail  after  which  I
continued to Diamond Pass where the main trail led all the  way  to  Diamond
Point, a former lookout site. From Diamond Point I followed the  easy  ridge
to Ashnola Pass 1. More easy terrain led down to  the  saddle  with  Ashnola
Pass 2, where I crossed Trail 532 and noted its location for  my  return.  I
had thought that I would have trouble fitting all five objective peaks  into
one day, but the terrain was so easy that I reached Ashnola Pass 2 at  3:20.
That did not mean, though, that I had much time to spare before  dark  as  I
still had a long way to get back to camp. But the whole day went faster  and
easier than anticipated.

I returned to the saddle where I picked up Trail 532. It started quite  good
and I  thought  I  would  have  no  trouble  following  it  but  it  quickly
deteriorated and became quite faint. It was well cairned, however, and  with
care I was able to stay with it back to Diamond Pass  and  on  to  the  spur
about tarn 7119 where I again lost the trail. I pulled into camp at 6:50  in
fading light, very pleased with my pleasant day of high ridge  rambling  (13
miles, 5700 ft, 10:20 hrs).

Day 3(Sunday): Billy Goat Mtn 5 and Ashnola Pass 3  (aka  Flintstone  Pk)  -
Again I was on my way at 8:30. I wasn\'t all  that  thrilled  with  my  first
objective of Billy Goat Mtn 5. It really didn\'t  look  very  interesting  on
the map but it turned out to be  delightful.  Despite  traversing  a  recent
burn the terrain was rather attractive with open meadows and the odd  golden
larch contrasting picturesquely with blackened trees. I reached  the  summit
at 10:50 where I had a good  view  of  Ashnola  Pass  3,  my  next  possible
objective. This peak looked to be a bit  more  difficult  than  any  of  the
others, was a long ways away and involved an elevation loss of  2000  ft.  I
considered passing on it and just going back to camp early but the  day  was
too nice not to continue even though I knew I  would  be  returning  in  the
dark.

I returned to the ridge saddle before  dropping  to  Fox  Cr  Trail  514.  I
followed this trail to Lake Cr Trail 500 at the distressingly low  elevation
of 5300 ft and then climbed along Lake Cr toward Ashnola Pass.  I  left  the
trail at 6100 ft and worked my way  up  a  series  of  gullies  that  snaked
through broken cliffs arriving at the summit plateau at  3:30  (3400  ft,  7
hr). I descended the same way and followed Trail 514 until I  could  take  a
short cut to Fox Lakes, rather than continue all the way to Diamond Pass.  I
reached the lower lake with just enough light to find a trail. There were  a
number of confusing way trails in this area, none of which were  marked,  so
I was very relieved when I finally came  to  the  junction  with  Trail  532
(also unmarked) and was once again on familiar territory. I reached camp  at
8:30, another long but rewarding day (15 miles, 5900 ft, 12 hrs).

Day 4 (Monday) - I slept in until awakened by sun on my tent.  I  soaked  my
tired feet in the lake before packing up and heading out at 10:00.  I  found
no trace of Trail 532 on the traverse above Fool  Hen  Lake  until  reaching
the basin where I had lost it on the way in. I have no idea  where  it  goes
or if it even exists in this area. But I was thankful for the  section  that
climbed up to the large cairn on the ridge above Fool  Hen  Pass.  I  stayed
with the trail over Pt 7836 but lost it in the broad pass  itself.  The  map
shows the trail dropping on a long traverse to Drake Cr but I couldn\'t  find
it so just headed downhill. I came upon it a couple of hundred  feet  below,
much lower than I would have expected. I  soon  lost  it  again  and  headed
straight downhill to Drake Cr. On the other side of the creek I came upon  a
fairly good trail that led to the well used Billy  Goat  Pass  trail  at  an
unmarked junction. Then it was just a short jaunt up to Billy Goat Pass  and
down the other side to the TH which I reached at 3:00 and the end to a  most
pleasant trip. (8 miles, 1700 ft, 5 hrs)

Total: 46 miles and 19,000 ft in 4 days

Fay Pullen



