            'tr' => '
I spent Wednesday and Thursday climbing these 9 peaks near Packwood.

Strawberry Mtn (5739 ft -  1859P)  and  Strawberry  LO  (5440+  ft  -  560P)
-Taking a cue from John, the first  day  I  climbed  these  two  peaks.  The
weather was sunny and bright but my enjoyment  of  the  lovely  terrain  was
tempered by gale force winds. I had trouble keeping my balance on  the  open
sections of the ridge which translates to about  50  mph  gusts.  I  made  a
direct assault from the south on The Strawberry, no more than class 3,  then
made the mistake of taking off my gloves on top and having one  blown  away.
I spent the next 20 minutes searching for it on a steep  snowy  hillside  to
the northwest. I did find it which was a good thing as it was the only  pair
I had with me (6.7 miles, 2100 ft, 3:50 hrs RT). Then I had trouble  finding
the trail to Strawberry LO as it does not start right from the saddle  so  I
went straight up from the road to the east.  I  came  down  the  trail  (1.2
miles, 575 ft, :50 hrs).

Spirit Lake East 3 (4581 ft - 461P) - I had hoped to drive on to the  Norway
Pass TH and climb a few peaks there but I discovered Road 99 gated  shut  at
the Bear Meadow Viewpoint. So Instead  I  climbed  this  peak  by  following
Boundary Trail 1 until as close as possible and then  going  uphill  to  the
top (1.4 miles, 660 ft, 1:20 hrs). I spent the  night  at  the  Bear  Meadow
Viewpoint.

The next day I gave my poor Jeep a real workout.

French Butte 3 (4520+ ft - 400P) - This peak was an  easy  stroll  from  the
nearest point on the road to the east that left Road  25  at  Elk  Pass  (.3
miles, 180 ft, :20 hrs).

French Butte 2 (4560+ t - 440P) - I accessed this peak from a  road  several
miles south of Elk Pass. The road started well but the spur  that  heads  up
the peak required high clearance and low range 4X4. I was able to  drive  to
the last switchback where a fallen tree blocked the way (.6 miles,  120  ft,
:25 hrs).

French Butte 4 (4120+ ft - 400P)  -  The  road  for  this  peak  is  on  the
opposite side of Road 25 from the above one. It is  rather  obscure  but  do
not despair. It is actually better than it looks at the start and  is  quite
drivable by any 4 wheel drive. I was stopped  but  a  large  tree  past  the
switchback and very near the end of the road.  There  is  a  nice  viewpoint
just west of the summit (.5 miles, 90 ft, :18 Hrs).

The Loaf (4520+ ft - 360P) - I drove back to Elk Pass and  took  a  road  to
the east hoping to get close enough to climb The Loaf. I  was  shocked  when
about 3 miles in I came to a gate proclaiming the road closed  to  motorized
vehicles. I am not sure why. But I could see vehicle tracks in the  snow  on
the other side of the gate and on closer examination I discovered  the  gate
was not locked and could not be locked due to being  deformed.  Knowing  the
gate could not be locked behind me  gave me the  courage  to  drive  through
though I still worried about getting caught. But it would not be as  bad  as
getting caught in the Cedar River Watershed. So I was able  to  drive  to  a
point very close to my objective and climb to the top  (.5  miles,  420  ft,
:45 hrs).

French Butte 1 (5360 ft - 400P) - As long as  I  was  already  in  forbidden
territory I decided to go for this peak also. I drove a 4X4 spur to its  end
and parked. I  felt  fairly  comfortable  parking  here  as  there  were  no
previous tracks in the snow and the road  was  rough  enough  I  thought  it
unlikely anyone would drive up it. This peak turned out to take  longer  and
to be more of a  challenge  than  I  thought.  In  keeping  with  its  named
neighbors (most of which I had climbed years ago) it  too  was  quite  rocky
and cliffy.

I worked my way through old  clearcut  and  open  forest  to  intersect  the
Boundary Trail on the ridge above Badger Lake  and followed  this  trail  to
the saddle north of the peak. I tried a direct approach up the  north  ridge
but ran into a cliff about 100 ft below the summit. It probably  could  have
been climbed (class 4) but it was wet and had snow  on  it  and  I  couldn\'t
tell if there were more cliffs beyond the initial  one.  I  decided  not  to
risk it and descended several hundred feet back to trail to follow it  until
past all the cliffs and gain the south ridge. That worked well.  The  summit
was rocky and open, the nicest summit of the day (3  miles,  1700  ft,  2:50
hrs). A view of The Loaf from the top clearly showed why it was so named.

French Butte (5306 ft - 1346P) - I still had a little time left in  the  day
and thought it appropriate to climb the peak for which the quad is named.  A
road goes all the way to the top. How hard could it be? Well, something  has
happened to this road since I drove it years ago to  climb  Pinto  Rock.  It
has deteriorated to a genuine 4X4 road. Do not even  try  this  road  unless
you have a high clearance 4X4 with low range gears. It is  awful  with  huge
tire swallowing ruts. It is steep too boot. After crawling  and  bumping  my
way at an average speed of maybe 6 mph up the 3.5 mile road when I  came  to
the final spur to the top I had had enough and walked the rest of  the  way.
Actually I probably could have driven it as it was no worse than what I  had
already done but I need to quit  rattling  and  shaking  for  a  while.  (.6
miles, 190 ft, :15 hrs).

Then I had to drive back down the road!

Fay Pullen



