            'title' => 'Mt Hardy (8080+ ft - 1480P - Mt Arriva Quad); and Porcupine Pk (7762 ft - 922 ft), Washington Pass Quad 2 (7552 ft - 552P) & Washington Pass Quad 3 (6820 ft - 420P) - Washington Pass Quad - October 25-27, 2008',
            'tr' => '
Mt Hardy (8080+ ft - 1480P - Mt Arriva Quad); and Porcupine Pk  (7762  ft  -
922 ft), Washington Pass Quad 2 (7552 ft - 552P) & Washington  Pass  Quad  3
(6820 ft - 420P) - Washington Pass Quad - October 25-27, 2008

Mt Hardy is most often climbed, I think, directly from  Hwy  20  near  Swamp
Cr. If that is all you are doing that certainly makes the most sense. But  I
had other plans and other peaks I hoped  to  climb  along  the  way  and  so
planned to climb it from Methow Pass with a camp at Cutthroat  Pass.  Beside
I wanted to return to the spectacular area near Tower Mtn and Goldenhorn.

Day 1 (Saturday): WashingtonPass2 - When I arrived at the PCT  North  TH  at
Rainy Pass I was greeted with several inches of new snow in the parking  lot
and could see more snow higher up. This did not bode well for making it  all
the way to Mt Hardy. Despite it being after noon  and  now  a  lovely  sunny
day, no one had been up the trail before me. Where the sun hit  open  slopes
there was actually very little snow, but in protected shady areas I  had  to
break trail in 8-12 inches. This all slowed  me  down  and  I  didn\'t  reach
Cutthroat Pass until 3:45 (5 miles, 2000 ft, 3:20 hrs).

I quickly set up camp on a bare patch of ground in full sun and set off  for
WashingtonPass2. This was a short pleasant stroll  up  gentle  south  facing
and hence little snow covered slopes. From the summit  views  were  gorgeous
and I could see my entire route along the PCT  to  Methow  Pass.  The  north
facing slopes on the descent to Granite  Pass  looked  very  snowy  but  the
trail was clearly visible and the long south  facing  traverse  below  Tower
Mtn was almost completely snow free. I breathed a sigh of  relief.  Snow  on
this traverse would have made my objective almost  impossible  to  reach  in
one day. As it was I would be pushing it but I thought it was still doable.

On the way down I made a small detour to find running water for  the  night.
I reached camp at 6:15 (1.5 miles, 750 ft, 1:50 hr RT) and settled in for  a
very long cold night.

Day 2 (Sunday): Mt Hardy and WashingtonPass3 - It was indeed a  cold  night.
My second water bottle inside my tent froze such that  I  couldn\'t  get  the
water out without heating it up first. I did have the bottle  I  put  in  my
sleeping bag to help with this. Fortunately I  had  deliberately  chosen  my
campsite to catch the early morning sun, if you  consider  8:00  early,  and
things quickly warmed up. The traverse to the high point above Granite  Pass
had a fair amount of snow, much of it now annoying breakable crust that  had
partially frozen during night, and was slow going. The  600  ft  descent  to
Granite Pass had drifts to knee  deep  but  it  was  powdery  and  no  great
problem.

At the pass I left the trail and ambled up easy south slopes to  the  summit
of WashingtonPass3. On the way I  was  startled  to  come  across  an  alien
rocket ship communications tower of some sort. You just can\'t get away  from
these things no matter where you go. At least this one was not on  the  high
point, was next to a tall tree and was camouflaged  so  it  was  not  really
very visible from afar. I descended  snowy  north  slopes,  winding  my  way
through a few unexpected cliffs, to intersect the trail once again  a  short
ways below the saddle with Tower Mtn.

The next 2 miles of traverse to Methow Pass was mostly snow  free  and  went
quickly. I had never paid much attention to  Mt  Hardy  during  my  previous
trip to area, but Hardy is really a very good  looking  peak,  even  holding
its own with nearby higher Tower Mtn and  Golden  Horn.   From  the  pass  I
followed the ridge W  through  booby  trapped  powder  covered  talus  until
reaching the steep sunny SE slope. I worked past a couple ridge bumps and  a
final notch until I could climb the final  easy  ramp  to  the  airy  summit
blocks (7 miles, 2900 ft, 7 hrs).

It was now 3:30. Actually for a while I thought it  was  only  2:30.  I  was
going by the time on my GPS and it was  set  to  automatically  change  from
Daylight Time at the old date (which was today) and not the new date  (which
is next Sunday). Then I looked at my watch and instantly lost  an  hour.  Oh
these electronic gadgets that think for you! My VCR did the  same  thing  at
home and taped a program  at  the  wrong  time.  When  Congress  willy-nilly
changed the date for ending (and starting) Daylight  Time  saying  it  would
save energy  or  some  such  nonsense  they  gave  no  thought  to  all  the
preprogrammed electronics out there. But I digress.

The bottom line was I would be returning by headlight, not that that  was  a
great problem. In fact I welcomed it. I would rather spend  a  couple  extra
hours on the trail than in the  tent.  However,  by  the  time  I  made  the
seemingly endless pull up out of Granite Pass and  then  the  long  traverse
from the top across snow that had once again frozen to breakable  crust,  my
tent was looking pretty good to me (13.5  miles,  4000  ft,  11  hrs).  This
night was noticeably warmer than the previous one and my  water  bottle  did
not freeze.

Day 3 (Monday): Porcupine Pk - What a glorious day this turned  out  to  be.
It was so beautiful I was reluctant to leave. I  had  Porcupine  Pk  in  the
back of my mind to climb on the way out, but I wasn\'t sure I was up  to  it.
About a month ago I seriously injured my right shoulder in a short fall  and
have had limited use of that arm ever since.  Although  it  hasn\'t  kept  me
from going out, I have stayed with mellow  trips,  mostly  on  trails,  that
involved no serious scrambling, and it has gradually been getting better.  I
had very little information on how difficult Porcupine  was.  Beckey  wasn\'t
very helpful either, but when I got an actual look at the peak I  could  see
it might be a problem. Still, the day was so nice I just had to  give  it  a
try.

I descended the trail to about  5900  ft,  stashed  my  overnight  gear  and
headed up at 10:40 through open woods to the basin  SE  of  Porcupine.  Part
way up I had to shed long underwear as it gradually turned to a  summer-like
almost hot day.  Porcupine Basin was beautiful and generally  snow  free.  I
worked my way through a short cliff band  onto  upper  slopes  and  to  just
below the saddle in the  south  ridge.  Yes  it  did  look  like  a  serious
scramble from here, but a nice ramp led  diagonally  upward  and  it  didn\'t
look too hard so on I went. I crossed two ribs  and  gullies  to  reach  the
blocky ridge crest and thought I had it  made.   But  remember  one  of  the
basic laws of climbing - "there is always a false  summit".  I  topped  out,
descended slightly to a small  notch  and  a  final  wicked  looking  narrow
vertical exposed 20 ft pitch. My heart fell. This was more than I  bargained
for in my condition. Then I looked at it more closely. It  was  more  broken
than at first appearance. I would call it class 4 but the  holds  were  good
and really didn\'t give me any trouble even with my gimpy  arm.  I  guess  it
really is getting better. I reached the summit at 1:20 absolutely  delighted
with both the peak and my performance. I hung around on top for a good  half
hour enjoying the views and sun. I highly recommend  this  peak  as  a  very
pleasant scramble.

I was back to a my pack at 3:30 (2 miles, 1900 ft, 4:50 hrs RT) and the  car
at 4:45 to end 3 days of gorgeous weather in late October.  Who  would  have
thought?

Total: 27 miles and 7900 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen





