            'tr' => '
Silver Star Mtn (4360+ ft - 1380P), Sturgeon Fin (4160+ ft  -  120P),  Bluff
Mtn (3928 ft - 448P), Little Baldy (3920+ ft - 400P) - Bobs  Mtn  Quad;  and
Gumboot Mtn Quad 1 (3977 ft - 497P - Gumboot Mtn Quad) - November 17, 2008)

I had vaguely heard of Silver Star Mtn and the Yacolt Burn  in  the  Gifford
Pinchot National Forest just north of the Columbia  River,  but  because  of
the drive distance and perceived better  things  to  climb  just  never  got
around to going there before now. I didn\'t know what I was missing.  What  a
gem this trip turned out to be!  Although of fairly low  elevation  most  of
the terrain on the mountain is wide  open  meadows  with  expansive  vistas.
This is due to the devastating (at the time) 1902 Yacolt  Fire  that  burned
238,000 acres in 3 days. The lower elevations have since reforested but  the
higher ridges have yet to recover and remain sparsely treed.

I approached from Battleground and Forest Roads 41 and 4109.  Road  4109  is
rough with many deep waterbars (I scrapped bottom with my Subaru on  one  of
them) but is passable to the roomy TH at 3080 ft.  Shortly  before  reaching
it I came face to face with a dead van stopped in the middle of the road.  A
crusty old guy was trying to hand  winch  it  out  of  the  way.  He  seemed
surprised but very happy to see me, explaining he had  a  dead  battery  and
just needed a jump. How he ended up with  a  dead  battery  on  his  vehicle
facing downhill in the middle of the road I never really understood.  But  I
obliged his request and saw him on his way. He was darn lucky I  came  along
as it was a long walk to anywhere and I met no one else the  entire  time  I
was on the forest roads.

A long abandoned Jeep road climbs all the way to the summit of  Silver  Star
on the west side of the ridge, but a  newer  trail  (Ed\'s  Trail)  has  been
constructed on the east side. I took this trail and found it delightful  and
very scenic as it worked its way past the cliffs of Pt 4200.  At  one  point
it went through a natural "doorway" arch.  It  then  descended  slightly  to
the Silver Star-Pt 4200 saddle and a  4-way  intersection  with  the  Silver
Star Trail, the Sturgeon Rock Trail and the Bluff Mtn Trail.  At this  point
I took a side trip  up  The  Sturgeon  Fin,  a  fascinating  outcropping  of
columnar basalt. It is imposing from all but the SW sides, which is an  easy
scramble. I went to the summit  then  followed  the  fin  downhill  a  short
distance to the small cairn marking the highpoint of Clark County. I am  not
really into county high points yet but  in  this  case  I  was  so  close  I
couldn\'t pass it by.

I next followed the old road to the top of Silver Star Mtn  for  lunch  with
great views and shelter from  the  wind  in  the  remains  of  a  demolished
lookout (3.5 miles, 2000 ft, 2:30 hrs). I could see the trail leading  along
the ridge to Bluff Mtn in the distance. Rather  than  return  to  the  4-way
junction, I dropped straight down the east and north side to intersect  this
trail. I was now in heaven. I love ridges and this  was  a  ridge  to  love.
Simply gorgeous.  I passed the junction with the  Starway  Trail  which  the
map showed going over the top of Gumboot 1. I would pick  up  this  peak  on
the way out. The trail contoured around Little Baldy to  the  wooded  saddle
beyond where I left it to follow the ridge to the  grassy  summit  of  Bluff
Mtn (6.5 miles, 2600 ft, 4:30 hrs).

Back at the saddle I climbed open talus to the bare summit of  Little  Baldy
(7.5 miles, 3100 ft, 5:30 hrs)  where  a  welcome  rock  windbreak  provided
relief from the wind scouring the exposed slopes. I continued  down  the  NE
ridge to once again intersect the trail.  In  fading  light  I  reached  the
junction with the Starway Trail (9 miles, 3500 ft,  6:30  hrs).  It  was  my
plan to do Gumboot 1 in the dark thinking it would be  easy  to  follow  the
"trail" to the top by headlamp. Well, this would have been a  good  plan  if
the trail had been a good one. The problem was,  it  was  not.  It  is  very
little  used,  almost  non-existent  in  spots  and  very  hard  to  follow,
particularly in the dark. I lost  it  several  times  in  the  steep  wooded
section down to the saddle at which point I gave up on the  trail  and  just
went up the mostly open grassy ridge to  the  summit.  It  was  fairly  easy
returning to the saddle but I had to take great care in  finding  the  Bluff
Mtn Trail junction again as that ridge is quite cliffy.  Fortunately  I  had
set several key waypoints on my GPS to help with this. But stumbling  around
in the dark looking for the trail, the RT from the  junction  took  3  hours
for a distance of 2 miles and 1000 ft gain. Not too swift.

Once on the good Bluff Mtn trail the rest was a piece of cake. At the  4-way
junction I stayed with the easier to follow old jeep road (rather than  Ed\'s
Trail) and was dazzled by the lights of the Portland-Vancouver  area  on  my
left and a rising partial moon on my right the rest of the way  to  the  TH.
It was always my intention to spend the night  in  the  car  so  I  was  not
unhappy with my arrival time of 10:30. That just  meant  I  didn\'t  have  to
spend excessive time in the sleeping bag.

Total: 14 miles, 5000 ft and 11 hours.

Fay Pullen



