It is a long drive to this area and in addition stuff happened. I  went  out
the door without my maps and had to go back for them. I stopped to  get  gas
in Stevenson and then got lost looking for  Willard  and  ended  up  on  the
Underwood Road. I knew I was  going  the  wrong  way  when  I  found  myself
paralleling the Columbia River instead of heading in toward  the  mountains.
To make a long story short it was 1:00 before  I  hit  the  trail  to  Monte
Cristo. Although sunny on the drive down it was now foggy and my  hoped  for
views  did  not  materialize  except  for  a  small  window  when  Mt  Adams
spectacularly made a brief  appearance.  That  almost  made  up  for  seeing
nothing else the rest of the day.

I made short work of the good trail up Monte Cristo and continued along  the
crest a total of about 3 miles to  intersect  an  old  road,  which  I  then
followed to the unnamed high point of Monte Cristo  Range  2.  Another  road
led to near Guler Mtn, a short but brushy off road ascent. I  wandered  more
old roads to Dry Creek Ridge,  an  interesting  small  cinder  hill,  before
completing my loop by headlamp to intersect the trail once again near  Monte
Cristo. I reached the car at 7:30 for  a  comfortable  and  not  excessively
long night, by the time I had dinner, at the Monte  Carlo  TH  a  half  mile
away.

Total: 10.5 miles, 3200 ft and 6:30 hrs.

Monte Carlo (4040+ ft - 880P) - Northwestern Lake Quad - December 4, 2008

I started for Monte Carlo at first light (7:30). The trail  climbed  steeply
for 800 ft then leveled off for a pleasant mile to the  high  point  at  the
south end of the ridge. The weather was clear but  downright  frigid  and  I
had to walk fast to stay warm.

Total: 3 miles, 1000 ft and 1:40 hrs

Gifford Pk (5368 ft - 568P), Gifford Pk Quad 1 (4498 ft -  418P)  and  Berry
Mtn (5000+ ft - 200P) - Gifford Pk Quad - December 4, 2008

Although not that far away as crows fly, it took almost  2  hours  to  drive
the circuitous roads to the TH for these peaks. So once again I got a  later
than hoped for start at 11:00. This TH is part of the  PCT  and  enters  the
south end of the Indian Heaven Wilderness so  I  knew  the  trail  would  be
good. The trail was very good but evidently there had been a lot of rain  in
the area recently, or the ground just doesn\'t  drain  very  well,  as  large
sections of the first part of the trail had puddles  that  had  subsequently
frozen overnight. At one point I thought I had come to a small  lake  except
that the trail led right through the middle of the  ice.  And  at  the  real
lakes many were so high the trail was  under  water  where  it  skirted  the
edge. This made for many detours.

About 1.5 miles in at Sheep Lakes I took  a  side  trip  to  wander  through
leafless berry bushes up Gifford 1. Indian Heaven  is  well  known  for  its
plentiful huckleberries in season and in fact is how it got its name. I  can
see why.  At 3 miles I passed the junction to  the  Indian  Race  Track  and
began a gentle climb in long switchbacks up Berry Mtn.  This peak  has  some
interesting rock outcroppings but the summit itself is  a  trivial  distance
from the trail through forest. From here the way followed the  ridge,  where
an icy wind turned me into a Popsicle, before descending to the saddle  with
Gifford Pk. Shortly thereafter I left the  trail  to  climb  through  gentle
open woods and meadows to the only real snow patch of  the  entire  trip  on
the summit of Gifford. I arrived just as the sun was  setting  but  made  it
back to the trail before needing my headlamp. I reached the car at 8:00  and
spent the night at the TH. There is an official campground here but  it  was
closed for the season and the restroom locked.

Total: 15 miles, 3600 ft and 9 hrs

Little Huckleberry Mtn (4781 ft - 1641P) and Monte Cristo Range 1 (3960+  ft
- 560P) - Little Huckleberry Mtn Quad - December 5, 2008

Little Huckleberry was a very pleasant  well  maintained  trail  to  an  old
lookout site and a great viewpoint. I had fun sitting in the sun and  seeing
where I had been the two previous  days.  I  could  see  the  whole  of  the
horseshoe shaped Monte Cristo Range which  starts  with  Little  Huckleberry
Mtn at the SW end and goes through Monte Cristo 1, Monte Cristo 2 and  Monte
Cristo to end at Monte Carlo on the SE end. I was  also  fascinated  by  the
Big Lava Bed to the west - a huge no man\'s land of rugged lava that  is  now
lightly treed. No road or trail penetrates but Crater  sticking  up  in  the
middle is calling to me and I will have to climb it someday.

Total: 5 miles, 1900 ft and 2:15 hrs

I was able to get in one more peak before misfortune struck. I drove  up  an
old rough overgrown road farther than  I  should  have  before  starting  to
walk. I did make it up Monte Cristo Range 1 and  back  to  my  car.  I  even
checked the tires before starting the drive down. In a  previous  outing  to
this general area on  November  15  while  driving  another  rough  road  up
Gifford 3 (3000+ ft) I got a rear flat that destroyed a tire.  I  had  great
difficulty changing that tire (they are  very  big  and  heavy  on  a  Grand
Cherokee) and loosening lug nuts tightened by supermen, having to resort  to
pounding the lug wrench with a hammer to  get  the  job  done.  I  ended  up
buying two new rear tires so they would match.  So I was  slightly  paranoid
(but not so paranoid as to stay off rough roads completely). Well  within  5
minutes of starting down I knew I had another flat, this time in  the  front
as I couldn\'t steer the car. But this second time around I did a better  job
as I had had practice. I had also added a 2 foot steel pipe to my  tool  kit
that fit over the end of the lug wrench for added leverage.  Worked  like  a
charm and I changed the tire in half the  time  as  before.  But  really!  I
hadn\'t had a flat in several years and now all of sudden I have two in  less
than a month. My trips are getting expensive and I may have to rethink  this
whole rough 4X4 driving thing. My vehicle may make it up  the  road  but  my
tires don\'t seem to.

Total: 1.2 miles, 500 ft and :50 hrs

Fay Pullen





