Zekes Pk (4865 ft - 945P) - Index Quad - January 23, 2009

The hardest part of this trip was finding a way to Lake Isabel. I had  heard
there was a trail to the lake but finding it was not easy.   I  first  tried
following directions in the back of the book Hiking Snohomish County by  Ken
Wilcox. He had you going up ORV roads to an old RR grade which then  led  to
the trail. I got no farther than the bridgeless  crossing  of  May  Cr.  His
comment "scamper across on rocks" had me laughing incredulously as I  stared
at the rushing torrent of the creek. He must be talking about  fall  levels.
I could find no way across that did not risk life and limb. To  salvage  the
rest of that day I took a pleasant hike to nearby Wallace  Falls  which  was
also raging.

Back to square one, I reasoned that if I wanted to get  to  Lake  Isabel  my
route could not involve a crossing of May Cr low down. I vaguely  remembered
a route described up Zekes in  Dallas  Kloke\'s  Winter  Climbs  book  but  I
couldn\'t find it. That is because it is not listed under  Z  for  Zekes  but
under N for Nina - Pinta - Zekes traverse. I came  across  it  while  having
nothing better to do than go through the book  page  by  page,  looking  for
future ideas, while passing boring hours  on  jury  duty  (no  I  was  never
selected to be on a jury). Even with this description I had problems.  Kloke
gives very minimal directions and is a  master  at  understatement.  But  at
least I had an approach and a plan.

From Gold Bar I drove Reiter Road past May Cr Road and an old  quarry  to  a
DNR road on the left. This road starts out bad right away with deep  puddles
and whoop de doo\'s. Just past the power line (.4 miles) I took a right  onto
a rough and rocky 4X4 road 1.3 further miles to  a  switchback  and  parked.
The road could probably be driven farther by someone more aggressive  but  I
try to ere on the side of caution when out alone (although  I  don\'t  always
succeed and sometimes still get myself into trouble).  Not  knowing  exactly
where it was, I missed the TH for Lake Isabel and ended up walking past  old
mines to the very end of the road where I forced a route through forest  and
brush up a drainage and over a spur ridge. On the other side I ran into  the
trail which was in good shape but obviously little used. After about Â½  mile
I came to a gully where a massive landslide/avalanche  had  obliterated  the
trail. On the other side I picked up an old road bed. I left this road at  a
switchback, again missing the trail. I was led astray by flagging luring  me
into the woods. The flagging went on for  a  ways  but  seemed  to  have  no
relation to any tread on the ground so eventually I just  ignored  it.  This
area had many large downed trees and progress was slow. Increasing depth  of
often rotten snow and a steepening slope  next  to  a  waterfall  as  I  got
closer to the lake exacerbated the problem.

With all my route errors it took me more than 3 hours to reach the  lake  (3
miles, 2200 ft).  But I was pleasantly surprised to find a pole bridge  over
the slot outlet creek that fed the waterfall and a nice log jam crossing  of
the second outlet creek. I had been concerned about getting across  both  of
these creeks. I do find it somewhat odd that Lake Isabel  has  two  outlets.
From the second outlet I headed  uphill  to  the  right  of  a  small  creek
working my way through minor cliffs.  The  first  500  ft  or  so  were  the
hardest then the slope layed back a bit but the whole way  was  quite  steep
forest.  I hit the ridge right of the summit where icy  snow  made  crampons
useful. Only the very summit was open with extensive views  (4400  ft,  6:15
hrs). I looked at the traverse to Pinta and  Nina  mentioned  by  Kloke  and
described as "intermittently steep".  No kidding! As I mentioned  before  he
is a master of understatement.

Darkness caught me on the way down and I got off my up route near  the  lake
descending slightly to skiers left. This actually turned out to be a  better
way although I still did plenty of hanging off  branches  to  get  down.  At
least I didn\'t need to use my panic rope,  which  I  did  have  along.  Once
below the lake I stumbled onto the trail which was fairly obvious here  even
under snow and I followed it to the old road.  It  hit  the  road  past  the
switchback. I had a little trouble locating the trail past the landslide  in
the dark but once on it I was able to follow that section  all  the  way  to
the main road. Or rather almost to the road, as about 25 feet above  it  the
trail just came to a dead-end on the hillside. No wonder I couldn\'t find  it
on the way up. It is marked by faded blue flagging wrapped  around  a  stick
but it is not obvious and there is little sign of any pathway leading up  to
the trail proper. I wonder if  this  obscure  start  is  all  deliberate  to
prevent the ATVs and motorcycles that swarm the area from trying to use  the
trail.

On the drive down the 4X4 road to the power line I ran into a pickup  coming
up. By now it was about 9:00 at night. I couldn\'t believe it. Fortunately  I
could see their headlights from a long ways off and had time to find a  wide
spot in the mostly narrow road to wait for them to pass. As they went  by  I
could see the two people inside looking  at  me  as  if  I  were  crazy  and
wondering what the heck I was doing there. I was wondering  the  same  about
them. At least I was on my way home. What were they doing going up the  road
in the dark? Probably I don\'t want to know.

Total: 8 miles, 4500 ft and 10:45 hrs.

Fay Pullen

Directions to Lake Isabel:  From Gold Bar drive Reiter Rd past an  operating
gravel pit on the right to an old gravel pit  on  the  left.  Large  parking
area here and DNR sign. Just past this turn left onto a rough DNR  road  and
go .4 mile to a power line. Turn right and go 1.3  miles  to  a  switchback.
Drivable to  here  (and  possibly  beyond)  by  a  high  clearance  vehicle.
Continue on the road about .7  mile,  past  a  road  right,  to  a  spacious
switchback  just  beyond.  Marked  ATV  trail  intersects  here.  Take   the
switchback to just before an old mine  (about  .1  mile)  and  look  for  an
obscure blue flagged stake. Scramble up hillside through sticker  bushes  to
trail above. Follow trail about a mile to a washout gully. Find old road  on
other side. Follow road .2  mile  to  slightly  past  a  switchback  (ignore
flagging at switchback) to a spur left. Trail is a short ways up  this  spur
on the left (unmarked). Trail should lead all the way  to  lake  although  I
did run into some blowdowns and I couldn\'t find it  in  the  snow  near  the
lake. Despite heavy ORV/ATV/motorcycle use in the area below,  once  on  the
trail you leave them all behind and have a feeling of seclusion.  The  trail
is always within sound and sometimes sight of the rushing waters of May  Cr.
There are several nice camp sites at the lake that could be used as  a  base
for forays to more remote peaks in the vicinity.

