            'tr' => '
Bald Mtn (4760+ ft - 680P - Silverton Quad) - January 30, 2009

I was so annoyed at missing Mike T and Matt\'s trip last week  up  Bald  (too
late communication) that I set out to rectify  that  situation  as  soon  as
possible. Mike\'s TR came in handy but  I  ended  up  having  very  different
conditions. Whereas they had rock hard crust and used crampons much  of  the
time, I had 8-10 inches of new snow higher up, and  I  approached  on  skis.
What a difference a few days makes.

Except for some washout areas with steep ups and downs and two rather  large
avalanches, all of which offered a few challenges on skis,  the  skiing  was
pretty good on the Deer Cr Road the 3.5 miles to the  switchback.  Expecting
hard crust, I had intended to stash the skis here and continue on  foot  the
rest of the way. But by this time there was enough new snow that I was  able
to stay on skis. In fact the skiing was  quite  nice  traversing  the  lower
basin, as was the first part of the  upper  basin  where  most  of  the  old
avalanches were covered and fairly smooth. I finally ditched the skis  where
the slope steepened considerably at about 3500 ft.

 Although the old slick crust underneath  caused  occasional  problems,  for
the most part step kicking worked well and crampons were  not  used.  I  did
however, veer too far to the right going up trying  to  stay  in  the  trees
where the snow wasn\'t as deep, and soon  found  myself  stopped  by  a  deep
gully and cliffs. I had to work back left into the  open  and  up  partially
covered slabs. I hit the south ridge at 4400 ft. A  short  section  of  easy
going was followed by tiptoeing along an ever narrowing ridge. With the  new
snow I had to be very careful to tread  carefully  as  it  was  not  obvious
where solid ground ended and hazardous cornice began. I soon came to the 10-
foot step down mentioned by Mike in his report. I was prepared  for  it  and
set up a short hand line leaving it in place for the return. It  might  have
been possible to down climb it but I felt better using the  rope.  A  little
more scrambling brought me to the narrow pointed  snow  ridge  of  a  summit
(3500 ft, 5:30 hrs), a very nice vantage  point  with  some  stunning  views
highlighted by storm clouds gathering around a sunlit White Chuck Mtn.

I didn\'t stay long on the summit. With my usual not-so-early  start  it  was
now  almost  4:00,  quite  windy  and  I  could  see  bad  weather   rapidly
approaching. Rain had been predicted for the evening  but  I  had  hoped  to
beat it out. I did not. The first drops hit as I was putting  my  skis  back
on and by the time I reached the road it was raining steadily. It  was  also
dark. If you discount the rain and the dark and the avalanches to  cross  it
was still a fun run down the road.

The wind must have been pretty darn strong down low also as I had  to  dodge
minor debris on the Mountain Loop Highway all the way to Granite Falls.

Total: 9.5 miles, 3600 ft and 9 hours.   Fay Pullen

Additional Note: Mike is correct in saying you only want to  do  this  route
when the avalanche danger  is  low.  Avalanches  are  common  off  the  many
cliffs, slabs and steep slopes on the approach through the lower  and  upper
basins. In fact I was getting a little nervous myself on  the  descent  from
the south ridge as I set off many snow wheels in the ever softening snow.  I
wouldn\'t have wanted much more fresh snow than I had.





