            'tr' => '
Table Mtn (5742 ft - 422P - Shuksan Arm Quad) - February 3, 2009

I normally don\'t ski at Mt Baker in early winter due to the long  drive  and
short days, but I  was  dying  to  get  out  and  that  area  had  the  only
reasonable backcountry conditions on this day. My main goal  was  just  some
quality skiing, which I hadn\'t had for a while. My  secondary  goal  was  to
get up Table Mtn. I was able to accomplish both.

Heather Meadows is not open to downhill skiing during the week so the  upper
lots were virtually empty with just  a  handful  of  backcountry  travelers,
despite a 10:20 start. But since it is a 3.5 hour drive I really  left  home
fairly early for me. Immediately I was  in  heaven.  The  sun  was  shining,
everywhere I turned the views were spectacular and the snow  was  good  with
several inches of fresh from the day before. Since my main goal was  quality
skiing, I just headed where the touring looked good, wandering  from  Austin
Pass through delightful terrain on a low traverse to the far end of  Kulshan
Ridge (4694 ft - 54P) and then following that  ridge  up  and  over  Huntoon
Point (5247 ft - 167P) to Artist Point (5080+ - 0P).

Next on the agenda  was  Table  Mtn,  but  this  flat  topped  mountain  has
defenses on all sides. I remember having  to  give  up  on  it  from  Herman
Saddle years ago after skiing Mazama  Dome.  I  just  couldn\'t  see  how  to
penetrate the cliffs and I had never  been  back  for  a  second  try.  From
Artist Point the east face looked possible but when I got to the base of  it
was too steep and rocky for skis. I really wanted to  ski  to  the  top.   I
then tried traversing north to a break in the cliffs on the  east  side  but
again it got too steep for me. There was still time  left  in  the  day  and
Ptarmigan Ridge looked inviting so I decided to tour to the Ptarmigan Ridge-
Table Mtn Saddle and see if a route existed on the west side. It was  really
just an excuse to go where I had never been before.

I descended several hundred feet to the slopes south of Table. Once down  in
the basin the terrain is very nice but I sure wouldn\'t want to be here  with
high avalanche danger. I crossed  several  old  avalanches  and  even  today
snowballs were rolling off the cliffs in the filtered sunshine. I worked  my
way back up to the ridge just south of the summit where a direct snow  route
looked possible but challenging on  skis.  Instead  I  elected  to  continue
traversing north to a break on the west side that led easily  to  the  lower
plateau of the mountain. I thought I had it  made  until  I  saw  the  upper
plateau was guarded by a short snow wall topped by a  cornice.  I  tried  an
end run clockwise around the wall and cornice but was  stopped  by  a  steep
exposed slope. There was no other alternative but to leave  my  skis  behind
and climb  through  the  cornice.  I  wasn\'t  really  prepared  for  serious
climbing but I did have my wimpy tiny aluminum ice  axe  along,  the  one  I
take when I don\'t think I will need it. I  kicked  steps  up  the  wall  and
chopped my way through the cornice. It was really quite fun. The summit  was
at the west end of the flat upper plateau near some trees.

I had some decent skiing on the way  back.  Although  some  of  the  steeper
slopes exposed to earlier sun were beginning to ice  up,  more  gentle  ones
and those with a more northerly exposure remained powder snow.  I  did  beat
darkness back to the car but mine was the last one left in the lot.

Total: 10 miles, 2900 ft and 7:30 hours

Fay Pullen

