            'tr' => '
Hurricane Ridge (5645 ft - 605P) and Eagle Point  (6347  ft  -  487P)  -  Mt
Angeles Quad - February 6, 2009

I have always been very interested in the Olympics  and  in  the  past  have
made countless trips there. However, in recent years I have sadly  neglected
them while I pursued all things in the Cascades.  This  will  no  doubt  now
change. Three new peak lists have sparked renewed  interest  and  incentive,
the 100 Highest Olympic Peaks complied by Paul Klenke, and the  Rain  Forest
and Rain Shadow Courts complied by Jeremy Schmidt. All three are  posted  on
summitpost. So as I was perusing the Rain Shadow Court I saw  several  peaks
that could be skied from The Hurricane Ridge Road this time  of  year.  What
could be better than to combine  my  two  great  passions,  peakbagging  and
backcountry skiing?

The Hurricane Ridge Road is the only road in the Olympics kept open  to  the
high country in the winter, but it does have its restrictions.  It  is  only
open Friday-Sunday (and most holidays), the  gate  at  Heart  O\'  the  Hills
doesn\'t open until 9 am and is closed and locked every  night  at  dusk  (30
minutes after sunset), the only overnight parking is 3 miles down  from  the
Ridge and those going on tours are required  to  sign  in  and  out  at  the
lodge. This limits what can be done in a day - particularly  for  me.  There
can be no coming out after dark.

Since I have a major dislike of crowds I chose Friday  as  the  day  to  go,
despite forecasted precipitation. I had light rain  much  of  the  drive  to
Port Angeles, which I hoped would translate to fresh snow on the  Ridge.  It
did but only 1.5 inches at most. In fact I was rather shocked at  the  scant
snowpack in general at the 5200 ft road end. It had the appearance  of  much
recent rain and sun melting leaving behind an icy crust  barely  covered  by
the new snow. In places meadow plants were still visible. Never having  been
here before in the winter I don\'t know if this is normal.  I  do  know  that
the area is well known for fierce sudden storms and winds (hence  the  name)
that can scour fresh snow away, but maybe  it  is  also  really  in  a  rain
shadow. Darn! Well I was here and would just have to make  the  best  of  it
but the prospects for great skiing this day were  looking  dismal.  However,
it turned out not to be all that bad.

I began on the summer road to Obstruction Point right from the  parking  lot
that drops over 200 ft immediately on a steep open sidehill.  With  the  icy
crust under the minimal fresh snow this  section  was  challenging  and  did
nothing to change my opinion that the skiing was going to  be  lousy  today.
There is an alternate start to the Obstruction Point Road beginning  from  Â½
mile back down the Hurricane Ridge Road that avoids  this  sidehill,  though
not the descent. In retrospect I  should  have  taken  it.  Once  past  that
things began looking up as the road moderated in forest and snow  conditions
improved. The road descended another 200 feet  before  beginning  a  gradual
ascent to below Steeple Rock. Then an almost level couple of miles made  for
very nice skiing indeed. At Waterhole, the road tilted  upward  and  climbed
800 ft with two switchbacks. Below the south saddle of Eagle  Point  I  left
the road at 5800 ft to climb directly up steep open slopes to the ridge  and
followed it past some interesting rocks to the summit (6 miles, 1660  ft,  3
hrs). Snow cover was very thin on the final part.

The weather was constantly changing, from fog to  snow  showers  to  sun  to
spectacular cloud formations to tantalizing partial views. It couldn\'t  seem
to make up its mind what it wanted to do but it was never dull. I had to  be
fast with the camera because what views I did have would  quickly  come  and
go. The run back to Waterhole was  much  better  than  expected.  With  more
fresh snow there would have been all manner of  crosscountry  possibilities.
As it was I did a lot of slideslipping to the road, but the road itself  was
actually fun. The snow seemed to be softening up a bit and was not  terribly
fast. Once past Waterhole and Pt 5602, I left the road to climb easy  slopes
to the summit of Hurricane Ridge (9 miles, 2300 ft, 5 hrs).   I  found  some
very nice touring terrain on the way up. On  top  clouds  parted  enough  to
catch glimpses of Steeple Rock and Rocky Peak (both on my yet to  do  list),
the Strait of Juan de Fuca and Eagle Point.

Once back to the road I enjoyed the skiing the rest of the way  to  my  car.
Even the steep final sidehill wasn\'t bad going up. I did  have  to  turn  on
the speed, though, to keep my stated 5:00 return time. I made  it  at  4:50,
the last to sign in, and to the gate at 5:30.

So maybe my conditions weren\'t the best on this  tour,  but  they  ended  up
being reasonable and fun anyway. You just can\'t always hit it  right,  as  I
had 3 days earlier at Mt Baker, although I sure keep trying. I have come  to
the conclusion that in Western  Washington  lousy  backcountry  skiing  snow
conditions are the norm and good  conditions  are  the  aberration.  If  you
always go expecting this to be the case  you  will  never  be  disappointed.
You can only be pleasantly surprised.

Total: 12 miles, 2900 ft and 6:30 hrs.

Fay Pullen







