Mt Herman (6240+ ft - 1120P - Shuksan Arm Quad) - February 12, 2009

I sure underestimated this peak. I was just out for a great day  of  skiing,
planning on going to Herman Saddle and down to Chain Lakes and maybe see  if
I could ski up Barometer Mtn when I realized I was only Â½ mile away from  Mt
Herman. How long could it take to pop up that peak on a slight  detour?  How
about the rest of the day! It really shouldn\'t have taken that long, but  as
I said I was just out for some skiing and wasn\'t planning on a  real  climb.
I had no crampons (they are almost impossible to fit to  Nordic  boots)  and
no panic rope. I did at least have my wimpy ice axe.

I did very well for me and despite the long drive got started  at  9:00  am.
It was so cloudy and foggy to start, I wasn\'t sure I was going  to  get  any
views. But as I climbed toward Herman Saddle both  sun  and  views  appeared
intermittently. It never cleared completely though. In fact I think the  sun
coming out at my moment of decision to try for Herman lured me  on.  It  was
just too beautiful at that point not to go higher. However, I didn\'t get  as
high on my skis as I had hoped. Although  there  was  very  nice  powder  in
protected areas, it had not snowed for a day or so and  yesterday  had  been
sunny followed by a cold night. Steep slopes with a  southern  exposure  had
turned quite icy and they never softened. I left my skis at  about  5700  ft
and headed up on foot toward a high saddle in the ridge with Mazama Dome.  I
was barely able to kick reasonable steps up this section.

At the saddle a softer slope bypassed a rocky point  on  the  west  side  to
another saddle where an easy slope bypassed Point 6040 on the east.  Here  I
made a big mistake. Not wanting to drop a fair distance  under  cliffs  only
to climb again to Herman\'s south notch, I tried a straight  traverse,  found
it too steep and ended  up  climbing  to  the  ridge  above  the  notch  and
following it down. Do not go this way. It is better to  drop.  Once  at  the
notch I followed it to the steep south  ridge.  I  climbed  50  feet  or  so
before running into icy conditions that my Nordic (duckbilled)  boots  could
not kick a dent in. With climbing boots and crampons I could have  scampered
directly up.

Not giving up easily I looked for an alternative and on  the  map  the  east
ridge looked more gentle and would have, I hoped, softer snow. So I  made  a
long traverse under all the cliffs to this ridge. The snow WAS softer and  I
WAS able to kick steps but I wouldn\'t say it was less steep. This ridge  has
many ups and  downs  with  several  steep  rocky  and  snowy  steps  and  is
frightfully corniced and exposed. But it did go, although  the  difficulties
and uncertainty never quit right up to the end. And it was very  interesting
and exciting. I left my skis at 11:00 and reached the summit at  2:00  (2600
ft, 5 hrs), 3 hours to go less than half a mile.

I reversed my route on the east ridge. It wasn\'t as bad  as  I  had  feared,
just slow. If I had had a rope I could have descended  the  south  ridge.  I
dropped into the basin below the south  notch  to  avoid  the  traverse  and
climbed up to regain my tracks out. A much better way to go.  I  was  at  my
skis at 3:20 for a great ski down once I was off the icy slope. Chain  Lakes
and Barometer Mtn would have to wait for another trip.

Total: 6 miles, 3100 ft and 8 hours

Fay Pullen

