Barometer Mtn (5763 ft - 1043P - Shuksan Arm Quad) - February 17, 2009

Another 9 am start from Mt Baker. Am I turning over a new leaf and  becoming
a habitual early riser or what? Good thing I did get going at  a  reasonable
hour as this trip turned out to take longer than I expected. There  were  no
real problems (well, except maybe the descent  from  Herman  Saddle  on  the
return) but it is farther than it appears on the map with a lot of  ins  and
outs and ups and downs.

I was at Herman Saddle in an hour and a half. From the  Saddle  I  descended
500 feet, with very nice skiing, to Hayes Lake from where I climbed a  small
spur ridge only to descend on the other side into a small  basin.  This  was
followed by a rising traverse through woods until it was possible to  access
the SE ridge of Barometer. Once on  the  ridge  proper  there  were  several
bumps to go over. The snow was quite good to this point with 4-6  inches  of
fresh that started the day as powder  but  was  rapidly  deteriorating  with
rising temperatures. What was going on here? I thought the  snow  level  was
supposed to be 2000 ft. Obviously it wasn\'t. I checked  my  thermometer  and
it was already  37  degrees.  Darn.  This  gave  me  some  concern  for  the
stability of the snow and I was already noticing  a  tendency  for  the  top
layer to slide on the old crust on steeper traverses.

At about 5300 feet the ridge crest became  narrow  and  somewhat  rocky.  In
order to continue on skis I would have to drop slightly and  traverse  steep
slopes, something not advisable under the conditions. So I left my skis  and
continued on foot. Remembering the icy conditions on Mt  Herman  last  week,
this time I had crampons along (I had since found  ones  at  Marmot  with  a
very large front bail that would fit my  skis  boots).  Naturally  I  didn\'t
need them. I didn\'t even need my ice ax. A little before 2:00 I pulled  onto
the spacious summit (2500 ft, 4:45 hr). It was starting  to  snow  and  cool
off.

I skied down the ridge before it cooled enough to ice  everything  over  but
the snow became very sticky. It was so sticky I was able to  climb  back  to
Herman Saddle without putting skins on.  By  then  the  weather  had  really
turned. It was now cold enough for the snow to begin to crust over.  Add  to
this the fact that it was also so foggy the only thing I  could  really  see
were my ski tips and the resulting skiing was less than  bad.  Getting  down
to Bagley Lakes was not a pretty picture. I did, however, have a  very  nice
final mile zipping along the smooth flat track to the car.

Total: 8 miles, 3500 ft and 8:45 hrs.

Fay Pullen



