            'title' => 'Big Four Mountain Attempt (6160+ ft - 1080P - Silverton Quad) - February 21, 2009',
            'tr' => '
Big Four Mountain Attempt (6160+ ft - 1080P -  Silverton  Quad)  -  February
21, 2009

Mike T, Jim, Matt and I made a serious attempt  on  Big  Four  Saturday.  We
knew from the get go that the chances of summiting were slim.  The  freezing
level was much too high at 7000  ft.   Emails  flurried  back  and  forth  -
should we or shouldn\'t we go? We really shouldn\'t! We went anyway.  I  think
we needed to touch the mountain and see for ourselves and we knew that  with
the predicted new snow all the next week the mountain probably  wouldn\'t  be
in condition again for another month.

Mike had scouted the route a few weeks previously so we knew  exactly  where
to go. We hiked 2 miles from the end of the plowed  road  to  the  Big  Four
Picnic Area, crossed the river on a log next to the  washed  out  bridge  to
the Ice Caves, paralleled the river upstream 1 long mile to  the  Dry  Creek
basin and climbed through the lower cliff band via a hidden  gulley  to  the
upper basin. All this took about 4 hours and up to this  point  things  were
not looking all that bad. It was fairly warm but there  was  not  much  snow
left on the cliffs to come down and step kicking was good. It  was  when  we
reached the upper basin and needed snowshoes in the increasingly  deep  snow
that we began to see the handwriting on the wall. By the  time  we  were  at
the base of the summit couloir at 11:00 and 4500 ft  we  were  wallowing  in
knee deep snow.  That is as high as we got. It was difficult to turn  around
in such good weather with the summit beckoning and much of the day left  but
there was really no other choice.

Just to make sure, Jim dug a snow pit. As  he  dug  deeper  and  deeper  and
deeper without hitting a crust I got more and more freaked. Finally about  5
feet down he hit the crust. Above that  was  all  unconsolidated  snow  with
several very unstable sugary layers.  After seeing that I couldn\'t  get  out
of there fast enough. Oddly enough, what we were originally worried about  -
warm temperatures and debris coming down from  above  -  was  not  the  main
problem. The main problem was the deep  unstable  snow  underfoot  and  even
cold temperatures would not have changed that. Why all  this  snow  did  not
consolidate over  the  past  several  weeks  of  little  snowfall  and  much
sunshine I am not sure. I guess it is a combination of  this  couloir  never
seeing the sun all winter long and the north side of Big Four having  unique
weather and conditions. All I know is  the  expected  conditions  of  a  few
inches of soft snow on a hard crust that I have  been  running  into  on  my
recent tours did not materialize.

I have always been intimidated by Big Four and  this  trip  did  nothing  to
diminish that feeling. The climbing itself, up to where we  got,  is  pretty
straight forward and not really very difficult. It is the objective  dangers
of avalanches that are the problem. It is one impressive scary  mountain.  I
do not, however, regret our decision to go. I couldn\'t have gone with  three
greater guys and I got to touch the mountain  up  close  and  personal.  You
don\'t  always  have  to  make  the  summit  to  have  a  memorable  mountain
experience.

Total: to high point of 4500 ft - 9 miles, 3000 ft and 9 hours

Fay Pullen

