Washington Monument (4826 ft - 786P - Baker Pass Quad) - March 6, 2009

This is the last of the trilogy of peaks, which also includes Goat  Mtn  and
Red Rock Mtn, approached from roads around Grandy Cr.  It  is  the  farthest
and most challenging to get to. When I learned of Paul Klenke\'s interest  in
this peak I was pleased to have him join me, especially when it  turned  out
he was free on sunny Friday. He was on AT skis and I was on my  usual  light
touring gear.

Despite recent lowland snow around Seattle, there was  very  little  evident
in the Baker Lake area and we still had to walk the gated road  2  miles  to
the snowline at 1800 ft, the same as I did a week  earlier  when  I  climbed
Goat Mtn. We skied the road in several inches of  new  powder  another  3  Â¼
miles to the crossing of  Grandy  Cr.  Here  the  road  makes  a  very  long
switchback which we cut through tight  trees  to  hit  a  middle  spur  road
above. More open terrain led to the main road higher up. Another 2 miles  of
flat to slightly downhill road and then a final steeper spur  put  us  below
the NW ridge of the  Monument  where  we  left  our  skis.  We  ran  into  a
surprisingly slick crust under the new snow kicking steps up to  the  ridge.
Once on the ridge we were confronted by a final short but very  steep  pitch
that at first look seemed impossible to me.  Fortunately  Paul  was  unfazed
and proceeded up while I followed in his good steps. The  summit  was  roomy
but corniced (4500 ft, 6:15 hrs).

Once back to our skis we had a nice but short run down open  slopes  to  the
main road. To avoid some uphill on the road we contoured to the middle  spur
road then followed this to  its  intersection  with  the  main  road  again.
Neither one of us wanted to ski down through the tight trees  where  we  had
come up. The rest of the way was on variable conditions where Paul  had  the
edge on his AT skis. Protected areas were still powder and very nice.  Those
exposed to the sun and warming earlier had now frozen over. The worst was  a
mid section of deadly breakable crust that was very difficult  (for  me)  to
ski. Lower things improved to  consistent  crust  that  could  at  least  be
snowplowed. Still, by the time we reached the snowline I for  one  was  more
than ready to just plain walk. We reached the car before  complete  darkness
at 6:40.

Although the snow conditions were not as good for the downhill road  run  as
on my two previous trips (mainly because we came down too late) I  am  still
so impressed with this area that I am sure  I  will  return  just  for  many
skiing possibilities. I positively salivated over some of the terrain I  saw
but didn\'t have time to explore.

Total: 16 miles, 4700 ft and 10:20 hrs.

Fay Pullen





