            'tr' => '
Stevens Ridge (5561 ft - 201P - Mt Rainier East Quad) - March 12, 2009

I have had my eye on Stevens Ridge for some time  as  a  possible  different
ski tour out of Paradise. It lived up to all my expectations. It  is  lovely
gentle touring terrain and is so far off the beaten  track  you  are  almost
guaranteed to have the whole place to yourself.  It  is  a  very  long  way,
however, if you make Point 5561, which is the greatest prominence  point  on
the ridge, your destination.  The  only  slight  difficulty  was  the  final
access to the ridge from the Stevens Creek basin which I took  too  high  to
avoid losing elevation and ran into a very  steep  slope.  I  took  a  lower
track on the way out which was better. The day was gorgeous  and  warm,  the
snow good and the views all around. I  did  leave  skis  just  before  Point
5648, as I ran into a combination of ice, melted  out  rocks  and  a  narrow
ridge, and continued easily on foot. The  connecting  ridge  to  Point  5561
made for a satisfying scramble goal.

Early in the day I was shaken a bit by a very  large  avalanche  coming  off
the Nisqually Glacier. But I was so far away it was of little concern.  Then
I was shaken even more late in the day when crossing a flat near Point  6252
where I felt a large area under me settle with a thump and  a  loud  report.
It sounded just like an explosive charge going off. I have had  flat  slopes
settle under me before but never such a large one and never so loud.  I  set
off several more incidents as I  cautiously  crossed  the  basin.  I  didn\'t
really feel all that threatened as the slope was gentle  but  it  was  still
rather disturbing and a reminder that  there  are  unstable  conditions  out
there.

Then as I was preparing to leave Paradise at the end of the day (I  was  the
last car), I was surprised to see an unfamiliar critter,  black  and  medium
dog sized, prowling the parking lot in the gathering darkness. He  was  wary
but didn\'t seem that afraid  either.  Maybe  he  is  the  resident  Paradise
mascot. When I got home I positively identified him  as  a  red  fox  (black
phase) by his bushy white tipped tail.

Total: 12 miles, 3100 ft and 9:15 hrs.

Fay Pullen



