Long Mtn East Peak (4760+ ft - 200P - Silverton Quad) - April 21, 2009

When I climbed Bald Mtn in January I spied a possible ski route up the  East
Peak of Long Mtn from the upper basin and took this gorgeous  sunny  day  to
see if it would actually go. I ran into three short steep  areas  that  gave
some trouble on skis but for the most part it is a very viable  route  under
the right snow conditions and I was able to ski all the way to the summit.

The Deer Creek Road is beginning to melt  out  and  won\'t  be  skiable  much
longer, but I only had to remove my skis for one  short  bare  section  past
the Devils Pk road junction.  I  left  the  road  after  3.5  miles  at  the
switchback at 2834 ft. I took the traverse across the lower basin quite  low
to avoid most of the plentiful avalanche debris. The day was warm and  sunny
and the snow already wet and slushy but most of what would  have  come  down
had already done so during the preceeding warm and sunny  days,  although  I
did hear and see a few minor rumbles.  Also  the  surface  slush  got  quite
unstable as the day went on and it was very easy to set off small sluffs  on
steep terrain, even in the trees. Nothing serious but it did make  me  worry
about losing my edges and taking a slide downhill.

A short steep step beside a gushing waterfall put me into  the  upper  basin
where  skiing  was  very  nice.  Unfortunately,  this  basin  ended  in   an
impassible headwall and I had to struggle up another slightly  longer  steep
section to gain the gentle ridge on the left. More good skiing until  I  hit
cliffs and had to traverse left and slightly downhill past a  gully  to  the
last steep section and gentler slopes above. The rest of the way  was  quite
pleasant, always in the constantly changing  view  of  the  very  impressive
Viking  Horns.  Although  I  had  expected  that  it  might  give  me   some
difficulty, I had no trouble accessing the summit Ridge or following  it  to
the flat summit and marvelous 360 degree views (3400 ft, 5:15 hrs).

By the time I skied down, the snow was very wet and  heavy  but  the  skiing
wasn\'t really that bad. I managed a few turns here  and  there,  but  I  did
take my skis off for all three  steep  steps.  It  seemed  faster  and  more
prudent to do so. The run down the road  was  pleasant  enough,  though  not
overly fast, and a nice end to very enjoyable ski trip.

Total: 12 miles, 3500 ft and 8:15 hrs.

Fay Pullen

