            'tr' => '
Hurricane Hill (5757 ft - 707P - Hurricane Hill Quad) and Griff  Peak  (5120
ft - 620P - Elwha Quad) - April 24, 2009

With the Hood Canal Bridge closing for 6 weeks on May 1,  this  weekend  was
my last chance to ski to Hurricane Hill this  season.  Friday  was  forecast
sunny and clear but cold. After the slushy  conditions  of  earlier  in  the
week I fully expected crusty snow conditions  but  they  turned  out  to  be
downright icy. I ended up doing almost a third  of  the  trip  on  foot  and
could have used crampons, which for  some  inexplicable  reason  I  did  not
take.

I was the first to sign out at the Hurricane  Ridge  Lodge  at  9:30  AM.  I
began by skiing the 1.5 miles to the  end  of  the  road  that  goes  toward
Hurricane Hill, zipping along since it went mostly downhill. Fortunately  it
was very gentle. Leaving the road, I started along the  summer  trail  until
soon confronted by a  large  Park  sign  warning,  "Steep  and  Icy"  as  it
traversed around a minor bump in the ridge. Yikes! I wasn\'t expecting  this.
Although exposed to the sun, it was too early in the day  for  the  snow  to
have softened and I could not make it safely across without crampons.  So  I
climbed to the top of the ridge and did a bypass over the bump. Once on  the
ridge I could ski again, traversing less icy slopes into the wide  beautiful
basin south of Hurricane Hill. An easy ascent up open slopes put me  on  top
(3 miles, 1100 ft, 1:45 hrs) where I had great  views.  I  was  particularly
drawn to rocky Unicorn Peak and Horn.

To get to Griff Pk, my next objective, I had to descent some 1200  feet  off
the north side of Hurricane Hill. This would ordinarily be a great run,  but
with the icy conditions I found it unskiable and instead kicked steps  down.
It really killed me not to be able to ski  these  lovely  slopes.  Following
the easiest terrain, I ended up a bit low  on  the  traverse  to  the  Griff
Saddle. Above the saddle I was once again on sunny south facing  slopes  and
I skied easily up, despite having to thread through the charred trees of  an
old burn, to the wooded summit of Griff Peak (5 miles, 2000 ft, 3:45 hr).

By now the south slope of Griff was soft enough for reasonable skiing  down.
At the saddle I continued  on  skis  trying  a  higher  line  but  was  soon
compelled by cliffs and steep terrain to descend to  my  original  route.  I
kept my skis on as long as possible, but once in the North Basin  again  the
snow was still so icy I was forced to kick steps. Near the top of the  ridge
I ran into fresh ski tracks which had traversed out  into  the  North  Basin
only to dead-end at a line of steps kicked back up to the  ridge.  So  these
skiers had also judged it unskiable and had retreated.  That  made  me  feel
better and not so much of a wimp.

I had a marvelous ski down the sunny south  slope  and  basin  of  Hurricane
Hill and ran into many other skiers doing the same. Conditions  in  the  sun
were excellent, those in the shade never softened all day. I ran  into  even
more skiers and walkers (snowshoes were not necessary) farther on,  most  of
whom didn\'t go much beyond the end of the road, even though the  "Steep  and
Icy" trail traverse was now soft enough to cross.

Total: 10 miles, 3700 ft, 7 hrs.

Fay Pullen

