            'tr' => '
Klahane Ridge (6046 ft - 166P - Mt Angeles Quad) - April 30, 2009

I couldn\'t resist one last visit to the  Hurricane  Ridge  area  before  the
Hood Canal Bridge closes for 6 weeks. Crossing the bridge mere hours  before
the closure scheduled for May 1  at  12:01  AM  I  counted  5  barge  cranes
hovering close by ready to start work. I had hoped to climb  Rocky  Peak  or
least scout it out on this trip. But as I approached Port  Angeles  I  could
see there was too much new snow on the higher peaks  to  make  this  serious
rock scramble a reasonable prospect. I would have to  be  satisfied  with  a
lesser objective.

This being a Thursday, as expected, the Hurricane Ridge Road was  closed  so
I made my approach from the Lake Angeles Trail just before the gate.  I  had
never been up this trail before. It is in great shape and snow free to  just
before the 4200 ft lake. Above that the trail  was  completely  under  snow,
hard to follow and crosses downright dangerous terrain. I didn\'t  expect  it
to be so difficult. It took me 2 hours to go the 3.7 miles and 2300 feet  to
the lake but another 2 hours to find my way the next 1000 feet  past  cliffs
to easier terrain above. It appears from the map you might be able  to  just
climb the rib west of the lake. You cannot. It is too craggy and  rocky.   I
was able to find the trail as it crossed the  rib  to  the  west  and  began
traversing but soon lost it in deep snow. Without the help of a trail I  was
at a loss as to where to cross back to the east side. I  ended  up  on  very
steep sidehill through cliffy terrain that was not  helped  at  all  by  6-8
inches of unconsolidated new snow over a slick  crust.  After  a  couple  of
wrong detours I eventually found the correct crossing at 5200 ft.

Then it was all worth it. The terrain below Klahane Ridge  is  gorgeous.  Oh
how I wish I had my skis. Skiing would have been superb,  but  there  is  no
way I could have carried skis up. Views were fantastic. I  saw  several  eye
catching peaks that will warrant future trips. I never even  heard  of  Peak
5550, but this flat topped cliffy peak  is  most  impressive  as  it  towers
directly east of Lake Angeles. Locals call it Burnt Mtn  although  the  USGS
map places that name on a lesser 4910  ft  summit  farther  east.  Both  the
Middle Peak of Mt Angeles and Second Top also look to be worthy climbs.  And
then of course there is Rocky Peak, which has intrigued me  for  some  time.
It does not look any too easy.  I  will  have  to  try  again  under  easier
conditions and when I can make  the  shorter  approach  from  the  Hurricane
Ridge Road.

Total: 10 miles, 4500 ft and 8:20 hours

Fay



