Davis Pk (7051 ft - 1771P - Diablo Dam Quad) - May 9, 2009

Davis is an impressive peak that towers some 6000 feet directly above  Gorge
Lake to the north. I have been tantalized by views of it every time I  drive
home along the North Cascades Highway and finally got my chance to climb  it
on this great trip organized by Paul Klenke. Joining  were  Mike  T.,  Matt,
Martin, Carla, Tisha, Grant, Don Brooks and his son Scott, for  a  total  of
ten people. This made for a very  strong  party  that  I  had  a  hard  time
keeping up with. Then again I didn\'t have to carry any  ropes  or  kick  any
steps.

We started at 8:00 from the Gorge Falls  parking  lot,  crossed  the  bridge
over Gorge Cr and immediately  thereafter  went  straight  uphill  into  the
woods. There was a semi "trail" to start through the light brush and  sallal
but it soon disappeared. Several cliff bands had to be bypassed  but  mostly
we stayed closely east of a  minor  gully.  The  going  was  steep  but  not
difficult nor terribly brushy. It was actually much better  than  I  thought
it would be. Somewhere around 3700 ft we hit snow in  a  shallow  gully  and
travel eased as we made our way onto the south ridge.  At  a  lovely  scenic
flat spot on the ridge at 5500 ft we took a well deserved rest (4400  ft,  4
hrs).

We then followed the ridge to Pt 5872. There was a little steep bit off  the
other side where we put in a short rappel. Once down we saw an easier  route
that we climbed on the way back. Then we were confronted by the 300 ft  rock
step gaining the main summit ridge. It  appeared  rather  intimidating  from
afar. We scrambled up the first 100 feet of snow covered wet rock  and  dirt
to a belay tree, where we set up running belays  on  our  2  60m  ropes  the
final 200 feet of steep snow to the ridge. This ate up some  time.  Once  on
the ridge it was a lovely walk along a beautifully  corniced  ridge  to  the
summit at 3:20 (6300 ft, 7:20 hrs).

We did two rappels down the rock  step,  one  double  and  one  single  rope
length. Again, with 10 people this took time, about an hour per rappel.  For
Tisha this was her first mountain  rappel.  Nothing  like  being  forced  to
"swim or sink", but she did fine. And it was fun seeing a  whole  new  world
of experience being opened to someone for the first time.  By  the  time  we
were back to Pt 5872 and started down it was 6:00. The descent went  rapidly
helped immensely by a wonderful glissade 2000 ft down the  snow  gully,  one
of the best I have had in years. We reached the cars at 8:15.

This was a great group of climbers.  I wish I  could  properly  credit  each
one for their contributions but I was usually trailing so far  behind  I  am
not sure who did what. All I know is that they all worked together  to  make
this a successful climb.

As a side note, all afternoon  weather  threatened.  As  times  it  appeared
almost certain we would be rained on as black clouds formed all  around  us,
but we were spared. We stayed mostly  in  the  sun  with  good  near  views.
Avalanche danger was high and we saw and heard several  avalanches,  but  we
were relatively safe on our  ridge  route.  We  nixed  the  SW  basin  route
because of the danger.

Gear: 2 60m ropes, 4 pickets, light rack, harness, crampons (did  not  use),
ice axe

Total: 5 miles, 6400 ft and 12:15 hrs     Fay Pullen



