Mt Saul (7280+ ft - 1360P - Glacier Pk East Quad) and  "Airplane  Pk"  (6435
ft - 675P - Clark Mtn Quad) - May 22-23, 2009

Friday - After 2 weeks of relative inactivity (i.e. no peakbagging) with  my
family I was dying to get out. With the promise of a long  stretch  of  good
weather I opted for the first overnight of the year, but finding a  suitable
2-day trip was a challenge. I needed  something  fairly  easy  that  had  TH
access and no major creek crossings without bridges. With the  warm  weather
and recent snows all rivers were in spate. Fortunately I was able  to  drive
all the way to the White River TH and both the bridges over the White  River
and Indian Creek were intact. But I ran into snow  patches  from  the  start
and the melting made  for  a  soggy  wet  trail  with  many  detours  around
puddles. I also barely made it across  the  usually  minor  creek  about  .5
miles in by rock hopping. It was noticeably higher the next day on  the  way
out and I wasn\'t as lucky. I ended up wading  with  boots  on  which  didn\'t
really matter as by that time my feet were soaked anyway.

What with detours, inconsistent  snow  and  the  odd  downed  tree,  not  to
mention not being in backpacking shape, it took me  3:20  hr  to  go  the  5
miles and barely 1000 ft to the creek draining Airplane Lake, where  I  left
the trail. Heading up along the east side of the creek and  once  above  the
solid snow of the valley, I was surprised to run into the remains of an  old
trail. It had the look of a built trail (as opposed  to  a  booted  or  game
trail) and was fairly good in places. I soon lost it in snow higher  up  but
I was able to follow it for about 500 feet of gain and it got me  through  a
lower minor cliff band. Does anyone have knowledge of  a  trail  ever  being
built to Airplane Lake? I did find some wire  and  cut  timber  on  Airplane
Peak. Maybe there was a lookout up there at one time.

Once I hit "solid" snow (about 4500 ft) I was slowed even more as  the  snow
was anything but solid. I postholed up slush, taking an additional  3  hours
to climb the added 2200 ft to Airplane Lake and my intended  campsite  (6  Â¼
miles, 3100 ft, 6:20 hrs).  I still wanted to climb  Airplane  Peak  but  it
was now 6:00 and the snow was so soft I wasn\'t sure I would have  time  even
though it was only a bit more than 1000 feet above me.   I  quickly  set  up
camp and started up at 6:30 stopping by the melted outlet  of  the  lake  to
fill my water bottles on the way. The snow was very soft but I made  the  RT
in 2 hours. I would have liked to have glissaded  on  the  way  down  but  I
didn\'t want to have my pants completely soaked for the night. I settled  for
fast plunge stepping down tracks made by minor slides set off by me.

Saturday - I had hoped to get an early start the next day to take  advantage
of the cold night (36 in my tent). I went to  bed  at  10:00  and  the  next
thing I knew it was 7:00 in the morning. Darn! I guess I was  tired.  But  I
paid dearly for my late start. By the time I got going  at  8:00,  the  snow
was already softening. It had never really frozen overnight except  to  form
a weak breakable crust - no real help at all.  And  the  higher  I  got  the
worse it was. Considering the snow conditions, I  opted  for  the  shortest,
most direct route I could find, which was straight up the  east  slope  from
my camp, in the sun from the moment it rose. I postholed calf and knee  deep
much of the way. It goes without  saying  snowshoes  would  have  been  very
useful but I had elected not  to  bring  them.  Where  I  could  I  went  up
avalanche snow which was more consolidated.

The summit was a miniature rock horn (1950 ft, 2 hrs). At the base  I  found
an interesting Mountaineer register dating back  to  1984  and  filled  with
entries of many I know. I must be almost the last of my circle  of  climbers
to climb this peak. Although on my list for years (maybe even  decades),  it
has taken me a while to get to it.  I  took  over  30  minutes  reading  the
register and enjoying the expansive views even as the  sun  beat  down  full
force and I felt pressure to leave as the snow softened by the minute. If  I
thought the snow was bad on the way up it was torture on  the  way  down.  I
couldn\'t even glissade even though I didn\'t  care  now  about  getting  wet.
When I sat down I just sank into a hole. And strangely, I couldn\'t  set  off
any slides to get rid of the top layer even though  the  upper  slopes  were
quite steep. I was forced to posthole and wallow downhill through  knee  and
thigh deep slush. I was actually worried about not being  able  to  make  it
out. These have to be  some  of  the  worse  snow  conditions  I  have  ever
encountered on foot.

I dragged into camp at noon, having taken as long to get down as to get  up,
with the lower half of me soaked and frozen. I stripped and crawled into  my
sleeping bag for a peaceful hour nap while my  clothes  dried  in  the  sun.
Peaceful, that is until a refrigerator sized block of snow came off a  cliff
above the lake (not on my route) setting off  a  small  avalanche.  Oddly  I
wasn\'t worried  about  avalanches  when  on  my  route  (I  felt  everything
unstable had already come down)  but  maybe  I  should  have  been.   I  was
actually more worried about being swallowed  up  by  bottomless  slush.  But
then there really isn\'t that much difference between the two is there?

By the time I packed up and left at 1:30 my pants had dried. My  boots  were
another matter. I did have dry socks but it didn\'t take  long  for  them  to
get soaked again. Wading the creek just  before  the  TH  didn\'t  make  much
difference. There were maybe a dozen cars at the TH by now.  Most  indicated
on the trail register to be either climbing Mt David or Clark Mtn. None  had
made it up Indian Creek past the creek crossing.

Total: 16 miles and 6500 ft in 2 days.

Fay Pullen





