Independence Pk (5400+ ft - 1160P - Helena Ridge Quad) - May 28, 2009

This is a small but rocky peak just south of North Lake at the  end  of  the
Coal Cr Road off the Mountain Loop Highway. Beckey lists  the  elevation  as
5445 ft., the USGS map as 5400+ ft. When you can drive the road to  its  end
near Coal Lake it would be a short pleasant scramble.  Unfortunately  I  was
only able to drive the road 2 miles  before  being  stopped  by  a  wall  of
avalanche snow. I had brought skis in case I could ski the  road  but  there
was another 1.5 miles of bare road beyond  and  it  didn\'t  seem  worth  the
effort to carry them to ski the final 1 mile of snow-covered road.

I left the road past Coal Lake and climbed open easy  snow  slopes,  working
past the odd rocky gully and cliff to the west  ridge  saddle  at  5080  ft.
Here a wide ledge skirted the base of the cliff to the right going around  a
corner to a gully, mossy at the bottom, choked with cedar at the top,  which
provided access to the upper west ridge. Fun exposed  scrambling  along  the
crest on solid but lichen covered rock led to the summit at the far  end  of
the ridge  (3000  ft,  4:30  hrs).  I  found  a  pitiful  makeshift  plastic
container of a register that had completely deteriorated and an  older  film
can that had fared better. I left the  film  can  but  added  the  amazingly
still legible paper (after drying it in  the  warm  sun)  from  the  plastic
container to a new register of my own. I packed out the offending  crumbling
container.

Entries of interest I could read:  Earliest  10/30/83;  Grant  Meyer  1986?;
John Roper 7/21/90; Mitch Blanton 5/8/95; Jeff Howbert 8/3/02;  Fred  Beavon
9/27/06 and Don Beavon 9/29/06. I had fun trying to  read  all  the  scraps,
soaking up the sun and admiring the views for 45 minutes.

I did two rappels on the way down, one short one at a class 4  step  on  the
ridge and one the full length of my 100 ft rope to get  down  the  worst  of
the gully. The gully was mostly just class 3  but  it  was  mossy,  wet  and
slick. Then it was fast glissading and plunge stepping  down  soft  snow  to
the road.

Total: 8 miles, 3000 ft and 7:30 hrs

Fay Pullen





