            'tr' => '
Frozen Mtn (5080+ ft - 920P - Mt Phelps Quad) - May 30, 2009

Frozen Mtn is a somewhat obscure rocky peak hidden deep in  the  Tolt  River
drainage and guarded by miles of gated logging  roads.  Its  main  claim  to
fame is being on the Home Court List. I had been putting off climbing it  as
I knew it would be a real combined effort of biking and brush  bashing.  But
with the impending closure of Forest Road 62 at  Highway  2  (thanks  Stefan
for the heads up), I figured it was now or  never.   With  an  additional  6
miles one way of gated road to bike that would essentially  put  it  out  of
reach as a day trip. It is long enough as is.

I began by biking the road from the current gate. About 4 miles in I  had  a
fairly good view of the route. The only information I had was  a  report  by
Mike Collins from June 7, 2002.  He approached via a road on the south  side
of the North Fork Tolt which entailed crossing that river before heading  up
the west slopes of Frozen. With all rivers running very high now, I  knew  I
wouldn\'t be able to cross the North  Fork  without  a  log,  and  finding  a
suitable log could be a real problem. From my viewpoint (and from  the  map)
I could see two old roads, an upper and lower, paralleling  the  North  Fork
on the north side that could possibly get me through  the  worse  brush  and
close to the west side of my peak. I could also see a fairly  new  clear-cut
along the lower road that should mean that road had been improved. But  when
I got to clear-cut I couldn\'t find the road. So  I  opted  to  try  the  old
upper road.

I left my bike at the start of the old upper road but was confronted  almost
immediately by a major creek washout. I crossed the devastation  and  picked
up the road on the other side but it was  very  old  and  overgrown.  Now  I
could look down on the clear-cut and I saw a good road traversing  it  so  I
dropped down to it. Where the heck did it come  from?  I  found  out  on  my
return that the start of this road had been completely  obliterated  by  the
same washout as above. I followed the clear-cut road to its end  at  another
creek. The old lower road continued on the other side but again it was  very
old and overgrown and I soon lost it in a swampy brushy area. For  the  next
several hours I floundered in awful brush.  I  crossed  several  creeks  not
shown on the map expecting each to be the major one draining the north  side
of Frozen. I had to be on the south side of this creek before I could  start
uphill. Somehow, forced by terrain and brush, I ended up  on  the  banks  of
the North Fork Tolt very near its intersection with  my  target  creek.  The
good news was that the creek was braided enough here I  could  cross  it  by
boulder hopping. The North Fork Tolt was another matter.  It  was  a  raging
torrent and no logs were in sight. No way could I have gotten across. I  had
more brush to contend with but at least I could now start uphill.

I slowly climbed upward at a snail\'s pace all the while  feeling  the  hours
slipping away. It had taken a good portion of the day just  to  get  to  the
base of my peak. I alternated between chucking the whole climb as  a  really
bad idea and totally hopeless and stubbornly continuing no matter  how  long
it took even if it meant a bivy. At some point the latter sentiment won  out
as it became clear to me if I didn\'t get this peak this day  I  most  likely
never would. I sure wasn\'t coming back. Eventually I got  above  the  valley
brush and things improved. Mostly I followed a rib to the right of my  creek
until it seemed prudent to traverse right into the drainage west of  Frozen.
Here I ran into snow and, finally, blessedly open and friendly  terrain.  It
sure was a long time coming.

I now had to figure out a way up the summit block. Frozen is  a  north-south
ridge with a series of rocky points. The high point is the one  second  from
the north, about 300 ft high. I made my way to the notch  on  the  north.  I
went through to examine the east side and all  I  saw  were  horribly  steep
open snow slopes and wet  mossy  slabs.  I  should  have  looked  closer.  I
thought the west side looked better. I was wrong. I  made  my  way  up  gosh
awful wet mixed snow and rock in a very steep treed gully.  I  think  I  was
lured by the false security I thought  being  able  to  hang  onto  branches
would give. But I sure didn\'t feel secure. I emerged onto  the  snowy  north
ridge with a sigh of relief. No way was I going to  downclimb  that  (I  did
have my 100 foot rope if all else failed).

The summit was a pleasant rocky point in the sun (4000 ft, 7:40 hrs) with  a
nice view of the not often seen south side of Mt Index. There  was  a  cairn
but I couldn\'t find a register. I left one of mine. I  speculated  when  the
next person would sign in. I guessed no time too soon. I did take  a  moment
to catch my breath, but I had a long way to go to get down and it was  still
a tossup if I would make it before dark.  I descended  the  north  ridge  on
the east side, the route I had nixed from the notch. It was quite steep  but
continuous snow  with  good  step  kicking  (which  I  did  facing  in)  and
infinitely better than the way I had ascended. All things are relative.

On the way down I wanted to cross the major  creek  higher  up  so  I  could
descend directly to the clear-cut road and avoid  the  worse  of  the  lower
valley brush, but the creek was in a gorge with waterfalls and running  very
high. I began worrying about just getting across it at all.  As  luck  would
have it, when I was forced into the creek by terrain  and  brush  I  hit  it
where a good log provided a convenient crossing. Fairly nice forest  on  the
other side lasted until I reached the old road. I managed to stick  with  it
through the swampy brushy area (where I lost it earlier in the day)  to  the
creek at the clear-cut. This creek was also running high by now but again  a
convenient, if spindly, log offered a dry foot crossing. All  that  remained
was to walk the road back to my bike. This is when I  discovered  the  start
of the clear-cut road had been obliterated  by  flood/avalanche  debris.   I
did make it to my car before dark but it was close.

I am thinking there ought to be a better approach to this peak. Certainly  I
made many errors in choice of route and yet I doubt any way  would  be  very
easy. Sometimes it is these little guys that give you the most trouble.

This is #98/100 on the Home Court for me. I  still  have  Bears  Breast  and
Middle Index to do. I think I can do Bears Breast. Middle Index I am not  so
sure.

Total: 17.5 miles, 4300 ft and 12:15 hours (12 miles, 1000 ft and  2.5  hrs
RT on bike)

Fay Pullen



