            'title' => 'Mt Bullen (5960+ ft - 920P), Whitehorse 1 (5931 ft- 411P), Salish Pk (5680+ ft - 440P) and Buckeye Pk (5896 ft - 336P) - Whitehorse Mtn Quad - June 2- 4, 2009',
            'tr' => '
Mt Bullen (5960+ ft - 920P), Whitehorse 1 (5931 ft- 411P), Salish Pk  (5680+
ft - 440P) and Buckeye Pk (5896 ft - 336P) - Whitehorse Mtn Quad -  June  2-
4, 2009

Tucked between and somewhat dwarfed by higher Three Fingers  and  Whitehorse
Mtn, Mt Bullon is equally rugged and much more difficult to  access.  It  is
seldom climbed and hence has no beaten trail to  its  top.  A  trip  to  its
environs feels like a true wilderness experience. I have long had it  in  my
sights. There were also several lesser but interesting peaks nearby  that  I
wanted to include, hence 3 days seemed like the minimum time required.

Day 1 (Tuesday) - High Camp - The only route information I had was  that  in
Beckey and it was sparse indeed. I began  by  hiking  the  Squire  Cr  Trail
about 2.8 miles to 2000 ft and dropping  250  ft  through  brush  to  Squire
Creek. This was a hot day and I was worried about finding a crossing as  the
water was quite high. There are three braids of the creek here,  the  middle
being the main channel, and I had no trouble finding logs across  the  first
two. The third could be rock hopped. I then started uphill through light  to
moderate brushy forest until I hit a rock  wall  at  2600  ft.  I  traversed
northward at its base until I came to a creek partially  filled  with  snow.
This conveniently provided a crossing. I now had no definite idea of how  to
proceed but essentially was forced to climb up between  this  creek  on  the
left and another one on the right. The next 1000 feet were  horrible,  steep
and brushy where I soon found myself on a narrow rib sandwiched between  wet
slabs on the left and the gorge of a roaring creek on  the  right.  My  pace
was pitifully slow as I struggled upward through this section dripping  with
sweat in the enervating heat. When I hit continuous snow  (around  3700  ft)
and moderating slopes above the slabs I breathed a  sigh  of  relief.   With
each upward step views opened up. Finally, this is what I had  come  for.  I
found a flat spot on snow to camp at 4900 ft just below the notch  south  of
Pop Tart Tower on the Salish-Buckeye ridge (5 miles, 4000 ft and 7 hours).

Day 2(Wednesday) - Mt Bullen - I had positioned my camp with an eye to  what
might come off the ridge. I really thought most everything that  could  come
off already had, but just to make sure I  deliberately  pitched  my  tent  a
little lower and off to the side of the fall  line  than  my  first  choice.
Sure enough, while eating breakfast in my tent as  the  first  rays  of  the
intense morning sun hit the ridge I heard a frightening crash above  me  and
the unmistakable sound of a cornice falling. Too late to  make  any  evasive
action, I could only stick my head out of my tent  and  watch  incredulously
as ice chunks came crashing  down  very  near  my  original  thought  for  a
campsite.  That was a little too close for comfort.

The night was warm and the  snow  stayed  soft  for  good  step  kicking.  I
climbed the short distance to the 5240 ft notch above camp where  I  had  my
first view of Mt Bullon on the other side. It looked a  long  distance  away
and not all that straight forward. Beckey says it can be climbed in 2  hours
from the notch. I don\'t think so, at least not by the likes of me.  First  I
had to descend some 1000 feet to the basin north of Bullon  Lakes.  To  this
end I traversed NW almost all the way to the Bullon-Pk 5931 ridge  before  I
could see a way down through the cliff bands that surround the lakes. I  did
one short rappel down a slick wet gully (everything was wet and  melting  on
this very hot day) and scrambled some easy rock  before  hitting  the  lower
snow slopes. I traversed easy snow above the lakes to  pass  beneath  cliffs
and a waterfall creek at the low point before starting up again.

Now routefinding became a challenge. Beckey merely  says  to  climb  heather
and broken rock, all class 2, on the SE ridge. Well, the SE ridge is not  at
all an obvious feature and I wandered all  over  trying  to  find  an  easy,
preferably continuous snow, slope up. I failed. I contoured  beneath  cliffs
and past another nasty waterfall gully too far W  until  completely  stopped
by impassable terrain. Then I doubled back E and up. I would  find  a  short
snow slope that led up only to be blocked by cliffs above and I  would  have
to traverse E again. Several times I thought I was doomed but  each  time  I
would find a way past the difficulties and slowly I worked  my  way  upward.
After a particularly scary steep snow traverse  above  the  nasty  waterfall
gully, I finally broke out onto the upper gentler snow slopes. The last  bit
was indeed a scramble on heather and broken rock. I found  a  cairn  on  the
summit but no register (2100 ft, 4:45 hrs). I left one of mine.

What a glorious spot with Three Fingers to the south and Whitehorse  to  the
north. I stayed the better part of an hour eating lunch, soaking up the  sun
and drying out my boots. From the summit I could pick out a better route  on
continuous snow back to the Salish-Buckeye ridge and from there a way up  Pk
5931, next on the agenda. I also found a better  way  off  Bullon,  more  or
less straight down, that eliminated the scary traverse above the  waterfall.
I did run into some steep broken (and of course wet)  rock  where  I  almost
did a rappel but I found a scramble way down. Once back to my uphill  tracks
it was not at all obvious that was the way I should have  gone.  All  I  can
say is it is best to stay climber\'s  right  of  the  waterfall  gully  on  a
narrow rocky rib.

Peak 5931 - Using my better route seen from the summit of Bullon, I  climbed
up onto the SW slopes of Peak 5931. I went right past cute  Pop  Tart  Tower
then up steepening snow to the bouldery summit (3700 ft,  9  hrs).  I  found
neither register nor cairn and left both. I descended straight to the  notch
doing one rappel at a particularly steep and  rotten  snow  section  in  the
trees.

Salish Pk - I continued on past  camp  heading  for  Salish.  I  knew  if  I
stopped I wouldn\'t get going again and time was  running  out.  I  contoured
beneath Pt 5360 and gained the ridge S of there at 5280 ft to  climb  Salish
on its easy N slope (4600 ft, 11:40 hrs). Again there was  neither  a  cairn
nor a register but I didn\'t have another register with  me.  It  was  in  my
tent. I had a stunning view of the NE Buttress of Three Fingers but  it  was
too late in the day and Bullon was all shadows. I was back  in  camp  in  an
hour after a long but very satisfying day  (6  miles,  4700  ft,  12:40  hrs
total).

Day 3 (Thursday) - Buckeye Pk - Again the snow did not freeze.  If  anything
it was even warmer than the previous night. I started for Buckeye  at  8:00.
The approach was easy to the base of the E ridge.  Becky  says  to  climb  a
class 4 chimney to the E ridge and expect 200  feet  of  rock  climbing.  In
anticipation of this I  had  brought  a  minimal  rack  (left  at  camp  the
previous day) and a 100 ft rope. I never found the chimney but I did  see  a
fairly easy way onto the ridge via a snow finger. I roped  up  once  on  the
ridge but only because it was exposed, I was alone and I  wasn\'t  sure  what
difficulties I would run into. In retrospect,  from  where  I  accessed  the
ridge, the whole thing could be scrambled. There were a couple  of  class  4
moves but the holds were good. Most of the way was a very nice ledge. I  did
pass an old rappel sling just below the summit (1 mile, 950 ft,  2  hrs).  I
left a register in the cairn I found. I did do a rappel off  the  ridge  but
it could have been downclimbed.

I was back in camp by 11:30. I ate lunch then took a  glorious  hour  and  a
half relaxing and just enjoying  my  alpine  surroundings  (and  reading  my
favorite Nevada Barr book series).  I  was  reluctant  to  leave  especially
since I wasn\'t really looking forward to the descent. But  all  good  things
must come to an end and the bad is the price we pay for the good. I left  at
1:15. I was glad I had the route up marked on my GPS. There is  very  little
room for error on the way down. Get it wrong and you will end up  cliffbound
or trapped by gushing creek gorges. One  view  I  had  of  the  major  creek
draining the basin W of Squire Cr Wall was absolutely unreal. The  waterfall
appeared to shoot out a hundred feet into space there  was  so  much  water.
Anyway I nailed the down route. It was still unpleasant but not  as  bad  as
expected. I even came out right at my logs crossing  Squire  Creek.  It  was
only when I started up the last 250 feet to the trail that  I  realized  how
very tired I was. The brush seemed totally unreasonable and malicious and  I
could barely put one foot in front of  the  other.  Once  on  the  trail  it
seemed like heaven in comparison. I reached my car at 6:15 (5 hrs).

Grand Total: 18 miles and 9850 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen

