            'tr' => '
Rocky Pk (6218 ft - 498P - Mt Angeles Quad) & Second Top (6000+ ft - 200P  -
Port Angeles Quad) - June 10-11, 2009

I hate unfinished business. Ever since getting a view of  Rocky  Pk  when  I
climbed Klahhane Ridge from Lake Angeles in a day about a month and  a  half
ago I planned to return. I had a vague idea to climb it on that trip but  it
appeared to be no trivial matter and I ran out of  time.  Good  thing  as  I
doubt I could have made it under the snowy conditions I had  at  that  time.
This trip I planned to camp on Klahhane Ridge so  I  would  have  plenty  of
time.

Wednesday - High Camp and Second Top  -  I  approached  from  the  excellent
Switchback Trail, after getting a XC permit to camp on the ridge at the  WIC
in Port Angeles. The tourist season is in full swing  already.  The  parking
lot of the Visitor Center was completely full. The TH parking lot  was  also
full. It seems I picked the day the local Klahhane Hiking Club had  Klahhane
Ridge as its destination. I dodged dozens of hikers coming  down  the  trail
as I toiled up it. From Victor  Pass  (1.5  miles,  1500  ft,  1:15  hr),  I
followed the scenic ridge trail up and down about  1.5  miles  and  found  a
delightful secluded campsite on a rocky ledge just above the descent to  the
Klahhane-Rocky saddle (3 miles, 2000 ft, 2:15 hr).

I had planned for a leisurely trip but after setting up  camp  it  was  only
3:00. I didn\'t think I could handle just hanging around  doing  nothing  the
rest of the afternoon, despite having a good book to  read.  That  would  be
too leisurely. What to do? Well maybe I could make it up  Second  Top.  This
wasn\'t the most efficient way to do that as that meant I had to  retrace  my
steps 1.5 miles back to Victor Pass, but the ridge trail is beautiful and  I
really didn\'t mind. Once at Victor Pass I followed the Heather  Park  Trail,
first dropping 500 ft mostly on snow and then  climbing  snow  free  to  the
5800 ft saddle on the Mt  Angeles-Second  Top  Ridge.  This  ridge  is  very
pinnacled and once I crossed to the other side I saw that I  would  have  to
drop again several hundred feet to avoid cliffs. It was going to take a  lot
longer to get to Second Top than I had thought.

I lost the trail in snow to begin but found it lower down  as  it  traversed
past the appropriately named Egg Rock. Parts of this  steep  trail  traverse
also still had patches of tricky snow. There were no  footprints  indicating
anyone had been this way recently. I  had  to  go  almost  all  the  way  to
Heather Pass before the terrain  became  friendly  enough  to  start  uphill
toward Second Top. I worked my way  easily  to  the  summit  rocks  where  a
fascinating wide ramp on the S side led to a break in the wall and  a  short
class 3 pitch to the summit area (1500 ft, 3 hrs from camp).  I was back  to
my tent by 8:30 (6.5 miles, 2750 ft, 5:20 hrs RT from camp).

Total for the day: 9.5 miles, 4750 ft and 7:35 hrs

Thursday - Rocky Pk - I started at 8:30 by dropping almost 200 feet  to  the
5680 ft Klahhane-Rocky saddle. I further dropped to a low point of  5400  ft
following a faint goat/climber(?)  trail  that  traversed  at  the  base  of
cliffs on the south side of Rocky Pk. The Olympic Mountain Guide  Book  says
to "traverse  past  two  prominent  notches  to  an  obvious  greenish  rock
formation."  Well, I traversed up and down across several gullies past  what
I thought were two notches until I came to another deep  ravine  that  would
have required several hundred more feet of descent without ever  seeing  the
"obvious greenish rock". I have come to completely distrust the use  of  the
word "obvious" in route descriptions. Before this last ravine  was  a  break
(the only break) in the south side cliffs in the form of a broad  but  steep
gully. It looked doable to begin but also looked like it headed for  dubious
territory. Nevertheless, I took a chance and started up it.

All went well for several hundred feet. I climbed on the right edge  staying
out of the gully bottom until I came to a  short  step  that  gave  me  some
pause. I suppose it was only class 3 but the  rock  was  covered  with  ball
bearing slick loose gravel which did not inspire confidence. I tried on  the
right and backed off, but made it up  on  the  left.  And  then  I  hit  the
headwall, a small cirque of cliffs. I thought Rocky Peak was supposed to  be
class 3! There were  only  two  possible  breaks.  The  left  one  with  its
overhanging crack was impassible. The right one  was  a  full  on  class  4+
slab. I tried it and backed off, then dinked around for probably 45  minutes
looking for a better way. There  wasn\'t  one.  This  probably  meant  I  was
either off route or had once again been sandbagged by "Olympic Class 3".

With no other option (besides retreat) I tried  the  slab  again.  Expecting
nothing more than class 3 all I had with me was  my  100  ft  rope  and  two
slings and nothing at all to protect the lead. I really thought I could  get
up it. The slab was that solid volcanic rock peculiar to the  Olympics  with
good friction but rounded holds and void of cracks or horns.  But  I  really
couldn\'t see what was above and  I  was  worried  about  getting  into  more
difficulties than I could handle. I wasn\'t even sure I  could  find  anchors
to rappel down if I did run into trouble. With adrenaline  pumping  aplenty,
I made it up the slab. Above was a chimney,  still  steep  but  with  better
holds, and then ledges went right  around  a  gendarme  to  the  final  easy
slopes to the summit (1000 ft, 2:50). I left a register in a cairn  I  found
on the highest rock. Views were limited as  fog  and  clouds  were  swirling
about. I even heard some distant rumbling of thunder.

I used my two slings to rappel down the chimney  and  the  slab.  Luckily  I
found chockstone anchors for both. These were much steeper  rappels  than  I
usually like to do with the Dulfersitz but I had no other gear.  I  found  a
solid boulder to wrap the rope directly around to rappel the lower step  and
then I was home free and back to camp by 1:40 (2 miles,  1500  ft  5:20).  I
took a blissful nap before packing up and leaving at 4:00.

At the TH were signs warning of an aggressive goat harassing hikers.  I  ran
into this malevolent fellow just below Victor  Pass.  He  was  prancing  and
snorting and rearing and looked as though he would like nothing better  than
to do me bodily harm. He would not  let  me  pass.  I  could  just  see  the
embarrassing headlines - "experienced climber gored by a mountain goat."  To
avoid him I swallowed my ethics and cut a  switchback  to  the  trail  below
(1:45 hours out).

Grand Total: 14.5 miles and 6700 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen



