            'tr' => '
Tailgunner Pk (5842 ft - 482P) and Wing Pk (5760 ft - 400P) - Baring Quad  -
June 16, 2009

Beth wanted to climb Gunn. I wanted to climb  Tailgunner  and  Wing.  So  we
teamed up for the approach. We had both recently been in the area,  Beth  to
climb Tailgunner about a month earlier and me to climb Gunnshy in April,  so
we were familiar with the route. We still had the usual  trouble  connecting
the log jam crossing with the  climber\'s  trail  across  the  brushy  valley
bottom, but once we found it I for one was surprised at how good it was.  My
previous trip to Gunnshy had mostly been on snow and when  I  climbed  Gunn,
probably some 40 years ago, I didn\'t remember a trail at all.

The trail is very good until it hits a headwall where it traverses right  at
the base of the cliffs, descends steeply to cross a gully at 4000 then  goes
straight uphill through a wet slot to emerge from trees into an  open  basin
at about 4200 ft. Here was a trail junction. The  main  fork  took  a  sharp
left uphill while the right fork, which was covered with  sticks  indicating
the wrong way to go, went straight ahead into the basin.  Both  Beth  and  I
had previously gone straight but that had been  when  there  was  continuous
snow. Now much of it had melted and brush was appearing.  So  we  went  left
thinking this would avoid  the  brush.  Well,  it  led  steeply  up  through
unpleasant terrain with some brush and cliff bands on a seemingly  illogical
course until coming to a  small  waterfall  where  we  lost  it  completely.
Perhaps it just went up the waterfall  which  was  running  rather  wet  and
slippery for us and was not appealing.  Above  appeared  to  be  more  cliff
bands. At this point we gave up on the trail and  worked  our  way  slightly
down into the upper basin and onto snow. Perhaps when there is  no  snow  at
all and the basin very brushy the illogical  trail  makes  sense.  With  any
snow the basin is much easier.

 Once on snow we followed it up to the eastern-most (5400 ft) saddle on  the
Tailgunner-Wing ridge which inadvertently proved to be the best way off  the
ridge on the other side for Beth. This is where Beth and I parted company  a
little before 1:00. She headed for Gunn and I for Wing. Wing  proved  to  be
an enjoyable short 30 minute scramble along the ridge ending with  a  30  ft
class 3-4 pitch up the final summit rocks. Views were  still  good  while  I
was on top but they were rapidly  deteriorating  as  fog  began  rolling  in
while I made my way along the ridge to Tailgunner.  I  stuck  to  the  ridge
encountering a 10 foot vertical cornice  wall  on  top.  I  relaxed  on  the
summit until I could see Beth descending Gunn  (in  between  drifting  fog).
Not wanting to downclimb my vertical cornice, I descended to the W  thinking
it would be easier. It was not. I ended up on a very steep slope where  step
kicking down facing in some 100 ft slowed me  up  enough  that  Beth  and  I
arrived at the Wing saddle almost at the same time (at 4:00).  We  descended
from the saddle into the basin  following  snow  as  long  as  possible.  We
encountered some brush at the end getting back to the climbers trail at  the
bottom edge of the basin, but it was still better than our route up.

Total: 5.5 miles, 4400 ft and 9:30 hrs

Fay Pullen

