Repulse Pk (7923 ft - 523P - Mt Arriva Quad) - June 19, 2009

The original plan was to climb Bears Breast this weekend with  Stefan,  Erin
and Beth.  When the forecast didn\'t look good enough  for  that  major  rock
climb, Stefan changed it to a day climb of this peak. Beth made other  plans
but Greg joined us. Then the forecast deteriorated further to where  it  was
looking bleak indeed.  We went anyway. Well, we  didn\'t  have  the  best  of
weather but it certainly ended up so much better than it  could  have  been.
Rain constantly threatened but didn\'t become a reality  until  late  in  the
day when we were on our way out.

We began from the large turnout at Swamp  Cr  on  Hwy  20  a  little  before
10:00. Somehow we managed to hit Granite  Cr  right  at  the  wonderful  log
crossing a short ways above the confluence with "Repulse Cr". From there  it
was easy travel through lightly brushy woods up the left side of the  creek.
We were following the TR of Mitch (with Don and  cousin  Fred  Beavon)  from
2002. It soon became evident that we had much less snow than  they  had  and
we had more brush to contend with.  The worse patch was  in  the  middle  of
the lower basin.  Once  past  that  it  was  continuous  snow  to  the  many
waterfalled headwall. This was turned on the way up via a steep cruddy  dirt
gully with loose rock to a traverse above the waterfalls  that  led  to  the
upper basin. (Stefan found a better route on snow  for  the  way  down  that
avoided the gully.) From the upper basin it was an  easy  snow  traverse  to
the 7280 ft notch in the S ridge of Repulse (3300 ft, 4 hrs).

Now the fun began on class 3-4 rock up interesting and complicated  terrain.
To start it is important to drop slightly on the W side to a sandy  ramp  to
bypass a second notch. We followed the ramp up to cross  below  this  second
notch. Scrambling brought us to another  deep  gully  which  we  crossed  by
climbing up to the ridge crest at a third notch. It was pretty much class  3
to this point. From the third notch we had a choice of a short  gully  right
or a broken wall to the left. We chose the broken wall  to  the  left  which
had a short exposed class 4 section leading to a wide ramp and  ledge  above
the gully (the gully would be easier and led to the  same  spot).  The  next
section was the hardest, exposed class 4, again to the left, and  ending  at
a small tree. From the tree easier terrain appeared around the corner  above
yet another deep gully. We climbed up alongside this gully to a final  class
4 step that put us on the summit ridge at a fourth notch. The  rest  of  the
way along the crest to the summit was easy (4150 ft, 5:25 hrs).

The original summit register of 1971 mentioned  by  Mitch  was  still  there
with 4 entries total. Ours was the  fifth.  It  was  foggy  and  views  were
limited (never did get a good one of Arriva or Black),  but  we  were  happy
that it still had not done more than sprinkle. In fact we even had a  moment
of sun on the summit which heightened our  happiness.  We  stayed  maybe  20
minutes before heading down. We rappelled the class 4 pitch below  the  tree
and downclimbed everything else,  avoiding  the  second  class  4  pitch  by
descending the short gully from the broad ledge. Stefan had  placed  several
cairns on the way up which helped to keep us on track. It  waited  until  we
were back to the main notch before beginning to rain  lightly.  Nice  timing
as much of the rock is covered with black lichen and would be very slick  if
wet.

We had several reasonable glissades down the snow. By the  time  we  reached
the brush, it was wet though it still was not raining that hard, but by  the
time we reached the car at 7:40 we were all most definitely wet. Oh, but  it
could have been so much worse. At this point Stefan and Erin continued  east
for two more days of climbing, Greg drove home and I, not wanting to  tackle
the long drive home that night, car camped at Rainy  Pass  and  did  another
short climb the next day.

Total: 8 miles, 4300 ft and 9:40 hrs.

Fay Pullen



