Hinkhouse Pk (7560+ ft - 760P - Washington Pass Quad) - June 20, 2009

After climbing Repulse Pk, I spent a restful night at the PCT North  parking
lot at Rainy Pass. It rained off and on during the night but  the  next  day
(Saturday) the weather began to clear. I had several possibilities of  peaks
to climb in the area and finally settled on Hinkhouse, just N of  Washington
Pass. I wanted a short easy peak that would get  me  home  at  a  reasonable
hour. Although it wasn\'t quite as short or easy as I thought it would be.

I started from the entrance to the Washington Pass Viewpoint. The  viewpoint
road itself is closed and gated for renovations. Also a  bike  ride  was  in
progress and this spot was being used as one of their stops. I was lucky  to
find a place to park. But I had a nice conversation with  two  EMTs  manning
an aid car. They had watched as I got my gear ready and looked  at  the  map
and wanted to know where I was going. They mentioned  that  if  I  got  into
trouble they were right there ready to help. Very reassuring.

The route up Hinkhouse is short and straightforward,  just  head  uphill  to
the top. Well, it isn\'t quite that simple. First I had to skirt a soggy  wet
marshy meadow. Then there were several slabby cliffbands  to  work  through.
None were difficult but the rock was still wet and slippery so I had  to  be
careful. The brush was also wet, and my boots,  already  wet  from  the  day
before, didn\'t keep my feet dry for very long. But the biggest surprise  was
when I topped out on the false summit and looked  over  to  the  main  rocky
summit across a narrow notch. It looked difficult. I  wasn\'t  expecting  any
rock climbing. I got more worried when I didn\'t immediately see a  way  into
the notch. Then I spotted a wide ledge below accessed by descending  NE  off
the false summit. Once at the notch  what  appeared  difficult  was  nothing
more than easy and fun class 3.

There was an interesting and informative register on top placed  9/15/01  by
One Step At A time, a climbing group for  recovering  alcoholics.  The  peak
had officially been renamed on 12/8/2000 in honor of Jimmy D. Hinkhouse  who
died in 1995 on Denali and was active in that  group.  An  earlier  register
(placed by the Mazamas) with entries dating from 1968  when  it  was  called
Washington Pass Pk had been removed and returned to the Mazamas. I added  my
name and noted mine was the first of 2009 and  there  were  none  for  2008,
unexpected for such an easily accessible peak.

This peak is a splendid viewpoint for  all  of  the  Washington  Pass  area.
Unfortunately, although the sun was out by now  many  of  the  higher  peaks
were in the fog. Still, I had reasonable views of the closer ones.  I  could
also look directly down to my car and my descent route.

Total: 2 miles, 2300 ft and 4 hrs RT at a leisurely pace.

Fay Pullen









