            'tr' => '
Beargrass Butte (5830 ft - 830P - Packwood Lk Quad); and Old Snowy Mtn  Quad
1 (6754 ft - 1194P) & Chimney Rock (6708 ft - 278P) -  Old Snowy Mtn Quad  -
June 23-24, 2009

Day 1 - Tuesday - Beargrass Butte - If you want  solitude  try  this  seldom
visited area of the Goat Rocks Wilderness. I entered  via  the  Three  Peaks
Trail, still on maps and in books but unmarked, unmaintained  and  obviously
little used. I drove Road 1266 from Packwood 6 miles to spur 1266-070  where
it is best to park if you don\'t have a 4X4 vehicle. I was able to  drive  an
additional .6 mile in my Jeep to a washout at 3500 ft.  I  then  walked  the
old road another .5 miles to the start of real trail. There  were  no  signs
anywhere along the route, but the trail start was marked by a large cairn.

The Three Peaks Trail essentially followed the up and  down  ridge  all  the
way to Mosquito Lake. It had many blowdowns but was easy to follow  until  I
lost it in snow at about 4800 ft. The entire way is  in  forest  and  passes
the edge of an  old  clear-cut  at  about  2.5  miles  before  entering  the
wilderness. I bypassed Mosquito Lake, picking up the Packwood Lake Trail  in
the saddle near its junction with the Coyote Trail. I dropped to  completely
snowed in Lost Lake where I had to search to find  a  small  patch  of  bare
ground under trees to camp (6 miles, 2800 ft, 4:30 hrs).

After setting up camp, I started for Beargrass Butte. I had had  a  view  of
it from the Three Peaks Trail on the way in so knew I would run into  cliffs
on the ridge from Lost Lake. Sure enough, by following  the  ridge  crest  I
eventually found myself stopped by pinnacles and a deep notch. I managed  to
squeak out a sketchy route down to easier terrain  without  using  my  rope.
Beargrass Butte is aptly named as the final easy slopes are a solid mass  of
beargrass. Oh, to be there when they are all in bloom.  What  a  sight  that
would be! On the way back I traversed below the cliffs of the  pinnacles  on
the south slope but it was still no piece of cake (3 miles, 1500 ft,  3  hrs
RT from camp).

Day 2 - Wednesday - Snowy1 (Pk6754) and Chimney Rock - I backtracked to  the
Coyote Trail junction. This trail was maybe  75%  snow  covered  but  I  was
still able to follow it much of the way  facilitating  traversing  past  the
cliffs of Pt 6497. Then solid snow led to the basin W of Snowy1  from  where
I spotted a gully route through the summit cliffs to  the  top  (2.5  miles,
1700 ft, 2:30 hrs). There was no cairn. I had a great view  into  the  heart
of the Goat Rocks. I made a call to my Dad in Albuquerque  on  the  occasion
of his 98th birthday and waved to Mt Rainier (which he climbed in  his  60s)
on his behalf.

I was uncertain how to continue on to Chimney Rock. I thought maybe I  would
have to descend my up route and take a circuitous route  to  the  connecting
ridge, but I managed to find a reasonable scramble down a very  loose  gully
directly to the S ridge. Easy  snow  made  travel  easy  to  the  cliffs  on
Chimney\'s N side but I could  see  no  obvious  easy  route  to  the  summit
through them. Hoping for a better route there, I crossed a  6400  ft  saddle
to the S side. The map showed the  Coyote  Trail  almost  reaching  to  this
saddle but it was in fact several hundred feet below  down  cliffy  terrain.
This is when it began to dawn on me I was in for a very  long  day.   I  did
find a semi-scramble route down but only because  there  was  no  anchor  to
rappel two class 4 steps.

Once on the Coyote Trail I used  it  to  traverse  below  the  cliffs.  This
traverse took longer than I hoped and was not all that easy where the  trail
was filled in with steep snow. Finally I turned  the  corner  on  a  SW  rib
where I could leave the trail and head up broken terrain to a notch  on  the
W ridge. The final summit rocks were a class 3  scramble  to  a  nondescript
false summit. I proclaimed a small pinnacle slightly farther E as  the  true
summit and my altimeter backed me up by reading 5 feet higher. A  peak  with
the name Chimney Rock requires a rocky summit (4 miles, 2450 ft, 5 hrs).

It was now 2:00 and I had a long ways yet to go if I wanted to make it  home
today. I returned to the Coyote trail and followed it all the way  back.  It
was longer than my in route but easier. I reached camp  at  5:15  (9  miles,
3000 ft, 8:30 hrs RT). I took time for some nutrition and a regenerating  30
minute nap before packing up and leaving at 6:30. The trail  out  seemed  to
go up much too much and the blowdowns loomed larger and more  annoying  than
the day before. Still, I made it to  my  car  by  10:00  without  needing  a
headlamp (6 miles, 1150 ft, 3:30 hrs from camp).

Total: 24 miles and 8500 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen

