            'title' => 'Enigma Pk (8015 ft - 615P) & Castle Rock (8137 ft - 537P) - Stehekin Quad; and White Goat Mtn (7800+ ft - 400P), WyNorth Mtn (8202 ft - 402P) & WyEast Mtn (8280+ ft - 600P) - Mt Lyall Quad - July 2-7, 2009',
            'tr' => '
Enigma Pk (8015 ft - 615P) & Castle Rock (8137 ft - 537P) -  Stehekin  Quad;
and White Goat Mtn (7800+ ft - 400P), WyNorth Mtn (8202 ft - 402P) &  WyEast
Mtn (8280+ ft - 600P) - Mt Lyall Quad - July 2-7, 2009

What a wonderful, enjoyable and successful trip this turned out to  be.  Jim
and Eileen invited me along on their  plan  to  climb  Tupshin,  Devore  and
White Goat. Although I had  already  been  up  the  first  two  I  was  very
interested in the last one  and  there  were  several  other  peaks  in  the
vicinity I could climb on my own, so I  jumped  at  the  chance.  Beth  also
joined the party.

Day 1 (Thursday) - Bird Cr Camp - We  took  the  Lady  Express  to  Stehekin
where Beth and Eileen turned on the charm to hitch a ride  with  a  friendly
couple and their BIG dog on their private boat to Weaver Point.  This  saved
us 3 miles of extra walking along the river from Harlequin  Bridge.  It  was
still an effort though, to lug full packs heavy with  climbing  gear  and  6
days of food (for me) up the hot and brushy Devore Cr Trail and  all  of  us
were more than happy to stop at Bird Cr Camp (5 miles, 3000 ft, 5:30 hrs).

Day 2 (Friday) - Enigma Pk and Castle Rock - While the others were  climbing
Tupshin, I headed for Enigma.  I hiked about 2.5 miles up the trail until  I
was sure I was past the creek draining the west side of the peak  and  found
a nice log crossing of Devore Cr. Fairly open forest led to the  west  ridge
of Enigma which I followed, first on the crest and then on the  south  side,
to the summit pinnacles. The last 1000 ft was unpleasant  loose  scree.  All
the way up I was struck by the impressive view of the North Peak of  Riddle.
I was a little confused by which pinnacle was the highest. It turned out  to
be the one to the left of the notch I reached. I found no  register  in  the
cairn (3700 ft, 5 hrs).

From the notch I spotted a possible  route  directly  down  from  Enigma  to
Castle Cr Basin. I wasn\'t originally sure from looking at the  map  at  home
that this would go and was relieved when it did. But it was not without  its
challenges. I zigzagged my way 1800 feet down ledges and ramps  and  gullies
only needing one short rappel near the bottom to bypass  a  waterfall.  From
lovely Castle Cr Basin (elev 6200 ft), I started  up  again  once  past  the
rocky NW ridge of Flora. Pleasant  open  terrain  led  to  the  S  ridge  of
Castle. I tried staying on the crest but was forced by pinnacles  to  the  W
slope. After crossing two ribs, I was able to climb back to  the  ridge  and
summit where I could look straight down to Stehekin (5600 ft, 9 hrs).  Again
I found no register.

I now had to find a way back to  camp,  preferably  the  shortest  possible,
which certainly wasn\'t the way I had come. This  appeared  to  be  over  the
7200 ft saddle just to the N of Enigma. I had no  trouble  getting  to  this
saddle but once there I saw the other side was guarded by  a  200  ft  cliff
band. Darn! Well it did look steep on the map but I had hoped  it  would  be
easier. Nonetheless I did manage to tease out a sketchy scramble route  down
to skiers left. An open snow basin below  speeded  things  up  until  I  hit
horrible brush the last 1000 feet to Devore Cr. I could find no log  at  the
creek and with time getting short and me  getting  desperate  I  just  waded
across. I stumbled out of the brush on the other side  onto  the  trail  and
dragged into camp at 9:00. I was very surprised to find it still empty,  but
the others showed up shortly later at  9:30  after  a  successful  climb  of
their own. Total: 10 miles, 6500 ft and 14 hrs.

Day 3 (Saturday, July 4) - White Goat Mtn - With all  of  us  having  had  a
late day we didn\'t get a very early start. Beth,  more  interested  in  just
Tupshin and Devore and fighting the lingering effects of a virus elected  to
take a rest day. Jim, Eileen and I started for Bird Cr Basin  at  8:15.  Jim
did a great job of finding a mostly brush free  route  to  the  basin,  much
better than I remember from my climb of Devore several years ago. The  gully
leading to the Lakes Basin above was snow free.  We  reached  Bird  Lake  at
1:30. White Goat appeared to still be a depressingly  long  ways  away,  but
the distance was deceiving and the terrain easy and we were at the  base  of
the SE buttress at 3:00.

We all gasped at the route up the SE Buttress. My but  it  looked  steep.  I
was glad Jim was leading and what a marvelous job  he  did.  Eileen  belayed
Jim the full length of a 50M rope.  I went  second  cleaning  what  I  could
reach, and then belayed Eileen. It was steep but the holds were good.  There
was a nice belay ledge at the end. From the belay ledge Jim set a hand  line
for another half a rope length traverse  along  the  ridge  to  the  summit,
reached at 5:00 (3800 ft, 8:45 hrs). This section has to  be  the  narrowest
most exposed summit ridge I have  ever  been  on.  Jim\'s  description  of  a
potato chip on edge captures it perfectly.   It  simply  takes  your  breath
away and none of us could keep from wondering  what  kept  the  whole  thing
upright and from collapsing on sight.

The original 1940 summit register was still there. After signing it we  took
a few moments to revel in our airy perch before reversing the  traverse  and
doing one double rope rappel down the buttress. We  were  back  in  Bird  Cr
Basin at 8:45. Darkness caught us an hour later and greatly  contributed  to
us missing much of the up route and floundering in  brush  by  headlamp  the
rest of the way. We staggered into camp at 11:00, much to the  relief  of  a
worrying Beth. Total: 6.5 miles, 3900 ft and 14:45.

Day 4 (Sunday) -WyNorth - Another late night  led  to  another  late  start,
9:00. Our plan for this day evolved and changed with events. Originally  Jim
planned to move camp to Bird Cr Basin and do  both  Devore  and  White  Goat
from there. But none of us really wanted  to  lug  full  packs  through  the
brush up there. I could climb WyNorth from there  but  it  wasn\'t  the  most
direct route for me. While climbing Enigma I had a full  view  of  the  West
Fork Devore Cr. It sure looked like a good route to me to my peak  and  even
a good way up Devore. With additional beta I  had  gotten  before  from  Don
Goodman (and from some Beth had gotten from climbers passing through on  her
rest day) we decided to climb both peaks this way.

The West Fork Devore Creek turned out to be a  very  nice  route.  There  is
very little brush and the terrain is easy. A  short  waterfall  headwall  is
passed by traversing left at about 6200 ft to a gentle basin and then  right
again.  At about 7200 ft and 1:30 we parted company. I went left to  WyNorth
and the others went right to Devore. I climbed some  steep  snow  (the  only
time I needed my ice axe the whole trip) and some easy rock  to  the  summit
ridge just shy of Pt 8200+. Since I was so close I  climbed  this  point  on
the way. I then had to descend slightly to bypass  a  couple  of  pinnacles.
The summit block is climbed via a class 2 ramp  on  the  right  or  a  short
class 3-4 pitch on the left (4100 ft, 6 hrs). I  found  Don  Goodman\'s  film
can register from 2007. There were no other entries.  For  those  interested
in such details, I took my clinometer along and sighted from each summit  to
the other. 8202 is definitely higher than 8200+.

On my way down I caught sight of first  one,  then  two  figures,  at  about
3:45, on the summit of Devore so I knew my friends were successful.  It  was
an easy trip back to camp which I reached at 6:45 with finally  enough  time
and energy to wash up head to toe. I felt refreshingly clean. I also  ate  a
hearty dinner and took a nap before  the  others  showed  up  at  9:30  with
reports of beginning sprinkles, but nothing ever came  of  them.  (Total:  7
miles, 4350 ft, 9:45 hrs).

Day 5 (Monday) - WyEast - I had one more peak to climb if possible  and  was
prepared to stay a day longer than the others to accomplish  that.  Jim  and
Eileen packed up and left at 8:00. Beth was meeting a  friend  on  Wednesday
for a climb of Reynolds and planned on a layover day in Stehekin.  She  left
at 9:00, as did I - but for WyEast. The day was  cloudy  with  sunbreaks  to
start. I made it the 4 miles to the gorgeous flower meadows of 4th  of  July
Basin before  it  became  clear  to  me  that  the  weather  was  definitely
changing. I could see a front approaching and a cold  wind  kicked  up  that
lowered the temperature at least 20 degrees. I got cold for the  first  time
on this trip and had to put on all the extra clothes I was carrying. By  the
time I was in the summit gully (much loose scree) it began to  sprinkle.  At
the notch right of Pt 8220 it began to snow and visibility shrank.

 Uncertain exactly where the summit was, I traversed on easy ledges  past  a
first pinnacle, regained the ridge, went up a sandy gully to the  top  of  a
second pinnacle and followed the ridge on class 3-4 black lichened  rock  to
what appeared to be the high point except that I  saw  no  rappel  sling  or
cairn. It was snowing and blowing and I was  getting  cold  and  discouraged
when what to my wondering eyes should appear at my very  feet  but  a  cairn
with a film can register inside (4050 ft, 4:50 hrs). Glory be!  A  few  feet
away I found the rappel sling and the  class  4  chimney  mentioned  by  Don
Goodman. I had bypassed it completely.

I could have downclimbed my up route if the rock had had been  dry,  but  it
was not and the black lichen was  slicker  than  Teflon.  So  I  elected  to
rappel the chimney. My 100 ft rope made it easily.  It  rained  lightly  off
and on all the way back to camp, not enough to get the upper part of me  wet
but enough to saturate my feet in the wet meadows and  brush.  It  continued
to rain that evening and forced me to eat dinner in my tent.  I  was  lonely
that night and truly missed the cheerful company of  Jim,  Eileen  and  Beth
(Total: 10 miles, 4100 ft, 9:20 hrs).

Day 6 (Tuesday) - Stehekin - It didn\'t rain any more during  the  night  but
the brush was still wet on the way out. The lower half  of  me  got  soaked.
About 1000 ft above the lake the trail dried out and so did  I,  except  for
my feet which were hopeless at this point. I picked up  clothes  stashed  at
the junction with the river trail and walked the 3 miles we had  avoided  on
the way in to the Harlequin Bridge. I left at 7:15 and  reached  the  bridge
at 12:00 (8 miles, 300 ft, 4:45 hrs). I  washed  up  and  changed  to  clean
clothes and blessedly dry socks and was waiting for the 12:40  shuttle  when
a nice lady in a pickup offered  me  a  ride  into  town.  I  had  the  most
delicious ham sandwich I have ever had at the restaurant. I  can\'t  remember
when I have ever been so famished. Beth found me at the boat dock  and  gave
me some gear to  take  out  she  wouldn\'t  need  on  Reynolds.  I  was  very
reluctant   to   part    and    officially    end    a    fantastic    trip.
Grand Total: 46.5 miles and 22,150 ft in 6 days        Fay Pullen











