            'month' => '07',
            'subdir' => '2009-07-14-fury-challenger',
            'title' => 'Northern Pickets Loop (Mt Fury East Pk (8288 ft), Mt Fury West Pk (8292 ft) and Mt Challenger (8207 ft) - Mt Challenger Quad - July 14-21, 2009',
            'tr' => '
Northern Pickets Loop (Mt Fury East Pk (8288 ft), Mt Fury West Pk (8292  ft)
and Mt Challenger (8207 ft) - Mt Challenger Quad - July 14-21, 2009

Sometimes you just get lucky.  Tom Sjolseth had been planning this trip  for
months with 5 other companions when all 5 had to cancel at the  last  minute
for various reasons leaving him with no partner. When  he  contacted  me  to
see if I was available I could hardly believe it. To  do  a  climb  of  this
caliber with such an experienced climber  was  a  dream  come  true.  I  had
always thought such a trip beyond me, partially because I am not capable  of
carrying the required heavy gear and food for such a  long  trip.  When  Tom
added he would carry ALL the group gear - tent, stove, rope, rack  AND  half
my food, how could I refuse such an offer?  I had 2 days to get ready.  Good
thing I am retired.

Day 1 (Tuesday, July 14) - Luna Camp -  We made arrangements  to  catch  the
water taxi across Ross Lake to Big Beaver Trail at 11:15 and hiked  the  hot
and buggy 10 miles to Luna Camp. Tom arrived a good 30 minutes ahead  of  me
despite his very heavy pack (1360 ft, 4:45 hrs).

Day 2 (Wednesday, July 15) - Access Cr to Bivy Below Luna Col -  We  crossed
Big Beaver Cr on the logjam about Â½ mile upstream from Luna Camp,  traversed
to Access Cr, crossed to the north side at about 2800  ft,  crossed  to  the
south again at 3900 ft (cairn on large  rock  here),  hopped  talus  to  the
basin east of Luna and worked our way up steep gullies to the 6200 ft  notch
in the ridge above. From the notch views opened up as we  traversed  heather
and ledges to a nice bivy on slabs near running water at 6600 ft  (5  miles,
4800 ft, 12:30). A tough day. Bugs were ferocious and we had to  sleep  with
headnets on to remain sane.

Day 3 (Thursday, July 16) - East Fury - We moved camp to Luna  Col  at  7200
ft and then took off for East Fury intending to bivy with only sleeping  bag
and pad on the summit to allow a full day to  climb  West  Fury.  The  usual
route to the ridge takes an "obvious" ledge directly above the  col  but  we
found our own way up a gully to the SE. The route then winds its way up  and
down more or less along the ridge. Much of the way is easy  scrambling  with
several steps of class 4 -low class 5. We did it all  unroped.  The  steeper
stuff was fairly solid with good holds and I never felt  uncomfortable.  The
last step is usually turned by a low traverse  down  and  around  cliffs  to
snow on the SE slope (we returned this way). We elected to stay  on  a  more
direct line up the ridge, climbing exposed somewhat loose class 4 rock.  The
last bit to the summit was snow (3 miles, 3200 ft,  9  hrs).  A  Mountaineer
register dating back to 1984 was on top. We each found a flat  slab  to  set
up our bivy. This was my first summit  bivy  and  conditions  couldn\'t  have
been more perfect. It was really quite comfortable. Both sunset and  sunrise
were spectacular.

Day 4 (Friday, July 17) - West Fury - East and West Fury are very  close  in
elevation but the West Peak is generally considered to be the  higher  by  a
few feet. It is also much more difficult to  attain.  Despite  being  little
more Â½ mile away, Beckey quotes a RT time of 6-8 hours from  the  East  Peak
along a convoluted ridge with 4 major pinnacles to bypass.  Hence  our  bivy
and early start. The route itself is difficult to describe and  most  likely
different for every party. Tom did an excellent  job  finding  the  way.  We
began by descending rock and snow to the first wall. I needed  crampons  for
the last bit to access the rock. Tom managed without. Once on  rock  exposed
ledges led up and around to easier terrain. It would be  difficult  to  find
the way back down this section and in  fact  we  made  two  rappels  on  the
return to avoid it. We crossed several cols,  did  an  exposed  bit  on  the
ridge crest, downclimbed a steep dike 0.75 of the way but rappelling  the  last
bit to another col, (we were able to climb back up  the  whole  way  on  the
return) before coming to the last obstacle which was climbed via a  somewhat
hidden chimney with old rappel slings at the top. From  there  it  was  easy
scrambling to the summit which we reached at 10:15 (.5 miles, 900  ft,  3:50
hrs). The original summit register from 1958 was on top.

We were back to the East Summit by 2:50 for a RT time of 8:20.  We  did  the
whole route unroped but did do 4 rappels total. I found the climbing  to  be
within my comfort level and I really  enjoyed  all  the  rock  climbing.  We
continued on from the East summit to Luna Col downclimbing  the  whole  way.
It did seem to have gained in length though. We reached the col and camp  at
6:30 (4 miles, 3000 ft, 12:00 hrs).

Day 5 (Saturday, July 18) - Camp Below Challenger - Tom climbed Luna (2  hrs
RT!) in the morning while I rested and organized my gear. Then we packed  up
and headed for Challenger. The first part of  the  route  down  toward  Luna
Lake was delightful, through lovely heather and flower gardens with  gushing
creeks and waterfalls. We thought the descent ended at  the  lake.  No  such
luck. We still had to drop almost  a  thousand  feet  more  on  awful  loose
moraine scree and talus depressingly close to unattractive Lousy Lake.  Then
more unpleasant traversing until we could finally start  up  again.  It  was
very deceiving and much farther  than  it  looked.  We  worked  our  way  up
pleasant slabs near many waterfalls (one class 4 section) until Tom found  a
nice flat slab for the tent at 6200 ft, where I was more than ready to  stop
(4 miles, 3100 ft descent, 2500 ft gain, 7 hrs).

Day 6 (Sunday, July 19) - Mt Challenger - We took a direct route up snow  to
Challenger Arm at 7500 ft, dropped our  full  packs  and  continued  up  the
beautiful NW snow arÃªte to the base of the summit rocks where  Tom  led  the
5.7 pitch to the summit arriving at 12:30. This is the  only  place  on  the
entire trip where we roped up. There was no register. We enjoyed  the  views
for the better part of  an  hour,  rappelled  the  rock  pitch  and  quickly
returned to our packs. A long glissade brought us to the broad  saddle  with
Pk 7374. There were several nice tent  sites  here  but  we  elected  to  go
slightly farther to a delightful bivy on a  heather  bench  just  below  the
summit of Pk 7374 (4 miles, 2700, 7:30 hrs). There was  even  a  small  melt
water pond to soak my increasingly aching feet. This has to be  one  of  the
most scenic spots in all of the Northern Pickets. A little slice  of  heaven
with no bugs.

Being so close we also popped up to the summit of Pk 7374 (654P).

Day 7 (Monday, July 20) - Eiley-Wiley Ridge to Luna Camp  -  A  tiring  day.
Eiley-Wiley is a long ridge with many ups and downs. We began by dropping  a
bit to get around cliffy Pk 7374. Then it was pleasant ridge  rambling  past
Wiley and Eiley Lakes until coming to Pk 6984 (no time or  energy  for  this
one). This was turned on the SE to a nice basin at 6200 ft. From  the  basin
on was unpleasant steep sidehill crossing many gullies. We tried to stay  on
a high contour but terrain and cliffs forced us ever  downward  after  which
we had to climb back up to gain the forested exit ridge  that  led  straight
down to Beaver Pass. Here  the  bugs  became  almost  intolerable.  Once  at
Beaver Pass we intersected the trail on the east side of Big Beaver Cr  (not
so big here) and followed it 4.5 miles to Luna Camp. By  this  point  I  was
suffering greatly and slowly limped down the trail, reaching  camp  over  an
hour after Tom (9 miles, 1700 ft, 11 hrs).

Day 8 (Tuesday, July 21) - Big Beaver Dock - Our scheduled  pickup  time  at
the dock was 12:30. With the 10 mile distance, we left early,  Tom  at  6:15
and me at 6:30, to assure we didn\'t miss the boat  -  literally.  It  seemed
much longer than on the way in and seemed to go on forever.  Heat  and  bugs
didn\'t help. I limped in at 11:45. I  think  Tom  made  it  sometime  before
10:00. (10 miles, 560 ft, 5:15 hrs).  On the way back  from  a  drop-off  up
lake, the taxi saw us and picked us up early at  12:00.  We  still  had  the
mile and 500 ft climb from the lake to the  car  on  Highway  20  before  we
could both feed our starving bodies in Marblemount.

This trip was difficult and challenging for me into an area I never  thought
I would be able to go. But it was a wonderful adventure I will  remember  it
the rest of my life. I have Tom to thank for it.

Total: 51 miles and 20, 400 ft in 8 days.

Fay Pullen



