            'title' => 'West McMillian Spire (8000+ ft - 600P) & Glee Pk (7160+ ft - 920P) - Mt Challenger Quad; and The Roost (6705 ft - 865P) - Mt Triumph Quad - August 3-5, 2009.',
            'tr' => '
West McMillian Spire (8000+ ft - 600P) & Glee Pk (7160+  ft  -  920P)  -  Mt
Challenger Quad; and The Roost (6705 ft - 865P) - Mt Triumph Quad  -  August
3-5, 2009.

After seeing them from both my recent trips, to  the  Northern  Pickets  and
Thornton Peak, I was  eager  to  make  my  first  entry  into  the  Southern
Pickets. I felt I could  probably  solo  the  easiest  of  the  bunch,  West
McMillian Spire, but I did have some concerns about  the  condition  of  the
route. Then I learned John Roper and his son Aaron had just done  the  peak.
That synched it and off I went.

Day 1: Monday, August 3 - To High  Camp  -  At  the  Wilderness  Information
Center in Marblemount, upon recognizing my name Kelly Bush,  the  ranger  in
charge of search and rescue for the entire  North  Cascades,  appeared  from
the back room to greet me and find out what I was up to. She is such a  nice
woman although I sure hope I never have  to  use  her  services.  We  had  a
pleasant conversation after which the young ranger issuing my permit  didn\'t
question me other than to ask if I planned to get all the way to  high  camp
today. I said I sure hoped so.

I drove to the Upper Goodell Campground and parked in a  small  lot  at  the
very end of the road a couple hundred feet past the group  site.  The  whole
place was completely deserted. I had heard horror stories of the Goodell  Cr
climber\'s trail. It turned out to be much better  than  I  expected.  It  is
certainly better then the two  approaches  I  have  taken  to  the  Northern
Pickets - Access Cr and Eiley-Wiley Ridge. The first 4 miles follows an  old
road and is in generally good shape except for a  short  brushy  section  in
the middle and several washed out creeks. After leaving the road it is  very
steep but fairly brush free and for the most part  easily  followed  if  one
stays alert. The only really bad parts  are  a  vertical  root  ladder  just
before breaking out into heather and where it follows a stream bed  for  200
ft and all signs of tread disappear. This stream  had  a  trickle  of  water
that allowed me to camp nearby on a heather bench. It was  the  first  water
encountered since leaving the road.  I  wanted  to  camp  here  rather  than
farther on to allow me to also climb the Roost.

Total: 7 miles, 4800 ft and 7:20 hrs.

Day 2: Tuesday, August 4 - West McMillian Spire  and  Glee  Peak  (aka  High
Ross and Pk 7200+) - I picked up good tread as it left the  stream  bed  and
followed it up and down all the way to the 6240 ft saddle in a  spur  ridge.
Horrible loose scree and hard packed dirt  on  the  other  side  had  to  be
descended several hundred feet until reaching a nice flat area  at  5900  ft
with good camping sites. Now began a long descending traverse over  pleasant
terrain to a low point of 5500 ft  at  the  outlet  of  a  still  iced  over
glacial lake. Once across this I could finally start up beautiful  slabs  to
the edge of the Terror Glacier.  I  had  worried  about  the  glacier  being
broken up and difficult to cross but in fact this section was  more  like  a
snowfield and no problem at all. I climbed the glacier until it narrowed  to
a snow finger leading to the Inspiration-West  McMillan  col.  It  was  late
enough in the day that the snow had softened and crampons were  not  needed,
but it got steep enough and thin enough near the  top  that  I  exited  onto
awful loose cruddy rock and dirt. This soon gave way to heather  and  better
but still somewhat loose rock on the west ridge. I  reached  the  summit  at
1:45 and signed the register right after John and  Aaron  (3.5  miles,  3700
ft, 6:20 hrs). Views of Inspiration, Degenhardt and Terror were stunning  as
were the rest of the surrounding area. Although I really  didn\'t  think  the
climb of West McMillan to be of the highest quality, as a viewpoint  it  has
few peers.

I now focused my attention on getting to  Glee.  I  really  didn\'t  want  to
descend all the way back to the glacial lake outlet.  I  could  see  a  high
route that traversed above the cliffy glacial lake cirque  to  the  6200  ft
saddle in the ridge above Azure Lake that would save about 800 ft  and  this
is the way I went. It turned out to  be  a  delightful  route  on  snow  and
lovely slabs, across many little rushing creeks, in and out  of  mini  slots
and past several dramatic notches, full of interest and variety. One of  the
most enjoyable traverses I have ever done.  After traversing  below  several
bumps, I finished on the NW ridge which was capped by a short class  4  step
to the summit of Glee (5000 ft, 11:15 hrs). I was surprised to find a  large
register but it was a useless soggy mess and illegible. I  easily  descended
the south side to a snowfield that led to the heather spur ridge  above  the
6240 saddle where I picked up the climber\'s trail and returned to camp.

Total: 8 miles, 5100 ft and 13:15 hrs.

Day 3: Wednesday, August 5 - The  Roost  -  What  an  absolutely  delightful
climb this was along a gorgeous gentle heather ridge all the way.  It  ranks
up there with my best ridge rambles  ever.  And  what  a  roomy  comfortable
viewpoint the summit is. I can see why it is called The Roost. I would  have
liked to "roost" there for a very long time. It would certainly be  a  dandy
place to camp. Most climbers coming to this area are  lured  to  the  higher
West McMillan Spire (or other Picket peaks), but truth  be  told  both  Glee
and The Roost are more enjoyable climbs.  3 miles, 1600 ft and 3:50 hrs RT.

All too soon it was time  to  leave  and  begin  the  long  unpleasant  knee
jarring, foot sore descent out. I reached the old road in 3  hours  and  the
car in 2.5  more, after stopping for Â½ hour to soak my aching  feet  in  the
creek near the junction. I reached the car at 6:00 (7 miles,  200  ft,  5:30
hrs) only to be greeted with a notice  on  my  windshield  that  I  was  not
allowed to park where I did ("this is not a parking lot or a trailhead"  but
a reserved area and I was to pay $25 per night to camp). You have got to  be
kidding! Hot, sweaty and tired I really did not need this at the end of  the
day. I was not parked in any campsite and the  irony  was  that  the  entire
campground was still deserted. Where the heck are you supposed to  park?  It
was too late to resolve the situation at either the Newhalem Visitor  Center
or the Marblemount RS but  I  called  the  next  day  from  home.  Evidently
campground enforcement is completely separate from backcountry and  the  two
don\'t always communicate. I did after all have a  valid  backcountry  permit
with my license plate number in the computer system. I was told there is  no
other place to park except in the campground  but  there  is  another  small
area  before  the  group  site  that  might  be  more  acceptable   to   law
enforcement. If parking is  such  a  problem  perhaps  signs  should  direct
climbers where to legally park. The confusion  is  not  going  away  as  all
climbers using the Goodell Cr trail have to park somewhere.

Grand Total: 25 miles and 11,700 ft in 3 days.

Fay Pullen

