            'tr' => '
The Citadel (7120+ ft - 440P - Mt Daniel Quad) - August 15-16, 2009

Thwarted once again by weather to try Mt  Triumph,  we  came  up  with  this
absolutely delightful 2-day trip as  a  last  minute  alternative.  It  just
doesn\'t get any  better  than  this  -  easy  approach,  beautiful  scenery,
pleasant  cross-country  travel,  no  bugs,  no  brush,  ideal  weather  and
wonderful company (Jim, Eileen, Beth and John Myers).

Day1 (Saturday - August 15): The Citadel - From Cathedral Pass we  took  the
trail to Peggys Pond where we picked up a  very  good  fisherman\'s  path  to
Circle Lake (6.5 miles, 3500  ft,  5:20  hrs).  After  setting  up  camp  we
started for The Citadel traversing gentle heather and interesting  slabs  to
a short loose scree slope that led to the north ridge. This  was  capped  by
50 feet of class 3-4 with loose blocks that required caution  and  a  narrow
exposed summit ridge. We were all surprised to find a register in very  good
shape dating back several  decades  and  had  fun  reading  through  it  and
recognizing many names. Our  summit  was  under  a  sunny  hole  but  clouds
obscured most of the peaks around us except for Mt Daniel. We rappelled  the
rock pitch and were back in camp in time  to  complete  dinner  in  daylight
(1.3 miles, 1200 ft, 2:55 hr RT including almost an hour on top).

Day 2 (Sunday, August 16): Cathedral Rock -  Everything  had  gone  so  much
easier and quicker  than  expected  (how  often  does  that  happen  in  the
mountains?) that we were now left with the choice  of  going  out  early  or
seeking a way to extend our  stay.  In  such  a  beautiful  area  with  such
perfect conditions of course we chose the  latter.  The  choices  for  bonus
peaks nearby were Mt Daniel and Cathedral Rock. Jim, Beth and I had  already
climbed both, but John and Eileen had done  neither.  John  elected  to  add
Daniel to his resume with an early 6 am start, while the rest of us  decided
to accompany Eileen up Cathedral Rock, leaving camp several hours later.  We
returned to Cathedral Pass (600 ft, 1:45  hrs)  to  leave  our  large  packs
before starting the climb.

It had been several decades since I had climbed Cathedral Rock so my  memory
was a bit fuzzy, as was Jim\'s and Beth\'s. But we managed to find our way  up
the gully that steepened to a chimney (turned on the left) to  the  base  of
the summit pitch without a route description (no one  knew  Cathedral  would
be part of the agenda). This peak is climbed so often there  is  essentially
a climber\'s trail all the way up. We were also challenged by having  limited
gear - only a short 100 foot 8mm scramble rope  and  a  few  slings  but  no
other pro for the 4 of us. Fortunately the climbing portion  is  only  about
100 ft long with solid rock and good holds. Beth led up and the rest  of  us
came after on a fixed line with a  prussik.  After  that  a  scramble  of  a
couple hundred feet distance put us on top. Two rappels got us back down.  I
had forgotten how much fun this peak was (1.2 miles, 1100 ft,  3:35  hrs  RT
from Cathedral Pass). John was waiting for us  when  we  reached  the  TH  2
hours later. We ended a perfect outing with dinner at the Old #3 in Ronald.

Total: 16 miles and 6500 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen









