            'title' => 'Andrew Pk (8301 ft - 1581P), Amos Pk (8259 ft - 419P) & Peepsight Mtn (8146 ft- 986P) -Remmel Mtn Quad; and Freds Mtn (8080+ ft - 480P) - Ashnola Pass Quad - August 21-23, 2009',
            'tr' => '
Andrew Pk (8301 ft - 1581P), Amos Pk (8259 ft - 419P) & Peepsight Mtn  (8146
ft- 986P) -Remmel Mtn Quad; and Freds Mtn (8080+ ft - 480P) -  Ashnola  Pass
Quad - August 21-23, 2009

The challenge of a trip like this, where the travel is easy, is  to  combine
all the peaks in a day\'s timeframe in the most efficient manner possible.

Day 1 - Friday, August 21: Andrew Pass - The approach was  via  the  Andrews
Cr trail. The entire valley was burned in the devastating Farewell  Fire  of
a few years ago. There is much greenery in  the  understory  but  the  stark
black trees offer little to no shade. What with the 4.5 -hour  drive  I  got
none too early a start and by the time  I  hit  the  trail  (12:30)  it  was
already 82 degrees, which made for very hot going to  start.  Fortunately  a
stiff breeze soon materialized to cool things off although it  did  cause  a
spooky sound as it whistled through the dead trees. I was surprised  at  the
lack of campsites along this trail. There was only one other, at  about  the
7 mile mark, before reaching Andrew Pass.

I had planned to take the Peepsight Trail (8  miles  in)  and  camp  in  the
basin east of Peepsight Mtn but I could not find the trail junction.  I  was
forced to continue on the main trail another 4 miles. It  was  getting  late
and I was getting worried about finding a campsite with water when  I  found
both just before Andrew Pass. Andrew Cr had dwindled to a  mere  trickle  by
this time but it was sufficient to serve my needs.  This  location  actually
turned out to be a better starting point for a loop  peakbagging  trip  that
would not involve repeating any terrain (12 miles, 3800 ft, 7 hrs).

Day 2 - Saturday, August 22 - From Andrew Pass I just  headed  up  the  east
slopes to the summit of Amos Pk (1550 ft, 1:45 hr).  The terrain  was  open,
brushless and pleasant. I then followed the ridge south to  Andrew  Pk.  The
last bit had some interesting class 3+ blocky climbing before  leveling  off
near the summit (2200 ft, 3:25 hrs). The next objective was Freds Mtn.  This
is the peak I figured would give me the most  trouble.  Not  because  it  is
difficult but just because it is so darn far away. It  is  on  a  very  long
ridge that encompasses 3 basins and naturally the high point is at the  very
farthest end. It seemed to me the shortest route was  to  drop  1600  ft  to
Glory Lake in basin 1, traverse into basin 2 and climb onto the ridge  above
basin 3 near Pt 7960. Once past Pt 7960 I followed  the  west  side  of  the
ridge north to the summit where I  found  a  large  well  constructed  cairn
(3900 ft, 7:30 hrs).  From  Freds  I  essentially  followed  the  convoluted
ridge or its west side south all the way  to  Peepsight  Mtn  (4800  ft,  10
hrs). To return to Andrew Pass I descended to Crazy Man Pass where I  picked
up the Rock Lake Trail. This  trail  is  little  used  and  hard  to  follow
through meadows but is cairned and has been logged out since  the  fire.  In
waning light I lost the trail completely as it  traversed  the  east  slopes
below Andrew Pk so just headed downhill to intersect the Andrew  Pass  Trail
reaching camp at 9:00 (12 miles, 5100 ft, 12:45 hrs).

I left a register on each of the peaks as none had any I could find.

Day 3 - Sunday, August 23 - It was very windy and cold  in  the  morning.  I
waited until the sun hit my tent at 8:30 before packing up  and  leaving  at
9:30. On the way out I looked again for the  Peepsight  Trail  junction  and
again could not find it. I was having lunch at the 7 mile  campsite  when  a
wrangler leading a pack train of 6 mules showed up. He was bringing out  the
gear of a group of hikers who had spent a week at Remmel Lake. That mode  of
transportation was looking pretty good to me at that moment.  Maybe  someday
I will give it a try. Since I figured he would know, I asked him  where  the
Peepsight Trail was. He said it was about Â½ mile up from this  camp  but  it
was unmarked and hard to locate.  He told me the Pasayten Wilderness  had  a
policy of deliberately not marking lesser trails and  making  them  obscure.
Why on earth? And to  what  purpose?  He  really  didn\'t  know.  Perhaps  to
"increase the wilderness experience". And just how  does  it  "increase  the
wilderness experience", I would like to know, when you can\'t find  a  trail?
He told me of one couple who got lost and wandered around for a  day  and  a
half on unmarked trails trying to find Lower Cathedral Lake.

I stopped to soak my aching feet twice before reaching the car at 4:00.  (12
miles, 200 ft, 6:30 hrs).

Grand Total: 36 miles and 9100 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen





