            'tr' => '
Horseshoe Basin Peaks: Pick Pk (7628 ft - 410P), Horseshoe Mtn  (7956  ft  -
935P), Rock Mtn (7641 ft - 554P), "Mt Regard" (7858 ft  -  837P),  Armstrong
Mtn (8140+ ft - 1053P), Arnold Mtn (8090 ft - 577P) & Hodges  Horse  Pasture
(6739 ft - 735P) - Horseshoe Basin Quad;  and  Goodenough  Pk  (7382+  ft  -
295P) - Hurley Pk Quad; August 26-28, 2009

In June of 2005 I had to pass up half a dozen peaks around  Horseshoe  Basin
while climbing Windy, Bauerman Ridge, Apex, Wolframite and others on a  long
loop trip. I just didn\'t have the time.  But  I  had  always  planned  on  a
return just for those I missed. All these peaks are  easy  pleasant  ascents
through gentle meadows and open tundra, more hikes than climbs. There is  no
brush but terrain that is deep green in color often  indicates  bog  and  is
like trying to walk across a 6 inch deep sponge  carpet.  Despite  signs  of
plentiful water earlier in the area, sources were already beginning  to  dry
up and by late summer finding water could become a problem. I do  know  that
Louden Lake usually dries completely.

Day 1 - Wednesday, August 26: Pick Pk and Horseshoe Mtn - I  was  under  the
impression that Horseshoe Basin had been badly burned since  my  2005  trip.
That is certainly true for the approach from the Iron Gate TH. However,  the
Basin itself has been spared and it as lovely as ever. The 5.5  hour  drive
didn\'t put me on the trail until 2:00 but with a short and easy approach  of
6 miles I still had plenty of time to climb Pick Pk  and  Horseshoe  Mtn  on
the way in to camp. Pick I climbed from slightly before Sunny  Pass.  I  was
greeted by the cutest array of cairns I have ever encountered on  a  summit.
It appears that everyone who makes the top adds a rock and I  did  likewise.
For Horseshoe I headed  upslope  slightly  past  Sunny  Pass.  For  fun  and
variety I also climbed 3 tiny pinnacles just below the top.

I was hoping to camp right  at  Horseshoe  Pass  where  I  knew  there  were
several spacious sites but when I arrived there at 7:00 another  party  with
an annoying barking dog had already occupied it. So I continued on  a  short
ways and found a secluded spot in the trees  below  the  trail  and  near  a
small creek that gave me a buffer from  the  irritating  noise.  Talk  about
destroying the tranquility of the wilderness. I also heard  the  howling  of
coyotes in the distance (which may be why the dog  was  constantly  barking)
but that sound I enjoyed and it fit with the wilderness.

Total: 8 miles, 2500 ft and 5 hrs

Day 2 - Thursday, August 27: Rock Mtn, "Mt Regard",  Armstrong  Mtn,  Arnold
Mtn and Goodenough Pk - From my camp I crossed gorgeous meadows to the  base
of Rock Mtn, skirted a bog and easily climbed  the  east  slope.  It  was  a
glorious day with glorious views in all directions.  Windy  Pk  may  have  a
trail all the way to the top but it is still an impressive looking  mountain
and it dominated the vista. I descended the east slope on  the  way  to  "Mt
Regard". Upon hearing from John Roper that this peak had  no  name  that  he
was aware of we conspired to give it this  one  as  we  both  considered  it
worthy of "regard". The summit was an interesting jumble of boulders.

I descended Regard to climb the west slopes of Armstrong.  Armstrong  has  a
very broad flat summit plateau with  Monument  103  on  the  west  edge  and
Monument 104 of the US-Canada border on the east  edge.  The  US  summit  is
marked by a cairn south of Monument 104 but the highest point (by  about  10
feet and confirmed by my two  altimeters  and  by  clinometer  sighting)  is
actually slightly north of Monument 103 in Canada. I ate my lunch at the  US
summit cairn.

I dropped to wide and beautiful Snehumption Gap to climb Arnold,  marked  by
a windbreak cairn. All these high peaks are almost always windy. I had  been
going at a leisurely pace and spent at least 30 minutes on each  summit  but
such was the ease of travel that it was still only 3:00 and much  too  early
to return to camp. Since it looked so inviting I continued along the  grassy
east ridge of Arnold all the way to Goodenough Pk. I picked up the trail  in
the saddle between it and Arnold, following it back to  camp  at  6:00.  The
party with the barking dog was gone and I had peace and quiet for  the  rest
of the evening.

Total: 13 miles, 4300 ft, 10 hrs

Day 3 - Friday, August 28: Hodges Horse Pasture - I left  at  8:30  for  the
easy trip out to the TH (6 miles, 400 ft, 2:30 hrs).  On  the  drive  out  I
stopped by the side of the  road  for  the  short  hike  through  grass  and
sagebrush up Hodges Horse Pasture (.5 miles, 450 ft, :30 RT).

Grand Total: 27.5 miles and 7250 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen

