            'tr' => '
Mt Triumph (7240+ ft - 1720P - Mt Triumph Quad) - September 11-13, 2009

Jim, Eileen and I had made an attempt on Mt Triumph  the  end  of  July  but
were thwarted by 2 days of intense  thunderstorms.  We  had  to  settle  for
Thornton Pk and were darn lucky to get even that. We rescheduled for  August
but ended up limited to 2 days and had to change plans.  We tried again  for
the Labor Day weekend which as everyone knows  was  a  total  washout.  This
time around we finally hit it right and had perfect weather. We were  joined
by Kevin W and Kevin K.

Day 1: Friday, September 11 - We approached via the 6  mile  Thornton  Lakes
trail. From the lower lake outlet we followed a series of  way  trails  past
campsites, up  and  down  over  several  humps,  through  some  minor  brush
bypassing a cliffband and onto the broad lovely spur  leading  to  the  main
Thornton Ridge. Once on this, travel was delightful.  This being our  second
time here (3rd for Jim) we had no problem with route finding  and  used  the
same bivy site as before (adequate but not overly spacious).  Worried  about
water availability this late in the season, we all hauled some up  from  the
lake but we did find a source in a gully that still held some snow  not  too
far from camp. Good thing as  the  day  was  very  hot  and  we  all  needed
prodigious amount of liquid to stay hydrated.

Total: 8 miles, 4300 ft and 7:30 hrs.

Day 2: Saturday, September 12 - From camp we traversed  the  right  side  of
the ridge past a bump to the last saddle south of Thornton Pk  then  dropped
about 800 feet on talus, heather and blueberries  to  get  past  cliffs.  We
crossed one unpleasant loose dirt gully that had a good flow  of  water.  We
encountered several other smaller water sources en route that allowed us  to
refill. This was another hot day. After a long level traverse we  climbed  a
left slanting heather ramp to the bouldery SW shoulder of Triumph. From  the
shoulder we traversed some  more  under  "The  Great  White  Slab",  a  very
obvious feature on Triumph\'s SW face. We then climbed class 3 rock and  very
steep heather and grass (would be deadly slick  when  wet)  along  the  left
edge of the slab to a prominent broad right-slanting  bench  that  went  all
the way to a notch south of and about 250 ft below the summit. We  roped  up
here for an easy but wildly exposed  ledge  crossing  the  east  face  to  a
shallow gully. The gully started as  easy  heather  but  ended  in  a  steep
headwall with loose rock  that  was  difficult  to  protect.  Jim  led  this
section with essentially no  protection.   Once  up  the  headwall  a  short
narrow rib and final easy scramble put us on the summit (1900 ft 5:30 hrs).

On the summit I divulged  that  today  was  my  67th  birthday  and  that  I
couldn\'t think of a better way to spend it or a better birthday  present.  I
could not find any register other than a film can so far  down  a  crack  no
one could reach it. If it is an historic one it is probably just as well  as
that way no one can remove it.  But no way was I going to climb Triumph  and
not sign a register, especially on my birthday.  I  had  brought  one  along
"just in case". However,  we  shall  see  how  long  it  lasts  since  North
Cascades registers seem to have a very short life span. We spent an hour  on
the summit taking in the  views,  identifying  surrounding  peaks  and  just
generally enjoying ourselves.

One double and one  single  rope  rappel  got  us  back  to  the  notch.  We
downclimbed the bench, which seemed much scarier to me on the  way  down  as
it hung directly above the exposed Great White Slab. We did two more  double
and one single rappel alongside the slab to get below it  and  back  to  the
shoulder. Then came the long traverse, now mostly uphill, to arrive in  camp
just at dusk. Then it was party time.  Perhaps the less said about this  the
better.

Total: 4 miles, 2850 ft and 12 hrs.

Day 3: Sunday, September 13 - I  think  we  were  all  reluctant  to  leave.
Rarely do you have such great conditions for a climb - perfect weather  (not
even a morning dew), no bugs, and great companions. At the lake Kevin K  and
Jim took a swim to cool off. Eileen and I contented ourselves  with  dipping
both feet and head. But we all got hot and sweaty again as we made  our  way
up out of the lake basin and on down the  trail.  Once  in  Marblemount  for
nourishment it seemed on one could get enough of cooling drinks.

Total: 8 miles, 800 ft and 6 hrs.

Grand Total: 20 miles and 7900 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen

Added Note - Garmin Testimonial: I  must  make  mention  that  on  the  last
rappel I dropped my Garmin Oregon GPS. I was not happy (understatement!)  as
I watched this very expensive piece of modern electronics bounce down  about
150 feet of (hard) rock and explode into several pieces. Now normally  I  am
paranoid about just such a thing happening  and  keep  everything  of  value
(camera, altimeter, GPS, etc) well tethered to me. But just this once I  had
put my GPS in the top  pocket  of  my  pack  thinking  it  would  be  better
protected there than on the outside even tethered.  Well it would have  been
had I then remembered to zip the pocket shut. When I twirled around  to  get
into the rappel out flew the GPS through the open pocket. But  here  is  the
remarkable thing. I managed to find the GPS below the bottom of the  rappel.
The back cover, the batteries and the micro SD map  card  were  all  missing
(that is what I saw exploding) but the main case was  intact  and  unbroken.
If that was remarkable in itself what was even more remarkable was  that  it
still worked. The route map for this TR was downloaded from it. Now  I  just
have to see if I can replace the back cover. Maybe if I tell this  story  to
Garmin they will do that for me. They sure make one rugged GPS.

P.S. Garmin did replace the back cover free of charge under the warranty.

