Finney Pk (8110 ft - 830P), SÃ©ance Pk (8067  ft  -  467P)  and  Beefhide  Pk
(8030 ft - 510P) - Price Cr Quad - September 19-21, 2009

Day 1: Saturday, September 19 - Beefhide Butte - The forecast was  not  good
for Saturday. I wasn\'t sure what to expect but although it was raining  hard
going over Snoqualmie Pass by the time I reached the  East  Fork  Buttermilk
Cr TH (elev 4800  ft)  it  was  actually  sunny  and  warm.  It  had  rained
overnight, however, as the brush was wet. I followed the good trail for  5.5
miles to the 3rd crossing of the creek (nice forest camp here). Pleasant  XC
travel for a mile led  to  a  wonderful  camp  in  the  lovely  basin  below
Beefhide Butte, elev 6900 ft.  (6.5 miles, 2200 ft, 3:45 hrs).   During  the
hike in I could  feel  the  temperature  drop  as  a  predicted  cold  front
approached.

I hurriedly set up camp and started for Beefhide, only  1200  ft  above  me,
climbing talus and scree to the ridge. On the ridge I was  confronted  by  a
frigid wind, fog and deteriorating conditions. I made it along the ridge  to
the summit (where I found a pill bottle register  placed  by  Roy  McMurtrey
last year) before real weather hit. It began to snow while I was  descending
the talus to camp (1.5 miles, 1200 ft, 2:10 hrs RT). I quickly retreated  to
the comfort of my tent. I was glad I had brought my warmer sleeping bag.

Day 2: Sunday, September 20 - SÃ©ance Pk and Finney Pk - It froze during  the
night and was positively icy in the morning but the sun was shining and  the
sky blue. It took until 8:30 for me to warm up enough  to  get  going.  From
camp I worked my way up pleasant terrain to the saddle between Beefhide  and
SÃ©ance and followed the easy crest to the summit (1200 ft,  1:35  hrs)  from
where I had a great view of most of the Chelan-Sawtooth Top 100 peaks.  This
is lovely country especially this time of year  as  the  larches  were  just
starting to turn from green to gold. However, my view of Finney was  not  at
all encouraging. It was very far away and I worried if I  could  get  to  it
and back before dark from where I was camped.

I dropped off of SÃ©ance into gorgeous Bernice Lake  Basin  passing  by  both
that lake and a slightly lower tarn. I knew there was a way trail  from  the
main trail in the valley to the lake but the thought  of  dropping  all  the
way to 5600 ft was too depressing. And I really didn\'t know where the  trail
was. I thought I could save some elevation loss by crossing the ridge SW  of
the Lake and taking a higher traverse to hit the trail. I  would  have  done
better to just take the loss. I ended up on steep awful  loose  scree,  only
saved maybe 400 ft and lost time in the process. By the time I hit the  main
trail it was 1:00.

Once on the trail I moved rapidly, gaining back  all  the  elevation  I  had
lost. I took the trail to  Indianhead  Basin  at  the  next  junction.  This
section of trail is beautiful as it  traverses  meadow  after  meadow.  Just
below Indianhead Pass I left the  trail  and  traversed  heather  and  talus
below Pt 7985. The terrain was more rugged than I had anticipated  and  took
longer than I thought. Then as I got my first really good close up  look  at
Finney, my heart fell. This was no obvious walkup like Beefhide and  SÃ©ance.
The north face was one big cliff.  Maybe (ever the optimist) once I  reached
the N ridge an easy route would appear up the W side. It did not. I am  sure
there is an easy route up the S side but to  get  to  it  I  would  have  to
descend several hundred feet past the W face cliffs. I  simply  didn\'t  have
time for that. It was already 3:30.

The only possible route I saw from  where  I  was  on  the  N  ridge  was  a
ledge/gully that cut diagonally across the N face to a notch on  the  ridge.
Would it go? In fact it did go. In fact it  was  a  fun  interesting  route,
mostly class 3 with a few class 4 moves, that I thoroughly enjoyed.  But  it
was exposed over slabs. And the summit ridge was  even  more  exposed.  From
the notch there is an E and W summit. I couldn\'t tell which  was  higher  so
climbed them both but I left my register on the surveyed 8110  ft  E  summit
(3900 ft, 7:30 hrs).

It was now 4:30 and it was no longer a question of whether I would  make  it
back to camp before dark. The question was now just how long after  dark  it
would be. There was also the question of how the heck I would  actually  get
there. I could not retrace my down route from Bernice Lake.  In  addition  I
had a major ridge between me and the comfort of my tent and no easy  way  to
cross it. My hope was to find the way trail to Bernice Lake (even  though  I
wasn\'t sure where it was) and then cross the ridge  at  the  SÃ©ance-Beefhide
saddle.

Darkness caught me at the low point of the trail at the junction to  Boiling
Lake (elev 5600 ft). Luck was  with  me  though  and  somehow  I  found  the
unmarked trail to Bernice Lake a short ways farther on. This  made  all  the
difference. Without it I would either have wandered around  all  night  long
or had to bivy till first light. I easily followed  this  surprisingly  good
trail until it veered left toward the lake. I continued straight  up  toward
the ridge. Now I knew this ridge was cliffy in places.  It  was  pitch  dark
with no moon and I could see  nothing  outside  my  headlight  beam.  I  had
marked the low point of the saddle earlier in the day with  my  GPS  and  so
headed for that waypoint. I just hoped no cliffs were in the way. In fact  I
did have 100 feet of dicey steep stuff near the top but I managed to find  a
way through. Once on the ridge it was easy going down the other side  (as  I
knew it would be from my morning up route).  I  arrived  at  camp  at  10:30
tired but pleased I had made it (16 miles, 6400 ft, 14 hrs).

Day 3: Monday, September 21 - I slept in till the  sun  hit  my  tent.  Then
easily hiked out in 2:45 hrs.

Total: 29 miles and 9800 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen







