Remind me in the future that maybe it isn\'t so bad to spend 12  hours  in  a
sleeping bag.

Day 1: Sunday, October 4 - I approached via the South Creek and  Louis  Lake
Trails off the Twisp River Road. The day was sunny  and  warm  to  start.  I
even wore shorts to begin but that didn\'t last long. From  Louis  Lake  (5.2
miles, 2300 ft, 3 hrs) I went around the right side of the  lake  and  up  a
rock slide to frozen upper Louis Lake. Surrounded by  steep  cliffs  so  the
sun never shines in its depths this time of year and covered with  a  recent
dusting of an inch or so of snow, this upper basin,  though  beautiful,  was
not really very friendly. It is also filled with endless talus and I had  to
search hard to find a suitable spot to camp, which I did at 5:00, elev  5900
ft (6.7 miles, 3000 ft, 5:15 hrs). It was too cold to do anything  but  turn
in at 6:30 and snuggle in my warm sleeping bag.

Day 2: Monday (and Tuesday!), October 5 - Louis Pk  -  It  froze  hard  (low
20\'s) during the night and was positively frigid by  morning  but  after  12
hours in my sleeping bag I was  more  than  ready  to  get  up  despite  the
temperature. I didn\'t warm up until reaching the  tantalizing  sun  high  on
the south slope of Louis. I reached this summit at 10:00 (2000  ft,  2  hrs)
and found a plastic bottle register left  in  June  1989  by  Dallas  Kloke.
There were only 5 other entries, the most recent being that of  Stefan,  Jim
Brisbine and Mike Torok in May of 2004. This peak  isn\'t  climbed  all  that
often.

Mt Gibbs - I tried to follow the SW ridge off Louis but  it  was  too  rocky
and I was forced south into a loose  gully  until  I  could  traverse  below
cliffs to the Louis-Gibbs saddle. Easy terrain then led to  what  I  thought
was Gibbs summit. But the high point was  maybe  50  feet  farther  along  a
narrow ridge that I backed off of due to slick snow and  loose  boulders.  I
did an end run down to the left and back up again with a few class 4  moves.
This little detour cost me 30 minutes  (3500  ft,  4:30  hrs).  I  found  no
register.

Camels Hump - It was now 12:30 and too early to return to a camp  always  in
shadow. So I decided to  try  for  Camels  Hump.  Now  this  was  a  totally
unrealistic goal and I knew that at  a  minimum  I  would  be  returning  by
headlight. But I figured hiking in the moonlight was preferable  to  another
12 hours in my sleeping bag. How wrong I was. I kept  running  into  problem
