decent meadow to be found. Then I climbed a gosh awful gully  (steep  frozen
dirt  topped  by  1.5  inches  of  powder  snow).  Fortunately  (or   maybe
unfortunately as it lured me on), at the saddle I was greeted  by  sunshine,
gorgeous friendly meadows and easy travel. The traverse  to  below  Reynolds
was an absolute delight.

The second problem was to get across Reynolds SW ridge, no  trivial  matter.
I tried not to lose too much elevation and found a crossing  in  the  cliffy
forest at 6800 ft but ran into dicey  snow  covered  class  3.  Turning  the
corner of the ridge, I got a close up view of  my  objective  and  my  third
problem. Camels Hump may be a walkup from  the  south  and  west,  but  from
where I was on the north side it was going  to  be  a  real  challenge.  The
upper part turned out to some 400 feet of class 3-4. A light  snow  covering
didn\'t help. Everything took much longer than expected. I watched  the  full
moon rise as I summited at 6:45 (5400 ft, 10:45). Again no register.

The return to camp is kind of a blur where time stood still. I  concentrated
on each segment at  hand.  I  breathed  a  sigh  of  relief  when  down  the
technical section of the Camels Hump. I took the  traverse  around  Reynolds
at a lower contour and avoided the unpleasant forested class 3. In the  open
meadows I hiked without headlamp by the light of the full moon  and  it  was
