            'tr' => '
Horsethief Basin Peaks: North Navarre Pk (7963 ft - 723P)  &  Horsethief  Pk
(8002 ft - 402P) - Martin Pk Quad; Ferry Pk (7777 ft  -  537P  -  Prince  Cr
Quad); Uno Pk (7640+ ft - 560P - Big Goat Mtn Quad); and  South  Navarre  Pk
(7870 ft - 70P - South Navarre Pk Quad - October 9-11, 2009

This was a delightful, mellow but COLD  3-day  loop  trip  in  the  southern
Chelan-Sawtooth at the height of golden larch season  shared  with  Jim  and
Eileen and Jim A. We started from the Summer Blossom TH  and  ended  at  the
South Navarre campground TH. Approach was via  the  Grade  Creek  road.  Our
thanks to Charlie Hickenbottom for reporting  from  his  July  trip  on  the
condition of this road. The road is in good shape but seems to take  forever
to drive the 40 miles from Chelan.

Day 1: Friday, October 9 - North Navarre and  Horsethief  -  What  with  the
long drive it was 12:15 before we started up the Summer Blossom Trail.  This
is a beautiful (hiker only) trail, especially this time  of  year  with  the
larches at their peak. It only took 2 hours to reach  the  summit  of  North
Navarre, a short distance  off  the  trail.  From  there  we  descended  and
traversed lovely terrain to a camp  in  an  east  arm  of  Horsethief  Basin
directly below Horsethief Pk where we were surprised  to  still  find  water
this late in the season. After setting up camp, Jim, Eileen  and  I  ran  up
the 1000 ft to the summit of Horsethief returning just before dark.  Already
we were feeling the effects of the predicted arctic  outbreak  of  the  next
few days. We had a very chilly dinner after  which  we  were  all  happy  to
retreat to the warmth of our sleeping bags.

Total: 6 miles, 3100 ft and 7 hrs

Day 2: Saturday, October 10 - Ferry and Uno - I awoke to  a  temperature  of
21 degrees and a heavy coating of frost inside my tent which contributed  to
a fast exit from camp. I don\'t think any of us warmed up until  we  hit  the
sun on the spur ridge above. Horsethief is  a  gorgeous  basin  and  we  all
reveled in the beautiful traverse to Deadmans Pass, where we looked down  on
stunning Sunset Basin. From Deadmans Pass  we  traversed  and  dropped  into
Miners Basin, attractive but not quite up to the very high standard  of  the
previous basins. At a trail junction (nice forest camp here) we  went  right
on the Uno Pk Trail about a mile to a hunter\'s camp  for  our  second  night
(4.5 miles, 1200 ft, 4 hrs). We had time to dry out tents and sleeping  bags
in the sun before Jim, Eileen and  I  set  off  for  Ferry.  After  climbing
Ferry, Eileen elected to return to camp while Jim and I  continued  to  Uno.
The arctic outbreak was now in full force and we could feel the  temperature
dropping. But by the time we returned to camp (4 miles, 2000 ft, 4:20  hrs),
again at dusk, Eileen and Jim A had a most welcome  fire  going  which  made
dinner a tolerable affair.

Day 3: Sunday, October 11 - South Navarre - Talk about cold! In the  morning
the temperature was 10 degrees and everything was frozen solid.  I  think  I
broke a record for packing up and being ready to go in an hour. It was  just
too cold to dally. Jim and I took off at 7:50  planning  to  pick  up  South
Navarre while Eileen and Jim A took their time coming  out.  We  hiked  with
all our clothes on and still never really got very warm  even  on  the  1300
foot climb up to South Navarre campground. As cold as it was I was  thankful
there was very little wind. Had there been any significant at all the  wind-
chill would have been well below zero degrees.

I reached the campground at 10:20 (5 miles, 1300 ft,  2:30  hrs)  where  Jim
was waiting. We dumped our big packs and zipped up the easy ridge  to  South
Navarre Pk (2 miles, 1500 ft, 2:15  hr  RT  with  30  minutes  on  top).  We
returned just as Eileen and Jim A were arriving. The  timing  couldn\'t  have
been better.

We survived the arctic weather and had a good  time  doing  it  but  I  sure
wouldn\'t have wanted it to be any colder.

Grand Total: 21.5 mile and 9100 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen

