This is another example of how chasing a peak list led to hidden  treasures.
Were it not for McLeod being on  the  Top  200  list  it,  and  those  peaks
nearby, would never even have been on my  radar  screen.  Riddled  with  old
logging roads, grazed everywhere by cattle  and  on  the  edge  but  not  in
wilderness, the area was still surprisingly attractive.

Tuesday, October 20 - McLeod Mtn: From Goat Cr Road 62 near Mazama, I  drove
spur 500 up Long Cr to a suitable car camp site below  the  south  ridge  of
McLeod, elev 5280 ft. Hunters were out in droves  cruising  the  back  roads
hoping, I guess, to spot a deer from the comfort of their vehicles as I  saw
no one on foot once I left mine.

I began in an old burn with many downed trees that slowed  travel  but  once
past that the scenery  was  lovely  with  open  woods,  meadows  and  golden
larches. The final summit ridge was gentle scree and  talus,  with  a  bench
mark on top (3.0 miles, 2900 ft, 2:40 hrs). I had fairly clear views of  the
Monument Creek peaks but fog obscured Sunrise Peak (8144  ft)  most  of  the
day. I could see far enough, though, to determine  my  original  thought  to
run the ridge north to  that  peak  was  not  practical.  I  would  have  to
approach it another way on another day.

Peak 7670: I returned to the saddle with  Peak  7670  to  climb  that  peak.
Following the NE ridge crest produced  some  fun  class  3  scrambling  with
impressive views down the cliffy north face. Just below the  summit  I  came
upon a large cairn with a rock slab painted with the elevation of  7640  ft.
Very strange. I had more fleeting thoughts of  running  the  ridge  west  to
Setting Sun Mtn, but again reason prevailed. It was too  far  away  for  the
time available, although it did look to be feasible (4 miles, 3500 ft,  4:20
hrs).

On the way down I took a line slightly east of  my  up  route  that  avoided
much the tedious downed burned trees section and arrived at the car at  6:00
where I spent a comfortable night (7 miles, 3500 ft, 6:30 hrs).

Wednesday, October 21 - Setting Sun Mtn: It  rained  during  the  night  and
though still drizzling in the morning it wasn\'t bad  enough  to  prevent  me
from trying Setting Sun. Back on the main Goat Cr Road,  I  took  Road  5255
(an excellent dirt road) and spur 600 to  the  saddle  south  of  the  peak,
elevation 5000 ft. I was pleased to see  the  way  began  in  open  pleasant
woods that would be no great problem in light rain  (which  soon  turned  to
light snow). In fact this  south  ridge  of  Setting  Sun  was  an  absolute
delight, even in the fog. I was compensated  near  the  top  for  having  no
views by an area of gorgeous rimed covered larch trees.  The  summit  is  an
old lookout site, which means there must have been a  trail  to  it  at  one
time. This is such a beautiful ridge I would have no problem returning  some
time in good weather for the views, particularly into the Lost River  Gorge.
Highly recommended as an easy trip for short  days.  (4.5  miles,  2900  ft,
4:10 hrs RT)

Fay Pullen



