            'tr' => '
Gray Peak (8082 ft - 402P - Oval Pk Quad) - October 27-28, 2009

I set out to see if  enough  snow  had  fallen  in  the  high  mountains  to
completely prevent  access.  With  only  a  small  window  of  good  weather
forecast I figured my best chance of success was in the Chelan-Sawtooth.  My
goal was to climb Gray Peak above Oval  lakes.  My  approach  was  from  the
Eagle Cr TH off the Twisp River Road.

Tuesday, October 27 - With only one really good day forecast  on  Wednesday,
I was happy that I also had reasonable weather for my  approach  on  Tuesday
with only the occasional snow shower and even some sun breaks. There  was  a
dusting of snow at the TH (3040 ft) with the depth  increasing  to  about  2
inches by the time I reached my campsite 6 miles in at 5800 feet along  Oval
Creek. Under the trees I found a mostly bare ground spot for my  tent.  With
plenty of warm clothing  along  I  spent  a  comfortable  night  despite  it
dropping to 19 degrees by morning. I must  be  getting  used  to  this  cold
weather camping business.

6 miles, 2900 ft and 4:20 hrs

Wednesday, October 28: Gray Peak - From my camp the trail  steadily  climbed
and the snow steadily increased in depth until I was breaking trail in  calf
deep powder as I entered lovely Oval Basin. Here I lost the trail.  As  much
work as this was the deep snow was preferable to  the  icy  windswept  rocks
and I sought out a continuous snow route to Gray\'s summit ridge where I  hit
welcome sun. Views were expansive from the summit (2.5 miles, 2400 ft,  2:40
hr) and I could see all three Oval Lakes. The snow made for a rapid  descent
and I was back in camp in a little over an hour. Lovely  as  the  area  was,
another storm was predicted  for  Thursday  and  I  didn\'t  want  to  chance
getting caught in it so I quickly packed up and zipped out reaching  my  car
at 4:00. I made it home before any new weather hit.

Total: 17 miles and 5400 ft in two days

Fay Pullen

