            'tr' => '
Crow Hill (7366 ft - 926P - Pyramid Pk Quad), Big Hill (6827  ft  -  347P  -
Big Goat Mtn Quad), Crescent Hill (6750 ft - 30P - Brief Quad) and  East  Pt
(6835 ft - 195P - Brief Quad) - November 11-12, 2009

With another good two day forecast I figured I  could  still  access  fairly
high terrain in the Entiat for some interesting skiing. I don\'t really  like
to ski with a full pack but the approach was short and all on a well  graded
road.

Wednesday, November 11: Big Hill and Crow Hill - I was very surprised I  was
able to drive up the Shady Pass Road as far as I did, 4.1 miles  to  Halfway
Spring (elev 4680 ft). Actually I could have driven even farther but I  have
to be very conservative when alone on snowy back roads as I sure don\'t  want
to get stuck and I was satisfied with how high I got. Even though there  was
about a foot of snow  it  was  fluffy  powder  and  well  tracked  by  other
vehicles. Once underway on skis I met one  big  truck  and  two  snowmobiles
coming down, elk hunters all. I could tell they were shocked to  run  across
a skier. I reached Shady Pass a little after 2:00 and set up  a  comfortable
camp just out of sight of the road (4.5 miles, 1700 ft,  2:30  hrs).  I  was
using my serious winter double wall tent with a built in vestibule.

Everything takes longer in the snow and cold so by the time  I  started  for
Crow Hill it was already 3:15. Now I knew I couldn\'t  make  it  to  the  top
before dark, but that was part of my plan. Much of the route was on road  or
trail and would be easy to navigate  in  the  dark  and  I  wanted  to  have
something to occupy my time during the very long  night.  And  in  fact  the
skiing was easy and enjoyable on lovely powder. The truck  unbelievable  had
made it all the way to Shady Pass and maybe Â¼ mile farther on the  Big  Hill
road before being stopped by  an  impassible  drift.  The  snowmobiles  went
another mile before turning around. From then on it was  all  untracked  and
gorgeous. Sunset caught me at the end of the road  and  start  of  trail.  I
needed my headlamp soon thereafter. I reached the summit  of  Crow  Hill  at
6:15 (4.5 miles, 1650 ft, 3 hrs).

I had some very nice downhill  off  Crow  Hill.  I  really  like  skiing  by
headlamp and believe I can see as well as or better than  in  daylight.  The
only thing I missed was not having a view. I picked up Big Hill on  the  way
out and discovered a very usable cabin on the summit. By the time I made  it
back to camp (9 miles, 2200 ft, 5:40 hrs), melted snow  for  water  and  had
dinner I was pleased it was well past 10:00 and I had  killed  much  of  the
night.

Thursday, November 12: Crescent Hill and East Pt - I was  awakened  at  7:00
by two snowmobiles roaring past on the road. In my  experience  snowmobilers
are not early risers but these were really hunters and they are.  I  glanced
at my thermometer - 12 degrees inside my double wall tent!  That  translated
to single digits outside. And the inner wall of  my  tent  was  coated  with
frost so thick that when I got up it seemed like it was snowing inside.  For
a brief moment I questioned my sanity for putting myself  through  the  many
miseries of winter camping. Then the sun hit the tent and once warmed up  on
my way under blue sky it was all worth it again.

For today I followed the long gentle road to  Crescent  Hill.  It  was  well
tracked by snowmobiles but I never saw or even heard  any  (once  the  early
starters were gone). From Crescent Hill I took the easy  ridge  to  East  Pt
which provided some very pleasant untracked touring and nice views. I  would
have liked to have gone farther but I ran out of time. As it was I got  back
to camp at 3:15 (13 miles, 2100 ft, 6:40 hrs).  I  quickly  broke  camp  and
made it to my car just at dark. The ski down the  road  was  enjoyable  even
with a full pack.

Total: 31 miles and 6200 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen

