Stormy Mtn (7198 ft - P1398), Slide Pk (5598 ft  -  P638)  and  Slide  Ridge
(6214 ft - P294) - Stormy Mtn Quad - December 1-3, 2009

I have often thought winter camping would be fun if only I  didn\'t  have  to
spend the night, especially this time of year when they  are  so  darn  long
and cold. I can\'t say my opinion has changed all that  much  but  there  are
just some places I can\'t get to on a day  trip  and   modern  equipment  has
made it all much  more  tolerable.  An  extra  warm  yet  still  lightweight
sleeping bag and head to toe down clothing wards off the chill  and  a  tiny
media player providing entertainment in the form of music and  videos  helps
the dark hours pass more quickly. Now I have to  justify  investing  in  all
this high tech gear by actually using it. (I  am  still  searching  for  the
perfect winter tent - freestanding with a vestibule and a  frost  liner  yet
still lightweight - but I haven\'t found it yet.)

Tuesday, December 1 - Slide Pk: I was delighted when I was able to  drive  6
miles up the Slide Ridge Road (8410) before  being  stopped  by  snow.   Big
rigs had gone farther but the depth was already about 1 foot and  I  worried
about getting stuck trying to get out of the track to turn around if I  went
any farther. Besides, I had gotten far enough to put  Stormy  Mtn,  my  main
objective, within reach. With the air temperature never having gotten  above
freezing, the snow was only crusty where directly hit by  the  sun  and  was
mostly powder and really quite good for  skiing.  The  wheeled  track  ended
after 3 miles and thereafter the road was marred only by  numerous  animals.
I was quite surprised there was  no  evidence  of  snowmobiles.  I  found  a
wonderful spot for my tent that caught both the morning  and  afternoon  sun
just above the saddle NE of Slide Pk (5 miles, 1600 ft, 3 hrs).

By the time I set up camp (everything takes longer in  the  winter)  it  was
dark, but a glorious full moon afforded enough light that I only  needed  my
headlight when in the shadows. I skied up Slide Pk to the sound of  Mozart\'s
wind concertos. It is other worldly skiing at night anyway but  add  a  full
moon and beautiful music and I was truly in another universe (3  miles,  600
ft, 2 hrs RT).  More music during dinner and an hour  video  viewed  in  the
depths of my sleeping bag passed the rest of the evening.

Wednesday, December 2 - Slide Ridge and Stormy Mtn: The  very  hardest  part
of winter camping for me is the  morning  and  having  to  force  myself  to
emerge from the warm cocoon of my sleeping bag  (It  was  12  degrees).  But
once that is accomplished I am good to go.  Sun  hitting  my  tent  at  8:00
helped. Lively Celtic music made the 6 mile road ski to  below  Slide  Ridge
fly by. I left the road to climb onto the ridge where the  skiing  was  very
nice indeed (1400 ft, 3:30 hrs). From the high point I skied  SW  along  the
ridge over a bump to the next saddle to pick up the summer trail leading  to
the summit ridge of Stormy Mtn. Skiing was good to  reasonable  up  to  this
point but once on the ridge it deteriorated to marginal.  Wind  had  scoured
much it down to bare ice. I guess it is called "Stormy"  for  a  reason.  At
least there was no wind this day (3000 ft, 6:20 hrs).   I  watched  the  sun
set and the moon rise as I started down but made it back to the road  before
needing my headlight (much of the way on the road was in the  moon  shadow).
Harp concertos accompanied me the 2 hours back to camp (17 miles,  3200  ft,
10 hrs).

Thursday, December 3: It was another cold morning - 9 degrees. The  sun  was
out for maybe an hour and then it clouded up but nothing came of it.  I  had
a pleasant ski out to the car (5 miles, 400  ft,  2:20  hrs)  and  an  early
drive home in the daylight. Total: 30 miles and 5800  ft  in  3  days.   Fay
Pullen





