            'tr' => '
Jumbo Mtn (5840+ ft - P1800 - Helena Ridge Quad) - December 27, 2009

Jumbo had been on my wish list for years - make that decades -  but  somehow
I just never got around to it. So when Paul Klenke organized a  trip  I  was
all for it.  Others along were Jeff R, Erin, Suzanne and Brie.  It  must  be
noted that this trip report is from the perspective  of  someone  always  in
the rear just following and trying to keep up with those younger and  faster
than I. I contributed nothing to  the  somewhat  complicated  route  finding
which was left to Paul (making good use of the excellent TR from  Franklin).


We departed from the Squire Cr TH at 7:15 just as the day began to  lighten.
The old road had a light layer of snow and was very icy and slick.  Once  on
the climber\'s trail,  though,  the  woods  were  completely  snow  free.  We
followed the trail and open woods to a talus slope,  crossed  and  traversed
steep woods to a snow filled gully at 3500 ft where we donned  crampons.  At
a 4300 ft rib  we  descended  slightly  and  traversed  below  cliffs  to  a
somewhat icy gully that got the adrenalin going.  Above  the  gully  was  an
open basin with several inches  of  powder  where  Erin  did  her  thing  by
kicking steps the rest of the way to the summit ridge. All day we  had  been
in shadow and here we finally hit welcome sun. Erin and I  guarded  Brie  to
make sure she stayed put, while the others climbed  the  final  pitch  along
the narrow ridge with Paul setting a hand line on the most exposed  section.
Brie was not happy being separated from  her  master.  Once  Paul  returned,
Erin and I made the short  trek  to  the  top,  locating  the  register  and
signing in.

We made several fast glissades down to the basin. On the  last  one,  trying
to find a better line, we went a different way from our up route  and  ended
up on a very steep slope. The top  was  too  steep  (at  least  for  me)  to
glissade until I front pointed down a bit first. We were  all  down  and  at
the bottom when Paul realized that Brie didn\'t think much of our  choice  of
route and was stranded at the top whining and refusing to come  down.   This
was not good although personally  I  think  it  just  proves  Brie  is  more
intelligent with better sense than any of us.  It  was  awfully  steep.  She
would not come down without help. Anxious to get the icy gully  out  of  the
way, we three gals started down it while the two  guys  set  about  rescuing
Brie. They had to climb all the way back up to her and  rope  her  down.  We
waited for them at the rib.

Darkness caught us about an hour from the car. We  kept  losing  the  trail,
crashing brush and climbing over countless  logs.  Brie  was  absolutely  no
help in finding the trail. I thought  dogs  were  supposed  to  be  good  at
sniffing out the proper way. But she was probably still traumatized  by  her
little incident and tired from having gone twice as far as we did.  To  make
matters worse, my headlamp began to die and I had  trouble  seeing  where  I
was going. I did have two more with me but as  luck  would  have  it  I  had
grabbed the one with the weakest batteries. I could have stopped and  gotten
another one out of my pack  but  by  the  time  I  did  that  I  would  have
completely lost sight of everyone else. Erin, bless her, hung back a bit  to
help keep me on track. Just as my headlamp became almost completely  useless
we hit the road. Not a moment too soon as far as I  was  concerned.  It  was
questionable who was more tired, Brie or me.

Total: 6 miles, 5000 ft and 10:45 hours                Fay Pullen





