            'tr' => '
Lookout Mtn (6188 ft - P828 - Mt Clifty Quad) - January 6-7, 2010

Wednesday, January 6 - When the skiing is less than ideal, and I still  want
to ski, I turn to groomed snowmobile roads. Conditions  have  to  be  really
bad to make even these roads unskiable. Well, they were really bad  for  the
start of this trip. When I arrived at the Woods and Steel Snopark  near  Cle
Elum, the road had not been groomed and not a single snowmobile had been  up
it since it had been coated with layer of  freezing  rain.  For  a  fleeting
moment I considered aborting the whole trip, but  instead  I  plunged  ahead
optimistically thinking things had to get better higher  up.  They  did  but
only marginally. When I hit South Cle Elum Ridge at 5  miles,  the  freezing
rain crust had turned to just a simple crust formed  from  being  rained  on
and then freezing. Semantics? Not really! Freezing rain is a very  different
and absolutely horrible beast. Anyway, the  crust  was  now  very  thin  and
actually had soft snow underneath so was fairly skiable.  I skied another  4
miles along the ridge stopping at 4:15 with just enough light to  set  up  a
camp on the saddle south of Hicks Butte.  9 miles, 3300 ft and 5 hrs.

Thursday, January 7 - It was windy all night and 15 degrees when I  woke  at
7:30. I had experimented with adapting a vestibule from the Hilight tent  to
fit my Oneshot (none is  made  for  the  Oneshot).  It  worked  quite  well,
withstanding the winds and giving me a  roomy  space  to  cook  and  put  on
boots. But it was an effort to rig. I would prefer a tent with  a  built  in
vestibule and I continue to search for the perfect winter abode.

Starting at 8:30 in my down parka as a  shield  against  the  bitterly  cold
wind, I skied another 3.5 miles to end of a road and then onto the ridge  to
pick up the trail to Windy Pass. Skiing along the trail, although tricky  in
spots, was better than I would have thought and not too bad in  open  areas.
It was worst in the trees where it was quite icy. Once leaving the trail,  I
was able to ski about halfway along the ridge to Lookout before  leaving  my
skis. I could have skied more but I didn\'t want to carry them past  a  short
rocky bump. So I booted the rest of the way to the  summit  reaching  it  at
11:45. I was greeted by a stunning view of Mt Stuart floating  like  a  ship
on an ocean of clouds.

Skiing was reasonable on the way down and got even better when  I  got  back
to the main road and was  passed  by  three  snowmobiles.  I  am  sure  they
wondered who the heck was this lone skier miles from nowhere and  where  had
she come from. Their tracks broke up the crust to the soft snow  underneath.
I was back in camp at 2:00 (10 miles, 2200 ft, 5:30 hrs RT)  and  packed  up
and ready to go at 3:00. Only 9 miles left to go (sigh)!

I actually enjoyed the skiing along the gentle road back to where it  leaves
the ridge. But I dreaded the descent from there on. I hoped the  snowmobiles
had gone that way and broken up the freezing  rain  crust.  When  I  reached
that point much to my delight the road had been groomed since I came  up.  I
was saved. That is not to say it was a piece of cake  getting  down  it.  It
was still very fast and slick but  at  least  it  was  smooth  and  I  could
snowplow it. Otherwise I might have had to walk down. And,  of  course,  now
it was dark. And after 5 miles of snowplowing my legs were trashed.  When  I
reached the car at 6:15 I could barely walk. (9  miles,  550  ft,  3:15  hrs
from camp)

Total: 28 miles and 6050 ft in 2 days       Fay Pullen



