            'tr' => '
Pemmican Pk (5442 ft- P402 - Bedal Quad) - January 10, 2010

Pemmican is a modest little peak west of and overshadowed  by  Stillaguamish
Pk. It is rather difficult of  access,  guarded  on  most  sides  by  brushy
cliffs. The easiest approach is from high on the Perry Cr  Trail,  but  even
that is not straightforward, involving a long convoluted traverse  past  the
many ridges of Stillaguamish.

I was able to drive all the way to the Perry Cr TH (2200 ft) and  the  trail
was completely snow free until about 3000 ft. Thereafter  it  had  icy  snow
but was still easily followed to the big switchback at 4300 ft. Here I  left
the trail and headed straight uphill. I had to go all the way to  the  ridge
to get past a major gully and avoid cliffs. Up till now the  snow  had  been
hard and icy but above about 4500 ft I began potholing in slush or  annoying
breakable crust. Then began a seemingly endless traverse past  Stillaguamish
Pk with many obstacles and ups and downs. It was farther,  harder  and  took
longer than one would think looking on the map. Just when I  thought  I  had
it made another difficulty would appear. I had to descend more than  800  ft
total to finally be able to make my  way  to  the  5000  ft  saddle  between
Stillaguamish and Pemmican. Once there easy slopes led to  the  summit  (5.5
mile, 4200 ft, 5:30 hrs).

I know Jim Brisbine and Steve Fox climbed this  peak  a  few  years  ago.  I
don\'t recall many details from that TR but I do remember they went  straight
down to Perry creek on what Jim described as a descent from Hell. With  that
in mind I had intended to return the same way as I had come.  But  that  was
before I had come that long and convoluted way. I now see why Jim and  Steve
had elected to go straight down. It was less  than  half  the  distance  and
very direct and so very very tempting. Neither prospect was very  appealing.
But I just couldn\'t face potholing all the way back up that traverse.  So  I
just kind of let gravity pull me downward.

Jim was right. It was the descent from Hell. I had looked at the route  from
the trail in the morning. There were two major gullies with waterfalls  that
had to be avoided at all costs and cliffs all over the place.  But  an  open
avalanche track with broken trees to the west  looked  almost  feasible  and
that is what I headed for. I ended up right where I wanted  to  be  on  this
avalanche slope but just because I was where I wanted to be didn\'t  mean  it
was very good. I picked my way through a jungle of downed  trees,  slithered
down mossy cliffs hanging onto bush belays and crashed brush  in  the  trees
lower down.  I completely tore out the seat of  my  climbing  pants  in  the
process. There were times I really didn\'t know how  to  proceed  as  nothing
looked any good. The final 1000 feet were the worst. I did avoid  all  major
cliffs and find scramble routes down the small ones for all but one where  I
had to break out my panic rope. The one bright spot was that when I came  to
Perry Cr I found a huge log that even I could walk.

Total: 8 miles, 4500 ft and 9:30 hrs

 Fay Pullen





