            'tr' => '
Breccia Pk (6487 ft - P1047) and Spring Mtn (5770 ft  -  P450)  -  Sloan  Pk
Quad - January 21-22, 2010

With skiing still lousy, I perused Dallas Kloke\'s Winter Climbs book  for  a
possible new climb doable this time of year and  came  across  the  somewhat
obscure Spring Mtn.  Two good weather days  were  forecast  and  wanting  to
make the most of this opportunity, I figured that with  a  camp  at  Bingley
Gap I could also add Breccia to the itinerary.

Thursday, January 21: Spring Mtn - The North Fork Sauk Road 49 was  open  to
the Lost Creek Ridge TH (elev 1849 ft). The trail itself was in  good  shape
with only a couple of blow downs and was snow  free  to  about  3400  ft.  I
crossed the two snow filled avalanche gullies  mentioned  in  Kloke\'s  route
description and continued on to Bingley Gap crossing  a  couple  more  minor
gullies on the way. I soon  lost  the  trail  in  steep  icy  terrain  where
crampons were helpful. I found a level bench (elev 4300  ft)  a  short  ways
down the other side of the gap out of the wind  for  a  comfortable  if  not
particularly scenic camp (3.5 miles, 2650 ft, 3.5 hrs).

I left for Spring Mtn at 3:30 hoping to make the top before dark.  As  usual
it was farther and took longer than anticipated. Since I wasn\'t  approaching
from the avalanche gully on the south as  recommended  by  Kloke,  but  from
Bingley Gap, I had to drop on the north side to get  past  cliffs  before  I
could gain the east ridge. I then started (too  soon)  up  the  first  gully
that looked like it would go. It did but it also got very steep at  the  top
with a sporting partially filled rotten moat to  cross.  Once  on  the  open
ridge it was pretty straight forward, just long and slow trail breaking.  It
was also quite windy. I had a few impressive glimpses  of  Mt  Pugh  in  the
twilight, but by the time I reached the summit at 7:00 all was dark.   Going
down was much faster, my tracks easily  followed  by  headlight.  I  took  a
better gully down off the ridge and reached camp at 8:30 (3 miles, 2100  ft,
5 hrs RT). I was pleased that by the time I turned in it was after 10:00.

That night was positively balmy for January. It barely  got  below  freezing
and was the warmest night I have spent out since summer. I am  not  sure  it
even qualifies as winter camping.

Friday, January 22: Breccia Pk - I didn\'t get going  as  early  as  I  would
have liked. The day dawned overcast and being camped in the woods in a  dark
double walled tent I didn\'t even notice it was getting light until  7:45.  I
started out at 9:00 in crampons and  kept  them  on  all  day.  The  initial
wooded ridge to 5500 ft was quite icy. Then started  a  long  open  traverse
around three bumps on Lost Creek Ridge. Conditions  varied  from  calf  deep
powder to breakable crust to hard crust to windswept  ice,  entirely  doable
without snowshoes but inconsistent and quite tiring  trail  breaking  alone.
Once around the last point (Pt 5920) and at the saddle above  Sunup  Lake  I
climbed to Breccia\'s summit ridge which I hit to the right of a  small  bump
(Pt 6360). Here I made the error of dropping off the  ridge  into  the  east
basin and traversing very steep slopes to regain the summit ridge past  this
point. From where I was initially it  appeared  the  ridge  was  dangerously
corniced and would be treacherous. Once on the summit I  saw  this  was  not
the case. I easily returned along this ridge.

I reached the summit at 1:30. Up to now the day  had  been  mostly  overcast
with that flat winter light that doesn\'t make for the best photography.  But
now the sun began making an appearance and I reaped the  reward  of  a  late
start and slow pace. The views were breathtaking. I spent  a  glorious  half
hour savoring them. It wasn\'t even windy.  Unknown to  me  at  the  time,  a
group of friends were climbing Red Mtn (directly across Lost Creek) on  this
very day. Had I know I would have looked for them on that  summit,  although
they got a much earlier start and were probably already gone.

The return in my broken trail was much faster, despite  numerous  stops  for
added pictures. I reached camp at 4:00 (5 miles, 2200 ft,  7  hrs  RT),  and
left at 4:30. The hardest part of the whole trip was  the  first  1000  down
from Bingley gap.  The  snow  was  rock  hard,  very  steep  (crampons  were
essential) and the tendency without benefit of a trail to guide  you  is  to
head straight down whereas you really need to traverse right. I got too  low
and had to climb back up to cross a gully to get back on track.  I  breathed
a sigh of relief when I hit discernable trail in fading light. The rest  was
easy as I ambled down the trail enjoying the night sounds.   I  reached  the
car at 7:00.

Total: 15 miles and 7000 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen





