            'title' => 'Grouse Ridge (5882 ft - P322), Pk 5365 (P605), Lookout Mtn N Pk (5080+ ft - P840) and Lookout Mtn S Pk (5076 ft - P476) - Groat Mtn Quad - January 26- 27, 2010',
            'tr' => '
Grouse Ridge (5882 ft - P322), Pk 5365 (P605), Lookout Mtn N Pk (5080+ ft  -
P840) and Lookout Mtn S Pk (5076 ft - P476) - Groat Mtn Quad -  January  26-
27, 2010

Ever since seeing Grant Myers\' pictures of  Grouse  Ridge  from  his  TR  of
November 2008 I have wanted to ski to this area. I was just waiting for  the
proper combination of good weather and good conditions. After  hearing  that
Mt Baker had received over a foot  of  new  snow  Sunday  into  Monday  with
clearing predicted Tuesday and Wednesday, the time seemed right.

Tuesday, January 26: Lookout Mtn N &  S  Pks  -  Due  to  a  generally  high
snowline this year, I figured I would be able to  drive  the  Glacier  Creek
Road 39 quite a ways, but I was still surprised to get to 3500 ft  (Road  36
junction about 7.5 miles in). There were  several  snowmobile  rigs  already
parked and both Roads 39 and 36 were well tracked. I  quickly  skied  gentle
Road 36 to the junction with the road up Lookout Mtn. My original  plan  was
to camp in the broad saddle to the south (elev 4200 ft), but I got there  so
quickly and the day was so nice (at least to start) that I decided I  wanted
a view with my camp so I continued to the  summit  of  S  Lookout  Mtn  (4.5
miles, 1600 ft, 2:30 hrs). Well, I had a partial view for all of  5  minutes
before a weak unpredicted  weather  system  came  in,  the  view  completely
disappeared and by the time I set up my tent it had  begun  to  snow.  Darn!
Where did this come from? I guess the weather gods didn\'t pay any  attention
to the weathermen. I was glad I had  brought  my  Hilleberg  tent  with  its
roomy vestibule.

The turn of the weather didn\'t deter me from going  for  N  Lookout  Mtn.  I
found a delightful open slope with excellent snow to ski down to the  saddle
between the two peaks. From there a short clear-cut and wooded ridge led  to
the summit, all very skiable. By now it had  quit  snowing  (it  had  snowed
maybe an inch total) and was beginning to clear a  bit  and  I  returned  to
camp by the light of a hazy moon (2.5 miles, 1000 ft, 2:30 hrs RT).

Wednesday, January 27: Grouse Ridge and Pk 5365  -  I  awoke  to  completely
clear and cold (18 degrees) skies with a heavy frost. It was colder  than  I
expected but I did have my view. In taking my morning  photos (I  had  taken
none the previous day - too cloudy) I realized I hadn\'t replaced the  memory
card in my camera after downloading pictures onto my computer from  my  last
trip. It seems I always forget something. So all I had to work with was  the
built in memory of the camera (which is only good for a dozen or  so  photos
depending on resolution chosen) and I had to  be  more  discriminating  than
usual in choosing before clicking away.

I skied  west  from  camp  along  more  delightful  terrain  (despite  being
somewhat tracked by snowmobiles) before working my  way  down  to  the  road
heading toward Grouse Butte.  I  followed  this  road  to  its  end.  I  had
expected to find a snowmobile track continuing on to the basin below  Grouse
Ridge but all tracks ended here. I  soon  found  out  why.  A  steep,  thick
second growth side hill and an open stream cut had to be  negotiated  before
hitting easy open forest. With no other tracks in sight I was  beginning  to
think I would have the area unspoiled and all to myself. But when I  reached
the open basin,  much  to  my  dismay  I  found  it  completely  tracked  by
snowmobiles, so much so that it was rendered almost unskiable. How the  heck
did they get here? They certainly didn\'t come the way I had.  I  later  came
to believe they had come up from the end of the  Mt  Baker  Vista  Road.  At
least no snowmobiles were there while I was. In fact I saw and heard no  one
all day, so I did have the area all to myself. And the tracks  were  only  a
visual eyesore and did not really affect the  quality  of  my  skiing  as  I
didn\'t ski down that way.

I gained the ridge at a col and was  greeted  with  a  spectacular  view  of
Baker, Colfax and Lincoln. Lincoln  looked  particularly  ominous  with  its
fresh mantle of snow and ice. The flat ridge itself was  windy  and  icy.  I
quickly went to the high point and found a sunny protected spot  for  lunch.
Then I skied down the untracked north ridge. It was really  quite  good.  My
plan was to continue to Pk 5365. I had to go through two narrow notches  and
around Pt 5334 but it was all on very  interesting,  very  skiable  terrain.
The first notch is where I ran across snowmobile tracks coming up  from  the
north and presumably the Mt Baker Vista Road. At  the  second  notch  I  ran
into ski tracks. Evidently the steep open east slopes of Pk 5365 are  sought
after by the downhillers. They did look very nice and an approach  from  the
Vista road would make for a very pleasant day  trip.  I  saw  no  snowmobile
tracks on these slopes.

From the summit of Pk 5365 I continued north along the gentle ridge  to  the
first saddle and an absolutely sublime slope with perfect snow  and  perfect
steepness. It just doesn\'t get any better. It was lightly tracked  by  other
skiers. Unfortunately the best slope of the trip was followed by the  worst.
No tracks went below the open slope. I was on my own in getting back to  the
Grouse Butte road below. It would have been better in a  heavier  snow  year
with more coverage of obstacles. As it was I managed to stay on skies  until
I was funneled into a gully and couldn\'t avoid crossing a running  creek  on
a log. I had to remove skis for that. But once past that I came  to  an  old
clear-cut and found a reasonable route the rest  of  the  way  down  to  the
road. Would you believe this road had been freshly groomed  sometime  during
the day? I never cease to be  amazed  at  how  often  snowmobile  roads  are
groomed.

I now paid dearly for my desire for a camp with a  view  as  I  climbed  800
feet up my tent. Whose brilliant idea was this anyway? It had clouded  up  a
bit again so I never did have a sunny view from camp. I reached it at  4:45,
quickly packed up and left at 5:25. I skied down the gentle and now  groomed
road by headlight. The only tracks on the groomed road were those of a  lone
skate skier. There were none by any snowmobiles.

Total for day: 15 miles, 3800 ft and 10 hrs.

Total for trip: 22 miles and 6400 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen





