            'tr' => '
Skyline Divide (6560+ ft - P200 - Mt Baker Quad) - February 3-4, 2010

I had seen Chowder Ridge last week  from  Grouse  Ridge  and  it  looked  so
appealing I had to give it a try. Even though I never  made  it  to  Chowder
Ridge proper, the trip along Skyline  Divide  was  so  exquisite,  I  didn\'t
really care.  This is one gorgeous  ridge  in  the  winter  with  reasonably
friendly ski terrain. It combined two of my favorite things in life,  skiing
and ridges. I was in heaven. It being in the Mt Baker  Wilderness  I  wasn\'t
bothered by snowmobiles - or anyone else for that matter. It is not a  usual
destination for skiers and so I had miles and miles of completely  untracked
snow all to myself. I also hit perfect weather and snow conditions.

Wednesday, February 3 -  On  a  continuing  theme,  this  winter  of  little
lowland snow allowed me to drive Rd 37 some 10 miles  to  3360  ft  where  a
snow berm stopped all traffic. That left 2.5 miles to ski along the road  to
the Skyline Divide TH at 4360 ft. I was able to ski up  the  trail  but  the
snow cover was thin in the trees to begin and I knew I  would  have  trouble
skiing down the lower section. As the trail opened up higher  up,  the  snow
depth increased and skiing was quite good. There was 4-5 inches  of  new.  I
started under sunny skies but the day soon clouded over and  then  it  began
to snow lightly. This  was  forecast  and  not  unexpected.  The  next  day,
however, was supposed to be nice. I  just  hoped  it  was.  When  I  reached
Skyline Divide it was snowing and blowing and I sought a protected  spot  in
the trees below the ridge to camp (4.5 miles, 2700 ft, 4:30 hrs).

Thursday, February 4 - It snowed more during the night and got  down  to  25
degrees. I didn\'t know what would greet me in the morning until I  poked  my
head out of the tent at  first  light  -  it  was  clear  and  windless.  It
couldn\'t have been better. I had climbed Hadley Pk years ago in  the  summer
on a day trip. I vaguely remember Skyline Divide being a  very  long  ridge.
It is - very long, especially with no trail to  follow.  But  it  makes  for
splendid skiing - at least the kind of skiing I like. I followed  the  ridge
up and down for miles over varied and interesting terrain. The  only  slight
difficulties were a steep traverse to get  around  Pt  6160  and  one  short
vertical cornice where I had to take off skis to get up onto  Pt  6560  (the
high point of the divide).  Views were everywhere.

I continued on the ridge as far I could ski climbing  up  a  shadowed  north
facing bowl (a fantastic run back down)  to  a  saddle  on  the  NW  end  of
Chowder Ridge. I had hoped to get up onto that  ridge  itself  but  a  steep
rocky step prevented me access.  Besides  I  was  running  out  of  time.  I
contented myself with a small bump (Pt 6640)  above  the  saddle  (4  miles,
1800 ft, 4:30 hrs). It was probably a good thing I could go no farther or  I
would have continued past the point of prudence. I just didn\'t  want  it  to
end. My consolation was the ski out was just as good as the ski in.

I reached my tent at 3:30 (8 miles, 2600 ft, 7:30 hrs),  left  at  4:00  and
arrived at the car at 6:00. I did have to walk  at  last  Â½  mile  down  the
trail to the road.

Total: 17 miles and 5300 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen



