            'tr' => '
Fourmile Ridge (7128 ft - P1288), Devils  Backbone  (6709  ft  -  P429)  and
Angle Pk (6720+ ft - P0) - Brief Quad - February 10-11, 2010

With an iffy forecast I went  east  looking  for  better  weather  and  snow
conditions. I didn\'t do that well in either category  but  it  was  still  a
satisfying ski trip. It probably would have been better for  3  days  as  it
took much longer than anticipated, partially due to  conditions  but  mostly
because I had to ski  the  entire  access  road  starting  from  the  Entiat
Valley.  Unlike  the  west  side  the  east  side  snowline  appears  to  be
relatively low although still of below average depth.

Wednesday, February 10 - I started from the  Entiat  Valley  a  little  past
Brief (elev 1760 ft), skiing the road that goes up Preston Cr. The road  had
continuous crusty snow and was rutted by  snowmobile  tracks.  The  day  was
overcast with good visibility to begin. At 2 miles I took a  left  onto  the
road that goes to Brennegan Cr. No recent snowmobiles had been this way.  As
I got higher a light dusting of  fresh  snow  covered  the  crust.  I  found
myself hoping for more fresh  snow  overnight  or  the  ski  down  would  be
trying. After another 2 miles I took a right at  a  junction  skiing  around
the headwater branches of the creek and onto a gentle forested  ridge  where
I found a flat spot to camp at 4400 ft (7.5 miles, 2800 ft,  4:45  hrs).  It
began to snow lightly as I put up my tent and was barely below freezing.

Thursday, February 11 - Much to my disappointment it  snowed  less  than  an
inch overnight, barely enough for any improvement. If I was  going  to  have
fog and no views at least I  should  have  good  snow.  I  skied  along  the
forested ridge, at first on an old road,  until  it  broke  out  below  open
slopes. Under different circumstances, i.e. more fresh  snow,  skiing  would
have been very good here but a hard crust covered by a couple inches of  new
made for very slippery going. I  could  have  used  ski  crampons,  which  I
didn\'t have.  As the slope steepened I sought better conditions on the  spur
ridge to the left. Once  on  this  things  improved  a  bit.  They  improved
greatly on the forested main ridge to Angle Pk where skiing was very nice.

From Angle Pk I followed the  ridge  east  to  Devils  Backbone.  The  first
section was open, narrow  and  corniced  and  made  for  some  tricky  spots
especially since now it was snowing again and visibility  was  nil.  Several
times I skied off small drops simply because I had no depth  perception  and
couldn\'t see them. The final forested rise to  the  summit  was  again  good
skiing. The way back was easier since I had my tracks to guide me.

I went over Angle Pk again (I am not sure why this insignificant bump has  a
name as it has no prominence. Maybe because it is the  intersection  of  two
major ridges.) and continued west to  the  high  point  of  Fourmile  Ridge.
Again skiing was excellent along the gentle wooded  ridge  until  I  had  to
make a steep traverse around Pt 7102. On the way I got a brief distant  view
and had hopes the weather might clear. No such luck. By the time  I  reached
the summit of Fourmile it was snowing and blowing harder than  ever.  I  had
thought to find a more direct way down but with  no  visibility  I  couldn\'t
chance it and followed my tracks back to the flat Fourmile-Angle  saddle.  I
had some pleasant downhill along the ridge and onto  the  upper  spur  ridge
until I hit the steep. This time I elected to descend the  drainage  to  the
west. Although by now there was 3-4 inches of fresh snow  it  wasn\'t  bonded
enough to the crust underneath for me to do telemarks with  my  skill  level
and light gear. However it was perfect for slideslipping, which  I  did  for
the next 1000 ft. It worked very well and was really quite  fun.  The  slope
moderated and I entered forest again before hitting the road  about  a  mile
from camp.

Dragging into camp at 6:30 (10.5 miles, 4200  ft,  10.5  hrs)  I  considered
staying another night. It was very tempting but as bad as it was to pack  up
in the snow it would be worse to pack up in the  rain.  It  was  already  32
degrees here and the snow level was predicted  to  rise  during  the  night.
There was enough fresh snow on the road to make the ski  down  pleasant  for
the most part, that is except for the  last  mile.  A  combination  of  deep
ruts, mixed rain and wet snow and rubbery legs made for  anything  but  (7.5
miles, 200 ft, 3 hrs to the car).

Total: 25.5 miles and 7200 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen



