            'title' => 'Coleman Pinnacle (6503 ft - P243), Ptarmigan Ridge (5600+ ft - P280) & Lasiocarpa Ridge (5503 ft - P143) - Shuksan Arm Quad; and Pk 6527 (P527 - Mt Baker Quad) - February 18-20, 2010',
            'tr' => '
Coleman Pinnacle (6503 ft - P243), Ptarmigan  Ridge  (5600+  ft  -  P280)  &
Lasiocarpa Ridge (5503 ft - P143) - Shuksan Arm Quad; and Pk  6527  (P527  -
Mt Baker Quad) - February 18-20, 2010

I have always wanted to ski to Coleman Pinnacle on  a  multi-day  trip,  but
getting  there  requires  perfect  weather,  good  snow  and   very   stable
conditions, usually a rare combination. I was just  never  able  to  hit  it
right when I had time available, that is until now.

Thursday, February 18: Ptarmigan Ridge -  The  fresh  snow  of  Tuesday  was
still evident when I left the Mt Baker Ski Area parking lot at noon. It  was
preserved as delicious powder on all aspects  where  the  sun  did  not  hit
directly. On those where  it  did  a  crust  had  already  formed  that  was
beginning to soften in the heat of the afternoon. Skiing was quite  good  to
Artist Point. From there I dropped 200 feet to traverse below the  cliff  of
Table Mtn and then climb  to  the  5080  ft  saddle  with  Ptarmigan  Ridge.
Another short drop was required from the saddle before it  was  possible  to
climb the  gentle  slopes  onto  broad  Ptarmigan  Ridge.  Finding  a  semi-
protected spot to pitch my tent on this  scenic  but  very  weather  exposed
ridge took a bit of searching around. It was not windy at  that  moment  but
should it kick up at any time a  camp  here  would  be  very  vulnerable  (4
miles, 1500 ft, 3 hrs).

Once my camp was in order, I started for the high  point  of  the  ridge  at
4:00 up SW facing slopes. These were still in the sun and soft, but as  soon
as I rounded a corner onto a SE slope I  entered  shade  and  the  snow  had
already refrozen to a hard crust. I had  anticipated  conditions  like  this
and brought along ski crampons which helped greatly  traversing  around  the
false summit. The summit itself was still in sunshine and  I  took  time  to
enjoy the both the warmth and lovely evening views. Of course by the time  I
started down most all was in shade and made for a slick return  to  camp  (2
miles, 400 ft, 2 hrs RT).

Friday, February 19: Coleman Pinnacle, Pk 6527 and  Lasiocarpa  Ridge  -  It
dropped to 18 degrees  overnight  but  open  vents  and  a  constant  breeze
prevented any frost condensation inside my tent.  The  sun  hit  my  camp  a
little before 8:00 warming things  quickly  and  making  for  a  comfortable
start to the day. I followed the ridge SW beginning  with  ski  crampons  in
addition to skins as the snow had not yet softened in the sun.  The  terrain
was gentle enough that travel was easy. At the next saddle in  the  ridge  I
had thought to drop off the crest onto the NW slope where I  knew  the  snow
would be powder, but cornices prevented any easy escape. I couldn\'t get  off
the ridge.

I continued traversing around Pt 5831 on S slopes rounding a corner  for  my
first close-up view of Coleman  Pinnacle.  Good  Grief!  It  was  much  more
intimidating than I expected. With it being included in  every  local  guide
book as a primo ski destination somehow I naively thought  it  was  possible
to ski up it to the top. Not only could I not ski it I wasn\'t sure  I  could
get up it by any means. I suppose it being called a "pinnacle"  should  have
been a clue. I guess the guide books meant you skied  to  the  base  of  the
peak and not up it.

 I continued traversing below the pinnacle to the SW  notch  from  where  an
ascent at least looked feasible. But it was still intimidating and I  had  a
moment of doubt as to whether I really wanted to climb it. I left  my  skis,
donned boot crampons and with ice axe  in  hand  took  off  up  the  heavily
corniced ridge staying well away from the edge. I took my time testing  each
step and slowly worked my way up. It didn\'t help my confidence  that  I  had
neglected to bring a rope. It was also not helpful that as  I  climbed  past
ice covered rocks and trees chunks would break  off  and  slither  down  the
exposed slope below. Mindful of the huge  summit  cornice  (and  the  recent
accident on St Helens) I stayed well back of the edge  on  the  top.  I  was
most happy when I returned safely to my skis  at  11:45.  This  little  side
trip took 1.5 hrs of concentrated effort RT.

It was now on to my next objective to the NW, Pk 6527, but first  I  had  to
get off the ridge. Again  I  could  not  descend  directly  from  the  notch
because of cornices. I tried to contour the S side  but  rounding  a  corner
onto a SW aspect I hit a slope that was too steep and  icy  for  my  comfort
level even with ski crampons. From the summit of Coleman Pinnacle it  looked
as if the ridge crest could be followed W from the notch although the  first
part had steep fluted steps. So I booted up this section until I  could  ski
again.  Then I came to another notch that hadn\'t been visible from  Coleman.
Darn! I thought I was  trapped  with  nowhere  to  go.  However,  on  closer
careful examination, I found a break in the cornices and  a  reasonable  way
down onto the N slope where the snow was soft and powdery.

Inviting terrain led to the S ridge of Pk 6527 which I sought to follow  all
the way. Again I was thwarted, this time by a small  rocky  section  that  I
couldn\'t reasonably get past on skis. I was forced to descend some 200  feet
on the W slope and traverse below the ridge before climbing  back  up  to  a
notch past the problem area. The traverse was quite steep  but  by  now  the
snow here had softened in the sun. The last bit to the notch was  too  steep
for skis so I kicked steps up. From the notch it was  an  easy  ski  to  the
summit. I had lunch here at 2:00 and took in the 360 view.

Back at the notch it appeared I could descend directly to the E.  Again  the
first bit was too steep for  skis  but  once  below  that  I  had  the  best
downhill of the day, if not  the  season,  on  perfect  slopes  and  perfect
untracked powder snow. This more than made up for earlier hanging  onto  icy
slopes for dear life. The wonderful skiing continued on a traverse  all  the
way to Lasiocarpa Ridge, the summit of which I reached at 4:30.

I followed my tracks back to below Pk 6527. Then began a long  mostly  level
traverse on undulating terrain well below Coleman  Pinnacle  and  the  ridge
line. The snow remained good and I was able to proceed without  skinning  up
again. The traverse with all its ups and down and ins and  outs  was  longer
than it looked and darkness caught me still on the go.  On  the  way  I  was
treated to some of the most spectacular otherworldly sunset lighting  on  Mt
Shuksan I have ever had the privilege to  witness.  I  reached  the  welcome
sight of my tent at 7:00 (8.5 miles, 3300 ft, 11 hrs).

Saturday, February 20 - Not much needs to be said about this  day.  I  awoke
to the sun, took my time packing up and skied out as  a  leisurely  pace.  I
met two parties of weekend downhillers already coming in  (at  10:00)  as  I
climbed to the 5080 ft saddle below Table Mtn. Many more appeared at  Artist
Point and the ski area was an absolute zoo. It was a  challenge  for  me  to
ski down the last bit with my full  pack,  as  there  wasn\'t  a  slope  that
wasn\'t  tracked  and  rutted  by  now  and  skiers  and  snowboarders   were
everywhere. The parking lot was jammed, cars  parked  in  every  conceivable
spot. I was happy to be leaving the hordes behind.  But  I  just  smiled  to
myself in contentment.  I had already had my adventure (4 miles, 500  ft.  3
hrs).

Total: 18.5 miles and 5700 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen







