            'title' => 'Blankenship Mtn (5760+ ft - P480 - Spiral Butte Quad), Fryingpan Mtn (5720+ ft - P880 - White Pass Quad) and Pk 5934 (P734 - Cougar Lk Quad) - March 10- 12, 2010 
 Friday, March 12: Blankenship Mtn',
            'tr' => '
Blankenship Mtn (5760+ ft - P480 - Spiral Butte Quad), Fryingpan Mtn  (5720+
ft - P880 - White Pass Quad) and Pk 5934 (P734 - Cougar Lk Quad) - March 10-
12, 2010

The area north of White Pass is a generally flat plateau dotted with  dozens
of lakes and ponds that makes for wonderful ski touring but difficult  route
finding. Except for lakes and meadows it is all forested with  very  limited
views. This includes the few summits.  So  without  the  benefit  of  summer
trails it is hard to know where you are or how to get to where you  want  to
go. Unless you have an exceptional sense of direction  (which  I  don\'t),  a
map GPS is an absolute necessity to determine your location. Even with  such
a device, I did an awful lot of wandering around.  Every  time  I  tried  to
follow my instincts and the terrain to where I thought I should  go  I  went
astray, often by a large margin.  The main problem is you  cannot  follow  a
straight line from here to there. Each lake is  in  a  basin  surrounded  by
hills and small ravines and drainages. A lot  of  unseen  obstacles  can  be
hidden in 40 ft contours and what appears to  be  flat  on  the  map  really
isn\'t. Travel isn\'t all that difficult - it is just  not  direct  and  often
confusing.

Wednesday, March 10: Blankenship Lake - The only plowed  parking  spot  near
where  I  wanted  to  start  was  the  quarry  road  just  before  Dog  Lake
Campground. This put me on a steepish icy hillside above Dog  Lake  and  the
trail to Cramer Lake. I cast around for 30 minutes or so before  picking  up
an old snowshoe trench which led to the crossing of  North  Fork  Clear  Cr.
Fairly flat to here the trail then climbed steadily for about a  mile.  Snow
cover was thin and icy in this section and I remember  hoping  for  lots  of
new snow to make skiing out easier. Be careful what you wish for!

I lost all sign of the snowshoe trail in the next  gentle  mile  but  better
snow put me easily at Cramer Lake at 3:00 (1000 ft, 3  hrs).  From  here  my
planned route was to go directly to Hill Lake and I started off  in  what  I
thought was the "obvious" direction. I soon came to a  large  lake.  When  I
checked my GPS I was shocked to discover it was Dancing Lady Lk  and  I  was
off by 90 degrees. This is when it dawned on me that travel wasn\'t going  to
be as straight forward as I had thought and I would have to look at  my  GPS
more often. This I did, working my way over a shallow saddle to Hill Lk  and
then more or less contouring  in  and  out  of  numerous  drainages  on  the
hillside below Tumac Mtn. Eventually I  ended  up  at  Blankenship  Lake  (8
miles, 1700 ft, 6:40 hrs) where I set up camp in the dark. It had  begun  to
snow lightly and continued to do so all night long.

Thursday, March 11: Pk 5934 and Fryingpan Mtn - It was  23  degrees  in  the
morning and still  snowing,  which  made  for  great  skiing  conditions.  I
started at 8:00 heading for the saddle leading to Twin Sisters Lakes.  Again
I was forced by the terrain and an errant sense of direction to  wander  and
it took over an hour to get there. Then once there I got confused. This  was
no ordinary saddle with an obvious up on one side and  an  obvious  down  on
the other but a broad undulating flat with little ups and downs all over.  I
would also have difficulty on the return.

Once across the saddle lovely meadows led down to Twin Sisters  Lakes.  Here
I found numerous Otter slide tracks (I had seen my first one the day  before
at Dancing Lady Lk). These tracks are very distinctive  -  about  10  inches
wide, smooth troughs on hills  and  interspersed  with  paw  prints  on  the
flats. I read that these fun loving  creatures  prefer  to  slide  on  their
bellies to travel on snow even on level ground or slightly  uphill.  Judging
by the numerous slides I encountered, I would say the  Otter  population  is
healthy in this area.

In heavy snowfall I skied across both  Twin  Sisters  Lakes  to  a  steepish
gully at the far end leading to the gentle summit ridge  of  Pk  5934  (1200
ft, 4:30 hrs). This summit completed the Cougar Lake Quad for me.  I  had  a
nice run down to another confusing flat saddle below  Fryingpan  Mtn  before
finding the E Ridge. The first part of this ridge, which  I  turned  on  the
right, was quite steep, but it gentled near the summit (2200 ft, 8:30  hrs).
More nice skiing off Fryingpan was followed by more wandering to get  around
Pk 5934 and back to Big Twin Sister Lake. I crossed the  lake  by  headlight
in darkness and heavy snow. All I could see were my ski tips which was  very
disorienting. I couldn\'t ski a straight line and had to  constantly  correct
course by GPS.

It had been snowing steadily all day - my guess is at least 10 inches.  This
meant my previous tracks were gone and I had to break trail all over  again.
And since I couldn\'t even see my tracks I had to routefind  all  over  again
also. That meant using my GPS constantly and wearing down the  batteries.  I
did have a second set but I was already using them. Normally I don\'t use  my
GPS on the return as I can either see where I am  going  or  can  follow  my
tracks and two sets of batteries are more than  sufficient.  I  was  getting
nervous about being so dependent on an electronic  device  and  I  began  to
ration battery life by turning the GPS off after every location fix.

I got confused once again on the broad Twin Sisters-Blankenship  saddle,  so
much so that I started heading for Round  Lk,  almost  180  degrees  in  the
wrong direction. I was forced to use my GPS more than I would have liked.  I
reached my tent, which looked much like an igloo by now and had  to  be  dug
out, at 10:30 (15 miles, 3200 ft, 14:30 hrs).

Friday, March 12: Blankenship Mtn - It was 35 degrees and the inside  of  my
tent was all wet in the morning. This is what can  make  backcountry  skiing
in the  Pacific  Northwest  so  frustrating,  the  widely  fluctuating  snow
levels. At least it was snowing lightly and not raining. I  started  for  Pk
5760+ (which I have named  Blankenship  Mtn)  at  7:40.  Despite  a  nagging
feeling of impending doom, I didn\'t  want  to  leave  without  tagging  this
summit. It was just too close and I had worked too hard  to  get  here.  The
snow was still reasonable to start though  beginning  to  turn  into  mashed
potatoes,  Blankenship  Meadows  were  lovely,  the  summit  pleasant,   the
downhill fun, and I got to follow my tracks back (4 miles, 900 ft, 3.5  hrs
RT). All in all worth the time risk taken.

I packed up wet gear and headed out at 11:30. It took me longer to  get  out
than it had to get in. Trail breaking was more work, I was  more  tired  and
despite trying to improve on my in route, I didn\'t. Every more  direct  line
I tried gained me nothing and even lost time. Meanwhile  I  could  feel  the
temperature dropping as the snow level was on its  way  down  again.  I  was
able to ski down the steepish trail section to the creek  crossing,  despite
an icy crust just starting to form. There was enough new  snow  to  slow  me
down.

I completely lost the trail about Â½ mile before Dog Lake  in  the  darkness.
You would think a person couldn\'t possibly have problems here,  but  I  sure
managed to. Between the now very icy densely wooded  hillside  on  my  right
and the obstacle ridden marsh on my left and with no trail to  guide  me,  I
made very slow progress. And then my GPS completely died. There was  no  way
I could find a direct way through the woods to my car without it. I  had  to
fall back on the low tech but sure method of hitting a base line -  Hwy  12.
You can\'t imagine how happy I was to finally see  the  lights  of  vehicles.
With my tail between my legs and my ego shattered, I limped along  the  edge
of the road back to my car. I am sure I turned a few heads  in  the  passing
cars. One even stopped to offer a ride but by that time I  was  so  close  I
declined. Besides I just didn\'t  want  to  deal  with  an  explanation  (8.5
miles, 400 ft, 8:30 hrs).

My car was encased in about 5 inches of melted and refrozen crust.  It  took
30 minutes to chip the windows free. It snowed all the way down to  Packwood
where it finally turned to rain.

Total: 35.5 miles and 6200 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen





