            'title' => 'Heliotrope Ridge (7242 ft - P82 - Mt Baker Quad) - March 17-18, 2010',
            'tr' => '
Heliotrope Ridge (7242 ft - P82 - Mt Baker Quad) - March 17-18, 2010

Wednesday, March 17 - With 10 inches of new snow reported over night  at  Mt
Baker, I headed north. The new snow promised good skiing  but  made  getting
high on Glacier Cr Road a bit tricky. Fresh snow started about 2000  ft  and
rapidly increased to where I was forced to stop at 3100 ft about I mile  shy
of the current SnoPark at 3560 ft. Several other vehicles were  parked  here
including one hauling snow mobiles.

I skied the road past  the  SnoPark  to  the  Heliotrope  Ridge  TH  at  the
switchback (elev 3700 ft).  The new snow made the trail just  skiable  going
up at the start but I knew I would be walking down part of it as many  rocks
and roots in the dense woods were barely covered.  A party had already  been
up (and down) the trail and I had no trail breaking as  the  forest  thinned
and the snow depth increased higher. I found a  scenic  spot  to  camp  just
above the tree line at 5200 ft (3.5 miles, 2200 ft, 3 hrs). Despite  a  very
late start I had plenty of time to set up  camp,  relax  and  even  take  an
evening tour before turning in at 8:30.

Thursday, March 18 - I was on my way before  8:00  on  a  clear  but  frigid
morning, temps in the low twenties. I worked my way up easy terrain  to  the
crest of Heliotrope Ridge (hitting welcome sun just  below)  and  along  the
ridge to the high point (2200 ft, 2  hrs).  The  view  of  Lincoln  directly
across the Thunder Glacier was stunning, as  were  The  Sisters  beyond  the
Middle Fork Nooksack River. From my high point I skied W along the ridge  to
a  slightly  lower  but  very  attractive  knoll  with  inviting  completely
untracked slopes. Once on that I skied down the friendliest of  terrain  for
a delightful run back to camp (4 miles, 2450  ft,  4  hrs  RT).  I  met  two
parties coming up as I skied down. I took a short nap in a tent  sun  warmed
to a pleasant 60 degrees before heading out (2 hrs  to  car).   Surely  this
has to be one of my most leisurely pleasant trips in a while. A nice  change
of pace.

Total: 11 miles and 4650 ft in two half days

Fay Pullen

