            'tr' => '
The Portals, W Pk (6920+ ft - P400) and The Portals, E Pk (6520+ ft -  P320)
- Mt Baker Quad - March 23-24, 2010

On my trip to Coleman Pinnacle a month ago I was struck by  all  the  lovely
ski terrain on The Portals and the Sholes Glacier. Unfortunately I  ran  out
of time  to  include  them  then.  I  could  barely  wait  to  rectify  that
situation. All I needed was the right conditions again although neither  the
snow nor the weather was as perfect as I had hoped.

Tuesday, March 23 - The ski area had some 9 inches  total  fresh  snow  from
Sunday and Monday, all of which was rapidly turning to slush when I  arrived
at noon. Despite overcast skies, it was downright balmy. I worried that  wet
avalanches could be a problem. It turned  out  they  weren\'t.  I  skied  the
usual approach to Artist Point and under the cliffs  of  Table  Mtn  to  the
saddle with Ptarmigan Ridge.  There  were  no  fresh  tracks  of  any  other
backcountry skiers having gone this way. From the saddle  I  stayed  on  the
right side of Ptarmigan Ridge traversing between  5000  and  5200  ft  until
past Coleman Pinnacle. I had skied this traverse on my previous trip but  it
had been dark so it was like it was all new terrain. Once past the  pinnacle
I climbed up a N facing bowl where the snow was preserved powder to  a  6120
ft saddle. Here I set up camp by some rocks as  a  partial  protection  from
the growing wind (6 miles, 2700 ft. 5 hrs). It was a very scenic  spot.  The
wind increased during the night which did not bode well for  my  summit  day
but it did keep my tent condensation free.

Wednesday, March 24 - It barely got below freezing during the night and  the
day dawned hazy but that didn\'t  prevent  S  slopes  from  turning  to  hard
crust. From camp I made a descending traverse to the broad  6000  ft  saddle
below E Portal. One  short  stretch  was  so  crusty  I  carried  skies  and
cramponed down. But from then on I could ski and the snow was quite good.  I
easily reached the summit of E Portal at 9:30 (600 ft,  1:15  hr).   What  a
view point! It was windy but not horribly so.

I could not descend directly to Portal Saddle because of obvious  cliffs  so
I backtracked to a trough that appeared to go smoothly down  to  the  Sholes
Glacier. It did not. The first part was a fantastic  ski  but  it  ended  in
unseen cliffs. I was able to bypass them on the left on very steep snow  but
I had to boot down to do so. Once  on  the  Sholes  Glacier  it  was  heaven
skiing to Portal Saddle.  Continuous  snow  led  directly  from  here  to  W
Portal, however it looked awfully steep so I elected for an end  run  around
on friendlier terrain. The higher I got on W Portal the windier it  got.  On
the wide open summit plateau it was downright  brutal  and  I  could  barely
stay upright. My guess is a steady 40-50 mph with a few higher gusts. I  had
to sit down to take my summit photos to avoid  being  blown  off.  I  didn\'t
stay long on top (1700 ft, 3:15). I found a semi sheltered spot  in  a  wind
carved hole to remove my skins. I quickly skied out of  the  ferocious  wind
zone and had a great run down the Sholes Glacier  past  all  the  cliffs  to
where I could climb back to the 6000 ft saddle and then to  camp  (6  miles,
2300 ft, 5 hrs RT).

It was only slightly after 1:00. I had been prepared  to  stay  another  day
and ski to other destinations  but  the  brutal  wind  made  higher  terrain
unappealing. And the forecast  for  Thursday  was  rain.  So  I  decided  to
consider the trip a success and retreat. I left at 2:20.  By  now  all  snow
was melting but it was not bad skiing. By the time I reached  the  ski  area
runs they were closed so I didn\'t have  to  content  with  the  downhillers.
Snow in the shade was just beginning to crust over, but not enough to  cause
any difficulties. Good timing. I reached my car at 5:40 (6  miles,  500  ft,
3:20 hrs).

Total: 18 miles and 5500 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen

