            'title' => 'Carlton Ridge (5680+ ft - P520 - White Pass Quad) - March 30-April 1, 2010',
            'tr' => '
Carlton Ridge (5680+ ft - P520 - White Pass Quad) - March 30-April 1, 2010

I didn\'t think there would be enough lowland snow to ski the  trail  to  Jug
Lake this year, but all that changed with the recent new  dump.  Also,  this
is a perfect area to go to when the avalanche danger is high as the  terrain
is mostly gentle or heavily wooded.

Tuesday, March 30 - Over a foot of new snow stopped me on FR 4510 1.4  miles
past Summit Cr campground at 3000 ft. This left 1.6 miles of  flat  road  to
ski to the TH at Soda Springs, elev 3200 ft. It was snowing heavily  when  I
arrived but the sun came out by the time I got started. Such was  the  order
of the day - showers and sun breaks. The snow was very  wet  and  heavy  and
trail breaking an effort so progress was slow.  Snow cover was  adequate  to
ski the trail. The main problem was the numerous creek  crossings,  although
I only had to remove skis to get across one. I even managed to keep skis  on
at Jug Cr by bridging snow-covered rocks. Shortly after that  I  came  to  a
trail junction sign and headed uphill to Jug  Lake  arriving  at  7:30  with
just enough time to set up camp in fading light  (5  miles,  1550  ft,  5:45
hrs). The temperature was above freezing but dropping fast.

Wednesday, March 31 -  There  was  light  snow  during  the  night  and  the
temperature in the morning was 18 degrees.  Again  showers  and  sun  breaks
occurred all day. I skied around Jug Lake and then  meadows  toward  Carlton
Ridge. The meadows were lovely but had unexpected obstacles in  the  way  of
numerous melted out meandering creek  channels  that  were  hard  to  detect
until almost right upon them.  This  necessitated  frequent  small  detours.
Then the upper reaches of Jug Cr were not as friendly as  I  had  hoped  but
turned out to be steep dense woods above the stream cut. I would  have  done
better to head straight to Carlton Ridge lower down but I really  wanted  to
go to Kincaid Lake, which was totally worth the effort.  From  the  lake  it
was easy access to the ridge high point (1300  ft,  3:40  hrs).  I  hit  the
summit during a sun break and had a pleasant lunch in its warmth.

My main goal of reaching the summit of Carlton Ridge met, I  took  the  rest
of the day to wander wherever my skis led me. And wander I  did.  Slopes  in
the sun were melting and turning slushy so  I  skied  off  the  NW  side  in
delicious powder. I followed the W side of the  ridge  through  two  saddles
and on to Pt 5660, a definite top. I had a nice ski off  that  on  E  slopes
that were wooded enough to still  be  powdery.  I  meandered  the  Jug  Lake
meadows again until I could climb over the low saddle to Upper  Chain  Lake.
I returned to camp along the S shore of Jug Lake.  Open  water  was  showing
here so I didn\'t dare ski across the lake. I had some worry  about  crossing
the outlet creek. To my amazement there was a skiable snow bridge,  although
it was a bit spooky to cross. I reached my tent at 6:00 (7 miles,  2200  ft,
9:45 hrs). It was 36 degrees.

Thursday, April 1 - It had  snowed  about  an  inch  overnight  and  was  25
degrees in the morning. Everything that had melted the day  before  was  now
crusty. But in the woods much of the  snow  was  still  powder.  Skiing  was
really quite good and trail breaking much easier. I really wanted to ski  to
Fryingpan Lake. It was much harder than anticipated to make my way  up  what
appeared on the map to be a short easy slope to the lake. Again steep  dense
woods and the deep gully of upper Summit Creek were  impediments.  But  once
up that the terrain gentled and opened up as I made my way past Little  Snow
Lake to Fryingpan  Lake.  I  was  having  so  much  fun  I  couldn\'t  resist
extending my excursion and climbing Fryingpan  Mtn  again  (I  had  done  it
about 2 weeks ago) just for the downhill run. Despite what looked like  very
steep terrain on  the  map  the  woods  were  open  enough  and  the  powder
preserved and deep enough that I could ski  it  in  style.  And  the  summit
ridge was a delight. Sometimes you just can\'t  tell  from  a  map  what  the
terrain will be like. I returned to camp at 12:20 (4.5  miles,  1500  ft,  4
hrs RT). Again it was 36 degrees.

I left at 1:10. I was able to ski all the way out although  there  had  been
much melting on the lower trail and cover was getting thin in spots. When  I
reached the car at 4:40 it was snowing heavily (5 miles, 150 ft, 3:30 hrs).

Total: 21.5 miles and 5400 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen

Carlton Ridge finished the White Pass Quad for me.



