            'tr' => '
McNeil Pk (6658 ft - P938) and Arnesons Pk  (6400+  ft  -  P1080)  -  Spiral
Butte Quad - April 6-8, 2010

When I left on Tuesday the forecast was good for all of Wednesday. This  was
to be followed by snow levels rising briefly to 5000 ft and quickly  falling
to 1500 ft in advance of a strong  front  coming  in  Thursday.   Well,  the
front must have intensified and  come  in  early  as  I  got  caught  midday
Wednesday in a late posted winter storm warning. An  avalanche  warning  was
also posted for Thursday. Timing can be everything in winter trips and  mine
was about 24 hours off on this one.

Tuesday, April 6 - I drove over White Pass and up Indian Cr Road 1308  about
1.4 mile before being stopped by snow (elev 3150 ft), which left  1.5  miles
to ski to the TH. The new snow varied from 6-12 inches and was very wet  and
heavy to start. Trail breaking was  a  real  chore.  The  trail  was  easily
followed to the first crossing of Indian Cr, although one side  gully  where
it was washed out took some time. With no bridge, crossing  Indian  Cr  took
even more time. Steep switchbacks on the other side climbed out of the  deep
ravine onto a bench above. I lost the trail leading to the  second  crossing
but found a way across on a snow bridge and picked up  the  trail  again  on
the other side. By the time I reached the  third  crossing  it  was  getting
late and despite my goal to reach Indian Cr Meadows I decided to  stop  here
in a small meadow, elev 4840 ft.  Although the weather had been pretty  good
most of the day, it began to snow lightly as I set  up  my  tent  (6  miles,
2000 ft, 6:30 hrs).

Wednesday, April 7 - It was 27 degrees in the  morning  and  had  snowed  an
inch or so overnight. I recrossed Indian Cr and worked my way to  the  broad
saddle between Arnesons and McNeil Pks. The snow was much  drier  here,  the
woods open, the skiing quite good and  I  was  thoroughly  enjoying  myself.
From the saddle, I climbed onto McNeil\'s NW ridge, the upper part  of  which
was quite lovely, and then onto the SW ridge.  Here I  encountered  some  of
the most heavily rimed trees I have ever seen. There  must  have  been  some
extremely wild weather here recently. Fortunately, the weather was good  for
me up to this point, with even a few sun breaks and a  partial  view  toward
White Pass. I was optimistic it would stay that way. It  didn\'t.   I  booted
the last few feet to the summit (2200 ft, 4 hrs).

Skiing was good off McNeil back to the saddle. I had hoped to get a view  of
Arnesons Pk, the upper part of which is bare, but only got glimpses  through
the trees and thickening clouds. I wandered a bit through the  forest  until
breaking out onto open slopes. It was now beginning to snow and by the  time
I reached the summit of Arnesons (3400 ft,  7:15  hr)  it  was  blowing  and
snowing heavily and downright nasty. I could barely see  to  ski  down.  All
thought of extending my tour to Indian Cr  Meadows  was  abandoned.  By  the
time I reached my camp (7 miles, 3400 ft, 8:40 hr RT), it  was  questionable
whether what was coming down was snow or rain.  As  I  took  shelter  in  my
bombproof tent from the growing  storm  it  soon  became  just  plain  rain.
During  the  night  this  changed  to  heavy  snow  with  gusty  winds.  The
temperature was 36 degrees to start before falling rapidly to 26.

Thursday, April 8 - Packing up in the morning was not  fun.  It  had  snowed
about 8 inches and was still snowing hard. After being rained on and  snowed
on and freezing my tent was an icy disaster. When  I  unpacked  it  at  home
later there were still ice chunks clinging to it. And the poles were  frozen
and stuck. I had to breathe on them  to  get  them  apart.  My  tracks  were
almost completely covered and I had to  break  trail  all  over  again.   It
seemed as much work going out as coming in. I reached the  car  at  1:20  (6
miles, 250 ft, 5:20 hrs). Fortunately there was only a few inches  new  snow
here so I had no trouble driving out to Hwy 12, but I ran into  bad  weather
with blowing snow all the way to Morton. Beyond there  it  was  inexplicably
blue skies and sunny. Strange weather indeed.

Total: 19 miles and 5650 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen





