Ulalach Pk (5040+  ft  -  P440)  and  Higher  Squire  (4879  ft  -  P799)  -
Whitehorse Quad - May 7-8, 2010

Friday, May 7: Ulalach Pk - I started from the Eightmile TH (elev  1700  ft)
off the Clear Cr Rd 2060 and Rd 2065. This  TH  is  much  used  by  climbers
heading for Three O\'Clock Rock and the trail is fairly good to  that  point.
Beyond that it gets quite rough, steep, rocky, rooty and  wet.  I  ran  into
snow starting at 3000 ft and put on snowshoes at 3800 ft although  I  should
have put them on sooner. I used them to 3500 ft on the way out. No  one  had
been this way since the last heavy snowfall. Weather was partly  sunny  both
days with the afternoons cloudy and  threatening  showers.  Farther  to  the
east looked positively stormy. I set up camp at Squire Cr  Pass  (elev  4100
ft) with a lovely view of Three Fingers and Whitehorse (3  miles,  2500  ft,
3:20 hrs).

I started for Ulalach in late afternoon. The  distant  view  of  this  rocky
peak showed the  easiest  route  would  be  up  the  snow-covered  SW  face.
However, it looked steep and was in full sun and I wasn\'t sure it  would  be
safe. I would just have to go and see. I traversed through woods to  the  SW
ridge and followed this ridge to where I could drop off  it  onto  the  open
face. I was a little worried about crossing below  slabs  to  get  to  safer
terrain on a wooded rib on the far left. It might have  also  been  possible
to stay on the ridge all the way to the top but it  looked  to  be  possibly
class 4 and challenging with the partial snow cover. As it  turned  out  the
SW face was no problem and showed no  signs  of  instability  and  the  snow
consolidated enough that I soon ditched the  snowshoes.  But  just  to  make
sure I stayed on the wooded rib all  the  way  to  the  NW  ridge.  Cornices
prevented me from direct access to the summit. I had to drop off the E  side
and traverse below the ridge until right below the summit. This side was  in
the shade and step kicking good. On the return,  following  my  tracks,  one
small slide came off the summit slabs still exposed to the sun  but  it  was
far from me and it stopped as soon as it hit the snow slope (3  miles,  1500
ft, 4 hrs RT from camp).

Saturday, May 8: Higher Squire -  It  was  cold  enough  overnight  for  the
surface of the snow to form a crust so I didn\'t need snowshoes as I  started
for Higher Squire at 8:45.  As I climbed I heard several  slides  come  down
the E face of Three Fingers, which was in full morning sun.  I  reached  the
summit easily from the W saddle and ridge (850 ft,:50 hr). I then turned  my
attention to seeing if I could  find  a  way  up  Squire  Spire.  It  is  an
impressive looking little spire that looked to be  quite  challenging  under
the present snowy conditions. I first tried  from  the  saddle  with  Higher
Squire. I couldn\'t even get past the first bump. A traverse below  the  bump
on the S slope on thinly covered slabs or  a  direct  route  over  the  bump
along the ridge were both above my comfort level. I next tried  from  the  W
ridge. Trying for the first notch to the W I couldn\'t get across  the  moat.
I tried again farther W and made the ridge but again a  traverse  on  the  S
slope was too steep and exposed. I would have to return  at  a  later  date.
It did look to be a fun rock scramble when the snow is gone. I was  not  too
unhappy as that would give me an excuse to return to this lovely area.

I returned to camp at 11:00 (1.5 miles, 1100 ft, 2:15 hrs RT)  and  left  an
hour later. I reached Three O\'Clock Rock, which was swarming  with  climbers
on this Saturday, just as a rain  shower  hit.  I  heard  much  yelling  and
commotion from climbers quickly retreating as I passed.  The  shower  lasted
the rest of the way to the car (3 miles, 1:50 hrs).

Total: 10.5 miles and 5100 ft in a leisurely 2 days

Fay Pullen



