            'title' => 'Slate Mtn (6209 ft - P449 - Shuksan Arm Quad); and Goat Hunter (6452 ft - P412) & Mamie Pk (6108 ft - P362) - Mt Sefrit Quad - May 14-15, 2010',
            'tr' => '
Slate Mtn (6209 ft - P449 - Shuksan Arm Quad); and Goat Hunter  (6452  ft  -
P412) & Mamie Pk (6108 ft - P362) - Mt Sefrit Quad - May 14-15, 2010

The weather was lovely.  The  snow  conditions  were  not.  Both  days  were
unseasonably warm, SCARY WARM, with  deep  slushy  unstable  snow  and  high
avalanche danger. Because of this I chose these two  "relatively  safe"  day
climbs with a car camp at the Hannegan Pass TH  overnight.  Even  so  I  had
several moments of concern.

Friday, May 14: Slate Mtn - What I thought  would  be  a  short  easy  climb
turned into a bit more due to the snow  conditions.  Beginning  at  noon,  I
dropped north 300 ft from the Baker Ski Area parking lot on the  E  side  of
Bagley Cr until I could cross to the  W  and  start  an  ascending  traverse
below the cliffs of Herman Pk. It was slow  going  in  the  soft  snow  with
evidence  of  recent  avalanches  everywhere  but  nothing  current,   thank
heavens. I eventually rounded Herman to enter an open  basin  from  where  I
could work my way up the SE slope of Slate. There was much avalanche  debris
here with again no current activity  but  the  soft  snow  did  not  inspire
confidence as the slope steepened to 45-50 degrees. I stuck to the trees  as
much as possible using them as anchors and handholds but I was not happy  or
comfortable with the situation. When I pulled onto the summit at 4:00  (2500
ft) I had already decided I wasn\'t going down  that  way.   I  followed  the
gentle ridge SW until it turned rocky and I scrambled to a steep step  above
the col with Mt Herman. I was not expecting anything technical on this  peak
but I did have my 100 ft panic rope with me and two 50 ft rappels put me  on
easy snow. This was a  much  better  way  off  Slate  than  down  the  steep
unstable SE slope. The snow was even softer and more exhausting on the  rest
of the way back to the car but there were no other difficulties.

Total: 3.5 miles, 2800 ft and 7 hrs

Saturday, May 15: Goat Hunter and Mamie Pk - Again what I thought  would  be
reasonably easy and  straightforward  was  not  and  I  encountered  several
problems. From a car camp at the Hannegan Pass TH I headed into  the  brush,
seeking a direct route to Mamie Pass, and encountered problem #1. Unable  to
see where I was going I think I chose the worst possible line. I kept  going
left trying to get to big trees. I should have gone right.  I  ended  up  in
horrible brush  and  then  encountered  an  impassible  cliff  band  with  a
waterfall. It was so bad I very nearly gave up. After  much  verbal  ranting
and cursing I eventually worked my way up right along the base of the  cliff
to a wooded rib and salvation. It took me 2 hours to go this initial 800  ft
gain. But hey, I got to see a waterfall very few, if any, people  have  ever
seen.

Once on the wooded rib things went much better. Breaking out of the trees  I
hit a nice dirt gully and then continuous snow  and  problem  #2,  extremely
soft snow, even softer than on Slate,  and  enervating  trail  breaking.  It
seemed to take forever to reach the ridge at 5700 ft (2700 ft 4:30 hrs).  On
the ridge again things looked up. Views were fantastic and goat tracks  were
everywhere although I never saw one of the  critters.  I  went  over  a  few
bumps until I thought what I was looking at was the summit. It looked  quite
easy and I thought I had it made. Then I came to  a  notch  where  a  higher
pointed summit appeared in the near distance. What  was  this?  It  must  be
Goat Mtn. No it is too close for Goat. My  heart  sank  as  I  came  to  the
realization that this was my peak, Goat Hunter.

Now to problem #3. As I got a closer look I knew I couldn\'t climb this  peak
safely along the ridge. The snow was too steep and too unstable and the  top
was guarded by a vertical cornice. The only other possible  safe  route  was
from the SW side which would involve a drop of 600 ft to get  past  all  the
cliffs. This is when it dawned on me it was going to be  a  very  long  day.
This little detour would add two extra hours. I tried not to think about  it
too much as I dropped down easy slopes to the SW slope  and  plodded  slowly
back up again to the summit. I just went on  auto  pilot  while  time  stood
still. I reached the top at 2:30 (4100 ft, 7 hrs). Then I  reversed  it  all
over again - down 800 ft and up 600 ft back to  the  false  summit,  all  in
deep wet slushy snow.

I still wanted to climb Mamie Pk but  wasn\'t  sure  I  had  enough  time  or
energy left. I guess I got a second wind because I  quickly  made  it  Mamie
Pass (a lovely spot by the way) and charged up the remaining 900  ft.  Which
brings me to problem(s) #4  -  a  series  of  totally  unexpected  technical
difficulties not obvious from the distant view on Mamie. First was  crossing
a short (4 ft) vertical cornice and crack getting from the N onto  the  main
W summit ridge. It wasn\'t really that difficult. It was just that  the  snow
couldn\'t be trusted for secure steps and a slip here would  mean  a  serious
slide over cliffs. The same for a crack forming between snow and  rock  just
above the cornice.  I surmounted both by  excavating  and  harvesting  loose
surface snow to fill cracks and packing it to create  solid  steps.  Then  I
encountered two class 4 rock steps that  could  not  be  bypassed  on  snow,
again due to unstable cornices. All this took time but finally  I  stood  on
the summit of Mamie at 6:00 (5700 ft, 10:40 hrs).

I rappelled the top rock step, downclimbed the next rock step and  rappelled
the suspect snow above the cornice step since there was a handy  tree.  Then
it was fast down to Mamie Pass and on down to intersect  my  uphill  tracks.
Once on the wooded rib below the snow I stayed on it  all  the  way  to  the
valley floor bypassing all the horrible brush and cliffs I  had  encountered
on the way up and came out just slightly uphill of  my  car  at  8:20.  Good
thing I got an early start and the days are long.

Total: 4.5 miles, 5700 ft and 13 hrs

Fay Pullen



