            'title' => 'Battle Mtn (7710 ft - P430), Snowshoe Ridge (7816 ft - P736) and Duckbill Mtn (6536 ft - P616) - Oval Pk Quad - May 29-31, 2010 
 Sunday, May 30: Snowshoe Ridge and Battle Mtn 
 Lookout Mtn (5515 ft - P1435 - Twisp West Quad)',
            'tr' => '
Battle Mtn (7710 ft - P430), Snowshoe Ridge (7816 ft -  P736)  and  Duckbill
Mtn (6536 ft - P616) - Oval Pk Quad - May 29-31, 2010

I think I changed my plans 3 times  before  finally  settling  at  the  last
minute on the Chelan - Sawtooth area as giving the  best  chances  for  good
weather and safe travel. Miraculously I never had to use my  rain  parka.  I
even had a fair amount of sun.

Saturday, May 29: Duckbill Mtn - I ran into heavy rain over Snoqualmie  Pass
but by the time I got to the Eagle Cr TH (elev 3000 ft) up the Twisp  River,
all precipitation had ceased. I started up the trail at  1:30.  It  had  the
usual amount of downed trees for this time of year before  logging  out  has
taken place. At 1.5 miles the trail crosses Eagle Cr. I knew I might have  a
problem right from the TH as I could hear the water  roaring  from  all  the
recent rain and snow melt. Sure enough I could see  no  way  across  without
wading. To do this safely I would have to keep my  boots  on  and  I  didn\'t
want to start the trip with wet  ones.  What  to  do?  The  trail  has  been
rerouted recently to cross the creek to the  south,  continue  on  the  Oval
Lakes trail to a junction, parallel the creek on the  south  side  and  then
cross again to the north. The old trail stayed on the north side  and  never
crossed the creek. So I decided to try and follow the old  trail  and  avoid
the creek crossings altogether.

I found the old trail right at the  Wilderness  boundary  sign.  It  was  in
pretty good shape too, at least to start. Then I discovered why it had  been
abandoned and rerouted. A large section of trail on  a  steep  hillside  had
slid into Eagle Creek. I forced a way around  this  by  dropping  below  and
climbing very steeply back up to the trail. The next section  of  trail  was
fairly overgrown and brushy and I was most  happy  when  I  intersected  the
main trail again. This little escapade had cost maybe an hour but  at  least
I still had dry feet.

I started running into snow at about 4500  ft  and  was  forced  to  put  on
snowshoes about 5000 ft. The snow was unreliable crust in the woods and  wet
slush in any open area. It was  slow  going  with  no  views  to  break  the
monotony. At 6:30 I found a bare ground campsite under trees at the edge  of
a small meadow near Silver Lake, elev 5800 ft (5 miles, 2900 ft, 5  hrs).  I
even had a view of Oval Pk out my front door.

I started for Duckbill at 7:30 fully  expecting  to  get  back  after  dark.
First up I had to get across Eagle Creek. Admittedly it was much  tamer  and
smaller here but still not trivial. Fortunately I found a small  log  fairly
close by - fun crossing with snowshoes on. Then everything went much  better
than anticipated. It was easy snowshoeing through open forest  to  the  base
of the steepening S ridge. Here I  left  the  snowshoes  as  the  ridge  was
mostly melted out and bare. In fact Duckbill is  a  delightful  little  peak
with a wonderful view which I hit at  sunset  lighting.  I  only  needed  my
headlight for the log crossing returning to camp at 9:30 (2 miles,  900  ft,
2 hrs RT).

Sunday, May 30:  Snowshoe  Ridge  and  Battle  Mtn  -  Starting  at  8:00  I
continued on the trail until past the main cliffy S slope of Snowshoe  where
I could see a reasonable route up. Since it started quite steep  and  mostly
snow free, I left my snowshoes here. That was probably a mistake  as  I  ran
into more gentle terrain and deeper snow higher up but it was  not  a  major
problem. Snowshoe is a pleasant ridge with even better  views  (2000  ft,  3
hrs). Massive Oval Peak dominated the landscape and it continued  to  do  so
all day. The summit rocks were bare and I left a register in the  cairn  (as
I did on all 3 peaks).

I returned to my snowshoes and put them back on for  Battle.  The  snow  was
getting very soft by now and the last quite steep climb  to  the  summit  up
the E Ridge was exhausting. At the top I had to chop my way through a  small
cornice to gain the broad summit (3100 ft, 6 hrs). It was now only 2:30  and
too early to return to camp so I decided to climb Pt 6960+ ft.  Although  it
doesn\'t have the requisite prominence, this is  an  attractive  point  above
Eagle Pass.

Filtered sun and warm temperatures were causing numerous  small  spontaneous
slides off the steep E slopes of Battle Mtn and ridge  connecting  to  Eagle
Pass.  I dropped to 7000 ft and traversed below the activity. On the  way  I
came across a fascinating phenomenon I had never seen  before.  It  appeared
to be a type of "avalanche" where the top layer of snow "wrinkles"  down  as
a continuous unit much like a large carpet being pushed downhill.

From spacious Eagle Pass I tried to get up Pt 7960+ but gave  up  about  100
ft from the top. I hit a rock band and the snow was too steep  and  unstable
to traverse around it. But I had accomplished my goal of extending the  day.
I turned around at 5:00. Back at Eagle Pass I came across fresh tracks of  a
bear that weren\'t there on the way up. Mr. Bear needed snowshoes as  he  was
sinking in about a foot with each step. I looked around carefully but  never
saw the creature. The tracks  went  one  way  and  I  another  as  I  headed
directly back to camp. Lower down where I intersected my uphill track  below
Snowshoe Ridge I ran across the  bear  prints  again,  presumably  the  same
animal. He was using my tracks. Smart animal. The tracks continued  to  very
near camp and I feared maybe my dinner was gone. I had  hung  my  food  but,
thinking mostly of rodents, only 5 feet off the ground.  Not  to  worry,  my
food was untouched (8 miles, 4200 ft, 11 hrs).

Monday, May 31 - It rained lightly most of the night but considerately  quit
by the time I was ready to leave in the morning at 8:30. The sun  even  came
out. I was undecided about whether to  return  on  the  old  or  new  trail.
Finding a nice log at the upper crossing of Eagle Creek  swayed  me  to  the
new trail. Two wadings would have been too much. I had hoped that the  water
level would be less than on Saturday at the  lower  crossing.  It  was  not.
Even with my boots on for good footing and only knee deep, the crossing  was
dicey. The water was very forceful. Too  lazy  to  take  off  my  boots  and
change socks, I squished the remaining 1.5 miles back to the car  (5  miles,
3:30 hrs).

Total: 20 miles and 8000 ft in 3 days

Lookout Mtn (5515 ft - P1435 - Twisp West Quad) - Not  wanting  to  hit  the
peak of the Memorial Day backup over Snoqualmie Pass, I chose to  kill  some
time on the delightful trail up  this  peak  just  above  Twisp.  It  has  a
Lookout and the cutest little trail cattle guard. I didn\'t  know  they  came
that small. I did get rained on as the weather had  deteriorated  (3  miles,
1200 ft, 1:30 hrs RT). But I also missed the traffic.

Fay Pullen



