            'tr' => '
Talus Butte (7484 ft - P604), Boulder Butte (7350 ft - P450) and Splawn  Mtn
(7450 ft - P370) - Sun Mtn Quad - June 7-8, 2010

Monday, June 7 - After the long drive and eating lunch in my  car  I  didn\'t
get started on the War Cr trail until  2:00.  That  gave  time  for  morning
showers to improve to afternoon sunshine. My original plan was to go up  the
South Fork trail and climb Sun Mtn and Black Ridge. But I couldn\'t find  the
start of this unmaintained trail.  That was probably just  as  well  because
even if I could I would have had trouble crossing  War  Creek  which  was  a
raging torrent. Anticipating this could be a problem, it was on to Plan B  -
stay on the main War Cr trail and climb peaks near War Cr Pass.

I met a WTA work party coming out that had  logged  the  trail  to  about  3
miles. Past that were a few logs but the trail  was  in  pretty  good  shape
overall. The many small  creek  crossings  were  more  of  a  problem.  Snow
started around 5000 ft and became solid around 5800 ft. At 5  miles  I  came
across the sturdy War Creek Cabin (elev 4600 ft). I didn\'t  even  know  this
cabin existed. It is in excellent condition with a wood stove and  plentiful
supply of firewood. I was tempted to stay at the cabin but I  really  wanted
to get closer to my objectives.  I  began  to  regret  this  decision  after
pushing another 3.5 miles and ending up having a hard time  finding  a  snow
free site for my tent. I was becoming resigned to camping on snow  (which  I
really didn\'t want to do) when I stumbled upon a level spot under a tree  at
6000 ft (8.5 miles, 3200 ft, 6 hrs).

Tuesday, June 8 - After a very comfortable night, I started for Talus  Butte
at 7:00. The snow in the open had  frozen  overnight  enough  that  crampons
would have been useful, but since I didn\'t bring any I stayed off  the  more
direct steep south slope and instead  went  up  the  SE  ridge.  The  summit
itself was melted out to where I could build a cairn and  leave  a  register
(1600 ft, 1:40 hr). The snow was  beginning  to  soften  in  the  sun  as  I
descended the S  ridge  heading  for  Boulder  Butte.  So  much  so  that  I
occasionally broke through into a thigh  deep  hole.  Snowshoes  might  have
helped. Then again maybe not as in places the snow was so rotten and  hollow
that even a snowshoe would have broken  through,  all  a  moot  point  as  I
didn\'t bring any. There was evidence of  fresh  snow  and  weird  conditions
above 7000 ft.

I followed the S ridge to its low point  intending  to  traverse  around  Pt
6659 on the W side and a direct route to  Boulder  Butte.  This  had  looked
good from Talus. Looks  can  be  deceiving.  When  I  actually  got  to  the
traverse it was quite steep and still icy so a no go for me. Instead I  took
a circuitous route dropping and traversing on the sunny  E  side  and  going
through War Cr Pass. Once at the pass it was easy going  to  the  summit  of
Boulder Butte (2800, 4:30 hr). This summit  is  a  marvelous  viewpoint  for
every direction and with a warm sunny snow free  spot  to  hang  out  at,  I
thoroughly enjoyed my stay. I really didn\'t want to  leave.  I  particularly
liked the view across Lake Chelan to the Devore Cr peaks.

My last peak of the day was Splawn Mtn. I  descended  to  Lake  Juanita  and
traversed a long way around Pt 7252 and another bump until I could gain  the
W ridge to the summit (3800 ft, 7:30 hr). By now I  could  see  the  weather
changing as it began clouding up. The forecast  was  for  rain  tonight  and
tomorrow. My thought was to get as  far  as  the  cabin  tonight  and  avoid
spending a wet night out. First I  had  to  get  back  to  camp.  It  seemed
shorter and faster to take a direct line down rather than return the  way  I
had come through War Cr Pass. To this end I descended to the saddle  on  the
W ridge and dropped off the N side into the War Cr drainage. I am  not  sure
I gained much by doing this as I ran into some very steep  terrain  and  had
to wander a bit to find a way down. Even  so  I  ended  up  making  2  short
rappels. I then had to traverse  up  and  down  across  several  basins  and
gullies.  It took 1:40 hr to reach my tent (7 miles, 4100 ft, 9:40 hr RT).

I had a snack and a half hour nap before packing up and leaving at  6:00.  I
made the cabin at 7:40. That was sooner than expected and I figured I  still
had a good 2 hours of daylight left so I just kept going  and  darned  if  I
didn\'t make the TH without needing my headlamp  at  9:45  (8.5  miles,  3:45
hr). I spent the night in my car. I was awakened sometime during  the  night
to the sound of rain.

Total: 24 miles and 7400 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen

