            'tr' => '
Bears Breast Mtn (7197 ft - P1117 - Mt Daniel Quad) - June 12-14, 2010

This trip almost ended at the TH for me. But I am getting ahead  of  myself.
Stefan had researched  an  unproven  route  approaching  Bears  Breast  from
Shovel Lake. This route required snow cover to work best. He  had  tried  to
set it up last spring several times but was thwarted by bad weather so  when
a window of 3 good days appeared this spring he was ready  to  go.  He  also
wanted to come in from Fish Lake going over Cathedral Pass to  pick  up  The
Citadel and Mons Venus on the way to Shovel Lake. Carla and  Franklin  would
join him on this route. Since I had already done those two peaks I  was  not
interested and would approach alone via  the  less  strenuous  Waptus  River
Trail. We would meet at the inlet to Shovel Lake where his  route  up  Bears
Breast started.

Saturday, June 12 - I was at the Waptus River TH (2400  ft)  all  packed  up
ready to go and filling out my  camping  permit  when  I  just  happened  to
glance at the reader board and notice a  not  altogether  obvious  old  sign
(probably from last summer) that stated:

"Hiker bridge over the Waptus River  is  washed  out.  The  only  access  to
Waptus Lake is via the 2 foot deep horse ford."

I couldn\'t believe my eyes. I had crossed the hiker bridge in  the  fall  of
2005 when I had climbed Mons  Venus  from  Spade  Lake.  It  was  a  massive
structure built on rock walls well above the river. It never occurred to  me
that it could be washed out. Well apparently it could be and  it  had  been.
What to do now? It was too late to  join  Stefan  on  his  way  in  and  the
alternate via Pete Lake and  the  PCT  involved  extra  elevation  and  snow
travel that I wasn\'t mentally prepared for. Despite the fact that I  have  a
great fear of river crossings and I was certain the  ford  would  be  deeper
than 2 feet this time of year, I decided to just go see for  myself.  Either
I could get across the river or I couldn\'t. I did add trail  shoes  to  hike
in and use for wading so my boots would stay dry.

The day was sunny and hot and I started in shorts. I hiked the  8  miles  to
the  ford,  crossing  many  high  side  creeks  on  the  way,  in   complete
uncertainty while in constant view of the  raging  Waptus  River.  How  ever
would I get to the other side? But when I came to the ford it looked  to  be
within the realm of possibility. It was  at  a  very  wide  (maybe  200  ft)
relatively shallow spot. I couldn\'t really tell how deep it was  but  I  was
sure it was over 2 feet. And while not white water the  current  was  swift.
What decided me to give it a try  was  a  sturdy  rope  strung  between  the
banks. Without that I don\'t think I would have attempted it. The  water  was
up to my crotch but with the rope for support I never felt close  to  losing
it. The water was cold but not unbearable. I  was  elated  when  I  made  it
across. Somehow I blocked out the fact that I would have to do it  again  on
the return. I would worry about that later.

I had striped to my underwear and continued hiking in  it  to  dry  it  out.
Much to my surprise I passed several campers along Waptus Lake.  However,  I
had run into horse packers coming out which would explain that.   I  wish  I
had met them at the crossing as I would have paid them big bucks to take  me
across. I continued on very wet trail sloshing through  all  the  water.  It
was really quite liberating not to have to worry about keeping my feet  dry.
I began running into the odd snow patch. I missed the  obscure  junction  to
the Shovel Lake way trail and ended up at the PCT  crossing  of  the  Waptus
River above Waptus Lake. This  bridge  is  intact.  At  that  point  I  just
wandered in the woods until I stumbled upon the way trail. I passed  a  nice
campsite at 3200 ft that I noted for possible use on the return and  stopped
to change into dry socks and boots and put my shorts on again.

The way trail steepened as it climbed a wooded rib beside Shovel Creek  then
ended as it dropped into the talus filled canyon. The  next  mile  was  slow
tedious rock hopping with unreliable snow patches to  the  outlet  waterfall
of Shovel lake. I rounded the waterfall on  the  right  and  entered  Shovel
Lake Basin. And just like that I went from summer  to  winter.  Up  to  this
point it had been sunny and hot and I was still comfortable in  shorts.  The
lake is only 4138 ft and I had hoped for  at  the  very  least  a  few  bare
spots. But it  was  all  in  shade,  completely  snow  covered  and  like  a
refrigerator. I hiked the remaining longer than it  looked  distance  around
the east shore to the designated meeting spot  at  the  inlet,  arriving  at
8:00 (14 miles, 3100 ft, 9:30 hrs). There was no sign of  the  rest  of  the
party. I began to get worried. I really thought they would beat me here.

Even though I knew our route started from the west side of the  inlet  creek
I could see no way across other than wading and by now I was much  too  cold
to attempt this. I quickly changed into warm clothes and set up my  tent  on
the east side. I was lamenting the  fact  that  I  had  forgotten  the  fuel
canister for my stove and was eating a cold dinner when much  to  my  relief
Stefan, Carla and Franklin showed up at 9:00, tired and wet. They too  could
see no way across the inlet creek. We would deal with that  problem  in  the
morning.

Sunday, June 13 - Our revised plan was to pack up camp, hike to the  outlet,
leave overnight gear there, cross  (there  was  a  snow  bridge  there)  and
backtrack on the west side of the lake to the route.  We  started  from  the
outlet at 7:45. The route up to the base of Bears Breast  went  quite  well.
Other than a couple of steep sections through short cliff bands, it was  all
on nice snow.

We reached the notch below the rock at 11:00. Here we spent  about  an  hour
basking in the sun, drying out boots and warming cold feet. Then Stefan  led
off in rock shoes. The rest of us were in boots. There was  much  rope  drag
and cursing on the first pitch. Frankln went next carrying the second  rope.
Then Carla went on a prusik on the fixed rope while Franklin belayed  Stefan
on the second pitch. By the time Carla belayed me up, Franklin was ready  to
go up the rope protected by an ascender. Then I was belayed on one rope  and
Carla on the other after me. Up to now I could  not  see  the  upper  route.
When I rounded the corner into  the  chimney  pitch,  I  gasped.  It  looked
frightfully steep and difficult. There was a small snow patch  at  the  base
and solid ice in the floor. The whole pitch gave me  trouble.  I  pulled  on
slings to get over a bulge and then got  stuck  in  the  chimney.  I  didn\'t
rotate soon enough and my pack got caught.  Somehow,  after  much  thrashing
and using all of my limited arm strength I  pulled  myself  through.  Easier
cracks continued to a rappel station. From here  we  unroped  and  scrambled
the remaining short distance to the summit at 2:45 (3100 ft, 7 hrs from  the
outlet).

Two double rappels got us back to the notch and much glissading back to  the
outlet and our overnight packs. It was now 6:30 and we  hoped  to  get  down
Shovel Creek to the nice camp at 3200 ft I noticed the day before.  This  we
did reaching it at 7:45 (6 miles, 3300 ft, 12:45 hrs total for the day).  It
is amazing the difference 1000 ft can  make.  Shovel  Lake  camp  was  solid
snow, cold and damp. This one was bare, warm  and  dry.  A  constant  breeze
even dried most of our gear, excepting the boots.

Monday, June 14 - More revisions.  Stefan had originally planned  to  return
to his car at Fish Lake via the PCT and Deep Lake, but none of  them  wanted
to slog uphill in snow. It would be snow free and shorter to return with  me
down the Waptus River Trail. I for one was delighted to  have  the  company.
Of course there was the "small" problem of  the  river  crossing.  I  really
expected the water level to be lower this time around. At  9:00  am  it  was
earlier and the day was cooler and cloudy, at least to start,  than  it  had
been on Saturday. Well it wasn\'t  lower.  In  fact  it  was  several  inches
higher coming almost to my waist and this time I felt the current trying  to
take me away and without that rope to hang onto,  it  very  well  may  have.
After that it was just a matter of hiking 8 long miles. Carla, Franklin  and
I reached the TH a little before 2:00 (12 miles, 1250 ft, 6:45 hrs),  Stefan
an hour earlier.

I then drove Stefan to his car. By the way, the road to Fish  Lake  is  full
of potholes and in terrible shape, the worst I have ever seen  it.  And  the
Scatter Creek ford was running quite high. It took 2 hours RT to  drive  the
11 miles.  We then stopped for well deserved burgers at Old #3 in Ronald.

This was the first extended trip I had taken with Carla and Franklin  and  I
greatly enjoyed their humor and company.

Total: 32 miles and 7600 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen



