            'tr' => '
McAlester Mtn (7928 ft - P888), McAlester  Quad  5  (7045  ft  -  P405)  and
Banshee Pk (7628 ft - P548) - McAlester Mtn Quad - June 22-24, 2010

Tuesday, June 22 - After a 4.5 hour drive I arrived at the  South  Cr  TH  at
1:30 to a large group assembling gear. Upon talking with the leader, a  very
nice young man from Mazama by the way, I learned this was an  Outward  Bound
party going up South Creek, over McAlester Mtn  and  out  Rennie  Creek.  My
experience with large groups has not been all that pleasant over the  years.
Upon expressing concern we might be occupying the  same  area  at  the  same
time, the leader assured me not to worry. They were out for 13  days,  would
get no farther than 3 miles up the trail the first day and would be  nowhere
near McAlester for several more days. They left before  I  did  but  I  soon
caught and passed them and then never saw them again. I must say  they  were
one of the quietest and best behaved large groups I have met.  But  I  still
think encountering 12 people off trail in  a  wilderness  rather  diminishes
that "Wilderness Experience" the Powers-That-Be are so  eager  to  otherwise
protect.

The South Creek Trail is very nice and well maintained and I enjoyed  hiking
easily along until I came to the first  major  side  creek.  I  saw  no  way
across without wading. Now I had brought trail shoes, thinking to  only  use
them in camp. Or maybe I had a premonition, though I really didn\'t  think  I
would have a problem crossing creeks on this trail. But it  is  not  like  I
haven\'t had experience with this of late. So I changed  to  trail  shoes  to
wade across. I had two more creeks to wade, one over my  knees  and  running
so fast it sought to push me  off  balance.  Fortunately  it  was  short.  I
sloshed the rest of the way in wet feet. I should be getting used to this.

I began running into snow in the woods just past the third crossing at  5000
ft but it became bare again when the trail switchbacked  up  an  open  south
facing hillside above South Creek. It was sunny and quite  warm.  Where  the
trail entered woods again near the creek  draining  Banshee\'s  south  slopes
snow reappeared but I found a nice bare campsite  just  big  enough  for  my
little tent near the creek, elev 5840 ft (6.5 miles, 2800 ft, 4:30  hrs).  I
am sure there are better sites available when all the snow is  gone.  I  had
plenty of time to have a leisurely dinner and enjoy a lovely evening.

Wednesday, June 23 - Starting at 7:00, I  was  able  to  follow  the  mostly
snowcovered trail all the way to South Pass. It  had  not  frozen  overnight
and the snow remained soft. From South Pass I climbed  the  north  ridge  to
Peak 7045 (1200 ft, 2 hrs) and continued down the south ridge to  the  broad
saddle with McAlester. I could see no  direct  route  to  McAlester  but  it
looked, from a distance, as if I  could  access  the  east  ridge  from  the
saddle with Gibbs. However, when I got closer I saw the  entire  saddle  was
guarded by large overhanging cornices with no  way  up.  My  only  hope  was
where the cornice thinned higher on the far right. This ended  up  the  crux
of the climb. The cornice here had lessened to a 5 foot  vertical  wall  but
was doable by chopping away at it for 15 minutes. Once on the ridge  it  was
easy going though the sight of overhanging cornices  was  both  breathtaking
and scary.

At the intersection of the east ridge with the south  ridge  the  route  was
bare rock to the false summit. A fun 25 minute  scramble  along  the  narrow
crest led to the true summit (2650 ft, 5:45 hr). Here  I  found  a  register
that looked suspiciously like one of mine but it had been placed by  copycat
Steve Fox in October, 2002.

I returned to the saddle with Peak 7045. I had thought I could  bypass  this
peak by contouring around but the distant view from McAlester  showed  cliff
bands and steep sidehill. It was  easier  to  go  over  the  top  again.  My
original plan was to return to camp and climb Banshee  from  there  tomorrow
morning. But it was still so early I decided to  continue  on  the  inviting
looking ridge that led from South Pass toward that peak. This  plan  started
out well but what I couldn\'t see was that Pt 6869 hid a 250 ft drop  on  the
other side and I couldn\'t follow  the  ridge  the  whole  way  due  to  rock
pinnacles and steep terrain. I had to make another  250  ft  drop  into  the
south basin. Still it was a very scenic and enjoyable route. From the  basin
easy snow slopes led to the SW ridge past the pinnacles. The  summit  itself
was bare so I built a cairn and left a register (5000 ft, 11:20 hrs).

The  day  had  started  sunny  but  had  clouded  up   by   afternoon   with
thunderheads. It threatened serious thundershowers all around me on the  way
up Banshee and I was quite worried (in fact I heard  one  place  in  Eastern
Washington had 6 inches of hail), but nothing ever materialized. I was  darn
lucky. By the time I returned to camp at 7:50 the sun was shining  again  (7
miles, 5000 ft, 12:50 hrs).

Thursday, June 24 - This morning dawned sunny and hot. I left for  the  easy
trip out at 8:30. About Â½ mile down  the  trail  the  tracks  of  many  feet
coming up suddenly appeared, but not before. The NOLS group must  have  left
the trail somewhere around here. I have no idea where they went and I  never
heard or saw them. As I said before they were  uncommonly  quiet.  My  trail
shoes had dried yesterday but my boots were soaked from  being  all  day  on
wet snow so I waded the three creeks in my boots and put on dry trail  shoes
for the rest of the trip out, a real luxury (6.5 miles, 3:30 hrs).

Total: 20 miles and 7800 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen





