            'title' => 'Riddle Pk (8200+ ft - P1120 - Pinnacle Mtn Quad), Johnson\'s Jonah (7689 ft - P449 - Holden Quad), Puzzle Pk (7660 ft - P460 - Stehekin Quad) and; North Star Mtn (8096 ft - P936) & Cloudy Pk (7915 ft - P195) - Suiattle Pass Quad - July 2-8, 2010',
            'tr' => '
Riddle Pk (8200+ ft - P1120 - Pinnacle Mtn Quad), Johnson\'s Jonah  (7689  ft
- P449 - Holden Quad), Puzzle Pk (7660 ft  -  P460  -  Stehekin  Quad)  and;
North Star Mtn (8096 ft - P936) & Cloudy Pk (7915  ft  -  P195)  -  Suiattle
Pass Quad - July 2-8, 2010

An annual extended 4th of July trip  to  the  Lake  Chelan  area  with  Jim,
Eileen and Beth seems to becoming a tradition. This year we were  joined  by
father/daughter Steve and Lisa Dittmar. The main event was for  5  days  but
both Beth and I lengthened our stay to pick up additional peaks.

Friday, July 2: Tenmile Pass - The trip did not  start  well  when  Jim  and
Eileen literally missed the boat. I won\'t embarrass them by explaining  why.
We remaining four took the Lady II and bus to Holden while  Jim  and  Eileen
scrambled for alternate transportation  via  float  plane.  Steve  and  Lisa
elected to wait for their delayed arrival in Holden while Beth and I  forged
on up the trail to Tenmile Pass. At the campsite at 4600 ft and the  end  of
maintained trail, Tenmile Cr was running too high to wade  but  we  found  a
nice log 15 minutes upstream. Traversing  back  downstream  once  across  we
intersected the way trail leading to the main  trail  at  5200  ft.  In  the
middle of the path at 5800 ft we found a note left by Stefan the day  before
giving his itinerary. I  had  prior  knowledge  he  would  be  in  the  area
climbing multiple summits and that we might run into him. We  soon  came  to
continuous snow but found bare ground for camping on the  ridge  just  above
6500 ft Tenmile Pass (5 miles, 3400 ft, 5:30 hrs).

Saturday, July 3, Morning: Johnson\'s Jonah - Beth and I figured  the  others
wouldn\'t arrive before noon, so we  headed  off  to  climb  Johnson\'s  Jonah
which we figured could be done in half a day. This turned out to be  a  very
enjoyable scramble along the ridge from Pt 7409,  not  as  difficult  as  it
appeared, and mostly class 2-3. We also got a  very  nice  view  of  Riddle,
which looked more difficult than  expected,  and  decided  the  easiest  way
appeared to be up the SW Ridge. When we arrived back  in  camp  at  2:15  (3
miles, 1900 ft, 5:40 hrs RT), the others had arrived and set  up  camp  next
to ours.

Saturday, July 3, Afternoon: Riddle Pk - The six of us  started  for  Riddle
at 2:45, climbing and traversing below the cliffs of the NW Ridge to the  SW
Ridge. A scramble up a loose gully led to a notch  where  Jim  discovered  a
nifty hidden ledge system on the other side that bypassed pinnacles.  Easier
terrain followed to the false summit with a final slightly  tricky  traverse
past a remnant cornice to the true summit. We spent 30 pleasant  minutes  on
top and not finding a register I left one of mine. Before leaving  we  heard
shouting from the Riddle Cr basin. That could only  be  the  incredible  Mr.
Feller who saw us silhouetted against the sky from his camp below.  We  were
back in camp by 8:30 for a prolonged communal dinner and  social  hour  (2.5
miles, 1800 ft, 5:45 hrs RT).

Sunday, July 4: Puzzle Pk - While the other three slept in, Jim, Beth and  I
started together at 7:00, they to do Flora and I to do  Puzzle.  I  had  run
out of time last year when I did Enigma and  Castle.  While  I  would  never
have made a special return trip just for this minor  peak,  it  gave  me  an
excuse to accompany my friends most of the  way  to  Flora  with  the  added
incentive of something new to climb. I have  done  everything  else  in  the
area.

We dropped from Tenmile Pass and traversed steep but  thankfully  soft  snow
to the basin below North and Main Riddle. Then came an  unpleasant  somewhat
brushy traverse taken at 5700 ft to gain the gully north  of  North  Riddle.
Jim  and  I  became  separated  from  Beth  on  this   section   and   heard
unintelligible shouting from below. When we connected once again  with  Beth
we discovered she had incredibly run into Stefan. He  was  on  his  way  out
intending to catch the boat today. I was really disappointed to have  missed
him.

We gained the gully easily climbing  to  the  7040  ft  Devore-Riddle  Pass,
dropped  on  the  other  side  several  hundred  feet  and  climbed  to  the
indistinct 7440 ft Riddle-Castle Pass. Here we  parted  company.  I  dropped
all the way to Castle Creek Basin at 6400 ft before beginning  a  long  flat
traverse past Enigma and scrambling very loose gullies to  the  saddle  with
Puzzle. Once on the narrow ridge it seemed to  take  forever  to  reach  the
summit. It didn\'t help that the weather was not  the  best.  Visibility  was
not bad but a truly icy and gusty wind threatened to blow me off the  ridge.
It was so cold I had to resort to climbing in my down jacket. I reached  the
summit at 2:15 (3600 ft, 7:10 hr).

Since it had taken much longer than anticipated on the  interminable  ridge,
I was sure Jim and Beth had beat me back to the Castle-Riddle Pass.  We  had
agree not to wait for each other. But we actually reached  the  pass  within
minutes of each other (what timing!)  and thus could  retreat  together.  We
all pulled into camp around 9:15, dead  tired  (10  miles,  6250  ft,  14:10
hrs). It had been a cold, windy and inhospitable place all  day  (and  still
was) and Steve and Lisa had decided to call it a trip  and  go  out.  I  was
sorry they left as I had looked forward to more  time  together.   But  they
seemed satisfied with Riddle and I sure can\'t blame them for not wanting  to
hang around camp in such conditions. We all ate  dinner  separately  in  the
shelter of our respective tents.

Monday, July 5: Black Tower Attempt - It has been said  that  summer  starts
July 5 around here.  Right  on  cue,  Nature  flipped  a  switch  and  after
yesterday\'s wintry blast, today started a string of  increasingly  warm  and
sunny days. Jim, Eileen and Beth decided to break camp  intending  to  spend
the night at the 4600 ft forest  camp  along  Tenmile  Cr  after  attempting
Black Tower. I, on the other hand, wanted one more camp  at  scenic  Tenmile
Pass. This, plus a general lack of energy by all but Eileen, led to  a  late
start of 10:30. We reached the way trail junction an hour later,  where  the
others left their overnight  gear,  and  then  continued  on  the  trail  to
Hilgard Pass. We were all blown away by the beauty of the  basin  below  the
pass which was ablaze with an endless field of  yellow  Glacier  Lilies.  We
vowed to return next year and camp in this lovely spot. We  reached  Hilgard
Pass at 2:30 from where we started for  Black  Tower.  We  had  intended  to
climb the easier route on the SW face but  somehow  ended  up  climbing  the
snow couloir to the notch on the South Ridge. The route from  this  side  is
more difficult. We did one scramble  pitch  followed  by  a  roped  class  5
pitch, led by Jim. Increasingly difficult scrambling  loomed  above  and  it
became clear we simply didn\'t have the time to do the route  and  so  pulled
the plug at 7:00. A double rope rappel got us back to the notch at 8:00  and
the trail junction at 9:45 where I left my friends to  plod  slowly  up  the
trail by headlamp reaching my camp at 11:15.

Total for day: 10 miles, 4150 ft, 12:45 hrs

Tuesday, July 6: Hart Lake - I awoke at 8:30 enjoying  my  scenic  spot  for
another gorgeous morning before  leisurely  packing  up  and  heading  down,
making Holden at 2:00 (5 miles,  150  ft,  3:30  hr).  I  had  a  refreshing
shower, changed to clean clothes and reorganized gear. Jim and  Eileen  were
long gone on the Lady Express but I did run into  Beth.  She  was  taking  a
rest day in Holden before climbing Martin. I probably should have  done  the
same as by the time I started up the trail to Hart  Lake  in  the  afternoon
heat at 4:00 I was positively dragging. In addition the heat brought  out  a
swarm  of  mosquitoes  that  had  been  kept  at  bay  previously  by   cold
temperatures. It was only 4.5 flat easy miles to  the  lake  but  I  was  so
tired it took much longer than it should have (4.5 miles, 800  ft,  3  hrs).
I began to worry if I would have enough energy left to climb any  peaks  the
next day. I hoped a good night\'s rest would work its magic.

Wednesday, July 7: North Star Mtn and Cloudy Pk - I did feel better  in  the
morning but not a whole lot. Resident deer had  awakened  me  several  times
wandering around camp during the night and despite  hanging  my  food  high,
savvy rodents had chewed a hole in my  food  bag.  Critters  conditioned  to
associating people with goodies are why I like  to  avoid  camping  in  well
established sites.

I had hoped to find a direct route to North Star, but as I continued up  the
trail all I saw was thick brush and cliffs.  I  was  beginning  to  think  I
would have go almost all the way to Cloudy Pass (5.5 miles from  Hart  Lake)
when I came to a talus slope at 5200 ft that offered  a  possible  route  up
saving a little distance. This it did but not without some  difficulties  of
brush, wet slabs and skirting waterfalls. Once  above  these  it  was  clear
sailing and I found renewed energy on easy snow to  the  final  scramble  up
North Star. There were two survey markers on  top  but  no  register.  North
Star is in the shadow of Bonanza and has a stunning view of the SW  side  of
this much higher peak.

From North Star I headed for Cloudy, but first I  had  to  get  through  the
cliffs of its South Ridge. I traversed a long way under them looking  for  a
weakness. I saw several places that might go later in  the  season  but  now
they were still capped by large cornices. In fact it occurred  to  me  there
was some danger from falling cornices on this very hot day and I moved  past
them as fast as I could. I eventually found a crossing on  rock  much  lower
down at 7400 ft and proceeded up the easy ridge to the  summit  block.  This
summit had an unexpected short  class  3/4  pitch  made  more  difficult  by
remnant snow. But the rock was good and the climbing fun.

I was now in position to quickly descend the gentle  open  south  slopes  of
Cloudy Pk to Lyman Lake where I picked up the trail. I returned to  my  camp
at Hart Lake at 7:30 after washing in the creek just before. All the  creeks
were running quite high by now but this is  such  a  well  maintained  trail
that crossings were always possible without  wading  or  getting  feet  wet.
Camp was occupied by several other parties, one of which had a huge  bonfire
going. Since it was still quite warm, I  assume  this  was  either  for  the
ambience or to keep bugs away. As for me I avoided  the  biting  insects  by
sealing myself in my tent (12.5 miles, 5050 ft, 11 hrs).

Thursday, July 8: Holden - Today was even hotter but I got  an  early  start
at 6:45 to beat the heat and bugs and because of this enjoyed the  hike  out
much more than the one in. I reached Holden in plenty of time to  clean  up,
check out the store and make the bus for the Lady Express  (4.5  miles,  250
ft, 2 hrs).

Grand total: 57 miles and 23,750 ft in 7 days

Fay Pullen



