            'tr' => '
Devils Pk (8081 ft - P881) and "Devils View" (7280+ ft -  P600)  -  Robinson
Mtn Quad - July 12-14, 2010

There has to be an easier way up Devils Pk but I sure didn\'t find it. It  is
certainly appropriately named as only the Devil would feel at home  on  this
evil looking peak of terrible scree, loose  rock,  endless  ridge  pinnacles
and multiple nasty gullies. A dusty  of  fresh  snow  making  for  wet  rock
didn\'t help either.

Monday, July 12: Camp on Robinson Cr  -  I  hiked  6.5  miles  on  the  easy
Robinson Cr trail to a pleasant camp at the edge of a meadow, elev 4800  ft.
The trail crosses Robinson Cr twice and Beauty  Cr  all  on  large  bridges.
However the first bridge has been damaged and horses are banned  from  using
it. I saw three large  peeled  logs  harvested  from  and  lying  in  nearby
forest, presumably to soon replace this bridge. I  was  just  glad  the  old
bridge was still usable by  foot  as  I  would  have  had  trouble  crossing
otherwise. The third crossing of Robinson Cr was by log  but  that  was  far
enough upstream it was no great  problem.  It  was  sunny  and  hot  when  I
started at 1:30 but a forecast marine push made its appearance  as  the  day
wore on and temperatures took a dive so that about halfway along  I  had  to
change to long pants and warmer clothes. It was also very windy and  by  the
time I put up my tent it was drizzling. I had hoped to scope out  the  route
up Devils Pk but the poor visibility precluded this so I turned in early.

Total for day: 6.5 miles, 2200 ft and 5 hrs

Tuesday, July 13: Devils Pk - I awoke at 5:30 to light  rain.  I  guess  the
marine push was stronger than expected as real precipitation  had  not  been
predicted. At least the wind had abated. It did stop raining but  everything
was now wet as I started at 8:00. I was also dismayed to see  a  dusting  of
fresh snow high up. I left the trail about .7 miles up trail  from  camp  at
an open meadow, elev 5100 ft, heading for the west  ridge.  The  meadow  was
topped by wet brush some of which I avoided by heading  into  trees  on  the
left. I was soon funneled into a loose  scree  gully  and  more  loose  open
scree slopes above that. I kept thinking it would get better. It didn\'t.  It
only got looser and steeper, the kind of scree where  for  every  two  steps
forward you fall back one.  It  was  not  difficult,  just  frustrating  and
exhausting. I reached the base of the cliffs at  11:40  and  now  the  "fun"
really started.

I basically had no knowledge of the  route.  Beckey\'s  description  of  "the
ascent (from the W side) does not appear  to  offer  technical  difficulties
but will include talus and broken rock slopes"  is  totally  useless  and  I
didn\'t believe it for a minute. All you have to do  is  look  at  the  close
contours on the map and you know there will be problems. I did read  the  TR
of Stefan\'s climb with Greg but he approached from Slate Pass  and  Robinson
Pass and ended up bypassing pinnacles by going up  from  the  basin  on  the
north, far from my approach. So  I  really  didn\'t  know  where  to  go  and
wandered all over the mountain trying to  find  a  way,  making  many  false
starts that dead ended.

What follows is a condensed version of the way I went (not  to  be  confused
with a "route"). From the highest point of  the  scree  I  entered  a  steep
gully via a narrow ledge and  followed  this  to  notch  1.  The  ridge  was
impassible. I descended a hundred feet or so and  traversed  into  the  next
gully going  to  notch  2  and  another  dead-end.  I  descended  again  and
traversed broken face rock to the ridge and the top of a  pinnacle  which  I
rappelled off of to notch 3 and more  frightful  impassable  pinnacles.  You
would think I would have learned by this time that the ridge didn\'t  go  and
to stay away from it. I descended again farther until I could  make  a  long
traverse into a final gully that led directly to  the  summit  (3600  ft,  7
hrs). I found the climbing  interesting  and  challenging  but  not  exactly
enjoyable. While it was mostly class 3, with maybe a  little  class  4  here
and there, and not above my comfort level, the rock  was  very  loose,  wet,
slick and did not inspire a lot of confidence. At some point I  knew  I  had
probably reached the point of no return. I could not easily reverse  what  I
had done and my best course of action was to  make  the  summit  to  find  a
better way down.

It was now 3:20 and I was worried about getting down. I  was  relieved  when
the SE ridge looked reasonable as a descent route but looking at the  map  I
knew I would run into problems in  the  steep  gullies  lower  down.  Things
actually went better than I expected. I found a gully that took me  most  of
the way down and only had to do two rappels on  my  100  ft  rope  near  the
bottom where it steepened. More loose gully - golly gosh but I  was  getting
sick of loose gullies - some forest, some brush, some meadow and I  stumbled
upon the trail at 6:30 (3 hrs from the summit).

Ten minutes later I was in camp where I discovered an  Outward  Bound  group
had set up housekeeping a few hundred feet from my tent.  I  can\'t  seem  to
escape these large groups. But again the leader was a very nice young  woman
from Mazama and we had a pleasant chat. She was interested in  my  climb  of
Devils Pk and although she had not climbed it herself  she  seemed  familiar
with its reputation and aware of some of the difficulties. She also told  me
to let her know if  the  group  bothered  me  or  made  too  much  noise.  I
appreciated that. As it turned out there was no problem. We  were  separated
by trees and I was close enough to the  creek  that  it  masked  any  noise.
Besides I was so tired I slept like the dead.

Total for day: 4 miles, 3600 ft and 10:30 hrs

Wednesday, July 14: "Devils View", Pk 7280+ - I really wanted  a  good  view
of Devils Pk and so climbed this peak on the other side  of  the  valley  to
get it. Okay, I admit that it being a new summit  was  an  added  incentive.
What a contrast this pleasant little peak was. The  weather  was  good,  the
brush dry and the green meadows  balm  for  my  eyes  (and  feet).  I  won\'t
mention the 1000 feet of brush I had to bash to get to the good  stuff,  but
that was minor in comparison to loose gullies (3 miles, 2500  ft,  5:30  hrs
RT from camp).

Trip Total: 20 miles and 8300 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen









