            'tr' => '
Stonesthrow Pk (5823 ft - P423 - Mt Skokomish Quad) - July 17-18, 2010

I accompanied Jim, Eileen and Jim A on a delightful trip to climb Mt  Stone.
 I had climbed Mt Stone (and Mt Skokomish) in August 1997 but  I  remembered
it as so enjoyable that I was looking forward to a repeat,  this  time  with
good company. Jim had also been up Stone but Eileen had  not.  As  an  added
incentive there was a smaller peak to the NW that I had not done.

We hiked the steep Putvin Trail to snowed in Lake of the Angels and  set  up
camp on the only flat snowfree strip of ground in the basin (4  miles,  3500
ft, 4.5 hrs). Almost immediately we were visited by a curious  family  of  5
goats. Two were adorable kids that kept us all entertained for  20  minutes.
Jim A stayed in camp while Jim, Eileen and I headed for Stone  at  3:45.  It
was every bit as much fun as  I  remembered.  The  rock  is  classic  pillow
basalt (that geologist Jim couldn\'t get enough of) and offers  some  of  the
best rock climbing in the Olympics. Unfortunately, by the  time  we  reached
the summit at 5:45 marine air had rolled in and views were restricted.  Even
so we hung out for a good thirty minutes reading the large  summit  register
and catching the occasional glimpse of the rugged ridge to the middle  peak.
We were back in camp by 8:00 for a merry dinner (1700 ft, 4:15 hrs RT).

The next morning dawned with an extremely heavy dew  but  clear  and  sunny.
After a leisurely breakfast, Jim Eileen and I headed  to  the  SW  ridge  of
Stone, I to get to Stonesthrow, the other two for the views. They  ended  up
climbing a pinnacle on the ridge while I looked for  way  off  it  into  the
valley to the west. The ridge is quite cliffy but I  found  a  steep  narrow
snowfinger leading down that I used crampons for. Once in the valley it  was
a walk up to the saddle with Stone and then easy snow slopes to  my  summit.
Near the saddle I hear shouting and saw Jim and Eileen  silhouetted  on  one
of the pinnacles. It looked quite impressive. I had a great view of  the  NW
side of Stone from my summit and I lounged  in  the  warm  sun  for  a  hour
enjoying it all. On the way back I took a more direct route over  the  ridge
that avoided the snowfinger but did require a 50 ft rappel  to  descend  the
other side to. I reached camp at 1:30, the others long gone (1800  ft,  4:40
hrs RT), and left at 2:30.

I was descending the Putvin trail about 30 minutes from the T, alone  in  my
thoughts, and having met no one  when  a  joyous  voice  broke  the  silence
calling my name. What the heck? Who should it be but  Erin  Reading.  I  had
heard she had taken a job in the Olympic National Park during the summer  as
a ranger but what are the odds that I would meet  her  on  this  trail?  She
knew I was on the trail as she had previously run into Jim  and  Eileen.  We
had a nice long chat. She was starting a several day patrol to Lake  of  the
Angels and on to Upper Lena Lake.  Her  pack  was  enormous.  She  mentioned
casually she was carrying a gallon of gas for the ranger cache at  the  Lake
(I didn\'t know they had one there) and was looking and hoping  for  logs  to
saw. Oh the enthusiasm of the young. She was also going to climb  Stone.  It
would have been great if she  had  been  one  day  earlier.  We  could  have
climbed together.

Trip out: 2:i5 hrs including chatting with Erin.

Total for trip: 13.5 miles and 7200 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen

