            'tr' => '
Mt Terror (8151 ft - P1911) and  Mt  Degenhardt  (8000+  ft  -  P280)  -  Mt
Challenger Quad -July 22-25, 2010

Jim and I hatched this last minute trip the  weekend  before  on  Mt  Stone.
Despite attempts at recruiting several others to join us, we had  no  takers
with only three days notice.  So it ended up just the two of us,  which  was
fine with me. I couldn\'t have had a better partner than Jim.

Thursday, July 22: To High Camp - The trip did not start well. With what  we
thought was a bomber forecast and not a mention of  precipitation  anywhere,
we were shocked when it started to drizzle just as we pulled packs from  the
car at the Goodall Cr TH. This can\'t last, we  reasoned.  Just  some  marine
air. Surely it will get better. It didn\'t. It only got worse. It  went  from
drizzle to light rain and soon  everything  including  the  plentiful  brush
(and us) was dripping wet.

The Goodall  Cr  trail  was  in  good  condition,  in  fact  better  than  I
remembered it from last year. At the end of the  old  road  where  the  main
"trail" turns off to Terror Basin (4 miles, 1200  ft,  2:15  hrs),  we  went
straight ahead on a faint path that was hard to  follow.  It  traversed  up,
dropped to cross a ravine, climbed steeply and then went up and down to  the
crossing of Terror Creek at 2000 ft. This short section took  an  additional
1.5 hrs of rough travel. The normal log was under  water  and  not  useable.
There were several alternative ones in the  vicinity.  We  chose  the  least
intimidating one about 10 minutes upstream.

The way trail up to The Barrier ridge  starts  right  from  the  normal  log
crossing. It is fairly easy to follow but very steep as it winds its way  up
through heavy brush and cliffs 1600 ft to the crest at 3600  ft.  This  took
another 2 hours. Once on the crest we thought  things  would  improve.  They
didn\'t. The trail mostly disappeared into thick brush only reappearing  here
and there and we were confronted with several very steep  very  slick  steps
and it seemed to take forever to make any forward progress. By now  we  were
both so wet we couldn\'t possibly get any wetter. Hitting snow at about  5200
ft added to the chill. After 3 more  hours  of  misery  (after  hitting  the
ridge) we broke out into open terrain but had no  visibility  in  thick  fog
and, running out of time (it was 8:15) and getting desperate for a place  to
camp, found a marginal site in the heather at  6000  ft  that  under  better
conditions would have been  less  than  ideal.  Under  these  conditions  it
looked pretty darn good. We most definitely did not want to camp on snow.  I
immediately took refuge in my bivy eating a cold sandwich  for  dinner.  For
me a hot water bottle to warm my chilled feet had a higher priority  than  a
warm meal.  Jim, on the other hand, braved the elements to  sit  around  the
stove eating and drinking and hoping for a better  day  tomorrow.  This  was
the low point of the trip. If things did not improve the next day,  we  were
screwed.

Total: 7 miles, 5700 ft and 9:40 hrs

Friday, July 23: Mt Degenhardt - We awoke to blue skies and sunshine.  Glory
be! We were saved. We spent the next several hours reorganizing and  hanging
wet clothes to dry before starting for Degenhardt at 8:45. We discovered  we
were camped on the edge of  The  Barrier  literally  a  few  feet  from  the
precipice with a grand view into Terror Basin.  As we climbed  to  the  6400
ft col between The Stump and The Barrier we  realized  that  our  choice  of
camp was not that bad and one of the  few  bare  spot  around  with  running
water close by. The col itself had several bivy sites but I didn\'t  see  any
obvious source of water.  From the col we could  look  into  Crescent  Creek
Basin and the heart of the Southern Pickets. All was  snow-covered  and  the
approach to both Terror and Degenhardt looked to be relatively simple.

We descended about 300 ft and traversed  beneath  The  Barrier  until  below
Degenhardt where we took a direct but quite steep line straight  up  to  the
notch just left of the summit horn on the north ridge. It  was  snow  almost
the whole way with only the last little bit  being  loose  rubble.  Here  we
roped up for a very enjoyable short pitch on  excellent  rock  to  a  rappel
sling. An easy but exposed ledge on the east led to  the  final  section  on
the south side and the summit (2700 ft, 5:30 hrs). We spent over a  glorious
hour on top before heading down  at  3:20.  Down  climbing  and  one  single
rappel got us off the rock. Not wanting to descend the  steep  snow  of  our
ascent route we traversed to the notch just below the East Ridge  of  Terror
where an easier gully put us back on the traverse to the  col.  We  returned
to camp at 7:00 where all our hung clothing had dried  nicely  and  spent  a
much more comfortable evening than the previous one. Degenhardt  turned  out
to be an unexpectedly pleasant and leisurely  paced  climb  for  us,  highly
recommended when the rubble is covered with snow.

Total: 4.5 miles, 3100 ft and 10:15 hrs.

Saturday, July 24: Mt Terror - We got a somewhat earlier  start  for  Terror
at 7:15 again starting in crampons. It was a repeat climb  to  the  col  and
down the other side to traverse this time to the base of the Terror  couloir
at 9:30 where we roped up. The couloir was continuous  firm  snow,  slightly
icy in places. About halfway up it constricted to less  than  10  feet  wide
with nasty deep moats on either  side.  Here  Jim  placed  our  one  picket,
although we continued to climb  simultaneously.  We  reached  the  notch  at
10:50.

At this point I kind of lost track of time as the  problem  of  gaining  the
rock became apparent. We could see the rappel anchor one pitch above us  but
had trouble figuring out how to get to it.  We  could  not  cross  the  moat
directly to the best rock. We spent at least an hour  trying  varying  other
options. First we found an entrance into the base of the moat  that  put  us
20 feet or so directly below the step across the moat,  but  the  rock  here
was unprotectable. Jim tried several other places nearby  with  no  success.
We were both getting discouraged and could feel Terror slipping away.  As  a
last resort Jim went farther to the right up a steep but  protectable  crack
and made it work. We were jubilant when we  reached  the  rappel  anchor.  A
second low class 5 pitch gave way to several hundred feet of blessedly  easy
class 2 scrambling which we almost ran up in a rush of impending success.

As we crossed below the false summit to the gully leading to the notch  with
the main summit, we were absolutely shocked  to  hear  another  human  voice
calling to us and saw a lone climber just  entering  the  gully  behind  us.
Where the heck did he come from? Incredibly Randy had come up that day  from
a camp at the ice lake in  Terror  Basin,  crossed  the  Barrier  high  near
Degenhardt, climbed the couloir without  crampons  and  scrambled  the  rock
above the notch unroped. He certainly put us to shame. We all  continued  on
the good rock of the final class 3-4 section to the summit arriving at  2:45
(2500 ft, 7:30 hrs). Randy was an unassuming guy who  seemed  to  think  his
solo feat was no big deal but he was as thrilled to be on the top of  Terror
as we were. He graciously took multiple summit photos  of  Jim  and  me.  We
stayed for most of an hour with Randy taking off before  us.  We  never  saw
him again.

We downclimbed to the class 5 section where 2 single rope rappels got us  to
the notch. We then carefully cramponed down the couloir, leaving the  picket
at the scary constriction for a belay. All the way we saw the heel  plunging
steps of Randy\'s descent. It was absolutely unbelievable to me that  he  was
able to do this. He was either incredibly bold  and  talented  or  had  zero
fear. Probably all three. As for Jim and me we breathed  a  sigh  of  relief
when we reached the bottom of the couloir. Two more  hours,  fueled  by  the
glow of success, put us  back  at  camp  at  8:10  where  we  celebrated  in
contentment until after dark.

Total: 4.5 miles, 2900 ft and 12:45 hrs

Sunday, July 25: Trip out - Neither Jim nor I were looking forward  to  this
day and I would have to say it was pretty much as bad as expected.  Although
all was dry, this was a very hot day and we suffered in the heat even  going
downhill and couldn\'t seem to drink enough. It was difficult to stay on  the
climber\'s trail and we kept  losing  it  in  the  brush.  We  did  find  the
critical start of the trail off the ridge which I had marked  with  my  GPS,
but it seemed even steeper on the descent than it had on the ascent  and  by
the time I reached Terror Cr my knees (and other body parts) were  beginning
to complain. We again had trouble sticking to the path past the crossing  to
the Goodall Cr Trail, which seemed like a virtual highway in comparison.  At
this point Jim went on ahead with my blessing to lessen the duration of  the
pain and I limped in somewhat after him to the TH at 3:50 (7 miles,  400  ft
and 8 hrs).  We salved our various aches with burgers at Good Food and  milk
shakes at Cascadian Farm.

Total for the Trip: 23 miles and 12,100 ft in 4 days

Fay Pullen



