            'title' => 'Cloudcomb Pk (8085 ft - P445) and Squaretop Mtn (8189 ft - P309) - Pyramid Mtn Quad - August 6-8, 2010',
            'tr' => '
Cloudcomb Pk (8085 ft - P445) and Squaretop Mtn (8189 ft - P309)  -  Pyramid
Mtn Quad - August 6-8, 2010

With a good forecast for Friday but  a  dismal  one  for  the  weekend  most
areas, I had to scramble at the last minute to find a suitable objective.  I
wanted to go to the Entiat where  the  forecast  was  good  to  about  2  pm
Saturday, but Hwy 97A was closed between  Wenatchee  and  Entiat  due  to  a
mudslide from recent thundershower activity.  Upon  hearing  Friday  morning
it had reopened, that is where I headed.

Friday, August 6: Pugh Ridge - From the North Fork Entiat TH at 3900  ft,  I
elected to approach  via  the  scenic  Pugh  Ridge  Trail,  even  though  it
entailed extra elevation gain over going up South Pyramid Creek. I  was  not
disappointed with my choice as once on this  lovely  ridge  the  views  were
marvelous. I dropped off the ridge into  the  headwaters  of  South  Pyramid
Creek, passed luxurious Buck Camp on trail and headed cross-country  to  the
basin south of Pt 7378 where  I  had  my  choice  of  dozens  of  delightful
campsites. A crystal clear  creek  meandered  nearby  through  lovely  green
meadows.

Total: 8.5 miles, 3500 ft, 6 hrs

Saturday, August 7: Cloudcomb Pk - I got an early start at  6:30  hoping  to
beat the coming rain. Things didn\'t go exactly as planned. I  headed  toward
the ridge between Squaretop and (north of) Pt 8000, but when  it  came  into
view I saw cliffs would make access difficult so I did an abrupt right  turn
to the ridge between (south of) Pt 8000 and Pyramid. Up to now  I  had  been
questioning lugging crampons and ice  axe  along  as  I  had  seen  no  snow
anywhere on my route. However, my decision was justified  as  I  topped  the
7920 ft col and saw continuous snow plunging down for  a  thousand  feet.  I
also got my first view of Cloudcomb. My first thought was my that is a  long
ways off and I would have to descend a long ways. My second thought was  how
in the heck was I going to get up this  thing.  It  was  all  pinnacles  and
cliffs and gullies. I studied the view and came up with a plan. I could  see
a ramp that traversed between cliff bands and would get me to a major  gully
that led to a notch south of the summit ridge. I knew I didn\'t  want  to  go
all the way to that notch. I  had  to  reach  another  notch  farther  north
adjacent to the summit pinnacle. I couldn\'t  see  an  obvious  way  to  this
notch, but hoped I could traverse out of the gully just below the ridge.

I cramponed down to the end of continuous snow,  stashed  crampons  and  axe
and traversed talus to the ramp I had seen.  This  led  below  cliffs  to  a
minor notch.  I  descended  a  short  ways  on  the  other  side,  traversed
(generally at 6800 ft) just below  cliffs  to  a  creek  gully,  crossed  to
another minor notch and entered the major gully I had seen from  afar.  This
gully varied from enjoyable  class  3  -3+  to  unpleasant  loose  class  2.
Wherever it had a steep step the rock was solid with good holds.  I  climbed
upward always intending to eventually veer right but I saw  no  obvious  way
out of the gully and terrain led me all the way to the south notch.  I  knew
I didn\'t want to be here and knew where I wanted to go but I  just  couldn\'t
get there.

I reached the notch (notch 1) at 10:45 (2500 ft, 4:15 hrs).  This  is  where
things fell apart. I was over .1 mile from the summit with  a  jagged  ridge
of pinnacles between me and it and no obvious way  to  get  there.  I  first
crossed to the west side and tried various routes but there  were  too  many
nasty gullies and ribs to cross. I did make it the ridge at a  higher  notch
(notch 2) but the ridge looked impossible. I retreated to notch 1 and  tried
a gully on the east side. It steepened to class 4 and I spied a  rap  sling.
Hope surged that I was on route. I  continued  to  the  ridge  where  things
looked vaguely familiar. I was back at notch 2.  I  had  wasted  2  hrs  and
gained nothing. The sling was not on route. It  was  placed  by  someone  as
confused as I was.

Whereas previously I had dismissed a ridge route I now looked  at  it  again
with different eyes. I was running out  of  options  and  time  and  getting
desperate. Adding to my worries the weather  was  beginning  to  deteriorate
and I was racing  the  coming  rain.  I  worked  my  way  along  the  ridge,
bypassing several pinnacles. The holds were good, mostly class 3 with a  few
class 4 moves but quite exposed and I will  admit  I  was  at  or  a  little
beyond my comfort level. And the uncertainty  of  my  route  with  the  real
possibility of getting stuck made me nervous. Eventually I came  to  a  deep
notch (notch 3) where I could see one  more  pinnacle  between  me  and  the
summit. I rappelled into the notch and again down  a  gully  until  I  could
traverse to the final notch (notch 4) below the summit tower. I  crossed  to
the west, circled around to a  minor  west  notch,  crossed  and  climbed  a
chimney to the summit just as it began to rain lightly (3200 ft, 7:15  hrs).
It was 1:45. I snapped a few foggy  pictures  and  left  a  register  before
quickly retreating.

My worry now was how to get off this thing. I was  able  to  down  climb  to
notch 4 as the rock was not yet  terribly  wet  or  slippery.  I  could  not
return along the ridge so continued down the gully from the  notch.  It  was
quite steep in places but again I was able to down climb. I traversed  right
as soon as I could once below cliffs of the summit pinnacles and  darned  if
a reasonable route didn\'t appear back my ascent gully. This  is  the  way  I
should have come up. It would have  saved  hours  but  I  did  not  see  the
correct line from below. It was now clear sailing  down  the  gully,  across
the traverse to the ramp, across the talus and up to the col. It rained  the
whole way but only lightly and since there was no brush, it was not bad  and
I did not get very wet although I did have  to  move  carefully.  I  reached
camp and my dry spacious tent at 7:30 (5 miles, 4900 ft, 13 hrs). It  rained
for several more hours.

Sunday, August 8: Squaretop Mtn - The rain had quit and there  were  patches
of blue so at 8:00 I was  off  to  climb  Squaretop.  After  yesterday  this
turned out to be a very pleasant little scramble in  comparison.  Just  easy
meandering  through  larch  meadows  and  up  heather  and  scree.  My  only
disappointment was that I had no good view of  Cloudcomb  from  the  summit.
Clouds and fog kept wafting up from Lake  Chelan  emphasizing  the  peak  is
aptly named. I stayed on top for well over an hour hoping for  clearing.  It
never came. On the way down I went over the  inviting  gentle  ridge  of  Pt
7378 (2 miles, 1600 ft, 3:40 hr RT).

I hiked out via South Pyramid Creek. This trail crosses South Pyramid  Creek
four times. The third crossing I had to wade.  I  was  also  surprised  this
trail had not been logged out yet whereas the  North  Fork  and  Pugh  Ridge
Trails had (7.5 miles, 200 ft, 4:15 hrs).

Total: 23 miles and 10, 200 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen





