            'tr' => '
Mt Meany (6695 ft - P1895 - Mt Queets Quad); and  Mt  Christie  (6177  ft  -
P1777) & Pk 5448 (P448) - Mt Christie Quad - August 13-18, 2010

In 1998 I did the Skyline trail in 4 days  climbing  Zindorf,  Kimta,  Noyes
and Seattle on the way. I had run out of  time  for  Meany  and  had  always
wanted to return for it. Mt Christie was also on my wish list, so when  Paul
suggested this trip with Meany and Christie as the main  objectives,  I  was
all for it. Six days with just Paul and me! Now that would be an  adventure.
It actually worked out very well. I enjoyed Paul\'s company  and  his  humor.
He kept me entertained the whole time. I also appreciated his  attention  to
detail,  his  excellent  route  finding  skills  and  the   fact   that   he
accommodated my desire for a somewhat leisurely trip. I  am  sure  he  could
have done the whole thing faster and in less time  alone.  The  weather  was
sunny and very hot the whole time, until the last day.

Friday, August 13: Twelve Mile Camp -The first day we hiked the  North  Fork
Quinault River Trail to a very pleasant camp  on  the  river  at  Twelvemile
(11.4 miles, 2300 ft, 6:30 hrs).

Saturday, August 14: Low  Divide  and  Mt  Christie  -  The  second  day  we
continued up the North Fork Trail to a camp at Low Divide (4.6  miles,  1800
ft, 3:15 hrs) where we spent the next three nights. The  river  crossing  at
Sixteenmile Camp (inexplicably .7 miles from Twelvemile  Camp)  was  running
high and fast but fortunately a convenient large log was a few hundred  feet
upstream and fording was not necessary.

We arrived at Low Divide early enough  to  go  for  Mt  Christie.  From  Low
Divide we followed the rough Martins Lakes Trail  to  the  lower  basin  and
climbed a wide talus/snow gully to a 5560 ft notch on  the  ridge.  Here  we
had our first view of Christie. It is a very attractive mountain and  I  was
pleased to see the glacier was in good condition. From the notch we  dropped
about 150 feet (some looseness) to get onto the glacier. We donned  crampons
(probably not strictly needed) to get past an icy patch  and  climbed  to  a
6000 ft col on the East Ridge. Except for an annoying  patch  of  krummholz,
the ridge to the summit was easy and we were on top  at  4:30  (3000  ft,  4
hrs). Views were good except to the  SE  where  smoke  from  a  forest  fire
obscured the sky. I left a register. We would have  stayed  longer  but  for
the voracious mosquitoes. They chased us all the  way  back  to  camp  where
they were replaced by biting flies (6.5 miles, 3500 ft, 7 hrs RT).

Sunday, August 15: Mt Noyes and Mt Meany - We started for Meany at  7:30  by
taking the Skyline Trail about 3.5 miles to the high point at a creek. A  way
trail then led up and down on a traverse across meadows, talus and  snow  to
the 5480 ft notch in the ridge between Cougar Mtn  and  Mt  Noyes  (3  hrs).
From here, if only after Meany, it would be best to drop  300  feet  on  the
other side and climb back up  to  the  ridge  beyond  Noyes.  However,  Paul
wanted to also climb Noyes. I had already done this peak but was willing  to
repeat it.

Impenetrable krummholz right at the notch forced us onto the north slope  on
extremely loose unpleasant rock. Oddly I had no recollection  of  this  from
my previous ascent. Paul was very vocal as to his dislike of  this  section.
In fact he generally disliked Noyes so much he barely  stopped  long  enough
to acknowledge reaching the summit (4:40 hrs) before continuing on down  the
North Ridge toward Meany. This ridge proved just as  bad  with  some  tricky
moves and exposure thrown in for  good  measure.  We  lost  a  lot  of  time
climbing over Noyes.

Once at the low point in the ridge things improved and I began enjoying  the
scrambling. From a snow col to the right of the summit block we scrambled  a
short section along the ridge to the final steep section. We  roped  up  and
belayed this single pitch but the holds were good and it was  not  difficult
(maybe class 5.0). The solid rock of this pitch was  in  sharp  contrast  to
the loose shattered shale we had been encountering all  day.  Another  short
scramble above (again loose rock) and we were on the summit  at  3:00  (3850
ft, 7:30 hrs) where swarms of obnoxious flying insects made it difficult  to
take photos. There was a pill bottle register (in good shape)  with  only  2
entries since 1998 (one of which was Mike Torok\'s party) but  there  was  no
pencil so most likely there were more unrecorded ascents. In  order  to  fit
in my pencil I had to leave one of my registers.

We did one rappel and downclimbed everything else to the col.  Then  it  was
easy to the low point of the ridge where Paul had noticed a nice route  down
a rib (to get below steep snow) and into a gully  (some  looseness  but  not
too bad) until we were low enough to traverse below Noyes and climb back  up
to the Cougar-Noyes notch on snow.  This  way  was  infinitely  better  than
going over Noyes (1:15 hr from Meany col). It took an hour  from  the  notch
to the Skyline Trail and another 1.5 hours to reach a creek near  Low  Divide
where Paul had stashed a very much anticipated beer. I refreshed  myself  by
washing in the cold water. We pulled into camp at 8:00 (12  miles,  4700  ft
and 12:30 hrs).

Monday, August 16: Pk 5448 and Martins Lakes - We had thought  to  climb  Mt
Delabarre today but when we returned up the Martins Lakes Trail and  climbed
to the saddle between Pk 5448 and Christie, it just looked too far away  and
our ambition dwindled.  After our experience with the  ridge  between  Noyes
and Meany yesterday (this ridge was twice as long) we knew  it  would  be  a
mighty effort. We were tired and it  was  so  darn  hot  we  decided  to  be
satisfied with climbing Pk 5448 after which we meandered  to  Martins  Lakes
and spent over an hour cooling off in the water.  We  returned  to  camp  at
4:00 for a very leisurely day (7 miles, 2300 ft, 7:30 hrs).

Tuesday, August 17: Halfway House - Paul still had Mt Seattle  to  fit  into
his itinerary, so while I slept in and lounged around camp, he got up  early
and climbed the peak directly from Low Divide in 3.5 hrs RT. He  reported  it
as a nice route with no difficulties other than some  brush  at  the  start.
After his return, we packed up and left at noon making it to  Halfway  House
for the night (10.9 miles, 600 ft, 6 hrs)

Wednesday, August 18 - We hiked the remaining 5.1 miles to the  TH  arriving
at 10:00 (5.1 miles, 400 ft, 2:15 hrs.) after which  we  feed  our  famished
bodies hamburgers in Amanda Park and  further  entertained  ourselves  on  3
nearby little bumps. One (Higley Pk) had an  absolutely  delightful  Â½  mile
trail through lovely woods to the top. We still got home  at  a  respectable
hour.

Total for the Trip: 57.5 miles and 15,600 ft in 6 days

Fay Pullen

A note on bear wires: Low Divide has bear wires provided  but  the  resident
rodent population seems to have become proficient  in  climbing  the  wires.
The rodents are as much of a problem as the bears. They were  able  to  chew
into our stuff sacks each night to get to the food. If going to this area  I
recommend rodent proof (Kevlar) bags to hang food in.





