            'tr' => '
Mt Despair (7292 ft - P1852 - Damnation Pk Quad) - August 23-25, 2010

Unfinished business. I hate unfinished business and that is what Mt  Despair
was to me. I had failed miserably 3 weeks ago (July 30-August 1)  due  to  a
combination of unexpected bad weather  and  lousy  route  finding.  The  bad
weather was a deal breaker but even without that I doubt I could  have  made
it. I got hung up on cliffs descending into Triumph Cr valley  and  I  would
have run out of time in any event. I made it  to  Triumph  Pass  before  the
rain hit and it became clear I had to turn around. The return to my camp  on
Thornton Ridge in the rain and through impenetrable steep wet brush was  one
of the most miserable climbing experiences I have ever had (rivaled only  by
the wet approach to Mt Terror the week before). I vowed to return only  with
a foolproof forecast. I really didn\'t think I would get  to  it  this  year.
But when a 3 day stellar window appeared I  found  myself  trudging  up  the
Thornton Lakes trail once again.

This time my game plan changed. I do occasionally learn  from  my  mistakes.
Triumph Pass is the logical bivy site for a climb of Despair  but  I  really
didn\'t think I could carry a full  pack  over  the  rugged  terrain  to  get
there. I have trouble with heavy packs on difficult  moves.  Neither  did  I
think I could make it to Despair in one day from a camp  on  Thornton  Ridge
where I had camped before. I had Jim Brisbine\'s TR from 2006  when  he  took
18 hours to do just this. And I am slower than he is. My  new  plan  was  to
bivy as far as I could go before the horrible  steep  drop  to  Triumph  Cr.
This would save me several hours on summit day and most importantly put  off
the 1000 ft climb back to Thornton Ridge until the next day.

Monday, August 23 - From lower  Thornton  Lake,  I  followed  the  climber\'s
trail up onto the lovely open broad east spur leading to Thornton Ridge  and
along the main ridge, up and down, to the saddle at 6120  ft.  From  here  I
descended on the other side, steeply  at  first,  and  traversed  below  the
cliffs of Thornton Peak. This being my 4th time here (2 for  Triumph  and  2
for Despair) I pretty much have the route dialed. I have found  it  best  to
stay high just below the cliffs or snow remnants to avoid steep heather  and
brush as much as possible and to cross a very annoying loose erosion  gully.
This traverse is tedious, slow and unpleasant when snow is gone.  Once  past
the loose gully I began looking for a bivy  site  but  had  trouble  finding
anything remotely suitable. It  was  all  steep  slopes  and  talus.  I  was
beginning to think I would end up sleeping sitting sandwiched between  rocks
when I spied a reasonably flat boulder that would do nicely.  It  had  a  10
foot drop off the end so I tied my bivy to shrubs  to  prevent  falling  off
during the night but other than that it was really quite comfortable. I  had
a great view and there was even a small creek for water nearby  (8.5  miles,
4800 ft, 8 hrs).

Tuesday, August 24 - I left my bivy at 6:45  and  plunged  downhill  at  the
bottom of the last talus field. I did not  cross  the  creek  of  the  usual
route. I was funneled into a watercourse slot that gave a  way  through  the
brush. This was how I went on my failed attempt and it was reasonable  going
until I hit a final cliff at 4500 ft. Previously I  had  exited  to  skier\'s
right to get into the creek gully and  this  is  where  I  got  hung  up  on
waterfalls and cliffs. This time I exited to the left.  It  was  very  steep
forest and brush but I had branches to hang onto as I lowered myself  and  I
was at the bottom at 7:50. I traversed at 4300 ft at the base of  the  cliff
and past the waterfall creek of my previous drama. All in all not too bad  a
way to go. I had to drop farther than the regular route but once down I  was
on easy terrain the rest of the way  to  Triumph  Pass  (5480  ft)  which  I
reached at 9:10. My oh my but Despair still looked a long way away from  the
Pass.

I donned crampons for the snow descent to the 4800 ft lake where I  followed
fresh bear tracks around the shore to the moraine at the  far  end.  Here  I
climbed alongside a deep gully until I could cross at about 5300 ft. I  then
began a long  mostly  level  traverse  through  lovely  terrain  of  heather
benches, talus and numerous creek gullies. I really enjoyed  this  traverse.
I then dropped a bit to a sparkling tarn  at  5100  ft.  I  couldn\'t  resist
taking a 20 minute break to soak my feet. I  left  the  tarn  at  11:55  and
climbed up a heather slope, talus  and  some  snow  to  the  cliff  band  on
Despair\'s SE face at 6600 ft reaching it at 1:15.  I  spied  a  weakness  in
this band on the far left and traversed to  steep  heather.  I  was  feeling
really good and thought I would soon be on top  but  this  scramble  section
took longer than anticipated. It was not difficult but it  was  quite  steep
and I moved with care as I zigged and  zagged  on  ledges  across  the  face
avoiding remnant snow and seeking out the easiest route. At the base of  the
summit block I scrambled up the only  way  that  seemed  possible,  a  short
class 4 dihedral. When I came to the top at the summit  ridge  and  found  a
rappel sling I knew I was on route. An easier scramble  on  the  other  side
led to the summit at 2:30 (4750 ft, 7:45 hrs).

An historic Trailblazer register in a waterproof case was placed  9/5/65  by
Cliff Lawson but he had included every known previous ascent  starting  with
the first in 1939. The staples had rusted out so the pages  were  all  loose
but otherwise they were in good condition. They were also out  of  order  so
while I perused them I put them back in order. I saw many familiar names.  I
found Jim Brisbine\'s entry for 7/28/06. Mine was the 6th  entry  after  his.
Despair seems to be climbed  on  average  once  or  twice  a  year.  Despite
getting concerned about the time I stayed  40  minutes  on  top.  It  was  a
gorgeous day with views to match.

I figured it would take almost as long to  return  as  it  had  to  come.  I
wasn\'t far off the mark. I rappelled the dihedral and downclimbed  all  else
reaching the tarn at 5:00, the lake at 6:25, Triumph Pass at  7:00  and  the
base of my cliff at 8:15. I pulled myself up on branches  through  200  feet
of cliffy woods on climber\'s right and entered my drainage slot just  as  it
got dark. The rest of the way was by headlamp. It  is  funny  how  different
things can look in the dark. There were times I swore I  was  in  the  wrong
place and had lost my way. I wasn\'t and I hadn\'t but it sure  seemed  harder
than in the daylight and slower too. But I eventually emerged from  my  slot
onto the talus where marking my camp with my GPS paid off in spades (I  will
never again not do that). I reached my bivy at 9:45 (8 miles,  6000  ft  and
15 hrs).

Wednesday, August 25 - I left at 9:40 taking 2 hours to climb to the  ridge,
and another 2.5 hours to reach Thornton Lake. No one was  around  so  I  was
able to strip to cool off on this very hot day. A final  climb  out  of  the
lake and the rest was all downhill. As I hiked out  I  was  cheered  by  the
thought that I would never again have  to  do  that  horrible  traverse  and
descent into Triumph Cr valley (8.5 miles, 2000 ft, 7:30 hrs)

Total: 25 miles and 12,750 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen



