            'title' => 'Silver Moon (8252 ft - P532), Wolf Head (8082 ft - P402) and Shelokum Mtn (8069 ft - P709) - Silver Star Mtn Quad - September 9-12, 2010',
            'tr' => '
Silver Moon (8252 ft - P532), Wolf Head (8082 ft - P402)  and  Shelokum  Mtn
(8069 ft - P709) - Silver Star Mtn Quad - September 9-12, 2010

I knew Roy McMurtrey had climbed Silver Moon from Cedar  Creek  and  he  and
Don Duncan had climbed Wolf Head from Wolf Creek  earlier  this  summer  but
details were lacking. I knew nothing at all  about  Shelokum.  I  wanted  to
climb all three from Cedar Creek. I wasn\'t sure I could do it but I  had  to
try. I really  enjoy  puzzling  out  routes  on  my  own  with  very  little
information and an uncertain outcome. It makes success all the sweeter.

Thursday, September 9: Camp on W Fork Cedar Cr - The  weather  was  forecast
cool with showers through the period but it looked reasonable to me east  of
Washington Pass. When I arrived at the Cedar Creek TH it  was  partly  sunny
and warm. The trail was very good and well used to popular Cedar Falls  (1.7
miles), still good but less travelled thereafter with occasional brush  that
would only really be noticed if wet.  At 4700 ft I  found  a  nice  campsite
just before the trail crosses the West Fork. The sun had now  given  way  to
light sprinkles but I was able to set up my tent before things got too  wet.
It rained lightly the rest of the evening and night  (6.5  miles,  2000  ft,
4:20 hrs).

Friday, September 10: Wolf Head and Shelokum Mtn  -  It  was  still  raining
lightly when I awoke. I procrastinated, decided to start out anyway  and  by
the time I was ready to leave at 8:00 it magically stopped and the sun  soon
came out. I continued on the Cedar  Creek  trail  intending  to  follow  the
South Fork to the basin below Wolf Head once  the  trail  crossed  the  main
Cedar Creek. I ended up staying with the trail all the way to 5800 ft  as  I
saw nowhere appealing to leave it. At that point I had to  leave  it  as  it
headed up a break in cliffs to Abernathy Pass. I spent the next hour  and  a
half traversing above the South Fork through very unpleasant and  still  wet
brush until I emerged onto open terrain.  Here I was dismayed  by  my  first
view of Wolf Head. It presented as continuous slabby cliff with  no  obvious
easy scramble route. This was going to take some time to puzzle out  a  way.
I wasn\'t even sure I would be able to climb it from this side.

I made better progress on talus and through larch groves, crossed the  South
Fork and climbed a short headwall to a talus/scree slope beneath the  cliffs
and above Lamont Lake. I spied a weakness in the  cliffs  on  the  left  and
headed up. It was 12:25 and I was already worried about time. I knew  I  was
too far left but that seemed the only reasonable way to go. I worked my  way
up and when encountering impassible cliffs went  right.  I  always  found  a
scramble route though a few moves verged on class 4. I  reached  the  summit
at 2:40 (3800 ft, 6:40 hrs) where I found Don  and  Roy\'s  record  of  their
ascent in a plastic bag. I removed the paper and added it to the register  I
left.

I spent a pleasant 35 minutes eating lunch, basking in the  sun  and  trying
to dry out wet feet. Then it was off to Shelokum. Try as  I  might  I  could
come up with no alternative to descending the same way but it wasn\'t as  bad
as I thought it would be and I managed to stay on course. I thought I  would
have to drop all the way to the talus slope but I found  a  slightly  higher
traverse that went just below the 7320 ft saddle before climbing to  the  SE
ridge. I hoped I could climb the ridge all the way to the  summit.  I  could
not. After topping a false summit several pinnacles had to  be  bypassed  on
the left. A final loose gully led to the summit at 6:15  (5150  ft,  10  hrs
and 3 hrs from Wolf Head). I left another register.

From the summit I descended straight down a gully that continued  in  fairly
open forest all the way to the South Fork at 8:00. Once across the  creek  I
encountered the same horrible brush as in the  morning.  The  fact  that  it
wasn\'t wet anymore was offset by it now being  dark.  I  stumbled  onto  the
trail at 9:00 some 200 feet lower than where I had  left  it  and  staggered
into camp at 10:00 (9 miles, 5200 ft, 14 hrs).

Saturday, September 11: Silver Moon - I was still  hoping  to  climb  Silver
Moon and go out today. It  didn\'t  happen.  As  with  the  two  other  peaks
everything was harder and took longer than  expected.  Leaving  at  7:40,  I
traversed from camp heading for the NW Fork, crossed the creek   and  picked
up the way trail mentioned by Roy on the other  (N)side.  This  is  quite  a
good way trail though its beginning is a bit  obscure.  There  are  numerous
possibilities to camp in the NW Fork basin above 5800 ft.  I  think  I  made
the same mistake as Roy in getting too  high  too  soon  after  leaving  the
trail. I knew I needed to be farther  left  but  cliffs  prevented  me  from
getting there. I ended up climbing all the way to the base of  the  pinnacle
on the E ridge and having to make a sketchy  traverse  across  slabs  and  a
gully to get to the summit  gully.  I  had  to  make  one  short  rappel  to
accomplish  this.  Once  in  the  summit   gully   interesting   scrambling,
approaching class 4, on beautiful white slabs led to the false summit and  a
narrow exposed ridge to the true summit (3700 ft, 4:45).  I  confirmed  with
my clinometer that the far W point was higher than the small  pinnacle  with
boulders on top and I left my register there.

Worn out from my previous  strenuous  day  I  had  been  moving  slowly  all
morning. It was now 12:25 and clear to me that I would not have time to  get
out before dark and so made the decision to stay another  night.  With  that
in mind I enjoyed a  leisurely  hour  on  the  summit  enjoying  the  views,
especially gorgeous and rugged Silver Star Mtn. I was  not  looking  forward
to the descent. I had to find another way down as I  could  not  reverse  my
rappel.  I  essentially  went  straight  down  the  summit  gully  on  those
beautiful but treacherous white slabs. I  zigged  and  zagged  my  way  down
avoiding the steeper slabs by going to the sides  where  possible.  Lower  I
was funneled into boulders and finally a brushy water  course.  When  I  hit
the blessedly level and lovely meadows of the basin, I stopped at the  creek
to rest and soak aching feet for 30 minutes. I picked up the way  trail  and
followed it back to the main trail and then to camp at 5:00 (4  miles,  3850
ft, 9:30 hrs).

Sunday, September 12 - I awoke at 3:30 am to the sound of light rain  -  not
unexpected. Since I had gone to sleep at 7:00 the previous night I was  well
rested and so figured I might as well get up. I was packed and ready  to  go
by 4:25. It never really rained hard and I found the hike out on good  trail
half by headlamp, half by breaking daylight pleasant. I reached  the  TH  at
7:35 (6.5 miles, 150 ft, 3:10 hrs). I was able to stop  at  Cascadian  Farms
for my usual milkshake and box of blueberries (most likely the last  of  the
season) and still get home a little after 11:00  to  celebrate  my  birthday
with my family.

Total: 26 miles and 11,200 ft in 3.5 days

Fay Pullen

