            'tr' => '
Midnight Mtn (7595 ft - P835)  and  Abernathy  Ridge  (7855  ft  -  P335)  -
Midnight Mtn Quad - September 15-17, 2010

The continued unsettled weather had me looking for a mellow trip, mostly  on
trail with easy objectives close by that could be done  even  in  the  rain.
This trip fit the bill and even exceeded my expectations in  both  resulting
conditions and scenic quality.

Wednesday, September 15: Slate Lake - It is only 5 miles to Slate  lake  but
almost all the elevation (some 3600 ft) is gained in the first 3 making  for
one steep trail. The last 2 miles ramble up  and  down  along  a  delightful
ridge and around a spur before dropping slightly to  the  6645  ft  lake.  I
started in warm sunshine and shorts which gradually gave way to cool  clouds
and more clothing and finally drizzle and rain gear by the  time  I  reached
the lake at 6:30. I set up my tent in a nice site  nestled  in  a  grove  of
trees. It was the only one I found. Although it is a good trail, it  appears
to be lightly used. It rained lightly the rest of the night (5  miles,  4150
ft, 4:30 hrs).

Thursday, September 16 - Morning: Midnight Mtn - By  morning  the  rain  had
stopped and clearing begun. I started for Midnight Mtn at 8:30 by  wandering
down the lovely meadows of the  upper  Little  Slate  Cr  basin.  I  had  to
descend to about 6200 ft past cliffs to get  to  Little  Slate  Lake  outlet
creek where I picked up a way trail to that lake.  I  wandered  more  lovely
meadows above this lake until I could turn right and  climb  easily  to  the
summit of Midnight Mtn (1450 ft, 2 hrs). It remained  party  sunny  for  the
return to camp at 12:40 (4.5 miles, 1900 ft, 4 hrs RT).

Afternoon: Abernathy Ridge - I barely stopped at  camp  before  heading  out
again climbing the easy slope above the lake  to  the  saddle  south  of  Pk
7576. I traversed past this peak to the saddle on the NW  and  followed  the
ridge to the high point of Abernathy Ridge (1600 ft, 2 hrs). This is  a  fun
easy ridge  with  interesting  and  varied  terrain.  I  could  see  weather
approaching from the west and made it  to  the  summit  of  Pk  7576  (P376)
before it began to drizzle. I continued  on  to  PK  7195  (P395).  Although
neither of these peaks has 400 feet of  clean  prominence,  both  are  close
enough to catch my attention and  are  attractive  little  summits.  Shortly
after returning to camp, the drizzle turned to light rain (4.5  miles,  2650
ft, 4:30 hrs RT).

Friday, September 17 -  It  rained  moderately  all  night  so  I  was  very
surprised when once again it quit by morning and I had no rain for the  hike
out. However, the brush was wet so I still ended up with wet feet. Still,  I
could get used to this pattern of nightly rain and clearing during the  day.
I reached the TH at 11:30 (5 miles, 550 ft, 3 hrs).

Total: 19 miles and 9250 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen



