            'title' => 'Many Trails Pk (8241 ft - P921) & Trailblazer (8211 ft - P411) - Lost Pk Quad; and Pk 7452 (P412) - McLeod Mtn Quad - September 22-26, 2010',
            'tr' => '
Many Trails Pk (8241 ft - P921) & Trailblazer (8211 ft -  P411)  -  Lost  Pk
Quad; and Pk 7452 (P412) - McLeod Mtn Quad - September 22-26, 2010

I used Jim and Eileen\'s annual larch trip - a grand loop from  the  Robinson
Cr TH to the Monument Cr TH  -as  an  opportunity  to  climb  the  far  from
anywhere peaks of Many Trails and Trailblazer. Jim\'s main climbing goal  was
Lost Peak. Also joining the party were Kevin W, Kevin  K,  Maria,  Doug  and
Lisa (for the last 3 days). We  all  achieved  our  goals  despite  marginal
weather at times and a few adventures along the way.

Day 1 - Wednesday, September 22: Robinson Cr  TH  to  camp  on  Middle  Fork
Pasayten River - We began the trip in beautiful sunny warm  weather,  hiking
over Robinson Pass and dropping to a camp along  the  Pasayten  at  5000  ft
which we reached right at dusk. It rained lightly during the night.

Day total: 12.5 miles, 3750 ft and 7:45 hrs

Day 2 - Thursday, September 23: To camp east of Shellrock Pass  -  The  rain
stopped long enough to eat breakfast and pack up, then off  and  on  showers
occurred the rest of the day. We had a pleasant rain free  lunch  at  Fred\'s
Lake, more light rain climbing over Rolo Pass and dropping to Eureka Cr  and
 wind with snow flurries over Shellrock Pass. The  high  peaks  were  mostly
obscured by clouds and fog with the occasional tantalizing  view.  Kevin  W,
Kevin K and Doug had forged  ahead  hoping  to  pick  up  Blackcap  but  the
deteriorating weather caused them to give up on that idea. We found camp  at
6800 ft on the other side of Shellrock Pass, again at dusk. A short lull  in
the precipitation allowed us to eat dinner  outside  until  increasing  rain
and snow mixed chased everyone into their tents.

Day total: 11 miles, 4400 ft and 9:20 hrs

Day 3 - Friday, September 24: Trailblazer and Many Trails, camp on  Monument
Cr - We awoke to about an inch of new snow and brief blue  skies.  This  was
to be my summit day and I was encouraged by the seemingly good  weather.  It
was short lived. The party split into three groups.  The  guys  would  do  a
carry over Lost Pk planning to then drop straight down to  the  Monument  Cr
trail and up to a camp at Lake of the  Woods.  The  gals  would  follow  the
trail directly to Lake of the Woods. I was  on  my  own  planning  to  climb
Trailblazer and Many Trails and camp somewhere along Monument Cr,  hopefully
near the crossing by Clint\'s Cabin. I knew I wouldn\'t be able to make it  to
Lake of the Woods.

I took off first leaving my big pack at the Butte Pass  trail  junction  and
continuing on with a light day pack. I followed the trail  over  Butte  Pass
and a short ways down the other side until  I  could  traverse  to  a  small
tarn. From here I picked out my route up a gully and snow  covered  rock  to
the summit of Trailblazer (2000 ft, 3 hrs). I had some views on the  way  up
but the weather turned just as I reached the summit  and  was  so  miserable
with blowing snow that I could barely stay long enough to place a  register.
At that point I  seriously  considered  forgetting  about  Many  Trails  and
retreating. I still had time to make it to Lake of the  Woods  and  join  up
with the rest of the party. But the wind was so bad all I could think  about
was taking shelter from it, which happened to be on the side  of  the  ridge
opposite retreat and when I  spied  what  looked  like  a  reasonable  gully
leading down toward Johnny Lakes that is where I  headed  and  my  fate  was
sealed.

The gully was steep and slick with new wet snow. I soon came  to  a  section
that gave me enough concern that I did 3 short rappels off small trees  with
my 50 foot panic rope. Once past that I was able to find  a  scramble  route
the rest of the way down to Johnny Lakes where the  conditions  turned  more
hospitable. Johnny Lakes are lovely and I found myself wishing I could  stay
longer and camp. From the middle lake I began a long traverse  below  cliffs
and across a large gully until I could head up to the south  ridge  of  Many
Trails. Once on the crest it was an  easy  ridge  walk  to  the  high  point
although it seemed to take forever with numerous false  summits.  I  reached
the summit at 3:30 (3800 ft, 7 hrs).

It was no longer precipitating but the wind was as fierce as ever. I  needed
all my wind shells to block it. I quickly left a register  and  then  I  was
faced with the dilemma of how to retreat. It had taken 7 hours to  get  here
and wouldn\'t be all that much faster on the return.  I  considered  dropping
straight down the west slope to Ptarmigan Cr and picking up the trail  there
thinking it might be faster. But it looked so far  down  (I  would  have  to
drop to 5200 ft before climbing back up to 6900 ft  Butte  Pass)and  I  knew
from my experience with that  trail  while  climbing  Ptarmigan  Pk  several
years ago that is was very slow going with many logs and much  brush.  So  I
ended up just  reversing  my  route,  except  I  took  an  easier  route  up
Trailblazer south of my descent gully. This put me  on  Trailblazer\'s  south
ridge 300 feet below the summit. I was worried  about  finding  a  way  down
through the cliffs on the other side to the tarn but as luck would  have  it
I hit the ridge right at a reasonable gully. It was not pleasant but it  did
go. I was back to my pack at 8:30 needing my headlamp from the tarn on.

I still hoped to get to Clint\'s Cabin before  stopping  for  the  night  but
soon discovered the Monument Cr  Trail  in  this  section  is  difficult  to
impossible to follow in the dark. After losing it a few  times,  I  gave  up
when I found a perfect campsite near the creek at 9:30, elev 5800 ft. I  set
up my tent under clearing skies and by the light of a full moon.

Day Total: 10 miles, 5500 ft and 13 hrs

Day 4 - Saturday, September 25: Pk 7452, camp on Eureka Cr/Lost  River  -  I
awoke to a glorious day with glorious views. I hadn\'t  gotten  as  far  down
Monument Cr the night before as I had wanted so I was concerned I  would  be
late meeting up with the main party. The fact that the  trail  continued  to
be difficult to follow in daylight didn\'t help  the  situation.  I  lost  it
several times but always managed to find it again. I learned later that  the
others had trouble with the trail also. In fact Eileen  and  Maria  lost  it
completely and had their own adventure making  their  way  to  Lake  of  the
Woods. Once past the crossing near Clint\'s Cabin the trail  improved  and  I
had no more trouble with it other than the fact that it  climbed  2500  feet
to Pistol Pass.

Shortly past Pistol Pass I ran into Maria  relaxing  in  the  sun.  Jim  and
Eileen had left the trail at this point to climb Pistol  Peak  and  she  was
waiting for them. I learned that Lisa had made it to Lake of the  Woods  the
day before and she and the other guys  were  all  climbing  Lake  Pk  before
heading out. So I went from being  worried  about  holding  everyone  up  to
being at the head of the pack and even having time to run up  Pk  7452  (900
ft, 1:10 hr RT from trail) before the whole  party  came  together  for  the
masochistic 4000 ft descent to our last camp at the Eureka/Lost  confluence.
Not wanting to break the cycle we again had dinner in the dark, but  it  was
brightened by feelings of success, good company and a cheerful Eileen fire.

Day Total: 14 miles, 3700 ft and 11 hrs

Day 5 - Sunday, September 26: Monument Cr TH - Once again it  rained  during
the night and once again I packed a wet tent. But the short  leisurely  trip
out on good trail was sheer delight and a pleasant way to  end  a  wonderful
loop trip.

Day Total: 4 miles, 400 ft and 1:30 hrs

Total for trip: 51.5 miles and 17,750 ft in 5 days

Fay Pullen

