 Liberty Bell Mtn - Beckey Route (7720+ ft - P200) - Washington Pass Quad - October 1, 2010',
            'tr' => '
Big Kangaroo (8280+ ft - P1000) - Silver Star Quad - September 30, 2010

I started from the hairpin curve on Hwy 20 at 10:10  and  followed  the  way
trail to Kangaroo Pass about .6 miles to a clearing where I  could  traverse
to a crossing of Early Winters Creek.  Here I ran across an  extensive  area
of old airplane wreckage.  I  wonder  what  the  story  is  behind  this.  I
encountered moderate (and wet from heavy dew) brush for the next  1000  feet
or so before things began to open up. Eventually I ended  up  in  the  major
gully southwest of the summit. It steepened to a class 3 section  then  laid
back a bit but became very loose and unpleasant.

Approaching the summit rocks I crossed left into another gully topped  by  a
chockstone. Serious scrambling began here. I wiggled under  the  chockstone,
and climbed to the right above it on solid rock to the ridge  north  of  the
summit where there was a rappel  anchor.  I  crossed,  downclimbed  maybe  5
feet, traversed a short distance and climbed back to the ridge at  the  base
of the summit tower. Here I put on rock shoes and  roped  up.  An  easy  but
exposed ledge led to a spacious shelf below the final slab.  It  took  me  a
while to get up the nerve to make  the  unprotected  move  to  a  depression
midface where I was able to get  in  a  cam.  I  couldn\'t  quite  reach  the
slinged bolt on top so instead traversed right to the ridge and finished  au
cheval (5 hrs).

There was no room to stand on top so I  took  my  pictures  and  set  up  my
rappel sitting straddling the crest. I rappelled the  slab  and  downclimbed
the rest to the rap anchor on the  ridge  above  the  chockstone  where  one
rappel got me down to the gully below the chockstone. My  120  ft  rope  was
sufficient. The upper gully descent was very unpleasant with loose  rock.  I
followed a better line with less brush lower down and still  hit  the  creek
crossing right at the plane debris. I reached the car at 6:00.

Total: 3 miles, 3150 ft and 7:50 hrs



Liberty Bell Mtn - Beckey Route (7720+ ft - P200) - Washington Pass  Quad  -
October 1, 2010

I car camped at the Blue Lake TH and  had  it  all  to  myself  until  other
climbers started showing up beginning at 5:30 am. Jim and Eileen made  their
appearance promptly at the appointed hour of 9:00 and we were under  way  by
9:30. We followed the smooth Blue  Lake  Trail  1.6  miles  to  the  cairned
junction of the rough climber\'s trail to the Liberty  Bell  notch  which  we
reached at 11:40. Here we all changed to rock shoes and roped  up.  Although
the day was sunny and generally warm the notch itself was in the  shade  and
quite cold. The sun was just out of reach about halfway up the first  pitch.
I had to put on all the meager clothing I had  brought  along  in  order  to
stay warm while waiting for my turn to climb.

Jim led, followed by Eileen and I was last. The first pitch  traversed  easy
ledges to a rib and up this rib to a  spacious  belay  at  a  tree  below  a
chimney. While Jim was climbing another party of 3 showed up  at  the  notch
but there was never any conflict between our groups. They  were  just  ready
to start by the time I had finished the first pitch.

The second pitch went up a strenuous  (for  me)  chimney  and  a  series  of
cracks to a belay at the base of a moderate slab.

The third pitch went up the slab to a fixed pin below  a  short  wall,  then
went left on a finger tip traverse, right to  a  lieback  crack  on  another
slab and around a corner to another spacious belay at a tree.

The fourth pitch went across a shoulder to  the  base  of  the  white  slab.
Being of short stature I had some trouble  with  this  slab  as  I  couldn\'t
reach the key handhold at the top. I finally just  had  to  go  for  it  and
launch myself upward to reach for it.

Above the slab was a short easy class 4 bit at the top of which we left  the
ropes for the last easy scramble to the roomy summit (6:40 hrs).   The  view
was fantastic and we spent a glorious hour on top. I am not sure any  of  us
really believed we were actually finally on Liberty Bell  and  we  were  all
positively beaming. Success was sweet indeed. It had certainly been  a  long
time coming but well worth the wait.

We downclimbed to our ropes, did one single rappel over the white  slab  and
downclimbed easy slots and ledges to the rappel  bolts  directly  above  the
notch. These bolts (with chains attached) are on a  vertical  wall  above  a
wide but sloping and  very  exposed  ledge.  We  all  took  care  to  anchor
ourselves carefully as we set up the final double rope rappel to the  notch.
Two 50 m ropes just reach. There is also an intermediate  rap  station  half
way down for those with only one rope. We reached the notch at 6:15 and  the
car at 8:00 using headlamps for the last 30 minutes on the trail.

I found the Beckey Route to live up to its reputation. It is  a  challenging
and enjoyable route on solid rock with much  variety.  All  the  belays  are
spacious with room to relax, regroup and access packs without  the  fear  of
losing things. It is very popular for good reason.

Total: 4.5 miles, 2300 ft and 10:30 hrs.

We celebrated with a  gourmet  dinner  in  Mazama  before  crashing  at  the
Klipchuck campground. Jim and Eileen pulled out the next morning at 6:30  to
meet Mike Torok at 7:00 for a climb of Cutthroat. I (having already  climbed
Cutthroat) passed on joining them. I slept in  and  had  a  leisurely  drive
home stopping at the Washington Pass  Overlook  for  a  short  walk  and  at
Colonial Creek Campground for the delightful 4  mile  RT  trail  up  Thunder
Knob.

Fay Pullen





