            'tr' => '
Sheep Mtn (8274 ft - P2034) & Two Point Mtn (7955 ft - P795) -  Ashnola  Mtn
Quad; and Pk 7665 (P505 - Ashnola Pass Quad) - October 5-7, 2010

Most people climb Sheep Mtn from Canada. It is certainly shorter  that  way.
But I also wanted to climb Two  Point  Mtn  and  to  experience  the  lovely
terrain between Larch  Pass  and  Peeve  Pass.  Gorgeous  doesn\'t  begin  to
describe it this time of year with the larches in full color. It  is  simply
to die for.

Tuesday, October 5: Camp below Larch Pass - I started from  Billy  Goat  TH,
elev 4800 ft, at 11:15. The day was warm in the sun but icy  in  the  shade.
The trail was in excellent shape making for speedy travel except  for  those
previous muddy and now frozen sections  that  had  been  churned  by  recent
horse traffic to a minefield of deep divots. I climbed to  6600  Billy  Goat
Pass, dropped to 5500 ft Drake Creek, climbed to 6000 ft Three  Fools  Pass,
dropped to 5500 ft Diamond Creek and contoured several miles  before  making
the final climb to below Larch Pass. I had  to  backtrack  slightly  when  I
realized Larch Creek had dried up in the meadows below the pass. I  found  a
nice spot to camp at the last running water at 6:15, elev 6600 ft.

Day total:  12 miles, 3700 ft and 7 hrs

Wednesday, October 6: Sheep Mtn, Sand Ridge, Pk 7665 and Two Point Mtn  -  I
awoke in the dark and was ready to  go  at  7:15.  It  froze  overnight  but
warmed quickly during the 40 minutes to 7200 ft Larch  Pass  where  I  broke
out into welcome sunshine. From this point on I  was  in  heaven.  A  mostly
level traverse led to wide open McCall Gulch and 7500 ft  "McCall  Pass".  A
sign here listed Peeve Pass as 4 miles distance and Billy Goat  Pass  as  11
miles. I dropped 500 ft  into  stunning  larch  meadows  above  Timber  Wolf
Creek, climbed to 7300 ft on a  shoulder  of  aptly  named  Sand  Ridge  and
dropped to 6900 ft Peeve Pass. From the pass it was a  gentle  stroll,  with
some minor talus, to the broad summit of Sheep Mtn, which I reached  shortly
before noon (8 miles, 2800 ft, 4:40 hrs).

Sheep Mtn is a twofer. In addition to being on the Top 200 list it also  has
over 2000 feet of prominence. So despite being a gentle summit  it  commands
quite a view of the Pasayten highlands, which I  thoroughly  took  in  while
eating lunch. I improved a bit on the summit  cairn  and  added  a  register
before leaving at 12:25. On the way back I climbed  to  the  high  point  of
Sand Ridge becauseâ¦ well, because I cannot resist ridges. Then I had my  eye
on Pk 7665 across the way. It just looked so inviting  I  had  to  climb  it
also despite still wanting to get up Two Peak Mtn this day. I knew doing  so
it would be close for making the latter before dark.

I returned to Larch Pass at 5:30 where  I  picked  up  the  abandoned  trail
(shown on the USGS map but not GT) that goes  to  Dollar  Watch  Pass.  This
trail soon essentially ended at  a  camp  on  a  bench  so  I  just  climbed
straight uphill to the south ridge of Two Point East. The  main  summit  was
west along a rocky but easy ridge that I ran as fast  as  possible  arriving
on top just as the sun set. A glorious experience but not one  conducive  to
summit photos. Naturally I had to climb both points  of  Two  Point  Mtn  so
went over the east summit on the way down. I made a direct  descent  to  the
trail by headlamp. Despite being camped no more than a hundred  feet  or  so
off the trail I was happy I had marked it with my GPS. Everything  looks  so
different in the dark. I stumbled into camp at 8:05 glad  to  have  used  up
some of the hours of darkness.

Day Total: 19 miles, 5900 ft and 12:50 hrs.

Thursday, October 7 - All I had to do this day was hike out  so  I  took  it
leisurely just enjoying the scenery and  trail  hiking.  I  stopped  to  eat
lunch and soak tired feet at cute Two Bit Creek. I could have  done  without
the 1100 ft climb up to Billy Goat Pass but other than that  it  was  mostly
pleasant and I reached the TH at 3:00. I saw no one else the entire trip.

Day Total: - 12 miles, 1800 ft and 6 hrs

Trip Total: 43 miles and 11,400 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen

