            'tr' => '
Dollar Watch Mtn (7679 ft - P719), Ashnola Mtn (7780 ft  -  P300),  Pk  7330
(P410) and Quartz Mtn (7530 ft - P770) - Ashnola Mtn Quad -  October  12-14,
2010

I was so enchanted by the area I  visited  last  week  I  couldn\'t  wait  to
return. My main goals this time, besides just being in  heaven  once  again,
were Dollar Watch and Ashnola and I really wanted to  visit  Whistler  Basin
which looked so unreal on the map. There were several other  possible  peaks
if I had the time  and  energy,  most  notably  Quartz  Mtn.  This  one  was
doubtful as if anything it was farther away than Sheep. I  accomplished  all
my goals and then some but at a toll on my body.

Tuesday, October 12: Camp below Dollar Watch Pass -  I  again  started  from
the Billy Goat TH hiking over Billy Goat Pass and Three Fools  Pass  but  at
8.5 miles took Trail 451 to Dollar Watch Pass instead of the  one  to  Larch
Pass. The day was not as sunny as I had hoped and quite  chilly  but  I  had
plenty of clothes to keep me  warm.  I  had  also  switched  to  my  heavier
sleeping bag. There was a very nice camp at Tony Creek but I wanted  to  get
as far as possible so continued to just below  Dollar  Watch  Pass  where  I
found a scenic flat spot for my tent with water nearby at 5:30.

Day Total: 12 miles, 4100 ft and 7 hrs

Wednesday, October 13: Ashnola Mtn, Pk 7330 and  Quartz  Mtn  -  It  was  28
degrees and cloudy and so again quite chilly  when  I  started  at  7:00.  I
climbed the short distance to Dollar Watch Pass  and  descended  850  ft  to
cross the E Fork Pasayten River. I had hoped to take a higher traverse  into
upper McCall Gulch but XC travel was not appealing  and  it  was  easier  to
stick with the trail until it took a definite turn downhill  and  away  from
where I wanted to go. At this point I did strike out XC until  I  hit  Trail
548 higher up. I stuck with this trail until I hit open  terrain  with  easy
travel to the summit of Ashnola Mtn (5 miles, 1900 ft, 3:15 hrs).  From  the
summit I got the surreal view I was looking for into Whistler Basin.

Next up was Pk 7330 across Whistler Basin. Rather than follow the ridge  all
the way to Whistler Pass and an easy way down I opted for a  direct  descent
down a gully through cliffs, class 3 except for  one  class  4  move  off  a
ledge. Once in the mile wide basin I was in heaven again.  What  a  gorgeous
place! Camping would be superb. And water is no problem. Even this  time  of
year I crossed several small  running  creeks  and  even  marshy  areas.   I
strolled across the flat lower basin heading  for  the  saddle  east  of  Pk
7330, climbed the short steep rocky SE nose and  did  more  strolling  along
the gentle ridge to the high point (7 miles, 2300  ft,  5:15).  I  found  no
signs of a previous ascent so built a cairn for  my  register  while  eating
lunch.

I left Pk 7330 at 12:50 hoping to continue on to Quartz Mtn.  It  looked  an
awfully long ways away and I didn\'t know if I had time to make  it.  It  all
depended on if I could find the dotted trail shown on GT and what  condition
it was in. Well, I ran into it easily a short ways from the  saddle  and  it
was in excellent condition. Usually I  am  cursing  the  trail  builders  in
horse country that consider only horse travel and not foot travel and  think
nothing of adding unnecessary distance and elevation. This  time  I  blessed
the trail builders. The trail was an  almost  perfect  contour  beneath  the
slopes of Sand Ridge, flat and smooth, making for  swift  and  easy  travel.
Without such a trail I doubt I could have made Quartz. The day  had  finally
turned warm and sunny so much so that I  shed  to  shorts.  I  followed  the
trail past the junctions to Peeve  Pass  and  Quartz  Lake  until  below  SE
slopes where another XC stroll led to the summit, an  outcrop  of  rock  for
which the peak is named (12 miles, 3400 ft, 8 hrs).

I took a slightly more direct route down to  the  trail  to  return  beneath
Sand Ridge and across enchanting  upper  Whistler  Basin  to  Whistler  Pass
(16.5 miles, 4400 ft, 10:30  hrs).  A  cool  wind  and  lengthening  shadows
prompted adding warm clothes. I continued on trail to McCall  Pass  where  I
headed uphill to "Pk 7821". Why  climb  this  particular  bump  of  so  many
others on the ridge? Because  for  some  strange  reason  it  is  in  Beckey
despite having only 221 ft prominence and limited climbing appeal. Well,  it
did have a cute cairn and was a nice viewpoint - or it would  be  with  more
light. I reached the top at sunset (17.75 miles, 5000 ft, 11:15 hrs).

I now had to think about how the heck I would get  back  to  camp.  I  could
return on good tread via Trails 548 and 451 but this meant  dropping  to  at
least 6100 ft (more if I stayed entirely on trail) before climbing  to  6960
Dollar Watch Pass. Or I could take Trail 502 to Larch  Pass,  pretty  level,
and pick up the abandoned  trail  going  over  Two  Point  ridge.  This  was
shorter and involved climbing only about 400 feet but I wasn\'t sure I  could
follow this trail. To add to the mix my bad right leg, the one  I  broke  in
1997, was starting to bother me. This is not unusual as it has  bothered  me
off and on for years when I overdo, the result of damage  from  3  surgeries
to add and remove hardware to both the ankle and the knee. Well I would  say
I was certainly "overdoing" and my leg was  letting  me  know.  It  manifest
itself such that I was now beginning to have trouble  lifting  the  leg  and
bending the knee. That made going uphill difficult. So I reasoned  the  less
uphill the better and opted to return over Larch Pass.

At Larch Pass I picked up the abandoned trail by headlamp. My  progress  was
pitifully slow as I could now only step up with  my  left  leg.  But  I  was
pleased I was able to stick with the trail all the way to  Two  Point  ridge
and was even congratulating myself on that fact when I couldn\'t  find  where
it left the ridge and I was hit with a dose of reality. For  the  next  1.5
hours  I  wandered  in  the  wilderness  never  finding  the  trail   again,
descending to Tony Cr and making an unpleasant traverse around Two  Point  S
Ridge. Fortunately it was all downhill and downhill didn\'t bother my leg  as
much. But by the time  I  reached  camp  at  9:30  my  leg  was  essentially
nonfunctional.

Day Total: 22 miles, 5500 ft and 14:15 hrs

Thursday, October 14:  Dollar  Watch  Mtn  and  Pk  7455  (P392)  -  My  leg
recovered enough overnight to take  me  up  Dollar  Watch  Mtn  on  a  sunny
morning. A good trail the whole way. There was a nice  campsite  with  great
views on top but water would have to be carried. I  returned  to  camp  over
Peak 7655 just because it looked inviting and its  prominence  is  close  to
400 (3 miles, 1500 ft, 3 hrs RT).

I left at 11:30, had lunch at Diamond Cr and reached the  car  at  6:00.  My
leg lasted the trip out (12 miles, 1900 ft and 6:30 hrs).  Again  I  saw  no
one the whole time, not even at the TH.

Trip Total: 49 miles and 13,000 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen





