 Thursday, October 21: Golden Horn Revisted and Pt 7140',
            'tr' => '
 Holliway Mtn (8000+ ft - P600 - Washington  Pass  Quad)  -  October  19-21,
2010

Holliway is overshadowed by  loftier  neighbors  on  all  sides  -  Azurite,
Hardy, Golden Horn and Tower  -  and  probably  for  that  reason  is  often
overlooked and seldom climbed. It is also not that easy to  get  to.  Stefan
climbed it two years ago from Tower Cr. Roy approached last  week  by  going
up Swamp Cr to Methow  Pass.  Both  ways  are  shorter  than  my  choice  of
Cutthroat Pass but I didn\'t mind the extra distance and elevation. I  really
like the scenic PCT from Cutthroat Pass to Methow Pass. It is  an  excellent
trail with easy hiking. I saw no one  in  this  usually  popular  area  from
Cutthroat Pass on.

Tuesday, October 19: Camp in Snowy  Basin  -  I  hiked  the  10  miles  over
Cutthroat Pass, down to Granite  Pass  and  on  to  the  beautiful  spacious
campsite in the basin at the Snowy Lakes junction, elev 6200 ft.  The  views
were as spectacular as ever but the larch color was gone  with  most  having
lost all their needles. The day was warm enough for shorts in the sun and  I
had visions of setting up camp  in  the  comfort  of  sunshine  only  to  be
disappointed. In spite of  it  still  being  fairly  early,  the  basin  was
already in the shade when I arrived and you know what that means  this  time
of year - the temperature plummeted.

Day Total: - 10 miles, 2400 ft and 6 hrs.

Wednesday, October 29: Holliway Mtn - I started at 7:00 and was  treated  to
a gorgeous sunrise while hiking the mile to 6600 ft Methow Pass.  The  trail
then dropped 4 miles into perpetual shade to 4600 ft Wills  Camp  on  Golden
Cr. Here I left the trail and went up the left side of the  creek  intending
to go to Nugget Lakes. Easier said than done. I  began  in  reasonable  open
forest but soon found myself traversing  steep  brushy  sidehill  below  the
slabs mentioned by Roy. This was not fun. I gave up on the idea of going  to
the lakes and as soon as I felt I was past the slabs I headed on  an  upward
traverse to a gully that goes directly from  the  lakes  to  the  summit.  I
reached the edge of this gully and the first sunshine of the day  at  11:30.
Now things were looking up. The gully itself  was  slabby  and  loose  so  I
climbed on the rib to the left. Near the top I went  to  the  right  of  the
summit tower up a steepening gully and then left to the summit  cairn  (3900
ft, 6:30 hrs), mostly class 2 with maybe some class 3-3+ depending upon  the
exact route taken. No rope needed.

I dug in the summit cairn and found the original film can register  left  by
Dan Sjolseth and Cliff Lawson on their first ascent of July 3,  1981.  There
were no other names entered. I found this puzzling. I know personally  of  4
parties who have climbed this peak and surely there were others.  Were  none
of them able to find the register? It was  only  under  one  rock.  Then  it
occurred to me that perhaps there was a newer  register  that  everyone  had
signed that has since disappeared. I left the film can in the  same  spot  I
found it for historic reasons while adding my own register  well  buried  in
the center of the cairn.

I spent an hour basking in sunshine and views. I knew I would  soon  descend
into shade and would get back to  camp  well  after  dark.  But  I  was  not
worried. All I had to do was get to the PCT in daylight and I  could  easily
follow that to camp by headlamp. I went down the gully, or on  skiers  left,
directly to the lakes. The whole way was dominated by the sheer  north  wall
of Golden Horn looming ominously above. Slightly before hitting the lakes  I
entered shade. I had only a short distance to get around  the  eastern  lake
but as is often the case with mountains lakes the  shore  was  quite  steep.
And it was frozen and slippery. This was probably the  most  dangerous  part
of the whole climb as I traversed icy turf and  rock  above  deep  water.  I
could have used both crampons and ice axe. Fortunately it was  short  and  I
had brush to hang on to. The surface of both lakes had a thin layer of  ice.
I would venture a guess that this time of year the sun never shines in  this
deep dark hole and the temperature never gets above freezing.

Seeking a better way down I followed Golden Cr, first on the right  to  pass
a frozen slab waterfall, then on the left, then on the right and finally  on
the left again. I still ran into brush but it was better than my  up  route.
My only suggestion in hindsight as to route is to stick fairly close to  the
creek and cross as terrain dictates. I hit  Wills  Camp  and  the  trail  at
5:00. The 2000 ft up to Methow Pass took until  7:30  from  where  I  zipped
down to camp by the light of a full moon at 8:00.

Day Total: 14 miles, 6000 ft and 13 hrs

Thursday, October 21: Golden Horn Revisted and Pt 7140 -  This  was  another
beautiful day so I just couldn\'t leave without visiting Snowy  Lakes  again.
Well one thing led to another and another and another. At the lakes I  still
wasn\'t ready to leave so I decided to head up toward Golden Horn for a  view
of Holliway. Well I had to go almost to the summit  to  get  my  view  so  I
figured I might as well climb it again. Darned if  there  isn\'t  a  10  foot
sling now to hang onto on the final tower. That wasn\'t there when I  climbed
it the first time a few years ago. Sure  makes  it  a  lot  easier.  Anyway,
Golden Horn is a delightful scramble and it is also a fast descent with  all
that plungestepable scree. I was having  so much  fun  and  it  was  all  so
beautiful I prolonged it even more  by  rambling  the  inviting  ridge  from
Upper Snowy Lake to Pt 7140  above  Methow  Pass  before  making  a  beeline
straight down to camp (4 miles, 3000 ft, 5:30 RT).

My little side trip had taken longer than I had intended so I  didn\'t  break
camp until 2:45, which insured I would get to the TH after  dark.  Oh  well,
that is what headlamps are for (10 miles, 1000 ft, 4:20 hrs).

Trip Total: 38 miles and 12,400 ft in 3 days

As an added comment, the leg that shut down on me last trip  did  okay  this
time. I guess I didn\'t reach the threshold distance. Oh sure  it  still  had
twinges, as did other body parts, but  it  was  nothing  serious.  Just  the
usual aches and pains and everything still  functioned  reasonably  well.  I
can live with that.

Fay Pullen











