Finney Pk (5083 ft - P1643 - Finney Pk Quad) and Finicky Bluff (4120+  ft  -
P400 Gee Point Quad) - November 2010

I have tried 3 times to get up Finney.  I  first  tried  several  years  ago
after climbing Big Gee only to discover Rd 1735 blocked several  miles  from
the peak. I tried again June 26 of this year and found Rd 18 (I  drove  from
Darrington) blocked by a new slide before I could get to  any  access  roads
(it has since been fixed). In an attempt to salvage the day I went  straight
up from Rd 18 toward Harry Lk to the S Ridge. I  ran  into  horrible  brush.
Once on the ridge it was  nice  but  I  was  stopped  at  the  S  Pk  by  an
impassible notch and I did not have the time to find a way around it.

The third time was the charm. I drove up the higher access  road  because  I
also wanted to get Finicky. After about a mile  this  road  gets  rough  and
overgrown. I stopped after 3  miles  of  abusing  my  Jeep  although  it  is
probably possible to drive all the way to the end if you  don\'t  care  about
scratching your vehicle. Brush was horrible and very  wet  from  heavy  rain
the day before along the ridge from the end of the road.  Approach  from  Rd
1735 would be better if all you want is Finney. The ridge led to  cliffs  on
the west face of Finney. I traversed below these to the  notch  with  the  S
peak and went up the S Ridge from there. The  first  part  was  steep  mossy
class 3+ rock. Then it eased back to a  pleasant  ridge  scramble.  About  1
foot of snow was on top. I found a large  summit  register.  It  was  filled
with water but the paper was double wrapped in  plastic  inside  and  stayed
dry. It was placed in 2003. Surprisingly the  only  name  I  recognized  was
Fred Beavon from 8/03. Maybe others climbed it before  03  or  the  register
was under snow.

On the way back I also climbed Finicky Bluff.  Brushy  and  wooded  with  no
view it is a typical dumpster with nothing going for it but a cute name.

Total: 9 miles, 3440 ft and 8 hrs

Fay



