            'tr' => '
Klone Pk (6820 ft - P900) and Kelly Mtn (6760+ ft -  P480)  -  Silver  Falls
Quad - November 4-5, 2010

Thursday, November 4 - I drove up the Entiat River Road  past  Silver  Falls
and  took Rd 5605 some 7 miles to its end at the North Tommy  TH  which  was
completely snowfree despite being at 4500 ft. Elk season was still going  on
so I was somewhat surprised to find the parking lot  empty.  I  did  however
meet a pickup coming  down  the  narrow  road.  The  tough  looking  driver,
accompanied by an equally tough looking  dog,  did  not  appear  pleased  at
having to yield space for me to pass and did not return my wave. I was  glad
he was on his way out.

The North Tommy Trail is a designated motorcycle trail and although open  to
multiple use is obviously built mainly for these  machines.  It  is  smooth,
which I like, but it also has an annoyingly low grade and interminable  long
switchbacks that take forever to get anywhere. The first  part  to  Pt  5863
goes through a burn that is nicely reseeding with a thick  green  carpet  of
small pines. I took a pleasant rest in the sun on top of Pt 5863,  which  is
a good viewpoint with a couple of rough wooden seats. It also has a  strange
log platform about 10 feet square. I am not sure what this  was.  There  was
sparse snow to this point but descending the other side and  along  the  now
wooded up and down ridge its depth gradually increased. There were  numerous
footprints which I presumed to  be  mostly  from  previous  hunters.  I  had
planned to camp at a spot labeled "Three Creek Ridge Camp" on the  USGS  map
even hoping for amenities that hunter camps often  provide  such  as  rustic
shelters and furniture but I found no  sign  of  anything  there.  The  camp
either no longer exists or was buried under the now foot  plus  of  snow.  I
did, however, find a nice spot a short ways on under a tree that  was  level
and essentially snowfree.  There was no water though, so  I  would  have  to
melt snow.

Total: 7 miles, 2400 ft and 5 hrs

Friday, November 5: Kelly Mtn and Klone Pk - I had hoped for an early  start
but I slept like a rock and didn\'t awaken until  6:30,  somewhat  surprising
as I had turned in at 7:30 the night before. I have been sleeping  amazingly
well lately in the mountains. Come to think of it that has been  even  since
I switched to the NeoAir air mattress by Thermarest.  It  is  so  shockingly
comfortable it can lead to late starts. Of  course  a  toasty  sleeping  bag
also contributes.

Even so, I got going at 7:30, early enough to see the sunrise.  I  continued
on the trail following the beaten path. The  snow  quickly  got  deeper  and
although the tracks were old I could tell whoever made them had  now  donned
snowshoes. When the track left the trail near the saddle with Klone  Pk  and
headed for Kelly Mtn, it finally dawned on me  that  these  weren\'t  hunters
but peakbaggers like me. The track led all  the  way  to  the  summit.  What
luck! They saved me much postholing in the soft snow  as  I  did  not  bring
snowshoes. Anyone who knows me knows I  dislike  these  clumsy  contraptions
and I gambled I could do without them.

I returned to the saddle and darned if the  track  didn\'t  continue  up  the
trail and on to Klone Pk. These guys had the same plan as I and again I  had
no trailbreaking. Klone is an old lookout site. The  lookout  is  long  gone
but the foundation and the views remain. I still  had  visibility  into  the
heart of the Entiat but the  day  was  clouding  up,  a  sign  of  impending
weather. This is why I wanted an early start - to beat the incoming  weather
out. From the summit I went straight off the NE side taking a shortcut  back
to camp. Snow was quite deep here but it was downhill so no problem.  I  ran
across vestiges of the old abandoned trail that used  to  climb  steeply  up
this side. I reached camp at 11:00.

Total: 3.5 miles, 1500 ft and 3:30 hrs

On the way out I couldn\'t tolerate the long switchbacks anymore and  so  cut
them on snow where possible. This actually saved over a mile  of  trail  and
close to an hour of time. I left at noon, reached the car at  3:00  and  did
beat the weather (5.5 miles, 500 ft, 3  hrs).  The  parking  lot  was  still
empty.

Trip Total: 16 miles and 4400 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen



