            'tr' => '
Tyee Mtn (6654 ft - P574 - Tyee Mtn Quad); and  Pk  6998  (P1278),  Pk  6907
(P547), Cougar Mtn (6701 ft - P661), Ghost  Tree  Hill  (6522  ft  -  P442),
Whistling Pig Hill (6284 ft - P404) & Signal Pk (6920+ ft - P200)  -  Silver
Falls Quad - November 10-12, 2010

Wednesday, November 10: Tyee Mtn and Pk 6907 - My intention was to drive  up
the Mad River Road, FR 5700 and FR  5713  from  Ardenvoir  as  far  as  snow
allowed and ski from that point on, my main  goals  being  Tyee  Mtn  and  3
peaks on Tyee Ridge. I would camp out one night. Helped by  much  less  snow
than expected and  heavy  elk  hunter  traffic  making  tracks  I  was  very
surprised when I was able to drive all the way to  Tyee  Mtn  Lookout  (elev
6654). I was also a little disappointed as I really  wanted  to  ski  there,
although driving the final 3 miles on the  steep  narrow  road  in  my  Jeep
through 4-6 inches of new snow was an adventure in  itself.  After  checking
out the lookout I returned to the last switchback to park at  the  beginning
of the Tyee Ridge Trail, elev 6400 ft.

I now revised my plans. I had thought to access the peaks farther in  around
Cougar Meadow on another trip from the South Tommy Trail, but  since  I  was
able to drive so far I thought I could include them on this one if I took  3
days. I was prepared to do so. Weather wise this would probably  also  work.
Wednesday and Thursday were forecast sunny. Precipitation  was  to  come  in
Thursday evening but Friday was supposed to be nice once again.

What with the slow drive on snowy back roads and the side trip to Tyee  Mtn,
I didn\'t start on the trail until 12:30. I hoped to camp at  Boiling  Spring
5.5 miles away. I didn\'t want to have to melt snow for  water  if  I  didn\'t
have to. The Tyee  Ridge  Trail  is  built  for  motorcycles  and  would  be
excellent for skiing with a little more snow cover. As it was there was  not
quite enough, particularly at the beginning. The trail does a lot of up  and
down over several bumps on the ridge  and  a  few  of  the  steeper  rockier
sections I had to walk. Much of the ridge has dead  downed  trees  from  the
Tyee Fire of a few years back making most  off  trail  travel  difficult  on
skis. Conditions got better the farther I went.  At the closest point to  Pk
6907 I left skis and pack to easily hike up to  that  summit.  Since  I  was
running out of daylight I passed on Pk 6998 and Signal Peak on  the  way  in
planning on picking them up on the way out.

Darkness fell as I rounded Pt 6418. I expected the trail to  lead  right  to
Boiling Spring, as shown on all my maps. It did  not.  The  trail  has  been
rerouted. The South Tommy Junction is also not where shown  on  the  map.  I
was almost  all  the  way  to  the  saddle  below  Ghost  Tree  Hill  before
concluding I was completely bypassing the spring. I backtracked Â½  mile  and
found the old unmarked unmaintained trail leading to  Boiling  Spring,  elev
5960 ft. By the time I set up my full winter tent, found a way to get  water
from the spring without falling in and had dinner it  was  9:40  and  I  was
more than ready to turn in without further  entertainment.  Everything  just
takes longer in the dark and cold. And it did seem  unusually  cold.  Things
were freezing  instantly.  My  water  bottle  had  become  solid  slush  and
undrinkable until I added hot  water.  I  checked  my  thermometer  and  was
shocked to discover it read 7.7 degrees! I had a hard time believing at  the
time that it really was that cold especially since it  said  15  degrees  in
the morning. But I checked at home and the minimum recorded  in  the  memory
was 7.7 degrees so it was true. It was clear at  night  and  cloudy  in  the
morning and that could account for the rise in temperature. 7  degrees  ties
for the coldest night I have ever spent out.  By morning  my  water  bucket,
inside the tent, had frozen solid to 2 inches deep all around. Wherever  did
this cold come from? The forecast for the area was only  the  low  twenties.
However, I spent a toasty night in my winter bag with  down  parka,  booties
and hot water bottle to keep me warm.

Total: 7 miles, 1800 ft and 6:45 hrs

Thursday, November 11: Ghost Tree Hill, Cougar Mtn and Whistling Pig Hill  -
It is hard to get going when it is so cold and the  sun  isn\'t  shining.  It
took a while for my feet to warm up despite toe warmers in  my  boots.  From
camp I skied up a semi open slope that had the look of  an  old  fire  break
directly to Ghost Tree Saddle. There was enough snow  and  the  terrain  was
open enough that I could ski to the summit of Ghost Tree  Hill.  I  wondered
which of the many rime covered trees gave the hill its name.

I had a nice ski down to the saddle and  down  and  then  up  the  trail  to
Cougar Mtn. By the time I reached the summit the sun was out  and  I  had  a
pleasant lunch in its warmth. I half skied, half hiked down the N  ridge  to
Cougar Meadow where skiing was again good.  I  had  seen  from  Cougar  that
Whistling Pig Hill was all forested except for the very top  and  would  not
be skiable so I ditched skis a little below the meadow and hiked the  narrow
trail to Whistling Pig Meadow and on to  the  summit  arriving  at  2:40.  I
could see weather obscuring the Stuart Range and coming my way. Sure  enough
it began snowing on the way back to camp which I reached at 6:00. With  more
time on my hands I entertained myself with a video on my IPod  before  going
to sleep. It snowed 2-3 inches during the night and was very windy.

Total: 10 miles, 3100 ft and 9:30 hrs

Friday, November 12: Signal Pk and Pk 6998 - As predicted  the  morning  was
sunny although the sun did not reach me until I was ready to leave at  8:40.
It was also  much  warmer,  27  degrees,  the  wind  had  lessened  and  the
altimeter had dropped 200 ft, a significant rise in pressure. With  the  new
snow and wind much of my in track was obliterated but the skiing was  pretty
good. I was able to ski all the way to the  summit  of  Signal  Pk  on  open
terrain. Signal has two summits. Fortunately the SW is the higher as the  NE
peak is rocky and looked to be quite challenging.

I could also ski to the summit of Pk 6998, winding my way through a  ghostly
landscape of charred "broomstick"  trees.  Skiing  out  remained  reasonable
until the final mile or so  where  the  sun  had  already  melted  the  thin
snowcover on the south facing slopes to reveal rocks.  I  definitely  put  a
few new scratches on my skis. Good thing they were  an  old  pair.  It  took
much longer to get out than I had hoped  as  it  all  seemed  uphill  (maybe
because it was) and muscles unaccustomed to skiing, especially with a  heavy
pack, were getting tired. It probably wasn\'t the best idea to make my  first
ski trip of the season an overnight. At least I reached the car before  dark
(3:15).

Day Total: 7 miles, 2400 ft and 6:30 hrs

Trip    Total:    24     miles     and     7300     ft     in     3     days
                                                               Fay Pullen

