I had hoped to climb Pear Butte from Bumping Lake. I had  missed  this  peak
last winter on a ski tour to the area from White Pass. Well, it is  not  the
best idea to travel back roads  the  day  after  a  major  windstorm.  After
dodging much debris, numerous limbs and even sawing through one  small  tree
I was stopped dead by two large downed trees a very short way  up  the  Deep
Cr Road 1808 and a long way from Pear Butte.  What to do now? I wasn\'t  sure
but thought about  various  options  as  I  started  walking  up  the  road,
completely snowfree to start. Weather varied  from  cloudy  to  sun  breaks,
with fresh snow at higher elevations.

 I considered just going up Mt Aix  but  couldn\'t  get  excited  about  that
prospect. The road is officially closed and barricaded  slightly  after  the
Mt Aix TH. I was unaware of this. Then I ran into a horrible area  of  fresh
blowdown. Dozens of huge trees had come off the  steep  hillside  above  and
littered the road with an impenetrable mess. It probably took me 30  minutes
to get through that. After 3.5 miles I was  getting  discouraged  and  bored
with road walking and I was only half way to the end of  the  road.  It  was
clear I wouldn\'t have the time  or  patience  for  Pear  Butte.  So  at  the
crossing of Deep Cr (the bridge mostly intact) I changed goals  to  Pk  5810
and Miners Ridge. This went much better at the  start  than  the  steep  map
contours would indicate with small talus and nice  open  woods.  Then  where
the terrain moderated at a drainage I hit  a  large  several  acre  area  of
horrible blowblown where I think every tree in the vicinity came down  in  a
jumble of now snow covered debris. There was no way around it and I lost  an
hour in strenuous effort. Once past that it was  good  going  again  to  the
nondescript summit.

From Pk 5810 I descended easily to the saddle above  Granite  Lake,  crossed
Road 1809 and began a  rising  traverse  to  Miners  Ridge.  I  was  finally
starting to have fun and I enjoyed this peak. It was interesting terrain  as
I wound my way through minor cliffs, not brushy, had few blowdowns  and  the
upper part was good step kicking on snow. Then it threw me a curve  ball  as
the summit turned out to be a snowy rocky ridge  requiring  tricky  insecure
exposed moves the last 20-30 feet. Definitely class 4 under the  conditions.
I was not expecting this at all and had no rope along. I stuffed a  register
in a crack on top as daylight ended. Going down by headlamp was  even  worse
and quite nerve wracking. After that  I  followed  my  tracks  back  to  the
saddle and Granite Lake Road 1809 (a few more large blowdowns on  this  (but
nothing horrible) back to my car for what ended up being a  satisfying  loop
trip. No photos. Nothing to take a picture of.

Total: 11 miles, 3700 ft and 8:30 hrs

That is not the end. I thought I was being  so  clever  to  beat  the  storm
predicted for Wednesday to travel over Chinook Pass on Tuesday. In fact  the
pass was clear and easy going Tuesday morning. I  figured  they  would  most
likely close the pass on Wednesday.  But on the  return  I  discovered  they
had closed the pass at noon on Tuesday  in  ANTICIPATION  of  the  Wednesday
storm. I couldn\'t believe it. Tuesday night was still  clear  with  no  snow
coming down. What really annoyed me was  there  was  no  warning  they  were
going to do this. I passed the reader board in Enumclaw  that  usually  says
when the pass is closed and it was blank. I had no idea it was closed  until
I hit the barricade on the east side. I had to turn around  and  go  through
Yakima adding several hours to my drive time. I was not happy.      Fay

