Mt Finn (5280+ ft - P400 - Scenic Quad) - December 1, 2010

Somehow I had never gotten around to climbing this peak. When I  climbed  Mt
Sawyer and Tonga Ridge years ago I wasn\'t even  aware  that  it  existed.  I
thought it would make a fine ski trip. And so  it  would  with  better  snow
conditions and a shorter approach by being able to drive  part  way  up  the
Tonga Ridge Road. On this day I could get no farther than  the  RR  trestle,
the usual end of plowing, elev 1280 ft. From this point it is much  too  far
on the main road to make the top in a  day  trailbreaking  alone.  But  Road
6820 takes off from this point going up the north side  of  Tonga  Ridge.  I
had never been up this road before and had no idea what shape it was in  but
it looked more direct and I decided to give it a try.

As I was getting ready to start two tough dudes in a  Toyota  4X4  drove  up
and stopped to put on chains. That took them all  of  5  minutes.  Obviously
they had done this before many times.  It  usually  takes  me  at  least  30
minutes to put mine on. They then continued up the untracked road. I  wasn\'t
even tempted to follow in their tracks. I had enough  trouble  just  getting
my vehicle parked off the road right where I was and I sure didn\'t  want  to
chance getting stuck farther on.

Road 6820 is gated a short ways up, past the train tracks. The  road  is  in
good shape the whole way with a nice grade  for  skiing.  Unfortunately  the
snow was not as good as I had expected. It started as deep heavy slush  with
intermittent freezing rain crust in  open  areas  that  made  for  difficult
trailbraking. I was expecting deep snow but more powdery and not so wet  and
certainly not freezing rain way down here. The snow level must have shot  up
momentarily overnight. I knew right away that I would  get  out  well  after
dark - if I was even able to make it all the way to the top. Not  that  that
bothered me. I don\'t mind skiing roads by headlamp.

The snow improved a little as I got higher, thank heavens or I  never  would
have made it. Road 6820 is blocked by a mound just before  intersecting  the
main Tonga Ridge Road 6830 at 3880 ft (5 miles, 2700,4  hrs).  I  skied  the
short distance on the main road to Rd 310 and 1.3 miles on this spur to  the
Tonga Ridge TH (6.3 miles, 3200 ft, 5:20 hrs). Skiing  was  pretty  good  on
the trail. Where it started down off the ridge at the second saddle  I  left
it and headed for the summit of Mt  Finn  along  the  ridge.  The  snow  was
finally the powder  I  had  hoped  for  but  there  was  a  lot  of  it  and
trailbeaking slow. I emerged on top with no light left (8 miles, 4300 ft,  8
hrs).

The ski off Finn was very nice indeed as was  the  trail.  The  road  varied
from good to reasonable to awful. The problem was the freezing  rain  crust.
In places I could stay on top. Other times I broke through the  crust.  What
with these problems it took 2.5 hours to ski  down  the  road.  With  better
snow I bet it would take half that time and be a splendid run.

Total: 16 miles, 4450 ft and 12 hrs

Fay Pullen

