Bethel Ridge (6285 ft - P565 - Tieton Basin Quad) - December 4, 2010

When Stefan proposed skiing on Saturday I couldn\'t pass it up even though  I
was still worn out from my  12  hour  trailbreaking  marathon  the  previous
Wednesday. While we did have to do a little head scratching to come up  with
a suitable peak that neither of us had done before, this turned out to be  a
delightful trip.

We were able to drive 1.2 miles to 3200 ft up Road 1500,  which  leaves  Hwy
12 slightly past the junction of Tieton Road at the  end  of  Rimrock  Lake.
Here we came across three parked vehicles, one a truck  that  had  obviously
unloaded a snow cat. The cat track made skiing a breeze. It  was  almost  as
good as a groomed road. No trailbreaking for us this  day.  In  addition  we
saw signs of a wheeled vehicle continuing up the road. Sure enough  we  came
across this SUV, chains on all four wheels,  parked  at  4600  ft  some  3.5
miles farther on. That was some serious  4X4  snow  driving.   Interestingly
all four vehicles, this one and the three below, had out of state  licenses,
Idaho, Texas and Arizona. This resulted in endless speculation on  our  part
as to the reason and kept us entertained for much of the way up.

Bethel Ridge is an interesting  long  flat  ridge  with  a  cliffy  southern
escarpment. Due to rocks and light snow cover we could  not  take  a  direct
shortcut to the summit (at least on skis) and  had  to  stick  to  the  road
which hits the crest well east of the top. By this time we were so close  we
decided to visit the tower and see what the story  was.  We  sure  surprised
the guys working there. There were six of them and  they  were  doing  major
repairs/renovations to the communication tower. Five were tower  contractors
from out of state. Due to  snafus  in  planning  and  obtaining  the  needed
equipment they were running late in their schedule and  got  caught  by  the
snow. They then had to bring in another guy from Idaho  with  the  cat.  The
cat only held 5 in the cab. The sixth had to sit outside in the  back  cargo
area, which looked very uncomfortable and cold to me. He drove up as far  as
possible in his 4X4 to lessen his time in the cat. They  came  up  each  day
and stayed the night in either Yakima or Packwood.

After our visit, we left the road and skied along  the  flat  ridge  to  the
summit about 0.75 miles away (9 miles, 3400 ft, 4:40 hrs). The  snow  here  was
very nice and trailbreaking easy. The temperature was 19 degrees.  While  on
the summit Stefan discovered his favorite  hat  was  missing  and  while  he
backtracked to find it I started down. I found a skiable  shortcut  slightly
to the east directly down to the road below. I cut several more  switchbacks
with some decent skiing before having to the stick to the road the  rest  of
the way. The road was a good grade for skiing despite the  cat  track  being
quite fast. I could either snowplow or go into powder on the shoulder  if  I
had to slow down. It was really a very pleasant run down.  Just  before  the
car Stefan caught up to me. He had found his hat.  We  reached  the  car  at
4:15 with no headlamps required. I was in danger of  ruining  my  reputation
for late night returns. Stefan had even warned his wife not  to  expect  him
until very late as my last trip I hadn\'t gotten home  until  midnight.  This
time even with the long drive we were both back by 7:30. What  a  difference
snow conditions  can  make.  This  trip  was  about  the  same  distance  as
Wednesday\'s but took half the time.

Total: 15 miles, 3400 ft 6:30 hrs

Fay Pullen



