Round Mtn (5700 ft - P260 - Lake Wenatchee Quad) - December 9, 2010

Credit Don and Natala for giving me the idea to ski up this peak.  They  did
it on snowshoes  on  November  27.  Somehow  I  talked  Karen  Daubert  into
accompanying me. I\'m not sure she knew what she was getting into  but  I  am
grateful she came along as without her  help  trailbreaking  I  never  would
have made it. And she was great company. She was on heavy alpine gear  while
I used my usual light three-pin skis.

Don and Natala were able to drive 3.5 miles up Road  1690  to  3400  ft.  No
such luck for us. We got less than a mile (elev 2160 ft), as far as  it  was
plowed to homes, and had to squeeze in on the side of the road to  park  out
of the way. Trailbreaking was difficult right from the start  and  only  got
worse as we got higher. The snow was that  awful  Cascade  concrete  we  all
know and "love" - as wet and heavy as it could  possibly  be  without  being
liquid. It snowed most of the day, quite heavily at times.

It took us 3 hours to go the 4 miles to the Round Mtn TH at 3960 ft.  I  had
hoped things would improve once on the trail. They  didn\'t.  They  only  got
worse as the snow got deeper and deeper.  It was only  1.5  miles  on  trail
from here to the top but after 2.5 hours more of strenuous  effort  we  were
not even to the ridge and still about Â½ mile away. It was  3:00  and  Karen,
worried about skiing down the trail in the dark, decided she had had  enough
and reasonably decided  to  turn  around.  I,  not  being  known  for  being
particularly reasonable, gave Karen the car keys  and  stubbornly  continued
up alone. I struggled and wallowed in incredibly  deep  snow,  often  up  my
thighs. At times I could barely move. To make matters  worse  the  last  few
hundred feet were quite steep. Desperate, I tried taking off my  skis  so  I
could climb straight up. I sank in over my waist. I almost gave up. It  took
me until 4:20 to reach the top, 1:20 hours to go less than Â½ mile!

The snow was so deep I could not really ski down out of the track. And  when
I fell, and I did, it was disastrous getting up  again.  Once  back  on  the
trail the skiing was pretty good and the road was delightful. I  have  Karen
to thank for that as she set a nice track down. I  am  sure  she  went  much
slower than I did in the new snow. Because of this she hadn\'t  been  waiting
too long (about 45 minutes) at the car by the time I arrived at 6:45.

Total: 11 miles, 3750 ft and 9 hrs

Fay Pullen

