            'tr' => '
Udono Pk (4830 ft - P510 - Lake Shannon Quad) - December 19, 2010

This turned out  to  be  an  unexpectedly  delightful  ski  trip  with  good
weather, excellent snow conditions and mellow skiing. I wasn\'t sure I  would
be able to drive Jackman Creek Road  14  (off  Hwy  20  past  Concrete)  far
enough to get close to the peak but  I  was.   I  got  to  the  crossing  of
Jackman Creek about 7 miles in where an open  section  with  deep  snow  had
been chewed up by previous 4X4 traffic. I decided to stop  here  (elev  1920
ft) rather than risk getting stuck. I could have driven farther as once  the
road entered trees again the snow cover was very light with rocks showing.

The beginning of the road had previous 4X4 and ATV traffic but  that  didn\'t
greatly affect skiing as the shoulder was wide and the road smooth.  It  was
a beautiful sunny but cold day (21 degrees on top). All signs  of  vehicular
traffic ended about 2 miles up where  I  began  breaking  my  own  trail  in
lovely light powder. I followed the road, with increasingly  nice  views  of
Sauk Mtn across Jackman Cr, to the saddle SE of Udono Pk where a short  spur
led to the SW ridge. Here I left my skis and  kicked  steps  up  the  wooded
ridge to the gentle summit where I was rewarded with a gorgeous view  of  Mt
Baker for lunch. I ended the short day (I had gotten a late  start)  with  a
most pleasant run down the road by the light of a full moon.

Total: 10 miles, 3200 ft and 6 hrs

Cement Mtn (4769 ft - P529) and  Pk  4795  (P515)  -  Lake  Shannon  Quad  -
December 21, 2010

I had so much fun on Udono that I returned two  days  later  for  these  two
peaks. This time I drove Â½ mile farther where I knew there was a good  place
to turn around. I also got an earlier start. The lower  road  was  much  the
same with an additional 2-3 inches of snow, but it was warmer and  the  snow
wetter to start. It became better the higher I got (29 degrees  on  Cement).
It was also cloudier but still quite nice. I quickly retraced  my  route  to
Udono Saddle skiing my old track. From the saddle I picked up  a  spur  road
leading  toward  Cement  Mtn  which  ended  on  a  steep  sidehill.  It  was
challenging forcing a route through thick trees to the saddle to the  NE  of
the summit but once at the saddle the terrain was skiable  all  the  way  to
top (2800 ft, 4:15 hrs). It was wooded with no views.

I was back at Udono Saddle at 2:30. Cement had taken longer  than  expected.
I only had two hours of daylight left.  I  knew  I  couldn\'t  make  Pk  4795
before dark and yet I wasn\'t ready to turn around. The snow was so lovely  I
just had to continue on the road. Besides I was ready for a  workout  before
being sidelined by holiday responsibilities. And so I followed  the  road  2
more miles to the saddle E of Pk 4795. I left skis, got out my ice  axe  and
kicked steps up the very steep E ridge. It was slow going. I  broke  out  of
the dense trees onto a gentler corniced  ridge  that  would  have  had  nice
views had it not now been dark. I reached a high point  and  could  see  the
lights of Concrete and thought I was on top. My GPS said otherwise  -  still
200 linear feet to go. Darn! I went down slightly then farther W  along  the
ridge and back up a bit where I was confronted by a  rock  pinnacle.  Double
darn! Where the heck did this come from? I spent the next 20 minutes  trying
to find a way up it. To the right looked impossible so I went down left  and
traversed. It might go but was very exposed and since I  had  nothing  other
than an ice axe with me and  I  wanted  to  live  to  climb  another  day  I
retreated. In the end I climbed and stemmed between  a  tree  and  the  rock
wall right on the ridge to where I could  almost  spit  on  the  summit  and
called it good (3800 ft, 8 hrs). I may return another day to try again  from
the west or wait until summer to drive the road and climb under  less  snowy
conditions. Then again, I may not.

I had a mystical ski down the road by the light of a partially clouded  full
moon. Then it was shattered as I got to the lower road  and  saw  headlights
of a vehicle. I passed a beefy 4X4 truck stopped at the end of the  previous
old track with 6 young people. I am not  sure  who  was  more  surprised  at
meeting someone at 7:30 in the dark, them or me. At  this  point  the  truck
was wheel deep and dragging bottom but they seemed  unconcerned  and  to  be
having a good time. It amazes me that some people get great pleasure out  of
driving up snowy roads as far  as  they  can  go,  getting  stuck  and  then
driving back down. Crazy! Not that climbing up peaks,  touching  the  summit
and climbing back down is at all similar.

Total: 16 miles, 4100 ft 10:45 hrs

Fay Pullen



