            'tr' => '
West Church (5610 ft - P570) and West  Church  Ridge  (3502  ft  -  P461)  -
Glacier Quad - December 31, 2010-January 1, 2011

Friday, December 31: West Church Ridge - The wildlife gate on Road 3120  was
closed so I had to start from there. I was surprised at the  lack  of  snow,
maybe an inch or two of fresh light powder over no base, and had to  walk  a
mile or so before I put on my skis. Even  then  coverage  remained  marginal
until about 3000 ft in  many  places.  I  guess  the  previous  recent  warm
weather and heavy rains had decimated the lowland snowpack in this area.

Since I was also planning on skiing up West Church Ridge  the  logical  spot
to camp was at the road junction but when I got there it was  all  in  shade
and unappealing so I continued to Church Saddle (3.5 miles,  1400  ft,  2.30
hrs). Here I found a pleasant spot in the afternoon sun with a  view  of  Mt
Baker. I couldn\'t have asked for  more.  Being  in  the  sun  made  all  the
difference in comfort as I set up camp.

While arranging things inside my tent I  heard  a  strange  shuffling  sound
outside like something moving. I poked my head out shocked to see  3  skiers
going by. Where the heck did they come from? There were no tracks  ahead  of
me on the road although there was another vehicle parked at the  gate.  They
had come from West Church and said they  approached  up  "the  gully".  What
gully? I didn\'t know there was a route up a gully. But  any  lowland  cross-
country travel couldn\'t be very good given the lack  of  snow.  They  hadn\'t
made the summit saying they were about 1.5  hours  away  when  they  turned
around. I was a little fuzzy on the details of it all. They  were  in  heavy
AT gear (well actually one guy was on a split board), which to  me  was  not
well suited to this route until quite high on the mountain. Maybe  they  too
thought there would be more snow cover. I think they were  as  surprised  to
see me as I was to see them.

I started for West Church Ridge at 3:40  retracing  my  route  to  the  road
junction. I didn\'t mind as I was looking for ways to kill time and make  the
night shorter. I reached the towers at the end of the road just in time  for
a sunset view of Mt Baker. When I  returned  to  camp  the  temperature  was
already 17 degrees and dropping (4 miles, 1000 ft, 2:20 hrs RT). I  snuggled
in for a long night entertaining myself with a leisurely dinner,  music  and
2 videos on my IPod between naps. At midnight I toasted the  New  Year  with
Irish Cream laced hot chocolate (yum) and emerged from my tent  for  a  view
of a clear starlit sky. As  a  bonus  I  was  treated  to  a  few  fireworks
courtesy of the tiny town of Glacier which I could see directly below me.  I
reheated my hot water bottle before turning in for  good  to  spend  a  warm
comfortable night.

Saturday, January 1: West Church - It is hard to get going early when it  is
13 degrees and it doesn\'t get light  until  7:30.  It  didn\'t  help  that  I
forgot my ice axe and had to return for it.  That  lost  me  30  minutes.  I
think my brain was frozen. I finally  got  underway  for  real  at  8:30.  I
followed the road all the way to the end at 4100 ft  (1:20  hrs).  Here  the
skier\'s tracks ended. Darn! I had hoped they would  have  made  a  track  at
least part way up the mountain. They were no help at all.  I  sure  expected
them to have gotten farther. I was really  puzzled  as  to  the  purpose  of
their trip. AT gear and they never got beyond the end of the road?

I now had my work cut out for me. The first  bit  above  the  road  was  too
steep and forested for skis so I kicked steps until things opened up  and  I
could put skis on again. The higher I got the better the snow cover  became,
beautiful light powder. In places it was quite deep, but as I ventured  onto
the wide open south slopes I began running into a  tricky  hard  crust  only
lightly covered where my skis would occasionally lose their  grip  and  slip
downhill. It wasn\'t everywhere  but  quite  disconcerting  when  encountered
especially as the slope got steeper with no runout.  Not  wanting  to  slide
uncontrollably out of sight downhill, I finally gave up on  skiing,  stashed
the skis and kicked steps the rest of the  way.  It  was  fairly  good  step
kicking not being hard enough to require crampons.  The  terrain  forced  me
toward the false summit from where I followed the ridge to the summit  (2800
ft, 3:50 hrs). It had taken 2.5 hrs from road end. The skier\'s  estimate  of
being 1.5 hrs from the top was a little optimistic.

The summit of West Church was a broad snow mound with a gorgeous view,  well
worth waiting for a sunny clear day. Church Mtn was  especially  impressive.
Now that would be a challenging winter climb. Once back to  my  skis  I  had
some good downhill to the road and a great run down the road itself  despite
5 annoying small open creek crossings. I reached my tent in  1.5  hours  at
2:00 (7 miles, 2800 ft, 5:30 hrs RT),  quickly  packed  up  (once  again  in
sun!), skied as far as I possibly could  (adding  a  few  new  scratches  to
already scratched ski bases) before being to forced to walk. Even so I  made
it to the car in 1:15 hrs. The end of a great start to 2011.

Total: 18 miles and 5200 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen

