            'tr' => '
Damnation Pk (5635 ft - P715 - Damnation Quad) - January 26, 2011

Lisa Loper and I had been planning on climbing Damnation together  for  over
a year just waiting for an intersection of  proper  conditions  and  a  time
when good snow wasn\'t luring me  to  backcountry  skiing.  Her  friend  Bill
joined us when things came together on Wednesday.

Considering how the lowland snowpack has been decimated by the recent  rains
and warm weather, we were somewhat surprised to be stopped by  snow  on  the
Thornton Lakes Road at  1850  ft  about  0.75  mile  before  the  old  spur  up
Damnation Cr. However, this meant we had ample snow cover on  that  road.  I
am not really sure this helped all that much, though, as the snow  was  very
slushy and rotten making for frustrating progress even  with  snowshoes.  We
all  experienced  sinking  into  nasty  holes.  Some  very  large  blowdowns
encountered near the beginning didn\'t help. It took us  2  hours  to  travel
the 2.5 miles to the end of the old  road  at  3150  ft.   But  overall  the
roadbed was in better shape than I expected with minimal brush.

From the road end we  dropped  a  short  way  to  easily  cross  a  fork  of
Damnation Cr. We then worked our way left  through  forest  up  increasingly
steep terrain, a real effort on snowshoes, to the  crest  of  the  southeast
ridge of Damnation. The ridge began to open up around 4100  where  the  snow
became deeper and slushier. Oakes, across Damnation Creek, was the  dominate
view along the lower part of the ridge and is quite an attractive peak  from
this side. Trailbreaking, done mostly by Bill and Lisa, was  work.  A  steep
step, turned on the left, was encountered below the false summit. The  ridge
above this step was lovely with expanded views  in  all  directions  despite
the mostly cloudy conditions. I  was  especially  entranced  by  Triumph  to
Despair, an area that has  given  me  several  challenging  trips  the  past
couple of years. Bill cracked me up when  he  made  the  oh  so  understated
comment, "This does not suck!"

We topped out on the summit at 3:00 (4000 ft, 6:00 hrs) and had  a  pleasant
30 minute rest until the chilly wind and diminishing daylight hours  spurred
on our descent. I descended the whole ridge in  boots  for  greater  control
and for the most part stayed on top in the track.  Bill  and  Lisa  switched
back and forth between snowshoes and  boots  depending  upon  steepness  and
degree of sinking in. We turned on our  headlamps  shortly  before  reaching
the old road at 5:30 where we all put snowshoes on for the final  plod  back
to the car.

Total: 9 miles, 4100 ft and 10:30 hrs.

Fay Pullen







