            'tr' => '
Groat Mtn (5581 ft - P1021) and Stewart Pk (4280+ ft -  P440)  -  Groat  Mtn
Quad - February 1, 2011

With skiing continuing to  be  lousy  I  was  casting  about  for  something
interesting to climb with good views to take advantage of the  good  weather
when I received an unexpected invitation from Mike T to join him  for  these
two peaks. Perfect! I had done neither, views of Baker should be superb  and
I hadn\'t been out with Mike in quite some time. I always enjoy his company.

Mike drove in his truck up Road 38 (Middle Fork  Nooksack)  and  about  2.75
miles up Warm Cr Road before being stopped by a deep snow patch at 3100  ft.
He made a gallant effort to plow on through to a bare  section  just  beyond
but it was too deep. We were only Â½ mile from the spur up the south side  of
Stewart and I was happy we got that far. We began walking the road at  10:00
and were at the end of it on the ridge below Stewart in  a  little  over  an
hour. From here someone had cut a cute little trail along the  narrow  ridge
(there was even a hand line on one steep section!) to the flat area  of  the
summit where we had to search around a bit for the high point  (2  Â¼  miles,
1350 ft, 1:45 hrs).

We returned to the last switchback on the road and  followed  the  ridge  to
the 3800 ft saddle with  Groat  Mtn  in  a  clear-cut.  Some  unpleasantness
followed as we worked our way out of the clear-cut into timber. The  terrain
was deceiving as we ran into unforeseen ribs,  gullies  and  rock  outcrops,
none of which was apparent from the map. Once in the trees the  snow  became
so icy and steep I was forced to put  on  crampons.  Mike  somehow  made  do
without. Once above this section the terrain moderated and  even  though  it
looked very steep on the map it was quite reasonable (though still  somewhat
icy) as we worked right to the main south ridge and on to the  false  summit
(3300 ft, 4:30 hrs).  We dropped from here to a broad saddle for  the  final
fun tiptoe along the narrow corniced summit ridge to the top (4 miles,  3600
ft, 5:30 hrs).

Views were outstanding and the sun warm but the air was  cold,  the  shadows
were lengthening and the sun softened snow starting to refreeze so  soon  it
was time to go at 4:00. We retraced our steps to where we had met the  south
ridge then angled left heading for a lower road traversing  the  south  side
we had seen on the way up. I had taken my crampons off  on  the  summit  but
had to put them on again in the  lower  trees  where  the  snow  once  again
turned icy. The whole descent went quite well, though, until just above  the
road where we ran into a multitude of downed trees. And then the  road  that
had  looked  so  obvious  from  a  distance  turned  out  to  be  completely
decommissioned and not all that easy to  follow,  especially  in  the  dark.
Mike did a great job keeping us on  the  line.  I  would  have  gone  astray
several times. We intersected our up route on the  good  road  at  6:00  and
were back to the car at 6:30 to end a very enjoyable climb  with  much  more
interesting peaks than I had thought they would be.

We took snowshoes but never used them. Crampons were the order of the day.

Total: 7 miles, 3800 ft and 8:30 hrs

Fay Pullen

