            'tr' => '
Grouse Butte (5041 ft - P841), Pk 4926 (P886) and Pk  4846  (P446)  -  Groat
Mtn Quad - February 8-10, 2011

With Mt Baker reported to have 10 inches new snow I  had  visions  of  great
backcountry skiing. Alas it was not to be. I had nowhere  near  that  amount
and skiing was not all I had hoped it  would  be.   Despite  that  this  was
still a very good trip. Grouse Butte was  more  challenging,  Pk  4926  more
interesting and Pk 4826 more pleasant than expected, even  if  I  wasn\'t  on
skis.

Tuesday, February 8: Grouse Butte - I drove Glacier Cr Road 39  to  milepost
7 (elev 3080) where I was stopped by a  sign  "No  wheeled  vehicles  beyond
this point". Just the sign. No other amenities, not even a turn  around  and
you were on your own finding a spot to park out of the way.  The  snowmobile
rigs must have known this as they were all parked a mile  or  so  back  down
the road where there was more room. This road is well  used  by  snowmobiles
for access to Grouse Ridge and Lookout Mtn, both expansive  play  areas  for
the machines. So I had no trail breaking in  the  several  inches  of  fresh
snow on Roads 39 and 36 all the way to the junction with  3630  (4.5  miles,
1250 ft. 3 hrs). Here I found a secluded campsite in the  saddle  just  east
of Grouse Butte (elev 4160 ft) where the steep sides protected me  from  the
sound and sight of passing machines.

After setting up camp I figured I still had time to make it up Grouse  Butte
before dark even though I left at 4:00. It was only about Â½  mile  and  less
than 1000 feet. How long could it take? Well, a heck of a lot longer than  I
thought. First I found out right away that skiing off road this trip  wasn\'t
going to be very good. Mt Baker may have gotten 10 inches of  new  snow  but
that certainly didn\'t apply here. At most it was 3  inches  in  open  areas,
less in the woods, which was not adequate to cover  the  hard  lumpy  frozen
crust. I soon had to ditch skis for foot travel. Also, although the day  had
started sunny it gradually turned cloudy to the point I was now in fog  with
limited visibility.

Grouse Butte is guarded by cliffs on all sides but the NE which is  where  I
headed up.  It started well but as the slope steepened I quickly  discovered
I had made an almost fatal error in not bringing crampons. With an  expected
10 inches of new snow I really didn\'t think I would need them and I have  to
carry enough stuff for winter camping without taking stuff I don\'t  think  I
will need. Well, in places the snow was not only crusty but icy as well  and
I couldn\'t even kick good steps. I did a lot of  micro  wandering  searching
for good foot placements and I had to chop a few steps.  Then I hit  a  snow
wall that was too steep for me to get up and I was forced to  traverse  left
beneath it. I did eventually find a way through but it was  very  steep,  my
guess 55 degrees or so. Fortunately the snow was such that  I  could  plunge
my axe through the crust in to hilt most of the way  so  I  felt  reasonably
secure. Even so I breathed a sigh of relief when I topped  the  wall.  Above
was easy.

All this wandering around and chopping steps took so long that it  was  6:00
and the sun had set when I reached the summit. However,  Mt  Baker  was  now
above the fog. My photo of this view in low light does not  do  it  justice.
It was absolutely stunning. I enjoyed the view and  what  was  left  of  the
sunset for a few minutes before reality set it. Holy Cow, now I  had  to  go
down that wall! At this point I dearly wished I also had a rope.  There  was
even a nice tree for a rappel. Well, wishing don\'t make it so. There was  no
other alternative but to slowly and carefully back down my steps.  Obviously
I made it and I dragged into camp  at  7:40  somewhat  frazzled.  My  little
jaunt had taken twice as long as expected (1 mile, 1100 ft, 3:30 hrs).

Wednesday, February 9: Pks 4926 & 4846 - I was up  early  on  a  cold  clear
morning (8 degrees). I wanted at least some good skiing and my best bet  was
the open slopes of Grouse Ridge and I wanted to beat the  snowmobilers  that
come in just for the day.  With  this  in  mind  I  was  underway  at  7:30.
Following the snowmobile route from the end of Rd 36 I was on  Grouse  Ridge
at 9:30 just as I heard the first snowmobiles arriving. I found some  mostly
untracked snow for a nice downhill run. Here the snow was really very  good.
On Rd 36 again I ran into more snowmobiles and a groomer (4 miles, 1700  ft,
4 hrs RT to Grouse Ridge)

At 11:30 I started downhill on Rd 3630  to  head  for  PK  4926.  This  road
skirts Grouse Butte on the south. At the switchback I left the road  heading
for the 4000 saddle between Grouse Butte and Pk  4926.  I  stashed  my  skis
here as the terrain was not remotely  skiable.  What  followed  was  a  very
unpleasant traverse through nasty dense woods on a  steep  hillside  lightly
covered with an inch or so of fresh snow over  frozen  duff.  There  was  no
base at all. But once I made it  to  the  saddle  things  improved  and  the
higher I got the better it became as I worked my way up the SE ridge to  the
summit. The snow was very good for step  kicking  and  the  ridge  partially
open and quite interesting with a cliff on the south. Unfortunately  another
day that had started clear and sunny once again turned cloudy and foggy  and
I had few views. I reached the summit at 2:30.

Then it was down the lovely open gentle  north  and  west  ridge  (would  be
great skiing if I had my skis) to the 4400 ft saddle with Pk 4846. The  easy
SE ridge led to that summit at 3:45. It was all in woods but pleasant  going
and since it was foggy no views did not matter. I followed  my  tracks  back
to the 4000 saddle, did some slipping and sliding  down  slick  frozen  dirt
and emerged at my skis and Rd 3630 again at  6:00.  Darned  if  the  groomer
hadn\'t been down this road too which made it an easy ski  back  to  camp  at
7:00 (6.5 miles, 2700 ft, 7:30 hrs).

Thursday, February 10 - This morning was a  little  warmer  at  14  degrees.
With no agenda I slept in and didn\'t  leave  until  9:30  just  as  all  the
snowmobiles were streaming in. It was a gorgeous sunny  morning,  maybe  the
best of the three days but by now there would be no untracked snow  left  to
ski on Grouse Ridge. I stopped often to take in views.  Near the car  I  ran
into two Border Patrol officers on foot walking down the road. I stopped  to
chat. They said they were just out for a stroll  and  getting  to  know  the
area but they were armed with the big weapons. Made  me  wonder.  (200,  4.5
miles, 2 hrs)

Total: 20.5 miles and 6950 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen





