 "East Rock" (5120+ ft - P480 - Sawtooth Ridge Quad) - February 18, 2011',
            'tr' => '
Allen Mtn (5095 ft - P615 - Sawtooth Ridge Quad) - February 13, 2011

Sunday - I got so excited with the first prospect of new snow for skiing  in
a while I couldn\'t wait to get out. I think I  jumped  the  gun  a  bit,  at
least as far as this trip was concerned. I parked on  Rd  8440  at  3100  ft
where the old snow was covered by an inch or so of new. This increased to 1-
3 inches as I got higher but that wasn\'t enough for good  off  road  skiing.
Still it was a good trip and skiing on the road to  Towhead  Gap  was  nice.
Once in the trees of the NW ridge above the Gap there  was  only  a  dusting
over bare ground. I hiked this carrying skis hoping I could use them  later.
I did put them on again near the summit where it opened  up  but  it  wasn\'t
very good and I really should have left  the  skis  behind.   Katoolas  were
useful both for the bare frozen ground of the ridge and the summit rocks.

Total: 11 miles, 2150 ft and 6:30 hrs

"Catt Pk" (5120+ ft - P800) and "Greenwood Pt" (4982 ft - P382)  -  Sawtooth
Ridge Quad - February 16, 2011

Wednesday - What a treasure this peak turned out to  be!  I  parked  in  the
same place as Sunday and was lucky to get that far as there  was  a  good  6
inches of fresh snow on the road. I skied the main road about 1.5  miles  to
a spur right. This was probably a mistake as it was overgrown and  had  some
blowdown to start. But at least the bridge over Catt Cr was still intact.  A
better choice would have been a second spur another mile  up  road.  It  was
farther but would have made for better skiing.  Anyway,  I  stuck  with  the
first spur and it did improve as I got higher. I followed it to  a  clearing
at 3700 ft then went straight uphill to cross the end of the second spur  at
4200 ft. The new snow depth was now over a foot and breaking trail slow  and
laborious. Steep slopes above this led to Rd 8511 on the ridgeline  which  I
crossed to lovely terrain on the NW slope.

I had been in fog and light snow up to now when all  of  a  sudden  the  sun
came out just in time for my final ascent up  the  delightful  NW  ridge  of
Catt Pk. It was gorgeous skiing. I sure didn\'t expect this  peak  to  be  so
nice. I reached the summit at 3:00 (4 miles,  2150  ft,  5  hrs).  I  had  a
pleasant 30 minute lunch in the sun where views came and went but were  good
enough to lure me into continuing on the ridgeline to make a big loop  trip.
I had a wonderful ski down the E ridge to  intersect  Rd  8511,  skied  this
road to its end, climbed over Greenwood Pt, skied down to  a  broad  saddle,
up and over the next bump and along the flat ridge  until  I  could  descend
toward Cougar Gap. From here I fully expected problems forcing a route  down
upper Catt Cr drainage but in fact it turned out  to  be  not  half  bad.  I
followed a series of open glades down into the  trees  and  even  there  the
forest was open enough that it was quite skiable. I only had to remove  skis
once for a crossing of Catt Cr. Here I was treated to the spectacular  sight
of a full moon rising above snowy trees. I  emerged  onto  the  second  spur
whose bridge got me across Catt Cr again and to main  Rd  8440  at  7:30.  I
ended with a gentle 2.5 miles run down the road and back to the car  to  end
one of the best ski tours I have had all year.

Total: 10 miles, 2800 ft and 10:45 hrs.

"East Rock" (5120+ ft - P480 - Sawtooth Ridge Quad) - February 18, 2011

Friday - Skiing was so good on Catt Pk I was back again two days  later  and
once again parked in the same spot. No one had been on road in the  interim.
There were another couple of inches of new snow,  not  enough  to  cover  my
tracks from Wednesday so I only had to break new  trail  starting  from  the
second spur at 2.5 miles. At Towhead Gap (4.5 miles) I continued on Rd  8440
downhill another mile until I could  head  uphill  to  the  4600  ft  saddle
between High Rock and East Rock. I ran into a good trail  below  the  saddle
which made for easy travel, especially on the way back. I  followed  the  NW
ridge from the saddle until it turned narrow and rocky about  .2  mile  from
the top where I left my skis. Now things got  interesting  and  it  took  me
over an hour to go this short  distance.  But  I  expected  some  difficulty
here. I had seen Klenke\'s photo of East Rock on List of John\'s  website  and
knew it could be problematic under snowy conditions and  so  it  was.  There
was not enough snow cover to make for good step kicking to start so I  began
by very carefully "crawling " the crest on a line just between  the  cornice
on the left and the solid rock on the right. At a notch  I  was  forced  off
the crest onto the steep exposed right-hand slope  but  here  the  snow  was
deeper and stepkicking feasible. I traversed past the icy summit rocks  then
worked back up through better snow and trees to approach the top from the  S
ridge. The very top was an overhanging cornice  which  I  stayed  well  back
from (2500 ft, 5:45 hr).

With route established and steps kicked it took much less time to return  to
skis at which point I had a wonderful ski down the remainder  of  the  ridge
and the trail to Rd 8440. At the road I was shocked to find fresh tracks  of
a lone snowmobile. This is the first sign of use of this area  by  others  I
saw all week. Then again it was the beginning of a long holiday weekend.  Oh
well. It did make for a faster return up and down the road.

Total: 12.5 miles, 2900 ft and 9 hrs

The approach for all three trips was from Highway 706 near Ashford to  Skate
Cr Rd 52, Rd 85 and Rd 8440.

Fay Pullen



