            'tr' => '
Cornell Mtn (4760+ ft - P760 - Groat Mtn Quad) - Friday, March 11, 2011

This ended up being a gem of a trip for skiing although it didn\'t start  out
all that promising. I ran into old icy snow almost immediately  on  Rd  3010
right out of the town of Glacier and couldn\'t drive it very far. Because  of
this I decided to ski the spur road (elev 1060 ft) at about .5  mile  rather
than the main road as it appeared more direct and  shorter  by  at  least  a
mile. I originally  had  some  concerns  that  it  would  be  overgrown  and
unskiable as it was not shown on many of my  maps  but  it  looked  fine  to
start. I should have listened to my gut. In less than Â¼ mile  I  came  to  a
berm past which the road was abandoned and overgrown. Darn! It was too  late
to reconsider so I stuck with it. After some  short  initial  unpleasantness
that required walking, it soon became marginally skiable and improved  as  I
climbed higher. After 1.5 hours of this I came to  the  good  road  I  would
have taken had I stayed on Rd  3010  (1300  ft,  2  Â¼  miles).  Things  were
looking up.

Continuing on this nice road I crossed Gallop Cr  on  a  sturdy  bridge  and
began getting into  fresh  snow  and  more  interesting  terrain.  I  passed
several logging spurs heading to other inviting  areas  that  would  warrant
future exploration. After another 1.5 hours  of  gentle  climbing  the  road
curled around to head up the Gallop Cr drainage and entered a  large  clear-
cut. Somewhat past the top of the clear-cut I left the road at  3800  ft  in
forest, skinned up and headed directly for the summit of  Cornell  Mtn  (5.5
miles, 2850 ft, 4:20 hrs). This is where the trip turned  into  a  gem.  The
forest began semi open and quickly expanded  to  a  series  of  lovely  open
glades on the broad north ridge that led all  the  way  to  just  below  the
summit on the east ridge. The skiing was delightful. The summit  itself  was
a short ways farther into the trees (3800 ft, 5:50. 6.5 miles).

I had a great ski off the summit down those beautiful glades to the road,  a
1000 foot run. I also  cut  the  clear-cut  switchback  for  a  little  more
downhill but by then the snow was getting a little wet and  heavy.  The  day
began as drizzle, graduating to snow flurries (and fog) as I got higher  but
it never amounted to much and I never got wet.  It  cleared  enough  in  the
afternoon for some distant views. The snow varied from  crust  to  start  to
nice new snow higher to wet slush for the  road  trip  down  but  was  quite
skiable all the time. I thought about staying on the main road all  the  way
to the car but it was getting late and the shorter direct route on the  spur
won out. For the most part it  was  reasonable  but  I  must  admit  it  was
challenging at times dodging obstacles and trying not to  get  skis  tangled
in brush. I did walk the very last bit.

If (when) I return to this area I would stick to the main  road  for  better
skiing. Hopefully I could drive farther and get closer to  the  good  stuff.
And there is plenty of good stuff higher up below Cornell Mtn.

Total: 13 miles, 3900 ft and 9 hrs

Fay Pullen

