            'tr' => '
Slide Mtn (4884 ft - P204 - Canyon Lake Quad) and  Jockey  Mtn  (4905  ft  -
P785 - Groat Mtn Quad) - March 17-18, 2011

Slide Mtn is a long gentle ridge west and  south  of  the  town  of  Glacier
between the North Fork Nooksack River  and  Racehorse  Creek.  The  area  is
riddled with logging roads one of which follows most of the  length  of  the
ridge and makes for very pleasant skiing. It is a bit too  long  for  a  day
trip this time of year but made for an easy 2 days with a camp near a  small
unnamed lake ("Slide Lake"?).

Thursday, March 17 - I took the North Fork Road off Mosquito Lake Road  some
5.5 miles to the turnoff up Racehorse Creek then left at another .7 mile  on
the road up Slide Mtn which I drove to the snowline  at  2  miles  and  2000
feet. I skied this road 5.5 miles to a lovely  campsite  on  a  bench  above
Slide Lake that had a nice view of Church Mtn, elev  4200  ft  (2200  ft,  5
hrs). I had plenty of time to set up camp, ski to the little lake  and  part
way farther up the road while watching the almost full moon rise before  the
sun set. The day had started sunny and warm but  once  shade  hit,  anything
that had melted soon froze  to  either  a  breakable  or  solid  crust.  The
temperature dropped to 19 degrees overnight.

Total for the day: 7 miles and 2500 ft

Friday, March 18 - I was underway before 7:00 and watched the sun rise as  I
warmed up. Once past my track set the night before  I  simply  continued  on
the road. I ran into some very hard crust  on  any  previously  sun  exposed
slopes. Shaded slopes were still powder. Because  of  this  I  bypassed  the
summit of Slide on the way in so I could ski down the north side on the  way
out. I also left the road at the saddle with Pt 4844 to traverse  the  north
slope of Pt 4844 and avoid the icy south side. I reached the flat summit  of
Jockey Mtn at 9:40. On the return I stayed on the ridge all the way  to  the
summit of Slide arriving at 11:00. I had a marvelous though short  ski  down
the north side in perfect powder to intercept my tracks on  the  road  below
before returning to camp at noon (6.5 mile, 2000 ft, 5 hrs)

Views had been quite good all day although Baker never made it  out  of  the
clouds. But I could now see  weather  approaching  from  the  south.   So  I
quickly packed up and left, reaching the  car  in  less  than  2  hours  and
encountering nary a drop of precipitation. I ran  into  heavy  rain  on  the
drive home.

Trip total: 19 miles and 4500 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen

