            'tr' => '
Toboggan Mtn (5004 ft - P1164 - Canyon Lk Quad) - Wednesday, March 23, 2011

What a beautiful day this turned out to be, warm  and  sunny  with  stunning
views in all directions. The skiing wasn\'t too shabby  either.  I  used  the
same approach as last week for Slide Mtn, this time staying right  with  the
road up Racehorse Cr for 4 miles until stopped by snow at 2300 ft  (about  1
mile before the spur  that  crosses  Racehorse  Cr).  I  could  have  driven
farther but the snow was icy and slick and I didn\'t  want  to  risk  it.  In
fact another vehicle had driven about half a mile more before parking.  From
there I followed the tracks of 3 skiers catching up  to  them  at  Racehorse
Saddle (4.5 miles, 2400 ft, 2:45 hrs). I was really surprised  to  run  into
other people as this is not a high use area,  especially  during  the  week,
and I half expected (hoped) them to be fellow peakbaggers known to me.  What
a kick that would have been! But alas, they were strangers  from  Bellingham
just out for some BC skiing. They were not going for Toboggan  and  in  fact
weren\'t even aware of that peak. After leaving the saddle I never  saw  them
again.

From the saddle I traversed around Racehorse Mtn to the next saddle but  ran
into some unexpectedly steep slopes that were  fully  exposed  to  the  sun,
softening and that began triggering concern for setting  off  avalanches.  I
declined to cross and had to climb quite a bit to get above them. Once  past
Racehorse I entered trees to get around the next  bump,  came  to  the  wide
open ridge to the false summit of Toboggan  and  skied  through  trees  once
again to the true summit (6 miles, 3100 ft, 4:15 hrs). I went  back  to  the
false summit with its expansive views for lunch.

After lunch I followed the crest of the ridge all the way to Racehorse  Mtn.
Just before the Relay Station I came to a short narrow  rocky  section  that
required removing skis and kicking steps. Then it was on to  the  flat  open
summit with more lovely views before skiing down  to  Racehorse  Saddle.  It
was all so nice and the day so gorgeous I extended it by  skiing  up  to  Pt
4760 to the north of the saddle. This allowed me to ski down the north  side
on preserved powder for a fantastic 800 ft drop until  I  hit  the  road.  I
then had a fast run down the rest of the road on icing snow that  thankfully
softened a bit as I got lower. I did a lot of  snowplowing.  I  reached  the
car at 6:20 to end a marvelous trip.

Total: 13 miles, 3900 ft and 8 hrs

Fay Pullen





