            'tr' => '
Porter Peak (4760+ ft - P520 - Canyon Lk Quad) - Friday, April 8, 2011

This is another of the small peaks in the heavily logged  area  between  the
North and Middle Fork Nooksack Rivers on  the  outskirts  of  the  Mt  Baker
Wilderness that I have been accessing on skis  this  snow  season.  I  could
drive the Clearwater Road (off the Middle Fork Nooksack River Road)  only  2
miles before being halted by a fresh slide across the road  at  2000  ft.  I
would say it happened within the last week. So I walked the road .6 mile  to
the first spur left where there was then enough snow to ski.  This  spur  is
bermed and abandoned at a creek .5 mile farther but is skiable all  the  way
to its end at 4200 ft (3 miles, 2200, 2:45 hrs) The going was quite good  to
this point - then it all fell apart.  The  road  ended  on  a  steep  wooded
hillside with trees really too close together for skis  and  snow  too  deep
and wet and slushy for postholing. I was forced to  slowly  struggle  upward
on my skis. Okay, I admit snowshoes would have been  better  here  but  even
they would have required a mighty effort. This short  section  of  300  feet
and .2 mile to the ridge line  took  a  full  hour.  I  was  coming  to  the
realization that either I wouldn\'t make Porter Peak or it was going to be  a
very long day.

Once on the ridge the going was better. However, I now had a view of  Porter
and it was still a long ways off. I continued along the ridge to the  summit
of Pt 4758 (3000 ft, 4:15 hrs)  thinking this  may  well  end  up  being  my
destination for the day. But from  the  summit  inviting  terrain  led  down
toward the saddle with Porter. So on I went. I actually  had  a  nice  short
run on reasonable snow before once  again  running  into  some  thick  trees
prior to hitting a road at the saddle coming up from Porter Creek. From  the
saddle it got worse again but I wasn\'t going to  quit  now.  A  steep  step,
more thick trees, lots of ups and downs and  terrible  snow  conditions  all
melting in the warm sun.  It was hard believe the snow could be so  wet  and
heavy  and  unconsolidated  so  late  in  the  season.   Trailbreaking   was
exhausting. I finally arrived at the wooded summit at 5:00 (5.5  mile,  3800
ft, 6:45 hrs).

The trip out was a blur of very  cautious  survival  skiing  on  alternating
trapping deep slush, freezing crust and breakable  crust  depending  on  sun
exposure and time in the shade. I tried a more  direct  route  bypassing  Pt
4758 but in the end determined it was easier to go back up over the  top.  I
reached the road just at dark. Of course by this time the snow had  refrozen
completely but in comparison to what I had previously come  down  it  was  a
vast improvement. I reached the car at 10:30 totally done in. Not one of  my
better ski outings. At least the views were nice.

Total: 11 miles, 4500 ft and 12:15 hrs

Fay Pullen

