            'tr' => '
Timberwolf Mtn (6391 ft - P1111 - Timberwolf Mtn  Quad);  and  Shellrock  Pk
(6835 ft - P1515) & Burnt Mtn (6536 ft - P696) - Rimrock Lk Quad - April 26-
28, 2011

Tuesday, April 26: Timberwolf Mtn - With unsettled weathered west I  decided
to head east and hope for something better.  My plan  worked.  Despite  much
fresh snow over White Pass the roads were clear and by the  time  I  reached
the Bethel Ridge Road I was in sunshine and able to drive to 4600  ft,  much
higher than expected.  Sunshine persisted for the most part as I  skied  the
road 4 miles to a lovely camp in Cash Prairie at  6000  ft  (1400  ft,  2:30
hr).

I had reached my intended campsite early enough  I  thought  I  could  still
make Timberwolf Mtn this day. I took a  shortcut  straight  down  from  Cash
Prairie to intersect the road to Timberwolf at 5300 ft. Although  mostly  in
woods, small glades with nice snow offered some good downhill.  Once on  the
road  I  followed  it,  cutting  one  large  switchback,  to  meadows  below
Timberwolf. Weather was still reasonable but sun  now  came  and  went  with
some light snow showers. Views west were clouding up. Near the summit  ridge
I lost the road. In fact I could hardly  believe  a  road  went  along  this
ridge. Large cornices obliterated it  completely.  The  final  Â¼  mile  went
slowly as I threaded my way over and between the cornices  but  I  was  able
the ski the entire distance. A sign incongruously sticking out of  the  snow
proclaimed the summit and identified surrounding peaks (5.5 miles, 1500  ft,
3 hrs). Can you really drive to this point in the summer? For a peak with  a
road to the top Timberwolf was surprisingly interesting and challenging.

The return took just as long. I stuck to the road as any snow previously  in
the sun had crusted over and made for  tricky  skiing.  The  road  was  more
consistent. As soon as possible at an open drainage I left the road for  the
climb back to Cash Prairie. I might have done better to stick  to  the  road
the whole way even though it would have added well over a mile as  the  snow
was too icy for skis and yet I broke through the crust on foot. I  struggled
slowly upward for several hundred feet until hitting more gentle  woods  and
better snow where I could ski again. I reached  camp  at  10:30  (11  miles,
2500 ft, 6:30 hr RT).

Wednesday,  April  27:  Burnt  Mtn  and  Shellrock  Pk  -  With  a   morning
temperature of 21 degrees and after  my  experience  with  crusty  snow  the
night before I didn\'t hold out much hope for great off  road  skiing  today,
as least until the day warmed up. Starting at 7:30 I skied the road  to  its
end at the boundary with the William O. Douglas Wilderness. I dropped a  bit
and traversed the north side below cornices and  cliffs  to  a  small  basin
where I could gain the ridge to the south side. Here I ran into snow so  icy
I had to remove skis. I decided to leave them  and  proceed  on  foot  as  I
didn\'t think skiing would improve that  much.  I  descended  a  short  steep
section then followed the ridge to a low  point  before  entering  woods  to
climb to Burnt Mtn. Of course I ran into some deep powder where I  wished  I
had my skis but that didn\'t last. Overall, the effort of carrying  skis  and
putting them on and off was not worth it. It was more efficient to walk.  So
I toughed it out postholing deeply in places and making slow progress.

I reached Burnt Mtn at 10:30 (3 miles, 1150 ft, 3 hrs). I  still  thought  I
could make Shellrock despite my slow pace as I had all  day.  Good  thing  I
had all day as I sure needed it. Shellrock was farther than it  looked  with
an 800 ft drop and much meandering along the ridge. But the route was  quite
interesting and the final  open  corniced  summit  ridge  stunning.  I  sure
wouldn\'t want to be on this ridge in bad weather. There is  zero  protection
from the wind and it would be easy to get disoriented in fog. In fact I  did
enter fog the last hundred feet  or  so  and  had  to  carefully  follow  my
footsteps to head down the right direction and not  go  over  a  cornice.  I
reached the summit at 1:30 (5.5 miles, 2250 ft, 6 hrs).

The return was slow and an effort. Combined with my strenuous day  before  I
was running out of energy. I did have a nice run  though  once  back  to  my
skis and pulled into camp at 6:30. I still had time to go out that day.  But
just as I reached the shelter of my tent the weather deteriorated with  wind
and heavy snow and I wisely decided to hunkered down for the night.

Total: 11 miles, 3900 ft and 11 hrs

Thursday, April 28 - It stormed all night long  with  wind  and  snow.  Some
wind gusts had to be in excess of 60 mph but I was snug  and  secure  in  my
bombproof Hilleberg tent. I kept thinking I was glad I wasn\'t  on  Shellrock
under such conditions. I prepared myself for unpleasant packing  up  in  the
morning but I awakened to sun on the tent and very little  wind.  It  was  a
beautiful morning and I had a very enjoyable run down to the  car  on  fresh
snow for a lovely end to a very interesting trip (4 miles, 1:30 hrs).

Trip Total: 30 miles and 7750 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen



