            'title' => 'Dome Pk (6591 ft - P7110) & Strobach Mtn (6397 ft - P277) - Foundation Ridge Quad; Divide Ridge East (Jumpoff) Pk (5760+ ft - P960) - Tieton Basin Quad; Divide Ridge East Pk (6880+ ft - P800) & Pk 3737 (P457) - Darland Mtn Quad; and Pk 4128 (P848) - Rimrock Lk Quad - May 3-5, 2011',
            'tr' => '
Dome Pk (6591 ft - P7110) & Strobach Mtn  (6397  ft  -  P277)  -  Foundation
Ridge Quad; Divide Ridge East (Jumpoff) Pk (5760+ ft - P960) - Tieton  Basin
Quad; Divide Ridge East Pk (6880+ ft - P800) & Pk 3737 (P457) - Darland  Mtn
Quad; and Pk 4128 (P848) - Rimrock Lk Quad - May 3-5, 2011

Divide Ridge is a long (over 15 miles) high ridge east  of  White  Pass  and
south of Rimrock Lake and the Tieton River.  There are 4 peaks either  named
or of prominence along its length all of  which  I  hoped  to  ski.  I  also
planned to climb on foot two smaller bonus peaks accessed  along  the  drive
to the snowline.

Tuesday, May 3: Pks 4128 and 3737 - Pk 4128 turned  out  to  be  a  pleasant
little  scramble  up  open  woods  to  a  cute  flat  summit  rimmed  by  an
interesting columnar basalt wall with good views to Rimrock  Lake  (1  mile,
1000 ft, 1:25 hr RT). Pk 3737 was an even shorter scramble along a  steepish
ridge to a nice viewpoint of Divide Ridge (.6 miles, 530 ft,:35 hrs RT).

From the road in the saddle below Pk 3737 I continued driving until  stopped
by snow at 3900 ft. I needed the 4 wheel drive on my Jeep to  punch  through
several snow patches but still didn\'t get  as  high  as  I  had  hoped.  The
previous week I had been able to drive to 4700 ft on the Bethel Ridge  Road,
the difference, I guess, between a northern and a southern exposure.

I began skiing the road at 2:45. I thought I had plenty of time  to  get  to
my planned campsite at the saddle on Divide Ridge below Dome Peak.  My  maps
showed "roads" all the way. I should have paid more  attention  to  Stefan\'s
recent report of Dome. He did not recommend skiing this route. I soon  found
out why. The upper roads are not really roads at all but  narrow  steep  4WD
trails that are difficult to follow in the snow and not really suitable  for
skis. I lost my way,  got  on  the  wrong  trail  and  ended  up  traversing
difficult forest to get back on track. The terrain eventually opened up  and
skiing improved in the basin below the saddle but that was after  struggling
for several hours. The last bit over the rim was steep and rocky and  I  had
to remove skis. I couldn\'t see how any semblance of a  "road"  could  go  up
through here, despite one shown on the map.  I  began  regretting  the  time
spent on my 2 bonus peaks but I did make  the  lovely  flat  meadow  in  the
saddle (elev 5800 ft) just in time to set up  camp  in  daylight  (5  miles,
2300 ft, 4:30 hrs).

Wednesday, May 4: Dome Pk, Stroback Mtn and Divide Ridge  E  Pk  -  The  day
dawned sunny, the snow crusty to start but  soon  softening.   This  is  the
first overnight trip this year I  didn\'t  need  toe  warmers  in  my  boots.
Skiing was wonderful up open slopes to Dome Peak and I  reached  the  summit
at 9:00 (1 mile, 800 ft, 1:00). I  continued  along  the  delightful  ridge,
with views constantly dueling between  Mt  Adams  and  Mt  Rainier  and  the
Tieton Valley, to Strobach Mtn (4 miles, 1150 ft, 3 hrs).

Once past Strobach the skiing quality deteriorated rapidly. I had some  good
stuff along the open ridge but soon entered forest and began a drop of  1600
ft to Louie Way Gap at 4800 ft. A traverse around Pt 5360 where  I  couldn\'t
see where I was going followed. I found no evidence of any useful trails.  I
had to leave  skis  for  the  last  bit  as  the  final  south  slopes  were
completely melted out and bare rock.  I  climbed  to  the  rocky  rim  at  a
distinctive memorial cross and continued from there across the flat  plateau
to the summit at 3:30 (9 miles, 2300 ft, 7:30 hrs).  By  now  it  was  quite
windy and I ate lunch in a sheltered spot below Jump BM just off the rim.

The return took just as long. Whatever possessed  me  to  come  this  far???
Sometimes I just don\'t know when to quit.  I tried  to  contour  around  the
summits but it didn\'t help that much. It goes without saying  I  was  caught
by darkness and the soft snow crusted over. But it  was  a  beautiful  night
and I was dazzled by the lights of Yakima. I reached my camp  at  11:00  too
tired to do much more than have a  cup  of  tea  and  a  quick  bite  before
falling into a deep sleep (18 miles, 4600 ft, 15 hrs).

Thursday, May 5: Divide Ridge W Pk - This  day  started  cloudy  with  light
sprinkles, threatening more than it ever  produced.  I  started  for  Divide
Ridge W Pk at 8:00. I actually found the sign in the saddle marking the  4WD
trail going to Strobach Spring but I immediately lost the  way.  I  wandered
through the forest and  ended  up  climbing  to  the  ridge  directly  above
instead of traversing as the trail did. Once on the  broad  flat  ridge  the
skiing was very nice but it was windy and getting windier.  I  followed  the
ridge to the open summit (3 miles, 1300 ft, 2 hrs). It was foggy and  I  had
no views. I returned to camp on a traverse below  the  ridge  to  avoid  the
increasing wind (6 miles, 1400 ft, 4 hrs).

Although windy the sun was making an appearance and I took a welcome nap  in
the warm tent until awakened by a gust so strong it tore all the stakes  out
of my tent (12" snow stakes). I have no doubt had I not  been  in  the  tent
and anchoring it with my weight my tent and  all  its  contents  would  have
been blown across the meadow. I took that as a sign  to  leave.   Once  down
from the windy saddle skiing was quite good. The sun was shining,  the  snow
soft and at times it was downright hot. I did a better job  of  finding  the
4WD trail below the open basin which led to a real, though  annoyingly  flat
and even up at times, road and back to my car (5 miles, 200 ft, 2:40 hrs).

Trip Total: 34 miles and 8600 ft in 3 days (not counting bonus peaks)

Fay Pullen



