            'tr' => '
Darland Mtn (6981 ft - P1621 - Darland Mtn Quad); Spencer  Pt  (6680+  ft  -
P1200 - Jennies Butte Quad); Coyote Rocks (6121 ft - P41  -  Fairview  Ridge
Quad); and Pk 3920+ ft (P440) & Kamiakin Butte (3516 ft  -  P356)  -  Spiral
Butte Quad - May 9-11, 2011

My main goal for this trip was  Klicton  Divide  (with  its  two  prominence
points of Darland Mtn and Spencer Pt) on the edge of the Goat Rocks and  the
Yakima Indian Reservation. Divide Ridge (where I was last week)  turns  into
Klicton Divide at Darland Mtn. On the drive in I picked up  two  more  bonus
peaks above Clear Lake.

Monday, May 9: Pk 3920 and Kamiakin Butte - I accessed Pk 3920 via  a  short
road on the north off Hwy 12 just  before  Tieton  Road  and  drove  to  the
saddle with Pt 3606. An easy hike up a continuing  rough  track  then  trail
then open woods led past a pond full of croaking frogs to the  open  summit.
I had a taste of things to come with an enticing partial view  of  the  Goat
Rocks (1.5 miles, 640 ft, 1:15 hrs RT).  I started for rocky Kamiakin  Butte
from the entrance to Camp Dudley skirting cliffs until I could  scramble  up
the NE slope (.75 miles, 450 ft, :45 hrs RT). Both these little  peaks  were
more fun than their diminutive size might indicate and it was nice  to  hike
on bare ground.

Disaster: After climbing these two  bonus  peaks  I  drove  the  South  Fork
Tieton River Road 1000 where I hoped to get close to Conrad Meadows at  4000
ft. Those hopes were soon dashed when I began running into significant  snow
at 3300 ft with about 7 miles still to go.  I  kept  punching  through  snow
patches interspersed between bare stretches until finally my  jeep  wouldn\'t
go anymore at 3600 ft, 4 miles still to go. This is  when  my  trip  took  a
disastrous turn and almost ended for good. While backing  up  to  get  to  a
bare spot I lost concentration for a moment, got out of the track and  slide
into the soft snow on the side. I was  stuck.  Man  was  I  ever  stuck!  In
surveying the situation I saw that I was high  centered  with  my  two  left
wheels on the packed track and my two right wheels in  deep  slush  with  no
traction whatsoever. There was no way I was going anywhere,  either  forward
or backward until I could get off the high center. Do you know how  hard  it
is to dig out snow from under the center of a vehicle? I will spare you  the
gruesome details but it is not easy. Especially for  this  little  old  lady
alone. I would have gladly accepted  help  from  any  redneck  who  happened
along. But alas, no one came by. In fact no one came  by  the  entire  three
days I was parked there.  I really thought I might have to swallow my  pride
and either hike out or climb up to cell  phone  reception  and  call  a  tow
truck. But I stubbornly kept digging and hacking away at the snow,  put  the
chains on and after 3 hours of strenuous work I was free.

The question was what to do now? It was 5:00. I still had a good 3.5  hours
of daylight and I could get several miles up the road but not  all  the  way
to my desired camp. However I was tired and demoralized  and  all  wet  from
lying in the snow (I had a change of clothes in the car but  they  were  not
climbing clothes). So I decided to car camp where I was, dry out  and  start
early the next morning rested and refreshed.

Tuesday, May 10: Spencer Pt - I was up and going  by  7:00  and  in  a  much
better mood. I walked/ skied the uninteresting flat road 3.5 miles  to  Road
1070, Â½ mile before Conrad Meadow. Thank heavens for iPods or I  would  have
been bored  silly.  There  were  long  stretches  of  bare  road  that  made
continuous skiing impossible but it will still be several weeks  before  the
road is completely melted out to Conrad Meadows. After  crossing  the  South
Fork Tieton River, Rd 1070 was skiable all the way to  "Diamond  Saddle"  at
5350 ft where I set up camp (8 miles, 2000 ft, 5 hrs).

I decided to go for the more scenic south end of Klicton Divide and  Spencer
Point on this beautiful warm sunny  day  as  the  weather  was  supposed  to
change for the worse tomorrow. I set out at 1:30. It was so warm I  stripped
down to my long johns and shirt sleeves. I am thinking it is  time  to  make
the switch to warmer weather gear next trip. I skied along  the  edge  of  a
clear-cut, then traversed woods until I could make a  steep  ascent  to  the
ridge below Pt 6490. This steep section was the only place I  needed  skins.
Once on the ridge skiing was easy and the terrain opened  up  as  I  rounded
the point. Views were gorgeous. I tried to stay on the ridge but ran into  a
rocky pinnacle that I turned on the south side. Back on the ridge past  this
I was directly across from  the  heart  of  the  southern  Goat  Rocks.  All
memories of my previous difficulties were erased. The  final  ridge  to  the
summit was glorious (4.5 miles, 1680 ft, 3:20 hrs).

I was oh so very tempted to continue along Klicton Divide,  which  goes  all
the way to Mt Curtis Gilbert. It looked delicious. But I controlled  myself,
learning from my last trip not to go too far. I really wanted  to  get  back
to camp before dark and before the snow crusted over and made  for  horrible
skiing. And because of this I  had  a  wonderful  ski  back.  The  snow  was
perfect spring snow. I reached camp with the sun still shining on  the  tent
at 7:45 (9 miles, 2050 ft, 6:15 hrs).

Total for the day: 17 miles, 4050 ft, 11:15 hrs

Wednesday, May 11: Darland Mtn and Coyote Rocks - I got an  early  start  at
6:45 as I wanted to beat the weather. The day started cloudy with a few  sun
breaks at times and although it didn\'t freeze during the night the snow  was
crusty and I needed full skins. I followed the gentle ridge north.  Most  of
the way was open or through burned forest. It was very pleasant  travel.  At
Narrowneck Gap the final rise to Darland steepened  and  the  snow  had  not
softened yet so it was an effort to ski up the slick crust. The flat  summit
plateau was very expansive, the highest point marked by  a  cell  tower  and
flag (4 miles, 1860 ft, 2:45 hrs).

By the time I left the snow had softened enough  that  I  was  able  to  ski
(rather than boot) down to Narrowneck Gap. From there I could  see  that  it
would be good skiing to  Coyote  Rocks  and  since  the  weather  was  still
holding I decided to add the extra 1.5  mile side trip to  my  itinerary.  I
am glad I did. Coyote Rocks was a delight and to my mind had a nicer  summit
than Darland (6 miles, 2020 ft, 4:25 hrs). I had a lovely ski back  to  camp
arriving at 12:55 (9 miles, 2240 ft, 6:10 hrs).

I could tell the rain wouldn\'t hold off for much  longer  so  I  immediately
packed up to leave at 1:40 for the trip out. The ski  down  Road  1070  went
well, but Road 1000 was an absolute pain. I skied what I could  but  I  lost
count after a dozen of the times I had to take my skis off for bare  ground.
But I did beat the rain (8 miles, 150 ft,  3  hrs).  It  rained  the  entire
drive home.

Trip total: 34 miles and 6450 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen



