Mt Church (4780 ft - P1180 - Mt Tebo Quad) - Friday, May 11, 2011

I wanted good weather for this little peak which I knew would  require  some
rock work. I drove FR 23 and  2361  up  the  South  Fork  Skokomish  to  the
junction with 2363. I had hoped to drive this road to the snowline  and  ski
to its end. The 4th edition Olympic Mountain Climber\'s Guide (2006) has  the
road drivable for 5 miles. It is  no  more.  It  is  blocked  right  at  the
junction with 2361 and is now ditched and decommissioned. And I mean  REALLY
DECOMMISSIONED. There are  deep  ditches  every  100  feet  for  its  entire
length. I fail to understand why old roads  are  ditched  and  why  this  is
better for the environment then just letting them revert  slowly  to  nature
and make a pleasant hiking path. Please, someone  explain  to  me  how  huge
ditches that disturb the soil are good for anything.  They certainly  render
the road completely useless for skiing and biking not to mention  making  it
a real pain to even hike. Sure, put in 4  or  5  ditches  at  the  start  to
prevent vehicular traffic. But I hiked this road for over  2  miles  with  a
ditch every 100 feet. Do the math. That adds up to about 100 ditches.

After 2 miles on the road I grew weary of the ditches  and  as  soon  as  it
seemed feasible headed uphill to cut the switchbacks. The first part was  in
unpleasant thick second growth but as the snow  got  deeper  and  the  trees
thinner travel became easier. At the end of the upper  road  I  entered  old
forest, which though steep, was very pleasant going. I stayed just  left  of
the SE rib and any rocky outcrops. The rib gentled about  4000  ft  where  I
began heading right toward the col in the south ridge. Snow was not too  bad
for step kicking and I sank in about ankle deep.

I went all the way to the col but once there could  not  find  an  easy  way
onto the ridge. I dinked around for half an hour trying  to  find  a  direct
route up on damp holdless rock before deciding that wouldn\'t work for me.  I
thought I might have to drop way below the summit  rocks  and  work  my  way
around to the right on nasty looking  steep  snow  when  I  spied  a  hidden
chimney behind a tree slightly down from the col. I squirmed  up  this  into
more trees where I came across a rappel sling  with  a  rap  ring  attached.
This assured me I was on someone\'s route. But I was not happy that they  had
considered it necessary to rappel. I was even less happy when I  popped  out
of the trees and got a good look at  the  ridge.  Good  grief  -  it  looked
rather daunting. The climber\'s guide rates this peak as class 3. But I  know
by now it always underrates climbs so expected some class 4. I  did  have  a
rope along but didn\'t really want to use it.

The ridge was not as bad as it first looked - mostly  class  3  with  a  few
class 4 moves here and there. But it was exposed and longer than expected  -
several ropes  lengths  -  with  many  ups  and  downs  to  get  past  small
pinnacles. One of the worst spots for me was just below the summit  where  I
had to cross a short exposed snow patch without my axe (I  had  left  it  at
the chimney). I found a large summit register on top but it was so soggy  as
to be useless so I left a new one. I spent about 30 minutes  on  top  trying
to identify distant peaks and not being very successful at it.

It took about as long to downclimb the ridge as to climb it  but  I  managed
without any rappels. It was fast down the snow although  I  sank  in  a  lot
deeper, over my calf in places. The whole road thing  and  rocky  ridge  had
taken longer than expected but I planned to car camp that night  so  was  in
no great hurry. In keeping with my usual MO I did the last of  the  road  by
headlamp.

Time up: 5:45 hrs - Time down: 2:30 hrs - Total: 7 miles, 3800 ft  and  8:45
hrs

Saturday, May 12 - After a car camp, the next day  I  hiked  up  Dusk  Point
(3241 ft - P481 - Mt Tebo Quad)  and Pk 2321 (P561  -  Mt  Tebo  Quad).  The
road up Pk 2321 has also been decommissioned so I went straight  up  the  NW
slope. Steep but not too bad (.5 miles, 575 ft, 1:10 hr RT). I was  able  to
drive the road up Dusk Point to 2500 ft before being stopped by  snow.  From
there I gained the S ridge to hit the road high up. From  the  looks  of  it
(trees growing in the middle) I would say the road  is  no  longer  drivable
all the way to the top even when the snow is gone. But  at  least  it  isn\'t
ditched. The open top is a nice viewpoint where I got  a  good  look  at  my
route up Church (1.5 miles, 685 ft, 1:45 RT).

Fay Pullen





