            'title' => 'Ironstone Mtn (6441 ft - P601 - Rimrock Lk Quad), Russell Ridge (6186 ft - P186 - Spiral Butte Quad), Pk 4480+ ft - (P680 - Rimrock Lk Quad), Westfall Rocks (4060 ft - P100 - Rimrock Lk Quad) and Chimney Peaks (3870 ft - P230 - Tieton Basin Quad) - May 24-25, 2011',
            'tr' => '
Ironstone Mtn (6441 ft - P601 - Rimrock Lk Quad), Russell Ridge (6186  ft  -
P186 - Spiral Butte Quad), Pk 4480+ ft - (P680 - Rimrock Lk Quad),  Westfall
Rocks (4060 ft - P100 - Rimrock Lk Quad) and Chimney Peaks (3870 ft  -  P230
- Tieton Basin Quad) - May 24-25, 2011

Tuesday, May 24 - This was to be the only good  weather  day  of  the  week.
Wednesday looked wet. So how to make the most of my one good day?

Chimney Peaks - I have passed by Chimney Peaks several  times on the way  to
Kloochman Rock and often seen them from afar. They looked intriguing  and  I
always wanted to climb them. I needed dry rock though  so  thought  I  could
fit them in today before the main event of Ironstone rather  than  after  on
tomorrow when I would have more time but  also  most  likely  rain.  In  the
interest of saving time I had planned to climb only the highest peak  but  I
found the scrambling so much fun on fascinating horizontal  columnar  basalt
that I continued on the ridge going over every bump (7 or 8  depending  upon
what you count) along the way (1.2 miles, 1130 ft, 2:10 hrs RT).

Ironstone Pk and Russell Ridge - I drove the  road  up  the  south  side  of
Wildcat Cr where I ran into many woodcutters, some commercial that  appeared
to be thinning small trees and  some  private  that  looked  to  be  cutting
firewood. I was stopped by snow .2 miles before the road  end  at  4260  ft.
This road does not go to the official Wildcat TH but did get me  higher  and
farther. I started at 2:50. There is no connector path that I found  but  it
was easy to find a way through minimal brush and across a log  over  Wildcat
Cr to the main trail. The first part was mostly snow free to the  William  O
Douglas Wilderness boundary. Would you believe that the signpost  there  was
already (or maybe still) stocked with permits? I dutifully  filled  one  out
although I saw no signs of anyone having been this way, did  not  expect  to
see anyone and in fact did not see anyone.

Past the Wilderness boundary I  quickly  began  running  into  snow.  I  was
travelling light. I was done with hard core winter camping  for  this  year.
I had a 3 season tent, lighter sleeping bag, no snow stakes  and  no  shovel
so I really wanted to camp on bare ground. I  figured  my  best  chance  was
away from the valley floor on an open higher  bench  fully  exposed  to  the
sun. I headed uphill in search of such a place and indeed did  find  one  on
relatively dry gravel (all meadows were soggy wet) at  5360  ft.  (3  miles,
1200 ft 2:10 hrs). Running water was everywhere. No more  melting  snow  for
water either.

It took an hour to set up camp. I started for Ironstone  at  6:00.  I  would
have preferred to lounge around in the warm sun but I  knew  tomorrow  would
be wet. It was not far to  Ironstone  and  despite  spending  more  time  on
Chimney Peaks than I had planned, I still thought I had time to make it  and
Russell Ridge before dark. If not, there was always the headlamp. I did  not
bring snowshoes but did bring an ice axe. I didn\'t  need  either.  The  snow
was soft but consolidated enough for good walking. I only broke through  the
occasional rotten spot. I headed for the NE ridge of Ironstone. Once on  the
ridge I came across very fresh mountain goat tracks. Just below  the  summit
I startled the track maker and he took off running across the snow.  I  just
managed to get my camera out and take a photo  before  be  disappeared  from
sight.

The summit was melted out (1050 ft,  1  hr).  I  found  a  large  PVC   tube
register but it was empty  except  for  one  soggy  scrap  of  paper.  I  am
continually amazed that someone will carry a huge register  container  to  a
summit only to skimp on the quality of the paper register inside.  I  repeat
again that a register must be made of WATERPROOF paper to be of any use  and
remain legible when wet (and they all get wet eventually). Had I known  such
a container was on top I would have  brought  one  of  my  large  waterproof
booklets to put inside. As it was I only had a small register with me  so  I
just stuck the whole thing inside the larger one.

I quickly descended to Fox Meadow and started up Russell Ridge. The way  was
mostly wooded but I had a partial view of Ironstone shining  bright  red  in
the late afternoon sun clearly showing why it is so named. I made  the  high
point at 8:20, quickly returned to Fox meadow and traversed below  Ironstone
back to camp at 9:30 (4 miles, 1750 ft, 3:30 hr RT). I did use  my  headlamp
the last bit.

Wednesday, May 25  -  I  awoke  to  clouds  with  rain  not  far  behind.  I
thankfully packed up while it was still dry, the rain  starting  just  as  I
left at 8:00. It rained steadily the whole 2 hours going out  and  the  rest
of the day.

Pk 4480+ - I saved this prominence peak  for the drive out as I  figured  it
could be done in the rain. Again woodcutters were busy in the area. In  fact
I had to squeeze past parked vehicles and  move  some  debris  left  in  the
roadway in one place. In another a guy was parked right  in  the  middle  of
the road and I could not get by. He was starting his chainsaw so  I  had  to
honk to get his attention. He cheerfully moved his truck. I don\'t  think  he
expected anyone to come by. I get that a lot. I drove road spurs to the  end
on the SE side of the peak and hiked pleasant open terrain to the  cute  top
marked by a cairn. Views would be nice on a clear day but I saw  nothing  in
the fog(1 mile, 530 ft, :50 hr RT).

Since it was so close I also hiked up Westfall Rocks. It was only  .4  mile,
100 ft and :15 hr RT. It too would be a nice viewpoint.  In  fact  I  had  a
fairly nice close view through the rain of  Rimrock  Lake,  Tieton  Dam  and
straight down to Hwy 12 but I hadn\'t bothered to bring a camera.

Fay Pullen









