            'tr' => '
Bearcat Peak (7960+ at least - P640 - Lucerne Quad) and Peak  7942  (P662  -
Pinnacle Mtn Quad) - June 8-11, 2011

Wednesday, June 8 - This trip had been scheduled to start on Tuesday  but  I
lobbied Mike successfully to have it  pushed  to  Wednesday.  I  desperately
needed another day to recover after being hit by a small snow block  on  Big
Four the previous Sunday and tumbling downhill fifty feet or  so.  I  wasn\'t
sure even then I would be able to make it but  the  damage  to  my  leg  was
temporary and not as bad as I first thought. It ended up  not  hindering  me
at all.

I met Roy and Mike at Field\'s Point for the boat ride to Lucerne.  I  wanted
to be completely independent just in case I had to retreat  early.  That  is
where I discovered I had forgotten my camera. I would have to rely  on  Mike
taking pictures. We began hiking the trail to Emerald Park  at  12:10  under
sunny skies. Once past the Domke Lake junction, the trail went most  of  the
way through burned forest. It was in good shape with only mild brush  and  a
few small logs to cross. It was completely snow  free  to  about  4500  feet
except for some avalanche snow in gullies. By the time we made camp  at  the
first reasonable place at 4900 ft  snow  was  continuous  and  several  feet
deep. We were still about 1 mile from Emerald Park. Roy found a  small  bare
patch that accommodated his tiny tent while Mike  and  I  leveled  spots  on
snow just as it began to rain lightly. It rained into the night.

Total: 6.5 miles, 3750 ft and 6:40 hr

Thursday, June 9: Peak 7942 -Mike and I got a leisurely start  at  7:45  for
our bonus peaks in warm sunshine. Roy stayed in  camp  and  rested  for  the
main event of Bearcat the next day. We decided to  go  for  the  farther  Pk
7942 first.  We wound our way through dense trees toward Emerald Park  until
we could head uphill to the 6700 ft  saddle  above  Mirror  Lake.  There  is
supposed to be a trail to here but we saw no sign of it. From the saddle  we
dropped 500 feet, traversed below cliffs to a lovely basin  NE  of  Pinnacle
Mtn before climbing to the south ridge of Pk 7942. There were many signs  of
recent avalanches. The terrain was  easy  but  the  snow  soft  and  getting
softer. Trail breaking was a chore and we  traded  off  frequently.  It  was
particularly bad the last bit along the ridge to the summit  where  we  were
sinking in to the knees or deeper.  Mike being heavier had a harder time  of
it than I. He would even often break through my tracks when I  was  leading.
There was evidence of maybe a foot or more  of  recent  new  snow  here.  We
reached the summit cairn (melted out) at 1:00 (3540 ft 5:15 hrs).

I found the most unusual register I  have  ever  seen  buried  deep  in  the
summit cairn - a single piece of paper inside  a  plastic  bag  and  wrapped
tightly in athletic tape. It took me over  5  minutes  to  unwrap  the  darn
thing. It had been placed by Mitch  Blanton  on  his  FA  in  2001  and  was
obviously not meant to be used by anyone else.  At  least  it  was  dry  and
still legible. I placed the paper inside one of my registers.

We now hoped to get Peak 7738. It was  easier  going  following  our  tracks
back to the 6700 ft saddle. From there we tried  to  follow  the  ridge  but
soon got stopped by pinnacles and a steep nasty sidehill of  snow  and  rock
below the false summit. With no rope, uncertain prospects and  time  running
out we mutually agree to turn around. We were back in  camp  by  7:00  where
Roy had a welcome fire going that helped to dry out wet pants and boots.

Total: 9 miles, 4750 ft and 11 hrs

Friday, June 10: Bearcat Pk - Today was the main event and what we  had  all
come for, the TOP 200 peak of Bearcat. We were on the go by 6:30 and in  the
basin of Emerald Park in an hour. At this point we  weren\'t  sure  where  to
go. All the available route descriptions were so vague or confusing that  we
weren\'t even sure which side to approach from. But Mike and  I  had  a  good
view from the previous day and decided on the NE ridge.  We  climbed  slopes
to below the NW  face then cut left  to  cross  the  north  ridge  into  the
beautiful NE basin where a steep gully led to a 7600  ft  notch  in  the  NE
ridge (2800 ft, 4 hrs).

Here is where it all fell apart. We had hoped for  easy  melted  out  ledges
traversing the south side to below the summit. What we found instead  was  a
series of steep ugly snow filled gullies between rocky ribs.  If  it  hadn\'t
been for Mike\'s optimism I would have thrown in the towel  then  and  there.
The whole traverse looked like a nightmare to me, and  it  wasn\'t  far  from
it. We took turns leading across the soft snow. The snow  was  topped  by  a
layer of several new inches that had to be removed before solid steps  could
be kicked. It was slough off the top layer, watch it slide downhill  out  of
sight, kick a step and  repeat.  Step,  slough,  step,  slough.  Slow,  slow
going. And all this on slopes so steep with no runout that if  you  lost  it
you were dead. I haven\'t been so freaked out since I climbed  Lincoln.  This
went on for hours, crossing gully after gully and  rib  after  rib.  I  lost
count how many. At one place Mike had to chop his  way  through  a  vertical
cornice to gain a rib. On another I had to step across a scary moat  onto  a
wet ledge with minimal handholds. And at the last rib we had  to  rappel  to
get off. Finally we were at the  gully  below  the  summit  and  could  head
uphill. As we were finishing the rappel a  spontaneous  slide  came  roaring
down this gully\'s runnel spilling over the cliffs below. I think  even  Mike
was shaken by that.

Fortunately we crossed the runnel without mishap and  climbed  ever  steeper
snow above to the summit ridge and then the summit at 3:45  (3500  ft,  9:15
hrs). We found no previous register although I know some were left.  I  hope
mine stays a while longer. We didn\'t linger long on top. The way  back  went
easier with a packed track and  known  route  but  we  took  it  slowly  and
carefully often going one at a time. We were able to  up  climb  the  rappel
but did a rappel at another especially tricky spot. We reached the notch  at
7:00 and camp just before 9:00. I was so tired I barely had  the  energy  to
down a bite of dinner before falling into bed.  Roy  didn\'t  even  make  his
trademark fire.

Total: 6 miles, 3700 ft and 14: 15 hrs

Saturday, June 11 - Roy did make a morning fire before  we  all  left  about
8:00 for the trek out, each at his own pace. We easily made  the  2:30  boat
(6.5 miles and 4:00 hrs).

Grand Total: - 28 miles and 12,200 ft in 4 days

Fay Pullen

I want to make a comment about Roy. This guy is amazing.  At  82  and  still
climbing peaks of this caliber. He puts us all to shame. I only hope  I  can
equal him when I am that age. My hat is off to "Amazing Roy".







