            'title' => 'Crescent Mtn (7816 ft - P656), Mother Lode (7905 ft - P1585) and South Creek Butte (7670 ft - P190) - Gilbert Quad - June 16-18, 2011',
            'tr' => '
Crescent Mtn (7816 ft - P656), Mother Lode  (7905  ft  -  P1585)  and  South
Creek Butte (7670 ft - P190) - Gilbert Quad - June 16-18, 2011

Thursday, June 16 - The drive to the  Twisp  River  Valley  is  long  and  I
didn\'t get a particularly early start so it was 1:20 before I stared up  the
South Creek trail. No problem. All I  had  to  do  was  get  to  a  campsite
reasonably close to my peaks before dark and I figured I  still  had  plenty
of time for that. The trail  showed  little  signs  of  recent  use.  A  few
parties had signed the trail register listing either Louis  Lake  or  "none"
as their destination. I doubt those headed for Louis Lake made it  as  South
Creek was a raging torrent and  would  be  difficult  to  cross.  I  luckily
didn\'t have to cross any major creeks.

The trail was snow free to where I left it at 4400 ft (3.5 miles,  1200  ft,
2:20 hrs), just past an inviting meadow and just before  crossing  the  side
creek draining Crescent Basin. It was tempting to  camp  there  but  it  was
only 3:40 and much too early to stop. I headed uphill in  open  woods  on  a
rib paralleling the creek. The going was very nice from the start with  very
little brush and it got even better when I ran into a way trail. This  trail
had the look of an old built trail with switchbacks in places. As the  slope
steepened so did the trail and it became crisscrossed  with  various  animal
trails but for the most part it was easily followed. I sure didn\'t expect  a
trail. Was it an old miner\'s trail (many mines in this  area)  or  was  this
the way to the old lookout on South Creek Butte?

At 5:30 and 5760 ft the rib flattened with snow beginning. I could see  that
from here on snow would be continuous and I really didn\'t want  to  camp  on
snow again so began looking for a site. I found a lovely flat spot  on  bare
ground with a tiny babbling brook nearby for water. Perfect.

Day total: 4.5 miles, 2500 ft, 4:10 hrs

Friday, June 17 - Since I had turned in at 8:30 the night before  I  had  no
trouble getting up early and being ready to go by 6:10.  It was  39  degrees
in my tent. I began in trees gradually working my way to a broad snow  gully
directly below Crescent Mtn. Since the  gully  was  quite  steep,  still  in
shade and the snow frozen I donned crampons. I kept them on until  the  last
100 feet of rock scrambling to the summit which I reached at 8:50 (2140  ft,
2:40 hrs). I found neither cairn nor register and left both.

 Views were expansive though a bit hazy in the distance. I  was  immediately
taken by a very impressive looking peak with a sheer rock face to  the  west
peaking up over the ridge. I became briefly concerned when I  realized  this
was Mother Lode and next up on my agenda.  It  looked  very  difficult  from
this aspect but my fears were quickly allayed when I determined I would  not
be climbing it from that side. I put crampons back  on  to  descend  to  the
head of Crescent basin at 7000 ft then removed them as  I  entered  sunshine
and the snow quickly turned to slush.  I  traversed  below  the  ridge  line
until I could gain the ridge at the only possible place between cornices  on
the 7560 ft saddle north of South Creek Butte. The final bit to  the  saddle
was very steep and I had to pass  under  a  cornice  that  was  melting  and
sending down small sloughs. After recent events this made me very nervous.

From the saddle I traversed downward north across a  series  of  loose  rock
ribs and snow gullies to the lower 7440 ft saddle  SE  of  Mother  Lode  and
followed the easy SE ridge to the summit at 12:15 (3300  ft,  5:30  hrs).  I
found a cairn but no register so left one of mine. It  was  so  pleasant  on
the summit with sun and no wind that I spent a  full  hour  for  lunch  even
removing boots to dry a bit and taking a short nap while  ladybugs  used  me
for a launching pad.

I returned to the Mother Lode saddle. I didn\'t want to repeat my mixed  rock
and snow traverse from South Creek Butte saddle. Instead it  was  easier  to
take the further drop to 7280 to  continuous  snow  below  all  rock  before
climbing directly up to the summit of South Creek Butte at  2:30  (3700  ft,
8:20 hrs) where I stayed 30  minutes.  Debris  from  a  burned  lookout  was
scattered about. To return I followed the left side of the ridge  the  short
distance to the saddle and picked up my tracks going down past the  cornice.
Again I was nervous. I kicked off sloughs as  I  went  down.  The  top  snow
layer has still not consolidated.

I soon left my uphill track from Crescent  for  a  more  direct  descent  to
Crescent Basin. I am not sure it was any better as I was forced way  to  the
right to avoid cliffs. Once in the flat of the  basin  it  was  easy  travel
back to camp at 4:40. I certainly had time to go out this day but  I  really
didn\'t want to also do the long drive  home  partially  in  the  dark  which
meant I would car camp. It was so pleasant in my  camp  I  decided  I  would
rather spend another night there even though the forecast was for  rain  the
next day, and so I did. It was a real treat  lounging  around  in  the  warm
sunshine. Usually when I return to a high camp it is too late, I am  in  too
much of a hurry, I am too tired or the weather is too  lousy  to  completely
enjoy myself.

Day total: 4.5 miles, 3700 ft and 10:30 hrs

Saturday, June 18 - Sure enough light rain came in during the night  however
by the time I was packed and ready to go at  6:45  it  had  stopped  and  it
rained no more on the way out. Wet brush did require putting on  rain  pants
though but trip out was really  quite  enjoyable.  Being  rested  helped.  I
reached the car at 9:15 ready to tackle the long drive home (4.5  miles  and
2:30 hrs). Once over Snoqualmie Pass it rained constantly.

Trip total: 13.5 miles and 6300 ft in 2.5 days

Fay Pullen



