            'tr' => '
Marsupial Mtn (7917 ft - P717 - Gilbert Quad) - June 21-22, 2011

Tuesday, June 21 - I had so much fun last week on Crescent and  Mother  Lode
I returned to the Twisp area this week for another  trip.  Then  I  went  up
South Creek so this time I thought it appropriate to go up  North  Creek.  I
got a very late start (2:45) as I couldn\'t leave town until after a  morning
orthodontist appointment.  Thanks heavens for long daylight hours this  time
of year (this was, by the way, the first  day  of  summer).   I  was  slowly
plodding up the trail in the hot sun (definitely shorts weather) when I  was
passed by two young gals with two large yellow labs  out  for  a  day  hike.
When I mentioned in conversation that I was  worried  about  getting  across
North Creek (I could see it raging below  the  trail)  they  seemed  unaware
that the trail even crossed the creek and that if it did there would  be  no
bridge. I caught up to them at a side creek about a  mile  and  a  half  up.
They thought this was the crossing I was talking about. Hardly! It  was  not
a problem, barely 4 feet across and even had  a  log  across  it,  but  they
decided to turn around anyway worried about their dogs. I  would  think  the
dogs could jump across in a single leap but then  I  tend  to  underestimate
the concerns of the ordinary hiker. I have been  hanging  out  with  climber
types too long. They watched to make sure I crossed  safely  which  made  me
self-conscious. It sure would have been embarrassing  to  have  slipped  and
fallen in.

I continued on the trail through several lovely  green  meadows  alive  with
avalanche lilies before I began running into snow about 5000 ft. At 3  miles
and 5100 I came to the crossing of North Creek. As feared I could  not  find
a way across. On the Plan B, which was to parallel the creek  on  the  south
side. This worked well except for being slow going in the now  solid  slushy
snow cover. My main concern was that I now doubted I would find a snow  free
spot to camp being stuck on the shady side of  the  creek.  That  being  the
case I figured I might just as well go  all  the  way  to  North  Lake  even
though I was sure it would be completely snowed  in.  I  pulled  into  North
Lake at 7:30 and to my pleasant surprise found a tiny bare  spot  of  ground
large enough for my tiny tent right on the lake shore.

Total: 5.5 miles, 2100 ft and 4:45 hrs

Wednesday, June 22 - I was up and going by 5:55. It appeared there might  be
a route directly from camp up the east slope but  the  map  contours  looked
awfully close together and I was  afraid  I  might  get  into  trouble  from
something I couldn\'t see from below. The surest route looked to  be  up  the
south slope so that is where I headed. I began climbing up too soon and  got
above cliffs that prevented me from getting into  the  gully  to  the  south
basin which is where I really wanted to be. So  I  just  kept  climbing  and
turned the south ridge just below its cliffs. The snow in the open was  hard
enough to require crampons and got harder  the  higher  I  went.  The  upper
south slope was quite steep and hard and required 4-5 kicks for  each  solid
toe hold. The summit block was a short class 3 scramble. I reached  the  top
at 9:10 (2200 ft, 3:15 hrs).

I found a cairn and a film can register. I fully expected it  to  have  been
placed by someone I knew well. Imagine my surprise when I read the  name  of
some stranger from Massachusetts who had climbed the peak  in  September  of
2001. What is up with that? I left his film can  but  added  a  register  of
mine. Despite gorgeous views, I only stayed on top 25 minutes  as  I  wanted
to get home at a reasonable hour. I was leaving town for  a  family  reunion
on Friday and had things to do. I had to back down  the  upper  south  slope
but the snow was already getting softer and  I  easily  made  better  steps.
Later I imagine it would get worse as the day warmed  even  more,  with  the
surface soughing off and breaking out. I hit  it  just  right.  I  descended
directly into the south basin and down the exit gully (solid snow)  all  the
way to North Lake, a much better way than my traverse route  up.  I  reached
camp at 11:00 (2 miles, 2200 ft, 5:05 hrs RT). I  rested  30  minutes,  then
packed up and left at noon. I hit the trail at 1:45  and  the  car  at  3:15
(5.5 miles, 3:15 hrs).

Trip Total: 13 miles and 4300 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen





