            'title' => 'Mt Tragedy [Sable Ridge South Pk] (7800+ ft - P560) & Sable Ridge North Pk (7730 ft - P690) - Mt Lyall Quad; and Black Tower (7880+ ft - P480) - Holden Quad - July 2-5, 2011',
            'tr' => '
Mt Tragedy [Sable Ridge South Pk] (7800+ ft - P560) & Sable Ridge  North  Pk
(7730 ft - P690) - Mt Lyall Quad; and  Black  Tower  (7880+  ft  -  P480)  -
Holden Quad - July 2-5, 2011

Last year over the 4th  of  July  Jim,  Eileen,  Beth  and  I  had  made  an
unsuccessful attempt on Black Tower (we got off route and ran out  of  time)
after climbing Riddle, Flora and Puzzle. We were struck  by  the  beauty  of
Tenmile Basin which at that time was a field of gorgeous glacier lilies  and
completely melted out. We vowed to return for Black Tower and  camp  in  the
basin.  Joining for this trip were Mike, Kevin and George. Mike and  I  also
wanted to do the two prominence points  on  Sable  Ridge.  The  others  were
adding WyEast, which Mike and I had already done. Since Mike and I  had  the
same agenda we carpooled and tented together. This worked out very well.

Saturday, July 2 - We took the holiday crowded Lady II to Holden  and  hiked
the Tenmile Cr Trail to Tenmile Basin at 5600 ft. We were helped  by  a  WTA
work party\'s recent efforts on the first part and by the fact that  we  knew
exactly where the easy log across Tenmile Cr was located since we  had  used
it last year.  But our hope of camping  in  stunning  glacier  lily  meadows
were dashed by a still almost entirely snow filled basin.  Mike and  I  were
able to find a snow free tent site under a tree while the  others  ended  up
camping on snow. This year of unusual late snowpack continues to confound.

Total: 5 miles, 2700 ft and 4:40 hrs

Sunday, July 3: Sable Ridge  -  We  all  started  together  at  8:00  toward
Hilgard Pass before soon separating, Mike and I to head for Sable Ridge  and
the other five for WyEast  approaching  it  from  the  Black  Tower/Johnsons
Jonah Col. At 6600 ft Hilgard Pass  we  were  confronted  by  a  frightfully
steep descent of 300 feet on  the  other  side.  The  trail  was  completely
hidden under snow and of no help  whatsoever.  Left  to  my  own  devices  I
probably would have rappelled some of it  but  Mike  kicked  bomber  buckets
down the 45+ degree snow and teased out a way on equally  steep  slick  dirt
and rock outcroppings.  It  took  about  an  hour  to  slowly  descend  this
section. I breathed a sigh of relief when we  reached  the  lower  open  and
more gentle snow slopes of Hilgard Basin for a  further  500  foot  drop  to
5800 ft.

Once in the basin an obvious easy  looking  broad  snow  corridor  lured  us
immediately upward to what I call Col 1. The only problem was this  was  not
the col we wanted. We really wanted to be at the one farther north  (Col  2)
past what I call Sable Point. This little error cost us a  lot  of  time  as
once at Col 1 we had to traverse the west slope get past numerous  pinnacles
and we found we had to  descent  several  hundred  feet  to  get  below  the
cliffs. But before descending we decided to climb Sable Point since we  were
so close and it was an attractive summit with great views.

Once past all the pinnacles we were able to climb back up to Col 2 at  2:00,
which is where we should have been in the first place. Once at Col 2 it  was
an easy ascent to Sable South at 2:50 (3400 ft, 6:50  hrs).  After  a  short
little scramble on loose rock we found the summit  cairn  and  Roper\'s  film
can register where we learned he named it "Mt  Tragedy"  because  one  could
see the Hilgard Pass Trail where packer Ray Courtney fell to his death  with
his horses. I was not aware of this little  bit  of  history  and  I  really
didn\'t need to know that.  I  had  found  Hilgard  Pass  frightening  enough
without knowing someone had died there. Roper\'s register neglected  to  list
the date but we found out later it was  9/2/1986.  Mitch  Blanton  and  Mike
Collins had also signed in on 6/7/03 and Don and Natala Goodman on  9/11/06.
I added a new register with a pencil.

As time continued to slip past us we were coming to the conclusion  that  we
might not have time to make Sable  North  even  though  we  both  wanted  it
badly. We could see that if we could just get to Col 3  to  the  north  easy
snow slopes led all the way to that peak. But how to get  there?  Then  from
the summit of Tragedy I spotted a friendly looking snow descent. I  couldn\'t
quite see if it was continuous but I convinced Mike  we  should  give  it  a
try. Of course it wasn\'t continuous and  ended  in  a  cliff  with  a  nasty
gully. I thought we were screwed but Mike found a way down  without  needing
a rope. Once down that an easy traverse led to Col 3 at 4:15. At this  point
there was no way I wasn\'t going to make our second  summit  even  though  it
was clear we would get back to camp after dark.  I  had  invested  too  much
time and energy to give up now.  Fortunately, the rest of the  way  was  for
the most part on easy snow slopes although we had to take  another  drop  of
400 feet after crossing a rib before climbing to Col  4  and  following  the
ridge to the summit. We arrived at 6:15  to  find  Mitch  Blanton  and  Mike
Collin\'s first ascent register. Oddly they too forgot to  record  the  date.
We assumed it was the same date as  Tragedy,  6/7/03.  We  were  the  second
ascent.

Despite the time pressure we spent 30 minutes on the summit  before  quickly
retracing our steps down to Col 4 and up and over the  rib  to  near  Col  3
where we diverged from our  tracks  and  headed  on  a  descending  traverse
toward Hilgard Creek. This took less than an hour to the diverge  point  but
we soon ran into difficulties of brush and cliffs and lost  more  time.  Our
time table kept changing throughout the day.  Originally  we  wanted  to  be
back to camp by 8:30, then 9:30, then 10:00. Then we hoped  to  still  climb
up Hilgard Pass in daylight. In the end I  just  hoped  to  be  back  before
midnight. We did make this last goal. We found a reasonable  route  down  to
the valley floor and followed it about a  mile,  through  massive  avalanche
debris (more slow going) that had come down from all  sides,  to  the  upper
basin where we picked up our route to Hilgard Pass just as darkness hit.  We
needed headlamps for the steep ascent in the woods. Our buckets  steps  sure
helped as the snow was now freezing and hard. We pulled  over  the  pass  at
10:30 and soon ran into the rest of the party\'s glissade tracks coming  down
the Black Tower gully. The snow was  quite  hard  and  crampons  would  have
helped but we didn\'t stop to put them on. As we neared camp we  could  first
see a beacon of flashing light and then  a  friendly  campfire.  Jim,  bless
him, had kept the fire going for us and had hot  water  all  ready  when  we
dragged into camp at 11:15. Without that already prepared I would have  just
fallen into bed without any dinner. He even stayed up with us while  we  had
a quick dinner before turning in about midnight. I hope he  knows  how  much
we appreciated his thoughtfulness.

Total: 8 miles, 6500 ft and 15:15 hrs

Monday, July 4: Black Tower - In comparison to Sable Ridge, Black Tower  was
a walk in the park. Good thing as I for one was totally wiped out. We got  a
late start at 9:30 after a very leisurely  breakfast.  The  snow  was  still
frozen and crampons helpful. All seven of us were together  for  this  climb
as we climbed to a notch on the west ridge. Here we puzzled out a route  via
an easy ledge that led to a series of easy  but  loose  gullies  on  the  SW
slope. Don Goodman\'s advice was the most helpful of any of the  other  vague
route descriptions we had, "if you need a rope  you  are  off  route".  With
this in mind we worked our way to the summit at 1:00  (2300  ft,  3:30  hr).
The final bit was a scramble on a fun class3+ fin. We spent over an hour  on
top all looking at where we had been the day  before.  Though  not  strictly
necessary we did two rappels to get down, mostly to avoid a section of  very
loose down climbing in a gully.

Partway down the snow gully Kevin and George took their  leave  to  head  to
Stehekin via Company Creek Trail. They had stashed their heavy packs on  the
way up. Mike and I warned them about the steep descent off Hilgard Pass  and
wished them luck. They had two ropes so should  have  had  no  problem.  The
rest of us glissaded and plunge stepped the now soft snow reaching  camp  at
5:00. After a final dinner together, Beth, Jim and  Eileen  then  also  took
their leave to camp lower down and catch the earlier boat, Beth to  Stehekin
to climb Dark Pk, Jim and Eileen to Chelan for R&R, the next day. That  left
Mike and me to relax the rest of the day and turn in early.  Neither  of  us
wanted to go anywhere or do anything.

Total: 2 miles, 2400 ft and 7:30 hrs

Tuesday, July 5 - Mike and I woke at 7:00  and  left  at  9:30.  We  had  no
problem getting to Holden by 12:30 in time to clean up a bit  and  have  ice
cream at the store which opens at 1:00.  I  couldn\'t  believe  the  generous
scoop of yummy Huckleberry Heaven I got for only $1. Then the  bus  at  1:45
and the boat at 2:30. We ended this wonderful trip with a delicious meal  at
the Big Y and a stop for fresh cherries at Miller Orchard. The only  fly  in
the ointment was we got stopped for close  to  an  hour  for  rock  blasting
going over Snoqualmie Pass (8-9:00). A minor inconvenience  in  the  overall
scheme of things.

Day Total: 5 miles, 250 ft and 3 hours

Trip Total: 20 miles and 11,850 ft in 4 days

Fay Pullen

