                      ],
            'month' => '07',
            'subdir' => '2011-07-09-napeequa',
            'title' => 'Napeequa Pk (8073 ft - P1273), Mt Berge (7960+ ft - P1000) & Mt Cleator (7625 ft - P545) - Clark Mtn Quad; and Helmet Butte (7400+ ft - P1000), Liberty Cap (6760+ ft - P280) & Flower Dome (6332 ft - P492) - Suiattle Pass Quad - July 9-11, 2011',
            'tr' => '
Napeequa Pk (8073 ft - P1273), Mt Berge (7960+ ft  -  P1000)  &  Mt  Cleator
(7625 ft - P545) - Clark Mtn Quad; and Helmet  Butte  (7400+  ft  -  P1000),
Liberty Cap (6760+ ft - P280) & Flower Dome (6332  ft  -  P492)  -  Suiattle
Pass Quad - July 9-11, 2011

Saturday, July 9 - There were only 3 cars parked at Trinity when  I  arrived
at 10:30, pretty sparse for a sunny weekend. I think the  late  snowpack  is
keeping the usual hikers and backpackers away. The good trail  was  pleasant
easy hiking for the first five miles with  a  dozen  or  so  logs  to  cross
despite the website saying the trail had been logged out already. Not a  big
problem to foot travel but why would they say this  if  it  were  not  true?
Then snow began intermittently, gradually becoming more solid. Still  enough
sections were visual I was able to stay  on  course  until  the  last  mile.
There was no sign of anyone else having been this way. I was  dismayed  when
I pulled into 5900 ft Buck Creek Pass and found it completely snowed  in.  I
was hoping for a few bare spots, however small, but I  could  find  none  at
all. Of more concern than the snow (I could camp on snow) was the fact  that
I could also find no running water.  I did not bring  enough  fuel  to  melt
snow for water for 3 days. I wandered around for the better part of an  hour
getting more and more desperate when I happened upon a tiny flat  bare  site
with a tiny snowmelt trickle nearby on a bench below  Liberty  Cap  west  of
the pass at 5800 ft. I was saved. This was evidently in an established  camp
area as signs were on the trees.

Total: 10.5 miles, 3600 ft, 7 hrs

Sunday, July 10: Liberty Cap, Mt Cleator, Mt Berge and Napeequa Pk - I  knew
this would be a long day and it was. My main goals were the Top200 peaks  of
Berge and Napeequa. Anything else would be frosting on the cake. I began  by
going over Liberty Cap which seemed the  most  direct  approach.   Snow  was
frozen rock hard on the steep slopes and crampons essential. In fact I  kept
crampons on all day except when on rock.  I reached the flat summit at  7:50
(1000 ft, 1:05 hrs) where I had a good view of where I was going. Years  ago
I had climbed Buck Mtn from Louis Cr and came out via the  trail  over  High
Pass to Buck Creek Pass. I vaguely remember it  as  wandering  up  and  down
along the ridge bypassing cliffs and high points. But  without  the  benefit
of this trail I had my work cut out just getting to High Pass. First  I  had
to drop off Liberty Cap to the saddle  with  Pt  6909,  then  traverse  west
around that rocky point to the saddle to the north  with  Rally  Cap.  As  I
then traversed east around Rally Cap I was disheartened  to  see  the  ridge
saddle with Cleator completely guarded by a continuous wall of  cornices.  I
could see no obvious way through. I lost a lot of time here searching for  a
route. I backed off one attempt as  too  steep  and  exposed.  I  eventually
found a weakness in the wall high up on the ridge about  300  ft  below  the
summit of Rally Cap.

Once on the ridge again it was an easy climb to the  summit  of  Mt  Cleator
(2500 ft, 4:30 hrs), which I thought  would  be  a  direct  approach  to  Mt
Berge. It wasn\'t. I couldn\'t follow the ridge and had to  drop  to  7000  ft
High Pass (5:30 hrs). I also couldn\'t see a direct route (that I  could  do)
up the north slope to the saddle between the two  Berge  summits.  The  snow
couloir looked frightfully steep and broken by a schrund. So I  did  an  end
run dropping farther to 6760 ft and  climbing  a  snow  gully  on  the  west
flank. It was still steep with a broken section in the middle and  I  didn\'t
like it but I made it up. More gentle snow and heather led  to  the  western
summit block with class 3+ scrambling to and along the  ridge  to  the  high
point at 2:00 (3650 ft, 7:15 hrs). I took a 30 minute  lunch  break  in  the
sun to air out wet feet.

I did not want to go down the steep gully. I had a hard enough  time  coming
up. I thought I could find a better way down farther  south.  I  didn\'t.  To
make a long story short I got hung up on slabby  cliffs  and  lost  over  an
hour doing three 50 foot rappels with my panic rope. Once on  snow  again  I
made a beeline for Napeequa traversing around  the  basin  below  High  Pass
before climbing to the East Ridge. Here I made a strategic error by  gaining
the ridge too soon and lost more time scrambling class 3-4 blocks along  the
ridge to the true summit. A direct  approach  would  have  been  better.   I
finally reached the summit at 7:00 (5200 ft, 12:15 hr). I had no time to  do
anything but add a new register  to  the  two  pitiful  soggy  ones  already
there.

From Napeequa I made a high traverse to  High  Pass  arriving  at  8:30.  It
killed me to have to pass on both Cirque Mtn and Rally Cap  when  I  was  so
close but I had no time left. As it was I was going to get back  well  after
dark in a repeat reminiscent of Sable Ridge last week with Mike. I  retraced
my steps to the Rally Cap saddle arriving to  stunning  sunset  lighting  on
Glacier Pk and made it to Pt 6909 saddle with still  enough  light  to  see.
From there on I needed my headlamp. I elected  to  traverse  around  Liberty
Cap rather go over it as I was running out of steam. That went  well  and  I
dragged into camp at 11:30.

Total: 10 miles, 6050 ft and 16:45 hrs

Monday, July 11: Helmet Butte and Flower Dome - I wasn\'t sure I  would  have
the time or the energy for these two peaks. I decided  to  let  my  wake  up
time decide. Well I woke up at 7:00 and figured  I  could  squeeze  them  in
before heading out. I did but in  a  recurring  theme  of  this  trip  where
everything turned out to be harder than expected they  did  too.  Or  rather
Helmet Butte did. It was a straight shot up the south slope but  was  capped
by class 4 rock (the Helmet?) and in going as light as possible I  had  left
my panic rope in camp. Dumb! Actually the rock was not  that  difficult  but
getting to it was as it was guarded by steep snow and nasty moats. I had  to
drop a bit on the west side to the west ridge and ascend from there.  It  is
a marvelous viewpoint but Glacier Peak was in the clouds - a sign of  things
to come. Then it was straight down and up to the easy Flower Dome  and  then
back to camp.

Total: 3 miles, 2250 ft and 5 hrs RT

I ate lunch and even napped  for  30  minutes  in  partial  sunshine  before
heading out at 3:20. The trip out was uneventful except for a few  sprinkles
the last mile. I did make the car before dark.

Total: 10.5 miles, 300 ft and 5:30 hrs.

Trip Total: 34 miles and 12,200 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen



