            'tr' => '
Frisco Mtn (7760+ - P480) - McGregor Mtn Quad and Crooked Bum (6937 -  P857)
- Mt Arriva Quad - July 19, 2011

After failing on The Needles the day before  (we  couldn\'t  get  across  the
moat at the notch) I didn\'t want to leave the area completely  empty  handed
so car camped another night at the Cutthroat Lake TH  with  several  options
in mind depending upon weather. Upon awakening  to  fog  I  settled  on  the
easiest, Crooked Bum directly above Heather Pass.

I parked at the Rainy Lake Picnic area, which still does not  have  complete
access  due  to  snow  impassible  to  vehicles.  I  easily   followed   the
intermittently snow covered Lake Ann/Maple Pass trail to  Heather  Pass  and
from there mixed snow/rock to the summit  of  Crooked  Bum  (2100  ft,  2:30
hrs). The entire way was in fog and I could see nothing. As I was placing  a
small register on top the clouds suddenly began to part revealing the  lower
flank of Black Peak. Wow! This would be a great viewpoint on  a  clear  day.
As I descended the  visibility  improved  to  the  point  I  could  see  the
beautiful Maple Pass ridge and all the way to Frisco Mtn. This  suckered  me
in to climbing that peak.

I was aware that Franklin and Carla had climbed Frisco  a  couple  of  weeks
previously but had not read their TR and had no detailed knowledge of  their
route. So it is interesting that I independently ended up  going  the  exact
same way. I wandered the lovely ridge from Maple Pass to cross the  shoulder
on the north ridge of Frisco at 6960 ft, dropped to the tarn at 6080 ft  and
traversed around cliffs into the big basin NE  of  Frisco.  I  saw  the  col
between Frisco and Rainy was corniced so nixed accessing the east  ridge  at
that point and instead headed for a  higher  one  at  essentially  the  same
place as Franklin and Carla. They didn\'t mention any moat problem but I  was
nervous crossing a suspect snow bridge onto the rock  so  either  conditions
had changed, I was at a slightly different place or I am a wimp.

By now the weather had completely deteriorated and it was  raining  steadily
with no visibility. It was all I could do to force  my  way  to  the  summit
(4800 ft, 7:50 hrs). Thank heavens the rock was easy. I stayed on  top  only
long enough to add a register next to the survey  marker.  Adding  Rainy  to
the itinerary was now out of  the  question  (I  had  thought  I  might).  I
chuckled to myself - too rainy for Rainy. I returned to  the  tarn,  climbed
to the ridge above Rainy Lake, picked up  the  Maple  Pass  loop  trail  and
followed it back to the car. Despite the turn of the weather I felt  pleased
with my day\'s adventure.

Total: 10 miles, 5300 ft and 11:20 hrs

Fay Pullen

