            'tr' => '
Tenpeak Mtn (8200+ ft - P400) - and Tenpeak Mtn, West Peak (7960+ - P480)  -
Glacier Pk East Quad - July 22-24, 2011

Friday, July 22 - Mike, Matt and I started from the  White  River  Trail  at
close to noon. There were no bugs at the TH to start but barely  20  minutes
into the hike they came out  in  droves,  nasty  mosquitoes  with  voracious
appetites that neither clothing nor repellant seemed to quell completely.  I
got drilled through both my shirt and gloves. I think they  were  making  up
for lost time on this warm day, one of the few  of  the  season.  The  White
River Trail was  in  good  shape  to  the  Boulder  Pass  junction  but  has
evidently been completely abandoned  after  that.  The  next  2.2  miles  to
Thunder Creek is almost all in thick overgrown brush, much of it head  high.
It is slow going and tiring. It would be awful if wet. This  is  really  too
bad as the tread is still good (when you can see it) and all it needs  is  a
good brushing out.

The old  bridge  over  Thunder  Creek  was  washed  out  but  engineer  Mike
constructed a useable if somewhat scary one by adding a comforting  handrail
to a spindly log already in place. We left the trail about  0.75  miles  beyond
Thunder Creek (7 miles, 750 ft, 4:30 hrs).  The  beginning  of  the  Thunder
Creek trail is obscure to non-existent. We sure didn\'t find  it  right  away
even though both Mike and I had been on it before (Mike  many  times).   But
you definitely want to take the time to find  this  trail  or  you  will  be
crashing horrible brush for hours. As it was we missed it and lost  an  hour
before running into it. It is quite good, once on  it,  to  the  open  slope
below Luahna then becomes more obscure as it enters  trees  again.  We  also
started running into snow which didn\'t in help sticking to the  trail.  When
we pulled into the lovely meadows of Lower Thunder Basin at 7:00  we  called
it a day even though we had planned to camp in the Upper Basin. It  was  too
late and it was clear the Upper Basin would be under  snow  (9  miles,  2200
ft, 7 hrs).

Saturday, July 23 - Starting at 6:30 we hiked to the far end  of  the  lower
basin where Mike knew about a trail (he had worked on it years ago)  through
the brush to the left of the waterfall. Again it pays to locate this  trail.
It is not as good as the lower trail but it really helps in getting  through
this brushy section. Look for cut brush and logs. We did  a  better  job  of
finding this one and followed it to the Upper  Basin  which,  as  suspected,
was completely covered with snow. We then  climbed  steep  heather  next  to
creek that drains some  tarns  to  the  upper  snow  slopes.  The  snow  was
somewhat icy so we donned crampons for the traverse  to  the  notch  in  the
East Ridge of Tenpeak. Below the notch we stashed unneeded gear.

Snow led almost to the notch, covering much of what  is  reported  to  be  a
loose gully. The notch itself was a cramped airy perch above  a  chockstone.
The first moves out of the notch were the hardest (est. 5.6). Then it  eased
to a belay at a rappel anchor. Matt did a nice lead  followed  by  Mike  and
last me. I was glad to have a top rope for that section.  The  second  pitch
was much easier, really a scramble. We made the summit  at  1:45  (4200  ft,
7:15 hrs). The old register placed in 1972 was still in good  shape  and  we
happily added our names. We were the first to sign in  since  2006.  Tenpeak
is not climbed as often as it used to be what with the  now  more  difficult
access.

We scrambled down on top rope, with Mike  belaying,  to  the  rappel  anchor
where one 80 ft rappel got us down to the snow  below  the  notch.  We  then
headed for West Peak on a high traverse to reach the saddle  south  of  that
summit at 5:30, where again we stashed unneeded gear.  The  south  ridge  of
West Peak turned out to be a delightful climb marred only  by  the  pressure
of time running out. The first part was  easy  scrambling  onto  the  almost
level crest. We bypassed two pinnacles on the left with a few  harder  moves
to the final notch below the start of  the  impressive  narrow  knife  edged
ridge where we set up the first belay. Again Matt led. I followed next  then
Mike. The knife edge looked impossibly steep but the holds were so  good  it
could almost be considered a scramble except  for  the  wild  exposure.  One
slip unroped and you would be dead.  Surely  this  has  to  be  one  of  the
classic ridges of the Cascades. The second pitch was  up  the  final  summit
tower which looked a lot more difficult than it turned out to be.  From  the
last belay it was a short scramble to the  summit  cairn  at  7:30  where  I
found an empty tube (5100 ft, 13 hrs). I added a large register.  This  peak
deserves one.

We rappelled the summit tower then belayed along the knife  edge  with  Mike
going last. We made it back to the saddle at 9:00. The rest of  the  evening
was a blur of descending  refreezing  snow  (crampons  on  again)  to  Upper
Thunder Basin then wandering around in the dark looking  for  the  trail  to
the Lower Basin. A combination of collective memory  and  waypoints  entered
on my GPS on the way up helped to keep us on track. But it was  slow  going.
We did eventually find the trail. We reached camp at 12:45 am  still  taking
time for dinner before turning in at 1:45. I for one was starved.

Total: 8 miles 5300 ft and 18:15 hrs

Sunday, July 24 - I took Mike at his word who proclaimed  the  night  before
he wasn\'t getting up until the sun hit his tent. This happened at  8:45.  We
had a leisurely breakfast before packing up and heading out at  10:45.  None
of us were looking forward to the prospect of brush, bugs and heat,  all  of
which turned out to be as bad as expected but  mercifully  came  to  an  end
when we hit the TH at 4:15.

Total: 9 miles, 300 ft and 5:30 hrs

Trip Total: 26 miles and 7800 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen

