            'title' => 'Mt Index, Middle Peak (5493 ft - P533 - Index Quad) - July 29-31, 2011',
            'tr' => '
Mt Index, Middle Peak (5493 ft - P533 - Index Quad) - July 29-31, 2011

I always felt that if any peak would prevent  me  from  finishing  the  Home
Court List it would be the Middle Peak  of  Index.   Beckey  describes  this
extremely rugged peak as one of the most inaccessible spots in  the  Cascade
Range. I pondered for years how I could possibly climb it looking  at  every
conceivable approach and route and concluded there were only two options,  a
traverse from the North Peak or a  traverse  from  the  Main  (South)  Peak.
After reading trip reports from both Don Goodman and Tom Sjolseth  of  their
climbs I feared the peak was simply beyond my capability.  Still  I  dreamed
and continued working on the list until I only had this  one  left.  Perhaps
some super climber would take pity on me and help me achieve my  goal.  Well
one did - Tom. He was the force behind getting me up this beast and I  can\'t
thank him enough. I must also thank Franklin who joined forces with Tom  and
greatly contributed to the success of a very  difficult  climb.  There  were
moments when I wasn\'t sure if we were going to make it off the mountain.

Friday, July 29 - The plan was to  traverse  from  the  Main  Peak.  Mike  C
joined as the fourth member of the party. We started from  the  Lake  Serene
TH at 9:00, hiked to the lake (1:50  hr),  skirted  the  west  side  to  the
saddle in the NE ridge and followed the climber\'s trail up  the  brushy  and
rocky crest to where it flattened at 3900 ft. From here we  traversed  south
Â¼ mile to enter the snow  filled  east  gully.  This  gully  had  a  schrund
forming at about 5200 ft in  a  narrow  constriction  and  the  snow  bridge
looked as if it only had days of life left. Near the top  of  the  gully  we
exited right onto steep slopes that led to the gentle SE ridge  crest  where
we found a pleasant camp at 4:15 on heather at 5800 ft about  .3  mile  from
the main summit.

After setting up camp we all climbed to the main summit  and  beyond  for  a
view of the Middle Peak and the start of the route for the next day.

Total: 7 miles, 5500 ft and 7:15 hrs

Saturday, July 30 - We were up at 4:00 and underway by first light at  5:10.
Our goal was to get to the Main-Middle notch at 4960 ft. The  first  problem
was where exactly to drop off the Main Peak. We had the advantage  that  Tom
had just done the traverse from the North Peak the year before and had  been
up the route. But going down everything looks different. I have no clue  how
one would find the way without at least some prior  knowledge.  The  terrain
is extremely rugged and complicated. We started by  scrambling  down  the  N
Ridge a short ways and doing a double rappel to heather  benches  below.  We
traversed the heather to notch 1. Two more double rappels took us into  what
I call the Evil Gully (a truly nasty feature splitting the upper  face)  and
crossed in the moat of some snow. Then up one  pitch  to  the  base  of  the
Wedge Gendarme at a saddle. Here while waiting last to come up I was hit  in
the shoulder by a small rock. Not devastating but unnerving none the less.

The route describes climbing the crest of the Wedge Gendarme which  must  be
easier in reverse as  Tom  backed  off  climbing  to  the  top.  Instead  we
retreated to notch 2 lower on skiers left for more rappels to get  past  the
gendarme. Then up to a wooded notch 3 and a rappel down the other side to  a
slabby ramp (above a deep gully) that we scrambled down and  around  and  up
to cross a minor rib. We were now on the Lake  Serene  side  of  the  ridge.
More rappels straight down brought us to  the  Main-Middle  notch  at  12:30
(7:20 hrs). I actually lost count  of  the  rappels  but  I  think  Franklin
counted 9 (he kept notes), all double rappels on our two 50m ropes.

We donned crampons to cross the icy snow and moat in  the  notch  (unroped).
At the far side I lost sight of Franklin who came last.  I  heard  a  scream
and the noise of a  body  falling.  Panic  then  relief  when  I  heard  his
reassuring voice. He had slipped on a loose rock and tumbled  head  first  a
few feet. He did some  damage  (nose  and  knee  mostly)  but  was  able  to
continue.

From the notch a short pitch in a chimney put us on scrambling  terrain  the
rest of the way up. This is not to say it was obvious  finding  the  correct
line up but at least the climbing was not difficult. We topped  out  on  the
summit at 2:30 (1000 ft, 9:20 hrs).  Now  stressed  for  time  we  took  the
minimum amount for pictures and to place a new register  then  took  off  at
2:55. We scrambled down doing one rappel directly into the  notch  bypassing
the chimney.

Now it was all uphill with several problems looming ahead. Many of our  down
rappels could not be reversed and we had to find other routes up. The  first
problem was a difficult (5.6 or 5.7?) pitch right out of  the  notch.   Then
easier terrain to a ledge system that led climbers left  to  the  minor  rib
where we had rapped from earlier. From here Tom tried going straight up  but
backed off. So it was down to scramble the same slabby ramp up that  we  had
scrambled down to the base of the rappel from  notch  3.  Here  was  another
difficult pitch to the right that put us at wooded notch 3.

Darkness was now encroaching and it was clear we would not  make  camp  this
day but Franklin put in an another pitch in waning  light  to  notch  2  and
left a fixed line before we settled in for  a  bivy  at  notch  3.  We  each
claimed a spot but  none  was  comfortable  with  more  than  sitting  room.
Franklin had carried a stove and he set it up to melt some nearby  snow  for
water. Tom had a sil shelter that we rigged in case it began to rain  during
the night. Franklin had gotten an updated  forecast  on  his  Smartphone  at
6:00 that had changed since the start of the trip from 0 %  chance  of  rain
to 37% starting after  11  pm,  the  worst  news  possible  in  our  present
position.

I had taken long johns, extra socks, full rain  gear,  a  polyester  sweater
and down jacket so started off  reasonably  warm  but  eventually  the  cold
seeped in as the night crawled by. I think I dozed a total of  2  hours  all
night. Somewhere around midnight Tom went downhill  a  ways  and  started  a
fire. We kept the fire going  off  and  on  for  a  few  hours  but  it  was
difficult for all of us to get around it at  the  same  time  on  the  steep
slope. Still it was comforting and warm when close to it and scavenging  for
firewood gave us something to do. Luckily the rain held off so  that  didn\'t
add to our problems, at least not yet.

We left the bivy at the first glimmer of light, about 4:30 by which time  we
were enveloped in thick fog. We made it up the fixed pitch  when  the  first
raindrops hit.  Another  pitch  took  us  to  the  saddle  below  the  Wedge
Gendarme where progress came to a standstill.  For  a  couple  of  hours  we
stood in the same spot with the rain coming down trying to  figure  out  how
to do this last pitch across the Evil Gully. The  ramp  route  left  of  the
gully was not that steep but was exposed, terribly slick  in  the  rain  and
offered no reassuring protection.  We at the very least needed an anchor  to
rap into the gully. When I saw Tom faltering I knew we were  in  trouble.  I
kept thinking of Beckey\'s warning about the Middle Peak,  "the  consequences
of either accident or bad weather could be  serious".   Serious?  How  about
deadly! I began to wonder if maybe we wouldn\'t make it off this mountain.

My life was now in the hands of Tom and Franklin and bless  them  they  both
came through under very trying conditions. They ended up leaving 2 cams  and
a nut in questionable cracks to make a reasonable anchor. We made it  across
the gully and onto the ledge leading to the first notch and salvation.  From
there it was a scramble back to camp at 12:00 (2250 ft and 31  hrs  RT  from
camp, 7:30 hrs from bivy).

Completely drenched we packed as quickly as possible and headed down. As  if
we hadn\'t had enough problems, near the top of the steep snow  of  the  east
gully Mike slipped about 40 feet and fell into a 10  foot  moat.  I  watched
this happen and it looked really bad. I thought we would have to call for  a
rescue. But miraculously Mike was ambulatory although he hit  his  head  and
turned his ankle. He abandoned his pack in the moat so he could hobble  out.
Franklin and I decided to rappel  to  below  the  schrund  bridge  and  Mike
followed us. Good thing as Tom downclimbed the  snow,  discovered  the  snow
bridge was gone and had to jump across. The rest of the way out was  without
incidence although  we  did  several  more  single  rope  rappels  down  the
slippery climbers trail on the rocky ridge crest. We reached Lake Serene  at
7:00 and the cars at 8:50 where finally I could let my guard down, happy  to
have survived the most difficult and intense climb of my life. Once again  I
want to thank Tom and Franklin for making  it  happen  and  getting  us  out
safely.

Trip Total: 16 miles and 8100 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen







