            'title' => 'Kololo Peaks (8200+ ft - P880), The Hive aka Sweet Pk (7560+ ft - P440) and Kopeetah Divide (7723 ft - P563) - Glacier Pk East Quad - August 6-8, 2011',
            'tr' => '
Kololo Peaks (8200+ ft - P880), The Hive aka Sweet Pk (7560+ ft - P440)  and
Kopeetah Divide (7723 ft - P563) - Glacier Pk East Quad - August 6-8, 2011

My main goal on this trip was theTop200 Kololo.  Mike  had  already  climbed
that peak but was keen to get both The Hive and Kopeetah Divide  nearby.  He
was willing to reclimb my peak if I would  accompany  him  for  his.  So  we
joined forces for mutual benefit. It  was  nice  to  have  his  company  and
support. The problem was how to approach.  The  best  would  have  been  The
North Fork Sauk but the road is still currently closed  some  9  miles  from
the TH. I had thought to go up Lightening Creek but neither of us wanted  to
battle the horrible brush of the White  River  Trail  again  so  soon  after
Tenpeak. So we settled on the Meander Meadow Trail.

Saturday, August 6 - We got started on the  trail  at  10:00.  There  was  a
party of 4 young women starting just before us carrying snowshoes. We  tried
to tell them any snow would be hard and they wouldn\'t  be  needed  but  "the
report says Meander Meadow is 70% snow covered", they replied.  They  seemed
to equate any snow with snowshoes being necessary. I must say I  have  never
seen anyone take snowshoes on a trail  trip  in  August  before.  We  played
leapfrog with them all the way to Meander Meadow where  they  were  planning
to camp for 2 nights.

The trail is well used but has not been brushed  out  for  some  years.  The
brush is nowhere near as bad as the White  River  Trail  but  is  still  bad
enough to be annoying in the open areas. After about 4.5 miles of  flat  the
trail climbs steadily another 1.5 miles to Meander  Meadow.  The  trail  has
been rerouted to the south slope since I  was  last  here.  Previously  (and
still shown on maps) it crossed the meadow to the north  slope  and  took  a
roundabout way to the ridge crest. This more direct approach saved  us  both
time and distance. We reached the ridge below Kodak Peak at 3:00, elev  5760
ft (7.5 miles, 2800 ft, 5 hrs).

We now had to drop some 700 ft to Indian Pass at 5000 ft. On  this  northern
slope it was all snow and there was no sign of anyone having been this  way.
We lost the trail but picked it up again at Indian Pass. The trail was  then
easily followed around the west side  of  Indian  Head  Peak  and  past  the
junction with the White River Trail. This is a beautiful section of the  PCT
and I particularly enjoyed  the  greenness  of  it.  Shortly  after  passing
Reflection Pond, as the trail rounded the ridge to the northern  slope,  the
terrain became all snow covered once again. As we neared White Pass  we  met
up with a party of four returning from having  climbed  Glacier  Peak.  They
had biked and hiked from the North Fork Sauk and were camped in the  closest
spot to the pass (camping is not allowed on the pass itself or ridge) so  we
had to drop over 100 feet on the south side to find a  site  for  ourselves,
arriving at 7:00. Our hopes for a few hours of camp sunshine  vanished  when
it began to fog in as soon as we had the tent up. Where the  heck  did  this
come from? I thought we had a  bomber  bluebird  forecast.  You  just  can\'t
count on any forecast this year.

Total: 13 miles, 3900 ft and 9 hrs

Sunday, August 7 - We didn\'t get as early a start as we  wanted  as  it  was
completely fogged in when we awoke at 5:00. It is so hard to  get  motivated
when you can\'t see anything and we weren\'t even sure what was going  on,  if
a system was moving in or if it was just marine air  that  would  burn  off.
There is no way we could find our way if it remained foggy all  day.  So  it
was 6:30 before we left. We knew we  had  a  long  day  ahead  and  we  were
already behind schedule.

We picked up the Foam Creek Trail at White Pass and followed it to where  we
could access the White Mtn Ridge saddle. As the  snow  steepened  we  donned
crampons and left them on most of the day. Meanwhile the fog began  to  thin
and sunshine appear but a heavy fogbank persisted all day below  us  to  the
west. To the east it was clear. We crossed the ridge at 6600 ft and  dropped
400 ft on the other side to the large White  Chuck  Flat.  We  actually  had
hoped to camp here but ran out of time and  energy  and  it  was  completely
snow-covered. We had a much nicer snow free campsite at White Pass.

From the flat we worked our way up gentle slopes to the White Chuck  Glacier
then steeper slopes to the notch in the ridge NW of Kololo.  There  were  no
signs of crevasses so we didn\'t bother  roping  up  but  developing  suncups
were annoying. We crossing the notch at 7900 ft and headed up  the  snowy  W
peak first before climbing the rocky main summit at 11:30 (4.5  miles,  3000
ft, 5 hrs).  There was no register.

I had my peak, now it was Mike\'s turn to get his. We  had  removed  crampons
to climb the rock of Kololo and had left  them  off.  While  descending  the
south side Mike slipped on a  very  icy  patch  and  warned  me  to  put  my
crampons back on. It was water ice and I had trouble  crossing  it  even  in
crampons. We had to drop farther than wanted to pass cliffs and  then  climb
back up to the saddle to the Honeycomb Glacier. Once  on  the  Honeycomb  it
was a very gentle and gradual descent to the saddle below  the  Hive.  Again
crevasses were not yet an issue so we didn\'t rope up.

I had looked down on The Hive from W Tenpeak a  few  weeks  ago.  It  is  an
attractive horn of a peak and so I was not unhappy to climb it  even  though
it was a heck of a distance from Kololo and all downhill  (which  of  course
means uphill on the way back). From the  saddle  a  short  steep  snowslope,
then heather, pumice and a final fun rock scramble led to the  summit  where
we found a Roper film can buried in the cairn (6.5 miles, 3800 ft,  8  hrs).
He had evidently named it "Sweet Peak". The view of Tenpeak was  impressive.


Kopeetah Divide was next. It is not as attractive as The Hive but  the  view
of Glacier Peak from the flat spacious summit is  to  die  for  (7.5  miles,
4600 ft, 10 hrs). It would make a grand bivy site. We found no  register  in
the cairn so left one. Now to get home we had to  regain  the  lost  900  ft
back to Kololo Notch. We stayed on a direct  route  on  the  north  side  of
Kololo reaching the notch at 7:00 (10 miles, 5600 ft, 12:30  hrs).  We  were
dismayed to see the west side fog boiling up ever higher in  our  direction.
It was clear we were going descend into it. It was also  clear  we  wouldn\'t
make camp before dark. Great! Just what we need - the dual problem of  route
finding in the fog and the dark.

Once on the featureless White Chuck Glacier we were essentially in  a  white
out and could see no  landmarks.  Fortunately  Mike  has  a  good  sense  of
direction and I had a track to follow on my  GPS.  So  between  the  two  we
slowly navigated our way out reaching camp  at  9:45.  Hey  compared  to  my
track record of late that was early. We even got to bed before 11:00.

Total: 14 miles, 6000 ft and 15:15 hrs.

Monday, August 8 - Again it was foggy in the morning but it cleared  quickly
after we left at 9:00. The rest of the day was in  sunshine  and  heat.  And
bugs. A few annoying ones appeared in the  lower  meadows  where  there  had
essentially been none on the way in. Surprisingly we met several parties  on
the way out. One was camped above Indian Pass and on a  day  trip  to  White
Mtn. Another was camped on Kodak Peak and headed  for  Reflection  Pond.  We
met a lone fellow at Kodak Saddle intimidated by the  snow  down  to  Indian
Pass and uncertain whether to continue. We met  another  lone  fellow  lower
down doing the Cady Ridge Loop and finally a family of three backpacking  to
Meander Meadow. By the time I reached the flat river trail my feet were  wet
and complaining in my boots. So I changed  to  dry  socks  and  trail  shoes
(doubled as camp shoes) for the rest of the way out. That really  helped  my
poor feet. I pulled into the TH a little before 6:00  a  few  minutes  after
Mike who had already washed and changed clothes.

Total: 13 miles, 1200 ft, 8:50 hrs

Trip Total: 40 miles and 11,100 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen







