            'tr' => '
Horsemans Pack aka The Needle (8152 ft - P472) and  Neve  Peak  (7505  ft  -
P505) - Diablo Dam Quad - August 12-14, 2011

I have found the naming of the peaks  on  the  Snowfield  Icecap  a  puzzle.
According to Beckey the UGSG Diablo Dam Quad has  The  Needle  mismarked  at
Peak 8152. Peak 8152 is actually the Horsemans Pack and the real  Needle  is
the 8040+ ft peak farther to the north. In addition  The  Horseman  is  also
mismarked on the map.  It  is  actually  the  tower  closely  north  of  the
Horsemans Pack. Adding to the confusion is that Beckey lists  the  elevation
of the Horseman as 7760+ ft and states The  Needle  is  clearly  higher.  It
appeared to me that The Horseman is 40 ft or so  lower  than  the  Horsemans
Pack which would make it at least 8100 ft (it shows as 8080+ ft on the  map)
and thus clearly higher than the Needle. This is all very confusing  to  say
the least and I still may not have it right. All I know is  I  climbed  Peak
8152 which is a Top200 peak whatever its name.

Friday, August 12 - I hiked the Pyramid  Lake  trail  and  then  the  easily
followed but steep climber\'s trail to Pyramid Ridge. This was my third  time
on this trail so I was quite familiar with it. About half way  up  I  met  a
lone fellow coming down traveling very  fast  and  very  light.  He  had  on
shorts and carried a tiny hydration pack with  room  for  very  little  else
except crampons strapped on the outside. I assumed he climbed  Snowfield  as
a daytrip but I never verified this as he blew  right  by  me  with  nary  a
word. No time to chat I guess. I found a scenic bare spot to  camp  at  5480
even though there was much more snow than usual for this time of  year.  The
pond was still completely snowed covered  and  running  water  was  hard  to
find. There was another tent on a  heather  bench  just  below  me  but  the
occupants were gone. I was surprised when they had not returned by the  time
I turned in at 9:00. As I poked my head out of the tent  an  hour  later  to
view a beautiful full moon  I  saw  three  headlights  descending  from  the
Colonial Glacier. I figured they had a long day climbing multiple peaks.

Total: 4 miles, 4400 ft and 6 hrs

Saturday, August 13 - Before taking off for my  peaks  I  stopped  to  visit
with the party camped  below  me.  They  had  only  climbed  Snowfield,  the
lateness being due to the older fellow having knee problems  and  having  to
go very slowly. He  was  with  his  son.  When  I  mentioned  my  name  they
immediately recognized it from all the registers I have placed. I  get  that
a lot. I wished them  well  on  the  trip  out.  I  would  think  the  steep
climber\'s trail down would be a challenge for bad knees. After chatting  for
close to 20 minutes I took my leave at 7:20. I started in thin  fog  that  I
soon climbed above.

I found the ramp leading down off  the  ridge  onto  the  slopes  below  and
climbed snow (crampons needed) past a lovely waterfall onto the  flat  lower
Colonial Glacier. Here the Colonial Tarn was much larger than I  remembered,
completely filling in the basin from rock wall to rock wall. It  was  mostly
frozen and the only easy way was straight across.  This  made  me  a  little
nervous as there was open water on the edges. I was especially  freaked  out
on the return. I followed old tracks and hoped for the best. Easy  snow  put
me at the Neve Saddle at 10:00 from where I dropped onto the  Neve  Glacier.
At this point I wasn\'t sure which bump  was  Horsemans  Pack  and  ended  up
heading too far right. For the most part the  few  crevasses  I  encountered
were very small, really just cracks, and no problem but I ran into one  that
was big enough to fall into and very long that required a detour.

As I neared the ridge crest  I  headed  left  and  ran  into  an  unexpected
corniced spur ridge that required a  steep  downclimb  before  reaching  the
base of the Horseman and the Horsemans Pack. The Horseman looked  positively
wild and unclimbable but the Horsemans Pack didn\'t  look  too  easy  either.
Darn. I was under the impression this peak was non technical. There must  be
an easier way. There was. A loose dirt ramp led to the east  ridge  where  a
ledge traversed the south side to a class 3+ gully that went to the top.  It
was almost fun except for the fact that the rock was very loose  and  I  had
to be very careful. I found Don Goodman\'s register on  top  (3400  ft,  5:30
hrs). No one else had signed in  since  2006.  I  found  this  odd  since  I
thought Stefan had climbed it since that date and I know Tom and Jeff H  had
done so this year. I guess they either didn\'t find the register or they  had
no pencil (none was in it but there is one now).

I found a cozy alcove in the sun just below the  summit  where  I  spent  45
minutes on lunch and views. I then took the scenic route down heading  first
to the base of the Needle. I had thought to climb this  peak  but  the  only
access I could see was on  a  very  steep  snow  slope  above  an  extremely
intimidating bottomless schrund. Were I to lose it  and  slide  in  I  would
either be killed instantly or die in it unable to get out.   No  thank  you!
So it was on to the base of the Cats Ear. Again it  was  too  scary  for  me
alone but I did enjoy my scenic route.

I returned to Neve Saddle from where I climbed easy Neve Peak  (4500  ft,  9
hrs) with its stunning view of the Snowfield Icecap.  I  sat  on  the  broad
summit for over 30 minutes in  full  view  of  where  I  had  just  been.  I
consider Snowfield one of the most beautiful  peaks  in  all  of  the  North
Cascades, on a par with Mt Challenger. I didn\'t want to leave.  I  also  had
great views of Colonial, Paul Bunyans Stump, Pinnacle and Pyramid all  which
I had climbed on previous trips.

I was back to camp by 7:00, never having felt rushed.  What  a  pleasure  to
make it before dark and even have some time in the sun. I found a  party  of
seven camped nearby and went to  visit.  I  didn\'t  know  any  of  them  but
somehow they knew of me. The "leader" called himself Big  Steve  and  was  a
big friendly guy. They  were  on  the  Isolation  Traverse  and  since  some
weather was forecast for Monday hoped to get past  Snowfield  the  next  day
before it hit. They were prepared to spend a day in their tents.

Total: 8 miles, 4800 ft and 11:40 hrs

Sunday, August 14 - The day dawned cloudy which made the  trip  out  for  me
cool and pleasant. I am not so sure about the  Isolation  Party.  I  watched
them head up into fog about 30 minutes before I left.  On  the  way  down  I
somehow got off onto a variation trail that connected with  the  main  trail
at Pyramid Lake. I hadn\'t seen  it  on  the  way  up  but  it  made  a  nice
diversion.

Total: 4 miles, 100 ft and 4:15 hrs

Grand Total: 16 miles and 9300 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen





