            'title' => 'Spider Mtn (8280+ ft - P920 - Cascade Pass Quad; and Old Guard Pk (8240+ ft - P360) & Sentinel Pk (8261 ft - P1661) - Dome Pk Quad - August 19-22, 2011',
            'tr' => '
Spider Mtn (8280+ ft - P920 - Cascade Pass Quad; and Old Guard Pk (8240+  ft
- P360) & Sentinel Pk (8261 ft - P1661) - Dome Pk Quad - August 19-22, 2011

Friday, August 19: To Kool-Aid Lake - The parking lot at  the  Cascade  Pass
TH was almost full when I arrived  near  noon  and  I  had  some  difficulty
finding a spot for my car. When I left a  ranger  was  taking  down  license
plate numbers. I let him know  I  would  be  gone  for  five  days.  It  was
reassuring to know that they keep track  of  people  in  case  of  a  needed
rescue. I did not need a permit for the North Cascades Park as  I  would  be
over the boundary once past Cache Col but I still signed  in  the  Climber\'s
Register at the Marblemount Ranger Station.

In 2 hours I was at Cascade Pass where the usual crowd was  gathered.  After
a short rest I took off on the good climber\'s trail up Mixup  Arm  to  Cache
Col. Most of the way to Mixup rib was on trail. Once past that  it  was  all
snow. The large cornice at the Col was passed on the  left  after  which  it
was all downhill to Kool-Aid Lake. It was only 6:00 and I  had  time  to  go
farther but the campsite was so  pleasant  here  with  flat  ground,  nearby
running water, an open dipping pool (most of the lake was still frozen)  and
rock furniture it was hard to pass up. So I opted for an early  stop  and  a
leisurely dinner with several hours to relax in the sun. Besides I  was  not
looking forward to crossing the Red Ledge. I would face my demons tomorrow.

In 2005 on the return from soloing Formidable I had fallen some 40  ft  down
the steep gully dissecting the middle of the Red Ledge when  a  rotten  snow
step broke out and I landed in a moat below. I  had  injured  my  left  arm,
which was essentially useless, could not climb back up, had  to  rappel  all
the way down the gully and struggled back to camp at Kool-Aid  Lake.  I  was
lucky to have survived and to be able to get myself out  after  a  night  of
rest. I had not been back since.

Total: 6.5 miles, 3400 ft and 5:45 hrs.

Saturday, August 20: Camp below  Spider-Formidable  Col  and  Spider  Mtn  -
After a very restful night I started at 8:00. Trail and a  long  stretch  of
unpleasant talus brought me to the base of the Red Ledge. I was  very  happy
to see it completely melted out and no problem at all. But the  snow  finger
leading to it was thin and icy and traversed above a nasty moat, so just  to
be extra safe and cautious I  donned  crampons.  Once  across  the  ledge  I
rounded the corner to begin the traverse, up and down on heather,  snow  and
scree to the base of the Middle Cascade Glacier. I stayed high on  the  left
side of the glacier, to minimize crevasses,  to  the  Spider-Formidable  Col
(the left-hand of the twin cols at the top). I then descended about  500  ft
on the other side where I found a surprisingly comfortable bivy  spot  on  a
flat slab of rock at 11:50. This would be my home for 2 nights. I  wanted  a
strategically located camp from which I could climb all three of my peaks.

I started for Spider at 1:00 by traversing upward about half a mile  to  the
first snow gully that  looked  reasonable.  It  started  out  well  but  was
steeper than it looked (I did have crampons on) had a deep runnel  down  the
center and holes  began  to  appear.   After  several  hundred  feet  I  got
uncomfortable and wanted out of the gully. I remembered Beckey  recommending
exiting the main gully (was this the  "main"  gully?)  to  the  rib  on  the
right. Problem was I couldn\'t see any reasonable exit  right  except  higher
where I really didn\'t want to go. I did see an exit left - or so I  thought.
Again it was much harder than it looked.  Nothing  more  than  class  3  but
nasty, nasty loose insecure rock. I  struggled  up  getting  more  and  more
freaked. I was stuck now as I didn\'t think I could safely  down  climb  this
stuff. So up I went. 600 feet of awful rock. I did not like it  at  all.  It
was very slow going as I carefully picked my way  up  testing  every  single
hold. Finally it eased and I topped out on  the  summit  ridge  at  a  small
cairn. Pt 8286 which I had marked as the summit on my GPS was  to  my  right
but this was obviously not the high point. That was to my  left  (which  the
map shows as 8280+ ft) and looked frightful. However, it was not as  bad  as
it looked.  In fact compared to what I  had  just  come  up  it  was  almost
pleasant. I reached the summit with its historic register of 1968  at  4:30.
Several parties had climbed it this year  with  Dave  Creeden  just  2  days
earlier. Interestingly almost every entry that came up the south side  as  I
did mentioned the horrible loose rock. Some even wondered if they  were  off
route and in the wrong gully. No  one  liked  it.  This  is  one  peak  that
deserves it terrible reputation.

Spider may have little to recommend it as  an  enjoyable  climb,  but  as  a
viewpoint it is superb. Expansive panoramas  in  every  direction  into  the
heart of the North Cascades and the Glacier Peak Wilderness. I  also  got  a
good look at my route of tomorrow. My but Old Guard and Sentinel looked  far
away!

Now to get off this pile of junk. No way was I going down  the  way  I  came
up. I thought I could find a better  way.  I  did  but  only  marginally.  I
followed the ridge toward Pt 8286 then  headed  down  easy  scree  into  the
gully to skiers left of the one I came up. I then exited  onto  the  rib  to
the left. This went well until the cliffs steepened near the bottom where  I
had to again pick my way carefully down zigzagging on ledges. Again  it  was
nasty and slow going but better I think than my way up.  Once  on  the  snow
slopes it was easy going back to camp at 7:00.

To Camp: 3 miles, 1600 ft and 3:50 hrs

To Spider: 2 miles, 1700 ft and 6 hrs RT

Sunday, August 21: Old Guard and Sentinel - I knew this would be a long  day
and it sure was. I started at 7:30 traversing easy snow around the  head  of
Flat Cr before starting a 1000 foot descent to Yang Yang Lakes. The day  was
partly cloudy which made for cool travel. Just before the lakes I  ran  into
a party of 8 coming out. They had camped at the lakes and climbed Old  Guard
and Le Conte. They gave me a valuable tip to climb Old Guard  via  the  snow
finger on the NW from col with Sentinel. They had first tried  it  from  the
NE and that didn\'t go.

The lakes were mostly melted out and would be  a  lovely  spot  to  camp.  I
followed trail from the lakes up a draw to a steep  snow  gully  leading  to
the ridge above. From there the way went down  slightly  to  Le  Conte  Pass
then up to below Le Conte Pk, then down to pass cliffs left  of  that  peak,
then up to the Le Conte Glacier. A lot of up and down. The glacier was  easy
going and no problem. This is a good year for solo  glacier  travel  as  few
crevasses have opened and those that have are easily  avoided.  However,  it
is not a good year for schrunds and moats. The schrund on Sentinel was  huge
and I would not be climbing it from this side. Old  Guard  though  was  easy
and a joy (in comparison to Spider) up the short  snow  finger  to  a  nifty
ledge and then broken rock on the NW slope. I reached  the  summit  at  1:45
(3350 ft, 6:15 hrs). No register (I left one).

Now for Sentinel. In order to climb this peak I would have  to  descend  and
cross over Sentinel Col to the upper part of the South Cascade  Glacier  and
traverse to the SW slope. This went well. Beckey mentions just  climbing  up
the SW slope and then following a ledge  left  and  finishing  on  the  west
slope. Sounds simple. I could see a broad easy looking  ledge  leading  left
from the top of the snow but when I got to it  I  couldn\'t  get  across  the
moat. I could see no alternate way in the vicinity to access this  ledge.  I
feared I was destined to fail on this peak. But before leaving I decided  to
try one other thing. It looked broken above the easy ledge. Maybe there  was
another way higher up - if I could get to it.

So I traversed farther right to the south ridge and began working my way  up
not really thinking it could possibly go as the rock was  quite  steep  with
several pinnacles. Yet I always found a way. The hardest part was a class  4
chimney. When I found an old rappel sling  at  the  top  I  was  encouraged.
Others had been this way. Below the  final  sheer  summit  wall  I  found  a
narrow ledge heading  down  to  above  the  lower  broad  ledge.  It  looked
feasible. Again looks can be deceiving. It was much harder than it looked  -
narrow, downsloping and very exposed. If I lost it I would  end  up  it  the
very moat that had stopped me below. The saving grace was  that  there  were
good handholds. But the whole  thing  was  very  scary  and  I  was  totally
freaked. The ledge got me to the west slope where  easy,  but  loose,  scree
led to the summit at 5:50 (4850 ft, 10:20 hrs). This whole detour  had  cost
me about 2 hours. On top I  found  a  matchbox  register  that  suspiciously
looked like a Jim Brisbine Special. It was and had been placed in 2005.

I took a few moments for photos and to collect myself before  heading  down.
I knew this was turning into another epic. My ledge was easier  on  the  way
back as it was uphill. I downclimbed the chimney to save  time  rather  than
set up a rappel. Then quickly down the snow and back to the Sentinel Col  at
7:10 and the base of the Le Conte Glacier at 7:45. Darkness caught me  below
Le Conte Pk. I had to descend the snow gully off  the  ridge  in  the  dark.
Maybe that helped as I couldn\'t see how steep it was. I  also  couldn\'t  see
the footsteps which didn\'t help. I got lost in the flat of Yang  Yang  Lakes
and had to use my GPS to find the trail. The  1000  ft  ascent  out  of  the
lakes went at half speed as I constantly lost the track. I ran  into  cliffs
I didn\'t know were there and used  my  GPS  constantly  to  correct  course.
Finally at 1:00 my headlamp picked up the reflective tape on  my  bivy  tent
and I was home.

Total: 14 miles, 7200 ft and 17:30 hrs.

Monday, August 22 - I felt surprisingly good considering. Up at 7:00 and  on
my way by 8:00. I had gotten a weather forecast via FM radio and it did  not
sound good - certain rain by  afternoon.  I  could  see  it  coming.  I  had
planned another camp at Kool-Aid Lake for a more leisurely trip but  because
of this I went all the way out and cut my trip short by a  day.  I  did  not
want to spend a night in the rain in a bivy  tent.   Rain  hit  just  beyond
Cache Col and continued steadily all the way to the TH at 5:00.

Total for day: 9.5 miles, 2000 ft and 9:00 hrs

Trip total: 35 miles and 15,900 ft in 4 days

Fay Pullen





