            'tr' => '
McGregor Mtn (8122 ft - P2122) & McGregor BM (7424 ft  -  P504)  -  McGregor
Mtn Quad; and Bowan Mtn (7895 ft - P1655) - August 26-29, 2011

Most people climb McGregor Mtn via the trail up the  south  side.  I  credit
Paul Klenke with the idea for this different route on  the  north  side  via
the Sandalee Glacier.  It was certainly more interesting than the trail  and
I wouldn\'t have to take the boat to Stehekin and be tied  to  its  schedule,
which I dislike. Besides I wanted to combine  this  peak  with  Bowan  which
could be done from strategic Dans Camp.

Friday, August 26: To Dans Camps - Since I was only  planning  on  going  to
Dans Camp, an easy 9 miles on trail, much of it downhill, I got a  leisurely
start from the Bridge Creek TH at 1:30. This trail goes gently downhill  all
the way to Stehekin. I, however, cut off at the South Fork and the trail  to
Rainbow Lake at 6 miles. Here I discovered that one must ford Bridge  Creek.
The rangers didn\'t tell me this when I got my permit. No  matter,  the  ford
was quite easy, part on a stumpy log and the rest less than knee deep.  That
did mean, though, that I had to get my camp shoes wet and it  would  take  a
day to dry them out. I pulled into wooded Dans Camp at 6:00 with  plenty  of
time to set up camp. Although there is room here for several tents only  one
permit is allowed. There is a bear wire  (you  must  provide  the  cord),  a
toilet and a fire pit grill. Positively  luxurious  by  my  standards.  This
would be my home for three nights. Bugs were moderate.

Day Total: 9 miles, 900 ft and 4:30 hrs

Saturday, August 27: McGregor Mtn - Starting at 8:30  (I  know  -  a  rather
late start but I am getting lazy and slow  in my  dotage),  I  went  up  the
trail about .4 mile before plunging downhill toward the South  Fork.  I  was
vaguely following Klenke\'s directions from  SummitPost  but  ran  into  more
brush than he indicated. I don\'t seem to have his brush bashing  acumen  and
it took me well over an hour to find the crossing of the South  Fork,  which
I did on a spindly alder branch. Once  across  the  creek  open  forest  led
easily to  a  talus  slope  and  then  more  open  forest  that  provided  a
reasonable route above the brush clogged valley floor to a basin at 4600  ft
where I recrossed the creek. There I stayed low  on  talus  just  above  the
brush band and below cliffs to where I could access the First Gully.  Lovely
waterfalls decorated the way up as I climbed this gully, first on the  right
then on the left. Above the First Gully things leveled out to  the  base  of
the short Second Gully. There was  nothing  more  than  class  3  in  either
gully.

Above the Second Gully fun  broken  rock  led  to  the  snow  of  the  lower
Sandalee Glacier, a climb to the upper glacier and a  long  rising  traverse
to  below  the  north  buttress  of  McGregor,  pleasant  travel  all   with
increasing views. This side of McGregor has a distinctive alpine flavor  and
I was enjoying it all immensely. I had to drop slightly to bypass cliffs  of
the buttress before I could gain the west ridge at a steep cornice.  Here  I
ran into segments of the painted red arrow trail to the  top  but  much  was
still buried in snow. I topped out at the radio tower at 3:30  (4500  ft,  7
hrs).

I probably stayed longer than I should have on  the  spacious  sunny  summit
before heading down. The glacier segment went fast as  I  followed  snow  as
low as possible, all the way to the top of the  Second  Gully.  Then  things
went much more slowly. Nothing was difficult - it was just slow and  tedious
as I descended the rock and talus carefully. I reached  the  first  crossing
of South Creek at fading light. I was floundering in brush and  downed  logs
in the darkness trying to follow my morning route before giving up  on  that
idea and deciding to traverse higher above the creek even though this  meant
more elevation gain. This worked better as I encountered less brush.  I  hit
the trail about .2 mile from where I had left it and made camp at 9:00.

Day Total: 8 miles, 4800 ft and 12:30 hrs

Sunday, August 28: McGregor BM and Bowan Mtn - My main  goal  today  was  to
climb Bowan Mtn. I had no idea as to the route so I first went  up  McGregor
BM for a good view to figure one out. With another late  start  of  8:45,  I
hiked the Rainbow Lake Trail 3.3 miles to Rainbow Pass at 6200 ft,  followed
the ridge to Pt 6880 (I went around this point on the way back), dropped  to
the saddle on the other side and continued on the ridge  to  the  top  (3700
ft, 4:30 hrs)-all delightful travel. The summit gave me a splendid  view  of
Bowan but I  didn\'t  really  like  what  I  saw.  It  looked  difficult  and
unpleasant and I was running out of time and energy and  rapidly  losing  my
enthusiasm. Still I had to give it a try.

A route on the broken SW slope, just right of  a  major  gully,  to  the  SE
ridge looked like my best bet. The main question would be if  I  could  then
traverse the ridge to the summit area and find a way to the top. I  returned
to Rainbow Pass and followed the trail toward Rainbow Lake about Â½  mile  to
where it crossed the afore mentioned gully. Here I left the trail  at  3:30.
I knew I would be hard pressed to get up and down before dark.

Things started very well. The SW slope was  broken  and  easy  climbing.  In
fact there seemed to be a series of goat paths up. Then I made  the  mistake
of going all the way to the ridge at a notch.  Well  maybe  not  a  complete
mistake as there was snow at the notch and I was able to replenish my  water
supply which was rapidly being depleted on this very hot  day.  But  then  I
tried to follow the ridge crest and ran into impasses. It is best not to  go
all the way to the ridge but begin a traverse  100  feet  or  so  below  the
crest. This goes well until hitting a deep slot that must be  crossed  by  a
short down climb. On the other side lovely solid white slabs  in  a  shallow
depression led to the summit pinnacles. Here I made another  tactical  error
in climbing up too soon. I ran into some low class 4  here.  I  passed  over
two false summits before finally reaching  the  high  point,  naturally  the
farthest pinnacle. I found a cairn but no register (6000 ft, 9:45 hrs).

I reached the summit at 6:30and left at 6:45 staying  only  long  enough  to
leave a register and take a few pictures. I nailed the route down. There  is
really nothing harder than class 3 IF you go the  right  way.  I  found  the
whole climb much more fun than I expected and to be recommended. I  hit  the
trail just at dark (8:30). It was then I discovered how very tired I  really
was and I literally dragged back to camp at 11:00  with  every  part  of  my
body aching. It took me 2.5 hours to go 3.8 miles even though it was  mostly
downhill and all on trail. It didn\'t help  that  bugs  were  milling  around
attracted to my headlamp flying in my face and eyes and making it  difficult
to see. It was enough to drive a person insane.

Day Total: 12 miles, 6300 ft and 14:15 hrs

Monday, August 29 - I slept in till 8:00 and couldn\'t  get  my  body  moving
enough to leave until 10:30. The cold water of the Bridge  Creek  ford  felt
wonderful to tired muscles  and  sore  feet  but  the  uphill,  even  though
gentle, of the Bridge Creek Trail back to the car seemed to go  on  forever.
I really need a long rest.

Day Total: 9 miles, 1600 ft and 5:15 hrs

Trip Total: 38 miles and 13,600 ft in 4 days

Fay Pullen



