Devils Tongue (8048 ft - P528) and Silver  Ridge  (6434  ft  -  P554)  -  Mt
Spickard Quad - September 9-11, 2011

Both heaven and hell. That best describes this trip. The  hell  started  the
minute  we  opened  the  car  doors  at  the  Chittenden  Bridge  and   were
immediately besieged by swarms of mosquitoes. We had to wait until the  next
day for heaven.

Friday, September 9 - We started from the Chittenden Bridge just before  the
US border on the Silver-Skagit Road at 11:20, elev  1600  ft  following  the
trail to Galene Lakes. This provided an easy way  across  the  Skagit  River
but added an extra 3 miles of trail along  the  river,  some  of  which  was
rough near the end. We knew there was a shortcut that connects  right  where
the trail heads uphill and eliminates these 3 miles but it required a  river
ford and we didn\'t know exactly where to access it. We did see the  junction
on the way up and vowed to use it on the way out.

The bugs were so bad right from the start that it didn\'t  take  long  before
we all covered up from head to toe despite  the  heat.  This  included  head
nets and, for me, gloves and a wind  shell  since  they  were  biting  right
through my long sleeved shirt. Repellant seemed to have little or no  effect
on these voracious little beasts. We hoped we would get above the bugs  once
we started climbing but, other than a  short  respite  midway  up  in  mossy
forest, that did not happen. If anything they got worse as  we  got  higher,
something we didn\'t think was possible at the time.

The trail was easily followed and in pretty good shape except for  a  couple
of creek washouts. It became slightly  brushy  as  the  forest  thinned.  We
pulled into Middle Galene Lake at 5:50 but  the  bugs  were  still  bad  so,
thinking they might get better, we pushed on  to  Upper  Galene  Lake  (elev
6000 ft) arriving at 7:00.  They didn\'t. It anything they were worse but  we
did find a nice spot to camp. I have never seen bugs this  bad  that  lasted
over such a wide elevation range in all my years of  climbing.  It  reminded
me of the nightmare stories I have read about the mosquitoes in  the  Alaska
tundra. Needless to say it put a damper on the enjoyment of the evening.  No
washing up in the lake. No lounging around a leisurely dinner (ever  try  to
eat with a head net on?). We all did the  minimum  necessary  chores  before
retreating to the protection of the netting of our shelters.

Total: 10 miles, 4900 ft and 7:30 hrs

Saturday, September 10 - The bugs  semi-retired  shortly  after  we  did  at
night but were at it again with as much  malevolence  as  ever  as  soon  we
emerged from our sleeping bags at 6:00.  This  gave  no  incentive  to  hang
around camp but also slowed us in getting ready so  we  didn\'t  leave  until
7:30. We quickly climbed to the ridge above the lake and gradually made  the
transition from hell to heaven. The scenery was heaven from the get go  with
gorgeous meadows and views, but it took a while to get  above  bug  hell.  I
had no good Canadian maps, either hardcopy or  on  my  GPS,  and  so  was  a
little fuzzy as to how much up and down there was to the route. There  ended
up being a lot more than I expected. We followed  the  ridge  taking  a  big
drop (about 800 ft) to Monument 70 on the border. Then  it  was  up  to  the
5840 ft saddle on Silver Ridge and then up and down along  the  broad  crest
to Pt 6545. Somewhere in here we entered true heaven.  Head  nets  came  off
and joy returned to our steps as we  rambled  along  this  truly  delightful
ridge with the even present vista of attractive Devils Tongue and  neighbors
in front of us. This is what we came for.

More up and down along the gentle ridge brought  us  to  Pt  7103  which  we
turned on a left  slanting  ramp  that  ended  at  a  very  unpleasant,  but
blessedly short, loose gully to the top. Another drop from  Pt  7103  and  a
downward traverse on talus led to snow, a broad bench left to  the  base  of
the broken SE summit ridge and about 800 feet of  extremely  pleasant  solid
class 3 scrambling on a nifty series of ledges. I was having so much  fun  I
was almost sorry to reach the summit at 2:30  (3800  ft,  7  hrs).  Spickard
towered above sparkling Silver Lake. This  is  a  side  of  the  Chilliwacks
seldom seen.

We spent over an hour on the summit. Oddly I found a  lone  scrap  of  paper
recording an ascent from 2008 that had somehow survived its removal  from  a
film can (we found the lid  but  not  the  body).  I  added  it  to  my  new
register. We slowly retraced our steps savoring  every  minute  (except  the
loose gully off Pt 7103). No one was in a hurry to get back  to  camp  early
and fight the insect hordes so when Mike suggested we take the short  detour
to Pk 6434 on Silver Ridge no one objected too  strongly.  We  reached  that
summit just at dark to a  dazzling  full  moon  (5300  ft,  12:15  hrs).  We
wandered a bit getting off Silver Ridge as both Mike\'s and my GPS  were  not
functional (my batteries were dead - I need to  get  new  ones  as  they  no
longer hold a charge for very long). However, reverting to  Jim\'s  low  tech
but reliable compass we managed to come out right at Monument  70.  Then  it
was just the final climb from there. We arrived in camp  at  9:30  with  the
bugs semi-retired again, good timing from that point of view.

Total: 10 miles, 6000 ft and 14 hrs.

Sunday, September 11 - We were up at 7:00 and left at 8:30 with bugs  at  us
immediately. We hiked  out  the  whole  way  in  head  nets  and  protective
clothing. We did take the shortcut and ford across the Skagit River. It  was
not fast but it was up to my waist and I was happy to have Jim to hang  onto
in the deepest part. The trail came out on the  Silver-Skagit  Road  at  the
Nepopekum Day Use Area 3.5 miles before the Chittenden  Bridge.  Jim  jogged
back to the car in an hour while Mike and I hunkered down  under  cover.  We
chatted with a local fisherman who had been  coming  to  this  area  for  20
years and had never seen the bugs this  bad  before.  When  Jim  returned  I
could barely stand to strip long enough to change clothes.  During  the  few
minutes that took I endured dozens of new bites and was driven to the  brink
of insanity. My tolerance for the hungry devils had completely surpassed  my
limit. I will have buzzing nightmares for weeks to  come  and  although  the
climb itself was wonderful and I wouldn\'t have missed it for  the  world  my
hope is to never again encounter such horrific swarms of insects.

Day Total: 8 miles 300 ft and 4:30 hrs

Trip Total: 28 miles and 11,200 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen



