            'title' => 'Elk Mtn (6779 ft - P819), Maiden Pk (6434 ft - P434), Blue Mtn (6000+ ft - P1080) and Green Mtn (5622 ft - P62) - Maiden Pk Quad - October 19-20, 2011',
            'tr' => '
Elk Mtn (6779 ft - P819), Maiden Pk (6434 ft - P434), Blue Mtn (6000+  ft  -
P1080) and Green Mtn (5622 ft - P62) - Maiden Pk Quad - October 19-20, 2011

I had wanted to hike the trail from  Deer  Park  to  Obstruction  Point  for
years but other harder trips always took precedence. It is a long drive  for
a relatively easy trail trip. With me recently slowed by an  overuse  injury
the time now seemed right. In fact I couldn\'t  have  timed  it  better.  The
Olympic National Park website stated Deer  Park  was  to  close  on  Sunday,
October 16 but when I called the  Wilderness  Center  the  recorded  message
said it was still open. I doubted it would be open much longer  (little  did
I know how little longer). I had a forecast of one day of  good  weather  on
Wednesday with rain coming in on Thursday. It was  now  or  never  for  this
year.

Wednesday, October 19: Green Mtn, Maiden Peak and Elk Mtn - When  I  arrived
at the TH at 11:30 it was a lovely sunny day. The trail  began  by  dropping
400 ft and then following the wooded ridge to Green Mtn. I  took  the  short
detour to that summit before continuing on toward Maiden  Pk.  Shortly  past
Green Mtn the trail entered  lovely  meadows  with  expansive  views.  After
rounding Pt 6319 I headed up open terrain to the summit of Maiden  Pk  where
I ate my lunch in the sun (1750 ft, 2:45 hr).

It had been my intention to stop at  Maiden  Pk  as  I  wanted  to  keep  my
elevation gain between 2-3000 ft. Elevation is bad  for  my  injured  muscle
and I didn\'t want to stress it. But it was still early  and  everything  was
so beautiful I just couldn\'t stop. I am not known for self  control.  So  of
course I had to continue on  to  Elk  Mtn  along  the  beautiful  ridge.  My
favorite thing in the mountains is rambling along ridges so I took  my  time
and savored every moment. Clouds were beginning  to  form  but  rather  than
detracting from the views they added spectacular effects.

From Maiden Pk the trail dropped about 400 ft to a saddle and Roaring  Winds
Camp. Fortunately it did not live up to its name this day. It would  make  a
lovely place to camp but there is no water  source  after  the  snow  melts.
From the saddle the trail climbed steeply onto  the  broad  plateau  of  Elk
Mtn. There was some drifted  snow  here.  The  highest  point  was  a  rocky
promontory at the west end of the ridge (6 miles, 2700 ft, 5 hrs).

I left Elk Mtn at 5:00. Obviously I wasn\'t going to make it back to the  car
before dark but I didn\'t mind. The night was beautiful and I  was  going  to
car camp at Deer Park and so was in no hurry. At one point I even laid  down
to rest my poor leg. I had a few sprinkles of rain before  reaching  the  TH
at 8:30 (12.5 miles, 3500 ft, 8:30 hrs)

I was all alone in the campground and had the  pick  of  campsites.  In  the
dark I couldn\'t really see much but the next morning I discovered Deer  Park
is a fantastic place to  camp.  It  is  located  in  a  silver  forest  with
marvelous views. There are two large shelters for inclement weather.  And  I
got to camp for free as all the pay  envelopes  had  already  been  removed.
However the outhouse was still unlocked and still stocked with TP. Nice.

Thursday, October 20: Blue Mtn and Deer Ridge -  It  rained  lightly  during
the night and I fully expected to wake up to  the  forecast  rain  and  fog.
Instead I found sunshine and views. How lucky was that! I  had  intended  to
take the short (.5 mile, 165 ft,:19 hr) loop  hike  up  Blue  Mtn  and  then
leave but the day was so beautiful how could I? So I hiked  the  Deer  Ridge
trail toward Slab Camp and the Gray Wolf River until  it  plunged  into  the
forest. More ridge rambling and lovely meadows. I returned  to  the  car  at
2:00 by which time the forecast was beginning to come true and I was in  fog
(5 miles, 1250 ft, 3:45 hrs). I ended up  doing  much  more  elevation  gain
than I had wanted (5000 ft for the 2 days) but I took it slow and  easy  and
had minimal repercussions. And it was SO worth it.

Just as I was leaving I ran into a park ranger. He told me  he  was  closing
Deer Park for the season. He had thought to close it the day before but  the
weather was so nice he decided against it. Wow! He  said  the  gate  at  the
park entrance (7.7 miles down) was closed but not locked.  I  would  be  the
last person to leave. Talk about timing.

Fay Pullen



