            'title' => 'Nelson Butte (7160+ ft - P720), Pk 7146 (P506) and Pk 7041 (P441) - Timberwolf Mtn Quad - November 1-3, 2011 
 3.5 miles, 600 ft, 1:50 hrs',
            'tr' => '
Nelson Butte (7160+ ft -  P720),  Pk  7146  (P506)  and  Pk  7041  (P441)  -
Timberwolf Mtn Quad - November 1-3, 2011

Tuesday, November 1 - Because of commitments I  was  unable  to  leave  town
until 1:30 but I figured I could still make it to  my  planned  campsite  on
Dog Cr by dark. I really wanted to squeeze in one more overnight before  the
snows hit. I had thought I was past the general deer season but as  I  drove
up Road 1500 and 1502 from Nile east of Chinook Pass it was  obvious  I  had
totally misinterpreted  the  schedules.  Hunters  occupied  every  nook  and
cranny and I soon learned it was now elk season. One  runs  into  the  other
and there is no avoiding hunters this time of year. Darn! Oh well, they  all
seemed friendly, even protective when they learned I was alone  and  once  I
hit the East Mt Aix Trail I ran into only two hunters coming out just  as  I
was going in. I saw no one else the rest of the trip. Still I was very  glad
I had brought my bright orange windbreaker along.

I started on the trail at 4:30 and easily hiked the trail up  to  Buck  Lake
and down to Dog Creek. I was pleasantly surprised to find that  the  western
larches were near their peak of color. I thought I had missed most of  larch
season. I arrived at the creek with just enough light to find the nice  camp
at the junction with the Richmond Mine Trail. By the time I set up  my  tent
it was pitch dark and well below freezing and I wanted nothing more than  to
retreat to my warm sleeping bag.

3.5 miles, 600 ft, 1:50 hrs

Wednesday, November 2: Nelson Butte, Pk 7146 & Pk 7041 - It is  so  hard  to
get moving in the morning when it doesn\'t  get  light  until  7:30  and  the
temperature is 25 degrees. But it was a sunny day and the sun  even  hit  my
tent by the time I started at 9:20 so I  warmed  quickly.  I  began  on  the
Richmond Mine Trail until it began to veer away from Nelson Butte  at  about
5600 ft, then went up easy open slopes to hit the  summit  ridge.  The  last
bit along the  ridge  was  tedious  talus  that  I  was  thinking  would  be
treacherous if wet, icy or covered with fresh snow. Fortunately I  had  none
of that. But I did have a howling frigid wind strong enough to blow  me  off
balance. I reached the summit at 12:50 (3000 ft, 3:30  hrs).  Too  windy  on
top I found a protective sunny spot for lunch down the ridge a ways.

I then followed the ridge down to the saddle  with  Pk  7146.  I  must  have
crossed the Richmond Mine Trail somewhere in here but I  never  noticed  it.
Many of the trails in this area are lightly used  and  somewhat  obscure  in
places, especially meadows. But I did find a nice elk trail that led to  the
basin NE of Pk 7146. Here I ran into  some  intermittent  old  snow  on  the
steepening hillside. I found the snow gave better footing  than  the  frozen
ground. I topped out on the summit at 3:00 (3850 ft, 5:40 hrs).

I had planned to end the day here, return to camp  and  climb  Pk  7041  the
next day via the Mt Aix Trail. But the weather was holding, I  had  3  hours
of daylight left and I was still feeling good. I was also worried  that  the
snow predicted to come in during  the  night  would  make  travel  difficult
tomorrow. I thought I could make a high traverse below  Mt  Aix  around  the
head of Dog Creek, save some 2000 ft of elevation gain and get all three  of
my peaks in one day. This plan sounded better in concept than  it  ended  up
being in execution. Of course it was longer than it  appeared,  I  ran  into
unforeseen difficulties and I had to  drop  farther  than  expected  and  so
maybe saved only 1500 ft of gain. But it was a grand  and  interesting  loop
traverse route.

At one point I came to an "ice stream".  This  was  more  than  your  normal
frozen creek, but literally a solid sheet of water ice that I doubt I  could
have crossed with ice axe and crampons, neither of which I  had.  I  had  to
climb 100 feet to get to a level spot above where  the  ice  was  broken  by
tuffs of meadow. Even then I slipped, fell a few  feet  and  lost  one  pole
which skittered down the ice out of sight. I made it  across  to  the  other
side and went downhill until I could see my pole but darn if  it  wasn\'t  on
the opposite side of the ice stream from me. I was not going to cross  again
to get it. Better to abandon my pole than chance another slip.

I encountered no more ice but the ground was  frozen  solid  everywhere  and
make for bad footing. Eventually I worked my way around Mt Aix up  and  down
past cliffs until I could climb to the ridge with Pk 7041. I was now on  the
more gentle south side where the sun had thawed the ground and I could  move
much more easily and quickly. I raced the  setting  sun  to  arrive  on  the
summit of Pk 7041 at 6:00 (5350 ft, 8:50 hrs). After leaving a  register,  I
quickly left to plunge straight downhill worried  that  in  the  encroaching
darkness I would miss the Mt Aix trail. I  might  have  too  except  I  came
right out at the junction with the Lookout Creek Trail with  signs  pointing
the way. At this point I  felt  I  could  take  a  short  rest  then  slowly
followed the trail the rest of the way to  camp  by  headlamp,  arriving  at
8:40.

Total for day: 11 miles, 5500 ft and 11:20 hrs

Thursday, November 3 - The predicted snowstorm never amounted  to  much  and
all I got was a  dusting  overnight.  It  was  even  partial  sunny  in  the
morning. Tired, I slept in until 8:30 and didn\'t leave until 10:30  reaching
the TH at 12:30 (3.5 miles, 600 ft, 2 hrs).

Total for trip: 18 miles and 6700 ft in 3 days.

Meeks Table (4480+ ft - P240 - Meeks Table Quad) - On the drive  out  I  had
time to take the short trail to Meeks Table. This high plateau is  protected
by cliffs and as such is a fascinating preserved ecosystem  that  has  never
been disturbed by grazing. It is well worth a visit. It also  gave  a  great
view of where I just been and was a fitting end to a lovely trip.

2.2 miles, 700 ft, 1:35 hrs

While I only got a dusting of snow Chinook Pass had several inches  although
the road was bare and wet by the time I drove over.

Fay Pullen







