            'title' => '"Tubal Cain Pk" (6628 ft - P708 - Mt Townsend Quad) - November 6-7, 2011',
            'tr' => '
"Tubal Cain Pk" (6628 ft - P708 - Mt Townsend Quad) - November 6-7, 2011

Sunday, November 6 - Although this peak could be done in a day, the  longish
drive and short days made an overnighter with a  camp  at  Tubal  Cain  more
appealing to me. To this end I hiked the easy Tubal  Cain  Trail  3.5  miles
and 1100 ft to the camp area arriving before  noon  (2  hrs).  There  was  a
dusting of fresh snow on the rhododendrons in the semi  open  at  the  start
but oddly this diminished as I climbed higher into denser  woods  and  there
was virtually no snow where I set up my tent. However  the  temperature  was
well below freezing, never rising above that level either  day,  and  I  had
some trouble getting stakes into the hard ground.

By 1:00 I was ready to start for my peak. I crossed Copper Cr and  continued
about 1.5 miles on the trail before finding a suitable spot to leave  it  to
head uphill. The slope above the trail was continuously steep and  not  very
appealing for XC travel before this point. I worked my way  up  on  a  right
diagonal until past cliffs then straight  up  into  a  shallow  basin.  From
there I again went diagonally right until almost  to  the  rocky  NE  ridge,
then went up and left below the cliffs until I  could  gain  the  ridge  and
cross over it to the broad flat summit plateau. Here I ran into  some  snow.
The whole route was quite interesting but nothing more than  class  2.  This
summit plateau brought to mind the descriptive  name  "Lost  World  Plateau"
and just being there was worth the  price  of  admission.  The  view  itself
seemed from another world, especially with the clouds coming and going.  The
actual summit (2400 ft, 3 hrs) was a small rock  outcrop  where  I  built  a
cairn for a register before leaving after 20 minutes on top.

I wandered the plateau to the south on the way  down  but  didn\'t  like  the
looks of possible cliffs below in that direction so  decided  to  head  back
north toward my up route.  After  that  little  detour  I  was  able  to  go
straight down, much of the way on easy plungeable scree, to  the  trail  and
save considerable time.  I  saved  more  time  by  cutting  the  long  trail
switchback and made it back to camp at 5:30 (4 miles, 2500 ft, 4:30 hrs).

Monday, November 7 - I arose at 8:00, more than ready to  move  after  14.5
hrs in the tent. Before packing up and leaving I explored around  the  area.
I found dozens of delightful places to camp in the bouldery forest.  I  also
found the trail to the main Tubal Cain mine about 100 feet above  the  camp.
The tunnel went back as far as I could see into solid  rock.  I  would  have
liked to have gone to the end but the  floor  was  flooded  with  a  running
stream, in places over the top of my boots, and I  didn\'t  want  to  get  my
feet wet on this cold day. I will save that for a warmer day  when  I  won\'t
mind wading.

I finally left at 10:30 for the short hike out (3.5 miles, 1:30 hrs).

Total for trip: 11 miles and 3800 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen



