            'title' => 'Siouxon Pk (4169 ft - P1369), Huffman Pk (4106 ft - P506) and Huffman, SW Pk (4000+ ft - P440) - Siouxon Pk Quad - November 14-16, 2011',
            'tr' => '
Siouxon Pk (4169 ft - P1369), Huffman Pk (4106 ft - P506)  and  Huffman,  SW
Pk (4000+ ft - P440) - Siouxon Pk Quad - November 14-16, 2011

This trip was all about deep  mossy  forest,  big  trees,  wild  creeks  and
spectacular waterfalls (with three easy peaks thrown in for  good  measure).
I had no idea Siouxon Creek was so beautiful. I was totally  blown  away  by
it. If it has not yet been designated a Wild and Scenic River  it  certainly
should be. We peakbaggers sometimes don\'t  fully  appreciate  lowland  river
valleys in our pursuit of highland goals. This valley  makes  for  a  worthy
destination in its own right.  It  is  particularly  suitable  for  the  off
season where rain only adds to the volume of the creeks  and  falls  and  to
the greenness of the vegetation. And to camp within sight and sound  of  the
rushing water is a rewarding experience. The only caveat is that  the  trail
is open to mountain bikers and popular with them on summer weekends. But  go
midweek during the late fall as I did and chances  are  encounters  will  be
few. I only met one.

Wednesday, November 14 - I began from the Upper Siouxon TH which is  at  the
end of Rd 5701, elevation 1350 ft. It was drizzling lightly  but  that  soon
ended. This was the final day of elk season and as I was getting  ready  two
hunters returned to the only other vehicle parked. I  had  a  friendly  chat
with them before starting. Trail 130 began by descending  200  feet  to  the
creek bottom in lovely forest. Being  up  to  mountain  bike  standards  the
tread was wide and smooth and gentle, suitable for toddlers and  old  ladies
alike. The way is always in sight of scenic  Siouxon  Creek  with  its  many
small cascades and waterfalls  and  inviting  campsites  abound  everywhere.
Almost immediately West Creek is crossed. At 1.2 miles is the side trail  up
Horseshoe Ridge. At 1.7 miles is Horseshoe Creek and Falls.  At  3  miles  I
came to the Wildcat Trail 159 junction, my  intended  destination  and  camp
for the day. But I was shocked to find no bridge  across  the  Siouxon.  All
accounts I had read indicated there was a bridge and I fully  expected  one.
This sure put a kink in my plan to access my peaks via that trail.  What  to
do now?

While mulling over my options I set up  camp  in  a  choice  spot  near  the
junction, elevation 1400  ft.  If  all  else  failed  I  could  just  go  up
Horseshoe Ridge on loop Trail 140. In checking out the creek I found no  log
anywhere. Mindful that water  is  always  deeper  than  it  looks,  I  still
concluded a ford was possible but not desirable and since I had not  brought
wading shoes (who knew they would be needed?)  it  would  mean  starting  my
climb in wet boots (I cannot wade a big creek  barefoot).  Then  looking  at
the map I saw that by taking Chinook Trail 130 A  I  could  also  access  my
peaks, although this would be longer by several miles. But for that  I  also
had to cross the Siouxon and, in addition, Chinook Creek.  To  see  if  this
was possible I used the rest of the afternoon to hike  the  additional  mile
upstream to the Chinook Trail junction. I was delighted  to  find  a  sturdy
bridge across the Siouxon and  an  excellent  trail  leading  to  impressive
Chinook Falls. There was also a log across  Chinook  Creek  just  below  the
falls. My plan was set for the following day.

To camp at Wildcat Junction: 3 miles, 400 ft and 1:30 hrs

Chinook Falls: 2 miles, 250 ft and 1:10 hrs RT

Thursday, November 15 - I returned the mile to Chinook Trail 130  A  in  the
morning and crawled the slick wet log over Chinook Creek.  I  was  not  sure
what condition the trail would be on the other side as I was  sure  the  log
would deter many hikers.  I  was  happy  to  find  that  while  not  up  the
standards of main Trail  130  it  was  in  very  good  shape.  It  began  by
traversing downstream a short ways and then  switchbacking  upstream  again.
At the switchback was a junction and sign indicating a  side  trail  led  to
Wildcat Trail 159. This was a total surprise. This trail is not  on  any  of
my maps and not mentioned in any books. I surmised that this  was  a  cutoff
trail that provided access to Trail 159 when the bridge at the main  Wildcat
Junction is out. It makes for a 2 mile detour. I almost changed plans  again
and took it but I knew I would also have to  cross  Wildcat  Creek  and  was
worried that could be a problem. So I stuck with the plan  to  hike  up  the
Chinook Trail. Besides I liked the idea of a big loop by  returning  on  the
Wildcat Trail. After about 2 miles the trail morphed into a  road/trail.  At
3.5 miles I hit the end of  drivable  Road  6403  where  another  road/trail
(listed as Trail 129) became true trail again  at  5  miles.  Here  I  began
running into snow and came across unmistakable fairly  fresh  cougar  tracks
which stayed with me all the way to the short spur  trail  up  Siouxon  Peak
(6.5 miles from camp, 3100 ft, 4 hrs).

The day was mostly sunny but clouds hung over the  high  peaks  and  distant
views were limited from this old lookout site. There was a brutal cold  wind
that forced me to eat my lunch  on  the  lee  side  of  the  slope.  I  soon
continued downhill along the wooded ridge following Huffman  Trail  129.  It
was in good shape with only a few minor blow downs. At mile 7.5  I  came  to
the upper junction of Wildcat Trail 156. This was to be my  intended  return
route. I stayed with Trail 129 another  1.5  miles,  passing  below  Huffman
Peak, to the junction with Trail 126 where I went cross-country up the  easy
ridge to the summit of the SW Peak of Huffman (10 miles, 3800  ft,  6  hrs).
This had a cute little open top with a nice view into the Siouxon Valley.

I returned to Trail 129 following it back toward Huffman Peak until I saw  a
reasonable way up the steep NW slope to the rocky  summit  (11  miles,  4450
ft, 7:40 hrs). This time I had some reasonable  distant  views  although  Mt
Adams remained shy. Since this also was an old lookout  site,  there  should
have been a trail up this peak and some books  imply  there  is  one  but  I
found none. It has likely disappeared. The easiest way  up  is  via  the  NE
ridge, the way I went down. I reached the Wildcat  Trail  junction  at  4:20
with little daylight left. There the trail annoyingly climbed 200 feet  over
a knoll before plunging down the ridge line. I had hoped to get  to  Wildcat
Falls with enough light left to view it and take photos but darkness  caught
me well before making it that far. I could feel the spray, hear the roar  of
the water and barely make out a  giant  wall  of  gushing  white  so  I  was
greatly disappointed to miss seeing what had to be a spectacular  waterfall.


A half mile past the falls the trail ended on the bank of  the  Siouxon.  It
was 6:00 and very dark. What to do now? I could look for  the  cutoff  trail
and take the 2 mile detour. But I didn\'t know where to  pick  it  up  and  I
would still have to cross Wildcat Creek. On  the  other  hand  my  camp  was
directly across the creek from me only a few hundred feet away. The lure  of
my tent so close was too great. Without thinking too much more and before  I
changed my mind I plunged into the water. I didn\'t even stop to  remove  any
clothing. I am sure there were shallower places to cross but in the  dark  I
managed to find a spot that was hip deep. I really didn\'t think it would  be
that deep. But I stayed upright and made it across. It all happened so  fast
I didn\'t have time to get cold. And since my tent was right there,  I  could
immediately change into dry clothing and crawl into my cozy sleeping bag.  I
did make a hot water bottle to warm my feet.

Day Total: 15 miles, 4750 ft and 10:25 hrs

Friday, November 16 - The day dawned  sunny  and  the  rain  held  off  till
afternoon which gave me time and incentive to make  a  return  trip  to  see
Wildcat Falls, which I had felt cheated to miss. I also wanted to check  out
the cutoff trail. Despite hanging them on a line overnight, my wet  climbing
pants had not dried much in the high humidity. So  I  hiked  in  rain  pants
over long johns. That was quite comfortable. My boots were  another  matter.
I had left them upside down to drain but they too were still soggy. As  soon
as I put them on they saturated my dry socks. I would just have  to  put  up
with that. I still had one more dry pair  for  the  trip  out.  So  back  to
Chinook Falls I went once again and across the log over Chinook Creek  where
I picked up the cutoff trail. I found this trail to be very good and by  the
look of the mossy cut logs very old. Either the bridge has been out  a  long
time or is washed out frequently. There was a log crossing of Wildcat  Creek
but it also was wet and slick. The junction with the main Wildcat Trail  was
obvious and even signed. How I had missed it the night before I don\'t  know.
No matter, I don\'t think I would  have  wanted  to  do  either  of  the  log
crossings in the dark not to mention the  extra  2  miles  and,  all  things
considered, the ford was really the lesser of two evils.

I hiked back up the trail Â½ mile to Wildcat Falls.  As  I  expected  it  was
well worth the effort. Of all the waterfalls it was  the  most  spectacular,
free falling for well over a hundred feet. I stayed a good half hour  taking
pictures and absorbing the energy.

To Wildcat Falls: 3 miles, 750 ft and 2:50 hrs RT

Hike out: 3 miles, 400 ft and 1:30 hr

Trip Total: 26 miles and 6550 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen









