            'tr' => '
April Pk (6356 ft - P396 - Mt Townsend Quad) - December 5-7, 2011

Monday, December 5 - I wanted to try for this peak while  access  was  still
possible. I only wanted to get to the Tunnel Creek Shelter the first day  to
allow a full day for climbing the peak so to fill the  rest  of  the  day  I
went up Pk 1441 (P441) and Little Skidder Hill (P371) on  the  nearby  Uncas
Quad. Neither is worth saying much about but they did  accomplish  the  goal
of entertaining me for a few hours and not get me to  the  Tunnel  Creek  TH
too early.

The road was clear except very near the  TH  where  all  of  sudden  some  8
inches of sugar snow appeared in the open parking area and caused me to  get
briefly stuck turning around. By the time  I  got  unstuck  and  got  myself
ready to go it was 3:00, an hour later than planned. The  first  0.75  mile  of
trail was quite slick with a thin covering of icy snow.  It  made  me  think
about putting crampons on but I never took the time. The middle  section  of
trail away from the creek and higher on the hillside was almost  snow  free.
The last mile the snow gradually  got  deeper  until  there  was  continuous
coverage.

I was surprised to find another car parked at the TH. What  on  earth  would
anyone else be doing here? As it got later and  still  no  one  came  out  I
became convinced they were also spending the night. Maybe they would  be  at
the shelter and I would have company. That would entertain more  hours.  But
alas, as darkness was descending I ran into two fellows and a dog. We had  a
nice chat. They had gone no farther than the bridge just  past  the  shelter
and got caught up photographing icicles  along  the  creek.  One  carried  a
large tripod. They were from Kingston and often came  up  this  trail.  They
expressed some concern about going down the last section of trail that  they
too had found slick and icy. From the passionate way  they  talked  I  could
tell they were enchanted with the  beauty  of  winter  in  the  forest.  But
climbers they were not. I don\'t think they knew of April Pk or where  I  was
headed.

I reached the shelter at 5:20 hiking the last bit by moonlight.  The  almost
full moon was high in the sky and gave off a surprising amount of  light  on
the trail. Despite the shelter being in good condition, since I  had  lugged
it along (just in case) I set up my tent on the bare  floor.  I  thought  it
would be warmer. By the time I did all my chores, ate dinner and  watched  a
video it was 9:00 and late enough to go to sleep.

Total for day: 3 miles, 1400 ft and 2:20 hrs

Tuesday, December 6 - One disadvantage of being in a tent inside  a  shelter
is that it is very dark and I couldn\'t really tell when it got  light  until
I emerged from both. That led to a somewhat late start of 8:00.  Then  again
I really didn\'t want to get going much earlier. I continued on the  trail  a
short ways until it crossed Tunnel Creek at the  confluence  of  two  forks.
Here I found a flagged way trail that followed along the right hand fork  to
an open lower basin. I got  an  omen  of  things  to  come  by  encountering
slowing calf deep snow. I lost the flags in the forest  on  the  other  side
and ended up heading too far right and getting too high. I  had  to  contour
steep hillside to get back on track. More lost time.  Then  I  came  to  the
large middle basin and my pace slowed to a  crawl.  I  inconsistently  broke
through  crust  into  knee  deep  sugar  snow  while  winding  through  huge
boulders. Very slow and exhausting.

Once across the middle basin I began  climbing  a  broad  gully  toward  the
March-April col. The inconsistent snow continued with the soft  crust  being
replaced by a hard icy one. Even more exhausting going uphill. At this  rate
I wondered if I was ever going to make it  before  dark.  I  began  thinking
there was a good reason my peak was named "April" - it would be much  better
to climb it in April than December.

I finally reached the col and blessed  sunshine  at  12:45  (2350  ft,  4:45
hrs). It was a beautiful day but up to  now  I  had  been  entirely  in  the
shade. However things were still not looking all  that  good.  According  to
the Olympic Mountains: A Climbing Guide, from the col the route goes up  and
left on a ledge to the summit ridge, class 3.  I  always  get  nervous  when
this guide calls something class  3  as  it  is  notorious  for  underrating
difficulty. Class 3 could very well be close to class 4 and  perhaps  beyond
me under the present conditions of snow and ice.

I took a much needed rest to soak up the warmth  while  I  mulled  over  the
situation. I could see  nothing  I  wanted  to  tackle  on  the  rock  cliff
directly above the col.  But I saw the tracks of  a  mountain  goat  heading
down the other side of the col and up an impossibly steep looking snow  ramp
bypassing the cliff. Mountain goats are smart critters  and  know  the  easy
ways to go. Perhaps there was something beyond that. Sure enough,  the  snow
ramp wasn\'t as steep as it looked and on the other side was a  hidden  gully
that looked reasonable. It was steep (when I bump my knees stepping up  that
means over 45 degrees) and icy enough (I was in  the  shade  again)  that  I
wished I had stopped to put on crampons (I didn\'t and  had  to  chop  a  few
steps because of that), but I made it up.

When I reached the summit ridge I had my first view of Mt Constance and  its
surroundings.  What a wild beautiful peak! The last bit to the top was  easy
and I reached the summit  at  2:20  (2900  ft,  6:20  hrs)  having  had  the
distinction of more than doubling the guidebook time of  3  hours  from  the
shelter. I found a nice register that had been placed in 2007. It  had  only
one entry. I guess this peak isn\'t climbed all that often. I only  know  for
sure of one person who has done it, Mike Torok, but he  must  have  done  it
pre 2007 since his name wasn\'t in the register.

It was sunny and warm on the summit and I squeezed out as  much  time  as  I
dared enjoying my scenic perch before plunging back down into the  shade.  I
left a little after 3:00. I did put crampons on for the down climb and  left
them on all the way back to the shelter. It sure helped having my  track  to
follow although I still broke through in some new places to over  my  knees.
Darkness overtook me at the lower basin and my headlamp was  needed  in  the
forest despite the full moon. I reached the shelter at 6:00.

Total for day: 4 miles, 3000 ft and 10 hrs

Wednesday, December 7 - All I had to do today  was  hike  out  3  miles  and
drive home so I was in no hurry. I left at 9:45. I did put crampons  on  for
the last icy bit of the trail and was glad I did.

Trip Total: 10 miles and 4400 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen





