            'tr' => '
Puyallup LO (4877 ft - P557 - Ashford Quad) - December 31,  2011  -  January
1, 2012

Saturday, December 31 - I had an uncontrollable urge to see the New Year  in
from a snow camp and chose this peak as my destination. I  had  long  wanted
to ski up it but it is 10 miles one way from the Copper Creek  SnoPark,  too
long for a reasonable day trip. It would have been nice to spend  the  night
at the Copper Creek Hut but it  was  full,  not  surprising  for  a  holiday
weekend, so it would be tent camping for me.

Road 92, the north access to the Mt Tahoma Trail  System  and  Copper  Creek
Hut, is now permanently gated at the former middle SnoPark,  elevation  3240
ft, regardless of snow level. The last time I was here one  could  drive  to
the upper SnoPark, elevation 3500 ft. The road is still  perfectly  drivable
so I am not sure why this is so. Whatever the reason this adds 1.1 miles  to
the distance. More to the point this must often be walked as the snow  cover
is frequently marginal in this section. I was lucky this  day  and  had  1-2
inches of lovely fresh powder snow that allowed skiing from the start but  I
knew it was unlikely to remain so until my return.

The snow cover remained thin until hitting grooming  which  started  at  the
Valley Vista junction about 2.75 miles in. I met many people coming out  from
the hut, most on foot or snowshoes. I  bypassed  the  junction  to  the  hut
opting to head straight for my desired camp. Since I  was  carrying  a  tent
anyway I wanted to get a bit closer to my peak as the LO is  still  6  miles
from the hut. I soon came to another junction where  I  was  pretty  sure  I
should go left downhill on an untracked road to some  small  lakes  but  the
grooming went right uphill. There was no trail sign  to  help  out.  My  map
didn\'t show a connection to the LO road this way but my map  is  not  up  to
date and doesn\'t show many of the current maze of roads in the area.  And  I
really thought the grooming went all the way to the LO. Well it  didn\'t.  It
dead-ended at a viewpoint on the ridge. It would have been easier for me  to
retrace my steps back to the untracked road to the lakes, but  when  have  I
been known to ever do the easy thing?

 Instead I forced a way off the  ridge  down  steep  terrain  through  thick
trees, not terribly easy with a full pack. I did manage to stay  upright  by
going very slowly but it took the better part of an hour to  reach  a  lower
road that then led to a suitable campsite on  a  minor  saddle  (elev  4400)
with a view of Mt Rainier (7.5 miles, 2000 ft, 5:15 hrs).  I  set  up  camp,
ate dinner and then went on an evening tour on a spur road that  went  above
the lakes. It was a beautiful night  with  a  quarter  moon  and  delightful
snow. Pure magic. I returned to camp, watched a video and  took  a  nap.  At
11:30 I awoke in time to toast the New  Year  with  Irish  CrÃ¨me  laced  hot
chocolate. I could hear fireworks from civilization  in  the  valley  below.
Not a bad end to 2011.

Sunday, January1 - I could feel the temperature rising during the night  and
the wind picking up. By the time I got going at 8:00 it  was  near  freezing
and all my beautiful powder was beginning to melt or had  been  blown  away.
But it was still quite good skiing. I had skied down to a junction  slightly
below my camp the day before where a puzzling sign  pointed  both  left  and
right to Puyallup LO. This confused me. After studying the map  I  concluded
there were two routes, one a  lower  one  and  one  an  upper  ridge  route.
Naturally I chose the ridge route, despite  the  somewhat  windy  conditions
and some added elevation gain, as anyone who knows me knows I love ridges.

The skiing was delightful along the ridge road.  I  had  some  views  of  Mt
Rainer but it was shy today and stayed mostly hidden  under  a  large  cloud
cap. I climbed to a high point of about 4700 ft then dropped to a saddle  at
4300 ft after passing the junction with the alternate route. The final  road
to the lookout steepened for the last  500  ft  climb  to  the  summit  (3.5
miles, 1000 ft, 2:20 hrs). It was very windy on top with no real shelter  so
I didn\'t stay long.

I had a wonderful ski back in my track to camp arriving at 12:40  (7  miles,
1500 ft, 4:20 hrs RT). After a quick lunch I packed up  and  left  at  1:30.
For the return I followed the  untracked  road  past  the  small  lakes  and
uphill on now wet and sticky snow to intersect the groomed road.  As  I  was
climbing the last few feet  I  encountered  a  skier  watching  me  who  was
totally puzzled as to where I had come from (I  was  making  new  tracks  so
obviously hadn\'t gone down that way). It took me a while to  explain  and  I
am not sure she ever totally understood. I met more skiers  and  snowshoers,
most of whom had stayed at the hut. As I got lower extensive melting  became
more apparent and I had to walk the last now  bare  mile  to  the  car  (6.5
miles, 400 ft, 2:30 hrs from camp).

I did run into one couple out for the day who told me they  had  planned  to
ski at Paradise but were turned away at the Nisqually entrance and told  the
entire park was closed - with no other explanation. When I turned on my  car
radio while driving home I learned the tragic reason  for  this  closure  -a
park ranger had been shot and killed and the killer was still on the  loose.
And to think I almost chose Paradise as my overnight for the New Year.  Good
thing I didn\'t.

Trip Total: 22 miles and 4250 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen







