Mt Margaret via Rocky Run

Monday, January 23 -I skied  up  Rd  4832  from  the  motorized  Gold  Creek
SnoPark on a dusting of fresh powder over recent  snowmobile  tracks.  There
was only one machine in the lot when I arrived and he quickly zipped out  of
sight and sound. At the junction 2.5 miles up I went left onto  Rd  136.  No
recent snowmobiles had been this way so the fresh snow was  deeper  but  not
deep enough to make trail  breaking  hard.   At  3.75  miles  I  passed  the
junction to the left for the road that crosses Rocky  Run  and  climbs  onto
the ridge of Dungeon Pk. After 5.5 miles, at the third  switchback,  I  left
the road to climb through open woods toward the summit  of  Mt  Margaret.  I
was aiming for the true summit but the easier terrain  kept  pushing  me  to
the right and I ended up on the false summit. It got fairly steep  near  the
top. I had not gotten a particularly early start and it was getting late  so
I called it good for the day.  The ski down was delightful on perfect  snow.
I cut the switchbacks to my tracks on lower Rd 136. After a  short  slightly
uphill section I hit the main Rd 4832 which  to  my  pleasant  surprise  had
been freshly groomed. This made for a very fast run down to I-90.  The  only
slightly unpleasant portion of  the  entire  day  was  skiing  back  to  the
SnoPark next to I-90. I have never liked this mile section.

Total: 12 miles, 3175 ft and 7:45 hrs.

Friday, January 27 - I had so much fun  on  Monday  I  returned  on  Friday.
However, this time I had much more company in the SnoPark  to  the  tune  of
more than a dozen snowmobiles revving  their  engines.  "Sharing"  the  road
with them was not appealing. I had been thinking about a way to  avoid  both
the machines and the stretch along I-90. An old spur  leaves  Rd  4832  very
near the SnoPark. It is ditched  and  blocked  at  the  start  and  slightly
overgrown but very skiable. It  dead  ends  on  the  hillside  above  but  I
thought a way could be forced to a connection with Rd 136.  To  this  end  I
skied the spur and a right junction to its end at 3200 ft and then tried  an
upward traverse to hit the road that goes to the Dungeon  Pk  Ridge.  But  I
was too low and got into steep and nasty terrain for  skis.  It  would  have
been better to climb immediately to hit the road  higher  up  despite  added
elevation gain.

Once on the road I skied down it to cross Rocky Run and join Rd 136  on  the
other side. This is a shorter more direct route to this  junction  than  the
way I went Monday, 2 miles as opposed to 3.75, but  it  is  not  any  faster.
They both took about  2  hours.  Once  on  Rd  136  I  skied  to  the  first
switchback where I left the road to traverse left past cliffs until I  could
climb steeply up to the Twin Lakes Basin. Lovely terrain led past the  lakes
to the NW ridge and true summit of Mt Margaret.

I wanted to descend the same way I had on Monday as it was shorter  and  the
skiing was better than the way I had come up today. It sure  helped  that  I
knew the way. Without prior knowledge it would be easy to get  into  trouble
as there are many cliffs on the west side of Mt Margaret. The ski  down  was
every bit as good as Monday - until I hit the road. This was a  sunnier  day
and in areas hit by full sun a strong breakable sun  crust  had  formed.  It
was particularly bad on the descent from the Dungeon  Ridge  Road  (which  I
took from a higher point) to the spur road and almost unskiable.   But  once
on the spur road itself the snow was  protected  and  powdery  again  and  a
lovely ski down.

Total:       8       miles,       3600       ft       and       9       hrs.
         Fay Pullen

