Dungeon Pk Circumnavigation - February 2, 2012

Tuesday, January 31 - My interest  of  late  is  finding  new  (to  me)  and
interesting ski routes up or around peaks previously climbed. On  Tuesday  I
skied up the spur road from  the  motorized  Gold  Creek  SnoPark  with  the
express purpose of clipping it out to make it more skiable.  I  spent  about
two hours doing this, all the way to the end of longer left branch below  an
open slope. From there I checked out  a  new  reasonably  good  way  to  the
Dungeon Ridge road about 300 ft above. This was meant to be a short  day  as
a reconnaissance for a longer trip later but I had time to continue  up  the
ridge a ways before returning the same way. I discovered that Dungeon  Ridge
makes a splendid ski tour in its own right.

Thursday, February 2 - Two days later I returned with a much earlier  start.
My goal was to climb up Dungeon Pk from the south ridge, ski down the  north
side to Lake Lillian and return via  a  traverse  past  Twin  Lakes  and  Mt
Margaret. I had always wanted to ski the inviting looking  area  above  Lake
Lillian and I thought this would make a grand  loop.  Conditions  were  good
with about 4 inches new powder,  moderate  avalanche  danger  and  predicted
sunshine.

I quickly made short work of the now clipped spur road  and  onto  Dungeon\'s
south ridge, following the road along the upper ridge to its end in a clear-
cut at 4600 ft. When I first climbed Dungeon Pk on 3/28/95 I  had  continued
up the ridge until stopped by cliffs. I then left  skis  and  descended  200
feet off the ridge to the west and traversed  below  cliffs  until  I  could
kick steps up a steep snow gully to the NW ridge and on  to  the  summit.  I
returned the same way. This time I traversed through trees below  the  ridge
directly from the clear-cut. It was steep in places but doable and  I  ended
up right where I wanted to be at the base of the gully.  The  gully  however
was quite steep and about at my limit for climbing on skis. It  was  also  a
bit nerve-wracking despite  avalanche  danger  being  moderate,  as  it  was
exposed to the direct sun and funneled into a nasty black abyss  below.  Not
a place I wanted to be caught in a slide,  however  small.  Fortunately  the
day started cloudy and  the  snow  had  not  yet  warmed  up  significantly.
Nevertheless I breathed a sigh of relief when I reached the  5500  ft  notch
at the top and I most certainly did not want to return that way.

I had a  stunning  view  of  Rampart  Ridge  from  the  notch.  Easy  slopes
continued on the north side to the summit at 1:30 (5 miles,  3500  ft,  5:30
hrs). Despite warm sunshine it was too windy to have  lunch  here  so  after
snapping a few pictures I immediately skied down the inviting  north  slope.
This  much  anticipated  run  did  not  disappoint.  Fun,  fun,   fun   over
interesting and varied moderate terrain on excellent  snow  that  ended  way
too soon at lovely Lake Lillian.  Lovely as it was again I  could  not  stop
at the lake for lunch  due  to  wind  and  snow  swirling  across  the  open
expanse. I finally found a spot for lunch out of the wind  and  in  the  sun
just past the outlet creek at 2:30.

The traverse from 4800 ft Lake Lillian to 4700  ft  Twin  Lakes  went  quite
well except for having to drop  slightly  below  a  cliff  band  coming  off
Running Rock Pk, after which I had to climb back up again.  I  reached  Twin
Lakes at 3:50. These protected  north  facing  slopes  preserved  the  fresh
powder snow and skiing was excellent in the basin. I  was  now  on  familiar
territory from my trip up Mt Margaret of last  week.  I  continued  climbing
over Margaret\'s NW shoulder to get past cliffs. Up to now I had run into  no
signs of anyone else. However, on the descent from this point on I ran  into
fresh tracks of two other skiers coming off Mt Margaret. And when I  hit  Rd
136 it was tracked by a few snowmobiles. However, by now it was late  enough
(5:20) that everyone else had gone home and I never ran into any  makers  of
the tracks. I  cut  a  couple  of  switchbacks  but  the  snow  quality  was
deteriorating quickly and I soon stuck to the gentle road. No matter. I  was
getting tired and skiing was quite pleasant in  the  snowmobile  track.  The
moon was up high enough and bright enough that I was able to use  its  light
solely almost all the way to the junction with Rd 4832 at  6:20.  This  main
road was so well tracked as to be almost, but not quite, as  good  as  being
groomed. Even the un-looked-forward-to section along I-90 was not  half  bad
with a stiff easterly wind at my back propelling  me  all  the  way  to  the
SnoPark. I ended my grand loop at 7:20 to an empty lot.

Total: 13 miles, 4400 ft and 11:20 hrs

Fay Pullen



