Quilcene Area Dumpsters



February 9, 2012

Powerline Peak - 1980 ft - P420 -Uncas Quad - From Blyn I drove  Snow  Creek
Road/Rd 2850 turning  left onto Spur 120. This road is narrow but good  most
of way before getting quite muddy after about 2 miles. At 2.6 miles  I  took
a rough track left .2 miles before being stopped by deep muddy tracks.  From
here I hiked the track to its end then through forest to the power line  and
the benchmark on a large boulder next to a tower. There  is  a  track  under
the power line so presumably one could drive directly to this spot  - but  I
don\'t know how drivable it is.  (.6 miles, 200 ft, :39 hrs)

Pk 2018 - P680 - Gardiner Quad - After Powerline I returned  to  Snow  Creek
Road and took Rd 2906  (and obvious junctions - see map) about 4.5 miles  to
below this peak where I drove a very rough track left a short way.  This  is
a true 4X4 track probably best walked but I was in 4X4 mode and  having  fun
in the mud in my Jeep. The track was blocked at a good road coming from  the
north which I hiked up. The actual summit is slightly off the road  in  open
forest. (.6 mile, 180 ft, :37 hrs)

On the way out, since I was in the area and still  in  4X4  mode  I  took  a
rough muddy crossover road to the good road up to Blyn LO. Nothing  to  see.
It was too foggy.



February 12, 2012

Blyn Mtn - 2120+ ft - P1240 - Gardiner Quad - The key  to  Blyn  is  finding
the correct start to the road to  the  top.  On  the  way  to  Powerline  on
February 9 I checked out every possibility from the east  and  north.  Roads
shown on the map to go through either were  non-existent,  abandoned,  ended
in private property or were gated.  I even thought a  spur  off  2906  might
connect. No such luck. The proper road is  Casselary  Road  off  West  Uncas
Road where a short mile up there is  a  gate  and  a  small  "towers"  sign.
Parking is tight. I biked up this road. After 2.5  miles,  at  a  switchback
right, it gets quite steep and I pushed the bike the  last  mile.  There  is
another gate to go through before reaching the towers on top. I  counted  12
towers but it was so foggy I may have missed a few. A  fun  fast  run  down.
(6.8 miles, 1650 ft, 2:20 hrs)

Lordodendron Hill - 2204 ft - P644 - Uncas Quad - I  drove  toward  Quilcene
and onto Snow Creek Rd, Lords Lake Loop and Little Quilcene Rd to park in  a
wide spot SW of the peak just past the  clear-cut.  I  hiked  up  reasonable
forest and mild brush to the W saddle. Cliffs forced a route  to  the  north
until I could swing back to gain the summit ridge. The top  was  a  not-too-
thick rhododendron forest. (1.5 miles, 1050 ft, 2 hrs)

I had time to check out the 2 roads up Skid Row but  no  time  to  climb  it
before heading home.





February 15, 2012

Big Skidder Hill - 2126 ft - P1166 - Uncas Quad - I took Wycoff Rd off  West
Uncas Rd to the gate.  Again  tight  parking.  This  road  goes  through  to
connect with Snow Creek Road on the west but I  determined  it  was  shorter
from this east end. I biked the road easily for 2 miles to B6000 left.  This
is a good but very steep road that I pushed the bike up almost  2  miles  to
where it finally flattened. It was an exhausting effort but the  thought  of
the ride down kept me going. At the saddle the main road went  straight.  My
map indicated a spur right, slightly downhill, went all the way to the  top.
However this spur soon ended at huge ditches at the edge of  the  clear-cut.
I left my bike here. Oddly, once through the several ditches  the  road  was
quite good and would be bikeable if you could get the bike past the  ditches
and downed trees. Near the top a junction came in from the left,  not  shown
on my map. It is possible this road connects to the main road but I  am  not
sure. Anyway my way worked and I hiked the road all  the  way  to  the  top.
Once back to the bike it was a fast and furious ride down,  well  worth  the
effort of pushing the bike up. (9.5 miles, 2100 ft, 4:10 hrs)

Skid Row - 2563 ft - P483 - Uncas Quad - On to Snow  Creek  Road  again  and
the first Skid Row Rd. I parked at the  end  and  climbed  up  rather  nasty
brush/slash to the road above. This can be avoided  by  driving  the  second
road and hiking or biking the gated spur 1.7 miles to the same  point.  Take
your pick. I hiked the upper road a short distance to an old overgrown  spur
right.  Recent activity, survey markers  and  boundary  cut  signs  indicate
changes might happen in the future. I followed the  spur  to  a  brushy  end
above Rixon Cr, crossed the creek and entered pleasant open  forest  on  the
NW ridge to the summit. I left a small register on this one in  a  stump  on
top as there seemed to be a definite high point  and  the  whole  thing  was
surprisingly more enjoyable than expected. (2.6 miles, 825 ft, 2:40 hrs)



February 17. 2012

Skid Mark - 1341 ft - P760 - Uncas Quad  -  This  peak  gave  me  a  lot  of
trouble finding a way up that didn\'t cross private property.  I  tried  from
the south up Elkhorn Ln (which presumably goes all the way to the  house  on
top) but that ended at a high security gate not easily circumvented with  no
parking and no turnaround. I tried the road on the SW but that has a  cable,
private property sign and official looking no parking sign. I looked at  the
road on the north opposite the road up Scalped Hill  (I  think  Stefan  went
this way)  but  it  is  signed  no  trespassing.  I  try  not  to  cross  no
trespassing signs unless there is no other way to go. I finally  settled  on
starting from the gated road on the east. No signs, public  property  and  a
good place to park. I expected this route to be rather nasty and it was  but
at least I didn\'t cross any private property - except at the very top.

I hiked the road and a spur right that ended in  a  clear-cut.  Rough  paths
allowed a way through the clear-cut to the edge of a wide  marsh  at  Ripley
Creek. I crossed on tuffs of earth and logs. On the other  side  things  got
unpleasant with stitchery brush. It did improve somewhat as I got higher.  I
ended up almost directly below the house on top at a short slabby cliff.  No
one appeared to be around but it was so foggy I doubt they would  have  seen
me in any event. The high point was slightly off the driveway in the  woods.
This peak completed the Uncas Quad for me. (2 miles, 780 ft, 2:50 hrs)

Pk 2720+ - P400 - Mt Zion Quad - This was an easy one. I  drove  Snow  Creek
Road past both roads up Skid Row to the first junction  left,  Rd  2852.  At
the junction with Rd 2845 I went a short ways left to a  ditched  spur.  The
ditch was minor and others had gone through it  so  I  did  also.  Past  the
ditch the road was quite good. The road continues in  a  loop  drivable  all
the way around the peak although to the right is the better road.  I  parked
at an old grassy ditched spur on the south side.  This  track  and  pleasant
open forest led easily to the top. (.4 mile, 270 ft, :26 hr)

Pk 2600+ - P400 - Mt Zion Quad - This should have been trivial.  It  wasn\'t.
I continued on Rd 2845 and Rd 2840 to where 2 spurs took off right.  I  took
the right hand one (071) and drove to below the peak. I was  less  than   .1
mile away but the area had been recently thinned  of  scrub  trees  and  the
downed branches and trunks littered the entire summit hill  with  an  almost
impassible mess of bottomless debris. There was no  solid  ground  anywhere.
It took me over 30 minutes to struggle  to  the  top  and  back.  Positively
awful leg breaking stuff. If it had been any farther I would have passed  on
this true bottom-of-the barrel dumpster. (.2 mile, 130 ft, :32 hrs)

Just to make sure I visited the other two 2600 ft  closed  contours  on  the
ridge. Not nearly as bad, just some  ordinary  brush,  but  unfortunately  I
really think the pick-up-stick thinnings pile is the high point.

Lookout Hill - 1960+ ft - P400 - Mt Zion Quad - I returned to Rd 2840  until
it ran into Palo Alto Rd. I had been this way many times and knew  the  road
up Lookout was gated. I parked at the gate and biked 1.8 miles to  the  spur
going to the top. Unfortunately this spur  is  almost  non-existent,  barely
followeable and covered with large downed trees at the  start.  I  left  the
bike and struggled to the top. Why this hill is called  Lookout  I  have  no
clue. It is heavily wooded with no view. The fact that is was foggy and  now
raining didn\'t help. I had planned on being able to bike all the way to  top
and when I couldn\'t the whole thing took more time  than  expected.  It  was
getting late and darkness was encroaching. Urgency was  added  by  the  fact
that I had neglected to put my  headlamp  in  my  bike  pack.  Not  good.  I
whizzed back on my bike down the road to the car with just enough  light  to
avoid obstacles. That was cutting it a little too  close.  (4.6  miles,  485
ft, 1:28 hr)

Fay Pullen



