            'tr' => '
Dow Mtn (2514 ft - P1674), Saddle Mtn  (1840+  ft  -  P1000)  and  Pk  1680+
(P480) - Hoodsport Quad - February 23, 2012

I started from the DNR gate off the Lake Cushman Road. Note that  this  gate
is open from April 15 to October 1 and so these roads can be  driven  during
those dates. I am usually off doing more exciting things in that time  frame
so elected to bike during the closure. I am always looking  for  new  things
to do during the winter to stay in shape and  this  makes  for  a  wonderful
bike trip with a good workout. The roads are all  in  good  shape  and  very
bikeable although the spurs up both Saddle and Pk 1680+ (they are not  shown
on maps but are on satellite) are quite steep. The  others  are  all  fairly
gentle.

I first biked up Saddle going left at the first major junction  at  .7  mile
and pushing up the final steep spur. The road goes all the way  to  the  top
which is quite flat and I wandered a bit looking for the high point.  I  had
a pleasant lunch on top in the sun (4.7 miles, 1125 ft, 1:30 hrs).

I returned to the first junction and went the other way. This road  is  flat
to slightly downhill until crossing the creek flowing into Price Lake. At  a
major junction right it then begins to climb, but not  too  steeply.  I  was
initially dismayed to find the road freshly graveled.  Gravel  is  not  good
for biking. But it was fairly  compacted  and  not  a  real  problem.  At  a
junction at 1200 ft and marked "Dow Mtn Loop" and "1700" I went  left  on  a
lesser road to the steep spur that led to the  top  of  Pk  1680+.  Again  I
pushed. This spur is beginning to slough down the steep hillside  and  might
be a problem in a vehicle. The summit was just off the road in  a  stand  of
"leave trees" (12.4 miles, 2170 ft, 4 hrs).

I returned to the 1200 ft junction and began a long gentle  traverse  toward
Dow Mtn. My map showed this road going all the way to the top  but  alas  it
did not. After passing a junction left  pointing  to  a  woodcutting  permit
area my road began to look less used. Sure enough about .6 mile farther  the
road ended. It was completely decommissioned and unusable  by  bike.  But  I
determined I was not that far from the summit as  the  crow  flies  and  the
forest did not look that bad. So I left  my  bike  here  at  1700  ft  (17.5
miles, 2900 ft, 5:30 hrs) and hiked to the  top.  Although  the  forest  was
completely snowfree I was surprised to find about a  foot  of  snow  in  the
opening on top (18.2 miles, 3800 ft, 6:30) I also was surprised to  find  no
tower. For some reason I thought there would be one as a good road comes  in
from the south.

I returned to my bike, the roundtrip having taken 1:40 hrs with 1000  ft  of
gain with ups and downs (18.7 miles, 3900 ft, 7:10  hrs).  Although  it  was
getting late I took time to have a snack and bundle up for  the  anticipated
cold ride down. It was now 5:45 and the sun was setting.  No  problem.  This
time I did not forget my light. I got down most of the  way  to  the  valley
bottom before needing it and I reached the car at 7:00.

Total: 25.5 miles, 4100 ft and 8:30 hrs

Fay Pullen

