            'title' => 'East Rock (4269 ft - P349 - Mt Jupiter Quad) and Webb Mtn (2773 ft - P53 - Brinnon Quad) - Thursday, March 8, 2012',
            'tr' => '
East Rock (4269 ft - P349 - Mt Jupiter Quad) and Webb Mtn (2773 ft -  P53  -
Brinnon Quad) - Thursday, March 8, 2012

I have long been intrigued by the description of this little rocky  peak  in
the Olympic Mountains: A Climbing Guide. I saved it for  a  warm  sunny  day
when high avalanche danger kept me off higher summits. I  expected  snow  on
the approach roads so brought skis. Even so I was surprised  that  the  snow
level was so low. I ran into some almost immediately  off  Hwy  101  on  the
Hamma Hamma Road. Good grief! This road  is  only  600  ft  elevation.  Then
again I did hear the Hood Canal area got a big  dump  (like  8  -10  inches)
with the  last  lowland  event  so  I  guess  I  shouldn\'t  have  been  that
surprised. I was worried I wouldn\'t be able to get close  enough  to  do  my
trip in a day and I nearly wasn\'t. Turning off onto Road 2510 I  encountered
a deep patch a mere mile up.  My  Jeep  barely  made  it  through.  Then  it
actually got better once out of the shady valley and I even  had  some  bare
patches of ground where the sun  had  hit.  Luckily  I  was  able  to  drive
another 4 miles before being stopped for good at  elevation  1680  ft.  This
was still a mile shy of the junction with Road 2503 where  I  had  hoped  to
get but it was good enough.

I began by skiing up the road. In 30 minutes I was to the junction of  2503.
The climber\'s guide describes this road as a bit  overgrown.  Well  it  must
have been brushed out since the guide was written as it is now a  very  good
wide road. Perhaps new logging has  occurred  somewhere  along  its  length.
Anyway I easily followed it 3.2 miles to a spur right at elevation  2850  ft
(1270 ft, 2:15 hrs). This spur began very brushy and was  a  real  trial  on
skis. I almost gave up. Fortunately I didn\'t and it improved  greatly  after
rounding a rib. It actually became very nice  skiing,  gaining  very  little
elevation. After about 1.5 miles (1625 ft, 3:35 hrs) I left skis and  kicked
steps up a broad drainage and hillside through mostly open forest (with  the
occasional annoying rhododendron grove) to the SE Ridge. Once on  the  ridge
it was a matter of picking my way along the cornices.

Where the ridge steepened below the false summit I worked left up  and  over
it to the base of the summit block. The climbers guide describes this  as  a
short exposed class 4 pitch. My experience with  this  guide  is  that  they
often underestimate difficulty so I came prepared with rope and pro.  I  was
pleasantly surprised when it didn\'t appear to  be  as  bad  as  I  expected.
However, since it was exposed and I had it, I  roped  up  and  self  belayed
myself. Perhaps the snow made it  easier  as  I  could  kick  steps  up  the
vertical section but I really didn\'t need all that gear.

I popped over the small cornice above  the  pitch  onto  the  gentle  summit
ridge and followed it to the top (6.5 miles, 2760 ft,  5:30  hrs).  I  found
the benchmark labeled "Watson" which explains the alternate  name  for  this
peak and placed a register in the empty cairn. There was  a  great  view  of
The Brothers. A wind was kicking up so I  downclimbed  to  my  pack  at  the
bottom of the pitch for "lunch". I would have rappelled  but  could  see  no
obvious anchors.

I quickly retraced my steps to my skis. It was pleasant  skiing  the  gentle
spur road (except for the short brushy section) and very  nice  indeed  down
Road 2503. By the time I made it back to the junction  with  Road  2510  (12
miles, 2900 ft, 8:30 hrs) it was dark and  I  needed  my  headlamp.  Despite
that I decided to continue to Webb Mtn since I was so close. I  had  planned
on car camping and was in no great hurry.

There is not much to say about Webb. The entire trip was in  forest  and  in
the dark; however I was treated to the occasional glimpse of the  full  moon
reflecting off Hood Canal that added loveliness. A road goes all the way  to
the wooded summit although the final spur was so overgrown I gave up  on  it
and kicked steps straight uphill. Oddly, I  found  a  plastic  garden  chair
half buried in the snow of the small opening on top (13.8  miles,  3750  ft,
10 hrs).  But as near as I could tell there was no view so I am not sure  of
its intended purpose. I myself preferred to sit on my insulating pack  while
having a snack and finishing off the last of my hot chocolate.

I ended this long trip with an enjoyable  glide  down  the  road  under  the
light of a now high full moon. Oh I do love skiing in the moonlight.

Side trip to Webb: 3.6 miles, 850 ft and 2:30 hrs

Trip total: 15.8 miles, 3750 ft and 11:30 hrs

Fay Pullen













