            'title' => 'Watch Mtn (4805 ft - P645 - Randle Quad) - Wednesday, March 21, 2012',
            'tr' => '
Watch Mtn (4805 ft - P645 - Randle Quad) - Wednesday, March 21, 2012

Once again the avalanche danger was high.  This  seems  to  be  a  recurring
theme this ski season limiting choice of destinations.  I  thought  I  could
safely do this trip as it is all on logging roads or through forest.  I  was
able to drive Rd 75 out of Randle 4 miles to elevation 2080 ft before  being
stopped by deep new snow. I really pushed it the  last  mile  with  my  Jeep
dragging bottom and the bumper acting as a snow plow spewing powder up  over
the hood and onto the windshield. I really should have  stopped  sooner  and
paid for this error in judgment with 30 minutes  of  shoveling  so  I  could
turn around and park.

I skied the flat road 1.1 miles and then went up through the  woods  to  cut
off more flat road and a very long switchback. I figured I  saved  about  an
hour and at least 1.5 miles by doing so and it wasn\'t  too  bad  although  I
did have  to  take  off  my  skis  for  one  short  steep  section.  Once  I
intersected Rd 7561 above, I followed it through a  clear  cut  (1)  and  up
several switchbacks on the east end of the long main Watch Mtn ridge  before
turning a corner to the north side. The snow was very nice though there  was
a lot of new and trail breaking was slow. From the corner a  short  traverse
and downhill led to another clear cut (2). Up to now it had been cloudy  but
not snowing and there were some distant views. That  began  to  change  with
light snowfall and reduced visibility.

I stuck with the road as it climbed through  the  clear  cut  and  around  a
knoll as I wasn\'t quite sure how I was going to  gain  the  main  Watch  Mtn
ridge. I had thought I could  go  farther  toward  Watch  Lake  but  I  soon
determined that the whole north side of the ridge from  here  on  was  steep
and cliffy. My best bet was to follow a rib up the clear cut  to  the  broad
saddle above and cross to the south side. This I easily did. The  clear  cut
ended at the saddle where I entered woods. I knew from the map that I  would
most likely hit a steep section crossing a south running rib before I  could
gain more gentle terrain on the south slope proper.  What  I  didn\'t  expect
was this rib to turn out to be a cliff band that forced a descent of 300  ft
before I could get past it. But once past this, delightful  open  woods  led
to another clear cut (3) at the saddle just east of the main summit.

I picked up the road in clear cut 3 and followed it past cliffs on the  east
slope to where I could access easy terrain on the south  slope.  The  actual
summit ridge itself was wooded. Three closed 4800 ft contours  show  on  the
map and I visited all three. The surveyed 4805 point is the west one  but  I
am sure the east point is higher (5.5 miles, 3500 ft, 7:50 hrs).

I had a delightful run off the summit, even managing a few  telemark  turns,
and an even more delightful run through the open woods -  until  I  hit  the
cliff band. Then it all went to h###. I didn\'t want to follow my  in  tracks
as they were very steep and right at the base of the cliff wall. So I  tried
a lower tack on what I thought  would  be  easier  terrain.  It  wasn\'t.  If
anything it was worse. There were many obstacles:  steep  deep  snow  banks,
gullies, downed trees, creeks. I couldn\'t just go straight  up  and  had  to
wander back and forth finding a way often wallowing in bottomless snow.  And
of course it was now dark and snowing steadily. But how hard  could  it  be,
really? All I had to do was go uphill until I crossed  my  tracks  near  the
saddle. Well I did cross some tracks eventually but these  were  not  my  in
tracks, they were my out tracks. I had gone in a complete circle!  Not  only
did I do this once but I did this TWICE.  I still  can\'t  understand  how  I
managed to do this. Let me tell you one you get confused  wandering  in  the
woods  in  the  dark  it  is  hard  to  get  unconfused.  It  is  also  very
embarrassing. I hesitate to even admit I had done it.  I  offer  this  as  a
lesson in humility. At one point I thought about digging  a  snow  cave  and
waiting until morning. But I had an important engagement to  make  the  next
day. If I missed that I would be even more embarrassed especially when  they
found out why. That kept me moving.

I ended up finally making it to the saddle with  the  constant  help  of  my
GPS. I had referred to it before intermittently but that  wasn\'t  enough  to
keep me on track. And remember a GPS can tell you where you need to  go  but
not what line can be taken to get there. It does not allow for obstacles  in
the way. My guess is that all my wanderings, which  lasted  about  an  hour,
were in a very small area, probably less  than  a  baseball  field.  Anyway,
once back at the saddle all went well from then on and I  just  followed  my
tracks out. I really rather enjoy skiing  roads  by  headlamp.  But  I  must
admit reaching the car at 11:00 was a bit much.

To make matters worse, I had lowland snow falling and sticking to the  roads
all the way home until Puyallup. That added to the drive time.  Not  what  I
needed after a long and tiring trip.

Total: 11 miles, 4200 ft and 13 hrs

Fay Pullen



