            'tr' => '
Bergen Mtn (3760+ ft - P80 - Morton Quad) - April 4, 2012

Although of low elevation and little prominence this is the highest peak  on
the Morton Quad and it made for a nice ski tour.

The hardest part of this trip was driving the maze  of  logging  roads  from
the south close enough to do it. From Hwy 508 out of Morton I  turned  right
onto Road 73 then Road 7302. The latter road has numerous  very  deep  water
bars, almost impassible in places. My high  clearance  Jeep  scraped  bottom
and struggled on several of them but did make  it  through.  After  about  2
miles of this I came to an even worse washed out  section  where  I  had  to
straddle a deep creek ditch for a couple hundred feet. Past  that  the  road
improved again until I was stopped by  snow  just  before  a  switchback  at
about 2000 ft elevation. The total distance on Rd 7302 was 2.4 miles.

I only had to walk about Â¼ mile to  consistent  snow  where  I  could  start
skiing.  After about a mile I took a junction  right  and  in  another  half
mile a junction left onto an overgrown but skiable spur. This  spur  climbed
up onto the ridge, crossed to other side and traversed at the top of an  old
clear-cut. Rather than continue to the  end  of  the  spur  (which  did  not
connect to the good roads up Bergen coming from  the  north)  I  elected  to
take a more direct route up through pleasant open forest to the ridge  above
and west peak road. Once there it was delightful skiing  up  good  roads  to
Bergen Mtn (3.5 miles, 2000 ft, 3 hrs). I had nice views north to Mt  Elbert
and The Rockies.

So far the weather was holding with light snow showers and  sun  breaks.  It
was still early and the terrain looked inviting to continue exploring  so  I
skied to the little summit to the north that is actually a tad  higher  than
Bergen but is unnamed (Pt 3800). A  little  rocky  pinnacle  along  the  way
added interest. Then I skied back to the west peak  by  following  the  road
around the summit almost in a circle to its end and up a short  steep  slope
to the top. By now the weather had deteriorated to a heavy snow  squall  and
low visibility. I had no more views.

To return, I skied down the edge of the clear-cut  on  semi-open  slopes  to
pick up the spur road below and intersect my in tracks. Once  off  the  spur
road and on the main road it was a quick run down. This  little  peak  ended
up being a lot more fun than anticipated.

Total: 8.5 miles, 2600 ft and 7 hrs

Fay Pullen

