            'tr' => '
Salvation Pk (5560+ ft - P640 - Damnation Pk Quad) - April 7, 2012

Originally I wasn\'t going to write a TR for this as  Matt  and  company  had
just done it two weeks previous and I couldn\'t really add much to  his  fine
report               and                excellent                photographs
(http://www.nwhikers.net/forums/viewtopic.php?t=7997245).  Also   I   didn\'t
take that many photos. I was too tired. But it was such a  fun  trip  and  I
was so excited to finally be able to do a  big  elevation  peak  (the  first
since my injury of late last summer) that I couldn\'t  resist.  Matt  prefers
the name "Hellfire" while I have always had it  on  my  list  as  Salvation.
That name now seems even more appropriate to me personally  since  it  marks
the start of my return to the real thing after 6 months  of  slow  recovery.
So it shall always be Salvation Pk to me.
This trip was organized by Lisa. Others  joining  along  were  Jim,  Eileen,
Carry, Bill and Paul. It was a very enjoyable group. We were able  to  drive
the Bacon Creek Road all the way to the spur just  before  the  crossing  of
Bacon Creek, elev 800 ft. We hiked  this  spur  a  short  half  mile  before
taking off up fairly open mossy woods essentially  following  Matt\'s  route.
The trees were dripping melting new snow. At 3000 ft we  put  on  snowshoes.
There was at least a foot of new snow in open areas as we worked our way  up
to the saddle with Oakes at 4800 ft. By the time we had  done  the  4000  ft
gain to the saddle everyone, except  me,  was  all  for  calling  this  peak
Hellfire. The ascent is steep and relentless with no views. But once at  the
saddle it was all worthwhile with glorious views in  every  direction  along
the beautiful open up and down ridge to the summit (5300 ft, 6:15 hrs)

There was a cold wind on the summit that prevented  hanging  out  there  for
long. We did fine a sheltered spot out of the wind and in the  sun  a  short
ways below for a pleasant lunch break. Although small,  the  ups  along  the
ridge on the way back were a real effort for me as  I  was  running  out  of
steam. Then it was all downhill from the saddle. When the  slope  got  steep
we elected to  remove  snowshoes  and  boot  down  despite  some  impressive
postholing. The snow was very soft and wet. Due to  a  somewhat  late  start
the last hour was done by headlamp but our  overall  time  was  exactly  the
same as Matt\'s.

My thanks to Matt for the beta, to Lisa  for  organizing  the  trip  and  to
everyone else for their excellent company.

Total: 7 miles, 5600 ft and 11 hrs.

Fay Pullen



