Kiona Pk (4849 ft - P1529 - Kiona Pk Quad) - Friday, April 27, 2012

There are certainly easier and shorter ways up Kiona  Pk.   But  ever  since
skiing up Watch Mtn a month ago I really wanted to approach from  the  north
side of that peak.  The  terrain  looked  interesting,  variable  and  quite
skiable linking a series of roads.  I also wanted to visit  Watch  Lake  and
Watch Mtn Lookout. It turned out to not  disappoint  although  it  was  very
long with lots of ups and downs.

I again drove Road 75 out of Randle and this time  was  able  to  drive  5.5
miles to the current end of drivable road  at  a  washout,  elevation  2100.
From there I went straight uphill through an  unpleasant  clear-cut  to  hit
the road above. I only had to walk another half mile or so  before  I  could
start skiing at about 2900 ft. It had snowed a couple  of  inches  overnight
above 3500 ft. I repeated my route of Watch Mtn by  following  the  road  to
the first clear-cut on the north side then diverged  by  dropping  600  feet
through forest and a second clear-cut to Watch Lake. I could see  the  ridge
road I was aiming  for  in  the  distance  on  the  other  side  but  cliffs
prevented reaching it without dropping all the way to the lake.

At the lake I was stymied by 5 ft vertical snow walls on either side of  the
outlet creek. I had no ice axe and I didn\'t  think  I  could  cross  without
difficulty and the risk of falling into the water. Luckily  I  was  able  to
ski all the way around the lake and pick up the road on the other side.   An
upper spur of this road dead-ended 400 feet below the ridge  road  but  semi
open slopes  provided  an  easy  connection.  The  ridge  had  been  heavily
corniced many of which had collapsed with warm weather onto the road  in  an
impressive display of snow blocks. I sure wouldn\'t want to  be  around  when
that debris came crashing down. The lookout was  perched  above  me  on  the
ridge but it would have to wait for my return. For now it was on  to  Kiona,
still a ways away.

I climbed to a minor 4600 ft saddle on the ridge, crossed to the south  side
and dropped 500 ft to the saddle north of Kiona  where  I  followed  a  spur
road that dead-ended on the east ridge at 4400 ft.  I  left  skis  and  pack
here for a mad dash to the summit. Although the day  had  started  promising
with sun breaks and partial clearing it had  now  deteriorated  and  it  was
beginning to snow steadily. I quickly kicked  steps  in  soft  snow  to  the
summit (7.5 miles, 3900 ft, 6:20 hrs). The last bit was steep and  a  little
tricky without an ice axe (really  dumb  but  I  wasn\'t  expecting  anything
technical). However, the snow was so soft I was able to  use  my  ski  poles
upside down and insert the handles deep enough for good support.

I had just enough time  to  visit  Watch  Mtn  Lookout  on  the  return  but
unfortunately had no views. It was still snowing and also windy so I  didn\'t
hang around for long. Winter is not yet done in  the  mountains.  It  snowed
all the way out. With all the ups and downs it was  nice  the  snow  was  so
soft and sticky I didn\'t have to use skins at all. The no  wax  base  worked
fine. That saved a lot of time not having to put them on and take them  off.
Darkness did catch me but by then I was on the main  road  and  at  least  I
didn\'t get lost and confused as I had on my Watch Mtn  adventure.  That  was
an improvement.

Total: 16 miles, 5300 ft and 11:30 hrs

Fay Pullen





