            'tr' => '
Gibson Pk (4517 ft - P1437) and Colonel Bob (4510 ft - P1070) - Colonel  Bob
Quad - May 15-17, 2012

Colonel Bob is a tiny wilderness area  adjacent  to  Olympic  National  Park
east of Lake Quinault.  Its  main  claim  to  fame  is  Pete\'s  Creek  Trail
climbing from the West Fork Humptulips River.  There  is  also  a  connector
trail from the Lake Quinault side. The trail ends at the  old  lookout  site
(4492 ft) just west of the true summit (4510 ft). I had climbed  to  the  LO
in September of 1999 when I also  climbed  nearby  Mike\'s  Spike.  That  was
before I was aware of prominence so had missed the true summit. This time  I
also wanted to climb Gibson Pk which is the highest point (by  a  few  feet)
in the Wilderness. Since it is a long drive I planned to make a several  day
trip of it and take my time.

Tuesday, May 15 - I was unable to leave town until 3:30 and didn\'t start  up
the trail until 6:45. No matter. All I had to do was get to the  campsite  I
knew was at 2 miles (elev 2400 ft). The trail began in gorgeous rain  forest
carpeted by blooming oxalis, trillium and yellow violet. A color  feast  for
eyes tired of the monotones  of  winter\'s  snow  and  rock.  The  trail  had
several rough areas of washouts and/or avalanches that had been flagged  and
a few downed trees but was otherwise in good condition. At one mile was  the
crossing of Pete\'s Creek. It was running too high to rock hop but luckily  a
large log was just upstream. At 2 miles I  came  to  the  campsite  and  was
shocked to find a tent there. How could this be? There were  no  other  cars
at the TH. On closer inspection it became obvious the tent had been there  a
long time and was abandoned. It was littered  with  junk  including  trashed
food, an old sleeping bag and  a  large  (1.75  liter)  empty  bottle  of  R&R
Canadian Whiskey. Various scenarios played in  my  head  as  to  what  would
cause someone to leave valuable gear, all  of  them  involving  the  whiskey
bottle and a raucous party gone bad. I even  looked  for  bodies  but  found
none. I dismantled the tent and tossed it and the junk aside  to  make  room
for me. Despite the specter of ghosts it was a very pleasant campsite.

2 miles, 1350ft, 1:45 hrs

Wednesday, May 16 - I was underway at 7:20  next  morning.  Just  beyond  my
camp the trail opened up and became snow covered. I headed  straight  up  to
the obvious break in the cliffs west of Gibson working my way to the  ridge.
No real problems. Once on the ridge it was a short steep section  along  the
crest to the summit of Gibson (2150 ft, 3 hrs).  I  found  no  register  and
left none as it was completely snowed in.

So entranced was I by the beautiful basin to the NE that I did not  want  to
leave yet. This basin is surrounded by  several  other  high  points,  3  of
which are mentioned in the Olympic Climber\'s Guide. So in order  to  prolong
my stay I continued along the ridge to Pt  4454,  dropped  into  the  basin,
climbed to Pt 4418 (where the name Gibson is placed on  the  map)  and  then
returned through the basin below the ridge to Pt 4500.  All  were  easy  fun
peaks. Pk 4418 actually had a better summit with bare rock and Pk  4500  had
the best view of Colonel Bob.

I left Pk 4500 at 1:00 (3050 ft, 5:40) heading for  Colonel  Bob,  I  had  a
good view and picked out a route though the cliff  bands.  I  had  hoped  to
make a direct descent to Moonshine Flats. No such luck.  I  first  descended
the ridge in a different place than  my  up  route.  After  backing  down  a
hundred feet or so of steep snow I hit an icy section, gave up and made  one
50 ft rappel to get down the worst of it. From there I  could  see  no  easy
way straight down and ended up traversing back to my up route  and  dropping
all the way to 3100 ft where I more or less followed the trail to  Moonshine
Flats. From there I headed straight up to Colonel Bob. I got  off  route  in
the woods, hit the cliff band at a waterfall gully and got into  a  mess  of
steep brushy rock forcing my way up past it to the right.  At  one  point  I
had to take off my pack to get through. Open easy snow above the cliff  band
led to the base of the impressive summit rocks and ridge. From the looks  of
things I wasn\'t sure I could make it up. Then I saw a  snow  finger  to  the
right. And it sure looked like old tracks going that way luring me  on.  Had
someone else been here? Not likely. The snow finger ended in a brushy  rocky
slot that showed no signs  of  previous  passage.  It  was  worse  than  the
waterfall gully but I grunted and groaned  my  way  up  it  pulling  on  the
brush. I prayed it was easier once on the ridge. Mercifully it was. I  found
the bench mark on the rocky summit and left a register next to it (4600  ft,
10 hrs). I had a great view of Gibson and saw why I couldn\'t make  a  direct
descent to Moonshine Flats.

I was dismayed to see that there appeared to be an easy route  from  the  LO
and the NW side. But I couldn\'t be sure.  I  may  have  missed  seeing  some
cliffs looking down. I might have tried going down that way but had left  my
axe and pole at the base of the slot and so had had to return the same  way.
I rappelled the slot and bypassed the waterfall gully for  a  quick  descent
to camp.  It was now after 7:00, my feet were soaked and I was  tired  so  I
decided to spend another night.

Total: 4.5 miles, 4750 ft, 11:45 hrs

Thursday, May 17 - After a leisurely breakfast I packed up and left at  9:00
and reached the car  at 10:30.

Trip Total: 10.5 miles, and 6200 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen

P.S. I did check out Quinault Ridge Road 2280 on the drive  out.  It  is  in
good condition to the ridge crest where it is gated. It would  make  a  nice
bike ride along the ridge to near the various high points.  I  did  hike  to
the first one (2654 ft, P454, Lake  Quinault  East  Quad),  then  had  lunch
before heading home (3/4 mile, 370 ft, 1 hr RT).







