            'tr' => '
Big Methow Needle (8160+ ft - P1700 - Washington Pass Quad) - May 26, 2012

This peak was unfinished business for Matt, Mike and me. Last July we  three
made an attempt but were thwarted by  a  combination  of  factors  including
iffy weather, a late start, minimal gear and  totaling  underestimating  the
seriousness of the climb. We made it all the way to the col at the  base  of
the rock where an intimidating moat crossing was the final  straw  to  cause
us to pull the plug. We vowed to return earlier in  the  year  with  greater
determination and more preparedness.

As events unfolded we ended up with two more or  less  independent  parties,
Matt and Mike and Jim Eileen, Kevin and me. I drove over early on Friday  to
snag the last campsite in Klipchuck Campground at about 7:45  pm.  It  would
have been closer to camp at Lone Fir but it was still  snowed  in.  By  some
miracle the others found me in the dark crowded campground about  10:45  and
we all settled in for the night.

We didn\'t get a terribly early start starting  on  the  old  trail  up  Pine
Creek (8:00 am), but even so we had run into Matt and Mike at Lone  Fir  who
left maybe 30 minutes ahead of us. We followed their tracks to the  crossing
of Pine Creek where our routes diverged, they going up  the  right  side  of
the main gully and we up the left side.  The left side appeared to us to  be
more straightforward - all on snow and with no cliffs. As it turned  out  we
both arrived at the col to the right of the summit block at the  same  time,
1:00. The day had started sunny and warm but as it progressed  clouds  began
to  build.  There  was  enough  buildup  that  we  worried  it  could  begin
precipitating, which would be bad news if it caught us on the rock.  In  the
end it never amounted to anything other than causing  chilly  conditions  as
we waited our turn to climb.

We roped up, again as two separate rope teams. Everyone,  except  Mike,  was
in rock shoes which really helped. Matt led the first team. Conditions  were
much better than during our previous attempt. There was no moat and  it  was
easy to step off the snow onto the rock. That is not to say the first  moves
were easy. We all had trouble there as the holds were minimal. I found  this
section the hardest of the climb. In fact, I peeled off it when I pulled  on
a piece of pro that let loose. But Eileen caught me on belay and  I  had  no
damage other than a rip in my down jacket that spewed wisps of feathers  the
rest of the day.

Above the initial difficulty, the climbing eased as it  went  up  a  groove,
and then curved right to a spacious belay and rappel station. Matt went  all
the way to here on his first lead. Jim led the second team of four  and  had
to break it into two belays due to shorter ropes. Above the  rappel  station
was a fun lieback then easier terrain to the fairly roomy ledge right  below
the pointed summit. All six of us were able to hang out there. We found  the
register which had last been signed in 2009. We arrived at 4:00 and  started
down at 4:30 (4600 ft, 8 hrs).

We did two single rappels to the large ledge below  the  lieback,  then  one
double rope which easily reached to the col. That  took  about  an  hour.  A
fantastic glissade got us rapidly down much of  the  snow.  We  reached  the
cars at 8:00 where Mike and Matt said goodbye. The rest of  us  returned  to
Klipchuck for a celebratory evening around a campfire for a  most  enjoyable
end to a very enjoyable climb.

Total: 6 miles, 4600 ft and 12 hrs                    Fay Pullen





