            'tr' => '
Columbia Gorge Peaks

With the weather being so iffy lately that I  couldn\'t  put  two  good  days
together back to back, I headed south to the Columbia Gorge on two  separate
car camping trips. I still got rained on but  probably  less  than  anywhere
else in the state and I managed one good weather day  for  each  trip.  This
area deserves its reputation for scenic beauty  and  is  well  worth  repeat
visits.

Thursday, May 31

Dog Mtn (2948 ft - P1148 -  Mt  Defiance  Quad)  -  Dog  Mtn  is  an  iconic
Columbia  Gorge  peak  famous  for  its  spectacular  early  season   flower
displays. It did not disappoint despite my arriving to drizzle  and  fog  at
the TH. The massive fields  of  arrowleaf  balsamroot  on  the  open  summit
slopes were some of the best I have ever seen but I was  also  impressed  by
the beauty of the lower forest. The fog even nicely cleared  a  bit  on  the
way down. I went up the "old trail" and down the "new" for a loop trip  (7.3
miles, 2900 ft and 4:30 hrs).

Wind Mtn (1907 ft - P947 - Carson Quad) - Wind   Mtn  is  an  archaeological
preserve that was used for vision quests by Native Americans and as such  is
a scared place. I was racing darkness to  the  summit  which  added  to  the
mystical experience for me. There is a (normally) nice trail up the NE  side
but unfortunately recent storms have not treated it kindly  and  there  were
numerous large windfalls that had to be climbed over or around  (2.8  miles,
1100 ft and 1:35 hr).

I then drove on to Beacon Rock State park to spend  the  night.  This  is  a
lovely campground set in old grove forest. It is  a  little  pricey  for  my
taste ($22/night with no break for seniors) but does have all the  amenities
like hot running water and showers. A Discover Pass is required in  addition
to the camping fee. The weather cleared during the night and  the  next  day
dawned partly sunny and warm.

Friday, June 1

Hamilton Mtn (2438 ft - P318 - Beacon Rock Quad) - Beacon  Rock  State  Park
is much more than just Beacon Rock.  It  is  a  large  park  with  miles  of
trails. One is the trail up Hamilton Mtn. This can be accessed  from  either
the campground or a large parking lot and picnic area slightly  lower.  Both
require a Discover Pass. The flower displays were not as showy  as  Dog  Mtn
but the upper rocky cliffs more than compensated for this.  The  trail  also
goes past impressive Rodney Falls. Many hikers  never  get  beyond  here.  I
went up the Hamilton Mtn trail, which is quite steep,  and  down  the  Hardy
Creek trail, which is longer and less steep with much of  it  on  old  road.
This made another nice loop trip (8.2 miles, 2300 ft and 5 hrs).

Wednesday, June 6

Table Mtn (3417 ft - P377 - Bonneville Dam Quad) - Table Mtn is  responsible
for The Bridge of the Gods when centuries ago a massive landslide  slid  off
it and dammed the Columbia River. I had a look at this  peak  from  Hamilton
and was back less than a week later to climb it on the  only  good  forecast
day of the week. I started from the Dick Thomas Trail that can  be  accessed
from the Bonneville Hot Springs gravel lot to the NW. This trail  intersects
an old road in about a mile which is then followed another 1.5 miles to  the
PCT. From there it is .2 miles to the  Table  Mtn  Heartbreak  Ridge  Trail.
Evidently this trail is notorious for its steepness.  I  actually  found  it
quite good but then my standards are low as I am used  to  climber\'s  trails
or no trail at all. I even enjoyed the  section  that  goes  straight  up  a
talus slope for 300 ft.  Shortly below the top I took the side trail to  the
Gorge Overlook at the edge of sheer cliffs. I then  followed  the  ridge  to
the flat summit area and returned on the Westway Trail, slightly less  steep
than the Heartbreak. It should be pointed out that the Bonneville  Dam  Quad
has 80 ft contours and so to those of us used to 40 ft  contours  everything
looks less steep on the map than it really is.

Aldrich Butte (1141 ft - P341 - Bonneville Dam Quad) - On  the  return  from
Table I hiked the old road up this peak to  an  ancient  WWII  defense  site
with crumbling concrete foundations. Views were limited due  to  encroaching
trees. Total for both peaks: 10.2 miles, 4100 ft and 7:20 hrs

I then drove road CG2020 north of Stevenson about 7.5 miles to the  five-way
intersection at the saddle between  Greenleaf  and  Birkenfeld.  This  is  a
rough steep road with many waterholes. A high clearance 4X4 is  recommended.
I had hoped to car  camp  at  the  saddle  but  found  nothing  suitable  so
continued on the spur toward Greenleaf where I found a  wide  spot  to  park
under the power line swath.

Thursday, June 7

Greenleaf Pk (3422 ft - P702 - Bonneville Dam Quad) - I awoke to heavy  rain
at 5:30. I went back to sleep for a couple of hours and dreamed my  car  was
towed. This prompted me to bite the bullet and get going  before  I  had  an
even worse dream. Actually the hike up Greenleaf was quite pleasant  despite
the rain. I followed the power line road to the ridge where I stumbled  upon
an old trail that looked to me as though it were  built.  Sure  enough  just
below the summit I came across a derelict  cabin  which  accounted  for  the
trail (1 mile, 775 ft and 1:20 hr).

Birkenfeld Mtn (3763 ft - P1563 - Beacon Rock Quad) - Back at the  saddle  I
took Rd 2026 toward Birkenfeld for 1.4 miles which  seemed  longer  as  this
road was even rougher and rockier than 2020.  I  parked  below  a  swath  of
forest that I thought would offer the most brush free route  to  the  ridge.
On the ridge I picked up the PCT which I then left too soon to go up  the  S
ridge (quite brushy). I returned on the less brushy W ridge. If there  is  a
trail up this peak  I  never  found  it.  Since  there  were  zero  views  I
concentrated on flora and was fortunate to see the rare  chocolate  lily  (2
miles, 850 ft and 2:30 hrs).

Rock Cr Butte (1934 ft - P414 - Bonneville Dam Quad) - I  drove  CG2000  and
the road up Rock Creek Butte (both very good roads) to the  intersection  on
the SW side. Both roads are blocked from here. I hiked up the spur that  led
almost to the top but it is so overgrown as to be more trouble  than  it  is
worth. It is easier to ascend straight up the hill  from  the  intersection.
This is the way I  came  down.  It  had  stopped  raining  by  now  and  was
beginning to clear enough that I had a decent view of Greenleaf through  the
trees. But the highlight of this trip was almost stepping on a  fawn  hiding
right smack on the summit waiting for its  Mom  to  return.  They  are  well
trained not to move a muscle  and  give  away  their  existence.  I  quickly
snapped a photo and retreated before causing it further  distress.  This  is
only the second time in my life I  have  been  treated  to  such  a  special
moment (.5 miles, 400 ft, 1 hr).

With no dry gloves left and rain forecast again for Friday  I  headed  home.
But    I    will    be    back.     I     really     like     this     area.


Fay Pullen





