            'tr' => '
Twin Lakes BM (5301 ft - P581), "Stolen Thunder" (5045 ft  -  P405)  and  Pk
5113 (P393) - Mt Townsend Quad - June 14-16, 2012

Stefan and company had climbed the  first  two  of  these  peaks  this  past
winter on a day trip by approaching via the steep trail from  the  S  Tunnel
Cr TH. I planned on approaching from the better trail of the N Tunnel Cr  TH
and taking a more leisurely three days by camping  somewhere  near  Harrison
Lake. Stefan named Stolen Thunder on his trip. Again I had to make  do  with
a  short  weather  window  during  this  spring   of   continued   unsettled
conditions.

Thursday, June 14: Pk 5113 - Buoyed by partial clearing and the prospect  of
some sunshine  on  the  drive  over,  I  was  dismayed  that  it  turned  to
consistent fog and drizzle by the time I arrived at  the  TH.  Though  never
very heavy, it persisted for the rest of the day. I began running into  snow
about .5 miles before the shelter where it was pretty solid. After  crossing
Tunnel Creek on a footlog, the  trail  became  mostly  snowfree  again  once
above the valley floor and easily followed to the first of the  twin  lakes,
Karnes Lake which was completely under  snow  as  was  the  slightly  higher
Harrison Lake. Not able to find any obvious bare ground here to camp  on,  I
continued to 5050 Pass hoping something on  the  south  side  of  the  ridge
would be melted out. I found nothing so returned to Harrison Lake (4700  ft)
where at least I had running water. And to my delight, after some  searching
around, I located a bare flat spot, under a tree, just large enough  for  my
tent.

After setting up camp, I did the short easy climb up  Pk  5113  via  the  SW
ridge. No problem other then the wet brush that soaked  both  my  pants  and
gloves. I had zero  views.  I  fell  asleep  that  night  listening  to  the
constant drip, drip, drip on my tent  fly  and  thinking  if  things  didn\'t
improve come morning I was out of here.

To camp: 5 miles, 2300 ft and 4 hrs           Up Pk 5113:  1  mile,  500  ft
and 1:20 hrs RT

Friday, June 15: Twin Lakes BM and Stolen Thunder - Things did  improve.  In
fact I woke up to blue skies. In fact I was able to dry my pants  enough  in
the sun while having breakfast that it wasn\'t total repulsion  putting  them
on.

My objective peaks were not all that much higher than my  camp  but  getting
to each entailed a lot of up and down. First  I  had  to  get  to  the  main
ridge. I decided to try a direct traverse to  saddle  1  at  4680  ft.  That
didn\'t work too well as I had to drop over 300  feet  and  deal  with  steep
hillside to get past cliffs. Once at saddle  1,  I  elected  to  climb  Twin
Lakes BM first which I did by following the ridge the whole  way,  easy  and
pleasant although it did entail climbing over a  sub  peak.   And  why  this
ridge was mostly snowfree while the one by 5050 Pass was not I am not  quite
sure.

I reached the summit at 11:30 (850 ft, 2:40 hrs) and stayed for  the  better
part of an hour having lunch in the sun and enjoying  the  magnificent  view
of the east face of Mt Constance.

I found an old film can register dated 1981. It  was  in  surprisingly  good
shape for being 30 years old but only had the one entry. It was well  buried
and I would have missed  it  myself  had  I  not  been  turning  over  rocks
building a cairn for my own register next to the bench mark.  I  would  have
left it alone but since it had no pencil I decided to leave mine along  with
it. A register is useless if  it  cannot  be  signed  and  it  has  been  my
experience most climbers do not carry pencils.

From Twin Lakes BM I didn\'t want to reclimb the sub peak so  again  tried  a
direct route to the next saddle 2. Again I had  to  drop  below  cliffs  but
travel was reasonable and I think it was easier than staying on  the  ridge.
Once at saddle 2 the nature of the ridge changed.  It  started  as  pleasant
forest but soon deteriorated to gosh awful rhododendron  jungle.  For  those
not familiar with eastern Olympic rhododendrons trust me  when  I  say  they
are as bad, or even worse, than slide alder.  They  grow  as  thick  and  in
addition have branches that go every which way  and  entwine  you  in  their
snare. I was slowed by this obnoxious stuff until  eventually  breaking  out
into the increasingly rocky and cliffy area near the summit.  I  dropped  to
the south slope to bypass a first cliff, got back  on  the  crest  and  then
soon came upon the final pinnacle mentioned by Stefan. I  tried  going  over
the top but in the end took Stefan\'s route by dropping down the north  side.
This was the only place I needed and used my ice axe. I reached  the  summit
of Stolen Thunder at 3:40 (2350 ft, 6:50 hr). I built both a cairn and  left
a register.

By now the weather  was  beginning  to  change  and  Constance  was  already
obscured by clouds. The window had been  short  indeed.  For  the  return  I
stuck on the ridge the entire way and arrived back at camp at 8:00.

Total: 5.5 miles, 3450 ft and 11:15 hrs

Saturday, June 16 - I fully expected to wake  to  rain  and  was  pleasantly
surprised when I did not. I even made it all the way to the  TH  before  any
weather hit (2:30 hrs out).

Trip Total: 16.5 miles and 6600 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen









