            'tr' => '
Muncaster Mtn (5910 ft - P990) and "Fire Cr  Pk"  (5624  ft  -  P544)  -  Mt
Christie Quad - June 20-22, 2012

Wednesday, June 20 - Beginning from the Enchanted Valley TH (elev  600  ft),
I hiked the 4 miles to Fire Cr where I left the trail to go up the ridge  on
the right-hand side. I was able to follow a faint way trail  for  the  first
1000 feet or so after which I lost it. I ran into  minor  brush  and  it  is
quite steep and slow  going  with  a  full  pack,  but  overall  this  is  a
reasonable route. At 3300 feet the hillside leveled out a bit and I found  a
comfy bare spot to camp near a small creek. It would have been nicer to  get
farther but I had gotten a late start so it was already 7:40  by  this  time
and time to stop. However, I felt I had gotten close enough to  be  able  to
climb my peaks the next day. This was just before the snowline.

Total: 5.5 miles, 3100 ft and 6:10 hrs

Thursday, June 21 - From my camp I continued up alongside Fire  Creek,  soon
running into solid snow, to a large basin at  3800  ft  ringed  by  a  cliff
band. A gully on the left provided a way through  the  cliffs  to  an  upper
basin and easy snow slopes to 5150 Fires Cr notch.  From  the  notch  I  had
great view into the heart of the wild Olympics where few people  venture.  I
wished I had more time to travel the inviting terrain toward July  10th  Pk,
and beyond. But for now my goal was to get up Muncaster, which I  could  not
yet see. The climber\'s guide was a bit vague in describing  the  route  only
saying to drop "a few hundred feet" to an open basin. What  the  heck  is  a
few hundred feet? Since it then said to contour to regain  the  ridge  at  a
5000 ft saddle I took that to mean you drop to 5000 ft or about 150  ft.  So
I did just that to get past the initial cliffs of the notch after  which  an
easy snow slope appeared to lead back to the ridge. Well it wasn\'t  as  easy
as it looked.  I made it to the ridge but I then  could  see  Muncaster  and
that I was too high and above where I supposed to be and had to  descend  to
the aforementioned 5000 ft saddle.  I really think I was totally  off  route
and should have descended farther to begin with, probably an  additional  5-
600 ft.

From the 5000 ft saddle the climber\'s guide now says to "traverse  right  to
the NE face".  The only problem was there was a continuous  band  of  cliffs
on the E ridge barring access to the NE face. The guide made no  mention  of
cliffs and I saw no easy way through these  cliffs  without  a  considerable
drop of nearly 1000 ft. The only possibility was a high  snow  traverse  and
that looked rather iffy as I saw several discontinuities. Still,  I  decided
to go for it. It started well but about halfway across I began running  into
problems. The snow was very steep and exposed with no run out over  vertical
cliffs and I would have to descend a bit to get past gullies. So  instead  I
went up with the terrain getting more and more difficult.  At  one  point  I
saw a goat above me. He was probably laughing at  me  as  at  this  point  I
realized I was so NOT on route it was funny and things were going  from  bad
to worse. I knew where I had to be, i.e. the NE face, but  I  just  couldn\'t
seem to get there. Yet somehow I managed  to  force  a  way,  several  times
squirming through thick trees just so I had  something  to  hang  onto,  and
emerged onto the E ridge. Another 100  feet  of  steep  but  straightforward
snow put me on the summit at 2:30, much later than I  had  hoped  (3400  ft,
6:40 hrs).

I stayed on the summit over 30 minutes. I found and left no register as  the
high point was all snow. I was now faced with how to get down. No way was  I
going down the way I came up. If worse  came  to  worse  I  would  take  the
considerable drop. I started down the E ridge until I was more or less  even
with the snow traverse of my way up.  I could now see it might go and so  it
did. It seemed less difficult in this direction. I had some up and  down  in
and out of gullies and one particularly  steep  snow  traverse  but  it  was
better than my up route. I do think this is the route and that it  would  be
easier with less snow when more of the goat trails I came across are  melted
out.

I then essentially followed my high route back to Fire Creek notch  since  I
was familiar with it. I still think it would  probably  be  better  to  drop
father below the notch but I am not sure as I did not do that.  There  could
be hidden cliffs to get by. In any event I was back to the  notch  at  6:20.
It was getting late but I still really wanted to climb Fire Cr  Pk.  It  was
so close. I crossed through the notch and climbed easy snow to the  base  of
the west face rock. It looked broken enough to be scrambleable.  And  so  it
was, though marginally so and not a lot of fun. From the top of the  snow  I
went up some slabs to a chimney/gully that led to the W ridge. The floor  of
this deep slot was steep wet dirt that was so  slick  it  gave  no  reliable
purchase for my feet. I struggled up often using heather on  the  sides  for
hand holds to pull on. I thought things  would  improve  at  the  top.  They
didn\'t. They were replaced by struggling  through  thick  cedar  pulling  on
branches. There must be a better way up this  peak  that  involves  pleasant
rock scrambling but I didn\'t have the time to seek it  out.  I  reached  the
summit at 7:30 (4800 ft, 11:40 hrs). At least the views were nice.  I  built
a cairn, as none existed, and left a register.

I slithered down through the trees and rappelled the  slot.  Then  was  fast
fast fast down the snow. I  reached  my  tent  at  9:35  without  needing  a
headlamp. Thank heavens for the long days of the solstice.

Total: 6 miles, 4800 ft, 13:45 hrs

Friday, June 22 - I fully expected to hear rain on my tent during the  night
as the latest forecast had indicated, so when I awoke at 5:30 to  none  yet,
just clouds and fog I was very pleased and inspired  to  get  moving  faster
than usual. I quickly got ready, broke camp and was on my way  before  7:00.
It would have been miserable to descend that steep ridge to the  Quinault  R
Trail in the rain. I almost made it all the way out  before  the  rain  hit,
only having light precip the last mile to the car.

Day Total: 5.5 miles, 500 ft and 3:50 hrs

Trip Total: 17 miles and 8400 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen



