            'tr' => '
Mt Hoquiam (4909 ft - P229 - Mt Hoquiam Quad) - June 27-28, 2012

Wednesday, June 27 - I thought this would be a  simple  little  trip  easily
fit into 1.5 days but things didn\'t go as  smoothly  as  expected  (do  they
ever?).  My daughter had been visiting for over a  week  and  departed  just
the day before which left me totally unorganized and led to  a  late  start.
Then I ran into snow on the approach road (Rd  2270)  above  Wynoochee  Lake
beginning at 2900 ft. I was able to push through several patches to make  it
another mile to 3300 but this was still short of where I wanted to be.  Will
this snow never melt? So I had to hike an additional mile to  the  beginning
of my route. I left the road where it crossed  the  stream  exiting  from  a
small pond following Route 2 in the climber\'s guide but in  retrospect  this
is not the best way to go. I ran into steep slick brushy forest  getting  to
the pond and the spur ridge above it. This turned out to be rocky and I  had
to descend to get off it. And the traverse past Pt 4520 to the ONP  boundary
ridge had lots of ups and downs and was very slow going.  So  I  reached  my
planned campsite in the SE basin below Hoquiam at  the  late  hour  of  5:00
(2.5 miles, 1450 ft, 3:15 hrs) considering I still wanted to climb my  peak.
Then I discovered the basin was totally snowed in.  I  really  thought  some
bare meadow would be melted out by now but the best I could find was a  tiny
spot in a grove of trees. However, there was no running water  to  be  found
anywhere. It was all locked beneath the snow. Despite all  it  was  still  a
pleasant camp.

I quickly set up my tent  and  took  off  for  Hoquiam  at  5:50  worried  I
wouldn\'t have enough daylight  left.  I  took  my  large  collapsible  water
bottle along hoping to find running water somewhere along the way but  never
did. Finally I just filled it with snow and set it in the sun  to  at  least
partially melt by my return.  I easily crossed the basin, which  I  am  sure
would be lovely meadows later in the season, to the S ridge of Pt 4640.  The
ridge crest was snow free. A gully slightly to the right gave a way  through
the upper cliffs to the top. I descended open snow on the other side to  the
saddle with Hoquiam. I regained the S ridge which  was  very  narrow,  rocky
and covered with thick twisted trees. I soon left my poles as  they  were  a
real impediment but kept my axe as I had seen snow higher  up.  Sure  enough
after battling through the brush I was forced to go right below cliffs  onto
a snow traverse that led up and around left to the summit  rocks.  A  simple
scramble then put me on the summit at 7:30 (950 ft, 1:40  hrs).  I  found  a
large (dry) register placed in 2007. A total of 10  parties  had  signed  in
during the 5 years. I left the summit at 8:15 after enjoying  the  view  and
trying, mostly unsuccessfully, to identify the sea of inner  Olympic  peaks.
I was back to camp just before dark at 9:30 (2  miles,  1150  ft,  3:40  hrs
RT).

Thursday, June 28 - Rain was forecast to move in today about noon. I  didn\'t
have far to go to get out so I slept in, took  my  time  getting  ready  and
even painted a picture, my first in a while.  Usually  I  neither  have  nor
take the time for such a luxury. It was nice not to be in a rush. I  finally
left at 10:00. Not wishing to repeat my in route,  once  I  gained  the  ONP
boundary ridge I dropped straight down to  the  road.  This  seemed  a  much
better route to me despite having to lose additional elevation. I  did  have
to climb several hundred feet up the road to get back to my car (2.5  miles,
550 ft 2 hrs). However, when the snow is  melted  you  could  drive  to  and
start directly from this lower road. I did get out before any rain hit.

Trip Total: 7 miles and 3150 ft  in  1.5  days                          Fay
Pullen





