            'tr' => '
Mt Torment Attempt (8120+ ft - P200 - Forbidden Pk Quad) - July 5-7, 2012

I was both too early and too late for this peak via the SE  face,  the  only
route I thought I was capable of soloing. How could this be  you  ask?  Well
easy in this crazy weather  year.  I  was  too  late  for  the  moat  to  be
crossable and I was too early for the recent snow to  have  consolidated.  I
knew going into this that my chances of soloing this peak were iffy.  I  did
have gorgeous weather but good weather does not  always  translate  to  good
climbing conditions.

Thursday, July 5 - There were several cars parked at  the  Boston  Basin  TH
but not as many as  expected  considering  the  warm  sunshine  and  holiday
weekend. It was a slow grunt up the steep  trail,  especially  since  I  was
carrying so much technical gear (rope, rack, crampons). I had my  first  bad
omen when I met a guide coming out. She reported not being  able  to  summit
Sahale due to bad snow and an ominous cornice. Her 3 clients had elected  to
stay another day.  Then  I  met  2  rangers.  They  too  reported  bad  snow
conditions with it having snowed 3-4 feet the previous week  at  the  higher
elevations. They also said Boston Basin was completely  snowed  in  with  no
bare campsites but that they were able to dig out the toilet  at  the  lower
camp. I ran into solid snow beginning about 5000 ft. I  stopped  briefly  to
chat with the clients still at the lower camp (5600  ft).  There  were  some
bare spots for sitting and cooking (none big enough for  a  tent)  but  they
were spread out covering most of them so I decided to keep going. I found  a
reasonable site at 6200 ft that I ended up sharing with a  resident  marmot.
It took me about 30 minutes to level a spot in the  snow  with  my  ice  axe
large enough for my tiny bivy tent.

Total: 3 miles, 3100 ft, 6 hrs.

Friday, July 6 - I was awakened by a party of 3  heading  for  the  Torment-
Forbidden Traverse. Good. I wouldn\'t have to break trail. They were about  2
hours ahead of me. I followed their footsteps up the Taboo Glacier to  where
they diverged to go  to  the  South  Ridge  Notch,  their  chosen  route  up
Torment. I was headed to the SE Face. Beckey states that after  July  1  the
moat above the Taboo Glacier can be difficult. Somehow  I  thought  that  in
this high snow year it would be in condition longer. That was not the  case.
It went all the way across and I knew I was in trouble. I dinked around  for
over an hour searching for a way across but  this  is  one  nasty  moat.  In
places it was such a deep dark dank bottomless pit that it scared  the  sh..
out of me. I am becoming convinced that a high snow year does NOT make  moat
crossings last longer and easier but simply makes them bigger and deeper.

I did eventually find a way across the moat on questionable bridges  to  the
far right but then I could not traverse back left above the moat  to  regain
the route. My only option was to continue straight up  on  broken  rock  and
hope to traverse higher up. This might have worked and  I  wasn\'t  the  only
one with this idea as I came across a  hex  in  a  crack.  But  I  ended  up
stopped by an icy chimney. I began hacking steps and a  chunk  of  ice  came
off and hit me in the knee. Not incapacitating but  then  I  heard  a  slide
come down from somewhere near the East Ridge notch. I watched as it  bounced
down over the moat and onto the glacier below. I was in a safe  spot  but  I
saw the handwriting on the wall. I had had enough. It just wasn\'t  meant  to
be. On the rappel down I heard two more smaller slides or rockfalls.  And  I
heard voices of the traverse party above me. They did  not  sound  happy.  I
not sure what was going on with them but I doubt it was anything good.  They
may even have been the cause of some of those slides. I could see they  were
traversing off the S Ridge and were high on the SE  Face  and  had  not  yet
summitted Torment.

I turned around about 1:30 and was back to camp by 3:00. I  didn\'t  want  to
go out this day so to fill the rest of  it  I  decided  to  wander  over  to
Sharkfin Tower and check it out. Possibly I could still get up it  though  I
doubted it. In 2 hours I was at the base of that peak\'s  access  gully.  For
the last hour I had watched a party of 4 on the snow slope above the  gully.
I was really puzzled as to what they were doing.  They  didn\'t  seem  to  be
moving very fast and they were way left of the up route. This could  not  be
good. As luck would have it I reached the gully  just  as  they  started  to
rappel down it. Again there was a moat but it could be bypassed on  rock  to
the left. I was preparing to go that way when a slide  came  down  over  the
rock. I then made contact with the lead climber. They were  just  trying  to
get off the peak and had rappelled directly off the summit (not down the  up
route). He reported the snow was very unstable. So once again I turned  tail
and returned to camp where I had a pleasant 2 hours in  the  sun  before  it
set behind the ridge. I noticed that there were  fresh  tracks  coming  back
from the direction of Torment while I had been gone. If I  had  to  guess  I
would say the traverse party  bailed  on  continuing  to  Forbidden.  I  was
beginning to wonder how many other climbers  ran  into  difficulties  during
this weekend.

Total: 4.5 miles, 3000 ft and 8:40

Saturday, July 7 - One more note on the trip out. It was uneventful for  me.
However, just after I reached the old mine road I was surprised to run  into
a French family hiking up  the  trail.  The  two  kids  were  young  and  in
tennies. The parents didn\'t have much better gear either.  I  tried  to  ask
gently if they were in the right  place or really wanted  the  Cascade  Pass
trail. I tried to explain this was a  difficult  climber\'s  trail  but  they
would have none of it or maybe they didn\'t understand me. I probably  should
have minded my own business. Maybe they really  did  want  an  adventure  of
their own. In any event they would soon figure it out as just a  short  ways
on the "trail" left the old road and became very steep and nasty.

So in the end I climbed nothing. Yet I felt oddly satisfied with  the  trip.
I camped in a fantastic alpine setting and essentially traversed the  entire
length of beautiful Boston Basin. And that counts for something.

Trip Total: 10.5 miles and 6100 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen



