            'title' => 'The Brothers, North Peak (6650 ft - The Brothers Quad) - July 13 - 15, 2012',
            'tr' => '
The Brothers, North Peak (6650 ft - The Brothers Quad) - July 13 - 15, 2012

Sandbagged once again by the Olympic Mountains  Climbing  Guide.  This  peak
turned into more of a challenge than the brief description  of  Route  1  in
the guide would indicate. Class 3 turned out to be class 5 and  snow  slopes
of 20-30 degrees became 45 degrees. However, I must say the listed  time  of
9 hours from Lena Forks was fairly accurate. None the less it was a  classic
Olympic alpine adventure that Jim and I both thoroughly enjoyed.

Friday, July 13 - The plan was for me get a head start by hiking  into  Lena
Lake the night before and meet Jim, Eileen and Lisa  the  following  day  at
Lena Forks. From there we would continue on to  bivy  somewhere  near  Lunch
Rock. Then Eileen and Lisa  would  climb  South  Brother  while  Jim  and  I
tackled North Brother.  I first climbed West Rock (4211 ft -  P371  -  Eldon
Quad) from the end of the upper spur of Cabin Creek Road  (2.5  miles,  1400
ft, 4:20 hrs RT). I ran into brief thunder showers  that  made  the  initial
rhododendron brush wet and unpleasant but the summit itself was  lovely  and
a nice viewpoint for the route up North Brother.

By the time I started up the Lena Lake trail it was 6:30.  The  parking  lot
was a total zoo. I reached the  lake  at  8:30  where  I  found  every  tent
campsite taken but since I was in a bivy I was  able  to  use  a  tiny  spot
along Lena Creek just past the bridge (3 miles, 1300 ft, 2 hrs).

Saturday, July 14 - In no hurry, I slowly strolled up the  trail  along  the
East Fork of Lena Creek through the Valley of  Silent  Men.  With  its  moss
covered boulders and waterfalls this has to be one  of  the  most  beautiful
low valleys in all of the Olympics. It is worth a trip in itself and  I  was
happy to go at a pace where I could enjoy it to its fullest. Going  at  half
speed and with one long stop to soak aching body parts in the cold water  of
the creek I reached Lena Forks camp at noon (3 miles, 1300 ft, 3:30 hrs).  I
had 2.5 hours to eat lunch and relax before the others showed  up  at  2:30.
Meanwhile there was more thunder but no rain materialized.

Regrouping we all started up the usual  South  Brother  route  at  3:30  and
found a small but adequate spot above Lunch Rock for the four of us to  bivy
at 7:00, elev 5500 ft (1.5 miles, 2500 ft, 3:30 hrs  from  Lena  Forks).  We
did have to share it with a family of five  mountain  goats,  two  of  which
were adorable babies.

Day Total: 7.5 miles and 3800 ft

Sunday, July 15 - We started at 7:00, Eileen and  Lisa  for  South  Brother,
Jim and I for North. From our bivy we diverged from the South Brother  route
almost immediately heading right and up. The first problem  was  to  get  to
the SE spur at a point that could be descended on the other  side  into  the
eastern Great Basin. The guide gives no  clue  as  to  what  elevation  this
would be. All began well with a series of easy class 2-3 ramps  and  we  had
visions of making the summit early. Then it all fell  apart.  Following  the
line of least resistance we hit the SE  spur  at  about  6200  ft  but  were
dismayed to discover we could not descend the other side.  We  saw  we  were
too high and would have to be about 200 feet lower but getting there was  no
easy task. We ran into pinnacles, deep gullies  and  cliffs.  After  several
false leads with sketchy scrambling, Jim found a key ledge  that  led  to  a
lower 6000 ft notch at 9:20. There was a large cairn here so we  had  to  be
at the right place.

Looking into the Great Basin it looked easy once on the snow  but  again  it
didn\'t turn out that way. We did  descend  from  the  notch  with  no  great
difficulty, first on a heather rib then on the steep  snow  finger  next  to
it. We put on crampons for this  last  and  were  glad  we  had.  We  easily
crossed the upper Great Basin until past cliffs and could  climb  up  toward
the summit. The upper snow finger became increasingly steep. 20-30  degrees?
I don\'t think so. The finger ended in a gully where we came across a  frayed
sling. There were a few difficult moves to get to easier stuff  after  which
we scrambled to the ridge  above.  Somewhere  about  here  we  heard  shouts
coming from the South Brother. We assumed that was Eileen and  Lisa  but  by
now the originally forecast sunny day had deteriorated to fog and  mist  and
we could not see far. About this time we also heard the  unmistakable  sound
of a large avalanche somewhere below.

Now the question was which of the several pinnacles on  the  ridge  was  the
summit? I relied on Jim to figure that out. We scrambled to the right  along
the crest over huge blocks, in and out, up and down, quite  interesting  but
also slow going. Finally at the base of what Jim  chose  as  the  summit  we
could see no easy way up. It was definitely class 5 and all  we  had  was  a
rope, one prusik and one sling. Due to a miscommunication the  other  slings
were with Lisa and Eileen. How to get up this thing?  Well  fortunately  the
pinnacle was not that high and could be accessed from several sides. So  Jim
threw the rope over the top and we used the prusik as a belay. Jim  went  up
first and then me. We were ecstatic to find a register on top  which  proved
we were on the right pinnacle. It was an  old  Mountaineer  register  dating
back to 1974. Our only disappointment was we had no views and could not  see
to the South Brother. It was noon.

Thirty minutes later we were ready to leave. The mist had turned to  drizzle
and the rock was getting wet and slick. Using our  one  sling  we  rappelled
down the gully to the old frayed sling which we then used to  get  onto  the
snow. Fortunately it held. We downclimbed the snow  by  backing  down.  Near
the bottom of the steep part I tried facing out. A step broke out  and  down
I went. I was shocked that it took a good 50  feet  for  my  self-arrest  to
completely stop me. The snow was so soft that the pick just  sliced  through
very gradually slowing me down.  After  that  it  was  backing  down  again.
Passing under the cliffs we came across evidence of  the  avalanche  we  had
heard. It appeared that a massive snow block  perched  high  above  had  let
loose. The debris completely covered our up tracks. I  hate  to  think  what
would have happened had we been there at that time.

We were back to the SE spur notch at 2:30. We  did  one  more  short  rappel
using the rope around a tree at a  dicey  spot  then  it  was  careful  down
climbing. What would have been easy in dry conditions  took  extra  care  on
the wet slick rock. We reached our bivy at 3:40 where  everything  was  wet.
Eileen and Lisa were long gone as it  had  been  prearranged  that  I  would
drive Jim home. We packed quickly and left at 4:10. The rest of the  day  is
a blur of tired muscles and aching feet.  Lena Forks at 6:10, Lena  Lake  at
8:00 and the TH at 10:00. But hey, it did stop drizzling.

Day Total: 9.5 miles, 2400 ft and 15 hrs

Trip Total: 15.5 miles and 7500 ft in 2.5 days

Fay Pullen

