            'tr' => '
West Challenger (8000+ ft) -Mt Challenger Quad - July 21-28, 2012

Going into this trip I knew it was unlikely I would  get  all  three  of  my
main objectives - West Challenger, Crooked Thumb and  Phantom.  The  Pickets
have a way of humbling climbers and wrecking havoc with  agendas.  Yet  even
though things didn\'t exactly go as planned I count this trip as  one  of  my
best ever and a truly sublime alpine  experience  shared  with  two  special
friends. I couldn\'t have asked for better companions than Beth  and  Eileen.
And the fact that we three pulled  it  off  on  our  own  made  it  all  the
sweeter. I am still  digesting  the  experience,  much  of  which  was  very
personal and cannot adequately be expressed in words.  I will have to  limit
myself to a brief summary for the purposes of this TR.

Day 0 - We caught the 5:30 pm boat up Ross Lake to camp  at  Big  Beaver  in
the company of good friends - Jim, Derek, Steve,  Steve\'s  sister,  Deb  and
Janet.

Day 1 - Everyone else saw us off when they caught the  8:30  boat  to  climb
Desolation. Eileen, Beth and I spent the rest of the day  hiking  with  very
heavy packs 14 miles to Beaver Pass. This time I did not have the  advantage
of Tom to carry half my gear and I wasn\'t sure how I would do with all  that
weight. I did make it but it took its toll on various body parts.

Total: 14 miles, 2700 ft and 9:30 hrs

Day 2 - It began to rain during the night and continued into  late  morning.
We discussed options while lounging in our roomy 3-man  tent.  As  the  rain
began to let up we decided to go for it leaving at noon. I was  not  looking
forward to the steep brushy initial ascent to Eiley-Wiley ridge in the  wet.
Once we got going though it actually was not that bad  despite  not  picking
the best line up and running into a cliff band  (we  were  too  far  to  the
right). We were barely able to force a route through up a very  steep  slick
dirt gully. Once above that things improved as the ridge opened  up  and  we
followed the crest. We had a few  more  problems  in  route  finding  before
descending into the basin SE of Little Beaver Pk (6984)  where  we  found  a
nice tent site and water. It was still foggy but  had  stopped  raining.  We
went to bed not knowing what we would wake to in the morning.

Total: 2.5 miles, 3300 ft and 8 hrs

Day 3 - We awoke to glorious sunshine  and  a  full  view  of  the  Northern
Pickets. Unknowingly we had chosen a primo spot to camp. We dried out a  bit
in the sun before continuing on  our  way  at  9:30.  Again  we  had  a  few
problems route finding but nothing serious and worked our way, up and  down,
past both Eiley and Wiley Lakes to a lovely  campsite  on  a  heather  bench
just below Big Beaver Pk (7374) with a stunning view of Challenger at  3:00.
While I set up camp, Beth and Eileen rushed off to climb Challenger  (I  had
already climbed it). They reported  fresh  snow  on  top  that  caused  some
difficulties but working together sharing leads they summited at about  8:00
and returned at 10:15. Meanwhile I thoroughly enjoyed  a  restful  afternoon
in the sun in one of the most beautiful spots on earth.

Total: 3 miles, 2000 ft and 5:30 hrs (for me)

Day 4 - I naively thought we might still fit in my peaks  despite  our  lost
time. To this end Eileen and I started at 9:00 with bivy  gear  planning  to
climb West Challenger and have Beth meet us at  the  West  Challenger  notch
where we would then descend  to  the  basin  below  Crooked  Thumb.  But  we
totally underestimated West Challenger. Rated class 3 in  Beckey  I  thought
it would take only a couple of hours. It ended up taking over 8  hrs.  I  am
sure we did  not  always  go  the  best  way  but  we  did  follow  Beckey\'s
description which said to climb the W Ridge from  the  saddle  west  of  the
peak to a notch, rappel into the notch and cross a loose  knife  edged  rock
ridge to the main summit. We did all this but  I  still  shake  my  head  in
disbelief at what we encountered. First we ran into at  least  mid  class  5
very exposed climbing that put me at my limit. I do believe the  last  pitch
to above the notch was the hardest lead I have ever done.  Then  it  was  no
simple rappel to the notch but we had to go off to the side and  do  3  with
our 100 ft rope. That  put  us  about  100  feet  below  the  notch  in  the
cruddiest loosest scree  and  rock  gully  imaginable.  Eileen  and  I  took
different lines up this gully to avoid killing one other. She went up a  sub
gully on the far right which gave access to the summit block sooner. I  went
all the way to the knife edge at the gully  top  and  then  had  to  descend
slightly. I have never in my life seen such a feature  as  this  knife  edge
loose rock ridge. I marveled that it could  even  exist  without  completely
and instantly disintegrating. There  wasn\'t  a  solid  hold  anywhere.  Once
across the gully the last few hundred feet on the summit  block  were  quite
pleasant and true class 3. We reached  the  summit  at  6:00.  We  found  an
easier way down and were back to the West Challenger notch  where  Beth  was
patiently waiting for us. It was now obvious that neither Crooked Thumb  nor
Phantom were possible anymore.  I  was  totally  fried  and  had  passed  my
tolerance for loose rock. I felt the mountain gods  had  chewed  us  up  but
then spit us out in one piece. They might not be so kind again if we  pushed
for more. And so we retreated back to camp.

Total: 5 miles, 2600 ft and 11 hrs

Day 5 - The trip now morphed into  one  with  three  friends  enjoying  each
other\'s company while sharing the surreal beauty of the  Pickets.  We  slept
in, moved leisurely and took 3 days to go out. That was a refreshing  change
of pace from the usual climbing schedule of cramming as much into a  day  as
possible. It was also much easier on this aging body. I should  do  it  more
often. This day we returned to the same camp as Day 3 but first  climbed  to
the top of Little Beaver Pk.

Total: 3 miles, 1100 ft and 5:30 hrs.

Day 6 - We found a much better route off the  ridge  than  our  way  up  and
although it was quite steep forest there were no cliffs. We camped  at  Luna
with plenty of time to wash up in a real creek.

Total: 6.5 miles, 600 ft, 7:30 hrs

Day 7 - We were picked up by the boat at 3:30 and hiked the  mile  trail  up
to the car. And so ended our wonderful adventure. No I  didn\'t  get  all  my
peaks but that seems insignificant in comparison to what I did get. And  now
I have an excuse to return to what has become my favorite place on earth.

Total: 11 miles, 600 ft and 6:30 hrs

Grand Total: 45 miles  and  13,000  ft  in  7  days                      Fay
Pullen









