The Ptarmigan Traverse - August 4-11, 2012

I had done segments by coming in and out from both the north (Cascade  Pass)
and south (Downey Creek) several times to do various  peaks  but  had  never
done the entire Ptarmigan Traverse. I  was  missing  the  section  from  the
South Cascade Glacier to  the  Dome  Glacier.  So  when  Jim  organized  the
"classic" one way traverse I was keen to sign on. Since I had  already  done
most of the main peaks along the way I could  concentrate  on  the  traverse
itself, which is challenging and scenic enough in its own right. But  I  did
hope to add a few new peaks, most notably both Spire Point and  Gunsight.  I
did manage to get up the former (just barely)  but,  alas,  not  the  later.
However, I still consider the trip a great success and fantastic  experience
enhanced by the company of good friends.  Others  along  were  Jim,  Eileen,
Mike T, Steve  and  Deb  (she  did  a  great  job  with  her  first  glacier
experience), Kevin K and George. Peaks climbed (by me) along the way were:

Arts Knoll (7200+ ft - P280) - Cascade Pass Quad

Peak 7004 (P484) - Cascade Pass Quad

LeConte Mtn (7762 ft - P842) - Cascade Pass Quad

Lizard Mtn (7400+ ft - P440) - Dome Pk Quad

Spire Point (8264 ft - P784) - Dome Pk Quad

Day 0: August 4 - We spent a full half day doing the  car  shuttle.  It  was
lengthened by over two hours because  the  Suiattle  River  Road  was  still
closed between mile 2 and 8 and we had to take the annoying detour over  Rat
Trap Pass. We left 2 cars at the current road end at mile 12 and car  camped
at Mineral Cr Campground on the Cascade  River  Road  planning  to  leave  2
other cars at Cascade Pass the next day.

Day 1: August 5 - We started from the Cascade Pass  TH  at  7:30  on  a  hot
sunny day. I was very annoyed with myself when I discovered  30  minutes  up
the trail I had left my maps in the car and had to go back  for  them.  That
put me behind the group but I caught up  to  everyone  at  Mix-up  Arm.  The
Cache Glacier was easy travel and the moat at Cache Col no real problem.  We
pulled into still frozen Kool-Aid Lake at 2:40 to set  up  camp.  While  the
others "hurried" off to climb Hurry-Up Pk, Steve, Deb and I  lounged  around
camp and washed up in the icy lake. Two other parties showed up late in  the
day, but we never saw them again after the next day.

Total: 6.5 miles, 3200 ft and 6:30 hrs.

Day 2: August 6 - This day took us over the notorious (for  me)  Red  Ledge.
It was completely melted out and other than a steep snow approach  no  great
problem but I was still happy that I would not be  returning  this  way  and
hoped never again to have to cross it  in  my  lifetime.   At  Arts  Rib  we
dropped packs to scamper up the enjoyable heather ridge of Arts Knoll  where
we had an impressive view of both Hurry-Up and the north face of Spider  (RT
from pack drop: 800 ft, 1:20 hrs).

We continued on to the Middle  Cascade  Glacier  and  the  Spider-Formidable
Col, dropping down the other side to a lovely camp at  beautiful  Yang  Yang
Lakes. We arrived just in time to wash up before the sun left the valley.

Total: 6 miles, 2450 ft and 9 hrs.

Day 3: August 7 - I really wanted to climb LeConte Mtn as I  had  missed  it
on my previous trips. No one else seemed  interested  but,  Jim,  bless  his
heart, didn\'t want me to solo it, so agreed to accompany me. We  left  about
an hour earlier than the rest of the crew. Somehow we got  separated  (don\'t
ask) and we each gained the ridge by different routes  while  still  tucking
in Pk 7004 on the way to join up again at the base of  LeConte.  We  dropped
packs to scurry up the  peak.  After  some  steep  snow  we  gained  the  SE
shoulder and were confronted by a little more than we bargained for  with  a
steep exposed class 4 summit ridge.  It  looked  very  intimidating  but  we
managed to tease out a  scramble  route  without  using  the  rope.  It  was
actually a very enjoyable climb. I left a register (RT from our  pack  drop:
900 ft and 2 hrs).

While Jim hurried to catch up to everyone else (who had passed us),  I  hung
back with Mike who independently also climbed Pk 7004 and  was  waiting  for
me. We travelled together to The LeConte-Sentinel  Saddle  where  we  caught
the others just as they were leaving for Old Guard.  I  continued  on  above
the South Cascade Glacier to add Lizard Mtn (easy scramble, 450 ft and  1:15
hrs from pack drop) before again meeting everyone at Lizard  Pass.  We  then
dropped down steep snow and scree to camp at White Rock Lakes.

Total: 7 miles, 4600 ft and 12:50 hrs

Day 4: August 8 - It was quite windy all night and we awoke to  rolling  fog
which soon cleared. From the look of  all  the  rock  windbreaks  previously
built around campsites I would guess wind is common at this lake. We  picked
up a good trail out of the lake to traverse  toward  the  Dana  Glacier  but
soon lost it in talus. At the edge of the snow we took a  break  where  some
excitement  ensued  when  Eileen\'s  pack  rolled  down  a  waterfall  gully.
Disaster was averted when the pack was quickly retrieved  but  much  of  the
contents were soaked, though nothing critical (like the sleeping bag).

While the group took time to dry out the pack, Mike and I took off to  climb
Spire Point. We headed uphill toward Spire Col and dropped packs on  a  rock
rib at about 6900 ft. We reached the base of the rock at 8000  ft  at  2:45.
Somehow we completely missed the class 4 route and were led  astray  by  the
Beckey Route description (2nd Edition) which calls it the NE route and  says
to make a LONG rightward traverse on a wide ledge to a  trough  on  the  far
right. This we did. Mike made the first lead and immediately thought it  too
hard for class 4. But he found a rap station and brought me up. I  continued
the lead and passed a piton. This lured us on thinking we were on route  but
the climbing became harder and harder. I was stumped as to where to  go  and
soon at my limit. I  was  10  feet  above  my  last  pro  on  holdless  slab
literally hanging on my fingernails and wanting to retreat but  not  knowing
how to do that. This dilemma was solved by  me  suddenly  peeling  off.  The
next thing I knew I was hanging upside  down  20  feet  lower  spread-eagled
backward on the slab with the rope wrapped  tight  around  my  legs  and  me
unable to move. I think I scared the  bejeebers  out  of  Mike.  Fortunately
Mike gave me a good belay, my pro (a stopper) held and the  slab  was  clean
so I had minimal damage and was still functional. Somehow I managed  to  get
upright and extricate myself from the situation but that was it.  We  called
it quits and I was resigned to failing mere feet from the  summit.  We  were
on some route but certainly not the class 4 one and not  one  either  of  us
was capable of climbing.

While retreating along the ledge back to the  snow,  on  a  slightly  higher
line, I happened to glance up and there it was, the obvious class  4  route.
It was a very SHORT distance along the ledge and in the middle of  the  east
face and not to the NE as described. We just  didn\'t  look  for  it  in  the
right place. We scrambled up to the summit in  15  minutes.  We  did  rappel
down though. Our entire misadventure had taken  several  hours  longer  than
necessary and nearly cost me grave injury.  Interestingly when I got home  I
read the 3rd Edition of Beckey where he renamed the  route  the  East  Face.
Others must have complained about the description and confusion.

Moving fast once back on the snow, we made it to the Dana-Dome Col  and  our
intended campsite just  15  minutes  after  the  others  had  returned  from
climbing Dome Pk. Deb and Steve had been there all  afternoon  and  had  the
foresight to collect water for  all  of  us  which  was  sorely  needed  and
greatly appreciated.

Total: 5 miles, 3750 ft and 10:20 hrs

Day 5: August 9 - Gunsight was out. No one had the desire or energy at  this
point. So while Jim and Eileen took  off  for  some  quality  time  together
exploring around Dome Peak, the rest of us lounged around  camp  warming  up
in the sun after a cold night on snow. I examined more  closely  the  damage
done by my fall and was happy to discover it  no  worse  than  a  bad  thigh
bruise and stiff leg. Once again I was lucky. The mountain  gods  sure  seem
to be looking out for  me.  We  left  camp  around  noon.  I  took  my  time
travelling the familiar terrain (my fourth time) to Itswoot  Ridge  and  Cub
Lake. We had thought to camp at the lake but it  was  still  snowed  in  and
unappealing so we decided to continue on and found a very pleasant  spot  in
cushy meadow just before the trail drops to Bachelor Creek.

Total: 4 miles, 950 ft and 6 hrs.

Day 6: August 10 - Again familiar territory,  down  the  brush  of  Bachelor
Creek to Downey Creek and out to the Suiattle River Rd. Although I must  say
both trails are better than I remember. Usage has improved Bachelor  Cr  and
Downey Creek has had a lot of work done on it. However, both my feet and  my
bruised leg were hurting by the end. We camped that night along the road.

Total: 11 miles, 400 ft and 8:40 hrs.

Day 7, August 11  -  All  that  remained  was  the  9  mile  road  trip  and
retrieving the cars at Cascade Pass but that took most of the day.

Trip Total: 39.5 miles and 15,350 ft in 6 days

Fay Pullen







