            'tr' => '
The Painted Traverse - August 17-19, 2012

Portal Peak (6999 ft - P479), Purple Pk (6910 ft - P370), Skullcap Pk  (6603
ft - P203), Black Mtn (7262 ft - P902), Magenta Mtn (6735  ft  -  P455)  and
Red (Painted) Mtn (6975 ft - P935) - Glacier Pk West and Sloan Pk Quads

The Painted Traverse is not a true traverse in the strictest  sense  of  the
word but really a loop as it starts and ends at the same TH.  This  made  it
ideal for me alone as no car shuttle was needed. I have long had  this  trip
on my agenda and in fact almost joined Matt B and Eric J on  their  trip  in
2010. But since they had planned to do  it  in  2  days,  I  declined.  They
actually ended up taking longer than they expected but I knew I  would  need
and want 3 full days. I found this trip to give a lot of bang for the  buck.
It makes a wonderful 3 day trip with much variety, great  scenery  and  some
routefinding challenges along the way. I love the colorful names  of  the  6
peaks I climbed along the way (there could be 7 if you include White  but  I
had climbed that on a previous trip).   I  found  registers  on  Portal  and
Skullcap and added mine to the other 4 peaks where I found none.

Day 1: Saturday, August 18 -  I  arrived  at  the  North  Fork  Sauk  TH  to
overflowing parking. Cars and horse trailers filled every  available  space.
This is why I don\'t like to go out on weekends but I was  forced  into  this
time frame by various commitments. I finally found a spot to  park  off  the
road under a tree at the far end of  the  campground.  From  the  number  of
vehicles I expected plenty of company but most of the activity  was  due  to
the Backcountry Horsemen working on the first 2 miles of  trail.  Once  past
this point the number of people and horses thinned considerable.

I took my time hiking the first 5  miles  of  gentle  trail,  which  was  in
excellent condition, to Mackinaw Shelter.  Once past here the  trail  tilted
up to gain 3000 ft to the junction with the PCT just before White Pass.  The
muggy heat was oppressive  and  the  biting  flies  very  annoying  in  this
section. Part way up two young fellows passed me and asked  if  I  knew  how
much farther it was to the top. I assumed they meant White Pass and  had  to
break it to them that they still had almost 2000 ft  to  go.  They  did  not
look happy but continued past me. Later I caught  up  to  them  again.  They
were waiting for the rest of their party. I cautioned  they  would  be  hard
pressed to get to White Pass before dark as it was now 6:30, they still  had
1000 ft to go and their party was nowhere in sight. I really felt sorry  for
them but there was nothing I could do to help and I was running out of  time
myself.  I reached the PCT junction at 7:30 and continued  on  to  Red  Pass
arriving at 8:00. I found a nice campsite with  running  water  and  even  a
small melt pool to wash in just below the  pass.  All  during  this  time  I
heard yelling back and forth below me that  added  a  bit  of  drama  to  my
evening. I figured it was the two fellows still trying to connect  with  the
rest of their party. I have no idea what eventually transpired but  I  doubt
it was anything good as it  was getting dark fast and where they were  there
was no water and no place to camp.

Day Total: 10.5 miles, 4500 ft and 7:30 hrs

Day 2: Sunday, August 19 - Since I had already done  White  Mtn,  for  me  I
consider the true start of the Painted Traverse to  be  Red  Pass.  That  is
where I left the PCT to start a delightful ridge ramble. I felt like  I  was
in heaven. The meadows were alive with flowers of every color and the  views
were to die for  in  every  direction  but  always  dominated  by  beautiful
Glacier Pk on my right. First up was Portal Pk followed by Purple  Pk,  both
easy strolls. The descent off  Purple  offered  a  little  more  excitement.
Beckey suggests  "dropping  into  Red  Creek  to  avoid  W-side  cliffs  and
traversing to regain the ridge". I decided to  try  staying  on  the  ridge.
That went well until I came to a cliffy spot I didn\'t want  to  try  with  a
full pack. That forced me off the ridge to the left on steep vegetation  but
I found a way down by hanging onto scrubby  trees.   It  was  then  a  short
climb back to the ridge and easy terrain again to Skullcap Pk where I  spent
a glorious hour for lunch.

Now came the hard part - getting from Skullcap  to  Black.  Beckey  says  to
follow the ridge N over a 6360 ft saddle and descend to the basin on  the  S
side of Black at about 5750 ft. Exactly how to do  this  is  very  vague.  I
began by descending from the 6360 saddle but soon found myself  forced  down
to 5400 ft by cliffs and terrain before I could start traversing and when  I
did I ran into horrible brush. Maybe I  should  have  stayed  on  the  ridge
longer before starting the traverse or even gone over Pt 6844.  All  I  know
is the way I went was awful and not to be recommended. It took me  3.5  hrs
to force a way from Skullcap. Where I ended up was in a basin  at  6000  ft,
considerably above where Beckey says to be. But the good thing was  I  found
a dramatic place to camp right above a waterfall that put me in a good  spot
to climb Black via an easy gully. I took off at 5:00 and was on  the  summit
at 6:25. The last bit was an airy traverse along the rocky NW ridge.  I  was
back to my tent by 7:30 with more  daylight  for  dinner  than  my  previous
camp.

To Camp: 3.5 miles, 2200 ft and 8:30 hrs

RT to Black from camp: 1 mile, 1250 ft and 2:30 hrs

Day 3: Monday, August 20 - Next up was Magenta. From various viewpoints  the
previous day I had chosen a line that climbed onto the shoulder of  Pt  6824
at 6300 ft then traversed between 6000 and 6200 ft to get past Pt  6716.  It
was all very steep sidehill of heather and vegetation that was  so  slick  I
kept slipping. After about  a  half  dozen  slips  I  gave  up  and  put  on
crampons. That decreased the slip factor but increased the trip factor.  But
at least I had positive footholds. I just had to  proceed  very  slowly  and
carefully. I also kept running into hidden gullies. Just when I  thought  it
was all smooth hillside ahead I would run into another nasty gully.  Finally
I passed the last one and entered the gentle basin just  south  of  Magenta.
From there I climbed onto a rocky S rib to gain the easy  summit  slopes  of
Magenta which I summited at 1:00 (2  miles,  1300  ft,  4:20  hrs).  Magenta
isn\'t a particularly impressive looking peak but  is  a  splendid  viewpoint
and I spent a very enjoyable hour on top.

It was an easy descent to the Magenta-Red saddle and  more  easy  slopes  to
the top of Red Mtn though the last loose scree was a bit tedious. I  reached
that summit at 4:00 (3.5 miles, 2500 ft, 7:20 hr). I only stayed 20  minutes
as I was worried about the 5000 ft descent to the  North  Fork  SauK  TH.  I
knew there was a climbers trail branching off from the Lookout Trail  but  I
had never been up it and feared I would have trouble finding it on  the  way
down. I knew I HAD to find it or I would be in big trouble. The terrain  was
very steep and cliffy. I had no trouble on the first 1000 feet to  the  flat
above Ruby Lake as the terrain was open and all I had to do was stay on  the
obvious ridge. I picked up the trail here then lost it in the brush. I  soon
found myself too far to the right above a horrible  cliffy  ravine.  I  cast
around heading left until I ran across it again. This put me on the  correct
ridge just skiers left of the horrible ravine. I lost the trail again in  an
area of recent blowdown lower but  found  it  at  the  critical  point  just
before reaching the Lookout Trail. Thus is a critical  spot  because  it  is
very steep and cliffy and the correct line must be located.

Once on the Lookout Trail I  breathed  a  sigh  of  relief  and  thought  my
troubles were over. I was tired, my feet were killing me from all the  steep
sidehill and downhill and I was expecting easy trail. But no.  I  discovered
the trail had not been logged out and had a dozen or so blowdowns,  some  so
big I could barely muscle my way over them. Why  hadn\'t  the  horsemen  done
their thing on this trail? Once  past  the  blowdowns,  I  limped  down  the
remainder of the trail to a TH almost deserted compared to what it had  been
on Saturday.

Day Total: 7 mile, 2500 ft and 11:45 hrs

Trip Total: 22 miles and 10,450 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen



