            'tr' => '
Skalabats Pk (6697 ft - P537 - Glacier Pk West Quad) - August 24-26, 2012

It has been said that if  you  leave  something  behind  anyplace  you  wish
subconsciously to return to that place. Well, I guess I wanted to return  to
Magenta Mtn because on the last day of  my  Painted  Traverse  of  the  week
before I left my map case on that summit. I realized it too late to go  back
for it. I thought I would just write it off. No  big  deal  really.  Then  I
looked longingly at Skalabats Pk as I was descending Red  Mtn.  It  appeared
so inviting - an interesting yet not very difficult peak that looked  as  if
it would be a lot of fun and there was a  nice  place  to  camp  in  meadows
below the Red Skalabats saddle. I had really wanted to include  it  as  part
of the traverse but ran out of time. So I ended up  with  three  reasons  to
return - to climb Skalabats, to retrieve my map case  and  to  just  revisit
and enjoy again a lovely area. But I would have to do it soon, if it was  to
be this year, before my map case deteriorated in  the  elements  and  before
the meager snow patches I had seen below the saddle  melted  out  completely
and there would be no water available for camping.

Friday, August 24 - I headed up the now familiar  Red  Mtn  Trail  from  the
North Fork Sauk TH at 1:00. I only needed to get to a camp  below  the  Red-
Skalabats Saddle so was in no hurry. I even did about 1  hr  of  trail  work
sawing the smaller annoying blowdown branches  on  the  first  part  of  the
maintained LO Trail. At the end of this trail I found a  much  better  route
past the rock cliff by following a class  2  ledge  rather  than  the  awful
steep dirt gully on the right that I had come  down  previously.  Once  past
this spot I picked up the climbers trail which is a lot easier to follow  on
the way up than on the way down. The day was sunny but with  a  cool  breeze
and no bugs so the ascent, though steep, was quite pleasant. The  fact  that
my pack was 5 pounds lighter than on the traverse  also  helped.  I  reached
the flat at 5900 ft above Ruby Lake where the  obvious  way  trail  ends  at
5:50. I had hoped to make a direct traverse from here to  the  Red-Skalabats
saddle, but could see no good  line  through  the  woods,  brush  and  steep
terrain. I had to make the traverse about 400 feet higher and then  drop  to
below the saddle where I found a nice site for my bivy tent  at  6:40,  elev
6100 ft. A small meltwater creek was nearby.

Total: 3.5 miles, 4200 ft and 5:40 hrs

Saturday, August 25 - I started for Skalabats at 8:30 waiting  for  the  sun
to warm my campsite after a windy and chilly  (in  comparison  to  what  has
been) night. I quickly reached the 6200 ft saddle and dropped  150  ft  down
the other side on very steep heather to  the  snow  basin  below  the  north
slope. I traversed snow and talus to a broad gully which I climbed to  below
cliffs where a wide ledge led left to  gentle  slopes.  I  gained  the  main
ridge 200 feet below the top  and  the  summit  at  10:15  where  I  left  a
register (900 ft, 1:45 hrs). The east side of this ridge is all heather  and
flowers.  A most enjoyable climb.

I now wanted to find a way to Magenta  without  climbing  over  Red  Mtn.  I
descended to the large snow basin  at  5700  ft,  then  climbed  400  ft  to
traverse at about 6100 ft on the east slope of Red Mtn  to  the  Red-Magenta
saddle. This went quite smoothly although there were  several  minor  hidden
gullies to cross. I crossed a  larger  ravine  low  where  it  also  was  no
problem. Nowhere was the heather  steep  enough  on  this  trip  to  require
crampons. I reached the saddle at 12:50 and Magenta  summit  at  1:50  (2100
ft, 5:20 hrs) and sure enough there was my map case. I had for some  strange
reason stuck it on a rock ledge above where I sat to have   lunch  which  is
why I hadn\'t noticed it when I left.

With my first two goals of the trip achieved  I  could  concentrate  on  the
last - just enjoying my gorgeous surroundings. I wandered back down  to  the
beautiful Red-Magenta saddle where I found a small pond to  soak  in.  There
are a multitude of splendid sites here and I almost wished I had  come  this
far to camp. To return to my camp I took a higher line (6300-6400 ft)  below
Red Mtn meandering through meadows and  rock  garden.  This  too  went  well
except I hit the large ravine at a cliffy spot and had to climb  up  to  get
past it. I then crossed the Red-Skalabats ridge at  a  higher  saddle  (6400
ft) which avoided the considerable drop to the snow basin.  I  reached  camp
at 5:00. I still had time to go out this  day  but  really  didn\'t  want  to
leave so spent the rest of the afternoon and evening  relaxing  and  soaking
up the scenery.

Total: 4 miles, 2900 ft and 8:30 hrs

Sunday, August 26 - Again I slept in and didn\'t leave until 8:50.  From  the
summit of Skalabats I had had a good view of a direct route to the trail  at
the 5900 ft flat that would seem to work. And so it did, saving  the  excess
climbing of my in route. With this now being my 3rd time on it  I  was  able
to stay on the trail with no problem all the  way  to  the  LO  Trail.  Just
below the cliff, on the maintained trail, I ran into a  lone  hiker  with  a
heavy pack. He obviously was out for a few days. I thought  perhaps  he  was
doing the Painted Traverse from this direction but on  talking  with  him  I
discovered his goal was Ruby  Lake.  He  was  pleased  when  I  told  him  a
reasonable trail went all the  way.  He  had  never  been  there  before.  I
reached the car just before noon to  end  another  wonderful  trip.  And  to
think I probably wouldn\'t have done it had I  not  forgotten  my  map  case.
Things frequently work out for the best even they originally seem not to.

Day Total: 3.5 miles, 200 ft and 3 hrs

Trip Total: 11 miles and 7300 ft in 3 easy days

Fay Pullen

BTW Skalabats is a shortening  of  an  Indian  name  (Skahala-bats)  meaning
"Painted Mountain" that was originally applied to Red Mtn.

