            'tr' => '
Mad Eagle Pk (8111 ft - P391), Goliah Pk (7742 ft  -  P542)  and  Canuck  Pk
(7365 ft - P405) - Mt Redoubt Quad - September 7-9, 2012

My main goal for this trip was the Top200 peak Mad Eagle.  Beckey  calls  it
class 3 but a photo I had seen taken from the  SW  by  John  Roper  under  a
beautiful early season coat of snow gave  me  some  trepidation.  From  this
aspect it looked quite difficult but also clearly showed how  the  peak  got
its name. Fortunately I would be climbing it from the opposite NE side.

Friday, September 7 - I drove into Canada and  along  the  Chilliwack  River
Road to the end of pavement at Chilliwack Lake Provincial  Park.  Past  here
the road  becomes  the  Gold  Standard  for  truly  awful  potholes.  It  is
impossible to drive the 5.6 miles to the Depot Creek turnoff with any  speed
at all and is even worse than I remember from my two previous trips  up  it.
In fact the beginning of the Depot Creek Road itself to  the  first  parking
area at .9 miles is almost an improvement. However, past that  point  it  is
strictly 4X4 territory. I managed to get to the end of  "drivable"  road  at
2.1 miles (elev 2500 ft) but even my Grand Cherokee had a hard time  of  it.
I began hiking from this point.  It  did  look  as  though  quads  had  been
farther on the old road almost to the US border.

This, of course, is the usual access route to  the  Chilliwack\'s  and  peaks
such as Custer, Rahm, Redoubt and Spickard. But  for  these  peaks  climbers
continue up the trail past the spectacular waterfall. I, on the other  hand,
left the trail before the falls, at about  3200  ft,  to  head  up  what  is
referred to as the Lake Fork. This was probably the most difficult  part  of
the trip as I was uncertain exactly where to go. In general  I  stayed  well
right of the actual Lake Fork Creek. I crossed Depot Cr easily on a log  and
immediately was immersed in awful brush, most of  which  was  devil\'s  club.
Fortunately the worst only lasted a  hundred  feet  or  so.  Beyond  that  I
worked my way up very steep hillside and  mossy  talus,  trending  right  to
avoid cliffs. I came out onto more gentle terrain at a broad saddle at  4500
ft where I dropped slightly into the Lake  Fork  Creek  to  follow  it  over
talus to a tiny muddy pond at 4800 ft. I had hoped to get to an  upper  lake
(which I call Goliah Lake) shown on the map but  with  the  long  drive  and
more difficult travel than expected I was running out of daylight. The  tiny
pond was not that appealing as the shores were very muddy but I did  find  a
useable grassy island just big enough (probably 5X10 ft) to set up  a  camp.
And the nearby inlet creek supplied a clean source of water.

Total: 5 miles, 2400 ft and 6:20 hrs

Saturday, September 8 - From my camp I headed for Goliah Lake  wandering  up
talus and around huge boulders. Travel here would be much better  with  snow
cover. I reached snow just below the lake in 40 minutes and stopped  to  put
on crampons. I now had to get through a cliff band circling the lake. I  saw
several possibilities and chose a middle snow gully as it seemed  the  least
scary. It did have a break at a small waterfall but luckily I  was  able  to
bypass it on rock to the right and regain the snow above. Easy snow  led  to
an upper small glacier between Mad Eagle and Goliah. Once on the  glacier  I
turned left to follow a steepening arm toward Mad Eagle. The upper part  had
a very steep wall so I worked my way even farther left onto slabs and  scree
until above the wall. I left ice axe  and  crampons  and  gained  the  loose
north ridge of Mad Eagle. I had to climb to the right of  a  small  pinnacle
before the summit rock came into view. My first view was not encouraging.  A
direct assault looked difficult but knowing it was supposed to be class 3  I
looked closer and saw a possible route to the right. I dropped  slightly  to
a narrow notch where a wide ledge led around the corner to  an  easy  gully.
The final summit rocks steepened again but by once  again  going  right  and
spiraling around it really was class 3 all the way  to  the  top  (3300  ft,
5:30 hrs).

Mad Eagle lives in the shadow of much higher Redoubt. In fact  it  is  often
difficult to pick it out from a distance. Still, it is a rewarding climb  in
its own right and views from the top are spectacular. It  shows  a  side  of
Redoubt seldom seen. The day was warm and sunny and I felt  no  great  hurry
at that time (1:30) so I found a  comfortable  spot  to  hang  out  for  the
better part of an hour. I even took off my boots. Perhaps I  shouldn\'t  have
stayed so long as I still had two peaks to climb and the  days  are  getting
noticeably shorter but I just couldn\'t resist.

I descended my up route to the small glacier then climbed  to  the  7120  ft
col SE of Goliah. A direct ascent  from  here  did  not  look  pleasant  but
Beckey said the W ridge was no problem so I headed for that. I  crossed  the
col to the SW slope and traversed what seemed endless talus and scree  until
I could gain the W ridge well past cliffs. The ridge itself was  a  pleasant
enjoyable scramble (4200 ft, 8:50 hrs).

It was now 5:00 and I could see I would be hard pressed get  up  Canuck  and
still make it to camp before dark. Wherever did the  time  go?  I  descended
the W ridge and then continued traversing toward Canuck, first past Pt  7487
then on to the 6920 col, again on endless talus. Once  to  the  col  it  was
quick to the summit of Canuck (4600 ft, 10:25 hrs). I left a register  here,
as I also had on Goliah and Mad Eagle.

From the 6920 ft col I descended a short awful loose dirt slope  to  a  nice
snow slope (but I still needed crampons) toward Goliah Lake some  1600  feet
below. When the snow ran out I encountered more talus and boulders,  then  a
snow band around the lake shore that was undercut  and  had  deep  unnerving
cracks that appeared as if they could calve off into the deep  lake  at  any
moment. And yet that seemed the lesser of two evils compared  to  the  steep
unstable talus above the snow. Darkness caught me at  the  far  end  of  the
lake and my pace slowed to a crawl as I picked  my  way  down  more  tedious
talus by headlamp. I was really getting tired of all this  talus.  I  pulled
into camp at 9:00.

Total: 5 miles, 4600 ft and 13 hrs.

Sunday, September 9 - I awoke to thick fog that kept me in  my  tent  longer
than I would have liked. It showed no signs of getting better  so  I  packed
up and left at 9:00. It carried just  enough  moisture  to  make  the  mossy
talus a bit slippery so I had to be extra careful.  I  was  so  thankful  my
summit day had been sunny. I hoped I might  find  a  better  way  down  that
avoided the devil\'s club. However, nearing Depot  Creek  I  again  ran  into
brush, though not quite as bad as the way up. I found a  lovely  spot  along
the creek to stop for lunch and to soak feet very sore from all that  talus.
I reached the car at 2:15 (5:15 hrs) where I had driving those  awful  roads
to look forward to.

Trip Total: 15 miles and 7000 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen



