',
            'tr' => '
Pasayten Pk (7850 ft - P1050), Buckskin Ridge (7815 ft  -  P1295),  Pk  7606
(P446), & Gold Ridge (7605 ft - P245) -  Pasayten  Pk  Quad;  and  Slate  Pk
(7440 ft - P440) & Haystack  Mtn  (7303  ft  -  P223)  -  Slate  Pk  Quad  -
September 28-30, 2012

Friday, September 28 - I began this day by walking up the gated road to  the
top of Slate Pk (.5 miles, 300 ft, :20 hrs RT). Views  would  ordinarily  be
great from the top but skies  hazy  from  forest  fires  detracted.  I  did,
however, get a good look at Haystack Mtn and Gold  Ridge.  After  this  side
trip and the long drive, I didn\'t get started on the  Buckskin  Ridge  Trail
until 1:00. I followed the trail up and over  Slate  Pass  leaving  it  just
before the junction with the Middle Fork Trail to climb  Haystack  Mtn  (900
ft, 1:20 hrs). My intent was then to drop back down to the  trail  and  hike
to Silver Lake to camp for the night. But once on Haystack the ridge  looked
so inviting with such pleasant travel that I was suckered  into  staying  on
it. Anyone who knows me  knows  I  love  ridges.  I  thought  I  might  even
possibly be able to follow it all the way to Pasayten Pk. And so I did.  The
first part was a delightful ramble with  views  in  every  direction.  There
were many ups and downs, over Pts 7121, 7456 and 7393. Much of the  way  had
a path. Then past Pt 7493 the  ridge  got  narrower,  more  rocky  and  more
convoluted. Nothing was difficult but it took time and  Pasayten  Pk  didn\'t
seem to be getting closer very fast. Just when I  thought  I  was  over  the
last bump, another hidden one would appear.  I was able  to  contour  around
one bump to below Pt 7588 but I had to climb over the later and drop to  the
saddle south of Pasayten. The final climb  to  the  summit  was  over  large
talus blocks,  not  difficult  and  actually  rather  fun,  but  again  time
consuming.

I reached the summit of Pasayten Pk at 7:00 and took a few precious  minutes
to place a register. The light was fading fast. I had come across  no  water
the entire day and was completely out. At this point I could no  longer  get
off the ridge to Silver Lake. My best bet was to descend the NW ridge  to  a
small lake (and sure water) I could see in the basin below  Gold  Ridge  (Pt
7605). I just hoped I could get down it as it looked quite  steep  in  spots
on the map. Sure enough, after about 400 feet I came to  a  rocky  step  and
had to drop to the left off the ridge down a class 3-4 gully. By now it  was
dark (the full moon was masked by clouds)  and  I  was  finding  my  way  by
headlamp down tricky terrain while carrying a full pack. I was not happy.  I
was forced down way below the ridge line and then had to climb  back  up  to
regain it. Then once on the ridge there was another small rocky  section  to
work down on the other side before  hitting  easy  meadows  leading  to  the
lake. The good news was there was a marvelous campsite there. The  bad  news
was it was 10:00 and I was beat. And it began to rain lightly  for  a  brief
period but by then I had my tent up.

 Total: 6 miles, 3000 ft and 9 hrs

Saturday, September 29 - What with my adventure the night before I slept  in
and didn\'t get going until after 9:00. My goal for the  day  was  to  ramble
Buckskin Ridge as far as possible. A short distance below camp,  by  another
smaller lake, I came across two people with 5 pack goats  getting  ready  to
leave. They were as shocked to see me as I was to see them. I  had  seen  no
one since leaving the TH and they were puzzled where I had come  from  until
I explained that I had descended from Pasayten  Pk.  They  were  a  charming
couple (Sharon and Perry)  that,  despite  not  being  climbers,  I  had  an
immediate rapport with. They were of my  generation,  had  been  hiking  and
backpacking since their youth and obviously  loved  what  they  were  doing.
They had taken to using pack goats as various body parts began  giving  them
trouble. We chatted for well over half an  hour.  They  were  headed  toward
Buckskin Lake. As I would be returning via that  trail  it  was  possible  I
would see them again. I was very impressed by the goats. They  seemed  quite
friendly and well behaved and could carry a fairly heavy pack.  I  may  have
to look into this option for the future. Goats seem so much simpler to  deal
with than horses.

I found a path leading to Silver Pass. From there  I  just  headed  up  semi
open slopes to Pt 7632 and then went along the easy ridge to  Pk  7815,  the
hi pt of Buckskin Ridge. The day was partly cloudy with  an  incessant  wind
that kept things quite cool. Views were a bit clearer than the  day  before.
From 7815 I continued easily  along  the  ridge,  again  enjoying  my  lofty
vantage point, until I came to Pt 7580. Here I ran into a  cliff.  The  only
way down was a nasty loose gully. It was unpleasant but it did  go.  Shortly
past that I came across the main trail which I  followed  until  it  dropped
off the saddle toward Buckskin Lake. I continued along the ridge,  bypassing
Pt 7521, to Pk 7606 (2600 ft. 6:40 hrs). I had hoped to get to  nominal  end
of the ridge at Buckskin Point but ran into impassible cliffs  so  ended  my
ramble here. It was now 4:30.

I returned to the trail at the saddle and followed it  down.  About  5:30  I
ran across Sharon and Perry camped in a flat basin  below  the  trail.  They
seemed genuinely happy to see me again as did the goats  but  I  could  only
chat about 15 minutes. I really thought I could still make it back  to  camp
before dark though I knew it would be close. Of course I  didn\'t.  I  hadn\'t
counted  on  the  frustrating  trail  which  proceeded  to  drop  more  than
necessary below Silver Pass and then climb steeply back up so  it  was  8:20
before I got to my tent. But hey, that was an  improvement  over  the  night
before. And this night was clear so I had the magic  of  the  full  moon  to
inspire me.

Total: 9 miles, 4400 ft and 11 hrs

Sunday, September 30 - Before breaking camp I zipped up Gold Ridge  Pk  7605
(1 mile,700 ft, 1:30 hr RT) then left at 11:00 picking  up  the  main  trail
below Silver Pass. Again this trail is very frustrating with  many  ups  and
downs. I did take the side trip to Silver Lake where I ran  into  the  first
people I had seen besides Sharon and Perry. I met two more people going  out
with day packs but that was it.

Total: 7.5 miles, 2000 ft and 5:20 hrs

Trip Total: 24 miles and 10,400 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen





