            'tr' => '
Mt Winthrop (7850 ft - P1690), Mt Winthrop N Pk(7604 ft - P444)  &  Blizzard
Pk (7622 ft - P1142) - Castle Pk Quad; and  "High  Parks  Pk"   (6632  ft  -
P752) & Monument 83 Pk (6520+ ft - P620) - Frosty Cr  Quad  -  October  4-8,
2012

This was to be Jim\'s annual Golden Larch Trip. It didn\'t quite  live  up  to
that name as we saw few if any Golden Larches,  why  I  am  not  sure.  They
seemed to stop growing just south of where we were. But  the  good  weather,
lovely meadows, many little adventures and good company more  than  made  up
for this. There were nine total in  the  party:  Jim,  Eileen,  Steve,  Deb,
Kevin K, Maria, George, Karen and of course me.

Day 1: Thursday, October 4 - We drove in two cars to the Monument  78/83  TH
in Manning Park in Canada and started  on  the  trail  at  12:40  travelling
counterclockwise. We were greeted with the first obstacle of the  trip  with
a sign saying the Monument 78 trail was closed due  to  washouts.  Undaunted
we continued on. How bad could it be? Not that bad really. About a mile  was
washed out and hard to follow but most of the way was just an overgrown  and
neglected road. At a little over 7 miles  we  joined  the  PCT  and  shortly
beyond that came to Monument 78 and entered the US.  This  is  the  northern
terminus of the PCT and while there we encountered 3 through hikers  at  the
end of their long trek. It was fun to hear their stories.  We  continued  on
another 4 miles to camp at Castle Pass. There was  no  water  here  but  the
guys packed water from a creek (campsite here also) Â½ mile below  the  pass.
The temperature dipped to 22 degrees during the night.

Total: 11.5 miles, 2100 ft and 5:40 hrs

Day 2: Friday, October 5 - I started out about a  half  hour  ahead  of  the
group as I had hopes of climbing 3 peaks and knew I would  be  hard  pressed
for time. It was also much too cold to hang around waiting. In 1 hour I  was
at Frosty Pass (1.75 miles, 1100 ft). I left my big pack here, continuing  on
with a small day pack, following open meadows and easy ridge to  the  summit
of Mt Winthrop (2600 ft, 2:50). By the time I took 30  minutes  to  place  a
register and eat lunch the rest of the  group  had  joined  me.  They  would
relax for a while then return to  Frosty  Pass  and  climb  Blizzard  Pk.  I
continued on to the North Peak of Winthrop solo. I descended to  the  saddle
north and traversed around Pt 7496. I tried to follow the  ridge  past  that
but it was too rocky and had to  traverse  below  on  the  left.  The  final
summit block was a fun class 3 scramble to the top (3300 ft, 4:50 hrs).

For the return I really didn\'t want to climb back over Winthrop  so  took  a
traverse from slightly below the saddle. This  went  well  to  start  across
easy talus and meadow until I came to an extensive cliffy slab area. It  was
very interesting but I was forced to descend 400 feet on unpleasant  terrain
to get past it. I lost time here and didn\'t get back to  Frosty  Pass  until
4:30, much later than desired. I only took time to replenish water  from  my
pack before heading out again for Blizzard Pk.  Shortly  above  the  pass  I
passed the rest of the party coming down. They reported it an easy  scramble
with no problems. Easy it was but it also seemed long as by this time I  was
running out of steam. I reached the summit at 5:50. I stayed  no  more  than
10 minutes. The others had already placed one of my registers  so  I  didn\'t
have to take the time to build a cairn. I made it back to Frosty  Pass  just
as it got dark at 7:00. I took a few minutes to rearrange my big  pack  then
took off down the trail to find where the others had camped.  Originally  we
had thought to camp at Frosty Lake some 3.5 miles away. I was so happy  when
I ran into them a scant mile on. They had stopped at the first  water.  This
night was much warmer than the previous one.

Total: 10.5 miles, 5800 ft and 9:30 hrs

Day 3: Saturday, October 6 - The sun hit our camp early  and  warmed  things
for a very pleasant leisurely breakfast.   This  led  to  a  late  start  at
10:00, which suited me fine as I was tired. It was a good  thing  we  didn\'t
try to camp at Frosty Lake as we found no suitable spots  there  or  even  a
way trail to it. We also had  some  confusion  finding   the  trail  to  The
Parks. The junction is obscure and the trail  unmaintained.   Once  located,
though, it was easily followed and we reached the Parks in  time  for  lunch
(4.5 miles, 1600 ft, 3:45 hrs). The Parks is  a  high  meadow  plateau  that
reminds me of Grand Park in Mt Rainier. Jim, Kevin, Steve and I strolled  up
easy High Parks Pk at the far end of the Parks while everyone  else  enjoyed
the meadows. We then took the ridge SE to Pt 6525 before  plunging  straight
down  to  Frosty  Cr.  Travel  was  surprisingly  good.  The  only  slightly
difficult part was crossing Frosty Cr in  downed  trees  and  brush  to  the
trail on the other side. From there it was a short distance to a  nice  camp
near the trail junctions on Chuchuwanteen Cr.

Total: 9.5 miles, 2400 ft and 8 hrs

Day 4: Sunday, October 7 - Before  leaving  camp  we  checked  out  the  old
Chuchuwanteen Cabin. We found evidence of several  other  old  buildings  in
the area. Again we left at 10:00 taking the trail down Chuchuwanteen Cr.  It
was immediately apparent this trail has not been maintained  in  some  time.
But it wasn\'t too bad to the crossing of the creek, at least  in  comparison
to what we encountered on the other side. I would say the  trail  from  that
point on has been completely abandoned. It was difficult to  even  find  the
start of it and once  on  it  the  numerous  downed  trees  presented  major
obstacles. I think everyone came away with some injuries due to battle  with
the windfall. Our pace was so slow we fell far short of our  goal  of  lunch
at the Lookout. However, things did improve somewhat as we  got  higher.  We
passed Monument Spring but found the water undrinkable. We reached  Monument
83 and the twin historic Lookouts at 4:00 spending about an  hour  exploring
and climbing the tower. From the tower we entered Canada  again  and  had  a
welcome easy road/trail from then on. We polished off over  3  miles  in  an
hour and camped in the middle of the  trail  at  the  bridge  over  Monument
Creek, the first good water.

Total: 8.5 miles, 2500 ft and 8 hrs

Day 5: Monday, October 8 - We were on the go by 9:00 and did  the  remaining
easy 6 miles to the TH in 2 hours. I think everyone was anxious to  get  out
to real food and a warm shower.

Trip Total: 46 miles and 12,800 ft in 5 days

Fay Pullen





