            'tr' => '
Lemei Rock (5925 ft - P2405), Bird Mtn (5706  ft  -  P586)  &  Sawtooth  Mtn
(5353 ft - P473) - Lone Butte Quad; and East  Crater  (5297  ft  -  P497)  -
Gifford Pk Quad - October 17-19, 2012

Indian Heaven is a small but charming Wilderness Area SW of  Mt  Adams.  The
PCT runs through the middle of it and a network  of  other  well  maintained
and well signed trails connects the many small lakes and  meadows  that  dot
the landscape.  My goal for this trip was the 4 peaks in the  northern  half
of the Wilderness. I  had  previously  climbed  Gifford  and  Berry  in  the
southern half. I expected to find  many  hunters,  as  I  had  the  previous
weekend in the Wenaha-Tucannon Wilderness when I climbed Oregon  Butte,  but
in fact found none. And except for one very special encounter, I saw no  one
on the trails the entire 3 days.

Day1: Wednesday, October 17 - Starting from the Indian Heaven TH  in  Cultus
Cr Campground (completely deserted) I hiked Trail  33  to  a  nice  camp  at
Cultus Lake (2.5 miles, 1200 ft, 2:15 hrs).  After  setting  up  my  tent  I
immediately headed for Lemei Rock on Trail 34 leaving it after about 1  mile
at a red cinder slope below the NW ridge. This being a  P2000  peak  with  a
fair amount of traffic, there was an obvious path most of the way.  Once  on
the rocky north ridge the way wandered up and down  trying  to  avoid  dense
small trees. Interest was added with a fresh coating  of  snow  and  ice  on
both rock and trees. I reached the summit cairn (900 ft, 1:20 hrs)  in  time
to witness a spectacular sunset over Mt St Helens.  I  was  surprised  there
was no register. On the descent I could feel the  temperature  dropping.  By
the time I got back to my tent ice was forming on my  wet  pole  shafts.  It
dipped to 28 degrees that night.

Lemei Rock: 3 miles, 900 ft and 2:30 hrs RT from camp

Day 2: Thursday, October 18 - My wet  boots  froze  overnight  and  ice  had
formed in the open meadows but the sun soon warmed things up. I hiked  Trail
33 and 179 to Junction Lake and the PCT. From there I took Trail 48 a  short
distance until I saw a reasonable  way  up  the  forested  hillside  through
berry bushes to the small open summit of East Crater (3 miles, 800 ft,  2:10
hrs).

Back at Junction Lake I followed the  PCT  north.  Near  the  junction  with
Trail 33 I saw a person in bright orange that I first took for a hunter  but
which on closer inspection was not. She introduced herself as  Bonnie  Acker
Lamb. I hiked with her a mile, chatting the whole way, until she turned  off
on the Placid Lake Trail. She had lived all her life in Carson  on  a  farm.
She had all her wood in for the winter so decided  to  hike  one  last  time
this year to Acker Lake. Her maiden name was Acker and the  lake  was  named
for her family. They had camped on its shores ever since she  was  a  youth.
As a teenager she had manned the  LO  on  Observation  Pk.  She  had  worked
forest service crews wielding a chain saw. She had scattered  her  husband\'s
ashes on Grassy Knoll. Did I mention she was 82 years  old?  Did  I  mention
she moved like someone much younger and I had a hard time  keeping  up  with
her? What an interesting woman she was and I felt  privileged  to  have  met
her.

After leaving Bonnie I continued  on  the  PCT  to  the  junction  with  the
Sawtooth Mtn Trail 107 which I hiked to below the summit rocks.  I  found  a
way trail that led steeply to the base of the rocks where  I  encountered  a
short class 3 pitch that others had obviously been up. So I  went  that  way
and I found a geocache. Then I looked along  the  ridge  and  saw  a  higher
point. Darn! The geocache was not on the high point. So  I  went  back  down
and along the ridge to the true summit where I left  a  register  (9  miles,
2000 ft, 7 hrs). The climbing was interesting and  fun  class  3  -  4  that
looked harder than it turned out to be. The rock and holds were  so  good  I
had no need of a rope, which was a  good  thing  since  I  didn\'t  have  one
along. It never occurred to me I might need one.

I returned to the PCT and followed it back south until below Bird Mtn.  Semi
open slopes led to that easy summit (12 miles, 2900 ft, 9  hrs).  In  waning
light I continued on the ridge going south bypassing Pt 5518 until  I  could
descend meadowy terrain to intersect Trail 33 very near my camp. I did  make
it before needing my headlamp. The predicted rain  came  shortly  thereafter
and I had a wet and windy night - a very wet and windy night  -  but  I  was
snug and dry in my tent.

Day Total: 13 miles, 3000 ft and 10 hrs

Day 3: Friday, October 19 - By morning the heavy rain had let up and  I  was
able to pack up and hike out in just damp fog (2.5 miles, 100 ft, 1:15 hrs)

Trip Total: 21 miles and 5200 ft in 3 days

Before leaving the area for the drive home I drove  to  and  took  the  easy
trail up Sleeping Beauty (4907 - P347). This is an  old  lookout  site  with
the interesting trail blasted into the summit rocks.  It  is  well  worth  a
repeat visit on a good day. Unfortunately I had fog and wind and  no  views.
I also climbed Peak 5040+  (P1160)  on  the  connecting  ridge  to  the  NW.
Totally wooded with no views regardless of weather,  this peak is not  worth
a repeat visit.

Total for both: 4.5 miles, 2100 ft and 3:15 hrs

Fay Pullen



