Trapper Creek is another small Wilderness Area  SW  of  Mt  Adams  and  near
Indian Heaven but unlike that one, which is dotted with lakes  and  meadows,
it is essentially entirely forested and has lower peaks.  It  makes  a  nice
destination in the  off  season  and  during  questionable  weather  and  is
accessible much of the year. The trails are well  maintained,  well  signed,
there are several nice places to camp and there are many  possibilities  for
loop trips.

Thursday, November1 - I had hoped to approach from the lower Trapper  Cr  TH
on the south, hike into the interior of the Wilderness and  climb  my  peaks
from a camp there but the weather changed those plans.  When  I  arrived  in
Carson it was raining steadily and the thought of hiking several  hours  and
setting up camp in  such  conditions  was  unappealing.  But  I  had  to  do
something after such a long drive, so I drove to the trailheads on the  west
side via FR Rd 54 to do short day trips. I began by hiking up  West  Crater,
just outside the Wilderness. I had a little trouble locating  the  trail  as
the sign marking the start is gone but once I did it is good all the way  to
the top (1.5 miles, 500 ft, 1 hr RT). I then drove to the Soda  Pks  TH.  By
now it was raining so hard I used an umbrella in an attempt to stay dry.  It
worked quite well on the trail and even on the cross country section to  the
summit, which had very little brush. I also went  up  the  lower  East  Peak
since they are called Soda Peaks, plural, and it was simple enough to do  so
(3.5 miles, 1250 ft, 2:30 hrs RT).

Once back to the car I drove on to the  higher  Observation  Pk  TH  on  the
north side. I considered car camping there and day hiking the next  day  but
by the time I got there it had stopped  raining.  So  I  was  suckered  into
backpacking even though it was after 5:00 before I got going and  I  knew  I
would get to my destination close  to  dark.   And  naturally  just  when  I
arrived at Berry Camp and started  putting  up  my  tent  it  began  raining
again. But once set up I was quite snug and  comfy  and  there  was  a  nice
spring for water a few hundred feet down the trail (1.8  miles,  600  ft,  1
hr).  It continued to rain hard during night until about 2 am.

Friday, November 2 - By morning it was no longer raining  but  it  was  very
foggy. That wasn\'t a real problem as I was in forest pretty much all day.  I
began on the main Observation Pk Trail, bypassing the spur to the summit  of
that peak, until it dropped off Howe Ridge at a saddle toward Trapper Cr.  I
stayed on the easy crest following it to the high point and on  to  Pt  3724
(just to make sure). Travel was pleasant with minimal brush and windfall  (3
miles, 625 ft, 2 hrs). For variety, on the  way  back  I  went  directly  up
steep slopes to the summit of Observation Pk. This is an old  lookout  site.
There would be a nice view on a clear day. All I got was  a  glimpse  of  Mt
Adams as the fog and clouds briefly parted - and I was lucky to get that.  I
picked up the spur trail on top  and  followed  it  back  to  camp  where  I
quickly packed up (5.5 miles, 2000 ft, 5:30 hrs). On the way out  I  dropped
my pack at the Sister Rocks Ridge where a side trail  led  to  that  summit.
The 4268 high point is actually a nondescript grassy knoll  but  the  summit
of more interest is the rocky 4261 point slightly farther on at trails  end.
It was now raining again and continued to do so the rest  of  trip  out  and
drive home (2.7 miles, 550 ft, 1:40 hrs).

Despite the rain and lack of views I did have fun on this mellow  trip.  The
forest was quite lovely. And I do enjoy camping in my little  tent  although
I must admit I really don\'t like putting it up (or taking it  down)  in  the
rain.

Day Total: 8.2 miles and 2550 ft

Trip Total: 15 miles and 5150 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen





