Thursday, November 9 - I began on the Big Creek (Irely Lake) Trail near  the
end of the North Fork Quinault Road. This is the start of the Skyline  trail
which I had done in its entirety in September of 1998. But that was so  long
ago I remembered little and it was like a new experience.   The  first  mile
to Lake Irely was very wet and marshy. I don\'t know if this was  because  of
recent torrential rains or if it is always so, but due to  the  many  bypass
paths and boardwalks I suspect it is the latter. Once past this section  the
trail traversed lovely forest with big trees and sword  ferns.  At  about  4
miles a high sturdy steel bridge crossed a branch  of  Big  Creek.  For  the
next 2 miles the trail climbed steadily until I came across a sign  pointing
to a record Alaska cedar. Past that things leveled out a bit but  the  trail
became increasingly rough and rocky and wet. Often it looked  like  a  small
stream bed. This became somewhat of a problem as I got higher  into  meadows
where temperatures had been cold enough to snow and freeze and turn much  of
the trail to ice. Although the day was sunny, by the time  I  got  to  Three
Lakes it was in the shade and downright frosty. I  found  a  bear  wire  and
toilet but only one campsite that was not flooded. The  entire  Three  Lakes
area is quite marshy and it is difficult to even  get  to  open  water.  The
temperature dropped to 22 degrees that night under clear skies.

7 miles, 3050 ft and 5 hrs

Friday, November 10 - The official Skyline Trail starts at  Three  Lakes.  I
understand that the Park Service is no longer  maintaining  this  trail  and
now considers it a "route",  but it is still in good shape as far as I  took
it to near Reflection Lake with only a few downed trees.  Here  I  left  the
trail to gain the ridge. I did not think I could  follow  the  ridge  to  my
peak as there were two rocky nasty looking points I would have  to  go  over
to get there. Instead I planned to drop into the  Elip  Creek  drainage  and
traverse a series of meadows below the ridge  on  the  north  side  until  I
could climb up again. It looked easy on the map. Looks can be deceiving.  It
was anything but easy. First the meadows were not really meadows  but  small
marshy areas in brushy forest. Second I ran  into  several  unexpected  deep
ravines that were difficult to cross. I had to climb back up 200 ft  to  get
across one of them. And third I was on the shady and snowy  north  side  and
had to contend with about 2 inches of fresh snow covering everything.

I eventually made it to where I could actually traverse and  miraculously  I
ran into a fairly decent elk trail. Without the  help  of  this  I  think  I
would have given up. This trail led to the flat basin NW of the peak. I  now
thought things would improve. They didn\'t. The terrain above the  basin  was
steeper  than  it  looked  on  the  map,  frozen  solid  and  covered   with
unconsolidated snow making for very slick conditions. I could  not  get  any
traction for my feet. I really needed crampons which I didn\'t  have.  I  was
making such slow progress that reaching my goal  was  becoming  doubtful.  I
almost made it to the summit ridge but couldn\'t quite get up  the  last  100
ft and had to back off. Before throwing  in  the  towel,  I  made  one  last
attempt by descending and traversing on easier terrain to  a  northern  spur
that bypassed the trouble spot. This worked and got me to the summit  ridge.
I worked my way up the ridge using a route that went from bush to bush so  I
had something to hang onto and reached the summit at 2:30, much  later  than
I had hoped (2400 ft, 6 hrs). There would have been a nice view but while  I
was struggling for hours the day that had started sunny had deteriorated  to
fog and light snow.

I did better route finding on the return but it was still  not  without  its
difficulties. I did much slipping and sliding down  steep  sections  hanging
onto brush. I was down to my last pair of dry gloves. It  was  so  cold  the
snow was not really wet but constant hanging onto snowy branches  eventually
soaked them. At least my feet were fairly warm and dry. I reached the  trail
at dusk and returned to camp by headlamp. My tent had about Â½ inch  snow  on
it. Again the temperature dropped to 22 degrees that night.

Total: 7 miles, 3050 ft and 10 hrs

Saturday, November 11 - Determined to have at least  some  views  I  climbed
the small peaks right above Three Lakes  during  the  morning  that  started
sunny. I found the old Finley Pk trail that led to the saddle below Pk  3960
and on to that summit. Alas it was so wooded  I  had  no  view  as  was  the
similar elevation west peak. So I returned to the saddle to climb  to  Three
Peaks BM 4008. There was no trail but the  going  was  reasonable  and  even
fun. But alas, once again by the time I got there  (noon)  the  weather  had
deteriorated to snow showers. I was destined to be denied any views  at  all
this trip. Then again it is the Olympics and it  is  November.  What  did  I
expect?

Peak side trip: 2.5 miles, 1450 ft and 4:15 hrs RT

Hike out: 7 miles, 300 ft and 4:30 hrs

Trip Total: 23.5 miles and 7800 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen



