Rinker Ridge (3760+ ft - P1360 - Finney Pk  Quad)  -  December  31,  2012  -
January 1, 2013

Despite  being  handicapped  by  another  painful  overuse  injury,  I   was
determined to keep up my tradition of the last two years of bringing in  the
New Year on a snow camping trip. A good forecast added incentive. But I  had
to keep the trip mellow and limit myself to an easy road  ski  with  minimal
elevation gain or suffer dire consequences.  I  first  tried  going  up  the
Cascade River Road to Rd 1550 but was stopped by an icy track  when  plowing
ended shortly after the Lookout Mtn TH. So I cast around for an  alternative
and settled on Rinker Ridge. I had no idea what I would run into  but  found
it to be a wonderful ski trip.

Monday, December 31 - I began just off the  Finney  Creek  Rd  on  the  road
leading up the north side of the mountain, elevation 900 ft. In addition  to
a gate there was a sign prohibiting vehicles so I knew  I  would  be  alone.
There was snow right from the start though it was  quite  crusty.  I  got  a
very late start at 3:00 but I wasn\'t planning on going  far.  As  it  was  I
skied up the gentle road until 4:30 to a nice  viewpoint  of  Mt  Baker  and
Sauk Mtn. I couldn\'t have asked for anything better given my parameters.

I set up my tent, had dinner, watched a video and  then  fell  sound  asleep
almost missing the New Year. I awoke at 11:30 and had to hustle  to  prepare
my celebratory hot drink in time for the festivities. I took  a  quick  peek
outside to take in the view by the light of a partial  moon  and  heard  the
local fireworks in the Skagit Valley below but preferred watching the  Space
Needle extravaganza on my  iPhone  from  the  warmth  of  my  sleeping  bag.
Reception was very good. All this excitement kept me awake for another  hour
and another video and I finally nodded off after 1:00. It was 25 degrees.

Day Total: 2 miles, 800 ft and 1:30 hrs

Tuesday, January 1 - The New Year dawned sunny but since I was on the  north
side of the mountain I didn\'t benefit from the  sun  until  both  it  and  I
climbed higher. The snow quickly got better, ranging  from  1  inch  of  new
snow over the crust down low to 8 inches of delicious powder near  the  top.
A series of roads and spurs crossed the hillside  and  the  many  clear-cuts
would allow opportunities for shortcuts with  the  proper  snow  conditions.
Given  my  limitations  I  stuck  to  roads  except  when  not  possible.  A
continuous road does goes all the way to top if you can find it and stay  on
it but it takes a long roundabout way up the west  side.  I  took  the  more
direct route up north side roads but then had a 300  ft  climb  through  the
forest to connect with  the  summit  road.  Once  on  that  the  skiing  was
delightful. I followed the road to its end just below the true  summit  then
wandered through the trees searching for the top (4  miles,  2300  ft,  3:50
hrs). A leisurely lunch was in the warm sun.

The run back to camp (1:10 hrs) was sheer heaven. I even  managed  a  couple
of turns in a high clear-cut connecting the  upper  and  lower  roads  on  a
slightly different route down. The run from camp to the  car  (44  minutes),
which I reached just as it was getting dark,  was  not  as  good,  the  snow
still being crusty and very fast. Fortunately that part of the road is  very
gentle so it was manageable with slow snowplowing.

Day     Total:     10      miles,      2300      ft      and      7      hrs
                          Trip Total: 12 miles and 3100 ft

Fay Pullen

