 Thursday, February 14 - Washington Butte (4390 ft - P180) and Cooper Ridge (5521 ft - P261)',
            'tr' => '
Echo Ridge Ski Trails - February 12 - 14, 2013 - Cooper Ridge Quad

Echo Ridge is a charming and uncrowded Nordic ski area  above  Lake  Chelan.
All the trails have cute names and are  well  groomed  and  well  marked.  I
spent 3 days skiing the trails and even managed to  bag  4  new  summits.  I
stayed the 2 nights with friends who have a luxurious condo on Wapato  Point
in Manson. Sure beats car camping in a Sno-Park.   The  weather  was  mostly
sunny each day. Views are plentiful. There is still  enough  snow  cover  on
all the trails but some are thinning fast and many of the hillsides  in  the
sun are getting bare. New snow is needed.

Tuesday, February 12 - Russell\'s Butte (4324 ft - P404) - For my  first  day
I parked at the Zoom TH starting at 1:30. I skied  Zoom  to  North  Junction
where I picked up the Outback Trail skiing the loop  clockwise.  This  trail
is open to snowshoes,  dogs  and  boots  and  was  a  tad  lumpy  but  still
reasonable skiing. Supposedly there is a trail to the summit but  it  seemed
to end on the ridge to the south, the remainder  being  XC  on  crusty  thin
snow to the top and tricky on track skis. However, I found lovely  preserved
powder on the NW slope to descend back to Outback (good  enough  for  a  few
telemarks) and more powder on the north aspect of Outback.  By  the  time  I
reached Zoom it was in shade, freezing over and  found  out  why  it  is  so
named (8.2 miles, 1365 ft and 3:30 hrs).

Wednesday, February 13 - Wells Summit  (3825  ft  -  P308)  -  I  spent  the
morning skiing from  the  Upper  TH  to  easy  Wells  Summit  via  Nuthatch,
Chickadee, Ridge View, Morning Glory and Upsy-Daisy (3.5 miles, 450  ft  and
1:30 hrs).

I skied with my friends (who are not peakbaggers) from the Upper TH  in  the
afternoon to the very pleasant Alley-Oop  loop  (5.3  miles,  235  ft,  2:20
hrs).

Thursday, February 14 - Washington Butte (4390 ft - P180) and  Cooper  Ridge
(5521 ft - P261) - For my final day I wanted to get up Washington Butte.  To
this end I again started at the Upper TH and  took  No-Where  To  Hide  1.75
miles to North Junction. There I picked up  the  snowmobile  road.  Although
quite crusty in the morning, the first 3 miles or so were  very  gentle  and
it had been recently groomed so the skiing  was  excellent.  When  the  road
steepened just before Washington Butte I put on kicker  skins  that  fit  my
narrow track skis (50mm). I soon left the  snowmobile  road,  cut  up  to  a
higher ungroomed road that led to the saddle on the west  and  followed  the
ridge to the summit (5.75 miles, 1125 ft, 3:00 hrs). It was still early,  the
day so lovely and I was feeling so good that I wasn\'t ready to leave yet.  I
could see a reasonable route NW from the  saddle  and  decided  to  continue
along the connecting ridge to Cooper Ridge. The route turned  out  to  be  a
delight.  I was high above the valley (and  the  snowmobile  road)  on  open
slopes in full sunshine. Narrow track skis may have  their  limitations  for
backcountry skiing but they do traverse very well. I crossed the  snowmobile
road high and followed the main ridge to the summit  (8.5  miles,  2570  ft,
5:50 hr). I returned on the snowmobile road  which  was  now  in  shade  and
icing over. The upper part was very steep and  very  fast.  By  the  time  I
reached North junction it was  dark  and  the  last  bit  of  trail  was  by
headlamp. Needless to say I was the last car in the parking lot.

Day total: 16.2 miles, 2755 ft and 8:20 hrs               Fay Pullen

















