Mt Spokane Ski Trails - February 16-18, 2013
 Tuesday, February 26 - Mt Spokane (5883 ft - P3503) & Bald Knob (5080+ ft - P0) - Mt Spokane Quad; and Mt Kit Carson (5282 ft - P322), Day Mtn (5057 ft - P97) & Beauty Mtn (5200+ ft - P0) - Mt Kit Carson Quad -
 Wednesday, February 27 - Tripp\'s Knob (3960+ ft - P80), Shadow Mtn (4880+ ft - P120), Horse Mtn (5103 ft - P103) and Quartz Mtn (5160+ ft - P600) - Mt Spokane Quad
 Thursday, February 28 - Linder Ridge (4680+ ft - P80 - Mt Spokane Quad) and Round Top Mtn (4480+ ft - P280 - Newman Lk Quad)',
            'tr' => '
Mt Spokane Ski Trails - February 16-18, 2013

Mt Spokane, a P2000 peak, has long been on my to-do list but I  was  waiting
until I could ski up it. With my new interest this year  in  groomed  Nordic
areas, and Mt Spokane is one of the best in the state, I finally decided  to
make the long drive and get it done. I would fill out the  3  days  allotted
by skiing a combination of groomed trails and off trail easy summits  within
Mt Spokane State Park. No overnight camping is allowed in the  park  but  it
is open until 10 PM. Unfortunately, Bear Creek Resort  at  the  entrance  to
the park, where I had hoped to stay, was not open when I arrived on  Tuesday
(maybe because the downhill area is closed on Tuesdays) so I  had  to  drive
back  to  Spokane  to  find  a  motel  for  both  nights.  There  are   some
disadvantages to going out during midweek.

Tuesday, February 26 - Mt Spokane (5883 ft - P3503) & Bald Knob (5080+ ft  -
P0) - Mt Spokane Quad; and Mt Kit Carson (5282 ft - P322), Day Mtn (5057  ft
- P97) & Beauty Mtn (5200+ ft - P0) - Mt Kit Carson Quad  -  What  with  the
long drive I didn\'t get started until 2:00 but figured I  could  easily  get
up my main objective of Mt Spokane before dark  and  the  other  peaks  were
easy enough they could be finished in the dark. I parked at  the  snowmobile
SnoPark and skied the groomed snowmobile road to  flat  Bald  Knob.  Here  I
decided to head straight up the south side to the summit. There  is  a  road
to the top but it is 4 times  the  distance  of  a  direct  approach  and  I
figured I didn\'t have the time. It was just as well as  when  I  got  higher
onto the open slopes they were so wind packed, the wind so  fierce  and  the
fog so thick I could not have seen the road to stay on  it.  It  was  all  I
could do to follow a faint snowshoe track and ski area boundary  markers  to
the towers on the summit. I removed my skins in the shelter  of  a  building
wondering how on earth I was going to  ski  down  in  a  complete  whiteout.
Somehow I managed to descend by following the snowmobile tracks on the  west
side even though all I could see were my ski tips. But once into  the  trees
the skiing was fantastic in delicious fresh  powder.  Even  with  my  skinny
skis I could do reasonable telemarks.

I soon crossed the groomed snowmobile road and reached the cabin  on  Beauty
Mtn. I again crossed the road, since skiing XC was so delightful,  to  reach
the saddle with Mt Kit Carson. A snowmobile track led to  the  top.  It  was
fairly steep in places but I made it without putting on skins.  More  lovely
untracked downhill to the saddle  with  Day  Mtn  where  another  snowmobile
track led to that summit. It was now pitch dark.  I  was  feeling  cocky  so
forged my own route back to the road. I did run into a few tight  trees  but
the snow was so forgiving it was actually fun dodging them. I then stuck  to
the road all the way back to the car reaching it at 8:30.

Day total: 9 miles, 2450 ft and 6:30 hrs

Wednesday, February 27 - Tripp\'s Knob (3960+ ft - P80),  Shadow  Mtn  (4880+
ft - P120), Horse Mtn (5103 ft - P103) and Quartz Mtn (5160+ ft  -  P600)  -
Mt Spokane Quad - I made the most of my one  full  day  but  after  my  late
night and since I had to make the 40 minute drive from Spokane I didn\'t  get
started as early as I would have liked (10:00). Still, since I had  all  day
(and all night if necessary) I didn\'t feel rushed. This time I started  from
the Nordic SnoPark at the large Selkirk Lodge. The website said there  would
be no grooming Tuesday or Wednesday but to my surprise I  discovered  Linder
Ridge Trail (and a few others) was in  fact  freshly  groomed.   I  followed
this trail to Junction 6 and Upper Tripp\'s Loop which was  not  groomed  but
still nice skiing. Upper Tripp\'s goes downhill gradually for several  miles.
All major trail junctions are numbered and all trails well  signed.  At  the
Junction 11 intersection with  Lower  Tripp\'s  Loop  the  way  finally  went
uphill a short ways to the summit of Tripp\'s Knob (5.5 miles,  250  ft,  and
2:50 hrs).

I returned past Junction 11 to an  unmarked  road  not  part  of  the  trail
system which I followed to its end below the  ridge  leading  SW  to  Shadow
Mtn.  I climbed this ridge crossing Tamarama Trail and Mica Road  Trail  and
on to Shadow\'s summit all on very pleasant terrain. I dropped off Shadow  to
pick up the Shady Way Trail (ungroomed but tracked by  skiers)  until  below
Horse Mtn. I needed skins to get up this hill  but  it  was  through  lovely
forest. Then another short descent off  Horse  and  up  to  the  lookout  on
Quartz Mtn (8.5 miles, 2050 ft and 7:20 hrs).  I  had  enough  daylight  for
another fantastic powder forest descent off Quartz, again to the  Shady  Way
Trail below and then back to the car at 6:30 on  groomed  trails  Lodgepole,
Sam\'s Swoop and Mtn View.

Day Total: 11 miles, 2200 ft and 8:30 hrs.

Thursday, February 28 - Linder Ridge (4680+ ft - P80 - Mt Spokane Quad)  and
Round Top Mtn (4480+ ft - P280 -  Newman  Lk  Quad)  -  It  was  raining  in
Spokane when I awoke in the morning. I hoped that would  mean  snow  on  the
mountain. It didn\'t. I began in light drizzle. Since I  had  to  drive  home
today I didn\'t want to be out too long. I did  get  an  hour  earlier  start
than the day before. All the major trails were freshly groomed overnight.  I
began by taking Brian\'s Hill to  the  summit  of  Linder  Ridge  and  on  to
Junction 1, then Alpine to Junction 2 and Lodgepole to Junction  3  and  the
charming and spacious Nova Hut. I continued on Quartz Mtn Trail  leaving  it
at its lowest point to go XC to the  saddle  with  Round  Top  Mtn.  It  had
stopped drizzling but was now foggy  and  so  warm  that  all  the  gorgeous
powder of the previous two days was fast turning to mashed potatoes.  Still,
it remained skiable - just not as much fun. At the  saddle  I  picked  up  a
road with fresh snowmobile tracks (this is outside the  park)  that  led  to
the south side of Round Top and skiable slopes to  the  summit  (4.5  miles,
750 ft and 2:30 hrs). At the saddle on the way back I ran  across  a  summer
ORV trail that provided a nice route up to Quart Mtn Trail  again.  However,
I did have some problems with  sticky  snow  clumping  to  my  ski  bottoms.
Although no colder, it was precipitating again, but this time  in  the  form
of snow so skiing back to the car was again very nice.

Day Total: 9 miles, 1550 ft and 4:50 hrs.

Trip Total: 29 miles and 6200 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen

