            'title' => 'Wednesday, January 30 - Pk 4658 (P618) - Buck Mtn Quad',
            'tr' => '
Loup Loup Ski Trails - January 30 - February 1, 2013

I had always wanted to check out the ski trails at Loup Loup Pass but up  to
now the drive just seemed too long.  But  with  my  new  interest  in  track
skiing this seemed the year to give it a try.  And  there  were  a  few  new
peaks that could be skied up to  add  incentive.  There  are  two  areas  of
groomed trails. On is south of the pass at the South  Summit  Sno-Park.  The
other is north of the pass at the private Ski Area. No Sno-Park is  required
here but a daily trail fee is (a whopping $5 for  super  seniors  over  70).
The ski area is open Wednesday and Friday-Sunday and gated 1 mile  from  the
lodge when closed. The whole area is heavily wooded with  few  views,  hence
no photos. There had been no new snow for a while but temps  were  generally
cold so there was still powder in protected areas and either crust or  slush
where the sun hit depending upon time of day. The South Summit had a lot  of
debris in the tracks from windblown needles and branches almost making  them
unusable in places. The private trails were in better shape.  I  car  camped
at the South Summit Sno-Park.

I used Rossignol BC 65 metal edged skis with NNNBC bindings for  this  trip.
These skis are 65 mm at the tip and 50 mm at  the  waist  which  makes  them
wide enough for moderate off-trail but still narrow enough  to  fit  in  the
track. I custom cut a pair of full length skins to fit them as I  figured  I
would need them for South Ridge and Bear Mountain. You cannot buy 50mm  full
skins any more that I am aware of. But Black Diamond does  still  make  50mm
kicker skins. I use those for easier off-trail climbing.

Wednesday, January 30 - Pk 4658 (P618) - Buck Mtn Quad

I began at the South Summit Sno-Park skiing trails to as close  as  possible
to Pk 4658. Cross country travel on skis was not  great  but  I  managed  to
make it to the summit and back to the trail without major mishap. To  extend
the day I took a longer way on trails back to the car where I  met  a  local
skier just starting who liked to ski by headlamp. I  warned  him  about  the
debris. When I saw him again on his return he agreed it  was  a  bit  rough.
After that I had the Sno-Park to myself except for a mouse who nibbled  away
at something in my car all night long (6.2 miles, 985 ft and 3:30 hrs).

Thursday, January 31 - Pole Pick Mtn (4760+ ft - P760) - Thrapp Mtn Quad

I again started from the South Summit Sno-Park, first on the shared  use  Rd
41 then the K9 Trail to Trail 10. I then went downhill a bit to  a  junction
with an ungroomed road leading to Pole Pick Mtn. This road was  very  gentle
and took forever to get anywhere but XC travel did not look inviting to  cut
the long switchback so I stuck with it to the saddle SW of  the  summit.  At
least the last bit along the ridge was reasonable going. I did have sun  for
lunch but no real views through the trees. Once back to the  main  trails  I
kept to Rd 41 all the way back to the Sno  Park  (15.5  miles,  1730  ft,  9
hrs). Once again the mouse annoyed me all night long. (He stayed in the  car
all the way home where I caught him in a trap a few days later)

Friday, February 1 - Bear Mtn (5440 ft - P480) and South Ridge  (5634  ft  -
P1154) - Loup Loup Summit Quad

For these peaks I started from the Loup Loup Ski area on the north  side  of
the pass. I skied up Nexus to a sign  on  the  ridge  marking  the  Telemark
Trail to the summit of Bear Mtn (2.5 miles, 1450 ft, 2  hrs)  but  this  was
ungroomed and not great skiing. And it was a challenge skiing off the  north
end to pick up the Bear Mtn Loop Trail which I then followed  south  to  the
saddle with South Ridge. Here I skied an ungroomed road to  just  below  the
summit. I was delighted that this north aspect road  held  preserved  powder
that made for the best skiing of the whole trip -  until  I  left  the  road
that is. The final slope to the summit in dense forest  was  steep  and  icy
(6.5 miles, 2300 ft and 5 hrs). I skied  up  with  skins  but  gave  up  and
walked down most of it. Once back at the  saddle  I  returned  via  Nirvana,
Nexus and Outer Loop. (11.8 miles, 2400 ft and 7:15 hrs).

Fay Pullen





