            'subdir' => '2013-03-07-lone-butte',
            'title' => 'Lone Butte (4780 ft - P980) & Crazy Hills (4165 ft - P845) - Lone Butte Quad; Termination Point (3690+ ft - P960) & Pk 3640 (3640+ ft - P400) - Termination Point Quad; and Burnt Pk (4106 ft - P266 - Burnt Pk Quad) - March 7-8, 2013',
            'tr' => '
Lone Butte (4780 ft - P980) & Crazy Hills (4165 ft  -  P845)  -  Lone  Butte
Quad; Termination Point (3690+ ft - P960) & Pk 3640  (3640+  ft  -  P400)  -
Termination Point Quad; and Burnt Pk (4106 ft - P266  -  Burnt  Pk  Quad)  -
March 7-8, 2013

While hiking in the Indian Heaven Wilderness last October I was struck by  a
lone butte sticking up out of the vast forested area southwest of Mt  Adams.
Darned if I didn\'t discover it was named Lone Butte. On further  examination
of the map it appeared it would make a fine winter ski ascent  as  the  Lone
Butte SnoPark is located nearby. There were also several  other  summits  in
the vicinity that would keep me busy on a multiday trip and  make  the  long
drive more worthwhile. I didn\'t  expect  anything  particularly  outstanding
from any of these low peaks, just miles of road skiing  which  I  happen  to
enjoy. However, Lone Butte turned out to be much more interesting  than  its
mostly wooded appearance would suggest with the summit  ridge  being  almost
alpine in nature. Snow conditions on the trip varied from  powder  to  slush
to solid crust to gosh awful breakable crust as temperatures ranged from  23
degrees at night to mid forties during the day.

Thursday, March 7: Pk 3640 and Termination Point - From Carson I  drove  the
Wind River Road 30 about 20 miles to the junction with Road 31 and the  tiny
Lookout Mtn SnoPark, which was only a wide spot in the road with room for  a
couple of cars and 5 ft snow banks.  When  I  saw  the  road  had  not  been
recently plowed and there was 6-8 inches new snow I knew  I  would  have  my
work cut out for me as that meant no trails would  be  groomed  either.  The
snow was deep enough that I needed the low range on my Jeep to  get  through
and in places I dragged bottom. Again a disadvantage of going out midweek.

I started up Road 31 at 1:45. A sign proclaimed it  closed  to  snowmobiles.
It showed no recent non-motorized travel either.  It was a warm day and  the
snow was melting in the sun and skiing was quite good to start. I  took  the
turnoff spur to Pk 3640 at  0.75  mile  and  cut  the  big  switchback  through
pleasant woods making my way to the summit at 3:30 (2 miles,  900  ft,  1:45
hr). From there I elected to save time by taking a shortcut west to  hit  Rd
31 directly below. This steep heavily wooded slope  was  unskiable  but  was
great plunge stepping on foot and I quickly intersected the  road.   It  was
now getting late enough that  breakable  crust  was  beginning  to  form  in
shaded areas. That made skiing the open road  slow  and  undesirable  so  as
soon as possible I left it for a direct approach through  open  woods  where
the snow was still preserved powder. I hit a spur higher up and followed  it
to its end just north of the summit. I left skis here and booted to the  top
at 6:00 (4.5 miles, 1800 ft, 4:15 hrs).

I had a nice run back to Rd 31. What followed then was one of my worst  road
skis ever in recent memory. The temperature had plummeted and the  snow  had
turned to dreaded "death crust", crust soft enough to break through on  skis
but hard enough to form a thick surface layer that traps a ski  beneath  it.
On steep slopes it is deadly and totally unskiable.  Fortunately,  the  road
was very gentle. I ended up slowly walking out on skis breaking through  one
step at a time. I got very little glide. Things  improved  slightly  at  the
spur turnoff to Pk 3640 where I hit the track I had set  earlier  in  softer
conditions. But the whole trip out took much longer than it should  have.  I
reached the car at 8:00. I then drove on up the Road 30 another 6  miles  to
the huge Lone Butte snowmobile SnoPark where I spent the  night.  There  was
no one else there.

Day Total: 8 miles, 1800 ft and 6:15 hrs

Friday, March 8: Lone Butte  -  After  the  awful  snow  conditions  of  the
previous night I wasn\'t sure how the skiing would be to start but  it  ended
up not being all that bad.  From  the  SnoPark  the  main  snowmobile  route
continued on Road 30. It had not been recently groomed but much  of  it  was
in perpetual shade with preserved powder so in fact  the  skiing  was  still
very good even in the frigid morning. There were  the  odd  crusty  sections
but they were not a great problem going up. Turns out they would  not  be  a
problem going down either as after about an hour out  I  heard  a  motorized
noise coming toward me. Sure enough it was the groomer. I waved to  the  two
guys inside.  Evidently they started from the Atkisson SnoPark  (near  Trout
Lake) which connects to the Lone Butte SnoPark via some 30 miles of roads.

After 2.5 miles I came to the minor saddle east  of  Lone  Butte,  left  the
groomed road and skied up the east ridge. The beginning was  quite  nice  in
moderate open forest but soon steepened to  where  it  was  easier  to  kick
steps then ski. As I climbed the route  became  more  interesting  going  up
alongside an open gully, then semi-open slopes to a small  rock  outcropping
at the false summit. It all  had  an  unexpectedly  alpine  feel  to  it  in
contrast to the tree farm feel of the previous two summits. The  ridge  from
the false to true summit even had  fresh  mountain  goat  tracks,  though  I
never saw him. He also had made a bed right on the summit. I  had  lunch  in
the sun but unfortunately clouds were obscuring Mt Adams, though I  did  get
a nice view of St Helens. For the return I  dropped  down  the  steep  south
slope on foot to the spur road below and skied that to the now groomed  road
and then back to the SnoPark (6 miles, 1650 ft and 5 hrs).

Burnt Pk and Crazy Hills - It was too early (2:30) and too nice out to  quit
for the day, so after restocking food and drink I began again for  my  final
two peaks even though I knew I would return after dark and  run  into  lousy
skiing conditions again as things froze. This time I took Rd 32  north  from
the SnoPark. It was ungroomed but snowmobiles had  been  on  it  previously.
Oddly, a sign identified this as entering the Lone Butte Natural Area  where
motorized vehicles are prohibited. I guess snowmobiles  don\'t  count.  There
was a gate but it was buried under snow. The skiing was  good  in  the  warm
afternoon. After 2 miles I took a spur left, followed this to a  saddle  and
dropped down a gully to pick up the spur road to Burnt  Pk.  The  final  bit
through gentle forest with no real discernible landmarks was  confusing  and
I doubt I could have found the summit (at 5:15) without my GPS. I  did  more
ski wandering through forest to get to the spur road up Crazy Hills. I  left
my skis at the final saddle to kick steps up the final rise  to  the  summit
which I reached at 6:40. Back to my skis, I plunged south down steep  slopes
to a road that connected to the Burnt Pk spur and closed  the  loop  when  I
picked up my in tracks. I walked up the gully and cut a  switchback  to  get
to Rd 32 again. The final 2 miles out was not bad skiing  as  I  had  set  a
nice track and the road was very gentle but  it  was  slow.  I  reached  the
SnoPark at 9:10. It was too late and I was too tired  to  drive  home  so  I
spent another night in my car (9 miles, 1650 ft and 6:40 hrs).

Trip Total: 23 miles and 5100 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen







