            'title' => 'King Mtn (4720+ ft - P720), Smith Butte (4320+ ft - P400), Snowplow Mtn (5087 ft - P167), Snipes Mtn 4761 ft - P161) and Bunnell Butte (4120+ ft - P200) - King Mtn Quad - March 21-22, 2013 
 Friday, March 22: Snowplow Mtn, Snipes Mtn and Bunnell Butte',
            'tr' => '
King Mtn (4720+ ft - P720), Smith Butte (4320+  ft  -  P400),  Snowplow  Mtn
(5087 ft - P167), Snipes Mtn 4761 ft - P161) and Bunnell Butte (4120+  ft  -
P200) - King Mtn Quad - March 21-22, 2013

These five peaks were all accessed from the large SnowKing SnoPark  on  USFS
Road 82 6 miles NE of  Trout  Lake.  This  is  a  combined  snowmobile/skier
SnoPark.  The  snowmobile  trails  are  ungroomed.  The  skier  trails   are
supposedly groomed but I saw no evidence of this while I was there.   I  had
about 6 inches of fresh snow on the approach road when  I  arrived  at  1:30
Thursday afternoon. It had not yet  been  plowed  but  was  early  the  next
morning. There were several snowmobile rigs and  skier  cars  parked.  There
are many back roads in the area that allow access to  gentle  terrain  ideal
for skinny skiing. Most snowmobiles that use this  SnoPark  make  a  beeline
for the vast open southern slopes of Mt Adams  and  leave  the  lower  roads
untouched. I was surprised by the dearth of snow in  the  SnoPark  (at  3200
ft) and on south facing slopes  nearby.  If  it  hadn\'t  been  for  the  new
snowfall some would have been almost bare. But  there  was  plenty  of  snow
once above 3800 ft. The ski  trails  at  nearby  lower  (2800  ft)  Pineside
SnoPark had so little snow skiing would have been very marginal.

Thursday, March 21: King Mtn and Smith Butte - I began from the  SnoPark  at
2:00 by skiing up Rd 82 to the first road on the  right.  This  was  a  very
minor road and I soon lost it but that didn\'t matter as a series  of  lovely
open glades allowed easy travel in the direction I wanted to go. It was  all
very pleasant skiing with delicious fresh powder underfoot. I worked my  way
to the base of the south ridge of King Mtn and up it  to  intersect  a  road
(coming from the east side and not shown on my map) leading to  a  tower  on
the summit (3.5 miles, 1600 ft, 3 hrs). I started in  sunshine  but  by  the
time I got to the top it turned foggy and I had  no  views.  That  seems  to
frequently be the story of my life.

I had a truly delightful run descending very friendly open  forest  directly
toward Smith Butte. This is my kind of terrain and my kind of skiing. I  was
in seventh heaven. All too soon I reached Rd 82, crossed it and had  to  put
on skins to climb the steep east side to the summit of the Butte  (6  miles,
2250 ft, 4:10 hrs).  No views and there were signs a squall was  approaching
fast. I had to descend the even steeper south side on foot as there was  not
enough snow cover to allow skiing through the dense brushy  forest.  At  the
base I hit a minor road which according to my map should have run  into  the
skier trail system. By now it was dark and snowing heavily and I  could  not
see very well with the light of my headlamp reflecting  off  the  flakes.  I
had some trouble following the somewhat brushy obscure road  and  it  didn\'t
seem to be going where I thought it should  so  I  was  very  happy  when  I
finally intersected a major trail with fresh ski tracks.  From there it  was
a very nice ski back to the SnoPark at 8:45. I was all alone.  It  snowed  a
couple of inches total overnight.

Day Total: 9 mile, 2250 ft and 6:45 hrs.

Friday, March 22: Snowplow Mtn,  Snipes  Mtn  and  Bunnell  Butte  -  I  was
awakened at 5:00 by the snowplow clearing the access road. I  went  back  to
sleep after it left, arising again at 7:00. At 8:00  the  snowmobiles  began
arriving and I had quiet no longer. I started at 8:50  up  Road  82.  Skiing
was good on the shoulder in untouched snow, not so good in the rutted  bumpy
snowmobile tracks. In 2.5 miles I came to  the  old  no  longer  in  service
Smith Butte SnoPark and a gorgeous  view  of  Mt  Adams  glistening  in  the
sunshine. Alas that would not last long. In another 2 miles  I  entered  the
Yakima  Reservation,  identified  by  a  large   sign   declaring   "permits
required." I was confused by  what  this  meant  but  since  the  snowmobile
tracks ignored it I did too. There was a large clear-cut here that  provided
my last good view of Adams. I took a rest of 5 minutes turning  my  back  on
the mountain and when I turned around again it was  completely  obscured  by
clouds and never saw it again the rest of the day. Good grief that  happened
fast! I continued on the road to the minor saddle  below  Snowplow  Mtn  and
skied up the short slope to the summit (7 miles, 1900  ft,  4:20  hrs).  One
look at the map and you can see how this peak was named  for  the  shape  of
its two wedge-shaped ridges.

I returned on Rd 82 until past Bird Creek and then began a long XC  traverse
to Snipes Mtn. This was quite interesting through varied but  easy  terrain,
much of it in a section of the vast Cascade Creek Fire of last fall.  Skiing
through  the  extensive  burned  trees  had  its  own  stark  beauty  and  I
thoroughly enjoyed it. The burn extended to the summit (10 miles,  2350  ft,
7 hrs). From Snipes I skied off the south side to another  major  snowmobile
road below, following this to skin up the north side of tiny Bunnell  Butte.
I am not sure why this bump is named when  other  similar  ones  nearby  are
not, but maybe it is because there is a large gravel pit on its  west  side.
I walked off the south side back to the snowmobile road and  skied  this  to
Road 82 again and its bumpy tracks to the SnoPark. It was past  7:00  and  I
was too tired to make the  long  drive  home  so  I  stayed  another  night.
However, I moved to the lower Pineside SnoPark to avoid  being  awakened  by
snowmobiles arriving early on a Saturday morning.

Day Total: 16 miles, 2600 ft, and 10:15 hrs

Trip Total: - 25 miles and 4850 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen

