"Snowflea Hill" (3804 ft - P564) and "Nadwrap Ridge"  (3748  ft  -  P468)  -
Shuksan Arm Quad - March 30-31, 2013

I could not pass up going out on such a gorgeous weekend even though I  knew
skiing conditions would not be all that great. With that in mind I  chose  a
gentle road trip that would still allow  for  views  to  the  big  peaks  to
compensate.

Saturday, March 30 - I could not drive as far up Shannon Creek Road 1152  as
I had hoped, only 1.8 miles to 1500 ft elevation. I was not stopped by  snow
but by a large blowdown, the first of  many.  As  I  was  getting  ready  to
leave, 2 guys in a Jeep Wrangler appeared. They were  planning  to  camp  on
the  Sulphide  Glacier  on  Shuksan.  I  thought  this  rather   unrealistic
considering their late arrival (12:00) but then I guess  they  thought  they
would be able to drive to the TH since they had  both  a  beefy  4X4  and  a
chain saw. With the latter they proceeded to start in on the  logs.  I  left
them to play with their toys and wondered how long it  would  take  them  to
realize it was hopeless.

I myself had no such lofty ambitions  and  began  by  walking  up  the  road
carrying my skis. I had to work my way through  dozens  of  blowdowns.  This
road will not open until the Forest Service brings in a  large  work  party.
After about 1.5 miles I grew weary of crawling over and under  downed  trees
and cut the large switchback before Shannon Creek. I don\'t  think  I  gained
much other than a change of scenery. When I came out on the  upper  road  at
2300 ft the snow was consistent enough  to  ski  with  minimal  trees  down.
Where Spur 014 takes a switchback right to the Shannon Ridge TH I went  left
on the main Road 1152 (gated and blocked with  boulders).  I  was  in  heavy
forest with only brief tantalizing views of both Shuksan and Baker. On  such
a gorgeous weather day I really wanted a scenic campsite and so  kept  going
until I reached this goal, much farther than I had anticipated. I had to  go
Â½ mile up Rd 1155 to a small clearing at 2900 ft. However, it was worth  the
effort and was really a lovely spot with a lovely  view  of  Mt  Baker  (5.5
miles, 1650 ft, 4 hrs).

After setting up camp, at 5:30, I continued on road 1155 to a junction  with
1157. It was warm and sunny and the snow soft and good skiing. I decided  to
do Nadwrap Ridge first as the road ended about Â½ mile from  the  top  and  I
wanted daylight to find my way whereas Snowflea had a road all  the  way  to
the top. From the end of the road in a clear  cut  I  had  a  splendid  view
across Baker Lake to Blum and Hagan. However, there were too many trees  and
I was too low to get a good view of Shuksan. From the clear cut I  traversed
into forest and skied up to the saddle on the ridge. I left  skis  here  and
booted up the steep narrow but easy ridge to the forested top at  6:50  (1.5
miles, 900 ft, 1:20 hrs). No Views. Then on to  Snowflea.  Already  I  could
feel a crust forming in shady areas open to the sky. That did not bode  well
for my descent. The  road  wound  back  and  forth  up  the  north  side  of
Snowflea. At one point I caught a stunning glimpse of Shuksan in  Alpenglow.
Then in a clearcut just below the summit views opened  wide  to  Blum-Hagan-
Bacon but by now the sun had set. On reaching the actual top I  also  got  a
view in the other  direction  to  Baker.  I  kicked  myself  for  not  doing
Snowflea first when the sun was still up.  Still,  the  evening  views  were
very dramatic, much more so than the photos would indicate.  I  reached  the
summit of Snowflea at 8:10 (3.5 miles, 1500 ft, 2:40). As expected  the  ski
down was challenging in the forming crust. I was  glad  when  I  reached  my
camp at 9:20 (5 miles, 1500, 3:50 hrs).

Day Total: 10.5 miles, 3150 ft and 7:50 hrs.

Sunday, March 31 - I spent a warm and comfortable night and got  a  solid  8
hours of sleep. I did peek out my tent door for sunrise on Baker but  didn\'t
arise for real until the sun hit my tent about 8:30. I was in no  hurry  and
wanted to wait until the snow softened before leaving. Unfortunately it  was
still crusty when I was ready to go at 10:00 as I was on the shady  side  of
the hill. But I only had the short steeper distance to Road  1152  that  was
challenging before hitting softer conditions on the more gentle  lower  road
that remained good skiing the rest of the way  out.  At  the  junction  with
Spur 014 I ran into footprints postholing knee deep.  No  doubt  from  chain
saw guys. In addition to a late start they  didn\'t  have  snowshoes  either?
What were they thinking? I gave them little chance of getting anywhere.

I stuck with the road, not repeating my "shortcut"  of  the  way  up.  As  I
turned the switchback near Shannon Creek I  ran  into  two  dogs  and  their
interesting old timer owner from Sedro Woolley. I chatted a while with  him.
He too had no snowshoes and was struggling even following the  trail  broken
by chain saw guys and was surprised the snow level was so low. He  was  just
out to give his dogs some exercise who seemed to be having a blast.  Shortly
past that encounter I came to the end of the skiable snow and the  start  of
the cursed blowdowns. When I reached my car the Wrangler  was  gone.  I  saw
evidence of a new campfire in the middle of  the  road  so  it  was  obvious
chain saw guys camped by their car before leaving.  I had to  chuckle.  They
had cleared about 3 blowdowns to the first switchback, a distance  of  maybe
200 ft before calling it a day. I must admit though that  they  did  a  good
job on what they did do.

Day Total: 5.5 miles, 100 ft and 3:00 hrs

Trip Total: 16 miles and 3250 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen





