            'tr' => '
"Burton Mtn" (5456 ft - P416 - Packwood Quad) - April 9, 2013

I was stopped by snow on Road 20 south of  Hwy  12  near  Packwood  after  4
miles, elevation 2560 ft.  Snow was consistent enough shortly thereafter  to
ski although it couldn\'t have been much wetter without  turning  to  liquid.
It was warm with sun breaks to start then clouded over. In .3 mile I  turned
right onto spur 2010. The first mile of this spur  was  fairly  brushy  with
slushy new snow barely covering many holes over  the  brush.  Actually  skis
worked well (better than short  snowshoes)  by  bridging  these  holes,  but
wandering back and forth  around  obstacles  was  slow  going.  Things  were
beginning to improve with more snow cover when I came  to  a  deep  washout.
The old culvert was sitting  in  the  bottom  of  a  ten  foot  trench  with
vertical snow topping crumbly dirt walls. It took me a good  20  minutes  to
figure out how to get  across.  Shortly  after  that  I  came  to  a  second
washout. However, this one was not as bad with solid snow walls I  was  able
to side step down and up while crossing the water in-between on  skis.  This
is not particularly good for skis but I had beaters that I usually  use  for
spring conditions so didn\'t care. Once past all  these  obstacles  the  road
was clear and nice skiing.

After about 3 miles views began to open up.  First  across  Smith  Creek  to
rocky South Point. There is a nice trail up the north ridge  of  this  peak.
Then up to the SE slope of Smith Ridge. There is no  trail  but  this  is  a
nice ridge that culminates in a class 4 chimney route up Smith Point.  Then,
as I rounded the south  end  of  Smith  Ridge,  to  Castle  Butte  and  Twin
Sisters.  Again there are nice trails to near these peaks  though  they  are
accessed from a different road. All these peaks  have  fascinating  geology,
many  with  long  rocky  ridges.  The  granddaddy  of  them   all   is   the
appropriately named Stonewall Ridge (2 drainages away  and  not  visible  on
this trip) with its impressive 2 mile long  sheer  rock  wall  on  the  east
slope (I skied up this ridge from the easier side in wonderful fresh  powder
earlier this winter on an  "almost"  Stefan  trip  -  but  that  is  another
story). I mention all these peaks to emphasize that, despite  being  riddled
with logging roads, there is much of interest in this area  even  for  those
other than obsessive peak baggers.

After 5 miles I came to the end of the road at Dry Creek  Pass.  From  there
an easy route led up open forest to lovely Burton Meadows below  the  gentle
summit  ridge.  With  powder  snow   this   would   be   fantastic   skiing.
Unfortunately I had Cascade concrete. My consolation was it was so sticky  I
never had to use skins, even on the steeper sections. The summit  ridge  has
3 closed 5440 ft contours. The north one is surveyed at 5456 ft and  is  the
one listed as the summit by Howbert. Listsofjohn calls  the  south  one  the
summit at 5460 ft. Neither gives it a name. Just to be sure  I  visited  all
three. I would have anyway as it is a  lovely  ridge.  If  anyone  cares  my
altimeter indicated the middle one  was  highest.  I  have  also  taken  the
liberty of naming this ridge "Burton Mtn"  in  keeping  with  nearby  Burton
Meadows and Creek.

The trip down was fairly pleasant though not very  fast  in  the  "I  didn\'t
think it was possible to get any wetter" wet slush. Even the lower road  was
fun in a perverted  way,  dodging  branches  and  tree  limbs.  I  did  not,
however, like crossing the  washout  again.  But  as  my  organic  chemistry
teacher always used to tell me after I had messed up and had  to  repeat  an
experiment "it is always easier the second time".

Trip Total: 12.5 miles, 3300 ft and 9:20 hrs

Fay Pullen





