            'tr' => '
Big Huckleberry Mtn (4200+ ft - P960) & Grassy Knoll (3680+ ft - P40) -  Big
Huckleberry Quad; and Augspurger Mtn (3667 ft - P1507),  Hauk  Butte  (2880+
ft - P640) & Goat Pt (2361 ft - P241) - Willard Quad - April 26-27, 2013

Friday, April 26: Big Huckleberry Mtn and Grassy Knoll - I took  paved  Bear
Creek Road off Wind River Road which soon became dirt  FR  6808.  After  7.1
miles at Triangle Pass I turned left onto FR 68 2.1 miles  to  the  spacious
Grassy Knoll TH where I planned to car camp. No facilities. Both dirt  roads
were clear but had many deep potholes making for slow travel.

I started up the trail at 1:45. It was warm and sunny and shorts  the  order
of the day.  At a little over a mile I  came  to  a  rocky  outcrop  with  a
lovely view across Big Lava Bed to Little  Huckleberry  Mtn  and  Mt  Adams.
Oddly Little Huckleberry (4781  ft)  is  higher  than  Big  Huckleberry.  Go
figure. After a couple of more ups and downs along  the  ridge  I  made  the
final rise to Grassy Knoll, an old lookout site with a splendid view  of  Mt
Hood. I took a late lunch here in full sunshine (2.2 miles,  1100  ft,  1:15
hrs).

After lunch I continued on the trail along  the  ridge  to  Big  Huckleberry
Mtn. I gradually ran into more and more snow until  I  completely  lost  the
trail where it traversed the hillside below the ridgeline in  thick  forest.
I had to drop a couple hundred feet  to  a  saddle  then  work  past  cliffs
before making a direct approach to the summit from the SE. The trail  avoids
this area by circling around to the west ridge. The summit was  semi  wooded
which made the view from Grassy Knoll the better  of  the  two  (5.6  miles,
2120 ft, 3:45 hrs).

Finding my way back to open trail through the snowy  woods  was  facilitated
by GPS waypoints I had marked on the way in. Otherwise it  would  have  been
very confusing. Once on the trail again I enjoyed  the  evening  sun  on  Mt
Hood front and center most of the way and took  my  time  until  I  suddenly
realized I had forgotten to put my headlamp in my pack. Really  dumb  but  I
had packed in a hurried frenzy after  returning  from  a  weeklong  trip  to
Albuquerque the day before  and  was  totally  disorganized.  This  omission
added an urgency to my step and I made it back to  car  with  barely  enough
light to see my feet in the woods. I spent the night in the car.  I  met  no
one on the trail or on the back roads all day. Although this is a very  good
trail I don\'t think it gets all that much use.

Day Total: 11.2 miles, 3000 ft and 7 hrs

Saturday, April 27: Augspurger Mtn, Goat Point and Hauk Butte - There  is  a
nice trail up the south side of Augspurger Mtn from the Dog Mtn TH  off  Hwy
14 but this trail is long (14 miles RT) with many ups  and  downs  (4200  ft
elevation gain) and I didn\'t think I had the time to do it and  still  drive
home today. Since there is reported to be a TH on the  north  side  where  I
already was and since I love to explore I thought I would  see  if  I  could
find it.

I returned to Triangle Pass where I stayed on FR 68  going  east.  Since  on
the way the road went very close to Goat Point,  I  parked  at  the  closest
point and went XC to that summit.  It  was  actually  very  pleasant  travel
through lovely mossy forest but I was disappointed  there  was  no  view  on
top. I really thought a "point" would have a view (.7 miles, 450 ft and  :47
hrs RT).

About a half mile past where I parked for Goat Point I turned right onto  an
unmarked spur that my map showed going all the way to the  north  Augspurger
TH. It did but I couldn\'t drive it as it was blocked almost  immediately  by
a washout at a large creek. Darn. I was still a good 3 miles from the TH.  I
didn\'t expect to be able to drive on obscure back roads all the way  to  the
TH but I really thought I would get farther  than  this.  What  to  do  now?
There were probably other roads that went through but it would take time  to
find the correct ones and even then there were no guarantees they  would  be
drivable. 3 miles wasn\'t really that far if the road past  the  washout  was
easily walked and not decommissioned or overgrown. So I decided  to  go  for
it.

I had to wade the creek but once on the other side the road  was  very  good
and made for very pleasant walking. In fact some serious 4X4s  had  made  it
across the creek and driven on the road. But from the looks of it, this  and
other roads past various junctions seemed better than those  that  would  be
the exclusive domain of 4X4s. There  must  be  another  access.  However  it
could very well be gated. I met or saw no vehicles on  this  sunny  Saturday
and I did come across a No Trespassing  sign  posted  by  a  timber  company
although oddly it was facing the opposite direction and I only saw it on  my
walk back out.

After 3 miles of roads I came to a power line and gravel pit at the base  of
the cliffy north ridge of Augspurger Mtn.  I  was  getting  worried  as  the
terrain looked very difficult for XC travel and  I  didn\'t  know  where  the
trail started. As it turned out it was no great  problem.  I  just  followed
the highest spur to the gravel pit and it ran right into the TH.  There  was
an old sign at that point but no other prior indication of its existence  (3
miles, 920 ft, 1:30 hrs).

The trail, though obviously little used now, was really quite  good.  A  lot
of work had been done on it at one time to cross a  large  talus  field  and
steep wooded hillside as it switchbacked up onto the ridge crest  above  the
gravel pit and cliffs. Once on the ridge it was a  delight  as  it  wandered
along the rocky crest with views of Adams and St Helens  and  Hood.  It  was
somewhat brushy in places but nothing horrible.  It  was  also  very  windy.
Although  the  trail  to  it  was  interesting   the   summit   itself   was
disappointingly wooded with no views (5 miles, 2200 ft, 3 hrs). I  did  find
a place for lunch slightly downhill from the top  with  a  semi-view  of  Mt
Hood and out of the wind for lunch.

I had time on the way out to hike the side road up  Hauk  Butte  (10  miles,
3100 ft, 5:50 hr). I then took a shortcut straight down  to  the  main  road
that cut off a good 1.5 miles of walking. I was worried that  this  shortcut
would be brushy but it was surprising pleasant open forest. Once at the  car
I continued east on Rd 68 to Willard, shorter and faster than returning  the
way I had come.

Day Total: 12 miles, 3100 ft and 6:45 hrs

Fay Pullen

