            'tr' => '
Mt O\'Neil (4295 ft - P415), Quinault Ridge 5 (4072 ft - P872) and Wooded  Pk
(3865 ft - P 505) - Lake Quinault East Quad - May2-4, 2013

Accompanying me on this trip for  the  first  time  was  "Freddy".  I  found
Freddy abandoned in  a  parking  lot,  disheveled,  dirty  and  squashed.  I
cleaned him up and decided to bring him along.  He  would  always  be  ready
exactly when I was, go wherever  I  wanted  to  go,  move  at  my  pace,  be
indifferent to weather, never complain and always smile - in other words  be
the perfect climbing companion.

Thursday, May 2: Quinault Ridge 5 - I had been up  Petes  Creek  Trail  last
May when I climbed  Gibson  Pk  and  Colonel  Bob.  Conditions  were  almost
identical this year with lovely blooming oxalis and trillium  on  the  lower
trail and consistent snow once the trail broke into the open at  about  2500
ft. I passed up last year\'s campsite hoping to get a little  higher  to  the
junction with the Colonel Bob Trail coming from Lake Quinault.  When  I  got
to the junction (2800 ft) it was all snow but after a  bit  of  searching  I
found a bare spot nestled in the trees just large enough for  my  tiny  tent
(2.5 miles,1800 ft, 2:45 hrs). I set up camp and  immediately  set  off  for
Quinault Ridge 5.

Why the name Quinault Ridge 5? Quinault Ridge is the  major  divide  between
the Quinault and Humptulips Rivers. It has 5 peaks of prominence  along  its
length none of which are named individually. On  Howbert\'s  Master  List  he
numbers them 1 to 5 from south to north. Pk  4072  is  the  most  northerly,
hence it is number 5. When I started for this peak it was already 4:45,  but
I only had a little over a mile and 1200 ft to go to the  summit.  How  hard
could that be? Well, a lot harder than I thought. At first  I  was  able  to
find sections of the Colonel Bob Trail leading  to  the  3200  saddle  below
Quinault Ridge 5 but soon all  was  lost  under  snow.  From  the  saddle  I
followed the ridge. It soon became narrow and rocky and slow  going  finding
a way. I surmounted one particularly nasty steep step  to  where  the  ridge
flattened just before the final east notch and I  thought  I  had  it  made.
Then I saw I had to descend more nasty terrain down to the  notch.  At  this
point I could not get off the ridge to either side and had no other  choice,
other than retreat the way I had come, but to continue.

I made it to the notch and then traversed left on  easy  snow  below  cliffs
toward a second notch on the south ridge. Just before  this  notch  a  broad
snow gully led right to the summit area. While climbing this I  witnessed  a
slide come from forested cliffs above the notch and continue  down  a  lower
gully. It was small and I  was  well  out  of  the  way  but  it  was  still
unnerving as it came out of nowhere with no  warning  in  an  area  I  least
expected. At the top of the gully easy but slick, wet,  mossy  rock  led  to
what I thought was the summit at 7:45. There I saw a higher point about  100
ft away along a narrow exposed rocky crest. By the time I  made  my  way  to
that top it was 8:00 (1400 ft, 3:15 hrs) and by the time I left  a  register
and took a few photos it was 8:15. I was so pressed for  time  I  forgot  to
photograph Freddy but he was in my pack and this  did  count  as  his  first
summit.

For the return I took a chance and once back to near the  south  notch  kept
descending the gully on easy snow (the same  gully  the  slide  went  down).
When I thought I was below all the cliffs I began a  traverse  back  to  the
trail saddle. This actually went  very  well  and  would  be  the  route  of
choice. Too bad I didn\'t know about this on the way up. I intersected my  in
tracks and followed them back to camp by headlamp at  9:30  (2  miles,  1600
ft, 4:45 hrs).

Day Total: 4.5 miles, 3600 ft and 7:30 hrs

Friday, May 3: Mt O\'Neil and Wooded Pk - After my  late  night  I  was  late
getting up.  Had I known what I was in for I might never have  emerged  from
my cozy sleeping bag.  I started up the snow, which was  already  calf  deep
slush, toward Colonel Bob at 9:50. By noon I was at  the  saddle  below  the
LO. Here is where I began  the  route  to  O\'Neil.  The  Olympic  guide  was
typically vague saying to "bypass several rock  promontories  following  the
path of least difficulty" which really wasn\'t all that helpful. I  traversed
steep and sometimes icy snow in the trees on the south side  of  the  ridge,
gained the ridge too soon and had to drop off it again to make my way  to  a
notch before the last 4200 ft bump. I was not able to climb  over  this  nor
continue traversing on the south side but  luckily  a  not  too  steep  snow
gully descended to the north side where I could easily traverse to the  3840
saddle below the final rock dome of Mt O\'Neil.

Almost immediately above the  saddle  I  encountered  a  rock  step.  I  was
contemplating how to surmount this when I spied a rope hanging down  from  a
tree. It was old but sturdy and provided a way up a slab  to  a  ledge  that
led right to an ice choked chimney which I struggled  up  helped  by  branch
belays. Above this the terrain eased to enjoyable class 2 and I reached  the
summit at 2:30 (2 miles,  2250  ft  4:40  hr).  I  found  a   large  plastic
register that had lost its rubber seal and was filled with  water.  However,
the booklet was waterproof paper so it was still in  good  condition.  While
enjoying the views and having lunch I dried it out. It had  been  placed  on
8/30/94 and there had been 14 entries since. Seven  were  repeat  climbs  by
the same fellow, George Bauer. He must have really liked  this  peak.  I  am
thinking maybe he was the one who left the rope. The  last  entry,  and  the
only one I recognized, was by Kevin Koski and John Myers on 2/20/10.  I  was
the first since that. This peak is not climbed all that often.

After over an hour on  the  summit  I  decided  to  head  for  Wooded  Peak.
Although I thought it might be a challenge I was encouraged  by  the  person
who placed the O\'Neil register mentioning he was continuing on to Wooded  PK
to place another register. He must have  known  it  could  be  climbed  from
O\'Neil. Right? Besides with a name like Wooded how hard could it be? Will  I
never learn? Peaks are always farther, harder and take longer than I  think,
especially in the Olympics.

I returned to the saddle, rappelling the icy chimney and rock slab.  I  then
began a long convoluted downward traverse toward Wooded Peak. It began  well
but soon turned ugly. Wooded Peak was indeed wooded but hidden in the  woods
were numerous nasty cliffs. I was forced  down  away  from  the  ridge  that
connects with O\'Neil, where I wanted to be, by these cliffs. I could see  no
way onto it and had to  descend  several  hundred  feet.  I  then  hoped  to
contour around the nose of the ridge to the 3300 ft saddle with  Wooded  but
again was prevented from doing so by cliffs. Now I was forced to climb  back
up to ridge on steep hard snow. Once on the crest,  which  was  refreshingly
gentle where I hit it, I thought I had it made. But no! Following the  ridge
down, it again turned steep, narrow,  rocky  and,  to  make  matters  worse,
brushy. At one particularly bad spot I almost got out  the  rope  to  rappel
but instead found a log propped against the rock wall I could scoot down.

Eventually, I made it to the saddle and thought I had it made. But  no!  The
"saddle" was really a series of several deep rocky  notches  each  of  which
required care and time to negotiate. I could not follow the  ridge  but  had
to drop on the north side each time. Finally I was able to  gain  the  ridge
past all the cliffs and thought I had it made. But no! The ridge though  not
all that cliffy was littered with house  sized  mossy  boulders  that  again
took time and care to negotiate. I finally made the wooded  summit  at  7:20
(3.2 miles, 3300 ft, 9:25 hrs). I found no register or evidence  anyone  had
ever been there. I left one of mine (though I doubt anyone  will  ever  sign
it), snapped a photo of Freddy and headed down  to  what  was  now  sure  to
become an epic. To make matters worse I had discovered my headlamp,  despite
having the lock on, had somehow inadvertently been turned  on  in  my  pack.
How long it had been on I do not know but it  was  flashing  red  indicating
low batteries. So now I had the additional worry of my headlamp quitting  on
me. However do I manage to get myself into these situations?

There was no way I could return  the  way  I  came  given  the  time  so  my
strategy now was to descend  straight  down  the  forested  south  slope  of
Wooded Pk to hit the Colonel Bob Trail at  1900  ft  in  the  Zeigler  Creek
drainage. I would then have to climb back up to the 3200 foot  saddle  below
Quinault Ridge 5 where I had been  yesterday.  From  there  I  would  be  on
familiar territory back to camp. I tried not to  think  about  the  1300  ft
ascent to come. One step at a time. First get to the trail. Fortunately  the
line I chose down was not too bad. It was steep and I had to be careful  but
there were no cliffs, I was soon out of the snow and the forest was not  all
that brushy by Olympic standards. I stumbled onto the trail  at  9:00.  Step
one accomplished. (Note: Should anyone be crazy  enough  to  want  to  climb
Wooded Pk this would be the way to go, up and down.)

Next to get to the saddle. The trail was  good  enough  I  could  follow  it
without a headlamp for another 15 minutes to  the  crossing  of  Zeigler  Cr
where I filled up on much needed water. I continued up the  trail  using  my
headlamp on its lowest beam. This was easy going until I  hit  the  snowline
at about 2500. Then I lost the trail completely  in  horrible  terrain  with
700 feet still to go. I had trouble finding the right  line  up  this  steep
hillside without the use of a trail and with a wimpy light that  continually
got dimmer and  dimmer.  My  GPS  helped  but  I  still  kept  running  into
unexpected small cliffs and wandered up and down to find  a  route.  And  by
now my GPS batteries were also getting low. More to worry about.

I finally pulled over the ridge at 11:30 where I picked up my tracks of  the
day before, but I was so worn out by now it took another hour for this  last
step to camp. Both my headlamp and GPS had continued  to  work.  I  was  too
tired to make a real dinner. I just drank lots of liquids, quickly downed  a
Hammer recovery bar and crashed in my sleeping bag.  Freddy,  on  the  other
hand, was in great shape.

Day Total: 5.5 miles, 4900 ft and 13:40 hrs

Saturday, May 4 - I slept in till 9:00, ate breakfast, fell back asleep  and
finally left at noon. I actually felt better than I thought I had any  right
to on the way out. Maybe I  was  just  happy  to  simply  have  survived  my
adventure.

Day Total: 2.5 miles and 1:45 hrs

Trip Total: 12.5 miles and 8500 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen



