            'tr' => '
Capitol Pk (5054 ft - P1494 - Mt Tebo Quad), Capitol Pk, W  Pk  (4949  ft  -
P349 - Wynoochee Lk Quad) and Pk 4375 (P535 - Mt Hoquiam Quad) -  May  8-10,
2013

I had originally planned to climb Capitol  Pk  from  the  S  Fork  Skokomish
River trail up the north side, but that entails two bridgeless crossings  of
the river which I thought would be difficult with the  recent  warm  weather
and high snow melt.  So I changed to an approach from  the  Wynoochee  River
and Copper Creek Pass. This  route  first  climbs  over  Pk  4949  and  then
follows the connecting ridge to the south side of  Capitol  Peak.  I  wasn\'t
sure how this would go as the ridge looked steep and rocky on  the  map  but
at least I wouldn\'t have to contend with fast water.

Wednesday, May 8: Pk 4375 - I drove the long road  up  the  Wynoochee  River
valley past Wynoochee Lake (a total of 42.2 miles from Hwy 12) to  spur  300
where Rd 2270 goes left to cross the river. This  spur  only  goes  .4  mile
farther before being blocked at 1900 ft. Parking is very tight  at  the  end
and turning around a challenge.  The abandoned road has turned into  a  very
pleasant trail for hiking. It gets some traffic as it is also  the  approach
for Wynoochee Pt, the Grays Harbor  CoHP.  At  about  2800  ft  I  ran  into
consistent snow. At 3500 I  came  to  Copper  Creek  Pass  and  my  intended
campsite. I was lucky to find a flat bare spot melted out  on  the  edge  of
the road to pitch my tent (2.5 miles, 1700 ft, 2:25 hrs).

After setting up camp I headed for Pk 4375, continuing  north  on  the  road
from the pass until below the peak. I avoided cliffs by climbing steep  snow
to the SW ridge which I then followed to the small rocky summit. I was  back
in camp well before dark (3 miles, 1000 ft, 4 hrs RT). This ended  up  being
an interesting but not too difficult bonus peak that had the  added  benefit
of providing a nice view of Capitol Pk and the first part of  the  route  to
Pk 4949.

Day Total: 5.5 miles, 2700 ft and 6:25 hrs

Thursday, May 9: Capitol Pk and Pk 4949 - With the  insight  I  gained  from
the Pk 4375 view I climbed left from Copper Creek Pass to a snow gully  that
avoided the initial steep cliffy area. At  the  top  of  the  gully  I  then
traversed right in forest under more cliffs until  reaching  easier  terrain
that led straight up to open snow slopes below Wynoochee Pt. Although  I  am
not really into county high points, since I was so close I took  the  slight
detour to that high point before climbing Pk 4949 (1450 ft, 2:20 hrs).

From Pk 4949 the route looked nasty. I wasn\'t even sure where the  ridge  to
Capitol started or how to get onto it as the first part was rather  obscure,
steep and brushy. But once on the ridge it wasn\'t really  all  that  bad  if
you went the right way. However there were many ups and  downs  and  it  was
slow going. Except for dropping on the north side to a low point of 4500  ft
to get past a pinnacle, I found it best to stay right  on  the  crest  until
coming to Pt 4840. This I then passed high on the south side  only  to  drop
again to the saddle with the main peak. A traverse under  cliffs  led  to  a
snow gully on the right that ended on the SE ridge. The final  summit  ridge
looked very intimidating but did lay back as I got closer,  except  for  the
last 40 feet. I struggled up the initial slab via a crack  on  the  left  to
where it eased at a ledge, went up and through a notch and on to the  summit
(2300 ft, 5 hrs).

I found a summit register in a large container but the booklet  was  such  a
sodden mess it was totally useless. I was really disappointed  as  I  wanted
to see when this peak was last climbed. I don\'t  think  it  is  very  often.
Will those who place registers ever  learn  that  you  MUST  USE  WATERPROOF
PAPER? All homemade registers seem to leak and  regular  paper  never  lasts
long. I placed my new smaller register inside the old  larger  one.  (As  an
interesting  sidebar,  although  I  am  not  sure  why,  the  register  also
contained a dollar bill that was in good condition. Our currency is  printed
on quality paper.)  I also found a benchmark  with  the  identification  "Mt
Church". Has the name changed since the benchmark was  placed  in  1949?  Mt
Church is actually the peak 1.5 miles to the  south  (another  good  climb).
Oddly the benchmark is also named Mt Church right next to the peak  name  of
Capitol Pk on the 7.5 minute USGS Mt Tebo Quad.

After an hour on top enjoying the views and drying my socks in  the  sun,  I
left at 2:30.  I  rappelled  the  rock  pitch  using  a  sling  on  a  horn,
downclimbed to the top of the gully and did two more rappels off trees  down
the top section. I could have downclimbed it but it was quite steep and  the
snow was soft with steps breaking out. I tend to be very careful  when  solo
climbing as I cannot afford to make any mistakes. I then  just  followed  my
footsteps back. It was easier as now I knew exactly where to go but  it  was
still slow going and much of it was up. It took just as long to get back  to
Pk 4949 as it had taken coming. Then it was all downhill  to  camp  which  I
reached at the refreshingly early hour of 6:15. I still had time to  go  out
but I had a nice camp, it was a beautiful day, I  was  in  no  hurry  and  I
really didn\'t want to drive home in the dark.  So  I  stayed  another  night
relaxing and enjoying the views and sounds  of  nature.  I  also  watched  a
video of one my favorite series, "I Shouldn\'t Be  Alive."  I  like  watching
that because I can relate to many of the episodes and could even  contribute
a few of my own.

Day Total: 3 miles, 3000 ft and 8:00 hrs

Friday, May 10 - All I had to do was hike out which I  did  in  short  order
reaching the car at 9:15.

 Day Total: 2.5 miles and 1:15 hrs

Trip Total: 11 miles, and 5700 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen



