Chelan Lakeshore Trail: Moore Point to Prince Creek - May 26-27, 2013

A change of pace backpack with my son  Walter  and  daughter-in-law  Jessica
that we did after first spending two nights at our cabin in Douglas  County.
It ended up being a delightful trip. We did a shorter version  and  went  in
the opposite direction than is usual, starting at Moore Point and ending  at
Prince Creek. Most people start at Prince Creek and  go  to  Stehekin.   But
this worked very well for a holiday weekend as it resulted in  running  into
much fewer people. The weather was constantly threatening  and  unseasonably
cool but we had no serious  rain.  The  high  peaks  stayed  mostly  in  the
clouds.

On Sunday we took the boat to  Moore  Point.  On  this  middle  day  of  the
holiday weekend  the  boat  was  surprisingly  empty.  However  Moore  Point
campground was very crowded and 30 Boy Scouts  were  waiting  to  board  for
Stehekin. Once on the trail things thinned rapidly. We saw maybe  3  parties
this first day all going the other way. The section of the  Lakeshore  Trail
we hiked does not really follow the  shore  and  is  not  really  level  but
immediately climbs 3-400 feet above the Lake and for  the  most  part  stays
there with many small ups and downs until near  Prince  Creek.  Much  of  it
traverses through the 2001 Rex Creek Fire. This is not  all  bad  as  it  is
regenerating nicely and the thinned trees allow  for  better  views  of  the
lake. We camped at Cascade Creek Camp  which  is  right  on  the  shore  and
requires dropping over 300 feet on a side trail to access  it.  We  had  the
entire camp to ourselves. Who would have thought this possible on a  holiday
weekend along a popular trail!

On Monday we continued to Prince Creek.  I  found  this  section  particular
scenic. The trail alternated between open rocky benches, grassy meadows  and
weaving in and out of lush gullies.  The  terrain  was  quite  varied,  more
vegetated and wetter than  I  expected,  and  always  in  constant  view  of
beautiful Lake Chelan. After crossing Rex Creek short switchbacks  descended
all the way to lake level to avoid a sheer cliff, immediately  climbed  back
up again, and then began a gradual final descent to Prince Creek. Near  here
we ran into a couple who had started at Prince Creek  two  days  before  and
were now returning. They were the only people we encountered going the  same
direction as we were. It was fortunate we ran into them as they  knew  where
the boat would land on the shore. It  was  not  obvious  to  us  as  it  was
several hundred feet away from the dock. The campground  was  deserted.  The
boat was 40 minutes late picking us up and jam packed, not surprising  given
the departing crowds up lake. But since the weather had  taken  a  turn  for
the bad with wind driven drizzle as we waited, we were just  happy  to  make
it to the protection of the boat.

Trip Total: 11.4 miles and 2600 ft in 2 days (5.2 miles & 1100  ft  -  Moore
Pt to Cascade Creek Camp; 6.2 miles and 1500 ft  -  Cascade  Creek  Camp  to
Prince Cr)

Fay Pullen



