            'tr' => '
Mt Misery Highline  - Diamond Pk (6379 ft - P779) and Mt Misery (6366  ft  -
P526) - Diamond Pk Quad - also Horse Ridge, Elk Flat and Al  Williams  Ridge
- May 31 - June 2, 2013

I made my first trip to the  beautiful  Wenaha-Tucannon  Wilderness  of  the
Blue Mountains in extreme SE Washington last October to climb Oregon  Butte.
That was a few days before hunting season started  and  already  the  Teepee
parking lot was full with horse parties getting a head start to claim  their
campsites. This is a very popular place with hunters and I do not  recommend
visiting then. But June, when meadow  wildflowers  are  at  their  peak,  is
another matter. I also timed it so the  higher  (5850  ft)  Diamond  TH  was
still closed due to snow which assured solitude near Diamond Pk.

Friday, May 31 - I started from the lower (3200 ft) Panjab TH just  after  a
party of 4 from Spokane. They asked me to  take  their  picture.  They  were
only going to Indian Corral and coming out the next day.  The  Panjab  Trail
follows lush Panjab Creek for 5 miles before breaking out of the  forest  at
the Mt Misery Trail junction. A  short  ways  on  I  passed  the  Spokane  4
setting up camp. After that I saw no one the rest of the trip.

Why this trail is named Misery I have no idea. It is anything  but.  It  has
to be one of the premiere ridge routes in the state.  I  was  totally  blown
away  by  the  miles  of  gorgeous  open  meadows  filled  with  carpets  of
wildflowers. Never have  I  seen  such  extensive  meadows  for  so  long  a
distance. Meadows were everywhere I looked in every  direction.  The  entire
distance from Indian Corral to Mt Misery stays above 5600 ft but  since  the
trail is mostly on the south side of the ridge the snow was almost  entirely
melted except for forested sections. I was surprised by how  wet  the  tread
was. Seeps were plentiful and fed floral displays. I am sure these  all  dry
up by summer but springs are also common along the way and are  said  to  be
reliable. I made it to one of these, Clover Spring, which had cleverly  been
rigged to provide a hose of  flowing  water.  I  found  a  perfect  campsite
nearby in the trees.

Day Total: 7.6 miles, 3000 ft and 5:45 hrs

Saturday, June 1 - I continued on along the trail from Clover  Spring  at  a
leisurely pace enjoying every step. This section had  more  wooded  sections
and I ran into more snow then the previous day, but I also had better  views
south into the heart of Wenaha-Tucannon Wilderness and beyond to  Oregon.  I
passed Bear Wallow, Squaw, Sheephead and  Diamond  Springs,  all  with  nice
camps. But Squaw was mostly snowed in, Diamond  completely  snowed  in,  and
the springs for the other two a ways downhill off the trail.  After  passing
the junction to Diamond Peak, I soon came to the road at the Diamond TH.  Mt
Misery is not actually in the wilderness but  I  was  under  the  impression
there was still a trail up it. If so I never found it. I ended up  following
the road to  where  I  could  climb  up  the  west  ridge.  I  was  somewhat
disappointed with this turn of events. How could the Mt Misery Trail not  go
to Mt Misery? Perhaps it did so at one time.

On the return I took the side trail, mostly under snow, up Diamond  Peak.  I
found a register declaring this the Garfield County High Point at  6379  ft.
This is at odds with Lists of John which  calls  the  rounded  bump  to  the
west, at 6380 one foot higher, the CoHP because it uses  average  elevations
and not clean elevations as its base. My feeling is Diamond  Pk  is  higher.
Whatever, I climbed them both since I am compelled to climb  every  and  all
bumps anyway. So I guess I ticked off another CoHP unintentionally.

 Views from the summit were nice as long as you looked away from  the  radio
tower on top. Diamond Peak is in the wilderness. Let me see if I  understand
this correctly. You can\'t leave rappel slings or bolts in a  wilderness  but
a  radio  tower  is  okay?  Seem  contradictory  to  me  but  maybe  it  was
grandfathered in.

Near camp I ran into a fresh bear track in the snow  that  wasn\'t  there  in
the morning. Sobering but I had hung my food high. I also  saw  7  deer  and
many tracks of elk. Wildlife is plentiful.

Day Total: 14.6 miles, 3000 ft and 10:45 hrs

Sunday, June 2 - I was intrigued by Elk Flat that I saw on the map  near  my
camp, and before heading out I had to go for a visit. Evidently  others  had
the same idea as a faint trail led from Clover Spring to  it.  It  surpassed
my expectations and even in an area of spectacular meadows Elk  Flat  stands
out. I came across the thickest carpet of grass  widow  wildflowers  I  have
ever seen. It was well worth the side trip.

Side trip to Elk Flat: 2.8 miles, 350 ft and 1:30 hrs RT from camp.

On the trip out I stayed on  the  Mt  Misery  Trail  1.2  miles  beyond  the
junction with the Panjab Trail so I could  climb  Al  Williams  Ridge.   The
ridge itself was rather anti-climatic compared to what had gone  before  but
it did allow me to prolong being in meadows for a while longer and  to  vary
the return route.  All morning I watched thunderheads  build.  They  reached
their climax while I was on the summit and I had to  hurry  off  the  ridge.
Naturally the rain hit with the  worst  possible  timing,  as  I  descending
steep brushy forest to intersect the Panjab Trail. It didn\'t rain  long  but
it was enough get both the brush and me wet. Once I was on the  trail  again
it quit.

Trip out: 8.5 miles, 550 ft and 5:30 hrs

Trip Total: 33.5 miles and 7000 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen

