            'tr' => '
Kitling Pass Peaks - Pk 6865 (P505 - Mt Logan Quad) and Pk 6882 (P682  -  Mt
Arriva Quad) - June 7-9, 2013

Jim graciously allowed me to tag along on his trip with Kevin and Eileen  to
a base camp at Kitling Pass.  While the three of  them  then  climbed  Kimta
(which I had already done years ago), I entertained myself  with  these  two
lesser peaks north of the pass. While not in the  same  category  as  higher
Ragged Ridge they were both  very  enjoyable  scrambles  in  a  very  scenic
setting. In fact I would consider a trip to Kitling Pass in  and  of  itself
well worth the trip.

Weather was partly sunny all three days, with minor  short  lived  sprinkles
Friday going in and some high fog late Saturday afternoon.

Friday, June 7 - We took the Easy Pass Trail to about  4000  feet  and  then
contoured for over a mile through reasonable forest (some  minor  brush  and
downed trees) to Kitling  Creek.  Snow  began  shortly  after  entering  the
valley at 4200 ft. We followed the creek through an open basin (short  patch
of slide alder to bash through) past Kitling Lake to Kitling Pass.  This  is
an  unusually  broad  interesting  feature,  over  a  quarter   mile   long,
connecting Kitling and Panther Creeks. We camped at  the  far  west  end  in
full view of Mesahchie and Kimta Peaks, elevation 5960 ft. Truly a  gorgeous
spot.

Day Total: 4.5 miles, 2400 ft and 5:30 hrs.

Saturday, June 8 - I had a leisurely morning, starting  a  full  hour  after
watching the others take off for Kimta. I began  by  climbing  to  the  wide
6300 ft saddle directly north of camp. Heading for Pk 6865 first, I  decided
a ridge route looked questionably so descended  about  400  ft  to  traverse
under cliffs to a gully that allowed a way back up  to  the  corniced  ridge
very near the summit. I reached the top at 11:30 (1300 ft, 2:30 hrs). I  had
a stunning view of the entire length of Ragged Ridge and spent an  enjoyable
hour in the sun absorbing it. I had hoped to spot my friends as I could  see
the majority of their route but I was not able to do so.

The actual summit was a snow mound so I don\'t know if  a  cairn  was  buried
underneath. In any event I built one of my own and placed a  small  register
in the rocks just below before leaving. Just for fun I tried  to  return  by
staying on the ridge, but as I feared it did not go. I  ended  up  retracing
my up route. Once below the cliffs I began a long traverse around  the  head
of the basin to regain the ridge of Pk 6882. This gentle ridge  was  a  pure
delight, though it did seem to go on forever. There was also  a  short  rock
step to overcome. I reached the summit at 4:30 (2750 ft, 7:30 hrs)  where  I
found no cairn. Here Ragged Ridge was somewhat obstructed  by  the  Pk  6865
ridge but I did have nice views of Gabriel, Elijah and Beebe.

I left at 5:00 and was back to camp by  6:45.  Not  surprising,  my  friends
were not back yet. I really didn\'t  expect  them  for  several  more  hours.
Meanwhile I relaxed and ate dinner. When they still hadn\'t shown  up  as  it
began to get dark (and cold) I turned in. I was awaked by  their  return  at
11:00 and stayed up until 12:00 entertained by tales  of  their  adventures.
They were happy but very tired climbers.

Day Total: 5 miles, 3050 ft and 9:45 hrs

Sunday, June 9 - Considering the late night we got going at  the  reasonable
hour of 9:00. On the trip out through Kitling Basin we  came  upon  a  fresh
avalanche that had not been there on the way in. It had started  high  above
and come down a scary looking  deep  gully  to  spread  out  a  considerable
distance over the flattish basin. A reminder  that  slides  that  can  still
happen at any time. We took the forest traverse on a better lower tack  than
our in route and hit the trail right at the bridge over  Granite  Creek.  It
couldn\'t have been more perfect.

Day Total: 4.5 miles, 100 ft and 4:45 hrs

Trip Total: 14 miles and 5550 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen







