Mt Torment (8120+ ft - P200 - Forbidden Pk Quad) - June 14-17, 2013

The third time is the charm. I had tried Torment twice last year, first  via
the SE Face (stopped by the moat) then via the South Ridge (stopped by  lack
of time and sketchy loose exposed rock).  Then Tom told me he had skied  the
NW Glacier (in a day!) and thought it might be a viable route for me. If  he
had skied it how hard could it be? Well a lot harder than  I  envisioned.  I
should have known. Tom had done it in mid-May 2011 when  snow  covered  many
of the obstacles and, after all, it was Tom who has no fear of  steep  snow.
That said I did make it go but it was dicey and I was almost too late.  This
route is best done in early season.

Friday, June 14 - I found the start of  climber\'s  trail  to  Torment  Basin
just past the bridge over the  Cascade  River,  elevation  2360  ft.  It  is
unmarked but there is a small turnout large enough  for  two  cars  directly
opposite. The trail is steep but fairly easily  followed  at  first  through
brushless forest along a rib near Torment Creek.  There  is  the  odd  cairn
here and there marking the way. After about 2000 ft I ran into a section  of
downed trees on a side hill. Above that I started running into  patchy  snow
and lost the trail completely, but nowhere was  anything  really  difficult.
Eventually I was forced left, crossing a minor creek to avoid  a  waterfall,
and soon after encountered solid snow slopes alongside a cliff  wall.  Above
that I entered wide open Torment Basin which is a  mirror  image  of  Boston
Basin but wilder. I found a tiny but comfortable  spot  for  my  bivy  on  a
minor rock rib with boulders conveniently  placed  for  a  table  and  chair
several hundred feet below Torment Col, elevation 6360. I was  surprised  to
intersect a fresh boot track coming from Boston Basin  very  near  here  and
continuing up. I wondered  where  this  party  was  headed.  I  found  water
dripping off a rock wall slightly above me.

Day Total: 2 miles, 4250 ft and 6:30 hrs

Saturday, June 15 - It froze  solid  during  the  night  and  crampons  were
needed from the get go. I followed the boot track to Torment Col (elev  6700
ft) where I discovered a party of eight had camped overnight. They had  left
slightly before I arrived and were heading up the slopes on More  Rain  Mtn.
My guess is they were on some long traverse, perhaps to Eldorado or  beyond.
There are nice places to camp at the col  and  there  was  even  a  pool  of
water.

From the col I descended easy slopes to  5800  ft.  Here  is  where  it  got
tricky. I had to cross the steep gully that goes down to Moraine  Lake,  get
onto the rock rib on the other side and somehow get onto the glacier  below.
Beckey mentions a 150 ft rappel and slab  problems  here.   I  managed  with
some down climbing and two rappels with my 120 ft rope. At the  last  rappel
I looked up and didn\'t think I could reverse it  so  decided  to  leave  the
rope in place. This left me without a  rope  for  the  rest  of  the  climb,
rather chancy.

I descended a bit more until I could gain access to the  snow  at  5600  ft.
This is a far western arm of the Forbidden Glacier generally referred to  as
the NW Glacier. Once on the snow it was pretty straightforward  until  below
the bergschrund (elev 7250 ft), although it  does  cross  a  vast  avalanche
deposition  zone  with  deep  slide  runnels  which  was  a  bit  unnerving.
Fortunately nothing came down while I was there. However, surrounding  areas
were active with icefalls all day long,  especially  the  lower  Inspiration
Glacier. I was happy to see a snow bridge crossing  the  left  side  of  the
bergschrund but it was thinner than it first appeared and I don\'t  think  it
will remain crossable for very long.

Above the bergschrund was 800 feet of consistent 40 degree snow with no  run
out. A slip would be a fall over cliffs or into  the  bergschrund  or  both.
This is what freaked me out the most. I almost threw in the towel  here  and
turned around. If the snow had been harder I would have.  The  view  up  the
unrelentingly steep slope was very intimidating. The only way I felt  secure
was to use the ice ax self-belay with every step. The snow was solid  enough
yet soft enough for this to work though I sometimes had to jam it 2-3  times
to get it all the way in. So I would jam the ax in, take a step and  repeat,
endlessly. Very slow and tiring. It seemed to take forever and there was  no
place to rest. It took close to 2 hours to do those  800  ft.  As  the  snow
gentled below the summit rocks I was elated to see the final bit was just  a
scramble. I pulled onto the  summit  at  3:00  (2800  ft,  7:30  hrs).   The
register was almost completely full but I found a small space to sign in.

I stayed about 40 minutes on the summit but could not fully enjoy  the  warm
sunshine and expansive views as I  was  very  worried  about  getting  down.
While there a medium slide came down over the top of  the  bergschrund  onto
my up route below. This did nothing to help my  confidence.  However,  going
down turned out not to be as  bad  as  anticipated  though  still  slow  and
intense and I had to concentrate completely. The snow was softer and  I  had
the use of my up steps and ax holes. The snow was still solid and  no  steps
broke out. After I gingerly crossed the berschrund I almost felt a  sign  of
relief but I still had one more major obstacle to surmount, the rappel.  The
snow lower down was very soft now and I postholed knee deep in places.

 I reached the rappel rope at 7:15. I proceeded to spend the next  1:45  hrs
trying to get up and could not. I first tried going  straight  up  the  rope
using a prusik belay but there were no holds. I  am  not  strong  enough  to
pull myself up by my arms. I really needed ascenders which I didn\'t have.  I
tried to the side where there were more holds but it was wet and  slick  and
a fall would result in a pendulum. I tried around the corner  but  the  rope
then wasn\'t above me and I essentially had  no  belay.  I  tried  again  and
again and failed. I envisioned myself falling  onto  the  prusik  unable  to
move up or down. What an ignominious end to it all that would  be.  What  is
the definition of insanity? Doing the same thing over  and  over  again  and
expecting a different result! This was not working. I was  too  hung  up  on
following the rope. I had  to  try  something  different.  That  is  when  I
decided to look at  the  gully.  It  appeared  sketchy  but  I  was  getting
desperate and so went for it. I rappelled into the gully and climbed up  the
steep snow. There were a couple of thin sections to get past but  they  were
not too bad. I remembered seeing an old rappel sling lower down  near  where
I got onto the glacier  and  it  now  occurred  to  me  that  other  parties
probably also got out by rappelling into the gully.

At 9:10 I topped out of the gully onto gentle slopes. I still  had  the  800
feet to climb up to Torment Col but the fact that I was safe now  and  would
not end my days on Torment gave an added spring to my step.  I  crossed  the
col, filled up on water at the pool and collapsed in camp at  11:00  totally
fried physically and especially mentally. I had surpassed my  tolerance  for
scary.

Day Total: 4 miles, 3850 ft and 15:30 hrs

Sunday: June 16 - I slept in until the sun hit my bivy at 8:30 and  left  at
10:45. It had not frozen overnight and the snow was soft and slushy. It  was
also sticky and tended to ball up on my boots. I had several  slips  due  to
this on the way down. I was so happy I had not had  these  snow  conditions,
which undermine what confidence I do have, on the climb itself. The rest  of
the trip out was straightforward and I reached the  car  at  2:30  happy  to
leave my torment behind.

Day Total: 2 miles, 50 feet and 3:45 hrs.

Trip Total: 8 miles and 8150 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen



