            'tr' => '
White Mtns (7045 ft - P405 - Clark Mtn Quad) - June 21-23. 2013

After Torment I was looking for  something  mellow  and  (relatively)  safe.
Jim graciously once again allowed me tag along to base camp  on  a  trip  of
his, this time to climb Clark Mtn via the Walrus Glacier.  I  would  not  be
doing Clark but saw that there was a peak south of Boulder Pass  I  had  not
climbed that could occupy my time while the others (Eileen, Deb,  Steve  and
Lisa) were on Clark. My main goal was to get out with friends yet not  trash
myself.

Friday: June 21 - We followed the  White  River  Trail  4  miles,  then  the
Boulder Creek trail another 4.5 miles to a camp in  Boulder  Basin  at  4900
ft. Both trails were in good shape, the only  impediment  to  travel  a  few
blow downs and the upper ford of Boulder Cr (cold!). We  found  bare  ground
just large enough to squeeze in two tents, side by side -  Deb  and  Steve\'s
and Lisa and mine. Jim and Eileen tented on snow. We arrived earlier in  the
day than usual which made for a leisurely sociable dinner and bedtime  while
still light.

Day Total: 8.5 miles, 3000 ft and 6 hrs

Saturday: June 22 - We all had breakfast together then the others  took  off
at 7:20. I left  about  an  hour  later  delayed  a  good  20  minutes  with
difficulties fitting my crampons to my new boots. They were  too  small  for
the connecting plate which I had to let hang over the heel.  I  should  have
checked this at home before leaving as I frequently  have  this  problem.  I
made them work on the hard snow of morning and began by climbing  up  slopes
directly east of camp. White Mtns turned out to be a lot more craggy than  I
expected with much of the west side essentially a  continuous  wall,  but  I
teased out a route up steepening snow to the highest  point  possible  where
the cliff was broken and short and an  easy  scramble.  Once  on  the  ridge
proper the west side was gentle  and  a  pleasant  walkup.   I  reached  the
summit at 12:00 (2100 ft, 3:45 hrs).

The day had started sunny, then clouded up to  the  point  where  Clark  was
shrouded in fog. I feared the weather was turning but I had warm  sun  again
for my hour summit stay. It  continued  to  improve  during  the  afternoon.
Before leaving I built a cairn and left a register.  It  was  too  early  to
return to camp so after I was below all the cliffs I continued  on  an  easy
traverse to Boulder Pass at 3:30. I could see my friend\'s tracks where  they
had dropped off the pass to head for the Walrus Glacier. Earlier in the  day
as I was climbing my peak had actually seen them on this slope  through  the
telephoto lens of my camera.

After enjoying the view for 30 minutes or  so  I  headed  down  to  camp.  I
wanted to return via the route of the  trail.  I  had  hoped  to  follow  my
friend\'s tracks but could not find them on this side of the  pass.  I  guess
the snow was too hard in the morning. I had a little  trouble  locating  the
trail but eventually did so with the help of my GPS. About half way  down  I
ran into a Mountaineer party of 9. They were planning to camp  at  the  pass
and climb the Walrus the next day. I think they were puzzled as where I  had
come from and what I had done. I am kind of used to that. I reached camp  at
5:00 and had plenty of time to dry clothes in the full sun  and  rest  until
everyone else showed up at 8:00. They were all on a summit high and  we  had
another fun sociable dinner together.

Day Total: 4.5 miles, 2750 ft and 8:45 hrs.

Sunday:  June  23  -  The  day  downed  cloudy  and  with  a   forecast   of
deteriorating weather we didn\'t tarry too long in camp. We left at 8:40  and
with very few stops reached the cars at 1:20. But during breakfast  we  took
the time to witness a landmark event - the first  meeting  between  Francine
and Freddy. I think it was love at first sight. I am going to have  to  keep
an eye on Freddy on future trips with Francine or I may find  him  wandering
off getting into mischief.

Day Total: 8.5 miles, 250 ft and 4:45 hrs.

Trip Total: 21.5 miles and 6000 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen



