            'tr' => '
Whatcom Pass - Red Face Mtn (7141 ft - P1341 - Mt Redoubt Quad) -  July  24-
28, 2013

This was the second annual Girl\'s Trip organized by Eileen (in  response  to
and at the same time as Jim\'s Guy\'s Trip). The main goal  was  to  have  fun
and enjoy each other\'s company. Some of us had also hoped to  climb  Whatcom
Peak but snow conditions  had  other  ideas  and  that  didn\'t  happen.  But
Whatcom Pass is a lovely area in itself,  beautiful  Tapto  Lakes  are  well
worth the price of admission and the cable car crossing  of  the  Chilliwack
River is a hoot. I also managed to get up Red Face Mtn ending  my  July  dry
streak of no summits. Also on this trip, in addition to Eileen  and  myself,
were Maria, Tiffany and Beth

Day 1 - We hiked up the very hot trail to Hannegan  Pass.  The  black  flies
that had started the previous week in the Pickets were  out  in  full  force
once again. From the pass we dropped into the Chilliwack  River  valley  and
camped at spacious US Cabin. Miraculously the bugs were  dormant  there  and
we had a pleasant evening.

Day Total: - 10 miles, 2150 ft and 7 hrs

Day 2 - A half mile from US Cabin we had the joy of crossing the  Chilliwack
River on the cable car. What a fun experience. I had never done this  before
and have never seen anything like this crossing in the  backcountry.  It  is
very safe and well engineered although it does require a little more  muscle
than my wimpy arms can supply alone. Past the cable car the trail  traverses
a mile to the bridge across Brush Cr. Shortly above that is the junction  to
Whatcom Pass. The trail is in good shape although somewhat  brushy  in  open
areas.  Black flies were bad. While resting at the  Graybeal  Camp  junction
who should we run into coming down the trail but Greg  on  his  marathon  24
miles trek to retrieve their car at Hannegan TH. Stefan and  Matt  had  gone
the other  way  out  to  Ross  Lake.  We  chatted  for  a  good  30  minutes
commiserating about none  of  us  getting  Crooked  Thumb.  We  pulled  into
Whatcom Camp at 5:00 having it all to ourselves. The black flies  diminished
in the evening only to be replaced by noseeums.

Day Total: 7 miles, 2700 ft and 8 hrs

Day 3 - Tiffany, Beth and I started for Whatcom Peak while Maria and  Eileen
lounged in camp planning to spend  the  day  at  Tapto  Lakes.  Eileen  also
thought she might go for Red Face Mtn above the lakes.  My  party  hiked  to
Whatcom Pass and took  the  climbers  trail  right  planning  on  traversing
around Whatcom to the easy south side. However, when we got a  look  at  the
Whatcom Glacier it was so broken up as to  look  impassible  to  us.  So  we
continued up the arm to the North Ridge. But on closer inspection  that  too
looked intimidating. It had more snow on the upper section than  I  expected
which was very steep and  very  exposed.  I  just  wasn\'t  mentally  up  for
anything that scary on this trip.

We all went back to Whatcom Pass. Beth returned to camp  to  drop  off  gear
and change boots  while  Tiffany  and  I  took  the  trail  to  Tapto  Lakes
together. I was planning to climb Red Face. On the ridge above the lakes  we
ran into Maria who had accompanied Eileen part way up Pt 6921 on her way  to
Red Face. Maria had enough and was heading down to the lakes. Tiffany and  I
continued up. On top of Pt 6921 we spotted Eileen past the saddle  near  the
Red Face ridge. At this point, with a nasty descent  to  the  saddle  below,
Tiffany had enough and retreated to  the  lakes.  I  still  hoped  to  catch
Eileen. I descended to the saddle, not difficult but slow and  not  terribly
pleasant, then went up loose rock to the ridge. Once on  the  ridge  it  was
quite enjoyable. I came upon Eileen waiting just below the summit  horn.  It
was more than she wanted to do  without  a  rope  and  since  she  had  been
waiting over 30 minutes was ready to leave.  I  was  determined  not  to  be
skunked again. The final bit was not more than class 3+  and  short  but  it
was very exposed. I managed to get up it by crawling along the  very  crest.
It was actually pretty fun. Not as much fun coming down but I  did  make  it
safely, and then headed back along the ridge to  near  the  saddle  with  Pt
6921. From there I went straight down to the  lakes  where  I  met  up  with
everyone else. We spent the rest  of  the  afternoon  relaxing,  eating  and
cooling off in the water. The lakes were gorgeous and  the  bugs  reasonable
so no one was in a hurry to leave. We finally left to reach camp at 7:30  by
which time at least the flies were gone.

Day Total: 6 miles, 4050 ft and 11:30 hrs

Day 4 - We hiked down the trail, had good times on the  cable  car  crossing
again then hiked up to Copper Cr Camp for the night. While we  were  gone  a
group of boy scouts were doing some  badly  needed  brushing  of  the  trail
which was much appreciated. They were camped at US Cabin.

Day Total: 9.5 miles, 1100 ft and 8 hrs

Day 5 - This day was a little cooler than on  the  way  in  which  helped  a
little with both the bugs and the heat  climbing  to  Hannegan  Pass  again.
Still the trip out seemed longer than it should be what with feet tired  and
sore from multiple long July trips.

Day Total: 7.5 miles, 2050 ft and 5:45 hrs

Trip Total: 40 miles and 12,050 ft in 5 days

