            'title' => undef,
            'tr' => 'Even though we didn\'t make the summit of Crooked Thumb, Eileen and I had a grand adventure venturing into the remote and beautiful northern Pickets with just the two of us, one I will cherish always. We sure gave it our all and got darn close (to 170 ft of the top) and had great fun meeting the many challenges and problems thrown our way. We worked very well together as a team. If it weren\'t for the bad luck of having the only rain in the entire month of July coincide with our two summit days we probably would have made it. 

Day 1 - We caught the boat for Big Beaver at 1:00 and hiked to Luna Camp.
Day Total: 11 miles, 1400 ft and 6 hrs

Day 2 - We continued on the trail to just before Big Beaver Shelter and headed up Eiley-Wiley Ridge. We had been up this way last year and I had waypoints marked on my GPS that helped us find the best way to the ridge. Our route was almost brush free except for that which cannot be avoided at the beginning in the flat crossing the creeks. Once past that it is semi open forest. It is however very steep duff with poor footing and I especially suffered in the heat with a pack much heavier than I am accustomed to. We broke out into subalpine terrain about 5500 ft and picked up the remarkably good climber\'s trail along the ridge. At a 6200 ft notch where the ridge turned cliffy we dropped left on a steep grass and dirt traverse into a lovely basin with a bubbling pool at 6000 ft for camp 2.
Day Total: 6.5 miles, 4300 ft and 10 hrs

Day 3 - We climbed back up to about 6600 ft and traversed below cliffs at a key spot marked by a cairn through some thick scrub then descended and followed open crest up and down past first Eiley then Wiley Lake. This section of the route is delightful and very scenic. We were making good time and ahead of schedule until hitting the notch closely SE of Pk 7374. It was easily gained but a 20 ft vertical snow wall on the other side prevented direct access to the route off the other side onto the Challenger Glacier. Where the heck did this come from? I don\'t remember it from last year. We had to drop about 400 ft to work our way past the wall then climb up again. Once on the Challenger Glacier it was easily followed to the West Challenger Notch although there were more crevasses opened up than last year even though we were earlier in the season.
At the West Challenger notch we found a rap sling at the skier\'s right gully which lured me into going down that way. The better gully is the one on the skiers left.  The rap was very awkward with a full pack and our rope (37 M) wasn\'t quite long enough. We had to downclimb into the moat and climb out of it. We lost more time here. Continuous snow, steep at first, led down to the gentle glacier below which had a surprising number of parallel small crevasses. Fortunately they were all easily stepped over. We headed for a rock rib at the far edge expecting to find bivy sites. We found none. So while I went in search of water (I found none) Eileen worked on excavating a spot for our tiny tent. Meanwhile the wind kicked up and by the time we put up the tent it was blowing steadily at 40-50 mph. It took us over an hour to get the thing up and reinforced so the wind wouldn\'t blow it away. Low on water with the wind threatening all night to shred the tent we got little sleep that night, which didn\'t bode well for our summit day on the morrow.
Day Total:  6 miles, 3500 ft and 12 hrs

Day 4 - Somehow my tent made it intact through the night. The wind was still blowing in the morning, but with somewhat less intensity, which contributed to a late start. We headed up the right side of the glacier encountering several large crevasses at the steepest section. It leveled off to a flat area above where we began a downward traverse to the base of the hidden snow finger. I was dismayed to discover that a very steep slope with a moat almost all the way across guarded access to the finger and that it was rock hard. We protected it with our 2 flukes but I was totally freaked out and very slow. I almost gave up here. What kept me going was I didn\'t want to downclimb with the snow so hard. Once I reached the finger proper things improved as it was in the sun, softer and not as steep. Where the snow ended we moved right into a rock gully, scrambled to the headwall, took ledges right and worked our way onto the ridge. The section along the ridge with big blocks was actually fun. Near the summit horn I got confused as to how to corkscrew around to the south side. I first took a low ledge that led nowhere. By the time I found the proper ledge it was 5:00 and we could see weather heading our way. In fact it looked as if it was already raining all around us. Had the weather looked stable I believe we would have elected to continue with an enroute bivy. But no way did we want to be on the peak in rain. So reluctantly, within 170 ft of the summit, we turned around and started down at 5:30. Several rappels got us down the rock. The snow was much softer now but we still protected the steep section with flukes. We made it back to camp at 10:00 just as it began to rain in earnest. It rained steadily all night, with wind and thunder added for good measure.
Day Total: 1 mile, 1500 ft and 12:30 hrs

Day 5 - It was still raining in the morning so we went back to sleep. We didn\'t even consider Phantom. Our climbing trip was all but ended. About noon the rain and wind quit so we packed up and left at 1:00. Out immediate concern was how to get back over the West Challenger Notch. We didn\'t think we could climb up our rappel route on climbers left, at least not with full packs. This time though we checked out the other notch on climbers right. It was much easier and could be scrambled. We should have gone that way in the first place, but the bridge across the moat was thin and didn\'t look like it would last much longer. Once at the notch we thought our troubles were over only to be confronted by a complete whiteout on the Challenger Glacier. This caused some consternation as we tiptoed slowly down while waiting for gaps in the fog to appear so we could find the route. Soon we were below the fog and joyously made our way to my favorite campsite in the whole wide world (below Pk 7473). I have now camped there 4 times in 3 different years. It is truly a gorgeous spot.
Day Total: 2.5 miles, 1300 ft and 6 hrs

Day 6 - The day dawned clear. We took it easy stopping often to enjoy the spectacular scenery. All we had to do was get to the basin of camp 2. Our only obstacle was getting off Pk 7473 which we did by following the ridge north to an easy step onto the glacier above Wiley Lake. We pulled into camp at 4:30 with lots of time to wash up, rest and rehydrate with plentiful water.
Day Total: 3.5 miles, 1000 ft and 6 hrs

Day 7 - Our goal today was Luna Camp. Once back on the ridge we enjoyed our last pleasant rest on a scenic promontory before plunging steeply down to Big Beaver. We had a slight misstep by following a well beaten trail to the left that soon ended in brush. We knew we needed to be farther right to get on our up route and worked our way in that direction. The route was good but during our time up high there had been a hatch of black flies that tormented us all the way down. It was so bad that even Eileen, who always hikes in shorts, had to cover up with long sleeves and pants. They were with us most of the way to Luna Camp.
Day Total: 6.5 miles, 700 ft and 9 hrs

Day 8 - We hiked to Big Beaver landing, caught the boat at 2:30 and hike up to the Ross Lake TH to end another fantastic trip into the remarkable Northern Pickets.
Day Total: 11 miles, 1000 ft and 6 hrs

Trip Total: 48 miles and 14,700 ft in 8 days
