            'tr' => '
Baekos Pk (7529 ft - P449 - Glacier Pk West Quad) - August 7-9, 2013

Baekos is an attractive multi-pinnacled peak rising above  the  NW  edge  of
the White Chuck Glacier on Glacier Peak. It caught my eye when Mike T and  I
climbed Kololo two years ago but we  didn\'t  have  the  time  or  energy  to
include it on that trip. It gave me a good excuse to return to lovely  White
Chuck Basin. However, I could find no beta at all for this peak and knew  no
one who had climbed it. It did look as if it could  be  difficult  but  just
how difficult I had no clue. So I went prepared  with  rope,  harness,  full
alpine rack and crampons. As it turned out I only used the rope but  it  was
a close call. All this uncertainty added to the allure as I love  to  figure
out my own route on seldom climbed peaks.

Wednesday, August 7 - Jim Brisbine had organized a 6 day trip with  7  other
people (beginning the previous  Sunday)  starting  from  Lost  Creek  Ridge,
going over Glacier Peak via the Kennedy  Glacier  and  Frostbite  Ridge  and
coming out the North Fork Sauk. I had no interest in a carryover on  Glacier
but thought this would the perfect opportunity to go for Baekos. Their  last
camp would be in Foam Creek Basin which would also make a  great  base  camp
for me for two nights. If all went well I would meet up  with  them  at  the
end of both our climbs, though I  was  totally  prepared  for  this  not  to
happen.

Starting from the North Fork Sauk TH at 10:45, it  was  5.5  easy  miles  on
excellent trail to Mackinaw Shelter. However, my pack  was  heavier  than  I
would have liked loaded as it was with climbing gear  and  I  was  not  very
fast. I was even slower beyond the shelter as I plodded up the  interminable
switchbacks in the heat of day plagued by biting black flies. I suffered  on
this section. Both the bugs and the heat diminished as I neared White  Pass.
Things improved even more on the lovely Foam Creek Trail,  but  my  intended
campsite in Foam Creek Basin still seemed a long ways off (a good  2  miles)
and I was running out of time. I followed this trail, which has  become  the
main route for climbing Glacier Peak and is well used, to  a  cairn  marking
the junction with the climber\'s path going uphill. Past here the Foam  Creek
Trail rapidly fades until I lost it completely. Steep terrain bars a  direct
descent into Foam Creek Basin. I had to drop about 500 feet only  to  regain
200 to get to my intended camp where I found a flat site at 7:45 right  next
to a babbling creek. However, even though I had had very little all  day,  I
now had gale force winds that hampered putting up my tent,  using  my  stove
for dinner and kept me awake much of the night. Where  the  heck  did  these
come from?

Day Total: 11.5 miles, 4700 ft and 9 hrs

Thursday, August 8 - It was still windy in the morning, though much less  so
and I was able to get the stove going for a cup of hot tea.  I  started  for
Baekos at 7:45 by climbing uphill to intersect  the  climber\'s  trail  going
over 6600 ft "Foam Pass" where I was greeted by a  gorgeous  view  of  White
Chuck Basin and Glacier Peak. I dropped on the climber\'s trail  then  headed
straight for Baekos at the far end of the basin. It ended  up  being  harder
to get to than it had first appeared. I could not  make  a  direct  approach
due to a large meltwater lake (not shown on the  map  and  evidently  a  new
addition formed by the receding glacier) that was difficult to  get  around.
I had to go up over a shoulder then down awful  loose  steep  dirt  to  drop
into the basin at the foot of my peak, below the  large  lake,  where  there
was a second smaller lake. Then I had  to  get  across  the  rushing  outlet
creek (the headwaters of the White Chuck River). I could see no  way  across
other than wading. It was not that wide but it was fast and the water  milky
so I could not tell how deep it was and the footing was insecure.

Once across the creek I headed uphill to a broad saddle  SE  of  the  summit
staying right of an unattractive gully on steep  but  easy  heather.  I  had
hoped that an easy route would present itself once at the saddle. Instead  I
was dismayed by a series of difficult looking pinnacles and  cliffs.  I  had
no idea where to go from  here.  So  I  sat  down  to  have  a  snack  while
pondering the situation. To aid  in  the  description  I  have  labeled  the
pinnacles 1 to 3 starting from the saddle. I first had to get past  pinnacle
1 directly above and left of the saddle. I could see  a  ramp  heading  left
across its face but I feared this would lead to  an  impasse  on  the  other
side. The right side was all cliff. Across the saddle a steep snowslope  led
up between pinnacle 1 and pinnacle 2 but I couldn\'t see how far it went  and
it appeared to end in a cliff. Still, this seemed my  best  bet.  So  off  I
went in that direction. Miraculously I was able to exit the snow at  a  nice
spot onto class 3 rock that  I  could  easily  scramble  to  a  notch  below
pinnacle 2.

Once at the notch I  could  see  nowhere  else  to  go  except  directly  up
pinnacle 2, which looked beyond my capabilities. Still, I had  to  try.  The
first part was much easier than it had appeared. Then  I  came  to  a  wall.
Here I put on my harness and geared up just in case. I also left  everything
else behind except my PLB, water bottle and register to  make  the  climbing
moves easier. As it turned out I was able to traverse  to  the  right  below
the wall and then go up a series of ledges. There was  nothing  harder  than
class 4, if even that, but it was exposed and the rock loose.  I  went  very
slowly carefully testing each hold. I never used my rope or pro.

I pulled over the top of pinnacle 2 thinking I had it made only to  see  the
summit still .1 mile away and a pinnacle 3 in the way. Again it was  not  as
hard as it first appeared (I was able to bypass pinnacle  3  easily  on  the
left) and in fact was an enjoyable mostly ridge top scramble. I reached  the
summit at 1:15 (2600 ft, 5:50 hrs). I stayed only long  enough  to  build  a
cairn, place my register and snap some photos as  my  food  and  more  water
were back at the base of the wall. To return I did one rappel  directly  off
the end of pinnacle 2 over the wall to avoid downclimbing the exposed  ledge
traverse. With that out of the way I could then relax and  enjoy  eating  my
lunch.

I reversed the rest of my route without difficulty. Once down  to  the  lake
basin I decided to return by going past Pk 6810 via a route I saw  from  the
summit as I didn\'t want to repeat  the  loose  slope  above  the  big  lake.
Actually, this way was no better and I ran into more awful loose steep  dirt
traverses. I guess there is no pleasant way to  the  lake  basin  after  the
snow has melted. But once on the flat to the  SE,  which  contained  another
tarn, it was easy going up the ridge to the summit of Pk 6810  (P390)  where
I had a great view of my route up Baekos.

From 6810 I wandered pleasant terrain past more tarns and meadows to make  a
loop through White Chuck Basin and  reconnect  with  my  in  route.  Shortly
below Foam Pass, at about 5:45, I spied a  party  of  3  crossing  the  snow
above me. It turned out to be Steve, Tim and Cassie. What luck to  run  into
Jim\'s party coming off Kololo. I hiked the rest of the way with  Steve.  Deb
and Eileen were already ahead near my camp and Jim, Beth and Kevin were  not
far behind in the other direction. We all united in camp. It was a good  day
for me in the mountains. I had a challenging successful solo climb  followed
by the company of good friends in camp. What could be better?

Day Total: 7.5 miles, 3900 ft and 10:45 hrs

Friday, August 9  -  I  hiked  to  White  Pass  with  Eileen.  Here  we  all
reconnected. Jim, Eileen, Kevin, Cassie and Tim  went  up  White  Mtn  while
Steve, Deb, Beth and I headed down the trail. I never  saw  Jim  and  Eileen
again. The switchbacks were miserably hot and buggy once again but at  least
we were going downhill. Fast Kevin, Tim and Cassie  caught  us  at  Mackinaw
and soon passed us never to be seen again either.   The  four  of  us  stuck
together the rest of the way out taking several long  breaks,  most  notably
at Red Creek to soak aching feet. Shortly before the  TH  we  had  one  loud
clap of thunder then a brief shower which actually felt good.

We reached the TH at 5:15. It would have  been  a  great  end  to  the  trip
except that I was greeted with a flat tire on  my  Subaru.  Steve  gallantly
changed it for me, and then followed me all the  way  to  Granite  Falls  to
make sure I reached civilization safely. That was  much  appreciated  as  my
spare was one of those "fake" small tire that do nothing to  make  you  felt
secure on back roads and adversely affect the handling of  an  AWD.  I  hate
those spares. All my jeeps have always had a full sized spare. Yes,  friends
are useful for things other than good company. Thank you Steve.

Day Total: 11.5 miles, 900 ft and 8:45 hrs

Trip Total: 30.5 miles and 9500 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen

P.S. I made it all the way home (over 100 miles) on  that  wimpy  spare  and
had the tire fixed the next day. The flat was caused by a sharp rock  caught
in the tread.



