            'title' => 'June 10th Pk (6019 ft - P1139 - Chimney Pk Quad) - August 13-15, 2013',
            'tr' => '
June 10th Pk (6019 ft - P1139 - Chimney Pk Quad) - August 13-15, 2013

This was essentially to be a reconnaissance trip to  see  if  Pyrites  Creek
would be a feasible route to approach seldom climbed  Chimney  Peak  and  Mt
Delabarre.  I knew my allotted 3 days was not enough time for either. But  I
did hope to get up one or more of the  peaks  located  around  the  head  of
Pyrites Creek. The forecast I had before leaving town was for light rain  to
come in Wednesday  after  6  pm  with  heavier  rain  that  night  and  into
Thursday. I thought this would give me enough time to do what  I  wanted  on
Wednesday. I could then go out in the rain. It didn\'t quite  work  out  that
way. And I may have to rethink this as a good route to  those  more  distant
peaks. It was not all that easy. Then again I doubt there is any easy way.

Tuesday, August 13 - I hiked up the Enchanted Valley Trail 9.5 miles  taking
5:15 hours to arrive at Pyrites Creek at 4:20. In  general  I  am  not  that
fond of long river trails, but this one is lovely  rainforest  and  the  day
was relatively cool with minimal bugs so it was fairly  pleasant  going.  On
the north side of the creek I headed uphill hoping  to  find  the  abandoned
trail. I did run into sections of it here and there but I couldn\'t  stay  on
it long and it wasn\'t that useful to  try  and  do  so.  The  old  trail  is
essentially gone. However, for the first  1000  feet  no  trail  was  really
needed in the open forest and it was often easier to just  go  straight  up.
After that the going got more difficult with more brush and steep  sidehill.
I made the mistake (corrected on the way down)  of  climbing  too  high  too
soon, ran into cliffs where I had to descend on very  steep  duff  to  avoid
them and probably lost an hour. By then it was getting late  enough  that  I
knew I wouldn\'t make my originally planned campsite at timberline  near  the
East Fork of Pyrites Creek. In fact I was  getting  desperate  to  find  any
place with water when I stumbled upon a site in the forest at  3600  ft  (so
flat it needed no embellishment) that had a small brook right  next  to  it.
What good luck! It was 8:20 and almost dark.

Day Total: 11.5 miles, 4300 ft and 9:20 hrs

Wednesday, August 14 - I decided my first goal of the day would be to  climb
June 10th Peak. To get to it I would have to make a long  horseshoe  circuit
around the head of Pyrites Creek. From camp I traversed to the  deep  ravine
of the East Fork and climbed along its edge in open forest to where I  could
cross near timberline at 4400 ft. This took an hour. Once across the  ravine
I proceeded on a long  up  and  down  traverse  through  alternating  brushy
meadows and steep forest to the 4840  ft  saddle  at  the  head  of  Pyrites
Creek. The occasional elk trail helped. I reached the saddle at 11:15  (1700
ft and 3:15 hrs). I dropped slightly from the saddle and picked  up  a  very
good elk trail that took me on  the  second  leg  of  the  horseshoe  across
seemingly impassible steep sidehill until past Pt 5565. From  there  meadows
and scree led to the NE ridge of  the  peak.  From  a  distance  this  ridge
looked straightforward but on closer inspection  was  more  convoluted  than
first appeared with a series of knobs and steps to overcome which I  did  by
staying mostly on the very crest. The climber\'s guide calls it class  2  but
that is an understatement. I have  come  to  expect  this  -  but  class  2?
Really?  Two steps in particular gave me pause. The first was  a  steep  fin
about 40 ft high which I surmounted head on. It was difficult enough that  I
rappelled it on the way down. The second was a very short (5 ft?) step  with
one class 4 move. Fortunately it had a branch belay on the left or  I  would
have wanted a rope for it also. The rest  of  the  ridge  was  an  easy  fun
scramble. I reached the summit  at  1:35,  having  taken  much  longer  than
anticipated (3000 ft, 5:35 hrs).

I stayed 20 minutes on top to eat lunch, take pictures, build  a  cairn  and
place a register. I still had views into  some  the  remotest  area  of  the
Olympics but I could see weather coming and hurried  to  get  off  the  rock
before it hit. Sure enough the rain hit on the elk trail  traverse  back  to
saddle 4840. This was much sooner than the  forecast  and  it  wasn\'t  light
rain either.  It was heavy and steady. I am sure it rained at least Â½  inch.
By the time I was back  to  the  saddle  all  the  brush  was  wet  and  fog
enveloped everything. You just can\'t trust the weatherman. I  had  hoped  to
climb Pk 5827 on the way back, which looked very inviting  up  the  W  Ridge
from the saddle, but the rained put an end to that  notion.  Instead  I  had
hours of wet miserable slipping and sliding on  very  slick  vegetation  and
duff just to make it to camp. I couldn\'t seem to stay  upright  and  I  took
even longer going out than coming in. I was just thinking to  myself,  after
my umpteenth small slip, that it would be  a  miracle  if  I  made  it  back
without injuring myself when I lost it on a very slick section in the  woods
and slid down rough terrain about 10  ft  hitting  my  thigh  hard  on  some
obstacle  or  other.  Ouch!  That  really  hurt!  Fortunately  I  was  still
functional. It was only painful if inadvertently hit or  touched.  On  later
examination I discovered a grapefruit-sized swollen lump and ugly bruise  on
my left back thigh.

I managed to make it the rest of the way back to  my  welcome  camp  without
further incident. I was however, literally dripping wet.  Everything  I  had
on and everything in my pack was soaked despite rain gear and a pack  cover.
It is impossible to stay dry while wallowing in wet brush. I took refuge  in
my dry tent, carefully removed all my wet clothes and put them a  waterproof
stuff sack to keep them separated from my dry gear.  The  saving  grace  was
that it was so warm and muggy I never got cold. Still, a warm dinner, a  cup
of tea and a hot water bottle were very much appreciated.

Day Total: 7 miles, 3700 ft and 11:30 hrs

Thursday, August 15 - It wasn\'t raining in  the  morning,  which  thankfully
allowed me to stay dry while packing up. I could hardly believe it. In  fact
I had no rain all the way out. My conclusion was the front came  in  earlier
and stronger and left sooner than expected. However,  I  did  not  stay  dry
long.  My dry socks became soaked the minute I put on  already  soggy  boots
and I was soon drenched once again head to toe by the  still  wet  brush.  I
did slide some on the slick duff but avoided more damage to myself  and  hit
the trail at 11:00 (3 hrs).  Then it was just a matter of pounding  out  the
remaining 9.5 miles to the trailhead. My clothes dried while hiking  but  my
feet stayed wet all day. At the car I weighed my pack. It was  heavier  than
on the way in what with all that wet gear. This is not the natural order  of
things. Packs should be lighter on the way out.

Day Total: 11.5 miles, 1000 ft and 9:30 hrs

Trip Total: 29 miles and 9000 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen



