            'title' => 'Mt Lawson (5401 ft - P2521 - Mt Christie Quad) - August 21-23, 2013',
            'tr' => '
Mt Lawson (5401 ft - P2521 - Mt Christie Quad) - August 21-23, 2013

Mt Lawson is a seldom climbed peak located north of the  confluence  of  the
North Fork Quinault River and Rustler Creek. If  it  weren\'t  for  the  fact
that it has over 2000 feet of prominence I doubt  it  would  catch  anyone\'s
interest much at all as it is not that easy to get to or all  that  pleasant
a climb. Still, once on top it does provide a striking  viewpoint  into  the
heart of the Olympics. I deliberately went late in the season because I  was
worried I would have to ford the North Fork Quinault and wanted a low  river
level. The trade off was there was no snow in the gullies which made  travel
much more difficult and much slower. The irony was  I  ended  up  finding  a
convenient log anyway and did not need to ford. But this cannot  be  counted
on as yearly floods are constantly changing things. Shetter and Creeden  had
a log in 2009, but Klenke had none in 2005 nor did Boos on 2010. Both  those
crossings were challenging without one.

Wednesday, August 21 - I hiked the North Fork  Trail  10  miles  to  a  just
before where it takes a switchback and is in sight of  the  large  avalanche
cone across the river coming off the north side of Lawson. I was  pleasantly
surprised to see a log from the trail near a level spot  to  camp  right  on
the riverbank, elev 1700 ft.

Day Total: 10 miles, 2100 ft and 7 hrs.

Thursday, August 22 - I crossed on the log by  straddling,  slow  but  safe,
then hiked upstream to the avalanche cone and entered the  gully  (Gully  1)
on the right side, (generally following Shetter\'s  TR  directions).  It  was
dry to begin  but  had  water  higher  up.  I  followed  this  gully  to  an
intersection with another gully (Gully 2) on the  right  at  2400  ft.  This
gully was mostly easy talus but slow going and  I  kept  thinking  how  much
easier and faster it would have been with snow.  I knew  from  Shetter\'s  TR
that I was supposed to move right into a third  gully  (Gully  3)  at  about
3700 ft and kept looking for a place to do so. I could hear a stream on  the
right, supposedly in this gully, but didn\'t see a good place to  cross  into
it. Then I hit an impasse at cliffs that forced me to move right. I  climbed
up an awful dirt slope to a rib above Gully 3 and  was  shocked  to  see  it
filled with snow for a hundred feet or so. I had brought neither ice ax  not
crampons and knew I couldn\'t climb the snow and yet to  continue  I  had  to
somehow get past the snow and into the gully above. I lost  a  lot  of  time
considering various options, including ending the climb, as I could  see  no
obvious way out of this impasse.

Not one to give up easily, I first tried to continue  along  the  rib  above
the snow but that ended in a sketchy exposed hardpack  dirt  traverse  above
cliffs I wasn\'t willing to chance. I retreated back to my starting point  on
the rib. On closer examination a short (30 ft) but  steep  dirt  slope  went
down into the moat alongside the snow. I couldn\'t see around the  corner  to
how far it went but maybe I could crawl the moat. So I slid down  the  slope
(not being at all sure I would be able to climb back up it)  into  the  moat
and was happy to see the moat led to a cave under the snow  (formed  by  the
creek) and out the other end to once again snow free  gully.  The  cave  was
like entering a shower and was very spooky as parts  of  the  entrance  roof
had collapsed in big chunks. If a new chunk came down while I was  in  there
I was a goner. Fortunately none did.

Above the snow Gully 3 was easy again for a few hundred feet then  gradually
got steeper and steeper, and brushier. Actually the brush helped as I  could
use it for hand holds to pull myself up the  steep  dirt.  Then  I  hit  the
rocky headwall around 4100 ft. I wasn\'t quite sure where to go. I could  see
possible gullies to either side but neither looked good  to  me.  Instead  I
elected to go straight up the brushy middle between them where I had  secure
branches to hang on to. I again lost a lot of time wandering back and  forth
trying to find a way I could  bodily  pull  myself  up  the  cliff  on  tree
branches. I wore myself out almost to the total fatigue of  my  arm  muscles
on this section. The worse of it was probably not  more  than  100  vertical
feet and yet it took me over an hour. Eventually I pulled onto  flatter  and
less brushy ground above and left of a rocky rib at 4300 ft  and  thought  I
had it made. But this peak just wouldn\'t quit. After  several  hundred  feet
of steep but reasonable forest I hit what looked from a distance  to  be  an
easy dirt trough up through cliffs. However, when I got to it,  it  was  the
dreaded hardpack dirt again that gave zero purchase to  the  boot.  I  don\'t
know if conditions this year are unusual because it has been so dry and  the
dirt has turned to concrete hardness or if it is always  like  this,  but  I
can\'t remember when I have run into so much of this horrible stuff. It  took
me 2-3 times as long as it should have. Again I wished for snow.

I gratefully reached the summit ridge (5150 ft)  again  thinking  I  had  it
made. I was immediately dismayed to see this ridge was not the  gentle  open
crest I had envisioned from looking at the map but instead was a  series  of
rocky pinnacles guarded by dense twisted trees. With  all  the  time  I  had
lost with various problems it was now 2:50 and I  figured  I  had  at  least
another hour to the summit. I was really past a reasonable  turnaround  time
but no way was I going to give up now after  what  I  had  been  through.  I
resigned  myself  to  a  headlamp  return  and  doggedly   plunged   onward.
Fortunately, the ridge was not as bad as  it  first  appeared.  I  had  some
krumholz as I followed the crest but was able to find open ground with  good
footing on the left much of the way as I climbed  over  and  past  Pt  5202.
Beyond that easy terrain led down into the  basin  and  up  to  the  summit,
which I reached at 3:40 (4200 ft, 7:15  hrs),  actually  bettering  my  hour
estimate.

I found the summit register in a large waterproof pill bottle.  It  was  dry
and in good  shape.  It  had  been  placed  in  1992  by  The  Grays  Harbor
Olympians. The next ascent was  by  John  Roper  and  Silas  Wild  in  2001,
followed by Klenke in 2006, Shetter and Creeden in 2009  and  Andy  Boos  in
2010. I added my name for a total of 6 ascents in 21 years.  No,  this  peak
is not often climbed and of names  I  recognized  all  were  completing  the
P2000 list.

Despite the late hour, I took a half hour to enjoy my hard  won  views  into
the heart of the Olympics. Then I quickly headed down  not  looking  forward
one bit to the descent. I had several obstacles to overcome. The  first  was
the steep hardpack dirt trough off the summit ridge. This  was  even  harder
going down and I believe I did  my  first  ever  (deliberate)  sitting  dirt
glissade on the worse section. I actually used a cushion  of  forest  leaves
and debris to slide down on. It was really the safest way  as  I  could  not
stand upright without slipping. The second was the headwall. I  had  a  rope
but didn\'t think I could rappel the way I had come up as the trees were  too
thick. So I followed Shetter\'s down route staying on the rocky  rib  as  far
as possible (not bad going) until I  could  rappel  down  a  wall  and  then
tarzan down the rest of  the  way  hanging  onto  branches.  The  third  was
climbing back through the snow cave and up the dirt slope  out  of  Gully  3
and into Gully 2. I had to cut  steps  in  the  hard  dirt  to  get  up  it.
Although I did not have an ice ax I did have my Whippet  pole  ax  head  and
that worked (barely). From then on I had no  more  difficulties,  relatively
speaking. It was just a matter of picking my way slowly and  carefully  down
the talus. I hit Gully 1 at dusk (8:40)  and  put  on  my  headlamp  shortly
thereafter. I crossed  the  log  in  the  dark,  which  seemed  to  take  an
inordinately long time as it felt slightly uphill and my  arm  muscles  were
fried. I pulled into camp at 10:10 taking time  to  make  a  several  course
dinner and down multiple drinks before turning in at 11:30.

Day Total: 4.5 miles, 4600 ft and 13:45 hrs

Friday, August 23 - I slept in not leaving  until  9:45.  Shortly  down  the
trail I ran into a blind woman being led by  her  guide  dog.  She  and  her
husband were out for several days. Admittedly the  NF  trail  is  gentle  as
mountain trails go, but it has many rough, rocky sections and  tricky  creek
crossings. I can\'t imagine navigating it blind.  Her  challenges  were  much
greater than the ones I encountered. Just when I start feeling pleased  with
myself for what I have done, I meet someone who does me one better.

Day Total: 10 miles, 900 ft and 7 hrs

Trip Total: 24.5 miles and 7600 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen



