            'title' => 'Eagle Cap Wilderness Peaks - September 6-10, 2013 - Eagle Cap (9572 ft - P1232), Glacier Pk (9495 ft - P315), Pk 9020 (P480), Matterhorn (9826 ft - P333) and Pk 8441 (P685) - Eagle Cap Quad',
            'tr' => '
Eagle Cap Wilderness Peaks - September 6-10, 2013 - Eagle  Cap  (9572  ft  -
P1232), Glacier Pk (9495 ft - P315), Pk 9020 (P480), Matterhorn (9826  ft  -
P333) and Pk 8441 (P685) - Eagle Cap Quad

The Eagle Cap Wilderness is a unique and  scenic  area  of  scores  of  high
mountain lakes, meadows and lofty peaks and ridges located  in  the  Wallowa
Mountains of NE Oregon. It had been on my radar screen  for  years,  if  not
decades, but being a mostly Washington  peakbagger  I  had  never  made  the
effort to make the long drive. That is until Deb and Steve invited me  along
on their trip. Deb and her friend Sandra  had  made  a  couple  of  previous
trips and waxed poetic over its beauty which convinced me to finally  remedy
my omission. I am very glad I did. It did not disappoint.

Day 1: Friday, September 6 - Deb and Steve, along with Sandra and Dave,  had
driven to the TH the previous day and hiked in to a camp at Mirror Lake  (in
the Lakes Basin Management Area) early on this day. Not able to get away  on
Thursday, I made the long (7 hr) drive alone arriving  at  the  Two  Pan  TH
(elev 5600 ft) at 1:30 and starting on the trail at  2:00.  There  had  been
heavy rain the day before, which made hiking pleasant and cut down on  trail
dust, but was now sunny. After  2.5  miles  of  steady  climbing  the  trail
entered the gorgeous East Lostine River Valley  where  for  the  next  2  .5
miles I hiked in full view of Eagle  Cap  Peak.  After  another  2  miles  I
arrived at the junction to Mirror Lake where I followed a paper  note  trail
left by Deb directing me to their campsite (elev 7600 ft).  I  arrived  just
in time to enjoy having dinner with the group.

Day Total: 7.5 miles, 2100 ft and 5 hrs

Day 2: Saturday, September 7 - The entire  group  started  out  together  to
climb Eagle Cap and followed the trail to  the  summit  (2000  ft,  2  hrs).
Views were superb of the Lakes Basin and entire Wilderness area.  I  got  my
first real look at Matterhorn in the distance and was immediately  intrigued
by its distinctive white rock. At the time I had no idea what it  was.  Most
of the rock in the Lakes Basin was lovely granite which  provided  excellent
friction for climbing but that on the Matterhorn was obviously different.  I
knew I had to climb that peak to get a closer look.

From Eagle Cap we all descended the gentle south slope to the  ridge  saddle
where a convenient way trail  appeared  leading  down  toward  Glacier  Lake
which we followed until below cliffs and steep remnant snow. I  had  my  eye
on Glacier Peak above while the others headed for Prospect  Lake  below.  We
separated and I worked my way up interesting slabs on  a  leftward  traverse
past cliffs to the SE ridge. Here an easy but loose rock/dirt slope  led  to
the summit where I found a summit register filled with a wad of  unorganized
loose pages dating back to 1994 (2800 ft, 4:20 hrs).

After spending 30 minutes on  top  eating  lunch  I  started  down  and  had
descended a couple hundred feet when I spied Steve climbing rapidly  upward.
He had left the others at the saddle above Prospect Lake  and  followed  the
gentle east ridge up. I continued down this  delightful  crest.  Steve  soon
caught up to me after sprinting up to the summit and we  continued  together
to rendezvous with the rest of party at the Prospect saddle. From  there  we
all descended to beautiful Glacier Lake. We  made  a  stop  for  water  then
picked up the trail to Glacier Pass. I now had my eye on Pk 9020  above  the
pass. Steve, Deb and Sandra accompanied me to the first bump before  turning
around. I descended to a first notch and continued along  the  narrow  rocky
crest which became quite exposed in places. At a second notch I was  stymied
and had to backtrack to descend and then regain the ridge past the notch.  I
made it past a third notch even though it was somewhat sketchy and  then  on
to the summit at 4:45 (3900 ft, 8:30  hrs).  Oddly  I  found  two  ammo  box
registers on top, each placed by a member of  the  same  climbing  club  and
each with similar notebooks inside but each with a different  name  for  the
peak. They were placed within a week of each other in 1993. I would love  to
know the story behind this one.

From the summit I descended straight down the NW slope  avoiding  the  ridge
entirely and intersected the trail well  below  Glacier  Pass.  At  Moccasin
Lake I stopped to wash up as the last rays of sunshine left  the  basin  and
pulled into camp at 7:00, well after everyone else.

Day Total: 10 miles, 4200 ft and 10:45 hrs.

Day 3: Sunday, September 8  -  This  was  to  be  my  day  to  try  for  the
Matterhorn. The problem was we were really on the wrong  side  of  a  cliffy
ridge to climb it. It is  normally  approached  from  Ice  Lake.  Since  Deb
wanted to go to Razz Lake (she is more  into  lakes  than  peaks  but  I  am
working on converting her) I decided to accompany the group to  see  if  the
ridge could be crossed from there. I am glad I dd. We followed the trail  to
the Hurricane Creek junction, then past Crescent and Douglas Lakes  to  near
Horseshoe lake where we found an old abandoned trail that led  all  the  way
to Razz Lake. From there we went cross-country (some faint trails) to  upper
Razz Lake. This whole area of lakes and tarns  and  polished  granite  slabs
beneath pinnacled cliffs is unbelievable gorgeous.

From Upper Razz Lake Deb, Steve, Sandra and I made our way up an easy  talus
and dirt ramp that went diagonally beneath cliffs  to  a  small  notch  just
right of a spire that resembled a miniature Prusik Peak.  Here  I  left  the
others to descend a horrible loose rock/dirt gully to a  green  basin  below
in the Ice Lake drainage on the other side. This was one nasty gully,  about
as  steep  as  it  could  possibly  be  without  having  the   whole   thing
spontaneously respond to the pull of gravity. In fact much of it  did  as  I
carefully picked my way down constantly questioning the wisdom of doing  so.
The top couple hundred feet were the  worst.  After  a  total  of  800  feet
descent I reached the blessed green basin and from then on the rest  of  the
route was a delight of lush meadows, rock gardens and bubbling creeks.

After about 1000 feet of this pleasant travel I crossed  a  spur  ridge  and
dropped slightly to climb another  spur  to  a  large  flat  barren  plateau
beneath the pure white cliffs of Matterhorn. I had to  blink  several  times
to convince myself these cliffs were rock as at first glance  I  would  have
sworn they were ice. A dark ridge led up  from  the  plateau  to  the  white
rounded summit mass that to me resembled a white whale.  In  the  background
Hurwal Divide loomed almost black. This  contrast  of  light  and  dark  was
positively stunning. I have never seen anything  like  it  before.  I  later
found out that the white rock is limestone and the dark is  volcanic  but  I
need to research more about the fascinating geology of these  mountains.  To
add icing on the cake, as I crossed the plateau I  spied  2  white  mountain
goats silhouetted against the black of Hurwal Divide.

I crossed the plateau to the dark ridge  where  I  ran  into  the  climber\'s
trail coming from Ice Lake. This led to the "White Whale",  along  the  back
of the whale, down to a notch and up to the summit at the  far  end  of  the
ridge. There was "trail" the whole way but at times it traversed across  the
side of the "whale" on sketchy ledges to avoid  steep  slabs.  These  ledges
were often narrow and covered  with  ball  bearing  sand  and  I  discovered
limestone does not have as good a friction as granite so care was needed  to
avoid slipping, especially if a section  of  obscure  trail  was  missed.  I
reached the summit at 3:45 (3600 ft, 7:15 hrs). There was  no  register  but
there was an artistic cairn. I spent as much time on top as I dared  knowing
I had a long way to go to get out, but I couldn\'t help  standing  in  awe  a
few minutes at the view along the ridge to Sacajawea (the  highest  peak  in
the Wallowas at 9838 ft)  with  more  of  the  same  contrasting  darks  and
lights.

Reluctantly I started down at 4:00. My plan was  to  descend  directly  into
Hurricane Creek. No way was I going to return the way I  had  come  up  that
horrid gully. However  the  ridge  above  Hurricane  Creek  was  cliffy  and
impassible for quite a distance and I had to retrace my steps  all  the  way
back to the first spur before I could find a reasonable way  over  it.  From
the basin below this spur I had to climb 500 feet up a  scree  slope,  loose
but infinitely better than the horrid gully, to a broad 9000  ft  saddle  in
the main ridge which I reached at 5:30. From the  saddle  I  worked  my  way
down 2000 ft to Hurricane Creek. I had scoped  this  route  out  from  Lakes
Basin and it looked feasible but there were some cliffs enroute.  I  managed
to avoid most of them by zigzagging back and forth but failed in  one  small
area at two small 10 foot drops I could find  no  way  around.  I  rappelled
these with my small "panic" rope (which I am never without). That slowed  me
up such that it took 1.5 hours to hit the trail in the valley  bottom.  From
there it was about 2.5 miles and 500 ft of uphill to the junction  with  the
Lakes Basin trail which I reached at 8:00. The last bit was by headlamp  and
I pulled into camp at 8:30 much to the relief of both myself and my  waiting
friends.

Day Total: 12 miles, 5100 ft and 12 hrs

Day 4: Sunday, September 9 -  We  spent  a  leisurely  day  climbing  scenic
mellow Peak 8441 right above camp (800 ft, 1:00 hr). We  lounged  around  on
top for 2 hours taking in the views before  returning  to  camp  for  lunch,
packing up and moving camp down to the far end  of  the  Lostine  Valley  (2
hrs).

Day Total: 7 miles and 900 ft

Day 5: Monday, September 10 - We hiked the short remaining distance  to  the
TH reaching it at 9:00. During the long drive  home  I  had  ample  time  to
reflect on the trip. I found The Eagle Cap Wilderness to be a  very  special
experience well worth the long drive and vowed to  return  soon.  Thank  you
Deb and Steve for introducing it to me.

Day Total: 2.5 miles, 1:15 hr

Trip Total: 39 miles and 12,300 ft in 4.5 days.

Fay Pullen





