            'tr' => '
Nook Mtn (6760+ ft - P960 - Mt Sefrit Quad) and Sackout Mtn (6596 ft -  P516
- Mt Shuksan Quad) - October 8-10, 2013

These 2 peaks could probably be climbed in day from  the  Hannegan  Pass  TH
during spring daylight and snow conditions, but I didn\'t think  I  would  be
able to do so this time of year and allowed more time. Good thing I  did.  I
expected maybe 2 feet of new snow from recent storms,  but  was  shocked  to
find it almost twice as much as that at higher elevations. There were  times
I could barely move it was so  deep.  In  retrospect  I  should  have  taken
snowshoes, but I really didn\'t think it would  be  so  bad  and  anyone  who
knows me knows I hate snowshoes and will go  to  great  lengths  and  endure
great suffering to avoid using them. Well,  I  certainly  suffered  on  this
trip.

Tuesday, October 8 - The forecast was not  good  for  the  morning  but  did
indicate clearing later in the day. With this in  mind  and  since  my  only
goal was to hike the 3.5 miles to Hannegan  Camp,  I  didn\'t  start  on  the
trail until 3:00. My strategy worked. I did begin in light rain/snow but  it
soon cleared to sunshine. The trail was completely  snow  free  until  about
4500 ft. After encountering only small patches thereafter I was confident  I
would find a snow free spot to camp. However, when I came  to  the  Hannegan
Camp junction it was like a switch had been flipped  and  all  of  a  sudden
there was a solid foot of snow covering everything.  I  couldn\'t  even  find
the established campsites. I wandered around for 30 minutes before  I  found
a bare spot next to the trail a short ways up  from  the  junction.   I  had
remembered this spot from my previous recent visits. It would do nicely.

Day Total: 3.5 miles, 1700 ft and 2:30 hrs

Wednesday, October 9 - It was cold  enough  during  the  night  for  a  mild
freeze which formed a light crust on snow that had been exposed to the  sun.
My first objective was Sackout Mtn and to access it I had to first get  into
Ruth Creek Basin below it. I tried contouring from camp into the  basin  but
soon gave that up on the steep densely treed slope  and  ended  up  dropping
500 feet directly to the creek. Once there it was straightforward  but  slow
going on snow-covered rocks. At the head of the basin I veered right into  a
gully that led to an upper basin below a headwall. To bypass the  cliffs  of
this headwall I went right onto a wooded rib. Once above  the  headwall  the
terrain opened up and was  easy  but  the  snow  was  getting  progressively
deeper while I was getting progressively slower. Often my poles  (which  did
not have ski baskets on them) would sink in all the  way  to  their  handles
and on steeper sections I would kick a step only to have it  collapse  as  I
weighted it leaving me in a hip deep hole and struggling to get out. It  was
very slow going indeed. Oh but it was so beautiful with  all  the  new  snow
and gorgeous views it made it all worthwhile.

Eventually I worked my way to the base of the  summit  rocks.  I  could  see
only one possible route up.  It looked darn steep and it  was.  Actually  it
wouldn\'t have been that bad had  the  snow  been  better  but  it  was  deep
unconsolidated stuff loosely plastered over the rock and not to be  trusted.
My biggest fear was a step would give way or collapse into a hole  alongside
the rock. I carefully built steps up by first using my  axe  to  remove  the
top 6-12 inches of loose snow to allow me to kick or cut  a  step  into  the
soft crust underneath. Then I would carefully compact the snow with my  foot
before trusting my weight to it. I doubt the bad part was more 100  vertical
feet but it took about an hour of  total  focus  to  surmount.  Once  I  had
committed to it the only thing that kept  me  going  was  that  I  was  more
afraid to go down than to continue up.

I reached the summit of Sackout Mtn at  2:50  (2400  ft,  6:20  hrs)  having
taken way more time than expected. I still wanted  to  climb  Nook  Mtn.  It
didn\'t look that far or  that  hard  but  if  I  had  the  same  awful  snow
conditions  it  could  take  a  very  long  time,  time  I  no  longer  had.
Fortunately, conditions were much better as I  was  now  following  a  ridge
which was windblown crust. I was able to run down to the Nook saddle  in  20
minutes. The snow depth increased a little as I climbed up from  the  saddle
but it was still not bad, only ankle to calf deep at  worst.  The  only  bad
part on the ridge was when I had to traverse out onto a steep  exposed  snow
slope to bypass a short rock  step.  The  rest  was  straightforward  and  I
reached the summit of Nook at 4:45 (3200 ft, 8:15 hr).

Now I had to get down. I knew from previous views that I could  not  descend
directly from the Nook saddle, which led to a nasty  gully  and  cliffs.  So
instead I dropped down the north ridge until past cliffs and then  traversed
back to the east toward Ruth Creek basin. This  went  well  for  about  1000
feet until I hit increasingly deep  soft  snow  where  every  other  step  I
seemed to break through into holes. Some were as deep as my  waist.  It  was
maddeningly frustrating. I did a lot  of  floundering  and  cursing.  If  it
weren\'t for the fact that I was going downhill I don\'t think  I  would  have
been able to make any progress  at  all.  When  I  could  I  did  a  sitting
glissade but the snow was really too soft to do much sliding.  Eventually  I
made it through this awful section.

At about 4900 ft I came to a deep gully on my right. I really wanted  to  be
on the other side but I could not easily cross and so  was  forced  straight
downhill on the left through dense small trees. This wouldn\'t have  been  so
bad except the branches were all wet. I couldn\'t understand why as  the  day
had been mostly sunny. I guess the fresh snow of  yesterday  had  melted  on
the branches. So between this and wallowing in the upper deep snow,  by  the
time I hit Ruth Creek (some 200 feet  lower  than  on  the  way  up)  I  was
soaking wet. I warmed up and dried out a bit on the 700 ft climb back up  to
camp, which I did by headlamp, arriving at 8:20.

Day Total: 4.5 miles, 3900 ft and 11:50 hrs

Thursday, October 10 - I fully expected to wake up to rain as that had  been
the forecast. I did not. I was not, however, spared  the  unpleasantness  of
packing up a wet tent, due to a combination of dripping trees,  condensation
and just general dampness.  I took my time ambling  out  enjoying  the  fall
color along the lower trail.

Day Total: 3.5 miles, 100 ft and 2:10 hrs

Trip Total: 11.5 miles and 5700 ft in 1 full day, 2 half days and 2 nights

Fay Pullen

