            'tr' => '
"Pomas Peak" (7320+ ft - P840 - Saska Pk Quad) - October 16-17, 2013

The main purpose of this trip was to visit the golden larches by camping  at
appropriately named Larch Lakes. Coincidently there was a new  peak  for  me
to climb nearby. It has no official name but I  am  calling  it  Pomas  Peak
since it rises directly above Pomas Pass.

Wednesday, October 16 - I started up the Entiat River Trail  at  11:00.  The
first part of the trail along the river is open to motorcycles and  as  such
is smooth and easy hiking. Since it was hunting season, I ran  into  several
of the machines and one horseman leading a pack animal, but  all  were  very
friendly and courteous. Several of the motorcycle riders  not  only  yielded
to me but turned off their engines until I passed. Their  consideration  was
greatly appreciated. Once I turned off the main trail onto the  Myrtle  Lake
Trail I met no one. This route allows use of  the  bridge  over  the  Entiat
River and avoids the ford higher up. I was fascinated by  a  tree  that  had
fallen onto and penetrated the bridge deck. Fortunately it  seemed  to  have
done no major structural damage but it was very impressive.

From the lake I picked up the hiker-only trail that connects  to  the  Larch
Lakes Trail. I ran into the first snow just before the Lower Lake  at  about
5500 ft. As expected, the snow increased rapidly as soon as  I  entered  the
lake basin (5650 ft) and in the open meadow was over  a  foot  deep.  Others
had been this way recently and there was a packed trail to  the  Upper  Lake
(5750 ft) which had even more snow. I fully expected to  camp  on  snow  but
was delighted when I found a snow free established  campsite  right  on  the
lake. I arrived at 4:30, quite early  by  my  standards,  but  the  sun  had
already set behind the ridge and the day, which had  been  sunny  and  warm,
quickly cooled off.

Day Total: 7.6 mile, 2900 ft and 5:30 hrs

Thursday, October 17 - I woke up at 6:30.  Since  I  had  gone  to  bed  the
previous night at 7:30 that meant I had slept 11 hours, and they were  solid
hours. Good grief, I never sleep that long at home. I  sure  sleep  well  in
the mountains. Of course it helped that I had switched to my winter bag  and
was toasty warm all night.  But it was darn cold to start and  the  water  I
left outside had a thick layer of ice. I managed to get going  by  8:15  and
followed the Pomas Pass Trail. No one had been beyond the lake and the  only
tracks were those made by deer. The snow  had  frozen  hard  enough  that  I
didn\'t break through the crust and I made rapid  progress  to  the  6440  ft
pass in the ridge above. On the other side the trail traversed  slopes  that
were steep enough crampons would have been useful  but  I  had  not  brought
them. I was, however, happy to have brought an axe.

Once below my peak I climbed up to the ridge and then  along  the  crest  to
the top. I found a cairn on top and thought I was on the high point until  I
saw another point to the north that looked higher. Darn!  It  was  not  that
easy to get to as the intervening ridge was narrow and rocky and it took  an
additional 30 minutes. I had to descend  below  the  cliffs  until  I  could
traverse on steep snow. Once below the  North  Peak  it  was  then  an  easy
ascent. I also found a cairn on this summit. On the map  each  point  has  a
7320 ft contour but I am convinced the North Peak is higher than  the  South
Peak by 10-15 feet. My altimeter and my eye (which admittedly  is  not  that
reliable) both confirm this. Anyway I left my register  on  the  North  Peak
which I reached at 10:45 (1700 ft, 2:30 hrs).

I left the North Peak at 11:00 carefully reversing  the  traverse  to  below
the South Peak.  Once past the 6440 ft pass, the sun  had  begun  to  soften
the snow and I bogged down in a few places. I reached camp at 12:30. I  then
enjoyed 1.5 hours of basking in the sunshine before  leaving  for  the  trek
out. Again I met no one until regaining the main Entiat River  Trail,  where
I ran into several hunters and one couple who had climbed Pinnacle  Peak  on
a multiday trip.  Oddly, despite all the hunters I  heard  not  one  gunshot
and my tranquility was undisturbed. In fact the whole trip was a delight.

Pomas Peak: 3.6 miles, 1700 ft and 4:15 hrs RT from camp

Hike out: 7.6 miles, 300 ft and 4:10 hrs

Trip Total: 18.8 miles and 4900 ft in 2 days

Fay Pullen



