            'tr' => '
Whalehead Ridge (5280+ ft - P720 - Purcell Mtn Quad) - November 1, 2013

Whalehead Ridge is an impressive looking rocky highlight in a  small  alpine
oasis rising above a maze of logging roads north of Randle.  I  first  tried
Whalehead Ridge on April 2, 2013 via  the  route  Klenke  describes  in  his
October   2006    ascent    (http://www.summitpost.org/whalesback-southeast-
ridge/239599).  I didn\'t get very far up the actual peak but I  did  have  a
nice ski trip to the saddle below the SE Ridge. I concluded  his  route  was
too difficult for me to climb solo (he described  a  Class  5.3  pitch  just
below the summit) and my only possible  alternative  would  be  an  approach
from the opposite direction via the NW Ridge.  And so I returned some  seven
months later to hopefully complete this unfinished business.

The hard part was finding a way onto the NW Ridge. Maps show  logging  roads
climbing high onto the slopes north and west of Whalehead but in fact  these
are for the most part undrivable and barely  hikeable.  I  got  as  close  I
could by driving FR 52 to FR 47 (note that FR 47 can  no  longer  be  driven
directly from Randle due to a  permanent  washout  near  the  East  Fork  of
Silver Creek) to FR 63 to FR 6353. This last spur can be  driven  1.3  miles
to a washout but it is quite overgrown. There is an  ample  turnaround  here
and a nice spot to park. I continued on foot. The  road  immediately  became
so overgrown with alder as to be almost impenetrable.  I  persevered  for  a
very unpleasant 0.75 mile until I couldn\'t take it anymore and figured  it  was
safe to head straight uphill. Once off the road travel improved. I  did  hit
one short bad brush section but I was able to avoid it on the  way  down.  I
crossed the switch backing road several times but continued to ignore it  as
it was of no use. Just below the ridge I  came  to  a  welcome  open  meadow
slope which I climbed to the crest very near Pt 5178 (1700 ft, 2 hrs).

Now the real fun began. I got a good view of Whalehead summit and it  looked
formidable. It appeared my best bet would be  to  stay  high  on  the  ridge
crest above all the nasty steep slabs and side hill. However, I could see  a
notch just before the summit pyramid and I was not sure how  difficult  that
would be to cross. The ridge was partially  wooded  and  easy  up  and  down
until just below Pt 5183 where a steep,  somewhat  unpleasant  traverse  was
necessary to bypass that pinnacle. Once  past,  I  regained  the  delightful
open ridge. I was now near the notch I had  seen  from  afar  and  was  very
happy to discover it to not be a problem at all, just a short class  3  step
down. More of a problem were the thick trees to  wrestle  through  right  at
the notch itself. Then it was steep mossy rock the rest of the  way  to  the
summit (2300 ft. 3:20 hrs). I found a cairn but no summit register.  I  also
found a white sling attached to a rather wimpy  looking  root  a  short  way
down the SE Ridge. I assumed this was the rappel anchor used by  Klenke  but
in rereading his report he said it was black. Either it  had  faded  greatly
in 7 years or someone else had added a new sling.

Since I had run into many fewer problems  and  taken  much  less  time  than
expected, I was able to enjoy my summit views for  40 minutes on what  would
turn out to be the last sunny, snow free day high up before bad weather  set
in for good. I even made it back to the car before dark. Although I did  not
like that alder choked road walk, the rest of the  trip  turned  out  to  be
downright enjoyable.

Total: 4.5 miles, 2700 ft and 6:30 hrs

Fay Pullen

