            'tr' => '
Lizard Head Peak (5350+ ft - P600) and Pk 5150+  (P450)  -  Lake  Sutherland
Quad - November 8-10, 2013

Aurora Ridge is the  long  divide  between  the  Lyre  (Lake  Crescent)  and
Soleduck Rivers. The east  end  blends  into  Happy  Lake  Ridge  where  the
distinction between the two  is  indefinite.  There  are  several  peaks  of
prominence and name along this length. I planned to climb two of  them  that
could be accessed from the Barnes Creek and Aurora Divide Trails.  The  last
time I had tried to hike the Barnes Creek Trail, many years ago,  the  trail
appeared to have little maintenance and the bridge was out.  So  I  was  not
sure what I would run into or how far I would get this time  around.  I  was
surprised to find a well maintained trail  in  excellent  condition  with  a
very nice log crossing in place. This lowland trail is now a  lovely  forest
hike that is accessible most of the year.

Friday, November 8 - I began from the Storm King Ranger  Station  (elev  600
ft), which is also the TH for Marymere Falls and Storm  King,  both  popular
destinations. At .5 miles the Barnes Creek Trail left the wide path  heading
for the falls to become a delightful narrow but  good  tread  that  followed
alongside the creek. Soon it crossed to the  other  side  and  commenced  to
wander up and down through beautiful mossy forest.  After  climbing  several
hundred feet in a series of switchbacks, it came to Dismal Draw and a  small
campsite. Though I love this name, Dismal Draw is not all  that  dismal  and
made for a pleasant rest stop.  Shortly beyond there was a brief glimpse  of
cliffy Storm King across the valley and then the trail divided at a 2000  ft
junction (4 miles, 1700  ft,  3  hrs).  The  Barnes  Creek  Trail  continued
straight ahead staying low in the valley while I went right  on  the  Aurora
Divide Trail that climbed steadily alongside an unnamed  side  creek  toward
Aurora Ridge. At about 3700 I began running into fresh  snow  which  quickly
increased in depth. At 4250 feet  I  found  the  only  campsite  along  this
section of trail. Although there was consistent snow at  this  elevation  in
the open, the spot was protected enough under trees that with a little  work
I was able to pitch my tent on bare ground. A little stream nearby  provided
water. It was quite a nice camp.

Day Total: 7 miles, 4050 ft and 5:15 hrs.

Saturday, November 9 - After a long but comfortable night, I was on  my  way
at 9:00 continuing up the trail to the divide saddle at 4700 ft. From  there
I followed the ridge to the summit of Pk 5150. It was not as easy  going  as
the map might indicate, there being many  downed  trees  and  much  annoying
debris to work through and around and it took  longer  than  expected  (1000
ft, 1:30 hrs). Note that the Aurora Ridge Trail does NOT go over the top  as
is shown on both the USGS Lake Sutherland and GT  Lake  Crescent  maps.  The
Custom Correct Lake Crescent-Happy Lake Ridge map correctly shows the  trail
contouring about 400 feet below the summit.

I returned to the saddle and the  nearby  trail  junction  with  the  Aurora
Ridge Trail (which is not right at the saddle) to  continue  on  this  trail
toward Lizard Head Pk. Snow depth in the open was now about 1 foot but  only
a few inches in the trees and the trail was easily  followed  and  no  great
chore. At a likely looking spot I left the trail to gain the east  ridge  of
the peak. Again this ridge was  more  difficult  than  expected  with  tight
trees  and  hidden  small  outcrops  requiring  steep  bypass  traverses  in
deepening fresh snow. I reached the snowy summit cairn atop a small  boulder
tucked in amongst trees at  1:20  (1950  ft,  4:20  hrs).  The  morning  had
started with good visibility and I had a few reasonable  views  enroute  but
it was now snowing very lightly and continued to do so the rest of the  day.
Even so I spent over 30 minutes on top placing a register and  eating  lunch
as there was no wind and it was not that cold.

It was too early to return to camp. I wanted to minimize time spent  in  the
tent as much as possible, so once on the trail again I  continued  along  it
to the Happy Lake Trail Junction and then even farther to the high point  of
Crystal Ridge. Since the trail was easy to follow I  figured  I  could  keep
going until dark and then return by headlamp with no  problem.  This  I  did
and also made a slight detour on the way back to  pick  up  Pk  5175  (P300)
although I must admit it was not worth the effort.  I  don\'t  think  I  have
ever run into such  thick  summit  trees.  They  were  almost  impenetrable,
requiring crawling under, slithering over and  other  major  contortions  to
force a way through. But it did eat up more  time  away  from  the  sleeping
bag. I was back in camp at 7:30 having done justice to the day.

Day Total: 9 miles, 3200 ft and 10:30 hrs

Sunday, November 10 - I enjoyed a leisurely trip  out  taking  my  time  and
enjoying the truly beautiful green forest again once out of the  snow  zone.
I was tempted to explore the continuation of the Barnes  Creek  Trail  which
looked very inviting beyond the junction with the Aurora  Divide  Trail  but
decided to save that for another day. I fully  expected  some  precipitation
going out but had none. In fact I essentially  had  none  the  entire  trip,
other than the light snow on Saturday afternoon which  got  nothing  wet.  I
never even had to use my rain  gear.  Pretty  darn  good  I  would  say  for
November in the Olympics.

Day Total: 7 miles, 350 ft and 4:30 hrs

Trip Total: 23 miles and 7600 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen

