Tirzah Pk (5208 ft - P128 - Mowich Lk Quad) - November 14, 2013

The new guide to 100 peaks in Mt Rainier had me looking at what I  had  left
to do to complete this list. Not that many it turns out (7), this being  one
of them. So off I went all prepared to climb it via  the  usual  route  from
the Chenuis Falls Trail. I even took a bike along for the 4 miles along  the
closed Carbon River Road to the TH. Then  I  stopped  at  the  "new"  Carbon
River Ranger Station 2.5  miles  before  the  park  entrance,  which  I  was
surprised to find open on a Thursday in November, and  the  ranger  informed
me that the bridge over the Carbon River had washed out about 2 months  ago.
Why did the Longmire Ranger Station not know this when I  called  them  just
before my trip (they said they had no information)?  So it was  on  to  Plan
B.

I drove up Cayada Creek Road 7810 about 3.5  miles  to  a  side  road  right
(this is at the same junction for the  Jeep  road  that  goes  left  to  Old
Baldy) and was able to drive it .3 miles to the first ditch. This  old  road
(7840) contours the hillside below Cayada Mtn above  the  Carbon  River  and
into the Chenuis Cr drainage and I thought it could be used as a way to  get
close enough to Tirzah to climb it. I started on my bike,  since  I  had  it
along anyway, but there were so many ditches that it was more  trouble  than
it was worth and I gave up after 1.5 miles to continue  on  foot.  The  road
became more and more overgrown but is  very  walkable.  After  another  half
mile I left the road to plunge downhill an unpleasant brushy 400 feet  to  a
crossing of Chenuis Creek. The creek was flowing higher than  expected  with
no easy way across. I tried to hop rocks but slipped and  ended  up  getting
both feet wet. Not good, but I decided to continue anyway despite  squishing
in my boots the rest of the day.

The other side of the creek was less  brushy  and  I  soon  intersected  the
trail from Chenuis Falls. It was so nice to be on good tread I  stayed  with
it as long as it went uphill, maybe .4 miles. This put me on the north  side
of the peak away from the normal route but although steep  the  forest  here
(now inside the park) was not bad travel to the ridge.  Once  on  the  ridge
things got  interesting  as  it  has  many  rocky  outcroppings.  None  were
difficult to get past, first on the left then on the right, then  along  the
crest but the whole ridge, though enjoyable scrambling, seemed  much  longer
than it appeared on the map and seemed to  take  forever.  All  day  it  had
never really rained much, just mist and drizzle,  but  near  the  summit  it
turned to light snow that began to stick. The summit (2700 ft, 5 hrs) was  a
small opening in the trees. I was surprised to find no  cairn  much  less  a
register, which I spent the next 30 minutes remedying (and eating lunch).

The ridge was somewhat confusing on the descent  and  GPS  waypoints  helped
keep me on track. Once back to the crossing of Chenuis Creek I  didn\'t  even
try to stay dry and just waded across  without  stopping.  It  was  over  my
knees. The climb back to the road was very unpleasant and sure  seemed  more
than 400 ft. And I can\'t remember the last time I hiked in wet boots for  so
long. Still, overall I was pleased to have  made  my  route  work.  I  doubt
anyone else has ever gone this way to climb Tirzah Pk.

Total: 8 miles, 3400 ft and 10 hours

Fay Pullen

