Sweet Pk (4560+ ft - P200 - Golden Lakes Quad) - November 19, 2013

Each year I try to go on a  special  birthday  climb  with  my  son  Walter.
Despite having the misfortune to be born in  November,  arguably  the  worst
month for weather  or  quality  destinations,  we  usually  manage  to  find
something to do and always have fun, rain  or  shine.  This  year,  with  my
renewed interest in cleaning up the few peaks in  Mt  Rainier  that  I  have
missed, we settled on Sweet Pk, which can be accessed from the Carbon  River
entrance of the Park. His birthday on Tuesday was  a  transition  day  after
heavy rain on Monday and before sun on Wednesday. Although we  had  none  of
the latter neither did we have any significant precipitation which was  more
than we had hoped for. Many of his birthday trips have  been  in  torrential
rain or heavy snow.

We began on the West Boundary trail  which  branches  off  the  Rain  Forest
Nature Trail loop right at the Park entrance (1750  ft).  The  last  time  I
took this trail (many years ago to climb Florence Pk)  I  remembered  it  as
being rough and seldom maintained. No more.  The  first  1.5  miles  to  two
waterfalls has had major work done to it  and  is  in  excellent  shape  and
traverses lovely forest.  The  trail  crosses  the  creek  between  the  two
waterfalls. Ordinarily I doubt this crossing would cause much of a  problem,
but due to heavy rain the day and night before, it was  running  very  high.
We barely made it across with dry feet. The trail was noticeably rougher  on
the other side yet not that bad except  for  the  sections  that  still  had
running water left over from the recent downpour. At 3650, where  the  trail
veers away from the creek toward Alki Crest, we left it and headed  for  the
south ridge of Sweet Pk, which we hit very near  the  saddle.  We  ran  into
minor crusty snow here. It was then an easy ridge walk to the  summit  (3:15
hrs).

As the day progressed  we  could  feel  the  temperature  dropping.  It  was
snowing lightly on top with a cold wind so  we  retreated  to  the  relative
warmth of my bothy bag for our lunch and birthday party which  included  one
candle in a cookie.  After  festivities  we  built  a  cairn  and  placed  a
register before leaving. We both liked the name of this peak and agree  that
this was a very pleasant trip. But then any trip with my son is a delight.

Total: 7 miles, 3000 ft and 5:30 hours

Fay Pullen

