            'tr' => '
Baldy Ridge (5050+ ft - P1400 - Lake  Sutherland  Quad)  -  November  21-23,
2013

When I hiked up the Barnes Creek Trail two weeks ago and turned  off  it  at
mile 4 onto  the  Aurora  Divide  Trail  to  climb  Lizard  Head  Peak,  the
continuation of the trail appeared so inviting  I vowed to return  and  hike
it to its end. I didn\'t know at that time I would return so soon.  But  with
unusual stable high pressure continuing, I was lured back for another  three
day trip. This time I hoped to gain access to Baldy Ridge from  the  end  of
the trail. I was a little concerned  with  forecast  nighttime  temperatures
into the low twenties and icy trail condition but they turned out to not  be
a problem. I  actually  had  warmer  temperatures,  once  above  the  valley
bottom, than I did for my Lizard Head trip.

Thursday, November 21 - I almost postponed this trip when I saw the  traffic
cam on Highway  101  at  Indian  Valley  showing  several  inches  of  white
alongside the road. How on earth could there be snow  at  600  ft?  If  that
were the case, my trip was in jeopardy.  I  was  somewhat  relieved  when  I
discovered in person  this  white  stuff  was  heavy  frost  and  not  snow.
Evidently Indian Valley is a sink hole of cold air next to a big  source  of
moisture where the sun never shines and is very conducive to forming  frost.
Even so the temperature was frigid and still so a few miles farther  at  the
Storm King Ranger Station (elev 600 ft) when I started out. It remained  icy
until the trail climbed above the valley. I was glad I had thought to  bring
microspikes for crossing the 3 slick bridges. Higher up the trail was  frost
free though the ground was still frozen in places.

Once past the Aurora Divide Trail junction  I  was  on  new  territory.  The
trail was noticeably less used now but still in very good  condition.  I  am
extremely pleased to  see  some  these  previously  abandoned  trails  being
resurrected. I am not sure when this  happened  but  it  had  to  have  been
logged out after the Third Edition (2000) of  Robert  Wood\'s  Olympic  Trail
Guide as he describes the Barnes Creek trail in that  book  as  unmaintained
and essentially abandoned after the junction. I continued a very pleasant  3
more miles, winding in and out of several  side  valleys  through  beautiful
forest, to a nice campsite (mentioned by Wood) just  past  the  crossing  of
Happy Lake Creek (elev 2700).

Total: 7 miles, 2600 ft and 4:40 hrs

Friday, November 22 - It barely got  to  below  freezing  during  the  night
outside and was a balmy 37 inside my 4 season tent. I was  almost  too  warm
in my winter bag. Being in dense forest on the shady side of  the  hill,  my
camp saw little early light and I was shocked when it was already 7:45  when
I woke up. No alpine start today. I  continued  along  the  trail  which  in
places was a solid carpet of moss signaling little use. After  2.5  miles  I
came to a junction. The right branch went a very short distance  to  an  end
at a saddle on the wooded ridge crest. The left went a bit farther  climbing
to a viewpoint known as Lookout Dome, elev 3800 ft.  It  is  interesting  to
note that the USGS Lake Sutherland Quad does not  show  this  trail  in  the
correct location. It shows it climbing from low in the  valley  directly  to
Baldy  Ridge,  which  it  doesn\'t  come  close  to  doing.  This  is  rather
reminiscent of the depiction of a trail all the way  to  the  summit  of  Mt
Storm King, which also does not exist. GT does not show  the  trail  at  all
even though it often shows  worse  trails.  And  even  Wood  has  the  trail
splitting at 4800 feet and ending at 5090 ft on  Lookout  Dome  (he  has  no
detailed maps). He is off on his elevations by 1000  feet  which  caused  me
great confusion in trying to figure out exactly where the trail  went  while
planning my trip. He also said the trail ended  at  the  park  boundary  (it
does not) adding more confusion. The only  map  showing  the  trail  in  the
correct location is the Custom Correct Lake Crescent-Happy Lake Ridge one.

So I now found myself on Lookout Dome and could see major cliffs between  me
and my objective of Baldy Ridge with no assurance I  could  get  there  from
here. Not really where I wanted to be. Still, I make it  work.  I  continued
along the ridge, which went well at first, until coming upon a  cliff  wall.
I turned this on the left going through a critical notch that I  fortunately
marked with a cairn. That would be very useful on the  way  back.  From  the
notch I traversed on the left slope, gained the ridge again,  dropped  to  a
saddle and came to another wall. I could not see  a  way  through  this  one
without dropping a couple hundred feet farther on the left until  below  it.
From that point on it was easy forest and talus to the summit  ridge.  There
are two closed 5050 ft contours along the ridge and I am not sure  which  is
higher so I visited both. My guess is the East  summit  is  higher  but  the
West summit is more open and I ate my lunch there (3200 ft, 5 hrs).

I left the East summit at 3:45. I thought I could  make  a  direct  traverse
from the low point of the cliff wall  to  avoid  climbing  back  up  to  the
ridge. Bad idea. I ran into a wicked gully I couldn\'t cross.  I  would  have
had to descend several hundred more feet with no certainty even then that  I
could make it go. So I climbed straight up very steep terrain trying to  get
back to the critical notch. I had it marked with a waypoint but the  terrain
was so steep and rugged even when it showed I was within 50 feet I  couldn\'t
readily find it and nothing looked familiar. Of, course by now it was  dark.
If it hadn\'t been for the cairn I placed I am not sure  I  would  have  ever
recognized it. It was not obvious.

I had a few more moments of confusion working my way down  from  the  notch,
then it was easy along the ridge to Lookout Dome  to  intersect  the  trail.
The remainder was pleasant as I  do  enjoy  hiking  a  trail  in  the  dark,
especially when the alternative is more hours  than  I  would  like  in  the
sleeping bag. I reached camp at 8:00.

Total: 7.5 miles, 3850 ft and 10:30 hrs

Saturday, November 23 - It was even warmer in the tent this morning  at  41.
I did get up earlier than the previous day but hung around camp  for  a  few
hours before leaving at 9:30. As I was taking a rest  break  at  the  Aurora
Divide Trail junction I met an enthusiastic young man coming up on  his  way
to climb Lizard Head. He is the only person  I  met  on  both  my  trips  up
Barnes Creek. On chatting with him for a while I realized  I  had  read  his
Storm King attempt posted on NWhikers in July, which gave me a few  pointers
for my ascent. Small world! I found out later that he did make it up  Lizard
Head. Oddly, I entered the frost zone as I descended from the  junction  and
again I appreciated the microspikes to cross the icy bridges. I reached  the
car at 1:30 and even at that hour Indian Valley along Highway 101 was  still
below freezing and all white with frost.

Day Total: 7 miles, 600 ft and 4 hrs

Trip Total: 21.5 miles and 7050 ft in 3 days

Fay Pullen

