            'tr' => '
Anderson Butte (3400+ ft - P960 - Wynoochee  Lk  Quad)  and  Anderson  Butte
Lookout (3358 ft) - December 11, 2013

I must confess this is my second trip up  Anderson  Butte  in  less  than  a
week. I must also admit that the actual summit is not worth a repeat  visit.
So why return, you may ask? Because somehow  during  my  first  trip  I  had
failed to locate the nearby lookout site which  I  really  wanted  to  find.
But let me start at the beginning.

Anderson  Butte,  though  of  low  elevation,  rises   steeply   above   the
bottomlands between the Wynoochee and West Fork Satsop Rivers. I  have  long
been intrigued by a 1952 photo of the Anderson Butte Lookout in  Spring  and
Fish\'s Lookouts book (1996). It shows a cabin perched atop a rocky  pinnacle
reached by a trail, with a cable handrail, blasted  into  the  summit  rock.
The cabin was built in the 1930s and removed in 1968.  It  was  reported  to
have fine views of the southern Olympics. A trail formerly climbed from  the
valley up Anderson Creek but has since been obliterated by  logging.  Wood\'s
Olympic Trail Guide describes a remnant of the old trail, as of 2000,  still
accessible from Road 2372-040. The only problem was  neither  book  gave  an
exact location for the lookout and, silly me, I just assumed it was  on  the
highest summit. It was not.

So on Friday, December 6 I set out to climb  Anderson  Butte  thinking  this
would also include the lookout site. I was  not  naÃ¯ve  enough  to  think  I
would still be able to drive the logging road up the south  side.  Expecting
the worst, I didn\'t even try to drive it,  parked near its obscure  junction
with Rd 2372 and started walking. The road was actually  drivable  about  .2
mile to a washout where a steep switchback continued  up  and  left.  Hoping
this might be a way around the washout I followed  it,  but  it  soon  dead-
ended at a water tower (for the nearby Satsop Center?). I  returned  to  the
washout and crossed it. Much to my surprise,  the  road  was  in  very  good
shape for hiking and in  fact  someone  had  done  a  fair  amount  of  work
brushing out the more overgrown sections. This was a good sign.  There  was,
however, little evidence of much recent use.

I easily followed the road about 3  miles,  past  another  washout,  a  nice
viewpoint at a corner and a switchback to the end of trail maintenance on  a
rib at 2800 ft. Here I found a large cairn and wooden arrow  pointing  to  a
steep path up the rib. This was an even better sign. It had to lead  to  the
lookout. But it was not a simple path and I am sure it is not  part  of  the
"old trail" but rather a "new route" put in by some  interested  party.   It
started well enough in the forest with a faint tread and a few  stray  flags
to guide the way, then got steeper and  steeper.  The  slick  frozen  ground
didn\'t help. Near the main ridge I ran into an  area  of  massive  blowdowns
with huge logs lying every which way.  A way  through  this  mess  was  well
flagged. It was not pretty or easy, what with crawling over and  under  logs
and in and out of debris, but it did  get  me  through  and  was  infinitely
better than being left to fend for myself.

I lost the flagging near the false summit, but since  I  was  now  past  the
horrible blowdowns I just headed straight up, still  with  the  preconceived
notion that the summit and lookout site were one in the same. As I  followed
the easy ridge to the true  summit  and  the  forest  refused  to  thin,  it
gradually dawned on me  they  were  not.  The  summit  was  a  disappointing
forested bump with zero views only of interest to a peakbagger.  I  realized
I had no idea where the lookout site was and I saw no  prospects  nearby.  I
might have explored around the area further, but this was  during  the  deep
freeze. It hovered near twenty all day with  stiff  breezes.   I  got  quite
cold during my brief lunch stop,  my  water  bottle  froze  solid,   it  was
getting late and I did not want to descend the tricky frozen ground or  find
my way through the blowdowns in the dark. So I gave up.  Despite  that,  the
last hour on the road was by headlamp anyway. (Total: 7 miles, 2900  ft  and
6:30 hrs)

Wednesday, December  11  -  And  so  I  returned  less  than  a  week  later
determined to find the lookout site. While home I studied the satellite  map
of the area and could see an open rocky area on  a  spur  ridge  SW  of  the
highest summit. This had to be where it was. It sure helps to know where  to
look.

I got an earlier start, drove directly to  the  first  washout  and  started
from there (1100 ft).  I  found  the  repeat  hike  up  the  road  downright
pleasant and reached the way trail cairn in 2 hours. I  didn\'t  know  it  at
the time but the lookout site is visible  from  this  spot.  Once  past  the
blowndowns where I had lost the route before, I carefully  looked  for  more
flags  in the direction I now knew I had to go - and found them.  The  route
traversed beneath the false summit west to a saddle. Here I  found  a  faint
trail, partially obscured by some debris, that went  down  slightly  on  the
other side to the base of the lookout crag. This crag is not visible at  all
from the forest until right upon it. And then there it  was  -  the  blasted
trail, the old iron posts for the hand cable, the foundation  of  the  cabin
and the views. It was a sunny and much  warmer  day  (above  freezing)  than
before and I spent a pleasant half hour on top (2450 ft, 3:30 hrs)

Just for completeness, I went back to the true summit (200 ft and  :30  from
LO). I then returned to the lookout again, since it was so  nice,  to  watch
the setting sun. I used up the remaining daylight working  on  the  trail  a
bit (I had brought a hand  saw  just  for  this  purpose)  and  adding  more
flagging.  I really feel this route could be  and  should  be  made  into  a
better trail. The lookout site deserves one. Meanwhile it is  accessible  to
anyone willing to tackle the rough way trail. For  those  into  old  lookout
sites it is well worth the effort.

Total: 7 miles 2900 ft and 8 hrs

Fay Pullen







