Langille Pk (5372 ft - P252 - McCoy Pk Quad) - December 19, 2013

The closest approach to this peak is  from  the  northern  terminus  of  the
Langille Ridge Trail #259. However, I was  under  the  impression  that  the
access Road 2809 bridge over Yellowjacket Creek was still washed  out.  Both
the 2002 GT McCoy Peak map and the current  Gifford  Pinchot  NF  web  site,
which I read the day before leaving, confirmed this to be true.  Still  that
is the way I wanted to go so I went prepared to  ford  with  hip  waders  (I
couldn\'t handle wet feet in cold  water  this  time  of  year).  Imagine  my
surprise when I came to the crossing and found a new bridge in  place.  What
luck! My glee at not having to wade was quickly replaced with  despair  when
barely .6 mile up the road I came to a pickup blocking the road with a  sign
propped against it saying "tree felling ahead". I should have known  logging
and not hiker convenience was the reason the bridge was replaced.

I mulled over my options. I thought about going somewhere else but the  days
are so short I  didn\'t  have  the  time  and  I  really  wanted  this  peak.
Obviously they didn\'t want anyone in the area nor did I want to  be  smashed
by a falling tree. I could have driven around the pickup  but  didn\'t  think
that wise as it would be too obvious having a vehicle past the  sign  and  I
didn\'t know what I would run into farther  on.  However,  on  foot  I  could
probably sneak through if I was  alert  and  careful.  So  I  parked  a  few
hundred feet in front of the pickup (elev 2300 ft) and  started  walking.  I
could hear chainsaws and trees falling a ways below me but I met no one  and
saw no activity whatsoever on the road  itself.  The  area  of  concern  was
limited to near where the pickup was parked and I was quickly  beyond  that.
My annoyance at having to walk a perfectly  good  road  was  soon  muted  by
reaching the end of the drivable portion in a short .5 mile.  I  would  have
had to walk the majority of  the  road  anyway.  In  another  1.5  miles  of
pleasant walking I came to the old TH and the start of true  trail  at  2700
ft. The trail itself was in good  shape  and,  remarkably,  almost  snowfree
until I left it at 4700 ft (4.5 miles, 2400 ft. 3 hrs).

I was looking for the boot track mentioned in Dan Nelson\'s Day Hiking  South
Cascades. I naively thought this would lead to the summit as  that  was  the
implication. In hindsight and on closer rereading of  the  book,  I  do  not
believe Nelson was talking about the true summit but rather a rounded  knoll
some distance to the south. I really  should  have  realized  that.  Both  a
distant view of the peak  and  an  examination  of  map  contours  indicated
extensive cliffs and should have prepared me for no walkup ascent. At  least
I did think to take a rope.

In any event I came to what I thought was a boot  track  (probably  just  an
animal track) and started uphill. Almost immediately I  lost  all  signs  of
the track and ran into cliffs. I first tried to  turn  them  by  going  left
where I ran into a continuous wall I couldn\'t see any way  through.  Then  I
tried to the right and found a way  to  above  the  wall  but  then  had  to
traverse left a ways below upper cliffs until past those. I eventually  made
my way up to the main south ridge but could not follow  it  or  get  off  it
directly to easier terrain below due to more cliffs. I had to  backtrack  to
where I could descend into the basin below the ridge and  climb  up  to  the
left of it to the base of the summit rocks. All the while the  whole  summit
area was looking increasingly frightful. I saw no easy way up.  But  I  know
not to give up until rubbing noses with the rock. It often looks worse  from
a distance than it turns out to be.

And so it was. Once closer I could pick out a route through the cliffs.  The
hardest part was a class 4 pitch up an initial short vertical wall.  A  dead
tree leaning against the wall provided a few helpful  holds.  Above  that  a
class 3 ledge and gully led to a notch in the ridge. Actually  the  climbing
was fun, although it would have been more fun without the snow and  ice  and
cold and having to use gloves (temps were low 20\'s).  That  made  everything
seem more serious. On a warm summer day  this  would  be  a  very  enjoyable
climb. It was then an easy scramble along the ridge to the  summit  although
I did take care due to the exposure and snowy rock. I  reached  the  top  at
3:00 (5 miles, 3400 ft, 4:30). There was a cairn  but  no  register.  I  had
some good views; however Rainier  was  already  beginning  to  disappear  in
clouds due to an approaching front.

While not strictly necessary, I did rappel from the notch to the cliff  base
for fear of slipping on the snowy rock. I reached  the  trail  at  dusk  and
descended the rest of the way out by headlamp. All  day  long  I  had  heard
logging activity in the valley below. Often  it  was  quite  loud  with  the
sound of heavy equipment and trees falling and they kept at it right  up  to
the last daylight at  4:30.  I  just  hoped  my  car  was  still  there  and
unaffected. It was, but it was sobering to find a  half  dozen  large  trees
newly felled and still lying across the road just before I reached  it.  The
sign really meant what it said and I am glad I paid attention to it.  Had  I
driven around the pickup I might still be there.

Trip Total: 10 miles, 3550 ft and 8:30 hrs.

Fay Pullen

