Wallace Peak (5760+ ft - P600 - Mowich Lk Quad) - January 1, 2014

I got a late start (even late by my standards) as I had to drop my  daughter
off at the airport before leaving home. I approached this peak the same  way
I did Tirzah  on November 14 but followed  abandoned  Road  7840  1.5  miles
farther (3.5 miles total) before dropping to Chenuis Creek.  This  was  just
before the creek that drains the SW side of East Bearhead  Mtn.  Once  again
Chenuis Creek gave me problems. I cast around for 30 minutes looking  for  a
good crossing without success. I finally just went for it on sketchy  rocks,
slipped and ended up with a wet foot but not  as  bad  as  on  Tirzah.  Once
across, the forest offered good travel and I  made  better  time.  Below  Pt
4855 at the edge of a snowy talus basin I encountered very icy terrain  that
required my microspikes to prevent slipping. Once on the crest of the  north
ridge travel improved until the final steep slope to the summit which  again
was very icy.  I reached the summit at 4:30 (3050 ft, 6  hrs)  where  I  was
shocked to find a register newly placed on December 28th and fresh  snowshoe
tracks made earlier on this same  day.  That  is  3  parties  (counting  me)
summiting this obscure Peak in 5 days. That new book on Rainier  Peaks  sure
is generating interest among peakbaggers. This was even 100/100 for some  of
them.  For me it was 98/100. I have no idea  what  approach  they  used.  My
guess is they biked the old closed road to the Carbon  River  TH,  took  the
higher bridge across the  Carbon  River  to  the  Northern  Loop  Trail  and
traversed from Chenuis Mtn. They certainly didn\'t come the way I did.

The return was slow  and  tedious  due  to  the  slick  icy  conditions  and
darkness. Even  with  microspikes  I  did  a  lot  of  slipping  as  I  have
discovered that, as good as they are for  trails,  they  don\'t  really  work
that well on steep sidehills since they don\'t fit tight enough. But then  my
aluminum crampons wouldn\'t be that  great  either  on  the  mixed  dirt  and
rocks. Maybe the tougher Katoolas with short steel spikes, no  front  points
and a more positive strap attachment would be the best  thing  to  use.  But
truth be told what is really needed is a deeper snow cover.  Hopefully  that
will soon come. However, my real  nemesis  was  Chenuis  Creek.  This  creek
definitely does not like me. I cannot stay dry while crossing it and on  the
return slipped for the fourth time (counting Tirzah).  This  time  I  really
slipped and fell completely in soaking both  feet,  both  gloved  hands  and
even much of my lower body. I was not happy as I once again sloshed  my  way
back to the car dripping wet.

Day Total: 11 miles, 3400 ft and 12:50 hrs

Fay Pullen

