            'tr' => '
Tumwater Mtn (5240+ ft - P1040 - Cowlitz Falls Quad) and Vanson Peak  (4920+
ft - P520 - Vanson Pk Quad) - January 4-6, 2014

Saturday, January 4 - My original plan  was  to  climb  only  Vanson  Pk  by
driving Road 2600 to that TH.  However,  I  found  the  road  (which  is  on
private Champion Timber lands) gated shortly after the bridge  crossing  the
Cowlitz River. This was still some 13 miles from the TH  so  it  was  on  to
Plan B.  Nearby Road 2750 leading to  the  Goat  Creek  TH  was  not  gated.
Although much longer, I could still access Vanson Pk  from  this  trail.   I
might even be able to add  Tumwater  Mtn  to  the  itinerary.  Since  I  had
planned to backpack and had food for 2 nights I would have enough time.

I drove Road 2750 4 miles to its end at the TH and  was  surprised  to  find
two other cars. One couple was just starting out as  I  arrived.  The  trail
started on a short section of abandoned road that ended in .2  mile  at  the
old TH then entered gorgeous old growth forest. After about a mile I  caught
up to the couple who were stopped at an  overhanging  waterfall  by  an  icy
section of trail. Although short it was  pure  water  ice,  very  slick  and
along a  drop-off  where  a  slip  would  have  serious  consequences.  They
declined to continue. Even with micro spikes I found it tricky  enough  that
I chopped steps with my axe for better footholds. Fortunately  it  was  only
about 5 steps across to bare ground again.

The waterfall itself was quite interesting. Though not that  large  it  fell
in wispy sprays from high up on a massive  rounded  overhanging  cliff  with
the trail passing  behind  it  through  a  cave  like  grotto.   Beyond  the
waterfall the trail was etched into the hillside above the valley,  skirting
mossy cliffs, weaving in  and  out  of  lovely  side  creeks  and  gradually
dropping to gorgeous Goat Creek with its myriad cascades and  waterfalls.  I
had no idea this trail was  so  beautiful.  It  is  certainly  a  well  kept
secret. I thoroughly enjoyed hiking it.

At 2 miles I came to the junction with the  Tumwater  Trail  and  the  trail
that led to Vanson Pk.  I had hoped  to  camp  here  as  it  was  a  central
location for both my peaks, but I saw nothing suitable and had  to  continue
another .5 mile to the crossing of Goat creek where I  found  a  nice  level
spot on a gravel bar for my tent. By the time I  got  camp  set  up  it  was
3:00. I was now closer to Tumwater than Vanson so decided to  try  for  that
peak even though I knew I couldn\'t make the summit before  dark.  The  first
problem was crossing Goat Creek. All the creek  crossings  (and  there  were
several) on this trip were of some difficulty, not  because  of  high  water
but because of slick icy rocks. I made it across without getting  wet  feet.
I wasn\'t so lucky on the return in the dark.

I quickly gained elevation on the trail. The dense forest prevented much  in
the way of any views but there was one spot  on  a  rocky  outcrop  where  I
could look across to Vanson Pk and up the valley of Goat Creek. I  gradually
began running into some minor snow but it never amounted to more than a  few
inches. It was icy in spots yet not enough to require  micro  spikes.  After
about 3 miles I came to a snowy pond at 4800 ft. The map showed  two  closed
contour high points, both at 5240+ ft above this pond. I first went  to  the
east peak,  a  short  trek  from  the  trail,  which  turned  out  to  be  a
disappointing rounded bump with no views. I then followed the ridge  to  the
west peak which was a much nicer rocky summit which would certainly  have  a
good view. Unfortunately by the time I got there (6:00)  it  was  completely
dark and I saw nothing except the lights of Glenoma in the  Cowlitz  Valley.
I think this point is higher and I left my register here (3.5 m, 2700 ft,  3
hrs).

I now decided to continue west  along  the  ridge  to  intersect  the  trail
rather than returning east the way I had come.  It  looked  much  "shorter",
the ridge had been easy to this point and  the  map  did  not  indicate  any
obvious difficulties. This was not one of my better ideas.  Beware  of  what
can be hidden in 40 foot contours. I  unexpectedly  ran  into  a  series  of
small rocky steps and cliffs and steep  frozen  ground  that  gave  me  fits
finding a way down in the dark. I would have rappelled  but  I  hadn\'t  even
brought my panic rope. Since this trip was all on trail so why would I  ever
need a rope?  That would have held true had I stayed on the  "trail".  After
slithering down steep slopes, wandering back and forth  through  cliffs  and
lowering off branch belays I eventually hit the trail but it  took  over  an
hour. A "shortcut" it was not.

The rest of the trip out on trail  was  downright  pleasant  in  comparison-
until I came to the crossing of Goat Creek again. In the dark I misjudged  a
foot placement on a submerged rock and went in over the top of my boot.  But
hey, I only got one foot wet and I  was  right  at  camp  with  a  dry  sock
immediately available so it wasn\'t that bad.

Day Total; To Camp: 2.5 miles, 700 ft, 1:30 hrs. and RT to Tumwater  Mtn:  7
miles, 2850 ft, 5:40 hrs.

Sunday, January 5 - I returned to the trail junction and  headed  up  toward
Vanson Peak. This trip truly was all on trail and good trail  at  that,  the
first part through more gorgeous mossy forest.  Much  of  the  way  followed
alongside a little creek that had more waterfalls than its small size  might
first suggest. I ran into more snow on this northern exposure trail than  on
Tumwater but never enough to hinder progress and I followed  the  tracks  of
the occupants of the other car at the TH. They had gone all the way  to  the
summit. At 4.5 miles I  reached  the  south  ridge  of  Vanson  Pk  and  the
junction with the trail that came up the other side  from  Road  2600.  From
there it was half a mile farther to the open summit and expansive  views  (5
miles, 2600 ft, 3:45 hrs). I had lunch in the sun.

Back at the trail junction I went south another half mile  along  the  ridge
to a bump hoping for more views toward Mt St Helens but there were too  many
trees. I briefly considered continuing on to Deadmans Lake  and  picking  up
the Tumwater Trail there for a big loop back to camp but that  was  12  more
miles and I was feeling lazy so I turned around. As it was  by  the  time  I
got back to camp it was 5:00 and almost dark.  I could  have  gone  out  but
again I was feeling lazy, I didn\'t want to pack up and hike out in the  dark
and since I already had a  comfortable  camp  set  up  I  decided  to  spend
another night.  The days are just too  darn  short  this  time  of  year.  I
passed the long night getting caught up on videos of The Blacklist.

Day Total: 11 miles, 3250 ft and 7:30 hr.

Monday, January 6 - I was glad I had waited for daylight to  hike  out  this
beautiful section of trail and I enjoyed it just as much as  I  had  on  the
hike in.

Day Total: 2.5 miles, 400 ft and 1:30 hrs.

Trip        Total:        23        miles        and         7200         ft
                                                                         Fay
Pullen





