            'tr' => '
Persindex (5360+ ft - P440 - Index Quad) - January 26, 2014

I had put off climbing this peak for years due to reports of horrible  brush
on the direct approach from the horseshoe curve on  Road  6220.  Nor  did  a
traverse from Persis appeal all  that  much.  Then  on  further  research  I
discovered a longer but less brushy route in  a  report  by  Justus  S  from
September 2006 where he used old roads on the west side for his  descent.  I
decided to try this route although I was uncertain how the roads  had  fared
in the intervening seven years and  what  it  would  be  like  under  winter
conditions. It turned out rather well, with one caveat.

I drove to the horseshoe curve at 2600 ft and parked. There was an  unlocked
gate here that vehicles had gone through. However, there was a washout  just
beyond. It was passable to a 4X4 but very rough, the road icy and  I  didn\'t
think it worth the risk so I walked. The road was  actually  still  drivable
for another .75 miles. It then gradually became  worse  and  more  overgrown
but was not really that bad and provided  a  good  way  through  the  valley
brush. After 2.5 miles I took a spur  road  left  that  led  to  a  4880  ft
saddle. The spur continued a short distance past the saddle to  end  on  the
north side below the extensive cliffs of Persindex\'s west ridge.

Up to this point what snow there was had been fairly soft but at  I  entered
the  shady  north  slope  it  turned  hard  and  crusty  and  crampons  were
necessary. I traversed the old clear-cut to cross a rib just below  a  tooth
like pinnacle. On the other side the terrain opened up onto  a  large  talus
bench. Fortunately most of the rocks were well covered with solid  snow  and
travel was relatively easy.  Although  I  occasionally  ran  into  breakable
crust, for the most part I stayed on top and never really needed  snowshoes,
which was a good thing as I had not brought them along.

So far things were going great. Then I entered the "obvious and easy"  gully
mentioned by Justus that provided access through the  cliffs  to  the  south
side.  Well, it may have been easy when bare  but  what  I  encountered  was
rock hard icy snow. Even with crampons the footing wasn\'t  that  secure  and
as the steepness increased near the notch at the top  I  had  to  resort  to
cutting steps to get up. In places I also had to search for a  spot  to  get
my axe pick all the way in. It was slow going and I probably lost  close  to
an hour here. To make matters even worse all the way  up  small  ice  pieces
were constantly falling from off  the  cliffs  on  either  side.  The  gully
itself was in perpetual shade. Not so with the upper cliffs. Nothing  really
big ever came down but it was unnerving all the same.  When  I  reached  the
notch I breathed a sigh of relief while still dreading the  descent  on  the
way back.

I entered welcome sunshine on the other side of  the  notch.  The  snow  was
softer yet still had a hard layer underneath so I kept  my  crampons  on.  I
descended slightly to bypass a cliff then climbed to a level bench  below  a
cliff band. I traversed this until I could cut up through the cliffs to  the
broad basin above which contained several frozen tarns.  Then  it  was  easy
slopes to the base of the summit tower and on to the top where I arrived  at
3:40 (3050 ft, 5:40 hrs).  Mindful of recent events I stayed well back  from
the cornice hanging over the steep east face.  I  looked  across  to  Middle
Index remembering the epic Franklin and I had shared on that peak  and  felt
his strong presence. I hoped his spirit would help get me down safely as  he
himself had done many times before.

I returned quickly to the notch where if anything descending the  gully  was
worse than climbing it. It went okay at first  backing  down  my  previously
chopped steps until I  reached  the  end  of  those  steps  and  still  felt
uncomfortable without them. So I had to chop new steps going down,  which  I
find very awkward to do. Thank heavens  for  my  Whippet  which  gave  me  a
handhold for my left hand while I chopped  with  my  right.  Eventually  the
angle lessened enough that I could just crampon  down  but  by  then  I  was
pretty fried. It had taken a lot of time under fading light  conditions  all
while  stuff  continued  coming  down  off  the  sides.  Under  better  snow
conditions it would not be that bad to climb this gully but  it  could  also
have great avalanche potential with dangerous slides  coming  off  the  side
walls. It reminded me of the Dry Creek Route gully on  Big  Four  but  on  a
smaller scale. No, I did not like this gully at all.

The rest of the way out was by headlamp but I didn\'t  mind.  I  rather  like
traveling at night if the terrain is reasonable. It was a beautiful  evening
perfect for reflecting on friends and family, present and past.

I reached the car at 8:30.

Total: 9 miles, 3250 ft and 10:32 hrs

Fay Pullen



